<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000009.tif" N="1">
<HEAD>I. La estorie del Euangelie. (A FRAGMENT.)<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ed. before by me in <I>Engl. Stud.</I>, viii. 2.</NOTE></HEAD>
<ARGUMENT><P>(Title:) <MILESTONE N="Ciiib" UNIT="folio"> I ceste liuere est escrit la estorie del Euangelie en engleis solum ceo ke ele est escrit en latin, et continue de la Anunciacion nostre seignour Ihesu crist. De la Natiuite be|nette. De sa Passion. De sa Resurexion. De sa Ascension e de sa Glorificacion. Et de soun Auenement a Jugement et de nostre presentement en cors en alme.</P><P>(<I>Picture cut out.</I>)</P></ARGUMENT>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sum-while ich was wi&thorn; sunne i-bounde,</L>
<L>And sunne me hath icast to grounde;</L>
<L>Bote, swete Ihesu, &thorn;i swete woundus</L>
<L N="4">Leesed me ha&thorn; of harde stoundus.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon I to &thorn;e tornde my &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>Pynes to &thorn;ole ne greue&thorn; me nouht;</L>
<L>&THORN;y De&thorn; me haue&thorn; of serwe i-brouht</L>
<L N="8">And loue to &thorn;e in me ha&thorn; wrouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e to loue is al my blisse,</L>
<L>Me longe&thorn; sore &thorn;i woundus to kisse.</L>
<L>Swete Ihesu, my &thorn;ouht &thorn;ou wisse,</L>
<L N="12">On &thorn;e to &thorn;enche &thorn;at I ne misse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffole &thorn;ouhtes me were woned to tille,</L>
<L>ffeole tymes to don ille,</L>
<L>In word, In dede, In wikked wille,</L>
<L N="16">Niht and Day, al me to spille:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bote whon I me vndurstod</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou for me scheddest &thorn;i blod,</L>
<L>ffolye to leue me &thorn;houhte good</L>
<L N="20">And to &thorn;e, Ihesu, I tornde my mood.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bote &yogh;it I me bi-gon to drede</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;at egge&thorn; mon to quede</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sunfol &thorn;ouht me wolde lede</L>
<L N="24">To wikked wille or fool dede.
<PB REF="00000010.tif" N="2"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;erfore my &thorn;ouht on &thorn;e i feste;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er i wot to fynden reste&mdash;</L>
<L>Of vche loue &thorn;ou art &thorn;e beste,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;ou art &thorn;e loue &thorn;at euere wol leste.</L>
<L>Nis no mon, Ihesu, bote in &thorn;e</L>
<L>In whom bi-houe&thorn; us I-borwed be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;i loue to winne, i wolde fonde,</L>
<L N="32">&YOGH;if I me mihte wel vndurstonde,</L>
<L>Sum &thorn;ing of &thorn;e to write and rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-&thorn;orwh of &thorn;e to winnen mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And heo &thorn;at scholden hit iheren,</L>
<L N="36">Of &thorn;e Gospel mowe sumwhat leren</L>
<L>&THORN;at writen is &thorn;er-Inne of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>On Englisch tonge &thorn;orwh swynk of me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wyse men bi Olde dawes</L>
<L N="40">Bokes made of goode lawes,</L>
<L>Hou me scholde hem wi&thorn; rihte leden</L>
<L>And wys to ben in alle heor deden;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;ei no-&thorn;ing ne wusten of &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="44">But goddus heo maden of ston and tre,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ing &thorn;at ne mihte seo ne here</L>
<L>ffor God heo honourede and heolde dere:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sonne and Mone, Day and Niht,</L>
<L N="48">Sterre and al &thorn;at &yogh;iue&thorn; lyht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Goddus weren alle &thorn;ei wenden,</L>
<L>And God of heuene no-&thorn;ing ne kenden.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of grete Clerkes also we fynde</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at Bokes made of Beestes kynde,</L>
<L>Of ffoul, of Ston, of Gras, of Treo,</L>
<L>And al for Mon &thorn;eron to seo,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Solace to haue and techinge,</L>
<L N="56">And hem to holde from fool lykynge&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor whose here&thorn; of Beestes kynde</L>
<L>Mony wondrus he may &thorn;er fynde,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffeole &thorn;inges seon and here</L>
<L N="60">Wher-&thorn;orwh he may him-self lere</L>
<L>Hys lyf to lede wi&thorn; more wynne,</L>
<L>Good to do and haty&yogh;e synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A wys mon sei&thorn; &thorn;at bestes weren,</L>
<L N="64">Hert and Eddre, &thorn;eos &thorn;reo, and Ern,
<PB REF="00000011.tif" N="3"></L>
<L>&THORN;at heore lyf chaungede &thorn;orwh here kynde&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;us of hem I-write we fynde:</L>
<L>&THORN;at kuynde &yogh;if&thorn; vche mon eggynge,</L>
<L N="68">Of vche good &thorn;ing haue &yogh;eornyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bote beter &thorn;yng ne mai no mon fynde</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e, lord of alle &thorn;ynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Beest and ffoul and alle wiht</L>
<L N="72">At wille beo&thorn; vndur Monnes miht.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu louerd, &thorn;i loue to wynne</L>
<L>&YOGH;if me grace to bi-gynne,</L>
<L>Loue me sende to fordo synne,</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at al monkynde was bounden Inne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ar Godus sone in &thorn;e Maiden alyhte,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e deuel we nedde no mihte;</L>
<L>ffor we weren vndur his mihte,</L>
<L N="80">Of good to don we loren &thorn;e sihte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at tyme was sunne so ryf,</L>
<L>In Old, In &yogh;ong, In Mon, In Wyf:</L>
<L>As sone as heo laften &thorn;e lyf,</L>
<L N="84">To helle heo wenden wi&thorn;-outen stryf.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Habraham, Ysaak, and seint Ion,</L>
<L>Dauid &thorn;e kyng, and Salamon,</L>
<L>&THORN;idere heo wenden, euerichon,&mdash;</L>
<L N="88">Heo nedden &thorn;o no beter won.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>fforte Godus sone was don on Rode,</L>
<L>&THORN;idere<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;iderre</NOTE> wente wikkede and goode,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wikkede to pyne, wi&thorn; dreri mode,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;ere to beo &thorn;e deueles foode;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bote &thorn;ulke soules swete</L>
<L>&THORN;at here on lyue heore synnes leete,</L>
<L>In freo prisun &thorn;enne was heore sete,</L>
<L N="96">To abyde &thorn;e biheste of &thorn;e prophete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Prophetes weren I-woned to grede:</L>
<L>"Ow schal comen wi&thorn;-oute drede</L>
<L>&THORN;at flesch schal taken in Maydenhede</L>
<L N="100">And us to Ioye of pyne lede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon God of heuene herde &thorn;is cry,</L>
<L>Of Monkynde he hedde mercy:</L>
<L>And ches a Mayde of gret ferly,</L>
<L N="104">Clene in soule and in body.
<PB REF="00000012.tif" N="4"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To hire he sende a swete fere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him was swi&thorn;e leof and dere:</L>
<L>Gabriel, wi&thorn; swete chere,</L>
<L N="108">And hire gon grete on &thorn;is manere:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Heil, ful of grace, God is wi&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>A-Mong wymmen I-blessed &thorn;ou be!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maide was dred on him to seo,</L>
<L N="112">And &thorn;ouhte what &thorn;is mihte beo.<NOTE PLACE="inter">(<I>Here picture: Mary and angel.</I>)</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enne him spac &thorn;e Aungel fre:</L>
<L>"Marie, nouht ne dreed &thorn;ou &thorn;e!</L>
<L>A child schal beo boren of &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="116">Iesus schal his nome be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He schal &thorn;e ffader of heuene qweme,</L>
<L>In Dauid sete sitte and deeme,</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk of Israel he schal &yogh;eme</L>
<L N="120">And heore fon from hem fleme."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;enne onswerde &thorn;at swete Mayde</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Aungel Gabriel and sayde:</L>
<L>"Hou schal &thorn;is be? nou&yogh;wher I ne leide</L>
<L N="124">Mi &thorn;ouht to luste of mon vpbreide."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;e Aungel hire herte dihte,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;is gretynge hedde in-sihte:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e holy gost (he seide) schal in &thorn;e alihte</L>
<L N="128">And in &thorn;e worche wi&thorn; his mihte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e chyld &thorn;at of &thorn;e schal beo bore,</L>
<L>Godus sone he schal beon i-core;</L>
<L>He schal &thorn;e folk, &thorn;at herbi-fore,</L>
<L N="132">To blisse bringe, &thorn;at heo hedden forlore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;e so&thorn;e lere,</L>
<L>&THORN;i nece Eli&yogh;abe&thorn;, lo here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is in elde feole &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="136">Heo ha&thorn; chyld take of hire feere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e sixte Mone&thorn; now is anon</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo ha&thorn; wi&thorn; chylde igon&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor to God of heuene, &thorn;at is on,</L>
<L N="140">Nis word of vnmihte non."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nolde Marie no lengore plede,</L>
<L>&THORN;is wordes in hire herte heo sede:
<PB REF="00000013.tif" N="5"></L>
<L>"Lo me her Godus Mayde,</L>
<L N="144">Wi&thorn; me do God as &thorn;ou hast sayde!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As sone as &thorn;is was in hire &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>In hire was Monnes kuynde i-wrouht</L>
<L>And so&thorn;fast God was &thorn;erto i-brouht&mdash;</L>
<L N="148">Mon, &thorn;er-of ne dred &thorn;e nouht!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e Aungel Marie God bi-kende</L>
<L>And to him eode &thorn;at him sende.</L>
<L>And sone aftur &thorn;at mayde wende</L>
<L N="152">To Eli&yogh;abe&thorn;, hire kuynde frende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone so &thorn;e Mayde Marie</L>
<L>Entrede &thorn;e hous of &YOGH;akarie,</L>
<L>Eli&yogh;abeth In prophecie</L>
<L N="156">&THORN;e Maide custe and &thorn;us gon crie:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"A," heo seide, "how may &thorn;is be</L>
<L>&THORN;at my lordus modur come&thorn; to me?</L>
<L>As sone as ich herde &thorn;e steuene of &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;e Child in my wombe makede gle.</L>
<L>&para; A-Mong wymmen I-blessed &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>And blessed beo &thorn;e fruyt of &thorn;e!"<NOTE PLACE="marg">Here should follow v. 275 ff.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er bilafte &thorn;at swete may</L>
<L N="164">Wi&thorn; Eli&yogh;abeth wel moni a day&mdash;</L>
<L>Ne louede heo no foles play,</L>
<L>Bote louede God and &thorn;onked ay.<NOTE PLACE="inter">(<I>Picture: Mary and Elizabeth.</I>)</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enne &thorn;er was a swete metynge,</L>
<L N="168">Swete cluppinge and swete cussynge!</L>
<L>A Mayde &thorn;at bar &thorn;e lord of alle &thorn;inge,</L>
<L>A wyf &thorn;at bar seint Ion in holy weddinge!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is was seynt Ion for whom bi-fore</L>
<L N="172">His ffader hedde his speche for-lore,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he was bore,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e Aungel seide bi-fore.</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;akarie was his ffadre name;</L>
<L N="176">Gret mon he was and of good fame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tyme com of &thorn;e seruyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he don scholde in heore wyse:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e temple he saih vp rise</L>
<L N="180">Bifore him a mon, and him gon agrise.
<PB REF="00000014.tif" N="6"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HIt was an Aungel, Godes sonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gon at &thorn;e Auter stonde,</L>
<L>And &YOGH;akarie he com to fonde,</L>
<L N="184">Don his seruyse bad him not wonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&YOGH;akarie," he seide, "ne dred &thorn;ou nouht!</L>
<L>Bifore God &thorn;i bone is wrouht;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast him bi-souht,</L>
<L N="188">Schal in Eli&yogh;abeth ben i-wrouht:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A child &thorn;ou schalt on hire winne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at schal ben Ioye to al his kinne,</L>
<L>I-blessed he beo hire wi&thorn;-Inne;</L>
<L N="192">Ion he schal hote, clansere of sinne.<NOTE PLACE="inter">(<I>Picture: Zacharias and Angel.</I>)</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At his Burth-tyme me schal gamen &amp; pleye:</L>
<L>He schal grei&thorn;en godus weye,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e folk he schal so&thorn; seye</L>
<L N="196">And mis-bileue he schal doun leye."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;akarie onswerde wi&thorn; dreri chere:</L>
<L>"Hou may &thorn;is ben on eny manere?</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e we be&thorn; olde, ich and my fere,</L>
<L N="200">And for&thorn; igon in feole &yogh;ere."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e Aungel seide: "&THORN;is schalt &thorn;ou se.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at &thorn;ou leuest not me,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt beo Doumbe, ich sigge &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="204">fforte &thorn;at child ibore be."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e Aungel bi-lafte no lengore &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>Ne &YOGH;akarie ne spac no more,</L>
<L>Bote out he eode, sikynge sore&mdash;</L>
<L N="208">&THORN;e folk hedde wondur wherfore hit wore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bote heo seiden alle by-dene</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ha&thorn; sum wondur i-sene</L>
<L>&THORN;at he so longe ha&thorn; i-bene</L>
<L N="212">In &thorn;e temple, as we wene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;akarie &thorn;enne dude his dede,</L>
<L>Nout for his fleschliche nede,</L>
<L>But child to wynnen, &yogh;if he miht spede,</L>
<L N="216">And so of God to wynne meede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at swete couple at &thorn;at metynge</L>
<L>Of ffleschliche lust hedde no lykynge,
<PB REF="00000015.tif" N="7"></L>
<L>Bote holy wille and swete egginge</L>
<L N="220">To Godus seruyse chyld for&thorn; bringe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A child he won &thorn;orwh godus mihte,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh Godus heste, and hedde insihte:</L>
<L>In Eli&yogh;abeth &thorn;e holigost lihte</L>
<L N="224">And &thorn;at child in hire dihte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Eli&yogh;abeth ful glad was &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo gon wi&thorn; chylde go!</L>
<L>A-wey heo let al hire wo</L>
<L N="228">&THORN;at heo hedde fourti &yogh;er and mo.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon &thorn;at child scholde iboren be,</L>
<L>His frendes aboute of &thorn;e cuntre</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; blisful chere, gamen and gle</L>
<L N="232">Alle he comen &thorn;e child to se.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;enne seiden his frendes alle</L>
<L>&YOGH;akarie heo wolden him calle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at herde &thorn;e Modur, &thorn;er heo lay,</L>
<L N="236">And onswerde and seide: "nay,</L>
<L>"Mi leue frendes, do&thorn; a-way!</L>
<L>Ion he schal hote, &yogh;if I may."</L>
<L>&para; Alle heo seiden &thorn;at &thorn;er nas non</L>
<L N="240">In al heore kynde &thorn;at hihte Ion.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To &YOGH;akarie &thorn;e word heo brouhte</L>
<L>And bad him sigge what he &thorn;ouhte.</L>
<L>And he a table sone souhte</L>
<L N="244">And &thorn;eron &thorn;e nome wrouhte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On &thorn;e tablet he wrot anon</L>
<L>&THORN;e childes nome, he wrot Ion&mdash;</L>
<L>"God bi-fore he schal gon<NOTE PLACE="marg">v. 247-8 should follow v. 196.</NOTE></L>
<L N="248">And to him torne mony on."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wondur hedde &thorn;o al his kynde</L>
<L>Hou he mihte &thorn;is nome fynde.</L>
<L>Bote God his tonge let vnbynde;</L>
<L N="252">And he him louede wi&thorn; al his Mynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"God," he seide, "i-blessed &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of his folk wolde haue pite,</L>
<L>And his Merci ha&thorn; i-sent to me,</L>
<L N="256">&THORN;at &thorn;is child schulde i-bore be!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">This stanza follows v. 266 in the MS.</NOTE>And &thorn;ou, child, schalt ben clept prophete,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt grei&thorn;e godus strete,
<PB REF="00000016.tif" N="8"></L>
<L>Godus folk &thorn;ou schalt . . . . .gete</L>
<L N="260">And hem teche heor sunnes bete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is speche to godus folk &THORN;ou schalt preche,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hem schalt &thorn;e so&thorn;e teche</L>
<L>Hou heo schulle to heuene reche."</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inter">(<I>Picture: Birth of John.</I>)</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="264">Also as ich er seyde, &thorn;e Maide Marie</L>
<L>Hire lyf ladde wi&thorn;-oute folye</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Eli&yogh;abeth and hire cumpaygnye.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hem &thorn;enne was heo &thorn;ore</L>
<L N="268">&THORN;reo Mone&thorn;es, o&thorn;ur more,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen sunne, wi&thorn;-outen sore&mdash;</L>
<L>Heo louede god, &thorn;at was hire lore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As sei&thorn; &thorn;e holy mon seint Bede:</L>
<L N="272">ffrom hire nece nout heo ne eode</L>
<L>Ar heo say fulliche in dede</L>
<L>Eli&yogh;abeth seint Ion fede.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;enne heo &thorn;onked god, ful of blisse,</L>
<L N="276">&THORN;at he wolde seo hire mekenesse</L>
<L>And hire a sone sende in swetnesse,</L>
<L>To taken in hire monnes liknesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;erfore me schal al Monkynde</L>
<L N="280">Blisful telle in heore mynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wolde in me Mekenesse fynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mihtful is to lame and blynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of Merci he was leche</L>
<L N="284">ffrom kynde &thorn;at dredde his speche.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e proude of herte he dude wreche,</L>
<L>And dude &thorn;e Meke an hei&yogh; to reche;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e hungri in god he made stronge,</L>
<L N="288">And &thorn;e riche he lette al swonge.</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk of Israel ha&thorn; vndurfonge</L>
<L>&THORN;e child &thorn;at heo abide longe;</L>
<L>&para; Also him spac &thorn;e heuene kyng</L>
<L N="292">To Abraham and his ofspring."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon Marie hedde i-se&yogh;e &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e child and al &thorn;e neode,
<PB REF="00000017.tif" N="9"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Mayden hire bi-gon to spede</L>
<L N="296">And leue tok and hom heo eode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon heo com hom, Iosep to queme</L>
<L>&THORN;at als his spouse hire hedde to &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>In his herte he gon hire deme,</L>
<L N="300">Hou heo mihte wi&thorn; childe seme.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whar-of hit were, no&thorn;ing he nuste,</L>
<L>So as he neuere hire Mou&thorn; custe</L>
<L>Mid wille of sunne, ne neuer luste</L>
<L N="304">Hire Maidenhod fulliche vpbreste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for in him nas no falshede,</L>
<L>In word ne in &thorn;ouht ne in dede,</L>
<L>In his herte nas no drede</L>
<L N="308">&THORN;auh heo hedde ilore hire Maydenhede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for he neuere ne sai&yogh; wi&thorn; ei&yogh;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo to fool dede gon hire bey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Loth him was on hire to ly&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="312">Of<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Of of</NOTE> fleschliche dede hire be-wrye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor wel he wuste, nas &thorn;er no speche,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;e lawe of spousbruche,</L>
<L>Bote hire &thorn;e domesmon bi-teche,</L>
<L N="316">Sone of hire to take wreche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A&yogh;e &thorn;e lawe him lyked ille</L>
<L>&THORN;at me scholde a Mayde spille.</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i bi-fel hit in his wille</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;at Mayde lete and leuen hire stille.<NOTE PLACE="inter">(<I>Picture: An Angel appears to Joseph in his sleep.</I>)</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;O Ioseph in his herte wende</L>
<L>Ho[u] &thorn;is scholde come to ende,</L>
<L>A-slepe he fel, as god him kende,</L>
<L N="324">And to him his Aungel sende:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Ioseph," he seide, "no-&thorn;ing ne drede,</L>
<L>Marie as &thorn;i spouse &thorn;ou lede;</L>
<L>&THORN;at child in hire &thorn;o[u] schalt fede:</L>
<L N="328">Hit is &thorn;e holigostes dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e holigost hire ha&thorn; beo mylde</L>
<L>And Marie ha&thorn; i-brouht wi&thorn; chylde;</L>
<L>God in hire ha&thorn; i-do vertu:</L>
<L N="332">His nome &thorn;ou schalt clepe Ihesu."
<PB REF="00000018.tif" N="10"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon Ioseph herde &thorn;is ty&thorn;inge,</L>
<L>Marie he heold in clene weddynge</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e Maide in good lykinge</L>
<L N="336">Mayde bi-lafte to his endynge.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bi hem &thorn;at weore bi-fore</L>
<L>Ioseph wuste whon god scholde be bore . . . . .</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at tyme was mih<NOTE PLACE="marg">Last words cut out with the picture on the front page.</NOTE> . . . . .</L>
<L N="340">Augustus Cesar wa . . . . .</L>
<L>In al &thorn;at lond nas . . . . .</L>
<L>Ouer al &thorn;at lond w . . . . .</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He criede his ban . . . . .</L>
<L N="344">To alle &thorn;at weren . . . . .</L>
<L>&THORN;at vndur him no . . . . .</L>
<L>&THORN;at were of eny o&thorn;u . . . . .</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon Ioseph &thorn;us h . . . . .</L>
<L N="348">Wi&thorn; him tok &thorn;e Ma . . . . .</L>
<L>Out of Na&yogh;areth h . . . . .</L>
<L>And to Bethlehem h . . . . .</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In Bethleem he tok his wonynge,</L>
<L N="352">ffor Marie was neih childynge,</L>
<L>And for his kun and his ofspringe</L>
<L>Weoren of Dauid&thorn;es hous, &thorn;e kynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In Bethlehem hous he tok,</L>
<L N="356">Luytel and pore, as sei&thorn; &thorn;e Bok,</L>
<L>In an old cote and al to-falle&mdash;</L>
<L>Nedden heo no bettere halle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seint Ierom a Mayde kende</L>
<L N="360">In a writ &thorn;at he hire sende:</L>
<L>&THORN;at [&thorn;at] Mayde won hire bred</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hire nelde and hire &thorn;red.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon &thorn;at child was for&thorn; brouht,</L>
<L N="364">Luytel heo hedde o&thorn;ur riht nouht</L>
<L>fforte leggen Inne &thorn;at Bern,</L>
<L>But a luyte hei o&thorn;ur vern;</L>
<L>Heo wounden him wi&thorn; &thorn;at heo mihten gete,</L>
<L N="368">And leyden him, &thorn;er bestes ete.<NOTE PLACE="inter">(<I>Picture: Birth of Jesus.</I>)</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heo leyden him in Bestes stalles,</L>
<L>I-loke bi-twene two olde walles&mdash;
<PB REF="00000019.tif" N="11"></L>
<L>&THORN;enne was fuld &thorn;e prophecie</L>
<L N="372">&THORN;at bi-fore seide Ysay&yogh;e:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e Oxe and &thorn;e Asse hedde kennynge</L>
<L>Of heore lord in heore stallynge.</L>
<L>And Abacuc also haue&thorn; i-seyd:</L>
<L N="376">By-twene two bestes he scholde be leyd.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So bi-fel &thorn;at ilke tyde</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e cuntre &thorn;erbisyde</L>
<L>Herdes wakede in a Mede,</L>
<L N="380">Heore bestes and heore schep to fede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone to hem an Angel wende</L>
<L>And to hem brouhte a swete ty&thorn;inge&mdash;</L>
<L>Heo bi-gonne to ben in doute</L>
<L N="384">Of liht &thorn;at was &thorn;er hem aboute.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e Aungel seide: "nou&yogh;t &yogh;e ne drede!</L>
<L>Ich wole ow telle a blisful dede:</L>
<L>A child is boren for oure nede,</L>
<L N="388">&THORN;at schal his folk of pyne lede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And [&thorn;at] ich ou &thorn;e so&thorn;e bringe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich &yogh;iue ow to tokenynge:</L>
<L>In Bethlehem he liht, i-wounde</L>
<L N="392">In clo&thorn;us, and in a Crubbe i-bounde.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">This stanza is corrupt.</NOTE>In a Crubbe he is leyd,</L>
<L>As ich ow habbe er i-seid.</L>
<L>He schal his [folk] of sunne bringe,</L>
<L N="396">As crist and lord of alle &thorn;inge."<NOTE PLACE="end">(<I>Picture: An Angel appears to the Shepherds.</I>). . . . .(<I>The other leaves of this Poem are wanting in the MS.</I>)<NOTE PLACE="foot">The Index to MS. Vern. gives the following description of the poem: CIIII Of &thorn;e Anunciacioun ihesu crist. Of his Natiuite. Of his circumcisioun. hou he [was] offred to Symeon. Of &thorn;e passioun. Of &thorn;e resurrexioun. Of &thorn;e ascen|syoun. Of &thorn;e sendynge of &thorn;e holi gost. Of &thorn;e comyngge to &thorn;e day of dom. &para; And o&thorn;ere diuerse Stories of ihesu crist and of his modur; &thorn;e whyche [be] in diuerse paneles in peyntur, and euery panel had his scripture acordaunt &thorn;erto, &thorn;e whiche peynture his table suffisaunt.&mdash;Then followed: fol. CXI &THORN;e pyte of crist stondynge in &thorn;e sepulcre. &THORN;e scheld off &thorn;e fey. &THORN;e scheld of &thorn;e passioun. Diuerse orisones to &thorn;e fadur and to &thorn;e sone and to &thorn;e holy gost, whit peyntures. CXII Salutaciones to vre lady, wi&thorn; peynture annex. CXIII &YOGH;yt salutaciouns to vre lady. Then Miserere &amp;c.</NOTE></NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000020.tif" N="12">
<HEAD>II. Verse Paraphrase of Psalm LI.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>(From the Seven Penitential Psalms, by Rich. Maidenstoon. Ed. by Adler and Kaluza in <I>Engl. Stud.</I> 1887, X, p. 242 ff., from MS. Digby 18, with various readings from MSS. Rawl. A 389 and Ashm. 61; there are, however, several more MSS. In MS. Rawl. the poem is ascribed to Richard Maidenstoon, in MS. Digby to Rich. Hampole. The Psalm Miserere begins v. 385, MS. Vern. v. 407. Beginning wanting, supplied from MS. Digby 18.)</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Miserere mei, deus, secundum magnam misericordiam tuam:</HEAD>
<L>Mercy, god, of my mysdede,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Penit. Psalms, v. 385.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;i mercy, &thorn;at mychel is.</L>
<L>Late &thorn;i pite springe &amp; sprede,</L>
<L N="4">And of &thorn;i mercy &thorn;at I not mys,</L>
<L>And aftir &thorn;i goostly grace I grede.</L>
<L>Now, dere god, &thorn;ou graunte me &thorn;is,</L>
<L>That I may lyue in loue &amp; drede,</L>
<L N="8">And neuere eft to don amys!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Et secundum multitudinem miseracionum tuarum dele iniquitatem meam.</HEAD>
<L>And aftir &thorn;i mercies &thorn;at ben fele,</L>
<L>Lord, fordo my wickidnesse,</L>
<L>And helpe me forto hide &amp; hele</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;e blames of my freelnesse!</L>
<L>&yogh;if eny sterynge wolde me stele</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e cloos of &thorn;i clennesse,</L>
<L>Wise &thorn;ou me, in woo &amp; wele,</L>
<L N="16">And kepe me from unkyndenesse!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Amplius lava me ab iniquitate mea, &amp; a peccato meo munda me.</HEAD>
<L>More-ouere &thorn;ou wasche me fro [my] synne,</L>
<L>And fro my fil&thorn;is clense &thorn;ou me;</L>
<L>Enserche my soule wi&thorn;oute &amp; ynne,</L>
<L N="20">That I no more defoulid be;</L>
<L>And as &thorn;in herte cleef atwynne</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; deolful dee&thorn; on rode-tre,]</L>
<L>So let me neuere werk bi-ginne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Penit. Psalms, v. 407.]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="vernon folio" N="Cxiii"></L>
<L N="24">Lord, but &yogh;if hit like &thorn;e!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Quoniam iniquitatem ego cognosco &amp;c.</HEAD>
<L>ffor al my wikkednesse i knowe,</L>
<L>And sunne is euere me a&yogh;eyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore let &thorn;i grace growe,</L>
<L N="28">Ihesus, &thorn;at were wi&thorn; Iewes slayn.</L>
<L>Riche and pore, hei&yogh;e and lowe,</L>
<L>Smale and Grete, ich am certeyn,</L>
<L>At domes-day whon &thorn;ou schalt bowe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. D: whan bemus blowe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="32">Of &thorn;i merci schul beo fayn.
<PB REF="00000021.tif" N="13"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Tibi soli peccaui &amp; malum coram te &amp;c.</HEAD>
<L>To &thorn;e only trespast haue I,</L>
<L>Wrouht wikkedliche a-&yogh;ein &thorn;i glori,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wordus and wi&thorn; tricheri.</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;ou demest riht and hast victori:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;i blis nou beo-seche I;</L>
<L>ffor told hit is in moni stori</L>
<L>&THORN;at hose crie&thorn; to &thorn;i Merci,</L>
<L N="40">Is endelesliche in &thorn;i memori.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Ecce enim in iniquitatibus conceptus.</HEAD>
<L>Bi-hold hou in sunne i was conceyued</L>
<L>Of my Modur, as Men beon alle,</L>
<L>And of my ffadur nou&yogh;t receyued</L>
<L N="44">Bote flesch ful ffrele and fayn to falle.</L>
<L>Bote se&thorn;&thorn;he &thorn;i flesch, lord, was parceyued</L>
<L>And for vr sake strauht on stalle,</L>
<L>Was neuer sinful mon deceyued</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;at wolde to &thorn;i merci calle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Ecce enim veritatem dilexisti.</HEAD>
<L>Lo, for &thorn;ow hast loued riht,</L>
<L>&THORN;e priue counseil of &thorn;i wit</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast me schewed &thorn;orwh &thorn;i miht:</L>
<L N="52">Twei kuyndes be&thorn; to-gedere I-knit,</L>
<L>&THORN;ral is fre and knaue is kniht,</L>
<L>God is mon, as gospel writ.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if my soule in peril is piht,</L>
<L N="56">Merci, God, and help &thorn;ou hit.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Asperges me domine ysopo &amp; mundabor.</HEAD>
<L>Wi&thorn; holi watur &thorn;ou schalt me sprinke,</L>
<L>And as &thorn;e snouh I schal be whit.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;auh my soule in sunne sinke,</L>
<L N="60">Wi&thorn; weopyng watur I<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> it</NOTE> may ben quit.</L>
<L>Dedly drauhtes &thorn;auh I drinke,</L>
<L>Of repentaunce &yogh;if me respit.</L>
<L>ffor on &thorn;i peynes hose &thorn;ynke,</L>
<L N="64">In worldly wel&thorn;e ha&thorn; no delyt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Auditui meo dabis gaudium.</HEAD>
<L>To myn herynge &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;iue</L>
<L>Gladnesse, to glade bones meke.
<PB REF="00000022.tif" N="14"></L>
<L>In louhnesse lere &thorn;ou me to liue,</L>
<L N="68">Leoue lord, I &thorn;e by-seke.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;eoues gult hit was for&yogh;iue,</L>
<L>On Rode-treo [his]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. he<SUP>o</SUP>re</NOTE> bones breke.</L>
<L>A serwful herte and clene i-schriue</L>
<L N="72">Saue&thorn; soule and bodi eke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Auerte faciem tuam a peccatis meis.</HEAD>
<L>ffrom my sunnes &thorn;ou torne &thorn;i face,</L>
<L>Put al my wikkednesse a-way.</L>
<L>Gret is my gult, grettore &thorn;i grace,</L>
<L N="76">And elles fayle&thorn; al vr fay.</L>
<L>Sunnes fele &thorn;at me deface</L>
<L>Make&thorn; &thorn;at I ne con not say,</L>
<L>But crie Merci whon I trespace&mdash;</L>
<L N="80">Ichot &thorn;er nis non o&thorn;ur way.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Cor mundum crea in me, deus.</HEAD>
<L>Make in me, god, myn herte clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at rihtful gost in me &thorn;ou rewe.<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. newe</NOTE></L>
<L>ffrom seuen sunnes<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. sunnes seuen</NOTE> &thorn;ou make hit schene,</L>
<L N="84">Wher so &thorn;ou go I may &thorn;e suwe.</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;i tormentes for tene,</L>
<L>&THORN;i bodi blak, &thorn;i bones bluwe!</L>
<L>Mekeful lord, &thorn;ou make hit sene</L>
<L N="88">Wi&thorn;-Inne myn herte, &thorn;at hidous hewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>NE proicias me a facie tua &amp; spiritum sanctum t.</HEAD>
<L>Cast me not out from &thorn;i visage,</L>
<L>Tac not from me &thorn;yn holigost!</L>
<L>To bi-holde &thorn;at feir Ymage,</L>
<L N="92">Of alle mur&thorn;us hit is &thorn;e most.</L>
<L>A blisful brid was brouht in Cage,</L>
<L>Cauht<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> cou&thorn;</NOTE> and Cud in eueri cost,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou weore drawen in tendre age</L>
<L N="96">To driuen adoun &thorn;e fendes bost.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Redde michi leticiam salutaris tui.</HEAD>
<L>Of hele&thorn;e &yogh;if me ioye and blisse,</L>
<L>And streng&thorn;e me wi&thorn; &thorn;i spirit chef,</L>
<L>And al my fyue wittes wisse,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;at I may loue &thorn;at &thorn;e is lef;</L>
<L>And as &thorn;ou miht my langour lisse,
<PB REF="00000023.tif" N="15"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou brouhtest mon to gret bonchef,</L>
<L>So let me neuere &thorn;i Merci misse</L>
<L N="104">Whon I am gret wi&thorn; gostly greef.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Docebo iniquos uias tuas: &amp; impii.</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e wikkede i schal &thorn;i weies teche,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sunfule schule to &thorn;e conuerte.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sunful soule, beo war of wreche,</L>
<L N="108">And &thorn;enk hou<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. on</NOTE> crist is hed and herte,</L>
<L>Breste, bak and bodi bleche,</L>
<L>Hou hit was bete wi&thorn; scourges smerte.</L>
<L>To rewe on him I wolde areche,</L>
<L N="112">Allas &thorn;er may no ter out sterte!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Libera me de sanguinibus, deus, deus.</HEAD>
<L>Deliuere me from blameful blod,</L>
<L>Almihti god, lord, myn hele&thorn;e:</L>
<L>&THORN;en schal my tonge wi&thorn; mylde mood</L>
<L N="116">Apertly schewe &thorn;i seli sel&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;i rihtful blod ran doun of Rod,</L>
<L>To wasschen vs from vr flescly ful&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And mony a storm a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e stood</L>
<L N="120">To wissen vs from &thorn;is worldly wel&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Domine labia mea aperies &amp; os meum.</HEAD>
<L>Mi lippes, lord, &thorn;ou schalt vndo,</L>
<L>And my mou&thorn; schal &thorn;i preisyng spelle:</L>
<L>&THORN;i merci and &thorn;i miht also</L>
<L N="124">Parfyt[li] may no tonge<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. no tonge may</NOTE> telle.</L>
<L>ffor whon we dedly sunne do,</L>
<L>&THORN;i riht vs dampned anon<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> deme&thorn; doun</NOTE> to helle;</L>
<L>But whon we sese and con sei ho,<NOTE PLACE="marg">sei ho, <I>i. e.</I> stop.</NOTE></L>
<L N="128">&THORN;i Merci is vr wasschyng-welle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Quoniam si voluisses sacrificium dedissem.</HEAD>
<L>Weore sacrifice to &thorn;i likyng,</L>
<L>I hedde hit &yogh;iue wi&thorn; herte fre;</L>
<L>But, certeynly, no such &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="132">As in him-self plesaunt may be.</L>
<L>&THORN;i-self were offred, a child ful &yogh;ing,</L>
<L>And afturward on Rode-tre,</L>
<L>Whon of &thorn;in herte &thorn;e blod con spring:</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;erfore myn herte I offre to &thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000024.tif" N="16"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Sacrificium deo spiritus contribulatus.</HEAD>
<L>To God hit is a sacrifice</L>
<L>A greued gost &thorn;at serwe&thorn; sore,</L>
<L>An huymble herte wol not despise,</L>
<L N="140">Whil repentaunce may hit restore.</L>
<L>I haue forloren<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. R. forleten</NOTE> &thorn;i seruice</L>
<L>And luitel i-lyued aftur &thorn;i lore;</L>
<L>But i repente nou and aryse:</L>
<L N="144">Merci, god, I wol no more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Benigne fac domine in bona voluntate.</HEAD>
<L>Wi&thorn; meke wil do to syon,</L>
<L>Ierusalem walles &thorn;at &thorn;ei weore wrouht.</L>
<L>Ierusalem, as sei&thorn; seint Ion,</L>
<L N="148">Is<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. In</NOTE> holy churche &thorn;at erre&thorn; nouht.</L>
<L>Two testamentes cordynge<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> acorde&thorn;</NOTE> in on</L>
<L>&THORN;e walles were to-gedere i-brouht,</L>
<L>Whon him-self was Corner-ston</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;at Monkuynde ha&thorn; so deore abouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Tunc acceptabis sacrificium iusticie.</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;enne schaltou sacrifice accepte</L>
<L>Of rihtfulnesse [&amp;] tru&thorn;e entere,</L>
<L>And calueren after &thorn;i precepte</L>
<L N="156">&THORN;ei schul beo leyd on &thorn;in Autere.</L>
<L>On Caluarie a calf &thorn;er crepte,</L>
<L>Crist on Cros, bo&thorn;e clene and clere.</L>
<L>ffor teres &thorn;at his Modur wepte,</L>
<L N="160">He schylde vs alle from helle fere!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>III. her biginne&thorn; an orisun of &thorn;e trinite.</HEAD>
<P>The same in northern dialect in MS. Thornton, ed. by Perry, <I>Religious Pieces in Prose and Verse</I>, E. E. T. S. 1867, No. 6, p. 75 ff.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FAdur and Sone and Holigost,</L>
<L>Lord, to &thorn;e I crie and calle,</L>
<L>Studefast god of mihtes most,</L>
<L N="4">My sunful lyf is steken in stalle:</L>
<L>I preye &thorn;e, lord, &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. me</NOTE> haste</L>
<L>Me to helpe, &thorn;at I ne falle,</L>
<L>And mak my soule clene and chaste</L>
<L N="8">Of dedly sunnes and vueles alle.
<PB REF="00000025.tif" N="17"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lord, haue Merci of my synne,</L>
<L>And bring me out of al my care;</L>
<L>Euele to do wol I nou<NOTE PLACE="marg">P T couthe neuer</NOTE> blynne,</L>
<L N="12">I haue I-wrouht a&yogh;eynes &thorn;i lawe<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. lare</NOTE>:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou rewe of me [bo&thorn;e] out and Inne,</L>
<L>And hele me of my woundes sare;</L>
<L>Lord, &thorn;at al &thorn;is world schal winne,</L>
<L N="16">Hele me ar i fonde and fare.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FAdur in heuene &thorn;at wel<NOTE PLACE="marg">P all</NOTE> may,</L>
<L>I preye &thorn;e, lord, &thorn;at &thorn;ou me lede</L>
<L>In rihte weyes of stable fay;</L>
<L N="20">At myn endynge whon I haue drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;i grace ich aske [bo&thorn;e] niht and day,</L>
<L>And &yogh;if me merci of my misdede.</L>
<L>Of myn askyng sei not nay,</L>
<L N="24">But help me, lord, at al my nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, for me was boren,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou here my preyere loud and stille,</L>
<L>ffor pyne &thorn;at me is leid bi-foren</L>
<L N="28">Ofte i sike and wepe my fille.</L>
<L>Ofte so haue I ben for-sworen</L>
<L>Whon I haue don a&yogh;eynes &thorn;i wille,</L>
<L>Suffre neuere &thorn;at I beo loren,</L>
<L N="32">Lord, for myne dedes ille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E holygost, i preye to &thorn;e</L>
<L>Niht and day in good entent,</L>
<L>Of al my serwe cumforte me,</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;in holi grace &thorn;ou me sent,<NOTE PLACE="marg">P be to me sent</NOTE></L>
<L>And schild me, &yogh;if &thorn;i wille be,</L>
<L>ffrom dedly sunne, &thorn;at I ne beo schent,</L>
<L>ffor Marie loue, &thorn;at Maiden fre,</L>
<L N="40">In whom &thorn;ou lihtest, verreyment.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I preye &thorn;e, ladi Meoke and mylde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou preye for my misdede,</L>
<L>ffor [&thorn;e] loue of &thorn;i swete childe,</L>
<L N="44">As &thorn;ou him sauh on Rode blede.</L>
<L>Euer&yogh;ite haue I ben wylde,</L>
<L>Mi sunfol soule is euere in drede:</L>
<L>Merci ladi, &thorn;ou me schilde,</L>
<L N="48">And helpe me euere at al myn nede.
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="18"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Merci, Marie, Mayden clene!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou let me neuere In sunne dwelle,</L>
<L>Preye for me &thorn;at hit beo sene,</L>
<L N="52">And schild me from &thorn;e pyne of helle.</L>
<L>ffor certes, ladi, riht wel i wene</L>
<L>&THORN;at al my fomen mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou felle.</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i my serwe to &thorn;e I mene,</L>
<L N="56">Wi&thorn; ferful mod my tale i telle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>BI-&thorn;enk &thorn;e, ladi, euere and ay</L>
<L>Of alle wimmen &thorn;ou berest &thorn;e flour;</L>
<L>ffor sunfol mon, as I &thorn;e say,</L>
<L N="60">God ha&thorn; don &thorn;e gret honour.</L>
<L>Receyue my preyere niht and day,</L>
<L>Whon I &thorn;e be-seche in eny a Our;</L>
<L>Help me, ladi, so wel &thorn;ou may,</L>
<L N="64">Me bi-houe&thorn; &thorn;ou beo my counseilour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Off counseil, ladi, i preye to &thorn;e</L>
<L>Niht and day, in wele and wo;</L>
<L>Of al my serwe cumforte me,</L>
<L N="68">And beo my scheld a&yogh;eynes my fo.</L>
<L>ffor, certes, &yogh;if &thorn;i wille hit be,</L>
<L>Al my fo-men mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou slo.</L>
<L>Help me, ladi hende and fre,</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;ou take &thorn;at &thorn;e is fallen fro.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At myn endynge &thorn;ou stonde bi me</L>
<L>Whon I schal henne fonden and fare,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at I quake and dredful be,</L>
<L N="76">And al my sunnus I rewe hem sare.</L>
<L>As euere myn hope ha&thorn; ben in &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;enk &thorn;eron, ladi, and help me &thorn;are,</L>
<L>ffor [&thorn;e] loue of &thorn;at swete tre</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at Ihesu spradde [on] his bodi bare.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, for &thorn;at ille<NOTE PLACE="marg">P ilke harde</NOTE> stounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou woldest on Rode blede,</L>
<L>At myn endynge whon I schal founde</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;ou haue merci of my misdede,</L>
<L>And hele me of my dedlich wounde,</L>
<L>And help me in &thorn;at muchele nede;</L>
<L>Whon de&thorn; me take&thorn; and bringe&thorn; me<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. me</NOTE> to grounde,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;en schal i, lord, &thorn;i domes drede.
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="19"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOrd, for my sunnes to do penaunce,</L>
<L>ffor my dedes<NOTE PLACE="marg">P Be-fore my dede</NOTE> &thorn;ou graunte hit me</L>
<L>A<NOTE PLACE="marg">P And</NOTE> space of verrey Repentaunce</L>
<L N="92">In serwe of herte, I preye to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>In &thorn;i merci is myn affyaunce;</L>
<L>Of my folye &thorn;ou haue pite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou of me ne take veniaunce,</L>
<L N="96">Lord, for &thorn;i benignite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOrd, as &thorn;ow art ful of miht</L>
<L>And as &thorn;ou alle &thorn;inges wost,</L>
<L>My lyf amende, my dedes riht,</L>
<L N="100"><NOTE PLACE="marg">This verse added on the margin.</NOTE>ffor mari loue &thorn;at maiden chost,<NOTE PLACE="marg">P chaste</NOTE></L>
<L>And bringe me sone in to &thorn;at liht</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen ende &thorn;er ioye is most,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e to seo &thorn;at swete siht,</L>
<L N="104">ffadur and Sone and Holigost. AMEN.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>IV. A confessioun to Jhesu crist.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu crist, to &thorn;e</L>
<L>A gulti wrecche Ich &yogh;elde me</L>
<L>ffor sunnes &thorn;at ichaue ido</L>
<L N="4">In al my lyf hider-to.</L>
<L>In Pruide, in Envye, In lecherye,</L>
<L>In Sleu&thorn;e, In Wra&thorn;&thorn;e, In Glotenye,</L>
<L>In al &thorn;is worldus Couetyse,</L>
<L N="8">Ichaue isunged In alle &thorn;yse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I-broken Ichaue &thorn;i Comaundemens</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes myn owne Conciens,</L>
<L>And not iserued &thorn;e to queme:</L>
<L N="12">Lord Merci, ar &thorn;e dom is deme.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO ofte ichaue in my lyue</L>
<L>Isunged in my wittes fyue,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Eres I-herd, wi&thorn; Ei&yogh;en siht,</L>
<L N="16">Wi&thorn; sunful speche day and niht,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Honden I-hondlet, wi&thorn; feet I-go,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Neose i-smullet eft also,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; herte sunfulliche i-&thorn;ouht,</L>
<L N="20">Wi&thorn; al my bodi vuel I-wrouht:
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>And of alle my folye</L>
<L>Merci, lord Ihesu, Ich crye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al-&thorn;auh ichaue i-sunged euere,</L>
<L N="24">Lord, i ne forsok &thorn;e neuere,</L>
<L>Ne o&thorn;ur god ne tok i none,</L>
<L>ffadur of heuene, but &thorn;e one.</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore, lord, i &thorn;e biseche</L>
<L N="28">Wi&thorn; rihtful hertliche speche,</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;if &thorn;ou me none mede</L>
<L>Aftur my sunfule dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But aftur, lord, &thorn;i grete pite</L>
<L N="32">Ihesu lord, asoyle &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L>And send me ofte, ar I dye,</L>
<L>Serwe in herte, and ter in ei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>ffor sunnes &thorn;at ichaue i-do</L>
<L N="36">In al my lyf hider-to.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And let me neuere eft biginne</L>
<L>To do no more dedly synne,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at I at myn endyng-day</L>
<L N="40">Clene of synne dye may,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Schrift and Hosul at myn ende;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at my soule mowe wende</L>
<L>In to &thorn;at blisful Empyre</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;er &thorn;at &thorn;ou regnest lord and sire.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete ladi seinte Marie,</L>
<L>fful of Alle Curtesie,</L>
<L>Modur of Merci and of pite,</L>
<L N="48">Myn hope, myn help is al in &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Wel ich wot, ibore &thorn;ou were</L>
<L>In help of al vs wrecches here;</L>
<L>And wel ich wot &thorn;at alle &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;i sone wol don at &thorn;i biddyng.</L>
<L>Bi-sech &thorn;i sone lef and dere</L>
<L>ffor me synful wrecche here;</L>
<L>Bi-seche him, for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;at he haue merci of me;</L>
<L>And help me at myn ende-day</L>
<L>ffrom &thorn;e foule fendes affray.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>BI-seche also &thorn;e flour of alle,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;i sone, for my frendes alle,
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="21"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he hem kepe wi&thorn; his grace</L>
<L>ffrom alle perels in vche place,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ef hem god lyf and god ende,</L>
<L N="64">And Ioye whon &thorn;ei schul he&thorn;ene wende;</L>
<L>And also alle cristene men.</L>
<L N="66">God lord Ihesus, Amen AMEN.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seint Michel and seint Gabriel</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e Angeles<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Angls</NOTE> also wel,</L>
<L>Preye&thorn; for me to vre ladi,</L>
<L N="70">&THORN;at Ihesus of me haue merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HOli Patriarkes and prophetes,</L>
<L>Alle i preye ow and bi-seches:</L>
<L>Preye&thorn; for me to vre ladi,</L>
<L N="74">&THORN;at Ihesus of me haue merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>PEter and Poul, &thorn;e Apostles alle,</L>
<L>Alle i beo-seche ou &yogh;erne and calle:</L>
<L>Preye&thorn; for me to vre ladi,</L>
<L N="78">&THORN;at Ihesus of me haue merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Steuene and seint Laurens</L>
<L>And alle gode Martires &thorn;at &thorn;oleden turmens,</L>
<L>Preye&thorn; for me to vre ladi,</L>
<L N="82">&THORN;at Ihesus of me haue Merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Martin and seint Nicholas</L>
<L>And alle gode confessours &thorn;at euer was,</L>
<L>Preye&thorn; for me to vre ladi,</L>
<L N="86">&THORN;at Ihesus of me haue merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seinte Katerine and seinte Mergrete</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e virgines gode and swete,</L>
<L>Preye&thorn; for me to vre ladi,</L>
<L N="90">&THORN;at Ihesus of me haue merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seinte Marie Maudeleyne,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e I pre&yogh;e and eke pleyne:</L>
<L>Preye&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Prey</NOTE> for me to vre ladi,</L>
<L N="94">&THORN;at Ihesus of me haue merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle Halewen &thorn;at euere were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at beo&thorn; crist lef and dere,</L>
<L>Preye&thorn; for me to vre ladi,</L>
<L N="98">&THORN;at Ihesus of me haue merci.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000030.tif" N="22">
<HEAD>V. A prayer to &thorn;e fiue woundes.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu crist, my lemmon swete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at di&yogh;edest on &thorn;e Rode-tre,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al my miht i &thorn;e be-seche,</L>
<L N="4">ffor &thorn;i woundes two and &thorn;re,</L>
<L>&THORN;at also faste mot &thorn;i loue</L>
<L>In to myn herte ficched be</L>
<L>As was &thorn;e spere in to &thorn;in herte</L>
<L N="8">Whon &thorn;ou soffredest de&thorn; for me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesus &thorn;at di&yogh;edest on &thorn;e Rode</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e loue of me</L>
<L>And bouhtest me wi&thorn; &thorn;i blode,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;ou haue Merci of me:</L>
<L>What me lette&thorn; of eny &thorn;ing</L>
<L>ffor to loue &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Beo hit me lef beo hit me lo&thorn;,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;ow do hit a-wey from me, AMEN.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>VI. A preiere to vre ladi.</HEAD>
<P>A similar poem in short verse, from a MS. of the 15th cent., see in Wright, <I>Rel. Ant.</I> II. 212. In the MS. the poem is written in half-lines; the colons (:) were added by me.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MArie Modur and Mayden : Euere wel &thorn;e be!</L>
<L>Modur and Mayden mylde : Marie, &thorn;enk on me!</L>
<L>Modur bo&thorn;e and Mayden : Was &thorn;er neuere non</L>
<L N="4">To-gedere, ladi Marie : But &thorn;i-self al-on.</L>
<L>&para; Marie Mylde, &thorn;at Modur art : And mayden hol and clene,</L>
<L>To-day me schilde and euere : ffrom serwe and herte-tene;</L>
<L>Marie, out of synne : Euere kep &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L N="8">And from &thorn;e deueles cumbrement : And out of his pouste.</L>
<L>&para; Marie ful of Merci : ffor &thorn;i Ioyes fyue</L>
<L>Help me now and euere : To lyuen in clene lyue;</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e deo[l]ful<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. deoful</NOTE> teres : &THORN;ou lettest vndur &thorn;e Rode,</L>
<L>Send me in my lyue : Grace of gostly fode,</L>
<L N="13">Wher-wi&thorn; I may my soule : Vche day her feden;</L>
<L>And of bodily godus : Mi lyf also wi&thorn; leden.
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="23"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HElp me, swete ladi : And alle frendes myne,</L>
<L N="16">And schild us here from alle vr fos : And from helle-pyne;</L>
<L>Swete ladi of heuene : Schild us from worldus schame,</L>
<L>And from &thorn;e deueles wyles : And from wikkede fame,</L>
<L>Nomeliche from dedly sunne : And from vilenye,</L>
<L N="20">And from alle-maner folk : Of wikked Cumpaignye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete ladi Maiden : Godus Moder Milde,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes &thorn;e fendus turnes : &THORN;ou vs euere schylde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no wikkede &thorn;ing : Neuere vs do dere;</L>
<L N="24">ffrom sunne, ladi, euere : &thorn;ou saue vs and were.</L>
<L>&para; In alle tymes, ladi : Bo&thorn;e day and niht</L>
<L>Help us, seinte Marie : Wi&thorn; al &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. my</NOTE> meyn and miht.</L>
<L>I preye &thorn;e for my frendes : And eke also for me,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;at we moten here : Amendet beo &thorn;orw &thorn;e;</L>
<L>As mest vr soule is nedful : And also to vr lyue,</L>
<L>Marie, mak hit so : Wi&thorn; us, for &thorn;i Ioyes fyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LAdi, for myn Enemys : I preye &thorn;e also,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at heo in &thorn;is lyue : Moten her do so</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo neuer in synne : Ne in wra&thorn;&thorn;e dye;</L>
<L>Swete ladi Marie : Herteliche I &thorn;e preye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for alle &thorn;ulke : &THORN;at ben in clene lyue</L>
<L N="36">I preye &thorn;e, Marie : ffor &thorn;i serwes fyue;</L>
<L>Euere whil heore lyf laste : &THORN;er-Inne &thorn;ou hem holde,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e whil &thorn;ei ben &yogh;onge : And eke whil &thorn;ei ben olde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FOr alle &thorn;o, ladi, i preye &thorn;e : &THORN;at ben in dedly synne;</L>
<L N="40">Suffre hem neuere for no &thorn;ing : &THORN;at &thorn;ei dye &thorn;er|Inne;</L>
<L>Swete ladi Marie : Heom wisse euere and rede,</L>
<L>And do hem amenden, ar &thorn;ei dyen : heere heore misdede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MArie, for &thorn;i Ioyes : &THORN;at blisful weren alle,</L>
<L N="44">Let me neuere here : In dedly sunne falle;</L>
<L>Preye &thorn;ou &thorn;i deore sone : Ihesu heuene-kyng,</L>
<L>He graunte me so&thorn;fast schrifte : Hosel and god endyng,</L>
<L>And for his precious blod : And his holy grace</L>
<L N="48">In heuene-riche wi&thorn; him-self : &THORN;at I mowe hauen a place.
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="24"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MArie, as my trust : Enterliche is in &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="50">ffor &thorn;i leoue sones loue : &THORN;eos preyers graunt &thorn;ou me;</L>
<L>And beo myn help studefast : To gete me &thorn;at blisse</L>
<L>&THORN;at euermore schal lasten : Wi&thorn;-outen eny misse AMEN.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>VII. A preyer at &thorn;e leuacioun.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Title in the Index: Sixe salutacions to &thorn;e trinite in tyme of &thorn;e eleuacioun of godis body.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WElcome, Lord, In fourme of Bred!</L>
<L>In &thorn;e is bo&thorn;e lyf and Ded,</L>
<L N="3">Ihesus is &thorn;i nome.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;at art In Trinite,</L>
<L>Lord, &thorn;ow haue Merci of me</L>
<L N="6">And schild &thorn;ou me from schome.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Ihesu, godus sone,</L>
<L>Holigost from heuene i-come,</L>
<L N="9">Kyng &thorn;ou art i-Coren;</L>
<L>Heil mon of most miht,</L>
<L>Godus sone &thorn;at art so briht,</L>
<L N="12">Of Marie &thorn;ou were boren.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil god, best &thorn;e be,</L>
<L>heil Blosme vppon tre,</L>
<L N="15">Heried beo &thorn;i sonde!</L>
<L>Heil fruit, heil flour,</L>
<L>Heil be &thorn;ou Saueour</L>
<L N="18">Of watur and of londe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil kyng, heil kniht,</L>
<L>heil mon of most miht,</L>
<L N="21">Prince in &thorn;i Trone,</L>
<L>Heil Duyk, heil Emperour,</L>
<L>Heil beo &thorn;ou gouernour</L>
<L N="24">Of al &thorn;is worldus wone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil flesch, heil blod,</L>
<L>heil mon of mylde mod,</L>
<L N="27">Heil beo &thorn;ow kyng;</L>
<L>Heil God ffeirest,</L>
<L>Heil beo &thorn;ou, bern best,</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;ow madest alle &thorn;yng.
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="25"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Rose vppon Rys,</L>
<L>heil mon of most pris,</L>
<L N="33">ffor us &thorn;ou were ded;</L>
<L>Heil God ful of miht,</L>
<L>Godus sone &thorn;at art so briht,</L>
<L N="36">In fourme &thorn;ou art of bred.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="8" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>VIII. A preyer at &thorn;e leuacioun.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Title in the Index: An orysoun to godes body at &thorn;e leuacioun.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>I</B> &thorn;e honoure wi&thorn; al my miht</L>
<L>In fourme of Bred as i &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>Lord, &thorn;at in &thorn;at ladi briht,</L>
<L N="4">In Marie Mon bi-come for me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;I fflesch, &thorn;i blod is swete of siht,</L>
<L>&THORN;i Sacrament honoured to be,</L>
<L>Of Bred and Wyn wi&thorn; word i-diht;</L>
<L N="8">Almihti lord, I leeue in &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>I</B> Am sunful, as &thorn;ou wel wost:</L>
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;ou haue merci of me;</L>
<L>Soffre &thorn;ou neuere &thorn;at I be lost</L>
<L N="12">ffor whom &thorn;ou di&yogh;edest vppon &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;orwh &thorn;at ladi of Merci most</L>
<L>Mi soule &thorn;ou bringe in blisse to &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Repentaunce to-fore mi de&thorn;,</L>
<L N="16">Schrif[t] and Hosul &thorn;ou graunte me,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ffadur and Sone and Holygost,</L>
<L N="18">&THORN;at Regne&thorn; God In Trinite. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="9" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>IX. &THORN;e fyue Joyes of vr ladi.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HAue Ioye, Marie, Modur and Maide,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e Angel Gabriel Message to &thorn;e saide</L>
<L N="3">And brouhte &thorn;e ti&thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;at crist wolde in &thorn;e aliht.</L>
<L>Help us, ladi, &thorn;orw &thorn;i miht</L>
<L N="6">To habben his blessyng.
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="26"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HAue Ioye, Marie, for &thorn;ou were</L>
<L>Glad of Ihesu &thorn;o &thorn;ou him bere,</L>
<L N="9">And<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. al?</NOTE> wi&thorn;-outen pyning;</L>
<L>fful &thorn;ou weore of Godus grace.</L>
<L>Help me, Ladi, to seo &thorn;i face,</L>
<L N="12">ffeirest of alle &thorn;yng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HAue Ioye, Marie, feole si&thorn;e,</L>
<L>ffor Ihesus a-Ros from de&thorn; to lyue</L>
<L N="15">In a morwenyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde day &thorn;at he was ded.</L>
<L>Ladi, schild us from &thorn;e qued</L>
<L N="18">And from his wikked tysyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HAue Ioye, Marie, for &thorn;ou se&yogh;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at Ihesu crist to heuene stei&yogh;e</L>
<L N="21">In to his woni&yogh;ing,</L>
<L>And euere &thorn;ou se&yogh;e him at &thorn;i wille.</L>
<L>Help us, ladi, &thorn;at we ne spille,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;orw&yogh; &thorn;i beo-seching.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HAue Ioye, Marie, &thorn;ow were vp fet</L>
<L>And bi Ihesu crist I-set</L>
<L N="27">&THORN;er &thorn;at he is kyng;</L>
<L>Qween he made &thorn;e wi&thorn; Croune.</L>
<L>Help us, ladi, &thorn;orwh &thorn;i bone,</L>
<L N="30">And to blisse us bring. Amen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffadur and sone and holigost,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at is and nis &thorn;ow wost,</L>
<L N="33">And art wi&thorn;-oute bigining:</L>
<L>Lord, for &thorn;i Modur loue</L>
<L>Graunt vs &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at is aboue,</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;at neuer ha&thorn; endyng. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="10" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>X. An orisoun to god.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Title in the Index: An orysoun to god &thorn;e fadur.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOrd, my God al Merciable,</L>
<L>I &thorn;e bi-seche wi&thorn; herte stable</L>
<L>&THORN;at I mouwe euere wilne &thorn;at &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;at most may beo to &thorn;y lykyng,
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>And wysliche folewen euere &thorn;i wille,</L>
<L>Sikerliche knowen and folfulle</L>
<L>&THORN;e louereden of &thorn;i nome and blis,</L>
<L N="8">Mi stat ordeynen as &thorn;i wille is.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;in askyng and &thorn;i wille</L>
<L>Euere do me, lord, folfille;</L>
<L>As me may most in soule nede</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;i wissynge help to spede.</L>
<L>Mi wei to &thorn;e beo siker and riht,</L>
<L>And harde i-fastnet wi&thorn; &thorn;i miht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I in weole &thorn;e &thorn;onke so</L>
<L N="16">And euere beo pacient in wo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I ne falle neuer mo</L>
<L>In nou&thorn;ur of hem bo&thorn;e two;</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;at I neuere glad ne be</L>
<L N="20">But in &thorn;ing &thorn;at lyke&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ne serwe neuere bote for &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;at torne &thorn;e to mis-lykyng,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;at I neuere desire to plesen</L>
<L N="24">No mon falsliche ne displesen</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;e, deore lord, al-one,</L>
<L>ffor no drede of monnes mone.</L>
<L>&para; Al er&thorn;liche &thorn;ing beo vyl to me,</L>
<L N="28">Lord, for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;yne be</L>
<L>Leof and deore mak hem me,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou al-one, Almihti kyng,</L>
<L N="32">Out and ouer al o&thorn;ur &thorn;yng</L>
<L>Euer beo most in my lykyng,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; me derwor&thorn;est ouer alle &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>&para; Alle Ioyes beo nuyous to me</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;at ben, lord, wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;e.</L>
<L>In alle trauayles &thorn;at ben for &thorn;e</L>
<L>Euer-more al my lykyng be.</L>
<L>Restes alle &thorn;at ne ben in &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="40">Anuy and trauayle beo &thorn;ei to me.</L>
<L>Euere myn herte to &thorn;e &thorn;ou dresse,</L>
<L>Mi sunne to clanse wi&thorn; serefulnesse.</L>
<L>Boxum me make wi&thorn;-oute feyning,</L>
<L N="44">And glad wi&thorn;-outen ryotyng,
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="28"></L>
<L>Serwhful wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;at lu&thorn;er last</L>
<L>To maken of my-self out-cast,</L>
<L>Meur wi&thorn;-outen greuoushed,</L>
<L N="48">And Murie wi&thorn;-outen wyldehed,</L>
<L>So&thorn; wi&thorn;-outen falshed</L>
<L>Or eny o&thorn;ur doublehed</L>
<L>Of fikel word wi&thorn; double entente</L>
<L N="52">To bleenden &thorn;at &thorn;e sawe mente;</L>
<L>Dredful wi&thorn;-outen wonhope,</L>
<L>And trust wi&thorn;-outen ouer-hope;</L>
<L>Min euencristne to vndurnyme so</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;at &thorn;er ne beo no feynyng to,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn;-outen eny pruyde</L>
<L>Hem to edefyen in alle tyde,</L>
<L>In word, ensaumple, and in dede,</L>
<L N="60">To alle gode from alle quede;</L>
<L>Vmble wi&thorn;-outen &yogh;ein-siggyng,</L>
<L>Suffraunt wi&thorn;-outen grucchyng.</L>
<L>Waker herte &yogh;if &thorn;ou me</L>
<L N="64">Euere, lord, a-bouten &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer non o&thorn;ur curiousete</L>
<L>Ne led my herte fromward &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if me herte so noble and fre</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;at no fals loue hit drawe fro &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if me herte &thorn;at neuermore fayle,</L>
<L>Ne bi<NOTE PLACE="marg">= be</NOTE> conqueret in no trauayle.</L>
<L>&para; ffreo herte, lord, &yogh;if me wi&thorn; wynne,</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at vuel delyt naue kalange Inne.</L>
<L>&para; Rihtful herte &yogh;if me also</L>
<L>&THORN;at no wrong wit ne enclyne to.</L>
<L>&para; Lord, ffadur of alle Merci,</L>
<L N="76">I &thorn;e bi-seche hertely</L>
<L>Cunnynge, &thorn;e to knowe ariht</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bisi sechinge day and niht,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. wit?</NOTE> &thorn;at I kunne fynde,</L>
<L N="80">Mi &thorn;ewes in &thorn;i lykyng bynde;</L>
<L>Perseueraunce &thorn;e to abyde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if me, lord, in vche a tyde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hope trewe and studefast,</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at &thorn;e, lord, ay bi-cluppe fast;<NOTE PLACE="marg">some vv. wanting?</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="29"></L>
<L>&THORN;orwh penaunce &thorn;at I mowe do</L>
<L>&THORN;i pyneful [l]yf<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. pynefulyf</NOTE> mowe lykne to;</L>
<L>&para; And whil me laste&thorn; lyues space,</L>
<L N="88">Gode werkes vsen &thorn;orwh &thorn;i grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;yne Ioyes vsen and wi&thorn; &thorn;e wone</L>
<L N="90">In &thorn;i glorie, wi&thorn; ffadur and sone. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="11" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>XI. An orisoun to vr lord Jhesu.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Title in the Index: An orysoun to god &thorn;e sone. In the MS. the poem is written in half-lines.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOrd, Swete Ihesu crist : Haue Merci of me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at out of heuene come : In to eor&thorn;e for me,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e Mayden Marie : Boren were for me,</L>
<L N="4">And on &thorn;e cros suffredest : Bitter de&thorn; for me.</L>
<L>Of Merci I &thorn;e bi-seche : &THORN;at mest of mihtes may,</L>
<L>Swete Ihesu my cumfort : Mi solas and my play;</L>
<L N="7">Of alle vices me deliuere : And of pruide, I &thorn;e pray,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I may &thorn;e louen as lord : And knowen for God verray.</L>
<L>fful muchel ouhte i &thorn;e to louen : In stable treu&thorn;e and fay,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou were god and art : And schalt ben euere and ay,</L>
<L>Com in to eor&thorn;e for my loue : To take my kuynde of clay,</L>
<L N="12">In &thorn;e world to wynne<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. wynnes</NOTE> vs wele : &THORN;ou suffredest men worchen &thorn;e way.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e world, as I seide er : In bodi, fflesch and Bon,</L>
<L>Hunger and ffurst heddestou bo&thorn;e : In hot and Cold to gon,</L>
<L>Blod and watur &thorn;ou swattest bo&thorn;e : And Teres Mony on,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;hen for &thorn;e loue of vs : &THORN;i de&thorn; &thorn;en hastou tan.</L>
<L N="17">fful hard and deolful was &thorn;i de&thorn; : Hose hedde hit in &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at &thorn;i blessede bodi : &THORN;at neuere no sunne wrouht,</L>
<L>Among &thorn;is false Iewes : &THORN;i-seluen hast hit brouht,</L>
<L N="20">And se&thorn;&thorn;en wi&thorn; &thorn;i blessed blod : ffrom bale &thorn;ou hast us bouht.
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="30"></L>
<L>A Croune of &thorn;ornes vppon &thorn;in hed : &THORN;ei setten scharp and fresch,</L>
<L>Heo &thorn;e nayleden hondes and feet : Bo&thorn;e &thorn;orwh bon and flesch;</L>
<L>A spere &thorn;orwh &thorn;i syde stong : &THORN;yn herte was ful nesch,</L>
<L N="24">Whon &thorn;e blod and watur sprong : &THORN;at vs of synne wesch.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, Ihesu, I preye &thorn;e : &THORN;at ful art of pite,</L>
<L>ffor my sunnes &thorn;at ichaue don : Let me neuere dampned be;</L>
<L>But graunte me grace in to myn herte : Ihesu in Trinite,</L>
<L>Of stable treu&thorn;e and rihtwys werkes : Loue and Charite.</L>
<L N="29">fful ofte ichaue &thorn;e wra&thorn;&thorn;ed : And broke &thorn;i Comaunde|ment,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al my fyue wittes : In lyf &thorn;at &thorn;ou me hast lent,</L>
<L>Vnwisliche hem dispendet : And not in good entent,</L>
<L N="32">Bo&thorn;e &thorn;orwh myn owne wille : And o&thorn;ure entisement.</L>
<L>Bote, swete Ihesu, woltou me here : wi&thorn; schrift ichaue &thorn;e souht:</L>
<L>In mony werkes, as I seide ere : Vuele ichaue I|wrouht,</L>
<L>Non of hem schal ben vnpunissched&mdash; : &THORN;eron is al my &thorn;ouht;</L>
<L N="36">I take me al to &thorn;i Merci : ffor loue for-&yogh;et me nouht.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Mylde mod and sikyng sore : I be-seche &thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor my ffrendes, Ihesu crist : As wel as for me.</L>
<L>On domes-dai whon &thorn;ou schalt demen : Scheuh us &thorn;i face freo,</L>
<L N="40">And bring vs in to paradys : &THORN;er endeles blisse schal beo. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="12" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[XII. An orison to vr lady.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">So the title in the Index. In the MS. the poem is written in half-lines.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HEil beo &thorn;ou, Marie: Mylde qwen of heuene!</L>
<L>Blessed is &thorn;i Nome : And good hit is to nemene.<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. neuene</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e i Make my mone : I prey &thorn;e, here my steuene,</L>
<L N="4">And let me neuere dye : In non of &thorn;e sunnes seuene.
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="31"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LAdi seinte Marie : Qween Corteis and hende!</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at &thorn;ou were Inne : Whon god his Angel dude sende,</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at &thorn;e holygost : Schulde in &thorn;i bodi lende,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;ou bringe me to &thorn;at blisse : &THORN;at is wi&thorn;-outen ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ioyful was &thorn;in herte, ladi : &mdash;&THORN;erof haue I no drede&mdash;</L>
<L>Whon Ihesu crist was boren of &thorn;e : ffeirest of alle &thorn;ede,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou were Maiden biforn : And aftur, as we rede.</L>
<L N="12">Marie, for &thorn;e loue of him : Help us at al vr nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete ladi, &thorn;ou rewe on me : And mak myn herte clene,</L>
<L>Bring us out of sunne : &THORN;at do&thorn; us traye and tene;</L>
<L>Wo hit vs byginne&thorn; : In werkes as we han sene;</L>
<L N="16">Schild us from &thorn;e peynes : &THORN;er non may o&thorn;ur mene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LAdi ful of grace : Ioyful was &thorn;i chere</L>
<L>Whon Ihesu crist from de&thorn; vp ros : &THORN;at was &thorn;e lef and dere.</L>
<L>Marie, for &thorn;e loue of him : &THORN;at lay &thorn;yn herte so nere,</L>
<L N="20">Bring us out of synne and serwe : While &thorn;at we aren here.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LAdi ful of muche miht : &THORN;at mylde art of mod!</L>
<L>ffor his woundes fyue : &THORN;at Ronnen alle on blood,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e loue of swete Ihesu : &THORN;at dyede on &thorn;e Rod,</L>
<L N="24">Get me heuene blisse : Ladi feir and god.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LAdi seinte Marie : Corteis, feir &amp; swete!</L>
<L>ffor loue of &thorn;e teres : &THORN;at for &thorn;i sone &thorn;ou lete</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou se&yogh;e him hongen : Nayled honden and fete,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;ou sende me grace in eor&thorn;e : Mi sunnes forte bete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN counseil art &thorn;ou best : And trewest in eueri nede,</L>
<L>To sunfol men ful prest : In saumple of good dede :</L>
<L N="31">ffor loue of &thorn;i deore sone : &THORN;ou se&yogh;e on Rode blede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou help us nou and euere : And schild us from mis-dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LAdi seinte Marie : So Rose in Erber rede,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e i crie and calle : To &thorn;e I make my beode:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou help me at myn ende : Whon I drawe to &thorn;e dede,</L>
<L N="36">And let me neuer falle : In bondes of &thorn;e quede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LAdi, for &thorn;e ioye : &THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;i-self were Inne</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou se&yogh;e Ihesu crist : fflour of al mon|kinne,
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="32"></L>
<L N="39">Steih in to his riche : &THORN;er Ioye schal neuer blynne,</L>
<L>Of Bale &thorn;ou beo my bote : And bring me out of synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LAdi, for &thorn;at Ioye : &THORN;at &thorn;ou to crist weore tan</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e blisse of heuene : Wi&thorn; Aungeles moni an,</L>
<L>And set bi swete Ihesu crist : In ffel, in flesch and bon,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;ou bringe me to &thorn;at blisse : &THORN;at neuer schal beo gon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LAdi ful of grace : &THORN;at hei&yogh;e sittest in trone,</L>
<L>Loue of alle blisse : Send &thorn;ou me my bone :</L>
<L>Ihesus to louen and drede : My lyf to amenden sone,</L>
<L N="48">And comen to him &thorn;at hende : &THORN;at welde&thorn; Sonne and Mone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FOr &thorn;i Ioyes fyue : Ladi feir and briht,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;i clene Maidenhod : And for &thorn;i muchele miht,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &yogh;if me miht and grace : To come to &thorn;at liht,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;er Ioye is euere newe : And day wi&thorn;-outen niht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LAdi seinte Marie : &YOGH;if &thorn;i wille ware,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou art ful of Ioye : And I am ful of care,</L>
<L>Schild me from synne and schome : &THORN;at I falle no mare,</L>
<L N="56">And send me hosul and schrift : Ar I he&thorn;ene fare.</L>
<TRAILER>A. M. E. N.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="13" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[XIII. A confessioun of wyrschip in orysoun.<NOTE PLACE="foot">So the title in the Index.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God &thorn;at al hast mad of nouht,</L>
<L>ffor loue of mon &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast bouht;</L>
<L>Wher in &thorn;e world so &thorn;at i be,</L>
<L N="4">Wi&thorn; al myn herte I &thorn;onke &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at &thorn;ou me madest on of &thorn;yne,</L>
<L>And bouhtest me wi&thorn; bitter pyne.</L>
<L>I &thorn;onke &thorn;e, lord, wi&thorn; good entent</L>
<L N="8">Of wit and grace &thorn;ou hast me sent.</L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; al myn herte and mylde moode</L>
<L>I &thorn;onke &thorn;e, lord, of alle gode.</L>
<L>I preye &thorn;e, lord, &thorn;ou graunte me miht</L>
<L N="12">Wi&thorn; al myn herte to loue &thorn;e riht.</L>
<L>&para; I preye &thorn;e, lord, out and Inne</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou me schilde from dedly synne;</L>
<L>I preye &thorn;e, lord, &thorn;at &thorn;ou me wisse</L>
<L N="16">And bring me to &thorn;i muchele blisse. Amen.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="14" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000041.tif" N="33">
<HEAD>[XIV.] [Another Prayer to the Virgin Mary.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MArie Modur, Qwen of heuene,</L>
<L>&THORN;enk on me and here my steuene!</L>
<L>Marie Meke and Mylde of mood,</L>
<L N="4">ffor loue of &thorn;at holy Rood,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. blood? orig. 2 vv. om.?</NOTE> . . . . .</L>
<L>Marie, &thorn;at &thorn;ou se&yogh;e on Rode</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou bi &thorn;i sone stode,</L>
<L>Marie, &thorn;at Ran out of his syde</L>
<L N="8">fforte falle &thorn;e fendes pryde,</L>
<L>Marie, &yogh;if me knowynge of my synne,</L>
<L>And let me neuere die &thorn;er-Inne;</L>
<L>Marie, schild me from vueles alle,</L>
<L N="12">And let me neuere in fondynge falle.</L>
<L>Marie, prei for me &thorn;i sone</L>
<L>&THORN;at myn herte euere on him mone,</L>
<L>Marie, to louen him ouer alle &thorn;yng</L>
<L N="16">Wi&thorn; herte trewe to myn endyng.</L>
<L>Marie, i preye &thorn;e Meke and Mylde,</L>
<L>ffor loue of &thorn;i swete childe,</L>
<L>Marie, my scheld beo a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e fende</L>
<L N="20">Whon I schal out of &thorn;is world wende.</L>
<L>Marie, of myn ende is al my drede,</L>
<L>Of my sunnes and of my misdede:</L>
<L>Marie, for&thorn;i &thorn;ou rewe on me,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at I &thorn;orwh &thorn;e may I-saued be.</L>
<L>Marie, Mi ffrendes, quike and dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hem wisse and &thorn;ou hem rede,</L>
<L>Marie, In to &thorn;at holy blis</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;er Ihesu crist him-seluen is.</L>
<L>Marie, at my de&thorn; whon I schal fare</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world, droupe and dare,</L>
<L>Marie, help me &thorn;enne as on of &thorn;yne,</L>
<L N="32">And bring me out of serwe and pyne,</L>
<L>Marie, in to blisse, wi&thorn; &thorn;e to wone,</L>
<L>ffor Ihesu loue, &thorn;i deore sone. AMEN.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="15" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000042.tif" N="34">
<HEAD>[XV. Prayer for the Seven Gifts of the Holy Ghost.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GOd &thorn;at art of mihtes most,</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen &yogh;iftus of &thorn;e holigost</L>
<L N="3">I preye &thorn;at &thorn;ou &yogh;iue me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I may &thorn;orwh &thorn;e grace of hem</L>
<L>Wynne &thorn;i loue and <I>of alle men</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">By another hand on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6">And euere to qweme &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOrd, for &thorn;e &yogh;ifte of pite</L>
<L>&YOGH;if me grace sunne to fle,</L>
<L N="9">&YOGH;if hit beo &thorn;i wille;</L>
<L>And &thorn;orwh &thorn;e &yogh;ifte of drede also</L>
<L>Euere godnesse forte do,</L>
<L N="12">And neuere to don ille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN wit, louerd, wys me make,</L>
<L>Worldus pruyde euere forsake,</L>
<L N="15">ffor &thorn;i woundus fyue.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ift of streng&thorn;e graunte &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L>Out of sunne euer to be,</L>
<L N="18">Whiles icham a-lyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN-sihte &yogh;if &thorn;ou me also</L>
<L>&THORN;e to knowe, in weole and wo</L>
<L N="21">Whe&thorn;er &thorn;at i beo Inne.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ift of counseil put in me</L>
<L>Euere for to serue &thorn;e</L>
<L N="24">Clene wi&thorn;-oute synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEnde me wisdam, forte se</L>
<L>Mi wrecchednesse and my frelete</L>
<L N="27">Now and eueri day;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at at my lyues ende</L>
<L>To &thorn;at Ioye &thorn;ow me sende</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;at laste&thorn; now and ay. A m e n.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="16" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[XVI. A Confessioun for necligence of &thorn;e dedes of mercy.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">So the Title in Index.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lord, I &yogh;elde me gulti</L>
<L>&THORN;at I neuere fedde &thorn;e hungri,
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="35"></L>
<L N="3">Lord, as &thorn;ou bede me;</L>
<L>I &yogh;af no drinke &thorn;e &thorn;hursti,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wille ne wi&thorn; bodi:</L>
<L N="6">Merci, lord, I crie &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E naked, lord, I ne haue not clad</L>
<L>To my pouwer, as &thorn;ou bad,</L>
<L N="9">Nou&thorn;ur wi&thorn; dede ne wille;</L>
<L>Ne sek folk ne cumforted I:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, lord, mak me sori</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at I haue don so ille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Dede bodies haue I graue non,</L>
<L>But heold despyt of vchon</L>
<L N="15">Wher &thorn;at I hem sawe.</L>
<L>In myn herborwh herborwhed I non,</L>
<L>Pore Mon ne Pilgrym, of fflesch and bon,</L>
<L N="18">To folfulle &thorn;e lawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Prisones &thorn;at harde i-bounden lay,</L>
<L>I ne visitede hem Niht ne day:</L>
<L N="21">Lord, for-&yogh;iue hit me,</L>
<L>And alle o&thorn;ur wikkedhed,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I may comen aftur my ded</L>
<L N="24">And wonen euere, lord, wi&thorn; &thorn;e. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="17" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[XVII. An orysoun for sauynge of &thorn;e fyue wyttes.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">So the Title in Index.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LO[r]d, sunged haue I ofte</L>
<L>In my fyue wittes, wi&thorn; wille and &thorn;ou&yogh;te:</L>
<L N="3">In Lecherouse sihtes,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; myn Eres herd wikkede sawes</L>
<L>Of myn Euencristne a-&yogh;eyn &thorn;e lawes,</L>
<L N="6">Bo&thorn;e day and nihtes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In tast haue I had gret lykyng</L>
<L>And passed mesure In Mete and drink:</L>
<L N="9">Lord, for-&yogh;iue hit me;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ichaue sunged in smellyng,</L>
<L>And also, lord, in synful felyng,</L>
<L N="12">&YOGH;if &thorn;i wille be. A M E N.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="18" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000044.tif" N="36">
<HEAD>[XVIII. An orisoun for negligens of &thorn;e X Comaundemens.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">So the Title in Index.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>INwardliche, lord, bi-seche i &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Al my trespas for-&yogh;iue &thorn;ou me:</L>
<L>&THORN;at I haue broken &thorn;i Comaundemens</L>
<L N="4">A&yogh;ein &thorn;i wille and &thorn;i defens.</L>
<L>I haue not loued &thorn;e ouer alle &thorn;yng</L>
<L>And worschiped as my lord, my kyng;</L>
<L>Min Euencristen ne loued I nouht</L>
<L N="8">As my-self, in wil ne &thorn;ouht.</L>
<L>&THORN;i nome not nempned in worschupe,</L>
<L>Bute ofte-si&thorn;es in Idelschupe.</L>
<L>In holi-dayes haue I wrouht,</L>
<L N="12">To holychurche eode I nouht.</L>
<L>ffadur and Modur worschupet haue not I,</L>
<L>But a&yogh;eyn hem don vnboxumly.</L>
<L>Men haue I slawen wi&thorn; my wille,</L>
<L N="16">And Bakbited hem bo&thorn;e loude and stille.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wrong ichaue had muche &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of &yogh;ifte and of stelyng.</L>
<L>Boren ichaue fals witnesse</L>
<L N="20">And seldene i-don Rihtwysnesse.</L>
<L>In lecherie haue I sunged ille</L>
<L>Ofte-si&thorn;es a&yogh;eynes skille.</L>
<L>I-chaue coueyted more &thorn;en me hihte</L>
<L N="24">Mi neih&yogh;ebores god wi&thorn; vnrihte,</L>
<L>His wyf, his seruaunt, his o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i, Almihti heuene-kyng,</L>
<L>ffor-&yogh;if me now, and alle men</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;at haue broken &thorn;i comaundemens ten.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="19" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000045.tif" N="37">
<HEAD>[XIX. Patris Sapiencia<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>So the title in Index.</P></NOTE> sive Horae de Cruce.]</HEAD> 

<P>The Latin text is ed. in Daniel Thes. Hymnolog. I. p. 337. In the MS. the Engl. poem is written in half-lines.</P>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<DIV4 TYPE="canonical hour" N="matins">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>PAtris sapiencia, veritas diuina</I></L>
<L><I>deus homo factus est hora matutina,</I></L>
<L><I>A notis discipulis cito derelictus,</I></L>
<L><I>A Iudeis traditus, venditus, afflictus.</I></L>
</LG>
<P>v. <I>Adoramus te, criste, &amp; benedicimus tibi, Quia per crucem tuam redemisti mundum.</I></P>
<P>[Oremus] <I>D[omi]ne Ihesu criste, fili dei viui, qui pro nobis reis passionem in cruce ad mortem pie sustulisti, ob nostram vitam redimendam: In iudicio futuro animabus nostris &amp; in hora mortis nostre succurrere digneris; prestando viuis misericordiam &amp; graciam, defunctis veniam &amp; requiem, ecclesie pacem et con|cordiam, &amp; peccatoribus vitam &amp; gloriam sempiter|nam. Qui uivis &amp; regnas deus &thorn;er omnia secula seculorum. amen.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Erliche in &thorn;e morwenyng : Ihesu &thorn;e Iewes gunne take,</L>
<L>His frendes and his diciples : Hedden him sone forsake;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei blyndfelden him and Boffeteden : And al niht heold him wake:</L>
<L N="4">And al soffrede swete Ihesu : ffor monkunne sake</L>
<L>&THORN;at sorwe.</L>
<L>How may I for-&yogh;ete Ihesu : At Euen or at Mor[w]e?</L>
<L>v[ers.] Crist, honoured mote &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at bouhtest al &thorn;e world on tre!</L>
<L>or[emus.] Lord Ihesu, godus sone : &THORN;at synful mon wolt not tyne,
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="38"></L>
<L>Bi-twenen vr soules and &thorn;i dom : Puttest &thorn;e in hard pyne:</L>
<L>&THORN;i Cros, &thorn;i De&thorn; now and euere : And at vre endyng-tyme</L>
<L N="12">Graunte liuynde men : Grace and Merci &thorn;yne;</L>
<L>To dede, reste and pardoun;</L>
<L>To Churche, pes, loue in londe; : To sunful, contricioun.</L>
<L>v[ers.] Cristes passion, heuene kyng,</L>
<L N="16">Bring us to blisse &thorn;at is wi&thorn;-outen endyng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="canonical hour" N="prime">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>HOra prima ductus est Ihesus ad pilatum,</I></L>
<L><I>ffalsis testimoniis tradunt accusatum,</I></L>
<L><I>In Collo percuciunt manibus ligatum,</I></L>
<L><I>Vultum dei conspuunt, lumen deo gratum.</I></L>
</LG>
<P>v. <I>Adoramus te, criste, &amp; benedicimus tibi, Quia per crucem tuam redemisti mundum.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At prime crist &thorn;e Iewes : Bi-fore Pilat gunne drawe,</L>
<L N="18">ffalslich &thorn;ei him a-cuiseden : Wi&thorn; mony a wikked sawe;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei spitteden in his feire face : &THORN;e men wi&thorn;-outen lawe,</L>
<L N="20">Ne wolde &thorn;ei neuere blinne : Til &thorn;ei hedde him slawe.</L>
<L>Ihesu, my dere lemmon,</L>
<L>Blo for-bled was &thorn;i bodi : &THORN;i brihte Rode was al won.</L>
<L><I>v.</I> Crist, honoured mote &thorn;ou beo,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at bou&yogh;test al &thorn;e world on treo.</L>
<L><I>or.</I> Lord Ihesu, godes sone : &THORN;at sunful mon wolt not tyne,</L>
<L>Bi-twenen vr soules and &thorn;i dom : Puttest &thorn;e in hard pyne:
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="39"></L>
<L>&THORN;i Cros, &thorn;i de&thorn; nou and euere : And at vre endyng-tyme</L>
<L N="28">Graunte liuinde men : Grace and merci &thorn;yne;</L>
<L>To dede, reste and pardoun;</L>
<L>To Churche, pes, loue in londe : To sunful, contricioun.</L>
<L><I>v.</I> Cristes passion, heuene kyng,</L>
<L N="32">Bring us to blisse &thorn;at is wi&thorn;-outen endyng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="canonical hour" N="terce">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>"Crucifige" clamitant hora terciarum;</I></L>
<L><I>Illusus induitur veste purpurarum,</I></L>
<L><I>Capud eius pungitur corona spinarum,</I></L>
<L><I>Crucem portat humeris ad loca penarum.</I></L>
</LG>
<P>v. <I>Adoramus te, criste, &amp; benedicimus tibi, Quia per crucem tuam redemisti mundum.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At vndurne to do Ihesu on cros : loude gunne &thorn;ei crie,</L>
<L N="34">And beoten him naked wi&thorn; scourges : Whil &thorn;ei mihte drie,</L>
<L>And crouned him wi&thorn; &thorn;ornes : &THORN;e blod ron in to his ei&yogh;e;</L>
<L N="36">And si&thorn;en maden him bere &thorn;e cros : To &thorn;e Mount of Caluarie</L>
<L>On his bac for-bete.</L>
<L>ffor drede of de&thorn; men mihte seo : &THORN;e blod &thorn;at he gon swete.</L>
<L><I>v.</I> Crist, honoured mote &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at bou&yogh;test al &thorn;e world on tre.</L>
<L><I>or.</I> Lord Ihesu, godus sone : &THORN;at sunful mon wolt not tyne,</L>
<L>Bitwenen vre soules and &thorn;y dom : Puttest &thorn;e in hard pyne:</L>
<L>&THORN;i Cros, &thorn;i de&thorn; now and euere : And at vre endynge-tyme</L>
<L N="44">Graunte lyuinde men : Grace and Merci &thorn;yne,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e dede, reste and pardoun;</L>
<L>To churche, pes, loue in londe : To sunful, contricioun.</L>
<L><I>v.</I> Cristes passion, heuene kyng,</L>
<L N="48">Bring us to blisse &thorn;at is wi&thorn;-outen endyng.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="canonical hour" N="sexte"><PB REF="00000048.tif" N="40">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>HOra sexta cristus est cruci conclauatus</I></L>
<L><I>Et est cum latronibus pendens deputatus,</I></L>
<L><I>Pre tormentis siciens felle saturatus;</I></L>
<L><I>Agnus crimen diluit sic deificatus.</I></L>
</LG>
<P>v. <I>Adoramus te, criste, &amp; benedicimus tibi, Quia per crucem tuam redemisti mundum.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At Midday Ihesu hondes : &THORN;ei nayleden to &thorn;e Rode,</L>
<L>Bi-twene twey &thorn;eues : &THORN;ei him hengen as wode;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &yogh;euen him galle and Eysel : Ihesu &thorn;at blisful fode.</L>
<L>Serewful were bo&thorn;e Marie an Ion : &THORN;er &thorn;ei bi him stode,</L>
<L N="53">As folk &thorn;at were mad.</L>
<L>Whose &thorn;enke&thorn; on Marie serwe : May he neuere be glad.</L>
<L><I>v.</I> Crist, honoured mote &thorn;ou beo,</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;at bouhtest al &thorn;e world on treo.</L>
<L><I>or.</I> Lord Ihesu, godes sone : &THORN;at sunful mon wolt not tyne,</L>
<L>Bi-twenen vr soules and &thorn;i dom : Puttest &thorn;e in hard pyne;</L>
<L>&THORN;i cros, &thorn;i de&thorn; nou and euere : And at vr endyng-tyme</L>
<L N="60">Graunte liuinde men : Grace and Merci &thorn;yne,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e dede, reste and pardoun;</L>
<L>To churche, pes, loue in londe : To sunful, contricioun.</L>
<L><I>v.</I> Cristes passion, heuene kyng,</L>
<L N="64">Bring us to blisse &thorn;at is wi&thorn;-outen endyng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="canonical hour" N="nones">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>HOra Nona dominus cristus expirauit,</I></L>
<L><I>"Heli" clamans spiritum patri comendauit,</I></L>
<L><I>Latus eius lancea myles perforauit.</I></L>
<L><I>Terra tunc contremuit, &amp; sol obscurauit.</I></L>
</LG>
<P>v. <I>Adoramus te, criste, &amp; benedicimus tibi, Quia per crucem tuam redemisti mundum.</I>
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="41"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">At Non &thorn;er &thorn;urlede Ihesus herte : Longius, a Blynd kniht;</L>
<L>He wupte his Ei&yogh;en wi&thorn; his blod : &THORN;orwh &thorn;at he hedde his siht.</L>
<L>&THORN;e eor&thorn;e quok, &thorn;e stones clouen : &THORN;e sonne les his liht,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;e dede a-risen of heore graues : In tokene of godus miht</L>
<L>&THORN;at us on Rode bouhte.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soules &thorn;at weren in helle : Ihesus sone out brouhte.</L>
<L><I>v.</I> Crist, honoured mote &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at bou&yogh;test al &thorn;e world on tre.</L>
<L><I>or.</I> Lord Ihesu, godus sone : &THORN;at sunful mon wolt not tyne,</L>
<L>Bi-twene vr soules and &thorn;y dom : Puttest &thorn;e in hard pyne:</L>
<L>&THORN;i cros, &thorn;i de&thorn; nou and euere : And at vr endyng-tyme</L>
<L N="76">Graunte liuynde men : Grace and Merci &thorn;yne;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e dede, reste and pardoun;</L>
<L>To churche, pes, loue in londe : To<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Wi&thorn;</NOTE> sunful, contricioun.</L>
<L><I>v.</I> Cristes passion, heuene kyng,</L>
<L N="80">Bring us to blisse &thorn;at is wi&thorn;-outen endyng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="canonical hour" N="vespers">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>DE Cruce deponitur hora vespertina,</I></L>
<L><I>ffortitudo latuit in</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &amp;</NOTE> <I>mente diuina.</I></L>
<L><I>Talem mortem subijt vite Medicina!</I></L>
<L><I>Heu, Corona glorie iacuit sub spyna.</I></L>
</LG>
<P>v. <I>Adoramus te, criste, &amp; benedicimus tibi, Quia per crucem tuam redemisti mundum.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At Euensong Ihesus was taken : Doun of Rode-treo.</L>
<L N="82">Marie bi-heold hire deore sone : ffor wepyng miht heo not seo;
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="42"></L>
<L>"A, sone," heo seide, "wi&thorn; &thorn;e fader : of heuene is &thorn;i pouste,</L>
<L N="84">But &thorn;ou schalt rise from de&thorn; to lyue : As &thorn;ou er seidest me,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e God and Mon;</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Wher &thorn;orwh</NOTE> &thorn;at de&thorn; is blisse ibou&yogh;t : &THORN;at loren was &thorn;orwh Sathan."</L>
<L><I>v.</I> Crist, honoured mote &thorn;ou beo,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at bouhtest al &thorn;e world on treo.</L>
<L><I>or.</I> Lord Ihesu, godus sone : &THORN;at sunful mon wolt not tyne,</L>
<L>Bi-twene vr soules and &thorn;i dom : Puttest &thorn;e in hard pyne:</L>
<L>&THORN;i Cros, &thorn;i de&thorn; now and euere : And at vre endyng-tyme</L>
<L N="92">Graunte liuinde men : Grace and Merci &thorn;yne,</L>
<L>To dede, reste and pardoun;</L>
<L>To churche, pes, loue in londe : To sunful, Contrissioun.</L>
<L><I>v.</I> Cristes passion, heuene kyng,</L>
<L N="96">Bring us to blisse &thorn;at is wi&thorn;-outen endyng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="liturgical hour" N="compline">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>HOra completorij datur sepulture</I></L>
<L><I>Corpus cristi nobile, spes vite future;</I></L>
<L><I>Conditur Aromate&mdash;complentur scripture.</I></L>
<L><I>Iugis sit memoria mortis sue iure.</I></L>
</LG>
<P>v. <I>Adoramus te, criste, et benedicimus tibi, Quia per crucem tuam redemisti mundum.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At Complin Crist was enoynt : And buried in a ston.</L>
<L N="98">Pilat bad his frendes : &THORN;er scholde leue non;</L>
<L>He sette knihtes him to kepen : &THORN;at he a-wey nere don:</L>
<L N="100">And &yogh;ut he ros to lyue : ffor hem euerichon</L>
<L>Of &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And schewede him to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">overlined.</NOTE> Maudeleyn : To peter and mony mo.
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="43"></L>
<L><I>v.</I> Crist, honoured mote &thorn;ou beo,</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;at bouhtest al &thorn;e world on treo.</L>
<L>Lord Ihesu, Godus sone : &THORN;at synful mon wolt not tyne,</L>
<L>Bi-twenen vr soules and &thorn;y dom : Puttest &thorn;e in hard pyne:</L>
<L>&THORN;i Cros, &thorn;i de&thorn; nou and euere : And at vr endyng|tyme</L>
<L N="108">Graunte liuinde men : Grace and Merci &thorn;yne,</L>
<L>To dede, reste and pardoun;</L>
<L>To Churche, pes, loue in londe : To synful, Con|tricioun.</L>
<L N="111"><I>v.</I> Cristes passion, heuene kyng,</L>
<L>Bring us to blisse &thorn;at is wi&thorn;-outen endyng. Amen.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E Pope Ion ha&thorn; graunted : A ful feir pardoun</L>
<L>To alle &thorn;at siggen &thorn;is Matyns : Wi&thorn; good deuo|cioun:</L>
<L>A &yogh;er in purgatorie : Of Remissioun,</L>
<L N="116">So &thorn;at heo ben clene i-schriuen : Wi&thorn; verrey Con|tricioun,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh Grace.</L>
<L>God sende us lyues fode : And in heuene a place. AMEN.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>


<DIV3 TYPE="similar poem">

<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="37">
<HEAD>[Another poem on the same subject, in MS. Miscell. Lit. 104]</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Another poem on the same subject, in MS. Miscell. Lit. 104, Bodl., fol. 50 (temp. Edw. III. or II.), has been edited by Morris, <I>Leg. of the Holy Rood</I>, p. 222. It is this, as given by Morris:</P></HEADNOTE>

<P><I>Hic incipiunt matutine de passione domini nostri ihesu cristi.</I></P>
<P>Antiphona: <I>Patris sapiencia ueritas diuina, &amp;c.</I></P>
<P>Vers. <I>Adoramus te criste &amp;c.</I></P>
<P>Or. <I>Domine ihesu criste fili dei uiui pone passionem crucem et mortem tuam &amp;c. Amen.</I></P>

<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">In the be|ginning a stanza must be wanting.</NOTE>Swete ihesu cryst, goddis sone of lyue,</L>
<L>&THORN;in passion, &thorn;in croys, &thorn;in ded, &thorn;in wondes five</L>
<L>
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="38">Beelde us (!) houre sinful soules in<NOTE PLACE="marg">M. &amp;</NOTE> &thorn;in iugement,</L>
<L N="4">Nou and in tyme of ded &thorn;at we ne be y-schent.</L>
<L>[D]eyne to &yogh;eue myt an grace to hem &thorn;at moten lyuen,</L>
<L>And to dede<NOTE PLACE="marg">M. dare</NOTE> reste, here sinnes &thorn;ou for-yyue;</L>
<L>To holi chirche and kyndom loue and pes &thorn;ou sende,</L>
<L N="8">And to vs wreche sinful, lif wyt-outen ende;</L>
<L>&THORN;at leuest kyng god and man wyt-outen endingge,</L>
<L>ffader and sone and holy gost to &thorn;ulke bl[i]se us bringge.</L></LG>
<P><I>Ad primam horam.</I></P>
<P><I>HOra prima dominum ducunt ad pilatum &amp;c.</I></P>
<P>v. <I>Adoramus te &amp;c.</I> or. <I>Domine ihesu criste.</I></P>
<LG>
<L>At prime ihesus was y-lad pilatus by-fore,</L>
<L N="12">Many false witnesse on hym were i-bore,</L>
<L>Hiis schines were y-beten, hiis honden weren y-bonden,</L>
<L>Hiis face hy gonne on spete&mdash;lyt of heuene &thorn;ey fonde.</L></LG>
<P>
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="39"><I>Ad terciam horam, amen</I> [leaf wanting]</P>
<P><I>Crucifige clamitant hora terciarum</I></P>
<P>v. <I>Adoramus.</I> or. <I>Domine ihesu criste.</I></P>
<LG>
<L>At hondren "do ihesu on rode<NOTE PLACE="marg">M. day on wde</NOTE>" &thorn;e giwes gonne grede,</L>
<L N="16">In schorn he was i-wonden in purpil-palle wede.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>On his schulder he bar &thorn;e crois to &thorn;e piningge.</L></LG>
<P>
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="40"><I>Sicut oculi ancille in manibus domine sue</I> [<I>&amp;c.</I>]</P>
<P><I>Hora sexta ihesus est cruce conclauatus</I></P>
<P>v. <I>Adoramus te.</I> or. <I>Domine ihesu criste filij.</I></P>
<LG>
<L>At midday was ihesus crist y-nailed to &thorn;e rode</L>
<L N="20">Bi-twixe tweye &thorn;eues he hongid for houre gode.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;urst of stronge pine y-fuld he was wy[t] galle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e holi lomb<NOTE PLACE="marg">M. Ve holi louird</NOTE> so god y-wrout &thorn;er bui&yogh;t houre sinnes alle.</L></LG>
<P><I>Deus in adiutorium.</I></P>
<P><I>Hora nona dominus ihesus expirauit.</I></P>
<P>v. <I>Adoramus.</I> or. <I>Domine ihesu criste filij.</I></P>
<LG>
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="41">
<L N="23">At none houre louerd crist of &thorn;ysse lif he wende,</L>
<L>He gradde "hely," &thorn;e holi gost to his fader he sende.</L>
<L>A knyt wit a kene spere &thorn;erlede his syde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e her&thorn;e quakede, &thorn;e sonne bi-com swart, &thorn;at erer schon wel wide.</L></LG>
<P><I>Deus in adiutorium.</I></P>
<P><I>De cruce deponitur hora uespertina</I></P>
<P>v. <I>Adoramus.</I> or. <I>Domine ihesu criste filij.</I></P>
<LG>
<L>At euensong he was i-nome a-doun &thorn;at dere us hadde ibou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="28">His mytte, his<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. hys his</NOTE> stre[n]g&thorn;e lotede in hei&yogh;e holi &thorn;out.</L>
<L>
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="42">Swech de&thorn; he under-feng, hele of alle wo.</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;e croune of worschepe to lowe hy leide &thorn;o.</L></LG>
<P><I>Conuerte nos deus salutaris noster.</I></P>
<P><I>Hora completorii datur sepulture</I></P>
<P>v. <I>Adoramus.</I> or. <I>Domine ihesu criste.</I></P>
<LG>
<L>He was y-&yogh;eue to beryyng ate laste tyde,</L>
<L N="32">Cristes body noble, hope of liue to byde,</L>
<L>In-oynt he was wyt aromat, holi writ to fulle.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oruful meynde of his de&thorn; bee in myne wille. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="20" TYPE="part">
<PB N="43" REF="00000051.tif">
<HEAD>[XX. Veni Creator Spiritus,<NOTE PLACE="foot">So the Title in Index.</NOTE> englisht.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Veni, creator spiritus,</I></L>
<L><I>mentes tuorum visita,</I></L>
<L><I>imple superna gracia</I></L>
<L><I>que tu creasti pectora.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Cum, lord vr makere, Holigost,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ouhtes of &thorn;yne forte sene;</L>
<L>&THORN;e hertes &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;i schaftus wost,</L>
<L N="4">fful hem of &thorn;i grace by-dene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Qui paraclitus diceris,</I></L>
<L><I>donum dei Altissimi,</I></L>
<L><I>fons viuus, ignis, caritas,</I></L>
<L><I>et spiritalis vnccio.</I>
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="44"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Clept art &thorn;ou cumfort, and euer schalt be,<NOTE PLACE="marg">This v. in MS. written in half lines.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;ift of god &thorn;at al good sent,</L>
<L>Quik welle, ffuir, and Charite,</L>
<L N="8">And also gostly Oynement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Tv septiformis munere,</I></L>
<L><I>dextre dei tu digitus;</I></L>
<L><I>Tu rite promissum patris,</I></L>
<L><I>Sermone ditans guttura.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou art in &yogh;ifte seuenfold,</L>
<L>Godus riht hond ffinger art &thorn;ou;</L>
<L>As us bi-het ffader al-wold,</L>
<L N="12">Richesse of word<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. world</NOTE> &thorn;ou &yogh;iuest inouh.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Accende lumen sensibus,</I></L>
<L><I>Infunde amorem cordibus,</I></L>
<L><I>infirma nostri corporis</I></L>
<L><I>uirtute firmans perpeti.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lord, in vr<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;i</NOTE> wittes tend &thorn;i liht,</L>
<L>And in vr hertes &thorn;i loue sende;</L>
<L>Vr bodi feblenesse &thorn;orwh &thorn;i miht</L>
<L N="16">Streng&thorn;e hit euere wi&thorn;-outen ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Hostem repellas longius,</I></L>
<L><I>pacemque dones protinus;</I></L>
<L><I>ductore sic te preuio</I></L>
<L><I>uitemus omne noxium.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Put fer from us &thorn;e fend, ur fo,</L>
<L>And send us so&thorn;fast pees anon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we &thorn;orwh &thorn;e &thorn;at laft (!) us so</L>
<L N="20">Blenchen sunnes euerichon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>PEr te sciamus, da, patrem,</I></L>
<L><I>noscamus atque filium,</I></L>
<L><I>te utriusque spiritum</I></L>
<L><I>credamus omni tempore.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;e ffadur &yogh;if us witing,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e Sone knowyng also,</L>
<L>Siker be-leeue and riht tokenyng</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at &thorn;ou art god of bo&thorn;e two.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Dvdum sacrata pectora</I></L>
<L><I>tua replesti gracia:</I></L>
<L><I>dimitte nunc peccamina</I></L>
<L><I>et da quieta tempora.</I>
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="45"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Holi hertes sum-tyme was</L>
<L>&THORN;ou fuldest, lord, &thorn;orwh grace &thorn;yne:</L>
<L>ffor-&yogh;if now gultus and trespas,</L>
<L N="28">And &yogh;if us reste in alle tyme.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Sit laus patri cum filio,</I></L>
<L><I>Sauncto simul paraclito,</I></L>
<L><I>nobisque mittat filius</I></L>
<L><I>carisma sauncti spiritus. Amen.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffader and Sone and Holigost be</L>
<L>Worschiped<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Worschipest</NOTE> as &thorn;ei mowe beo most,</L>
<L>And send us schrift for his pite,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;e &yogh;iftus of &thorn;e holygost. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="21" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[XXI. The Sweetness of Jesus.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Same poem in MS. Lamb. 853, ed. by Furnivall, <I>Hymns to the Virgin and Christ</I>, p. 8, E. E. T. S. 1867; in MS. Thornton (best MS.), ed. by Perry, <I>Rel. Pieces</I>, 1867, N. 8; and in MS. Rawl., A. 389, 104. The poem was originally composed in the North.</NOTE>Ihesu, &thorn;i swetnesse whose miht hit se</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-of haue a clene<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> clere</NOTE> knowyng,</L>
<L>Al eor&thorn;ly loue bitter schulde be</L>
<L N="4">But &thorn;in al-one, wi&thorn;-outen lesyng.</L>
<L>I preye &thorn;e, lord, &thorn;at lore lere me:</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;i loue to haue longyng,</L>
<L>And sadly set myn herte on &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="8">In &thorn;i loue to haue most lykyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SO lykyng loue In eor&thorn;e non is,</L>
<L>In soule whos cou&thorn;e him so&thorn;ly se;</L>
<L>Him to loue were muche blis,</L>
<L N="12">ffor kyng of loue called is he.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; trewe loue I wolde i-wis</L>
<L>So faste to him bounden be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at myn herte weore holly his,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at no &thorn;ing lykede me but he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;If I for kyndenes schulde loue mi kinne,</L>
<L>&THORN;enne me &thorn;inke&thorn; in my &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>Bi kuynde skil I schulde bi-ginne</L>
<L N="20">At him &thorn;at ha&thorn; me maad of nouht:
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="46"></L>
<L>His semblaunt he sette my soule wi&thorn;-Inne,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is world for me he wrouht;</L>
<L>As ffader he fonde&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. fonded</NOTE> my loue to winne,</L>
<L N="24">ffor to heuene he ha&thorn; me bouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AS Modur of him I make mynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bi-foren my bur&thorn;e to me tok hede,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en wi&thorn; Baptym wesche &thorn;at kynde<NOTE PLACE="marg">P. strynde</NOTE></L>
<L N="28">&THORN;at suyled was &thorn;orwh Adam dede;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; noble mete he norsched my kynde,</L>
<L>ffor wi&thorn; his flesch he dude me fede&mdash;</L>
<L>So good a foode may no mon fynde,</L>
<L N="32">To lastyng lyf he<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> it</NOTE> wol us lede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MI Bro&thorn;ur and Suster he is wi&thorn; skyl,<NOTE PLACE="marg">This v. written in half lines.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor he seide and leret &thorn;at lore:</L>
<L>Hose wrouhte his fadur wil</L>
<L N="36">Bro&thorn;ur and Suster to him &thorn;ei wore;</L>
<L>Mi kuynde he tok also &thorn;er-til.</L>
<L>fful trewely trust I him &thorn;erfore.</L>
<L>He<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at he</NOTE> &thorn;at wol neuere lete me spil,</L>
<L N="40">Wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> But wi&thorn;</NOTE> his Merci salue my sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">This stanza om. in P.</NOTE>&THORN;E loue of him passe&thorn;, i-wis,</L>
<L>Al eor&thorn;ly loue &thorn;at may beo here:</L>
<L>God and Mon, my spouse he is&mdash;</L>
<L N="44">Wel ouhte I wrecche to loue him dere!</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e heuene and eor&thorn;e holliche is his,</L>
<L>He is a lord of gret powere,</L>
<L>And called he is &thorn;e kyng of blis&mdash;</L>
<L N="48">His loue me longe&thorn; for to lere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Afftur his loue bi-houe&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">P. me burde</NOTE> me longe,</L>
<L>ffor he ha&thorn; myn ful dere abouht:</L>
<L>Whon I was went from him wi&thorn; wronge,</L>
<L N="52">ffrom heuene to eor&thorn;e he me souht,</L>
<L>Mi wrecched kuynde for me he fonge</L>
<L>And his nobley sette at nouht,</L>
<L>Peynes he soffrede and pouert stronge,</L>
<L N="56">A&yogh;eyn to blisse or he me brouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon I was &thorn;ral, to make me fre</L>
<L>Mi loue from heuene to er&thorn;e him ledde;</L>
<L>Mi loue al-one haue wolde he,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;erfore he leyde his lyf in wedde.
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="47"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; my fo he fauht for me,</L>
<L>Woundet he was and bitterly bledde,</L>
<L>His precious blod ful gret plente</L>
<L N="64">fful piteuously for me was schedde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HIs sydes blo and blodi were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sum-tyme were ful briht of ble;</L>
<L>His herte was perced wi&thorn; a spere;</L>
<L N="68">His wyde woundes were reu&thorn;e to se.</L>
<L>Mi Raunsoun, I-wis, he payed &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And &yogh;af his lyf for gult of me.</L>
<L>His de&thorn; most beo to me ful dere<NOTE PLACE="marg">P. His dulefull dede burde do me dere</NOTE></L>
<L N="72">And perce myn herte for pure pite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FOr pite myn herte most breke a-two,</L>
<L>To his kyndenesse &yogh;if I tok hede:</L>
<L>Enchesun I was of al his wo,</L>
<L N="76">He suffrede ful harde for my misdede;</L>
<L>To lastinde lyf &thorn;at I schulde go,</L>
<L>He suffrede de&thorn; in his Monhede.</L>
<L>Whon his wille was to lyue also,</L>
<L N="80">He ros a-&yogh;eyn &thorn;orwh his godhede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO heuene he wente wi&thorn; muche blis,</L>
<L>Whon he [had] vencust his batayle.</L>
<L>His baner ful brode displayed is,</L>
<L N="84">Whon so my fo wol me assayle.</L>
<L>Wel ouhte myn herte [&thorn;en] to ben his,</L>
<L>ffor he is &thorn;at frend &thorn;at neuer wol fayle;</L>
<L>No &thorn;ing wol he haue, i-wis,</L>
<L N="88">But trewe loue for his trauayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us wolde he<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> my spouse</NOTE> for me fiht,</L>
<L>And for me was he woundet sore;</L>
<L>ffor my loue his de&thorn; was diht&mdash;</L>
<L N="92">What kyndenesses miht he do more?</L>
<L>To &yogh;elden his loue haue I no miht,</L>
<L>But loue him trewely I schulde &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L>And worche wel<NOTE PLACE="marg">P. his will</NOTE> wi&thorn; werkes riht</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;at he ha&thorn; lered wi&thorn; louely lore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HIs louely lore wi&thorn; werk<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> werkes</NOTE> folfille</L>
<L>Wel ouht I, wrecche, &yogh;if I were kynde,</L>
<L>Niht and day to worche his wille,</L>
<L N="100">And euermore haue &thorn;at lord in mynde.
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="48"></L>
<L>Bote gostly fos greuen me ille,</L>
<L>And my frelete[s]<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> frele flesch</NOTE> maken me blynde:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore his merci I take me tille,</L>
<L N="104">ffor beter bote con I non fynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Beter bote nis non to me</L>
<L>&THORN;en to his merci trewely me take,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; his flesch ha&thorn; mad me fre</L>
<L N="108">And me wrecche his child wolde make.</L>
<L>I preye &thorn;at lord for his pite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he for sunne neuer me forsake,</L>
<L>But &yogh;if me grace from synne to fle,</L>
<L N="112">And him to loue let me neuer slake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, for &thorn;e swetnesse &thorn;at is in &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Haue Mynde of me whon I henne wende;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; studefast trou&thorn;e my wittes wis,</L>
<L N="116">And, lord, &thorn;ou schilde me from &thorn;e fende;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;i Merci for&yogh;if me mi mis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wikkede werk my soule ne schende;</L>
<L>And led me, lord, in to &thorn;i blis,</L>
<L N="120">Wi&thorn; &thorn;e to wone wi&thorn;-outen ende. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="22" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[XXII. A Prayer to Jesus.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IEsu, &thorn;at art heuene kyng,</L>
<L>Sothfast God and mon also,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if me grace of good endyng,</L>
<L N="4">And hem &thorn;at I am holden to.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu lord, &thorn;at madest me,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;i blisful blod hast bouht,</L>
<L>ffor-&yogh;if &thorn;at I haue greued &thorn;e</L>
<L N="8">Wi&thorn; word and wille and wi&thorn; &thorn;ouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, in whom is al mi trust,</L>
<L>&THORN;at di&yogh;edest on &thorn;e Rode-tre,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-drauh myn herte from flesches lust</L>
<L N="12">And from worldly vanite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu crist, to &thorn;e i calle</L>
<L>&THORN;at art ffadur ful of miht,</L>
<L>Kep me clene, &thorn;at I ne falle</L>
<L N="16">In flescly sunne as I haue hiht.
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="49"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, for &thorn;i blisful blod</L>
<L>Bring &thorn;e soules in to blis</L>
<L>ffor<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. ffro</NOTE> whom I haue had eny god,</L>
<L N="20">ffor-&yogh;iue hem &thorn;at &thorn;ei han don amis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, for &thorn;at wor&thorn;i wounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at wente to &thorn;in herte-Rote,</L>
<L>ffor<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. ffro</NOTE> sunne &thorn;at ha&thorn; my soule bounde</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;i blisful blod mot beo my bote.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, for &thorn;i woundes smerte</L>
<L>Of feet and of &thorn;in hondes two,</L>
<L>Mak me Meke and louh of herte,</L>
<L N="28">And &thorn;e to loue as I scholde do.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, for &thorn;e deolful teres</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou weptust for my gilt,</L>
<L>Heere and spede my pore preyeres,</L>
<L N="32">And saue me &thorn;at I ne beo spilt!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="23" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[XXIII. Psalterium b. Mariae. BY ALBERTUS MAGNUS.] (With the first Verse of every Psalm and Canticle.)</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Title in Index: Of euery psalme of &thorn;e sauter &thorn;e furste vers. The Latin Quatrains, however, frequently refer to other verses of the psalm, or to other parts of the Bible quoted by the com|mentators as illustrative of the psalm. The Latin poem is mentioned in Mone, <I>Latein. Hymnen des Mittelalters</I>, 1854, II. p. 252, but still unprinted; other MSS. are at Darmstadt (No. 2242) and Munich (Tegernsee 2005).</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Beatus vir qui non abijt in co[n]silio impiorum et in uia peccatorum non stetit et in cathedra pestilencie non sedit.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Beginning of Ps. 1.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe uirgo uirginum, parens absque pari,</I></L>
<L><I>Sine viri semine digna fecundari:</I></L>
<L><I>ffac nos legem domini crebro meditari</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">refers to Ps. 1, v. 2.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Et in regni gloria beatificari.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1">Heyl Mayden ouer Maydenes vchon,</L>
<L>Modur wi&thorn;-outen pere,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen knowyng of Mon</L>
<L N="4">A wor&thorn;i chyld &thorn;ow beere:</L>
<L>Mak vs vr lordus lawes kepe</L>
<L>And ofte to haue in mende,
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="50"></L>
<L>In to kyngdom of Ioye to lepe,</L>
<L N="8">Beo blessed wi&thorn;-outen ende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Quare fremuerunt gentes, et populi meditati sunt inania</I>?<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 2.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue, cuius viscera natum ediderunt</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius ad interitum gentes fremuerunt:</I></L>
<L><I>Audi uoces supplicum qui te pie querunt,</I></L>
<L><I>Mali causas remouens que nos inuenerunt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="9">Heil &thorn;e entrayles o whom</L>
<L>Brouhten for&thorn; a sone</L>
<L>At whos de&thorn; bo&thorn;e alle and som</L>
<L N="12">ffolk grucche bi-gone:</L>
<L>Heore<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. here</NOTE> deuoute voices al-way</L>
<L>&THORN;at sechen &thorn;e here in grounde;</L>
<L>Euel causes remoue a-way</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at vs here han I-founde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Domine, quid multiplicati sunt qui tribulant me? multi insurgunt aduersum me.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 3.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo, speculum sauncti celibatus,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius est ex utero puer nobis natus</I></L>
<L><I>Qui compassus mortuo, morte soporatus</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">refers to Ps. 3, v. 5.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Morte mortem terminat, expiat reatus.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="17">Heil, Mayden and Mirour</L>
<L>Of holy heuenly lyuyng,</L>
<L>Of whos wombe wi&thorn; honour</L>
<L N="20">Is boren a child, vr kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hedde compassion of &thorn;e ded,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his dedliche slepyng</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; de&thorn; [de&thorn;]<NOTE PLACE="marg">om.</NOTE> he termyned,</L>
<L N="24">Vr gult awey wassching.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Cum inuocarem exaudiuit me deus iusticie mee, in tribulacione dilatasti michi.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 4.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Ave nati filia, parens genitoris,</I></L>
<L><I>Preter modum</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. mortem</NOTE> <I>generans consucti moris:</I></L>
<L><I>Nos ad statum reuoca vite melioris,</I></L>
<L><I>Quos tam diu tenuit vanitas erroris.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">refers to Ps. 4, v. 2.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">Heil douhtur of &thorn;e sone,</L>
<L>Modur of &thorn;e getere,</L>
<L>Hauyng child a&yogh;eynes old wone</L>
<L N="28">O&thorn;ur elles comuyn manere:
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="51"></L>
<L>Calle us a&yogh;eyn in to &thorn;at staat</L>
<L>&THORN;at is of better lyuyng,</L>
<L>ffor us ha&thorn; holden longe al maat</L>
<L N="32">Vanyte of erryng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Verba mea auribus percipe, domine; intellige cla|morem meum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 5.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue que</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. qui</NOTE> <I>nos redimens ab Egipti luto</I></L>
<L><I>Subvenire</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. subvenite</NOTE> <I>satagis vicijs imbuto:</I></L>
<L><I>Tu nos bene</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. bone</NOTE> <I>protegens voluntatis scuto</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">refers to Ps. 5, v. 11.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Coronatos gloria colloces in tuto.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="33">Heil &thorn;ou, buggyng us a&yogh;eyn</L>
<L>Out of Egyptes cley,</L>
<L>In vices wounden to helpe, certeyn,</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;ou art redi al-wey:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou defendyng us wel riht</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e scheld of wil,</L>
<L>Vs Corouned in blisse briht</L>
<L N="40">Set sikerly wi&thorn; skil.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Domine, ne in furore tuo arguas me, neque in ira tua corripias me.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 6.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue vite ianua, salus penitentis,</I></L>
<L><I>Respice miseriam anime languentis;</I></L>
<L><I>Ne in ira senciam uocem arguentis,</I></L>
<L><I>Me peccatis exime simul et tormentis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="41">Heil, louelich &yogh;ate of lyf,</L>
<L>Hele of &thorn;e for&thorn;inkyng:</L>
<L>Bi-hold &thorn;e wrecchednesse so rif</L>
<L N="44">Of soule &thorn;at is serwyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;at in wra&thorn;&thorn;e I ne feel</L>
<L>&THORN;e vois of repreyuing,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. repreyning</NOTE></L>
<L>Clanse me from sunnes eueridel</L>
<L N="48">And eke from tormentyng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Domine deus meus, in te speraui; saluum me fac ex omnibus persequentibus me, &amp; libera me.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 7.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue mater vnica, cura nostre spei,</I></L>
<L><I>Tuis queso meritis sis miserta mei,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt ab enigmatibus huius speciei</I></L>
<L><I>Plena plene perfruar</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. perfruat</NOTE> <I>visione dei.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="49">Heil Modur, &thorn;ou onliche</L>
<L>Hed art of vr hope:
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="52"></L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;i merites specialiche</L>
<L N="52">Haue merci on me mope,</L>
<L>&THORN;at from alle &thorn;e liknesse</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is lyuyng heer</L>
<L>I may haue wi&thorn; fulnesse</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;e siht of god so cler.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Domine deus</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. dominus</NOTE> <I>noster, quam admirabile est nomen tuum in vniuersa terra!</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 8.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo regia, summa gaudiorum,</I></L>
<L><I>Per quam rex mirabilis, dominus cun[c]torum,</I></L>
<L><I>Reuocat inmeritos in spem filiorum,</I></L>
<L><I>Quos proscribit multiplex causa uiciorum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="57">Heil kynges Mayden, swete &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Somme of ioyes I calle,</L>
<L>Bi whom &thorn;e wondurful kyng,</L>
<L N="60">Lord &thorn;at is ouer alle,</L>
<L>Calle&thorn; us a-&yogh;eyn wi&thorn;-oute deseruyng</L>
<L>In to his sones hope,</L>
<L>&THORN;at aren ofte put in to flemyng,</L>
<L N="64">In vices whon we ben crope.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Confitebor tibi, domine, in toto corde meo, narrabo omnia mirabilia tua.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 9.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue thronus gracie, Mater Ihesu cristi,</I></L>
<L><I>Que sola concipere virgo meruisti:</I></L>
<L><I>Confitebor domino quem sic genuisti,</I></L>
<L><I>Quod nec nomen virginis mater amisisti.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">Heil feir trone of grace,</L>
<L>Modur of Ihesu crist,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to conceyue in &thorn;i space</L>
<L N="68">Onliche Mayden deseruedist:</L>
<L>I schal knowleche to &thorn;at lord</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou so dust<NOTE PLACE="marg">= dudest</NOTE> bi-gete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;e name in dede ne word</L>
<L N="72">Of Mayden and Moder ne lete.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>IN domino confido; quomodo dicitis anime mee</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 10 V (11).</NOTE> <I>transmigra in montem sicut passer?</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo virginum, per quam transmigratur</I></L>
<L><I>Super vnum moncium in quo victimatur</I></L>
<L><I>Vepre tentus aries</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Gen. 22, v. 13.</NOTE> <I>vnde redimatur</I></L>
<L><I>Prodigus qui rediens veniam precatur.</I>
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="53"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="73">Heil Mayden ouer o&thorn;ur met,</L>
<L>Beo whom is mad passyng</L>
<L>Vppon on of hulles gret</L>
<L N="76">In whuch is don offring,</L>
<L>&THORN;e we&thorn;er holden wi&thorn; a Brer,</L>
<L>Whuche was a-&yogh;eyn biggyng</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e wastour &thorn;at was in wer,</L>
<L N="80">ffor&yogh;iuenes &thorn;at com askyng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Saluum me fac domine, quoniam defecit sanctus,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 11 (12).</NOTE> <I>quoniam diminute sunt veritates a filiis</I> hominum.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue mater domini, mater inquam aue,</I></L>
<L><I>ffac ut cristi baiulem iugum presuaue,</I></L>
<L><I>Quo beatitudinis particeps octaue</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">refers to the title of the psalm.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Liberari merear prime matris aue.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="81">Heil Modur of vr lord,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it I sey Modur heil!</L>
<L>Cristes &yogh;ok in dede and word</L>
<L N="84">To bere mak me not fayl;</L>
<L>&THORN;at I of &thorn;e ei&yogh;te&thorn;e blisse</L>
<L>Beo parciner me borwe,</L>
<L>To beo diliuered and euer misse</L>
<L N="88">Vr furste modur sorwe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Vsquequo, domine, obliuisceris me in finem? vsquequo auertis faciem tuam a me?</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 12 (13).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue uirgo nomine matris insignita,</I></L>
<L><I>Graciarum fertili dote</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. doce</NOTE> <I>premunita:</I></L>
<L><I>Purga mentis aciem, quo sit expedita,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne vmquam obdormiat in morte sopita.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">refers to Ps. 12, v. 4.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="89">Heil Mayden feir of face,</L>
<L>Worschiped wi&thorn; nome of Moder;</L>
<L>So plentiuous I-douwed wi&thorn; grace</L>
<L N="92">Was &thorn;er neuer non o&thorn;er:</L>
<L>Purge &thorn;e scharpnesse of vr &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at hit beo sped,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hit to longe ne slepe nouht</L>
<L N="96">In slep of sunful ded.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>DIxit insipiens in corde suo: non est deus.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 13 (14).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue templum gracie, templum sanctitatis,</I></L>
<L><I>Templum sancti spiritus, tronus maiestatis:</I>
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="54"></L>
<L><I>Salua me, per graciam salua queso gratis,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt sortiri ualeam regnum cum beatis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="97">Heil temple of grace most,</L>
<L>Temple of Sauntite,</L>
<L>Temple of &thorn;e holygost,</L>
<L N="100">Trone of &thorn;e Maieste:</L>
<L>Saue me, be grace me saue,</L>
<L>I preye &thorn;e nou, freliche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I mowe &thorn;e kyngdom haue</L>
<L N="104">Wi&thorn; seintes &thorn;at ben godliche.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Domine, quis habitabit in tabernaculo tuo? aut quis requiesset in monte sancto tuo?</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 14 (15).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue tabernaculum regis manu fortis,</I></L>
<L><I>Per quam cristus particeps factus nostre sortis,</I></L>
<L><I>ffractis seris</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. eris v.</NOTE> <I>uectibus &amp; inferni portis</I></L>
<L><I>Nos a morte reuocat, triumphator mortis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="105">Heil tabernacle Cleer</L>
<L>Of kyng strong in honde,</L>
<L>Beo whom crist is maad parciner</L>
<L N="108">Of vre lot her in londe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at brak &thorn;e bondes and &thorn;e loke</L>
<L>Of helle foule &yogh;ates,</L>
<L>Called us fro de&thorn; &thorn;er we weore stoke,</L>
<L N="112">Victor of de&thorn; algates.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Conserua me domine, quoniam speraui in te. d[ixi] domino: deus meus es tu, quoniam b[onorum] meorum non eges.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 15 (16).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue tronus gracie Regi preparatus,</I></L>
<L><I>Ex qua nobis prodiit felix aduocatus:</I></L>
<L><I>Nostra sit hereditas cristus ex te natus</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 15, v. 5.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Conseruetque seruulos, condonans reatus.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="113">Heil, of grace &thorn;ou art trone</L>
<L>Arayed for a kyng,</L>
<L>Of whom sprong for&thorn; for us vchone</L>
<L N="116">An Auoket lyking:</L>
<L>Crist nou beo vr heritage,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;e is boren,</L>
<L>And kepe his seruauns in alle age,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at &thorn;ei beo not for-loren.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm"><PB REF="00000063.tif" N="55">
<P><I>Exaudi, domine, iusticiam meam, intende depreca|cionem meam.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 16 (17).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue solis ciuitas, in quam introiuit</I></L>
<L><I>Rex regum et dominus, qui te concupiuit:</I></L>
<L><I>Per te nos exaudiat sibi quos vniuit,</I></L>
<L><I>Suo vultu sacians quibus esuriuit.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 16, v. 15.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="121">Heil of Sonne &thorn;e Cite,</L>
<L>In to whuche he<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;ou</NOTE> entrid</L>
<L>Kyng of kynges, lord of pite,</L>
<L N="124">&thorn;e whuche &thorn;e coueyted.</L>
<L>Beo &thorn;e now he us here,</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke &thorn;at he ha&thorn; oned;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he fulle hem wi&thorn; his chere</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;at he &thorn;rustyng be-mened.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>DIligam te, domine fortitudo mea: dominus firma|mentum meum &amp; refugium meum &amp; liberator meus.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 17 (18).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo virginum, de qua mediator</I></L>
<L><I>Ad nos venit, hostium vetus triumphator:</I></L>
<L><I>Hostes nostros conterat fortis expugnator</I></L>
<L><I>Et fiat per graciam glorie collator.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="129">Heil of Maydenes Mayden clene,</L>
<L>Of whom a Mene of diuis<NOTE PLACE="marg">= device</NOTE></L>
<L>Com to vs wi&thorn;-outen wene,</L>
<L N="132">Victor of olde Enemys:</L>
<L>Vr Enemys he al to-tere,</L>
<L>ffihtere &thorn;at is so strong,</L>
<L>And beo grace beo he &yogh;iuere</L>
<L N="136">Of Ioye &thorn;at laste&thorn; long.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Celi enarrant gloriam dei, et opera manuum eius annunciat firmamentum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 18 (19).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue solis regia, de qua verus exit</I></L>
<L><I>Veri solis radius, fraudes qui detexit</I></L>
<L><I>Hostis &amp; versucias quibus nos illexit;</I></L>
<L><I>Ouem querens perditam, gregi quam reuexit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="137">Heil kynges sone (!) briht,</L>
<L>Of whom go&thorn; for&thorn; vche while</L>
<L>&THORN;e verrey sonnes bem liht,</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;at huyde&thorn; al &thorn;e gyle
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="56"></L>
<L>Of vr fon, and queyntises most,</L>
<L>&THORN;at drawen vs in to veyn;</L>
<L>Seching &thorn;e scheep &thorn;at was lost</L>
<L N="144">To bringe to folde a-&yogh;eyn.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Exaudiat te dominus in die tribulacionis, protegat te nomen dei Iacob.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 19 (20).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue plena gracie, speciosa tota,</I></L>
<L><I>Virgo prudens, humilis, sine sordis nota:</I></L>
<L><I>Nostrum sacrificium suscipe deuota</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 19, v. 3.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Mores nostros ordinans, affectus &amp; uota.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">Heil ful of grace, eke</L>
<L>Speciouse at al,</L>
<L>Mayden wys and &thorn;erto Meke,</L>
<L N="148">Wi&thorn;-outen ful&thorn;e gret or smal:</L>
<L>In alle maner vr<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. of vr</NOTE> sacrifice</L>
<L>Deuouteliche take &thorn;ou now,</L>
<L>Ordeyne vr Maners on &thorn;i wyse,</L>
<L N="152">Desires and eke a-vow.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Domine, in uirtute tua letabitur rex, &amp; super salutare tuum exultabit uehementer.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 20 (21).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue salus hominum, digna salutari,</I></L>
<L><I>Salutare pariens, sola carens pari:</I></L>
<L><I>Nostra spes &amp; gloria sit in salutari</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 20, v. 5.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>C[u]ius participio credimus beari.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="153">Heil hele of monkynde,</L>
<L>Wor&thorn;iful to beo gret,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou bar hele vs alle helynde,</L>
<L N="156">Saunc&yogh; pere &thorn;ou art set.</L>
<L>Al vr hope and eke vr blis</L>
<L>In hele beo vs be-tid;</L>
<L>&THORN;erof to haue part wi&thorn;-outen mis</L>
<L N="160">We leeue to beo blessed.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Deus deus meus, respice me: quare me dereliquisti? longe a salute mea verba delictorum meorum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 21 (22).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius vterus vermem procreauit</I></L>
<L><I>Qui sub-mordens hederam Ione desiccauit;</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 21, v. 6, and Jon. 4, 6-7.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Dum quod legis littera clausum conseruauit,</I></L>
<L><I>In apertum proferens nobis propalauit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="161">Heil whos wombe sikerly</L>
<L>Brouht for&thorn; a worm &thorn;at dred,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. died?</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="57"></L>
<L>&THORN;at vnder-bityng priuely</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;e Iuy of Ione dried;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e lettre of &thorn;e laue</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;ing in clos keped,</L>
<L>Aperteliche wi&thorn; open sawe</L>
<L N="168">To vs forso&thorn;e he schewed.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Dominus regit me &amp; nichil michi deerit: in loco pascue ibi me collocauit.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 22 (23).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue Iesse virgula graciarum donis</I></L>
<L><I>Habundanter predita : tu correccionis</I></L>
<L><I>Virga sis, &amp; baculus consolacionis</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 22, v. 4.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Quo nos criste pascuis collocet in bonis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="169">Heil &thorn;ou &yogh;erde of Iesse,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; giftus of grace</L>
<L>Maad riche wi&thorn; plente;</L>
<L N="172">Of correccioun in vche place</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art staf, and eke &yogh;erde</L>
<L>Of consolacioun,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whuche crist, &thorn;at is nou&yogh;t ferde,</L>
<L N="176">Vs sette in pasture boun.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Domini est terra &amp; plenitudo eius, orbis terrarum &amp; vniuersi qui habitant in eo.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 23 (24).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue terra glorie, terra non arrata,</I></L>
<L><I>Rore tamen gracie plene fecundata,</I></L>
<L><I>ffructum ferens cuius est gustu recreata</I></L>
<L><I>Proles Ade veteris, diu captiuata.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="177">Heil lond of blis,</L>
<L>Eor&thorn;e nouht hered,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e deuh of grace i-wis</L>
<L N="180">ffulliche for euer wered,</L>
<L>Beryng fruit of whos sauour</L>
<L>Reformed was verreyliche</L>
<L>Olde Adames sone, &thorn;e furste synnour,</L>
<L N="184">&THORN;at holden was wrecchedliche.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Ad te, domine, leuaui animam meam; deus meus, in te confido, non erubescam.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 24 (25).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius gloriam boant vniuersi,</I></L>
<L><I>Per quam sursum redeunt in profundum mersi:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. merci</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Per te fiat, domina, ne semel conuersi</I></L>
<L><I>Redeant ad uomitum sibimet aduersi.</I>
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="58"></L>
<L N="185">Heil on whos blisse certeyn</L>
<L>Alle crien and ben not feynt,</L>
<L>Be whuche gon vp a-&yogh;eyn</L>
<L N="188">In depnesse &thorn;at weoren dreynt:</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;e, ladi of delyt,</L>
<L>Heo &thorn;at ben conuerted ones</L>
<L>Torn &thorn;enne a-&yogh;ein not to vomyt,</L>
<L N="192">As hound &thorn;at ha&thorn; eten bones.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Iudica me domine, quoniam ego in innocencia mea in|gressus sum: &amp; in domino sperans non infirmabor.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 25 (26).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue Mater, populi prospice defectum,</I></L>
<L><I>Et maternum filijs exibens affectum</I></L>
<L><I>Mores nostros ordina, tollens inperfectum,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt pes noster tendere qeat in directum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 25, v. 12.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="193">Heil Modur, bi-hold &thorn;ou</L>
<L>Defautes of &thorn;e peple,</L>
<L>Modres affeccion schewh &thorn;ou now</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;i sones &thorn;at ben feble;</L>
<L>Ordeyn &thorn;ou vr maners so,</L>
<L>Weyuyng inparfyt &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vr fot mowe &thorn;en go</L>
<L N="200">Streiht for&thorn; wi&thorn;-outen lettyng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Dominus illuminacio mea &amp; salus mea: quem timebo?</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 26 (27).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue mater domini suos protegentis,</I></L>
<L><I>Qui cateruas hominum fregit in trecentis:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. increcentis. cf. Ps. 26, v. 3, et Jud. 7, 6-14 (application made to Gideon).</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Queso nos respicias oculis attentis,</I></L>
<L><I>Procul pellens tenebras erumpnose mentis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil modur of &thorn;at lord al on</L>
<L>&THORN;at his men do&thorn; defende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; &thorn;re hundred ouercom</L>
<L N="204">Gret cumpaignies and schende:</L>
<L>I preye &thorn;e, ladi, vs bi-holde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;yn e&yogh;en clere,</L>
<L>Derknesses fer fro us folde</L>
<L N="208">And kepe vr &thorn;ouhtes here.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Ad te domine clamabo, deus meus ne sileas a me: ne quando taceas a me &amp; as [similabor] d[escen|dentibus] in lacum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 27 (28).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo domini mater illibata,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius est ex utero caro deodata</I>,
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="59"></L>
<L><I>Caro carnem liberans, caro mori nata,</I></L>
<L><I>Caro que refloruit morte triumphata.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 27, v. 7.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="209">Heil Mayden of a lord,</L>
<L>Modur saun&yogh; tecche I-&thorn;riue,</L>
<L>Of whos wombe &thorn;orwh Godus word</L>
<L N="212">fflesch to god was &yogh;iue;</L>
<L>&THORN;at flesch dilyuered flessche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at flesch boren was to dye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at flesch refloured &thorn;at was nessche,</L>
<L N="216">Of de&thorn; &thorn;at hedde Maystrie.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Afferte domino filij dei, Afferte domino filios arietum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 28 (29).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam filius fratres adoptauit,</I></L>
<L><I>Quos &amp; dei filios recte nominauit.</I></L>
<L><I>Eant ergo filij quos ad se vocauit,</I></L>
<L><I>Agnos Innocencie ferant quos</I> mandauit.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="217">Heil be whom godus sone, i-wis,</L>
<L>Bre&thorn;eren him wolde purchase,</L>
<L>To beo clept godus sones of blis</L>
<L N="220">Be rihte In vche place.</L>
<L>Go&thorn; nou sones deuoutelye</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ha&thorn; called him to,</L>
<L>Offre&thorn; &thorn;e lombes of Innocensye,</L>
<L N="224">ffor he comaundet so.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Exaltabo te domine, quoniam suscepisti me, nec de|lectasti</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 29 (30).</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. dilatasti</NOTE> <I>inimicos meos super me.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue tabernaculum cristo dedicatum,</I></L>
<L><I>Supra Matres optinens sola principatum,</I></L>
<L><I>Nostris aptans usibus saccum veteratum</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 29, v. 12, Gen. 37, 31.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Propter nostra vulnera gratis vulneratum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="225">Heil tabernacle of crist</L>
<L>Halewed wor&thorn;ily,</L>
<L>Of alle Modrus i-wist</L>
<L N="228">To haue &thorn;e pris only:</L>
<L>Mak us redi<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <SUP>g</SUP>redi, r. grei&thorn;e?</NOTE> to vr vs</L>
<L>&THORN;e olde sacke verreyly</L>
<L>&THORN;at for ur woundes as refus</L>
<L N="232">Was wounded wilfully.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>IN te domine speraui, non confundar in eternum:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 30 (31).</NOTE> <I>in Iusticia tua libera me.</I>
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="60"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue nostrum gaudium, nostra fortitudo,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius est dulcedinis magna multitudo:</I></L>
<L><I>In te nostra sit sita spei certitudo,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius piis laudibus libere desudo.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="233">Heil vr Ioye of wor&thorn;inesse,</L>
<L>And vr streng&thorn;e &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>Whos noble swetnesse</L>
<L N="236">Is muchel and gret also:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e beo myn hope i-set</L>
<L>Sadly, in certeyn,</L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;in heriing nou I swet</L>
<L N="240">ffreoliche and nou&yogh;t in veyn.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Beati quorum remisse sunt iniquitates, et quorum tecta sunt peccata.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 31 (32).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius utero deus est deorum</I></L>
<L><I>ffactus homo, tollere spinas delictorum.</I></L>
<L><I>O beatus vterus, &amp; beati quorum</I></L>
<L><I>ffecit se participem factor seculorum!</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="241">Heil of whos wombe verrey</L>
<L>God is of goddus alle</L>
<L>I-maad mon, to don a-wey</L>
<L N="244">&THORN;e &thorn;ornes of synne and falle.</L>
<L>A, blessed is &thorn;at wombe so sad!</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei ben blessed also</L>
<L>&THORN;at god ha&thorn; partyng-felawes maad,</L>
<L N="248">To dwelle wi&thorn; him euer-mo!</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Exultate iusti in domino: rectos decet laudacio.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 32 (33).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam reuocat dominus eiectum,</I></L>
<L><I>Que[m]</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Que, r. qui?</NOTE> <I>a solo patrio peregre profectum</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. pro grege perfectum</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Medicus dum reperit vicijs infectum,</I></L>
<L><I>Morbi causas abstulit simul &amp; effectum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="249">Heil bi whom God called a-&yogh;eyn</L>
<L>Hem &thorn;at weoren out cast,</L>
<L>&THORN;at from his ffadur seete certeyn</L>
<L N="252">Went for&thorn; in gret hast,</L>
<L>Leche, &thorn;at monkynde &thorn;at was mad</L>
<L>Parfyt, he fonde infecte,</L>
<L>Causes of sikenes &thorn;en he forbad</L>
<L N="256">And eke &thorn;erof &thorn;e efecte.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm"><PB REF="00000069.tif" N="61">
<P><I>Benedicam dominum in omni tempore: semper laus eius in ore meo.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 33 (34).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue mater pariens fructum benedictum,</I></L>
<L><I>Tactu cuius soluitur Eue maledictum,</I></L>
<L><I>Que transgressa temere tangens interdictum</I></L>
<L><I>Transtulit in posteros ulcionis ictum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="257">Heil Modur bringinge for&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;e feireste fruit i-founde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e touche of whuche was so muche wor&thorn;</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;at Eues curs was vnbounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche trespaced folilyche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was forboden touchyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e strok of veniaunce sikerliche</L>
<L N="264">Laft to hem &thorn;at were comyng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Ivdica domine nocentes me, expugna inpugnantes me.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 34 (35).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam dominus apprehendens scutum</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 34, v. 2.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>In extento brachio propulit astutum;</I></L>
<L><I>Qui de scuto</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. sputo</NOTE> proprio <I>comiscendo lutum</I></L>
<L><I>Ceco lumen homini reddidit acutum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">Heil beo [whom] &thorn;e lord of liht</L>
<L>A scheld tok priuely,</L>
<L>And in his hond I-streyht ariht</L>
<L N="268">Put of his enemy;</L>
<L>&THORN;at of his owne propre cheld (!),</L>
<L>Mengyng &thorn;erwi&thorn; cley,</L>
<L>As moni men &thorn;o bi-heold,</L>
<L N="272">Maad a blynt mon se<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. so</NOTE> al-wey.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Dixit iniustus ut delinquat in semet ipso ; non est timor dei ante oculos eius.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 35 (36).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue templum gracie, tronus deitatis,</I></L>
<L><I>Torrens affluencie, domus vbertatis:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 35, v. 9.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Per te-solam reddita spes est desperatis:</I></L>
<L><I>ffluctuantis Anchoram rege nostre ratis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="273">Heil temple of grace,</L>
<L>Trone of &thorn;e godhed,</L>
<L>Plenteuous ryuer in vche place,</L>
<L N="276">And eke hous of freohed:</L>
<L>Beo &thorn;e, hope is &yogh;olde a&yogh;eyn</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at hedde dispeir:
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="62"></L>
<L>Gouerne &thorn;e Anker in certeyn</L>
<L N="280">Of vr floteryng schip in Eir!</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>NOli emulari in malignantibus, neque zelaueris facientes iniquitatem.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 36 (37).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue carens simili, nusquam malignata</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 36, v. 9.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Dignitatis titulo triplicis</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. duplicis</NOTE> <I>ornata:</I></L>
<L><I>Virgo mater diceris; iungis</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. iunge</NOTE> separata,</L>
<L><I>Es vtrumque, docet hec fides oculata.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="281">Heil &thorn;at hast non lyk to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; vuel neuer ouer-come,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;reo maner of dignite</L>
<L N="284">Wi&thorn; title maad feir and nome:</L>
<L>Maiden and Modur &thorn;ou art told,</L>
<L>Disseuered ioy[n]e[st]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. ioye</NOTE> &thorn;ou goodlye;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art bo&thorn;e two, as we be-hold&mdash;</L>
<L N="288">Vs teche&thorn; vr fei&thorn; at e&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Domine, ne in furore tuo arguas me, neque in ira tua corripias me.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 37 (38).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue sancti spiritus fecundata rore,</I></L>
<L><I>Conseruato pariens castitatis flore:</I></L>
<L><I>Queso fac ne arguat iudex in furore</I></L>
<L><I>Quos a morte proprio redemit cruore.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="289">Heil wi&thorn; deuh I-mad feir</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e holigost, parde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou beryng child wi&thorn;-outen leir</L>
<L N="292">Kepst flour of chastite:</L>
<L>Mak &thorn;ou &thorn;at he us not missey,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iuge, in no woodnesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he bouht wi&thorn; his blood verrey</L>
<L N="296">ffrom de&thorn;, bo&thorn;e More and lesse.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Dixi: custodiam vias meas, vt non delinquam in lingua mea.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 38 (39).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius filio psalmus decantatur,</I></L>
<L><I>Et eiusdem habitus in quo figuratur</I></L>
<L><I>Qui terrena transiens</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 38, v. 7.</NOTE> <I>in hoc delectatur</I></L>
<L><I>Si uel mentis gressibus capud consequatur.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="297">Heil of whos sone deuoutely</L>
<L>A psalm is songe wi&thorn; cure,</L>
<L>And of his habit ful sotily</L>
<L N="300">In whuche is suche figure
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="63"></L>
<L>Whos, laft &thorn;is world outerly,</L>
<L>Dilyte&thorn; him to take heed</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; steppes of good &thorn;ouht holy</L>
<L N="304">To suwen crist, vr hed.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Exspectans expectaui dominum, et intendit michi.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 39 (40).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue tabernaculum regis inpollutum,</I></L>
<L><I>Per quam soluit dominus ope destitutum:</I></L>
<L><I>Tuis iuua meritis sponte prouolutum</I></L>
<L><I>In lacum miserie &amp; in fecis lutum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 39, v. 2.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="305">Heil tabernacle of kyng</L>
<L>In-pollute, wondur clen;</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;e &thorn;e lord of alle &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="308">&THORN;at hedden non help leosed men:</L>
<L>Help &thorn;orwh &thorn;i wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>Him &thorn;at is woundun al-wey</L>
<L>In &thorn;e lake of wrecchednesse</L>
<L N="312">And in &thorn;e ful&thorn;e of cley.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Beatus qui intelligit super egenum &amp; pauperem:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. pauperum</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 40 (41).</NOTE> <I>in die mala liberabit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. liberauit</NOTE> <I>eum dominus.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue solis</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. solus</NOTE> <I>ciuitas quam dauid erexit,</I></L>
<L><I>De qua sol iusticie nube tectus exit,</I></L>
<L><I>Qui de summis pauperum causas intellexit</I></L>
<L><I>Et egroto similis egros non despexit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="313">Heil of Sonne &thorn;e cite</L>
<L>&THORN;at dauid reised on ende,</L>
<L>Of whom &thorn;e sonne of riht, wuste</L>
<L N="316">Wi&thorn; cloude, hit gan for&thorn; wende;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e causes of pore and meke</L>
<L>ffrom heuene heede he tok</L>
<L>And made him lyk to &thorn;e seke</L>
<L N="320">And sek folk nouht forsok.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Quemadmodum desiderat ceruus ad fontes aquarum, ita desiderat anima mea ad te, deus.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 41 (42).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue de qua prodeunt vbertatis riui,</I></L>
<L><I>De qua in-undans profluit aqua fontis uiui:</I></L>
<L><I>Peto, mater, ueniam, qui per sordes</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. sordis</NOTE> <I>iui;</I></L>
<L><I>ffac ut fontem siciam magis quam sitiui.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="321">Heil from whom<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. whon</NOTE> gon ay for&thorn;</L>
<L>Riueers of plente rif,
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="64"></L>
<L>Of whom flowe&thorn; of gret wor&thorn;</L>
<L N="324">&THORN;e watres of welle of lyf.</L>
<L>Modur, ich aske nou &thorn;i merci:</L>
<L>Bi ful&thorn;es haue I gon;</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at welle mak me &thorn;ursti</L>
<L N="328">Oftur &thorn;en I haue don.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Iudica me, deus, &amp; discerne causam meam de gente non sancta, ab homine iniquo &amp; doloso erue me.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 42 (43).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius thalamo iudex est egressus</I></L>
<L><I>Causas qui determinat, uindicat ex[c]essus;</I></L>
<L><I>Per quem mentis oculus tenebris oppressus</I></L>
<L><I>Discat vt in lumine ponat suos gressus.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="329">Heil from whos chaumbre her</L>
<L>A Iuge is for&thorn; passet</L>
<L>&THORN;at determine&thorn; vr causes cler</L>
<L N="332">And punissche&thorn; hem &thorn;at trespasse&thorn;;</L>
<L>Beo whom of vr &thorn;ouht &thorn;e e&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; derknes &thorn;at is ouer-fet,</L>
<L>Mow lerne &thorn;enne wi&thorn; liht in hy&yogh;e</L>
<L N="336">His steppes forte set.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Deus auribus nostris audiuimus, patres nostri an|nunciauerunt nobis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 43 (44).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius filius prouehit egentes</I></L>
<L><I>Et affligit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. affugit</NOTE> <I>improbos in nos insurgentes:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 43, v. 8.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Pie queso dirigat nostras in se mentes,</I></L>
<L><I>Reprimendo turbinum motus iminentes.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="337">Heil whos wor&thorn;i sone</L>
<L>Bringe&thorn; for&thorn; neodful, certeyn,</L>
<L>And proude puite&thorn; in tribulacione</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;at risen vs a&yogh;eyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;at al vr &thorn;ouhtes in to him</L>
<L>He dresse, I &thorn;e preye,</L>
<L>And refreyn of tempest grim</L>
<L N="344">&THORN;e sturinges in &thorn;is weye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Eructauit cor meum verbum bonum; dico ego opera mea regi.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 44 (45).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam genitor verbum eructauit,</I></L>
<L><I>Verbum quod hominibus se contemperauit,</I></L>
<L><I>Qui</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Quod</NOTE> <I>dei &amp; hominum federa dictauit</I></L>
<L><I>Et pro nobis moriens mortem relegauit.</I>
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="65"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="345">Heil be whom bi&yogh;etere</L>
<L>A word sum tyme for&thorn; sende,</L>
<L>Word &thorn;at to men here</L>
<L N="348">Him-self tempred and bende;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche of god and of man</L>
<L>Endited feire &thorn;e bonde,</L>
<L>And for us alle diede &thorn;an</L>
<L N="352">And de&thorn; put out of londe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Deus noster refugium &amp; uirtus, adiutor in tribulaci|onibus que inuenerunt nos nimis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 45 (46).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue tabernaculum domini virtutum,</I></L>
<L><I>In quo sumens dominus nostre carnis lutum,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt captiuum redimat ope destitutum,</I></L>
<L><I>Arcum fortis conterit &amp; comburit scutum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 45, v. 9.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="353">Heil of &thorn;at lord &thorn;e tabernacle</L>
<L>&THORN;at is of vertue al-way,</L>
<L>In whom he tok wi&thorn;-oute obstacle</L>
<L N="356">Of vr flesch &thorn;e Clay,</L>
<L>To Bugge a&yogh;ein &thorn;e wrecched wiht</L>
<L>&THORN;at non hope felede;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e strong he brak in fiht</L>
<L N="360">&THORN;e bouwe and eke &thorn;e schelde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Omnes gentes plaudite manibus, iubilate deo in uoce exultacionis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 46 (47).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius filius regnat super gentes,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius psallunt nomini manibus plaudentes.</I></L>
<L><I>Iubilemus igitur attollendo mentes,</I></L>
<L><I>Indefesso capiti cristo adherentes.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="361">Heil whos sone so gent</L>
<L>Ouer folk regne&thorn;, parfey;</L>
<L>To whos name men verrey[me]nt</L>
<L N="364">Syngyng wi&thorn; hondes pley.</L>
<L>Make we nou Ioye wi&thorn; al vr list,</L>
<L>Vr &thorn;ouhtes an hei&yogh; resynge</L>
<L>To vr noble hed crist,</L>
<L N="368">To him euer cleuynge.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P>MAgnus dominus <I>&amp; laudabilis nimis, in ciuitate dei nostri, in monte</I> sancto <I>tuo.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. eius</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 47 (48).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo generans regem sempiternum</I></L>
<L><I>Quique noster deus est, deus in eternum,</I>
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="66"></L>
<L><I>Qui pro nobis moriens spoliat auernum,</I></L>
<L><I>Solium nos faciens scandere supernum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="369">Heil Maiden bringinge for&thorn; wi&thorn; mood</L>
<L>&THORN;e euerlastinge kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche is vre god so good,</L>
<L N="372">God wi&thorn;-outen endyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;at for us whon he dude dye,</L>
<L>Al to-spoyled helle,</L>
<L>To his ffadur trone on hi&yogh;e</L>
<L N="376">To make us stye to dwelle.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Audite hec omnes gentes, auribus percipite omnes qui habitatis terram.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 48 (49).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue nostrum gaudium, nostre spes salutis,</I></L>
<L><I>Per quam cecis redditur lux, &amp; sermo mutis:</I></L>
<L><I>Nobis innocencie uestibus exutis</I></L>
<L><I>Redde queso graciam statumque salutis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="377">Heil vr Ioye &thorn;at art certeyn,</L>
<L>And eke hope of ur hele,</L>
<L>Bi whom to blynde is &yogh;olde a&yogh;eyn</L>
<L N="380">Siht, and word to doumbe at mele:</L>
<L>To us naked in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Of clo&thorn;es of innocencie,</L>
<L>We preye &thorn;e gete us nou grace</L>
<L N="384">And staat of vertues hy&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Deus deorum dominus locutus est, et uocauit terram.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 49 (50).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue salutarium summa gaudiorum,</I></L>
<L><I>Saluatorem generans &amp; deum deorum,</I></L>
<L><I>Qui misertus miseris &amp; consors eorum</I></L>
<L><I>Culpas lauans pertulit penas peccatorum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">Heil summe of honour,</L>
<L>Of heleful ioyes i calle,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou brouhtust for&thorn; vr saueour,</L>
<L N="388">God of goddus alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on wrecches hedde Merci</L>
<L>And wox heore felawe anon,</L>
<L>Wasschynge heore gultus witerli</L>
<L N="392">And tok vr peynes him on.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>MIserere mei deus, secundum magnam misericor|diam tuam.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 50 (51).</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="67"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue uirgo generans, nostri miserere,</I></L>
<L><I>Languescentis animi morbos intuere;</I></L>
<L><I>Tu miserta miseris et compassa vere,</I></L>
<L><I>Morbi causas auferens mentibus medere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="393">Heil Maiden Mylde and meke,</L>
<L>On Monkuynde haue Merci,</L>
<L>Eueles of soules &thorn;at beo seke</L>
<L N="396">Bi-hold &thorn;ou witerly;</L>
<L>Of wrecches haue Merci verrey</L>
<L>And eke Compassioun,</L>
<L>Causes of vueles doynge a-wey</L>
<L N="400">To hele &thorn;ouhtes beo boun.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Quid gloriaris in malicia, qui potens es in ini|quitate?</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 51 (52).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue was mundicie continens vnguentum,</I></L>
<L><I>Veteris malicie comprimens fermentum:</I></L>
<L><I>Cordis nostri comprime motum turbulentum,</I></L>
<L><I>Tue nobis gracie conferens augmentum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="401">Heil vessel of Clannesse</L>
<L>Holdyng Oygnement I-nouh,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e olde wrecchednesse</L>
<L N="404">Holdyng doun sourdouh,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mouinges &thorn;at ben troublus</L>
<L>Of vr herte refreinynge,</L>
<L>&YOGH;iuinge<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &yogh;iue?</NOTE> of &thorn;i grace to vs</L>
<L N="408">Euer-more echynge.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P>Dix[i]t <I>insipiens in corde suo: non est deus.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 52 (53).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue nostri generis presens ad tutelam:</I></L>
<L><I>Audi quam effundimus gemitus loquelam:</I></L>
<L><I>Tu corrumpi</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. corrumpe</NOTE> <I>nescia tolle</I> cor[r]uptelam</L>
<L><I>Et morbosis mentibus adhibe medelam.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="409">Heil &thorn;at euer art present</L>
<L>Vr kuynde forte defende:</L>
<L>Here ur speche wi&thorn; good entent</L>
<L N="412">&THORN;at we for&thorn; to &thorn;e sende:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;at wost no corrupcioun,</L>
<L>ffrom us do hit a-wey,</L>
<L>To seke &thorn;ouhtus loke &thorn;ou beo boun</L>
<L N="416">Medicyn to do verrey.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm"><PB REF="00000076.tif" N="68">
<P><I>Deus, in nomine tuo saluum me fac, &amp; in uirtute tua iudica me.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 53 (54).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius filius patri coequalis</I></L>
<L><I>Nobis se contemperans factus est mortalis.</I></L>
<L><I>Nos experiencia doceat realis</I></L>
<L><I>Quod in eius nomine saluemur a malis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="417">Heil whos sone glorious,</L>
<L>To his ffadur euene,</L>
<L>Ha&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;at</NOTE> comformed<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. confermed</NOTE> him to us</L>
<L N="420">I-maad of dedly steuene:</L>
<L>Nou beo we tauht spiritualy</L>
<L>Beo experience<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. experimence</NOTE> Real,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in his nome ful sikerly</L>
<L N="424">Saued we ben from eueles alle.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Exaudi, deus, oracionem meam, et ne despexeris de|precacionem meam; intende michi et exaudi me.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 54 (55).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue secretarium exaudicionis,</I></L>
<L><I>Nostre verba suscipe deprecacionis</I></L>
<L><I>Nosque tue gracie predotatos donis</I></L>
<L><I>Ad diuine transferas pacem visionis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="425">Heil &thorn;ou holy sacrarie,</L>
<L>Vr askynges euer heryng,</L>
<L>Vr<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;e</NOTE> wordus &thorn;ou take deuoutly</L>
<L N="428">Al-wei of vre preying;</L>
<L>Vs also &thorn;at of &thorn;i grace</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &yogh;iftus maade riche ariht,</L>
<L>Of pees translate to &thorn;e place</L>
<L N="432">Of heueneliche siht.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>MIserere mei deus, quoniam conculcauit me homo: tota die inpugnans tribulauit me.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 55 (56).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue Mater venie, potens misereri:</I></L>
<L><I>In tuorum numero fac nos recenceri,</I></L>
<L><I>Et cum ventilacio</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. ventulacio</NOTE> <I>ceperit haberi,</I></L>
<L><I>Iram nobis tempera iudicis seueri.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="433">Heil Modur of for&yogh;ifnesse,</L>
<L>Mihti to haue merci:</L>
<L>Make us be founde &thorn;orwh &thorn;i godnesse</L>
<L N="436">Among &thorn;i seruauns herti;</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;e wynewyng schal be-ginne</L>
<L>To parte euel from good,
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="69"></L>
<L>Tempre &thorn;ou &thorn;en to us wi&thorn; &thorn;i ginne</L>
<L N="440">Of wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;e Iewes<NOTE PLACE="marg">= juge's</NOTE> mod.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>MIserere mei deus, miserere mei, quoniam in te confidit anima mea.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 56 (57).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue nostri generis potens aduocata:</I></L>
<L><I>Miserere miseris, misereri nata;</I></L>
<L><I>Nos qui per te canimus solui iudicata,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. medicata</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Per te solui petimus: solue postulata.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="441">Heil, for &thorn;ou art of monkynde</L>
<L>An Aduoket mihti:</L>
<L>Haue merci, and haue in mynde</L>
<L N="444">Of wrecches &thorn;ou haue merci;</L>
<L>We &thorn;at syngen &thorn;at bi &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at iuged is to paye,</L>
<L>We asken alle vnbounde to be,</L>
<L N="448">To<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;ou</NOTE> pay &thorn;at asked is ay&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>SI uere utique iusticiam loquimini, recte</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. recta</NOTE> <I>iudicate filij hominum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 57 (58).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue que iusticiam semper es locuta,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius ope demonum fraus est imminuta:</I></L>
<L><I>Senciat &amp; sapiat</I> per <I>te plebs adiuta</I></L>
<L><I>Libertati pristine</I> quo[d]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. quo</NOTE> <I>sit restituta.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="449">Heil &thorn;ou &thorn;at rihtwysnesse</L>
<L>Hast i-spoken al-way,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whos help &thorn;e queyntenesse</L>
<L N="452">Of &thorn;e fend is lutled ay;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e peple holpen beo bi &thorn;e,</L>
<L>ffeele &thorn;ei hit in certeyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e furste liberte</L>
<L N="456">&THORN;ei beo restored a-&yogh;eyn.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Eripe me de inimicis meis, deus meus, et ab insur|gentibus in me libera me.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 58 (59).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue mater nesciens in delicto thorum,</I></L>
<L><I>Ad quam clamat iugite[r] turba filiorum:</I></L>
<L><I>Nos a malis eripe, quos a uia morum</I></L>
<L><I>Detorquere satagit tractus viciorum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="457">Heil modur &thorn;at nost sikerliche</L>
<L>Trespas don abedde,</L>
<L>To whom &thorn;e peple bisiliche</L>
<L N="460">Crie&thorn; and longe ha&thorn; gredde:
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="70"></L>
<L>Lyuere vs from eueles euerichon,</L>
<L>Whuche from good maner</L>
<L>Vs to wi&thorn;-drawe is bisy mon</L>
<L N="464">&THORN;e drauht of vices her.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Deus, repulisti nos &amp; dest[r]uxisti nos, iratus es et misertus es nobis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 59 (60).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam deitas carne palliata</I></L>
<L><I>Idumeam</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">of. Ps. 59, v.9.</NOTE> <I>visitat corrigens errata:</I></L>
<L><I>Tibi, mater, iugiter psallat plebs renata,</I></L>
<L><I>Dei participio per te sociata.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="465">Heil beo whom &thorn;e godhed</L>
<L>In vr flesch was laced,</L>
<L>So Idumeam he visyted</L>
<L N="468">To mende &thorn;at hedde trespaced:</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, Modur of worschipe,</L>
<L>Synge&thorn; peple &thorn;at cristen is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to Godus felaschipe</L>
<L N="472">&THORN;ey mowe beo ioyned in blis.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Exaudi, deus, deprecacionem meam, intende ora|cioni mee.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 60 (61).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue lux exposita loco preminenti,</I></L>
<L><I>Lux illustrans omnia radio patenti:</I></L>
<L><I>Nos a malis omnibus serues in presenti,</I></L>
<L><I>Lumen verum conferens nubilose menti.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="473">Heil, &thorn;ou hast sent for&thorn; liht</L>
<L>In place most principal,</L>
<L>Liht euer schynynge briht</L>
<L N="476">Wi&thorn; open bem ouer-al:</L>
<L>Kep us from vuel &thorn;at us ha&thorn; souht,</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;at we dwellen here,</L>
<L>&YOGH;iuynge to vre derke &thorn;ouht</L>
<L N="480">Verrey liht and clere.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>NOnne deo subiecta erit anima mea? ab ipso enim salutare meum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 61 (62)</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam deitas peregre profecta</I></L>
<L><I>Visitauit exules, nube carnis tecta:</I></L>
<L><I>Nostra per te deo sit anima subiecta,</I></L>
<L><I>Ad soluendas domino grates circumspecta.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="481">Heil beo whom &thorn;e godhed</L>
<L>Went for&thorn; a-pilgrimage
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="71"></L>
<L>And &thorn;e flemed visyted,</L>
<L N="484">Huled wi&thorn; fflesch of age:</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;e vr soules to God, ladi,</L>
<L>Soget beo &thorn;ei and meke,</L>
<L>To &thorn;onke vr lord ful hertily</L>
<L N="488">Ay to<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;ei?</NOTE> beo bisy eke.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Deus deus meus, ad te de luce vigilo.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 62 (63).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue vite pabulum, virginum lucerna,</I></L>
<L><I>Quam plus ditat ceteris gracia superna:</I></L>
<L><I>Pietate filijs subueni materna,</I></L>
<L><I>Sanctitatis adipe sacians interna.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="489">Heil, &thorn;ou art code of lyf,</L>
<L>And Maydens cke lanterne;</L>
<L>Whom bi-foren o&thorn;ur riche and rif</L>
<L N="492">Ha&thorn; maad &thorn;e grace of heuene:</L>
<L>Help &thorn;i sones of &thorn;i godnesse</L>
<L>As Modur of pite,</L>
<L>ffullyng hem of &thorn;i fatnesse</L>
<L N="496">Of inward saunctite.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Exaudi, deus, oracionem meam cum deprecor: a timore inimici eripe animam meam.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 63 (64).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo generans per quem</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. quam</NOTE> <I>defecerunt</I></L>
<L><I>Hij qui velud gladium</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. gladij</NOTE> <I>linguas acuerunt</I>;<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 63, v. 3.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Qui tendentes laqueos, in quos inciderunt,</I></L>
<L><I>Ex defectu proprio nobis p[r]ofuerunt.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. posuerunt</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="497">Heil Mayden, him for&thorn; bringynge</L>
<L>Be whom al &thorn;ei dude fayle</L>
<L>&THORN;at hedden tonges of scharpynge</L>
<L N="500">As<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. And</NOTE> swerd &thorn;at kerue&thorn; Mayle;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei maden panters for o&thorn;ur men</L>
<L>And fullen in to &thorn;e same;</L>
<L>Of heor oune defaute &thorn;en</L>
<L N="504">To vs &thorn;e profyt came.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>TE decet ymnus, deus, in syon, et tibi reddetur uotum in Ierusalem.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 64 (65).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam deitas, carnis indumento</I></L>
<L><I>Tecta, curat morbidum gracie fomento:</I></L>
<L><I>Queso fac ut centupli gaudens incremento</I></L>
<L><I>Habundare valeam vallium</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. valli non</NOTE> <I>frumento.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 64, v. 13.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="72"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="505">Heil &thorn;orwh whom godhed i-wis</L>
<L>Of vre flesch tok clo&thorn;inge,</L>
<L>fforte helen us of seknis</L>
<L N="508">&THORN;orwh his grace helpynge.</L>
<L>&THORN;at i mou, Ioynge, prei i &thorn;e,</L>
<L>An hundredfold of encrece and hete,</L>
<L>Haue plentiuouse charite</L>
<L N="512">Of &thorn;e valeye of whete.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>IVbilate deo omnis terra, psalmum dicite nomini eius, date gloriam laudi eius.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 65 (66).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo generans plebis salutare,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius laudes resonent celum, terra, mare,</I></L>
<L><I>Qui naturam hominis uolens exaltare</I></L>
<L><I>Moriendo voluit mortem terminare.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="513">Heil Mayden, bringyng for&thorn;</L>
<L>Of folk &thorn;e hel&thorn;e, parde,</L>
<L>Of whos herying sounen in wor&thorn;</L>
<L N="516">Heuene, Er&thorn;e and S&eacute;&eacute;,</L>
<L>Him &thorn;at al monkynde</L>
<L>Wolde en-haunce wel hi&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And so for us eke dyinge</L>
<L N="520">Put out de&thorn;es ei&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Deus misereatur nostri &amp; benedicat nobis: illuminet uultum suum super nos &amp; misereatur nostri.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 66 (67).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam miseris deus miseretur,</I></L>
<L><I>Per quam</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. quem?</NOTE> <I>nostri generis scelus aboletur:</I></L>
<L><I>Per te sic miseria nostra releuetur</I></L>
<L><I>Vt in finem gaudio uero permutetur.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="521">Heil &thorn;orwh whom God ha&thorn; muynde</L>
<L>On wrecches and ha&thorn; merci,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whom al Monkynde</L>
<L N="524">Clansed is &thorn;at was gulti:</L>
<L>Beo &thorn;e al vr wrecchednis</L>
<L>So beo releued a-wey</L>
<L>&THORN;at in to &thorn;e ende of<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. wi&thorn;?</NOTE> ioye and blis</L>
<L N="528">hit beo chaunged verrey.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Exurgat deus &amp; dissipentur inimici eius, &amp; fugiant qui oderunt eum a facie eius.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 67 (68).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue de qua natus est triumphator mortis,</I></L>
<L><I>Deus ex te particeps factus nostre sortis,</I>
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="73"></L>
<L><I>Qui captiuos eruens ab inferni portis</I></L>
<L><I>Reddat nos consorcio celice cohortis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="529">Heil of whom boren was her</L>
<L>He &thorn;at de&thorn; ouercom,</L>
<L>God of &thorn;e vr parciner</L>
<L N="532">Was maad and vre lot nom.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at wrecches wi&thorn; worschip</L>
<L>Lyuered fro &yogh;ates of helle,</L>
<L>Restore vs to &thorn;e felaschip</L>
<L N="536">Wi&thorn; heuenlich folk to dwelle.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>SAluum me fac deus, quoniam intrauerunt aque usque ad animam meam.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 68 (69).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue stella fulgida, stella salutaris,</I></L>
<L><I>Stella de qua prodijt radius solaris:</I></L>
<L><I>Mentis pelle tenebras, nec nos paciaris</I></L>
<L><I>Absorberi fluctibus procellosi maris.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 68, v. 16.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="537">Heil &thorn;ou sterre schynyng briht,</L>
<L>Of vr hele &thorn;ou art sterre;</L>
<L>Sterre from whom went for&thorn; riht</L>
<L N="540">&THORN;e Sonne-Beem, our herre:</L>
<L>&THORN;e derknesses of vr &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>Make &thorn;ou a-wey to fle;</L>
<L>&THORN;at we be swolewed, suffre &thorn;ou nouht,</L>
<L N="544">Wi&thorn; tempestes of &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute;.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Deus in adiutorium meum intende, domine ad adiu|uandum me festina.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 69 (70).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue vallis humilis, in quam cum descendit</I></L>
<L><I>Deus verus, Abrahe semen apprehendit,</I></L>
<L><I>Et sic adiutorium miseris inpendit</I></L>
<L><I>Conterendo laqueos hostis quos tetendit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="545">Heil valeye of humilite,</L>
<L>In whom whon &thorn;er doun cam</L>
<L>Verrey God &thorn;at tok of &thorn;e</L>
<L N="548">&THORN;e seed of Abraham,</L>
<L>On such maner he &yogh;af helpyn[g]</L>
<L>To wrecches &thorn;at weoren in wer,</L>
<L>&THORN;e panters al to-brekyng</L>
<L N="552">&THORN;at vre Enemy made heer.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>In te domine speraui, non confundar in eternum; in</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 70 (71).</NOTE> <I>iusticia tua libera me &amp; eripe me.</I>
<PB REF="00000082.tif" N="74"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue vite ianua, speciem</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. species?</NOTE> <I>virtutis,</I></L>
<L><I>Protectorem generans ope destitutis:</I></L>
<L><I>Nostrum sis refugium, nostre spes salutis</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 70, v. 3 ff.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Per quam dure soluitur iugum seruitutis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="553">Heil &yogh;ate of lyf wi&thorn; honour,</L>
<L>Of vertues &thorn;ou art spice,</L>
<L>Bringyng for&thorn; &thorn;e protectour</L>
<L N="556">To helples &thorn;orw vice;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art refuyt to eueri age,</L>
<L>Hope of hele i-founde,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whom now of bondage</L>
<L N="560">&THORN;e harde &yogh;ok is vnbounde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Deus, iudicium tuum regi da, et iusticiam tuam filio regis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 71 (72).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue celi pluuia vellus iroratum</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 71, v. 6.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Indumentum preparans regi purpuratum,</I></L>
<L><I>Qui se nostri generis gerens aduocatum</I></L>
<L><I>ffecit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. fferit</NOTE> <I>finem litibus, finem perbeatum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="561">Heil, of heuene &thorn;ou art reyn,</L>
<L>And fleos wi&thorn; dewh i-wet,</L>
<L>Clo&thorn;ing of purpre &thorn;ou art, certeyn,</L>
<L N="564">To &thorn;at kyng arayed and met,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him-self to vr kuynde</L>
<L>Schewed him so Aduoket,</L>
<L>Of alle stryues made an ende,</L>
<L N="568">In blisse vs forte set.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">This stanza refers to Ps. 71, v. 9-12, but is headed in the MS. by Ps. 72 (Quam bonus), and so the next Qua|trains till Ps. 78 have the wrong heading.</NOTE><I>Aue cuius filio gens ab Oriente</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 71, 9 ff.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Trina trino detulit, stella precedente;</I></L>
<L><I>Sic iunctura fidei duos u[n]iente,</I></L>
<L><I>Liberauit pauperem deus a potente.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 71, v. 12.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="569">Heil [to] whos sone gent</L>
<L>&THORN;reo kynges fro &thorn;e Est</L>
<L>Comen feire wi&thorn; heore present,</L>
<L N="572">A sterre hem ladde best;</L>
<L>So &thorn;e ioynture of &thorn;e fey</L>
<L>Twi&yogh;en &thorn;en onynge,</L>
<L>God &thorn;e pore lyuered awey</L>
<L N="576">ffrom &thorn;e mihti nuwynge.<NOTE PLACE="marg">= ags. niowunga anew</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Quam bonus, israel, deus hijs qui recto sunt corde!</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 72 (73).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo generans orbis architectum</I>,
<PB REF="00000083.tif" N="75"></L>
<L><I>Qui dum mortis moriens terminat effectum,</I></L>
<L><I>Mentis nostre gressibus iter parat rectum,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt nequaquam transeant cordis in affectum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 72, v. 7.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="577">Heil Mayden, for &thorn;ou him beer</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e world do&thorn; keuere;</L>
<L>&THORN;at for vs alle dy&yogh;inge heer</L>
<L N="580">de&thorn; destruyed for euere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e rihte wey a-rayed so</L>
<L>to steppus of vr &thorn;ouhte,</L>
<L>ffor we schulde on nowyse go</L>
<L N="584">As men &thorn;at no-&thorn;ing rouhte.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Vt quid, deus, repulisti in finem? iratus est furor tuus super oues pascue tue?</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 73 (74).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius filius operans salutem</I></L>
<L><I>In terrarum medio</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 73, v. 12.</NOTE> <I>mouet ad uirtutem.</I></L>
<L><I>Erumpnosam remoue, mater, seruitutem,</I></L>
<L><I>Presens ut exilium gaudio permutem.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="585">Heil whos sone has wrouht</L>
<L>Al vr hele sponnewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e myddes of eor&thorn;e vs souht</L>
<L N="588">To meoue us to vertue.</L>
<L>Remuwe &thorn;ou, Modur gentil,</L>
<L>Bondage from vr graunge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mowen vre exil</L>
<L N="592">Wi&thorn; Ioye of heuene chaunge.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Confitebimur tibi, deus, confitebimur, et inuocabimus nomen tuum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 74 (75).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius gracia ueniam meretur</I></L>
<L><I>ffidem qui catholicam pie confitetur:</I></L>
<L><I>Tuis, virgo, meritis precibusque detur</I></L>
<L><I>Vt quod Eua perdidit per te reformetur.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="593">Heil &thorn;orwh whos grace may haue</L>
<L>ffor&yogh;iuenes verreyliche</L>
<L>He &thorn;at &thorn;e holy fei&thorn; wol saue</L>
<L N="596">And knowleche hit mekeliche:</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;i merit, mayden dere,</L>
<L>To vs beo hit i&yogh;iue</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit beo refoormed here</L>
<L N="600">&THORN;at lost was &thorn;orwh Eue.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm"><PB REF="00000084.tif" N="76">
<P><I>NOtus in Iudea deus, in israel magnum nomen eius.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 75 (76).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam dominus pietate motus</I></L>
<L><I>Humilis apparuit in iudea notus:</I></L>
<L><I>ffortem redde spiritum, frangens carnis motus,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt deuote seruiat tibi toti totus.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="601">Heil &thorn;orwh whom &thorn;e lord of miht</L>
<L>Was stured wi&thorn; pite,</L>
<L>And schewed him meke to monnes siht</L>
<L N="604">And knowen was in Iudec:</L>
<L>Mak &thorn;ou vs of spirit strong,</L>
<L>Sturynges of flesche brekyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we ben alle wi&thorn; herte and tong</L>
<L N="608">Deuout to &thorn;e seruyng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>VOce mea ad dominum clamaui; uoce mea ad deum, &amp; intendit michi.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 76 (77).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue mater gracie, gemmis redimita,</I></L>
<L><I>Mater per quam pauperum uox est exaudita:</I></L>
<L><I>Tuus nobis filius in presenti uita</I></L>
<L><I>Via sit &amp; veritas in futuro sita.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="609">Heil modur of grace i calle &thorn;e &thorn;en,</L>
<L>Schinyng as precious stones,</L>
<L>Modur &thorn;orwh whom of &thorn;e pore men</L>
<L N="612">&THORN;e vois is herd at ones:</L>
<L>To vs &thorn;i sone of wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>In &thorn;is lyf hol and some</L>
<L>Beo he bo&thorn;e wey and so&thorn;fastnesse</L>
<L N="616">ffor lyf &thorn;at is to come.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Attendite popule meus legem meam, inclinate aurem uestram in uerba oris mei.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 77 (78).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue terra glorie germinans frumentum</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 77, v. 24 ff.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Animabus conferens uite nutrimentum,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 77, v. 25.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Quod in crucis cornibus a iudeis tentum</I></L>
<L><I>Moriendo centupli tulit incrementum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="617">Heil, &thorn;ou noble lond of blis</L>
<L>Whete wel feir borionyng,</L>
<L>To mennes soules &thorn;ou &yogh;iuest i-wis</L>
<L N="620">Of lyf &thorn;e norisschyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on &thorn;e hornes of &thorn;e Croys</L>
<L>Iewes helden wi&thorn;-outen les;
<PB REF="00000085.tif" N="77"></L>
<L>Dy&yogh;inge he &yogh;af wi&thorn;-outen noys<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. uoys</NOTE></L>
<L N="624">An hundred-fold encrees.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Deus, uenerunt gentes in hereditatem tuam, pollue|runt templum sanctum tuum, posuerunt ierusalem in p[omorum] c[ustodiam].</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 78 (79).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">Latin Quatrain to Ps. 78 wanting.</NOTE>Heil from whom went for&thorn; &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffadur of fadurles,</L>
<L>Whos temple defouled also</L>
<L N="628">&THORN;e peple of corsudnes:</L>
<L>Ioyne &thorn;i seruauns euerichon</L>
<L>To holi cumpaygnye;</L>
<L>&THORN;i sones take in possession</L>
<L N="632">&THORN;at peyned ben heer to dye.<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 78, v. 11.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Qui regis israel, intende; qui deducis uelud ouem Ioseph.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 79 (80).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue lumen fidei, summa spei certe,</I></L>
<L><I>Caritatis vinculum; veritatis per te</I></L>
<L><I>Via nobis paruit: queso nos conuerte,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 79, v. 4.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Et ne mala videant, oculos</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. ouculos</NOTE> auerte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="633">Heil, &thorn;ou art &thorn;e liht of fei&thorn;,</L>
<L>And vr he&yogh;e hope, parde,</L>
<L>And eke of Charite, men sei&thorn;,</L>
<L N="636">&THORN;e bond. &THORN;erfore &thorn;orwh &thorn;e</L>
<L>Of so&thorn;nesse to us &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>Was schewed. we preye &thorn;e now,</L>
<L>Conuerte us, &thorn;at wi&thorn; vr ei&yogh;e</L>
<L N="640">Seo vueles we ne mow.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Exultate deo adiutori nostro, iubilate deo iacob.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 80 (81).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius filius dextera potenti</I></L>
<L><I>Ab egipti cophino</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 80, v. 7.</NOTE> <I>suos in presenti</I></L>
<L><I>Liberando reficit adipe frumenti,</I></L>
<L><I>Et de petra saciat melle profluenti.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 80, v. 17.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="641">Heil whos sone fyn</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his mihti honde</L>
<L>ffrom Egiptus cofyn</L>
<L N="644">Diliuered us her in londe,</L>
<L>After &thorn;at vs refetyng</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e ter<NOTE PLACE="marg">'teer of flowre, amolum,' <I>Pr. Parv.</I></NOTE> of whete,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e ston hony flowyng</L>
<L N="648">ffulled vs at mete.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm"><PB REF="00000086.tif" N="78">
<P><I>Deus stetit in synagoga deorum, in medio autem deos diiudicat.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 81 (82).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius filius stetit in deorum</I></L>
<L><I>Synagoga, iudicans principes eorum;</I></L>
<L><I>Qui pupillos refouens spes est egenorum,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 81, v. 3.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Nos adoptans erigit in spem filiorum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="649">Heil, whos deore sone stod</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Synagoge of goddes</L>
<L>And iuged &thorn;er wi&thorn; stille mood</L>
<L N="652">Princis lyuynge as dogges;</L>
<L>And foode &yogh;af to &thorn;e faderles,</L>
<L>And hope eke to neodi;</L>
<L>Vs to his sones he dude purches</L>
<L N="656">In to hope on hy&yogh;.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Deus, quis similis erit tibi? ne taceas neque com|pescaris, deus.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 82 (83).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam nobis est similis effectus</I></L>
<L><I>Deus, iudex hominum paciens &amp; rectus:</I></L>
<L><I>Purga conciencias, ordinans affectus,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt non nobis noceat noster inperfectus.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="657">Heil &thorn;orwh whom, as we haue mynde,</L>
<L>To us is maad nou lyke</L>
<L>God, &thorn;at iuge is of monkynde,</L>
<L N="660">Suffring and rihtful eke:</L>
<L>Purge &thorn;ou vr concience,</L>
<L>And ordeyne vre delyt,</L>
<L>&THORN;at us greue nou&yogh;t vre offence</L>
<L N="664">Of wrecches in-parfyt.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Quam dilecta tabernacula tua, domine virtutum: concupiscit &amp; deficit anima mea in atria domini.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 83 (84).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue tabernaculum facta deitatis,</I></L>
<L><I>In quo saluat seculum cristus a peccatis:</I></L>
<L><I>Solue queso vinculum nostre prauitatis,</I></L>
<L><I>Prestans habitaculum noue claritatis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="665">Heil tabernacle cler</L>
<L>Maade of &thorn;e godhed,</L>
<L>In whom crist saued &thorn;e world her</L>
<L N="668">ffrom synne and wrecchedhed:</L>
<L>&THORN;e bond, we preye &thorn;e, vnbynde</L>
<L>Of vre schrewednesse,
<PB REF="00000087.tif" N="79"></L>
<L>And &yogh;if us place to vre dwellynge:</L>
<L N="672">&THORN;at is of newe clernesse.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Benedixisti domine terram tuam, auertisti captiui|tatem iacob.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 84 (85).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue terra gracie fecundata donis,</I></L>
<L><I>Noue fructum proferens benediccionis:</I></L>
<L><I>Nostrum desiderium facies in bonis,</I></L>
<L><I>Nos a malis eximens praue nacionis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="673">Heil noble eor&thorn;e of grace</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &yogh;iftus wel arrayed,</L>
<L>To bringe for&thorn; fruyt in luytel space</L>
<L N="676">Of newe blessyng assayed:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt make al vre desyr</L>
<L>In godnesse to be stede;</L>
<L>Of al vuel quenche &thorn;ou &thorn;e fyr</L>
<L N="680">And eke of wikkedhede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>INclina domine aurem tuam &amp; exaudi me, quoniam inops &amp; pauper sum ego.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 85 (86).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue uite speculum, uirginum regina,</I></L>
<L><I>Quam lustrauit vndique gracia diuina:</I></L>
<L><I>Aurem tuam pauperum precibus inclina,</I></L>
<L><I>Quos inuoluit misere sordium sentina.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="681">Heil &thorn;ou cler myrour of lyf,</L>
<L>Of Maydens &thorn;ou art queene,</L>
<L>Whom grace of heuene ouer-al ful ryf</L>
<L N="684">Schynyng schewed schene:</L>
<L>Beende &thorn;yn eres bisyliche</L>
<L>To pore mennes preyere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche ben wrapped wrecchedliche</L>
<L N="688">In ful&thorn;e and serwe in-feere.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Fundamenta eius in montibus sanctis:</I> diligit<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 86 (87).</NOTE> <I>dominus portas syon super omnia tabernacula iacob.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue dei ciuitas, cuius fundamentum</I></L>
<L><I>Samarites construit, qui nos in iumentum</I></L>
<L><I>Semiuiuos [subleuans] plagis dat vnguentum,</I></L>
<L><I>Viuo</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. vino: cf. Luc. 10, 34.</NOTE> <I>legis adhibens gracie fomentum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="689">Heil cite of god and man,</L>
<L>Of whuche &thorn;e foundement
<PB REF="00000088.tif" N="80"></L>
<L>Buylded &thorn;e Samaritan,</L>
<L N="692">&THORN;at us vppon his iument</L>
<L>Sette &thorn;at br[o]u&yogh;t was<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. war</NOTE> neih [of]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. to</NOTE> dawe,</L>
<L>And &yogh;af us vnement,</L>
<L>Eching to hem &thorn;at lyuen beo lawe,</L>
<L N="696">Of grace help verrement.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Domine deus salutis mee, in die clamaui et nocte coram te.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 87 (88).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue mater domini qui spes est</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &amp;</NOTE> <I>salutis,</I></L>
<L><I>Qui contriuit moriens iugum seruitutis:</I></L>
<L><I>Iuua nos in tempore nostre senectutis,</I></L>
<L><I>Nos in celum subleuans gradibus virtutis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="697">Heil Modur of [&thorn;e] lord and kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hope art of vr hele,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche brac in his dy&yogh;ing</L>
<L N="700">Of bondage &yogh;okkes fele:</L>
<L>Help us nou wi&thorn; &thorn;i preying&mdash;</L>
<L>We ben in ful gret age;</L>
<L>In to heuene vs up liftyng</L>
<L N="704">&THORN;orwh vertus, stage vp stage.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Misericordias domini in eternum cantabo.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 88 (89).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue nostri generis terminans lamentum,</I></L>
<L><I>Per quam rex disposuit uite testamentum:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 88, v. 20.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Gregem tuis laudibus iugiter intentum</I></L>
<L><I>Non pauere facias iudicis aduentum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="705">Heil of Monkynde ende makyng</L>
<L>Of alle serwe and stryf,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whom disposet ha&thorn; vr kyng</L>
<L N="708">&THORN;e Testament of lyf:</L>
<L>&THORN;is folk &thorn;at in &thorn;yn herying</L>
<L>Heer trauayle&thorn; day bi day,</L>
<L>Mak &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue no dredyng</L>
<L N="712">Whon Iuge schal come verray.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Domine, refugium factus es nobis, a generacione in generacionem.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 89 (90).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue que refugium facta desperatis</I></L>
<L><I>Procellose comprimis motus tempestatis:</I></L>
<L><I>Paca nos &amp; applica portubus optatis,</I></L>
<L><I>Vultui</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Vultru</NOTE> <I>nos offerens summe trinitatis.</I>
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="81"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="713">Heil, for &thorn;ou art help ful good</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at han non hope;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou a-batest &thorn;e grete flood,</L>
<L N="716">In tempest whon we ben lope:</L>
<L>To &thorn;at hauene &thorn;ou vs brynge</L>
<L>&THORN;at ay desyre schulde we,</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e siht vs offringe</L>
<L N="720">Of &thorn;e hei&yogh;e Trinite.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Qui habitat in adiutorio altissimi, in protectione dei celi commorabitur.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 90 (91).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue quam inhabitat verbum caro factum,</I></L>
<L><I>Qui collapsos uetiti ligni per contactum</I></L>
<L><I>Nos fecisse condolens cum inferno pactum,</I></L>
<L><I>Ligno vite reparat figuli was fractum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 2, v. 9.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="721">Heil in whom word made flesch</L>
<L>Dwelle&thorn;, &thorn;at ha&thorn; mournyng</L>
<L>Of fallyng of Monkynde so nesch,</L>
<L N="724">fforboden a treo touchyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;at bouhte mon fro pyne of hel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er schulde haue bi stoke;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e treo of lyf he heled wel</L>
<L N="728">&THORN;e vessel &thorn;at was broke.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Bonum est confiteri domino, et psallere nomini tuo</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 91 (92).</NOTE> <I>altissime.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam domino pie confitemur,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius pie veniam consequi meremur:</I></L>
<L><I>Tuis sanctis precibus, mater, adiuuemur,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt cum cristo iugiter tecum gloriemur.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="729">Heil &thorn;orwh whom to god mekeliche</L>
<L>Men make confession,</L>
<L>And aftur &thorn;at mercifuliche</L>
<L N="732">Graunte&thorn; us remission:</L>
<L>Modur, &thorn;orwh &thorn;i preyere</L>
<L>Beo we so holpen a-way,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. al-way?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; crist and &thorn;e i-fere</L>
<L N="736">Ioye we mowe haue ay.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Dominus regnauit, decorem indutus est; indutus est dominus fortitudinem &amp; precinxit se.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 92 (93).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam dominus induens decorem,</I></L>
<L><I>Matris Eue moriens terminat merorem,</I>
<PB REF="00000090.tif" N="82"></L>
<L><I>Prime nos originis uocans ad honorem,</I></L>
<L><I>Immo statum reuocans multo meliorem.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="737">Heil &thorn;orwh whom God clo&thorn;ing</L>
<L>Of feirnesse tok at morwe,</L>
<L>Of Eue, vr modur, for us dying</L>
<L N="740">He endet al &thorn;e sorwe,</L>
<L>Callynge a&yogh;ein vs to honour</L>
<L>Of vr furst springyng for&thorn;,</L>
<L>And us sette, soffring hard schour,</L>
<L N="744">In staat muche more wor&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Deus ulcionum dominus; deus ulcionum libere egit.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 93 (94).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue mater domini miseracionum,</I></L>
<L><I>Mea delens crimina spiritum da bonum,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt astare valeam gaudens ante tronum,</I></L>
<L><I>Cum in finem venerit deus vlcionum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="745">Heil modur of &thorn;e lord</L>
<L>Of Merci &thorn;at is parfyt:</L>
<L>Do wey my synnes of dedes<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. dede</NOTE> and word,</L>
<L N="748">And &yogh;if me good spirit,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I may stonde wi&thorn; cher gladyng</L>
<L>To-fore &thorn;e trone of blis,</L>
<L>Whon god schal come at &thorn;e endyng</L>
<L N="752">To venge dedes mis.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Venite, exultemus domino, iubilemus deo salutari nostro.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 94 (95).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue mater inclita</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. indica; the translator read modica.</NOTE> <I>mater inquam dei,</I></L>
<L><I>Per quem datur Sabbatum uere requiei;</I></L>
<L><I>Hic est qui nos liberat anno iubilei:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 94, v. 10, 11.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Vnde nec in-merito iubilamus ei.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="753">Heil modur meke wi&thorn;-oute debat,</L>
<L>Heil modur<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. modur of modur of</NOTE> of Ihesu crist,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whom to us &thorn;e Sabat</L>
<L N="756">Is &yogh;iuen of verrey rist<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. riht</NOTE>;</L>
<L>He hit is &thorn;at lyuere&thorn; vs</L>
<L>In &thorn;e &yogh;eer of Iubilee:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore vchon as men ioyus</L>
<L N="760">To him nou synge we.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Cantate domino canticum nouum, cantate domino</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 95 (96).</NOTE> <I>omnis terra.</I>
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="83"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam domino nouit decantare</I></L>
<L><I>Nouum terra canticum laudans salutare;</I></L>
<L><I>Qui nos, cum redierit orbem salutare</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. indicare; cf. Ps. 95, v. 13.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Summi patris ouibus velit agregare.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="761">Heil &thorn;orwh whom to vr lord</L>
<L>Men han lernd to synge</L>
<L>A newe song wi&thorn; vois and word</L>
<L N="764">Of hele&thorn;e hinf hery[i]nge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. he?</NOTE> wole, whon he come&thorn; a&yogh;eyn</L>
<L>&THORN;e world forte grete,</L>
<L>His ffadres schep &thorn;en in certeyn</L>
<L N="768">To-gedere he wol gete.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Dominus regnauit: exultet terra, letentur insule multe.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 96 (97).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius filius regnans sine fyne</I></L>
<L><I>Egrotanti factus est auctor medicine,</I></L>
<L><I>Qui naturam hominis vniens diuine</I></L>
<L><I>ffit per mortis terminum terminus</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. terminis</NOTE> <I>ruine.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="769">Heil whos sone in pouste</L>
<L>Regne&thorn; wi&thorn;-outen ende,</L>
<L>To syke men mad is he</L>
<L N="772">Medicyn, hem to mende;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche of monkynde and diuyn</L>
<L>Maade an onynge,</L>
<L>And in his dy&yogh;inge dude termyn</L>
<L N="776">&THORN;e terme of vre fallynge.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Cantate domino canticum nouum, quia mirabilia fecit.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 97 (98).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue que libidinis non sensisti motum,</I></L>
<L><I>Per quam fecit dominus salutare notum</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 97, v. 2.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Qui, quod erat hominis, assumendo totum</I></L>
<L><I>Ergo se contemperat, sanet ut egrotum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="777">Heil &thorn;ou &thorn;at of lecherie</L>
<L>ffeledest neuer no sturyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;e &thorn;e lord of glorie</L>
<L N="780">Maade hele to vr knowyng:</L>
<L>He tok al &thorn;ing him vppon</L>
<L>&THORN;at was of Monkuynde eke,</L>
<L>fforte helen hem euerichon</L>
<L N="784">&THORN;at in soule weren seke.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm"><PB REF="00000092.tif" N="84">
<P><I>Dominus regnauit: irascantur populi; qui sedet</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. sedes</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 98 (99).</NOTE> <I>super cherubin, moueatur terra.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue que iusticie solem nube</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 98, v. 7.</NOTE> <I>tegis,</I></L>
<L><I>Tronus facta gracie, tronus summi regis:</I></L>
<L><I>Nostri queso uigiles ad tutelam gregis,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt in nobis uigeat plenitudo legis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="785">Heil &thorn;ou &thorn;e sonne of rihtwysnes</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; clene cloude huledest,</L>
<L>Made trone of grace and goodnes,</L>
<L N="788">Trone of kyng hi&yogh;ist:</L>
<L>Vr flok forte defende</L>
<L>We prey &thorn;e wake and dawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mowe &thorn;riue and us amende</L>
<L N="792">Wi&thorn; ffulnesse of &thorn;e lawe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Iubilate deo omnis terra, seruite domino in leticia.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 99 (100).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue mater, cuius est pietas in-mensa,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius ope languidis salus est inpensa:</I></L>
<L><I>Mentis uota suscipe iubilumque pensa,</I></L>
<L><I>Et perhenne gaudium nobis recompensa.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="793">Heil Modur swete, whos pite</L>
<L>May no mon &thorn;enke ne telle;</L>
<L>To seke men is &yogh;iue &thorn;orwh &thorn;e</L>
<L N="796">An hele, so&thorn; as gospelle:</L>
<L>Tac &thorn;ou deuocions of vr &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>And of gladnesse tak hede;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ioye euerlastynge for&yogh;ete &thorn;ou nouht</L>
<L N="800">To gete us to vr mede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P>MIsericordiam &amp; iudicium cantabo tibi, domine.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 100 (101).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue Mater solitum gignens preter morem,</I></L>
<L><I>Que gignendo retines virginis pudorem:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 100, v. 2.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Iuris &amp; iudicij feruidum rigorem</I></L>
<L><I>per misericordie tempera</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. tempora</NOTE> <I>dulcorem.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="801">Hei[l] Modur child for&thorn; bringynge</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes comuyn custome,</L>
<L>Of Maydenhod &yogh;it stille holdynge</L>
<L N="804">Clannesse wi&thorn;-outen schome:</L>
<L>Of lawe and of &thorn;e Iuggement</L>
<L>&THORN;at ilke brennynge hardnesse</L>
<L>Tempre &thorn;ou wi&thorn; good entent</L>
<L N="808">Of Merci wi&thorn; swetnesse.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm"><PB REF="00000093.tif" N="85">
<P><I>DOmine, exaudi oracionem meam, et clamor meus ad te veniat.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 101 (102).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam pauperum uoces exaudiuit</I></L>
<L><I>Passer solitarius</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 101, v. 8.</NOTE> <I>qui post mortem viuit;</I></L>
<L><I>Qui per penas diluens culpam quam nesciuit,</I></L>
<L><I>Iugum mortis moriens opido contriuit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="809">Heil &thorn;orwh whom of pore men</L>
<L>Voyces heere&thorn; of bre&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sparwe in &thorn;e euene soleyn</L>
<L N="812">&THORN;at lyue&thorn; aftur his de&thorn;;</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; peynes harde wassching</L>
<L>&THORN;e gultus &thorn;at he nouht kneuh,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;ok of de&thorn; for us dying</L>
<L N="816">He al to-brac and dreuh.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>BEnedic anima mea domino, &amp; omnia que intra me sunt nomini sancto eius.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 102 (103).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue Mater titulo benediccionis</I></L>
<L><I>Illustrata celitus gracieque</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. graciaque</NOTE> <I>donis:</I></L>
<L><I>Nos illustra cumulo miseracionis,</I></L>
<L><I>Statum mutans misere conuersacionis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="817">Heil Modur &thorn;at aboute by-gon</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; tytle of good blessynge,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; grace and vertues mony on,</L>
<L N="820">&THORN;orwh &yogh;iftus of vr kynge:</L>
<L>Resseyue &thorn;ou vs &thorn;orwh &thorn;i goodnes</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; plenteuous merci,</L>
<L>Chaungynge ur stat of wrecchednes</L>
<L N="824">In to lyuyng holy.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Benedic anima mea domino: domine deus meus</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 103 (104).</NOTE> <I>magnificatus es uehementer.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue Mater gracie, Mater Benedicta,</I></L>
<L><I>Malediccionibus Eue non astricta:</I></L>
<L><I>Moles queso criminum aufer &amp; delicta,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt seueri iudicis temperes edicta.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="825">Heil &thorn;ou modur of grace,</L>
<L>Modur al-wey blessid. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 vv. wanting.</NOTE>:</L>
<L>&THORN;e Moles of vr crym, we prey,</L>
<L N="828">Do wey, and vre trespas,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iuges harde biddynges verrey</L>
<L N="830">Tempre &thorn;ou in luytel spas.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm"><PB REF="00000094.tif" N="86">
<P><I>COnfitemini domino &amp; inuocate nomen eius; Annun|ciate inter gentes opera eius.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 104 (105).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue Mater filij, per quam</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. quem?</NOTE> <I>liberantur</I></L>
<L><I>Qui sub mole criminum</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. crimini</NOTE> <I>pressi condempnantur:</I></L>
<L><I>Ipsi, per quem federa gracie ditantur,</I></L>
<L><I>Pie nos confedera cum hijs qui saluantur.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="831">Heil Modur of Sone i-blest,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whom dyliuered beone</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &thorn;at wi&thorn; crymes ben opprest,</L>
<L N="834">And dampned wi&thorn;-outen wene.</L>
<L>To him, &thorn;orwh hom<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. him</NOTE> euer-mo</L>
<L>Bondes of grace ben maade,</L>
<L>Meke<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Make</NOTE> him &thorn;ou bynde us to,</L>
<L N="838">Wi&thorn; hem &thorn;at ben saue and glade.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>COnfitemini domino, quoniam bonus, quoniam in seculum misericordia eius.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 105 (106).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius filio pie confitemur,</I></L>
<L><I>Quod Egipti tenebris;</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. tenebras</NOTE> per hunc amouemur<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. admonemur</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Qui pro nobis gladium ponit super femur,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 44, v. 4.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Quo accinctus dimicet, ne nos expugnemur.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="839">Heil to whos sone in so&thorn;nes</L>
<L>We knowleche wi&thorn; good fey,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of Egiptus derknes</L>
<L N="842">&THORN;orwh him we ben [don] a-wey;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche for vs ha&thorn; put a swerd</L>
<L>Vppon his syde ful riht,</L>
<L>And so igurt nis nou&yogh;t a-ferd,</L>
<L N="846">ffor vs redi to fiht.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Confitemini domino, quoniam bonus, quoniam in seculum misericordia eius.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 106 (107).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue Mater domini qui te preelegit,</I></L>
<L><I>Qui cateruas hostium</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. hominum</NOTE> <I>moriens confregit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">ef. Ps. 106, v. 16.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Et inferna uisitans, predo quos abegit</I></L>
<L><I>A predonis faucibus preda factus egit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="847">Heil Modur of &thorn;e lord of al</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e to-fore o&thorn;ur ha&thorn; chosun;</L>
<L>&THORN;at cumpaygnyes grete and smal</L>
<L N="850">[Of] &thorn;e fendes dy&yogh;inge ha&thorn; brokun,</L>
<L>And aftur &thorn;at helle visityng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;at &thorn;e?</NOTE> rauynour drof a-way,
<PB REF="00000095.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. And?</NOTE> fro &thorn;e chekes of &thorn;e Rauyning</L>
<L N="854">Dyliuered us, whon he was pray.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>PAratum cor meum deus, paratum cor meum: can|tabo &amp; psallam in gloria mea.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 107 (108).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue nostrum gaudium, nostra spes &amp; vita,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius ope salus est egris inpertita:</I></L>
<L><I>Generalem generis sortem non oblita,</I></L>
<L><I>Ad eterne pabulum uite nos inuita.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="855">Heil vr ioye and al vr blis,</L>
<L>Vr hope and eke vr lyf;</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whom to seke men heer is</L>
<L N="858">Hele &yogh;iuen ful rif:</L>
<L>&THORN;e comuyn lot nou of monkynde</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t for&yogh;ete,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e lyf euer-lastinde</L>
<L N="862">&THORN;ou bidde us to &thorn;e mete.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Deus, laudem meam ne tacueris, quia os peccatoris &amp; os dolosi super me apertum est.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 108 (109).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam dominus nostri miseretur,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius laus in filio digne recensetur;</I></L>
<L><I>Qui dum pacis osculum ficte non veretur,</I></L>
<L><I>Sibi laudem, gloriam nobis promeretur.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="863">Heil &thorn;orwh whom &thorn;e lord of miht</L>
<L>On vs euere ha&thorn; merci,</L>
<L>Whos herying in Sone is riht</L>
<L N="866">Reherced eft wor&thorn;ily;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche whon he dredde no-&thorn;ing</L>
<L>Iudas feyned cos,</L>
<L>To him-self he won heriing,</L>
<L N="870">And ioye and blisse to vs.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Dixit dominus domino meo: sede a dextris meis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 109 (110).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius vterus factus est castellum</I></L>
<L><I>Quod intrauit dominus properans ad bellum,</I></L>
<L><I>Qui sibi de restibus faciens flagellum</I></L>
<L><I>Inimicos posuit pedum sub scabellum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 109, v. 1.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="871">Heil whos wombe was mad wi&thorn; riht</L>
<L>Castel of feir dwellyng,</L>
<L>In whuche entred &thorn;e lord of miht</L>
<L N="874">Toward batayle goyng;
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="88"></L>
<L>&THORN;at to him-self of wi&thorn;&thorn;es gret</L>
<L>Smart scourge made and hot</L>
<L>And his enemys so set</L>
<L N="878">Vndur &thorn;e stol of his fot.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Confitebor tibi domine in toto corde meo, in consilio iustorum &amp; congregacione.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 110 (111).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam genitor</I> filium premisit,</L>
<L><I>Redimendi populi cui curam commisit;</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 110, v. 9.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>In quem cum diabolus manum suam misit,</I></L>
<L><I>Quos ad mortem traxerat nescius amisit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="879">Heil &thorn;orwh whom &thorn;e getere</L>
<L>His sone sende bi-fore,</L>
<L>To whom he &yogh;af &thorn;en powere</L>
<L N="882">A&yogh;eyn-bugge &thorn;ulke &thorn;at weren lore;</L>
<L>On whom whon &thorn;e fend ful fawe</L>
<L>His hond hedde set wi&thorn; bost,</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke &thorn;at to de&thorn; he hedde i-drawe</L>
<L N="886">Vn-wityngliche he lost.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Beatus vir qui timet dominum, in mandatis eius volet nimis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 111 (112).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue stella nuncians veri solis ortum,</I></L>
<L><I>De qua verum tenebris lumen est exortum</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 111, v. 4.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Quod in nostris mentibus reperis distortum,</I></L>
<L><I>Tue participio lucis sit absortum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="887">Heil sterre to vs schewyng</L>
<L>Springynge of verrey Sonne,</L>
<L>Of whom verrey lihtyng</L>
<L N="890">To derknesse is bygunne.</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er hit beo croked o&thorn;ur vnriht</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou fyndest in vr &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sum partye of &thorn;i lyht</L>
<L N="894">Mak hit out beo brouht.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>LAudate pueri dominum, laudate nomen domini.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 112 (113).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue mater pueri per quem vita datur,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius laus a pueris digne predicatur.</I></L>
<L><I>Per te nobis puritas uite conferatur,</I></L>
<L><I>Que</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Qno</NOTE> <I>in puericie nomine signatur.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="895">Heil Modur of &thorn;at childe</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whom is &yogh;iuen lyf;
<PB REF="00000097.tif" N="89"></L>
<L>Whos heryinge of children mylde</L>
<L N="898">Preched is wel ryf:</L>
<L>Clannes of lyf wi&thorn;-outen blame</L>
<L>To us be &yogh;iuen &thorn;orwh &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of childhode in &thorn;e name</L>
<L N="902">Beo-tokned is, parde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>IN exitu israel de egypto, domus iacob de populo barbaro</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 113 (114).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius filius sudans in agone</I></L>
<L><I>Mare nobis consecrat merso pharaone;</I></L>
<L><I>Qui fit preda faciens predam de predone,</I></L>
<L><I>Sicque predo uictus est vetus a tyrone.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="903">Heil whos sone, whon he sweted</L>
<L>In his gret Agonye,</L>
<L>&THORN;e s&eacute;&eacute; to vs he halewed,</L>
<L N="906">Pharao dreynt is at ei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at was maad preye, ha&thorn; preyed</L>
<L>Mihtiliche his preyour,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;e olde preyour is venquised</L>
<L N="910">Of a Champioun of honour.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>DIlexi, quoniam exaudiet dominus uocem oracionis mee.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 114 (116).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue norma fidei, pacis disciplina,</I></L>
<L><I>Apis mella faciens, uitis fundens uina:</I></L>
<L><I>Vini meri calicem filiis propina,</I></L>
<L><I>Et de valle tristium transfer ad diuina.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="911">Heil, &thorn;ou art rule of fei&thorn;, parde,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e pees disciplyn,</L>
<L>Makyng hony &thorn;ou art &thorn;e Beo,</L>
<L N="914">A Vyne eke heldyng out wyn:</L>
<L>&THORN;e chalys of &thorn;e wyn so clere</L>
<L>ffulle to &thorn;i sones euene;</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is valeye of serwes here</L>
<L N="918">Translate us in to heuene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Credidi propter quod locutus sum, ego autem humili|atus sum nimis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 115 (116, v. 10).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue uitis fertilis docta propinare</I></L>
<L><I>Vinum quod inebriat, uinum salutare</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. v. 13.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Vinum de quo dominus risum fecit Sare</I></L>
<L><I>Dum promisit Abrahe semen ampliare.</I>
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="90"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="919">Heil &thorn;ou plentiuous vyn,</L>
<L>Tauht to for&thorn;fulle and dele</L>
<L>Wyn &thorn;at moyste&thorn; men wy&thorn;-in,</L>
<L N="922">&THORN;at wyn is al vr hele;</L>
<L>Wyn of whuche vr lord made game</L>
<L>And lauhtre eke to Saare,</L>
<L>Whon he bi-hiht to Habrahame</L>
<L N="926">His seed schulde encrece mare.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>LAudate dominum omnes gentes, laudate eum omnes populi.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 116 (117).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam factus est homo rex celorum,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius passim resonat laudes uox celorum:</I></L>
<L><I>Te laudare iugiter summa sit uotorum,</I></L>
<L><I>Donec nos suscipiat chorus angelorum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="927">Heil &thorn;orwh whom a Mon is maad</L>
<L>Kyng of heuene, and calle,</L>
<L>On whos heriinge crien ful sad</L>
<L N="930">Of heuene &thorn;e voises alle:</L>
<L>&THORN;e to herie bisi men hem make</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; herte deuoutelye,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at out of &thorn;is world us take</L>
<L N="934">Aungeles Cumpaygnye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Confitemini domino, quoniam bonus, quoniam in seculum misericordia eius.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 117 (118).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue vitis gracie, vitis salutaris,</I></L>
<L><I>Quam vallauit vndique lapis angularis:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 117, v. 22.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Nostram sepi uineam uallo quo vallaris,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne nos ledat rabies feri singularis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="935">Heil, &thorn;ou art vyn of grace,</L>
<L>And vyne of hele al-one;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche enuyround in al space</L>
<L N="938">He &thorn;at is kernere<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. corner</NOTE> stone:</L>
<L>Hegge &thorn;ou a-boute vr vyn-&yogh;ard</L>
<L>Now in &thorn;is valey here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at woodnes us hurte ne make aferd</L>
<L N="942">Of &thorn;e wylde best singulere.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>BEati in-maculati in via, qui ambulant in lege domini.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 118 (119).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue pia genitrix in-maculatorum,</I></L>
<L><I>Quorum lex est currere viam mandatorum;</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 118, v. 4.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000099.tif" N="91"></L>
<L><I>Ne a via deuient pedes uiatorum,</I></L>
<L><I>Quod nos grauat amoue, pondus peccatorum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="943">Heil &thorn;ou bringere for&thorn; so gent</L>
<L>Of men &thorn;at haue no synne,</L>
<L>In<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. In to</NOTE> &thorn;e [wey] of good comaundement</L>
<L N="946">Whos law es<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. lawes</NOTE> for to rinne.</L>
<L>Out of riht wey &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne go</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Ne</NOTE> feet of weyferynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vs sore greue&thorn; remoue also,</L>
<L N="950">&THORN;e bur&thorn;un of hem &thorn;at synde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Ad dominum cum tribularer clamaui: et exaudiuit me.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 119 (120).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue de qua prodiit potens aduocatus,</I></L>
<L><I>Culpe qui determinat veteres reatus;</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius patrocinio noster incolatus</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 119, v. 5.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Transeat in gloriam melioris status.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="951">Heil fro whom passed for&thorn; ful fre</L>
<L>An<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. And</NOTE> aduoket mihti,</L>
<L>&THORN;at determyned wi&thorn; humilite</L>
<L N="954">Vr olde dedes gulti;</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh his help wi&thorn;-outen mis</L>
<L>We &thorn;at dwellen heer al maate,</L>
<L>Beo we translated in to blis</L>
<L N="958">Of wel better state.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>LEuaui oculos meos in montes, vnde ueniet auxilium michi.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 120 (121).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo regia, mundi luminare,</I></L>
<L><I>Cece mentis tenebras potens propulsare:</I></L>
<L><I>Nos in montem doceas oculos leuare</I></L>
<L><I>Quo con[s]cendit Abraham, iussus immolare.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="959">Heil &thorn;ou kynges Mayden wrouht,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is world &thorn;ou art liht:</L>
<L>&THORN;e derknes of vr blynde &thorn;ouht</L>
<L N="962">Put &thorn;ou a-wey wi&thorn; miht;</L>
<L>Tech us in to &thorn;at hul wi&thorn; game</L>
<L>Vr e&yogh;en lufte on alle wyse,</L>
<L>In to whuche steih Abrahame</L>
<L N="966">I-beden do sacrifice.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>LEtatus sum in hijs que dicta sunt michi: in</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 121 (122).</NOTE> <I>domum domini ibimus.</I>
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="92"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue que leticiam mundo retulisti</I></L>
<L><I>Cum in verbo gracie verbum genuisti;</I></L>
<L><I>Qui cum nos preceperit ad tribunal sisti,</I></L>
<L><I>Ab auditu faciat non pauere tristi.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="967">Heil &thorn;ou, &thorn;at ioye and glad face</L>
<L>To &thorn;e world hast told,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at &thorn;ou in &thorn;e word of grace</L>
<L N="970">Brouht for&thorn; a word ful bold;</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. To</NOTE> whuche whon he us bidde cum schal</L>
<L>To-fore his Mageste,</L>
<L>Of serwhful heryng bo&thorn;e gret and smal</L>
<L N="974">Vs nouht to drede mak he.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Ad te leuaui oculos meos, qui habitas in celis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 122 (123).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo thalamus summi facta ducis;</I></L>
<L><I>Que de noctis tenebris miseros educis:</I></L>
<L><I>Nostre mentis oculos leues a caducis,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt intendant radio sempiterne lucis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="975">Heil Mayden maade chaumbre briht</L>
<L>Of Duyk &thorn;at sit an heih;</L>
<L>&THORN;ow out of derknesse of niht</L>
<L N="978">Wrecches ledest wel sleih:</L>
<L>&THORN;e e&yogh;en of vr inward &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>Lyft vp from slideri &thorn;inge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit take hede wi&thorn; al &thorn;e miht</L>
<L N="982">To lyht euer-lastynge.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>NIsi quia dominus erat in nobis, dicat nunc israel, nisi quia dominus erat in nobis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 123 (124).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo, gracie mater affluentis,</I></L>
<L><I>Per quam cedit strepitus populi furentis:</I></L>
<L><I>Muni queso fortiter pedes nostre mentis,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt torrentem transeant aque</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. aquam</NOTE> <I>uehementis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 125, v. 5.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="983">Heil Mayden, and Modur eke</L>
<L>Of grace, flowynge as flood,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whom is maad bo&thorn;e softe and meke</L>
<L N="986">&THORN;e noyse of peple wood:</L>
<L>We prey &thorn;e, kepe &thorn;ou strongliche here</L>
<L>&THORN;e feet of [vr] &thorn;ouhtes longe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mowe passe &thorn;e Riuere</L>
<L N="990">Of &thorn;e watur stronge.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm"><PB REF="00000101.tif" N="93">
<P><I>Qui confidunt in domino, sicut mons syon; non com|mouebitur in eternum qui habitat in ierusalem.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 124 (125).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue mons sanctissime speculacionis,</I></L>
<L><I>In quo nostra sita est spes ascencionis:</I></L>
<L><I>A carnalis strepitu nos commocionis</I></L>
<L><I>Liberando, filios fac adopcionis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="991">Heil hul ful heih of met</L>
<L>Of holiust beo-holdyng,</L>
<L>In whom vr hope is hollich set</L>
<L N="994">Of vre vp-steih&yogh;ing:</L>
<L>ffrom al flescliche lykynge</L>
<L>And eke commocion</L>
<L>Diliuere us, &thorn;i sones makynge</L>
<L N="998">So of adopcion.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>IN conuertendo dominus captiuitatem syon, facti sumus sicut consolati.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 125 (126).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue Mater affluens pacis vbertate,</I></L>
<L><I>ffucta consolacio plebis captiuate:</I></L>
<L><I>Nos ad portum applicans pacis preoptate,</I></L>
<L><I>Plena plene perfrui presta libertate.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="999">Heil Modur euer flowyng</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ful plente of pes;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art maad al counseylyng (!)</L>
<L N="1002">Of wrecches wi&thorn;-outen lees:</L>
<L>Bring us to &thorn;at hauene hom</L>
<L>Of pees &thorn;at we desyre,</L>
<L>And &yogh;iue us alle ful fredom&mdash;</L>
<L N="1006">ffor &thorn;at is vre best hyre.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>NIsi dominus edificauerit domum, in vanum labo|rauerunt qui edificant eam.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 126 (127).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue domus regia, quam edificauit</I></L>
<L><I>Rex qui pacis gaudia mundo nunciauit;</I></L>
<L><I>Qui dum fortis atria forcior intrauit,</I></L>
<L><I>ffortem ligans spolia fortis asportauit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1007">Heil kynges hous ful gay,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche a kyng ha&thorn; buylded</L>
<L>&THORN;at prince is of pees al-way</L>
<L N="1010">And ioye to world ha&thorn; schewed;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche strengore in to &thorn;e halle</L>
<L>Entred of &thorn;e stronge,
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>&THORN;e stronge byndyng he tok preies alle</L>
<L N="1014">&THORN;at he hedde holden longe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>BEati omnes qui timent dominum, qui ambulant in viis eius.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 127 (128).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue Mater domini, genitrix beata,</I></L>
<L><I>ffiliorum filijs plene uenustata:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 127, v. 6.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Da timere dominum mente tranquillata,</I></L>
<L><I>Vias nostras dirigens eius ad mandata.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1015">Heil Modur of &thorn;e lord so gent,</L>
<L>Of sones bringere for&thorn;,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sones mad feir verrement</L>
<L N="1018">&THORN;ou art fulliche, and wor&thorn;:</L>
<L>Graunt us alle vr lord to drede</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;ouht peisiblement;</L>
<L>Vr weys loke &thorn;ei ben dressede</L>
<L N="1022">To kepe his maundement.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Sepe expugnauerunt me a iuuentute mea, dicat nunc israel.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 128 (129).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam uiribus hostes destituti</I></L>
<L><I>Inbecilles facti sunt, debiles &amp; muti:</I></L>
<L><I>Nostre, uirgo, quesumus prospice saluti,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt fiamus iugiter te tuente tuti.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1023">Heil &thorn;orwh whom heore streng&thorn;es alle</L>
<L>Vr enemys han lost,</L>
<L>Vn-welde aren made and doun ek falle,</L>
<L N="1026">ffeble and doumbe of bost:</L>
<L>We preye &thorn;e, Mayden, swetliche,</L>
<L>To vr hele tak hede;</L>
<L>Mak vs siker verreyliche</L>
<L N="1030">Of &thorn;i defence at nede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>DE profundis clamaui ad te domine; domine exaudi uocem meam.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 129 (130).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue floris baiula, cuius ad odorem</I></L>
<L><I>Reuiuiscunt mortui: suscipe clamorem</I></L>
<L><I>Ad te supplicancium, nosque per hunc florem</I></L>
<L><I>Non pauere facias mortis ad honorem</I> (!).</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1031">Heil &thorn;ou berere of &thorn;e flour,</L>
<L>Of hos swete sauerynge</L>
<L>Tornen to lyf in an hour</L>
<L N="1034">&THORN;e dede: take &thorn;e criinge
<PB REF="00000103.tif" N="95"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;ulke &thorn;at preyen her to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And make vs bi &thorn;at flour</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t to drede, but glad to bee<NOTE PLACE="marg">or. beo</NOTE></L>
<L N="1038">Of de&thorn; wi&thorn; good honour.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Domine, non est exaltatum cor meum, neque elati sunt oculi mei.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 130 (131).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius detulit rex humilitati</I></L>
<L><I>Cum te verbi thalamum fecit incarnati;</I></L>
<L><I>Qui pro nobis offerens se captiuitati</I></L>
<L><I>Captiuatos reddidit prime libertati.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1039">Heil to whos humilite</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng so wolde obesch</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e chaumbre he made &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1042">Of word &thorn;at is mad flesch;</L>
<L>&THORN;at him-self offred for vs</L>
<L>And tok vr caytyf dom,</L>
<L>Whon he &yogh;af vs ful glorios</L>
<L N="1046">A&yogh;eyn to furste fredom.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Memento domine dauid, &amp; omnis mansuetudinis eius.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 131 (132).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue iesse uirgula, per quam exibetur</I></L>
<L><I>Quod de dauid semine pater pollicetur:</I></L>
<L><I>Per te quidem gracie tempus adimpletur,</I></L>
<L><I>Quia per te filijs pater miseretur.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1047">Heil &yogh;erde of Iesse good of pith,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whom is be-tyd</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e seed of Dauid</L>
<L N="1050">Sum-tyme &thorn;e fader heted:</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;e &thorn;erfore &thorn;e tyme of grace</L>
<L>ffolfulled is, serteynly,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;orwh &thorn;e in vche place</L>
<L N="1054">ffadur of sones hath merci.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Ecce quam bonum &amp; quam iocundum habitare fra|tres in vnum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 132 (133).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue stella gracie stillans vnccionem</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 132, v. 2.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Que nostrarum mencium firmat vnionem:</I></L>
<L><I>Nos vnitos mutuam per dilexionem</I></L>
<L><I>Vite presta consequi benediccionem.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1055">Heil, of grace &thorn;ou art sterre</L>
<L>An<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. And</NOTE> oynement droppynge,
<PB REF="00000104.tif" N="96"></L>
<L>&THORN;at, for vr &thorn;ouhtes schulde not erre,</L>
<L N="1058">Makest<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. make&thorn;</NOTE> studefast onynge:</L>
<L>Vs alle on and of on wille</L>
<L>To-gedere wel liuynge,</L>
<L>Mak vs, ladi, come &thorn;e tille</L>
<L N="1062">And of lyf haue blessynge.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Ecce nunc benedicite dominum, omnes serui domini.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 133 (134).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue nostrum gaudium, nostre spes salutis,</I></L>
<L><I>Celi scandens solium gradibus virtutis:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">refers to the title (Canticum graduum).</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Queso fer presidium noxia secutis,</I></L>
<L><I>Et a nobis excute iugum seruitutis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1063">Heil ioye of vs euerichon,</L>
<L>Hope of old hele and newe,</L>
<L>Steying vp to heuene-tron</L>
<L N="1066">Be de-grees of vertue:</L>
<L>Euere vs to helpe &thorn;ou beo aboute,</L>
<L>ffor we han ben outrage;</L>
<L>And eke from vs loke &thorn;ou schake oute</L>
<L N="1070">&THORN;e harde &yogh;ok of bondage.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>LAudate nomen domini, laudate serui dominum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 134 (135).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius filius gracie preconem</I></L>
<L><I>Nondum natus docuit exultacionem:</I></L>
<L><I>Doce nos per uicij supplantacionem</I></L>
<L><I>Ad beatam tendere cristi visionem.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1071">Heil whos sone, ar he weore bore,</L>
<L>To make ioye him tauhte</L>
<L>&THORN;at schulde prechynge go him beo-fore,</L>
<L N="1074">In wombe whon modur him auhte.</L>
<L>Teche vs vices to don a-way</L>
<L>And eke al vuel list,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we atteyne euere and ay</L>
<L N="1078">To &thorn;e blessed siht of crist.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>COnfitemini domino, quoniam bonus, quoniam in eternum misericordia eius.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 135 (136).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo generans per quem liberatur</I></L>
<L><I>Israel, &amp; pharao persequens necatur.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 135, v. 15.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Soluat quisque gracias &amp; confiteatur</I></L>
<L><I>Quod hic mirabilia solus operatur.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1079">Heil Mayden, &thorn;ou bar &thorn;at seynt</L>
<L>&THORN;at dilyuered Israel,
<PB REF="00000105.tif" N="97"></L>
<L>And Pharao, suwyng hem, dreynt,</L>
<L N="1082">And his peple eueridel.</L>
<L>Worschipe&thorn; God now euerichon,</L>
<L>And knowhleche&thorn; hertely</L>
<L>&THORN;at he con worche wondres al-on,</L>
<L N="1086">ffor he is Almihti.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Super flumina babilonis, illic sedimus et fleuimus, dum recordaremur syon.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 136 (137).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam principe uicto Babilonis</I></L>
<L><I>Cantica resumimus iubilacionis:</I></L>
<L><I>Per materne graciam miseracionis</I></L>
<L><I>Reduc nos in patriam repromissionis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1087">Heil &thorn;orwh whom &thorn;e Prince so strong</L>
<L>Ouercom his<NOTE PLACE="marg">= is</NOTE> of Babilon,</L>
<L>And we han taken vp &thorn;e song</L>
<L N="1090">Of Iubilacion:</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh grace of &thorn;e Merci fre</L>
<L>Of &thorn;y Moodurhede so swete</L>
<L>Lede vs a&yogh;eyn to &thorn;e cuntre</L>
<L N="1094">&THORN;at vs alle is by-hete.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>COnfitebor tibi domine in toto corde meo, quoniam audisti verba oris mei.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 137 (138).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue Mater inclita, que sine pudoris</I></L>
<L><I>Tactu nostri mater es facta saluatoris:</I></L>
<L><I>Te laudantes muniat intus atque foris,</I></L>
<L><I>Per te qui remedium nostri fit doloris.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1095">Heil Modur deore wi&thorn; honour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn;-outen schame</L>
<L>Maad Modur art of vr saueour,</L>
<L N="1098">And &thorn;at is &thorn;i riht name.</L>
<L>Keep he wel hem &thorn;at &thorn;e don herye,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-inne and eke wi&thorn;-oute,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;e &thorn;at is remedie</L>
<L N="1102">Of vr serwes al-aboute.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Domine, probasti me &amp; cognouisti me; tu cognouisti sessionem</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. sensionem</NOTE> <I>meam &amp; resurrexionem m[eam.]</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 138 (139).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius filius habitu mendici</I></L>
<L><I>Carnem gerens similem carni peccatrici</I></L>
<L><I>Quasi dolo repulit dolos inimici,</I></L>
<L><I>Cum se mortis legibus passus est addici.</I>
<PB REF="00000106.tif" N="98"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1103">Heil whos sone so deore</L>
<L>In pore monnes clo&thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Beryng flesch among us here</L>
<L N="1106">Lyk to vr flesch takyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. synnyng?</NOTE></L>
<L>And so queyntelich a-wey put he</L>
<L>Vr Enemyes tricherye,</L>
<L>Whon he him-self soffred to be</L>
<L N="1110">Iugged &thorn;en forte dye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Eripe me domine ab homine malo; A uiro iniquo eripe me.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 139 (140).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue Mater filij cuius ad congressum</I></L>
<L><I>Mors eructa penitus abit in secessum:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. cecessum</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Nos a malis eripe, nostre mentis gressum</I></L>
<L><I>Ad paterne dirigens dextere consessum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1111">Heil Modur of &thorn;e Sone,</L>
<L>At whos hard batayle</L>
<L>Deth outurliche was ouercome</L>
<L N="1114">And put a-louh saun&yogh; fayle:</L>
<L>Liuere us from vueles heer in londe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e steppes of vr &thorn;yn[kyn]g<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;yng</NOTE></L>
<L>Dresse &thorn;ou, on &thorn;e ffadres riht honde</L>
<L N="1118">And make &thorn;er vre sittyng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Domine, clamaui ad te, exaudi me; intende uoci mee dum clamauero ad te.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 140 (141).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam deitas carne palliatur,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt ad vite semitas exul reducatur:</I></L>
<L><I>Nostra sic</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. sit</NOTE> <I>oracio per te dirigatur,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt succedens accio uitam consequatur.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1119">Heil &thorn;orwh whom &thorn;e godhed is</L>
<L>Clad in flesch of Monkynde,</L>
<L>To bringe a&yogh;eyn to lyf, i-wis,</L>
<L N="1122">&THORN;e flemed and put be-hynde:</L>
<L>Vr Orison nou euer-mo</L>
<L>So dressed beo &thorn;orw &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vr dedes suwynge also</L>
<L N="1126">Gete vs lyf of Charite.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>UOce mea ad dominum clamaui; uoce mea ad dominum deprecatus sum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 141 (142).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue de qua prodiens gigas manu fortis</I></L>
<L><I>Dormientes excitat a sopore mortis:</I>
<PB REF="00000107.tif" N="99"></L>
<L><I>Redde nos consorcio celice cohortis,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt sit cum uiuentibus locus nostre sortis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1127">Heil from whom for&thorn; goynge</L>
<L>&THORN;e geaunt of hond so strong,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. &thorn;at</NOTE> wel a-wake&thorn; &thorn;e slepynge</L>
<L N="1130">Of sleep of de&thorn; so long:</L>
<L>Bryng us a-&yogh;eyn to cumpaygnye</L>
<L>Of felawschipe of heuene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; hem &thorn;at lyuen murie</L>
<L N="1134">Vr place beo maad ful euene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Domine, exaudi oracionem meam, auribus percipe obsecracionem meam, in veritate tua exaudi m[e].</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 142 (143).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue Mater, suscipe preces quas effundo</I></L>
<L><I>Grauis, sterquilinij mersus in profundo;</I></L>
<L><I>Munda cordis thalamum, hauriens a fundo</I></L>
<L><I>Sordes quibus ceteris amplius habundo.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1135">Heil Modur, tak wi&thorn; mekenes</L>
<L>Preyeres &thorn;at i out helde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at dreynt am in depnes</L>
<L N="1138">Of dunghul, and am vnwelde;</L>
<L>Clanse &thorn;e chaunbre of myn herte,</L>
<L>Drawyng from &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L>fful&thorn;us &thorn;e whuche make me smerte,</L>
<L N="1142">Of whuche I ful abounde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Benedictus dominus deus meus, qui docet</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. doce&yogh;</NOTE> <I>manus meas ad prelium, &amp; digitos meos ad bellum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 143 (144).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue de qua nascitur puer Na&yogh;areus,</I></L>
<L><I>Per quem dum in prelio ruit philisteus</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Goliath</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Vite spem concipiens gaudet homo reus,</I></L>
<L><I>Voce clamans: "libera benedictus deus.</I>"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1143">Heil, for &thorn;e child of Na&yogh;are&thorn;</L>
<L>Boren was feir of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whom, as &thorn;e bok sei&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1146">Slayen was &thorn;e philist&eacute;&eacute;;</L>
<L>Hope of lyf &thorn;er-of takyng</L>
<L>Gulti mon wi&thorn; glad mood,</L>
<L>"Dilyuere me," wi&thorn; voys cri&yogh;ying,</L>
<L N="1150">"I-blessed beo, vr god."</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Exaltabo te, deus meus rex, &amp; benedicam nomini tuo in seculum &amp; in seculum seculi.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 144 (145).</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="100"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue de qua prodijt rex vniuersorum,</I></L>
<L><I>Regnum cuius omnium regnum seculorum:</I></L>
<L><I>Rege nos &amp; applica cetibus eorum</I></L>
<L><I>Quorum summa gloria laus est eternorum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1151">Heil &thorn;ou from whom riht for&thorn; went</L>
<L>Kyng of gret and smalle,</L>
<L>Whos kyngdom is verreyment</L>
<L N="1154">Kyngdom of worldus alle:</L>
<L>Gouerne and applye aftur &thorn;is</L>
<L>Vs to heore cumpaygnye</L>
<L>Of whuche &thorn;e hei&yogh;este ioye is</L>
<L N="1158">Euer-lastyng &thorn;yng to herye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>LAuda anima mea dominum: laudabo dominum in uita mea, psallam deo meo quamdiu fuero.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 145 (146).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam populi factus est adiutor</I></L>
<L><I>Rex qui dicit "ego sum deus, &amp; non mutor";</I></L>
<L><I>Qui per mortis semitas mortis persecutor</I></L>
<L><I>ffit collator glorie, libertatis tutor.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1159">Heil, &thorn;orwh &thorn;e an<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. and</NOTE> helper good</L>
<L>Nou to &thorn;e peple is maad,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng &thorn;at sei&thorn; "I am god,</L>
<L N="1162">Nou&yogh;t chaungynge, but al sad";</L>
<L>&THORN;at beo &thorn;e steppes of de&thorn; is</L>
<L>Of<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. Of</NOTE> de&thorn;es pursuwere</L>
<L>I-maad &thorn;e &yogh;iuere of blis,</L>
<L N="1166">Of freodam defendere.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>Laudate dominum quoniam bonus est psalmus; deo nostro sit iocunda decoraque laudacio.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 146 (147).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius laudibus laus est delectari,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius nos confidimus partu salutari</I></L>
<L><I>Post</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Per</NOTE> <I>hanc vitam glorie palma coronari,</I></L>
<L><I>Si velimus domino pie conformari.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1167">Heil in whos heryinge</L>
<L>Gret dilyt men haue;</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh hos heleful childynge</L>
<L N="1170">We bi-leeuen to beo saue</L>
<L>And [after] &thorn;is lyf corouned to be</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e palm of blis,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if to &thorn;e lord of al pite</L>
<L N="1174">We us conforme as his.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm"><PB REF="00000109.tif" N="101">
<P><I>Lauda Ierusalem dominum, lauda deum tuum syon.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 147 (147, 12).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue mater gracie, iugi laude digna,</I></L>
<L><I>Per quam uictis hostibus ruit ars maligna:</I></L>
<L><I>Captiuatis exibe pietatis signa,</I></L>
<L><I>Nosque post exilium patrie resigna.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1175">Heil Moder wi&thorn; grace Inome,</L>
<L>Wor&thorn;i worschiped to be,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whom enemys ben ouercome</L>
<L N="1178">And craft of malyngnite:</L>
<L>To caytiues heer now wi&thorn; good wil</L>
<L>Of Pit&eacute;&eacute; scheuh &thorn;ow &thorn;e signe,</L>
<L>And vs &thorn;en aftur &thorn;is exil</L>
<L N="1182">To good cuntre resynge.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<P><I>LAudate dominum de celis, Laudate eum in ex|celsis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 148.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue per quam tollitur hominum pressura,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius laudes reboat omnis creatura:</I></L>
<L><I>Laudes quas offerimus</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. offerrimus</NOTE> <I>acceptare cura,</I></L>
<L><I>Nos beatitudine ditans permansura.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1183">Heil &thorn;orwh whom a-wey is don</L>
<L>Of monkynde oppressure;</L>
<L>Whos heryinges alouwed don sum (!)</L>
<L N="1186">Al-Maner creature:</L>
<L>&THORN;e heryinges &thorn;at we offren to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Tac good heede hem to take;</L>
<L>In blessedhed &thorn;at euer schal be</L>
<L N="1190">Riche men to dwelle vs make.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="canticle">
<P><I>COnfitebor tibi, domine, quoniam iratus es michi, conuersus est furor tuus &amp; consolatus es me.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Canticles: Confitebor Isai. 12.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue fons clemencie venieque uena,</I></L>
<L><I>Per quam nobis redditur uite cantulena:</I></L>
<L><I>A peccati[s] solue nos &amp; peccati pena,</I></L>
<L><I>Et beatitudinis perduc ad amena.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1191">Heil welle of mekenes, certeyn,</L>
<L>Veyne of for&yogh;iuynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whom to us is &yogh;iuen a&yogh;eyn</L>
<L N="1194">&THORN;e song of lyf to synge:</L>
<L>Of sunnes vnbynd us euerichone,</L>
<L>And of peyne of synne,
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="102"></L>
<L>And to &thorn;at place &thorn;ou lede us sone</L>
<L N="1198">&THORN;er Ioye and blisse is Inne.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="canticle">
<P><I>Ego dixi: in dimidio dierum meorum vadam ad portas inferi.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Isai. 38,10 (Song of Ezechias).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue laus fidelium, iubar sanctitatis,</I></L>
<L><I>Domini triclinium, tronus magestatis:</I></L>
<L><I>Placa nobis filium precibus beatis,</I></L>
<L><I>Seruos tuos munerans dono libertatis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1199">Heil heriinge of trewe men,</L>
<L>Of holynesse &thorn;e clarte;</L>
<L>Vr lordes chaumbre men &thorn;e callen,</L>
<L N="1202">Trone of &thorn;e Maieste:</L>
<L>Pese &thorn;ou to us &thorn;i sone so dere</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; preyeres of pite,</L>
<L>Rewardynge &thorn;i seruauns here</L>
<L N="1206">Wi&thorn; &yogh;iftus of liberte.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="canticle">
<P><I>Exultauit cor meum in domino &amp; exaltatum est cornu meum in deo meo.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Regum 2 (Song of Anna).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue celi gloria, terre fundamentum,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius fit in utero continens contentum:</I></L>
<L><I>Tue nobis gracie prestet incrementum</I></L>
<L><I>Quod ad tue scribimus laudis monumentum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1207">Heil, &thorn;ou art &thorn;e blisse of heuene,</L>
<L>Of eor&thorn;e &thorn;e foundement;</L>
<L>Whos wombe is maad wi&thorn; mylde steuene</L>
<L N="1210">Conteynyng &thorn;at is content.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i grace graunte nou encresynge</L>
<L>To vs euerichon</L>
<L>&THORN;at writen to &thorn;i worschipynge</L>
<L N="1214">Wi&thorn; god deuocion.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="canticle">
<P><NOTE PLACE="foot">The following part has a separate Title in the Index: Cantemus domino gloriose.</NOTE><I>C[a]ntemus domino: gloriose enim honorificatus est, equum &amp; ascensorem deiecit in mare.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Exod. 15 (Song of Moses).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo generans moris fracto iure,</I></L>
<L><I>De qua gigas prodijt gemine nature:</I></L>
<L><I>Tu miserta miseris subueni pressure,</I></L>
<L><I>Nos in lucem transferens glorie uenture.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1215">Heil Mayden child beryng gent&mdash;</L>
<L>Comuyn maner &thorn;er was be-hynde;
<PB REF="00000111.tif" N="103"></L>
<L>ffor a Geaunt from &thorn;e for&thorn; went</L>
<L N="1218">&THORN;at is of double kynde:</L>
<L>On wrecches haue merci wi&thorn; miht,</L>
<L>Help hem from oppressynge,</L>
<L>And translate us in to &thorn;e liht</L>
<L N="1222">Of blisse &thorn;at is comynge.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="canticle">
<P><I>Domine, audiui audicionem tuam et timui.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Song of Habac. 3. </NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue virgo supplices potens exaudire:</I></L>
<L><I>Que sunt deo placita fac nos tecum scire,</I></L>
<L><I>Et</I> cum <I>iudex uenerit atque dies ire,</I></L>
<L><I>Iudicis ad dexteram iube nos uenire.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1223">Heil Mayden, mihti of mood</L>
<L>Meoke mennes preyeres to here:</L>
<L>&THORN;inges &thorn;at ben lykyng to god</L>
<L N="1226">Wi&thorn; &thorn;e knowe we in-feere.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e Iuge schal come ful grim,</L>
<L>And day of wra&thorn;&thorn;e and doom,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e Iuges riht hond to hym</L>
<L N="1230">Comaunde us &thorn;enne to cum.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="canticle">
<P><I>Audite celi que loquor, audiat terra verba oris mei.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Deuter. 32 (Song of Moses).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue nostri generis parens &amp; patrona,</I></L>
<L><I>Supra cunctas possidens graciarum dona:</I></L>
<L><I>Tuis sanctis precibus meritisque dona</I></L>
<L><I>Ne mens nostra solitum sit in malum prona.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1231">Heil kynnes-wommon of vr kynde,</L>
<L>Vr patrun in vche place,</L>
<L>Of alle wymmen &thorn;ou art hauynde</L>
<L N="1234">&YOGH;iftus alle of grace:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; [&thorn;i] holy preyer [&amp;] deseruyng</L>
<L>Gete us nou witerly</L>
<L>&THORN;at vr &thorn;ouht beo not to vuel doyng,</L>
<L N="1238">As hit is wont, to redi.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="canticle">
<P><I>TE deum laudamus, TE dominum confitemur.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Te Deum.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius filio cetus angelorum</I></L>
<L><I>"Sanctus" clamant iugiter: nos a uiciorum</I></L>
<L><I>Labe munda; perfrui in regno celorum</I></L>
<L><I>ffac nos cum feli[ci]bus premijs iustorum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1239">Heil to whos sone so dere</L>
<L>Angeles Cumpaygnye
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="104"></L>
<L>"Sanctus" crien wi&thorn; vois ful clere,</L>
<L N="1242">Bisiliche and heihe.</L>
<L>ffrom vices clans vs eueridel;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyndom eke of heuene</L>
<L>Mak us haue, wi&thorn; seintes to dwel&mdash;</L>
<L N="1246">Gete us &thorn;at wi&thorn; Mylde steuene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="canticle">
<P><I>Benedicite omnia opera domini domino, laudate &amp; superexaltate eum in secula.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Benedicite</I> (in the Service of Morning Prayer).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue dei genitrix! laudes acceptare</I></L>
<L><I>Cura quas offerimus, nosque presentare</I></L>
<L><I>Per has deo satagas, ut cum iudicare</I></L>
<L><I>Venerit, nos ouibus uelit aggregare.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1247">Heil godus Modur! nou at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>Tac &thorn;ou vre heryinge</L>
<L>&THORN;at we offren to &thorn;e so fast;</L>
<L N="1250">To God vs presentynge</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;i pit&eacute;&eacute;, beo &thorn;ou bysi,</L>
<L>Whon he schal come to dome,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he us gedere for his merci</L>
<L N="1254">Wi&thorn; his schep to beo nome.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="canticle">
<P><I>Benedictus dominus deus israel, quia uisitauit &amp; fecit redempcionem plebi sue.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Benedictus</I> (Song of Zacharias) Luc. 1, 68.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue deum pariens, quem pater preconis</I></L>
<L><I>Benedicens predicat resurrexionis</I></L>
<L><I>Cornu quod promiserat erecturum bonis;</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Luc. 1, 69.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Ad quod nostros dirigat pedes racionis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1255">Heil Mayden clene, God beryng,</L>
<L>Whom &yogh;akarie to-foren</L>
<L>Preched, him fulli blessyng,</L>
<L N="1258">Of vp-risyng beo horn,</L>
<L>To goode men &thorn;at beo-het</L>
<L>To a-rise bo&thorn;e more and lesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;at he of resun vre feet</L>
<L N="1262">&THORN;erto, &thorn;ow preye, he dresse.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="canticle">
<P><I>MAgnificat anima mea dominum.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Magnificat.</I> Luc. 1, 40.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius anima mutuo letata</I></L>
<L><I>Dominum Magnificat, plus humiliata</I></L>
<L><I>Quo fit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. fis</NOTE> <I>maior generans deum; hinc beata</I></L>
<L><I>Dicitur</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. diceris</NOTE> <I>a seculis, felix ad hoc nata.</I>
<PB REF="00000113.tif" N="105"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1263">Heil whos soule wi&thorn; a word</L>
<L>Wel gladed of Message,</L>
<L>Magnifie&thorn; vr aller lord,</L>
<L N="1266">&THORN;erfore meked in &yogh;ong age.</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;at mekenes &thorn;ou were mad gret,</L>
<L>God &thorn;ou beere &thorn;erfore;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e world &thorn;ou art seid and met</L>
<L N="1270">Blessed and sely bore.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="canticle">
<P><I>Nunc dimittis seruum tuum, domine, secundum verbum tuum in pace.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Nunc Dimittis</I> (Song of Simeon) Luc. 3,29</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Aue cuius filius templo presentatur,</I></L>
<L><I>Salutare gencium seni reuelatur,</I></L>
<L><I>Sicque petit postmodum paci dimittatur&mdash;</I></L>
<L><I>Que nostris laboribus tandem conferatur.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1271">Heil, to &thorn;e temple whos sone is</L>
<L>Presented feir and bolde,</L>
<L>Hel&thorn;e of folk schewed was i-wis</L>
<L N="1274">To Simeon &thorn;e Olde;</L>
<L>To pees him lafte he &thorn;ouhte saun&yogh;fayl,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er he schulde dye or liue.</L>
<L>To us &thorn;at pees aftur vre trauayl</L>
<L N="1278">ffor euere beo hit I-&yogh;iue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="canticle">
<P><I>Quicumque vult saluus esse, ante omnia opus est ut teneat catholicam fidem.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Quicumque vult</I> (Athanasian Creed).</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Virgo sancta, suscipe mentis in conclaui</I></L>
<L><I>Verba quibus tociens veniam rogaui,</I></L>
<L><I>Et audito sepius aue tam suaui</I></L>
<L><I>ffac me queso liberum prorsus a ue graui.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1279">Holy Mayden, tak &thorn;ou goodly</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ouht in priuete</L>
<L>&THORN;e wordes &thorn;orwh whuche so bisyli</L>
<L N="128">ffor&yogh;ifnes i aske of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And heer &thorn;e word &thorn;at i ofte sey,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e swete Aue;</L>
<L>Mak me freo, nou I &thorn;e prey,</L>
<L N="1286">ffrom heui serwe to be. AMEN.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="24" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000114.tif" N="106">
<HEAD>[XXIV. Psalterium b. Mariae,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Title in the Index: ffyfty salutaciouns to vre lady by &thorn;is word: Aue, Heyl be &thorn;ou, &amp;c. The Latin poem is mentioned by Mone, l. c. II, p. 257; another MS. is MS. Reichen. 36. In the MS. the poem follows No. XXVIII, but I place it here, because of its affinity to the preceding poem.</NOTE>ascribed to Thomas Aquinas, comprising the 50 first psalms.]</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe uirgo uirginum, per quam uir beatus</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Beatus vir is the beginning of Ps. 1.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 1.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Visitauit miseros, nobis ex te natus:</I></L>
<L><I>Tu[is], Mater, meritis nostras miseratus</I></L>
<L><I>Releuet miserias, deleat reatus.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1">Heil Mayde cheef of alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw whom &thorn;e blessed Mon</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e born was In a stalle,</L>
<L N="4">Vs wrecches so visyte con:</L>
<L>Modur, &thorn;orw &thorn;i wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>He mote vs so releue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of vre gret wrecchednesse</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;e gult no more vs greue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Ave cristi domini mater illibata,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 2.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Cuius est hereditas in gen[te]s translata:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 2, v. 8.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Ne nos ab hac dirimant conscios peccata,</I></L>
<L><I>Cum furor exarserit,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 2, v. 13.</NOTE> <I>subueni beata.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="9">Heil Modur In Mariage</L>
<L>Of crist vr lord Ihesu,</L>
<L>Of whom is flit &thorn;e heritage</L>
<L N="12">Til vs of gret vertu:</L>
<L>&THORN;at us from hit not twinne</L>
<L>Vre synnes &thorn;at we knowe,</L>
<L>Help, ladi wi&thorn; wynne,</L>
<L N="16">Whon wra&thorn;&thorn;e schal brenne and lowe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe cuius filius mortis per soporem</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 3.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Resurgentis meruit corporis honorem;</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 3, v. 5.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Quem per mortem colimus mortis destructorem,</I></L>
<L><I>Colamus post funera uite collatorem.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="17">Heil of whom &thorn;e sone so dere</L>
<L>ffrom slep of de&thorn;es stour</L>
<L>In bodi and soule bo&thorn;e ifere</L>
<L N="20">He ros wi&thorn; gret honour.
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="107"></L>
<L>His de&thorn; we worschipe nou i-wis,</L>
<L>Vre de&thorn; for hit con struye;</L>
<L>Such lyf he graunte vs</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at de&thorn; no more vs nuy&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe verbi thalamus, de quo</I> cum <I>exiuit</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 4.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Voces inuocancium cristus exaudiuit:</I></L>
<L><I>Consignet et muniat, sibi quos vniuit,</I></L>
<L><I>Qui nos sui lumine vultus insigniuit.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 4, v. 7.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">Heil of Crist &thorn;e chaumber derne,</L>
<L>Wher-of whon he out ede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e vois of hem &thorn;at called &yogh;erne</L>
<L N="28">He herde wi&thorn; ful gret spede:</L>
<L>Til him-self he so vs Merke,</L>
<L>And schilde vs also,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;orw his lyht from &thorn;e derke</L>
<L N="32">To-gedere mote we go.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe templum fidei, domus sanctitatis,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 5, v. 8.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 5.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Summe tabernaculum facta maiestatis:</I></L>
<L><I>Scuto nos premuniens bone voluntatis</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 5, v. 13.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Coronet in patria cristus cum beatis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. beatus</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="33">Heil &thorn;e temple of vre fei&thorn;,</L>
<L>Hous of holynesse,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e logge, as dauid sei&thorn;,</L>
<L N="36">I-mad of gret hihnesse:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his scheld vs schilde mote he</L>
<L>Of his owne good wille,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hem vs coroune in his cuntre</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at blesset ben, from ille.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe mater gracie, graciarum plena</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 6.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Tu spes penitencie, venieque vena:</I></L>
<L><I>A culparum nexibus soluens &amp; a pena</I></L>
<L><I>Ad celestis patrie transfer nos amena.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="41">Heil Modur ful of grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;i grace may I not leyne;</L>
<L>To repentaunt &thorn;ou getest space,</L>
<L N="44">Of Merci &thorn;ou art &thorn;e veyne:</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e bondes of vre synne</L>
<L>Vn-bynd vs, from vr peyne,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e blisse &thorn;at &thorn;ou art Inne</L>
<L N="48">So mote we atteyne.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm"><PB REF="00000116.tif" N="108">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe per quam particeps nostre factus</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. factis</NOTE> <I>sortis</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 7.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Deus iudex iustus est, paciens &amp; fortis:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 7, v. 12.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Nos auertens reuocet a gehenne portis,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. mortis</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Euasuros gladium, arcum, uasa mortis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 7, v. 13, 14.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="49">Heil &thorn;orw whom partiner</L>
<L>God is of vre chaunce,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Iuge is rihtwys fer and<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. ferand</NOTE> ner</L>
<L N="52">And vs may wel a-vaunce:</L>
<L>He mote vs torne and calle a-&yogh;eyn</L>
<L>ffrom &thorn;e &yogh;ate of helle,</L>
<L>ffrom Bouwe and swerd, &thorn;at, as men seyn,</L>
<L N="56">Of de&thorn; ben deop vesselle.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe per quam angelis se minorem fecit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 8, v. 6.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 8.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Cum se dei filius nostris interiecit,</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius pater pedibus omnia subiecit,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 8, v. 8.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Ex ore lactencium laudem cum perfecit.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 8, v. 3.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="57">Heil bi whom, to &thorn;e ffader euene,</L>
<L>Crist hym-self maad<SUP>e</SUP> lesse</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;e Angeles &thorn;at ben in heuene,</L>
<L N="60">Til vs hym-self con dresse;</L>
<L>And &yogh;it &thorn;e fader put alle &thorn;inge</L>
<L>In his sones pouweere,</L>
<L>Whon he schewed his heryinge</L>
<L N="64">Bi hem &thorn;at soukynge were.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe Syon filia, de qua legislator</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 9, v. 21.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 9.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Nobis constitutus est, saun[c]tus &amp; saluator:</I></L>
<L><I>Inimicum conterat fortis expugnator,</I></L>
<L><I>Dei iam &amp; hominum factus mediator.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">Heil of syon douhter briht,</L>
<L>Of whom wi&thorn; gret honour</L>
<L>&THORN;e lawe-&yogh;iuere til vs was diht,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;e holy sauiour:</L>
<L>Vre enemy mot he al to-drawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at stronge werreour,</L>
<L>Of God and Mon &thorn;at is bi lawe</L>
<L N="72">A skilful Mediatour.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe mons iusticie in quem transmigratur,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 10.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Vt in cristi nomine tota spes ponatur;</I></L>
<L><I>A quo cuius vterus dum inhabitatur,</I></L>
<L><I>Templum sanctum domini celumque vocatur.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. vacatur cf. Ps. 10, v. 5.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000117.tif" N="109"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="73">Heil &thorn;ou hul of Rihtwysnesse,</L>
<L>To whom &thorn;e wey is caste,</L>
<L>Vre hope in<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. and</NOTE> cristes holynesse</L>
<L N="76">Stabliche to faste;</L>
<L>In &thorn;i wombe whon he wolde dwelle,</L>
<L>He schewede ful gret loue;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy temple men miht hit telle</L>
<L N="80">And heuene of God a-boue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe uiri nescia virgo singularis,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 11.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Que salutem angelo salutante paris:</I></L>
<L><I>Opem fer, presidij stella salutaris,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne sanctus deficiat</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 11, v. 1.</NOTE> <I>inter fluctus maris.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="81">Heil vnknowen to Monnes moon,</L>
<L>Mayden wi&thorn;-outen make;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e Angel &thorn;e grete con,</L>
<L N="84">Vre hele bi-gon to wake:</L>
<L>&THORN;in help and &thorn;i swete socour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we han ofte bi-souht,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou graunte, &thorn;at in &thorn;e sees stour</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;e holy ne fayle nouht.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe per quam dominus nostri non oblitus</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 12.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Ne[c] auertens faciem, nobis est vnitus:</I></L>
<L><I>Purus mentis oculus sit &amp; expeditus,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne vmquam obdormiat in morte sopitus.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 12, v. 4.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="89">Heil bi whom &thorn;e lord of grace</L>
<L>Vs ha&thorn; not for-&yogh;eten</L>
<L>Ne tornd a-wey his feire face</L>
<L N="92">ffrom vs, neor not forleten:</L>
<L>Myn E&yogh;e beo cler, &thorn;at hit not wepe,</L>
<L>Of my soule so briht,</L>
<L>And neuer-more mote hit slepe</L>
<L N="96">To de&thorn; forte be diht.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe quam magnifice laudant vniuersa,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 13.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Vero sapiencie lumine respersa:</I></L>
<L><I>Senciat &amp; sapiat mens ad te conuersa</I></L>
<L><I>Quod per te captiuitas gentis est auersa.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 13, v. 7.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="97">Heil whom &thorn;ei preisen hollich</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at I con nemene,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou art douwet richelich</L>
<L N="100">Wi&thorn; &thorn;e liht of heuene:
<PB REF="00000118.tif" N="110"></L>
<L>Vre &thorn;ouht to &thorn;e beo torned so</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit may fele and saye</L>
<L>&THORN;at wrecchednesse from folk is gon</L>
<L N="104">And torned al a-waye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe cuius filius mons est sancte spei</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 14.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>ffactus tabernaculum uere requiei:</I></L>
<L><I>ffac vt per iusticiam in-herentes ei</I></L>
<L><I>Letemur in gloria coheredes dei.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="105">Heil, &thorn;i sone of gret Miracle</L>
<L>Is hul of holy hope,</L>
<L>Of reste he is vr tabernacle,</L>
<L N="108">To schilde vs from reyn-drope:</L>
<L>Do, ladi, &thorn;orw &thorn;i rihtwysnesse</L>
<L>In him &thorn;at we mowe reste</L>
<L>As heyres of his blisfulnesse&mdash;</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;at wol be vr beste.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe per quam reddita spes est desperatis,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 15.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Quibus est hereditas restituta gratis:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 15, v. 5.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Verus factus hostia cristus pro peccatis</I></L>
<L><I>Pars sit nostri calicis, pars hereditatis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 15, v. 5.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="113">Heil &thorn;orw whom to gret vauntage</L>
<L>Crist wolde vs restore,</L>
<L>To hope of vre heritage</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;at was from vs forlore;</L>
<L>ffor he was mad &thorn;e offringe</L>
<L>ffor vre synnes fele,</L>
<L>And part was of vre suffrynge,</L>
<L N="120">Part til vs to dele (!).</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe cuius vterum cristus cum intrauit</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 16.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Igne sancti spiritus cor examinauit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 16, v. 3.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Et vt mater fieres dignam approbauit:</I></L>
<L><I>Per te nos respiciat qui te visitauit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="121">Heil, wi&thorn;-oute pomp or bost</L>
<L>&THORN;i wombe whon crist com Inne,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fuir of &thorn;e holigost</L>
<L N="124">Assayet &thorn;in herte wi&thorn; gynne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou schuldest his Moder beo</L>
<L>fful wor&thorn;i he &thorn;e fonde:</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;e he mote vs al bi-seo</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;at visited vs so in londe.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm"><PB REF="00000119.tif" N="111">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe cuius filius celos inclinauit</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 17, v. 10.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 17.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Tibi cum altissimi virtus obumbrauit:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Luc. 1, 35.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Nos in celum subleuet saluans quos creauit,</I></L>
<L><I>Per te qui terrigenis se contemperauit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="129">He[i]l to whom &thorn;i sone, &thorn;e beste,</L>
<L>Heuene bouwed doun lowe,</L>
<L>Whon<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Whom</NOTE> &thorn;e vertu of aller-hexte</L>
<L N="132">Bi-schadewed &thorn;e al, I trowe:</L>
<L>In to heuene he mot vp lifte</L>
<L>Vs &thorn;at were for-lore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him-self so wolde schifte</L>
<L N="136">Among &thorn;at in eor&thorn;e weor bore.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe cuius vterum regum rex ingressus</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 18.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Vt sponsus de thalamo cristus est egressus;</I></L>
<L><I>Sic de tabernaculo</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. tabernaculum</NOTE> <I>solis sol progressus,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 18, v. 5, 6.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Nos in viam dirigat, corrigens</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. dirigens</NOTE> <I>excessus.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil whos wombe &thorn;e sauiour,</L>
<L>Kyng of alle, we Rede,</L>
<L>As a Brid out of his bour</L>
<L N="140">Crist him-self out eode,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e sonne in Morwtyd grey</L>
<L>&YOGH;eode out of his tente,</L>
<L>To<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. he?</NOTE> dresse vs in to Rihte wey,</L>
<L N="144">&THORN;at we be not forschente.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe que auxilium de sanclo misisti</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 19, v. 2.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 19.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Dum sancta sanctissimum digne concepisti:</I></L>
<L><I>Nostra sit saluacio fides vera cristi,</I></L>
<L><I>Quem fide concipiens virgo genuisti.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">Heil, &thorn;at help from holi place</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sendest to Monkynde,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou holy bi godus grace</L>
<L N="148">Conceyuedest in &thorn;i Mynde</L>
<L>Him &thorn;at was most holy,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is vr sauyour,</L>
<L>In ffei&thorn; Conceyuedest verreyli</L>
<L N="152">And bar hym wi&thorn; honour.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe salutarium causa gaudiorum,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 20.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Pariens in tempore Regem seculorum,</I></L>
<L><I>Sit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Sint</NOTE> <I>corona capitis gloria membrorum,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 20, v. 3.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>ffinis non deficiens summaque virorum.</I>
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="112"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="153">Heil vre gostly hele,</L>
<L>And cause of al vre bliss,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bar &thorn;e kyng of wele</L>
<L N="156">Of al &thorn;is world I-wis.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e hed is crouned feire,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e limes ben fayne&mdash;</L>
<L>Of heore worschip &thorn;at neuer schal peire,</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;ar vs neuer-more playne.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Ave de qua prodiit deus humanatus</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 21.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Nostros pie perferens in se cruciatus,</I></L>
<L><I>Propter nostra vulnera gratis vulneratus:</I></L>
<L><I>Nostros suo sanguine deleat reatus.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="161">Heil from whom God almiht</L>
<L>Went for&thorn; verrey Mon,</L>
<L>Peyne for vs and gret dispyt</L>
<L N="164">He soffred mony on,</L>
<L>ffor vre woundes delfuly</L>
<L>Woundet was he sore,</L>
<L>His Blood vre gultes clanly</L>
<L N="168">Wusch for euer-more.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe quam rex omnium Matrem preelegit,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 22.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Vt sis locus pascue gregi quam collegit:</I></L>
<L><I>Virga sis &amp; baculus</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 22, v. 4.</NOTE> <I>illis quos elegit,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt iam nichil desit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 22, v. 1.</NOTE> <I>his quos electos regit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="169">Heil whom &thorn;e kyng of alle &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; chose &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. &thorn;e</NOTE> to ben his Dame,</L>
<L>And to a folle pasturyng</L>
<L N="172">To his herde wi&thorn; game:</L>
<L>&YOGH;erde and staf &thorn;ou art<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. be</NOTE> bo&thorn;e</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at he ha&thorn; chose,</L>
<L>And nou&yogh;t hem wante hem-self to lo&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="176">He rule&thorn; hem nou&yogh;t to lose.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe terra glorie, terra quam fundauit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 23.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Cum nobis rex glorie se contemperauit;</I></L>
<L><I>Qui per mortem principes mortis triumphauit,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 23, v. 7.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Nos a morte liberet morte quos saluauit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="177">Heil of blisse &thorn;e riche lond,</L>
<L>&THORN;at foundet was bi reson</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e Ioyful kynges hond</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at to vs com in good seson,
<PB REF="00000121.tif" N="113"></L>
<L>He &thorn;at &thorn;e prince of de&thorn;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his de&thorn; ouer-com</L>
<L>And alle from &thorn;e harde Bre&thorn;</L>
<L N="184">Of de&thorn; he vs out nam.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe cuius filius dulcis est &amp; rectus</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 24.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Vt reducat exules peregre profectus,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 24, v. 4, 5.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Vere nobis gracie legifer efectus:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 24, v. 8, 12.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>In se nostros ordinet mores &amp; affectus.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="185">Heil &thorn;i sone &thorn;at is so swete</L>
<L>And rihtful of entent,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Outlawes synnes forte bete</L>
<L N="188">On pilgrimage he went;</L>
<L>Til vs of grace certeyne</L>
<L>Lawe-berer was i-kud:</L>
<L>In vs he mote ordeyne</L>
<L N="192">Vre werkes and &thorn;ouhtes hud.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe que</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. quem</NOTE> <I>dominicum circumdas</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. circumdans</NOTE> <I>altare</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 25, v. 6.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 25.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Concludens in vtero dei salutare:</I></L>
<L><I>Nostra purget</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. purge&thorn;</NOTE> <I>crimina potens expiare,</I></L>
<L><I>Pontifex &amp; hostia sancte factus are.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="193">Heil &thorn;at of vr lord of heuene</L>
<L>&THORN;at Auter vmbi&yogh;ede,</L>
<L>In &thorn;i wombe &thorn;ou speredest heuene<NOTE PLACE="marg">= euene</NOTE></L>
<L N="196">Hele of god, vre mede,</L>
<L>Of vre synnes clansyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; ful pouwere;</L>
<L>&THORN;at Bisschop him-self is offring</L>
<L N="200">Of &thorn;e holy Autere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe Mater domini nos illuminantis</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 26.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Mater inquam filij per te nos saluantis:</I></L>
<L><I>Tuis virgo meritis precibusque sanctis</I></L>
<L><I>Mentis pelle tenebras ad te suspirantis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="201">Heil modur of [&thorn;at] lord so mylde</L>
<L>&THORN;at lihtned vs alle ful schene,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art moder of &thorn;at childe</L>
<L N="204">&THORN;at sauede vs alle bi-dene:</L>
<L>Maide, &thorn;orw &thorn;i wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>And preyeres &thorn;at holy be,</L>
<L>Put hem from &thorn;e derknesse</L>
<L N="208">&THORN;at sikyng longen to &thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="114"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe pudicicie titulis</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. tutulus</NOTE> <I>ornata</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 27.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Mater facta filij, sed inuiolata,</I></L>
<L><I>Corporis materia illi ministrata</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius iam refloruit caro suscitata.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 27, v. 7.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="209">Heil! of clene chastite</L>
<L>&THORN;e worschipe nis not luitel,</L>
<L>ffor Modur and mayde &thorn;ouh &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L N="212">Worschipful is &thorn;at tytel.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mateer of &thorn;i swete bodi</L>
<L>Crist, he tok of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ouh he died delfuly,</L>
<L N="216">A&yogh;eyn to lyue ros he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe nostri generis decus</I> sempiternum,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 28.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Cuius scandens filius solium paternum,</I></L>
<L><I>Residens in dextera rex est in eternum:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 28, v. 10.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Affectum supplicibus exibe maternum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="217">Heil of vre kuynde, ladi,</L>
<L>Worschipe wi&thorn;-outen ende;</L>
<L>&THORN;i sone in to heuene stih,</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at is so good and hende,</L>
<L>And on his ffader riht syde</L>
<L>Sit for euere and O:</L>
<L>A Moderes lappe &thorn;ou open wyde</L>
<L N="224">To hem &thorn;at ben in wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe de qua gaudium fulsit matutinum,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 29, v. 6</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 29.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Quod detersit hominis fletum uespertinum,</I></L>
<L><I>Per concessum corporis sanctum cilicinum</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 29, v. 12.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Redemptis aperiens paradisi sinum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="225">Heil, of whom &thorn;e Morwenyng</L>
<L>Ioyful schon and briht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wiped awey vre wepyng</L>
<L N="228">On Euen and of niht;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e bodi as a Sekke</L>
<L>&THORN;at is i-Maad of here,</L>
<L>Of paradys he opened &thorn;e hekke</L>
<L N="232">To hem &thorn;at bouht were.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe regis omnium ciuitas munita,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 30, v. 22.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 30.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Ciuitas ab angelis digne custodita,</I></L>
<L><I>Virtutum mirifice gemmis insignita:</I></L>
<L><I>In te nostrum gaudium, in te sit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. sic</NOTE> <I>spes sita.</I>
<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="115"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="233">Heil &thorn;ou kynges feir Cite,</L>
<L>Walled wel a-boute,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; angeles &thorn;at in heuene be</L>
<L N="236">I-kept, wi&thorn; mony a route;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; riche stones wonderly</L>
<L>Of vertues &thorn;ou art by-set:</L>
<L>Vre Ioye in &thorn;e sikerly</L>
<L N="240">And vre hope ben met.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe cui non inputans dominus peccatum,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 31, v. 2.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 31.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Partum dedit glorie fructumque beatum:</I></L>
<L><I>Cor gerens &amp; corporis decus illibatum,</I></L>
<L><I>Erumpnosas contere spinas voluptatum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="241">Heil to whom no-maner synne</L>
<L>Vre lord a-rette con,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;af a bur&thorn;e of blisse wi&thorn;-inne,</L>
<L N="244">&THORN;e ffruit of Blod and bon;</L>
<L>Herte wi&thorn;-Inne nor bodi wi&thorn;-oute</L>
<L>Of fful&thorn;e hedde no dispit:</L>
<L>&THORN;e woful &thorn;ornes vs aboute</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;ow bruse of foul delyt.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe cuius anima in deo laudatur</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 33, v. 2.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 33. (<I>Ps.</I> 32 <I>want|ing.</I>)</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Benedicens dominum per quam exaltatur:</I></L>
<L><I>Tuis, virgo, benedic, &amp; benedicatur</I></L>
<L><I>Per quam</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. quem?</NOTE> <I>benediccio facta predicatur.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="249">Heil whos soule wor&thorn;ily</L>
<L>In god is fully preysed,</L>
<L>In Blessynde god ful hihly</L>
<L N="252">&THORN;orw whom &thorn;ou art vp-reiset:</L>
<L>Blesse alle &thorn;yne, Maiden dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;i-self also be Blesset,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw whom blessyng is preched here</L>
<L N="256">And from vs not lesset.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe de qua voluit nasci rex virtutum,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 34.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Non abhorrens tangere carnis nostre lutum;</I></L>
<L><I>Apprehendens iusticie arma syue scutum</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 34, v. 2, 10.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Hominem eripuit ope destitutum.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="257">Heil of whom he wolde be bore,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng of alle vertuwe,</L>
<L>And wlated nou&yogh;t to touche &thorn;erfore</L>
<L N="260">Vr fflesch of Cley&yogh;es huwe;
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="116"></L>
<L>&THORN;er-of (!) he made him-self a scheld</L>
<L>Priueliche to dare,</L>
<L>fforte rescouwe in &thorn;e feld</L>
<L N="264">Mon of help ful bare.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe fecundissime domus vbertatis,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 35.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Torrens indeficiens vere voluptatis.</I></L>
<L><I>ffonte nos inebria sancte karitatis,</I></L>
<L><I>Cor ad lumen exitans summe claritatis.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf Ps. 35, v. 9, 10.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">Heil &thorn;ou hous bi niht and day,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;at is</NOTE> of gret plente,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Brok &thorn;at rennes ay</L>
<L N="268">fful of likerouste:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou fulle vs alle of &thorn;at welle</L>
<L>fful of Charite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vr hertes mouwe euer dwelle</L>
<L N="272">In Brihtnesse wi&thorn; &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe benignissima, nusquam malignari,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 36.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Nec in malignantibus uolens emulari;</I></L>
<L><I>Cuius est in domino semper delectari:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 36, v. 4.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Eius nos deliciis dona saciari.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="273">Heil of wymmen mylde most,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noldest no lu&thorn;urnesse,</L>
<L>Nor haddest in no lu&thorn;ur gost</L>
<L N="276">Loue nor swetnesse,</L>
<L>But in vr lord &thorn;e lyked wel,</L>
<L>And euer-more &thorn;ou schal:</L>
<L>&THORN;erof &thorn;ou graunte vs sum del,</L>
<L N="280">To fullen vs &thorn;er-wi&thorn;-al.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe mater vnicum generans dulcorem:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 37.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Venientis iudicis tempera furorem,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne in ira senciam illum correptorem,</I></L>
<L><I>Set vite perpetue per te largitorem.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="281">Heil Moder of &thorn;e newe gyse</L>
<L>&THORN;at bar &thorn;e swete childe:</L>
<L>Whon he come&thorn;, &thorn;at hi&yogh;e Iustise,</L>
<L N="284">ffrom his wra&thorn;&thorn;e vs schilde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we fele not &thorn;at harde snibbyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at mony mon schal drede,</L>
<L>But of &thorn;e lyf euer-lastyng</L>
<L N="288">Mote we han vr mede.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm"><PB REF="00000125.tif" N="117">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe cui spiritus sanctus obumbrauit,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 38.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Dum carnis materiam caro ministrauit;</I></L>
<L><I>Cum nostram substanciam sibi sociauit</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 38, v. 8.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Ad suam nos gloriam deus exaltauit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="289">Heil whom of &thorn;e holigost</L>
<L>&THORN;e schadewe ha&thorn; vmbicast,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i flesch, as wel &thorn;ou wost,</L>
<L N="292">&THORN;i sones flesch made in hast;</L>
<L>Whon he vr kuynde in &thorn;at manere</L>
<L>Tok to his felawe,</L>
<L>To his Blisse &thorn;at is so dere</L>
<L N="296">On hei&yogh; he con vs drawe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe per quam reddita lux refulsit cecis,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 39.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Quam per Euam abstulit gustus ille necis:</I></L>
<L><I>De lacu miserie &amp; de luto fecis</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 39, v. 2.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Nos educat meritum tue sancte precis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="297">Heil &thorn;orw whom to &thorn;e blynde</L>
<L>Liht schon ful feire,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Eue, Modur of vre kynde,</L>
<L N="300">Wi&thorn; tast of de&thorn; con peire:</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e Slouh of wrecchednesse</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e dregge of cleye</L>
<L>To lede vs to &thorn;i wor&thorn;inesse,</L>
<L N="304">&THORN;yn holi preyere seye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe beatissima per quam nos respexit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 40.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Quando super pauperes deus intellexit;</I></L>
<L><I>Egestatem hominis diues non despexit,</I></L>
<L><I>Sed in nos carismatum munera conuexit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="305">He[i]l blesset beo &thorn;i mood,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw whom God bi-held</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e pore he vnderstod,</L>
<L N="308">In toune and in feld;</L>
<L>Vre neode nolde he dispise,</L>
<L>&THORN;ouh he were riche i-nouh,</L>
<L>But in mony a wyse</L>
<L N="312">His Richesse to vs drouh.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe quam fons glorie uoluit implere,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 41.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Vt in cristo fieres fons salutis uere:</I></L>
<L><I>Nostre desiderium mentis intuere,</I></L>
<L><I>Dans de plenitudine fontis nos gaudere.</I>
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="118"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="313">Heil whom &thorn;e welle of bliss</L>
<L>Wolde fulle ful of wele,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ou weore Maad, i-wis,</L>
<L N="316">&THORN;e welle of verrey hele:</L>
<L>Vr &thorn;ouhtes and vre &yogh;ernynge,</L>
<L>Ladi, &thorn;ou so bi-holde</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;e welles springe</L>
<L N="320">We mouwe beo glad and bolde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe quam de gentibus dominus discreuit,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 42.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Cum in ventre uirginis verbum requieuit;</I></L>
<L><I>Causam &amp; c[h]yrographum pleniter</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. plenum</NOTE> <I>deleuit</I></L>
<L><I>Quam in primum hominem prima lex decreuit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="321">Heil whom God specialy</L>
<L>ffrom o&thorn;ere wolde twynne,</L>
<L>Whon he &thorn;i bodi priuely</L>
<L N="324">Wolde reste wi&thorn;-Inne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cause of Obligacion</L>
<L>&THORN;at vs to helle bond,</L>
<L>He brac wi&thorn; gret fuson</L>
<L N="328">Of his riht hond.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe cuius uiscera cristum ediderunt,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 43.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Per quam</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. quem?</NOTE> <I>uicti subiacent qui nos afflixerunt:</I></L>
<L><I>Salua nos in brachio</I>, cuius <I>uim</I> senserunt</L>
<L><I>Qui victrici dextere cristi restiterunt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="329">Heil of whom &thorn;e holi gutte</L>
<L>Crist ha&thorn; for&thorn; sende,</L>
<L>Bi whom &thorn;ei ben vndurputte<NOTE PLACE="marg">orig. vndurpotte</NOTE></L>
<L N="332">&THORN;at vs &yogh;erne wolde schende:</L>
<L>Saue vs alle in his miht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei han ofte feled</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn;-stonden a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e riht</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;e hond &thorn;at ha&thorn; hem greued.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe stans ad dexteram domini Regina</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 44.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Quam ambit uarietas virtutum diuina:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 44, v. 10.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Vide, regis filia, &amp; aurem inclina,</I></L>
<L><I>Natus ex te fructus sit nobis Medicina.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="337">Heil &thorn;at stondest neuer lo&thorn;</L>
<L>On riht half of vr lord;</L>
<L>Whom sondernesse vmbigo&thorn;</L>
<L N="340">Of vertuwes in a-Cord:
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="119"></L>
<L>Bi-hold, &thorn;ou douhter of &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>And bouwe doun Ere &thorn;yne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffruit of &thorn;e spryngynge</L>
<L N="344">Beo vre Medicyne.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe tabernaculum, quam sanctificauit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 45.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>San[c]torum sanctissimus, in te cum intrauit;</I></L>
<L><I>Ex te nobis impetus fluminis manauit,</I></L>
<L><I>Ciuitatem domini qui letificauit.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 45, v. 5.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="345">Heil &thorn;ou tente for &thorn;e schour</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e hete of Sonne,</L>
<L>Whom god com in to &thorn;i bour,</L>
<L N="348">Wi&thorn; &thorn;e for to wonne;</L>
<L>ffrom &thorn;e to vs in gret plente</L>
<L>&THORN;e water ron a-flod</L>
<L>&THORN;at gladed al &thorn;e grete Cite&mdash;</L>
<L N="352">Wher-of we mowe &thorn;ink good.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe per quam filius dei cum descendit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 46.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Nos in sui nominis amore succendit;</I></L>
<L><I>Particeps substancie nostre cum ascendit,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Ps. 46, v. 6.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Ascendendi pariter nobis spem inpendit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="353">Heil &thorn;orw whom wi&thorn;-oute blame</L>
<L>God dounward wolde beende,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e loue of his name</L>
<L N="356">Vre hertes forto teende;</L>
<L>Of vre kuynde for he part hadde,</L>
<L>Whon he steih vp in to Blis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e rihte wey he vs ladde&mdash;</L>
<L N="360">We hopen &thorn;ider, i-wis.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe magna domina &amp; laudanda nimis,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 47.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Regis magni ciuitas, mons syon sublimis:</I></L>
<L><I>Tu magna, tu predita meritis opimis,</I></L>
<L><I>Tuos ad celestia transfer ab hijs imis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="361">Heil &thorn;at art so gret ladi</L>
<L>And gretlych artou preised,</L>
<L>Cite of &thorn;e kyng &thorn;at [sit] on hih,</L>
<L N="364">Hul Syon vp-reised;</L>
<L>Deserued &thorn;ou hast gret Richesses</L>
<L>&THORN;at gostly ben, i trouwe:</L>
<L>fflette us from &thorn;e wrecchednesses</L>
<L N="368">&THORN;at we dwellen in so lowe.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm"><PB REF="00000128.tif" N="120">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe per quam homines</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS hominis</NOTE> <I>natos ad laborem</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 48.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Ad amissum reuocans dominus honorem,</I></L>
<L><I>De nostra substancia sumptum carnis florem</I></L>
<L><I>Ipsis fecit angelis in se celsiorem.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="369">Heil &thorn;orw whom, &thorn;at was boren</L>
<L>Mon to gret vnreste,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e worschipe &thorn;at he hedde lore</L>
<L N="372">Whon he was lik a Beeste,</L>
<L>God restored hym a-&yogh;eyn</L>
<L>And set Monkynde aboue</L>
<L>&THORN;e hexte Angeles, as we seyn&mdash;</L>
<L N="376">&THORN;erfore we schulde him loue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>AVe mater filio digna nascituro,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 49.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Corporis materiam ministrans passuro:</I></L>
<L><I>Purges</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. purgans</NOTE> <I>consciencias, ut sic</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. sit</NOTE> <I>corde puro</I></L>
<L><I>Procedamus obuiam judici uenturo.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="377">Heil Modur most wor&thorn;i</L>
<L>To God &thorn;at schulde be bore,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e tok &thorn;e swete bodi</L>
<L N="380">&THORN;at pyned was so sore;</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;at peyne he clensed<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. clense</NOTE> vs so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; herte schene</L>
<L>Sikerly we mou go</L>
<L N="384">A&yogh;eyn vr Iugge bi-dene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="psalm">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Ave nobis miserans, nostri miserere,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. 50.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Quod misericordie mater dicta uere;</I></L>
<L><I>Misereris omnium qui tuis scincere</I></L>
<L><I>Laudibus &amp; gaudijs gaudent inherere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">Heil, of vs &thorn;ou haue merci,</L>
<L>Of Merci we &thorn;e prey,</L>
<L>ffor Moder &thorn;ou art witerly</L>
<L N="388">Of Merci, as we seye.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast merci of hem alle</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; deuocioun</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; preisyng on &thorn;e calle,</L>
<L N="392">&THORN;ou herest heore Orisoun.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="25" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000129.tif" N="121">
<HEAD>[XXV. A salutacioun to vre lady.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">So the title in the Index.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MAyden, Modur, and comely Qween,</L>
<L>&THORN;at art in heuene and euer schal ben,</L>
<L N="3">Euere beo &thorn;ou blessed,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ow sendes me help and grace,</L>
<L>Whon I was in a place</L>
<L N="6">&THORN;er Deth was to me dressed.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mi lyf I wende me hedde forsaken,</L>
<L>And drery de&thorn; to me taken,</L>
<L N="9">To make wi&thorn; him to wone:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; my tonge, als I cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>I Cri&yogh;ede, "Ladi, help me nou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;ow prey to &thorn;i swete sone!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;i grace com to me &thorn;at day</L>
<L>In to a Castel &thorn;er I lay,</L>
<L N="15">Men seide I was but ded;</L>
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;at &thorn;ou louedest dere,</L>
<L>Com to me &thorn;orwh &thorn;i preyere</L>
<L N="18">In &thorn;e fourme of bred.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Marie, of ioye &thorn;ou berest &thorn;e pris,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou art &yogh;ate of paradis,</L>
<L N="21">&THORN;er Ioye is Murie and long.</L>
<L>ffeire Modur and Mayden swete,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fyue Ioyes I &thorn;e grete,</L>
<L N="24">Ladi, here my song. Aue Maria.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HEil beo &thorn;ow, Marie Modur of crist,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Conceyuedest him al wyth lyst,</L>
<L N="27">Ihesu &thorn;at was so mylde;</L>
<L>He liht in to &thorn;e, so&thorn; hit was,</L>
<L>As dude &thorn;e Sonne &thorn;orwh &thorn;e Glas,</L>
<L N="30">And so &thorn;ow wex wi&thorn; chylde. Aue M.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heyl Marie, of Maydens &thorn;e flour,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow beer Ihesu, vr sauiour,</L>
<L N="33">Wi&thorn;-outen eny peyne.</L>
<L>ffeir hit was, &thorn;at ilke<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. ille</NOTE> bur&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in his &yogh; u&thorn;e made mur&thorn;e</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;i pappes tweyne! Aue.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Some stanzas seem wanting.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000130.tif" N="122"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Mayden, &thorn;at euer-more</L>
<L>Schalt beo Qween, and hast ben &yogh;ore,</L>
<L N="39">In heuene and in eor&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos ben foure of power most:</L>
<L>ffadur, and Sone, and holygost,</L>
<L N="42">And &thorn;ou, Ladi, &thorn;e feor&thorn;e. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil gracious qween Mari,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e vs neode&thorn; calle and cri</L>
<L N="45">Whon we ben sori and syke.</L>
<L>Heil hele in halle and boure;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou louest men &thorn;at &thorn;e honoure,</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;i loue is euere i-like. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil, sone boote &thorn;er bale is neih;</L>
<L>&THORN;auh &thorn;i wonynge beo an heih,</L>
<L N="51">&THORN;ou herknest to vs at nede.</L>
<L>Heil rest to weri bones;</L>
<L>Whon I was stoned wi&thorn; harde stones,</L>
<L N="54">&THORN;ow halp wi&thorn;-outen mede. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil, to al Angeles Ioye and blis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow art Qwen &thorn;er, I wot, I-wis,</L>
<L N="57">Witnes of vr Bokes.</L>
<L>Heil witti and wys of werkes,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou drawest bo&thorn;e prestes and Clerkes</L>
<L N="60">Out of &thorn;e fendes hokes. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil fendes fo, feirest of alle!</L>
<L>&THORN;i Bed was In an Asse stalle</L>
<L N="63">Whon &thorn;i sone was Born.</L>
<L>Heil weddet wyf and Mayden eke,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e &thorn;is holy prophetes speeke</L>
<L N="66">An hundred &yogh;er bi-forn. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil mihtiest of Middel<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Mildel</NOTE> ert,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e &thorn;e fendes ben a-ferd</L>
<L N="69">And douten &thorn;e ful sore.</L>
<L>Heil cumfort of Careful wyues;</L>
<L>When &thorn;ei ben ferd of heore lyues,</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;ou helpest hem euer-more. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil chyld boren In Na&yogh;areth,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou beere a child &thorn;at to[c]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. to</NOTE> &thorn;e deth,</L>
<L N="75">As alle trewe telle.
<PB REF="00000131.tif" N="123"></L>
<L>Heil Godus Modur gentyl and good,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;at</NOTE> let Adam and his blood</L>
<L N="78">Out of &thorn;e pit of helle. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Modur Merciabel,</L>
<L>He is &thorn;i sone wi&thorn;-outen fabel</L>
<L N="81">&THORN;at alle &thorn;ynge wot.</L>
<L>Heil Meke marie of renoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;i sone ha&thorn; for vs I-leyd a-doun</L>
<L N="84">His herte-blood al hot. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Mari &thorn;at to vs hi&yogh;es!</L>
<L>&THORN;i Modur bar &thorn;reo Maries&mdash;</L>
<L N="87">So feire hire beo-tydde;</L>
<L>On was Marie Iacobe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at o&thorn;ur Cleophe,</L>
<L N="90">And &thorn;ou, ladi, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Marie, wi&thorn; most honour</L>
<L>Corouned qween in heuene-tour</L>
<L N="93">Bi-fore &thorn;y sones face;</L>
<L>To alle neodful &thorn;ou art cou&thorn;,</L>
<L>Wel art &thorn;ou cald wi&thorn; Angeles Mouth,</L>
<L N="96">"Marie ful of grace." Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Heil Marie ful of grace,</L>
<L>Heil beo &thorn;ou in vche a place,</L>
<L N="99">ffor god is laft wi&thorn; &thorn;e."</L>
<L>In heuene and eor&thorn;e &thorn;ou beo honoured,</L>
<L>ffor my lyf &thorn;ou hast socoured</L>
<L N="102">And drawen de&thorn; from me. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil feirest of alle floures,</L>
<L>A-postles,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Of postles</NOTE> Martires an Confessoures</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;e for ladi calle;</L>
<L>Heil brihtor &thorn;en &thorn;e sonne-beem,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou beere Ihesu In Bedlehem,</L>
<L N="108">Wi&thorn; Blood &thorn;at bouht vs alle. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil feirest of alle landes,</L>
<L>To god &thorn;ou hef vp &thorn;yn handes</L>
<L N="111">Whon Gabriel &thorn;e grette.</L>
<L>Heil clerore &thorn;en &thorn;e Cristal-ston,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art in heuene, Blood and Bon,</L>
<L N="114">ffor &thorn;er &thorn;i sone &thorn;e sette. Aue.
<PB REF="00000132.tif" N="124"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heyl Marie, Blessed kidde,</L>
<L>A feir grace &thorn;e beo-tidde&mdash;</L>
<L N="117">&THORN;i peere is nouhwher leued:</L>
<L>God him-self &thorn;i bodi chees,</L>
<L>To sitte wi&thorn; him on his dees</L>
<L N="120">And bere Coroune on heued. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Marie as briht as day,</L>
<L>Goddus sone wi&thorn;-Inne &thorn;e lay</L>
<L N="123">His Burth to a-byde.</L>
<L>Whon he was two and &thorn;ritti &yogh;eer old,</L>
<L>He fauht for men as kempe bold,</L>
<L N="126">And baar ful blodi syde. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Marie, &thorn;at art ay boun</L>
<L>To kepe us from temptacion</L>
<L N="129">Of &thorn;e fendes Blake;</L>
<L>Heil riche Qween of vche a toun,</L>
<L>&THORN;i sone ha&thorn; soffred passioun</L>
<L N="132">ffor al Monkynde sake. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil briht Braunche of Rose rote,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e sprong a sauour swote</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;at sauere&thorn; ay so swete.</L>
<L>Heil Modur of al-holy Chirche,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at euere wol wysly worche,</L>
<L N="138">I rede &thorn;at heo &thorn;e grete. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Ioachyms Ioyful seed,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sayh whon La&yogh;arus was ded</L>
<L N="141">ffoure dayes and More;</L>
<L>Bi-fore Martha and Magdeleyn</L>
<L>Ihesu called him to lyue a-&yogh;eyn</L>
<L N="144">And for him rewed sore. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Marie, Mayden sleihe,</L>
<L>Mony goode dedes &thorn;ou sei&yogh;e</L>
<L N="147">Of &thorn;ulke &thorn;at Ihesu wrouhte:</L>
<L>A Mon was ded and lay on Bere,</L>
<L>His Moodur wi&thorn; ful reu&thorn;ful chere</L>
<L N="150">Grace at Ihesu souhte; Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Marie, of gret pite,</L>
<L>Ihesu for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e</L>
<L N="153">Made &thorn;at wommon bli&thorn;e:
<PB REF="00000133.tif" N="125"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e Bere he put his honde</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;e Cors anon vp stonde;</L>
<L N="156">To lyue hit ros als-swi&thorn;e. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Mayden, heil &thorn;ou,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;i Ioyes I may not nou</L>
<L N="159">In my song telle;</L>
<L>Is mony an hundred &yogh;er a-gone</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast ben, ladi, queen &thorn;yn one</L>
<L N="162">Of heuene, Er&thorn;e and helle. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Holy Mayden, wel &thorn;e be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was at &thorn;e feste of Galyle,</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;er was wanted wyn:</L>
<L>&THORN;i sone comaundet men in halle</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; watur fulle heor vessels alle</L>
<L N="168">By-fore Architriclyn; Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Marie, &thorn;at sauh al &thorn;at:</L>
<L>Whon Ihesu on &thorn;i Barm sat</L>
<L N="171">And blessed hit wi&thorn; his honde,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e watur &thorn;at &thorn;er was brouht</L>
<L>By-com red wyn al vn-souht,</L>
<L N="174">&THORN;er nis no beter in londe. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil semlokest vndur sonne,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;e was a werk by-gonne</L>
<L N="177">By-twene God and Mon;</L>
<L>Blessed beo &thorn;ou of alle wymmen,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e fruyt of &thorn;i wombe, Amen,</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at such a werk bi-gon. Aue. &mdash; &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;yn holy nome,</L>
<L>&THORN;at schilde[s]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. And schilde</NOTE> vs from synne and schome,</L>
<L N="183">And Makes &thorn;e fend vnglad;</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;at nempned is Mari,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fendes by-gynnen a-wei to fly</L>
<L N="186">And di&yogh;e&thorn; neih for drad. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;yn heued aboue,</L>
<L>&THORN;er god hath schewed his moste loue</L>
<L N="189">On heih riht in his halle:</L>
<L>&THORN;e Coroune of heuene &thorn;er-on is set,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e Angeles &thorn;ou art gret</L>
<L N="192">As ladi of hem alle. Aue.
<PB REF="00000134.tif" N="126"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;i</NOTE> witti Brayn:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast maad &thorn;e fend vn-fayn</L>
<L N="195">&THORN;at deope in helle sit;</L>
<L>Monnes soules &thorn;at weore lost,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou beer a child on &thorn;i Coste</L>
<L N="198">ffro helle-pyne ha&thorn; hem quit. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;at holy frount,</L>
<L>&THORN;at holy is holden and sount,</L>
<L N="201">&THORN;e cheef of al &thorn;i face;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-in is set a bond of wit,</L>
<L>Vndur &thorn;e croune comly knit</L>
<L N="204">Wi&thorn; a louely lace. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i Brouwes bent:</L>
<L>A feir grace God ha&thorn; &thorn;e sent,</L>
<L N="207">&THORN;i lookyng is louely ay.</L>
<L>Ladi, for &thorn;i louesum chere</L>
<L>Prey &thorn;i sone, &thorn;at we mowe here</L>
<L N="210">Serue him to pay! Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed be, ladi, &thorn;y Riht Ere:</L>
<L>&THORN;e holygost, he liht in &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="213">fflesch and Blod to take;</L>
<L>God sende his sone adoun,</L>
<L>To soffre pine and passioun</L>
<L N="216">And faiht wi&thorn; &thorn;e Drake. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, Ladi, &thorn;yn o&thorn;ur Ere,</L>
<L>ffor hit herknes ay-where</L>
<L N="219">To Men &thorn;at haue to done;</L>
<L>&THORN;yn Ere is open at vre callyng:</L>
<L>Whon we preye for eny &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="222">Vr erende come&thorn; sone. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, bo&thorn;e &thorn;yn Ei&yogh;en,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;reo kynges offringes se&yogh;en</L>
<L N="225">&THORN;at kneled &thorn;e by-fforen.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seost euer-more I-lyche</L>
<L>Ioye and Blisse in heuene-riche&mdash;</L>
<L N="228">To godur hele &thorn;ou weore boren! Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed be,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. be &thorn;ou</NOTE> ladi, a-mong &thorn;i wittes</L>
<L>&THORN;i ffeire Neose, &thorn;at comely sittes</L>
<L N="231">Amidde &thorn;i frount bi-ne&thorn;en.
<PB REF="00000135.tif" N="127"></L>
<L>Ladi, for &thorn;e loue of Anastas</L>
<L>Let vs seo &thorn;i feire ffaas,</L>
<L N="234">Whon we wenden he&thorn;en! Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, bo&thorn;e &thorn;i chekes:</L>
<L>Merci for vs to him &thorn;ou sekes</L>
<L N="237">&THORN;at &thorn;e for Modur Ches.</L>
<L>Ladi, as &thorn;ou art Modur mylde,</L>
<L>ffrom worldus schome &thorn;ou me schylde,</L>
<L N="240">And gete vs grith and pes! Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ladi, I-blessed beo &thorn;i Mouth:</L>
<L>Whon God &thorn;e sende in to &thorn;e south</L>
<L N="243">&THORN;e Aungel Gabriel,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow onswerdest Mekelych and sayde,</L>
<L>"I am heer Godus hond-Mayde"&mdash;</L>
<L N="246">&THORN;is word is in gospel. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed be, lady, &thorn;i trewe tonge:</L>
<L>A-Mong wymmen olde and &yogh;onge</L>
<L N="249">&THORN;at euer&yogh;ite han ben,</L>
<L>So treowe I-founden was neuer non;</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i &thorn;ou art in Blod and Bon</L>
<L N="252">Corouned heuene-Qween. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i Chin I-chose:</L>
<L>&thorn;er-on schal neuer mon lose</L>
<L N="255">To blesse hit niht and day;</L>
<L>Hit schal reue him serwe and synne,</L>
<L>And make him in his lyf to wynne</L>
<L N="258">&THORN;e Ioye &thorn;at laste&thorn; ay. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i brihte neb-schaft&mdash;</L>
<L>Of kuynde he cou&thorn;e ful wel his craft</L>
<L N="261">&THORN;at hit hedde entayled!</L>
<L>&THORN;e teres ron doun of<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. a?</NOTE> floode</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou se&yogh;e &thorn;i sone on Roode,</L>
<L N="264">ffeet and hondes nayled. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i white sweere:</L>
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;at &thorn;ou louest deere,</L>
<L N="267">Clupped hit ofte a-boute.</L>
<L>Whose wol his synne forsake</L>
<L>And of &thorn;at cluppyng Ioye make,</L>
<L N="270">Hym &thorn;ar no deueles doute. Aue.
<PB REF="00000136.tif" N="128"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, lady, &thorn;i clere &thorn;rote:</L>
<L>At neode euere &thorn;ou dost vs note</L>
<L N="273">Whon Bale vs ha&thorn; I-bounde.</L>
<L>Ladi, &thorn;ou neuere woldest &yogh;elpe,</L>
<L>Prey &thorn;i sone &thorn;at he vs helpe</L>
<L N="276">ffor his Blessede wounde! Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i scholdres two,</L>
<L>And &thorn;i cleer Canel-bonus also</L>
<L N="279">&THORN;at semely ben in siht:</L>
<L>As kyng, kniht or Champioun</L>
<L>ffor Men &thorn;ou art redi-Boun</L>
<L N="282">Wi&thorn; &thorn;e fend to fiht. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;yn Armes tweyne:</L>
<L>In vche a gederyng &thorn;ou art gayne</L>
<L N="285">To helpen vs at nede;</L>
<L>Vr wo &thorn;ou tornest to weole,</L>
<L>And sauest vs from wreches fele&mdash;</L>
<L N="288">Blessed beo &thorn;ou to Mede! Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, bo&thorn;e &thorn;in hondes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swa&thorn;eled him in swa&thorn;elyng-bondes</L>
<L N="291">&THORN;at Monnes soule ha&thorn; wrouht,</L>
<L>Heuene and helle and alle londes,</L>
<L>ffisch and ffoul, S&eacute;&eacute; and Sondes,</L>
<L N="294">Al he maade of nouht. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. beo &thorn;ou</NOTE> ladi, and feyre hem falle,</L>
<L>&THORN;i &thorn;hommes and &thorn;i ffyngres alle</L>
<L N="297">&THORN;at genteliche are Maket,</L>
<L>On ei&thorn;er hond wi&thorn; ffyngres fyue;</L>
<L>&THORN;ow &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Wi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ow</NOTE> hondelet him on lyue</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;at helle-fuir has<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. was</NOTE> slaket. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i brihte Brest:</L>
<L>Ihesu tok &thorn;er-in<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. on?</NOTE> Rest,</L>
<L N="303">Mon of miht most.</L>
<L>Was neuer non so clene of lyf</L>
<L>As &thorn;ow weore, bo&thorn;e Mayden and wyf,</L>
<L N="306">To Resseyue &thorn;e holygost. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i stable herte:</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou se&yogh;e &thorn;i sone smerte,</L>
<L N="309">Gret Care &thorn;ou keptest;
<PB REF="00000137.tif" N="129"></L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou sauh him Buffet and beten,</L>
<L>Al his bodi of blood by-weten,</L>
<L N="312">No wondur &thorn;auh &thorn;ou weptest. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i brihte wombe:</L>
<L>&THORN;er-in was &thorn;e holy Lombe</L>
<L N="315">&THORN;at bouht Adam and Eue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day also blyue</L>
<L>He ros vp fro de&thorn; to lyue&mdash;</L>
<L N="318">Such is vre bi-leeue. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i softe sydes,</L>
<L>In Ioye and blis &thorn;ou vs abydes,</L>
<L N="321">&THORN;er &thorn;ou schalt beo founden;</L>
<L>&THORN;i sone vs bouhte wi&thorn; Raunsoun</L>
<L>And drouh vs out of dungoun,</L>
<L N="324">&THORN;er Lucifer liht i-boundun. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed be, ladi, &thorn;i feire Bak,</L>
<L>And &thorn;i leendes wi&thorn;-outen lak,</L>
<L N="327">&THORN;at dwellen ay in Blis.</L>
<L>Ladi, for &thorn;i muchel honour</L>
<L>&THORN;in holy help and &thorn;y socour</L>
<L N="330">Let vs neuere mis! Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;y Maydenhede:</L>
<L>Neuer was in &thorn;e sowen sede</L>
<L N="333">As of wommon-kynde;</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i &thorn;ou art coround Qween</L>
<L>Of alle wymmen &thorn;at han I-ben</L>
<L N="336">Or euer schal Mon fynde. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i bo&thorn;e &thorn;hi&yogh;es,</L>
<L>To help vs ay &thorn;at hi&yogh;es</L>
<L N="339">ffrom &thorn;e vn-hold honde.</L>
<L>Ladi, to &thorn;i sone vs dresse,</L>
<L>And preye hym &thorn;at he vs blesse</L>
<L N="342">And mayntyme in sonde! Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i comely knen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for vs alle kneolynge ben</L>
<L N="345">Bo&thorn;e niht and day.</L>
<L>Hit is but on vs I-long,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er we worche ille or wrong,</L>
<L N="348">Hou we schul haue vr pay. Aue.
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="130"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed [beo], ladi, alle beo-dene</L>
<L>&THORN;i Schonkes and &thorn;i Schynes schene</L>
<L N="351">&THORN;at are strong and sty&thorn;e;</L>
<L>Ofte hast &thorn;ow erly and late</L>
<L>Don vr erende at heuene-&yogh;ate</L>
<L N="354">And Maked vs ful bli&thorn;e. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i Maydenhede,</L>
<L>&THORN;yn haunches and &thorn;i feire fete,</L>
<L N="357">&THORN;at for vs trauayle.<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. doost tr.; doost overl. by another hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ladi, for &thorn;i grete grace</L>
<L>A-Mong &thorn;i Ioyes of a place</L>
<L N="360">Let vs neuere fayle! Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed, ladi, beo al &thorn;i toos:</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou of Childbedde a-Ros,</L>
<L N="363">To &thorn;e Temple &thorn;ow &yogh;eode,</L>
<L>fforte folfulle &thorn;at lawe</L>
<L>&THORN;at was vsud by Olde dawe&mdash;</L>
<L N="366">Symeon sauh &thorn;at dede. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, al at ones</L>
<L>&THORN;i fflesch &thorn;i blod, &thorn;i skyn &thorn;i bones,</L>
<L N="369">And &thorn;in Entrayles wi&thorn;.</L>
<L>Ladi, for &thorn;i Muchel honour</L>
<L>Prey Ihesu vr sauyour,</L>
<L N="372">He graunt vs pees and grith! Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i grete streng&thorn;e:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast drawen my lyf on leng&thorn;e</L>
<L N="375">And don an Almus werk;</L>
<L>&THORN;ow holdest &thorn;e fend vndur foote,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow geete fro his herte-Rote</L>
<L N="378">Theophules lettre, &thorn;e Clerk. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i goode &thorn;ewes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at kepen vs from &thorn;e blake schrewes</L>
<L N="381">&THORN;at Mennes soules han craued;</L>
<L>&THORN;e grete o&thorn;us &thorn;at Men han sworen</L>
<L>Hedde I-maad &thorn;e world for-loren,</L>
<L N="384">But as &thorn;ou hast hit saued. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i stable &thorn;ouht:</L>
<L>Vre neodes for-&yogh;etest &thorn;ou nouht,</L>
<L N="387">&THORN;ow delest wi&thorn; non hoket;
<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="131"></L>
<L>Bi-fore &thorn;e kyng &thorn;at demes riht</L>
<L>&THORN;ou pledest for men day and niht&mdash;</L>
<L N="390">Blessed beo &thorn;at voket! Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i swetnes.</L>
<L>Al Monkynde more and les</L>
<L N="393">To helle were &thorn;ei gon,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei weoren alle in helle i-bounde,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;i Sone wi&thorn; blodi wounde</L>
<L N="396">Hed leesed hem out vchon. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed beo, ladi, &thorn;i feirhede,</L>
<L>Menget al wi&thorn; whit and Rede,</L>
<L N="399">Wi&thorn; brihtnes al bi-Ron.</L>
<L>Ladi, flour of alle londes,</L>
<L>Bryng him out of carful bondes</L>
<L N="402">&THORN;at hath &thorn;is song bi-gon! Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed ladi, Blesse I schal</L>
<L>&THORN;y Lyf, &thorn;i Soule, &thorn;i Bodi al</L>
<L N="405">&THORN;at eeuene to heuene went.</L>
<L>As wis, ladi, beo vr frend</L>
<L>And schild vs from &thorn;e foule fend,</L>
<L N="408">And let vs neuer be schent. A M. E N.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="26" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[XXVI. An orisoun to &thorn;e fyue woundes of ihesus cristus.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">So the title in the Index.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesus, &thorn;at di&yogh;edest vppon &thorn;e tre</L>
<L>And &thorn;oledest de&thorn; for loue of me</L>
<L N="3">And for myn elder sake,</L>
<L>ffrom &thorn;e deuel and al his miht</L>
<L>&THORN;ow kepe me, bo&thorn;e day and niht,</L>
<L N="6">Wher I slepe or wake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lord, &yogh;if me grace to worche &thorn;i wille</L>
<L>And &thorn;i Comaundement to for&thorn;fille,</L>
<L N="9">&THORN;at heuene may beo my Meede.</L>
<L>Ihesu, bring me to &thorn;i Reste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euere wi&thorn;-outen ende schal leste,</L>
<L N="12">And help me at al my nede.
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="132"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now God, &thorn;at died on &thorn;e Rode</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-on schedde &thorn;in herte-blode,</L>
<L N="15">And of Marie was boren,</L>
<L>Heer me whon I to &thorn;e calle,</L>
<L>And let me neuere in synne falle,</L>
<L N="18">Ne for my mis-dede be loren.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. for &thorn;i</NOTE> fyue woundes on &thorn;e Roode</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;oledest for monnes goode,</L>
<L N="21">Moot my socour be.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e worschipe of &thorn;i wounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;yn herte &thorn;olede in &thorn;at stounde,</L>
<L N="24">A Pater noster sei we. Pater.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &thorn;e worschipe of &thorn;i riht honde</L>
<L>&THORN;at was woundet in &thorn;e holy londe</L>
<L N="27">And nayled to &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>Heere to-day my preyere,</L>
<L>As wis as &thorn;ou bouhtest me dere</L>
<L N="30">Haue Merci, lord, on me. Pater.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu lord &thorn;at is so Mylde,</L>
<L>ffrom dedly synne &thorn;ou me schilde</L>
<L N="33">Bo&thorn;e day and niht;</L>
<L>Cumforte me, Ihesu, wi&thorn; &thorn;i sonde,</L>
<L>As wisliche as &thorn;i luft honde</L>
<L N="36">Was nayled wi&thorn; on-riht. Pater.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God, schilde my soule &thorn;at day fro care</L>
<L>Whon hit schal from my bodi fare;</L>
<L N="39">Haue Merci, lord, on me,</L>
<L>As wis as I leue wel and wot</L>
<L>&THORN;at on &thorn;e goode ffriday &thorn;i riht fot</L>
<L N="42">Was nayled to &thorn;e tre. Pater.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As wis as harde to &thorn;e tre</L>
<L>&THORN;i lift ffoot was nayled for me,</L>
<L N="45">Graunte me &thorn;i grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I may haue &thorn;i Ioyful reste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn;-outen ende schal leste,</L>
<L N="48">And seo &thorn;i louely face. A M E N. Pater.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="27" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000141.tif" N="133">
<HEAD>[XXVII. An orisoun to &thorn;e fyue ioyes of vre lady.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">So the title in the Index.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MArie Modur, wel &thorn;e bee!</L>
<L>Modur and Mayden, &thorn;enk on me</L>
<L N="3">ffor &thorn;i muchel miht!</L>
<L>Marie Mayden meke and mylde,</L>
<L>ffrom mis-chaunce to-day me schylde,</L>
<L N="6">&THORN;at me ne dere no wiht. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Marie, &thorn;ou hast no peere,</L>
<L>Heere to-day my preyere,</L>
<L N="9">&THORN;ouh I vn-wor&thorn;i be;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e I clepe and calle:</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou art flour of alle</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;ou haue Merci of me. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Marie Modur and Mayden eke,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at Ioye I &thorn;e by-seche</L>
<L N="15">&THORN;at Gabriel &thorn;e grette,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Ioye me kepe day and niht</L>
<L>ffrom &thorn;e deuel and al his miht,</L>
<L N="18">And of mis-dede me lette. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at God was boren</L>
<L>Let me not, ladi, beo forloren</L>
<L N="21">&THORN;at &thorn;i sone bouht dere,</L>
<L>But vndurfong to-day my beode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit may stonde me in sum steode</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;orwh &thorn;i preyere. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at fro de&thorn; to lyue</L>
<L>God vp-Ros wi&thorn; woundes fyue</L>
<L N="27">Vppon &thorn;e paske-day,</L>
<L>Beo-seche &thorn;i sone, ladi Mylde,</L>
<L>ffrom mischaunce &thorn;at he me schilde</L>
<L N="30">As wis as he best may. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for &thorn;e Ioye God steih to heuene</L>
<L>On holy &thorn;oresday wi&thorn; mylde steuene,</L>
<L N="33">Help me, ladi of miht,
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="134"></L>
<L>And beo bo&thorn;e my scheld and spere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no wikked mon me dere</L>
<L N="36">Ne deuel bi day no niht. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for &thorn;e Ioye aftur &thorn;yn ende,</L>
<L>Bi-fore<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. ffor?</NOTE> to heuene &thorn;er &thorn;ou dudest wende</L>
<L N="39">In Mur&thorn;e and Iolyte,</L>
<L>Bryng me in to &thorn;at reste</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer wi&thorn;-outen ende schal leste,</L>
<L N="42">&YOGH;if &thorn;i wille be. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ladi, flour of wymmen-kynne,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if me grace &thorn;i loue to wynne,</L>
<L N="45">Mayden feir and fre,</L>
<L>And let me neuer for no synne</L>
<L>ffor-go &thorn;at Ioye &thorn;at &thorn;ou art Inne,</L>
<L N="48">AMEN par Charite. Aue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="28" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[XXVIII. A salutacioun to vre lady.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">So the title in the Index. The first 6 stanzas are printed in Warton, <I>Hist. of Engl. Poetry</I>, 1871, II. p. 283.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil beo &thorn;ow, Marie Moodur and May,</L>
<L>Mylde and Meke and Merciable!</L>
<L>Heyl follich fruit of so&thorn;fast fay,</L>
<L N="4">A&yogh;eyn vche stryf studefast and stable;</L>
<L>Heil so&thorn;fast soule in vche a-say&mdash;</L>
<L>Vndur &thorn;i sone is non so able;</L>
<L>Heil logge &thorn;at vre lord in lay,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;e formast &thorn;at neuer was founden in fable.</L>
<L>Heil trewe, trou&thorn;eful and tretable,</L>
<L>Heil cheef i-chosen of Chastite,</L>
<L>Heil homely, hende and amyable:</L>
<L N="12">Do prey for vs to &thorn;i sone so fre. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil sterre &thorn;at neuer stunte&thorn; liht,</L>
<L>Heil Busch Brennyng &thorn;at neuer was brent;<NOTE PLACE="marg">A simile used by Chaucer.</NOTE></L>
<L>Heil rihtful rulere of eueri riht,</L>
<L N="16">Schadewe to schilde &thorn;at scholde be schent;
<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="135"></L>
<L>Heil, Blessed beo &thorn;ow, Blosme briht,</L>
<L>To trou&thorn;e and trust was &thorn;yn entent;</L>
<L>Heil Mayden and Modur most of miht,</L>
<L N="20">Of alle mischeues a-Mendement.</L>
<L>Heil spice sprong &thorn;at neuer was spent,</L>
<L>Heil trone of &thorn;e Trinite,</L>
<L>Heil soiourne<NOTE PLACE="marg">on erasure.</NOTE> &thorn;at Godus<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. god is</NOTE> sone to sent:</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;ow preye for vs &thorn;i sone so fre. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil hertely in holinesse,</L>
<L>Heil hope of help to heihe and lowe,</L>
<L>Heil streng&thorn;e and stal<NOTE PLACE="marg">on erasure.</NOTE> of stabelnesse,</L>
<L N="28">Heil wyndouwe of heuene-wowe,</L>
<L>Heil reson of al rihtwysnesse,</L>
<L>To vche a Caytyf cumfort to knowe,</L>
<L>Heil Inocent out of Angernesse,</L>
<L N="32">Vr takel, vr tol &thorn;at we on trowe;</L>
<L>Heil frend to alle &thorn;at beo&thorn; for&thorn; flowe,</L>
<L>Heil liht of loue and of lewte,</L>
<L>Heil brihtor &thorn;en &thorn;e blod on snowe:</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;ow preye for vs to &thorn;i sone so fre. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Mayden, heil Modur, heil Martir trewe,</L>
<L>Heil kyndely I-knowe Confessour;</L>
<L>Heil euenere of old lawe and of newe,</L>
<L N="40">Heil Buildere boold of cristes bour;</L>
<L>Heil Rose hi&yogh;est of hyde and hewe,</L>
<L>Of alle ffruytes feirest fflour;</L>
<L>Heil Tortul trustiest and trewe,</L>
<L N="44">Of alle trou&thorn;e &thorn;ou art tresour;</L>
<L>Heil puyred princesse of paramour,</L>
<L>Heil Blosme of Brere, Brihtest of ble,</L>
<L>Heil owner of eor&thorn;ly honour:</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;ou prey for vs to &thorn;i sone so fre. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil hende, heil holy Emperesse,</L>
<L>Heil quene<NOTE PLACE="marg">on erasure.</NOTE> corteis, comely and kynde;</L>
<L>Heil distruyere of eueri stresse,</L>
<L N="52">Heil mender of eueri monnes mynde;</L>
<L>Heil Bodi &thorn;at we ouhte to blesse,</L>
<L>So fei&thorn;ful frend may neuer mon fynde;</L>
<L>Heil lenere and louere of largenesse,</L>
<L N="56">Swete and swettest &thorn;at neuer may swynde;
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="136"></L>
<L>Heil Botenere of eueri bodi blynde,</L>
<L>Heil Borgun brihtes[t] of alle bounte,</L>
<L>Heil trewore &thorn;en &thorn;e wode-bynde:</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;ou pray for us to &thorn;i sone so fre. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil Modur, heil Mayden, heil heuene-qwene,</L>
<L>Heil &yogh;atus<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &yogh;ate</NOTE> of paradys,</L>
<L>Heil Sterre of &thorn;e Se &thorn;at euere is seene,</L>
<L N="64">Heil riche, Ryal and Riht-wys;</L>
<L>Heil Buyrde, I-blesset mote &thorn;ow beene,</L>
<L>Heil perle, of al perey &thorn;e pris,</L>
<L>Heil Schadewe in vch a schour schene,</L>
<L N="68">Heil fayrore &thorn;en &thorn;e flour delys;</L>
<L>Heil cher chosen &thorn;at neuer nas chis,</L>
<L>Heil chef chaumbre of Charite,</L>
<L>Heil in wo &thorn;at euere was wys:</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;ow prey for vs to &thorn;i sone so fre. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil welle of merci, watur of lyf,</L>
<L>Heil gentel &yogh;erde of Iesse Roote;</L>
<L>Heil Mayde, heil Moodur, heil wedded wyf,</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;i blessednes brouht us til vr bote;</L>
<L>Heil studefast stuntere of eueri strif,</L>
<L>&THORN;e feirest &thorn;at euer &yogh;eode vppon fote;</L>
<L>ffrom vs vche a deuel &thorn;ou deest drif;</L>
<L N="80">Heil swete, heil swettest, heil most swote;</L>
<L>Heil Mayden &thorn;at for vs most mote,</L>
<L>Heil puired princes of pite,</L>
<L>Heil Mirour vche mon on to tote:</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;ow pray for vs to &thorn;i sone so fre. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil holy herte, hope of hele,</L>
<L>Heil fostrere of vre ful fay,</L>
<L>Heil worchere of &thorn;is worldly wele,</L>
<L N="88">Heil wissere of vre rihtwys way,</L>
<L>Heil fallere of &thorn;e fendes fele,<NOTE PLACE="marg">or. frele</NOTE></L>
<L>Heil logge &thorn;at vre lord in lay,</L>
<L>Heil Chartre &thorn;at Ihesus gon a-sele:</L>
<L N="92">ffor vs, ladi, to &thorn;i sone &thorn;ou pray</L>
<L>&THORN;at at &thorn;e dredful domus-day</L>
<L>Vre a-vokes &thorn;at &yogh;e may be,</L>
<L>ffor non o&thorn;ur &thorn;en help us may</L>
<L N="96">Saue &thorn;i-self and &thorn;i swete sone fre. Aue.
<PB REF="00000145.tif" N="137"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil hed of worschip, cristes trone,</L>
<L>&THORN;e semely Temple of Salamon;</L>
<L>Heil brihtest Sonne, vn-meued Mone,</L>
<L N="100">Heil ful fles of gedeon;<NOTE PLACE="marg">on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L>Heil help to hem &thorn;at han to done,</L>
<L>Loue of Angel, mur&thorn;e of man:</L>
<L>&THORN;i socour, ladi, send vs sone</L>
<L N="104">And help vs, for we han mis-gan.</L>
<L>Charbokel neuer so cler schone</L>
<L>As &yogh;e schyne in cristes see.</L>
<L>To &yogh;ow, ladi, I make my mone:</L>
<L N="108">Prey for vs to &thorn;i sone so fre. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">This stanza in the MS. written at the foot of the page.</NOTE>Heil Archa federis euere I-loke,</L>
<L>Cristes trewe tresorie;<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. trosorie</NOTE></L>
<L>Heil Archa of noe neuer to-broke,</L>
<L N="112">ffor worldli wawe &thorn;at neuer wolde wrie;</L>
<L>Heil esterne &yogh;ate faste I-stoke</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e god &thorn;i sone eode out &thorn;er-bye;</L>
<L>Heyl chosen chastite &thorn;e &yogh;oke,</L>
<L N="116">engendreer of vre gentrie;</L>
<L>Heil kuyndenesse, heil cortesye,</L>
<L>Heil douweer of diuinite,</L>
<L>Heil susteynour of Seyntuarie:</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;ou preye for vs &thorn;i sone so fre. Aue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil lok, heil loue, heil Marie!</L>
<L>I heile &thorn;e wi&thorn; herte and &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>I heile &thorn;e wi&thorn; Mou&thorn; and ei&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="124">ffor my wilde werkes han beo nouht;</L>
<L>I heile &thorn;e and Merci crie,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al my bodi I haue mis-wrouht;</L>
<L>I heile &thorn;e whon I schal dye,</L>
<L N="128">And help to blisse &thorn;at we be brouht.</L>
<L>Pray &thorn;i sone, &thorn;at vs deore bouht,</L>
<L>Graunt vs grace for his pite,</L>
<L>&THORN;auh synnes haue vs &thorn;orwh-souht;</L>
<L N="132">Bring vs to &thorn;i blis &thorn;at euer schal be, Amen. Aue.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="29" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000146.tif" N="138">
<HEAD>[XXIX. Miracles of oure lady.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ed. before by me in <I>Herrig's Archiv</I>, 1876. On the various collec|tions of Miracles of our lady see Mussafia, <I>Sitzungsber. der Wiener Acad. der Wissensch.</I>, 1887-8.</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>I. [hou &thorn;e cite off croteye was delyuered of &thorn;eir enemys by vre lady coote.]<NOTE PLACE="head">(<I>A Picture.</I>)</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>So the title in the Index.</P><P>The Index to MS. Vern. gives the following list of these Miracles; only the first 9 (the 9th unfinished) are preserved in the MS.</P><LIST>
<LABEL>1.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou &thorn;e cite off croteye was delyuered of &thorn;eir enemys by vre lady coote.</ITEM>
<LABEL>2.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou &thorn;e Iewes, in despit of vre lady, &thorn;rewe a chyld in a gonge.</ITEM>
<LABEL>3.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou an holy hermyt prayde a synful womman pray god for hym.</ITEM>
<LABEL>4.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou a Iew putte his sone in a brennyngge ouene, for he was communed wit o&thorn;ur cristene children on &thorn;e pask-day.</ITEM>
<LABEL>5.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou a man, for ache, cut of his foot, and was heled a&yogh;eyn by vre lady.</ITEM>
<LABEL>6.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou a iew lente a cristenemon moneye, and took vre lady to borow.</ITEM>
<LABEL>7.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of a prest &thorn;at lay by a nonne.</ITEM>
<LABEL>8.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou vre lady &yogh;af mylk off heore pappes to a man &thorn;at hadde &thorn;e squynacye.</ITEM>
<LABEL>9.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of an incontinent monk, &thorn;at was drouned, and rered a&yogh;eyn by vre lady to lyf.</ITEM>
<LABEL>10.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of a clerk &thorn;at wolde euery day segge &thorn;e fyue ioyes of vre lady.</ITEM>
<LABEL>11.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou vre lady dude &thorn;e offys of a sextresse fyftene &yogh;eer for a nonne.</ITEM>
<LABEL>12.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou a god wyf by-nam fro an ymage of vre lady &thorn;e ymage of heore child.</ITEM>
<LABEL>13.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of a deuout knyt off kyrkeby.</ITEM>
<LABEL>14.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou a wommon slow heore doutour hosebonde, and was dampned to &thorn;e fuyr, and delyuered by vre lady.</ITEM>
<LABEL>15.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou &thorn;e deuel took lyknesse of a wommon, and seyde he was godes modur.</ITEM>
<LABEL>16.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou out of a monkes mouth, aftur his deeth, grew a lilie, and in euery leef was wryten wyt large lettres of gold: aue maria.</ITEM>
<LABEL>17.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou a nonne fur&yogh;at to grete vre ladye, and ful in apostasye.</ITEM>
<LABEL>18.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou seynt Bernard say twey children ydrouned for &thorn;eir inobedience.</ITEM>
<LABEL>19.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of &thorn;ys antynene: Salue regina.</ITEM>
<LABEL>20.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou vre lady sauter bygan.</ITEM>
<LABEL>21.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou vre lady was a medewyf in &thorn;e churche of seynt michel in monte tumba.</ITEM>
<LABEL>22.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou &thorn;e feste of &thorn;e natiuite of vre lady by-gan.</ITEM>
<LABEL>23.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of a deuout clerk &thorn;at died in drenkelenschipe, &amp; was wyrned sepulcre.</ITEM>
<LABEL>24.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of a &thorn;ef &thorn;at was &thorn;re dayes hanget, and saued by vre lady.</ITEM>
<LABEL>25.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of a prest &thorn;at coude non o&thorn;ur masse but salua sancta parens.</ITEM>
<LABEL>26.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou &thorn;e deuel, in liknesse of a bole and of o&thorn;ur bestes, encumbrede a monk for he was ones drunke.</ITEM>
<LABEL>27.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of a wommon off Rome &thorn;at conceyuede bi heore owne sone, &amp; slou heore child.</ITEM>
<LABEL>28.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Off a child &thorn;at weddede an ymage of vre lady.</ITEM>
<LABEL>29.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou at &thorn;e cite of Tholuse &thorn;e priuetes were knowe of Iewes.</ITEM>
<LABEL>30.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou vre lady &yogh;af to seynt Bonyte &thorn;e bisschoph holy vestemens.</ITEM>
<LABEL>31.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou &thorn;e deuel, in fals liknesse of seynt Iame, made a man cutte of his priue menbres.</ITEM>
<LABEL>32.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of a monk of Cisteus, &thorn;at vre lady took in heore armes, and custe hym.</ITEM>
<LABEL>33.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou Constantyn &thorn;e Emperour ordeynede for euere-mor in seynt petre churche at Rome, in wyrschip of seynt petre, a lampe wyt Baume perpetuelly brennyngge.</ITEM>
<LABEL>34.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of seynt fulbert &thorn;e bisschop, &thorn;at made &thorn;e storye, and &thorn;e legende and o&thorn;ur tretys off &thorn;e natiuite of vre lady.</ITEM>
<LABEL>35.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of a mayden &thorn;at was cald Musa.</ITEM>
<LABEL>36.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of a malicious priour of seynt sauyours of &thorn;e cite of papye.</ITEM>
<LABEL>37.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of seynt Ierom, bisschoph of papye.</ITEM>
<LABEL>38.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of a whyth corporaus was in-tync wit red wyn, in seynt Micheles churche, &thorn;at his cald cluse.</ITEM>
<LABEL>39.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou vre lady taute a clerk hou he schulde segge heore complyn.</ITEM>
<LABEL>40.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Of &thorn;e schrewednesse of Iustynyan &thorn;e emperour.</ITEM>
<LABEL>41.</LABEL>
<ITEM>And why &thorn;e feste of &thorn;e puryficacion was ordeyned.</ITEM>
<LABEL>42.</LABEL>
<ITEM>hou an ymage of &thorn;e child off vre lady taute ano&thorn;ur child and preyde hym to come dyne wyt hym.</ITEM>
</LIST></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOrdus, &yogh;if &yogh;e wol lusten to me,</L>
<L>Of Croteye, &thorn;e noble Cite,</L>
<L>ffurst hou hit bi-seget was</L>
<L N="4">And se&thorn;&thorn;en dilyueret &thorn;orw godus gras
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="139"></L>
<L>And &thorn;orw &thorn;e help of vre ladi,</L>
<L>So witnesse&thorn; Miracle of Mari.</L>
<L>Out of peihtes lond &thorn;er came</L>
<L N="8">A kniht &thorn;at Rollo was his name;</L>
<L>He gederet wi&thorn; him out of &thorn;e north Cost</L>
<L>Of diuerse nacions a wel gret host,</L>
<L>Out of Denemarch and North-wey,</L>
<L N="12">Of feolore folk &thorn;en I con sey.</L>
<L>Mony Cuntres he can destruye,</L>
<L>Wel muchel pepule he gan anuye,</L>
<L>In mony a Coost, bi Est and West,</L>
<L N="16">He won him londes bi Conquest.</L>
<L>ffurst he bi-gon in &thorn;e North Cuntre,</L>
<L>And aftur he schipet ouer &thorn;e S&eacute;&eacute;.</L>
<L>Sire Rollo wi&thorn; al his host</L>
<L N="20">Ariuede in ffraunce vp in a cost.</L>
<L>&THORN;at Cuntre gon he furst destrui&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore he called hit Northmondye,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei dude men to de&thorn;e i-lome</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at out of &thorn;e North cost come;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore he called hit Northmondye,</L>
<L>As writen I fynde in his storye:</L>
<L>Of Bruit &thorn;e Cronicle witnesset wel</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;is Conquest of Rollo eueridel.</L>
<L>Hit was &thorn;e furste Duik in &thorn;at lond,</L>
<L>ffor he furst won hit wi&thorn; his hond.
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="140"></L>
<L>Whon Rollo &thorn;at kniht was &thorn;ider I-comen</L>
<L N="32">And mony a toun &thorn;ei hedde I-nomen,</L>
<L>Mony a Mon &thorn;ei dude to de&thorn;e,</L>
<L>fful fewe &thorn;ei saueden, and &yogh;it vnne&thorn;e.</L>
<L>And as he trauayled on his Iorney,</L>
<L N="36">He com to a Cit&eacute;&eacute;, was called Crotey.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sone Sire Rollo wi&thorn; his Route</L>
<L>Bi-sette &thorn;at Cit&eacute;&eacute; wi&thorn; sege a-boute.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-Inne &thorn;e Cit&eacute;&eacute; men hedde gret drede:</L>
<L N="40">Heore Enemys weren so douhti of dede;</L>
<L>Of socour &thorn;ei se&yogh;en non o&thorn;ur won</L>
<L>But &yogh;elden &thorn;e Cite, or elles ben slon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AN holi Bisschop &thorn;er was &thorn;er-Inne,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at was called sire Waltelinne,</L>
<L>He was Bisschop of &thorn;at Cit&eacute;&eacute;,</L>
<L>A swuy&thorn;e noble mon was he.</L>
<L>He tauhte heom &yogh;erne knele and crie</L>
<L N="48">To crist and to his Modur Marie;</L>
<L>&THORN;orw help of hire &thorn;at bar vr lord</L>
<L>He hopede &thorn;ei schulden han sone cumfort.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;en him-self go&thorn; to &thorn;e Sextri&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at was &thorn;e Munstres treserye;</L>
<L>Vr ladi Curtel &thorn;er-Inne he found.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret Reuerence he kneled to ground,</L>
<L>&THORN;er to Marie he beed his bone</L>
<L N="56">To sende &thorn;at Cite socour sone.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; peple and gret processioun</L>
<L>He bar &thorn;at Relyk &thorn;orw al &thorn;e toun,</L>
<L>fful deyntely diht vppon a spere,</L>
<L N="60">As lordus Baner displayet in werre.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Bisschop heet cast vp &thorn;e &yogh;ate</L>
<L>And bad his folk folewe hym algate,</L>
<L>Him-self bi-foren and &thorn;ei be-hynde;</L>
<L N="64">He hoped in Marie help to fynde.</L>
<L>A-non as &thorn;ei were &thorn;us out went,</L>
<L>Heore enemys letten hem not but schent:</L>
<L>ffor so a-stoneyd and ferede men</L>
<L N="68">Nere neuer worse &thorn;en &thorn;ei were &thorn;en!</L>
<L>Whon on &thorn;at relyk &thorn;ei caste heore siht,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei woxe start<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. stare</NOTE>-blynde anon-riht;
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="141"></L>
<L>&THORN;ei mihten no more defenden heom &thorn;en</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;en so mony blynde or drounkene Men.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Citeseins token hem at heore wille,</L>
<L>Summe to Raunsum, and summe to spille.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en &thorn;ei turnen a&yogh;eyn to &thorn;e Cit&eacute;&eacute;</L>
<L N="76">Wi&thorn; Mur&thorn;e and gret solempnite,</L>
<L>And herieden heihly &thorn;at Mylde may</L>
<L>&THORN;at socourde and saued hem so &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>And do we on &thorn;e same wyse</L>
<L N="80">Bo&thorn;e glade and bli&thorn;e wi&thorn; bisy seruise,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same ladi forte qweme,</L>
<L>&THORN;at so in Mischeef to vs take&thorn; &yogh;eme</L>
<L>To hire sone crist vre erende to bede,</L>
<L N="84">And socoure&thorn; vs so at eueri nede.</L>
<L>Nou, ladi, preye &thorn;i sone on hih</L>
<L>To alle cristene he graunte Merci! Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>II. [hou &thorn;e Fewes, in despit of vre lady, prewe a chyld in a gonge.]<NOTE PLACE="head">(<I>Picture.</I>)</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WOse loue&thorn; wel vre ladi,</L>
<L>Heo wol quiten his wille wel whi,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur in his lyf or at his ende:</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e ladi is so freo and hende.</L>
<L>Hit fel [so] sum-tyme in Parys,</L>
<L>As witnesse&thorn; in holy writ Storys.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Cite bi-fel &thorn;is cas:</L>
<L N="8">A pore child was of porchas,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; &thorn;e Beggeri &thorn;at he con wynne</L>
<L>He fond sumdel what of<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. for</NOTE> his kinne,</L>
<L>His ffader, his Moder, and eke him-self;</L>
<L N="12">He begged in Cite bi eueri half.</L>
<L>&THORN;e child non o&thorn;ur Craftus cou&thorn;e</L>
<L>But winne his lyflode wi&thorn; his Mou&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Childes vois was swete and cler,</L>
<L N="16">Men lusted his song wi&thorn; riht good cher;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his song &thorn;at was ful swete</L>
<L>He gat Mete from strete to strete.</L>
<L>Men herked his song ful likyngly:</L>
<L N="20">Hit was an Antimne of vre lady,
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="142"></L>
<L>He song &thorn;at Antimne eueri-wher,</L>
<L>I-Called Alma Redemptoris Mater,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is for&thorn;rihtly to mene:</L>
<L N="24">"Godus Moder, Mylde and Clene,</L>
<L>Heuene &yogh;ate and Sterre of se,</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;i peple from synne and we."</L>
<L>&THORN;at song was holden deynteous,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;e child song hit from hous to hous.</L>
<L>ffor he song hit so lykynglye,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes hedde alle to hym Envye.</L>
<L>Til hit fel on a seters-day</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;e Childes wey &thorn;orw &thorn;e Iewerie lay:</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes hedden &thorn;at song in hayn,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;ei schope &thorn;e child be slayn.</L>
<L>So lykingly &thorn;e Child song &thorn;er,</L>
<L N="36">So lustily song he neuer er.<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 33-34, 35-36 to be transp.?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On of &thorn;e Iewes Malicious</L>
<L>Tilled &thorn;e child in to his hous;</L>
<L>His Malice &thorn;ere he gan to kuy&thorn;e:</L>
<L N="40">He Cutte &thorn;e childes &thorn;rote alswi&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;e child ne spared nout for &thorn;at wrong,</L>
<L>But neuer-&thorn;e-latere song for&thorn; his song;</L>
<L>Whon he hedde endet, he eft bi-gon,</L>
<L N="44">His syngyng cou&thorn;e stoppe no mon.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-of &thorn;e Ieuh was sore anuyet.</L>
<L>Leste his Malice mihte ben aspyet,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ieuh bi-&thorn;ouhte him of a gynne:</L>
<L N="48">In to a gonge-put fer wi&thorn;-Inne</L>
<L>&THORN;e child adoun &thorn;er-Inne he &thorn;rong.</L>
<L>&THORN;e child song euere &thorn;e same song;</L>
<L>So lustily &thorn;e child con crie,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at song he neuer er so hy&yogh;e:</L>
<L>Men mihte him here fer and neer,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Childes vois was so hei&yogh; and cleer.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E Childes moder was wont to a-byde</L>
<L N="56">Euery day til &thorn;e Non-tyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;en was he wont to bringe heom mete,</L>
<L>Such as he mihte wi&thorn; his song gete.</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;at day was &thorn;e tyme a-past.</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;erfore his Moder was sore a-gast;
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="143"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; syk and serwe in eueri strete</L>
<L>Heo souhte wher heo mihte wi&thorn; him mete.</L>
<L>Bote whon heo com in to &thorn;e Iewery,</L>
<L N="64">Heo herde his vois so cler of cry.</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at vois his Modur dreuh:</L>
<L>Wher he was Inne, &thorn;erbi heo kneuh.</L>
<L>&THORN;en of hire child heo asked a siht.</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;e Iew wi&thorn;-nayted him anon-riht,</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;er nas non such child &thorn;rinne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e childes Moder &yogh;it nolde not blinne,</L>
<L>But euer &thorn;e Moder criede in on.</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;e Ieuh seide euere &thorn;er nas such non.</L>
<L>&THORN;en seide &thorn;e wommon: "&thorn;ou seist wrong,</L>
<L>He is her-Inne, I knowe his song."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ieuh bi-gon to stare and swere</L>
<L N="76">And seide &thorn;er com non such child &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>But neuer-&thorn;e-latere men mihte here</L>
<L>&THORN;e child song euere so loude and clere,</L>
<L>And euer &thorn;e lengor, herre and herre,</L>
<L N="80">Men mihte him here bo&thorn;e fer and nerre.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Modur coude non o&thorn;ur won:</L>
<L>To Meir and Baylyfs heo is gon,</L>
<L>Heo pleyne&thorn; &thorn;e Ieuh ha&thorn; don hire wrong</L>
<L N="84">To stelen hire sone so for his song;</L>
<L>Heo preye&thorn; to don hire lawe and riht,</L>
<L>Hire sone don come bi-fore heore siht,</L>
<L>Heo preye&thorn; &thorn;e Meir par Charite</L>
<L N="88">Of him to haue freo lyuere.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne heo telle&thorn; &thorn;e Meir a-Mong</L>
<L>Hou heo lyue&thorn; bi hire sone song.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Meir &thorn;en ha&thorn; of hire pite,</L>
<L N="92">And sumne&thorn; &thorn;e folk of &thorn;at Cite.</L>
<L>He telle&thorn; hem of &thorn;at wommons sawe,</L>
<L>And sei&thorn; he mot don hire &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>And hote&thorn; hem wi&thorn; hym to wende,</L>
<L N="96">To Bringe &thorn;is wommons cause to ende.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei cum &thorn;ider, for al heore noyse</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;ei herde &thorn;e childes voyse,</L>
<L>Riht as an Angeles vois hit were,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;ei herde him neuer synge so clere.
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="144"></L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;e Meir make&thorn; entre,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e child he aske&thorn; lyuere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ieuh may nou&yogh;t &thorn;e Meir refuse,</L>
<L N="104">Ne of &thorn;e child hym wel excuse,</L>
<L>But nede he moste knouleche his wrong,</L>
<L>A-teynt bi &thorn;e childes song.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Meir let serchen hym, so longe,</L>
<L N="108">Til he was founden in &thorn;e gonge,</L>
<L>fful depe I-drouned in ful&thorn;e of fen.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Meir het drawe &thorn;e child vp &thorn;en,<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 vv. wanting?</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ffen and fful&thorn;e riht foule bi-whoruen,</L>
<L N="112">And eke &thorn;e childes &thorn;rote I-coruen.</L>
<L>Anon-riht, er &thorn;ei passede for&thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ieuh was Iugget for &thorn;at Mor&thorn;ere.</L>
<L>And er &thorn;e peple passede in-sonder,</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;e Bisschop was comen to seo &thorn;at wonder.</L>
<L>In presence of Bisschop and alle I-fere</L>
<L>&THORN;e child song euere I-liche clere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Bisschop serchede wi&thorn; his hond:</L>
<L N="120">Wi&thorn;-inne &thorn;e childes &thorn;rote he fond</L>
<L>A Lilie flour, so briht and cler,</L>
<L>So feir a Lylie nas neuere se&yogh;en er,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; guldene lettres eueriwher:</L>
<L N="124">Alma Redemptoris Mater.</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;at lilie out was taken,</L>
<L>&THORN;e childes song bi-gon to slaken,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swete song was herd no more;</L>
<L N="128">But as a ded cors &thorn;e child lay &thorn;ore.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Bisschop wi&thorn; gret solempnete</L>
<L>Bad bere &thorn;e cors &thorn;orw al &thorn;e Cite:</L>
<L>And hym-self wi&thorn; processioun</L>
<L N="132">Com wi&thorn; &thorn;e Cors &thorn;orw al &thorn;e toun,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; prestes and clerkes &thorn;at cou&thorn;en syngen,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e Belles he het hem ryngen,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; torches Brennynge and clo&thorn;us riche,</L>
<L N="136">Wi&thorn; worschipe &thorn;ei ladden &thorn;at holi liche.</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e Munstre whon &thorn;ei kem,</L>
<L>Bi-gonne &thorn;e Masse of Requiem,</L>
<L>As for &thorn;e dede Men is wont.</L>
<L N="140">But &thorn;us sone &thorn;ei weren i-stunt:
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="145"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Cors a-Ros in heore presens,</L>
<L>Bi-gon &thorn;en Salue sancta parens.</L>
<L>Men mihte wel witen &thorn;e so&thorn;e &thorn;er-bi:</L>
<L N="144">&THORN;e child hedde i-seruet vr swete ladi,</L>
<L>&THORN;at worschipede him so on er&thorn;e her</L>
<L>And brouhte his soule to blisse al cler.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore i rede &thorn;at eueri mon</L>
<L N="148">Serue &thorn;at ladi wel as he con,</L>
<L>And loue hire in his beste wyse:</L>
<L>Heo wol wel quite him his seruise.</L>
<L>Now, Marie, for &thorn;i Muchele miht</L>
<L N="152">Help vs to heuene &thorn;at is so briht!</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>III. [hou an holy hermyt prayde a synful womman pray god for hym.]<NOTE PLACE="head">(<I>Picture.</I>)</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GOd, &thorn;at al &thorn;is world ha&thorn; wrouht</L>
<L>And formed alle &thorn;ing of nouht,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en alle &thorn;ing wi&thorn;-outen him</L>
<L N="4">Is de&thorn; and dernesse and dim,</L>
<L>Graunt vs grace and space and miht</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mowe serue him so ariht:</L>
<L>Whon we out of &thorn;is world wende,</L>
<L N="8">To wynne &thorn;e Ioye wi&thorn;-outen ende.</L>
<L>To hele of soule is noble &thorn;ing</L>
<L>To louen and lyken holy talkyng</L>
<L>Of holy men &thorn;at sum-tyme were,</L>
<L N="12">And of heore holy lyf to here.</L>
<L>ffor synne i[s] cald &thorn;e deueles.schakel,</L>
<L>His net, his tool, his takyng takel;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; lust he eese&thorn; his put-falle,</L>
<L N="16">To gylen wi&thorn; cristene soules alle:</L>
<L>But grace a-&yogh;eynes &thorn;at is obstacle,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; help of halewen, &thorn;orw Miracle</L>
<L>Geten bi halewen specially,</L>
<L N="20">Bote souereynlokest &thorn;orw vre ladi,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sikerest socour is at vr nede,</L>
<L>Synful Monnes erende to beode;</L>
<L>Whon we ben synfol and vn-clene,</L>
<L N="24">To wynne vs Merci, heo is Mene:
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="146"></L>
<L>As sum-tyme in Rome bi-fel,</L>
<L>&THORN;e storie i-writen witnesset wel.</L>
<L>&THORN;er was sum-tyme in &thorn;at Cite</L>
<L N="28">A wommon &thorn;at louede not chastite;</L>
<L>Hire lyf heo ladde in gret folye,</L>
<L>In ful&thorn;e and lust of Lecherye;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; no Mon spared heo forte do synne</L>
<L N="32">Of whom heo hoped Moneye to wynne.</L>
<L>&THORN;at wommon grei&thorn;ed hire queynt and gay,</L>
<L>And wolk in &thorn;at Cite on a day.</L>
<L>Heo mette wi&thorn; an holy heremyt</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;at in deuocion hedde gret delyt;</L>
<L>He bad his beodes deuoutely,</L>
<L>And holi Aues to vre ladi.</L>
<L>&THORN;at wommon, as heo com hym bi</L>
<L N="40">And sayh hym clo&thorn;ed Boistusli,</L>
<L>Of synne and folye heo talked him tille</L>
<L>And temptede &thorn;e holy Monnes wille.</L>
<L>&THORN;e hermyte onswerde hire nouht,</L>
<L N="44">In his deuociun was al his &thorn;ouht.</L>
<L>Whon he of hire tok no Reward,</L>
<L>In scorn heo cleped hym papelard,</L>
<L>And seide: "&thorn;ou fol, &thorn;ou dotel ffrere,</L>
<L N="48">What chaffest &thorn;ou and chaterest &thorn;us here?</L>
<L>What is al &thorn;at pryue roun</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou whistrest her vp and doun?"&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor he folewede nout hire dilyt</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;e wommon hedde of him dispyt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E Hermite onswerde ful myldely:</L>
<L>"Damesele, &thorn;is is &thorn;e cause why:</L>
<L>I am my-self a synful Mon</L>
<L N="56">And of goodnes ful lutel I con,</L>
<L>To god I preye bo&thorn;e day and niht</L>
<L>ffor grace, to seruen hym ariht,</L>
<L>And [for] alle &thorn;at habe&thorn; hym ouht a-gult,</L>
<L N="60">And for &thorn;e, wommon, &yogh;if &thorn;ow wolt,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God graunte &thorn;e such grace</L>
<L>To serue &thorn;i god, whil &thorn;ou hast space.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;ou and I and alle o&thorn;ur,</L>
<L N="64">ffor eueri cristene is o&thorn;eres bro&thorn;er,
<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="147"></L>
<L>In gode bedes we moten tristen,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;ou and I and alle cristen."</L>
<L>&THORN;E wommon seide: "Biddestou for me?"</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;en seide &thorn;e Hermyte: "damesele, &yogh;e,</L>
<L>I preye for &thorn;e as for my-self</L>
<L>An alle o&thorn;ere cristene in godes half,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god for-&yogh;iue vs vre misdedes;</L>
<L N="72">So verrey Charite teche&thorn; vs nedes."</L>
<L>&THORN;en seide &thorn;e damesele a&yogh;eyn:</L>
<L>"To preye for me &thorn;ou worchest in veyn;</L>
<L>Leoue ffrere, of me tac non hede,</L>
<L N="76">ffor to &thorn;i preyere haue I non nede."</L>
<L>&THORN;o seide &thorn;e Hermite: "Damesel,</L>
<L>&THORN;e neode&thorn; me nouht, I leeue hit wel,</L>
<L>Me, ne non preyere of myne.</L>
<L N="80">But mekeliche I preye &thorn;e of &thorn;yne</L>
<L>To Ihesu and his Modur Mari,</L>
<L>To graunte me of my synnes Merci.</L>
<L>&THORN;e nexte chirche &thorn;at &thorn;ou comest Inne,</L>
<L N="84">I preye &thorn;e, damesele, so bi-gynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;at I &thorn;i bone &thorn;e bet may fele,</L>
<L>I prey &thorn;e, damesele, &thorn;at &thorn;ow knele;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; herte and good deuocioun</L>
<L N="88">Of my synnes get me pardoun;</L>
<L>Mekely knelyng on &thorn;i kne</L>
<L>&THORN;reo Pater Noster preye to god for me,</L>
<L>And to his swete Moder Mari</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;reo Aues &thorn;erto, for my Merci."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;En onswere&thorn; &thorn;e damysel:</L>
<L>"&THORN;is nis but luyte, I graunte hit wel;</L>
<L>Hose wuste &thorn;at hit mihte a-vayle,</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;is nis bote a luytel trauayle."</L>
<L>&THORN;enne onswere&thorn; &thorn;e Hermyte:</L>
<L>"Damysele, se&thorn;&thorn;e hit nis bote luyte,</L>
<L>I preye &thorn;e do &thorn;is &thorn;ing for me;</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;i trauayle I-quit riht wel schal be</L>
<L>Or in &thorn;i lyue or afturward;</L>
<L>I preie &thorn;e, damysele, hold foreward."</L>
<L>&THORN;enne seide &thorn;e damysel:</L>
<L N="104">"&THORN;e foreward i hope to holde wel;
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="148"></L>
<L>Wher hit a-vayle o&thorn;ur elles nouht,</L>
<L>I wol don as &thorn;ou hast bi-souht."</L>
<L>&THORN;e hermyte Mekely kneled adoun</L>
<L N="108">And &thorn;onked hire wi&thorn; deuocioun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E Damysele wende for&thorn; hire wey</L>
<L>Abouten hire mur&thorn;us and hire pley.</L>
<L>And as heo streihte &thorn;orw a strete,</L>
<L N="112">Heo &thorn;ouhte what heo &thorn;e Hermyte bi-hete;</L>
<L>And in a strete as heo com bi,</L>
<L>Heo seih a Chapel of vre ladi:</L>
<L>In to &thorn;at Chapel heo made entre.</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;er was an ymage of Marie fre,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at blisful Mayden Mylde,</L>
<L>Vppon hire barm heo bar hire childe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e damysele caste on hire a siht</L>
<L N="120">And &thorn;ouhte &thorn;at ymage swete and briht,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ouhte, bi foreward hou heo was bounde</L>
<L>To knele bi-foren hire on &thorn;e grounde;</L>
<L>Heo tok to god non o&thorn;ur reward</L>
<L N="124">But for schome to breke forward.</L>
<L>Heo kneled adoun vppon hire knes</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;e paternostres and &thorn;e Aues,</L>
<L>As was hire foreward furst bi-fore,</L>
<L N="128">And seide: "Ihesu, lord, &thorn;yn Ore!</L>
<L>ffor-&yogh;if &thorn;e Hermyte his trespas</L>
<L>And graunt hym Merci, &thorn;orw &thorn;i gras,</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;at euer he ha&thorn; mys-do</L>
<L N="132">In al his lyf &yogh;ut hider-to."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enne &thorn;hou&yogh;te &thorn;e damisele verreyly</L>
<L>&THORN;e Babe loked on hire wro&thorn;ly,</L>
<L>Hire &thorn;hou&yogh;te &thorn;o he tornde his Bak,</L>
<L N="136">Such wordes to his mooder he spak:</L>
<L>"Moder, seostou hou &yogh;ond neih hend</L>
<L>Myn enemy preye&thorn; for my frend?"</L>
<L>Hire &thorn;hou&yogh;te &thorn;e Moder onswered a&yogh;ein</L>
<L N="140">Wi&thorn; wordus Mylde, plat and pleyn:</L>
<L>"Sone, for &thorn;y ffrendes sake,</L>
<L>What-euere &thorn;in Enemy ha&thorn; mis-take</L>
<L>ffor-&yogh;iue hit, sone, of &thorn;i Merci,</L>
<L N="144">As &thorn;ou art, lord, God almihti,
<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="149"></L>
<L>And also, sone, for &thorn;e loue of me</L>
<L>Hire synnes I preye for-&yogh;iuen be."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E child onswerde wi&thorn; louely chere:</L>
<L N="148">"Mi swete Modur, Mi norice dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;i bone mot nedes I-graunted be,</L>
<L>What &thorn;ou wolt wol I not werne &thorn;e."</L>
<L>&THORN;enne seide Marie: "lo, Damysel,</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;ou schalt haue grace, &thorn;ou hast herd wel;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ow mai&yogh;t sen riht wel bi &thorn;is</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;ou hast lad &thorn;i lyf amis,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou hast liued in lu&thorn;ur lyue.</L>
<L N="156">Tac a prest and do &thorn;e schriue</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sereuful herte and repentaunce,</L>
<L>And gladly vnderueng penaunce;</L>
<L>ffor at &thorn;is fourti dayes ende</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;ou schalt out of &thorn;is world wende</L>
<L>And wone wi&thorn; vs in mur&thorn;e and play,</L>
<L>&THORN;at laste&thorn; in Ioye for euere and ay."</L>
<L>&THORN;is was &thorn;at synful wommons ende,</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;orw help of Marie, &thorn;at Mayden hende.</L>
<L>Bi-seche we &yogh;erne &thorn;at swete may</L>
<L>To helpen vs at vre laste day</L>
<L>Of hol Remission of vre synne</L>
<L N="168">And to Ioye &thorn;at heo wone&thorn; Inne. amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>IV. [hou a Few putte his sone in a brennyngge ouene, for he was communed wit o&thorn;ur cristene children on &thorn;e pask-day.]<NOTE PLACE="head">(<I>Picture.</I>)</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>The poem, most likely, was originally composed in 8-lined stanzas, which are still obvious in vv. 69, 117, 141, 157.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOrd, Makere of alle &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Almihti God in Maieste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer was wi&thorn;-oute biginning</L>
<L N="4">And art and euermore schal be:</L>
<L>Graunte vs bo&thorn;e miht and space</L>
<L>So to serue &thorn;e to pay,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mowe &thorn;orw &thorn;i grace</L>
<L N="8">Wone wi&thorn; &thorn;e for euere and ay!</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Miracles of vre ladi</L>
<L>We ouhten wel to hauen in Muynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at writen be&thorn; in so&thorn; stori,</L>
<L N="12">Hou helplich heo is euere to Monkynde.
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="150"></L>
<L>Sum-tyme fel in on Cite&mdash;</L>
<L>Herkne&thorn; wel, and &yogh;e may here&mdash;</L>
<L>As Iewes weren I-wont to be</L>
<L N="16">Among &thorn;e cristen and wone I-fere:</L>
<L>&THORN;e Cristene woneden in On halue</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at Cite, as I &thorn;e hete,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e Iewes bi hem-selue</L>
<L N="20">Were stihlet to wone in a strete.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Cristene children in a Crofte</L>
<L>I-mad hem hedden a wel feir plas.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-Inne a Iewes child ful ofte</L>
<L N="24">Wi&thorn; hem to pleyen I-wont he was.</L>
<L>&THORN;e childes ffader nom non hede,</L>
<L>Ne to his child he sette non ei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;e child bo&thorn;e com and eode</L>
<L N="28">As ofte as euere hem luste to pleye.</L>
<L>So ofte to pleyen hem fel i-fere</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes sone on heore pleyes coude,</L>
<L>&THORN;at riht as on of hem he were;</L>
<L N="32">Wi&thorn; loue &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei him alouwede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At an Aster tyme bi-tidde,</L>
<L>Whon cristen made solempnite&mdash;</L>
<L>A Menskful Munstre was mad amidde,</L>
<L N="36">As semed best, in &thorn;at Cit&eacute;&eacute;:</L>
<L>&THORN;erto &thorn;e cristene peple can drawe,</L>
<L>To here bo&thorn;e Mateyns and eke Masse,</L>
<L>As falle&thorn; bi &thorn;e Cristene lawe</L>
<L N="40">Bo&thorn;e to more and eke to lasse;</L>
<L>Eueri mon in his array,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e housbonde and wyf also,</L>
<L>As falle&thorn; wel for asterday</L>
<L N="44">And al as cristene men schul do.</L>
<L>&THORN;e children foleweden heore fadres in-fere,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei weore euere I-wont to do.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes child wi&thorn; wel good chere</L>
<L N="48">Wi&thorn; hem wel fayn was for to go.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-Inne &thorn;e chirche whon he was Riht,</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ouhte he nas neuer er so glad</L>
<L>As he was of &thorn;at semeli siht,</L>
<L N="52">Such on bi-fore neuer se&yogh;e he had:
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="151"></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e laumpes &amp; tapers, brenninde briht,</L>
<L>And Auters curiousliche de-peynt,</L>
<L>IMages ful deinteousliche i-diht,</L>
<L N="56">And guld of moni a good corseynt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Acomeli qween in O Chayer</L>
<L>fful semeli sat, al grei&thorn;ed in golde,</L>
<L>A blisful Babe on Arm<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. barm, ef. v. 160.</NOTE> heo beer,</L>
<L N="60">fful kyngly Corouned, as he scholde.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at ladi &thorn;e child tok hede,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;at blisful Babe also,</L>
<L>Hou folk bi-foren heore bedes bede,</L>
<L N="64">As cristen Men be&thorn; wont to do.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes child euere tok such &yogh;eme</L>
<L>To alle sihtes &thorn;at he &thorn;er sei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Him &thorn;hou&yogh;te hem alle so swete to seme</L>
<L N="68">ffor Ioye him &thorn;ou&yogh;te I-Rauessched neih.</L>
<L>Whon hei&yogh;-Masse of &thorn;at day was do,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Prest bad alle men knelen a-doun:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Confiteor, as falle&thorn; &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L N="72">He &yogh;iue&thorn; hem Absolucioun;</L>
<L>He bidde&thorn; hem More and lasse also,</L>
<L>To vengen heor sauiour busken hem boun.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes child tok tente &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L N="76">Among &thorn;e cristene he dude him doun.</L>
<L>AMong &thorn;e pres &thorn;auh he were poselet,</L>
<L>He spared no-&thorn;ing for no drede</L>
<L>AMong &thorn;e cristene til he were hoselet;</L>
<L N="80">Of such a child me tok non hede.</L>
<L>To ende whon alle &thorn;ing was brouht</L>
<L>And eueri cristene drouh him hom,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ieuh &thorn;orw toune his child ha&thorn; souht,</L>
<L N="84">And saih wher he from chirche com.</L>
<L>He asked his sone wher he hedde ben,</L>
<L>Whil he hedde souht him al &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>Al riht as he hedde i-don and seon,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;e child him rikenet al &thorn;e a-Ray.</L>
<L>His ffader &thorn;erfore wox wood-wro&thorn;,</L>
<L>And seide anon: "&thorn;ou getest &thorn;i mede!"</L>
<L>And to his houene al hot he go&thorn;,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;at glemede as glowyng as a glede.
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="152"></L>
<L>In to &thorn;e houene &thorn;e child he caste:</L>
<L>To askes he &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;e child to brenne;</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e Mou&thorn;-ston he steke&thorn; him faste,</L>
<L N="96">And &thorn;ouhte &thorn;at neuer cou&thorn; scholde him kenne.</L>
<L>&THORN;erof whon his moder herde,</L>
<L>In a stude &thorn;er as heo stood,</L>
<L>As ffrayed in ffrenesye heo ferde,</L>
<L N="100">ffor wo heo wente as waxen wood,</L>
<L>Eucr hotyng out, heo tar hire her,</L>
<L>In eueri stret of &thorn;at Citee,</L>
<L>Nou In, Nou out, so eueriwher;</L>
<L N="104">Men wondret on hire and hedde pite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>BO&thorn;e Meir and Bailifs of &thorn;e toun,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei herden of &thorn;at cri,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei aresten hire bi Resoun,</L>
<L N="108">A[nd] maden chalange enchesun whi</L>
<L>Heo criede so in &thorn;at Cite</L>
<L>And putte &thorn;e Peple in such affray,</L>
<L>To serwen in such solempnite,</L>
<L N="112">And nomeliche on heore Aster-day.</L>
<L>As sone as heo mihte sece of wepe,</L>
<L>&THORN;is was &thorn;e seyinge of hire sawe:</L>
<L>"Sires, &yogh;e han &thorn;is Cit&eacute;&eacute; to kepe,</L>
<L N="116">As lordus han to lede &thorn;e lawe:</L>
<L>Allas, Allas, I am i-schent,</L>
<L>And help of ow me mot bi-houen,</L>
<L>I prey ow of Iust Iuggement,</L>
<L N="120">Mi cause I schal bi-fore &yogh;ou prouen:</L>
<L>Mi hosebonde ha&thorn; my child ibrent,</L>
<L>I-stopped him in a glouwyng houen;</L>
<L>Goth seo&thorn;, sires, bi on assent,</L>
<L N="124">And I schal &yogh;iue ow gold to glouen."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>BO&thorn;e Meir and Baylifs wi&thorn; folk i-fere</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Iewes houene ben gon.</L>
<L>As sone as &thorn;ei &thorn;ider come were,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;e Meir Comaundet: "do&thorn; doun &thorn;e ston."</L>
<L>&THORN;er eueri Mon wel mihte i-seo</L>
<L>&THORN;e houene-Roof, &thorn;at was so round,</L>
<L>Hou hit was Blasyng al of bleo</L>
<L N="132">As glouwyng glos, from Roof to grount.
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="153"></L>
<L>&THORN;e child sat &thorn;ere bo&thorn;e hol and sound,</L>
<L>Ne nouht I-harmet, hond ny her,</L>
<L>A-Midde &thorn;e gledes of &thorn;e ground,</L>
<L N="136">As he seete in Cool Erber.</L>
<L>&THORN;e childes Moder, whon heo &thorn;at seih,</L>
<L>Hire &thorn;ouhte heo nas neuer er so glad;</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e houene heo sturte him neih,</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;us sone wi&thorn; hire him out heo had.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e peple &thorn;ere present</L>
<L>Wondred on &thorn;at selly siht,</L>
<L>And heried god wi&thorn; good entent,</L>
<L N="144">ffor Miracle is more &thorn;en Monnes miht.</L>
<L>Hou he ha&thorn; non harmes hent</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e brondes &thorn;at brenne&thorn; so briht,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei asken of him bi on assent.</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;e child onswered a-non-riht:</L>
<L>"Of alle &thorn;e Mur&thorn;es &thorn;at I haue had</L>
<L>In al my lyf &yogh;it hider-to</L>
<L>Ne was I neuere of gleo so glad</L>
<L N="152">As aftur I was In &thorn;e houene I-do!</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e Brondes and Gledes, trustily,</L>
<L>&THORN;at weren bi-ne&thorn;en vndur my fote,</L>
<L>As feire floures, fei&thorn;fully,</L>
<L N="156">As special spices me &thorn;hou&yogh;te hem swote;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Blisful Qwen, &thorn;at Maiden Milde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sitte&thorn; in Chirche in hih Chayer</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at comely kyng, hire childe,</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at Blisful Babe, on Barm heo ber,</L>
<L>ffrom alle &thorn;e schydes &thorn;ei cunne me schilde,</L>
<L>ffrom gledes and brondes &thorn;at brende so cler,</L>
<L>ffrom alle &thorn;e flaumes &thorn;at flowen so wilde,</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;at neuer non mihte neih&yogh;e me ner."</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e Men and wymmen, al &thorn;at &thorn;er wore,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei herieden God hertily,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e luytel and muche, lasse and more,</L>
<L N="168">Of &thorn;is Miracle, witerly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E Iewesse &thorn;orw hire sones sawe</L>
<L>Was conuertet to crist a-non;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Child tok hym to cristes lawe,</L>
<L N="172">And alle &thorn;e Iewes euerichon.
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="154"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Meir sat on &thorn;e Ieuh him-selue,</L>
<L>fforte beo Iuge of his trespas;</L>
<L>To siggen &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-sworen were twelue,</L>
<L N="176">To &yogh;iuen heore verdyt in &thorn;at caas.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei counseiled i-vere vppon &thorn;at caas,</L>
<L>And comen a&yogh;eyn bi on assent;</L>
<L>&THORN;e wordes of &thorn;at verdyt was:</L>
<L N="180">"In &thorn;at same houene he schulde be brent."</L>
<L>&THORN;us is endet &thorn;is stori</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Miracle</L>
<L>I-writen a-boue.</L>
<L N="184">God graunt vs Ioy</L>
<L>In heuene an hih,</L>
<L>Ihesu, for &thorn;i Moder loue. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>V. [hou a man, for ache, cut of his foot, and was heled a&yogh;eyn by vre lady.]<NOTE PLACE="head">(<I>Picture.</I>)</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">In the MS. the poem is written in half-lines.</NOTE>IEsu, God and Godus sone : &THORN;at were a Babe I-boren</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Mayden swete Marie : Kuynde Qween I|Coren:</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou rayled on &thorn;e Roode : On Crois, I-Crouned of &thorn;orn,</L>
<L N="4">To beete &thorn;e gultus of vre ffadres : &THORN;at fer weren vs bi|foren;</L>
<L>And aftur &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day : ffrom de&thorn;e &thorn;ou vp a-Ros,</L>
<L>To leesen hem out &thorn;at weren I-punt : ffor synne in helle clos&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e soules, lord, &thorn;at weren in helle : Were glad of &thorn;in vp-Rys,</L>
<L N="8">Wi&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;ou laddest hem whon &thorn;ou rise : To B[l]isse of Paradys;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffourti&thorn;e day &thorn;erafturward : &THORN;ou steih to heuene an<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. and</NOTE> heih,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ou sittest on his riht syde : &THORN;i ffader swy&thorn;e neih;</L>
<L>&THORN;eraftur &thorn;enne &thorn;e ten&thorn;e day : &THORN;ou sendest doun wi&thorn; &thorn;i sonde</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;e holigost to &thorn;i disciples : To don hem vndurstonde</L>
<L>Wit and wisdam, resun and skil : To knowen &thorn;i godhede</L>
<L>And preche &thorn;e bileeue among &thorn;e folk : And hem to good lyf lede:
<PB REF="00000163.tif" N="155"></L>
<L>Wel ouhte we alle to &thorn;onke &thorn;e, lord : Of alle &thorn;i goodnes,</L>
<L N="16">And eke &thorn;i Moder, swete Marie : Of whom com vre encres:</L>
<L>ffor riht as Eue, vre furste Moder : Of vre synnes was Roote,</L>
<L>Riht so of Marie, &thorn;i swete Moder : Sprong hele of al vr boote.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore we ouhten day and niht : To hauen &thorn;i Moder In Muynde,</L>
<L N="20">To louen hire eke wi&thorn; al vr miht : And seruen hire as &thorn;e kuynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FOr hose loue&thorn; &thorn;at ladi wel : Heo glade&thorn; him in his greef,</L>
<L>Heo is solase in eueri serwe : And Medicyn in Mischeef,</L>
<L N="23">In eueri serwe or seknesse ou&thorn;er : Heo is souereynest leche;</L>
<L>No Mon fayle&thorn; &thorn;at studefastlych : Vre ladi wol bi-seche.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; heo helpe nou&yogh;t anon : Beo not &thorn;erof agast,</L>
<L>ffor ofte heo tarie&thorn; of hir help : To Make Mon studefast.<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 25-6 are repeated.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ouh heo graunte not &thorn;i bone anon : Beo &thorn;ou not in despeir:</L>
<L N="28">ffor, &yogh;if &thorn;ou bidde hire studefastly : I fynde ensaumple feir,</L>
<L>What serwe or seknesse so &thorn;ou soffre : &THORN;orw hire &thorn;ou schalt spede.</L>
<L>To schewe &thorn;e &thorn;at bi good ensaumple : A ffeir Miracle I Rede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>[I]N &thorn;e Cite of Viuari : A Munstre I-foundet was</L>
<L N="32">In &thorn;e honour of vre ladi : &THORN;er schewed was muchel gras:</L>
<L>&THORN;er In muynde of vre ladi : Was a swete ymage,</L>
<L>To whuch &thorn;e peple of &thorn;at cuntre : Made gret Pilrymage:</L>
<L N="35">ffor hose of serwe or seknesse hadde : Or eny o&thorn;ur Mis|cheef,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw help and socour of vre ladi : &THORN;ere he fond Releef.</L>
<L>&THORN;idere come seke Mesels monye : Halte, Croked, and Blynde;</L>
<L>What-maner seknesse &thorn;at Mon soffred : &THORN;er hele was wont to fynde.
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="156"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AMong al o&thorn;ere &thorn;er com a Mon : I-bootned forte be,</L>
<L N="40">His leg was brennyng as a fuir : ffrom fot vp to &thorn;e kne.</L>
<L>fful longe he dwelled in &thorn;at Cite : fforte a-byden grace,</L>
<L>And eueri day in hope of hele : He visited &thorn;at same place,</L>
<L>To Marie his boones he bed : His hele forte haue:</L>
<L N="44">He felede no leggaunce of his peyne : ffor al &thorn;at he may craue;</L>
<L>Him &thorn;houhte &thorn;at he died almost : ffor serwe and peyne and wo.</L>
<L>He was Counseyled hewe of his leg : &THORN;en longe to suffre so.</L>
<L N="47">Hym &thorn;hou&yogh;te euere so leng so wors : While he haunted &thorn;at stude,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore riht as counseiled he was : So bi his leg he dude;</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e while he was so seek : He feled neuere lisse ne lith,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore hym &thorn;ou&yogh;te beter legles : &THORN;en so to suffre &thorn;er-wy&thorn;.</L>
<L>Whon his leg was smiten of : &THORN;e kneo, &thorn;at was bi-laft,</L>
<L N="52">He heled hit vp wi&thorn; salues and drunches : And plastres of leche-craft.</L>
<L>&THORN;erafturward whon he was hol : He haunted &thorn;e same stude,</L>
<L>He bad and offred to vre ladi : As he bi-fore &thorn;er dude.</L>
<L>But as he kneled &thorn;er on a day : His Bedes for to bidde,</L>
<L>Er he passet out of &thorn;e place : &THORN;is feir Miracle bi-tidde:</L>
<L N="57">[Wi&thorn;]<NOTE PLACE="marg">om.</NOTE> wepe and wringyng serufoly : To Marie he made his pleynt:</L>
<L>"Allas, Marie, Modur of grace : In sum synne I am Cleynt!</L>
<L>ffor alle &thorn;at soffren serwe and sor : &THORN;e seke, &thorn;e Croked, &thorn;e blynde,</L>
<L N="60">In eny Mischef hose preye&thorn; to &thorn;e : Sum grace &thorn;ei may fynde,</L>
<L>Saue I sunful Caytyf out-cast : In &thorn;e may fynde non."</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; syk and serwe, swounyng al-most : To Marie he make&thorn; his mon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And as he was in such serwyng : And mihte not stunte of wepe,
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="157"></L>
<L N="64">A-Middes alle his moste serwe : He fel riht [s]ofte on slepe.</L>
<L>Him &thorn;hou&yogh;te in sweuene, a fe[i]r ladi : Hondelede hym bi &thorn;e kne</L>
<L>And drouh out &thorn;er-of a newe leg : As furst was wont to be.</L>
<L>Whon he a-wok, he groped his leg : He feled hit hol and sount,</L>
<L N="68">In al his lyf neuer lihtore : Whon he wende on &thorn;e grount.</L>
<L>&THORN;en alle Men mensken<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. mensked</NOTE> &thorn;e Mylde ladi : &THORN;at se&yogh;en &thorn;is open Miracle.</L>
<L>In alle Mischeues heo is Medecyn : A&yogh;eyn seknesse obstacle.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore good is &thorn;at eueri mon : Serue vre swete ladi;</L>
<L N="72">In alle synnes and serwes eke : Heo gete&thorn; to vs Merci.</L>
<L>Now, ladi Marie, qween of heuene : And Emperisse of helle,</L>
<L>Help vs &thorn;at we mowe wi&thorn; &thorn;e : ffor euere In Ioye dwelle!</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="6" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>VI. [hou a iew lente a cristenemon moneye, and took vre lady to borow.]<NOTE PLACE="head">(<I>Picture.</I>)</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At Constantynnoble in &thorn;at Cite</L>
<L>Dwelled a Marchaunt of herte fre,</L>
<L>Sumtyme was riche, ful of lewte,</L>
<L N="4">And after fel in pouerte;</L>
<L>And, as &thorn;e Bokes telles vs,</L>
<L>He was i-clept Teodorus.</L>
<L>He louede god and vre ladi,</L>
<L N="8">And serued &thorn;at Mayden speciali.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at Cite, so&thorn;liche,</L>
<L>A Ieuh &thorn;er dwelled, was wonder Riche;</L>
<L>In his lay he hedde good name,</L>
<L N="12">He was I-clepet Abrahame.</L>
<L>Theodorus he louede wele,</L>
<L>Gret lykyng hedde wi&thorn; him to dele.</L>
<L>Theodorus hedde &thorn;ouht and care,</L>
<L N="16">ffor he nedde not wi&thorn; to chaffare;
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="158"></L>
<L>He caste him &thorn;erfore to borwe.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Ieuh he wente a-Morwe;</L>
<L>&THORN;er he told him his Mischeef</L>
<L N="20">And preiede hym of sum Releef,</L>
<L>Of his Gold him for to lene,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us to hym he gon hym mene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ieuh onswerde wi&thorn; gret honour:</L>
<L N="24">"Loke hou &thorn;ou maiht make me seur</L>
<L>Me to paye at certeyn day,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e to helpe I schal assay."</L>
<L>Theodorus seide: "icham be-hynde,</L>
<L N="28">ffor me &thorn;er wol no Mon hym bynde;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at sum-tyme was my fere</L>
<L>Me passe&thorn; bi wi&thorn;-outen chere.</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;ou dorstest be so hardi</L>
<L N="32">To take vr ladi seinte Mari</L>
<L>ffor my Borw, be Mi ffay,</L>
<L>I schulde &thorn;e pay wel at &thorn;i day."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ieuh seide: "my goode feere,</L>
<L N="36">I graunte &thorn;e, sire, &thorn;i preyere,</L>
<L>ffor I haue herd ofte-si&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at ladi is Corteis and Bli&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Men sei&thorn; heo wol hem neuer fayle</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at in hire seruise wol trauayle.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore go we in to &yogh;our chirche,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er &thorn;is forward we wol worche;</L>
<L>&THORN;er is an ymage of hire iliche,</L>
<L N="44">A-Rayed wel wi&thorn; Iuweles Riche:</L>
<L>Tac &thorn;ou hire me &thorn;er bi &thorn;e hond!</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e kep i non o&thorn;ur bond."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon he hed seid, &thorn;ei gonne to gon.</L>
<L N="48">To &thorn;at churche &thorn;ei comen anon.</L>
<L>Theodorus In good Manere</L>
<L>Kneled a-doun, bad his preyere,</L>
<L>And aftur &thorn;at wi&thorn; good visage</L>
<L N="52">Went hym vp to &thorn;at ymage,</L>
<L>And tok hit bi &thorn;at on hond,</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;e Ieuh scholde to him fond,</L>
<L>And seide: "sire, so god me saue,</L>
<L N="56">ffor my Borwh &thorn;is ladi haue,
<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="159"></L>
<L>&THORN;at i schal paye &thorn;e at my day</L>
<L>Treweliche and wel al &thorn;i Monay</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou schalt me nou take,</L>
<L N="60">Al my disese wi&thorn; to slake."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ieuh him tok a summe of gold,</L>
<L>Good Moneye and wel I-told,</L>
<L>And sette hym &thorn;er a certeyn day</L>
<L N="64">Him to paye hit wi&thorn;-oute delay.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Cristen Mon &thorn;en was ful fayn,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey wenten hom ful fayn a-&yogh;ayn.</L>
<L>And he arrayed him ful fast</L>
<L N="68">A schip wi&thorn; seil and eke a Mast:</L>
<L>To Alysaundre he gon sayle.</L>
<L>&THORN;er he a-Ryued wi&thorn;-outen fayle.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne he bou&yogh;te faste and solde,</L>
<L N="72">And eueri day &thorn;e pons tolde</L>
<L>He won faste day by day.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;eer passed sone a-way.</L>
<L>He &thorn;ouhte so muche on his wynnyng</L>
<L N="76">ffor-&yogh;at &thorn;e day of his pa&yogh;yng,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e Euen was I-comen</L>
<L>A-Morwe schulde paye &thorn;at he hedde nomen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hit fel in to his Muynde &thorn;on</L>
<L N="80">He schulde bi holde a fals Mon;</L>
<L>To &thorn;at Cuntre so fer a-twynne</L>
<L>In so schort while miht he not wynne</L>
<L>fforte holde his day of paye.</L>
<L N="84">Bote to vr ladi he gon to praye</L>
<L>Hym to counseyle and to rede</L>
<L>What mihte &thorn;enne be his beste spede;</L>
<L>And cast hit in herte outurly</L>
<L N="88">To truste in god and vre ladi.</L>
<L>He tok hym &thorn;enne a luytel kyst,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-Inne he putte, &thorn;at no wiht wist,</L>
<L>&THORN;e summe of gold, verreyment,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;at &thorn;e Ieuh hedde hym I-lent,</L>
<L>And a lettre, &thorn;at seide &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"&THORN;is to Abraham Ieuh sent Theodorus;"</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at, wi&thorn; his hond</L>
<L N="96">Aboute wi&thorn; Iren he hit bond,
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="160"></L>
<L>In to &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute; &thorn;en he hit cast,</L>
<L>Preied vr ladi ben Schip and Mast,</L>
<L>Hit to saue In Godes nam</L>
<L N="100">To &thorn;e Ieuh Abraham.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ieuh a-Ros vppon &thorn;e Morn,</L>
<L>As I ow telle, wi&thorn;-oute scorn,</L>
<L>And stilliche for&thorn; gon he stalke</L>
<L N="104">To &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute;-syde, &thorn;er forte walke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Ebbet and flowed faste bi his house</L>
<L>&THORN;er he dwellede and his spouse.</L>
<L>Soone he was war wel I-nouh</L>
<L N="108">Of a Cofre, touward hym drouh,</L>
<L>ffloterynge in &thorn;at salte s&eacute;&eacute;.</L>
<L>Gret wonder he hedde what hit mi&yogh;t be.</L>
<L>fful sone to hym he hit vp nom,</L>
<L N="112">Vndur his arm he bar hit hom.</L>
<L>he fond &thorn;er-Inne, verrement,</L>
<L>&THORN;e gold &thorn;at he hedde furst and lent;</L>
<L>Beo &thorn;e lettre he wuste also</L>
<L N="116">ffrom what Mon &thorn;at hit com fro.</L>
<L>He caste hit &thorn;enne in to an Ark,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was bo&thorn;e styf and stark.</L>
<L>To telle &thorn;erof no wiht him luste,</L>
<L N="120">But wente him for&thorn; as no wiht wuste.</L>
<L>Longe afturward in Godes nome</L>
<L>Theodorus was comen home.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him &thorn;er mette mony on</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;at him welcomede swi&thorn;e son.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Abraham &thorn;e Ieuh he mette,</L>
<L>fful Corteysliche he hym grette</L>
<L>And &thorn;onked hym of his fordede,</L>
<L N="128">And preied god schulde quite his Mede.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Ieuh seide &thorn;o: "so mot I &thorn;e,</L>
<L>I trouwe &thorn;at &thorn;ou scorne me;</L>
<L>Whi hast &thorn;ou broken &thorn;i terme-day</L>
<L N="132">Of &thorn;e pay&yogh;ement of Mi Monay?"</L>
<L>Theodorus seide: "&thorn;ou wost wel,</L>
<L>I haue &thorn;e payed eueridel;</L>
<L>I take my Borwh to my witnesse,</L>
<L N="136">I owe &thorn;e nou&thorn;er More no lesse;
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="161"></L>
<L>Go we to churche bo&thorn;e i-fere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er &thorn;e so&thorn;e &thorn;ou schalt here."</L>
<L>"I graunte wel," qua&thorn; &thorn;e Iewe;</L>
<L N="140">"But &thorn;ou me paye &thorn;ou schalt hit rewe!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iew made hit wonder touh</L>
<L>And wende hit hedde beo good I-nouh.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei were bi-fore &thorn;at ymage</L>
<L N="144">&THORN;at for &thorn;e gold was mad his gage,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Theodorus seide wi&thorn; Mylde steuene:</L>
<L>"Ladi, as &thorn;ou art qween of heuene,</L>
<L>Help me nou from worldly schome,</L>
<L N="148">I preye &thorn;e in &thorn;i sones nome;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wost wel, ladi, &thorn;er &thorn;ou sist,</L>
<L>I putte &thorn;e gold in to a kist</L>
<L>And, to &thorn;is Ieuh &thorn;at hit schulde wende,</L>
<L N="152">I preyed &thorn;e hit to him sende.</L>
<L>As I truste on &thorn;i sone and &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ladi, &thorn;e so&thorn;e scheuh for me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E ymage spac, as god hit wolde,</L>
<L N="156">And seide: "Ieuh, &thorn;ou hast &thorn;i golde,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e botme of &thorn;yn ark</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ou hast leid eueri Mark."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewh wox a-schomed &thorn;o</L>
<L N="160">And graunted wel &thorn;at hit was so.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at leeued on his lay</L>
<L>A-schomed weren &thorn;at ilke day.</L>
<L>&THORN;er he hedde saumple bi good dome</L>
<L N="164">Cristene mon forte bi-come.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is ladi is ful gracius,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;enke&thorn; euere &thorn;us on vs.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore to hire loke &thorn;ou be trewe,</L>
<L N="168">And chaunge we hire not for non newe!</L>
<L>Heo wole vs helpe in vre Mischeef</L>
<L>In &thorn;is world to vs<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. vr</NOTE> Releef,</L>
<L>And afturward wi&thorn;-outen mis</L>
<L N="172">Geten vs heuene-riche blis</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;e grace of hire sone,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him &thorn;ere forte wone.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hit mote so be</L>
<L N="176">Sei&thorn; alle AMen, Par charite. AMEN.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="7" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000170.tif" N="162">
<HEAD>VII. [Of a prest &thorn;at lay by a nonne.]<NOTE PLACE="head">(<I>Picture.</I>)</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN Bok we fynde, as we Rede,</L>
<L>Of a preest, was wylde of dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was I-wounde in mony a vice,</L>
<L N="4">But at &thorn;e laste he was not<NOTE PLACE="marg">? <I>read</I> so</NOTE> nyce</L>
<L>And to synne so wel dude wone</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; a Nonne he hedde to done.</L>
<L>&THORN;erof wolde he him not schryue</L>
<L N="8">Til &thorn;at he schulde lete &thorn;e lyue.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it he serued vre Ladi</L>
<L>Day bi day ful specialy,</L>
<L>Matyns and vres day Bi day</L>
<L N="12">Of hire he seide wi&thorn;-oute delay.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e laste he fel seek,</L>
<L>And schulde be ded as we schulen ek.</L>
<L>Vr ladi &thorn;at he hedde in Reuerence</L>
<L N="16">Wolde he schulde clanse his Concience,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hym fel riht wel in Mynde,</L>
<L>A trusti frend &yogh;if he mihte fynde.</L>
<L>A prest &thorn;er was he louede wel,</L>
<L N="20">He tolde his lyf to Eueridel;</L>
<L>He sykede sore and criede Merci</L>
<L>&THORN;at god schulde on him haue pite for&thorn;i,</L>
<L>And for his synnes was sori.</L>
<L N="24">He preyed &thorn;e prest ful fei&thorn;fuli</L>
<L>&THORN;at, as &thorn;ei hedden be felawes long,</L>
<L>He schulde &thorn;enken on him a-mong</L>
<L>His Masse and his Almes-dede,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;at God mihte quite hym his Mede</L>
<L>And &thorn;at his soule &thorn;at was vngeyne</L>
<L>&THORN;e sannore mihte passe out of peyne.</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er, &thorn;at he wolde, he seide.</L>
<L N="32">After he dy&yogh;ede, In eor&thorn;e was leyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E prest forso&thorn;e for-&yogh;at hym nouht,</L>
<L>But euere hedde hym in his &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at &yogh;eer, day Bi day,</L>
<L N="36">He song his Masse, as I ow say,</L>
<L>&THORN;at O day he song of vre Ladi,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er of Requiem, sikerli.
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="163"></L>
<L>Al &thorn;e &yogh;er &thorn;is Charge he nom.</L>
<L N="40">Atte laste his Mynde-day com.</L>
<L>As he stod at his Masse &thorn;o,</L>
<L>After &thorn;e sacryng In Memento,</L>
<L>He sauh stonden him bi-fore</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;e ffeireste ladi &thorn;at euere was bore,</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e Auter &thorn;er he stod.</L>
<L>Heo seide to him wi&thorn; Mylde Mod:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou hast me trauaylet wi&thorn; &thorn;i preyere,</L>
<L N="48">Now at &thorn;is tyme to ben here.</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou hast preyed in &thorn;i Messe,</L>
<L>I haue geten for&yogh;iuenesse</L>
<L>To &thorn;i felawe of my sone dere</L>
<L N="52">Of al &thorn;at euere he mis-dude here;</L>
<L>Of his peyne he is releset,</L>
<L>And his Ioye schal ben encreset;</L>
<L>Lo wher he knele&thorn; &thorn;e bi-hynde:</L>
<L N="56">To ben I-hoselet he ha&thorn; in Mynde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E prest torned hym softely</L>
<L>And sauh him knele faste by;</L>
<L>Anon wi&thorn; godes Bodi</L>
<L N="60">Hoselde him deuoutli.</L>
<L>&THORN;en sauh &thorn;e prest vr ladi &thorn;er</L>
<L>Come a-doun of &thorn;at Auter</L>
<L>And take his felawe bi &thorn;e honde,</L>
<L N="64">Out of &thorn;e Chirche forte fonde.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is siht he was ful fayn,</L>
<L>And tornede to his Masse a-&yogh;ayn;</L>
<L>&THORN;erof &thorn;enne he made an ende,</L>
<L N="68">Preyed god grace him to sende</L>
<L>&THORN;orw preyere of his Moder dere,</L>
<L>So to lyuen and to don here,</L>
<L>After &thorn;is world &thorn;at is al wast</L>
<L N="72">To haue &thorn;e blisse &thorn;at euer schal last.&mdash;</L>
<L>Wel are we holden day and niht</L>
<L>Worschipen hire wi&thorn; al vr miht</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer is so redi diht</L>
<L N="76">To bringen vs alle to heuene-liht.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hit mote so be,</L>
<L>Seye&thorn; to hire an Aue!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="8" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000172.tif" N="164">
<HEAD>VIII. [hou vre lady &yogh;af mylk off heore pappes to a man &thorn;at hadde &thorn;e squynacye.]<NOTE PLACE="head">(<I>Picture.</I>)</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>A</B> Mon of gret deuociun</L>
<L>Was sum-tyme in Religiun,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Bok sei&thorn; he was a Monk,</L>
<L N="4">And in godes seruise swonk;</L>
<L>To vr ladi he was deuout,</L>
<L>Hire to serue euer was a-bout.</L>
<L>Whon he herde of hire eny speche,</L>
<L N="8">Of al his dissese &thorn;at was his leche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hedde he leuere &thorn;en drinke or ete,</L>
<L>ffor Ioye &thorn;e teres wolde he lete.</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;er &thorn;inges rouht he nouht,</L>
<L N="12">So swete on hire was his &thorn;ouht.</L>
<L>&THORN;at tyme riht as men do&thorn; floures</L>
<L>Men gederede furst Matines and vres</L>
<L>&THORN;at men vsen now of vre ladi,</L>
<L N="16">And seiden hem deuoutly;</L>
<L>Whose mihte hem &thorn;enne gete,</L>
<L>His (!)<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Hit</NOTE> was holde for Miracle grete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is Monk hem hedde, I ow say,</L>
<L N="20">And seide hem riht wel eueri day,</L>
<L>And mony a special preyere</L>
<L>&THORN;at men han mad of hire here.</L>
<L>Atte laste, as hit schulde falle,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;e Monkes &thorn;rote grete swalle,</L>
<L>Men called &thorn;at vuel Comuynli,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hedde, &thorn;e Qwinaci.</L>
<L>His vuel bi-gon so to encrese,</L>
<L N="28">Wi&thorn;-outen eny relece,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;at &thorn;er abouten stood</L>
<L>Seide he was ded, bi &thorn;e Rood!</L>
<L>But neuer-&thorn;eles hit was not so.</L>
<L N="32">Vre ladi com to hym &thorn;o,</L>
<L>As he tolde aftur mony a Mon,</L>
<L>His leche to ben, as heo wel con;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hire pappe in to his Mou&thorn;</L>
<L N="36">Milk heo spreynt, &thorn;at is selcou&thorn;!</L>
<L>And seide to him: "Mi seruaunt swete,</L>
<L>I am comen &thorn;i bale to bete;
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="165"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; my seruauns haue I be, lo:</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at Made me beo so longe &thorn;e fro.</L>
<L>Beo not a-ferd, &thorn;ou schalt not dye,</L>
<L>I schal &thorn;e hele of Maladye,</L>
<L>&THORN;i feire &thorn;rote &thorn;at me ha&thorn; serued</L>
<L N="44">I schal not soffre beo ouer-torned,</L>
<L>&THORN;y vois &thorn;at &thorn;ou dest wi&thorn; me grete</L>
<L>At &thorn;is tyme schaltou not forlete,</L>
<L>And, for ichaue ben longe from &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;e sannore schaltou heled be."</L>
<L>Vnder his nekke heo putte hire Arm,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hire swete fyngres stroked his harm.</L>
<L>&THORN;e swellyng slaked, he feld no sore.</L>
<L N="52">He set him vp anon-riht &thorn;ore.</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;ou&yogh;te verreliche i-nouh</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo aweiward from hym drouh:</L>
<L>And after hire faste he rauhte,</L>
<L N="56">But he hire take mihte nauhte.</L>
<L>&THORN;en he cried an heih al oute</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at weren hym aboute:</L>
<L>"Vn-Corteis folk &yogh;e ben, I-wis,</L>
<L N="60">Whi worschiped &yogh;e not &thorn;e queen of Blis,</L>
<L>AMong ou alle a space i-lete</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e ladi mihte haue sete?</L>
<L>Ne seih &yogh;e nouht hou louh heo went,</L>
<L N="64">Wi&thorn; &thorn;e dost wel neih be-schent,</L>
<L>ffor to salue me of my sore</L>
<L>Whon my lyf was wel neih lore?</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &yogh;or noise, &yogh;e folk vn-&thorn;riue,</L>
<L N="68">Out of &thorn;is hous &yogh;e han hire driue."</L>
<L>&THORN;erwi&thorn; he wepte for Ioye wel glad;</L>
<L>And euer was hire seruaunt sad,</L>
<L>Worschuped hire Corteis and hende</L>
<L N="72">Euer to his lyues ende.&mdash;</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur help or o&thorn;ur leche</L>
<L>Vs nede&thorn; not no for&thorn;ere seche</L>
<L>But Mari, Modur and Maiden clene,</L>
<L N="76">In heuene &thorn;at is so briht and schene.</L>
<L>Preye we, heo preye hire sone Ihesus</L>
<L>&THORN;at euere he haue Merci on vs,
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="166"></L>
<L>&THORN;at to his blisse he take vs to</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at is and schal ben euer-mo. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="9" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>IX. [Of an incontinent monk, &thorn;at was drouned, and rered a&yogh;eyn by vre lady to lyf.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>A</B> Sexteyn was in an Abbey</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Ordre of Monkes grey,</L>
<L>&THORN;at louede to worschipe vr ladi;</L>
<L N="4">But fallen he was In lecheri.</L>
<L>Whon his Bre&thorn;ren were to bedde i-gon,</L>
<L>He wolde gon as stille as ston</L>
<L>Out of Cloystre on his wilde-hede,</L>
<L N="8">fforte parfourne his misdede.</L>
<L>&THORN;auh he hi&yogh;ed faste for his Corage,</L>
<L>Euere he wolde grete &thorn;e ymage</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e chirche was mad of vre ladi,</L>
<L N="12">As ofte as he passed hit by.</L>
<L>Hit bi-fel vppon a niht,</L>
<L>To his walk he hedde hym diht,</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;at ymage passed he</L>
<L N="16">And grette hit wi&thorn; an Aue.</L>
<L>Vnder &thorn;e Abbeye a water Ron,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-ouer was a Brugge of ston:</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;at Brugge lay his pas.</L>
<L N="20">But him bi-fel a wondur cas:</L>
<L>As a mon &thorn;at hedde ben a-teynt</L>
<L>He fel a-doun and was I-dreynt.</L>
<L>&THORN;er comen ffendes fers and felle</L>
<L N="24">To fecche his soule in to helle.</L>
<L>A Cumpaygnye of Angeles swete</L>
<L>&THORN;orw Godus pite dude wi&thorn; him<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. hem?</NOTE> mete,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ei mihte &thorn;orw godus gras</L>
<L N="28">Helpe &thorn;e soule of sum solas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffendes cri&yogh;eden sone anon:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e wi&thorn; &thorn;is soule haue nou&yogh;t to don,</L>
<L>He is Iugget wi&thorn; vs to gon</L>
<L N="32">ffor &thorn;e Misdedes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; don."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Angeles al astoneyet were,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei mihte schewe no good werk &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Wherfore &thorn;ei mihte him calange
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="167"></L>
<L N="36">And wi&thorn; hem lede for&thorn; in heore range.</L>
<L>But as &thorn;ei stonden alle a-gast,</L>
<L>&THORN;er com vre ladi swi&thorn;e fast.</L>
<L>Heo seide: "&thorn;is soule whi haue &yogh;e take,</L>
<L N="40">&YOGH;e foule ffendes blo and Blake?"</L>
<L>&THORN;ei onswerde sone schortly:</L>
<L>"ffor he diede sodeynly</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen eny gode dede;</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;erfore we schulen him quite his mede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vr ladi seide: "&yogh;e sey falsly;</L>
<L>Whon-euer he went and passed me bi,</L>
<L>He grette me wi&thorn; an Aue,</L>
<L N="48">And &thorn;us he tok leue of me,</L>
<L>Als euere he,<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. he</NOTE> whon he com a-&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L>To sey an Aue he was fayn.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schul not sei we take hym ow fro</L>
<L N="52">Wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e ne Manas ner-&thorn;e-Mo:</L>
<L>Put we hit In &thorn;e Iuggement</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e hei&yogh;e kyng, verreyment."</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei &thorn;us striuen I-fere,</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;orw Maries Mylde prey[er]e</L>
<L>Hit lyked God, of alle souereyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule to &thorn;e bodi wende<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. sende?</NOTE> a-&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mihte here him-self aMende,</L>
<L N="60">Til god wolde aftur hym sende.</L>
<L>His bre&thorn;eren &thorn;at slepten in here wyse</L>
<L>Weren awaked and wolden aryse,</L>
<L>Gret wonder &thorn;ei hedden hem among</L>
<L N="64">Whi &thorn;e sexsteyn was so long</L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[<I>rest of miracles wanting</I>]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>The next 40 leaves, f. CXXVI b&mdash;CLXVI b, are wanting, with the rest of Mary's Miracles (c. 7000 vv.), which, according to the Index, ended f. CXXXIIII, and the following poems, as given in the Index: f. CXXXIIII, &thorn;e seuene psalmes. To euery apostel an orysoun. An orisoun to alle &thorn;e apostles. An orison to seynt Michel. An orysoun to seynt Ion &thorn;e bap|tist. Salutacions to ihesu crist. An orysoun to &thorn;e Trynite. Salutacious to &middot; vre lady. O vere beata &amp; intemerata. An orysoun of bede off &thorn;e seuene wordes &thorn;at crist spak last in &thorn;e cros. Letanie off vre lady &thorn;at seynt bernard made. O&thorn;ur orisones to vre lady. Matyns of &thorn;e passioun. Orisons off seynt Anselmes Meditaciouns.</P><P>Then follow &THORN;e Gospeles, f. CLXVI b&mdash;CCXXVII, on which see <I>Altengl. Leg. N. F.</I>, p. LXXI ff; amongst them a later addition, the Sermon de festo corporis cristi.</P></NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="30" TYPE="part">

<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="168">
<HEAD>XXX. De festo corporis cristi. [<I>Panem angelorum manducauit homo.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in Vern.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Ed. before in Herrig's <I>Archiv</I> LXXXII, p. 167 ff. Of the 3 MSS. of this homily, MS. Harl. 4196 contains an <I>older, northern text</I>, MSS. Dd 1, 1, and Vernon a <I>southern transformation.</I> MS. Dd was written before MS. Vernon, but adds an introduction of 38 vv.; MS. Vernon adds a 2nd homily: Septem Miracula de corpore <I>cristi</I>, from Robert of Brunne's <I>Handlyng Synne.</I> Cf. <I>Altengl. Leg. N. F.</I>, p. LXVIII, LXXIII, LXXXII.</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>MS. Vern., f. CXCV b.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;E lewede Men, take&thorn; hede&mdash;<SUP>*</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">(<I>See l.</I> 39<SUP>*</SUP> <I>below.</I>)</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;eos clerkes ha&thorn; non nede</L>
<L>&THORN;at I hem opene &thorn;is latyn,</L>
<L N="4">ffor heo hit conne wel a-fyn,
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="169"></L>
<L>ffor holy Churche hit singe&thorn; meste,</L>
<L>Nomeliche of &thorn;is newe feste.</L>
<L>Ac no&thorn;eles hit is ful olde</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at Dauid in &thorn;e psauter tolde:</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;is is &thorn;e latyn &thorn;at Dauid sede</L>
<L>&THORN;at "Mon ete Angeles Brede;"</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is so&thorn;, for so hit wes</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;e tyme of &thorn;e prophete Moyses.</L>
<L>[He]<NOTE PLACE="marg">om.</NOTE> was in Egipte in gret truage,</L>
<L>And godus folk in foul seruage,</L>
<L>Vnder &thorn;e kyng Pharaon</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;er was mony a &thorn;ousund mon.</L>
<L>Longe hit were al to telle;</L>
<L>But atte laste hit &thorn;us bifelle</L>
<L>&THORN;at god nolde soffre hit no more</L>
<L N="20">His owne folk in &thorn;raldam wore,</L>
<L>And god bad Moyses he scholde fle</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his folk &thorn;orwh &thorn;e Rede s&eacute;&eacute;.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Moyses to &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute; com,</L>
<L N="24">Al druye his folk wi&thorn; hym he nom:</L>
<L>&THORN;e s&eacute;&eacute; stod vp-riht as a wal,
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="170"></L>
<L>Til &thorn;ei weore I-passed al.</L>
<L>Kyng Pharao him suwed faste</L>
<L N="28">Wi&thorn; his Chares and his hoste;</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;ei weore alle in &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute;,</L>
<L>God torned heore streng&thorn;e a-&yogh;e,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ei were ouer-seynt,</L>
<L N="32">And he and alle hise weren i-dreynt.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is place hit mai beo sede</L>
<L>&THORN;at mon ete Angeles brede:</L>
<L>&THORN;at tyme &thorn;at Moyses ladde &thorn;us</L>
<L N="36">His grete host In wildernus</L>
<L>God dude lete reyne a-doun</L>
<L>As hit were flour gret foysun,</L>
<L>Manna, so hit is I-write,</L>
<L N="40">And is I-clept Angeles Mete.</L>
<L>Heo hit gedrede and liueden &thorn;erbi,</L>
<L>And sunged sore I wol telle ou whi:</L>
<L>&THORN;ei gederde more, for drede of brede,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;en vche day &thorn;ei hedde to nede;</L>
<L>And hit nolde not ben on Morwe</L>
<L>fforte kepe ne for to Borwe.
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="171"></L>
<L>Ich holde &thorn;is a badde store</L>
<L N="48">To vche Mokerere &thorn;at bidde&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. bigge&thorn;</NOTE> more</L>
<L>Of Catel &thorn;en he ha&thorn; to nede</L>
<L>His owne Meyne forte fede;</L>
<L>He bugge&thorn; Corn a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="52">And kepe&thorn; hit til hit beo dere.</L>
<L>"&THORN;er-of he do&thorn; wysliche,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he departe hit skilfulliche."</L>
<L>Nay, forso&thorn;e, &thorn;enke&thorn; he nouht</L>
<L N="56">To pore men parten ouht;</L>
<L>Bou&yogh;te he neuere so good chepe,</L>
<L>He rewe&thorn; nout &thorn;e pore wepe;</L>
<L>He ne rouhte how al &thorn;e world &yogh;ode,</L>
<L N="60">So &thorn;at his owne bi-&yogh;ete were goode.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;is is &thorn;e Mokereres onswere:</L>
<L>"Go&thorn; or wey, Corn is dere!"</L>
<L>And forso&thorn;e, wi&thorn;-oute gabbe,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;e same onswere he schal habbe</L>
<L>Whon alle &thorn;e Angeles in heuene beo&thorn;</L>
<L>And alle on eor&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ole&thorn; de&thorn;</L>
<L>Schul ben at a parlement:
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="172"></L>
<L N="68">&THORN;en &thorn;e Mokerere schal be schent;</L>
<L>&THORN;er he schal vbbreyded beo</L>
<L>Of God him-self, &thorn;at is al freo,</L>
<L>In what manere he ha&thorn; spent</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;e godus &thorn;at God on eor&thorn;e him lent.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere god him-self schal &yogh;iue &thorn;e dome&mdash;</L>
<L>He may beo adred er he &thorn;er come;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;is is &thorn;e word &thorn;at God wol say</L>
<L N="76">To &thorn;e Mokerere at Domes-day,</L>
<L>And Certeynliche to non o&thorn;ur mon</L>
<L>But to &thorn;e wrecche Mokerere &thorn;on:</L>
<L>"I hungred whon &thorn;ou wernedest me mete;</L>
<L N="80">I was a-ffurst, I coude not gete;</L>
<L>Herborweles, &thorn;ou me forsoke;</L>
<L>Seek, in prisun, &thorn;ou ne come me to loke;</L>
<L>A-Cold, Clo&thorn;eles also,</L>
<L N="84">Naked &thorn;ou me lette go:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, Mokerere, &thorn;ou wende to helle,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e deuelen &thorn;er euere to dwelle."</L>
<L>&THORN;e wrecche Mokerere onswere schal &thorn;an</L>
<L N="88">"Lord, whon sauh we &thorn;e neodi Man?"
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="173"></L>
<L>"&YOGH;us, whon &yogh;e warned &thorn;e leste of myne,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e warned hit me wel a-fyne;"</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">or. him</NOTE> tit heore onswere:</L>
<L N="92">"Go&thorn; to helle, for heuene is dere."</L>
<L>At Domes-day &thorn;e meste schennes</L>
<L>Hit falle&thorn; vppon &thorn;e ny&thorn;inges;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei neuermore wole hem schryue</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;at &thorn;ei weore ni&thorn;inges in heore lyue,</L>
<L>But euere heore onswere hit is &thorn;us</L>
<L>"We &yogh;iuen more &thorn;en men &yogh;iuen vs."&mdash;</L>
<L>Torne we to vre gospelle,</L>
<L N="100">Of &thorn;e folk of Ysraelle,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;ei gedrede Angeles brede</L>
<L>More &thorn;en &thorn;ei hedde to nede.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore god wro&thorn; was</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;at &thorn;ei trist not to his gras,</L>
<L>And let hem dye; and were I-slay</L>
<L>ffourti &thorn;ousund on a day,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at gult and o&thorn;ur eke,</L>
<L N="108">And godus heste &thorn;at &thorn;ei breke;</L>
<L>&THORN;at of sixe [hundred]<NOTE PLACE="marg">om.</NOTE> and twenti<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. thirti? Cf. Num. 1, 46, Ex. 38, 25.</NOTE> &thorn;ousende&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us muche was &thorn;e noumbre to toknynge&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er come non to londe freo</L>
<L N="112">Saue tweyne, Calef and Iosue&mdash;
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="174"></L>
<L>And of &thorn;ulke tweyne com al &thorn;e strene</L>
<L>Of vre ladi, heuene-Qweene.&mdash;</L>
<L>Now is wel sene to-day</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;at he loue&thorn; vs more &thorn;en &thorn;ay.</L>
<L>ffor he ne sende hem but Angel brede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at laste&thorn; but a day to nede,</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; send us a Ricchor sonde:</L>
<L N="120">His owne bodi, ich vndurstonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wol laste euere &thorn;e soule wi&thorn;-Inne</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;ou art out of dedly synne.</L>
<L>&THORN;at was I-pyned for vre nede</L>
<L N="124">To-day &thorn;ou seost In ffourme of brede.</L>
<L>And &thorn;auh I wol &yogh;ow schewe and telle</L>
<L>Beo &thorn;is ensaumple hou hit bi-felle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is writen In &thorn;e Legent</L>
<L N="128">Of &thorn;i[s] holy sacrament.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Videmus in altari formam panis, non carnis, &amp; quare.</HEAD>
<L><B>A</B> Iew sum tyme and a Cristene mon</L>
<L>Were felawes in &thorn;e wey vppon.</L>
<L>And bi &thorn;e wey, as riht was,</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;e Cristene Mon herde Rynge to Mas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Cristene Mon seide: "a-byd me here,</L>
<L>Whil I go to my preyere!"
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="175"></L>
<L>&THORN;e cristene mon wente in to &thorn;e churche.</L>
<L N="136">And &thorn;e Iew bi-gon to grucche,</L>
<L>ffor hym &thorn;hou&yogh;te his felawe was</L>
<L>To longe biddinge<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. bidinge</NOTE> atte Mas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iew ros vp and for&thorn; ede</L>
<L N="140">In to &thorn;e Churche, to take hede.</L>
<L>&THORN;en sauh he atte weuede</L>
<L>&THORN;e Prest holde ouer his heuede</L>
<L>A ffeir child, I-woundet sore</L>
<L N="144">In ffot, in hond; &yogh;it sauh he more</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er nas nou&thorn;ur wyf nor mon</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;at in &thorn;e Chirche were on</L>
<L>&THORN;at ne helde vp here hondes and sat on kne;</L>
<L N="148">And from &thorn;at child sauh come fle</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;ur such as he sauh stonde,</L>
<L>A[nd] lihte bi-twene vche monnes honde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ieuh a-Bod, til &thorn;e Prest</L>
<L N="152">Vsede &thorn;e Eukarist,</L>
<L>&THORN;en sauh he him ete &thorn;e child</L>
<L>&THORN;at he bi-twenen his hondes held;</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at weore in &thorn;e churche &thorn;ermide</L>
<L N="156">&THORN;e Ieuh &thorn;hou&yogh;te &thorn;at so heo dude.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ieuh was agrise and wente him hyde</L>
<L>&THORN;er his felawe him bad abyde,</L>
<L>And bi him-self he seide &thorn;an:</L>
<L N="160">"A grisly lyf ha&thorn; Cristen Man!"
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="176"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Cristene Mon aftur &thorn;e mas</L>
<L>Com to &thorn;e stude &thorn;er &thorn;e Iew was.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ieuh asked: "hou farestou?"</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;e Cristene mon seide: "better &thorn;en &thorn;ou;</L>
<L>ffor si&thorn;en ichaue my god seye,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lihtore ich holde al my weye."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iew seide: "beo my scolle,</L>
<L N="168">Wel ouhte &thorn;i wombe be fulle!</L>
<L>Hedde I so muchel I-&yogh;ete,</L>
<L>&THORN;is &thorn;reo dayes nolde I no mete."</L>
<L>"fforso&thorn;e," qua&thorn; &thorn;e cristene mon,</L>
<L N="172">"To-day say&yogh; I siht of non,</L>
<L>Non eor&thorn;liche kunnes mete</L>
<L>&THORN;at my Mou&thorn; mihte ete."</L>
<L>"Let beo! I sauh wi&thorn; myn e&yogh;en two</L>
<L N="176">Where &thorn;ou and o&thorn;ur mo,</L>
<L>Vche of ow heold a child blodie,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en &yogh;e eten hit, I nul not lye;</L>
<L>Wherfore i seye &thorn;at oure<NOTE PLACE="marg">= &yogh;oure</NOTE> lawe</L>
<L N="180">Is not good." bi &thorn;at sawe</L>
<L>&THORN;e Cristen mon bi-gon to beo wro&thorn;;</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou lyest, Iew, &thorn;ou art me lo&thorn;;</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure lawe is fals, and so &yogh;e ben,</L>
<L N="184">&YOGH;e wol not leeue but &thorn;at &yogh;e sen.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore al-one I<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. 1?</NOTE> go &thorn;e bi,</L>
<L>I kepe no more &thorn;i cumpaygni."
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="177"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Iew seide: "ffelawe, greef &thorn;e nouht</L>
<L N="188">&THORN;eih I telle &thorn;e what I sayh and &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>Ac tel me bi sum o&thorn;ur preue</L>
<L>Wher-bi I may &thorn;e so&thorn;e leue!"</L>
<L>"&THORN;is is &thorn;e skile," qua&thorn; &thorn;e Cristene man,</L>
<L N="192">"&THORN;at god nout soffre&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;an</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou se&yogh;e wi&thorn; &thorn;in e&yogh;e</L>
<L>&THORN;e sacremens &thorn;at ben so sle&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his fflesch mihte so ben hud</L>
<L N="196">To vs cristene wi&thorn;-inne &thorn;e bred.</L>
<L>And &thorn;y kun made hym dye,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore al blodi &thorn;ou hym se&yogh;e."</L>
<L>"ffelawe," qua&thorn; &thorn;e Iew &thorn;on,</L>
<L N="200">"Help &thorn;at I were a Cristene mon;</L>
<L>ffor leuere ichaue cristned ben</L>
<L>&THORN;en euere seo such a siht a&yogh;en."</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;e Iew cristned, and o&thorn;ur mo,</L>
<L N="204">ffor &thorn;e Miracle &thorn;at fel &thorn;o.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is Bred &thorn;at is godus flesch,</L>
<L>What feiror preue wolde men esch</L>
<L>&THORN;at vche part is godus entere?</L>
<L N="208">&THORN;eih hit weore parted in &thorn;reo quartere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;eih hit weore an hundred dole,</L>
<L>Vche part is his bodi al hole.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at loke bi skile, lo here:</L>
<L N="212">Bi-hold &thorn;i-self in a schewere:
<PB REF="00000186.tif" N="178"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou ne sest but onliche &thorn;i faas,</L>
<L>&THORN;e while al hol is &thorn;e glaas;</L>
<L>And brek &thorn;e glas in two or &thorn;re,</L>
<L N="216">And so moni formes<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. faces</NOTE> &thorn;ou miht se.&mdash;</L>
<L>Beo &thorn;e makyng of &thorn;e oblee</L>
<L>Wel and skilfoliche me may se</L>
<L>Of w&yogh;uche we make Godus fflesch,</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;is is &thorn;e saumple whose wol esch.</L>
<L>Hit is maad beo seuen skiles</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e seuene dedly synnes:</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn Lecherie hit is whit,</L>
<L N="224">&THORN;at was Blak and stynkynge euere &yogh;it.</L>
<L>Hit is &thorn;unne a-&yogh;eyn Glotenye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al to muche wole swolewye.</L>
<L>Hit is round and liht to &thorn;rowe,</L>
<L N="228">A&yogh;eyn Sleu&thorn;e, &thorn;at make&thorn; men slowe.</L>
<L>Of swete whete mad hit is,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn Wra&thorn;&thorn;e, &thorn;at is bitternis.</L>
<L>Hit is mad wi&thorn;-oute leueyn:</L>
<L N="232">A&yogh;eyn Envye hit stont a&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L>ffor Envye make&thorn; Men swelle</L>
<L>Whon he seo&thorn; eny spede welle.</L>
<L>Hit is also wi&thorn;-oute Bryn</L>
<L N="236">Or eny o&thorn;ur Corn &thorn;er-In:
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="179"></L>
<L>Hit<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;at</NOTE> is a-&yogh;eyn Couetyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ne recche&thorn; In what wyse</L>
<L>Eny catel vndurfonge,</L>
<L N="240">Beo hit Riht beo hit wronge.</L>
<L>Hit is &thorn;erto clene and luyte,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn Pruide, &thorn;at euer &yogh;ute</L>
<L>Wolde beo gret and hei&yogh; of wille,</L>
<L N="244">As Lucifer, &thorn;at furst felle</L>
<L>ffor his Pruide out of heuene.</L>
<L>Do we &thorn;is Bred a&yogh;eyn &thorn;is seuene!</L>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Candida, triticia, tenuis, non magna, rotunda,</I></L>
<L><I>Expers frumenti,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. fermenti</NOTE> <I>non mixta sit hostia Cristi.&mdash;</I></L>
</LG>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And hou hit furst com and ede</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;at mon ete Angeles Brede,</L>
<L>Hit is liht so&thorn; to telle,</L>
<L>ffor vche cristene mon wot hit welle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e laste soper wi&thorn;-outen wene</L>
<L N="252">Was I-mad atte Ceene,</L>
<L>And God bad &thorn;e Apostles do so</L>
<L>Whon he weore to heuene I-go;</L>
<L>"Do &thorn;is in &thorn;e muynde of me;</L>
<L N="256">I go and come to ow a-&yogh;e."</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Apostles &thorn;at God sent</L>
<L>[tok] holichurche &thorn;e sacrament.&mdash;</L>
<LG>
<L>
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="180"><I>Et dicitur Eukaristia</I></L>
<L><I>Quasi bona gracia:</I></L>
</LG>
<L>&THORN;at is to siggen, eukarist</L>
<L N="260">As goode grace com from crist.</L>
<L>Wel may we seyen hit is good grace</L>
<L>Whon hit is wardeyn in godus place!</L>
<L>And grace is betere &thorn;en nature,</L>
<L N="264">Whose &thorn;erto wol take cure.&mdash;</L>
<L>I rede &thorn;e mon be in good entent</L>
<L>Whose take&thorn; &thorn;is grace in sacrement:</L>
<L>Seint poul sei&thorn;, and siggen I may,</L>
<L N="268">In &thorn;e pistel of to-day<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Cor. 11, 29.</NOTE>:</L>
<L>"Whose vnwor&thorn;iliche &yogh;ode</L>
<L>To fonge Godus fflesch and blode,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere he fonge&thorn; his owne dome"&mdash;</L>
<L N="272">Allas, hit falle&thorn; so to lome!</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore poul sei&thorn; bi &thorn;at halue:</L>
<L>"he<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. ho?</NOTE> deme&thorn; not God, he deme&thorn; him-selue."</L>
<L>In &thorn;ulke whose i-take be,</L>
<L N="276">Schal he neuere beo dampned a-&yogh;e;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we vre owne dom take,</L>
<L>What o&thorn;ur dom schal God vs make?</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore make ow alle Redi</L>
<L N="280">To take hit not as fool-hardi.&mdash;
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="181"></L>
<L>&THORN;eih seint Poul vs &thorn;rete &thorn;us,</L>
<L>Vr lord hym-self, swete Ihesus,</L>
<L>&THORN;is day in Markes<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Johnes.</NOTE> gospelle</L>
<L N="284">To his disciples he gon telle,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Iewes &thorn;at were ryue:</L>
<L>"I am my-self Bred of lyue.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Joh. 6, 48.</NOTE></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">Joh. 6, 56-9.</NOTE>"Mi fflesch so&thorn;fast mete is,</L>
<L N="288">And my Blod verrey drinke, iwis.</L>
<L>Whos ete&thorn; mi flesch and drinke&thorn; my blode,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">Here begins MS. Simeon.</NOTE>I wone wi&thorn; hym and he wi&thorn; me.<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 290 &amp; 291 transp. in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi ffader me sent and so I &yogh;ode,</L>
<L N="292">To lyue for hym and he for me:</L>
<L>So<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. ffor</NOTE> whose me ete&thorn;, for me schal libbe.</L>
<L>&THORN;is is &thorn;e Bred &thorn;at from heuene come,<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 293 &amp; 294 transp. in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Not lyk Manna, &thorn;at flour be sibbe,</L>
<L N="296">&THORN;ei &thorn;at hit ete, weore dede bi dome,</L>
<L>And hose ete&thorn; of &thorn;is brede,</L>
<L>He schal hue wi&thorn;-outen ende."</L>
<L>Ihesu, graunt vs so to spede</L>
<L N="300">Wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;at; Sim. Wi&thorn;</NOTE> &thorn;ulke bred to heuene wende. Amen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Off &thorn;ulke Bred in &thorn;e gospelle</L>
<L>Seint Ion we here &thorn;us telle:<NOTE PLACE="marg">Joh. 6, 54.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="182"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;if we ne ete of &thorn;ulke brede</L>
<L N="304">Ne drynke his blood, vr lyf were dede.&mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;eih we ete hit al &thorn;us here,</L>
<L>Hit is in heuene al entere.</L>
<L>So schaltou leeue, Cristene mon,</L>
<L N="308">&THORN;at in no weere &thorn;i leue beo on!</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;i fei&thorn; tit no mede</L>
<L>Where &thorn;ing of de&thorn; takest hede;</L>
<L>Hit is inpossyble to serue crist</L>
<L N="312">But &thorn;i be-leeue beo good and trist.</L>
<L>And e&yogh;e of fei&thorn; hit is ful kene</L>
<L>&THORN;at seo&thorn; a siht &thorn;at is not sene.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore alle &thorn;ing &thorn;at we [ne] seo&thorn;</L>
<L N="316">Leeue we as holychirche de&thorn;,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at I holde &thorn;e rihte fey</L>
<L>And to heuene &thorn;e nexte wey.&mdash;</L>
<L>To telle more I mot nede</L>
<L N="320">Hou men ete Angeles Brede.</L>
<L>Of ffoles I herde herby-fore</L>
<L>&THORN;at wyse men toke of hem heore lore,</L>
<L>And so a sek mon mihte teche</L>
<L N="324">A good skile perauenture bifore a leche.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Bred mihte<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. may</NOTE> neuermore be spende</L>
<L>Til<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. ffor</NOTE> God hym-self on eor&thorn;e hit sende,</L>
<L>To saue mon fro pyne of helle,</L>
<L N="328">So &thorn;at he kepe hit welle.</L>
<L>Sum tyme such lawe &thorn;er was</L>
<L>&THORN;at vche sonday after mas
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="183"></L>
<L>Eueri trewe wyf and Mon</L>
<L>Schulde be hoseled or &thorn;ei eode &thorn;on.<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 vv. wanting, ef. Harl. 387-8.</NOTE> . . . . .</L>
<L N="333">And &thorn;at for &thorn;is enchesun,</L>
<L>I wol ow telle for what resun:</L>
<L>On was, for &thorn;at folk mis-bere</L>
<L N="336">Hem-selue, whon &thorn;ei hoseled were.</L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;er was, for &thorn;e grete trauayle</L>
<L>&THORN;at holy churche hedde be &thorn;at entayle,</L>
<L>In nome of &thorn;at for Godus drede</L>
<L N="340">Me &yogh;iue&thorn; nou &thorn;e holy Brede.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;e pope ordeyned, &thorn;ries in &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Vche mon I-hoscled were;</L>
<L>And bote he were ones atte leste,</L>
<L N="344">&THORN;e pope Comaundet be his heste</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke bodi &thorn;at so ne dede</L>
<L>Schuld neuer be buried in holy stude.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore beo redi, I ow Rede,</L>
<L N="348">fforte fonge Angeles Brede.</L>
<L>And beo &thorn;is Bred I wol &yogh;ou telle</L>
<L>A luytel ensaumple hou hit bi-felle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>De manu sacerdotis &thorn;er hostiam penetrata.</HEAD>
<L>BE-fel sum tyme In Engelonde,</L>
<L N="352">&THORN;er was a prest, ich vndurstonde,
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="184"></L>
<L>&THORN;at ladde not his lyf, as was tolde,</L>
<L>Also clanliche as he scholde.</L>
<L>God wolde he scholde hym amende,</L>
<L N="356">And he hym a strong vuel gon sende,</L>
<L>So, he wende almost to dye.</L>
<L>And on a day &thorn;is siht he se&yogh;e:</L>
<L>A child bo&thorn;e he seih and herde,</L>
<L N="360">And<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. &thorn;at</NOTE> asked hym hou he ferde;</L>
<L>In his hond bret-ful he beere</L>
<L>Of bernynge Obeleis a paniere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest asked: "what is &thorn;at,</L>
<L N="364">And &thorn;ou &thorn;at askest of my stat?"</L>
<L>He seide: "Ich am Godes Messagere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;eos Obeleis &thorn;at ben here,</L>
<L>&THORN;us monye vnwor&thorn;ily &thorn;ou fong,</L>
<L N="368">Whon &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;i Masse song;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou nult I-leue me,</L>
<L>Scheuh for&thorn; &thorn;yn hond, and &thorn;ou schalt se."</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest heold for&thorn; his hond anon,</L>
<L N="372">And &thorn;e child tok vp on</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e obeleys &thorn;at were so rede,</L>
<L>And pult hit in &thorn;e prestes hond amidde.</L>
<L>Hit fel &thorn;orwh &thorn;e prestes hond on,</L>
<L N="376">And &thorn;e child a-wey gan gon.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest let men come hym to</L>
<L>And tolde hem whi he ferde so:
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="185"></L>
<L>"Lo," qua&thorn; he, "hou I am diht!</L>
<L N="380">Who sauh euere such a siht?"</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;orw his hond me mihte se</L>
<L>As brod as was &thorn;at obele.</L>
<L>And he not I-maymed nas,</L>
<L N="384">And afturward song mony a Mas,</L>
<L>And an hole &thorn;orwh his hond&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;at so&thorn;e men hit fond.</L>
<L>After for a &thorn;ousend pound of golde</L>
<L N="388">&THORN;e prest no more synne wolde,</L>
<L>But serued god wi&thorn; gret drede,</L>
<L>And afturward to heuene &yogh;ede.&mdash;</L>
<L>I holde &thorn;e Mon more &thorn;en mad</L>
<L N="392">&THORN;at take&thorn; &thorn;is bred and nis not drad</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e wreche &thorn;at mihte bi-falle.</L>
<L>So wor&thorn;i bred hit is wi&thorn;-alle</L>
<L>&THORN;at for &thorn;e miht of &thorn;ulke word</L>
<L N="396">&THORN;at god seide at his owne bord,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same miht &thorn;at word ha&thorn; here,</L>
<L>To torne &thorn;e bred in o&thorn;ur manere,
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="186"></L>
<L>And to torne &thorn;e wyn in blode,</L>
<L N="400">&THORN;e same &thorn;at was sched on Rode.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wordus perauenture I coude telle,</L>
<L>Ac I am not wor&thorn;i and &thorn;erfore I nelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac o&thorn;ur makyng of &thorn;e Mas</L>
<L N="404">I dar wel telle hou hit was.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Apostles seide no more</L>
<L>But what &thorn;ei herde of cristes lore&mdash;</L>
<L>No more to &thorn;e masse nolde &thorn;ei do,</L>
<L N="408">And &thorn;e paternoster to,</L>
<L>vppe &thorn;e bred and vppe &thorn;e wyn&mdash;</L>
<L>And so hem &thorn;hou&yogh;t hit good and fyn.</L>
<L>Non o&thorn;ur vestimens vsud &thorn;ay</L>
<L N="412">But as &thorn;ei wereden vche day;
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="187"></L>
<L>And in vessels of treo&mdash;</L>
<L>Non o&thorn;ur chalys hedden heo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;enne &thorn;e pope vrban,</L>
<L N="416">&THORN;at was a ful holy man,</L>
<L>Ordeynde &thorn;at &thorn;e Chalys scholde</L>
<L>Ben of seluer or of golde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a patin, to hule ouer al,</L>
<L N="420">Maked of &thorn;e same Metal.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E pope Celestyne, ordeyned he,</L>
<L>A psalme Men clepe&thorn; Iudica me</L>
<L>&THORN;at vche prest &thorn;at is and was</L>
<L N="424">Schulde siggen hit er he eode to Mas.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E Nyne kyries &thorn;at ben in Boke</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope Siluestre of gru hem toke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;cr-aftur come&thorn; Gloria in excelsis:</L>
<L N="428">&THORN;e Angeles of heuene furst song &thorn;is;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. And? or &thorn;an?</NOTE> seint hillari &thorn;at was</L>
<L>Erche-bisschop of peytas,</L>
<L>He made from laudamus te</L>
<L N="432">&THORN;e remenaunt &thorn;en synge we.
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="188"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enne &thorn;e pope Tollophornus,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at o&thorn;ur pope Cynacus,</L>
<L>Bi-twene hem bo&thorn;e ordeyned was</L>
<L N="436">To synge &thorn;e Gloria to &thorn;e Mas<NOTE PLACE="marg">4 vv. wanting.</NOTE> . . . . .</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He hit Confermede, pope Gregori,</L>
<L>And made &thorn;erto &thorn;e Offertori.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enne &thorn;e pope Anastasius</L>
<L N="440">Comaundet in lawe riht &thorn;us:</L>
<L>&THORN;at no mon schulde sitte, he beede,</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;e gospel were to Rede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Constantinus &thorn;e pope (!) made &thorn;e crede,</L>
<L N="444">fforte siggen hit he bede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Pope Steuene and pope Clemens</L>
<L>Ordeyned &thorn;e holy vestimens.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Pope Ciluester ordeyned &thorn;e Corporas,</L>
<L N="448">In tokne &thorn;at godus bodi was</L>
<L>In clene lynnen clo&thorn; I-wounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at tyme &thorn;at Iosep hit founde
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="189"></L>
<L>In his owne toumbe of ston</L>
<L N="452">And leyde a-no&thorn;ur gret vppon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enne &thorn;e Pope Leouns</L>
<L>Made alle &thorn;e Prefaciuns.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alisaundre &thorn;e Pope ordeynde &thorn;is:</L>
<L N="456">To do watur and wyn In &thorn;e Chalis,</L>
<L>In tokne &thorn;at bo&thorn;e com watur and blode</L>
<L>Of Godus syde on &thorn;e Roode;</L>
<L>&THORN;e blood bi-tokne&thorn; &thorn;at he vs bouht,</L>
<L N="460">&THORN;e watur bi-tokne&thorn; vre ffullouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sixtus &thorn;e Pope ordeynde vs</L>
<L>&THORN;ry&yogh;es to synge Sanctus.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Pope<NOTE PLACE="marg">Harl. Ielasius</NOTE> made &thorn;e Canoun &thorn;er,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="464">And God made &thorn;e Pater noster.</L>
<L>[A]nd hou and what-maner bi-felle</L>
<L>&THORN;at God made &thorn;e paternoster, I wol telle.</L>
<L>His Apostles seide hym on a day:</L>
<L N="468">"Teche vs, lord, how we schul pray."</L>
<L>And seint Ion<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Luc (11, 2).</NOTE> ha&thorn; tauht vs &thorn;is&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is on of his disciples&mdash;
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="190"></L>
<L>&THORN;at Ihesus tauhte hem &thorn;is preyer</L>
<L N="472">And bad hem seyen &thorn;e Pater noster.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;us muchel to seyen hit is:</L>
<L>"Vr ffadur &thorn;at in heuene is,</L>
<L>Halewed mot &thorn;y nome beo.</L>
<L N="476">And to &thorn;i kyngdam &thorn;at we teo.</L>
<L>&THORN;i wille in heuene and eor&thorn;e beo do.</L>
<L>Vre vche-dayes bred send vs to.</L>
<L>And vre dettes for-&yogh;iue vs,</L>
<L N="480">As we for-&yogh;iue vre dettours.</L>
<L>And lede vs in no fondynge,</L>
<L>But saue us from vche vuel &thorn;inge. Amen."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Off &thorn;e holigost &thorn;e seuen &yogh;iftis</L>
<L N="484">In &thorn;e pater noster I-touched is;</L>
<L>Of whuche to God &thorn;er touched &thorn;re,</L>
<L>And foure in on to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;is preyere, &thorn;eih hit beo schorte,</L>
<L N="488">But hit beo seid wi&thorn; a clene herte,</L>
<L>Hit is a-&yogh;ein &thorn;ulke man</L>
<L>&THORN;at in his herte wra&thorn;&thorn;e ha&thorn; tan.
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="191"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enne &thorn;e pope Innocent,</L>
<L N="492">Pax domini he ordeynt,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vche mon schulde cusse o&thorn;ur</L>
<L>And holden him for suster and bro&thorn;ur;</L>
<L>In tokne &thorn;at god made pes wi&thorn; man,</L>
<L N="496">&THORN;erfore &thorn;at pes is &yogh;iuen &thorn;an.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E laste word of &thorn;is hei&yogh;e fest</L>
<L>Is I-seid Ite Missa est,</L>
<L>&THORN;is is to seye "hit is i-sent</L>
<L N="500">To heuene for vs, &thorn;is sacrament";</L>
<L>Bi-fore &thorn;e holy Trinite</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste part of &thorn;e &thorn;re,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur for hem &thorn;at &thorn;ole&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;oled</NOTE> de&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde for hem &thorn;at alyue be&thorn;.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hit is ri&yogh;t &thorn;at furst inempned be</L>
<L>Vr ladi in &thorn;e Canone:</L>
<L>ffor God of hire &thorn;at flesch toke</L>
<L N="508">&THORN;at neuer cristen mon forsoke;</L>
<L>&THORN;at flesch he ha&thorn; take &thorn;e to fede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is i-cleped Aungel Brede.
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="192"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E twelue Apostles I-nempned be&thorn;,</L>
<L N="512">ffor heore prechynge &thorn;ei &thorn;olede de&thorn;&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Quia Apostoli dicuntur missi, &amp; Martires testes apostolorum:</I></P>
<LG>
<L>As &thorn;ing i-sent ben &thorn;e Apostles,</L>
<L>And Martires ben &thorn;e Apostles witnes;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e Martires &thorn;at weore dede</L>
<L N="516">ffor &thorn;ei weore witnesse of &thorn;is Brede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God di&yogh;ede for loue of vs,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei for loue of Ihesus.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Petur and Andrew, Philip, &thorn;eos &thorn;reo</L>
<L N="520">weore don vppon &thorn;e Rode-treo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Poul, Iames, and Mathew</L>
<L>Were be-heuedet, and Bartholomew</L>
<L>Was huld al naked quike</L>
<L N="524">ffor his witnesse of &thorn;is onlike.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;at o&thorn;ur Iamus,</L>
<L>Symon, and Taddeus,</L>
<L>Heore senewes for cristen lawe</L>
<L N="528">Out of heore bodi were i-drawe.
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="193"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seint Ion &thorn;e Ewangelist,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was sib to Ihesu crist,</L>
<L>He dronk venym, to make preue</L>
<L N="532">&THORN;at we han of &thorn;e rihte be-leeue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seint Thomas Didimus,</L>
<L>He was &thorn;orwh-stiked Riht &thorn;us.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-aftur come&thorn; &thorn;e xij Martiris</L>
<L N="536">&THORN;at in &thorn;e Canoun Rikned is;</L>
<L>Of whuche summe Popes were,</L>
<L>Summe Bisschops &thorn;at Mitre beere,</L>
<L>Summe Dekenes &thorn;at weore half prest,</L>
<L N="540">Summe lewede &thorn;at leeuede on crist&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor alle Ordres and alle degres</L>
<L>To &thorn;is sacrement bere&thorn; witnes.</L>
<L>Leouns, Clemens, and Cletus,</L>
<L N="544">Sixtus, and Cornelius,</L>
<L>&THORN;eose weore Popus, &thorn;at &thorn;olede de&thorn;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ulke Bred &thorn;at we nou seo&thorn;.</L>
<L>Ciprian was Bisschop of Cartiginus.</L>
<L N="548">Stephene, Laurence, Vincent weore Dekenus.
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="194"></L>
<L>Grisogon, Ion and Paulus,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei weore in heore lyue knihtus;</L>
<L>Cosma and Damianus,</L>
<L N="552">&THORN;ei weore leches, I-writen is &thorn;us.</L>
<L>Cecili, and Agnes, and Agace</L>
<L>Diede for &thorn;is bred of grace.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore is riht heore nomes to be</L>
<L N="556">Nempned in &thorn;e Canone:</L>
<L>ffor alle &thorn;eos di&yogh;ede In good entent</L>
<L>ffor to Meyntyme &thorn;e sacrament.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E sacrament mot &thorn;e soule fede</L>
<L N="560">&THORN;at is i-hote Angeles Brede.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wor&thorn;iliche hit fonge,</L>
<L>Hit schal kepe &thorn;e &thorn;us longe,</L>
<L>ffrom &thorn;ulke day &thorn;at &thorn;ou ded be</L>
<L N="564">Til &thorn;i bodi rise a-&yogh;e;</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne bo&thorn;e bodi and soule i-fere</L>
<L>Schal wende to &thorn;e graunt Mangere</L>
<L>Where neuer-more tit no nede</L>
<L N="568">To non eor&thorn;liche Brede,</L>
<L>But &thorn;e siht of &thorn;e Trinite
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="195"></L>
<L>Schal euermore &thorn;i fode be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;he we han &thorn;e Modur to preye &thorn;e sone,</L>
<L N="572">We han &thorn;e sone to prey &thorn;e ffader,</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;o</NOTE> holygost we han in wone&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is enteere we haue to-gader:</L>
<L>What lette&thorn; vs forte wynne</L>
<L N="576">&THORN;e Riche blisse is vs bi-hote,</L>
<L>Bote hit beo vr owne synne?</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis non o&thorn;ur &thorn;yng, I wote.</L>
<L>Of Pardoun I haue no pouste</L>
<L N="580">Non<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Nou?</NOTE> to &yogh;ow forte graunte:</L>
<L>But, &yogh;if &yogh;e don now aftur me,</L>
<L>I wol ow telle a quantite,</L>
<L>Hou Muchel pardoun &yogh;e may habbe</L>
<L N="584">To &yogh;oure meste nede,</L>
<L>To come to honoure wi&thorn;-oute gabbe</L>
<L>&THORN;is ilke Angeles Brede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ulke &thorn;oresday &thorn;at next is</L>
<L N="588">Aftur &thorn;e Trinite,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope vrban ordeynde &thorn;is</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit schulde &thorn;enne be.
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="196"></L>
<L>An hundred dayes of for&yogh;iuenes</L>
<L N="592">He graunted alle &thorn;ay</L>
<L>&THORN;at come to &thorn;e Matynes</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ulke same day;</L>
<L>ffourti dayes for vche a tyde,</L>
<L N="596">An hundred for &thorn;e Mas,</L>
<L>An hundred hose to &thorn;e Euensong abyde&mdash;</L>
<L>He graunte&thorn; hem no las.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at wike vche day</L>
<L N="600">&THORN;is pardoun laste&thorn; so,</L>
<L>Hose al &thorn;e seruyse hauen may;</L>
<L>And &yogh;it he schal han mo:</L>
<L>ffor vche dayes seruyse</L>
<L N="604">An hundret dayes to bote&mdash;</L>
<L>Wel him ou&yogh;te to seyen &thorn;ise</L>
<L>On hors and eke on foote.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">The next vv., wanting in Harl., are a new addition.</NOTE>&THORN;e laste pope &thorn;at was nou,</L>
<L N="608">Of Ion<NOTE PLACE="marg">It is John XXII, 1316-34.</NOTE> &thorn;at was hiht,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e pardun he graunte&thorn; ow</L>
<L>And double&thorn; hit wi&thorn; his miht.</L>
<L>Meilerous,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miler le Poer, Bishop of Leighlin, Ireland, 1321-41 (cf. Cotton's Fasti II, 384).</NOTE> &thorn;orwh godes grace
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="197"></L>
<L N="612">Bisschop of leihlinne,</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; mendet in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh miht &thorn;at he &yogh;af hymme:</L>
<L>ffourti dayes to pardoun</L>
<L N="616">He ha&thorn; &yogh;iue &thorn;erto &yogh;ete<NOTE PLACE="marg">orig. &yogh;ite</NOTE></L>
<L>To alle wi&thorn; good deuocioun</L>
<L>Here&thorn; hit or hit rede.</L>
<L>So hit a-mounte&thorn; holliche</L>
<L N="620">On and ffourti &yogh;ere</L>
<L>And sixcore dayes, treweliche,</L>
<L>Whose here&thorn; his seruyse here.</L>
<L>Ihesu graunte ow alle and some</L>
<L N="624">On eor&thorn;e so forte spede</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is pardoun ow make come</L>
<L>To &thorn;is Angeles Brede.</L>
<L>&THORN;at Mon eete Angel Brede,</L>
<L N="628">&THORN;us furst we be-gon;</L>
<L>To heuene [hit] mot ow alle lede</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e Wyf and Mon,</L>
<L>In nomine patris wi&thorn; ou go,</L>
<L N="632">Et spiritus sancti do also. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>MS. Dd. 1, 1 Cambr. Univ. Libr., fol. 32 b.</HEAD>
<EPIGRAPH><Q>Panem angelorum manducauit homo:</Q> <BIBL>Dauid in psalmo.</BIBL></EPIGRAPH>
<P><I>In nomine summi saluatoris, gloriosissimi sublimis creatoris, indiuidue omnipotentis ineffabilis trinitatis, incomprehensibilis et incommutabilis veri dei &amp; hominis, nostri principii, progreditur exordium : veri vbi christus est funda|mentum, nullum boni operis superest edificium: patebunt lingua materna, dei mediante gracia.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">The first 38 vv. are wanting in Vernon.</NOTE>In &thorn;e name of oure souereyn sauyour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is al-weldinge creatour,</L>
<L>&THORN;e heye holi trenyte</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;er o god is &amp; personis .iij.,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e veri god and man;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e holi gost, alle .iij. but an,</L>
<L>be a-mong vs in his grace to wone,</L>
<L>to helpe &thorn;e speche &thorn;at is here begunne.</L>
<L N="9">and if &thorn;er eny man be here</L>
<L>&THORN;at of his beleue ha&thorn; ben in a were</L>
<L>or ha&thorn; errid her-be-fore</L>
<L N="12">wher-bi his soule myhte be lore,</L>
<L>swich word he mote now here</L>
<L>to sauen him fro helle-fere;</L>
<L>and alle &thorn;at ben in riht fay,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at &thorn;ei mote hold &thorn;e saf way.</L>
<L>and &thorn;er-for beseke we him</L>
<L>&THORN;at may sauen eueri lyme,</L>
<L>to-berste, to-bete bon &amp; felle,</L>
<L N="20">to saue vs fro &thorn;e fire of helle;</L>
<L>and &thorn;is day lete his bodi be bore,</L>
<L>to techin vs &thorn;e riht wey before,</L>
<L>and &thorn;at he to vs take hede</L>
<L N="24">&amp; send vs &thorn;ing &thorn;at we han nede.</L>
<L>ffor, as I seyde beforn in latyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no werk ha&thorn; no good fyn,</L>
<L>It is nouht worth, verament,</L>
<L N="28">but if crist be &thorn;e fundament:</L>
<L>&THORN;er-for wile we him beseche</L>
<L>&THORN;at he be founder of oure speche,</L>
<L>and &thorn;at it ende in his name,</L>
<L N="32">&amp; &thorn;at &thorn;e foule fend it schame</L>
<L>and profite to oure soulis alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at non in mysbeleue ne falle.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-for alle &thorn;at ben here,</L>
<L N="36">preyth for me sum preyere,</L>
<L>ffor ihesu cristis owne loue,</L>
<L>&amp; also for &yogh;oure own behoue.&mdash; &mdash;</L>
<L><SUP>*</SUP>&YOGH;e lewid men, taki&thorn; hede&mdash;</L>
<L N="40">for &thorn;e clerkis han no nede</L>
<L>&THORN;at I hem opene &thorn;is latyn,</L>
<L>for &thorn;ei it knowe wel &amp; fyn;
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="169"></L>
<L>ffor holi chirche it singi&thorn; meste,</L>
<L N="44">nameliche in &thorn;is newe feste.</L>
<L>But nertheles it is ful old</L>
<L>&THORN;at dauid in &thorn;e sawtere told:</L>
<L>for &thorn;is it is &thorn;at dauid seyde</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;at "Man eti&thorn; aungelis brede;"</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at is soth, for so it wes</L>
<L>in tyme of &thorn;e prophete moyses.</L>
<L>He was in Egipte in gret truage,</L>
<L N="52">&amp; goddis folk in foul seruage,</L>
<L>vnder &thorn;e king pharao</L>
<L>&THORN;er was a &thorn;ousand men &amp; mo.</L>
<L>Longe it were al to telle;</L>
<L N="56">but atte laste &thorn;us it befelle</L>
<L>&THORN;at god ne wold suffren it no more</L>
<L>his owne folk in thraldom thore,</L>
<L>and god bad moyses he schuld fle</L>
<L N="60">wi&thorn; his folk &thorn;orw &thorn;e rede se.</L>
<L>and whan moyses to &thorn;e se com,</L>
<L>al drye his folk wi&thorn; him he nom:</L>
<L>&THORN;e se stod vpriht as a walle,
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="170"></L>
<L N="64">til &thorn;ei were passid alle.</L>
<L>King pharao him suyd faste</L>
<L>wi&thorn; al his meyne, &amp; al in haste;</L>
<L>and whan &thorn;ei were alle in &thorn;e se wi&thorn;-in,</L>
<L N="68">God turnid hire streng&thorn;e al a&yogh;en,</L>
<L>so &thorn;at goddis folk was al ouer went</L>
<L>&amp; pharao &amp; hise were alle schent.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is place it may ben seyde</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at man ete aungelis brede:</L>
<L>&THORN;e tyme &thorn;at moyses lad &thorn;us</L>
<L>his gret ost in wildernes</L>
<L>God fro heuene lete reyne adoun</L>
<L N="76">as it were a flour, gret foysoun,</L>
<L>Manna, so it is wrete,</L>
<L>&amp; it is seyd aungelis mete.</L>
<L N="79">&THORN;ei it gaderid &amp; lyuid &thorn;er-bi,</L>
<L>&amp; synnyd sore I wile telle &yogh;ow whi:</L>
<L>&THORN;ei gaderid mor of bred</L>
<L>&THORN;an eueri day &thorn;ei had to ned;</L>
<L>and it wolde not ben on morwe</L>
<L N="84">for to kepe ne for to borwe.
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="171"></L>
<L>I holde &thorn;is a badde stor</L>
<L>to eueri mokerere &thorn;at wold han mor</L>
<L>of catel &thorn;an he ha&thorn; to nede</L>
<L N="88">his owne meyne for to fede;</L>
<L>he bie&thorn; corn a&yogh;en &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>&amp; kepit it til it be dere.</L>
<L>"But &thorn;er-of do&thorn; he wiseliche,</L>
<L N="92">if he departe it skilfulliche."</L>
<L>Nay for so&thorn;e, &thorn;enki&thorn; he nouht</L>
<L>to pore men departen ouht;</L>
<L>Bouhte he neuere so good chepe,</L>
<L N="96">he ne rewi&thorn; not &thorn;e pore to wepe;</L>
<L>he ne rouhte how al &thorn;e world &yogh;ode,</L>
<L>so &thorn;at his owne geting were gode.</L>
<L>for &thorn;is is &thorn;e mokereris answere:</L>
<L N="100">"Go &yogh;oure wey, corn is ful dere,"</L>
<L>also for so&thorn;e, wi&thorn;-outen gabbe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same answere he schall habbe</L>
<L>whan alle &thorn;e aungelis, in heuene beth,</L>
<L N="104">&amp; alle on erthe &thorn;at suffrid deth,</L>
<L>schul ben at on parlement:
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="172"></L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;e mokerere schal ben schent;</L>
<L>&THORN;er he schal vpbraydid be</L>
<L N="108">of god him-self, &thorn;at is so fre,</L>
<L>In what manere &thorn;at he ha &thorn; spent</L>
<L>&THORN;e godis &thorn;at god on erthe him lent.</L>
<L>&THORN;er god him-self schal &yogh;euyn &thorn;e dome&mdash;</L>
<L>he may ben a-drad or he &thorn;er come;</L>
<L N="113">ffor &thorn;is is &thorn;e word &thorn;at god wile say</L>
<L>to &thorn;e mokerere at domys-day,</L>
<L>and so harde to non other man</L>
<L N="116">as to &thorn;e vnkynde mokerere &thorn;an:</L>
<L>"I hungrid whan &thorn;ou wernedist me mete;</L>
<L>I wold haue had drink, I cowde non gete;</L>
<L>herborwles, &thorn;ou me forsoke;</L>
<L N="120">&amp; sike, in prisoun, cam not me to loke;</L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[<I>folios</I> 34, 35, 36 <I>wanting in Cambr. MS.</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="185">"lo," quod he, "how I am diht!</L>
<L>who saw euere swich a siht?"</L>
<L>&THORN;orw his hond men myhte se</L>
<L N="420">als brod as was &thorn;at vble.</L>
<L>and he not maymed was,</L>
<L>&amp; afterward song many a mas,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e hole al-wey &thorn;orw his hond&mdash;</L>
<L N="424">&THORN;us &thorn;at so&thorn;e men it fond.</L>
<L>&amp; after for a &thorn;ousand pound of gold</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest no mor synne wold,</L>
<L>But seruid god wi&thorn; greet drede,</L>
<L N="428">&amp; afterward to heuene &yogh;ede.&mdash;</L>
<L>I hold &thorn;at man mor &thorn;an mad</L>
<L>&THORN;at taki&thorn; &thorn;is bred &amp; is not drad</L>
<L>of &thorn;e wreche &thorn;at myhte befalle.</L>
<L N="432">so wurthi bred it is wi&thorn;-alle</L>
<L>&THORN;at for &thorn;e myht of &thorn;at word</L>
<L>&THORN;at god seyde at his bord,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same myht &thorn;at word ha&thorn; here,</L>
<L N="436">to turne &thorn;e bred in to other manere,
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="186"></L>
<L>&amp; to turne &thorn;e wyn in to blod,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same &thorn;at was schad on &thorn;e rod.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wordis perauenture I coude the telle,</L>
<L>but I am not wor&thorn;i &amp; &thorn;er-for I nelle.</L>
<L N="441">al o&thorn;er making to &thorn;e mas</L>
<L>I dar wel tellin how it was.</L>
<L>&THORN;e apostelis seyde no more</L>
<L>but what &thorn;ei herde of cristis lore&mdash;</L>
<L N="445">no mor to &thorn;e masse wold &thorn;ei do,</L>
<L>and &thorn;e pater noster &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e bred and &thorn;e wyn&mdash;</L>
<L N="448">&amp; so hem &thorn;ouhte it good &amp; fyn.</L>
<L>non othere vestemens vsid &thorn;ai</L>
<L>but as &thorn;ei werid eueri day;
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="187"></L>
<L>and in vesselis of tre&mdash;</L>
<L N="452">Non o&thorn;er chaleys had he.</L>
<L>Than &thorn;e pope vrban,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was a ful holi man,</L>
<L>ordeynid &thorn;at &thorn;e chaleys scholde</L>
<L N="456">ben of siluer or of golde,</L>
<L>wi&thorn; a patene, to helin oueral,</L>
<L>made of &thorn;e same metal.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope Celestyn, ordeynid he,</L>
<L N="460">a psalme men clepe Iudica me</L>
<L>&THORN;at eueri prest &thorn;at is &amp; was</L>
<L>schuld it seye or he &yogh;ede to mas.</L>
<L N="463">&THORN;e .ix. kiries &thorn;at ben in boke</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope siluester of grew hem toke.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-after comi&thorn; Gloria in excelsis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e aungelis of heuene first son[g], I-wis;</L>
<L>Of seint hillari &thorn;at was</L>
<L N="468">Erchebischop of poytas,</L>
<L>he made fro laudamus te</L>
<L>&THORN;e remenaunt &thorn;an singe we.
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="188"></L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e pope Tellophorus,</L>
<L N="472">&amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;er pope Cinacus,</L>
<L>Be-twix hem bo&thorn; ordeynid was</L>
<L>to singen gloria at &thorn;e mas.</L>
<L>pope alisaundere ordeynid wel</L>
<L N="476">to redin Epistil and gospel.</L>
<L>Be Ierom &amp; ambrose ordeynid was</L>
<L>to make &thorn;e grayel to &thorn;e mas.</L>
<L>al &thorn;is confermyd pope Gregori,</L>
<L N="480">&amp; &thorn;er-to made &thorn;e offertori.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne &thorn;e pope anastasius</L>
<L>comaundid in lawe riht &thorn;us:</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man schuld sitte, he bed,</L>
<L N="484">whil &thorn;e Gospel were red.</L>
<L>Constantinus made &thorn;e Crede,</L>
<L>to singe it he &yogh;af &thorn;e rede.</L>
<L>pope steuene &amp; pope Clemens</L>
<L N="488">ordeynid holi vestymens.</L>
<L>pope siluester ordeynid &thorn;e corporas,</L>
<L>in tokne &thorn;at goddis bodi was</L>
<L>In clene sendel I-wounde</L>
<L N="492">whan Ioseph leyde it in toumbe
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="189"></L>
<L>in his owne graue of ston</L>
<L>&amp; leyde ano&thorn;er gret ston &thorn;er-on.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne &thorn;e pope leouns</L>
<L N="496">made &thorn;e prefaciouns.</L>
<L>alisaundere &thorn;e pope ordeynid &thorn;is:</L>
<L>to don watir &amp; wyn in &thorn;e chalis,</L>
<L>in tokne &thorn;at &thorn;er com bo&thorn; watir &amp; blod</L>
<L N="500">of cristis side &thorn;at heng on rod;</L>
<L>in blod is toknid &thorn;at he bouhte vs,</L>
<L>in watir &thorn;at cristenid be houi&thorn; vs.</L>
<L>&THORN;an ordeynid &thorn;e pope sixtus</L>
<L N="504">thryes for to singe sanctus;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an he made &thorn;e canoun &thorn;er,</L>
<L>and god made &thorn;e pater noster.</L>
<L>And how &amp; in what maner befelle</L>
<L N="508">&THORN;at god made &thorn;e pater noster, I wile telle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e apostelis seyde to crist on a day:</L>
<L>"teche vs, lord, how we schul pray."</L>
<L>&amp; seynt iohn ha&thorn; tauht vs &thorn;is&mdash;</L>
<L N="512">&THORN;at is one of his disciplis&mdash;
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="190"></L>
<L>&THORN;at ihesu tauht hem &thorn;is preyere</L>
<L>&amp; bad hem seyn &thorn;e pater noster.</L>
<L>and &thorn;us moche to seyn it is:</L>
<L N="516">"Oure fader &thorn;at in heuene is,</L>
<L>halewid mote &thorn;in name be.</L>
<L>to &thorn;i kingdom mote come we.</L>
<L>&THORN;i wil in heuene &amp; in erthe be do.</L>
<L N="520">oure ech-days bred send vs &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>and oure dettis for&yogh;eue &thorn;ou vs,</L>
<L>as we for-&yogh;euen oure detouris.</L>
<L>&amp; lede vs in to no fonding,</L>
<L N="524">but saue vs fro euil &thorn;ing. amen."</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e holi gost &thorn;e .vij. &yogh;iftis</L>
<L>in &thorn;e pater noster touchid is;</L>
<L>of whiche to god &thorn;er touchin thre,</L>
<L N="528">&amp; foure in one to the and me.</L>
<L>&THORN;is preyere, &thorn;ow it be schort,</L>
<L>but it be seyd in clene hert,</L>
<L>It is a-&yogh;en &thorn;at ilke man</L>
<L N="532">&THORN;at in to his herte wra&thorn;&thorn;e ha&thorn; tan.
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="191"></L>
<L>&THORN;er-for &thorn;e good pope Innocent</L>
<L>Pax domini ha&thorn; ordeynt,</L>
<L N="535">&THORN;at eueri man schuld kisse o&thorn;er</L>
<L>&amp; holden hem for suster &amp; brother;</L>
<L>in tokne &thorn;at god mad pes wi&thorn; man,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-for &thorn;at pes is &yogh;ouen &thorn;an.</L>
<L>&THORN;e laste word of &thorn;is heye feste</L>
<L N="540">is clepid Ite missa est,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to sey "it is I-sent</L>
<L>to heuene for vs, &thorn;e sacrament";</L>
<L>be-for &thorn;e holy trenyte</L>
<L N="544">&THORN;e first part of &thorn;e thre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er for hem &thorn;at suffrid deth,</L>
<L>&THORN;e thridde for hem &thorn;at alyue beth.&mdash;</L>
<L>It is riht &thorn;at first nemenid be</L>
<L N="548">oure ladi in &thorn;e Canone:</L>
<L>ffor god of hire flesch tok</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuere cristen man forsok;</L>
<L>&THORN;at flesch he ha&thorn; take the to fede,</L>
<L N="552">&THORN;at is clepid aungelis brede.
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="192"></L>
<L>&THORN;e .xij. apostelis nemenid beth,</L>
<L>for hire preching &thorn;ei suffrid deth&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Quia apostoli dicuntur missi, &amp; martires testes apostolorum:</I></P>
<LG>
<L>As &thorn;ing &thorn;at is sent ben &thorn;e apostelis,</L>
<L N="556">and marteris ben to hem witnes;</L>
<L>&amp; alle marteris &thorn;at were dede</L>
<L>for &thorn;ei were witnes of &thorn;is brede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god deyde for loue of vs,</L>
<L N="560">&amp; &thorn;ei for &thorn;e loue of crist ihesus.</L>
<L>petir, andrew, philip, these .iij.</L>
<L>were don vp-on &thorn;e rode-tre.</L>
<L>poule, Iamys, and mathew</L>
<L N="564">were heuedid, &amp; bartilmew</L>
<L>was helt al nakid quyk</L>
<L>for his witnes of &thorn;is vnlik.</L>
<L>and &thorn;at o&thorn;er lesse Iamys,</L>
<L N="568">and symon also, &amp; thadeus,</L>
<L>hire senewis for cristen lawe</L>
<L>out of hire bodi were drawe.
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="193"></L>
<L>and seynt Iohn Euangelist,</L>
<L N="572">&THORN;at was cosyn to ihesu crist,</L>
<L>he drank venym, to make preue</L>
<L>&THORN;at we han tru&thorn;e and riht beleue.</L>
<L>and seynt thomas didimus,</L>
<L N="576">he was &thorn;orw-stekid riht &thorn;us.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-after comi&thorn; .xij. marteris,</L>
<L>&THORN;at company in &thorn;e canoun reknid is;</L>
<L N="579">Of whiche summe popis were,</L>
<L>summe bischopis &thorn;at myter did bere,</L>
<L>summe deknes &thorn;at were half prest,</L>
<L>summe lewid men &thorn;at leuid on crist&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor alle ordres &amp; alle degres</L>
<L N="584">to &thorn;is sacrament bere witnes.</L>
<L>Leouns, Clemens, &amp; Cletus,</L>
<L>Sixtus, and Cornelius,</L>
<L>these were popis, &thorn;at suffrid deth</L>
<L N="588">for &thorn;at bred &thorn;at &yogh;e a-days seeth.</L>
<L>Ciprian was bischop of Cartaginus.</L>
<L>Steuene, laurens, &amp; vincent were dekins.
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="194"></L>
<L>Grisogon, Iohn and paules,</L>
<L N="592">&THORN;ei were on lyue knyhtis;</L>
<L>Cosmas and Damianus,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei were lechis, wretin it is &thorn;us.</L>
<L>Katerine, Mergrete, &amp; agace</L>
<L N="596">deyden for &thorn;is bred of grace.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-for it is riht hire namys to be</L>
<L>nemenid in &thorn;e Canone:</L>
<L>for alle these deyde in good entent</L>
<L N="600">for to mayntene &thorn;is sacrament.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sacrament mote &thorn;i soule fede</L>
<L>&thorn;at is clepid aungelis brede.</L>
<L>if &thorn;at &yogh;e wor&thorn;iliche it fonge,</L>
<L N="604">it schal kepe &yogh;ow &thorn;us longe,</L>
<L>fro &thorn;at day &thorn;at &yogh;e ded ben</L>
<L>til &yogh;oure bodyes risen a-&yogh;en;</L>
<L>and &thorn;an &thorn;e bodi &amp; soule in-fere</L>
<L N="608">schul wende to &thorn;e gret mangere</L>
<L>where neuere-mor schal ben no nede</L>
<L>to no maner of ertheli brede,</L>
<L>But &thorn;e sihte of &thorn;e blisful trenyte
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="195"></L>
<L N="612">schal euere-mor &thorn;i fode be.</L>
<L>&THORN;er we han &thorn;e moder to prey &thorn;e sone,</L>
<L>&amp; we han &thorn;e sone to prey &thorn;e fader,</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy gost we han in wone&mdash;</L>
<L N="616">&THORN;is entre we han to-geder:</L>
<L>what letti&thorn; vs for to wynne</L>
<L>&THORN;e riche blis &thorn;at is vs behote,</L>
<L>but it be oure owne synne?</L>
<L N="620">&THORN;er is non o&thorn;er &thorn;ing, I wote.</L>
<L>Of pardoun I haue no pouste</L>
<L>to &yogh;ow for to graunte of me:</L>
<L>but, if &yogh;e don now after me,</L>
<L N="624">I wile &yogh;ow tellin a quantite,</L>
<L>How moche pardoun &yogh;e may habbe,</L>
<L>grauntid to &yogh;oure moste nede,</L>
<L>to come to honour wi&thorn;-outen gabbe,</L>
<L>it is<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. it is</NOTE> &thorn;is ilke aungelis brede.</L>
<L N="629">That same thursday &thorn;at next is</L>
<L>after &thorn;e feste of &thorn;e trenyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope vrban ordeynid &thorn;is</L>
<L N="632">&THORN;at &thorn;an &thorn;is pardoun schuld be.
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="196"></L>
<L>an hundrid dayes of for&yogh;ifnes</L>
<L>he grauntid to hem alle in fay</L>
<L>&THORN;at come vn-to &thorn;e matynes</L>
<L N="636">on &thorn;at same thursday;</L>
<L>ffourti dayes for eueri houre &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>&amp; an hundrid for &thorn;e masse,</L>
<L>an hundrid who-so &thorn;e euensong abide&mdash;</L>
<L N="640">he grauntid hem no lasse.</L>
<L>and al &thorn;at woke eueriday</L>
<L>&THORN;is pardoun lasti&thorn; so,</L>
<L>who-so al &thorn;e seruyse han may;</L>
<L N="644">&amp; &yogh;et he schal han mo:</L>
<L>ffor eueri days seruise</L>
<L>an hundrid days to bote&mdash;</L>
<L>wel men auhte to seen therin<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. to seien</NOTE> &thorn;ise</L>
<L>on horse and also on fote.</L>
<L>&THORN;e laste pope &thorn;at was now,</L>
<L>his name Iohn hiht,</L>
<L>al &thorn;is pardoun he graunti&thorn; &yogh;ow</L>
<L N="652">&amp; doubli&thorn; it wi&thorn; his myht.</L>
<L>Meylerus, &thorn;orw goddis grace
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="197"></L>
<L>bisschop of ley&yogh;-lymme,</L>
<L>he ha&thorn; amendid al &thorn;is cas</L>
<L N="656">&THORN;orw myht &thorn;at god &yogh;af hym:</L>
<L>ffourti days to pardoun</L>
<L>he &yogh;af &thorn;er-to, wi&thorn;-out drede,</L>
<L>to alle &thorn;at wi&thorn; good deuocioun</L>
<L N="660">herin it or don it rede.</L>
<L>So it amounti&thorn; holliche</L>
<L>on and fourty &yogh;ere</L>
<L>&amp; sex-score dayes, truliche,</L>
<L N="664">who-so heri&thorn; his seruise here.</L>
<L>Ihesu graunte &yogh;ow alle &amp; some</L>
<L>in erthe so for to spede</L>
<L>that &thorn;is pardoun &yogh;ow make come</L>
<L N="668">vn-to &thorn;is heuenlich brede.</L>
<L>&THORN;at man ete aungelis brede,</L>
<L>&THORN;us first we began;</L>
<L>to heuene it mote vs alle lede</L>
<L N="672">bo&thorn;e wyf and man,</L>
<L>In nomine patris &amp; filij wi&thorn; vs go</L>
<L>Et spiritus sancti do also. amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">

<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="168">
<HEAD>MS. Harl. 4196. Sermo in festo Corporis Cristi.</HEAD>
<EPIGRAPH><Q>Panem angelorum manducauit homo</Q> <BIBL>(Ps. 77, 25).</BIBL></EPIGRAPH>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><SUP>*</SUP>Laude men herto tak hede&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor vnto clerkes it es no nede,</L>
<L>In &thorn;aire bukes may &thorn;ai se</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e gudenes of goddes preuete,</L>
<L>Gastly how he will vs fede</L>
<L>With his body in fowrom of brede,
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="169"></L>
<L N="7">Als haly kyrk now most and lest</L>
<L>Mase mynde now in &thorn;is new-fun fest;</L>
<L>Als dauid in &thorn;e sawter said,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e haly gast had him puruaid</L>
<L>By figures &thorn;e folk forto lere.</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;ar-fore he said on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>Als witnes beres in &thorn;is stede:</L>
<L>"Man," he said, "etis angell brede."</L>
<L>So was it in tyme of moyses</L>
<L N="16">Omang &thorn;e childer &thorn;at ihesu chese.</L>
<L>ffor when &thorn;ai war in thraldom broght</L>
<L>With farao &thorn;at &thorn;am wranges wroght&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at war ful lang now forto tell;</L>
<L N="20">Bot at &thorn;e last so it bifell</L>
<L>&THORN;at god wald suffer it namore</L>
<L>&THORN;at his folk in thraldom wore:</L>
<L>He bad moyses &thorn;at he suld fle</L>
<L N="24">With his folk thurgh &thorn;e [rede] se.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai to &thorn;e se war cumen,</L>
<L>A dri way sone haue &thorn;ai nomyn:</L>
<L>&THORN;e water stode vp als a wall,
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="170"></L>
<L N="28">vntill &thorn;ai war past ouer all.</L>
<L>Kyng farao with ful gret boste</L>
<L>pursued &thorn;am with all his oste,</L>
<L>And wele &thorn;ai wend &thorn;e way to hent</L>
<L N="32">Als &thorn;e childer oway had went:</L>
<L>&THORN;e se closed and &thorn;am vmcast;</L>
<L>&THORN;aire liues might no langer last.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was he and his men&yogh;e drownd,</L>
<L>And goddes folk past hale and sownd.</L>
<L N="37">In wildernes &thorn;an was moyses</L>
<L>With childer &thorn;at god him-seluen chese.</L>
<L>God sent to &thorn;am fra heuyn doune</L>
<L N="40">Als it war flowre ful gret foysowne;</L>
<L>Manna in clergi es it cald,</L>
<L>Angell mete men may it hald.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai gaderd it and lifed &thorn;ar-by,</L>
<L N="44">And sinned I sall tell &yogh;ow why:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai gederd more and broght to hend</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ai had mester forto spend;</L>
<L>And, if &thorn;ai samind it on &thorn;e day,</L>
<L N="48">On &thorn;e morn wald it be oway
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="171"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-in wald be no foysowne,</L>
<L>Bot turn in to corrupciowne.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai might wele se &thorn;an by &thorn;is thing:</L>
<L>God was noght paid of &thorn;aire gedering.</L>
<L N="53">&THORN;an may we se it es ill store</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ir mokyrers &thorn;at bies more</L>
<L>Corn or malt &thorn;an he has nede</L>
<L N="56">His men&yogh;e fully forto fede.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at byes corn so here</L>
<L>And &yogh;emes it till it be dere,</L>
<L>And are will lat it lig and rote</L>
<L N="60">Or he it do till o&thorn;er note,</L>
<L>He greues god, trewly to tell,</L>
<L>Als did &thorn;e childer of israel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at trowed noght with trew entent</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at fode Inogh suld &thorn;am be sent.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at corn gaders gude spede</L>
<L>And will noght part in tyme of nede</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;am &thorn;at fode has nane,</L>
<L N="68">Bot saues it to him-self allane,</L>
<L>fful hard rekining &yogh;eld sal he
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="172"></L>
<L>At &thorn;e dome, when he sall demed be</L>
<L>By-for god &thorn;at es high iustise</L>
<L>And euyn domes-man &amp; al rightwise,</L>
<L N="73">And bifor all his saintes sere</L>
<L>And his angels all in-fere;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sall he wit how he has spend</L>
<L N="76">Al &thorn;e gude &thorn;at god him send!</L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;is maner sall god say</L>
<L>vnto nithinges on domes-day:</L>
<L>"hunger I had and thrist ful grete:</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;ou gaf me now&thorn;er drink ne mete;</L>
<L>And herberles &thorn;ou me forsoke;</L>
<L>In preson wald &thorn;ou noght me loke;</L>
<L>Nakid when<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. whin</NOTE> I was also,</L>
<L N="84">With-owten clath &thorn;ou lete me go.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore now saltou wende to hell,</L>
<L>Euer-more with deuils to dwell."</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;e sinful say in hy:</L>
<L N="88">"lord, when saw we &thorn;e nedy</L>
<L>And did noght als vs fell to do?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal he answer &thorn;am vnto
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="173"></L>
<L>And say: "when &thorn;at &yogh;e saw in pine</L>
<L N="92">Any of &thorn;e lest of myne</L>
<L>And helpid &thorn;am noght in &thorn;aire nede,</L>
<L>vnto me did &yogh;e &thorn;at ilk dede."</L>
<L>&THORN;an thurgh dome he sal &thorn;am schende</L>
<L N="96">To won in wa with-owten ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;us on domesday &thorn;e most hething</L>
<L>Sall fall vnto &thorn;e hard nithing;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;arof will &thorn;ai noght &thorn;am schriue,</L>
<L N="100">If &thorn;ai be nithinges al &thorn;aire liue,</L>
<L>Bot euer-more &thorn;ai answer &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"We gif wele more &thorn;an men dose vs,"</L>
<L>And syn &thorn;ai say &thorn;at it [es] nane</L>
<L N="104">To saue all to &thorn;am-self allane</L>
<L>And spare it all vntill &thorn;ai dy&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at bargan sall &thorn;ai dere haby!</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore of nithinges lat we be</L>
<L N="108">And till oure mater turn will we:</L>
<L>More in &thorn;is tyme now will we tell</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e childer of israel,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ai gaderd angell fode</L>
<L N="112">More &thorn;an neded to do &thorn;am gude.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai traisted noght in goddes grace:</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-fore vnto &thorn;am wrath he was,</L>
<L>He sufferd &thorn;am peris ilkane</L>
<L N="116">And with &thorn;aire enmys to be slane;</L>
<L>With were he was opon &thorn;am<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;an</NOTE> wroken,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ai had his biding broken.</L>
<L>Ofsex and twenty hundreth thowsand(!)</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at war &thorn;are in desert dweland,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e land of hest &thorn;are come nane fre</L>
<L>Bot anly Calef and iosue&mdash;
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="174"></L>
<L>And of &thorn;a twa come all &thorn;e strene</L>
<L>Of milde mari, oure heuyn-quene.&mdash;</L>
<L N="125">Now in &thorn;is werld wele may we se</L>
<L>&THORN;at lufed with god wele more er we:</L>
<L>ffor he sent &thorn;am bot angels brede,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;at bot a day wald stand in stede,</L>
<L>And vntill vs here has he sent</L>
<L>His awin body, verrayment,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer-more will last vs in,</L>
<L N="132">If we be out of dedly syn.</L>
<L>Both his verray fless and blude</L>
<L>Gifes he till oure gastly fode</L>
<L>&THORN;at for vs was pined on a tre;</L>
<L N="136">Ilk day oure-self may it se</L>
<L>In faire fowrom of erthly brede</L>
<L>&THORN;at for vs in erth sufferd dede</L>
<L>And toke his hand-werk out of hell.</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;arby a tale he[r] will I tell,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wretin es in &thorn;e legent</L>
<L>Towcheand &thorn;is haly sacrament.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Aaracio de iudeo &amp; cristiano.</HEAD>
<L>Sum tyme, als clerkes tell &yogh;ow can,</L>
<L N="144">Was a iew and a cristen man;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai met togeder opon a day,</L>
<L>And so &yogh;ode samen by &thorn;e way.</L>
<L>And, als in bokes beres witnes,</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;e cristen man herd ring to mes.</L>
<L>He said to &thorn;e iew: "habide me here,</L>
<L>Whils I go mak my prayere."
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="175"></L>
<L>&THORN;e iew said: "I will assent."</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;e cristen man to kirk es went,</L>
<L>And made his prayers inwardly</L>
<L>vnto oure lord god al-mighty.</L>
<L>&THORN;e iew &thorn;an in &thorn;e way him held</L>
<L>And thoght his felaw ful lang dweld;</L>
<L N="157">&THORN;arfore vnto &thorn;e kirk he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>preuely forto tak hede</L>
<L>What maners was &thorn;am omang</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at his felaw dweld so lang.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he saw, or euer he leuid,</L>
<L>&THORN;e prist hald vp ouer his heuid</L>
<L>A knaue-childe, with wowndes sore</L>
<L N="164">In fete and hend; &yogh;it saw he more</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;are was now&thorn;er wife ne man</L>
<L>Of &thorn;am &thorn;at in &thorn;e kirk was &thorn;an [hend;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai ne kneled and held vp &thorn;aire</L>
<L>And fra &thorn;e child &thorn;an saw he wend</L>
<L>To ilk man swilk a child to sight,</L>
<L>And euyn bitwene &thorn;aire handes it light.</L>
<L>&THORN;e iew biheld &thorn;an to &thorn;e priste</L>
<L N="172">Bygan to vse &thorn;e ewkariste,</L>
<L>He saw him ett &thorn;e same childe</L>
<L>&THORN;at he bitwix [his] handes hilde;</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e same wise thoght him &thorn;are</L>
<L N="176">Did all &thorn;at in &thorn;e kirk ware.</L>
<L>&THORN;e iew &thorn;an went and stode &thorn;at tide</L>
<L>Whare his felow bad him abide,</L>
<L>And vnto him-self said he &thorn;an:</L>
<L N="180">"A lathly life ledes cristen men!"
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="176"></L>
<L>&THORN;e cristen man, when mes was done,</L>
<L>Come vnto &thorn;e iew full sone.</L>
<L>&THORN;e iew said: "how fars &thorn;ou now?"</L>
<L N="184">&THORN;e to&thorn;er said: "better &thorn;an &thorn;ou.</L>
<L>ffor I haue sene my sauiowre,</L>
<L>vnto wham be euer honowre;</L>
<L>And sen &thorn;at I haue sene &thorn;at sight,</L>
<L N="188">All &thorn;e day I am more light."</L>
<L>&THORN;e iew said: "so mot I the,</L>
<L>&THORN;i wombe aght wele full to be!</L>
<L>ffor, and I might so mekill ette,</L>
<L N="192">&THORN;ir thre daies suld I ett no mete."</L>
<L>&THORN;e cristen man &thorn;an said ful right:</L>
<L>"&THORN;is day come no mete in my sight;</L>
<L>Als fer als I on may think,</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;is day I saw no mete ne drink."</L>
<L>&THORN;e iew said: "for schame, lat be!</L>
<L>I saw both o&thorn;er men and &thorn;e</L>
<L>Ilkone hald a child blody</L>
<L N="200">And ett it se&thorn;in, sekerly.</L>
<L>And sertes, me think by &thorn;is scill</L>
<L>A lathly life &yogh;e gif &yogh;ow till!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e cristen man &thorn;an wex all wrath,</L>
<L>And said: "&thorn;ou lies, with-owten ath.</L>
<L N="205">&YOGH;owre law es fals and so er &yogh;e,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e will noght leue bot &thorn;at &yogh;e se.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore fare furth, opon &thorn;e fy!</L>
<L N="208">I will nomore &thorn;i cumpany."
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="177"></L>
<L>&THORN;e iew said: "felaw, greue &thorn;e noght</L>
<L>Al-if me here-of wonder thoght,</L>
<L>Bot tell me by sum graither preue</L>
<L N="212">How I might &thorn;e sertayn leue."</L>
<L>&THORN;e cristen man said: "&thorn;is es &thorn;e skill</L>
<L>&THORN;at god of heuyn noght suffer will</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i sinful eghen seghe</L>
<L N="216">&THORN;e sacrament &thorn;at es so heghe,</L>
<L>He wald noght schew &thorn;e in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>How his body es hid in brede:</L>
<L>&THORN;i kin him slogh ogains &thorn;e law.</L>
<L N="220">ffor-&thorn;i &thorn;ou him al blody saw,</L>
<L>And so sall all &thorn;i kin him se</L>
<L>At &thorn;e dome when &thorn;ai sal dampned be."</L>
<L>&THORN;e iew said: "felow, I prai &thorn;e &thorn;an</L>
<L N="224">&THORN;at I war made a cristen man."</L>
<L>&THORN;an was he cristend als I tell,</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;is miracle &thorn;at &thorn;us byfell.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Exemplum per speculum.</HEAD>
<L><B>A</B> faire ensample may men se</L>
<L>Of goddes body, how it may be</L>
<L N="229">In diuers parcels parted here</L>
<L>And ilkane be goddes body entere;</L>
<L>And how &thorn;at of ane eucharist,</L>
<L N="232">&THORN;at sakerd es &thorn;e cors of crist,</L>
<L>A hundreth men may haue &thorn;aire dale,</L>
<L>And ilkone haue cristes body hale&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at may men by ensawmple here.</L>
<L N="236">Bihald &thorn;i-self in a schewere:
<PB REF="00000186.tif" N="178"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou sese bot a face, more ne les,</L>
<L>Whils &thorn;e glas vnbroken es.</L>
<L>Breke &thorn;an &thorn;e glas in two or thre:</L>
<L N="240">And so many faces sall &thorn;ou se;</L>
<L>Breke in a hundreth peces &thorn;e glace</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou sall se a hundreth face.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at &thorn;e glas all hale ware,</L>
<L N="244">A face &thorn;ou suld se and nomare.</L>
<L>So &thorn;e sacrament of goddes body</L>
<L>May be departed in sere party,</L>
<L>And in ilk part all hale es he,</L>
<L N="248">All-if it neuer so litill be.&mdash;</L>
<L>Also &yogh;it, &thorn;at &thorn;e sacrament</L>
<L>Es ordand all by trew entent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at may ilk man him-seluen se</L>
<L>By &thorn;e making of &thorn;e vble.</L>
<L>By seuyn selles<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. scilles, of. v. 281.</NOTE> it es made euyn,</L>
<L>To stroy &thorn;e dedly sines seuyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e eukarist aw to be white,</L>
<L N="256">fforto destroy flesly delite</L>
<L>And alkins lust of lichery,</L>
<L>&THORN;at blac es euer and ful vgly.</L>
<L>Thin aw it to be al-gate,</L>
<L N="260">Glotony forto abate;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ai couait &thorn;at glotons es</L>
<L>Of mete and drink ay mekelnes.</L>
<L N="263">Rownd it es and light to thraw,</L>
<L>Ogains slewth, &thorn;at makes men slaw.</L>
<L>And it es made with-owten leuaine,</L>
<L>Wreth and enuy to stand againe;</L>
<L>ffor enuy bolnes mans hert</L>
<L N="268">When he sese o&thorn;er men in quert.</L>
<L>It es also with-owten bran,</L>
<L>And, als &thorn;ir clerkes declare it kan,
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="179"></L>
<L>&THORN;at es ogaines couatise,</L>
<L N="272">&THORN;at rekkes neuer on whatkin wise</L>
<L>&THORN;at he may reches vnderfang,</L>
<L>Be it right or be it wrang.</L>
<L>Also it es litill and clene,</L>
<L N="276">Ogains pride, &thorn;at euer es kene</L>
<L>And couaites to be grete and fell,</L>
<L>Als lucifer, &thorn;at went to hell</L>
<L>And fell for pride fra &thorn;e blis of heuyn.</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;e brede &thorn;us es ordand by seuyn</L>
<L>proper skils, forto reherce</L>
<L>Als funden es here in &thorn;is vers:</L>
<LG>
<L><I>Candida, triticia, tenuis, non magna, rotunda,</I></L>
<L><I>Ex-pers frumenti</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. fermenti</NOTE> <I>non mixta sit hostia cristi.&mdash;</I></L>
</LG>
<L>And when crist made &thorn;is sacrament?</L>
<L N="284">&THORN;at sal we trow with trew entent,</L>
<L>fful light it es in faith to fele,</L>
<L>ffor ilka cristen man wate wele</L>
<L>How &thorn;at crist sat at his sopere</L>
<L>When &thorn;at his passiown neghed nere,</L>
<L N="289">And till his appostels gan he bid</L>
<L>fforto do als he &thorn;an did&mdash;</L>
<L>And how he did, wele find men may</L>
<L N="292">In &thorn;e passion on gude friday;</L>
<L>He said: "on &thorn;is wise sall &yogh;e do,</L>
<L>ffor I most wende my fader vnto;</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &yogh;e do in mynde of me</L>
<L N="296">Als oft as it done sal be."</L>
<L>&THORN;us of &thorn;e appostels &thorn;at god sent</L>
<L>Toke haly kirk &thorn;is sacrament.&mdash;
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="180"></L>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Et dicitur sacramentum</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Quasi sacre rei signum.</I></L>
<L><I>Et dicitur eukaristia</I></L>
<L><I>Quasi bona gracia.</I></L>
</LG>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e first tels with trew entent:</L>
<L N="300">A haly signe es sacrament.</L>
<L>And noght els menes &thorn;e eukarist</L>
<L>Bot gude grace, cumen of crist.</L>
<L>Wele may we se it es gude grace,</L>
<L N="304">&THORN;at keper es in cristes place!</L>
<L>And grace es more worthi &thorn;an kinde,</L>
<L>Als cristen men may haue in minde.&mdash;</L>
<L>Men aw to be in clene entent</L>
<L N="308">&THORN;at sall resayue &thorn;is sacrament,</L>
<L>ffor saint paule sais, &amp; se men may</L>
<L>In &thorn;e pystell of &thorn;is day:<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Cor. 11, 29.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at what man so with euill mode</L>
<L>Resaiues goddes fless and his blude,</L>
<L N="313">He cums to his confusiowne</L>
<L>And resayues his dampnacioune.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore saint paule, ane of &thorn;e twelue,</L>
<L>Sais &thorn;at a man here demes him-selue</L>
<L>And of dampnacion takes his dome,</L>
<L>vnclene to goddes burd and he come.</L>
<L>Man &thorn;at dose so, wha-euer he be,</L>
<L N="320">Sall he neuer-more demed be;</L>
<L>ffor his awin dome wha-so will take,</L>
<L>What o&thorn;er dome suld god him make?</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore suld na man reklesly</L>
<L N="324">Wend to resayue &thorn;at blisced body,</L>
<L>&THORN;at life es, if &thorn;ai wele it ta,</L>
<L>And ded to &thorn;am &thorn;at dose noght swa.
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="181"></L>
<L>And &thorn;arofe here we saint mark<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. John (6, 56-9).</NOTE> say</L>
<L>In &thorn;e godspell of &thorn;is day,</L>
<L N="329">Whare we may find wretin &thorn;us:</L>
<L>To his desciples said ihesus</L>
<L>And also to &thorn;e iewes in-fere,</L>
<L N="332">Telland to &thorn;am on &thorn;is manere:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><BIBL>Euangelium secundum Marcum.<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. John (6, 56-9).</NOTE></BIBL> <Q>Caro mea uere est cibus, &amp; sanguis meus uere est potus:</Q></HEAD>
<L>"My fless," he said, "es brede of life</L>
<L>And verray mete to man and wife,</L>
<L N="335">And my blude es drink verray</L>
<L>To all &thorn;at lifes in cristen lay.</L>
<L>Wha ettes my fless and drinkes my blude,</L>
<L>In me he dwelles with mayne &amp; mode.</L>
<L>And I in him am ay dwelland,</L>
<L>Whils he in stabill trowth will stande.</L>
<L N="341">And als my fader lifand in blis</L>
<L>Has sent me, forto mend &yogh;owre mis,</L>
<L>And, als he lifes in lith and lim,</L>
<L N="344">So lif I for &thorn;e luf of him:</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at ettes my body fre,</L>
<L>He sall ay lif thurgh might of me.</L>
<L>&THORN;is es &thorn;e brede with-owten ende</L>
<L N="348">&THORN;at fra &thorn;e hegh of heuyn descend;</L>
<L>Noght like to manna &thorn;at doun fell</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e childer of israel,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;arof ette &thorn;ai in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>And neuer-&thorn;e-lese &yogh;it war &thorn;ai dede.</L>
<L N="353">He &thorn;at &thorn;is brede ettes worthily,</L>
<L>He sall ay lif and neuer dy,</L>
<L>Gastly life ay sall he haue,</L>
<L>And in heuyn sall his saul be saue."<NOTE PLACE="marg">355-6 added.</NOTE></L>
<L N="357">Crist grante vs for his moder sake</L>
<L>&THORN;at worthily we may it take.</L>
<L>More of &thorn;is mete we may here tell</L>
<L>How &thorn;at saint Iohn in his godspell<NOTE PLACE="marg">John 6, 54.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="182"></L>
<L N="361">Sais: bot if we ett cristes brede</L>
<L>And drink his blude, oureliueserded.&mdash;</L>
<L>All-if it here be parted in smale,</L>
<L N="364">Crist cors in heuyn it es all hale,</L>
<L>And euer with-owten end sall last.</L>
<L>&THORN;us aw oure trowth to be stedfast&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor no man may here serue crist,</L>
<L N="368">Bot if his trowth to him be trist.</L>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Oculus fidei acutus est,</I></L>
<L><I>Quia inuisibilia conspicit:</I></L>
</LG>
<L>&THORN;e eghe of faith es scharp and kene,</L>
<L>It sese &thorn;at may noght here be sene.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore vs aw to trow and wirk</L>
<L N="372">Efter kening of haly kirk,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at es here &thorn;e fastest fay,</L>
<L>And vnto heuyn &thorn;e rediest way.&mdash;</L>
<L>More will I tell &yogh;it in &thorn;is stede</L>
<L N="376">How &thorn;at men ettes angel brede.</L>
<L>&THORN;is blisced brede may neuer be spend,</L>
<L>ffor god him-self hider has it send</L>
<L>ffra &thorn;e fende man saul to fend</L>
<L>And giff &thorn;am blis with-owten ende.</L>
<L N="381">In &thorn;e bigining was ordand</L>
<L>A custum in ilk cristen land</L>
<L>&THORN;at men and wemen more &amp; les</L>
<L N="384">Suld ilka sunday efter mess
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="183"></L>
<L>Be howseld all with gude entent</L>
<L>And resaiue &thorn;is ilk sacrament.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;en was &thorn;at custum casten doun,</L>
<L N="388">I sall &yogh;ow tell by what chesoune.</L>
<L>ffor folk war howsild so comunly,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai toke &thorn;e les reward &thorn;arby,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;am-self &thorn;ai wald noght &yogh;eme</L>
<L N="392">Als to &thorn;e sacrament suld seme.</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er was, for men wex irk</L>
<L>With grete trauail in hali kirk,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at none wise &thorn;ai might forsake</L>
<L>In tyme when folk suld howsil take.</L>
<L N="397">&THORN;arfore &thorn;e pape on &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Ordand: &thorn;at thrise in &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Suld men resaiue &thorn;at blisced brede</L>
<L N="400">Thurgh cristen land in ilka stede;</L>
<L>And who did noght anes at &thorn;e leste,</L>
<L>He sall be halden bot als a beste,</L>
<L>And he sal noght, whe[n] he es ded,</L>
<L N="404">Haue his beriel in haly stede.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore pray we god in-wardly</L>
<L>&THORN;at we in werk may be worthy</L>
<L>&THORN;at brede enterely forto take,</L>
<L N="408">Sen it may all oure sorows slake.</L>
<L>And by &thorn;is brede now will I tell</L>
<L>Ane ensaumple &thorn;at sum tyme fell.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Narracio de presbitero.</HEAD>
<L>A prest sum tyme in ingland</L>
<L N="412">In a cete was wonand;
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="184"></L>
<L>He had noght led, als sum men tolde,</L>
<L>His life als clenly als he solde:</L>
<L>A grete euil god to him send,</L>
<L N="416">ffor &thorn;at he suld his mis amend.</L>
<L>And als he lay opon a night,</L>
<L>God of heuyn him schewed &thorn;is sight:</L>
<L>A child him thoght he saw and herd,</L>
<L N="420">&THORN;at asked him how &thorn;at he ferd;</L>
<L>A panier in his hand he broght</L>
<L>fful of brenand oblis, als him thoght.</L>
<L N="423">&THORN;e prest &thorn;an asked: "wha ertow?</L>
<L>And what es &thorn;at &thorn;ou bringes now?"</L>
<L>He said: "I am goddes messangere,</L>
<L>And lo, oblis I bring &thorn;e here;</L>
<L>&THORN;us many vnworthi has &thorn;ou tane</L>
<L N="428">At &thorn;i mes bi &thorn;e allane.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou will noght leue me,</L>
<L>Schew furth &thorn;i hand and &thorn;ou sal se."</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest put furth his hand onone,</L>
<L N="432">And &thorn;e childe has ane vble tone</L>
<L>Of &thorn;am &thorn;at semid so brinand,</L>
<L>And put it in &thorn;e prestes hand.</L>
<L>When it was laid in a moment,</L>
<L>A hole thurgh-out &thorn;e hand it brent.</L>
<L N="437">&THORN;e childe &thorn;an went oway in hy,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e prest bigan to cry.</L>
<L>O&thorn;er men &thorn;an come him to</L>
<L N="440">And asked whi &thorn;at he fore so.
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="185"></L>
<L>"Lo," he said, "how I am dight!</L>
<L>Wha saw euer swilk a sight?"</L>
<L>A hole in his hand might men se</L>
<L N="444">Als brade als was &thorn;e vble.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest &thorn;an wele amendid es,</L>
<L>And efterward sang many mes,</L>
<L N="447">And &thorn;e hole euer in his hand,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men &thorn;e suth might vnderstand.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He serued god in word and dede,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;in his sawl to heuyn &yogh;ede.&mdash;</L>
<L N="451">I hald, &thorn;e man es more &thorn;an mad</L>
<L>&THORN;at ettes &thorn;is brede and es noght rad</L>
<L>ffor vengance of god and for wrake,</L>
<L>If he vnworthily it take!&mdash;</L>
<L>Wroght it was thurgh goddes worde</L>
<L N="456">&THORN;at he said at his awin burde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e same might has ilka prest:</L>
<L>To turn &thorn;e brede till &thorn;e cors of crist,
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="186"></L>
<L>And forto turn wine in to blude,</L>
<L N="460">&THORN;e same &thorn;at was sched on &thorn;e rode.</L>
<L>Crist blisced &thorn;e brede, als sais &thorn;e boke,</L>
<L>And till his appostels he it toke,</L>
<L>And said to &thorn;am on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L N="464">"&THORN;is es my fless I gif &yogh;ow here."</L>
<L>And efter he toke &thorn;e chalis,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e same wise gan it blis,</L>
<L>And said to &thorn;am with mild mode:</L>
<L N="468">"Drinkes of &thorn;is, it es my blude.</L>
<L>And als oft-tymes als &yogh;e it take,</L>
<L>Mynde of me luke &thorn;at &yogh;e make!"</L>
<L>&THORN;us ordand crist &thorn;is sacrament.</L>
<L>And when he vnto heuyn was went,</L>
<L N="473">&THORN;ai did messes als he cumand,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai went in ilka land.</L>
<L>And when peter was pape of rome,</L>
<L N="476">Chef cownsailoure of cristendome,</L>
<L>Ne al &thorn;e o&thorn;er, whare &thorn;ai lend,</L>
<L>Said namore &thorn;an crist had kend;</L>
<L>Ne did &thorn;arto none o&thorn;er thing,</L>
<L N="480">When &thorn;ai suld &thorn;aire messes sing,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e pater noster gan &thorn;ai say,</L>
<L>Als crist had cumand &thorn;aim to pray.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai had noght els bot brede and wine,</L>
<L>And goddes wordes gude and fyne.</L>
<L N="485">Vestimentes none had &thorn;ai</L>
<L>Bot als &thorn;ai werid ilka day,
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="187"></L>
<L>And vessels &thorn;at of tre war made&mdash;</L>
<L N="488">None o&thorn;er chalises &thorn;an &thorn;ai hade.</L>
<L>&THORN;an efterward &thorn;e pape vrban,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was halden a haly man,</L>
<L>Ordaind &thorn;at &thorn;e chalis sulde</L>
<L>Be made of siluer o&thorn;er els of gulde,</L>
<L N="493">With a patene, to hill ouer all,</L>
<L>Ordand of &thorn;e same metall.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pape celestiene alswa</L>
<L N="496">Ordand a salme hat <I>Iudica</I></L>
<L>&THORN;at ilk prest &thorn;at ordand es</L>
<L>Sal say bifor he go to mes.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pape siluester toke out of grew</L>
<L N="500">&THORN;e nien kyries, als clerkes knew;</L>
<L>&THORN;e angell sang he did &thorn;ar-to</L>
<L>Gloria in excelsis deo.</L>
<L>Saint hillary &thorn;an, als men hers,</L>
<L N="504">Erchebisschop was of paters,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e remnand ordand he</L>
<L>&THORN;at we sing fra laudamus te.
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="188"></L>
<L>&THORN;an by &thorn;e pape it ordand es</L>
<L N="508">To sing &thorn;at Gloria at &thorn;e mes;</L>
<L>It confermed pape tellophorus,</L>
<L>And sc&thorn;in so did pape cinacus.</L>
<L>Pape alisander ordand rath</L>
<L N="512">&THORN;e pistell and &thorn;e godspell bath.</L>
<L>By ierom and ambrose ordaind es</L>
<L>To sing &thorn;e graell at &thorn;e mes.</L>
<L>It confermed pape gregori,</L>
<L N="516">And made &thorn;arto &thorn;e offertory.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e pape anastacius,</L>
<L>In his tyme he ordand &thorn;us:</L>
<L>&THORN;at men suld stand, was his biding,</L>
<L N="520">Whils &thorn;e godspell was in reding.</L>
<L>&THORN;e twelue appastels made &thorn;e crede:</L>
<L>To sing it damacius &thorn;e pape bede.</L>
<L>Pape steuen and pape clement,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ordand &thorn;e vestiment.</L>
<L>Pape siluester ordand &thorn;e corporas,</L>
<L>In tokining &thorn;at goddes body was</L>
<L>In clene clathes lapped<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. was lapped</NOTE> and laid</L>
<L N="528">When it in &thorn;e graue was graid.
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="189"></L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e pape Leones</L>
<L>Ordand &thorn;e preface at &thorn;e mes.</L>
<L>Pape alisander ordand sine</L>
<L N="532">To do in chalis water and wine,</L>
<L>In takin &thorn;at both water and blude</L>
<L>Come fra crist side on &thorn;e rode;</L>
<L>&THORN;e blude es tokin &thorn;at he vs boght,</L>
<L N="536">&THORN;e water wassches all euill thoght.</L>
<L>&THORN;an ordand &thorn;e pape Si[x]tus,</L>
<L>Thrise &thorn;at men suld say sanctus.</L>
<L>Ielasius made &thorn;e canon right,</L>
<L N="540">And crist &thorn;e pater noster dight.</L>
<L>And how &thorn;at praier ordand was,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sall I tell &yogh;ow or I pas.</L>
<L N="543">His desciples said on a day:</L>
<L>"Lord, tell till vs what we sal pray."</L>
<L>And saint Ion<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Luc</NOTE> sais he bad &thorn;am bid</L>
<L>&THORN;e pater noster, and it vndid,
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="190"></L>
<L>How &thorn;at it es ordand euyn</L>
<L N="548">fforte destroy &thorn;e sines seuyn.</L>
<L>ffor seuyn askins er &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L>And ilkone may for-do a syn</L>
<L>If it be said in gude degre</L>
<L N="552">And clene life als it aw to be;</L>
<L>Els prayes a man him-self ogayne,</L>
<L>And all his trauail es in vaine.
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="191"></L>
<L>Pape Innocent &thorn;an next folowand,</L>
<L N="556">Pax domini &thorn;an he ordand,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at ilk man suld kis o&thorn;er</L>
<L>And hald &thorn;am hertly als &thorn;aire bro&thorn;er.</L>
<L>In takining &thorn;at god ordand pese</L>
<L>Bytwix him and man, neuer to sese.</L>
<L N="561">&THORN;e last word &thorn;an of &thorn;e fest</L>
<L>Es said &thorn;us: Ite missa est,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say "now es it sent</L>
<L N="564">To heuyn for vs, &thorn;is sacrament."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Adhuc de canone misse.</HEAD>
<L>IN &thorn;e canon aw neuyned to be</L>
<L>ffirst mari, cristes moder fre:</L>
<L>ffor [of] hir, maiden milde of mode,</L>
<L>Toke he &thorn;at blisced fless and blude,</L>
<L N="569">&THORN;at same fless &thorn;at sufferd dede</L>
<L>And &thorn;at es named ay-lastand brede.
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="192"></L>
<L>&THORN;e twelue appostels &thorn;an neuind err,</L>
<L N="572">ffor &thorn;ai prechid both nere and ferr</L>
<L>&THORN;e trowth als he had preched playne,</L>
<L>And for his sake se&thorn;in war &thorn;ai slaine.</L>
<L>&THORN;e apostelis of crist war sent,</L>
<L N="576">And martires, when &thorn;ai war went,</L>
<L>Witnest &thorn;aire werkes fer and nere;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore all done to ded &thorn;ai were.</L>
<L>Ihesus died for luf of vs,</L>
<L N="580">And &thorn;ai died for luf of ihesus,</L>
<L>With mekill dole and diuers ded,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ai bare witnes of &thorn;is brede.</L>
<L>Peter, Andrew, and philip, find we,</L>
<L N="584">War hanged on &thorn;e cros all thre;</L>
<L>Paul, more Iames, and Mathew</L>
<L>War heuidded, and also bertilmew,</L>
<L>&THORN;at here was a ful haly man,</L>
<L>He was flain quik and heuidded &thorn;an;</L>
<L N="589">Simon, and Iudas thadeus,</L>
<L>And les Iames, &thorn;ai died &thorn;us,</L>
<L>Als it es with clerkes knawen:</L>
<L>&THORN;aire sins war fra &thorn;aire body drawen.
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="193"></L>
<L N="593">And saint Ion &thorn;e euangelist,</L>
<L>&THORN;at cosin was to ihesu crist,</L>
<L>In a tonn ful lang he dweld</L>
<L N="596">And brinand ole &thorn;ai on him held;</L>
<L>Venim he drank and dered him noght,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;in he died when god gude thoght.</L>
<L>Saint thomas &thorn;at es named of ynde,</L>
<L>He was thurgh-stiked, als folk may</L>
<L>&THORN;an in &thorn;e canon neuind es [finde.</L>
<L>Twelue &thorn;at war trew martires</L>
<L N="603">And died all with sorowis sere,</L>
<L>And sum papes and sum bisschops</L>
<L>Sum dekines &thorn;at suld be prest, [were,</L>
<L>And sum lawd men &thorn;at lifed on crist;</L>
<L>And all &thorn;ir marters more and les</L>
<L N="608">Of &thorn;is ilk brede &thorn;ai bare witnes.</L>
<L>Saint leo, clemens, and cletus,</L>
<L>Sixtus, and cornelius,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ir war papes, and sufferd ded</L>
<L N="612">ffor &thorn;ai bare witnes of &thorn;is brede;</L>
<L>Ciprian was bisschop of cartaginus;</L>
<L>Dekens war steuen and laurencius,
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="194"></L>
<L>And vincent was a dekin of mightes;</L>
<L>Grisogon, Ion and paul war knightes,</L>
<L N="617">Saint Cosma and saint damiane</L>
<L>&THORN;ai war lechis by &thorn;am allane.</L>
<L>Katerine, Mergarete, and agace,</L>
<L N="620">&THORN;ai died all for &thorn;is brede of grace;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore es reson &thorn;at &thorn;ai thre</L>
<L>Neuynd in &thorn;e canon be.</L>
<L>Al toke &thorn;ir<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;air?</NOTE> ded with gude entent</L>
<L N="624">fforto mayntene &thorn;is sacrament,</L>
<L>&THORN;at named es here angell brede</L>
<L>And saues man fro endles dede</L>
<L>And bringes him to &thorn;e blis of heuyn,</L>
<L>Whare more ioy es &thorn;an men may neuyn.</L>
<L N="629">&THORN;e sight of god &thorn;are sal &thorn;am fede,
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="195"></L>
<L>And his lightnes sall be &thorn;aire wede,</L>
<L>And werk &thorn;at &thorn;ai sall wirk ilkane</L>
<L N="632">Sall be loueing of god allane.</L>
<L>God grant vs in &thorn;at blis to bilde,</L>
<L>Thurgh prayers of his moder milde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>De indulgenciis inde concessis.</HEAD>
<L>Grete nowmber of pardon granted es</L>
<L>vnto all folk, both more and les,</L>
<L N="637">&THORN;at &thorn;is seruis will say or here</L>
<L>Ans als it fals in ilka &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es &thorn;e next thursday to se</L>
<L N="640">Efter &thorn;e fest of &thorn;e trinite.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pape vrban ordand &thorn;is fest,</L>
<L>ffor cristen men both most &amp; lest</L>
<L>Suld in &thorn;at tyme with gude entent</L>
<L N="644">honore &thorn;is haly sacrament.
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="196"></L>
<L>He granted to all men at &thorn;e mes</L>
<L>A hundreth daies of forgifnes;</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e matins who wald be,</L>
<L N="648">A hundreth daies haue suld he;</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e first euin-sang byfore</L>
<L>A hundreth daies by &thorn;e sex score;</L>
<L>And for ilk oure he vowched-saue</L>
<L N="652">ffourty dais &thorn;at men suld haue;</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e euinsang folowand</L>
<L>A hundreth daies he cumand;
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="197"></L>
<L>And fourty at &thorn;e cumplin clere</L>
<L N="655">vnto all men &thorn;at it will here.</L>
<L>And for&thorn;ermare, if men will luke,</L>
<L>&THORN;is same pardone es all &thorn;e woke</L>
<L>To &thorn;am &thorn;at cums with gude entent,</L>
<L N="660">vntill &thorn;e vtas be all went.</L>
<L>God grant vs so, whils we lif here,</L>
<L>&THORN;is seruise forto say or here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we may with &thorn;at pardon lend</L>
<L N="664">In life &thorn;at lastes with-owten end.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="31" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000206.tif" N="198">
<HEAD>XXXI. Septem<NOTE PLACE="foot">Only 6 miracles are given in the text.</NOTE> miracula de corpore cristi.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>(From Robert of Brunne's <I>Handlyng Synne</I>, p. 306-333, ed. Furnivall, Roxb. Club, 1862. That this 2nd homily is part of a longer poem on the Ten Commandments, Vices and Virtues, with Narrations, appears from v. 381 ff., 497 ff.)</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>MS. Vern., fol. CXCVI b&mdash;CXCVIII, b.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GOd Almihti &thorn;at alle &thorn;ing weldes,</L>
<L>Wyndes, watres, wodes and ffeldes,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">Furn. As</NOTE> so&thorn;ly, as &thorn;ou madest of nouht</L>
<L N="4">Alle creatures &thorn;at euer were wrouht,</L>
<L>ffor-&yogh;if vs, lord, &thorn;is day vr synne,</L>
<L>&THORN;is digne sacrament to bi-ginne,</L>
<L>And also worschupe<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &amp; wurschypfully</NOTE> &thorn;er-of to speke,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at we neuere &thorn;e trou&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. beleue</NOTE> breke,</L>
<L>Ne forte telle in &thorn;is Prolonge<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;ys long</NOTE> (!)</L>
<L>&THORN;ing &thorn;at falle&thorn; to eny wronge,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. fall-of may any wrong</NOTE></L>
<L>But &thorn;at hit mihte beo &thorn;e to queme</L>
<L N="12">And vs in studefast trou&thorn;e to &yogh;eme.&mdash;</L>
<L>Godus sone in heuene a-boue,</L>
<L>He schewed vs also<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. alle for</NOTE> muche loue:</L>
<L>ffor whon his passion neih&yogh;ed him neih,</L>
<L N="16">To his disciples &thorn;at weren him by</L>
<L>He &yogh;af his bodi, hem to fede&mdash;</L>
<L>More loue miht he not schewe in dede&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei schulde muynde haue</L>
<L N="20">Of hym &thorn;at miht hem &thorn;enne saue.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it a-forward<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. aftyrward</NOTE> he let hym slo</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; so gret<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. ful vyle</NOTE> de&thorn;-pyne and<NOTE PLACE="marg">and pynyng</NOTE> wo.</L>
<L>ffor vs and hem dude he &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="24">To bringe vs alle to his blis.</L>
<L>More loue miht he not do,</L>
<L>Ne neuer mon mihte do so;</L>
<L>ffor vs he dude hit, in certeyn,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;at we schulde loue hym wel a&yogh;ein.</L>
<L>&THORN;ouh we vr-self [&yogh;af] an hundred si&thorn;e,</L>
<L>O poynt of such loue miht we not ky&thorn;e
<PB REF="00000207.tif" N="199"></L>
<L>Lyk to &thorn;at loue he ha&thorn; vs done,</L>
<L N="32">ffor hit is vre saluacioune.</L>
<L>And of vs &yogh;it aske&thorn; he nouht</L>
<L>But &thorn;at may wel I-nouh be wrouht:</L>
<L>No&thorn;ing bote loue wi&thorn; good louyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. but loue-longyng</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">To loue him ouer al o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing</L>
<L>And for his loue to leue synne&mdash;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. his</NOTE> loue his blisse &thorn;en may we wynne.</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. ffor</NOTE> &thorn;ou may neuere haue hym to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="40">But &thorn;ou wolt furst synne fle:</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ing he loue&thorn;, but synne he hates;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou loue hym, wi&thorn; synne &thorn;ou bates.<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. wlates</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou loue on, &thorn;ou most nedes</L>
<L N="44">fforsake &thorn;at &thorn;yng &thorn;at he forbedes,</L>
<L>Elles hit is told for no loue,</L>
<L>And nomeliche to vr lord aboue.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mai&yogh;t not loue him, &thorn;e boc sei&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. wy&thorn; no greythe</NOTE></L>
<L N="48">But &thorn;ou haue wi&thorn; &thorn;e good fei&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to sey, leeue &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. to beleue</NOTE> hit wel</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at is writen of hym vchedel.</L>
<L>Studefast treu&thorn;e of loue hit semes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. comes</NOTE></L>
<L N="52">And of trew&thorn;e loue men nemes:<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. nomes</NOTE></L>
<L>So is &thorn;at on wi&thorn; &thorn;at o&thorn;ur,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; studefast treu&thorn;e loue, his<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. ys &thorn;e</NOTE> Bro&thorn;ur.</L>
<L>To whom ou&yogh;te vr loue be went?</L>
<L N="56">To trou&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. But to &thorn;e beleue</NOTE> of &thorn;is sacrament.</L>
<L>&THORN;is schulde leeue vche cristen mon</L>
<L>And lerne &thorn;e treu&thorn;e of on &thorn;at con:</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e bred &thorn;at sacrefyed is</L>
<L N="60">On &thorn;e Auter, is godus flesch,</L>
<L>fflesch and blod, &thorn;er hit is leid,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;e wordus &thorn;e prest ha&thorn; seid;</L>
<L>&THORN;at lihte wi&thorn;-Inne &thorn;e virgine Marie</L>
<L N="64">And on &thorn;e Rode for vs wolde dye</L>
<L>And from de&thorn; to lyue a-Ros,</L>
<L>God and Mon, in Miht and loos.</L>
<L>ffor hose trowe&thorn; not &thorn;is cler</L>
<L N="68">In &thorn;e sacrament of &thorn;e Auter,</L>
<L>He schal neuere &thorn;e blisse a-byde,</L>
<L>ffor no &thorn;ing &thorn;at him may be-tyde.
<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="200"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e Olde lawe &thorn;us is writen&mdash;</L>
<L N="72">Iewes and Cristene wel hit witen:</L>
<L>"God seide &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. and</NOTE> hit was wrouht,</L>
<L>He Comaundede alle &thorn;ing of nouht"&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is wordus aren verrey and cler,</L>
<L N="76">Dauid hem seide in &thorn;e psauter.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;he he made al of nou&yogh;t &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. alle &thorn;at no&yogh;t er</NOTE> was,</L>
<L>Lasse Maystrie were in &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>fforte chaunge on liknes</L>
<L N="80">In to a-no&thorn;ur &thorn;yng &thorn;en hit is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ilke liknesse in<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. of</NOTE> Bred and Wyn</L>
<L>In fflesch and blod to torne hit in.</L>
<L>His fflesch and blood in Bred is wrouht;<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Yn flesshe and blode &thorn;e brede be bro&yogh;t</NOTE></L>
<L>Si&thorn;&thorn;e he made [al] be-fore of nouht,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou seo hit not bodiliche in siht,</L>
<L>&THORN;i soule wi&thorn;-Inne schal trouwe hit riht;</L>
<L>And &thorn;au&yogh; &thorn;ow fele no sauour</L>
<L N="88">But verrey wyn and bred of fflour,</L>
<L>&THORN;is is wisdam of godus ordinaunce,</L>
<L>To saue vs alle from &thorn;is Chaunce:</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;if hit weore as flesch to take,</L>
<L N="92">Wi&thorn;-stonde<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. wlate</NOTE> we scholde and hit forsake;</L>
<L>And for he nolde we hit forsoke,</L>
<L>Bot alle men hit vndurtoke,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore his wisdam his owne rede</L>
<L N="96">Sauere&thorn; hit in wyn and Brede.</L>
<L>Hit seme&thorn; bred as to &thorn;e siht</L>
<L>And as Bred hit sauere&thorn; riht;</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;ur in siht ne in felyng</L>
<L N="100">Knowest &thorn;ou of no certeyn &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>What schal &thorn;enne &thorn;e most saue</L>
<L>But studefast &thorn;ouht &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt haue,</L>
<L>Studefast trou&thorn;e of vch a del,</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;at wol vs saue wondur wel.</L>
<L>And summe han hit seyen Bodily,</L>
<L>To whom he schewed his Mercy.</L>
<L>Lo her a tale al and sum<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. for of &yogh;ow sum</NOTE></L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at is In Vitas Patrum:
<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="201"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>1. Aarracio cuiusdam religiosi.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Simeon: Quod corpus cristi est veraciter in sacra|mento altaris, realiter, &amp; non figuratiue.</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Hit was a Mon of Religioun,</L>
<L>Of alle Men<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. almes</NOTE> he hedde gret renoun;</L>
<L>And,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. But</NOTE> for &thorn;e fend wolde him haue schent,</L>
<L N="112">IIe leeuede not in &thorn;e sacrament,</L>
<L>And seide, hit was not Ihesu</L>
<L>&THORN;at Conceyued was &thorn;orwh gret vertu,</L>
<L>Ne Ihesu was not &thorn;at Oble</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;at was reised atte sacre</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e folk honourede to;<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. And &thorn;o &thorn;at wurschep dede &thorn;arto</NOTE></L>
<L>To leeue hit was not to do.</L>
<L>Bi-fore two Abbotes &thorn;us he tolde&mdash;</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;is Abbotes write &thorn;is tale to holde,</L>
<L>Hit scholde be told to eueriche mon<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. euery wham</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at is a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e Cristendom</L>
<L>Til hit beo preued bi Clergye</L>
<L N="124">Wher hit beo treu&thorn;e or heresye.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Abbotes schewed him &thorn;e rihte wey,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e ensaumples &thorn;at &thorn;ei cou&thorn;e sey;</L>
<L>And al he seide hit was lye,</L>
<L N="128">But &yogh;if he se&yogh;e hit wi&thorn; his e&yogh;e</L>
<L>"Don<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Do&thorn;e</NOTE> &thorn;en so &thorn;at I hit seo,</L>
<L>&THORN;en wol I leue &thorn;at hit so be."</L>
<L>&THORN;is Abbotes preide a ful seue niht</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. god</NOTE> wolde schewe him, to trouwe<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;urghe</NOTE> his miht,</L>
<L>In fflesch, in Blod on &thorn;e Auteer,</L>
<L>To Conferme his trou&thorn;e cler.</L>
<L>And him-self preide specialy</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;at god wolde schewe hym in Body,</L>
<L>"Lord,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. L. he seyde</NOTE> for no mis-bileeue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow scholdest wi&thorn; me<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. me &thorn;e</NOTE> greue,</L>
<L>But forte schewe &thorn;e riht so&thorn;nes</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;at &thorn;ow art sacrament of &thorn;e Mes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I may make o&thorn;er certeyne</L>
<L>Whon I wi&thorn; e&yogh;en haue &thorn;e sey&yogh;ene."<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. seyne</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is Abbotes ly&yogh;e in orisoun</L>
<L N="144">Til &thorn;at &thorn;e seueniht were don.
<PB REF="00000210.tif" N="202"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Sonenday<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. seuen&thorn;e</NOTE> to Churche &thorn;ei come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur Mon wi&thorn; hem &thorn;ei nome.</L>
<L>A sege was ordeynt for hem &thorn;re,</L>
<L N="148">To bi-holde al &thorn;at priuite</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at holy Sacrament</L>
<L>&THORN;at scholde be schewed in here present.</L>
<L>Bi-twene hem sat &thorn;is ilke mon</L>
<L N="152">Of whom &thorn;e Miracle furst bi-gon.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e oble was on &thorn;e Auter leid</L>
<L>And &thorn;e prest &thorn;e wordes hed seid,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;re &thorn;ou&yogh;te hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;an</NOTE> verreylike</L>
<L N="156">By-fore &thorn;e prest a Child lay quik,</L>
<L>In feir forme, of fflesch and blod;</L>
<L>&THORN;is say &thorn;ei &thorn;re &thorn;er &thorn;ey stod.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e prest scholde parte &thorn;e sacrament,</L>
<L N="160">An Angel [doun] from heuene was sent</L>
<L>And sacrefyed &thorn;e child riht &thorn;ore:</L>
<L>As &thorn;e prest hit brac, &thorn;e Angel hit schore,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Blod in to &thorn;e Chalis Ron</L>
<L N="164">Of &thorn;at child, bo&thorn;e God and Mon.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;ys man</NOTE> &yogh;ede to &thorn;e hi&yogh;este degre,</L>
<L>To hosel him as hit fel to be;</L>
<L>Hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Hym</NOTE> &thorn;hou&yogh;te &thorn;e prest brou&yogh;te on &thorn;e patin<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. pateyn</NOTE></L>
<L N="168">Mosseles of &thorn;at child newe slayn</L>
<L>And beed him a Mossel of &thorn;at fflesch,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al &thorn;e blod &thorn;er-on al fresch.</L>
<L>&THORN;en gan he crie wi&thorn; loude steuene:</L>
<L N="172">"Merci, Godus sone of heuene,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Bred I sauh on &thorn;e Auter ly&yogh;e</L>
<L>Hit is &thorn;i bodi, I seo wi&thorn; e&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Bred &thorn;orwh sacrament</L>
<L N="176">To fflesch and Blod hit is went;</L>
<L>&THORN;is I beo-leeue, and euere I schalle,</L>
<L>ffor verreyliche we seon hit alle."</L>
<L>Whon he and &thorn;ei weore alle certeyne,</L>
<L N="180">In forme of Bred hit tornde a&yogh;eyne.</L>
<L>He dude him hosel as o&thorn;ur wore,</L>
<L>And was a good mon for euer-more.</L>
<L>And al o&thorn;ure beo<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. be&thorn;</NOTE> &thorn;e bettre</L>
<L N="184">&THORN;at here&thorn; &thorn;is tale or rede&thorn; &thorn;is lettre.&mdash;
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="203"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Prest &thorn;at sacre&thorn; Godus bodi,</L>
<L>He moste beo ful clene nedeli;</L>
<L>A lewed mon &thorn;at schal hit receyue,</L>
<L N="188">Alle-Maner ful&thorn;e moot he<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. behoue&thorn; hym</NOTE> weyue.</L>
<L>But<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> beo &thorn;ou neuere so good a prest</L>
<L>Ne neuer so gret wi&thorn;-Inne<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Ne so grete wytte yn</NOTE> &thorn;i Brest,</L>
<L>I rede &thorn;ou here hou &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;e propertes</NOTE> are schewed,</L>
<L N="192">Al-&thorn;auh &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;e langage be but</NOTE> ben of langage lewed.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wost wel, in<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;at</NOTE> &thorn;e Oble</L>
<L>Is<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. ys but</NOTE> a luytel &thorn;yng to se:</L>
<L>So schaltou beo luytel in wille,</L>
<L N="196">Luytel and Muchel<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. meke</NOTE> wi&thorn;-outen ille,</L>
<L>Nout in pride ne in heih&thorn;e,</L>
<L>ffor no wisdam ne no sleih&thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;e so&thorn;e hit is<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;at we ne falle</NOTE> wi&thorn; Lucifer,</L>
<L N="200">Proude men schal wone<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. ffor pr. m. w. wy&thorn; hym</NOTE> &thorn;er.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Oble is mad of whete,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Beste<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. louelyest</NOTE> corn &thorn;at men of<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> ete:</L>
<L>So schulde we beo meke and louely</L>
<L N="204">To alle &thorn;o &thorn;at ben vs by;</L>
<L>&THORN;is Mekenes is a-&yogh;eyn &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> Ire</L>
<L>&THORN;at is wi&thorn; Lucifer in &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> fyre.</L>
<L>&THORN;e paast of &thorn;e oble nouht ne owe</L>
<L N="208">Beo maad of no-maner sourdowe,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e sourdowe make&thorn; al soure</L>
<L>&THORN;e swettest<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. swetnes</NOTE> &thorn;at come&thorn; of &thorn;e floure.</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;is sourdowe is tokenynge</L>
<L N="212">&THORN;at Envye is a wikked &thorn;inge,</L>
<L>ffor hit for-do&thorn; alle swetnesse of dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god scholde &yogh;iue vr soules<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &yogh;yue for soule</NOTE> meede;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore make&thorn; he non herburgrye</L>
<L N="216">&THORN;er he fynde&thorn; biforen envye.</L>
<L>O vertue<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. A v. also</NOTE> In &thorn;e whete is</L>
<L>&THORN;at is muche a-&yogh;ein Slouhnes:</L>
<L>&THORN;er whete come&thorn; he wol<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. ffor whete-corne wyl</NOTE> not prike,</L>
<L N="220">As Otes don and Barlike;</L>
<L>Ne we ne scholde not be<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. haue any</NOTE> prikel</L>
<L>In<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Of</NOTE> Idelnesse ouer-Mukel;<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. mykyl</NOTE></L>
<L>Idelnesse grucche&thorn; and is heui of &thorn;ouht</L>
<L N="224">And is<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. also</NOTE> soone wro&thorn; for nouht,
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="204"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at wra&thorn;&thorn;he come&thorn; of sorwe,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;at</NOTE> of wonhope wol muche Borwe.</L>
<L>&THORN;is sacrament of &thorn;e Messe</L>
<L N="228">Loue&thorn; not such Idelnesse,</L>
<L>Not wi&thorn; non nul he dwelle</L>
<L>Bute &thorn;er men of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> Ioye spelle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e paast of &thorn;e oble seid beo-forn</L>
<L N="232">Schal not beo of medlet corn,</L>
<L>Bote al onliche of whete:</L>
<L>ffoule desires<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;e mastlyoun</NOTE> schal men lete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bi-mene&thorn;, In no wyse</L>
<L N="236">We schal vs &yogh;iue to<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. medel wy&thorn;</NOTE> Couetyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is also called<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. And namely wy&thorn;</NOTE> Aueryce,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche is a foul<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. ys tolde a</NOTE> wikked vice.</L>
<L>Also &thorn;ou seost &thorn;e oble is &thorn;inne</L>
<L N="240">And muche honeste wi&thorn;-Inne:<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &amp; grete dunhede ys noun &thorn;er-ynne</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at wol wel signefye</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e sinne of glotenye;</L>
<L>&THORN;er wol not &thorn;e sacrament reste,</L>
<L N="244">Ac<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;ere</NOTE> glotenye wol him out keste.</L>
<L>And as<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> &thorn;ou sest, &thorn;e oble is whit:</L>
<L>So schul we haue no-maner delyt</L>
<L>Of no-maner fflesches take,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. of flesshely lak</NOTE></L>
<L N="248">ffor lecherie<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Of l. &thorn;at</NOTE> make&thorn; &thorn;e soule blake.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos seuene partyes<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. propertes</NOTE> be&thorn;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Oble, as we seo&thorn;,</L>
<L>And eueri propurte &thorn;er-Inne</L>
<L N="252">Is a&yogh;ein an hed-synne.</L>
<L>A-&yogh;eyn &thorn;is sacrament do &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at aren in synne and &thorn;erto go,</L>
<L>Or aren in wille a&yogh;eyn to wende</L>
<L N="256">To synne and hem-self schende;</L>
<L>As<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Also a</NOTE> prest &thorn;at go&thorn; to synge Mes</L>
<L>&THORN;at in dedly synne is;</L>
<L>An hondred-fold he sunge&thorn; more</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;e[n] he a lewed mon wore.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at receyue &thorn;e sacrament</L>
<L>In dedly sunne or wikked entent</L>
<L>Or<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> in eny of &thorn;eose<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;ese yche</NOTE> seuene</L>
<L N="264">&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast here herd nempne,
<PB REF="00000213.tif" N="205"></L>
<L>Riht to<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Hyt ys to</NOTE> heore Dampnaciun,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore vengaunce schal be don.</L>
<L>And here I schal telle a tale</L>
<L N="268">Hou hit is to &thorn;at mon Bale:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>2. Aarracio presbiteri parochialis.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Simeon: Quod propter peccatum occultum communio non debet negari.</NOTE></HEAD>
<L><B>A</B> Parisch-prest was in a Toun,</L>
<L>Of ful gret discrecioun,</L>
<L>fful good and rihtful he was,</L>
<L N="272">And god sende hym of his gras:<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> F.: Dyscrecyun a ry&yogh;t wyt ys On bo&thorn;e partys ry&yogh;tly to ges.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of his parischens he vndurstode</L>
<L>Whuche wer vuel and w&yogh;uche wer gode.</L>
<L>Two he hedde forte gete</L>
<L N="276">&THORN;at nolde neuere synne lete.</L>
<L>And hit felde<NOTE PLACE="marg">= fell</NOTE> on an Asterne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e prest scholde non hosul werne</L>
<L>But hit were for &thorn;e gretur synne,</L>
<L N="280">Inobedience or Corsyng Inne:<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. As yn cursyng or yn vnbuxyme</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is prest was in ful gret &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>Wher he schulde hosele hem or nouht.</L>
<L>He preyede to God, heuene-kyng,</L>
<L N="284">&THORN;at he wolde sende him tokenyng</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er he scholde hem hosul<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> forbede;</L>
<L>To &yogh;iue hit<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. To housel</NOTE> hem he hedde gret drede.</L>
<L>ffrom god he hedde &thorn;is onswere:</L>
<L N="288">&THORN;at vch on scholde heor oune charge bere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he scholde werne hit none</L>
<L>But &yogh;iue hit for&thorn; to euerichone;</L>
<L>"Do as Ihesu dude in dede,</L>
<L N="292">And &thorn;ou schalt no mon hit forbede,</L>
<L>No more &thorn;en he dude Iudas</L>
<L>&THORN;at hedde I-don a gret trespas;</L>
<L>Ihesu &yogh;af alle wi&thorn; mylde mood,</L>
<L N="296">Whon Bred was turned to flesch and blod.</L>
<L>ffor summe &thorn;at hit take hit schal hem saue,</L>
<L>And summe &thorn;erfore peyne schal haue;</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;ey aren of synne clene,</L>
<L N="300">Also schal hit on hem beo sene."
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="206"></L>
<L>&YOGH;it preyed he god of More grace:</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mihte knowe be &thorn;e face</L>
<L>Whuche resceyued hit wor&thorn;ily,</L>
<L N="304">And w&yogh;uche to haue hit not wor&thorn;i.</L>
<L>And [god]<NOTE PLACE="marg">om.</NOTE> graunted him his wille,</L>
<L>To knowe &thorn;e goode from &thorn;e ille.</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk &thorn;at to &thorn;e prest went</L>
<L N="308">fforte receyue &thorn;e sacrament,</L>
<L>Of somme &thorn;e face was also briht</L>
<L>As &thorn;e sonne In somer<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. on days</NOTE> -liht;</L>
<L>And summe &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. here</NOTE> visage was also blak</L>
<L N="312">&THORN;at no&thorn;ing miht hit Blakore mak;</L>
<L>Of somme hit was<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. And some were</NOTE> as red as blod,</L>
<L>Starynge as &thorn;ei weore wood;</L>
<L>Of somme &thorn;e visage was bolled<NOTE PLACE="marg">And sum were swolle &thorn;e vyseges</NOTE> stoute,</L>
<L N="316">As bo&thorn;e heore e&yogh;en welleden oute;</L>
<L>And summe nymped<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. gnapped</NOTE> wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. here</NOTE> feet and hondes,</L>
<L>As dogges don &thorn;at gnawen heore bondes;</L>
<L>And somme hedde visages of Meselri;</L>
<L N="320">And somme were lyk foul Maumetri.</L>
<L>Moni wondres weore on hem seene,</L>
<L>Mo &thorn;en he cou&thorn;e &thorn;enne deme.<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. se at &thorn;at tyme</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e prest, whon he sauh alle &thorn;ise,</L>
<L N="324">Of &thorn;at siht he gan to grise,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at siht he<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> was hidouse</L>
<L>And dredful and Meruilouse.<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. perylous</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;it pre&yogh;ede he god wi&thorn; good entent</L>
<L N="328">&THORN;at he mihte wite what al &thorn;is ment.</L>
<L>And god almihti louede him wel</L>
<L>And wolde schewe him eueridel:</L>
<L>"&THORN;o Men &thorn;at weore so briht</L>
<L N="332">As &thorn;e sonne on day-liht,</L>
<L>&THORN;o Men aren &yogh;it in Charite</L>
<L>And clene of synne, and worschupe&thorn; me.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Men &thorn;at were so blake</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;at no &thorn;ing mihte hem blakore make,</L>
<L>&THORN;o weore<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. are</NOTE> lechours foul wi&thorn;-Inne</L>
<L>And haue no wille to leue heor synne.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Men &thorn;at weore so red as blood,</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;ei are tirauns<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Irus &amp;</NOTE> wikked of mood,
<PB REF="00000215.tif" N="207"></L>
<L>Heore Euencristen for to slo</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; dede<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. de&thorn;</NOTE> and wi&thorn; word also.<NOTE PLACE="marg">or wy&thorn; pyne do wo</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at &thorn;ow sauh wi&thorn; Bollen visage,</L>
<L N="344">&THORN;o aren Envyous and<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> ouer-outrage.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at nymped her fingres and hendes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. finger endes</NOTE></L>
<L>Are Bacbyteres bi-twene frendes.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at &thorn;ou sauh Meseles bi siht,</L>
<L N="348">&THORN;ey loue more good &thorn;en god almiht.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at &thorn;ou sauh lik Maumetrie,</L>
<L>On worldly &thorn;inges &thorn;ei most affye,</L>
<L>More loue &thorn;ei catel &thorn;at he ha&thorn; sent</L>
<L N="352">&THORN;en &thorn;ei don hym &thorn;at al ha&thorn; lent.</L>
<L>&THORN;eose-maner men are riht<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &yogh;yt</NOTE> in wille</L>
<L>In heore synne to leue stille,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore schal &thorn;e sacrament</L>
<L N="356">Of hem aske heor<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. harde</NOTE> Iugement,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei haue resceyued him vnwor&thorn;ily</L>
<L>And serued &thorn;e fend wi&thorn; ful Envy."<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. hys enemy</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is tale is told for loue of &thorn;o</L>
<L N="360">&THORN;at in synne to hosul go,</L>
<L>Or ben in wille to torne a&yogh;eyn;</L>
<L>Al heore trauayle &thorn;ei don in veyn.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wole<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. whan</NOTE> &thorn;yn hosel saue<NOTE PLACE="marg">shalt</NOTE> take,</L>
<L N="364">Beo in wille &thorn;i synne to forsake</L>
<L>Euermore in studefast herte;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;oghe; And om.</NOTE> &thorn;ou synne in bodi<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. sone aftyr and</NOTE> smerte,</L>
<L>God take&thorn; hit nou&yogh;t to so gret grim</L>
<L N="368">As &thorn;ou in tresun Receyuede hym.</L>
<L>In no &thorn;ing wot I more tresun</L>
<L>&THORN;en bringe &thorn;i lord on his felun,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it men sei&thorn; &thorn;e synne is to greue<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. here s. ys grefe</NOTE></L>
<L N="372">&THORN;at bringe&thorn; a trewe mon on a &thorn;eue.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou do &thorn;us &thorn;i witande,</L>
<L>&THORN;en chargen hit me<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. men hyt</NOTE> moste on hande.</L>
<L N="375">&THORN;erfore loke &thorn;ou wite nouht</L>
<L>No synne I-hud In herte ne &thorn;ouht!<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. has 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Also</NOTE> no Clerk &thorn;at is in synne,</L>
<L>Til he leue and &thorn;er-of blynne</L>
<L>He schulde not serue atte Auteer</L>
<L N="380">Ne hondle &thorn;ing &thorn;at come&thorn; &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Ne halewede &thorn;yng to come</NOTE> neer.
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="208"></L>
<L>I touched er<NOTE PLACE="marg">See Furniv., p. 274-5.</NOTE> of &thorn;is outrage</L>
<L>Whon I spac of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> sacrilage,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e holigost schewed him nouht</L>
<L N="384">ffor &thorn;e Dekene syngede in &thorn;ouht;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e tale of Ion Grisostomus</L>
<L>&THORN;is tale is told, for ow and vs.</L>
<L>Als is he wor&thorn;i to ben i-schent</L>
<L N="388">&THORN;at sone aftur &thorn;e sacrament</L>
<L>To folye and to synne drawes&mdash;</L>
<L>Luitel of Godus vengaunce hym awes!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou for&yogh;ete or ouer-sittes</L>
<L N="392">&THORN;e tyme of hosul &thorn;at &thorn;ou wel wittes,</L>
<L>Luitel fors of him &thorn;ou &yogh;eues,</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;ur &thorn;ou louest hym ne leues.<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;ou louest hym nat &thorn;at &thorn;ou by lyues</NOTE></L>
<L>And ouer al he loue&thorn; &thorn;e best;</L>
<L N="396">And &thorn;ou ne wolt a nihtes gest</L>
<L>Leten hym herborwe in &thorn;in hous!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art vnkynde and<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. ry&yogh;t</NOTE> Meruylous,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e &yogh;er &thorn;ou letest him weyue,</L>
<L N="400">Wi&thorn; worschipe woltou not him resceyue.</L>
<L>God Manase&thorn; for &thorn;is chesun,</L>
<L>ffor<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. And</NOTE> riht hit wole and eke resun:</L>
<L>ffor suche men aren holden vntrewe</L>
<L N="404">In &thorn;e Olde lawe and in &thorn;e newe.</L>
<L>Comaunded<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Comaundement</NOTE> In &thorn;e Olde lawe was</L>
<L>Ones in &thorn;e &yogh;eer to schewe &thorn;i trespas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e newe lawe is of &thorn;e more honour,</L>
<L N="408">Ones in &thorn;e &yogh;eer<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Ones to</NOTE> resceyue &thorn;i creatour,</L>
<L>Ones a &yogh;er him to knoweleche,</L>
<L>&THORN;i lord to plese for doute of wreche.</L>
<L>&THORN;at prest i blame ouer alle &thorn;inge,</L>
<L N="412">Wi&thorn;-outen gret skil &thorn;at lette&thorn; to synge;</L>
<L>ffor mony a soule mihte I-saued be<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. be saued</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at Masse &thorn;at &thorn;enne leue&thorn; he.<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. he ha&thorn; leued</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor alle &thorn;at in &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> peyne Is,</L>
<L N="416">Abyde&thorn; socour of &thorn;e Mes,</L>
<L>ffor eueri Masse make&thorn; Memorie</L>
<L>Of soules &thorn;at aren In purgatorie.</L>
<L>Muche &thorn;onk schal he<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;at prest</NOTE> haue</L>
<L N="420">&THORN;at helpe&thorn; soules for to saue;
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="209"></L>
<L>No &thorn;ing may so muchel avayle</L>
<L>Of heore peynes and heore trauayle</L>
<L>As &thorn;e sacrament of &thorn;e Auteer,</L>
<L N="424">Hit<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Ne</NOTE> make&thorn; hem of peynes cleer.<NOTE PLACE="marg">so c.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at may I schewe apertely</L>
<L>Bi a tale of seynt Gregori:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3.) Aarracio felicis presbitcri.</HEAD>
<L>Seint Gregori sei&thorn; for &thorn;e same:</L>
<L N="428">Hit was a prest, ffelix his name;</L>
<L>Bi-syde he wonede<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. hys wonyng</NOTE> in a pa&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Was a wassching In an hote ba&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;is prest ofte &thorn;ider &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="432">To wassche him whon he hedde nede.</L>
<L>&THORN;is prest &thorn;er euer [redi]<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. redy</NOTE> he fonde</L>
<L>A Mon to wassche him,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;at serued hym</NOTE> to foot and honde;</L>
<L>He drou&yogh; his hosen of and his schon</L>
<L N="436">And redi was hem on to don;</L>
<L>At eueri tyme he &thorn;ider com</L>
<L>His herneis<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Hys shone &amp; hys hosen</NOTE> feire of he nom,</L>
<L>And seruede him at eueri tyde</L>
<L N="440">In &thorn;at watur and ofte<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. eke</NOTE> beo-syde.</L>
<L>&THORN;is prest &thorn;at com &thorn;ider so ofte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is mon &thorn;er seruede so softe,</L>
<L>He ne askede hym neuer-more</L>
<L N="444">Whe&thorn;en he was ne hou he com &thorn;ore;</L>
<L>But eueri tyme he was redi</L>
<L>And seruede him ful apertely.<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. peynybly (penyblely)</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is prest &thorn;ou&yogh;te, "he serue&thorn; me wel,</L>
<L N="448">His trauayle wol I quite sum-del."</L>
<L>On a day he &thorn;ider &thorn;ouhte</L>
<L>And twey loues wi&thorn; hym he brouhte.</L>
<L>In to &thorn;at ba&thorn; &yogh;eode &thorn;at prest</L>
<L N="452">And wusch him as he dude nest;</L>
<L>&THORN;is mon was &thorn;ere him a&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L>To serue him wel he dude his Mayn.</L>
<L>&THORN;is prest, whon he scholde go,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. fur&thorn;e go</NOTE></L>
<L N="456">He &yogh;af &thorn;is mon &thorn;is loues two,</L>
<L>And &thorn;onked him muchel his seruyse,</L>
<L>And more he scholde haue<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. he wulde</NOTE> o&thorn;urwyse.
<PB REF="00000218.tif" N="210"></L>
<L>&THORN;is Mon onswerde &thorn;is prest a-&yogh;eyn:</L>
<L N="460">"&THORN;is bred &yogh;e bringe&thorn; to me in veyn,</L>
<L>ffor neuer-more schal I &yogh;ete</L>
<L>Bred ne non o&thorn;ur mete:</L>
<L>I am a Mon &thorn;at is ded,</L>
<L N="464">&THORN;at neuer-more schal ete bred."</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest asked: "on what manere</L>
<L>Is hit &thorn;at &thorn;ou wonest here?"</L>
<L>&THORN;is Mon onswerde in &thorn;at tyde:<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. a. &amp; seyd</NOTE></L>
<L N="468">"I was lord here ar I dyede,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. deyde</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;is seruise &thorn;at I am Inne</L>
<L>Is &thorn;e peyne for my synne.</L>
<L>Bote I &thorn;e preye par charite,</L>
<L N="472">Offre on &thorn;e Auter &thorn;es loues for me;</L>
<L>And I beseche &thorn;e ouer alle &thorn;ynge</L>
<L>&THORN;at sixe Masses for me &thorn;ou synge;</L>
<L>And heo weore songen, I hope to wende</L>
<L N="476">In to &thorn;e Ioye wi&thorn;-outen ende.</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;e sixte masse is left,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou ne fynde me her eft,</L>
<L>Trouwe [&thorn;ou] &thorn;enne forso&thorn;e i-wis</L>
<L N="480">&THORN;at for &thorn;i preyere I am in Blis."</L>
<L>&THORN;is prest al &thorn;at wike longe</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;ys same</NOTE> mon preyede and songe.</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;e wike was al gon,</L>
<L N="484">&THORN;e prest com &thorn;idere, and fond non;</L>
<L>He hopede<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. beleuede &thorn;an</NOTE> wel &thorn;at he was brouht</L>
<L>To blisse, for he ne fond him nouht.&mdash;</L>
<L>Beo &thorn;is tale &yogh;e may se</L>
<L N="488">&THORN;at hit is gret Charite</L>
<L>Masses for &thorn;e dede to synge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soules [out] of pyne forte bringe.</L>
<L>Ouer<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Passyng</NOTE> alle &thorn;ing hit ha&thorn; pouwer,</L>
<L N="492">&THORN;e sacrament of &thorn;e Auter,</L>
<L>And nomeliche whon hit is don</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; good monnes deuocion;</L>
<L>Him wol god sannore here</L>
<L N="496">&THORN;en on &thorn;at is him nouht so dere.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e seue&thorn;e Comaundement</L>
<L>Touche&thorn; to &thorn;is sacrament
<PB REF="00000219.tif" N="211"></L>
<L>In a tale of &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">F.a</NOTE> kniht,</L>
<L N="500">Hou &thorn;e prest &thorn;at liue&thorn; not riht,</L>
<L>Of his preyere is luytel prou,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere hit telle&thorn; wel hou.<NOTE PLACE="marg">See F. p. 72-76.</NOTE></L>
<L>And I schal telle ano&thorn;ur here</L>
<L N="504">Of a Masse of a good frere:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4.) hou a man of Sou&thorn;folk was saued &thorn;orou a masse.</HEAD>
<L><B>A</B> Mon in Sou&thorn;folk ones dyed,</L>
<L>Bi-sydes Sudburi, as men seid.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at mon such grace was diht</L>
<L N="508">&THORN;at him was graunted to come a niht</L>
<L>fforte speke wi&thorn; his wyf,</L>
<L>To mende &thorn;e fautes of his lyf.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;ef a Masse," he seide,<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> "were for me don</L>
<L N="512">Wi&thorn; a good monnes deuocion,</L>
<L>I hope to Ioye for to go</L>
<L>And beo dilyueret of al my wo.</L>
<L>I preye &thorn;e, dame, par charite</L>
<L N="516">To trauayle so muche for me."</L>
<L>Heo graunted hym &thorn;at ilke bone,</L>
<L>And ros vppon &thorn;e morwen sone</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e ffreres sone heo code,</L>
<L N="520">&THORN;er heo hopede best to spede.</L>
<L>Heo com and spac wi&thorn; a ffrere</L>
<L>And preyed heo moste his masse here,</L>
<L>And for hire hosebondes soule to synge,</L>
<L N="524">And heo wolde &yogh;iue hym offringe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffrere dude hire a Mes</L>
<L>In Comuyn, as &thorn;e seruise is.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;is Masse I-songen was,</L>
<L N="528">Heo wente hom a good pas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e niht aftur &thorn;enne com he.</L>
<L>"Slepestou?" he seide. "nay," seide heo;</L>
<L>"Are &yogh;e &yogh;it," heo seyde, "in blis?</L>
<L N="532">&THORN;e Masse for ow I-songen is."</L>
<L>"&THORN;e Masse," he seide, "&thorn;ou dudest do,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. be do</NOTE></L>
<L>A parti hit helpe&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. halpe</NOTE> me &thorn;erto;</L>
<L>Mi part ich hedde of &thorn;at Mes</L>
<L N="536">As of &thorn;ing &thorn;at Comuyn is.
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="212"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if on weore specialy for me seid,</L>
<L>Of my peyne I were ful leyd,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> F.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;e prest were of lyf so good</L>
<L N="540">&THORN;at God his preyere vndurstood;</L>
<L>I hope &thorn;enne grace to haue</L>
<L>&THORN;at his Masse mihte me saue;"</L>
<L>Ofte he seide to his wyf:</L>
<L N="544">"A prest, A prest of clene lyf!"</L>
<L>On &thorn;e Morwen for&thorn; heo eode</L>
<L>To &thorn;e ffreres eft to<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. et god</NOTE> spede,</L>
<L>And schewed hit to &thorn;e priour,</L>
<L N="548">And preyed him of socour;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he hedde eny bro&thorn;ur</L>
<L>&THORN;at he kneuh<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. hopede were</NOTE> beter &thorn;en o&thorn;ur,</L>
<L>"&THORN;at wol synge me a Mes</L>
<L N="552">ffor a Mon &thorn;at ded is,</L>
<L>At<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. And at</NOTE> myn ese he schal haue</L>
<L>To a pitaunce what he wol craue."</L>
<L>&THORN;e prior spac to<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. vn-to</NOTE> a ffrere</L>
<L N="556">And preyed him on alle manere</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wolde a Masse synge</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at soule heo made preyinge.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffrere was an holy mon;</L>
<L N="560">And ar [&thorn;at] he his Masse bi-gon,</L>
<L>He preyed to god his orison,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Yn</NOTE> a gret deuocion,<NOTE PLACE="marg">afflyceyoun</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hit mihte ben him to pay,</L>
<L N="564">&THORN;e Masse &thorn;at he scholde synge to-day.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e Masse was don to &thorn;e ende,</L>
<L>He bad &thorn;e wommon hom [to] wende,</L>
<L>"And whon &thorn;ou more eft heres,</L>
<L N="568">Cum and sey to vre ffreres!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e niht aftur&mdash;lustne&thorn; now!&mdash;</L>
<L>He com and seide: "slepestou?"</L>
<L>"Nay," heo sayde, "hou fare &yogh;e?"</L>
<L N="572">"Wel," he seide, "and so wor&thorn; &thorn;e!"</L>
<L>"Sire, weore &yogh;e a-payed of &thorn;at Mas</L>
<L>&THORN;at for ow to-day songen was?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e," he seide, "graunt Merci!</L>
<L N="576">&THORN;at Masse to me is more wor&thorn;i
<PB REF="00000221.tif" N="213"></L>
<L>&THORN;en al &thorn;e world an hundred si&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ne miht haue mad me neuer<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. half</NOTE> so bli&thorn;e.</L>
<L>His preyere was to god so dere,</L>
<L N="580">ffor al &thorn;at he preyede<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;at he besoghte wy&thorn;</NOTE> he wolde here;</L>
<L>&THORN;eih he hedde prei&yogh;ed for a &thorn;ousund mo,</L>
<L>ffrom peyne to blisse &thorn;ei hedde i-go;<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. he had bro&yogh;t &thorn;o</NOTE></L>
<L N="583">ffor what &thorn;ing he hedde asked bone,</L>
<L>God wolde ha<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. God hade</NOTE> graunted him ful<NOTE PLACE="marg">as</NOTE> sone.</L>
<L>Haue good day! for now I wende</L>
<L>To &thorn;at Ioye wi&thorn;-outen ende.</L>
<L>God lete &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. vs</NOTE> neuere &thorn;er-of mis,</L>
<L N="588">&THORN;ou ne he,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Wy&thorn;-outyn ende</NOTE> to haue &thorn;at blis."</L>
<L>&THORN;e wyf com sone on &thorn;e Morn</L>
<L>And fel on knes &thorn;at ffrere bi-forn</L>
<L>And tolde him &thorn;er eueridel</L>
<L N="592">Hou he for his preyere was wel.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ffrere ful wel he<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;arby</NOTE> lette,</L>
<L>And &thorn;onked God, for Ioye he grette.</L>
<L>Wel weore hym at his endynge</L>
<L N="596">Hedde such a prest for him to synge!&mdash;</L>
<L>In &thorn;is tale schewed is:</L>
<L>Of<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Ouer</NOTE> alle &thorn;ing good is &thorn;e mes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. For &thorn;e</NOTE> sacrament on &thorn;e Auter</L>
<L>Ouer alle passe&thorn; his pouwer.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Masse &thorn;ei hem a-fye</L>
<L>&THORN;e soules &thorn;at are in purgatorie.<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 vv. om.: ffor hyt make&thorn; mencyun of &thorn;e passyun As Iesu cryst to de&thorn; was doun</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e sone is offred to &thorn;e ffadur of heuene</L>
<L N="604">ffor &thorn;e soules &thorn;e prest wol nempne;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;us for to<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Also &thorn;ys tale wyl</NOTE> mene:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;e prest beo good and clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;enne wol Ihesu crist hym heere,</L>
<L N="608">ffor what &thorn;yng he make&thorn; preyere;</L>
<L>Preye he for soule or for bodi,</L>
<L>&THORN;at aren in pyne or<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. or here</NOTE> in nuy,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e wol god almihti saue</L>
<L N="612">What &thorn;e gode prest wolde haue.</L>
<L>Not only for soulus is he herd,</L>
<L>Bote eke for vs here in &thorn;is world.</L>
<L>Beo a Mon in seknesse or in prisun,</L>
<L N="616">Weyferynge, or in temptaciun,
<PB REF="00000222.tif" N="214"></L>
<L>Or in eny o&thorn;ur trauayle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sacrament wol vs a-vayle;</L>
<L>Hit wol delyuere vs out of peyn,</L>
<L N="620">&YOGH;if vr trou&thorn;e beo certeyn.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was wel schewed in dede</L>
<L>In Engelonde, so sei&thorn; seint Bede:</L>
<L>In his Bokes writen hit is,</L>
<L N="624">A feir Miracle of &thorn;e Mes:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5.) Aarracio Bede.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cf. Hist. Eccl. IV. c. 22.</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. What</NOTE> tyme seint Bede was liuonde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">man lyuande</NOTE></L>
<L>Weore Mony kynges in &thorn;is londe.</L>
<L>Bi-twene two was gret Batayle&mdash;</L>
<L N="628">&THORN;erfore i telle &thorn;is Meruayle;</L>
<L>&THORN;at on hiht Edfride, of North Cuntre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur of lindeseye was he.</L>
<L>Edfride hedde gret seygneri,</L>
<L N="632">Seynt Andreu hosbonde of hely.<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Audre</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is Batayle was bi bo&thorn;e heore a-sent</L>
<L>Bi-sydes a watur men calle&thorn; Trent.</L>
<L>Sire Elfride<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Edfrides</NOTE> bro&thorn;ur hette Eleswynne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Elfwynne</NOTE></L>
<L N="636">He was slayn &thorn;at Batayle Inne;</L>
<L>On bo&thorn;e partys ne was non</L>
<L>So feir a kniht of fflesch and bon,</L>
<L>Ne non so douhti was of Armes&mdash;</L>
<L N="640">&THORN;erfore seint Bede pleynede his harmes.</L>
<L>A-no&thorn;ur kniht was<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. also was</NOTE> feld doun</L>
<L>Nerhonde ded, and fel in swoun;</L>
<L>&THORN;e nome of &thorn;is &yogh;onge kniht</L>
<L N="644">Ruyna,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Iumna</NOTE> sei&thorn; seint Bede, he hiht.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;is Ruyna hedde long leyn,</L>
<L>He keuerde, and seet vp a&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L>And stopped his woundes &thorn;ei schulde not blede,</L>
<L N="648">And, as he mihte, &thorn;ennes he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>To seche him help sumwher to haue,</L>
<L>Of<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Or</NOTE> frendes fynde him to saue.</L>
<L>As he wente wi&thorn; muchel drede,</L>
<L N="652">He was taken wi&thorn; kyng Coldrede;<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Eldrede</NOTE></L>
<L>And brouht him <NOTE PLACE="marg">F. vn-</NOTE>to a lordyng,</L>
<L>An Erl, &thorn;at heold of &thorn;e kyng.
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="215"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Erl asked him what he was,</L>
<L N="656">And wher he hedde ben in hard cas.</L>
<L>ffor doute of de&thorn; he was a-friht</L>
<L>And dorste not seye he was a kniht;</L>
<L>He seide: "sire, &yogh;if &thorn;i wille<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. welle</NOTE> be,</L>
<L N="660">I am an hosebonde-mon<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. om. mon</NOTE> of &thorn;e cuntre,</L>
<L>I was wont to lede vitayle</L>
<L>To knihtes &thorn;at weoren in Batayle;</L>
<L>And nou I am a pore mon,</L>
<L N="664">&THORN;us fro &thorn;is Batayle I com,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. wan</NOTE></L>
<L>And wolde fonde to haue<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. saue</NOTE> my lyf,</L>
<L>Til I may come to my wyf."</L>
<L>&THORN;is Erl dude a leche bi stoundes</L>
<L N="668">To tente<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Tende</NOTE> to hym, to hele his woundes.</L>
<L>&THORN;at tyme was here mony &thorn;eodes,</L>
<L>Mony vsages, and<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. yn</NOTE> mony leodes,</L>
<L>ffor vche a kyng in &thorn;at dawes<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. dawe</NOTE></L>
<L N="672">Vsede his diuerse lawes:</L>
<L>Summe were cristene in vre fay,</L>
<L>And summe leeuede in paynymes lay;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;at tyme was muchel &thorn;ro,</L>
<L N="676">And ofte was bo&thorn;e werre and wo.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if a kniht<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. kyng</NOTE> miht o&thorn;er men take,</L>
<L>He scholde hem sulle or in seruage make.</L>
<L>Wherfore i telle so of &thorn;is kniht:</L>
<L N="680">&THORN;e Erl let him bynde eueriche niht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne scholde from hym fle</L>
<L>Ne stele a-wey to his cuntre.</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;at &thorn;ei mihte him bynde,</L>
<L N="684">Ofte loos &thorn;ei dude hym fynde;</L>
<L>Neuer so faste &thorn;eih heo him bounde,</L>
<L>Loos a-no&thorn;ur tyme &thorn;ei him founde.</L>
<L>&THORN;is bounden kniht, Ruyna,</L>
<L N="688">Hedde a Bro&thorn;ur, &thorn;at hihte Tymma;<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Tumna</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is Tymma was prest Religious,</L>
<L>ffor he was Abbot of an hous,</L>
<L>So longe he liuede in &thorn;at estre</L>
<L N="692">&THORN;at his nome heet Tymmestre;<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Tuncestre</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at tyme,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. tounne</NOTE> as ich vndurstonde,</L>
<L>Hit was in Northhumberlonde.
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="216"></L>
<L>&THORN;is Abbot hedde ti&thorn;inges certeyne</L>
<L N="696">&THORN;at Ruyna was in Batayle slayne.</L>
<L>He com to Trent, &thorn;is Abbot Tymma,</L>
<L>And fond a bodi lyk to Ruyna;</L>
<L>Honorabliche he dude hit graue</L>
<L N="700">In his chirche &thorn;er he wolde hit haue,</L>
<L>And song &thorn;erfore day and o&thorn;ur:</L>
<L>He wende hit hedde ben his bro&thorn;ur.</L>
<L>&THORN;auh Tymma hedde chosun wrong,</L>
<L>His bro&thorn;ur hedde &thorn;e goodus<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. godenesse</NOTE> of &thorn;e song&mdash;</L>
<L N="705">ffor God al wot, and wust hit &thorn;ere</L>
<L>ffor whom he made his preyere:&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;eih men a-niht &thorn;is kniht bounde,</L>
<L N="708">A-Morwe &thorn;ei hym loos founde,</L>
<L>Men mihte hym neuere bynde so fest<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. yn bondes so feste</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="marg">[the bonds]</NOTE> &thorn;at tyme nolde al to-berst.</L>
<L>&THORN;e men &thorn;at hedde &thorn;is kniht in holde,</L>
<L N="712">&THORN;is wondur to &thorn;e Erl &thorn;ei tolde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Erl hedde &thorn;er-of gret wondur</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is bondes weore so in-sondur;</L>
<L>He seide, him-self wolde wi&thorn; him speke</L>
<L N="716">And wite whi his bondes dude breke.</L>
<L>Bi-fore &thorn;e Erl was he set,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. fette</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e Erl feire he gret.</L>
<L>"Sey me," he seide, "&thorn;ou belamy,</L>
<L N="720">Const &thorn;ou wel on sorcery?</L>
<L>Sum wicche-craft I trouwe &thorn;ou bere</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i bondes &thorn;e not dere;</L>
<L>fforso&thorn;e," he seyde, "sumwhat &thorn;ou dos</L>
<L N="724">&THORN;at euer-more &thorn;ei fynde &thorn;e loos."</L>
<L>He seide: "wicche-craft con I nouht,</L>
<L>Ne for me schal non beo wrouht,</L>
<L>Ne I nul be by fendes craft</L>
<L N="728">vn-bounde beo,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. ne</NOTE> bi no wicche-craft.</L>
<L>Sire Erl," he seide, "hit is a-no&thorn;ur:</L>
<L>In my cuntre I haue a Bro&thorn;ur,</L>
<L>&THORN;at leeue&thorn; wel &thorn;at I beo slayn,</L>
<L N="732">ffor I com not hom a&yogh;eyn;</L>
<L>ffor me he synge&thorn; vche day a Mes&mdash;</L>
<L>prest, abbot forso&thorn;e he is.
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="217"></L>
<L>I wot wel, &thorn;at is &thorn;e enchesun</L>
<L N="736">&THORN;at my Bondus here<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. are so</NOTE> vndon;</L>
<L>ffor no &thorn;ing ne haues pouwer</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e sacrament of &thorn;e auter.</L>
<L>ffor, &yogh;if I weore ded, in o&thorn;ur werld,</L>
<L N="740">His preyere for me weore I-herd,</L>
<L>To bringe me out of peyne and wo,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en to blisse forte go."</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at Meyne and &thorn;at Erl</L>
<L N="744">Leeuede wel he was no cherl,</L>
<L>as<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. And as</NOTE> he to-fore hem hedde i-seid</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei on hym furst hond leyd;</L>
<L>Bi his semblaunt and feir beryng</L>
<L N="748">Hym semed wel a gret<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. to be a</NOTE> lordyng,</L>
<L>Bi his speche &thorn;ei vndurstood</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was mon of gentil blod.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Erl tok him in priuite,</L>
<L N="752">Whe&thorn;en he was telle scholde he;</L>
<L>"Sey me so&thorn;, and, as I am trewe<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> kniht,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt no ska&thorn;e haue, be my miht."<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. ne ply&yogh;t</NOTE></L>
<L>"Se&thorn;&thorn;he &thorn;ou me bi-hotest pes and gri&thorn;,</L>
<L N="756">I am &thorn;e kynges mon Eldri&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Edfryth</NOTE></L>
<L>Armes I bar in &thorn;at Batayle,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; my pouwer him to auayle."</L>
<L>"So me &thorn;hou&yogh;te," seide &thorn;e Erl,</L>
<L N="760">"&THORN;ou<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;e</NOTE> semed not to ben a cherl.</L>
<L>Bote for &thorn;i knowlechyng her me bye<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. But for &thorn;at y here &thorn;e seye</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou weore wor&thorn;i for to dye,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou halp<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. hylpe</NOTE> &thorn;er to slo,</L>
<L N="764">&THORN;at al my kynde is ded me fro;</L>
<L>Bote, for I er sikerde &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Scha[l]t &thorn;ou haue no ska&thorn;e for me."</L>
<L>He eode and sold him for Raunsoun</L>
<L N="768">At Londone to a ffrisoun.</L>
<L>A ffrisoun, &yogh;e schul vndurstonde,</L>
<L>Is a Mon of ffrys-londe.</L>
<L>&THORN;is ffrisoun scholde &thorn;is Mon for&thorn; lede,</L>
<L N="772">And dude on him bondes for drede,</L>
<L>ffor a-skapyng bi &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>He dude bondes on him leye.
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="218"></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at vaylede him no-&thorn;yng</L>
<L N="776">Neuer a day, &thorn;at byndyng:</L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;at tyme &thorn;e masse was songen,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bondes to-barst and al to-sprongen.</L>
<L>&THORN;is ffrison &thorn;hou&yogh;te: "hou may &thorn;is beo?</L>
<L N="780">He may riht wel from me fleo;</L>
<L>Happyliche hit a-vayle&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. vayled</NOTE> nouht</L>
<L>&THORN;e Catel &thorn;at I wi&thorn; him bouht."</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffrison seide: "wolt &thorn;ou wel</L>
<L N="784">Restore a-&yogh;eyn al my Catel,</L>
<L>And I schal &yogh;iue &thorn;e leue to go</L>
<L>To &thorn;i Cuntre &thorn;at &thorn;ou com fro.</L>
<L>But furst &thorn;ou schalt me trou&thorn;e pliht,</L>
<L N="788">And trewely hold hit wi&thorn; al &thorn;i miht,</L>
<L>To bringe &thorn;e Catel I &yogh;af for &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And elles I graunte &thorn;e not fre."</L>
<L>He graunted him al &thorn;at he seide,</L>
<L N="792">And trou&thorn;e in hond wi&thorn; hym he leide.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Ruyna wente to kyng loer,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was kyng of Caunturber&mdash;</L>
<L>He was seint Andreas<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. Andre</NOTE> suster sone,</L>
<L N="796">And Ruyna was wont wi&thorn; hym<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. here</NOTE> to wone;</L>
<L>Of al his stat, bo&thorn;e wo and wele,</L>
<L>Ruyna told him eueridele.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng &yogh;af him his Raunsun;</L>
<L N="800">And [he] bar hit to londun to &thorn;at ffrisun.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e eode he hom, &thorn;is kniht Ruyna,</L>
<L>To his bro&thorn;ur, Abbot Timma,</L>
<L>And tolde him of al his wo-fare</L>
<L N="804">And of his cumfort in al his care.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Abbot wel vndurstood</L>
<L>&THORN;at his Masse dude him gret good</L>
<L>And &thorn;e sacrament gon hym borwe</L>
<L N="808">Out of seruage and out of sorwe.</L>
<L>&THORN;is tale telle&thorn; vs seynt Bede</L>
<L>In his gestes &thorn;at we Rede.&mdash;</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;is tale may men lere</L>
<L N="812">&THORN;at Masses helpe&thorn; vs wel here:</L>
<L>ffor vs liuynge hit make&thorn; Memorie,</L>
<L>Also for &thorn;e soules in purgatorie.
<PB REF="00000227.tif" N="219"></L>
<L>Vche mon schal leeue &thorn;at riht</L>
<L N="816">&THORN;at helpen hit wolle as [hit] dude<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;at holpe wyl be as was</NOTE> &thorn;e kniht.</L>
<L>&THORN;is sacrament helpe&thorn; not &yogh;it alone,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;e offrynges euerichone,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at we offre atte Mes,</L>
<L N="820">Al to vre saluacion hit is.</L>
<L>Not only forte saue &thorn;e dede,<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;o &thorn;at dede be&thorn;</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e quike hit saue&thorn; also and rede;<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. rede&thorn;</NOTE></L>
<L>As wel haue &thorn;e quike &thorn;e prou</L>
<L N="824">As &thorn;e dede &thorn;erof &thorn;e vertu nou<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Quike and dede, More and lesse</L>
<L>Ben I-saued &thorn;orwh &thorn;e Messe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Offringe is as a present,</L>
<L N="828">&THORN;at helpe&thorn; vs wi&thorn; &thorn;e sacrament,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e ffadur of heuene tentefuly,</L>
<L>ffor whom &thorn;ou offerest to haue Merci.</L>
<L>A tale I fond ones I-writen,</L>
<L N="832">And as I sauh hit, I wol &yogh;e witen,</L>
<L>And wel a-corde&thorn; in alle &thorn;inge</L>
<L>&THORN;at God is payed of good offringe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6.) Of a man &thorn;at was closed in a myne.</HEAD>
<L>Hit was a Mon bi-&yogh;onde &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute;,</L>
<L N="836">A Mynour, wonede In a Citee.</L>
<L>Mynours, &thorn;ei make&thorn; in hulles holes,</L>
<L>As men don &thorn;at seche&thorn; coles.</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;is</NOTE> Mynour souht stones vndur molde</L>
<L N="840">&THORN;at Men of maken seluer and golde.</L>
<L>He wrouhte and holede in &thorn;e hille.</L>
<L>A perilous chaunce fel hym tille:</L>
<L>A gret parti of &thorn;e Myne</L>
<L N="844">ffel doun &thorn;er and closed hym Inne.</L>
<L>His felawes alle &thorn;at weren hym hende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he weore ded wel &thorn;ei wende;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei eode and tok hem alle to Rede,</L>
<L N="848">And tolde his wyf &thorn;at he was dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;is wommon bi-menede hir hosebonde sore&mdash;</L>
<L>God leeue &thorn;at mony such wymmen wore!&mdash;</L>
<L>Heo helped his soule in alle &thorn;ynge,</L>
<L N="852">In almes-dede and in offringe;
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="220"></L>
<L>Heo Offred for him atte Auter</L>
<L>fful of wyn a picher,</L>
<L>And [a] feir lof wi&thorn;-al,</L>
<L N="856">Eueri day as<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. as for a</NOTE> principal,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at twelf-mone&thorn; stabely,</L>
<L>Bote o day &thorn;at passed forby.</L>
<L>ffewe suche wymmen [now] we fynde</L>
<L N="860">&THORN;at to heore hosebondes are so kynde!</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;is wyf wi&thorn; al hire miht</L>
<L>Dude for him [bo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. bo&thorn;e; MS. Vern. om.</NOTE>] day and niht.</L>
<L>Hit fel at &thorn;e twelfmone&thorn; ende,</L>
<L N="864">His felawes to &thorn;e hul gon wende,</L>
<L>And come to &thorn;at same stude eft</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ei heore felawe in werk left.</L>
<L>Riht &thorn;ere &thorn;ei furst bi-gon</L>
<L N="868">&THORN;ei percede &thorn;orwh in to &thorn;e Mon:</L>
<L>&THORN;e Mon In good stat &thorn;ei founde,</L>
<L>Liuinge, wi&thorn;-outen wem or wounde.</L>
<L>Euerichone &thorn;ei hedde ferly,</L>
<L N="872">And &thorn;at was gret Resun why!</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;o men weore in gret weer</L>
<L>How he hedde lyued al &thorn;at &yogh;er.</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;enne he tolde hem euerichon</L>
<L N="876">How he hedde lyued &thorn;er al-on:</L>
<L>"I haue I-liued gracious lyf</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh cortesye of my wyf:</L>
<L>Eueri day heo ha&thorn; me sent</L>
<L N="880">Bred and wyn to present;</L>
<L>But o day, &thorn;enne eet I nouht,</L>
<L>ffor my mete me nas not brouht."</L>
<L>&THORN;ei ladde &thorn;e mon in to &thorn;e toun,</L>
<L N="884">And tolde &thorn;is Miracle vp and doun,</L>
<L>ffurst &thorn;orwh &thorn;e Cit&eacute;&eacute;,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;orwh al &thorn;e contre.</L>
<L>Hit com in spekyng<NOTE PLACE="marg">F. &thorn;ey asked hym</NOTE> atte laste</L>
<L N="888">&THORN;at day &thorn;at he dude faste.</L>
<L>He tolde hem &thorn;e dayes name,</L>
<L>And his wyf seide &thorn;e same:</L>
<L>&THORN;at day heo offrede neuer a del,</L>
<L N="892">&THORN;e goode ffriday hit mihte be wel.
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="221"></L>
<L>Now may &yogh;e here &thorn;at almes-dede</L>
<L>Gostlyche wole a mon fede,</L>
<L>And so may &yogh;e wel vnderstande</L>
<L N="896">&THORN;at God is payed of good offrande.&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;is tale in &yogh;or lyues</L>
<L>Trustne&thorn; not in &yogh;or wyues,</L>
<L>Ne in &yogh;our children no-&thorn;ing;</L>
<L N="900">Make&thorn; or-self &yogh;our offring!</L>
<L>So kynde a wommon as I of tolde</L>
<L>Liue&thorn; not now, beo &yogh;e bolde!</L>
<L>Ne no clerk &thorn;at &thorn;is redes</L>
<L N="904">Schal fynde non nou of so kynde dedes.&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e men &thorn;at are nou In present,</L>
<L>&THORN;at here&thorn; rede &thorn;is sacrament,</L>
<L>Ouer alle &thorn;ing hit ha&thorn; power,</L>
<L N="908">&THORN;e sacrament on &thorn;e Auter,</L>
<L>As I haue here to ow i-schewed,</L>
<L>Not to lered bote to lewed.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e lewede men, I telle hit ow&mdash;</L>
<L N="912">&THORN;is clerkes con hit wel I-nouh.</L>
<L>Prei&yogh;e we &thorn;enne vr creatour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> &thorn;e sacrament, vr saueour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Bodi and soule he wol vs saue,</L>
<L N="916">And we him to<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> loue and he us to<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in F.</NOTE> haue. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="32" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>XXXII. Hou a man schal lyue parfytly. (A translation of the first part of St. Edmund's Speculum).</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>This treatise follows the Gospels without being separated from them, either by a larger Initial or special title; yet it is a separate treatise, being a translation of the first part of St. Edmund's Speculum; it was made perhaps from a prose translation such as is found in MS. Vern., f. ccclv., and Thornton (E. E. T. Soc. 1867, p. 15 seq.). The sense is frequently obscured and corrupted. Another translation of St. Edmund's Speculum is &THORN;e Spore of Loue, p. 268 ff. The Speculum is printed in De La Bigne's Magna bibliotheca veterum patrum, ed. Col. 1618, vol. XIII, p. 355.</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">The following Introduc|tion (1-50) agrees with the Index to the prose-transl. in MS. Vernon (but is want|ing in MS. Thornton).</NOTE>IN nome of him Alweldyng<MILESTONE N="ccxxvii" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at is vr hei&yogh;e heuene-kyng,</L>
<L>Take&thorn; hede here in alle wyse</L>
<L N="4">To fleo &thorn;e sunne of Couetyse</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e dedly Synnes samed</L>
<L>&THORN;at her-aftur schul beo named.
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="222"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">In the Spec. precedes: Quo|modo homo debet respicere ad statum suum.</NOTE>&YOGH;e mouwe also here hardily</L>
<L>Hou mon schal lyue parfytly;</L>
<L N="9">&THORN;enne schul &yogh;e here also</L>
<L>What is &thorn;e wille of god euermo;</L>
<L>Also schul &yogh;e here now rede</L>
<L N="12">What &thorn;ing make&thorn; mon holy in dede;</L>
<L>&THORN;en schul &yogh;e here, &yogh;if &yogh;e wol trouwe,</L>
<L>Hou mon schal him-self knowe,</L>
<L>In bodi and in soule also,</L>
<L N="16">Wher he liue treweli or ne do;</L>
<L>Also mowe &yogh;e here in hi&yogh;</L>
<L>&THORN;e godnesse of god &thorn;at is euer redi;</L>
<L>&THORN;en mowe &yogh;e heere in &thorn;is ryme</L>
<L N="20">How a Mon schal spende his tyme.</L>
<L>Also heere lerne we may</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at we schule vre lord pay.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Spec.: Quomodo homo debet contemplari Deum in creatura.</NOTE></L>
<L>Herkne&thorn; alle feire and stille:</L>
<L N="24">Heere schul &yogh;e so of godus wille,</L>
<L>As witnesse&thorn; folliche hit</L>
<L>&THORN;e Bok &thorn;at is cald holi writ:</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen dedlich synnus, &thorn;e braunches also,</L>
<L N="28">I wol &yogh;ow telle, ar &yogh;e go;</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen vertuwes of Ion &thorn;e Ewangelist,<NOTE PLACE="marg">= the seven blessings, which however are given in Math. 5, 3. Spec.: De 7 virtutibus evangelicis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;as</NOTE> was ful wel wi&thorn; Ihesu Crist;</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen &yogh;iftus of &thorn;e holigost,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche ben of mihtes most,</L>
<L>And of heore streng&thorn;e also I-feere</L>
<L>Sumwhat &thorn;enne mowe &yogh;e lere;</L>
<L>&THORN;en schul &yogh;e heere in presens</L>
<L N="36">Whuch ben &thorn;e ten Comaundemens;</L>
<L>&THORN;e[n] schul &yogh;e heere feir and briht</L>
<L>Of &thorn;reo<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. v. 857 ff., where the 4 cardinal virtues (45-8) are included.</NOTE> vertuwes and of heore miht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is ffei&thorn;, good hope, and loue,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at wol vs bringe to blisse aboue;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e twelf Articles of &thorn;e ffey</L>
<L>Schul we also sumwhat sey;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e seuen Sacramens,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at euer ben in godus presens;</L>
<L>So schul &yogh;e heere sum or al</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffoure vertuwes Principal:
<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="223"></L>
<L>Prouwesse, Rihtwisnesse, and Meth,</L>
<L N="48">Streng&thorn;e also wi&thorn; hem he geth;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e seuen werkes [of merci] also&mdash;</L>
<L>Lord, &yogh;if vs grace hem wel to do.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD><Q>Videte vocacionem vestram.</Q> <BIBL>(Paul, 1 Cor. 1, 26.)</BIBL></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is wordus here &thorn;at I ow say,</L>
<L N="52">To Religious men longen &thorn;ay;</L>
<L>&THORN;us muche ben &thorn;ei forte mene,</L>
<L>As &yogh;e schul heere al bydeene:</L>
<L>"Seo," he<NOTE PLACE="marg">sc. Poul</NOTE> sei&thorn;, "bi-holde &yogh;e</L>
<L N="56">To what &thorn;ing &yogh;e cleped be."</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sei&thorn;, hem to redresse</L>
<L>And to sturen hem to Parfytnesse.</L>
<L>ffor<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;erfor</NOTE> eueri Mon &thorn;at lyue&thorn; here</L>
<L N="60">Ouhte ha Ioye and Serwe I-fere:</L>
<L>Ioye for &thorn;e wor&thorn;ily wonynge</L>
<L>&THORN;at is ordeynt to wel lyuynge,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Th.: Ioy for &thorn;e holy religion</NOTE></L>
<L>Serwe also to haue &thorn;erbi</L>
<L N="64">ffor vre liuynge vnrihtfuli.</L>
<L>ffor her sei&thorn; seint Eusebi</L>
<L>Wordus &thorn;at ben ful dredfuly:</L>
<L>"A Mon to Religiun him dresse</L>
<L N="68">Is aller-hext sikernesse;</L>
<L>Not parfyt liue &thorn;er-inne son</L>
<L>Is aller-hext Dampnacion."</L>
<L>In Religiun we to beo don</L>
<L N="72">Is aller-hext Saluacion:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow wolt &thorn;at saluacion proue,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at is good &thorn;ou most loue,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou most loue<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. leue</NOTE> eke also</L>
<L N="76">Al &thorn;at Religius<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;e world?</NOTE> longe&thorn; to;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou most al &thorn;i wille &yogh;iue</L>
<L>Parfytly and sikerly to liue.</L>
<L>And seint Bernard vs teche&thorn; in hi&yogh;</L>
<L N="80">To liue Mekeli, loueli, and worschipfuli.</L>
<L>&THORN;at "worschipfuli" is to mene,</L>
<L>To Godus worschipe feir and clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou do al &thorn;yn entent</L>
<L N="84">To don al his Comaundement;
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="224"></L>
<L>To don his biddyng &thorn;ou not asterte</L>
<L>In al &thorn;at &thorn;ou may &thorn;enke wi&thorn; herte,</L>
<L>And loke &thorn;ou no &thorn;ing &thorn;er-of breke</L>
<L N="88">Wi&thorn; al &thorn;at &thorn;ou wi&thorn; mou&thorn; mai speke,</L>
<L>Or worche in dede wi&thorn;-oute striue</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; eny of &thorn;i wittes fyue,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; si&yogh;t of E&yogh;e, wi&thorn; Tonge tastyng,</L>
<L N="92">Smellyng of Neose, of Ere heryng;</L>
<L>What &thorn;ou dost bi wei or strete</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bodi worching, going wi&thorn; feete,</L>
<L>Liggyng, stondyng, &thorn;enkyng<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. sittyng</NOTE> also,</L>
<L N="96">Loke &yogh;if hit beo godus wille or no.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if hit beo his wille, do hit son;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if hit ne beo, hit not don,</L>
<L>Do hit not &thorn;enne for no maystrie,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou scholdest &thorn;erfore dye.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;enne mony mon loud and stille</L>
<L>Wol aske, what is godus wille.</L>
<L>Hit is to vs bo&thorn;e more and les</L>
<L N="104">To haue vs euere in holynes.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;enne is to wite what, and whi,</L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; a mon &thorn;enne holi.</L>
<L>Two &thorn;inges &thorn;er ben In worchyng:</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at on is loue, &thorn;at o&thorn;ur knowyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is knowyng of alle so&thorn;nes,</L>
<L>And loue of alle grete goodnes.</L>
<L>To knowyng of god &thorn;at is so&thorn;nes</L>
<L N="112">Maist &thorn;ou not come in blod and flesch,</L>
<L>Bote to knowe<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;orw knowyng</NOTE> &thorn;in owne flesch,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. self?</NOTE></L>
<L>And also<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. to loue of</NOTE> godus grete goodnes,</L>
<L>Maistou not come, as I &thorn;e mene,</L>
<L N="116">Wi&thorn;-outen loue of &thorn;in Euencristene.</L>
<L>To knowyng of &thorn;i-sel[f] maistou</L>
<L>Come &thorn;orwh good &thorn;enkyng nou;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sp. per frequentem meditacionem</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou may&yogh;t come to godus knowynge</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;in owne feire plesynge.<NOTE PLACE="marg">per puram contemplacionem</NOTE></L>
<L>To knowe &thorn;i-self old or &yogh;inge</L>
<L>Maistou come bi &thorn;is bithinkynge:</L>
<L>&THORN;enk bisiliche, I preye &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="124">What &thorn;ou weore, art, and schalt be,
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="225"></L>
<L>ffurst as to &thorn;i bodi here,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;he to &thorn;i soule &thorn;at is so dere.</L>
<L>As to &thorn;i bodi: foulore hit is</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;en euer was eny donge, I-wis&mdash;</L>
<L>Was neuer &yogh;it dounge so foule</L>
<L>&THORN;at wolde so stinke, rote and moule;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou weore in so gret ful&thorn;e igete,</L>
<L N="132">Abhominable hit is &thorn;erof to speke;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt beo dilyueret to frete</L>
<L>To Todus and o&thorn;ur wormes mete.</L>
<L>What &thorn;ou hast ben &amp; art, haue in mynde,</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;at &thorn;i soule beo not beo-hynde;&mdash;</L>
<L>What &thorn;i soule schal beo in tyme comyng,</L>
<L>May no mon knowe but heuene-kyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;enk &thorn;ou hast In chele and hete</L>
<L N="140">I-do mony wikkednesse and grete,</L>
<L>&THORN;enk also, hem to redresse</L>
<L>&THORN;ow hast laft mony gret goodnesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;enk also, &thorn;at &thorn;is beo not weyued,</L>
<L N="144">&THORN;at longe hast lyued, and muche reseiued,</L>
<L>And hou &thorn;ou hast spendet &thorn;at reseit;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e &thorn;enne wol &thorn;is beo ful streit:</L>
<L>ffor vch a tyme, drede &thorn;e nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast not on god I-&thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast so loren of &thorn;i dispens</L>
<L>And don a&yogh;eyn &thorn;i lordus defens&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor hit is vr lordus biddyng</L>
<L N="152">To loue him ouer al o&thorn;ur &thorn;yng.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;elde also a-counte</L>
<L>What vch an Idel word wol amounte,</L>
<L>Also to Acountes &thorn;ou schalt beo brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="156">ffor euerich Idel werk and &thorn;ouht;</L>
<L>And as vch an her on &thorn;in hed is wried</L>
<L>&THORN;at is saued schal beo glorifyed,</L>
<L>Also schal no &thorn;ing ascape</L>
<L N="160">Wi&thorn;-outen a-counte erly or late. . . . .</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e soule &thorn;er hit is holde,</L>
<L>Is more &thorn;en al &thorn;is worldus molde&mdash;</L>
<L>Here is muche of godus grace!</L>
<L N="164">&YOGH;it schal hit ocupye no place.
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="226"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Bodi and &thorn;e soule ben al a-stray,</L>
<L>Diuerse &thorn;ou&yogh;tes, willes, disires al day:</L>
<L>Ho mihte &thorn;enne seche his herte so ni&yogh;</L>
<L N="168">To &yogh;iue acountes al trewely</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;at euere he hedde mys-wrouht</L>
<L>Or eny mis-dede hedde in &thorn;ouht?</L>
<L>Seo&thorn; now, bre&thorn;eren bi ten or twelue,</L>
<L N="172">How &yogh;e ha neode to knowe or-selue!&mdash;</L>
<L>Tac good &yogh;eme what &thorn;ou [now] art</L>
<L>To soule, and let hit not astart,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou hast in &thorn;e luytel of goode,</L>
<L N="176">Luitel of wit and pouwer and moode,</L>
<L>&THORN;is is &thorn;us muche forte say</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou coueytest vche a day</L>
<L>&THORN;ing &thorn;at nouht is wor&thorn; in dede</L>
<L N="180">Ne &thorn;at &thorn;e helpe mai at gret nede.</L>
<L>Help vs god &thorn;at sitte&thorn; on lofte,</L>
<L>ffor elles beo we bigyled ofte,</L>
<L>O&thorn;urwhile &thorn;orwh Ragynge as vnwitti,</L>
<L N="184">And o&thorn;urwhile beo veyn<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. veny</NOTE> glori;</L>
<L>Now are we trauaylet in to drede I-lope,</L>
<L>Now beo &thorn;e wey of fals hope.</L>
<L>&THORN;ow art so chaungable be-hynde &amp; bi-forn,</L>
<L N="188">&THORN;at we wol to-day we wol not to-morn;</L>
<L>Ofte vr-seluen for to plese</L>
<L>Are we aboute worldly ese,</L>
<L>But we haue hem at vr wille</L>
<L N="192">We beo turmented, us &thorn;inke&thorn; wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. wi&thorn;</NOTE> ille:</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou hem at &thorn;i wille most hast,</L>
<L>&THORN;en art &thorn;ou wi&thorn; hem agreued mast.</L>
<L>&THORN;enk wel &yogh;it, I rede &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="196">Hou liht &thorn;ou art to tempted be,</L>
<L>ffebel and Brutel to stonde a-&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L>Redi to asente wi&thorn; al oure mayn.</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;eos Merueylous chaunces</L>
<L N="200">Vr lord ha&thorn; sent vs diliueraunces,</L>
<L>And vche o&thorn;ur day &thorn;erfore<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;erfro</NOTE></L>
<L>He vs dilyuere&thorn; more and more.<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. mo</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou weore nou&yogh;t, he formede &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="204">&THORN;i soule to his liknesse to be,
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="227"></L>
<L>And &thorn;y stinkynde bodi also</L>
<L>ffoormed he wi&thorn; lymes two,</L>
<L>So feir and noble and of gret prise</L>
<L N="208">&THORN;at no Mon may no such deuise.</L>
<L>&THORN;enk bisiliche, &yogh;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at loue&thorn; or ffadres and modres fre,</L>
<L>Whi &yogh;e louen hem so tenderly&mdash;</L>
<L N="212">I wolde wite &thorn;e resun whi.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou seist &thorn;us, as so&thorn; hit is,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou wer born and geten of her flesch:</L>
<L>So don &thorn;e beestes, so&thorn; to say,</L>
<L N="216">&THORN;at breden of Mon and wommon al day.</L>
<L>&THORN;e so&thorn;e &yogh;if &thorn;ou wol lerne &thorn;en,</L>
<L>Bodi ne soule nastou of hem,</L>
<L>But bi him ful witterli</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at is vr lord, god Almihti.</L>
<L>What heddestou ben, I preye &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou heddest stille such i-be</L>
<L>In ful&thorn;e of synne as &thorn;ou i-gete were?</L>
<L N="224">fful Abhomynable hit is to here.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou loue bro&thorn;ur or suster &thorn;an</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei ben of &thorn;at fflesch i-tan</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou weore &thorn;i-self also&mdash;</L>
<L N="228">&THORN;erfore &thorn;at loue hast &thorn;ou hem to:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou scholdust &thorn;en loue hard and nesch</L>
<L>A pece of ffadur or Modur fflesch</L>
<L>In &thorn;is Maner, &thorn;at I sei here,</L>
<L N="232">Al on Schornes<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. of-shorne</NOTE> &thorn;ei&yogh; hit were.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou sigge in &thorn;is degre</L>
<L>&THORN;ou louest hem, for flesch figured &thorn;ei be</L>
<L>To &thorn;i liknes, and for &thorn;ei han</L>
<L N="236">Soule of god as &thorn;ou hast tan:</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;is is he no more &thorn;i bro&thorn;ur</L>
<L>But on as muche as is a-no&thorn;ur,</L>
<L>But in as muche neuer-&thorn;e-latur</L>
<L N="240">As &yogh;e hedde bo&thorn;e on flesch-fadur,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne &thorn;e biginnyng<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. bigimyng</NOTE> of vre flesch</L>
<L>Is stynkynde ful&thorn;e neuer&thorn;eles.</L>
<L>Of O flesch-ffadur alle we came,</L>
<L N="244">Adam was he cald bi name;
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="228"></L>
<L>And for he dude so gret folye,</L>
<L>Scholde we neuer loue her fleschlye,</L>
<L>Bute vche Mon &thorn;us scholde loue o&thorn;ur</L>
<L N="248">Gostlich here as sustur and bro&thorn;ur.&mdash;</L>
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;at is vr aller kyng,</L>
<L>As I seide atte bygynnyng,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou weor nou&yogh;t, &thorn;en formed he &thorn;e.</L>
<L N="252">Whon &thorn;ou weore lore, &thorn;en fond &thorn;e he,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou weore sold in sorwe and sinne,</L>
<L>&THORN;en bou&yogh;t he &thorn;e wi&thorn; muchel wynne;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou were diht, i-dampned also,</L>
<L N="256">&THORN;en mihtfulliche he saued &thorn;e &thorn;o;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou weore boren in synne eke,</L>
<L>He Baptised &thorn;e wi&thorn; wordus swete.</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;ou sungest, al day to se,</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;en Mekeliche he soffre&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And longe he wol &yogh;it &thorn;e abyde,</L>
<L>Resseyue &thorn;e aftur, so may be-tyde,</L>
<L>And putte &thorn;e in to his swete couent,</L>
<L N="264">Euer to beo to him present.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou mis-dost, he wol &thorn;e &thorn;rete,</L>
<L>Longe he byde&thorn; ar he wol bete;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou syngest wi&thorn; wille fre,</L>
<L N="268">fful sone wol he for-&yogh;iue hit &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou mis-gost eke also,</L>
<L>He &thorn;e Amende&thorn; wi&thorn; wille ful &thorn;ro,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at &thorn;ou in doute art ouht,</L>
<L N="272">In to &thorn;e techyng he ha&thorn; &thorn;e brouht;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou art hungri in eny neode,</L>
<L>ffeire he ordeyne&thorn; &thorn;e to ffeede;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou hast colde, he warme&thorn; &thorn;e, Mon,</L>
<L N="276">Whon &thorn;ou hast hete, he kele&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;on;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou wakest,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. walkest</NOTE> he saue&thorn; &thorn;e so,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou slepest, he kepe&thorn; &thorn;e to;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou rist vp, he &thorn;e sosteyne&thorn;,</L>
<L N="280">Whon &thorn;ou fallest, he &thorn;e reise&thorn;,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou sittest, he halt &thorn;e ek,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou stondest, he streng&thorn;e&thorn; &thorn;i feet,</L>
<L>And also, so&thorn; for to say,</L>
<L N="284">He vndursitte&thorn; &thorn;e euere and ay;
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="229"></L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou gost, he wol &thorn;e lede,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou a&yogh;eyn turnest, resseyue&thorn; &thorn;e eke,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou gost mis, a-&yogh;eyn calle&thorn; he,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;e</NOTE></L>
<L N="288">Whon &thorn;ou art seek, &thorn;i cumfort to<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. wol?</NOTE> be.&mdash;</L>
<L>Such goodnesses in mony degre</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; vr lord god I-do for &thorn;e.</L>
<L>And goodnesse in &thorn;yn herte wore,</L>
<L N="292">&THORN;ou weore holden euer-more</L>
<L>Alle dayes to &thorn;enke [on him] I-wis,</L>
<L>And alle tymes to &thorn;onke for &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Alle dayes to speke to [him] Aboue</L>
<L N="296">And alle dayes him hertly loue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">= praise</NOTE></L>
<L>And also wel, &yogh;it i &thorn;e say,</L>
<L>On niht as vppon &thorn;e day.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;ou &thorn;at art &thorn;us wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="300">At euen and morwe haue &thorn;us &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Hou mony &thorn;ousund men to say</L>
<L>Han perisched in &thorn;at niht or &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>Summe in bodi, so&thorn; hit is,</L>
<L N="304">Summe in soule leosen her blis;</L>
<L>Summe in fuire and o&thorn;ur maneere,</L>
<L>Summe in water &thorn;at is so clere;</L>
<L>Summe Robbed and woundet also;</L>
<L N="308">Summe sodeynly to de&thorn; han go</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen schrif and hosul &thorn;en</L>
<L>&THORN;at hem &thorn;e rihte wei scholde ken,</L>
<L>And for defaute of Confessiun</L>
<L N="312">Parauntur go to dampnaciun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enk also, a-no&thorn;ur is &thorn;is</L>
<L>&THORN;at niht and day moni mon is</L>
<L>ffalle in peril of soule way,</L>
<L N="316">&THORN;at &thorn;e fend ha&thorn; mad hem stray,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to sei &thorn;us for&thorn;i</L>
<L>In &thorn;e seuen synnes dedly:</L>
<L>In Glotenye and Lecherie,</L>
<L N="320">Monslau&yogh;t also and Envye.</L>
<L>And of alle &thorn;eose wikkede chaunses</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; crist mad &thorn;e diliueraunces,</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; &thorn;e saued as mihti kyng</L>
<L N="324">Wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;yn owne deseruyng!
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="230"></L>
<L>And what hastou don him and whare</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e kept from al &thorn;is care?</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou toke &thorn;us goode kepe</L>
<L N="328">Whon &thorn;ou awakest of &thorn;i slepe,</L>
<L>Hou mony goodnesses he ha&thorn; &thorn;e do,</L>
<L>And euer is to &thorn;e aboute mo,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow schuldest him loue souereynli</L>
<L N="332">Ouer al &thorn;is world, witterli;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt him fynde so bisy now</L>
<L>Euermore a-boute &thorn;i prow</L>
<L>As non o&thorn;ur &thorn;yng he aboute were</L>
<L N="336">But &thorn;e to kepe whil &thorn;ou art here.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou hast &thorn;ou&yogh;t in &thorn;is wyse,</L>
<L>A-Morwe soone vp arise</L>
<L>And &thorn;onke &thorn;i lord of al &thorn;is goode,</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;at for &thorn;e wolde dye on Roode,</L>
<L>And sei to him wi&thorn; herte fre</L>
<L>In &thorn;is maner &thorn;at i sei to &thorn;e:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Gracias ago tibi, domine Ihesu criste, qui me [mise|rum peccatorem]</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">so MS. Simeon</NOTE> <I>in hac nocte custodi[sti], [pro|texisti], visitasti, sanum saluum &amp; incolimem ad hanc horam peruenire fecisti, &amp; pro alijs vniuersis beneficiis que</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. qui</NOTE> <I>michi tua sola bonitate contulisti. Qui viuis &amp; regnas deus per omnia.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">The English translation is omitted.</NOTE></L>
<L N="343">Sey &thorn;us, for hit is to &thorn;i by-heue,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e on Morwen and at eue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 355-362 are not in the Spec.</NOTE>&THORN;Enk &thorn;enne, I rede, also,</L>
<L>Ar &thorn;at &thorn;ou to &thorn;i bed go,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;ou hast spendet &thorn;i tyme honeste</L>
<L N="348">Whon &thorn;ou vp ros til &thorn;ou go to reste;</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;ou hast bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;e wel,</L>
<L>Bi-sech god merci eueridel</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;e synnes &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="352">And goodnesse &thorn;ou hast do nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Whil vr lord &thorn;e lante miht,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at day ne in &thorn;at niht.</L>
<L>And loke &thorn;ou do non o&thorn;ur dede</L>
<L N="356">Til &thorn;ou haue &thorn;e Comaundet, I rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e and alle o&thorn;ur goode eke</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e hond of god ful meke,
<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="231"></L>
<L>And &thorn;enne schaltou &thorn;us<NOTE PLACE="marg">The Latin text (In manus tuas &amp;c.) is omitted.</NOTE> say</L>
<L N="360">In &thorn;is Manere, I &thorn;e pray. . . . .</L>
<L>What &thorn;eos wordus ben to mene,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schul on Englich here bi-dene:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"In to &thorn;in hondes, lord verray,</L>
<L N="364">And in to &thorn;in holy Aungeles ay,</L>
<L>I be-teche &thorn;is ilke niht</L>
<L>Mi bodi and soule to &thorn;e be diht,</L>
<L>Mi bre&thorn;eren and my sustren alle,</L>
<L N="368">And al my frendes, what-so bi-falle,</L>
<L>And my nexte frendes eke,</L>
<L>And al my gode doeres, i beo-seke,</L>
<L>And also I be-seche at ene</L>
<L N="372">Alle o&thorn;ur cristene for to mene.</L>
<L>Kep vs, lord, &thorn;is niht in hi&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;i</NOTE> beo-sechyng of &thorn;i Modur Marie</L>
<L>And of al halewen also</L>
<L N="376">&THORN;at euer weore on eor&thorn;e i-do,</L>
<L>ffrom vices and couetyse vn-hende</L>
<L>And ffrom temptaciun of &thorn;e fende,</L>
<L>Of sodeyn de&thorn; vnwarned to telle,</L>
<L N="380">And also from &thorn;e pyne of helle;</L>
<L>Liht myn herte of &thorn;e holy gost,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou art lord of mihtes most,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;i grete grace &thorn;ou me take,</L>
<L N="384">To &thorn;i Comaundemens me boxum make,</L>
<L>And neuer beo departet from &thorn;e</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen ende, so mot hit be."&mdash; &mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou vse &thorn;is-Maner &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="388">&THORN;en schaltou haue so&thorn;fast knowyng,</L>
<L>To knowe &thorn;i lord in whom is al,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e Mad and saue schal.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;enne &thorn;at &thorn;is beo &thorn;e rif,</L>
<L N="392">Her-wi&thorn; to lede holy lyf.&mdash; &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;reo Maners &thorn;er beo &thorn;en</L>
<L>Of Contemplaciun vs to ken:</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste of hem &thorn;at &thorn;er is,</L>
<L N="396">In Creatures hit is, i-wis;</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur in holy writ, we fynde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde in god and in his kynde.
<PB REF="00000240.tif" N="232"></L>
<L>Contemplaciun is, siker &yogh;e beo,</L>
<L N="400">&THORN;e goodnesse of god for to seo.</L>
<L>Bi his<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;is</NOTE> Creatures may &thorn;ou seo &thorn;an</L>
<L>&THORN;reo &thorn;inges ben In god and Man;</L>
<L>&THORN;is &thorn;reo ben, vs to redresse:</L>
<L>Miht, wit, and gret goodnesse.<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 vv. wanting (Miht is ap|propred to god &thorn;e Fader).</NOTE>. .</L>
<L N="405">Wit to god &thorn;at is sone,</L>
<L>Goodnes to god holigost in wone.</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh his miht, &thorn;at wel was torned,</L>
<L N="408">Alle &thorn;inges &thorn;ei ben formed;</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh his wit, so wel demeyned,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;inges wysliche he<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. be</NOTE> ordeyned;</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh his goodnesse, not denyed,</L>
<L N="412">Alle &thorn;eose &thorn;inges he<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. be</NOTE> multiplyed.</L>
<L>His pouwer maistou seo &thorn;e laft</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh her gretnesse and here schaft;</L>
<L>His wit also wi&thorn;-outen distaunce</L>
<L N="416">&THORN;orwh heore bounte<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. beaute</NOTE> and ordynaunce;</L>
<L>His godnesse may we seo ful newe</L>
<L>Bi heore Multiplicaciun and vertuwe.</L>
<L>Heore gretnesse may we seo</L>
<L N="420">Wi&thorn; foure propurtes<NOTE PLACE="marg">Lat. dimensiones</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;er beo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is folliche for to say</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh heore hei&yogh;nesse and depnesse ay,</L>
<L>&THORN;e o&thorn;ur two ben of streng&thorn;e</L>
<L N="424">&THORN;at is<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. was</NOTE> &thorn;orwh heore brede and lenge.</L>
<L>His wit maistou seo ful breme,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou &thorn;erof take good &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>&THORN;er as he ha&thorn; &yogh;iue sum creature &thorn;ore</L>
<L N="428">Beoyng wi&thorn;-outen eny more,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is as muche forte say</L>
<L>As stones &thorn;at ben in world al day.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Some vv. wanting: (to sum being &amp; liuing as to treon &amp; grases).</NOTE>. . . . .</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; &yogh;iue to o&thorn;ur &thorn;ynge</L>
<L N="432">Lyf, beoynge, and fleoynge,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. felynge</NOTE></L>
<L>And al &thorn;ise ben bi his hestes</L>
<L>To &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at men callen bestes.</L>
<L>To o&thorn;ur ha&thorn; he &yogh;iuen also</L>
<L N="436">Lyf, beoynge, and fleoinge<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. felynge</NOTE> bo,</L>
<L>And also more &thorn;ing of Renoun:</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; to hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. him</NOTE> I-&yogh;iue resoun;
<PB REF="00000241.tif" N="233"></L>
<L>&THORN;is &thorn;ing is I-&yogh;iuen &thorn;en</L>
<L N="440">Bo&thorn;e to Aungel and to men.</L>
<L>Stones no&thorn;ing may &thorn;ei feele,</L>
<L>Ne grases, and &yogh;it lyue &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="marg">sc. grases</NOTE> wele;</L>
<L>Bestes lyuen and fele&thorn; &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="444">Mon lyue&thorn; and waxe&thorn; as do&thorn; &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>And as a Best feele&thorn;, he do&thorn;,</L>
<L>And resun as Angel ha&thorn; he so&thorn;.</L>
<L>&THORN;enk &thorn;ou on &thorn;at dignite</L>
<L N="448">To creature of Mon is &yogh;iue so fre,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at his &yogh;ift wi&thorn; honoures</L>
<L>Sormounte&thorn; alle o&thorn;ur Creatoures.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore sei&thorn; Austyn &thorn;us fol riht:</L>
<L N="452">"I nolde ben Aungel, &thorn;ei&yogh; I miht,</L>
<L>Heore stat wolde I forsake &thorn;an</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at stude was purueyed for man."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enk also, Mon is wor&thorn;i</L>
<L N="456">Gret schenschipe, witerli,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wol not liue at godus wille</L>
<L>And his Comaundemens folfille,</L>
<L>Whon alle Creatures &thorn;at ben and were</L>
<L N="460">Ben ordeynd for monnes mestere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e goode bestes<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. creatures</NOTE> &thorn;at meke beo &thorn;on,</L>
<L>Beo&thorn; maad for &thorn;reo &thorn;inges for mon:</L>
<L>ffor to helpen vs wi&thorn;-outen fayle,</L>
<L N="464">As schep, hors, kuyn, in vre trauayle;</L>
<L>And vs to feede,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. hyde? cf. MS. Thornt.</NOTE> and vs to clo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>As le&thorn;er, fflesch<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. flax (Th. lyne).</NOTE> and wolle bo&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 vv. om.? cf. MS. Thornt.</NOTE></L>
<L>As Corn on eor&thorn;e and foules to be</L>
<L N="468">And also ffissches in &thorn;e S&eacute;&eacute;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e nuy&yogh;ing gra&yogh;es<NOTE PLACE="marg">= grases</NOTE> and bestes venimous</L>
<L>Ben ordeynd for &thorn;reo &thorn;inges to vs:</L>
<L>ffor chastisyng, and amendement,</L>
<L N="472">And for techyng wi&thorn; good entent.</L>
<L>Chatised and punissched we ben in route</L>
<L>Whon we ben hurt, and in such doute;<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>i.e.</I> in doubt of being hurt</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at is ful derwor&thorn;li</L>
<L N="476">Of Godus owne grete merci&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore bodili he com</L>
<L>To Chastise vs, bo&thorn;e god and Mon,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Th.: And &thorn;at es gret mercy of Godde &thorn;at he will chasty vs bodyly &thorn;at we be noght punescht lastandly.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="234"></L>
<L>&THORN;at we nere dampned wi&thorn;-outen ende</L>
<L N="480">ffor to dwelle wi&thorn; &thorn;e ffende.</L>
<L>We ben amendet whil we wol mynne</L>
<L>&THORN;at al vr wo come&thorn; fro vr synne;</L>
<L>Whon we seo &thorn;e so&thorn;e &thorn;us</L>
<L N="484">So smale creatures may greuen vs,</L>
<L>&THORN;en may we &thorn;inke &thorn;at we be</L>
<L>fful of ffebelnesse and of ffrelete,</L>
<L>We ouhten alle to beo ful Meke.</L>
<L N="488">Whon we godus werkes wol se and seke . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="marg">The 3rd point (teaching of noious creatures) is wanting.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou hast &thorn;us monyfolde</L>
<L>&THORN;e werkes of god folliche beo-holde,</L>
<L>Lift vp &thorn;yn herte wi&thorn; wille liht</L>
<L N="492">And &thorn;enk &thorn;e Muchelnes of Godus miht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;ing ordeyne&thorn; in delyt,</L>
<L>And al hit is for vre profyt.</L>
<L>A, Lord, Merci! what schul we say</L>
<L N="496">Bot we &thorn;e serue to &thorn;i pay?</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at he vs &yogh;af to Multiplie,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;o Bestes we distruye;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if God ordeyne and forme hem,</L>
<L N="500">We beo bisi to strui&yogh;e hem &thorn;en.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Some verses om.?</NOTE></L>
<L>Loue<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> &thorn;ei l.; loue = praise</NOTE> God for his goodnesse;</L>
<L>Honoure him for his feirnesse;</L>
<L>Glorifye him at &thorn;i redres</L>
<L N="504">And also for his grete prouwes.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;En is &thorn;er a-no&thorn;ur degre</L>
<L>Of Contemplaciun, I telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;e w&yogh;uche trewe and so&thorn; is hit:</L>
<L N="508">&THORN;at is cald holy writ;</L>
<L>&THORN;at wol teche &thorn;e wi&thorn;-Inne,</L>
<L>To drawe &thorn;e from peril of synne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e peyne forte douten ay,</L>
<L N="512">To loue &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at come may.</L>
<L>And euer loke, aboute &thorn;ou be</L>
<L>To holde wi&thorn; &thorn;e Charite,<NOTE PLACE="marg">513-14 ought to follow the 2 vv. om. after 518. The text is here very corrupt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is world also in alle wyse</L>
<L>&THORN;ou beo aboute to dispise;</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou what is to done,</L>
<L>And also loke what is to schone.<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 vv. om., cf. Spec.: Quan|tum illuminat intellectum in cognitione veritatis, et quan|tum inflammat affectum in fervore caritatis.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000243.tif" N="235"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;is two &thorn;inges seruen hit</L>
<L N="520">Al &thorn;at is writen in holy writ:</L>
<L>&THORN;is ben &thorn;o two, to trowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou schalt bo&thorn;e leeue<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. loue</NOTE> and knowe<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 vv. om.; Spec.: Ex scriptura debes extrahere et cognos|cere:</NOTE></L>
<L>W&yogh;uche ben &thorn;e seuen synnes dedly,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e seuen vertuwes &thorn;erby,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ten Comaundemens al-wey,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e twelf Articles of &thorn;e fey,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e seuen &yogh;iftus of &thorn;e holigost,</L>
<L N="528">And &thorn;e seuen sacremens most,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e seuen werkes of Merci,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e vertuwes of &thorn;e Ewangeli,<NOTE PLACE="marg">The 7 praiers of the Paternoster are om. here and in the poem.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e Ioyes also of heuen</L>
<L N="532">And &thorn;e peynes of helle to nemen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Off &thorn;e seuen dedly synnes.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEuen Sinnes &thorn;er ben dedly:</L>
<L>Pruide, Wra&thorn;&thorn;e, Sleu&thorn;e, and Envy,</L>
<L N="535">Glotonye, and gredines<NOTE PLACE="marg">= couetise, cf. v. 605.</NOTE> also,</L>
<L>Couetyse<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. Couetyse</NOTE> and lecheri, wi&thorn; hem to go.</L>
<L>Pruide no-&thorn;ing elles ne is</L>
<L>Bote loue to muche monnes hihnes.</L>
<L>And of him come&thorn; o&thorn;ur seuene:</L>
<L N="540">Vnbuxumnes, &thorn;at drawe&thorn; from heuene,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes god, be &thorn;ou serteyn,</L>
<L>Or elles a&yogh;eyn his souereyn;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to sei, I telle &thorn;e son,</L>
<L N="544">To leue &thorn;at is hym beden don&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us is he peired and not mendet,</L>
<L>He do&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. And do</NOTE> &thorn;ing &thorn;at him is defendet.</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing is Auauntyng,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">These vv. are corrupt; cf. V. pr. tr.: whon a mon avaunte&thorn; him of good &thorn;at he ha&thorn; of a-no&thorn;er or of an vuel (Th. of ill) &thorn;at he ha&thorn; of himself.</NOTE>Whon mon of o&thorn;ur monnes &thorn;ing</L>
<L>And to him-self bi wikkednes</L>
<L>He hate&thorn; and bringe&thorn; him in distres.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde spice is Ypocrisye,</L>
<L N="552">Whon mon feine&thorn; him to haue in hi&yogh;e</L>
<L>Holines &thorn;at he ha&thorn; nouht,</L>
<L>And do&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Vern. pr. tr. hut, Th. hydes.</NOTE> his wikkednes in dede and &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e spice, hit is &thorn;en</L>
<L N="556">Dispit &thorn;at he ha&thorn; to o&thorn;ur men,
<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="236"></L>
<L>Whon mon<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. men</NOTE> reherce&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. repreue&thorn;? (Th. lesses).</NOTE> o&thorn;ur mennes good dede,</L>
<L>He wolde beo holde &thorn;e beter in leode.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e spice is Arrogaunce boun,</L>
<L N="560">Whon a Mon Make&thorn; comparisoun</L>
<L>Bi-twenen his vuel doynges</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ur mennes for eny &thorn;inges,</L>
<L>ffor his wikkednes and trespas</L>
<L N="564">Scholde seme muche &thorn;e las.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sixte spice is boldnes<NOTE PLACE="marg">so V. pr. tr., Th. vnshamefulnesse</NOTE> in nome,</L>
<L>Whon a Mon ha&thorn; no schome</L>
<L>Of his grete wikkednes for&thorn;i</L>
<L N="568">&THORN;at he ha&thorn; don so openly.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen&thorn;e Elaciun is to rede,</L>
<L>Whon mon is proud of his vuel dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt wite bo&thorn;e in and out</L>
<L N="572">&THORN;at &thorn;is &thorn;reo &thorn;inges make&thorn; Mon prout:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to wite and haue in muynde</L>
<L>&THORN;e goodes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; of kuynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is of<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. of?</NOTE> feirnes, or streng&thorn;e to say,</L>
<L N="576">Or souereyn wit, or Noblay&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at noblei calle I in &thorn;is stage</L>
<L>He &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;at he</NOTE> is prout of hei lynage.</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing is and euer was</L>
<L N="580">&THORN;e godus &thorn;at men han of purchas,</L>
<L>As wittes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Th. cunnynge, V. sciens, Sp. scientia.</NOTE> vertuwes euerichane,</L>
<L>Graces,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> grace</NOTE> Dignite, and eke good fame.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde is worldly godus &thorn;us,</L>
<L N="584">As Clo&thorn;inge, housynge, Rentes, possessions,</L>
<L>Meyne, and also gret honour</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e worldly &thorn;inges in eueri stour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Off Envye come&thorn;, haue we no care,</L>
<L N="588">Ioye of o&thorn;ur mennes vuel-fare,</L>
<L>And also to make sweryng<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. serwyng</NOTE> gret</L>
<L>ffor o&thorn;ur mennes wel-farynge and get.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at may ben in herte stinkynge,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sp. per afflictionem, Th. with lykynge</NOTE></L>
<L N="592">Or in Mou&thorn; &thorn;orwh Bakbytynge,</L>
<L>Or in werkes of vuel entent</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh defaute of good entisement.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sp. per subtractionem boni vel incitamentum mali.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Chidyng waxe&thorn; of Wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;en,</L>
<L N="596">Swellyng of herte amonges men,
<PB REF="00000245.tif" N="237"></L>
<L>Schomeful wordus &thorn;enke to seyn,</L>
<L>Sclaundre, and also gret dedeyn.</L>
<L>Of slou&yogh;&thorn;e come&thorn; drerines, wikkednus, and swelling</L>
<L N="600">Of foul wille, wi&thorn; gret &thorn;retyng,</L>
<L>Aboute godus comaundemens not to do,</L>
<L>Wonhope, Rechelesnesse also,<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 601 and 602 to be transp. Sp. desperatio, negligentia erga dei pr&aelig;cepta.</NOTE></L>
<L>Outrage wille of herte to sen</L>
<L N="604">Aboute &thorn;inges &thorn;at defendet ben.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Off gredines<NOTE PLACE="marg">= couetise</NOTE> come&thorn; tresun prest,</L>
<L>fforswerynges, and wikked rest,<NOTE PLACE="marg">so MS. Th. (V. feble rest); Sp. inquietudo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Violence, and hardnes of herte</L>
<L N="608">A&yogh;eynes Merci wi&thorn; muchel vnquerte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enne &thorn;er come&thorn; of Glotonye</L>
<L>Veyne gladnesse, and Lecherye,</L>
<L>fful&thorn;i,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. ful&thorn;e, V. Pr. tr. ful&thorn;e, Sp. immunditia</NOTE> Muche speche in hi&yogh;ing,</L>
<L N="612">And ful feble vndurstondyng.</L>
<L>Of Lecherie come&thorn; blyndnes of herte,</L>
<L>In Orisun wi&thorn; muchel vnqwerte&mdash;</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e preyers he scholde in be</L>
<L N="616">Nis &thorn;er wi&thorn; him no stabulte;</L>
<L>Of him come&thorn; fool-hastines also,</L>
<L>Loue of him-self wol wi&thorn; hym go,</L>
<L>Hate of god &thorn;at vs bouht,</L>
<L N="620">Loue of &thorn;is world &thorn;at is nouht,</L>
<L>Drede of<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. and</NOTE> dispeir Is al his wone</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e world &thorn;at is to come.</L>
<L>&THORN;eose ben &thorn;e seuen dedly synnes for&thorn;i.</L>
<L N="624">Wel may &thorn;ei ben cald dedli:</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste &thorn;reo dispoyle&thorn; &thorn;e mon,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e abate&thorn; hym as he con,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e bynde&thorn; him in bonde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sp. prosternit eum</NOTE></L>
<L N="628">&THORN;e Sixte deseyue&thorn; him in londe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen&thorn;e him put in &thorn;raldome,</L>
<L>Him to muche harm and schome.</L>
<L>ffor Pruide, beo &thorn;ou &thorn;erof bolde,</L>
<L>Bi-nyme&thorn; a Mon his god<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. good, cf. v. 652.</NOTE> to holde;</L>
<L N="633">And Envye bi-nyme&thorn; also him fro</L>
<L>His euencristen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. owne self, cf. 654.</NOTE> from god to go;</L>
<L>Wra&thorn;&thorn;he, &thorn;at is a schrewed delf,</L>
<L N="636">Bi-nyme&thorn; a Mon his owne self;
<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="238"></L>
<L>Of Slou&thorn;e &thorn;at ilke foule synne</L>
<L>Euere hit tormente&thorn; hymme;<NOTE PLACE="marg">so Th.</NOTE></L>
<L>Gredines in eueri toun</L>
<L N="640">Caste&thorn; &thorn;e vnsely mon adoun;</L>
<L>Glotenye deseyue&thorn; hym in luytel stage;</L>
<L>Lecherie put him in foul seruage.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Seuen blessynges of god.<NOTE PLACE="marg">This passage, om. in MS. Thornt., agrees with the pr. tr. in MS. Vern.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A&yogh;ein &thorn;is seuene vices &thorn;us</L>
<L N="644">Ordeynt remedie sone Ihesus,</L>
<L>And send us seuen vertuwes in hihe</L>
<L>In &thorn;e holy Ewangelye,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Math. 5, 3.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sei&thorn; &thorn;us in &thorn;is Manere</L>
<L N="648">As &yogh;e schul her aftur here:</L>
<L>"Blesset be &thorn;e meke of spirit euene,</L>
<L>ffor heoren is &thorn;e kynedom of heuene"&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is is a&yogh;ein pruide and mood,</L>
<L N="652">&THORN;at bi-nyme&thorn; a Mon his god so good.</L>
<L>"I-blesset beo &thorn;e deboner &thorn;en</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes heore euen-cristen men,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei schul haue in to heore honde</L>
<L N="656">&THORN;e lond &thorn;at is euer lastonde"&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is is a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e foule Envye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bi-reue&thorn; mon his euencristen trie.</L>
<L>"Blesset beo &thorn;o &thorn;at wepen ofte,</L>
<L N="660">ffor &thorn;ei schul beo cumfortet on lofte"&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is is a&yogh;eynes wra&thorn;&thorn;e to delue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bi-nyme&thorn; a Mon him-selue.</L>
<L>"Blesset be &thorn;e Merciable men,</L>
<L N="664">ffor god schal haue Merci of hem"&mdash;</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes gredynes &thorn;is mot be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of no mon he ha&thorn; pite.</L>
<L>"Blesset beo &thorn;o &thorn;at hungri be &thorn;en</L>
<L N="668">Aftur Rihtful, disyr forte ken,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei schul be fed in blisse"&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is is a&yogh;ein Slou&thorn;e and rechelesnesse.</L>
<L>"Blesset mote &thorn;e clene of herte be,</L>
<L N="672">&THORN;e face of god schul &thorn;ei se"&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is is a-&yogh;eyn glotenye doyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer &thorn;enke&thorn; on flesch lykyng.
<PB REF="00000247.tif" N="239"></L>
<L>"Blesset be &thorn;e pesybles i-tald,</L>
<L N="676">Godus children schul &thorn;ei be cald"&mdash;</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes lecherie &thorn;is ordeynt wes,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e lechour na&thorn; neuer pes;</L>
<L>He na&thorn; no pes for his beste,</L>
<L N="680">He may in herte neuer ha reste.</L>
<L>&THORN;eose ben &thorn;e vertuwes seuene</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e vices forte nempne.<NOTE PLACE="marg">The last part of the Chapter in the Speculum is omitted.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Seuen medicines for &thorn;e seuen dedly synnes.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Afftur &thorn;is he wol vs teche,</L>
<L N="684">God &thorn;at is vr goode leche,</L>
<L>&THORN;is seuen medicines, trie to vs,</L>
<L>To helen vs of seuen Maledius,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he conferme&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">The poet or scribe took conferme&thorn; for conforme&thorn;.</NOTE> hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. men.</NOTE></L>
<L N="688">In to<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;o</NOTE> seuen vertuwes &thorn;en</L>
<L>Bi vertue of &thorn;e holy gost,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is lord of mihtes most.</L>
<L>&THORN;eose &thorn;ei ben to nempne &thorn;at &thorn;ing:</L>
<L N="692">&THORN;e holigost of wisdam and of vndurstondyng,</L>
<L>And also, wi&thorn;-outen fayle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e gost of streng&thorn;e and of counsayle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e gost of wit and of pite,</L>
<L N="696">&THORN;e gost of doute of god mot be.</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;is seuen &yogh;iftes god &yogh;af mon</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at he ha&thorn; neode of &thorn;on</L>
<L>To his Bodiliche lyf</L>
<L N="700">And to his soule wi&thorn;-outen strif.</L>
<L>Seo hou mon may in his mode</L>
<L>Leue &thorn;e vuel and take &thorn;e gode:</L>
<L>To leue &thorn;e vuel &thorn;at is forbod</L>
<L N="704">Teche&thorn; &thorn;e gost of &thorn;e doute of god;</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode to do, I telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at teche&thorn; &thorn;e gost of pite.</L>
<L>Two &thorn;inges &thorn;er beo &thorn;an</L>
<L N="708">&THORN;at lette&thorn; good doinge of man:</L>
<L>&THORN;at on is worldly riches,</L>
<L>And also gret frouwar[d]nes<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sp. adversitas mundi, Th. tribulacion, cf. v. 718.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Riches, hit mon deseyue&thorn;,</L>
<L N="712">ffrouwardnes from god him weyue&thorn;.
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="240"></L>
<L>&THORN;erfore a mon schal dispise</L>
<L>Worldly richesse in alle wyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he beo not deseyuet beo hit:</L>
<L N="716">&THORN;at vs teche&thorn; &thorn;e gost of wit.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou schalt suffre stalwor&thorn;li</L>
<L>Tribulacions and anguyses worldli,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou neuere ouercomen be:</L>
<L N="720">&THORN;us teche&thorn; &thorn;e gost of streng&thorn;e to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;eose foure ben souereynly</L>
<L>To bodiliche lyf for&thorn;y.</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur longen wi&thorn;-outen strif</L>
<L N="724">Alle to &thorn;e gostly lyf.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;reo maners bi resun</L>
<L>Ben of Contemplaciun:</L>
<L>On is [in] Creatures bi vre entent:</L>
<L N="728">&THORN;at teche&thorn; &thorn;e gost of entendement.</L>
<L>A-no&thorn;ur in holi writ also,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou seost what &thorn;ou schalt do</L>
<L>And what &thorn;ing &thorn;ou schalt lete:</L>
<L N="732">&THORN;at teche&thorn; &thorn;e gost of counseil swete.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde is of him-self, god and Mon:</L>
<L>&THORN;at teche&thorn; &thorn;e gost of wisdom.</L>
<L>Now seo we now hou Ihesu &thorn;e lele</L>
<L N="736">Is euer aboute vr help and hele.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>&THORN;e ten comaundemens of god.<NOTE PLACE="marg">This passage agrees with MS. Thornton.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Afftur &thorn;is schaltou witen &thorn;en</L>
<L>W&yogh;uche ben &thorn;e comaundemens ten.</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste, hit is be &thorn;in a-cord:</L>
<L N="740">Worschipe to<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;ou</NOTE> O god, vr lord.</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;e fend &thorn;e may not derue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou him only worschipe and serue.</L>
<L>Worschupe him &thorn;orw fei&thorn; and mode,</L>
<L N="744">And serue him wi&thorn; werkes gode.</L>
<L>&THORN;enk &yogh;if &thorn;ou haue alle tym</L>
<L>Trewely honoured hym,</L>
<L>And ouer alle o&thorn;ur &thorn;inges</L>
<L N="748">Serue[d] hym and his biddynges;</L>
<L>&THORN;enk &yogh;if &thorn;ou haue &yogh;olden him &thorn;i beo-hest</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou be-hi&yogh;test hym mest or lest:
<PB REF="00000249.tif" N="241"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou him be-hi&yogh;test fei&thorn;ful trist</L>
<L N="752">Whon &thorn;ou toke &thorn;i Baptist;</L>
<L>Or &yogh;if &thorn;ou haue lasse penaunce don</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;e was leyd penaunce vppon.</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;is comaundement al-to-gader</L>
<L N="756">Mon is ordeynt to god &thorn;e ffader.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;At o&thorn;ur bi-heste is forto seyn:</L>
<L>Nempne not godus nome in veyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;at is defendet lesynge,</L>
<L N="760">ffalshede, and forswerynge.</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;at is eueri good mon in wone</L>
<L>Ordeynt touward god &thorn;e Sone,</L>
<L>ffor he him-self bere&thorn; witnesse</L>
<L N="764">And sei&thorn; "I am so&thorn;nesse" expresse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E &thorn;ridde heste is forte say</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou kepe wel &thorn;in haly-day.</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to sei, vch an heih fest</L>
<L N="768">&THORN;at come&thorn; &thorn;e to, mest or lest,</L>
<L>Haue &thorn;in herte in pes and reste most.</L>
<L>&THORN;at ordeyne&thorn; mon to &thorn;e holygost.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;eose &thorn;reo hestes teche&thorn; ow and me</L>
<L N="772">To beren vs to god &thorn;e Trinite,</L>
<L>To whos liknesse Mon is mad</L>
<L>In soule, &thorn;at scholde be trewe and sad.</L>
<L>Seuene o&thorn;ure teche&thorn; men</L>
<L N="776">Hou &thorn;ei schul bere hem to her euen-cristen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E furste is: worschupe &thorn;ou folly</L>
<L>fflesch-fadur and modur and &thorn;i gostly.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at in two Maner of &thorn;inges:</L>
<L N="780">In boxumnesse and for-berynges,</L>
<L>And help hem bi &thorn;i pouwer in dede</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue nede.</L>
<L>&THORN;en schalt &thorn;ou beo of long lyf</L>
<L N="784">In eor&thorn;e here wi&thorn;-outen stryf.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt haue &thorn;e lyf longe,</L>
<L>Worschupe &thorn;i god<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> hem or him (the scribe took "him" for god).</NOTE> wi&thorn; wille stronge,</L>
<L>ffor he<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;at</NOTE> &thorn;e brou&yogh;t, wite hit wel,</L>
<L N="788">Al &thorn;i lyf euerich a del.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur heste, hit is &thorn;on:</L>
<L>In no wey &thorn;at &thorn;ou sle no mon.
<PB REF="00000250.tif" N="242"></L>
<L>&THORN;enne schaltou wite here,</L>
<L N="792">Mon-slau&yogh;t is in &thorn;reo manere,</L>
<L>In &thorn;reo manere hit is ful smerte:</L>
<L>Of hond, of tonge, and of herte.</L>
<L>Of hond hit is wi&thorn;-outen me&thorn;</L>
<L N="796">Whon a Mon wi&thorn; wepene sle&thorn;,</L>
<L>Or whon he putte&thorn; him in dede<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sp. in loco mortis</NOTE></L>
<L>In prisun or in o&thorn;ur stede&mdash;</L>
<L N="799">&THORN;at ilke doing cause may be</L>
<L>Of his de&thorn;, as I sei &thorn;e. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="marg">Some vv. wanting (manslaughter by tongue).</NOTE></L>
<L>Monslau&yogh;t of herte is also here</L>
<L>In o&thorn;ur two vuel manere:</L>
<L>Whon Mon coueyte&thorn; o&thorn;ures de&thorn; in hi&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="804">Or for de-faute lete&thorn; him dye</L>
<L>And nil not helpen him in &thorn;at mester</L>
<L>Ne him deliuere, &yogh;if he ha pouwer.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;En is hit &thorn;e &thorn;ridde heste:</L>
<L N="808">To do no lecherie, mest ne leste.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at wol lyue wi&thorn;-outen dy&yogh;ing</L>
<L>In &thorn;e blisse of heuene-kyng,</L>
<L>Him weore neod to kepe ful boun</L>
<L N="812">His dedlyche lyf from corupcioun,</L>
<L>ffrom &thorn;at corupciun, sei I,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wol come of his bodi.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E ffeor&thorn;e heste is, witerli:</L>
<L N="816">To do no &thorn;ef&thorn;e ne Robberi.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at wol spare o&thorn;urmennes lyf,</L>
<L>Bi-nyme him nouht wi&thorn; no strif,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh w&yogh;uche bi-nymynge</L>
<L N="820">&THORN;ou mai&yogh;t bi-reue his lyuynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E ffyf&thorn;e heste &thorn;en is &thorn;is:</L>
<L>&THORN;ow schalt bere no fals witnes</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes &thorn;in euen-cristen &thorn;en,</L>
<L N="824">Ne also &thorn;ou schalt not cumforten hem</L>
<L>&THORN;at wolden liue in reste and ro (!)<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cf. Th.: &thorn;ou sall noght bere f. w. agaynes thyne euencristyn with hym &thorn;at will noye hym or sla hym.</NOTE></L>
<L>Heore neih&yogh;ebors harm to do.</L>
<L>ffor bi a fals witnesse i-bore</L>
<L N="828">A Mon may worldli beo forlore.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou no counseil in no res</L>
<L>To him &thorn;at wolde liuen in pes
<PB REF="00000251.tif" N="243"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hys euen-cristen to debate;</L>
<L N="832">ffor &yogh;if &thorn;ou dost, hit torne&thorn; to wrake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E sixte heste wi&thorn;-outen strif:</L>
<L>Coueite &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebors wyf,</L>
<L>Ne non of his seruauns also,</L>
<L N="836">Ne nou&yogh;t &thorn;at him longe&thorn; to.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E seue&thorn;e heste is &thorn;us, I-wis:</L>
<L>Coueyte &thorn;ou not &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebors godis.</L>
<L>&THORN;is two hestes acordyng ben</L>
<L N="840">To &thorn;o bifore as &yogh;e may sen,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he sei&thorn; to &thorn;e in hi&yogh;e</L>
<L>"Do no &thorn;ef&thorn;e, ne lecherie,"</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;at ha&thorn; wikked wille and smert,</L>
<L N="844">Wikked entent is in his hert,</L>
<L>He may not longe for no &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Holden him from mis-doing.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore I warne &thorn;e nou so,</L>
<L N="848">&THORN;at &thorn;ou lecherie ne do;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt not stele nou,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur mennes good coueite not &thorn;ou.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos ben &thorn;e ten hestes to say</L>
<L N="852">&THORN;at god &yogh;af Moyses in &thorn;e Mount of Synay.</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste &thorn;reo, wite&thorn; hit wel,</L>
<L>Ben to godus honour eueridel;</L>
<L>And to &thorn;i-self longen &thorn;e seuene,</L>
<L N="856">To louen alle cristene euene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>&THORN;e seuen vertues of god.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Aftur scha[l]tou wite w&yogh;uche ben</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen vertuwes vppon to sen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to wite: ffei&thorn;, hope, and loue,</L>
<L N="860">Qweyntise, Rihtfulnes a-boue,</L>
<L>Temperaunce, and streng&thorn;e mest.</L>
<L>Of O Matere ben &thorn;eos two<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. ten?</NOTE> hest</L>
<L>And &thorn;e seue vertuwes in presens,</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;is is &thorn;e differens:</L>
<L>&THORN;e ten hestes teche&thorn; hou<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. what</NOTE> &thorn;ou schalt do,</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen vertuwes teche&thorn; &thorn;e matere<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. manere Cf. Th.: The x comandmente&yogh; kennes vs what we sall do, and &thorn;e vii vertus kennes vs how we sall doo.</NOTE> also.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffurste &thorn;reo &thorn;at ben aboue,</L>
<L N="868">Is to wite, ffei&thorn;, Hope, and Loue,
<PB REF="00000252.tif" N="244"></L>
<L>&THORN;ise &thorn;reo, &thorn;ei ordeyne hou &thorn;ou schalt</L>
<L>Touward god liue &thorn;at al walt;</L>
<L>And &thorn;is o&thorn;ere her-aftur scuene</L>
<L N="872">Teche &thorn;e to knowe &thorn;e wey to heuene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;E<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Ze</NOTE> wite wel, my leue ffrende,</L>
<L>Alle beo we formed to on ende:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to seye, god to knowe,</L>
<L N="876">Him to loue and honoure we owe.</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;reo &thorn;inges, ar we wende,</L>
<L>Beon nedful to come to vre ende:</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne is &thorn;is &thorn;at on</L>
<L N="880">To wite whodur we schulle gon;</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur, &thorn;at we ben willi</L>
<L>To gon in trust ful treweli;</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne is &thorn;e &thorn;ridde &thorn;inge:</L>
<L N="884">To haue trust of wel goinge&mdash;</L>
<L>Gret folye hit were to fo or ffrende</L>
<L>To bi-ginne &thorn;ing he may not ende.</L>
<L>A Mon &thorn;at wol wel do &thorn;er-tille,</L>
<L N="888">Meste ha miht, Connyng, and wille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to say &thorn;us &yogh;ow to:</L>
<L>&THORN;at he con, Mai, and wol [wel] do.</L>
<L>But for we haue not vs ner</L>
<L N="892">Of vr-self Miht,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Wil</NOTE> Wit, ne pouwer,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore ha&thorn; god &yogh;iuen vs tille</L>
<L>ffei&thorn;, alle &thorn;ise to folfille.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sp.: ideo donavit nobis Deus fidem ad implendum defectum cognitionis, spem ad implendum defectum potestatis, charitatem ad ordinandum voluntatem ad unum &amp; aliud.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffei&thorn; ordeyne&thorn; vs to god &thorn;e sone,</L>
<L N="896">To whom is a-propred wisdam in wone;</L>
<L>Hope ordeyne&thorn; vs to &thorn;e ffadur riht,</L>
<L>To whom is a-propred Miht;</L>
<L>Loue to &thorn;e Holigost do&thorn; vs dresse,</L>
<L N="900">To whom is a-propred alle goodnesse.</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore of god wi&thorn;-outen lesynge</L>
<L>ffei&thorn; do&thorn; vs to haue knowynge;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at knowynge of<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. sei&thorn;; cf. Th.: and &thorn;at knaweynge vs sayse &thorn;at he es wondyrfull[y] fre &thorn;at one &thorn;is manere and &thorn;us largely gyffes of his gudnes.</NOTE> god wi&thorn; mood</L>
<L>&YOGH;iue&thorn; vs frely and largeli of his good:</L>
<L>And out of &thorn;at godnesse<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. knowyng</NOTE> is i-crope</L>
<L>And come&thorn; to vs &thorn;enne hope;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at knowyng, I vndurstod,</L>
<L N="908">&THORN;er he sei&thorn; vs &thorn;at he is good,
<PB REF="00000253.tif" N="245"></L>
<L>&THORN;er-of come&thorn; feir aboue</L>
<L N="910">&THORN;e &thorn;ridde vertue &thorn;at is loue,</L>
<L>ffor vch a &thorn;ing, Resun whi,</L>
<L N="912">Schal loue &thorn;e goode kuyndeli.<NOTE PLACE="marg">The 4 cardinal virtues are treated separately v. 999, p. 247 ff, as in Th. and in the Spec.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>&THORN;e twolue articles of &thorn;e fey.<NOTE PLACE="marg">This passage differs from Spec., Th. and V. pr. tr.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;En schaltou wite, as I &thorn;e sei,</L>
<L>Whuche ben &thorn;e .xij. Articles of &thorn;e fei.</L>
<L>ffurst, god is on in him-self for to lende,</L>
<L N="916">And &thorn;re persones, wi&thorn;-outen ende,</L>
<L>And is verrey God and lord</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;ing made wi&thorn; his word.</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur article is ful trye:</L>
<L N="920">&THORN;at he tok flesch and blod of Maide Marie.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde Article<NOTE PLACE="marg">belongs to the 2nd in Spec., Th. and V. pr. tr.</NOTE>: &thorn;at he was bore &thorn;on</L>
<L>Of hire, so&thorn;fast god and mon.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffer&thorn;e Article, we sen hit red:</L>
<L N="924">Vndur Pilatus pouwer was he ded,</L>
<L>Not for nede, I sei ow tille,</L>
<L>But vs to buye of his ffreo wille.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">belongs to the preceding in Spec. and V. pr. tr.; is om. in Th.</NOTE> is, so&thorn; to telle:</L>
<L N="928">&THORN;at his soule wente doun to helle</L>
<L>And fet hem out in to his blis,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;o &thorn;at weren his.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sixte: &thorn;at he ros wi&thorn;-outen striue,</L>
<L N="932">God and Mon, from de&thorn; to lyue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seue&thorn;e is in vre sawes:</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;e fulle fourti dawes</L>
<L>Of his blisful and hard dy&yogh;ing</L>
<L N="936">He steih to heuene &thorn;er he is kyng;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at is lord of S&eacute;&eacute; and Sond</L>
<L>Sitte&thorn; &thorn;er on his fadur riht hond.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">In the Spec. &amp;c. these last articles belong to the preced|ing (5th), and the 7 sacra|ments form the 7 last.</NOTE>&THORN;e eihte&thorn;e is: he schal present</L>
<L>Beon atte day of Iugement,</L>
<L N="941">Goode and wikkede schal he deme</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;ing as him wol bi-seeme.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ni&thorn;e is wi&thorn;-outen bost:</L>
<L N="944">&THORN;at in god is &thorn;e holygost,</L>
<L>And euermore so wol be,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde persone<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. persones</NOTE> of &thorn;e trinite;
<PB REF="00000254.tif" N="246"></L>
<L>Of whom, &thorn;at is so hei&yogh; in blis,</L>
<L N="948">Al-holichirche halewed hit is.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ten&thorn;e is of comynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. comonynge</NOTE> of holi men,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to sei fulliche of hem</L>
<L>&THORN;at ben lymes of holychirche</L>
<L N="952">And no dedly synne nul worche,</L>
<L>Han part of alle goode dedes sone</L>
<L>&THORN;at in holi chirche ben done.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Elleue&thorn;e is: &thorn;orw &thorn;e sacrament</L>
<L N="956">Of holichurche wi&thorn; good entent</L>
<L>&THORN;e goode schul haue for&yogh;iuenesse</L>
<L>Of heore synnes more and lesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;e twelf&thorn;e is &thorn;at Mon and wyue</L>
<L N="960">Schullen arise from de&thorn; to lyue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;retten&thorn;e is: &thorn;e goode schul haue</L>
<L>Euerlastinde lyf &thorn;at schal hem saue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;is o&thorn;ure &thorn;enne schul wende</L>
<L N="964">To lastyng pyne wi&thorn;-outen ende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>&THORN;e Seuen sacromens of holy churche.<NOTE PLACE="marg">In Spec., Th. and V. pr. tr. included in the creed as forming the 7 last articles. The text is abridged.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Afftur &thorn;is schul &yogh;e here bi-ginne</L>
<L>&THORN;e sacramens seuen &thorn;at fordon synne;</L>
<L>He hem ordeynde synne to wi&thorn;-stonde</L>
<L>And &thorn;e gode to take on honde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste is cald Baptisme,</L>
<L>&THORN;at child take&thorn; er &thorn;en his crisme;</L>
<L>&THORN;at clanse&thorn; mon of &thorn;at synne</L>
<L N="972">&THORN;at vr forme-fader brou&yogh;t us inne.</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur sacrament is of renoun</L>
<L>And is cald Confirmacioun:</L>
<L>ffor whon he is so cristned &thorn;on,</L>
<L N="976">He conferme&thorn; &thorn;e holigost in mon.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde is penaunce to biginne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at frete&thorn; a-wei &thorn;e ful&thorn;e of synne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feor&thorn;e is sacrament of &thorn;e Auter,</L>
<L N="980">&THORN;at conferme&thorn; mon hol and feer</L>
<L>And &yogh;iue&thorn; him streng&thorn;e good wi&thorn;-alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he eft-sones in synne ne falle;</L>
<L>&THORN;at sacrament reconsile&thorn; him ay,</L>
<L N="984">Susteyne&thorn; him, &thorn;at he ne falle may.
<PB REF="00000255.tif" N="247"></L>
<L>&THORN;e ffif&thorn;e is ordre, &thorn;at &yogh;iue&thorn; power</L>
<L>To Men ordeynet in heore mester</L>
<L>&THORN;e sacramens to make and worche,</L>
<L N="988">To serue wi&thorn; god and holi churche.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sixte is Matrimoyne to bigynne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at defende&thorn; dedly synne</L>
<L>In werkes of generaciun &thorn;on</L>
<L N="992">Bi-twene mon and wommon.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seue&thorn;e is &thorn;e enoyling</L>
<L>Of seke in perel of di&yogh;ing,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is in Aleggaunce</L>
<L N="996">Of Bodi and soules penaunce.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos ben &thorn;e sacramens &thorn;en,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. teu</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at longe&thorn; to alle cristene Men.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>&THORN;e seuen<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. four, as in Spec.</NOTE> principal vertues.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Aftur &thorn;is nou wite we schal</L>
<L N="1000">W&yogh;uche ben &thorn;e iiij. vertuwes principal,</L>
<L>Bi w&yogh;uche vche monnes lyf here</L>
<L>Is gouernet in &thorn;is world so dere:</L>
<L>Qweyntise, Rihtfulnes bi chaunce,</L>
<L N="1004">Streng&thorn;e, and also Temperaunce.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;eos foure speke&thorn; &thorn;e holygost</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Bok of wisdam most</L>
<L>&THORN;at no &thorn;ing bi good delyt</L>
<L N="1008">In eor&thorn;e to Mon do&thorn; more profyt.</L>
<L>ffor hose to do wel vndurstode,</L>
<L>He moste knowe vuel from goode,</L>
<L>Also, he seo&thorn; here bi lettre,</L>
<L N="1012">He moste knowe &thorn;e gode from &thorn;e bettre:</L>
<L>&THORN;at vs teche&thorn; in alle wyse</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;yng &thorn;at is called queyntyse.</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;ou hast &thorn;us i-chose,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wikked from &thorn;e goode to lose<NOTE PLACE="marg">Spec.: Et quando elegisti bonum de malo aut de duo|busbonis melius, &amp; tune debes relinquere malum &amp; facere bonum, &amp; dimittere minus bonum &amp; facere maius bonum: &amp; haec virtus Iustitia appellatur.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at teche&thorn; &thorn;e vertue to distresse</L>
<L>&THORN;at is cleped Rihtfulnesse.</L>
<L>Two &thorn;inges &thorn;er ben in world ful &thorn;ikke</L>
<L N="1020">Lette&thorn; mon do good and take&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. forsake?</NOTE> wikke:</L>
<L>&THORN;e riches of &thorn;is world is on,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle weyes deseyue&thorn; mon,
<PB REF="00000256.tif" N="248"></L>
<L N="1023">He disseyue&thorn; mon in mony &thorn;inges,</L>
<L>&thorn;orwh swete restynges;</L>
<L>A-no&thorn;ur is Contek of worldli strif<NOTE PLACE="marg">Spec. adversitas, Th. tribulacyon</NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes mon, doun hym to dryf.</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes richesse mesure &thorn;e in tide,</L>
<L N="1028">Beo &thorn;ou not risen to muche in pride:</L>
<L>&THORN;at vertu is wi&thorn;-outen distaunce</L>
<L>&THORN;is &thorn;at men calle&thorn; temperaunce.</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes worldly cuntek and strif</L>
<L N="1032">Loke brennynge wille<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sp. audacia animi, Th. hardines</NOTE> beo &thorn;e rif,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou beo not so feble boun</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e world &thorn;e caste a-doun:</L>
<L>And &thorn;at vertue in brede and leng&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1036">Is &thorn;at &thorn;at is i-cleped streng&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Seuen werkes of mercy.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Afftur schaltou wite redili</L>
<L>W&yogh;uche ben seuen werkes of Merci.</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste is, &yogh;iue &thorn;e hungri mete;</L>
<L N="1040">&THORN;at o&thorn;ur, drinke &thorn;e &thorn;rusti to gete;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde, clo&thorn;e &thorn;e naked bi tymes;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e, to herborwe pilgrymes;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e, prisons to visyte swete;</L>
<L N="1044">&THORN;e Sixte is, cumforte &thorn;e seke;</L>
<L>&THORN;e seue&thorn;e, in certeyn place<NOTE PLACE="marg">Tob. 1, 20.</NOTE> we rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to helpe burie &thorn;e dede.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;en maistou sey in tour and toun:</L>
<L N="1048">"I &thorn;at am in Religioun,</L>
<L>I naue no pouwer to &yogh;iue no mete,</L>
<L>Ne drinke ne herborwe to hem gete,</L>
<L>Ne clo&thorn;ing to hem haue I non,</L>
<L N="1052">To visite prisones may I not gon:</L>
<L>I am in o&thorn;ur monnes pouwer;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore me were beter seculer,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I mihte do trewely</L>
<L N="1056">Alle &thorn;eose dedes of Mercy."</L>
<L>&THORN;enk not &thorn;us, I rede &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Leste &thorn;ou her-Inne deseyued be.</L>
<L>Betere hit is to &thorn;e in eueri toun</L>
<L N="1060">To haue pite and compassioun
<PB REF="00000257.tif" N="249"></L>
<L>In &thorn;yn herte in alle weyse</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at &thorn;ou seost in Meseyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;ou heddest al &thorn;e world wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1064">Hit forth to dele for charite.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;i-self, as I sei nou,</L>
<L>And more &thorn;en al &thorn;e world &yogh;iuestou.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Some vv. wanting. Spec.: Sed jam posses dicere: verum est quod melius est homini dare seipsum quam de suo; sed multum praevalet dare vnum cum alio quam vnum illorum per se. Dico quod non est ita: Vtrum praevalet vocari Dominus quam eius servus? Scis bene quod praevalet vocari Dominus. Sed illi qui &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei &thorn;at suffre in alle wyse</L>
<L>Chele, hungur, defaute and Miseise,</L>
<L>Ihesu sei&thorn; wher-so he go</L>
<L>And him-self he clepe&thorn; &thorn;o;</L>
<L>&THORN;us he sei&thorn; in his gospel&mdash;</L>
<L N="1072">Hose wol hit seche, may fynde hit wel:</L>
<L>"What to &thorn;e leste of myne don be,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e hit don al to me."</L>
<L N="1075">Whe&thorn;er weor beter or more sen</L>
<L>To Iuge or elles Iugged to ben?<NOTE PLACE="marg">Spec. adds: Tu scis bene quod praevalet judicare: et hoc faciunt pauperes</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;erfore to pore make &thorn;e liche,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e pore schul Iugge &thorn;e riche;</L>
<L>As vr lord sei&thorn; feire and wel</L>
<L N="1080">In his owne goode gospel:<NOTE PLACE="marg">Math. 19, 28.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&YOGH;e &thorn;at alle &thorn;ynges haue to proue,</L>
<L>Leue&thorn; hem for me and for my loue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Math.: Vos qui reliquistis omnia et secuti est is me &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>And at &thorn;e grete day of dome,</L>
<L N="1084">Whon I schal sitten in my trone&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ere &thorn;o men schul me se</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Seete of my Maieste&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &yogh;e</NOTE> schul sitte on twelf seges wel</L>
<L N="1088">And Iugge &thorn;e twelf kuyndes of Israel."</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er weore hit better at &thorn;e leste</L>
<L>Haue heuene in possession or in bi-heste?<NOTE PLACE="marg">Spec. adds: Certum est quod in possessione: sic habent pauperes</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;us sei&thorn; God, wite&thorn; wel,</L>
<L>In his holy Godspel:<NOTE PLACE="marg">Math. 5.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1093">"Blesset mote &thorn;e pore of spirit be,</L>
<L>ffor heoren is heuene," as I sei &thorn;e.</L>
<L>He sei&thorn; not &thorn;us in his steuen</L>
<L N="1096">Heoren "schal beo" &thorn;e kyngdam of heuen,</L>
<L>But he hem do&thorn; to vndurstonde</L>
<L>&THORN;ei ben in possessiun and in honde.</L>
<L>Seint Bernard in a sarmoun sei&thorn; euen:</L>
<L N="1100">"&THORN;e pore na&thorn; not in er&thorn;e, ne riche in heuen."
<PB REF="00000258.tif" N="250"></L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;e riche wol heuene haue,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e pore he mot hit buye and craue.&mdash;</L>
<L>Nou is hit good for to sen</L>
<L N="1104">W&yogh;uche &thorn;at verreylich pore ben,</L>
<L>And also &thorn;ulke o&thorn;ere iliche</L>
<L>W&yogh;uche &thorn;ei ben, &thorn;at ben cleped riche.</L>
<L>Summe ben &thorn;at han riches &thorn;ikke</L>
<L N="1108">And hem louen wi&thorn; al heor witte:</L>
<L>&THORN;o ben &thorn;is riche gredi men,</L>
<L>And euer coueyten &thorn;e world &thorn;en.</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur &thorn;er ben in dede and &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1112">Wolde be riche, but &thorn;ei may nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>ffor and &thorn;ei hadden worldus good,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei wolden hit loue as &thorn;ei were wod:</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke ben &thorn;eose, so&thorn; to telle,</L>
<L N="1116">&THORN;e caytyf beggers &thorn;at nou&yogh;wher wol dwelle,</L>
<L>But euer &thorn;ei reyken aboute to craue,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at &thorn;ei seon &thorn;ei wolde hit haue;</L>
<L>Also wi&thorn; hem sette we moun</L>
<L N="1120">&THORN;is fals folk of Religioun.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos ben as riche in vnquerte</L>
<L>As &thorn;eos o&thorn;ure and as proude of herte;</L>
<L>Crist speke&thorn; of hem in &thorn;e gospelle<NOTE PLACE="marg">Math. 19, 24.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1124">And &thorn;us &thorn;e wordus do&thorn; he telle:</L>
<L>"A Chamayle mihte beter pase</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh anelde y&yogh;e &thorn;enne in case,</L>
<L>&THORN;en miht such a riche mon</L>
<L N="1128">In heuene come to &thorn;at kyndom."</L>
<L>Summen &thorn;at richesse is to brouht,</L>
<L>Han hit, but &thorn;ei louen hit nouht,</L>
<L>But neuer&thorn;eles, &thorn;e so&thorn; to saue,</L>
<L N="1132">ffayn &thorn;ei ben riches to haue:</L>
<L>&THORN;os ben &thorn;ese, to seye ow here,</L>
<L>&THORN;e goode men of &thorn;e world so dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al heore richesse wol dispende</L>
<L N="1136">ffor loue of god &thorn;at hit sende.</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;e more harm is for&thorn;i,</L>
<L>Suche ben fewe, witerli!</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur &thorn;er ben, so&thorn; hit is,</L>
<L N="1140">&THORN;at haue not of &thorn;is worldus blis
<PB REF="00000259.tif" N="251"></L>
<L>Ne no &thorn;ing &thorn;erof do&thorn; craue</L>
<L>Ne nolde not, &thorn;auh &thorn;ei&yogh; mihte, hit haue:</L>
<L>&THORN;is ben holy religious &thorn;erfore</L>
<L N="1144">And o&thorn;ure, &thorn;at mai wel beo cald pore;<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;ore</NOTE></L>
<L>Heoren is &thorn;e Ioye euerlastonde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; god and wi&thorn; godus sonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;en may we here-of nou say:</L>
<L N="1148">"Blesset beo &thorn;e pore in spirit ay,</L>
<L>ffor heoren is &thorn;e kyndom</L>
<L>&THORN;er as dwelle&thorn; God and Mon."</L>
<L>&THORN;enne drede we on &thorn;at o&thorn;ur syde</L>
<L N="1152">Leste &thorn;e wariing hem bi-tyde,</L>
<L>To &thorn;is ilke riche men,</L>
<L>Leste &thorn;ei schulle in helle bren.</L>
<L>Pore &thorn;ei ben in heor herte</L>
<L N="1156">&THORN;at ben pore and louen pouerte,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei ben pore in querte</L>
<L>&THORN;at han riches and louen pouerte.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="33" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[XXXIII.] &thorn;e visions of seynt poul wan he was rapt in to paradys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ed. before in <I>Engl. Stud.</I> I. p. 295-9. This piece seems intended to supply the place of the last article (Ioyes of heuen &amp; Peynes of helle) of the preceding treatise, cf. p. 235, v. 531-2; it has no special initial or title.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lustne&thorn;, lordynges, leof and dere,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at wolen of &thorn;e sonday here!</L>
<L>&THORN;e sonday a day hit is</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;at angeles and archaungeles Ioyen, I-wis,</L>
<L>More in &thorn;at ilke day</L>
<L>&THORN;en eny o&thorn;ur, as l &thorn;e say.</L>
<L>&THORN;en wol we her ate dwelle</L>
<L N="8">Ho preyed furst rest for soules in helle.</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to witen, I sei &thorn;e so,</L>
<L>Poul and Michel Archaungel bo.</L>
<L>ffor god of his grete miht</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;e peynes of helle put in heore siht.</L>
<L>Poul sayh bi-foren helle &yogh;ates</L>
<L>Brennynge tres &thorn;at neuer slakes;
<PB REF="00000260.tif" N="252"></L>
<L>Mony on for heore synne &thorn;onne</L>
<L N="16">Weore I-pyned and honged &thorn;er-onne:</L>
<L>Summe bi hondes and bi feet &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Summe bi &thorn;e her, summe bi &thorn;e ere,</L>
<L>Summe bi &thorn;e Armes &thorn;at weore longe,</L>
<L N="20">And summe &thorn;er hengen bi &thorn;e tonge.</L>
<L>He sau&yogh; a caudren brennynge at enes</L>
<L>Of diuerse colours wi&thorn; seue lemes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er weore &thorn;ei for heore synne</L>
<L N="24">Diuersliche I-pynet &thorn;er-Inne;</L>
<L>And seuen peynes weoren &thorn;er also</L>
<L>&THORN;at duden &thorn;e soules muche wo:</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste of snou&yogh;, &thorn;e secunde of ys,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;e &thorn;ridde fuir in alle wys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e blod, as I &thorn;e say,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e Eddres of foul aray,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sixte leyt, as mon may &thorn;ink,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;e seue&thorn;e peyne hit was of stynk.</L>
<L>At &thorn;at penaunces were &thorn;ei in cast,</L>
<L>Synful soules, and al for-&thorn;rast,</L>
<L>&THORN;e w&yogh;uche &thorn;at nolden in no chaunce</L>
<L N="36">ffor heore synnes do no penaunce;</L>
<L>&THORN;er weore &thorn;ei turmented in &thorn;o ledes,</L>
<L>And vche reseyued aftur his deedes.</L>
<L>Summe wepten and &yogh;elled &thorn;enne,</L>
<L N="40">Summe gouleden, and summe dude brenne;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei disireden euere to dye&mdash;</L>
<L>Hit miht not beo, wi&thorn;-outen ly&yogh;e,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e soule, wher-so hit go,</L>
<L N="44">Schal neuer dyen, for weole nor wo.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore sore hit is to drede</L>
<L>&THORN;e places of helle for wikkedhede!</L>
<L>In &thorn;e w&yogh;uche &thorn;er is a whel brennynge,</L>
<L N="48">Wi&thorn; muche serwe euer-lastynge;</L>
<L>Vndur &thorn;at wheol is &thorn;er &thorn;ore</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousund grisly peynes sore,</L>
<L>ffyue tyme vche day, to telle,</L>
<L N="52">Beo turmented wi&thorn; &thorn;e Angel of helle,</L>
<L>In vche of &thorn;o fyue tymes</L>
<L>Ben a &thorn;ousund soules turmented in pynes.
<PB REF="00000261.tif" N="253"></L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at sayh he, &thorn;er he stod,</L>
<L N="56">A wondur orible grisly flod,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at flod say he &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Mony deueles bestes were:</L>
<L>As ffissches &thorn;ei were in &thorn;at flod &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="60">Todus, Neddres, Snakes, mony mo,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e synful soules in hi&yogh;</L>
<L>Eten and gnowen wi&thorn;-outen merci&mdash;</L>
<L>Of hem tok I<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;ei</NOTE> no more kep</L>
<L N="64">But as a Lyun do&thorn; of a schep.</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;at watur he say&yogh; ligge</L>
<L>A wondur long and an hei&yogh; brugge,</L>
<L>And ouer &thorn;at brugge saf goon &thorn;en</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;e soules of good rihtful men</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen harm of word or dede,</L>
<L>And also wi&thorn;-outen eny drede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soules of synne[r]s, as I &thorn;e telle,</L>
<L N="72">ffallen doun &thorn;er, in pyne to dwelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;er to take and resseyue so</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei on eor&thorn;e deserueden to.</L>
<L>Be war of &thorn;is, I sei, beo-fore,</L>
<L N="76">As God seide in &thorn;e gospel &thorn;ore:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Ligate per fasciculos ad comburendum:</HEAD>
<L>Bynde&thorn; hem in knucchenus for&thorn;i,</L>
<L>To brenne, lyk to licchi,</L>
<L>Spous-brekers wi&thorn; lechours,</L>
<L N="80">Rauisschers wi&thorn; rauisschours,</L>
<L>Wikked wi&thorn; wikked also,</L>
<L>ffor so schul &thorn;ei to-gedere go.</L>
<L>ffor eueri creature go schal</L>
<L N="84">Bi &thorn;at brugge sum or al,</L>
<L>And lasse or more schal he be deruet,</L>
<L>Er aftur he ha&thorn; heer deseruet.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Er sauh &thorn;e goode mon poule</L>
<L N="88">In &thorn;at pyne moni diuerse soule:</L>
<L>Summe to &thorn;e kne, and summe to &thorn;e hipes,</L>
<L>Summe to &thorn;e nauel, summe to &thorn;e lippes,</L>
<L>And summe he sau&yogh; bi-suyled as souwes</L>
<L N="92">In &thorn;at pyne vp to &thorn;e brouwes;
<PB REF="00000262.tif" N="254"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ei weore turmented euerlastyngly,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei wept and gouled and weore sory.</L>
<L>And Poules herte was so sor</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;at for serwe he wepte &thorn;or.</L>
<L>And of &thorn;at Angel asked he</L>
<L>Whi summe were &thorn;er in to &thorn;e kne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Angel seide to him &thorn;en:</L>
<L N="100">"Heo ben Bacbyters of men,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in word and dede, as I &thorn;e say,</L>
<L>Hyndren heor euencristen &thorn;at &thorn;ei may.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at to &thorn;e nauel &thorn;ou se,</L>
<L N="104">Spousbrekers and lechours &thorn;ei be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at aftur heore dedes, to vndurstonde,</L>
<L>Nolde no penaunce take on honde.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at weren up to &thorn;e lippes blake,</L>
<L N="108">Stryf and Iangelyng in chirche dude make,</L>
<L>Vche to o&thorn;ur Iangled wi&thorn; scorn&mdash;</L>
<L>To heere godus wordus &thorn;ei han forborn.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at weren vp to &thorn;e bri&yogh;es</L>
<L N="112">In &thorn;at flod aboue &thorn;e ei&yogh;es,</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke weore glade of &thorn;e mischeef</L>
<L>Of heore neih&yogh;ebors and of heore greef."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And Poul wepte and seide &thorn;o:</L>
<L N="116">"Muche wo is hem I-come to</L>
<L>&THORN;at so mony peynes grymme</L>
<L>Ben ordeynt to for heore synne!"</L>
<L>Seynt Poul &thorn;o bi-tornd his face</L>
<L N="120">And say&yogh; ano&thorn;ur derk place,</L>
<L>Moni Men and wymmen &thorn;er amongus</L>
<L>&THORN;at for-freten heore owne tonges.</L>
<L>And Poul asked of him &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="124">What-maner men &thorn;at &thorn;ei were.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aungel seide to him ful sleih:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ei vsuden Ocur and vsuri;</L>
<L>Merciable weore &thorn;ei nouht,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;erfore hit schal be dere abouht."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And Poul sau&yogh; &thorn;enne a-no&thorn;ur plas,</L>
<L>&THORN;at moni peynes &thorn;er-in was;</L>
<L>&THORN;er he sauh dispitous &thorn;ing:</L>
<L N="132">As Blake Maydens in Blac clo&thorn;ing,
<PB REF="00000263.tif" N="255"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ei sodun euerichon</L>
<L>In wellyng pich and Brumston;</L>
<L>Brennyng dragouns and serpentes ifere</L>
<L N="136">Hongynge aboute heor nekkes were,</L>
<L>Gnawyng hem, to don hem schom,</L>
<L>To-tere &thorn;e fflesch from &thorn;e bon.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er weore foure Angeles to telle</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;at weoren of &thorn;e hous of helle,</L>
<L>Brennynge hornes hedde &thorn;ei on hed;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei hem turmented and dude hem qued,</L>
<L>ffaste &thorn;ei wente &thorn;is pepul a-boute</L>
<L N="144">Wi&thorn; moni turmentes grete and stoute,</L>
<L>Seying to hem, as was heore wone:</L>
<L>"Knowe&thorn; &yogh;e," &thorn;ei seide, "godus sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;e w&yogh;uche &thorn;at muche on &yogh;ou &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="148">Al &thorn;e world whon he bou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;e nolde neuer knowen him</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schullen han here &thorn;eos pynes grym."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Poul &thorn;is asked feire and wel.</L>
<L N="152">And &thorn;enne onswered &thorn;e Aungel:</L>
<L>"&THORN;eos serued not chastite</L>
<L>Til tyme of heor weddynge schulde be,</L>
<L>But lyuede in heore lecherie,</L>
<L N="156">And heled heore children and dude hem dye</L>
<L>And &yogh;af hem to swyn or to houndes</L>
<L>Or drouned hem In flodes groundes,</L>
<L>And schewed hem to &thorn;e worldus degre</L>
<L N="160">As &thorn;ei maydens hedden i-be;</L>
<L>And in &thorn;is lyf &thorn;ei lyueden &yogh;ore</L>
<L>And duden no penaunce &thorn;erfore."</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;is he say&yogh; at ene</L>
<L N="164">Men and wymmen moni and lene,</L>
<L>Lene &thorn;ei weore, wi&thorn;-outen flesche;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei soffred harde and no&thorn;ing nessche:</L>
<L>Muche lay bi-foren hem of Mete</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;at hem deynet not of to ete.</L>
<L>&THORN;o weore &thorn;eose &thorn;at weore not trewe</L>
<L>And nolde not faste &thorn;at hem was duwe,</L>
<L>And hedden of mony metes dedeyn,</L>
<L N="172">But hit weore likerous, be certeyn.
<PB REF="00000264.tif" N="256"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;En sau&yogh; poul a serw&yogh;ful siht&mdash;</L>
<L>And he loked &thorn;er for&thorn; riht:</L>
<L>An Old mon sat &thorn;er wepynge</L>
<L N="176">Bi-twene four deueles foul &yogh;ellynge.</L>
<L>Poul asked what he was.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Angel seide in plas:</L>
<L>"He was Neclygent a&yogh;eynes forbod</L>
<L N="180">And kepte not &thorn;e lawes of God,</L>
<L>He nas not chast of bodi i-sou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ne of herte ne of his &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>But euer he was Couetous,</L>
<L N="184">Proud of herte and contrarius;</L>
<L>&THORN;erof nolde he him not schriue</L>
<L>Ne do no penaunce bi his lyue,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore he schal beo pyned ay</L>
<L N="188">Wi&thorn;-outen Noumbre til domus-day."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>POul wepte and bigon to goule.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Angel seide: "whi wepustou, poule?</L>
<L>&YOGH;it say&yogh; &thorn;ou not, as I &thorn;e telle,</L>
<L N="192">&THORN;e strengest peyne &thorn;at is in helle."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Angel him schewed wi&thorn;-outen weoles</L>
<L>A put a-scled wi&thorn; seuen seles.</L>
<L>He bad him stonde bac, for &thorn;at &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;at he mihte sustene &thorn;at stynk.</L>
<L>He opened &thorn;e Mou&thorn; of &thorn;at put:</L>
<L>Hit stonk foule w&yogh;on hit was vnschut;</L>
<L>&THORN;e stynk &thorn;at com out of &thorn;at plas</L>
<L N="200">Passed al &thorn;e peynes and stinkes &thorn;er was.</L>
<L>&THORN;en seide &thorn;at Angel, to biginne:</L>
<L>"Hose come&thorn; &thorn;is put wi&thorn;-Inne,</L>
<L>Bi-fore God and vre ladi</L>
<L N="204">Schal neuer of him beo no merci."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>POul askede: "w&yogh;uche ben &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at schulen to &thorn;is peyne go?"</L>
<L>He seide: "hose leeue&thorn; not in wone</L>
<L N="208">&THORN;at Iesu crist, Godus sone,</L>
<L>Tok fflesch and blod of &thorn;e virgine Marie</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;e was boren of hire bodye;</L>
<L>And also &thorn;ulke, I telle hit &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="212">&THORN;at neuer wollen Bapti&yogh;ed be,
<PB REF="00000265.tif" N="257"></L>
<L>&THORN;ulke &thorn;at resseyue not wor&thorn;ily</L>
<L>&THORN;e flesch and blod of godus bodi."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>POul loked for&thorn;ur &thorn;en</L>
<L N="216">And sau&yogh; ful mony men and wymmen;</L>
<L>Wormes and serpentes on hem seeten,</L>
<L>Euer as houndes &thorn;ei on hem freeten.</L>
<L>So mony soules &thorn;er weore in hold,</L>
<L N="220">Vchon on o&thorn;ur, as schep in fold.</L>
<L>Hit was also dep to nemene</L>
<L>As from &thorn;e eor&thorn;e vp to heuene.</L>
<L>Of heore serwyng was muche wondur,</L>
<L N="224">&THORN;ei made a noyse as hit weore &thorn;undur.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;enne poul loked touward heuene,</L>
<L>And out of eor&thorn;e he herde a steuene;</L>
<L>A synful soule he sau&yogh; comynge</L>
<L N="228">Among seue deueles waymentynge;</L>
<L>&THORN;e w&yogh;uche &thorn;at same day for&thorn;i</L>
<L>Was itaken from &thorn;e bodi.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Angeles of God, &thorn;at ben vr frendes,</L>
<L N="232">Cri&yogh;eden faste to &thorn;e ffendes,</L>
<L>Sey&yogh;inge allas, makynge heore mon:</L>
<L>"What ha&thorn; &thorn;at wrecched soule i-don?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffendes seiden: "verreyment,</L>
<L N="236">He ha&thorn; se&yogh;en his Iuggement;</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; ben muche mys-auyset,</L>
<L>Godus Comaundemens he ha&thorn; dispyset,</L>
<L>In eor&thorn;e he lyued in foly</L>
<L N="240">And &thorn;er dude he no remedi.</L>
<L>His owne cha[r]tre ha&thorn; he rad</L>
<L>&THORN;at his synnes were Inne I-sprad,</L>
<L>And so for&thorn;, we telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="244">His owne self &thorn;en Iugged he."</L>
<L>&THORN;en tok &thorn;e deueles and him bounde,</L>
<L>And caste hym in to &thorn;e derkeste grounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;er as was wepyng wi&thorn; muche vnsee&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="248">Goulyng and grisbatyng of te&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;En seide to poul &thorn;at Aungel:</L>
<L>"Leeue &thorn;ou hit and knowe hit wel:</L>
<L>So as Mon do&thorn; in his lyuing</L>
<L N="252">So schal he haue aftur his endyng."
<PB REF="00000266.tif" N="258"></L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at &thorn;is was for&thorn; so sent,</L>
<L>In-wi&thorn; &thorn;e space of a moment,</L>
<L>Aungeles of heuene sai&yogh; he come &thorn;on,</L>
<L N="256">Brouhten &thorn;e soule of a Rihtful mon.</L>
<L>&THORN;er was Ioye wi&thorn; loud steuene,</L>
<L>ffor so &thorn;ei beeren hit in to heuene;</L>
<L>Of a &thorn;ousund Angeles he herde &thorn;e vois,</L>
<L N="260">Ioynge wi&thorn; a semely noys,</L>
<L>And seiden: "murie soule, blesset &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>ffor euer mur&thorn;e schal beo wi&thorn; &thorn;e!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art i-blesset of God in trone:</L>
<L N="264">&THORN;e wille of Ihesu hastou done."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;En seide &thorn;e Angeles in heore sei&yogh;ing:</L>
<L>"Lede&thorn; hym vp to-foren vr kyng!</L>
<L>Glad may he ben of alle clerkes</L>
<L N="268">&THORN;at schal him-self rede his goode werkes."</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at Mihel lede him in hi&yogh;</L>
<L>To paradys to o&thorn;ur holi.</L>
<L>A Ioyful noyse was hem among</L>
<L N="272">Of Angeles and Archangeles wi&thorn; song.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Ei &thorn;at in peyne bi-ne&thorn;en ly&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Herden &thorn;is and al hit sei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &yogh;elleden wi&thorn; lodly cry:</L>
<L N="276">"Poul, Michael, on vs ha merci!</L>
<L>Prei for vs wi&thorn; good a-cord</L>
<L>To vre god and to vre lord!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;En seide &thorn;e Angel to hem &thorn;o:</L>
<L N="280">"Weputh! poul and I wolen also,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Almihti God, &thorn;at may best,</L>
<L>Send &yogh;ow sum refuit and sum rest."</L>
<L>And &thorn;eose &thorn;at in peyne weore</L>
<L N="284">Cried on God wi&thorn; delful beere;</L>
<L>Michael and poul also,</L>
<L>And a Legioun of Aungelus mo.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soun of hem was herd ful euene</L>
<L N="288">Vp in to &thorn;e ffeor&thorn;e heuene,</L>
<L>Sei&yogh;inge "haue merci on hem,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sone of God and eke of mon."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;enne &thorn;ei &thorn;e heuene seih</L>
<L N="292">Open a-non ful sodeynly,
<PB REF="00000267.tif" N="259"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Sone of god com doun &thorn;o</L>
<L>And herde hem preye, mony on mo,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei preieden alle ful tenderli</L>
<L N="296">"Haue merci on vs, sone of Daui!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E vois &thorn;enne of vre heuene kyng</L>
<L>Ouer al &thorn;e peynes was herd seying:</L>
<L>"What good ha &yogh;e don herbifore</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;at &yogh;e aske reste so sore?</L>
<L>I was don on cros for &yogh;ou wi&thorn; dere</L>
<L>And smiten wi&thorn; a ful scharp spere,</L>
<L>I-nayled also wi&thorn; nayles &thorn;ree,</L>
<L N="304">Eysel and Galle to drynke bode me;</L>
<L>I &yogh;af my-self for &yogh;ou to be,</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;e schulde ouer come wi&thorn; me.</L>
<L>Bote &yogh;e weore &thorn;eues, coueytous,</L>
<L N="308">Proude and wro&thorn;e and envyous,</L>
<L>Good neuer nolde &yogh;e do non</L>
<L>Ne to schrift nolde &yogh;e not gon,</L>
<L>Ne do penaunce for no &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="312">Wi&thorn; Almusdedes ne wi&thorn; fastyng,</L>
<L>But &yogh;e weore ly&yogh;ers al &yogh;or lyf</L>
<L>And liueden euere in serwe and strif."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;En kneled Poul and Mihel</L>
<L N="316">And a Milioun Angeles wel</L>
<L>Bi-fore &thorn;e sone of God, to pray</L>
<L>&THORN;ei moste ha reste &thorn;e sonenday.</L>
<L>&THORN;o weore &thorn;eos, as I ow telle</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;at weoren in &thorn;e pynen of helle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;En seide vr lord to hem in spelle:</L>
<L>"ffor Poul and also Michaelle</L>
<L>And myn o&thorn;ure Angeles on hi&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="324">&THORN;at ben in heuene so goode and tri&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And also of my grete goodnesse,</L>
<L>Hem to ese of heore distresse,</L>
<L>&THORN;is rest I &yogh;iue &yogh;ow ful soon</L>
<L N="328">ffrom &thorn;e seter-day at Non</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e secunde hour beo cum</L>
<L>On &thorn;e Monenday, al and sum."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Anon &thorn;e soules hedden &thorn;er rest&mdash;</L>
<L N="332">He &yogh;af hit hem &thorn;at mihte best.
<PB REF="00000268.tif" N="260"></L>
<L>&THORN;e soules cri&yogh;ed euerichon:</L>
<L>"Blesset beo &thorn;ou, lord, sone of mon,</L>
<L>Lord and God of Dauid kuynde!</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;is rest bi &thorn;e haue we in Muynde."&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, whos halwe&thorn; wel &thorn;e sonenday,</L>
<L>He schal ha part of &thorn;e reste ay</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e Angeles in heuene</L>
<L N="340">Han &thorn;ere wi&thorn; mylde steuene.</L>
<L>Beo war of &thorn;e serwe and drede</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e peynes &thorn;at we her rede,</L>
<L>And torne we in alle wyse</L>
<L N="344">Vr lord to serue, &thorn;at hi&yogh;e Iustise;</L>
<L>Bi w&yogh;uche seruyse we may come</L>
<L>To vre lord god and wi&thorn; him wone.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="34" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>XXXIV. &thorn;e Pope trental.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ed. before in <I>Engl. Stud.</I> VIII, p. 275. The poem occurs again in the same MS. Vern. fol. CCCIII (V<SUB>2</SUB>); other MSS. are Cott. Cal. A II (15th cent.), ed. by Furnivall, <I>Pol., Rel. and Love Poems</I>, London 1866, and MS. Lamb. 306; from these MSS. A. Kauf|mann has tried to give a critical text, based chiefly on MS. Cott., and retaining its spell|ing (<I>Erlanger Beitr&auml;ge</I> 3, 1889). A different version is extant in MS. Edinb. Adv. Libr. 19, 3, 1, ed. by Turnbull, <I>The Visions of Tundale</I>, Edinb. 1843, and MS. Cambr. Univ. Libr. KK 1, 6, ed. by Kaufmann 1. c., which MSS. again differ greatly.</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I-writen I fynde a good stori,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Title in V<SUB>2</SUB>: here bygunnet &thorn;e guldene trental &thorn;at ou&yogh;te be loued swy&thorn;e wel.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e Pope hit wrot seint Gregori,<NOTE PLACE="marg">The name here, and v. 31, is a later introduction to the poem (cf. MS. Cott.). (Gregory is said to have instituted the Trental.)</NOTE></L>
<L>Of his Modur and of hire lyf,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle men heolden an holi hosewyf,</L>
<L>So sad<NOTE PLACE="marg">V<SUB>2</SUB> good</NOTE> of Maner, so mylde of Mood,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle men heolden hire holi and good;</L>
<L>De-boner, deuout, so milde of steuene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle men gesset<NOTE PLACE="marg">V<SUB>2</SUB> gessed 8</NOTE> hire wor&thorn;i to heuene.
<PB REF="00000269.tif" N="261"></L>
<L>As holi I-holden as heo was,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend &yogh;it falled hire in a foul cas,</L>
<L>He truyled<NOTE PLACE="marg">V<SUB>2</SUB> gylede</NOTE> hire wi&thorn; his tricherye</L>
<L N="12">And ladde hire in to lecherye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lust wi&thorn; loue hire so be-gylede,</L>
<L>So foule, til heo was wi&thorn; childe.</L>
<L>So priueliche no&thorn;eles heo hire bar</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at &thorn;er-of nas no wiht I-war.</L>
<L>And for no wiht schulde wite hire cas,</L>
<L>Anon as hire child I-boren was,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Nekke heo nom, &thorn;e child heo woriede,</L>
<L N="20">And a-non &thorn;e child heo buriede.</L>
<L>&THORN;us was heo cumbred in careful cas,</L>
<L>Ne schewed neuer schrift &thorn;erof, allas!</L>
<L>ffor heo wolde holy I-holde be,</L>
<L N="24">Heo tolde neuer prest hire priuite;</L>
<L>Al<NOTE PLACE="marg">V<SUB>2</SUB> Alle</NOTE> folk fayn was of hire fame,</L>
<L>So holy as heo was holden of name.</L>
<L>Eft-sones hir fel &thorn;e same cas</L>
<L N="28">Riht as bi-foren bi-tyd hire was.</L>
<L>ffor heo was comen of prys parage,</L>
<L>Of riche kun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">V<SUB>2</SUB> kin</NOTE> of gentil lynage,</L>
<L>Hire sone was seynt Gregori &thorn;e pope,</L>
<L N="32">Men heolden hire holy wi&thorn; al heore hope,<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 31-2 om. in Cott.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;erfore heo schonede hir schrift to schowe,</L>
<L>Leste by schrift hire cas weor<NOTE PLACE="marg">V<SUB>2</SUB> were</NOTE> knowe.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 35-8 later addition.</NOTE>So schome make&thorn; men schone heor schrift</L>
<L N="36">And leose<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. leose&thorn;</NOTE> &thorn;e grace of godus &yogh;ift,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en to liuen so sunfulli<NOTE PLACE="marg">V<SUB>2</SUB> sinfulli</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000270.tif" N="262"></L>
<L>And sorily dyen and sodeynli.</L>
<L>&THORN;is wommones dedes ner not aspyet,<NOTE PLACE="marg">V<SUB>2</SUB> neore . aspyed</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">And softly sone &thorn;er-aftur heo dyed.</L>
<L>Whon heo was seyen<NOTE PLACE="marg">V<SUB>2</SUB> se&yogh;en</NOTE> so softly dye,</L>
<L>Men hopede heo weore in heuene ful hi&yogh;e,<NOTE PLACE="marg">V<SUB>2</SUB> hie</NOTE></L>
<L>Men heolden hir holy and so deuoute</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at of hire de&thorn; men hedden no doute,</L>
<L>But wenden witerly alle to-wisse</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo weore set in souereyn blisse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Er-aftur wi&thorn;-Inne a luytel tyme</L>
<L N="48">Vp-on a day sone aftur prime</L>
<L>Hire sone &thorn;e pope at Masse stood,</L>
<L>And of his Modur trouwed bote good.</L>
<L>Al sodeynliche a-Midde his messe</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;er drouh touward him such a derknesse</L>
<L>&THORN;at lakkede al &thorn;e dayes lyht</L>
<L>And was derk<NOTE PLACE="marg">V<SUB>2</SUB> as derk as is at m.</NOTE> as hit weore midniht;</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at derknesse a myst among,</L>
<L N="56">Al stoneyd he was, such stunch &thorn;er stong;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-of so grislich he was a-gast</L>
<L>&THORN;at al swounyng he was al-mast.</L>
<L>Beo-syde he loked vndur his leor:</L>
<L N="60">A-Midde &thorn;e derknesse &thorn;er drou&yogh; on ner</L>
<L>A wonder grisli<NOTE PLACE="marg">V<SUB>2</SUB> grislich</NOTE> creature,</L>
<L>Riht aftur a fend ferde hire feture;</L>
<L>So Ragget,<NOTE PLACE="marg">V<SUB>2</SUB> Ragged</NOTE> so Rent, so elyng, so vuel,<NOTE PLACE="marg">euel</NOTE></L>
<L N="64">As hidous to bi-holden as helle-deuel;</L>
<L>Mou&thorn; and Neose, Eres and E&yogh;es
<PB REF="00000271.tif" N="263"></L>
<L>fflaumed al ful of furi li&yogh;es.<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 lei&yogh;es</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE asked hit hei&yogh;lich: "&thorn;orwh his miht</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;at alle deueles schal dreden and diht,</L>
<L>And eke bi vertu of his blood</L>
<L>&THORN;at for Monkynde di&yogh;ed on Rod,</L>
<L>Sey me a-non<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 sikerly</NOTE> &thorn;e so&thorn;e soone:</L>
<L N="72">What hastou in &thorn;is place to done?</L>
<L>What is &thorn;i cause, &thorn;ou cursede wrecche,</L>
<L>&THORN;us me at Masse to derue and drecche?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E gost onswerde wi&thorn; dreri cher:</L>
<L N="76">"I am &thorn;i Moodur &thorn;at &thorn;e beer,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for vn-schriuene dedes derne</L>
<L>In bitter peynes &thorn;us i berne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;En onswerd &thorn;e pope: "allas,</L>
<L N="80">Allas, my Modur, &thorn;is wondur cas!</L>
<L>Allas, my Modur, hou may &thorn;is be,</L>
<L>In such aray I &thorn;e to seo?</L>
<L>Men wenden witerli to-wisse</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;ou weore wel wor&thorn;i to habbe blisse</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ful wel wi&thorn; God &thorn;ou were,</L>
<L>To preyen for us &thorn;at liuen &yogh;it here.</L>
<L>Sey me, modur, wi&thorn;-outen feyne,</L>
<L N="88">Whi art &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 artou</NOTE> put to al &thorn;is peyne?"</L>
<L>Heo seide: "my sone, so&thorn;fastly</L>
<L>I schal &thorn;e telle &thorn;e cause why:</L>
<L>ffor I nas not such as I seemed,</L>
<L N="92">But wikked and worse &thorn;en men me demed,
<PB REF="00000272.tif" N="264"></L>
<L>I sungede<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 sunged</NOTE> wikkedliche in my lyue,</L>
<L>Of w&yogh;uch I ne dorste for schome me schriue;"</L>
<L>Heo tolde him trewely al hire cas</L>
<L N="96">ffrom ende to o&thorn;ur riht as hit was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Sei me, Modur, for Marie flour,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ou&yogh;t may beo &thorn;i socour,<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 &thorn;i safs.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wher penaunce of fasting mai ou&yogh;t alegge,</L>
<L N="100">Beodes or Masses &thorn;i peynes abregge,</L>
<L>Or eny-maner o&thorn;ur &thorn;yng</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e mai helpe of eny lissyng?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"MI deore Blessede sone," seide heo,</L>
<L N="104">"fful wel I-holpen I mihte beo,</L>
<L>Holpen and saued I mihte beo wel</L>
<L>Hose vndurtoke a trewe trentel</L>
<L>Of ten cheef festes of al &thorn;e &yogh;er</L>
<L N="108">To synge for me in &thorn;is Maneer:</L>
<L>&THORN;reo Masses of Cristes Natiuite,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e Ephiphan o&thorn;ur &thorn;re,</L>
<L>&THORN;reo of &thorn;e Purificaciun,</L>
<L N="112">And &thorn;reo of &thorn;e Annunciaciun,</L>
<L>&THORN;reo of &thorn;e Resurrexiun,</L>
<L>And &thorn;reo of &thorn;e Ascenciun,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Pentecost o&thorn;ur &thorn;re,</L>
<L N="116">And &thorn;reo of &thorn;e holy Trinite,</L>
<L>&THORN;reo of Maries Natiuite,</L>
<L>And of hire Concepcioun o&thorn;ur &thorn;re"&mdash;
<PB REF="00000273.tif" N="265"></L>
<L>&THORN;eose weoren<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> ben</NOTE> &thorn;e cheef festes ten</L>
<L>&THORN;at souereynliche socourde<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> socour(en)</NOTE> synful men.</L>
<L N="121">"What godmon synge&thorn; &thorn;eos masses, saunfayle,</L>
<L>To synful soule<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 soules</NOTE> &thorn;ei schullen auayle,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e &yogh;eer wi&thorn;-outen treyne</L>
<L N="124">Diliueren a soule ful out of peyne.</L>
<L>Let sei &thorn;eos Masses bi &yogh;oure hestes</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-Inne &thorn;e vtaues of &thorn;e ffestes!</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at schal &thorn;eos Masses do,</L>
<L N="128">Let sei &thorn;er-wi&thorn; &thorn;e Orisun &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 129-146 a later paraphrase of the two vv. in MS. Cott.</NOTE>Treoweliche wi&thorn;-outen were</L>
<L>Eueri day &thorn;orwh-out &thorn;e &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>Heet him sei<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 seyen</NOTE> hit eueri day,</L>
<L N="132">O&thorn;ur he &thorn;at do&thorn; &thorn;e Masses to say."</L>
<L>Hose wol knowe &thorn;is orisun clene,</L>
<L>Hit is on Englisch &thorn;us muche to mene:</L>
<L>"God, vr verrey Redempciun,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Oracio</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="136">Vr so&thorn;fast soules sauaciun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at chose al<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 alle</NOTE> o&thorn;ur londes bi-forn</L>
<L>&THORN;e lond of bi-heste In to beo born,</L>
<L>And &thorn;i de&thorn; suffredest in &thorn;at same,<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 &thorn;e s.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">Diliuere &thorn;is soule from gult and blame,</L>
<L>Tak hit out of &thorn;e fendes bond,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at lond from &thorn;e he&thorn;ene hond,</L>
<L>And peple &thorn;at leue&thorn; not in &thorn;e</L>
<L N="144">&THORN;orwh &thorn;i vertu amendet mote be;</L>
<L>And alle<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 al</NOTE> &thorn;at truste&thorn; In &thorn;i Merci,</L>
<L>Lord, saue hem sone and so&thorn;fastli!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"<B>A</B> Modur," he seide, "&thorn;at wol I do,</L>
<L N="148">ffor I am mon most I-holde<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 holden (I- om.)</NOTE> &thorn;er-to&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou weore my Modur, I was &thorn;i sone&mdash;</L>
<L>To synge &thorn;e Masses I schal not schone<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. schome</NOTE>;
<PB REF="00000274.tif" N="266"></L>
<L>God graunte me, Modur, &thorn;e stonde in stede<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 stude</NOTE></L>
<L N="152">A&yogh;eynes &thorn;e synnes &thorn;at euer &thorn;ou dude.<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 A&yogh;eyn . sunnes . dede</NOTE></L>
<L>I halse &thorn;e hei&yogh;liche, Modur deere,</L>
<L>&THORN;is tyme twelf-Mone&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 a tw. m.</NOTE> to me a-peere,</L>
<L>Hol &thorn;in a-stat to me &thorn;ou schowe,</L>
<L N="156">&THORN;at, hou &thorn;ou fare, I mouwe wel knowe!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Mi sone," heo seide, "I wole, in ffey,"</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word heo wente hir wey.</L>
<L>So day from<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 fro</NOTE> day &thorn;e &yogh;er con passe,</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;e pope for-lette neuer his Masse</L>
<L>&THORN;e same dayes &thorn;at weoren<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 were</NOTE> asignet,</L>
<L>To helpen his Modur &thorn;at was so pynet,<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 pyned</NOTE></L>
<L>And tok &thorn;e Orisun al-gate &thorn;er-to</L>
<L N="164">Als, as his Modur prei&yogh;ede him do.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;At tyde twelf-Mone&thorn; at Masse he stod</L>
<L>Holyliche wi&thorn; deuociun good:</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at same tyde apliht</L>
<L N="168">He say&yogh; a swi&thorn;e selli siht,</L>
<L>A comeli<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 comly</NOTE> ladi, so dresset and diht</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e world of hire schon briht,</L>
<L>Comeli Corouned<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 crouned</NOTE> as a Qweene,</L>
<L N="172">Tweyn Angeles ladden hire hem bi-twene.</L>
<L>He was so Rauischt of &thorn;at siht,</L>
<L>Al-most for Ioye he swounede riht.</L>
<L N="175">He fel doun flat bi-foren hire feet,</L>
<L>&THORN;e teres of his e&yogh;en he doun leet,<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 Deuoutli teres wi&thorn; leores he leet</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000275.tif" N="267"></L>
<L>He grette<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 gret</NOTE> hire wi&thorn; wel mylde steuene</L>
<L>And seyde: "ladi, Qween of heuene,</L>
<L>Moodur of Ihesu, Mylde Marie,</L>
<L N="180">ffor my moodur Merci I crie."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"[D]O wey," heo seide, "I nam not heo</L>
<L>Ne whom &thorn;ou wenest<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 &thorn;e wenest</NOTE> &thorn;at I beo,</L>
<L>Bote, so&thorn;lyche, as &thorn;ou seost me her,</L>
<L N="184">I am &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;i; V2 &thorn;i</NOTE> Moodur &thorn;at &thorn;e beer.</L>
<L>Bi-foren i ferde, &thorn;ou wustest wel,</L>
<L>ffarynge as a fend of hel,<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 helle</NOTE></L>
<L>I am nou such as &thorn;ou sest her,</L>
<L N="188">&THORN;orwh help and vertu of &thorn;i preyer,</L>
<L>ffrom derknesse i-dresset<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 om. i-</NOTE> to blisse cleer.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tyme beo blesset &thorn;at I &thorn;e beer!</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e kuyndenesse of &thorn;i deede</L>
<L N="192">Souereyn Ioye schal beo &thorn;y Meede.</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at lete&thorn; &thorn;eos Masses &thorn;us do,</L>
<L>Schul saue hem-self and soules also.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, Sone, &thorn;is storie &thorn;ou preche!</L>
<L N="196">Mi dere sone, god I &thorn;e be-teche."</L>
<L>Whon heo hedde endet &thorn;is wordes euene,</L>
<L>Angeles token hire hom<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 euene</NOTE> to heuene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e same hom to<NOTE PLACE="marg">V2 om. to</NOTE> god vs sende,</L>
<L N="200">To wone wi&thorn; him wi&thorn;-outen ende. Amen.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Then follows in MS. Vernon, William of Nassington's <I>Mirrour of Life</I> (translation of John de Waldeby's <I>Speculum Vit&aelig;</I>), fol. CCXXXI&mdash;CCLXIIII b, extant also in a MS. of Lord Ashburnham (best MS.), MS. Reg. 17 CVIII (written 1418), Hatton 19; then Rich. Rolle's <I>Pricke of Conscience</I>, fol. CCLXIIII b&mdash;CCLXXXIII b; then <I>&THORN;e Spore of Loue.</I></NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">

<PB REF="00000268.tif" N="260">
<HEAD>Trentale sancti gregorij.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>MS. Cott. Cal. A II, fol. 86 (ed. in Furnivall's <I>Polit., Relig. and Love Poems</I>, E. E. T. S. 1866).</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A nobull story wryte y fynde,</L>
<L>A pope hit wrote to haue yn mynde,</L>
<L>Of his modur &amp; of her lyf</L>
<L N="4">That holden was an holy wyfe,</L>
<L>Of myrthes sadde &amp; mylde of mode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all men held her holy &amp; gode;</L>
<L N="7">Bothe deuowte &amp; mylde of steuen),</L>
<L>&THORN;at all men helde her wordy heuen.
<PB REF="00000269.tif" N="261"></L>
<L>So holy as she was holde of name,</L>
<L>All men were gladde of her fame.</L>
<L N="11">But as holy as she holden was,</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuell brow&yogh;th her yn a foule cas,</L>
<L>He trifeled her so with his trecherye</L>
<L>And ledde her yn lust of lecherye,</L>
<L>ffor with lust of lecherye he her begylde</L>
<L N="16">Tyll she hadde conceyued a chylde.</L>
<L>And also priuely she hit bare</L>
<L>That &thorn;er-of was no man ware.</L>
<L>And for no mon) shuld wyte of &thorn;at case,</L>
<L N="20">Anone as &thorn;e chylde born was,</L>
<L>The chylde she slow&yogh; &amp; wyryede</L>
<L>And pryuely she hit byryede.</L>
<L>&THORN;er was she combred yn a carefull case,</L>
<L N="24">And vnshryuen &thorn;er-of she was;</L>
<L>She ne tolde no preste her priuyte</L>
<L>ffor she wolde holy holden be.</L>
<L>Efte-sones she fell in &thorn;e same case</L>
<L N="28">Ry&yogh;th as beforn her be-tydde was.</L>
<L>ffor she was comen of hy&yogh; parage,</L>
<L>Of gentyll kynne &amp; wor&thorn;y lynage,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfor she wolde not her synne shewe</L>
<L N="32">Nor yn schryfte hit be-knowe,
<PB REF="00000270.tif" N="262"></L>
<L>And so her dedes wer not a-spyed.</L>
<L>But afturwarde sodenly she dyed.</L>
<L>When she was seyn so sodenly dye,</L>
<L N="36">Men hoped she was yn heuen hye;</L>
<L>They helde her so holy &amp; deuowte</L>
<L>&THORN;at of her deth &thorn;ey made no dowte,</L>
<L>But sykurly men wende y-wys</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at she was wor&thorn;y heuen blys.</L>
<L>Then aftur with-Inne a shorte tyme,</L>
<L>Vpon a day soone aftyr pryme,</L>
<L N="43">The pope as he at his masse stode,</L>
<L>Vpon his modur he hadde &thorn;ow&yogh;t goode,</L>
<L>Prayng to god with conciens clere</L>
<L>The so&thorn;e to knowe as hit were.</L>
<L N="47">And sodenly yn myddes his masse</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;row&yogh; to hym such a derkenesse</L>
<L>&THORN;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. he</NOTE> lakkede ner &thorn;e dayes ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L>ffor hit was derke as mydny&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="51">In &thorn;at derkenes was myste among,</L>
<L>All a-stonyed he stode so hit stongke.</L>
<L>Be-syde he loked vn&thorn;ur hys lere:</L>
<L>In &thorn;at derknes a &thorn;yng &thorn;rew hym nere,</L>
<L N="55">A won&thorn;urfull grysely creature,</L>
<L>Aftur a fend fyred with all her feture,</L>
<L>All ragged &amp; rente, bo&thorn;e clenge &amp; euell,</L>
<L>As orrybull to be-holde as any deuell;</L>
<L>Mowthe, face, eres &amp; yes
<PB REF="00000271.tif" N="263"></L>
<L N="60">Brennede all full of brennyng lyes.</L>
<L>He was so agast of &thorn;at grysyly goste</L>
<L>That yn a swonyng he was almoste.</L>
<L>He halsed hit: "&thorn;orow goddes my&yogh;te</L>
<L N="64">That &thorn;e fende he putte to fly&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And be &thorn;e vertu of hys blode</L>
<L>That for mankynde dyed on Rode,</L>
<L N="67">Sey me sykerly &thorn;e so&thorn;e soone</L>
<L>What &thorn;ou hast yn &thorn;is place to done;</L>
<L>What ys &thorn;y cause, &thorn;ou cursed wreche,</L>
<L>Thus at masse me for to drecche?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e gost answered with drury chere:</L>
<L>"I am &thorn;y modur &thorn;at &thorn;e beere,</L>
<L N="73">&THORN;at for vnschryuen dedes so derne</L>
<L>In byttyr paynes &thorn;us y brenne<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. berne</NOTE>."</L>
<L>Then sayde &thorn;e pope: "alas, alas!</L>
<L N="76">Modur, &thorn;is ys to me a wondur case.</L>
<L>A, leef modur, how may &thorn;is be</L>
<L>In suche paynes &thorn;e for to se?</L>
<L>ffor all men wende y-wys</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou hadde ben wordy heuen blys,</L>
<L>And full good<NOTE PLACE="marg">L well with god</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ou were,</L>
<L>To praye for vs &thorn;at ben here.</L>
<L N="83">Sey me, modyr, with-outen fayne,</L>
<L>Why art &thorn;ou put to all &thorn;is payne?"</L>
<L>She sayde: "sone, sykerly,</L>
<L>I shall &thorn;e telle &thorn;e cause why:</L>
<L>ffor y was not such as y semed,</L>
<L N="88">But myche worse &thorn;en men wened;
<PB REF="00000272.tif" N="264"></L>
<L>I lyuede in lustes wykkydly in my lyfe,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whyche y wolde me not shryfe;"</L>
<L N="91">And tolde hym trewly all &thorn;e case</L>
<L>ffro &thorn;e bygynnyng how &thorn;at hit wase.</L>
<L>The pope lette teres a-down Renne,</L>
<L>And to his modyr he sayde &thorn;en:</L>
<L N="95">"Tell me now, modur, for loue of mary flour,</L>
<L>If any &thorn;yng may &thorn;e help or sokour,</L>
<L>Bedes or masse, &thorn;y penaunce to bye,</L>
<L>Or ony fastyng, &thorn;y sorowe to aleye;</L>
<L>What crafte or caste or any o&thorn;ur &thorn;yng</L>
<L>The may help or be &thorn;y Releuyng?"</L>
<L N="101">"My blessed sone," sayde she,</L>
<L>"ffull well y hope &thorn;at hit may be;</L>
<L>Syker &amp; saf my&yogh;th y be well</L>
<L>Who-so trewly wolde take a trentell</L>
<L N="105">Of ten chef festes of &thorn;e &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>To syng for me yn &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>Thre masses of crystys natyuyte,</L>
<L N="108">And of &thorn;e xij day o&thorn;ur &thorn;re,</L>
<L>Thre of our ladyes puryfycacion,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ur &thorn;re of her Annunciacion,</L>
<L>Thre of crystes gloryous Resurreccion,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ur &thorn;re of his hy&yogh; Ascencion,</L>
<L N="113">And of pentecoste o&thorn;ur &thorn;re,</L>
<L>And &thorn;re of &thorn;e blessed trinite,</L>
<L>And of our ladyes Assumpcion o&thorn;ur &thorn;re,</L>
<L N="116">And of her Ioyfull natiuite &thorn;re;
<PB REF="00000273.tif" N="265"></L>
<L>These ben &thorn;e chefe festes ten</L>
<L>That sokour &thorn;e sowles &thorn;at ben fro heuen.</L>
<L>Who-so sayth &thorn;ese masses, with-out fayle,</L>
<L>ffor synfull sowles &thorn;ey shall a-vayle;</L>
<L>All a &yogh;ere, with-outen trayne,</L>
<L>They delyuere a sowle out of payne.</L>
<L>Lette say &thorn;ese masses be &yogh;our hestes</L>
<L N="124">With-Inne &thorn;e vtas of &thorn;e festes!</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at shall &thorn;ese masses do,</L>
<L>Sey he &thorn;er-with &thorn;is oryson also:</L>
<L N="127"><I>Deus qui es nostra Redempcio,</I></L>
<L>With all &thorn;e o&thorn;ur &thorn;at longen &thorn;er-to."</L>
<L>The pope was gladde her-of in fay,</L>
<L>And to his modur &thorn;en gon he say:</L>
<L>"Modyr," he sayde, "&thorn;is shall be do,</L>
<L N="132">ffor y am moste bounde &thorn;erto&mdash;</L>
<L>Thou were my modur, I was &thorn;y sone&mdash;</L>
<L>Thys same &yogh;ere hit shall be done;
<PB REF="00000274.tif" N="266"></L>
<L>God graunte me grace to stonde in stede</L>
<L N="136">A&yogh;eyns all &thorn;e synnus &thorn;at euur &thorn;ou dede.</L>
<L>I commaunde hooly, my moder dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is tyme twelfmone&thorn; &thorn;ou to me apere,</L>
<L>And hooly to me &thorn;y state &thorn;ou telle,</L>
<L>That how &thorn;ou fare y may wyte well."</L>
<L N="141">"My sone," she sayde, "y woll yn fay,"</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at worde she wente her way.</L>
<L>Day by day &thorn;e &yogh;er gon passe,</L>
<L N="144">The pope for-&yogh;ate neuur his masse</L>
<L>The same dayes &thorn;at were a-syned,</L>
<L>To helpe his modur &thorn;at was pyned,</L>
<L>And toke &thorn;e orysons all-way &thorn;er-to</L>
<L N="148">Ry&yogh;th as she bad hym for to do.</L>
<L>xij mone&thorn; aftur as he at masse stode</L>
<L>With gret deuocion &amp; holynesse gode,</L>
<L>At &thorn;at same tyme full Ryght</L>
<L N="152">He sawe a full swete syght:</L>
<L>A comely lady dressed &amp; dyght,</L>
<L>That all &thorn;e worlde was not so bry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Comely crowned as a qwene,</L>
<L>Twenty Angellys her ladde be-twene.</L>
<L N="157">He was so Raueshed of &thorn;at syght</L>
<L>That ny&yogh; for Ioye he swoned Ryght.</L>
<L>He fell down flatte by-fore her fete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. &thorn;at</NOTE> deuowtly teres wepynge he lete,
<PB REF="00000275.tif" N="267"></L>
<L>And grette her with a mylde steuen</L>
<L>And sayde &thorn;ere: "lady, qwene of heuen,</L>
<L>Modyr of Ihesu, mayde marye,</L>
<L N="164">ffor my modyr mercy I crye."</L>
<L>At &thorn;at worde with mylde chere</L>
<L>She hym answered on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L N="167">"Blessed sone, I am not she</L>
<L>Who wenest<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Whom &thorn;. w.</NOTE> &thorn;ou &thorn;at I be,</L>
<L>But certes as &thorn;ou seest me here</L>
<L>I am &thorn;y modyr &thorn;at &thorn;e bere,</L>
<L>That her-by-fore, &thorn;ou wyste well,</L>
<L N="172">I was wordy payne yn hell,</L>
<L>And now y am such as &thorn;ou seest her,</L>
<L>&THORN;orow help of &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;y prayer,</L>
<L>ffro derknesse I dresse to blysse clere;</L>
<L N="176">&THORN;e tyme be blessed &thorn;at y &thorn;e bere!</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e kyndenesse of &thorn;y good dede</L>
<L>Heuen-blysse shall be &thorn;y mede.</L>
<L>And all &thorn;o &thorn;at leten &thorn;ese masses be do,</L>
<L N="180">Shall saue hem-self &amp; o&thorn;ur mo;</L>
<L>&THORN;us may &thorn;ey helpe her frendes all</L>
<L>That Reche-lesly yn synne falle.</L>
<L>Therfore, sone, &thorn;is story &thorn;ou preche!</L>
<L N="184">And almy&yogh;ty god y &thorn;e be-teche."</L>
<L>At &thorn;e endyng of her wordes euen</L>
<L>An Angell her ber yn to heuen.</L>
<L N="187">In to &thorn;at place god vs sende,</L>
<L>To dwelle with her with-outen ende.
<PB REF="00000276.tif" N="268"></L>
<L>Thys ys &thorn;e vertu, y &thorn;e telle,</L>
<L>Of seynt gregory trentelle.</L>
<L>But who so wyll do hit trewely,</L>
<L N="192">He moste do more, sykurly:</L>
<L>&THORN;e preste &thorn;at &thorn;e masse shall synge,</L>
<L>At eche feste &thorn;at he do&thorn; hit mynge</L>
<L>He moste say with good deuocion</L>
<L N="196">Ouer Euen &thorn;e commendacyon,</L>
<L>Placebo &amp; dyryge also,</L>
<L>The sowle to brynge out of woo;</L>
<L N="199">And also &thorn;e salmus seuene,</L>
<L>ffor to brynge &thorn;e sowle to heuen&mdash;</L>
<L>Among o&thorn;ur prayeres &thorn;ey ben good</L>
<L>To brynge sowles fro helle f[l]ode,</L>
<L>ffor euery psalme qwencheth a synne,</L>
<L>As ofte as a man &thorn;oth hem mynne.</L>
<L>Loke with good deuocyon &thorn;ou hem say!</L>
<L>And to all halewes &thorn;at &thorn;ou pray,</L>
<L N="207">To helpe &thorn;e with all her my&yogh;te</L>
<L>The sowle to brynge to heuen bryght,</L>
<L>Ther euur ys day and neuur nyght&mdash;</L>
<L>Cryst graunt vs parte of &thorn;at lyght!</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ese ben sayde all in-fere</L>
<L N="212">Euery day yn &thorn;e &yogh;ere;</L>
<L>Neuer a day &thorn;at &thorn;ou for-&yogh;ete,</L>
<L>These to say &thorn;ou ne lette!</L>
<L>Also in &thorn;e vtas of euery feste</L>
<L N="216">Also longe as hit doth leste&mdash;</L>
<L>viij<SUP>te</SUP> dayus men callen &thorn;e vtas&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e preste moste say in his masse&mdash;</L>
<L>A nobull orysoun hit ys holde&mdash;</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;e colette &thorn;at fyrst y of tolde.</L>
<L>And aftur &thorn;e fyrste orysoun</L>
<L>&THORN;er ys an-o&thorn;ur of gret Renoun</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e sowle ys won&thorn;ur swete,</L>
<L N="224">Menne calle hit &thorn;e secrete.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e preste hath don his masse,</L>
<L>Vsed, &amp; his hondes wasche,</L>
<L>A-no&thorn;ur oryson he moste say,</L>
<L N="228">&THORN;at yn &thorn;e boke fynde he may,</L>
<L>&THORN;e "post comen" men don hit calle,</L>
<L>That helpeth sowles out of &thorn;ralle.</L>
<L N="231">And &thorn;at &thorn;is be don at eche a feste</L>
<L>As &thorn;e trentall<NOTE PLACE="marg">corr. fr. trentell</NOTE> speketh moste &amp; leste;</L>
<L>Then may &thorn;ou be sykur &amp; certayne</L>
<L>To brynge &thorn;e sowle out of payne</L>
<L>To endeles Ioye &thorn;at lasteth aye,</L>
<L N="236">&THORN;at god dyed fore on good fryday.</L>
<L>To &thorn;at Ioye he vs brynge</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys in heuen with-oute endynge!</L>
<L>Pray we all hit may so be,</L>
<L N="240">And say Amen for charyte.</L>
<TRAILER>Explicit.</TRAILER>
</LG>


</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="35" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000276.tif" N="268">
<HEAD>[XXXV. &thorn;e Spore of Loue.<NOTE PLACE="foot">So the title in v. 21, 1081; in the heading the title is <I>&THORN;e Prikke of loue.</I> A local reference, v. 163 ff., seems to imply that the poem was written in Leicester. The translation is very free, with frequent additions, omissions, and contractions.</NOTE>] <MILESTONE N="cclxxxiiib" UNIT="folio"> (A free translation of St. Edmund's <I>Speculum.</I>)</HEAD>

<ARGUMENT>
<L>Her beginne&thorn; &thorn;e Prikke of loue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at profitable is to soule be-houe.</L>
</ARGUMENT>

<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God &thorn;at art of mi&yogh;tes most,</L>
<L>ffader and Sone and holigost,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow graunte hem alle &thorn;i blessyng</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;at herken wel to &thorn;is talkyng.</L>
<L>ffor, lewed and lered, more and lesse,</L>
<L>Hit wol ow teche holynesse;</L>
<L>To loue God wi&thorn; fyn chere</L>
<L N="8">Hit wol ou teche, my leoue and dere.
<PB REF="00000277.tif" N="269"></L>
<L>ffor mony a tyme &yogh;e cone me preye</L>
<L>&THORN;er-of a lesson ow to seye;</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure dulnesse sum what to scharpe</L>
<L N="12">&YOGH;e han me preyed for to carpe.</L>
<L>ffor bisynes of worldli &thorn;ing</L>
<L>To monye hit is a gret lettyng,</L>
<L>And eke &yogh;or owne frelete,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at make&thorn; ow &yogh;eore heui to be</L>
<L>Of or-self and &yogh;oure liuinge,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;e ffendes entysynge.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;is bok to ow I make</L>
<L N="20">&YOGH;oure discumfort for to slake,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is cald "&thorn;e spore of loue,"</L>
<L>&THORN;at sture&thorn; or loue to god aboue.</L>
<L>Riht as &thorn;e spore make&thorn; hors to renne,</L>
<L N="24">So schal &thorn;is bok sone god<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. good</NOTE> ou kenne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is souereyn holynesse.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schul fynde heer-in swetnesse:</L>
<L>Loke &yogh;e take herto good hede!</L>
<L N="28">ffor I schal telle &yogh;ou, as I rede.</L>
<L>&THORN;is may be &yogh;or halyday werk,</L>
<L>Hit wol a-vayle bo&thorn;e lewed and clerk.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Of Meditacion of &thorn;i-self knowyng.<NOTE PLACE="marg">The poem begins with Chap. 3 of the Spec.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Take&thorn; good hede, of alle &thorn;inge</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;is tweyne to loue, good &thorn;ei wil &thorn;e bringe:</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffurste Is Meditacion,</L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;er is Contemplacion;</L>
<L>&THORN;enk of &thorn;i-self &thorn;at is to say,</L>
<L N="36">And on God, eueriche day.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mai&yogh;t not loue God ri&yogh;t wel</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;ou knowe him furst sumdel,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;i-self neuer &thorn;e more.</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at God is best wite wel &thorn;erfore;</L>
<L>And wene not &thorn;i-self be best,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;i while &thorn;en hast &thorn;ou lost.</L>
<L>&THORN;i-self loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou knowe,</L>
<L N="44">ffor &thorn;at schal make &thorn;e Meke &amp; lowe</L>
<L>And able to knowe &thorn;e grete bounte</L>
<L>Of God &thorn;at sitte&thorn; in Maieste.
<PB REF="00000278.tif" N="270"></L>
<L>Bi-&thorn;enk &thorn;e &thorn;enne, whil &thorn;ou hast quart,</L>
<L N="48">In Bodi and Soule what &thorn;ou art.</L>
<L>&THORN;i bodi was gendred of foul matere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is wlatsum for to here.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 51-86. This passage is wanting in the Spec.</NOTE>Bi al &thorn;in Issuwes hit is wel sene</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at &thorn;ou art not wi&thorn;-Inne ful clene.</L>
<L>Nyne Issuwes &thorn;ou hast, I wene,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou loke hem al bi-deene:</L>
<L>Tweyne Eren &thorn;ou hast, ben ful of wore,</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;yn E&yogh;en ben goundi whon &thorn;ei ben sore,</L>
<L>&THORN;i Neose-&thorn;urles ben ful of snit,</L>
<L>And &thorn;i Mou&thorn; of glet and spit,</L>
<L>&THORN;yn Issuwes &thorn;at aren in priuete</L>
<L N="60">ffor schome &thorn;ou letest no mon hem se.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, seint Bernard as he vs telles:<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. The sayings of St. Bernard.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou proude mon, &thorn;ou art nou&yogh;t elles</L>
<L>But of Muk bretful a sekke;</L>
<L N="64">Mon, schuldest &thorn;ou not so muche rekke</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i-self &thorn;en of ano&thorn;er,</L>
<L>ffor Rot is &thorn;i ffader, worm &thorn;i bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>ffor gendred he is riht of &thorn;e same</L>
<L N="68">As &thorn;ou. Proud mon, &thorn;ou art to blame,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow berest &thorn;e so stoutli</L>
<L>And hast &thorn;ow non enchesun whi!</L>
<L>Heddest &thorn;ow be maad of stones riche,</L>
<L N="72">Sonne or Mone or bodi heuenliche,</L>
<L>How nobliche &thorn;ow heddest be wrou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>As Lucifer &thorn;ow mi&yogh;test haue &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Of his beute proud he was:</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;erfore him tidde a wel foul cas,</L>
<L>In heuene he durede but a while.</L>
<L>Riht so pruide wol &thorn;e be-gyle</L>
<L>And caste &thorn;e doun riht to grounde,</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;i soule in peyne hit schal be bounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;i bodi, &thorn;at now is hol and sounde,</L>
<L>So foul rot hit schal be founde,</L>
<L>Hit schal not turne to gras nor flour,</L>
<L N="84">But in to wlatsum and foul odour.</L>
<L>&THORN;us mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou knowe &thorn;i bodily staate,</L>
<L>&THORN;i fleschli lust forto abate.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000279.tif" N="271">
<HEAD>Meditacion of &thorn;e Soule.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;i soule &yogh;it &thorn;enke &thorn;ow</L>
<L N="88">What staat hit is Inne now,</L>
<L>And what &thorn;ou hast don her-bi-foren&mdash;</L>
<L>Or elles &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t sone be loren.</L>
<L>&THORN;enk hou muche wikkednesse</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;ou hast don, and [left]<NOTE PLACE="marg">om.</NOTE> goodnesse,</L>
<L>How luitel good &thorn;ow hast wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;i tyme hast spendet aboute nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Of werk and word &thorn;at is gon</L>
<L N="96">And of &thorn;i tyme schal leue riht non</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne schalt &yogh;elde ful streit acounte,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou nost hou muche hit wol amounte.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou weore bounde for to telle<NOTE PLACE="marg">exemplum</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">In &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute; &thorn;e smale grauelle,</L>
<L>Or sterres in &thorn;e ffirmament,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow heddest gret neode, verrement,</L>
<L>fforto a-vise &thorn;e wonder wel!</L>
<L N="104">So most &thorn;ou rikene eueridel</L>
<L>Werk, and word, and &thorn;ou&yogh;tes alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ben wel mo &thorn;en grauel smalle;</L>
<L>And of &thorn;i tyme &thorn;at is past.</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;erof &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t ben sore agast</L>
<L>To &thorn;enke &thorn;us what &thorn;i soule ha&thorn; ben!</L>
<L>What hit is now, is good to sen.</L>
<L>So chaungeable is &thorn;i soule, my frende,</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;at nou&yogh;t &thorn;e pleset adai to &thorn;e ende;</L>
<L>Now art &thorn;ow sori, now art &thorn;ow glad,</L>
<L>Now art in hope, now art adrad;</L>
<L>&YOGH;it wilnest &thorn;ow &thorn;ing &thorn;at neuer ne was.</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;ou art more frele &thorn;en is &thorn;e glas:<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 116-121 wanting in the Spec.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-oute touche hit laste&thorn; ay,</L>
<L>&THORN;i soule is frelore atte assay:</L>
<L>&THORN;orw siht wi&thorn;-oute &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t wi&thorn;-Inne</L>
<L N="120">Hit may be broken, wi&thorn; dedly synne.</L>
<L>&THORN;erto assentest &thorn;ou lihtly,</L>
<L>And for to be fondet &thorn;ou art redi,</L>
<L>And forte wi&thorn;-stonde hastou no mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="124">But &thorn;orw &thorn;e grace of god almiht,
<PB REF="00000280.tif" N="272"></L>
<L>&THORN;at kepe&thorn; &thorn;e vp whon &thorn;ou schuldest falle.</L>
<L>&middot;ffrom mony mischeues he con &thorn;e calle:</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou art loren he &thorn;e fyndes,</L>
<L N="128">Of Bondus of synne he &thorn;e vnbyndes;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e deuel whon we were sold,</L>
<L>He Raunsound vs, bo&thorn;e &yogh;onge &amp; old;</L>
<L>Dedly synne whon &thorn;ou hast don,</L>
<L N="132">He venge&thorn; him not &thorn;er-on anon,</L>
<L>But Corteisliche he &thorn;e abydes;</L>
<L>&THORN;i schome &amp; synne &yogh;it he hydes.</L>
<L>He blames &thorn;e whon &thorn;ou dost mys,</L>
<L N="136">And euere he teche&thorn; &thorn;e, I-wys,</L>
<L>In hungur &amp; &thorn;urst he &thorn;e fedes,</L>
<L>Among &thorn;in enymys he &thorn;e ledes,</L>
<L>In hete and chele he &thorn;e refresches,</L>
<L N="140">Slepyng, wakyng he &thorn;e redresses.</L>
<L>Heron &thorn;ou &thorn;enke bo&thorn;e Euen &amp; morn!</L>
<L>And eke, hou mony men han be lorn,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e be water and londe also,</L>
<L N="144">&THORN;at God ne ha&thorn; not tendet to</L>
<L>As to &thorn;e so bisyli.</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore sei, "sire, graunt Merci,"<NOTE PLACE="marg">The Spec. has a complete prayer, beg. Gratias ago tibi, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ow be-&thorn;enkest &thorn;e day or niht</L>
<L N="148">Hou god &thorn;e kepe&thorn; wi&thorn;-oute dispit</L>
<L>In Bodi or soule, erli or late.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou knowe &thorn;in owne astate.</L>
<L>To loue god bi alle resoun</L>
<L N="152">ffor &thorn;is fordede &thorn;ou hast enchesoun.</L>
<L>&THORN;is &thorn;ou&yogh;t is Meditacion.</L>
<L>Now for&thorn; to Contemplacion.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Of Contemplacion in creature.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Contemplacion is to seye:</L>
<L N="156">Siht of god and his nobleye.</L>
<L>&THORN;at mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou se be &thorn;in Inwit</L>
<L>In creature, and in holy writ,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en in his owne kynde.</L>
<L N="160">Of &thorn;eose &yogh;if we wol haue good mynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e nobleye of god [we se] in his werkes,</L>
<L>As men mowe seo, Lewed &amp; Clerkes.
<PB REF="00000281.tif" N="273"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;at neuere se&yogh;e Duyk Henri,<NOTE PLACE="marg">exemplum</NOTE></L>
<L N="164">&THORN;at &thorn;e newe werk of Leycetre reised on hi&yogh;:</L>
<L>&THORN;er-bi mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou wel wyte and se</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was lord of gret pouste</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit made of his owne cost&mdash;</L>
<L N="168">I hope he naue &thorn;eron not lost.</L>
<L>&THORN;e makyng of vche a creature</L>
<L>Such is<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Schewis?</NOTE> godes mi&yogh;t wi&thorn;-oute Mesure.</L>
<L>And bi &thorn;e ordre of vch a kynde</L>
<L N="172">His wit we sen but we be blynde;</L>
<L>And bi &thorn;e creatures meyntenyng</L>
<L>Of his godnes we han witeryng.</L>
<L>So long and Brod as is &thorn;is world,</L>
<L N="176">Hei&yogh; and dep, schewe&thorn; him a lord</L>
<L>Of Miht and pouwer gret saun&yogh;faile,</L>
<L>Al made of nou&yogh;t wi&thorn;-oute trauayle.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 179-192 wanting in the Spec.</NOTE>Eyr &amp; ffuir on hei&yogh; ben founde,</L>
<L N="180">Water and Er&thorn;e heuy at grounde:</L>
<L>Of his wisdam hit schewe&thorn; a part,</L>
<L>And so to Ioyne hem a ful gret art.</L>
<L>Hedde fuir and water to-geder ben set,</L>
<L N="184">Not wysli don men wolden han let,</L>
<L>&THORN;at On &thorn;at o&thorn;er wolde distruye;</L>
<L>Hedde Eir be Ioyned to eor&thorn;e so druye,</L>
<L>Hit wolde for chyne, for to seye so&thorn;,</L>
<L N="188">No fruit wolde bere as hit now do&thorn;.</L>
<L>Water and Er&thorn;e are meynt to-gidere,</L>
<L>ffor grene &thorn;ing schulde not al to-whidere.</L>
<L>Gret wit and wisdam, as I ow tolde</L>
<L>In God &yogh;it &yogh;e may be-holde:<NOTE PLACE="marg">In the MS. vv. 189-190 &amp; 191-2 are transposed.</NOTE></L>
<L>How summe creaturs al-on</L>
<L>Han beoynge of him, as stok and ston;</L>
<L>And summe, as treo and gras and flour,</L>
<L N="196">Han lyf, but Ioye non ne no dolour;</L>
<L>Summe ben &amp; liuen &amp; fleon<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. felen</NOTE> lykyng,</L>
<L>As Beest and ffoul and ffisch fletyng;</L>
<L>Ouer alle &thorn;eose Mon bere&thorn; &thorn;e pris,</L>
<L N="200">ffor he ha&thorn; reson to make him wys&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; hym peringal lo here</L>
<L>To Angeles of heuene, to ben heor feere.
<PB REF="00000282.tif" N="274"></L>
<L>So muche may &yogh;it be monnes grace</L>
<L N="204">&THORN;at he mai passen an Angeles place.</L>
<L>Seynt Austyn, &thorn;e grete clerk, sei&thorn; ri&yogh;t so:</L>
<L>An Angeles place he wolde for-go</L>
<L>ffor to haue &thorn;e wor&thorn;i stede</L>
<L N="208">&THORN;at God ha&thorn; ordeynd for Monhede.</L>
<L>Herof I rede &thorn;ou take good keepe!</L>
<L>Elles &thorn;ou art wor&thorn;i gret schendschip,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou lyue aftur &thorn;i degre,</L>
<L N="212">Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ou hast such a dignite</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ing to beo &thorn;in vnderloute,</L>
<L>A-boue, bi-ne&thorn;e, and al aboute.</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;ing in eor&thorn;e, mon, in sum wyse</L>
<L N="216">Was maad of god for<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;or</NOTE> &thorn;i seruyse:</L>
<L>Hors &amp; Neet and eke Chamayle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e to ese in &thorn;i trauayle;</L>
<L>Lyn, fforre, fflax, Selk and Wolle,</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at diuersliche God &yogh;eue&thorn; at folle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e to kepe from chele and hete;</L>
<L>Beest, fisch &amp; foul, &amp; fruit, to &thorn;i mete.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;inke&thorn; par aunter hit is not so,</L>
<L N="224">ffor venymous bestes &thorn;ei don vs wo.</L>
<L>&THORN;e harmful creatures, verrement,</L>
<L>Weore maad til vre amendement,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei ben to vs a Chastisyng,</L>
<L N="228">And eke a wel feir techyng.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 229-234 wanting in the Spec.</NOTE>Whil &thorn;ou hast in &thorn;in hond a &yogh;erd,<NOTE PLACE="marg">exemplum</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e Child &thorn;er-of is sore aferd,</L>
<L>Of his vnti&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg">= Germ. Unzucht</NOTE> ful sone slakes</L>
<L N="232">And to his lore good keep he takes;</L>
<L>Hit make&thorn; &thorn;e child bo&thorn;e meke &amp; lowe,</L>
<L>A-Mende&thorn; him wel him-self to knowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e venymous beestes wel muche we dreden:</L>
<L N="236">&THORN;e beter &thorn;erfore vre lyf we leden.</L>
<L>ffor summe to vs &thorn;ei beo nuyouse,</L>
<L>Godes werk we knowe ful meruilouse&mdash;</L>
<L>Of Godes wisdam a wonder cast!</L>
<L N="240"><NOTE PLACE="marg">240 ff. wanting in the Spec.</NOTE>But of his goodnes be-hold atte last,</L>
<L>How Creatures &thorn;at ben Iure,<NOTE PLACE="marg">So V. and MS. Sim.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e Sky, Heuen, Sterres and heore nature
<PB REF="00000283.tif" N="275"></L>
<L>God ha&thorn; maad forte mowe endure</L>
<L N="244">Euermore wi&thorn;-outen eny gendrure;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ulke on eor&thorn;e eueri day &thorn;ei rote,</L>
<L>As on is ded, ano&thorn;ur is gote&mdash;</L>
<L>Such vertu in kuynde God con faste,</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;at longe I-nowh so mihte &thorn;ei laste,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if his wille were for euere and ay;</L>
<L>So multiplye &thorn;ei euer vche a day,</L>
<L>&THORN;at summe ben olde &amp; summe be newe,</L>
<L N="252">&THORN;orw &thorn;e godnesse of his vertue.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us mowe &yogh;e knowe bo&thorn;e more &amp; lesse</L>
<L>Godes Mi&yogh;t, his wit, and his goodnesse</L>
<L>In creatures, as I haue told,</L>
<L N="256">How gret, how good, how monifold.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e he ha&thorn; maad for vs al &thorn;is,</L>
<L>But we him loue we don amis.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow loue &yogh;iftes in &thorn;in entent,</L>
<L N="260">Loue him wel ra&thorn;er &thorn;at hit &thorn;e sent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is god al &thorn;ing aboue.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore me &thorn;inke&thorn; we schulde him loue;</L>
<L>And for him-self &yogh;it wel more,</L>
<L N="264">Whon we be-&thorn;enken vs of &thorn;is lore.</L>
<L>&THORN;is &thorn;e furste Contemplacioun</L>
<L>In Creatures of gret Renoun.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>&THORN;e secunde contemplacion In holy writ.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E secunde contemplacion is hit</L>
<L N="268">&THORN;at I seide, in holi writ.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &thorn;ow be lewed and con not rede,</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles ful wel &yogh;it may &thorn;ou spede</L>
<L>To herkene &thorn;e ffrere Sarmounyng</L>
<L N="272">And o&thorn;er priue Carpyng,</L>
<L>And loke &yogh;if &thorn;ou mowe ou&yogh;t &thorn;er lere</L>
<L>&THORN;in vnderstondyng to make more clere.</L>
<L>&THORN;er mai&yogh;t &thorn;ow lerne, as I trowe,</L>
<L N="276">Good from vuel for to knowe,</L>
<L>Sinne to hate, vertu to loue,</L>
<L>And to &yogh;erne &thorn;e Ioye aboue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pyne of helle for to drede,</L>
<L N="280">Nou&yogh;t loue &thorn;is world but for &thorn;i nede;
<PB REF="00000284.tif" N="276"></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at we of prechen,</L>
<L>Summe of &thorn;eos poyntes forso&thorn;e &thorn;ei techen.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore I prey &yogh;ou, take&thorn; good hede</L>
<L N="284">After holi writ &yogh;oure lyf to lede,</L>
<L>Godes wille so to knowe &thorn;er-Inne</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e mowe hate dedly sinne.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &yogh;e mowe knowe w&yogh;uch hit bene,</L>
<L N="288">I schal hem riken alle bedene,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e spices &thorn;at of hem launches.</L>
<L>Pride &thorn;e furste, ha&thorn; six<NOTE PLACE="marg">7 in the Spec.</NOTE> Braunches:<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 289 &amp; 290 are transp. in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e furste is cald vnbuxomnes:</L>
<L N="292">Of herte hit is a gret hi&yogh;nes,</L>
<L>Make&thorn; mon to leeten &thorn;at him is boden<NOTE PLACE="marg">orig. beden</NOTE></L>
<L>And to don &thorn;at is forboden</L>
<L>Of God or Mon, his ouerlyng.</L>
<L N="296">&THORN;e secounde spice is Bostyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; mon forto him auaunte</L>
<L>Of good &thorn;at he wolde neuere haunte.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde spice is Ypocrisye&mdash;</L>
<L N="300">Schewest &thorn;e beter to Monnes ei&yogh;e</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;ou art &thorn;i-self wi&thorn;-Inne,</L>
<L>And leetest as &thorn;ou heddest neuer do synne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feor&thorn;e is clept Arrogaunce,</L>
<L N="304">&THORN;at schewes o&thorn;ur mennes mischaunce</L>
<L>And opene&thorn; al out heore wikkednes,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;yn may seme &thorn;e les;</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;er mennes schendschipe</L>
<L N="308">To &thorn;e &thorn;ow takest worschipe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e spice, hit is dispyt,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er menne goodnes sette&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. settest?</NOTE> luit,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow seist hit is not wor&thorn; a Bore,</L>
<L N="312">So &thorn;at &thorn;in may seme &thorn;e more.<NOTE PLACE="marg">The 6th in Spec., impudentia, is om.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e Sixte is cald Elacion,</L>
<L>Boldnesse of vuel &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast don;</L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; mon for to fonde</L>
<L N="316">Correxion hou he may wi&thorn;-stonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos ben &thorn;e spices most comuyn of pride,</L>
<L>&THORN;at spreden in &thorn;is world ful wyde.</L>
<L>Pruide in heuene furst bi-gon,</L>
<L N="320">And se&thorn;&thorn;en in eor&thorn;e to mony a Mon.
<PB REF="00000285.tif" N="277"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;eos &thorn;reo &thorn;inges as I schal telle,</L>
<L>Of Pruide moni on ha&thorn; &thorn;e smelle:</L>
<L>Of godes of kuynde, or of grace,</L>
<L N="324">Or elles of worldes purchace.</L>
<L>Streng&thorn;e, feirnesse, good wit, or kynne</L>
<L>Bi kynde &thorn;is mon ha&thorn; him wi&thorn;-Inne;</L>
<L>ffei&thorn;, Hope, Loue and Charite<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> Spec.: Scientia, virtus, gratia, bona fama, &amp; dignitas.</NOTE></L>
<L N="328">Goodes of grace &thorn;ei ben, parde;</L>
<L>ffeir Clo&thorn;es, Lond, Hous and Rent</L>
<L>Worldes purchase ben, verrement.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;eos &thorn;reo &thorn;inges pruide is born,</L>
<L N="332">&THORN;at make&thorn; mony a mon to be forlorn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e secunde synne, hit is Envy:</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;ur mennes wele hit is sori,</L>
<L>And of heor harm hit is fayn.</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;reo spices hit ha&thorn;, as men sayn:</L>
<L>In herte hit is furst, &thorn;orw vuel wille;</L>
<L>In word: &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebor Bakbyte and spille;</L>
<L>In werk, hit make&thorn; lered and lewed</L>
<L N="340">To his nei&yogh;ebor forte beo schrewed.</L>
<L>Wra&thorn;&thorn;e to &thorn;i soule Is mischaunce&mdash;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebor hit wilne&thorn; veniaunce;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou in herte bere hit longe,</L>
<L N="344">Hattreden hit engendre&thorn; swi&thorn;e stronge.</L>
<L>Herof come&thorn; cheste and Manasyng,</L>
<L>Vileynous wordes, and eke grucching,</L>
<L>Discord, Repref, deynous lokyng&mdash;</L>
<L N="348">&THORN;eos ben alle a foul ofspring.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e is slou&thorn;e in godes seruise.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 350-398 differ from Spec.</NOTE>&THORN;e Braunches &thorn;erof I wol deuyse:</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste is feyntise wi&thorn;-oute likyng,</L>
<L N="352">&THORN;at make&thorn; &thorn;e heui wi&thorn; alle &thorn;ing;</L>
<L>&THORN;at to&thorn;er is a tendernesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at suffre&thorn; no disese nor duresse;</L>
<L>Recheleschipe is &thorn;e &thorn;ridde&mdash;</L>
<L N="356">&THORN;ou takest no kep what men &thorn;e bidde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e feor&thorn;e is called Idelnesse,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou ne wolt worche, more ne lesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e is cald Auarice,</L>
<L N="360">&THORN;at ha&thorn; mony a sori spice:
<PB REF="00000286.tif" N="278"></L>
<L>&THORN;erof come&thorn; treson, and Robberie,</L>
<L>fforsweryng, Oker, and Symonye,</L>
<L>&THORN;ef&thorn;e, Beryng of fals witnesse,</L>
<L N="364">Ly&yogh;ing, and of herte hardnesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; &thorn;e no reu&thorn;e to haue</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at &thorn;e good craue.</L>
<L>Glotonye is &thorn;e Sixte synne,</L>
<L N="368">&THORN;at foule&thorn; mon wi&thorn;-oute and wi&thorn;-Inne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste spice is of glotenye</L>
<L>To ete more &thorn;en &thorn;ou may&yogh;t defye,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou art in hele nomeli;</L>
<L N="372">Ano&thorn;er is to ete to lustili.</L>
<L>Glotonye make&thorn; mon in hast</L>
<L>To breke holychirche fast.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde make&thorn; bisili to &thorn;enche</L>
<L N="376">What maner of mete his lust may quenche.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feor&thorn;e, &thorn;at make&thorn; mon as ded,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is foul drounkenhed&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is dedly, bi enchesoun</L>
<L N="380">&THORN;at hit bi-reue&thorn; mon his resoun;</L>
<L>But &yogh;if hit come wi&thorn;-oute fayle</L>
<L>Of feble brayn or gret trauayle,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;e drinke be strengor &thorn;en men wenen,</L>
<L N="384">ffor venial synne we hit demen.</L>
<L>Lecherie is on of<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. of of</NOTE> &thorn;e seuene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at greue&thorn; muche vr lord of heuene.</L>
<L>In to &thorn;is synne whon tweyne falle</L>
<L N="388">&THORN;at ben sengle, is lest of alle;</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;e wommon a Mayde be,</L>
<L>Worse is &thorn;at, &thorn;e secounde degre;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde is clept Holorie,</L>
<L N="392">&THORN;at wedlak breke&thorn;, is synne ful hye;</L>
<L>Incest &thorn;e fer&thorn;e, whon &thorn;ou lyst bi</L>
<L>&THORN;i gostly kyn or bodili;</L>
<L>&THORN;e worste of alle is Sodomye,</L>
<L N="396">Vn-kyndely synne, foul Ribaudye&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore ha&thorn; God taken gret wreche.</L>
<L>Of dedly synne her ende&thorn; my speche.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000287.tif" N="279">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e Seuene blessynges of &thorn;e gospel, Seuene dedli Synnes remedie.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But of heore remedies nou wol I telle</L>
<L N="400">&THORN;at crist sei&thorn; in &thorn;e holi gospelle.</L>
<L>&THORN;o ben &thorn;e benisouns seuene;</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;eose synnes &thorn;ei ben ful euene.</L>
<L>"&THORN;e Meke of spirit &thorn;ei ben blest,</L>
<L N="404">ffor heoren is &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at euer schal last:"</L>
<L>&THORN;is Blessyng a&yogh;eyn pride is riht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at be-reue&thorn; mon God almi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>"&THORN;e Mylde be&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">on erasure; r. ben</NOTE> blessed &thorn;at loue&thorn; no strif,</L>
<L N="408">ffor &thorn;ei schul haue &thorn;e lond of lyf":</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes Envye &thorn;at was sayd,</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;ur mennes hauyng &thorn;at neuer was payd,</L>
<L>But of Mischef of his nei&yogh;ebore</L>
<L N="412">He is glad, and of his lore.</L>
<L>"Blessed ben &thorn;o &thorn;at Mournen I-wis</L>
<L>ffor heore frendes &thorn;at &thorn;ei mys;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei schul ben cumforted wonder wel":</L>
<L N="416">A&yogh;eynes wra&thorn;&thorn;e hit is sumdel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at discumforte&thorn; mon him-selue</L>
<L>And &thorn;o abouten him, ten or twelue.</L>
<L>"&THORN;e Merciful ben blessed, for-&thorn;i</L>
<L N="420">God of hem schal haue merci":</L>
<L>&THORN;at is a&yogh;eyn Couetyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e nedful wol not diuyse.</L>
<L>"&THORN;at hungren and &thorn;ursten ri&yogh;twysnesse,</L>
<L N="424">&THORN;ei<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;at</NOTE> [schul] ben fulled more and lesse":</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e Slowe &thorn;at nou&yogh;t wol wirke;</L>
<L>Of alle gode dedes him &thorn;inkes irke.</L>
<L>"I-blessed ben alle of herte clene,</L>
<L N="428">ffor godes owne face &thorn;ei schul sene":</L>
<L>Herof &thorn;e gloten may aske ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>ffor of his foule wombe is al his &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>"&THORN;at louen pes &thorn;ei blessed ben alle,</L>
<L N="432">ffor Godes children men schul hem calle":</L>
<L>&THORN;e Lechour in herte he ha&thorn; no rest;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. pes</NOTE> &thorn;erfore his part is lest.
<PB REF="00000288.tif" N="280"></L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;i woundes now hastou salue,</L>
<L N="436">&THORN;e blessynges &yogh;iuen of godes bi-halue.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it ben &thorn;ei spedful to lest [&amp;] most,</L>
<L>Seuen &yogh;iftes of &thorn;e holigost.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e Seuen &yogh;iftes of &thorn;e holigost.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon &thorn;ou art hol sound, &thorn;e to lede</L>
<L N="440">Tak heer furst &thorn;e spirit of drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; mon furst from vuel to wynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;e spirit of pite, wel forto bigynne</L>
<L>Gode werkes; &thorn;at han a wel gret fo</L>
<L N="444">Of worldes wele and eke of wo:</L>
<L>&THORN;e spirit [of] cunnyng teche&thorn; vs dispise</L>
<L>&THORN;e worldes wele [&yogh;if we ben wyse];<NOTE PLACE="marg">So MS. Sim.; V. and eke of wo</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e spirit of streng&thorn;e, to suffre &thorn;e wo.</L>
<L N="448">&THORN;eose foure to bisy lyf longen into,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we callen Actyf lyf.</L>
<L>&THORN;e o&thorn;er &thorn;reo rulen Contemplatyf.</L>
<L>In Creatures to knowen God verrement,</L>
<L N="452">&THORN;e spirit vs teche&thorn; of entendement;</L>
<L>&THORN;e spirit of counseil, what is to do</L>
<L>In writ, what is to leue also;</L>
<L>To knowe god In his owne kynde,</L>
<L N="456">&THORN;e spirit of wysdam vs bringe&thorn; to mynde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e Seuene vertues.<NOTE PLACE="marg">In the Spec. the 10 Com|mandments precede.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>After &thorn;is &yogh;it is good to knowe</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen vertues alle be rowe,</L>
<L>ffor aftur &thorn;is lyf &thorn;ei wol &thorn;e bringe</L>
<L N="460">To blisse &thorn;at neuer schal haue endynge.</L>
<L>ffei&thorn;, Hope, and Charite,</L>
<L>Diuine vertues &thorn;ei ben alle &thorn;re;</L>
<L>Streng&thorn;e, Mesure, Riht, qweyntise</L>
<L N="464">Of kuyndelich vertues &thorn;ei beren &thorn;e prise.</L>
<L>A bodilich Iurneye hose schulde go,<NOTE PLACE="marg">exemplum</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;reo &thorn;inges him were nedful &thorn;erto:</L>
<L>ffurst, &thorn;at he wuste whoder he schulde;</L>
<L N="468">And wille, his Iurney to be for&thorn;-fulde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde, Hope for to spede&mdash;</L>
<L>Elles &thorn;er-of nolde he take hede.
<PB REF="00000289.tif" N="281"></L>
<L>ffei&thorn; of God &yogh;iue&thorn; vs witerynge</L>
<L N="472">Of vr Iurney &thorn;at is endynge;</L>
<L>Hope vs &yogh;iue&thorn; streng&thorn;e and miht</L>
<L>To come to him as heo han tiht;</L>
<L>But wille &thorn;en &yogh;iue&thorn; vs Charite&mdash;</L>
<L N="476">How mi&yogh;te we &thorn;enne for-go &thorn;eose &thorn;re?</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">The 4 cardinal virtues form a separate chapt. in the Spec.</NOTE>Ne &thorn;e foure o&thorn;ure neuer &thorn;e more.</L>
<L>Her &thorn;ou now &thorn;e skile &thorn;erfore!</L>
<L>&THORN;er may no mon God wel qweme</L>
<L N="480">But he cunne good from vuel deme,</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode to hente, &thorn;e vuel forsake,</L>
<L>Of twei godes &thorn;e better to take.</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit is good, vche mon trowe&thorn;,</L>
<L N="484">ffor to &yogh;elde alle &thorn;ing &thorn;at him owe&thorn;,</L>
<L>And for to wi&thorn;-holde more or lesse</L>
<L>Is vuel: &thorn;at teche&thorn; vs Rihtwysnesse.<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 483-6 corrupted.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of twey goodes &thorn;e beter to hente,</L>
<L N="488">Qweyntise vs teche&thorn;, verremente.</L>
<L>Good &thorn;ing men mihte mis-vse, I-wis:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore Mesure neodful is.</L>
<L>Vuel mihte mon to muche doun bringe:</L>
<L N="492">Streng&thorn;e &thorn;erfore is nedful &thorn;inge,</L>
<L>To<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Ta</NOTE> make mon hard to suffre wo.</L>
<L>To ten Comaundemens now wol I go.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e ten Comaundemens.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Eose biddinges wol I not ouer-hippe.</L>
<L N="496">On God &thorn;ou schalt worschippe.</L>
<L>His nome &thorn;ou ne schalt in Idel munginge (!).<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. munge, minge</NOTE></L>
<L>Halewe &thorn;in halyday, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde biddinge.</L>
<L>&THORN;eose rulen &thorn;i lyf, alle &thorn;re,</L>
<L N="500">To &thorn;e holi Trinite.</L>
<L>A-&yogh;eyn &thorn;e furste biddyng &thorn;ou mischeuest,</L>
<L>On eny wicchecraft &yogh;if &thorn;ou bileeuest.</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e secunde &thorn;i-self &thorn;ou derest,</L>
<L N="504">Horible o&thorn;es whon &thorn;ou swerest&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;it mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou swere wi&thorn;-outen synne</L>
<L>ffalsede to dampne, &thorn;e ri&yogh;te to wynne.</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e &thorn;ridde &thorn;ou dost wronge</L>
<L N="508">Whon &thorn;ou lyst in &thorn;i bed so longe
<PB REF="00000290.tif" N="282"></L>
<L>&THORN;at Matyns nor Masse herest &thorn;ou non,</L>
<L>To ffreres prechinge wolt &thorn;ou not gon&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-Inne of swetnesse &thorn;ou felest no tast;</L>
<L N="512">Bote to &thorn;e tauerne &thorn;e &thorn;inke&thorn; more hast</L>
<L>&THORN;en to visyte &thorn;e seke or &thorn;e pore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at liggen a-tome or at &thorn;i dore;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou dost &thorn;us, so&thorn; to say,</L>
<L N="516">&THORN;ou halewest not wel &thorn;yn halyday.</L>
<L>Godes curtesye her mai&yogh;t &thorn;ow se:</L>
<L>To him-self he &yogh;af biddynges but &thorn;re;</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen &thorn;at comen herafter nou</L>
<L N="520">To &thorn;e and to &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebores prou.</L>
<L>ffader and Moder &thorn;ow most honoure;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; foul cher not on hem to<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. to</NOTE> loure;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if heo of &thorn;yne habbe&thorn; gret nede,</L>
<L N="524">But &thorn;ou hem helpe, vuel schalt &thorn;ou spede.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou sle no mon,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hond ne wi&thorn; wepene non,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;orw &thorn;yn owne gilerye</L>
<L N="528">Nou&yogh;where to puite him for to dye;</L>
<L>Sle no mon wi&thorn; tonge, biddynge,</L>
<L>Beo tisement ne bi procurynge;</L>
<L>In herte Coueyte no mon to spille&mdash;</L>
<L N="532">To borwe him ra&thorn;ure is godes wille,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou hit may do lawefully,</L>
<L>Elles of &thorn;is biddynge &thorn;ow art gulti.</L>
<L>Stele non o&thorn;ure monnes good.</L>
<L N="536">ffrom fals witnes &thorn;ow torn &thorn;i mood.</L>
<L>&THORN;i nei&yogh;ebores good &thorn;ow schalt not desyre,</L>
<L>Wyf nor Mayde-child for heor white swire.</L>
<L N="539">Loke &thorn;ou do no Lecherie,</L>
<L>&THORN;i-self for &thorn;at wol most anuye.<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 539-40 ought to follow v. 534.</NOTE></L>
<L>But i prei &thorn;e, &thorn;ou seist, telle me &thorn;e skile</L>
<L>Whi god forbed ra&thorn;ur vuel wille</L>
<L>Of worldes good, and of Monnes wyf,</L>
<L N="544">&THORN;en to bi-reue a Monnes lyf.</L>
<L>ffor, hose is in wille for to stele,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; o&thorn;er monnes wyf or wi&thorn; to dele,</L>
<L>Hit is hardore him-self &thorn;er-from to holde</L>
<L N="548">&THORN;en from monslau&yogh;t, be &thorn;ou bolde!
<PB REF="00000291.tif" N="283"></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;erof kyndeliche vche monnes sone</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; gret Abhomynacione;</L>
<L>But wra&thorn;&thorn;e ha&thorn; him his resun raft,</L>
<L N="552">Wi&thorn; him &thorn;erof horrour is laft,</L>
<L>After &thorn;e dede or elles be-foren&mdash;</L>
<L>Elles mony mon schulde be for-loren.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Of twelue articles of vre be-leue.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But no mon may, &thorn;e Bok hit sei&thorn;,</L>
<L N="556">Plese God wi&thorn;-outen fei&thorn;.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore mo &thorn;inges is good to meue:</L>
<L>&THORN;e twelue articles of vre bi-leue.</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e twelue &thorn;is is &thorn;e most:</L>
<L N="560">&THORN;at ffader &amp; Sone and Holi gost</L>
<L>On God Almihti in Trinite</L>
<L>Euer was, and is, and euer schal be;</L>
<L>Heuene and eor&thorn;e he ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="564">And al &thorn;is world he maade of nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffader sende his sone Ihesu</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;e holygost vertu,</L>
<L>God and Mon of Mayde Marie</L>
<L N="568">To be boren, and for vs to dye,</L>
<L>And buried was, &thorn;orw his good wille,</L>
<L>To sauen vs alle &thorn;at we ne schulde spille.</L>
<L>To helle he wente whon he was ded,</L>
<L N="572">&THORN;e soule Ioyned to his godhed;</L>
<L>ffrom helle he hem fette swi&thorn;e blyue</L>
<L>&THORN;at him hedde serued in heore lyue.</L>
<L>Vp he ros &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day,</L>
<L N="576">As he was God and Mon verray;</L>
<L>Riht so schul we, as sei&thorn; seint poule,</L>
<L>Rysen vp in bodi and in soule</L>
<L>At &thorn;e grete day of doom&mdash;</L>
<L N="580">&THORN;erof I rede we take good goom!</L>
<L>&THORN;en schal he demen al apert</L>
<L>Vche mon after his decert.<NOTE PLACE="marg">orig. dicert</NOTE></L>
<L>God and Mon to heuene he went;</L>
<L N="584">&THORN;e holigost to &thorn;e Apostles sent.</L>
<L>&THORN;orw him so mowe we heuene wynne,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we dyen out of dedly synne.<NOTE PLACE="marg">All these form 5 articles in the Spec.; the 7 last are the 7 sacraments.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000292.tif" N="284">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e seuene Sacramens.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Off<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. On</NOTE> &thorn;e seuene sacramens &yogh;it mote we trowe,</L>
<L N="588">&THORN;at I schal rikene al be Rowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffurste, hit is cristendom,</L>
<L>&THORN;at cryst receyued in &thorn;e fflom;</L>
<L>Hit make&thorn; vs clene of &thorn;at synne</L>
<L N="592">&THORN;at we be boren vchone Inne,</L>
<L>And opene&thorn; to vs heuene-&yogh;ate,</L>
<L>Elles may no mon come in &thorn;er-ate.</L>
<L>But &thorn;orw gret temptacion</L>
<L N="596">&THORN;at grace mi&yogh;te be struied soon:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore is Confirmacion&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at non may but Bisschop don;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holigost hit stable&thorn; ri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="600">In &thorn;e, a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e fend to fiht.</L>
<L>But after &thorn;eose we sungen al day:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore penaunce hit do&thorn; a-way</L>
<L>Dedly synne and venial,<NOTE PLACE="marg">orig. veniel</NOTE></L>
<L N="604">&THORN;at is to seye gret synne and smal;</L>
<L>&THORN;reo parties hit ha&thorn;, verrey penaunce,</L>
<L>&THORN;erof &thorn;e synful mai ha fyaunce:</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;inke &thorn;e synne wilfulliche,</L>
<L N="608">And schriue &thorn;e &thorn;enne verreiliche,</L>
<L>And make a-mendes to &thorn;i miht&mdash;</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;i synnes &thorn;en art &thorn;ow quiht.<NOTE PLACE="marg">= quit</NOTE></L>
<L>But leste in penaunce mon schulde fayle,</L>
<L N="612">Him neode&thorn; cumfort in &thorn;at trauayle:</L>
<L>Hosul &thorn;erfore, in Bredes heu&yogh;</L>
<L>Godes bodi, we tan, of gret vertu;</L>
<L>Vre gostli streng&thorn;e hit holde&thorn; Inne,</L>
<L N="616">&THORN;at we ne falle li&yogh;tli a&yogh;eyn to synne.</L>
<L>But in a wel-ruled halle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ben &thorn;er-Inne &thorn;ei serue not alle,</L>
<L>Out of array for &thorn;enne hit were&mdash;</L>
<L N="620">In holichirche &thorn;e same manere:</L>
<L>Ordre of presthod is maad &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L>Vs to serue lasse and more</L>
<L>Of Sacramens and vre rihtynges&mdash;</L>
<L N="624">Presthod ha&thorn; power of alle &thorn;eos &thorn;ynges;
<PB REF="00000293.tif" N="285"></L>
<L>Gret worschip owen we alle &thorn;er-to:</L>
<L>Prest sacres &thorn;at bodi, &thorn;at aungel ne may do.</L>
<L>But god schop mon forte restore</L>
<L N="628">&THORN;e noumbre of angeles &thorn;at is forlore,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw kyndelich generacioun,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto he &yogh;af his benisoun</L>
<L>&THORN;at Monkynde mihte multiplie,</L>
<L N="632">Wi&thorn;-oute synne of Lecherye</L>
<L>Mon and wommon to-gedere Ioyne;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore he ordeynde Matrimoyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at dedli synne hit do&thorn; a-wei&mdash;</L>
<L N="636">But &thorn;e venial wol I not sey.</L>
<L>But of &thorn;is world whon we schul wende,</L>
<L>Gret peyne we han &thorn;enne at vr ende:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore is holi Oynement,</L>
<L N="640">&THORN;at vs alegge&thorn;, verreyment,</L>
<L>Of peyne we han &thorn;enne bodily,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;at we dreden gostly;</L>
<L>Such vertu God herto con lene</L>
<L N="644">To folfille &thorn;e penaunce &thorn;at na&thorn; mad clene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e seuene dedes of Merci.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bute at &thorn;e dredful domes-day</L>
<L>Mon schal haue an hard a-say,</L>
<L>ffor he schal &thorn;enne a-posed be</L>
<L N="648">Of &thorn;e dedes of Charite.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore is good now to witen</L>
<L>W&yogh;uche hit ben, as hit is writen.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffurste is, fede &thorn;e hungri.</L>
<L N="652">&YOGH;eue drinke to &thorn;e &thorn;ursti.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde, &thorn;e naked for to clo&thorn;e.</L>
<L>To herborwe &thorn;e pore be &thorn;ou not lo&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Visyte hem &thorn;at ben in prisoun bounde.</L>
<L N="656">Cunforte &thorn;at seknesse ha&thorn; cast to grounde.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;eose sixe &thorn;e gospel speke&thorn;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seue&thorn;e Tobye vs he &thorn;at teche&thorn;:</L>
<L>To burie &thorn;e dede Is Charite&mdash;</L>
<L N="660">In Bodi and soule quit schal hit be.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The rest of the chapter in the Spec. is omitted. as well as the foll. chapter: De septem petitionibus orationis dominicae.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000294.tif" N="286">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e seuene druweries<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. doweres</NOTE> of Monnus bodi.<NOTE PLACE="marg">The Engl. text is more detailed than the Spec., which in 1 chapter contains: de dotibus corporis &amp; anime &amp; de penis inferni.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;I Bodi schal haue druweries seuene,</L>
<L>As Monye &thorn;i soule, bo&thorn;e to in heuene,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e [whuch] schal rise &thorn;i grete blis&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-bi mai&yogh;t wyte what heuene is.</L>
<L>&THORN;i bodi schal schyne so wondur feire,</L>
<L>No foulnesse schal hit a-peyre;</L>
<L>Seuenfold bri&yogh;tore &thorn;en is &thorn;e sonne</L>
<L N="668">Vche bodi schal be &thorn;at ha&thorn; hit wonne.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it was &thorn;er neuere foul of fli&yogh;t</L>
<L>As &thorn;i bodi so swift and li&yogh;t,</L>
<L>ffor in a twynclyng of an ei&yogh;e</L>
<L N="672">ffrom er&thorn;e to heuene &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t sty&yogh;e.</L>
<L>In bodi &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;it be so strong</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e er&thorn;e, wyd, dep, and long,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt mowe posse hit as a bal;</L>
<L N="676">As &thorn;ou wolt welde hit, &thorn;ou schal.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt ben fre, &thorn;at nou art bonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no &thorn;ing schal a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e stonde</L>
<L>To lette &thorn;e to passe whoder &thorn;ou schal,</L>
<L N="680">Er&thorn;e ne water ne stonene wal;</L>
<L>As oyle synke&thorn; &thorn;orw hol vessel,</L>
<L>So schal &thorn;i bodi perse al &thorn;ing wel.</L>
<L>Vre bodies &thorn;at here ben seke and sore,</L>
<L N="684">&THORN;ei schul haue hele for euer-more;</L>
<L>We schul beo so wel atese</L>
<L>&THORN;at hunger ne ferst nor no dissese</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;er wi&thorn;-Inne ne wi&thorn;-oute,</L>
<L N="688">Hurt nor langour we schul not doute.</L>
<L>&THORN;erto gret lykynge in &thorn;at lyue</L>
<L>We schul han in vr wittes fyue,</L>
<L>Vche a wit wi&thorn;-outen anguisch</L>
<L N="692">Schal haue his lykyng wi&thorn; a wusch:</L>
<L>ffeir siht lyking to &thorn;in ei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;yn Eres ful of melodye;</L>
<L>Tast, and Smel, and &thorn;y felyng,</L>
<L N="696">&THORN;ei schul be ful of gret lykyng;</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is Ioye schalt haue to-gider&mdash;</L>
<L>Vr lord of heuene bring vs &thorn;ider!
<PB REF="00000295.tif" N="287"></L>
<L>In &thorn;is lyf whon we best fare,</L>
<L N="700">Whon we be-&thorn;enk vs, we mai ha care</L>
<L>&THORN;at mischef of de&thorn; schal vs be-tyde;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore vr blisse may not a-byde:</L>
<L>But in heuene wi&thorn;-oute stryf</L>
<L N="704">Bodi and soule schal euere ha lyf;</L>
<L>&THORN;erof &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t &thorn;e wel affye,</L>
<L>ffor bodi and soule &thorn;ei schal neuur dye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e doweres of &thorn;e soule.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;I soule schal haue &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. his</NOTE> warisun:</L>
<L N="708">Of wit and wisdam so gret foysun</L>
<L>&THORN;at creatures alle, hi&yogh;e &amp; lowe,</L>
<L>In heuene &amp; eor&thorn;e, &thorn;ou schalt knowe;</L>
<L>Gret Ioye schal &thorn;at be, sikerliche!</L>
<L N="712">ffor mon disyre&thorn; kuyndeliche</L>
<L>To knowe &thorn;ing &thorn;at is vnkud;</L>
<L>ffrom &thorn;i knowyng nou&yogh;t schal ben hud.</L>
<L>ffrendschipe wi&thorn;-outen enemyte,</L>
<L N="716">&THORN;at schal ben a-no&thorn;er fe;</L>
<L>Such frendschipe in heuene among hem is</L>
<L>&THORN;at vs<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sim. vche</NOTE> is fayn of o&thorn;eres blis.</L>
<L>A-cord and pes wi&thorn;-outen stryf,</L>
<L N="720">fforso&thorn;e, hit schal be &thorn;ere so ryf:</L>
<L>&THORN;e bodi and soule, &thorn;at striuen here,</L>
<L>Vche to o&thorn;er schal be so dere</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e bodi schal no&thorn;ing wille</L>
<L N="724">But &thorn;at [&thorn;e] soule wol al be skille;</L>
<L>&THORN;yn e&yogh;en ben of so good assent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on lokes nowher verreyment</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;at o&thorn;er loke &thorn;er-wi&thorn;;</L>
<L N="728">&THORN;er schul ben alle in so good ki&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;at Bodi and soule vche wi&thorn; o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Schul to-geder no &thorn;ing so&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Worschipe wi&thorn;-outen vileny</L>
<L N="732">&THORN;er schul we haue, sikerly;</L>
<L>As kynges in trone sitte we schal,</L>
<L>Crouned wi&thorn; Angeles peryngal.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule, &thorn;at her ha&thorn; luitel maystrie</L>
<L N="736">Or &thorn;au&yogh; &thorn;e bodi be in gret anuye,
<PB REF="00000296.tif" N="288"></L>
<L>So gret miht &thorn;er schal hit haue</L>
<L>&THORN;at nou&yogh;t a&yogh;eynes hit schal quich nor quaue.</L>
<L>But trust nis non in worldes wele,</L>
<L N="740">Nou art &thorn;ou sek, nou art in hele,</L>
<L>Nou artou pore, now artou riche&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e blisse of heuene nis &thorn;at not liche:</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e meste part of &thorn;y Blis</L>
<L N="744">Schal be sikernesse of al &thorn;is.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seue&thorn;e blisse: &thorn;i soule in heuene</L>
<L>Schal &thorn;onke God wi&thorn; hi&yogh;e steuene,</L>
<L>As Angeles don wi&thorn; gret likynge,</L>
<L N="748">"Holi, Holi, Holi" is heore syngynge.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e peynes of helle, &amp; amonesting.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hit is no neod now for to telle</L>
<L>More of &thorn;e peynes &thorn;at ben in helle.</L>
<L>In bodi &amp; soule &thorn;ei han gret nuye,</L>
<L N="752">Of al &thorn;is Ioye &thorn;e contrarye.&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be-&thorn;enke &thorn;e, my dere frend, wel</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;is Ioye eueriche a del</L>
<L>&THORN;at god ha&thorn; ordeyned for &thorn;i solace</L>
<L N="756">Whon &thorn;ou schalt sen him in his face,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast gret Matere, sikerliche,</L>
<L>Him to loue souereynliche</L>
<L>&THORN;at such knowynge and such wit</L>
<L N="760">&YOGH;iue&thorn; vs of him in holy writ.</L>
<L>Nou hast &thorn;ou matere of holy speche</L>
<L>Vnwysore &thorn;en &thorn;ou for to teche;</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;ou spekest wi&thorn; eny mon</L>
<L N="764">&THORN;at more good con lere &thorn;en &thorn;ou con,</L>
<L>Sum of &thorn;eos Materes &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t enqwere,</L>
<L>Wel more good for to lere.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde Manere of contemplacion in god him-self.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tac hede nou &amp; &thorn;ou schalt se</L>
<L N="768">Of Contemplacion &thorn;e &thorn;ridde degre,</L>
<L>Of God hym-self wi&thorn;-outen doute,</L>
<L>Of Godhed wi&thorn;-Inne, monhed wi&thorn;-oute.</L>
<L>&THORN;re &thorn;inges &thorn;ou &thorn;enke, as I &thorn;e rede,</L>
<L N="772">Of crist vr lord in his monhede:
<PB REF="00000297.tif" N="289"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Incarnacion &thorn;e grete Mekenes,</L>
<L>And of his liuyng &thorn;e holynes,</L>
<L>And of his passion &thorn;e charite.</L>
<L N="776">At ones &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t not &thorn;enke &thorn;ise &thorn;re;</L>
<L>I schal departe hem, as I may,</L>
<L>Be &thorn;e houres of niht and day;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; double Contemplacione</L>
<L N="780">In vche an houre of god &thorn;ou mone:</L>
<L>Ones of his passioun,</L>
<L>And eft of o&thorn;er sesoun.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Contemplacion at Matines tyme.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At Mateynes &thorn;enk, aftur or bi-foren,</L>
<L N="784">W&yogh;at time &amp; vre, place crist was boren.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tyme was wynter, &yogh;if &thorn;ou be-holde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e vre was midni&yogh;t, wonder colde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e place, as doctours seyen and trowes,</L>
<L N="788">Was a toren hous wi&thorn;-outen wowes.</L>
<L>In Riche clo&thorn;us was he not wrapped,</L>
<L>In Cracche wi&thorn; ragges he was happed,</L>
<L>Bi-twene an Oxe and an As&mdash;</L>
<L N="792">Gret Meknes &thorn;er I-schewed was!</L>
<L>Be-&thorn;enk &thorn;e of &thorn;at cumpaignye</L>
<L>Of Iosep and of swete Marie,</L>
<L>Hou bisy &thorn;ei weren to kepe &thorn;at fode</L>
<L N="796">&THORN;at for us schulde dyen on Roode;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e herdes deuocion,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e Angeles &thorn;at songen abouen</L>
<L>"Ioye be to god &thorn;at is on hi&yogh;"&mdash;</L>
<L N="800">In herte so syng &thorn;ou priuely.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;enk how Iudas also outrayde</L>
<L>At midni&yogh;t, whon he crist be-trayde;</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;e Iewes &thorn;ei him be-caste,</L>
<L N="804">And as a &thorn;eef &thorn;ei bounden him faste,</L>
<L>And as a feloun &thorn;ei for&thorn; him lad.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e traitour a Cos him bad,</L>
<L>In speche he was so Meke &amp; hende:</L>
<L N="808">His traytur he calde his dere frende.</L>
<L>In dede also he schewed non awe,</L>
<L>fforbed al hise wepne to drawe,
<PB REF="00000298.tif" N="290"></L>
<L N="811">And Malcus ere, &thorn;at Peter of smot,</L>
<L>Heled hit a&yogh;eyn, not chid nor flot.<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 811-12 and 813-14 are transp. in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Biforen Anna i-lad and Cayphas</L>
<L>Vileynesliche &thorn;er I-boffeted was,</L>
<L>And petur &thorn;ryes wi&thorn;-Inne a &thorn;rowe</L>
<L N="816">ffor-sok him, ar cok hedde &thorn;ries crowe.</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e Apostles euerichon</L>
<L>A-wey &thorn;ei fledde, wi&thorn; him lafte non.<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 817-18 ought to precede v. 813.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Of contemplacion at prime: of &thorn;e passion, and of &thorn;e Resureccion.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Off &thorn;e passion &thorn;enk at prime,</L>
<L N="820">Of cristes vprist &thorn;e same tyme.</L>
<L>Crist in to a &yogh;ard at prime him<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. he, cf. v. 826.</NOTE> ladde</L>
<L>And fals witnesse a&yogh;eyn him hadde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seiden hou he hedde god dispised,</L>
<L N="824">&THORN;e cuntre al tornd and dyuised</L>
<L>ffrom Ierusalem to Galyl&eacute;&eacute;.</L>
<L>And in his face &thorn;en spitten heo,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei hudden his face &amp; bobed his hede</L>
<L N="828">And scorned him and bad hym rede</L>
<L>Ho him smot &thorn;o wi&thorn; his fuste.</L>
<L>Nout he ne seide, &thorn;ou&yogh; he wel wuste.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e Resurexion.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enk also at prime, whon crist vp ros&mdash;</L>
<L N="832">&THORN;erof wydewhere sprong &thorn;e loos&mdash;</L>
<L>Vyue si&thorn;es apecred he &thorn;at day</L>
<L>To his derlynges, so&thorn; to say:</L>
<L>ffurst to Maudeleyn, &thorn;at was him dere,</L>
<L N="836">Whon heo &thorn;houte him a gardynere.</L>
<L>To hire and o&thorn;ure, verrement,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei comen from his Monument;</L>
<L>And seide "al heil! God saue &yogh;ow."</L>
<L N="840">And si&thorn;en to Peter&mdash;but we nute how.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e tyme as a straunge pilgrim</L>
<L>To twey disciples, &thorn;at knew not him,</L>
<L>Toward Emaus, &thorn;e goode Castel;</L>
<L N="844">In bred brekyng &thorn;en kneu&yogh; &thorn;ei him wel.
<PB REF="00000299.tif" N="291"></L>
<L>&THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e tyme to &thorn;e apostles ten,</L>
<L>But Thomas was not wi&thorn; hem &thorn;en;</L>
<L>But &thorn;at hit was he &thorn;ei nou&yogh;t bileeued,</L>
<L N="848">ffor a gost to hem he furst bi-semed,</L>
<L>Til he schewede bo&thorn;e foot and honde</L>
<L>Amiddes hem &thorn;er he con stonde,</L>
<L>"Pees to &yogh;ow" he seide &thorn;on&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei kneu&yogh; him wel whon he was gon.<NOTE PLACE="marg">The Spec. adds the 5 other apparitions.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Biforen vndurne: Of &thorn;e passion, and of Witsuntyd.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enk how crist at vndurne-tyde</L>
<L>Was dispoyled, bo&thorn;e bak and syde,</L>
<L>And to a piler &thorn;enne was he bounde</L>
<L N="856">And skourged so sore wi&thorn; mony a wonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at from &thorn;e foot to &thorn;e heued</L>
<L>Hol skin was on [him] luitel be-leued.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Mantel of Red &thorn;ei him cladde,</L>
<L N="860">Bi-foren &thorn;e folk &thorn;ei for&thorn; him ladde,</L>
<L>ffor Septre a reod token him in honde,</L>
<L>Crouned him wi&thorn; &thorn;orn, I vndurstonde,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">In the MS. vv. 867-8 precede v. 863.</NOTE>And &thorn;enne &thorn;ei kneled him be-forn</L>
<L N="864">And called him kyng al in scorn.</L>
<L>Vp-on Pilate &thorn;en gunne &thorn;ei crye</L>
<L>Ihesu on Rode to Crucifye.</L>
<L>He bar his Cros wi&thorn; gret anuye</L>
<L N="868">To &thorn;e place &thorn;er he schulde dye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Bifore vndurne of &thorn;e holigost.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enk also at &thorn;is same vre</L>
<L>&THORN;e holigost wi&thorn; gret honoure</L>
<L>Crist his apostles sende amonge,</L>
<L N="872">So wonderliche to speke wi&thorn; tonge</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk &thorn;at weoren of o&thorn;ur langage</L>
<L>Heo[m] vnderstoden, &amp; seiden outrage</L>
<L>&THORN;at of wyn dronken &thorn;ey were.</L>
<L N="876">&THORN;e holygost also schewed him ful clere</L>
<L>In fuir, to make hem hard and bolde,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei schulde not in mischef folde.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000300.tif" N="292">
<HEAD>At Midday: of &thorn;e anunciacion, And of &thorn;e passion.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At Middai be-&thorn;enk &thorn;e witerli</L>
<L N="880">Hou Gabriel grette vr swete ladi,</L>
<L>&THORN;enne conceiued heo crist Ihesu</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;e holigost vertu.</L>
<L>But whi wolde he take flesch &amp; blode</L>
<L N="884">And si&thorn;en dye for vs on Rode,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he mi&yogh;te ha saued Monkynde</L>
<L>Bi an Angel, as I fynde?</L>
<L>But &thorn;en schulde we ha loued be ri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="888">&THORN;e Angel more &thorn;en god Almi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>He wolde we loued him be-foren al o&thorn;ur:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore him-self bi-com vr bro&thorn;ur.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Also of &thorn;e passion.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enk hou crist was don on Rode&mdash;</L>
<L N="892">His bodi &thorn;en ron al on blode;</L>
<L>Bi-twene twey &thorn;eues he hynged;</L>
<L>Galle &amp; Eysel to him &thorn;ei menged</L>
<L>To drinke, for &thorn;urst whon he him pleined.</L>
<L N="896">ffor vre gult so was he peyned.</L>
<L>In al &thorn;is world &thorn;ow<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;orw</NOTE> peynes alle</L>
<L>Vpon o Mon mi&yogh;te falle</L>
<L>And he mi&yogh;te suffre as muche more</L>
<L N="900">As alle men &thorn;at nou ben bore,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same de&thorn; twye or &thorn;rie</L>
<L>&THORN;at crist suffrede &thorn;ou&yogh; he mi&yogh;t dye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at peyne &yogh;it were not so liche</L>
<L N="904">Nou&thorn;ur nei&yogh; so as his so miche.</L>
<L>Hit seme&thorn; wel &thorn;enne bi &thorn;at i telle</L>
<L>His peyne passe&thorn; &thorn;e pyne of helle</L>
<L>&THORN;at pure creature mi&yogh;te &thorn;ole, i-wis,</L>
<L N="908">ffor euere so may neuer on his.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>At Noon: of &thorn;e passion, and of &thorn;e Assencion.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>BE-&thorn;enk &thorn;e at &thorn;e vre of noon:</L>
<L>Whon crist hed seid &thorn;at al was don,</L>
<L>Mildeliche wi&thorn;-outen bost</L>
<L>To his ffader he &yogh;eld his gost,<NOTE PLACE="marg">The Spec. here gives the 7 words of Christ on the Cross; the Engl. text follows the Horae de Cruce, No. XIX.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000301.tif" N="293"></L>
<L>And to him he made a cri</L>
<L>Hely lama&yogh;abatani,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to seye aftur &thorn;e Book</L>
<L N="916">"ffader, whiere &thorn;ou me forsok?"</L>
<L>As hos sei&thorn;, &thorn;us here for to spille;</L>
<L>A, lord, for hit was &thorn;i wille.</L>
<L>A blynd kniht &thorn;en atte laste</L>
<L N="920">A Spere &thorn;orw [his]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;in</NOTE> herte &thorn;raste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Blod and water &thorn;en out &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>&THORN;erof we schulde take good hede:</L>
<L>&THORN;e blynde kni&yogh;t &thorn;erof cau&yogh;te his siht,</L>
<L N="924">And vre Bapteme &thorn;ere hedde mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Lord, &yogh;if me grace day and niht</L>
<L>To &thorn;enke how deolfulliche &thorn;ou were diht!</L>
<L>&THORN;e sonne for deol &thorn;en lees his liht,</L>
<L N="928">ffor to be wreken of his dispiht;</L>
<L>Hulles and dales &thorn;ei al to-schoken,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e stones al to-broken.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>At Non of &thorn;e Assencion.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enk also at &thorn;e vre of non</L>
<L N="932">Of Ihesu Assencion</L>
<L>On &thorn;e Mount of Olyuete,</L>
<L>Whon al &thorn;e Apostles &thorn;er gunne mete,</L>
<L>And his deore Moder Marie,</L>
<L N="936">In al heore siht vp gon he sty&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And sitte&thorn; on his ffader riht hond,</L>
<L>&THORN;at welde&thorn; bo&thorn;e S&eacute;&eacute; and Lond.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Apostles bi &thorn;e wey &thorn;at was geyn</L>
<L N="940">To Ierusalem &thorn;ei torned a-&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L>In preyer &amp; fastynge &thorn;er for to abyde,</L>
<L>As he hem bad, til witsontyde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>At euensong-tyme: of &thorn;e passion, and of &thorn;e Maunde.<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Monhede</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At Euensong-tyme &thorn;enk verreyli:</L>
<L N="944">ffor ded was founden his swete bodi,</L>
<L>Ioseph &thorn;enne of Aramathi</L>
<L>Tok him doun deuoutli,</L>
<L>Of Pilat, &thorn;at &thorn;enne was hei&yogh; Iustise,</L>
<L N="948">He asked no more for his seruyse.
<PB REF="00000302.tif" N="294"></L>
<L>&THORN;i pouwer, lord, whon &thorn;ow were ded,</L>
<L>Hit was hud in &thorn;y godhed;<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. XIX, v. 131.</NOTE></L>
<L>As gras is stomped for medicyne,</L>
<L N="952">So were &thorn;ou fruscht wi&thorn; muche pyne;</L>
<L>Allas for deol, bo&thorn;e euen and Morn,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Croune of blisse lai vnder a &thorn;orn!<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cf. XIX, v. 131: Heu corona glorie iacuit sub spina.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Now of &thorn;e Maunde of Ihesu crist.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At euensong-tyme of his Maunde</L>
<L N="956">&THORN;enk; wi&thorn; hou gret Charite</L>
<L>He wu&yogh;sch his owne apostles feete,</L>
<L>And of his Bodi alle &thorn;ei ete</L>
<L>As he heom &yogh;af in bredes heu&yogh;,</L>
<L N="960">And to Iudas, &thorn;at waried Ieu&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; he him wuste in synne derne,</L>
<L>His flesch &amp; blood &yogh;it nolde he him werne.</L>
<L>Ensaumple herof &thorn;e prest may haue</L>
<L N="964">Non hosul to werne hose wol hit craue,</L>
<L>In priue synne &thorn;ou&yogh; he him knowe&mdash;</L>
<L>To warne hym stilly is best, I trowe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>At cumplin-tyme: of his passion, and of his buriinge.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At Cumplin &thorn;enk wi&thorn; good entent</L>
<L N="968">Hou crist in to a gardyn went</L>
<L>After &thorn;e Maunde, forto prey</L>
<L>His ffader &thorn;at passion to don a-wey;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Monhede of hym so sore dredde &thorn;at</L>
<L N="972">&THORN;at blod &amp; water &thorn;er so he swat</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit dropped doun in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e eor&thorn;e from his face.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e buryinge of Ihesu crist.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Enk at Cumplyn: &thorn;e bodi of crist</L>
<L N="976">Was leid in graue til his vpryst,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Ioseph di&yogh;te for him-self hadde;</L>
<L>And in Sendel he him cladde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Mirre and Aloyne, good oynement,</L>
<L N="980">He Baumede him, wi&thorn; good entent.&mdash;</L>
<L>Lord, &yogh;if me grace swetnes to fynde</L>
<L>&THORN;eos Vres &thorn;us to haue in mynde,
<PB REF="00000303.tif" N="295"></L>
<L>&THORN;at suffredest for me &thorn;is harde paas!</L>
<L N="984">At myn ende hit be my solas.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Of Contemplacion of god in his owne kynde.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us schaltou &thorn;enke on his Monhed.</L>
<L>Now schal I teche of his godhed,</L>
<L>&THORN;at from vr knowyng sumdel is hud,</L>
<L N="988">And in foure wise to vs is kud:</L>
<L>In Creature, and in holy writ&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;erof Ichaue my tale quit;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde be Reuelacion,</L>
<L N="992">&THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e be monnes reson.</L>
<L>Bi Reuelacion God schewe&thorn; him-selue</L>
<L>As he dude to &thorn;e prophetes twelue</L>
<L>And to o&thorn;ere Mony on,</L>
<L N="996">Or be Miracle open I-don.</L>
<L>Bi reson &thorn;us God mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou kenne,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;e be-&thorn;enke whenne</L>
<L>&THORN;ou were nou&yogh;t or &thorn;ou boren were;</L>
<L N="1000">Of o&thorn;er Creatures &thorn;e same manere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at comen &amp; gon eueriche day;</L>
<L>&THORN;e so&thorn;e &thorn;er-bi wel wite &thorn;ou may</L>
<L>And bi reson vndertake</L>
<L N="1004">&THORN;at &thorn;ei mi&yogh;t not hem-seluen make;</L>
<L>Heore biginnynge se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t se,</L>
<L>And of hem-self &thorn;ei mowe not be,</L>
<L>&THORN;enne mostou nede grante sum &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="1008">&THORN;at neuer hedde no bi-gynnyng,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur &thorn;ynges of whom comen alle,</L>
<L>God Almihti &thorn;at men calle.</L>
<L>But twei goddes &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;er were,</L>
<L N="1012">&THORN;er moste nede be sum manere</L>
<L>Of diuersete hem bi-twene&mdash;</L>
<L>Al on elles moste &thorn;ei bene;</L>
<L>&THORN;en moste &thorn;at on, as wel I wot,</L>
<L N="1016">Sumwhat haue &thorn;at &thorn;e to&thorn;er hedde not;</L>
<L>&THORN;en hedde &thorn;at on, sikerliche,</L>
<L>Ou&thorn;er to luyte or to muche;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at he hedde to luitel,</L>
<L N="1020">He were not god almihtful;
<PB REF="00000304.tif" N="296"></L>
<L>And to muche &yogh;if &thorn;at he hadde,</L>
<L>A sori god were and a badde</L>
<L>&THORN;at to muche mi&yogh;te not do him fro&mdash;</L>
<L N="1024">To alle &thorn;ing for &thorn;at is so.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en two goddes &thorn;enne mowe not be,</L>
<L>On-lepi god &thorn;en graunte we.</L>
<L>But Ioye is non here in no two afye (!)<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. in to affye</NOTE></L>
<L N="1028">Wi&thorn;-outen riht good cumpaynye.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en God is ful of Ioye and blis,</L>
<L>In Godhed Cumpaynye &thorn;er is.</L>
<L>Be-twene lasse &thorn;en two mai hit not be:</L>
<L N="1032">Two persones in God &thorn;en mai we se.</L>
<L>But cumpaignie were nou&yogh;t, I wene,</L>
<L>But &thorn;er were loue hem bi-twene:</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde persone, I wol warante,</L>
<L N="1036">In Trinite &thorn;en moste we graunte,</L>
<L>To make loue and Charite</L>
<L>In &thorn;e holy Trinite.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us mowe we knowe anon</L>
<L N="1040">&THORN;reo persones and God but on.</L>
<L>In &thorn;i-self &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t a-tame<NOTE PLACE="marg">exemplum</NOTE></L>
<L>Open ensaumple of &thorn;is same:</L>
<L>In &thorn;i soule &thorn;ou seost ful wel</L>
<L N="1044">Miht and Connynge &thorn;ou hast sumdel;</L>
<L>&THORN;i mi&yogh;t &amp; Connynge &thorn;e wi&thorn;-Inne</L>
<L>To loue hem bo&thorn;e &thorn;ou const not blynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;i miht is furst, and &thorn;enne cunnynge,</L>
<L N="1048">And of hem bo&thorn;e come&thorn; louynge.</L>
<L>&THORN;e same manere in god aboue:</L>
<L>Miht and Connynge and eke loue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffader we callen &thorn;e furst Miht,</L>
<L N="1052">Connynge &thorn;e Sone, of him come&thorn; riht;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holigost loue we calle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at come&thorn; of bo&thorn;e, knowleche we alle.</L>
<L>Al Monkynde [knowe&thorn;] in toun and felde</L>
<L N="1056">&THORN;e ffader waxe&thorn; feble in his elde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sone in his &yogh;ou&thorn;e is not wys,</L>
<L>Of Monnes gost come&thorn; Malys.</L>
<L>In god lest men wolde wene &thorn;e same,</L>
<L N="1060">&THORN;e ffader ha&thorn; mi&yogh;t, &thorn;e Sone wisdame;
<PB REF="00000305.tif" N="297"></L>
<L>His miht is euer gret inlike,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sones wisdam may nou&yogh;t be swike.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Holigost he ha&thorn; goodnesse,</L>
<L N="1064">Wi&thorn;-outen Malys More and lesse.</L>
<L>To knowe god &thorn;us furst men come</L>
<L>Bi resun&mdash;so mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou, &yogh;if &thorn;ou take gome</L>
<L>&THORN;in herte to god vp so to lifte,</L>
<L N="1068">In &thorn;eose &thorn;reo wyse as I skifte:</L>
<L>By his werk, and holy writ,</L>
<L>And bi resun of monnes wit</L>
<L>And of him-self in double kynde.</L>
<L N="1072">Wel ou&yogh;te we &thorn;enne haue him in mynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;is world wi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;er-Inne</L>
<L>&YOGH;af, and him-self, vr loue to wynne.</L>
<L>Nou &thorn;ou him knowest &amp; his bounte,</L>
<L N="1076">Loue him wel for Charite</L>
<L>Euer-more to &thorn;i lyues ende!</L>
<L>To Ioye &amp; blisse &thorn;en schaltou wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ha&thorn; ordeyned for vre solace.</L>
<L N="1080">Lord, bring vs &thorn;ider for &thorn;i grace. Amen.</L>
<L>&THORN;us ende&thorn; &thorn;e spore of loue&mdash;</L>
<L>God grant vs &thorn;e blisse of heuene aboue.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Then follows the well-known 'Disputacion bytwene &thorn;e bodi and &thorn;e soule,' ed. before by Th. Wright, <I>Walter Mapes</I>, p. 340 ff., and extant in 5 other, partly very old MSS. (MS. Auch., ed. in <I>Owain Miles</I>, Edinb. 1837, Laud 108, Digby 102, Reg. 18 A x, and Simeon), mostly printed, wherfore I omit it here. Cf. Anglia II. p. 225.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
