<L>[&THORN;en]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. ffor T &thorn;anne L &thorn;o</NOTE> al wox won Bodi and leore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &THORN;anne wax wan bo&thorn;e hyde &amp; lere L &THORN;o wex he al wan liche &amp; lere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="352">&THORN;at feirest was of alle fode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">TL fairest.</NOTE></L>
<L>"So feir &yogh;it was neuer nomon,<NOTE PLACE="foot">L ffor so. D fayr a man. DL om. &yogh;it. T was &yogh;ut. T noman D non L man.</NOTE></L>
<L>As bere&thorn; witnesse holy writ:<NOTE PLACE="foot">D beri&thorn; T beri&yogh;t. DL witnes. T in holy. D writte.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;enne was his beute al a-gon,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D &THORN;er TL &THORN;us. T bewte L beaute D fayrhed. D &thorn;an al gon. T agan.</NOTE></L>
<L N="356">As &thorn;e gospel telle&thorn; hit.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T Al-so. D &thorn;e apostelis tellin itte.</NOTE></L>
<L>I hedde a sone, nou haue<NOTE PLACE="marg">D &thorn;an had</NOTE> I non,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D had TL hadde. D &thorn;an had.</NOTE></L>
<L>Me wonte&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">D wantid</NOTE> bo&thorn;e weole and wit;<NOTE PLACE="foot">D wantid T wante&thorn; L wantes. DTL wele. D witte.</NOTE></L>
<L>I not<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> ne wiste, nyste</NOTE> in world whoder to gon<NOTE PLACE="foot">DTL Bernard (L And) I ne wiste (T y nyste) whedir (TL whyder).</NOTE></L>
<L N="360">ffor serwe &thorn;at in myn herte sit.<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Sorwe was in myn herte so knytte TL &THORN;e sorwe &yogh;ut (L &yogh;ette) at m. h. sit.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Bernard, hedde I honged him bi,<NOTE PLACE="foot">DT But (T ffor) had &thorn;ei (om. in D) hongid (T hanged) me (T my sone) him (T me) bi L Bot euery (!) I was him faste by.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sum-tyme my serwe hedde be pas.<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Mi sorwe had ben in schortere spas L ffor any &thorn;at euere &thorn;er was T S. my sorwe my&yogh;te pas.</NOTE></L>
<L>I stod and loked vppon hi&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">L stoed. D lokid TL lokede. T op an. L hey.</NOTE></L>
<L N="364">Wher heng my ioye and my solas,<NOTE PLACE="foot">TL Where &thorn;at henge al my solas.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes sei&yogh; me ful sori,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D saw L seyen T made. TL om. ful; D &thorn;an.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er as I stod in &thorn;e plas:<NOTE PLACE="foot">D &thorn;ei bad me leue wi&thorn; sori gras TL &amp; skornede(n) me bo&thorn;e (om. in L) more &amp; las.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at I made sereweful cri,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D But euerc I was him ful ny. T And for. TL om. &thorn;at. TL so reuful.</NOTE></L>
<L N="368">&THORN;ei beede me schome and harde gras.<NOTE PLACE="foot">D ffor al my care I folewid his tras. T beden L bede. TL shame. L grace.</NOTE></L>
<L>"ffaste I cri&yogh;ede in my manere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T Mekel L Often D And often. DT cride L criede. DTL on.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;ut ne was I not I-herd;<NOTE PLACE="foot">DT But &thorn;er L Bot fer. DL om. ne; T no. L I was &amp;. T no&yogh;t L nought D no&thorn;ing. DT herd.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o I cri&yogh;ede, he mihte me<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> not</NOTE> here,</L>
<L>Witnesse bo&thorn;e of lewed and lered<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 vv. om.: cf. D Wol febil I was, weping in fere, &amp; of here vilenye aferd.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>'Merci!' I cri&yogh;ede to my sone dere,
<PB REF="00000322.tif" N="314"></L>
<L>'Al-one &thorn;ou leue[st] me in desert!'</L>
<L>&THORN;enne he bi-tok me til a fere</L>
<L N="376">And bad, I scholde not ben a-ferd.<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 375-6 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">371-6 D &amp; whan I cride &thorn;ei (r. he) wold not here, My pyne witnessi&thorn; lewid &amp; lerid. I seyde 'Merci, my sone so dere, Alone &thorn;ou leuist me in deserd.' Wol febil I was weping in fere, And of hire vilenye aferd. T ffeble y was &amp; wep in fere, &amp; of here velenye aferd. &THORN;at y cride &thorn;e&yogh; (r. he) my&yogh;te no&yogh;t here, My pyne witnesse&thorn; bo&thorn;e lewed &amp; lerd. 'Mercy, my sone, my fader dere, Alone &thorn;ou leuest me in &thorn;is desert.' L 'Mercy, sone, my fader deore, Alone &thorn;ou leueste me in deserte, Contforteles &amp; of feble chere Ande of &thorn;e gewes vilanye aferde.' Bot &thorn;at I criede men myghte not here, &THORN;erof bere witnes lewed &amp; lerede.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Allas, Bernard, &thorn;at I scholde se<NOTE PLACE="foot">TL om. &thorn;at. D schuld.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi sone hongen bifore my<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> naylid &thorn;orw hand &amp;</NOTE> feete!<NOTE PLACE="foot">DTL naylid &thorn;orw (T &thorn;orgh L &thorn;oruh) hand (TL honde) &amp; fete (T fet).</NOTE></L>
<L>I seide: 'Sone, let me dye wi&thorn; &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">DIT cride L Leoue. T lat. D deyen T deye.</NOTE></L>
<L N="380">Er &thorn;en &thorn;ou &thorn;i lyf for-lete!<NOTE PLACE="foot">L Er &thorn;at DT Longe or (T er). D he his lyf. T forlet.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi sone, my lord and al my gle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">L om. sone. TD om. and, T in alle gle D myn herte gle. L gleo.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast euere be Milde and swete:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &THORN;at were euere meke. D hast ben bo&thorn;e, euere om. L om. be.</NOTE></L>
<L>But &thorn;ou haue pite now of me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">DT mercy. TL om. now. DTL on.</NOTE></L>
<L N="384">&THORN;er may no mon my Bale bete.'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>D Who myht ellis my b. b. L om. &thorn;er; TL noman. T bot.</P><P>After 384 DTL have the following stanza: Sone (L A, sone) &thorn;ou hast ben fayr &amp; hende (T hast euere &yogh;ut ben h., L hast beon euere h.), &amp; bletheli (L gladliche) don al (om. in TL) &thorn;at I (&thorn;e TL) bad; If (T And &yogh;if) &thorn;ou leue (L leuest T loue) me at (L atte) swich an (TL om. sw. an) ende, Of sorwe schal I neuere ben (TL ne (om. in L) wor&thorn; y neuere) sad. fful (om. in TL) loth is deth &thorn;er he wile (L wole T wolde) lende (T sende), But (om. in L, T And) now wold I (L I wolde) of him (T of him y wolde) ben (T be L beo) glad, He ne may so sone his (TL a) spere sende (L me s.), &THORN;at (om. in L) soner (TL ra&thorn;er) I wolde &thorn;erof ben stad (TL &thorn;at y it had).</P></NOTE></L>
<L>"<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 385-432, the discourse with Magdalen, added by the poet. It was taken up by the Charta Christi in MS. Reg. 17 CXVII.</NOTE>I criede: 'Maudeleyn, help now&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">DT cride. DTL Magdaleyn. DL helpe T help me. T nowe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi sone ha&thorn; loued ful wel &thorn;e:<NOTE PLACE="foot">DTL ha&thorn; euere &yogh;et (L om. &yogh;et T &yogh;ut euere ha&thorn;) louid the.</NOTE></L>
<L>Preie him &thorn;at I dye mow,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. now</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">T And praye D And bidde. L to him. DT deye. D mow TL mowe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at I nout for-&yogh;eten be!<NOTE PLACE="foot">TL y for&yogh;eten (L for&yogh;ete) here no&yogh;t (L ne). D for&yogh;etin. L beo.</NOTE></L>
<L N="389">Seost &thorn;ow, Maudeleyn, now,<NOTE PLACE="foot">DTL Magda|leyn (L Magdelyn) mylde (om. in TL) ne (om. in T) seest &thorn;ou (T sestow L seostou) how.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi sone is honged on a tre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T My lord. D hangi&thorn; T deye&thorn; L die&thorn;. DL vpon. TL &thorn;e D &yogh;one. L treo.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;it alyue am I and &thorn;ow,<NOTE PLACE="foot">DT And &yogh;et (T &yogh;ut). D on lyue L oliue T on kneo. T er y D I am.</NOTE></L>
<L N="392">And &thorn;ou ne preyest not for me!'<NOTE PLACE="foot">D &thorn;at I myht deye &thorn;ou preye for me. TL om. ne. T no&yogh;t L nothinge.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Maudeleyn seide: 'I con no red,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &THORN;o magdaleyne L &thorn;e Magdeleyn. DTL can.</NOTE></L>
<L>Care ha&thorn; smiten myn herte sore;<NOTE PLACE="foot">DTL Sorwe. D smetin. T my.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000323.tif" N="315"></L>
<L>I stonde, I seo my lord neih ded,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Her I stonde T &yogh;is stand. DTL &amp; se (L seo). D him. DT ner.</NOTE></L>
<L N="396">And &thorn;i wepyng greue&thorn; me more.<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. sore</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">L om. And; D But T &amp; &yogh;ut. D greui&thorn;. DTL more.</NOTE></L>
<L>Cum wi&thorn; me! I wol &thorn;e lede<NOTE PLACE="foot">DL Come T Kom. TL wi&thorn; me lady (T lefdy). D &amp; I schal. T wil L wile. T led.</NOTE></L>
<L>In to &thorn;e temple her be-fore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Vnto a stede &thorn;ou saw not ore. T Intil. TL a.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> &thorn;y</NOTE> Mournynge is bo&thorn;e feble &amp; fede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">TD &THORN;y. L om. bo&thorn;e. TL faynt (feynte) &amp; L fade T sed.</NOTE></L>
<L N="400">ffor &thorn;ou hast now I-wept ful &yogh;ore.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">399-400 D &THORN;er may we morne wi&thorn;|oute drede Stille oure loue as nouhte ne wore.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">TL weped (L wepen) now.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ich askede &thorn;e Magdaleyn: 'wher is &thorn;at place,<NOTE PLACE="foot">DTL I. D askid. L om. &thorn;e Magdaleyn; DT hire. DTL was. DTL plas.</NOTE></L>
<L>In pleyn, in valeye or in hille,<NOTE PLACE="foot">TL playn. T om. in D valey L vale. L o&thorn;er. T on. D hil.</NOTE></L>
<L>[&THORN;er] I mai me huyde for eny cas,<NOTE PLACE="foot">DTL &THORN;er (TL &thorn;at) I myhte ben (T by L beo). T fore. L any.</NOTE></L>
<L N="404">&THORN;at no serwe come me tille?<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &THORN;at me ne come no sorwe. DL sorwe. D ne come.</NOTE></L>
<L>He &thorn;at al my Ioye was,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Of him TL In him.</NOTE></L>
<L>Now de&thorn; of hym wol don his wille;<NOTE PLACE="foot">TL om. Now. DTL wi&thorn;. T shel L shal D ha&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Con I me no beter solas<NOTE PLACE="foot">D In no stede is my s. TL Wot y now (om. in L) no b. s.</NOTE></L>
<L N="408">&THORN;en for to wepe al my fille.'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>D But. T wepyn L weopen. D euere al.</P><P>After 408 TL have the foll. stanza: I cride (L criede) to &thorn;e gewes ilkon (L echone): 'Why lat (L lete) &yogh;e me &thorn;us longe chyde? My voys (noyse) &yogh;e my&yogh;te a-bate anon Longe er it were pas(s)ed tyde. I am a mayden (mayde), he is (&amp; he) a man (mon): Why ne wille (L nile) &yogh;e hange (honge) me be his syde (him besyde. In L v. 3-4 &amp; 5-6 are transp.). &THORN;anne &yogh;e my&yogh;te (L myghte &yogh;e) be (beo) awreke anon; Wherto wille (wole) &yogh;e lenger abyde?'</P><P>Then DTL the foll. stanza: I cride (on him D) 'Ihesu, sone (T sone ihesu) hende, Swete fader, me is wo (D what schal I do?), I may not bryng (TL bringe) the out of bende, Ne &thorn;ou (L Ion) ne (om. in D) may (T my&yogh;t) not (om. in T) come me (L &thorn;e) to, Ne &thorn;ou wilt (L nilt) me no solas (T no solas wilt me) sende, Ne (TL &THORN;e) Magdaleyn ne othere mo. Best (D And best) me were hom (L oute) to wende, But (T And) for sorwe I may not (TL y ne may (L I may note) for sorwe) go. In D v. 5-6 &amp; 7-8 are transp.</P></NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;e Maudeleyn cumfortede me &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D om. &thorn;e. DTL Magdaleyn(e). D comfortid T confortide L confortede.</NOTE></L>
<L>To lede me &thorn;enne, heo seide, was best.<NOTE PLACE="foot">D &amp; seyde Go hom, &thorn;at were &thorn;e beste. TL hom inst. of &thorn;enne. TL she. T is.</NOTE></L>
<L>Care hedde smiten myn herte so<NOTE PLACE="foot">D ha&thorn; smetin.</NOTE></L>
<L N="412">&THORN;at I mi&yogh;te neuere haue no rest.<NOTE PLACE="foot">411-2 TL Bote (om. in L) wepynge dede (dide) me (MS. ne) wexe (L my body) wo, ffor sorwe ful ne&yogh; my lyf was (L my lyf was ney) lest.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">D At hom schuld I fynde no r.</NOTE></L>
<L>'Soster, whoderward &thorn;at I go,<NOTE PLACE="foot">DTL I seyde to hir (T soster L sostren) whedir-so (T whider L whare) I go.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000324.tif" N="316"></L>
<L>&THORN;e wo of hym is in my Brest;<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Al my ioye now haue I leste TL Ne (om. in L) shel (Shal) I neuere take rest.</NOTE></L>
<L>While my sone honge&thorn; so,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Whil &thorn;at TL ffor. T &thorn;at h. D hongi&thorn; T hange&thorn; L henge&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L N="416">His peyne is in myn herte fest.<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Care comi&thorn; neuere out of my brest TL Sorwe (T &thorn;e s.) is smyten &thorn;orghe (&thorn;oruhe) my brest.</NOTE></L>
<L>"'I seih<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. se</NOTE> my sone, [my] ffader dere<NOTE PLACE="foot">D se L seo T saw. DTL my fader.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hei&yogh;e hongen vp-on a tre;<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Hie. T honge, D hange here. T oppon. D &thorn;is. L treo.</NOTE></L>
<L>I hedde blisse whon I him bere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Wi&thorn;-oute peyne I dide him bere. TL hadde. T whanne L &thorn;o.</NOTE></L>
<L N="420">And now de&thorn; for-do&thorn; my gle:<NOTE PLACE="foot">L om. And. DTL wile (T wil) deth fordon (TL fordo). L gleo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Scholde I leten him hongen here<NOTE PLACE="foot">DT How schuld (T my&yogh;te). DL lete him T him lete. D hangen L honge.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lete my sone al-one be?<NOTE PLACE="foot">DT &amp; suffere (T soffren) him alone to be. L my child. beo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Maudeleyn, &thorn;enne vnkynde I were,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Ow Magdaleyn. DTL om. &thorn;enne.</NOTE></L>
<L N="424">&YOGH;if he schulde honge &amp; I schulde fle!<NOTE PLACE="foot">D schuld TL sholde. DT hange L hongen. L om. schulde.</NOTE></L>
<L>"'Vnder &thorn;e Cros leuen I-schille<NOTE PLACE="marg">1. chille</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">T crois. D beleuen T byleue. DTL I wille.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seo my sone hongen &thorn;er-on;<NOTE PLACE="foot">DTL I inst. of And. DT se. DTL my flesch. D hongin T honge L honge&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L N="427">Of si&yogh;t I nedde neuere my fille,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Of &thorn;at sihte. T sich. T y hadde DL had(de) I.</NOTE></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> Whan I him saw on erthe gon</NOTE>Whon I loke[d] hym vppon.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Whil. DTL I saw him (TL him saw (L seye)) on erthe gon.</NOTE></L>
<L>I bad hem gon wher was heore wille,<NOTE PLACE="foot">L go. T whyder &thorn;e&yogh; wille. D &thorn;er w.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudeleyn and euerichon:<NOTE PLACE="foot">DT Magda|leyn(e) L Magdeleyne. T euerilkon L hem ilkon.</NOTE></L>
<L>'And my-seluen be-leuen I wole,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. wold leuen stille</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">TL And y my-self wil leue(n) stille D ffor I wold there beleue stille.</NOTE></L>
<L N="432">ffor I nil fle for no mon.'"<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> I wold not fle for Iewis non.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">DTL ffor om.; I wold (L nile) not (om. in TL) fle for Iewis (gewes) non.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 433&mdash;448 added by the poet.</NOTE>BErnard [seide]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. my sone</NOTE>: "wordes swete</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudeleyn also gon say;<NOTE PLACE="foot">433-4 TL Bernard seide &thorn;e wordis (wordes) were swete, &THORN;at &thorn;e magdaleyne &thorn;er (om. in L) gan (can) seye (say). D Than spak Bernard wordis swete, ffor Magdaleyn gan he say.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ladi, [heo sei&yogh;]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. we sen</NOTE> &thorn;i serwe vn-meete<NOTE PLACE="foot">DTL om. Ladi; Sche (L Heo) saw (L sey) &thorn;i sorwe (L dedes weren) so (om. in L) vnmete.</NOTE></L>
<L N="436">And fayn [heo] wolde<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. we wolden</NOTE> han it a-way<NOTE PLACE="foot">L om. And; D fful fayn T &thorn;at fayn. L heo wolde &thorn;i sorwe delay T sche was &thorn;e so&thorn;e to seye D schuld haue mad &thorn;e lay (crossed out; by a younger hand: wold sche an (?) had a way).</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000325.tif" N="317"></L>
<L>And, deore ladi, &thorn;i bale to<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. to</NOTE> beten;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Here in</I> D <I>a leaf</I> (<I>f.</I> 26) <I>is wanting</I>, with v. 437-512. T And fayn she wolde L &amp; blethely lady. TL om. to; bete.</NOTE></L>
<L>But in ri&yogh;t resun was his<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;i?</NOTE> way.<NOTE PLACE="foot">L om. But. L resoun T skele. T hadde hy L he hadde. T no weye L no nay.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ladi, &yogh;if I dorste &thorn;e be-sechen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T Leuedy. L &yogh;ou. L beseke T grete.</NOTE></L>
<L N="440">To aske &thorn;e more I wolde &thorn;e pray.<NOTE PLACE="foot">TD To wyte more. T &yogh;ut wolde y. L &yogh;ou. T preye.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Of angussche &thorn;ou hast told me strong;<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 v. om., cf. notes.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">TL Of &thorn;yn angwisch &thorn;ou hast me told, Leuedy (Lauedy), as y may vnderstonde (2 vv.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Myn herte is not as Ich wolde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T My. T y L I. T wold.</NOTE></L>
<L>I ne may hit wi&thorn; serwe fonge,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. fonde</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">TL om. ne. wi&thorn; no sorwe. T fonde L wonde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="444">And<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> But</NOTE> what my lord siggen wolde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">TL Bote. seye. T wold.</NOTE></L>
<L>To aske &thorn;e more nul I not wonde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">L asken. L om. &thorn;e more. T om. more. T wil y L I wolde. T no&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e Iewes Breme and bolde<NOTE PLACE="foot">T Whanne L Whan. TL gewes. T bold.</NOTE></L>
<L N="447">Naylede him &thorn;orw feet and honde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">TL Dryue(n) nailles &thorn;orgh (&thorn;oruh) his.</NOTE></L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at Iudas hedde hym solde."<NOTE PLACE="marg">This v. is superadded, to supply v. om.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>om.</P><P>After 448 TL have the foll. stanza: And sithen (sithe) hangeden (hon|gede) him ful (L vpon) he&yogh;e (heye), &amp; crounede him (om. in T) wi&thorn; thornes of tre (treo). Marie (L Lauedy), &thorn;ou were him ful ne&yogh;e (neye), I wot it may non o&thorn;er be (beo). Al &thorn;e sorwe &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;er se&yogh;e (seye), Swete leuedy (lauedy) tel &thorn;ou me. Whanne (L While) &thorn;y sone &thorn;o (T &thorn;e) peynes (L peyne) dre&yogh;e (L drye), What(e) wordis (wordes) seide he to &thorn;e (L &thorn;eo)?</P></NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"BErnard, I haue told my &thorn;ou&yogh;t:<NOTE PLACE="foot">T &thorn;e told L tolde &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wolt &thorn;ou now &yogh;it aske me more?<NOTE PLACE="foot">T What &thorn;ynge wiltow aske L Wonder what wiltou a. L om. me.</NOTE></L>
<L>Be I for&thorn;ere in tales brou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">L Beo. L it T &thorn;ou. T fer&thorn;ere. L tale T sorwe. TL y-bro&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L N="452">I-wis, &thorn;ou greues me ful sore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">TL greuest.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac for &thorn;ou hast me be-sou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">TL Bote (om. in L) louely (Loueliche) &thorn;ou hast.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ble&thorn;eliche I wol telle &thorn;e fore;<NOTE PLACE="foot">transp. in T.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">L Ande fayn I wole &thorn;e telle f. T To wyte what his wordis wore.</NOTE></L>
