<L N="712">And gunne to wepe alle &thorn;re.<NOTE PLACE="foot">D gan L begonne. D wepin L weopen. L threo.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;us, Bernard, we weren in care,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D were we Bernard L B. were we. D in greet c.</NOTE></L>
<L>In serwe of herte &amp; gret Mournyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">L &amp; DL sorwe. L &amp; in. L om. gret; D long.</NOTE></L>
<L>Til we wuste hou hit wolde fare<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Til &thorn;at. DL wiste . schuld.</NOTE></L>
<L N="716">At my sones vp-rysyng.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> Euer we were in greet longing.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">DL Euere we were (L Eche of vs was) in greet long|ing. 717-18 &amp; 719-720 transp. in L.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nou haue I told &thorn;e wi&thorn;-oute spare<NOTE PLACE="foot">L om. &thorn;e. L wi&thorn;-outen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle his<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> my</NOTE> peynes wi&thorn;-oute<NOTE PLACE="marg">at his</NOTE> partyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">L om. Alle. DL my. D peynys. D at his parting L of his departynge.</NOTE></L>
<L N="719">Bernard, I was euer &thorn;are,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D But B., L Ac B. D redi inst. of euer. L euere I was &yogh;are.</NOTE></L>
<L>To witen after his vp-rysyng."<NOTE PLACE="marg">717-18 &amp; 719-20 to be transp.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">L wayten him D kepin him. DL at.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Graunt Merci, dame, God &yogh;elde hit &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Seynt Bernard seyde God L Lauedy quod he G. L om. hit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wyf and Maiden, Moder Milde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">DL &amp; moder &amp; mayden.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast so muche i-told me<NOTE PLACE="foot">L om. &thorn;ou. DL so mekil (L &thorn;us myche) hast. DL told. D to me.</NOTE></L>
<L N="724">Of serwe of &thorn;e and of &thorn;i chylde!<NOTE PLACE="foot">L &THORN;e inst. of Of. D Of &thorn;i sorwe; of &thorn;e om.</NOTE></L>
<L>Now am I siker, wher &thorn;at I teo,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D sekir. DL wher-so (L om. so) I be (beo).</NOTE></L>
<L>In wode, in water or in felde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D In toun or feld in &yogh;ong&thorn;e or elde L In chirche in toun in fritthe in felde.</NOTE></L>
<L>To make &thorn;e foule fend to fleo,<NOTE PLACE="foot">L fforto. D don. L om. foule. L feonde. D fle.</NOTE></L>
<L N="728">&THORN;at euer was so wod and wylde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">D &THORN;at euere to helle wold don me helde L &THORN;at &yogh;ore ha&thorn; beon wod &amp; w.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ladi, for &thorn;i muchele wo,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D Now ladi for &thorn;at ilke wo</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at neuere no tonge may of telle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at no tunge may half telle</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e serwe of &thorn;e and him also<NOTE PLACE="foot">D om. &thorn;e serwe: Of the &amp; of &thorn;i sone also.</NOTE></L>
<L N="732">&THORN;at him dude &thorn;e Iewes felle:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;ow dide. Iewis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Leeue<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. And leeue</NOTE> vs neuere skape &thorn;er-fro,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And om. Late neuere non of alle tho</NOTE></L>
<L>But euer-more In ioye to dwelle;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at cristnid arn &amp; in &thorn;is world dwelle,</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon we schul dye and henne go,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Whan &thorn;ei schul passen &thorn;e world al fro,</NOTE></L>
<L N="736">Schilde vs from &thorn;e pyne of helle! Amen."<NOTE PLACE="foot">729&mdash;736 om. in L.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>To seen &thorn;e peyne &thorn;at is in helle.</P><P>After 736 D has 2 stanzas more: This ryme mad an hermyte, &amp; dide it writen in parchemyn; Barfot he wente in gray habyte, He werid no cloth &thorn;at was of lyn. &THORN;us on englisch he dide it write, He seyth he drow if of &thorn;e latyn; His mede lord Ihesu him quyte, &amp; seynt Bernard, clerk of deuyn.&mdash;And we schul preye &thorn;at here it rede, ffor him now an orisoun, &amp; don it smertlich in dede, Wi&thorn; a ful good deuocioun, &THORN;at Ihesu Crist his soule lede To blisse in his processioun, And there for to han his mede, &THORN;orw vertu of his passioun Amen.&mdash;With the last stanza agrees the concluding st. in L: Eueriche wi&thorn; goede deuocioun Grete wi&thorn; an hertly steuene To oure lady an orisoun, Hire ioye may no tonge nempne: &THORN;at for hire sones passioun Heo schilde vs fro &thorn;e sinnes seuene, &amp; saue vs fro &thorn;e feonde feloun, &amp; bringe oure soules into heuene. Amen.</P></NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="37" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000337.tif" N="329">
<HEAD>XXXVII. A dispitison bitwene a god man and &thorn;e deuel.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ed. before in <I>Engl. Stud.</I> VIII, p. 260&mdash;275.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swi&thorn;e muche neode hit is<MILESTONE N="CCLXXXVIII" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at vche mon be war and wys</L>
<L>To kepe him from &thorn;e fendes lore&mdash;</L>
<L N="4">ffor he fonde&thorn; euer-more.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at we mowen alle I-witen</L>
<L>As hit is in &thorn;e Bok I-writen,</L>
<L>I wol ow telle, as I con,</L>
<L N="8">How &thorn;e fend tempte&thorn; a Mon.&mdash;</L>
<L>Hit was vppon an haly-day: In an hei&yogh; feste of &thorn;e &yogh;ere;<NOTE PLACE="marg">In the MS. written in half lines.</NOTE></L>
<L>Muche folk was to churche gon: Godes word for to here;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Preost of &thorn;e chirche vndude &thorn;e gospel</L>
<L N="12">And lerede his parischens, as he cou&thorn;e wel,</L>
<L>And bad hem openly nyme good &yogh;eme</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;ei scholden god wel queme</L>
<L>And schenden &thorn;e foule fend of helle,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at fonde&thorn; euere iliche monnus soule to qwelle.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e prest hedde I-spoken &amp; don what he wolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk wente hamward, as ri&yogh;t was &thorn;ei scholde.</L>
<L>A good mon &thorn;er was, &thorn;at hamward gon rake,</L>
<L N="20">And &thorn;ou&yogh;te ful &yogh;eorne of &thorn;at &thorn;e prest spake;</L>
<L>He eode be him one wi&thorn;-oute fere &yogh;erne,</L>
<L>ffor no-mon of his &thorn;enkyng schulde hym werne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E wikked fend of helle &thorn;erof hedde onde</L>
<L N="24">And hastiliche sende to him his sonde.</L>
<L>His Messager redi was forte don his wille,</L>
<L>Him to bi-swyke, queynteliche &amp; stille.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e wei he hym mette</L>
<L N="28">And feire &thorn;enne he hym grette&mdash;
<PB REF="00000338.tif" N="330"></L>
<L>Was he no fend i-lyche,</L>
<L>But as a mon feir and riche;</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode Mon was not war</L>
<L N="32">Of &thorn;e deuel, &thorn;at com &thorn;ar.</L>
<L>Qua&thorn; &thorn;e wikked Counseyler:</L>
<L>"ffelawe, wel I-met her!</L>
<L>Sei me, as nou mote &thorn;ou &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="36">Wher hast &thorn;ow now I-be?"</L>
<L>"I com from &thorn;e chirche, what woldestou &thorn;er-bi?</L>
<L>What &thorn;ou art &amp; whi &thorn;ou askest, tel me nou, belamy!"</L>
<L>"I am a ferren mon and a wey-feryng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">From here the poem is extant in MS. Simeon.</NOTE></L>
<L>Spek wi&thorn; me feire, wi&thorn;-outen grucchyng!</L>
<L>Hastou atte churche I-herd eny sarmoun,</L>
<L>Vndoynge of &thorn;e gospel or of lessoun?</L>
<L>I prey&yogh;e &thorn;e, gode felawe, &yogh;if &thorn;i wille be,</L>
<L N="44">Al &thorn;at &thorn;ou herdest, tel hit nou to me!</L>
<L>ffor I con my-self, beo my lewete,</L>
<L>Of alle-maner lore gret plente.</L>
<L>I con wel I-knowe, I sei &thorn;e, for-&thorn;i,</L>
<L N="48">Wher hit were wisdam &thorn;at he spac, or elles foli.</L>
<L>Wys &thorn;ow schalt fynde me and hende;</L>
<L>ffor, &yogh;if he out fals ha&thorn; seid, I schal hit amende.</L>
<L>&THORN;auh &thorn;ow to me haue no trist,</L>
<L N="52">I con more &thorn;en &thorn;e prest,</L>
<L>And better I wot, forso&thorn;e I-wys,</L>
<L>How men schulen come to blis,</L>
<L>And also more I con telle</L>
<L N="56">Wherfore Men schule go to helle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E goode mon bigon his tale : &thorn;at o&thorn;ur &yogh;erne con luste;</L>
<L>Al cou&thorn;e he not telle : But dude &thorn;at he wuste.</L>
<L>"Ouer alle &thorn;ing he vs tauhte : To loue god, ful of miht,</L>
<L N="60">And si&thorn;en vre euencristene : As we ou&yogh;ten wi&thorn; riht.</L>
<L>He spac of dedli synnes : And seide &thorn;er weore seuene,</L>
<L>And whose dyede &thorn;er-Inne : Scholde neuere comen in heuene:</L>
<L>Pruide is &thorn;e furste : Envye is &thorn;at o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="64">Wra&thorn;&thorn;e is &thorn;e &thorn;ridde : &THORN;at mon ha&thorn; to his bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>&THORN;e feor&thorn;e is Couetyse : &THORN;e fyf&thorn;e is Lecherie,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sixte is Sleu&thorn;e : &THORN;e seue&thorn;e is Glotonye.</L>
<L>Mest he spac of pride, and lered more and lasse
<PB REF="00000339.tif" N="331"></L>
<L N="68">fforto leue pride and loue Buxumnesse;</L>
<L>ffurst, abouen alle &thorn;ing, wi&thorn; al vre miht</L>
<L>Worschipen &amp; louen god, bo&thorn;e day &amp; niht,</L>
<L>And louen vre kunrede, as &thorn;e lawe wile,</L>
<L N="72">And alle cristene men, as hit is skile.</L>
<L>ffor alle we schulen wi&thorn; ri&yogh;te louen vchon o&thorn;ur</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al vre mi&yogh;te, as suster do&thorn; &thorn;e bro&thorn;ur;</L>
<L>ffor bre&thorn;eren we aren &amp; sustren, as we schul al leue,</L>
<L N="76">Alle &thorn;at euere icome ben of Adam &amp; of Eue."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E wikked gost<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. god</NOTE> was ful &yogh;are</L>
<L>And &yogh;af &thorn;e gode mon onsware:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ow spekest," he seide, "of louyng,</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at mon schulde furst of alle &thorn;ing;</L>
<L>&THORN;at loue god schal eueri mon,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en his neih&yogh;ebor, as he con.</L>
<L>Bote hou mi&yogh;test &thorn;ou trewe loue</L>
<L N="84">Haue to him &thorn;at is aboue,</L>
<L>Whon he so ofte wra&thorn;&thorn;e&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>And let &thorn;e in muche myschef be?</L>
<L>He let &thorn;i catel from &thorn;e falle,</L>
<L N="88">Hors in stable and Oxe in stalle,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er &thorn;ing awey let go,</L>
<L>And suffre&thorn; &thorn;e be brou&yogh;t in muche wo.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou art sek in syde and Ribbe,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;at vnne&thorn;es mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou libbe,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;in hed sore ake&thorn;</L>
<L>And al &thorn;i bodi for serwe quake&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw him &thorn;e come&thorn; al &thorn;is.</L>
<L N="96">Loue him not, I rede, I-wis!</L>
<L>Hou mi&yogh;test &thorn;ou loue him wi&thorn; skile</L>
<L>&THORN;at mi&yogh;te &thorn;e helpe and ne wile?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E goode mon wel vnderstod</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;at he seide was not good.</L>
<L>"After &thorn;i red wol I not do,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e prest ne bad not so.</L>
<L>I wot of alle &thorn;ing, be hit what-so hit be,</L>
<L N="104">Bo&thorn;e beter &amp; wors, my lord sende&thorn; to me.</L>
<L>&THORN;auh I o&thorn;ur-while haue I-had wo,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw god &thorn;at hit sende hit ha&thorn; ouer-go;</L>
<L>Hit was for my gode&mdash;&thorn;onked be he&mdash;
<PB REF="00000340.tif" N="332"></L>
<L N="108">He wolde &thorn;at I scholde bi &thorn;at I-war be.</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; he me be-reue anon to my Ribbe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I haue vnne&thorn;e wher-wi&thorn; to libbe,</L>
<L>Ne wol I not be wro&thorn; &thorn;erfore, ne no ri&yogh;t hit nis:</L>
<L N="112">ffor al &thorn;at I haue, al hit is of his;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at I haue, he lene&thorn; me, I-wis,</L>
<L>He mai taken hit a&yogh;eyn, whon his wille is.</L>
<L>So he ha&thorn; don ful ofte&mdash;I-blessed mot he be&mdash;</L>
<L N="116">And &yogh;af me wel more &thorn;en he birafte me.</L>
<L>And &thorn;au&yogh; he of-pyne me in seknesse sore,</L>
<L>Hit is for my gode, I loue him &thorn;e more;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-wi&thorn; he me warne&thorn; his comaundement to breke,</L>
<L N="120">And sent me such teone him for to wreke;<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. reke</NOTE></L>
<L>I mai &thorn;en amende me of &thorn;at I haue don ille,</L>
<L>And beeten &thorn;at I haue agult a&yogh;ein godes wille.</L>
<L>&THORN;reo &thorn;inges &thorn;er be&thorn;, as I haue herd telle,</L>
<L N="124">Seide me &thorn;e prest in his lore-spelle,</L>
<L>ffor whom I ou&yogh;te loue Ihesu ful of mi&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. mahte</NOTE></L>
<L>And worschipe him as I con, as me wel i&yogh;te:<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. ahte</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e furste &thorn;ing of &thorn;e &thorn;re, is &thorn;at he me wrou&yogh;te</L>
<L N="128">After him-self, as hym best &thorn;ou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur, &thorn;at he bou&yogh;te me on &thorn;e swete Rode</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his oune flesch &amp; wi&thorn; his oune blode;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde, &thorn;at he cleped me to his oune feste</L>
<L N="132">In to &thorn;e blisse of heuene, &thorn;at euer schal i-leste.</L>
<L>ffor on of &thorn;ise I ou&yogh;te to louen him wel apli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Betere I ou&yogh;te for alle, &amp; &thorn;at is good ri&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E wikkede gost onswerde &thorn;o:</L>
<L N="136">"Lete we &thorn;is tale go,</L>
<L>Leue we &thorn;is disputyng</L>
<L>And speke we of o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>&THORN;ow spekest a&yogh;eyn pruide</L>
<L N="140">And &thorn;er-of takest muche hyde.<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. hede</NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e ri&yogh;te is &thorn;at &thorn;ou says,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore me mis-pays.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seist &thorn;e prest, &thorn;at synge&thorn; Messe,</L>
<L N="144">Lered &thorn;e to Boxumnesse;</L>
<L>He was wod, so art &thorn;ou ek,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;o &thorn;at so spek.</L>
<L>Leef &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t &thorn;at hit be so&thorn;!
<PB REF="00000341.tif" N="333"></L>
<L N="148">Hit nis no-mon &thorn;at so do&thorn;.</L>
<L>I sigge &thorn;at pruide nis no synne:</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er-&thorn;orw&yogh; come&thorn; worldes wynne.</L>
<L>&THORN;at mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou witen, I-wis,</L>
<L N="152">Whon &thorn;ou wost what hit is.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be knowen for wys</L>
<L>And holden art of muche prys</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou art riche mon and wlou&yogh;</L>
<L N="156">And of richesse hast inouh:</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; &thorn;ou ly&yogh;e, as mony mon do&thorn;,</L>
<L>Men wolle&thorn; wene &thorn;at hit be so&thorn;,</L>
<L>And clepe &thorn;e for&thorn; for heore euenyng,</L>
<L N="160">Bi-foren hem &thorn;at habbe&thorn; no-&thorn;ing.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou art proud and Modi</L>
<L>And berest &thorn;e bold and hardi,</L>
<L>Men &thorn;at stonde&thorn; &thorn;e aboute</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;enne of &thorn;e wolen haue gret doute,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e wolen &thorn;ei comen and speke,</L>
<L>&THORN;i loue to haue and hem to wreke.<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. reke</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou may&yogh;t for &thorn;i bolde beryng</L>
<L N="168">Be proud &amp; riche in alle &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>And ouur-al mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou comen and go,</L>
<L>Whon a Moppe dasart schal not so;</L>
<L>As a lord schalt &thorn;ou be cald,</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;er o&thorn;ure schul stonde be-hynde vn-bald,</L>
<L>And oueral &thorn;er &thorn;ou gost aboute</L>
<L>&THORN;e schal folewe ful gret route;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e schal vche mon stonde gret ei&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="176">Wher &thorn;ou wolt, &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t go pleye.</L>
<L>Do nou as I haue I-counseyled &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Proud &amp; stout euer &thorn;at &thorn;ou be!</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;if &thorn;ou drawe &thorn;e to cumpaigny</L>
<L N="180">Of pore wrecches &thorn;at wone &thorn;e by,</L>
<L>Vche a Mon &thorn;at beo &thorn;e wey go&thorn;</L>
<L>Of hem schalt &thorn;ou be swi&thorn;e lo&thorn;,</L>
<L>And alle wolle &thorn;ei ful &yogh;are</L>
<L N="184">Lauhwhe &thorn;e to bisemare</L>
<L>And sigge: "lo, Men mowe wel se</L>
<L>What Mon &thorn;at he &thorn;enke&thorn; to be!</L>
<L>A wrecche sone wol he ben,
<PB REF="00000342.tif" N="334"></L>
<L N="188">To wrecches he drawe&thorn;, as alle men sen;</L>
<L>Wel Men may seo alle bi &thorn;an</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer-more wol he beo man."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E gode Mon vnderstod</L>
<L N="192">&THORN;at &thorn;at &thorn;e to&thorn;ur seide was not good.</L>
<L>"Do wei," he seide, "&thorn;i lore : Ne spek no more of pryde:</L>
<L>Hit do&thorn; &thorn;e soule muche wo : And helpe&thorn; &thorn;e bodi luyte.</L>
<L>Whon I &thorn;enke on &thorn;inges &thorn;re : Bo&thorn;e niht and day</L>
<L N="196">Pruide ne worldes blisse : Glade me ne may.</L>
<L>ffurst, whon I beo-&thorn;enke me : And am wel I-ware</L>
<L>How I com in to &thorn;is world : Bo&thorn;e naked and bare;</L>
<L>Nedde I to myn hed houue ne hod,</L>
<L N="200">Ne Robe to my bac, badde ne good,</L>
<L>But a foul red clout, &thorn;at I was boren In,</L>
<L>&THORN;at tok I of my Moder, and was a foul skyn&mdash;</L>
<L>Al is so&thorn; &thorn;at I seye, &thorn;ei&yogh; I speke in Rym&mdash;</L>
<L N="204">&THORN;ei coruen hit of me &amp; wosch awei mi slym.</L>
<L>In to &thorn;is world &thorn;us com I wrecched &amp; bare,</L>
<L>And so, wot I wel, I schal he&thorn;en fare.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei wounden me in cloutes, for cold &amp; for schame,</L>
<L N="208">ffor I ne scholde forfare, &thorn;ei hulede mi licame.</L>
<L>Al-Maner quik &thorn;ing &thorn;at is &thorn;orw Godes miht,</L>
<L>Whon hit come&thorn; furst for&thorn;, con him-self diht,</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; of him-self kyndeliche wede,</L>
<L N="212">And con him-self purchase mete to his nede,</L>
<L>And ha&thorn; &thorn;orw kynde mi&yogh;t for to gon,</L>
<L>&THORN;er kynde of mon ha&thorn; ri&yogh;t non,</L>
<L>Bute vn-mi&yogh;ti wrecches alle are we.</L>
<L N="216">Hou scholde I be proud, whon I &thorn;is se?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur is, whon I &thorn;enke on Adam and Eue,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;ei weren in paradys wel &amp; wi&thorn; leue;</L>
<L>&THORN;er wi&thorn;-outen synne &thorn;ei mi&yogh;te haue ben in blis,</L>
<L N="220">&YOGH;if &thorn;ei nedden agult a&yogh;eyn god, i-wis;</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ei mi&yogh;ten han I-wonet in mur&thorn;e &amp; in wynne:</L>
<L>But sone &thorn;ei were driuen out, for &thorn;ei dide sinne.</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore ha we muche wo, serwe &amp; vuel-fare,</L>
<L N="224">And wonen in &thorn;is middel-ert in serwe &amp; in care.</L>
<L>Weilawei &amp; weilawo, &thorn;at synne was I-wrou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>In muche peyne for sinne are mony men I-brou&yogh;t;
<PB REF="00000343.tif" N="335"></L>
<L>Alle wo &amp; seknes &thorn;at eny mon is Inne,</L>
<L N="228">Al is, for he ha&thorn; i-greuet ofte god wi&thorn; synne.</L>
<L>&THORN;er is in &thorn;is world muche falshede,</L>
<L>&THORN;er is no treu&thorn;e wel nei&yogh;, in word ne in dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sone be-gile&thorn; &thorn;e fader, &thorn;e dou&yogh;tur &thorn;e moder,</L>
<L N="232">&THORN;e sibbe &thorn;e frende, vche mon o&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Nis no worldes blisse &thorn;at nul ouur-go,</L>
<L>Ne nout no<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. so</NOTE> murie on eor&thorn;e &thorn;at nis meynt wi&thorn; wo.</L>
<L>But &thorn;e blisse of paradys, &thorn;at laste&thorn; euer-more,</L>
<L N="236">Whon I &thorn;enke &thorn;eron, me longe&thorn; &thorn;ider sore.</L>
<L>Hou scholde I &thorn;enne be proud for eny &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Or eny o&thorn;er mon, &thorn;at is in longyng?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E &thorn;ridde &thorn;ing is &thorn;at I &thorn;enke, &thorn;at I schal wende henne</L>
<L N="240">Out of &thorn;is world, but wot I neuer whenne,</L>
<L>Ne wot I whodur mi soule schal. &thorn;erfore sore i drede:</L>
<L>ffor aftur mi werkes are, schal hit haue mede;</L>
<L>Riht as I haue deseruet, &thorn;e weole or &thorn;e wo</L>
<L N="244">Certeinliche schal I haue, i mai not fle &thorn;er-fro.</L>
<L>Beo I in mi put leid, &thorn;er wormus schul eten me,</L>
<L>Wor&thorn;e to nou&yogh;t schal I &thorn;enne, as neuer hedde I be;</L>
<L>&THORN;e her of myn hed, &yogh;eleu&yogh; so &thorn;e wex,</L>
<L N="248">Schal dwynen a-wey so do&thorn; &thorn;e drex,</L>
<L>Mi feire e&yogh;en schulen out renne,</L>
<L>Mi white te&thorn; schulen foule grenne,</L>
<L>Mi feire hondes and fingres longe</L>
<L N="252">Schul rote &amp; stynke swi&thorn;e stronge.</L>
<L>Men wol for mi good make striuyng</L>
<L>And puyte me out of al my &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke &thorn;at weren I-wont ofte me to grete,</L>
<L N="256">&THORN;ei wol not her &thorn;onkes wi&thorn; me meete.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e frendes &thorn;at I now haue,</L>
<L>ffor me gladliche wol &thorn;ei don al &thorn;at I craue;</L>
<L>Weore I in mi graue, out of heore siht,</L>
<L N="260">Luite wolde &thorn;ei for me do, be dai or be ni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Nedde I neuere so muche good, al hit wolde go,</L>
<L>Whon mi soule &amp; mi bodi ar parted a-two.</L>
<L>Mi bodi schal leuen her, mi soule faren henne,</L>
<L N="264">Al &thorn;e worldes pride luitel helpe&thorn; &thorn;enne.</L>
<L>Viterde<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Vtterde? Sim. Vitrede, ef. fytered, Mirk Instr. v. 1146.</NOTE> hodes and Clokes also,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at vile pride schal don hem ful wo;
<PB REF="00000344.tif" N="336"></L>
<L>&THORN;ei struye godes good &thorn;er-wi&thorn; : And torne hit to fen,</L>
<L N="268">&THORN;at muche mihte helpe : Sely pore men.</L>
<L>Now is non wor&thorn; a fart,</L>
<L>But he bere a baselart</L>
<L>I-honget bi his syde,</L>
<L N="272">And a swynes Mawe, &amp; al is for pride.</L>
<L>Godus grame, stirap on his cappe is knit,</L>
<L>&THORN;at an vnche ha&thorn; he not on for to sit;</L>
<L>Muche meschef and gret colde : On his hers he has,</L>
<L N="276">Men mi&yogh;te, &yogh;if his brech weore to-tore : Seon his genitras.</L>
<L>And also &thorn;is wymmen : &THORN;at muchel haunte&thorn; pride,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hornes on heore hed : Pinned on vch a syde,</L>
<L>Maad of an old hat : And of a luytel tre,</L>
<L N="280">Wi&thorn; selk scleyres I-set aboue : Apparisaunt to be;</L>
<L>Heore Reuersede gydes : On hem are streyt drawe&mdash;</L>
<L>But al be of &thorn;e newe aget<NOTE PLACE="marg">= get fashion</NOTE> : Hit is not wor&thorn; an hawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei wenen a ben ful feire : And wonder foul &thorn;ei be;</L>
<L N="284">And a wolden be-&thorn;enken hem : Of heore priuete</L>
<L>And hou foule &thorn;ei are : In soule and in bodi,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei ou&yogh;te wi&thorn; heore wepyng : Make heore chekes rodi.</L>
<L>But &thorn;ei leue pride, &amp; o&thorn;ur synnes mo,</L>
<L N="288">Schortly to telle, to helle schul &thorn;ei go.</L>
<L>Whon I &thorn;enke her-vppon : Mi care is wel &thorn;e more;</L>
<L>Luytel wonder is hit : &THORN;auh I sike sore.</L>
<L>Hou scholde I be proud or elles modi?</L>
<L N="292">Alle ou&yogh;te we to be for synne sori.&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;it &thorn;ou counseildest me a luytel while ere</L>
<L>&THORN;at I scholde not be pore mennes fere;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seidest I scholde ben holden an vn-mon.</L>
<L N="296">No-mon wol sigge so &thorn;at eny good con.</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; I &amp; a pore Mon, &thorn;at begge&thorn; his fode,</L>
<L>Be not I-liche riche of &thorn;e worldes gode,</L>
<L>Men mai seo &thorn;e so&thorn;e &amp; &thorn;e skile ri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="300">Hou we schule bitwene vs vre loue di&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if I do mi clo&thorn;us of anon to my liche</L>
<L>&THORN;at I am iclo&thorn;ed in, &thorn;at be&thorn; gode &amp; riche,</L>
<L>And a pore beggere, &thorn;at ha&thorn; muche wo,</L>
<L N="304">Wi&thorn; cloutede clo&thorn;es dude also,</L>
<L>And we stode naked bo&thorn;en I-fere:
<PB REF="00000345.tif" N="337"></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e mi&yogh;te we &thorn;enne ben o&thorn;ures pere;</L>
<L>Hose vs se&yogh;e and knewe vs ney&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="308">&THORN;enne mi&yogh;t &thorn;ei wene &thorn;at we were bre&thorn;er.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne most I louen him, and he louen me,</L>
<L>Whon vre kynde robes be&thorn; of o ble:</L>
<L>&THORN;o are &thorn;e Robes we were wi&thorn; I-bore&mdash;</L>
<L N="312">Ar we liggen &amp; rote, ne wor&thorn; &thorn;ei to-tore;</L>
<L>Let us be lyk in sum &thorn;ing, as wel I wot we are,</L>
<L>Al-&thorn;au&yogh; I be riche, &amp; he pore &amp; bare."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E wikked gost onswerde &thorn;o</L>
<L N="316">And bad let &thorn;at tale go,</L>
<L>"Lete we &thorn;is dispuytyng</L>
<L>And speke we of ano&thorn;er &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou spekest &amp; seist &thorn;e prest ha&thorn; forbode</L>
<L N="320">Wra&thorn;&thorn;e &amp; onde, &thorn;orw biddyng of gode.</L>
<L>Hit was neuer forbode of no wys mon,</L>
<L>But of sum folte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. folted, v. 606. O. Fr. folet, foolish.</NOTE> &thorn;at no good ne con.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou sest &thorn;i bro&thorn;ur or &thorn;i kun or a-no&thorn;ur</L>
<L>&THORN;at he be feiror &thorn;en &thorn;ou be, or wisor &thorn;en &thorn;ou ou&thorn;ur,</L>
<L>Or ricchor or baldor or be of beter i-told:</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; &thorn;in herte be wo</L>
<L>&amp; of-&thorn;inke &thorn;at hit is so,<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 326-7 in the MS. one verse.</NOTE></L>
<L N="328">Who mihte &thorn;e blame?</L>
<L>Wel mi&yogh;t &thorn;ou &thorn;enne &thorn;inke schame</L>
<L>And vuel may hit &thorn;e like</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schal be so hei&yogh;: And &thorn;ou not so riche."<NOTE PLACE="marg">In MS. 2 vv.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="332">&THORN;E gode mon wel vnderstod</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;at &thorn;e to&thorn;ur seide was not good.</L>
<L>"Aftur &thorn;i counseil wol I not do,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e prest seide not so.</L>
<L N="336">No mon ha&thorn; so muche good : &THORN;at I wolde<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. nolde</NOTE> he hedde more,</L>
<L>Ne so feir ne so strong ne so wys of lore,</L>
<L>Hit of-&thorn;unche&thorn; me nouht : Ne &thorn;er-to haue I non onde,</L>
<L N="339">ffor al &thorn;e godes &thorn;at mon ha&thorn; : Is of godes sonde.</L>
<L>God, &thorn;orw whom come&thorn; alle &thorn;ing : Con ful good skile,</L>
<L>Alle worldes winne : He sende&thorn;, whon<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. whom</NOTE> he wile.</L>
<L>Whi scholde I for monnes god haue sorinesse,</L>
<L>Whon I haue for him neuer &thorn;e lesse?</L>
<L N="344">God dele&thorn; his dole : To pore and to riche,
<PB REF="00000346.tif" N="338"></L>
<L>And &yogh;iue&thorn; wit and auhte : But not alle I-lyche.</L>
<L>Whon he ha&thorn; I-&yogh;iuen his &thorn;ing : As Ichaue I-seyd,</L>
<L>Vche mon of his del : Schulde holde him paid;</L>
<L N="348">No mon schulde grucchen : Of o&thorn;eres wel-fare,</L>
<L>And &yogh;if he do&thorn;, for so&thorn;e : He mispaye&thorn; god &thorn;are.</L>
<L>ffor god wol &yogh;iue : To whom his wille is.</L>
<L>Whose ha&thorn; envye &thorn;er-to : ffor so&thorn;e, he nis not wys."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="352">&THORN;E false schrewe onswerde &thorn;ore</L>
<L>And bad hym sigge so nomore.</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou spekest of wra&thorn;&thorn;e in &thorn;i tale</L>
<L>And seist hit is a&yogh;eyn soule-hale.</L>
<L N="356">&THORN;at is not so&thorn;, but falshede;</L>
<L>Wra&thorn;&thorn;e was neuere synful dede.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if eny mon a-gult a&yogh;eynes &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Smyte&thorn; or elles puite&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="360">O&thorn;er sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e is him lo&thorn;:</L>
<L>Ne most &thorn;ou &thorn;enne nedes be wro&thorn;?</L>
<L>&YOGH;if Mon mis-sei&thorn; &thorn;e or de&thorn; &thorn;e schame:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be wro&thorn;, ho schal &thorn;e blame?</L>
<L N="364">As he do&thorn; bi &thorn;e, ni&yogh;t and day,</L>
<L>Quit him wel, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou may;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou mowe, worse; in eny wyse</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou &yogh;elde him his seruyse;</L>
<L N="368">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou forberest O bisemare,</L>
<L>He wol &yogh;iue &thorn;e two ful &yogh;are.</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn o word sei &thorn;ou two</L>
<L>And mak him wro&thorn;, ar &thorn;ou go,</L>
<L N="372">And spek wi&thorn; hym baldeliche</L>
<L>And mis-seye hym schomefulliche!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if eny Mon &thorn;e mis-de&thorn;,</L>
<L>Smyt &thorn;yn hond vnder his te&thorn;,</L>
<L N="376">Wi&thorn; Swerd, Knyf, Staf or Ston</L>
<L>Lei on faste, and &thorn;at anon,</L>
<L>And bet him wel wi&thorn; &thorn;e beste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his te&thorn; al to-breste;</L>
<L N="380">Or on &thorn;e hed ponne hard,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he go wry&yogh;inge &thorn;enneward.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he is strong or of miht hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne miht comen hym nei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="384">Tac &thorn;e felawes &thorn;e by-syde:
<PB REF="00000347.tif" N="339"></L>
<L>&THORN;e hardiloker mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou abyde,</L>
<L>And go sech him be wei and strete,</L>
<L>Stint &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t til &thorn;ou him mete,</L>
<L N="388">Lei on faste, spare no-&thorn;ing,</L>
<L>To grounde sone &thorn;ou him bryng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;erfore grunte and grone;</L>
<L>And warne al o&thorn;ere bi him one!</L>
<L N="392">&THORN;en may &thorn;i word springe ariht</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou art hardi mon and wiht;</L>
<L>Alle men of &thorn;e &thorn;enne schule be fert</L>
<L>&THORN;at bifore wolde mis-seye &thorn;e in &thorn;i bert;</L>
<L N="396">&THORN;enne mi&yogh;t &thorn;ou go bo&thorn;e quit and sker</L>
<L>Wher &thorn;ou wolt, fer and neer."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E goode mon wel vnderstood</L>
<L N="399">&THORN;at his counseil was not good.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if I be wro&thorn; and sore agreued  Wi&thorn; eny Mon alyue,</L>
<L>Ich ou&yogh;te seche pees of hym : fful hastiliche and blyue.</L>
<L>Mi Pater noster ne my crede : Ne myn Aue Marie biddynge,</L>
<L>Whyle ich am in wra&thorn;&thorn;e : Avayle&thorn; me no-&thorn;hynge.</L>
<L N="404">&YOGH;if Mon be wro&thorn;, hym is &thorn;e wors : And &thorn;at on mony syde&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at schul &yogh;e wite &thorn;at hit is so&thorn; : &YOGH;if &yogh;e wolle&thorn; abyde:</L>
<L>Wra&thorn;&thorn;e and vuel wordes : Old sore newe&thorn;,</L>
<L>And make&thorn; to do &thorn;e dede : &THORN;at eft ful sore rewe&thorn;.</L>
<L N="408">Wra&thorn;&thorn;e is a wikked &thorn;ing : Hit menge&thorn; &thorn;e herte blod</L>
<L>And make&thorn; mon ofte out of wit : &THORN;at he con no good,</L>
<L>He<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Hit</NOTE> make&thorn; mon ofte do &thorn;e dede : &THORN;at eft torne&thorn; to grame,</L>
<L N="411">Bete Men and ofte sle : And do ful muche schame,</L>
<L>Wounde men and berne men : Robben and to-reuen;</L>
<L>And euere are &thorn;ei in serwe and wo : A-Morwen and at Euen.</L>
<L>Whon he is wel a-wreken : Aftur his wille,</L>
<L>&THORN;en he is wel apayed : And go&thorn; for&thorn; wel stille,</L>
<L N="416">He wene&thorn; to here &thorn;er-of : No more ti&thorn;inge:</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;e synne &thorn;er-after : Schal him to schome brynge;</L>
<L>Ne schal he him no-wyse : So wel him schilde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. hyde?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he (!) ne schal for &thorn;e synne : Sum schome be-tyde,</L>
<L N="420">But hit beo &thorn;orw schrift : And &thorn;e prestes rede
<PB REF="00000348.tif" N="340"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e synne be bet : And a-Mended &thorn;e deede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e hei&yogh;e kyng of heuene : Is ri&yogh;tful Iustise,</L>
<L N="423">Alle folk schal he deme : Bo&thorn;e foles and wyse;</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; set his lawes&mdash; : No-Mon scholde hem breke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no-mon in his wra&thorn;&thorn;e : Scholde him-self wreke.&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;it on o&thorn;ur wyse ofte mon is wro&thorn;</L>
<L>And sei&thorn; to his bro&thorn;ur &thorn;ing &thorn;at him is lo&thorn;.</L>
<L N="428">&THORN;e wysore of hem two : &THORN;en schal holde him stille</L>
<L>And suffre &thorn;e more fol : Siggen al his wille.</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;at chyde&thorn; al-one : Hit wol sone awey fare,</L>
<L>Hit wol not longe lasten : Wi&thorn;-outen onsware;</L>
<L N="432">Whon he ha&thorn; al seid : &THORN;at he sigge wile,</L>
<L>He wol ben in pes : And cunne &thorn;e more skile,</L>
<L>And [bid]<NOTE PLACE="marg">om.</NOTE> for-&yogh;iuen his wra&thorn;&thorn;e : &THORN;au&yogh; &thorn;ei duden ille,</L>
<L>And connen his felawe more &thorn;onk : ffor he heold him stille.</L>
<L N="436">&YOGH;if eny wikked wordes or dedes : Bi-fore weren I|wrouht,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei schul &thorn;enne &thorn;orw wra&thorn;&thorn;e : Ben al out I-brouht;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e worste &thorn;at &thorn;ei cunne : &THORN;enne wol &thorn;ei speke,</L>
<L>And dele grete strokes : ffor to ben a-wreke.</L>
<L N="440">Her-of is I-writen a word &thorn;at is cou&thorn;:</L>
<L>'He kepe&thorn; a feir castel &thorn;at kepe&thorn; wel his Mou&thorn;.' "</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E wikked schrewe onswerde &thorn;on</L>
<L>&THORN;us to &thorn;e gode mon:</L>
<L N="444">"Ne forbed he neuere : &THORN;at I &thorn;e plihte,</L>
<L>Mon to be riche : &YOGH;if he miht:</L>
<L>Hou mi&yogh;te men on e[n]y wyse</L>
<L>Be riche wi&thorn;-outen couetyse?</L>
<L N="448">&THORN;e riche Mon, wher he is,</L>
<L>Holden is bo&thorn;e &yogh;ep and wys,</L>
<L>ffor&thorn; I-cald and muchel of told,</L>
<L>ffor he ha&thorn; good mony-fold;</L>
<L N="452">He is holden of muche pris,</L>
<L>And al for good &thorn;at is his.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pore Mon al &thorn;at schal misse;</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; he non such worldes blisse;</L>
<L N="456">His Meeles are ofte lene&mdash;</L>
<L>Luitel hit helpe&thorn;, &thorn;au&yogh; he him mene&mdash;</L>
<L>His Robes are badde and &thorn;inne,
<PB REF="00000349.tif" N="341"></L>
<L>Luitel he ha&thorn; of worldes wynne.</L>
<L N="460">Purueye &thorn;e wel on vche a syde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at such teone &thorn;e ne be-tyde!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou ne const, I wol &thorn;e teche</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;ou schalt good to &thorn;e reche</L>
<L N="464">And riche mon bi-come and wlouh</L>
<L>And haue of alle goodes I-nouh,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn;-outen eny synne</L>
<L>Geten I-nou&yogh; of worldes wynne.</L>
<L N="468">Beo peny pound bi-twene two</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mai&yogh;t gedere mo and mo,</L>
<L>Al wi&thorn; queyntise and wi&thorn; ginne</L>
<L>Muche good mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou wynne.</L>
<L N="472">Slep &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t to muche a-niht,</L>
<L>But win &thorn;e good, hou &thorn;ou miht;</L>
<L>Ren a-boute bi &thorn;e strete,</L>
<L>Bi wey and bi weonlete;</L>
<L N="476">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou seost in eny wyse</L>
<L>Wher eny bi-&yogh;ete wol aryse,</L>
<L>Tac sum, and lef I-nouh&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou do so, hit nis no wouh;</L>
<L N="480">Haue &thorn;ou no doute, I rede, of &thorn;as,</L>
<L>No mon wot ho hit was.</L>
<L>&THORN;auh Mon make muche fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-of haue &thorn;ou no care,</L>
<L N="484">Ne dred no-&thorn;ing &thorn;e prestes curs&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;ou schalt neuere be &thorn;e wors.</L>
<L>Ne spare non, &thorn;er &thorn;ou gest,</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;er &thorn;e parsun ne &thorn;e prest;</L>
<L N="488">Tac &thorn;e part of heore ty&thorn;inge</L>
<L>And bere hit hom to &thorn;i wonynge.</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t muche good take</L>
<L>And be riche monnes make.</L>
<L N="492">Whon &thorn;ou hast &thorn;us wel bi-gonne</L>
<L>And muche good hast I-wonne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast, kep hit wel,</L>
<L>&THORN;erof &yogh;if &thorn;ou neuer a del;</L>
<L N="496">But men bringe two for on,</L>
<L>&YOGH;iue hem not, but let hem gon!</L>
<L>&THORN;er wol come to &thorn;in hous
<PB REF="00000350.tif" N="342"></L>
<L>Mony on ful coueytous,</L>
<L N="500">ffor to haue of &thorn;i &thorn;inge,</L>
<L>To bere a-wei, and nou&yogh;t to brynge:&mdash;</L>
<L>So wole &thorn;ei don eft-sone;</L>
<L>Let hem gon riht as &thorn;ei come;</L>
<L N="504">Let hem seche heor owne bi&yogh;ete</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou dudest, or elles lete;</L>
<L>Let hem fare neer and ferre</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e neuer be &thorn;e nerre!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="508">&THORN;E gode mon wel vnderstod</L>
<L>&THORN;at at o&thorn;ur seide was not good.</L>
<L>"Couetyse is not good : ffor hit is forbode,</L>
<L>So sei&thorn; &thorn;e prest on his bok : &THORN;orw biddyng of gode.</L>
<L N="512">Men mowe wel be riche : Whose hit may wynne</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; rihte &amp; wi&thorn; treu&thorn;e : And wi&thorn;-outen synne;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; trewe craft and Marchaundise : Wel wynnen he may,</L>
<L>But Robbe ne to-reue : Nou&thorn;er niht ne day.</L>
<L N="516">Mony on wi&thorn; falsnesse : And wi&thorn; Oker also</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; so muche good : &THORN;at he not wher hit do;</L>
<L>&THORN;at may ben here his heuene&mdash; : At his endynge</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e put of helle : Sone hit wole hym bringe.</L>
<L N="520">&YOGH;if Mon ha&thorn; eny &thorn;ing : Bi-gete wi&thorn; trewenesse</L>
<L>Of worldliche good : More o&thorn;er lesse,</L>
<L>Tac to his nedfulnesse : &THORN;er-of what he wile,</L>
<L>And do to holi chirche : &THORN;at riht wole and skile:</L>
<L N="524">Of al &thorn;at newe&thorn; him be &yogh;ere : Do his ti&thorn;inge,</L>
<L>And foure tyme in &thorn;e &yogh;ere : &YOGH;if his Offringe;</L>
<L>&THORN;e pore schal he helpe : Also, &thorn;at ha&thorn; nede,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if hem mete and drinke : And clo&thorn;e hem wi&thorn; wede.</L>
<L N="528">Hose wol not ti&thorn;e : &THORN;at god him ha&thorn; I-lent,</L>
<L>His lyf and his soule : Bo&thorn;e schul be schent;</L>
<L>He schal for &thorn;e synne : Haue Godes curs,</L>
<L>And eke alle his goodes : Schul fare wel &thorn;e wors;</L>
<L N="532">His godes schulen at-falle : And faste a-wey go,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at ilke synne : Mony on haue&thorn; wo.</L>
<L>&THORN;at is in toune and felde : Seene, sikerli,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fewe aren in londe : &THORN;at liuen rihtfuli:</L>
<L N="536">&THORN;e eor&thorn;e &yogh;elde&thorn; not fruit : As hit wont was,</L>
<L>Of Corn of &thorn;e feld : Ne of &thorn;e Medewe Gras,
<PB REF="00000351.tif" N="343"></L>
<L>Ne non o&thorn;er-cunne fruit : &THORN;e folk for to frore&mdash;</L>
<L>I-wis, hit is for synne : &THORN;at mony Mon is pore.&mdash;</L>
<L N="540">Haue &thorn;ou neuer so muche : Of worldes good here,</L>
<L>Al schal passen a-wey : As fantum hit were.</L>
<L>ffor to haue &thorn;in herte : To muche &thorn;er-Inne,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i mok to make &thorn;i god : Hit is dedly synne.</L>
<L N="544">And &yogh;it, ar &thorn;ow war be : ffrom &thorn;e wol hit fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;enne schalt &thorn;ou haue &thorn;erfore : Bo&thorn;e serwe and care,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it at &thorn;in ende : Gret stryf in cas,</L>
<L N="547">And puite &thorn;e out : Of al &thorn;at &thorn;in was;</L>
<L>&THORN;in Executours schul take : &THORN;i goodes at heore wille</L>
<L>And lete &thorn;i soule ligge : In pyne ful stille.</L>
<L>Beo &thorn;ou in &thorn;i put i-brou&yogh;t : Wormes schul eten &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And sone schalt &thorn;ou be for-&yogh;eten : Siker may&yogh;t &thorn;ou be.</L>
<L N="552">&THORN;erfore I rede, as Salamon his sone bad,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vche Mon skilfuli of his god mak him glad,</L>
<L>Mete and drynke and clo&thorn; : Catel and o&thorn;er &thorn;yng</L>
<L>&THORN;at nedful is to haue : Wi&thorn;-outen wastyng;</L>
<L N="556">&THORN;e pore schal he helpe : Wher &thorn;at is nede,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at god ha&thorn; him sent : Don his Almes-dede,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if him mete and drynk : And clo&thorn;e him wi&thorn; wede&mdash;</L>
<L>In al &thorn;i werkes, be &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;ou</NOTE> syker : &THORN;e better schalt &thorn;ou spede;</L>
<L N="560">&YOGH;if him of &thorn;i Cuppe : Of &thorn;at is &thorn;er-in,</L>
<L>Water to drynke : Ale o&thorn;er Wyn;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if he ha&thorn; nede : Clepe him &thorn;e neer</L>
<L>And make him sitte &amp; warme him : Bi &thorn;yn hote fuyr;</L>
<L N="564">Bedde hym esyliche : &YOGH;if &thorn;at he seek be,</L>
<L>And serue him wel, for his loue : &THORN;at al ha&thorn; &yogh;euen &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Worldes wele is wonderful : Wel may I seyn,</L>
<L>Lyk &thorn;e se &thorn;at flowe&thorn; : And ebbe&thorn; a-&yogh;eyn;</L>
<L N="568">&THORN;er nis no sikernesse : In &thorn;is worldes won,</L>
<L>No-mon not whon hit wole : A-wei from him gon,</L>
<L>Ne how longe hit wol laste : Ne how luytel while&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke &thorn;at hit loue&thorn; most : Ofte hit do&thorn; hem gyle.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at loue&thorn; catel wel : And bounden is in Couetyse,</L>
<L N="573">He schal ben I-bounden : In &thorn;reo-kynne wyse:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh;t and drede are &thorn;e two : &THORN;at schul bynden hym faste,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde is muche serwe : &THORN;at euermore schal laste.
<PB REF="00000352.tif" N="344"></L>
<L N="576">Ofte for his catel : Mon moot wake of slepe,</L>
<L>Trauaylen in reyn and in snowh : Beo &thorn;e weyes neuer so depe,</L>
<L>ffrom toune to toune : Bo&thorn;e fer and neer,</L>
<L>As Chapmen mote don : To heore mesteer;</L>
<L N="580">Ouer &thorn;e salte s&eacute;&eacute; ofte &thorn;ei fare</L>
<L>ffor heor Marchaundise, in gret peril and care,</L>
<L>And ofte and mony a tyme : [lese&thorn;]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. heore</NOTE> Catel and heore lyf</L>
<L N="583">And make&thorn; vuel to fare : Bo&thorn;e Chyld and Wyf.</L>
<L>O&thorn;er Men dyke and delue : And gon to &thorn;e plouh,</L>
<L>To Cart and to &thorn;reschynge : And o&thorn;ur swynk I-nouh.</L>
<L>Whon he wi&thorn; his swynk : Ha&thorn; wonne gret be-&yogh;ete,</L>
<L>Euere he is afert : &THORN;at he schal hit forleete;</L>
<L N="588">And &yogh;if he hit leten schal : Hym is wo &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L>And is so sori &thorn;enne : &thorn;at euer was he bore.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh;t and drede &amp; sorinesse : Aren Monnes fo&mdash;</L>
<L>He ou&yogh;te neuere loue : &THORN;ing &thorn;at do&thorn; hym so wo.</L>
<L N="592">&YOGH;if he leose eny &thorn;ing : And he gret good con,</L>
<L>Beo-&thorn;enk hym of Iob : &THORN;at was a good mon:</L>
<L>He hedde of alle richesses : Swi&thorn;e muche won</L>
<L>And in a luytel while : He nedde riht non;</L>
<L N="596">&THORN;o he hedde riht nou&yogh;t : But al was a-go,</L>
<L>Ne seide he for his harm : Enes 'me is wo,'</L>
<L>But louede<NOTE PLACE="marg">= praised</NOTE> God wel : And &thorn;onkede hym &thorn;on&mdash;</L>
<L>He dude as &thorn;e wyse : So schulde eueri mon;&mdash;</L>
<L N="600">Nolde he not for his los : No&thorn;ing sori be,</L>
<L>'God,' he seide, 'hit me &yogh;af : And bi-raft hit me;'</L>
<L>Ne grucched he nou&yogh;t, but &thorn;onked godes sonde</L>
<L>And seide 'blesset be his nome, in water &amp; in londe.' "</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="604">&THORN;E wikked gost onswerde &thorn;on</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at he was a folted mon.</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou spekest of Lecherie</L>
<L>And of fewe wordes makest monye;</L>
<L N="608">ffalse wordes wolt &thorn;ou leeue &amp; here hem gladli&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou nost what &thorn;ou menest, i sigge &thorn;e sikerli!</L>
<L>Of luytel wit hastou Mynde:</L>
<L>Ne mot a Mon don his kynde?</L>
<L N="612">Hit was ordeynd &thorn;orw Godes biddyng</L>
<L>At &thorn;e worldes be-gynnyng.
<PB REF="00000353.tif" N="345"></L>
<L>Beo &thorn;i tale &thorn;ow woldest hit bringe</L>
<L>Al to-gedere in to spousynge</L>
<L N="616">Or elles leue &thorn;at game,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me nedde of God blame.</L>
<L>Whose aftur &thorn;i counseil do&thorn;,</L>
<L>Repente him schal, I sei for so&thorn;:</L>
<L N="620">He &thorn;at take&thorn; hym to spousyng,</L>
<L>Mai not lyuen for<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. fre?</NOTE> no &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Bote holden he mot to his wyf</L>
<L>And ben in Cuntek and in stryf&mdash;</L>
<L N="624">Betere him were dihte and go&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor weddyng is &thorn;e longe wo.</L>
<L>Whon he ha&thorn; a wyf I-take,</L>
<L>He mai hire nou&yogh;t forsake;</L>
<L N="628">He &thorn;at ha&thorn; a schrewe to wyue,</L>
<L>Of vche a day him &thorn;inke&thorn; fyue;</L>
<L>Of muche Mur&thorn;e he schal misse</L>
<L>And euere ha serwe and neuer blisse,</L>
<L N="632">&THORN;er ano&thorn;er mai leue and take</L>
<L>Wher he wole, and eke forsake;</L>
<L>Lihtliche and glad may he go,</L>
<L>Whon he &thorn;at is bounden schal be ful wo,</L>
<L N="636">And be liht and Iolyf</L>
<L>More &thorn;en on &thorn;at ha&thorn; a wyf.</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i I rede &thorn;at men do so</L>
<L>And lete weddynge a-wey go."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="640">&THORN;E goode Mon wel vnderstod</L>
<L>&THORN;at his counseil was not good.</L>
<L>"He is a fol and no&thorn;ing wys : &THORN;at folewe&thorn; &thorn;i Red:</L>
<L>&THORN;e Mon &thorn;at folewe&thorn; his flesches lust : His soule schal be ded;</L>
<L N="644">But &yogh;if he do kuyndely : And wi&thorn; spoused fere,</L>
<L>In helle he schal a-buggen : His flessches lyking here.</L>
<L>&THORN;er beo&thorn; &thorn;orw godes lawen : Ten Comaundemens,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vche mon ou&yogh;te kepe : Elles he breke&thorn; his defens;</L>
<L N="648">Spous-bruche, forso&thorn;e : Is &thorn;e grettest of alle&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at aren I-weddet, kep hem wel : &THORN;at &thorn;ei &thorn;er-Inne ne falle;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at wol folewen his flessches lust : And &thorn;e lawe breke,
<PB REF="00000354.tif" N="346"></L>
<L>Ne &thorn;inke him no wonder &thorn;enne : &thorn;au&yogh; god on hym a-wreke.</L>
<L N="652">Mon in Godes lawe : Mai wel haue a Make,</L>
<L>To do wi&thorn; hire his wille : ffor childberynge sake,</L>
<L>And louen ei&thorn;er o&thorn;er : Whon tyme is and leue,</L>
<L>And holden hem wel to-gedere : As Adam dude and Eue.</L>
<L N="656">But hit beo in wedlac : In alle wyse lef &thorn;at game</L>
<L>And liue in chastite : And be wi&thorn;-outen blame!</L>
<L>Gret schome hit is and synne : I swere &thorn;e be heuene,</L>
<L>To spende &thorn;i fyue wittes : In eny of &thorn;e synnes seuene,</L>
<L N="660">&THORN;at God &thorn;e ha&thorn; I-&yogh;iuen : And &thorn;ine lymes alle,</L>
<L>ffor to kepe &thorn;e wi&thorn; : In synne &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne falle.</L>
<L>A foul chaunge hit is, forso&thorn;e : And a gret vuel,</L>
<L>To chaunge heuene for helle : And God for &thorn;e deuel;</L>
<L N="664">&THORN;at dostou, as ofte as &thorn;ou syngest dedli</L>
<L>And brekest godus comaundemens &amp; dost a gret foli;</L>
<L>&THORN;e deueles &thorn;ral &thorn;ou be-comest : Whon &thorn;ou dost &thorn;i miht</L>
<L>To foule &thorn;i clene soule : Bi daye or be niht . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="marg">(some vv. om.)</NOTE></L>
<L N="668">Niht and day he studie&thorn; : And caste&thorn; his gynne</L>
<L>How he may bi alle weyes : A wommons loue wynne;</L>
<L>Nil he neuer stunten : He swere&thorn; his o&thorn;,</L>
<L N="671">Ar he haue his wille i-don : Be god neuer so wro&thorn;.</L>
<L>And heo wol haue him, heo sei&thorn; : Euermore to dwelle,</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;er &thorn;en heo hym for-go : Ben<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. Ben</NOTE> in &thorn;e put of helle.</L>
<L>But wusten heo what hit were : &THORN;e leste pyne &thorn;er-Inne,</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e good in eor&thorn;e : &thorn;ei nolde don dedly synne!</L>
<L N="676">ffor &thorn;ei nolde not be war : Er &thorn;ei coome &thorn;are,</L>
<L>In pyne schul &thorn;ei euer be : In serwe and in care.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at aren gode : Liuen in muche wynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode gon a Godeshalf : &THORN;e deueles limes to synne.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei comen to-gedere : Ei&thorn;er on o&thorn;er wynke&thorn;;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei ne hedde heor synne i-do : Longe &thorn;er-to hem &thorn;inke&thorn;;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei seo heore tyme : Wol &thorn;ei not longe dwelle,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;ei do &thorn;e dede : &THORN;at eche&thorn; &thorn;e fuir of helle.</L>
<L N="684">&THORN;e fuir &thorn;at is in helle : Is euer Brennynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e synful wrecche soules : &THORN;er-Inne pynynge;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Mo &thorn;at are &thorn;er-Inne : &THORN;e hattore is &thorn;e lye,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e pyne hardore : &THORN;at &thorn;e soules drye.
<PB REF="00000355.tif" N="347"></L>
<L N="688">Heo beo&thorn; grete foles : ffor so&thorn;e I sigge, I-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; &thorn;e pyne more : And hattore &thorn;en hit is.</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke &thorn;at breke&thorn; godes word : &THORN;orw heor dedly synne,</L>
<L N="691">&THORN;ei lihten &thorn;e fuir : &THORN;at &thorn;ei schulen brennen Inne.</L>
<L>Godes Comaundement &thorn;ei breke : Al &thorn;at do&thorn; lecherie:</L>
<L>In helle-fuir schul &thorn;ei euer be : Heore peynes to drie"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E wikkede gost onswerede &thorn;o</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at hit was not so.</L>
<L N="696">"So &thorn;ou seist as false men do:</L>
<L>&THORN;at Sleu&thorn;e is synne, and is not so.</L>
<L>Men<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Mon?</NOTE> mot haue, &yogh;if &thorn;ei may,</L>
<L>Ese and reste, ni&yogh;t and day,</L>
<L N="700">In Bedde, in Mete beo al at his ese</L>
<L>And mak &thorn;e bodi euer wel at ese.</L>
<L>After &thorn;i de&thorn; wost &thorn;ou not what,</L>
<L>What &thorn;ou schalt haue, &thorn;enk wel on &thorn;at!</L>
<L N="704">While &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t, make &thorn;e glad and muri!</L>
<L>Lengor liue&thorn; a glad mon &thorn;en a sori.</L>
<L>Al knowe I wel &thorn;i resun</L>
<L>And what be-tokne&thorn; &thorn;i lessun:</L>
<L N="708">ffor Men scholde to chirche gonge,</L>
<L>To here Matins, Masse, and Euensonge,</L>
<L>Heore pater noster to sigge, Aue Marie, &amp; Crede,</L>
<L>And ete of prestes holy brede.</L>
<L N="712">What, wenest &thorn;ou for such &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;i soule in to heuene bring?</L>
<L>Ho bi-gon furst to worche,</L>
<L>And whi was maad, holichirche?</L>
<L N="716">Of Prestes couetise hit was bi&thorn;ouht</L>
<L>&THORN;at churche was furst I-wrouht,</L>
<L>ffor he wolde haue offryng</L>
<L>And liue bi o&thorn;ur mennes &thorn;ing.</L>
<L N="720">He wole a-Morwe Belle rynge,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne wol he Matyns synge;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;er luite folk come&thorn; &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>He wol hi&yogh;e faste and haue I-do;</L>
<L N="724">And &yogh;if &thorn;er muche folk come, I sigge &thorn;e,</L>
<L>He wol make gret solempnite:</L>
<L>Reuesten him &thorn;enne wole he wel</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; riche pal and sendel,
<PB REF="00000356.tif" N="348"></L>
<L>He wol don on his canter-cope<NOTE PLACE="marg">ags. cantelcapa pallium</NOTE></L>
<L N="729">And gon as he were a Pope;</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he wole wi&thorn; springel-stikke</L>
<L>&YOGH;iuen holy water a-bouten &thorn;ikke,</L>
<L N="732">And syngen loude wi&thorn; schil &thorn;rote,</L>
<L>And sei&thorn; hit is &thorn;e soule note</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e prest sei&thorn; and do&thorn;&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk wene&thorn; &thorn;at hit be so&thorn;;</L>
<L N="736">Bi-fore his Auter he wol stonden</L>
<L>And holde vp an hei&yogh; bo&thorn;e his honden,</L>
<L>He wol synge mony a &thorn;rowe,</L>
<L>Sum-time hei&yogh;e &amp; sum-time lowe,</L>
<L N="740">He wole him turne &amp; take good hede</L>
<L>&YOGH;if eny Mon him bringe mede.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if muche folk come and &thorn;ringe</L>
<L>Offringe faste him to brynge,</L>
<L N="744">He wole amende faste his song&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at tyme &thorn;inke&thorn; him not long.</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;ei wole him no-&thorn;ing brynge,</L>
<L>Lust him no-&thorn;ing for to synge,</L>
<L N="748">ffaste he hi&yogh;e&thorn; hym to spede</L>
<L>And &yogh;iue&thorn; hem of his holy brede&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e beste of al his dede,</L>
<L>ffor hit helpe&thorn; to monnes nede;</L>
<L N="752">&THORN;au&yogh; hit be luytel, hit turne&thorn; to gode,</L>
<L>ffor hit helpe&thorn; to Monnes foode.</L>
<L>Whon he ha&thorn; al I-do,</L>
<L>He &yogh;iue&thorn; heom leue and let hem go;</L>
<L N="756">But euer a-Mong al o&thorn;ur nede</L>
<L>His oune erende wol he bede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei brynge heore offrynges</L>
<L>To Chirche, and heore ty&thorn;inges.</L>
<L N="760">Wel &thorn;ou wost &thorn;at &thorn;is is so&thorn;:</L>
<L>Al for his owne gode he hit do&thorn;;</L>
<L>Kepe&thorn; he nou&yogh;t of heore comynge,</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;ei wole him eni good bringe.&mdash;</L>
<L N="764">But, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt on eny wyse</L>
<L>At Chirche here &thorn;i seruyse,</L>
<L>A-tome &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t ful wel abyde</L>
<L>Til he haue seid &thorn;e laste tyde;
<PB REF="00000357.tif" N="349"></L>
<L N="768">And &yogh;it mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou lengore dwelle</L>
<L>And come be tyme to &thorn;e gospelle;</L>
<L>A-tome mai&yogh;t &thorn;ow do good nede</L>
<L>And come to &thorn;e Masse crede;</L>
<L N="772">And &yogh;if &thorn;e luste ri&yogh;t wel slope,</L>
<L>Cum whon he do&thorn; of his Masse-cope;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei&yogh; &thorn;ou ne come, ne &yogh;if no tale,</L>
<L>Til he halibred be-ginne to dale:</L>
<L N="776">&THORN;enne mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou ben al &yogh;are,</L>
<L>And hom wi&thorn; &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebors fare."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E goode Mon wel vnderstod</L>
<L>&THORN;at his techynge was not good.</L>
<L N="780">"Al &thorn;at &thorn;ou spekest hit is nou&yogh;t : &THORN;ow mi&yogh;test wel be stille,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at &thorn;e bodi lyke&thorn; wel : Is a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e soule wille.</L>
<L>Ese and reste and muri lyf : Men lyke&thorn; wel and wymmenne,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ei brynge &thorn;e soule in strif : A&yogh;eyn &thorn;ei wenden henne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bodi and &thorn;e soule be&thorn; : Wel neih euere wro&thorn;:</L>
<L N="785">ffor &thorn;at &thorn;e bodi lyke&thorn; wel : Is to &thorn;e soule lo&thorn;.</L>
<L>Muche tale &thorn;ou makest : &THORN;e foule bodi to queme,</L>
<L>But of &thorn;e seli soule : Takest &thorn;ow no &yogh;eme.</L>
<L N="788">Aftur &thorn;at &thorn;e bodi do&thorn; : Schal &thorn;e soule fynde</L>
<L>And in peyne or in Ioye : Euere &thorn;erof haue mynde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if Men loue to slepe : Whon &thorn;ei scholden wake,</L>
<L>&THORN;enne schal &thorn;e soule : In stude of Ioye haue wrake.</L>
<L N="792">Monnes lyf nis bote schort : Sone wol hit go,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;e sely soule : Duyre&thorn; euer-mo;</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule schal faren his wey : &THORN;e bodi schal a-byde</L>
<L>And not nou&yogh;t of &thorn;e soule : What hit schal be-tyde.</L>
<L N="796">But wel I wot, and so&thorn; hit is : After monnes dede,</L>
<L>Whon he is for&thorn; faren : He schal hauen his mede:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he haue loued god : And kept his biddynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e blisse of heuene schal he haue : Wi&thorn;-outen endynge;</L>
<L N="800">Ou&thorn;ur in to peyne schal he be brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he haue &thorn;er-aftur wrou&yogh;t.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore is ned on alle wyse</L>
<L>Men to go to Godes seruyse</L>
<L N="804">And wake &thorn;e more and slepe &thorn;e lasse,
<PB REF="00000358.tif" N="350"></L>
<L>To here Matyns, Euensong, and Masse.</L>
<L>Whon men han a&yogh;eyn god : In dedly synne falle,</L>
<L>Heo ou&yogh;ten for to wepe : And Merci to God calle,</L>
<L N="808">And wenden to &thorn;e prest : Hastiliche and sone</L>
<L>And tellen him in schrif : What synne he ha&thorn; i-done.</L>
<L>A fool he is &thorn;at a-byde&thorn; : Eny gret stounde,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;er come more sor : And cleue to &thorn;e wounde.</L>
<L N="812">Also hit fare&thorn; bi synne : I wot wi&thorn;-outen wene,</L>
<L>As do&thorn; be &thorn;e wounde : While hit is nowe and grene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e leche clanse&thorn; &thorn;e wounde : Clene in &thorn;e ground</L>
<L>And lei&thorn; salue a-boue : And make&thorn; hit hol and sound;</L>
<L N="816">Mon may for a wounde : Or for a luitel sor,</L>
<L>Bote hit be sone I-heled : Be worse and wel mor:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if o sor come to ano&thorn;er : &THORN;enne are &thorn;er two,</L>
<L>And &yogh;if he longe a-byde : &THORN;en wol &thorn;er be mo;</L>
<L N="820">His owne bone mai hit be : Longe for to abyde&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore I rede, sech leche-craft : Soone, what be-tyde.</L>
<L>Also hit fare&thorn; bi synne : &YOGH;if hit I-hud is;</L>
<L>Bote hit be to &thorn;e prest : Soone I-told, I-wis,</L>
<L N="824">Hit drawe&thorn; hem to helle-grounde : And bynde&thorn; hem to peynes stronge;</L>
<L>&THORN;e hardore peyne schal he haue : &YOGH;if he &thorn;er-Inne ligge longe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lengor &thorn;at men a-byde : &THORN;e latere come&thorn; bote;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei stonde wel &thorn;e fastore : Whon &thorn;ei haue take rote.</L>
<L N="828">&THORN;au&yogh; Men fallen in synne : Gret wonder hit nis;</L>
<L>But ligge stille &thorn;er-Inne : &THORN;at is wonder gret, I-wis!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow liggest in &thorn;e fuir : And brennest on eny wyse,</L>
<L>Who is for to wyte : &THORN;i-self wolt nou&yogh;t arise?</L>
<L N="832">Mynde ha&thorn; he non : Of God &thorn;at hym wrouhte</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e Roode-tre : Wi&thorn; his passion him bouhte.</L>
<L>Wel hit is I-seene : &THORN;at &thorn;ei are ful slowe</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e prest nil not : Heore synnes ben a-knowe,</L>
<L>And luytel &thorn;onk &thorn;ei cunne god : ffor his goode seruyse,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei wole not for his loue : Out of synne aryse.</L>
<L>&THORN;inke no mon wonder : &THORN;auh god wi&thorn; hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. him</NOTE> be wro&thorn;</L>
<L>And take vengeaunce on hem : Beo hem neuer so lo&thorn;!</L>
<L>Schriue&thorn; ow be-tyme : ffor loue or for feer,</L>
<L N="841">ffor God take&thorn; wreche : Heer or elleswher;</L>
<L>Bi-weope&thorn; &yogh;oure synnes : And cri&yogh;e&thorn; God Merci,
<PB REF="00000359.tif" N="351"></L>
<L>And to alle his werkes : Beo&thorn; euere redi!</L>
<L N="844">Whon hit is halyday : Vche Mon ouhte wi&thorn; rihte</L>
<L>To heere his seruyse in chirche : &YOGH;if he on eny wyse mihte,</L>
<L>And not in sleu&thorn;e ligge, : In bed a-tome abyde</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e prest haue I-seid : &THORN;e laste non-tyde.</L>
<L N="848">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou go at morwe : And Matyns here erliche,</L>
<L>Hit is &thorn;e soule profyt : I sigge &thorn;e sikerliche;</L>
<L>&THORN;eih &thorn;i flesch grucche : Lette nouht &thorn;erfore&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ofter &thorn;ow ouercomest hit : &THORN;i Meede schal beo &thorn;e more;</L>
<L N="852">&YOGH;if &thorn;ow herest Matyns and Masse : And takest haly brede,</L>
<L>To Bodi and to soule : &THORN;ow wynnest muchel Mede.</L>
<L>After Mete loke &thorn;ou go to &thorn;e prechynge,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if eny beo in toune&mdash;lette for no &thorn;ynge&mdash;</L>
<L N="856">And &thorn;at &thorn;e prechur preche&thorn; : Vnderstonde hit wel,</L>
<L>And do as he &thorn;e teche&thorn; : I rede &thorn;e, vche a del.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;er no prechyng be : Go visyte &thorn;e seke,</L>
<L>Cumforte hem wi&thorn; &thorn;in Almes : And wi&thorn; &thorn;i wordes Meke.</L>
<L N="860">Aftur, whon &thorn;ei rynge : Go to Euen-song,</L>
<L>And lette for no cumpaignye : &THORN;at &thorn;ow art aMong;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow do not, for so&thorn;e : &THORN;ou dost &thorn;e deueles wille,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou in ganglyng and drynkyng : Dwellest wi&thorn; hem stille.</L>
<L N="864">Whon Euensong &amp; cumplyn bo&thorn;e ben ido,</L>
<L>Hom to &thorn;i soper &thorn;en wel mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou go.</L>
<L>I rede &thorn;enne, ar &thorn;ow go : ffulliche in to<NOTE PLACE="marg">overl.</NOTE> &thorn;i bed,</L>
<L>&THORN;onke crist of &thorn;at day : &THORN;at &thorn;ow hast wel I-sped;</L>
<L N="868">And &yogh;if &thorn;ou ou&yogh;t hast mis-done,</L>
<L>Aske him merci, I rede, sone;</L>
<L>Be-teche &thorn;i lyf and &thorn;i soule : To God Almihti:</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou slepe : wel and sikerly.</L>
<L N="872">Whon &thorn;ow risest vp, &thorn;onke god : Inwardliche wi&thorn; al &thorn;i miht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e ha&thorn; saued from encumbrement : Of &thorn;e ffend &thorn;at niht;</L>
<L>Be-teche al in godes hond : &THORN;i preyers and &thorn;i dedes,</L>
<L N="875">&THORN;i wittes and &thorn;i willes : And al &thorn;yn o&thorn;er nedes.
<PB REF="00000360.tif" N="352"></L>
<L>Avise &thorn;e in al &thorn;i werkes : &THORN;ow saue &thorn;e from dedli synne,</L>
<L>And do as I counseyle &thorn;e : And heuene schalt &thorn;ou winne.</L>
<L>In what werk, Mon, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be : worche euer trewli,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ou schalt haue peine &thorn;erfore : &YOGH;if &thorn;ou worche falsli;</L>
<L N="880">&YOGH;if &thorn;ow take here &thorn;i fulle huyre : And dost not fulliche &thorn;i werk &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L>In helle or in purgatorie : &THORN;i peyne schal be wel &thorn;e more.</L>
<L>Of what condicion so &thorn;ou art : Trewe in alle &thorn;ing &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>And do so to vche mon : As &thorn;ou woldest he dude to &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="884">And loke in al &thorn;at &thorn;ou seist &amp; dost : &THORN;at God be euere apayd,</L>
<L>And lef sleu&thorn;e &amp; al o&thorn;er synnes : As Ich haue I-seid!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E wikked gost onswerde &thorn;on</L>
<L>And seide: "&thorn;ou art a Mad mon!</L>
<L N="888">&THORN;au&yogh; &thorn;ou woldest now be-ginne</L>
<L>And sigge &thorn;at glotenye were sinne,</L>
<L>Beter &thorn;e were &thorn;i Ianglyng lete.</L>
<L>Men scholde dye, &yogh;if &thorn;ei ne ete,</L>
<L N="892">And bote &thorn;ei drinke wel, also;</L>
<L>No Mon mai liue wi&thorn;-outen hem two.</L>
<L>To Badde counseil art &thorn;ou euer &yogh;are,</L>
<L>To ffastyng and to vuel fare.</L>
<L N="896">What good come&thorn; of fastyng?</L>
<L>ffeyntyse, Idelnesse, &amp; non o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>&THORN;at mai&yogh;t &thorn;ow wel wite be skil.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e flesch ha&thorn; Mete &amp; drinke at wil,</L>
<L N="900">&THORN;en is he redi to fihte and chide</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;o &thorn;at gon and ride.</L>
<L>Ho mai duire for to swynke,</L>
<L>But &yogh;if he ete wel and drinke?</L>
<L N="904">Hunger make&thorn; men beo bi-hynde</L>
<L>In vche a werk, as I fynde.</L>
<L>Gode drinkes &amp; Metes wel I-diht</L>
<L>Are wel I-loued, and &thorn;at is riht.</L>
<L N="908">&YOGH;if he beo a stout sweyn,</L>
<L>He ete&thorn; til hit come vp a&yogh;eyn.</L>
<L>Al-&thorn;auh hit be so &thorn;at he caste&mdash;</L>
<L>So he mihte, &thorn;auh he faste&mdash;
<PB REF="00000361.tif" N="353"></L>
<L N="912">Hit nis for no dronkenesse,</L>
<L>But for o&thorn;er seknesse.</L>
<L>Whon he is heled of &thorn;at sore,</L>
<L>He may ete and drinke more,</L>
<L N="916">And make glad and bli&thorn;e chere&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor euere is ale and wyn good fere.</L>
<L>Et faste and drink wel : And sleep euere a-mong:</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne mayht &thorn;ow lyue : &YOGH;eres monye and long."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="920">&THORN;E gode Mon, &thorn;at in god was stable,</L>
<L>Vnderstod, &thorn;at he seide, was fable.</L>
<L>"Wel I wot &thorn;at men mote liue : Be Mete and be drynk,</L>
<L>As skile is and resun : And Mesure in alle &thorn;yng.</L>
<L N="924">&THORN;ei &thorn;at liuen as beestes : Aren wi&thorn;-outen lay,</L>
<L>&THORN;at erliche ete&thorn; and drynke&thorn; : And holde&thorn; on al day.</L>
<L>&THORN;e beest do&thorn; his kynde : And &thorn;e glotun synne</L>
<L>Do&thorn; a&yogh;eyn his kynde : &THORN;at wol neuer blynne.</L>
<L N="928">Suche foule glotounes : Do&thorn; a-&yogh;eyn &thorn;e lawe.</L>
<L>Ar &thorn;e wombe be ful : Beo &thorn;ei neuer fawe;</L>
<L>&THORN;enne wol &thorn;ei chiden and fi&yogh;ten also&mdash;</L>
<L>Serwe on heore hedes, but &thorn;ei wel do!</L>
<L N="932">Mete and drynke is &yogh;iuen to mon : As salue to sore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neodful is to take &thorn;erof : And neuere a del more.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow to muche salue : Leyst to &thorn;i sar,</L>
<L>Hit wol beo &thorn;i de&thorn; : Bote &thorn;ow sone be war;</L>
<L N="936">So wol hit of Mete &amp; of drinke be:</L>
<L>&THORN;i soule bone, &yogh;if &thorn;ou take mor &thorn;en nede&thorn; &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Whon mon ha&thorn; at Meel-tyme : Such as he wile,</L>
<L>Tak &thorn;at he ha&thorn; neode of : Be Mesure and bi skile,</L>
<L N="940">And parte wi&thorn; &thorn;e pore : Of &thorn;at is on [his]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;y</NOTE> bord,</L>
<L>And not in his wombe : Make al his hord&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er is foul tresorie : And al ful of stinke.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at &thorn;ou takest mor &thorn;en neod is : In peyne &thorn;ou schalt of-&thorn;inke.</L>
<L N="944">In &thorn;e Bok of priuetes : Glotons are Manased so:</L>
<L>'A&yogh;eyn O drau&yogh;t &thorn;ei drinke ouer-muche : &THORN;ei schul han &thorn;re or two</L>
<L>Of hot led and walled bras. : &THORN;ei schul beo ful wo,</L>
<L>ffor stynkyng brumston and for pich : &THORN;at in heore &thorn;rotes schal go.'</L>
<L N="948">&THORN;us seide &thorn;e prest &thorn;at god wol take wreche,
<PB REF="00000362.tif" N="354"></L>
<L>But &yogh;if &yogh;e leue synne and do as I ow teche."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E wikkede gost, &thorn;er he stood,</L>
<L>Wox for wra&thorn;&thorn;e wel-nei&yogh; wood,</L>
<L N="952">ffor he was ouer-comen and be-hynde&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor mo onsweres cou&thorn;e he not fynde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode Mon &thorn;enne was a-bascht</L>
<L>And lokede on &thorn;e wikkede gast</L>
<L N="956">And seide: "now wot I, &thorn;ow art non</L>
<L>Mon mad of flesch and bon;</L>
<L>I vnderstonde wel be &thorn;i spelle</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou art &thorn;e deuel of helle.</L>
<L N="960">I &thorn;e Comaunde, foule &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e nome of heuene kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow me no&thorn;ing drecche,</L>
<L>But bi-cum now, foule wrecche,</L>
<L N="964">As foul as &thorn;ou were</L>
<L>In helle wi&thorn; &thorn;i feere."</L>
<L>Ne mihte he no lengure a-byde,</L>
<L>Bote bi-com &thorn;o also-tyde</L>
<L N="968">ffoul as helle-Sathanas,</L>
<L>As Blac as eny pich he was&mdash;</L>
<L>How foul he was con I not telle,</L>
<L>But foul he stonk as stunch of helle.</L>
<L N="972">&THORN;e gode mon blessed him wi&thorn; &thorn;e Crois</L>
<L>And cri&yogh;ed on God wi&thorn; loud vois,</L>
<L>Bi-fore, be-hynde he blessed him fast,</L>
<L>And Comaundede &thorn;at sori gast</L>
<L N="976">ffor to wenden: and so he dude &thorn;o,</L>
<L>To &thorn;at stude &thorn;at he com fro.</L>
<L>Pouwer hedde he no lengore dwelle,</L>
<L>But wente doun riht in to helle.</L>
<L N="980">&THORN;e gode Mon wente hom his way,</L>
<L>And serued god wel to pay,</L>
<L>And &thorn;onked him&mdash;so ouhte he wel&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at him sauede from &thorn;e deuel.</L>
<L N="984">Ihesu Crist such grace vs sende</L>
<L>Hym to serue to vre lyues ende,</L>
<L>And kep vs from &thorn;e synnes seuene,</L>
<L>And graunt vs alle &thorn;e blisse of heuene!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Then follows in MS. Vern. &thorn;e ri&yogh;te put of helle, 3rd part of the legend of St. Michael in the South Engl. Legendary, fol. CCXCI, here written in half lines.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="38" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000363.tif" N="355">
<HEAD>XXXVIII. Castel of Loue. <MILESTONE N="CCXCII" UNIT="folio"> </HEAD>

<HEADNOTE><P>Ed. before by Weymouth, Philol. Soc. 1864, and from another (un|known) MS., by Halliwell, 1849. The poem is a very old translation of Rob. Groshed's (&dagger; 1253) <I>Chasteau d'amour</I>, or <I>Carmen de creatione mundi</I> (ed. by M. Cooke, R. Grossetete Carmina anglo-normannica, Caxton Soc. 1852), and was made in the latter half of the 13th cent., in the dialect and perhaps by the author of the 'Harrowing of Hell' and 'Marina' (MS. Harl. 2253). The subject, with its personification of the 4 cardinal virtues, resting ultimately on Psalm 88, 11, became a great favourite in medieval literature: it is treated in the Cursor Mundi, in the Abbey of the Holy Ghost, and in Lydgate's Life of St. Mary, and his Court of Sapience. Later translations are extant in MS. Egerton 927, made by a monk of Sawley in Yorkshire (ed. in the Appendix), and in MS. Ashm. 61, fol. 78 (ed. in Altengl. Legenden, Neue Folge, p. 349-354), which contains only the first part (to v. 554). Cooke's ed. of the French text is quite insufficient, and full of mistakes.</P></HEADNOTE>

<ARGUMENT>
<L>Her byginnet a tretys</L>
<L>&THORN;at is yclept Castel off Loue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bisschop Grostey&yogh;t made, ywis,</L>
<L>ffor lewede mennes by-houe.</L>
</ARGUMENT>

<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 1-18 cf. Fr. text: <Q><L>Ky bien pense bien puet dire;</L><L>Sanz penser ne peut suffire</L><L>De nul bien fet comencer.</L><L>Deu nus doint a li penser,</L><L>De ki, par ki, en ki sunt</L><L>Touz les biens ki sunt el mund,</L><L>Deu le pere e deu le fiz</L><L>E deu li seinz esperiz,</L><L>Persones treis en trinite</L><L>E un sul deu en unite,</L><L>Sanz fin, sanz comence|ment,</L><L>A ki honur e gloire apent.</L><L>Il nus doint ses oures fere</L><L>E nus defende de contrere.</L></Q> (The Engl. text does not give a favourable idea of the translator's intelligence.)</NOTE>&THORN;At good &thorn;enke&thorn;, good may do,</L>
<L>And God wol helpe him &thorn;erto;</L>
<L>ffor nas neuere good werk wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-oute be-ginninge of good &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ne neuer was wrou&yogh;t non vuel &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;at vuel &thorn;ou&yogh;t nas &thorn;e biginnyng.</L>
<L>God ffader and Sone and Holigost,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;ing on eor&thorn;e sixt and wost,</L>
<L>&THORN;at O God art and &thorn;rilli-hod,</L>
<L>And &thorn;reo persones in on-hod,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen ende and biginninge;</L>
<L N="12">To whom we ou&yogh;ten ouer alle &thorn;inge</L>
<L>Worschupe him wi&thorn; trewe loue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at kinewor&thorn;e kyng art vs aboue;</L>
<L>In whom, of whom, &thorn;orw whom beo&thorn;</L>
<L N="16">Al &thorn;e goodschipes &thorn;at we here i-seo&thorn;:</L>
<L>He leue vs &thorn;enche and worchen so</L>
<L>&THORN;at he vs schylde from vre fo.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 19-37 cf. Fr.: <Q><L>Tuz avum mester d'aie,</L><L>E trestuz ne poeut mie</L><L>Saver le langage en fin</L><L>D'Ebreu, de griu ne de latin,</L><L>Pur loer son creat[e]ur,</L><L>Ne la buche de chanteur</L><L>Ne soit clos de deu loer</L><L>Ne son seint nom nuncier.</L><L>Ke chescun en son langage</L><L>Le conuisse sanz folage</L></Q></NOTE>Alle we habbe&thorn; to help neode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;ah</NOTE> we ne be&thorn; alle of one &thorn;eode</L>
<L>Ne I-boren In one londe</L>
<L>Ne one speche vnderstonde.</L>
<L>Ne mowe we alle Latin wite,</L>
<L>Ne Ebreu ne Gru &thorn;at be&thorn; I-write,
<PB REF="00000364.tif" N="356"></L>
<L>Ne ffrench ne &thorn;is o&thorn;er spechen<NOTE PLACE="marg"><Q><L>Son deu, e sa redempcinn.</L><L>En romanz comenz ma rei|son</L><L>Por ceus ki ne sevent mie</L><L>Ne lettrure ne clergie.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at me mihte in world sechen,</L>
<L>To herie god, vre derwor&thorn;e drihte;</L>
<L>Ac<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. As; om. in H.</NOTE> vche mon ou&yogh;te wi&thorn; al his mihte</L>
<L>Lof<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Loft</NOTE> song syngen to god &yogh;erne</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; such speche as he con lerne;</L>
<L>No Monnes Mou&thorn; ne be I-dut</L>
<L N="32">Ne his ledene I-hud</L>
<L>To seruen<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. herien</NOTE> his god, &thorn;at him wrou&yogh;te</L>
<L>And maade al &thorn;e world of nou&yogh;te.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ON Englisch I-chul mi resun schowen,</L>
<L N="36">ffor him &thorn;at con not I-knowen</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;er ffrench ne Latyn.</L>
<L>On Englisch I-chulle tellen him</L>
<L>Wherfore<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. For why</NOTE> &thorn;e world was<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. was furst</NOTE> I-wrouht,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;er-aftur how he was bi-tauht</L>
<L>Adam vre ffader, to ben his,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al &thorn;e mer&thorn;e of paradys,</L>
<L>To wonen and welden to such ende,</L>
<L N="44">Til &thorn;at he scholde to heuene wende;</L>
<L>And hou sone he hit for-les;</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en, hou hit for-bouht wes</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 47-82 wanting in the Fr. poem, but taken from its Latin title or index.</NOTE>&THORN;orw &thorn;e hei&yogh;e kynges sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at here on eor&thorn;e wolde come</L>
<L>ffor his Sustren &thorn;at were to-boren,</L>
<L>And for a prison &thorn;at was for-loren,<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 49 &amp; 50 to be transp.?</NOTE></L>
<L>And hou he made, as &yogh;e schul heeren,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at heo I-custe and sauht weren;</L>
<L>And to w&yogh;uche a Castel he alihte</L>
<L>&THORN;o he wolde here for vs fihte&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e Marie bodi wes,</L>
<L>&THORN;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;at, H. Therin; cf. v. 666.</NOTE> he alihte and his in ches.</L>
<L>And tellen we schulen of Ysay,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Is. 9, 6.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at vs tolde trewely</L>
<L>"A Child &thorn;er is iboren to vs</L>
<L N="60">And a Sone I-&yogh;iuen vs,</L>
<L>Whos nome schal I-nempned beon</L>
<L>Wonderful, as me may I-seon,</L>
<L>And God, mihtful, and right wys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Lat. consiliarius</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e world &thorn;at [to]<NOTE PLACE="marg">om.; Lat. Pater futuri secull.</NOTE> comen is
<PB REF="00000365.tif" N="357"></L>
<L>LOrd &thorn;e ffader, and Prince of pes."<NOTE PLACE="marg">In the MS. written in 2 vv.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;eos nomen, hou he wes,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schulen I-heren and I-witen.</L>
<L N="68"><SUP>1</SUP>And of domus-day hou hit is I-writen;</L>
<L>And of heuene we schulen telle,</L>
<L>And sumdel of &thorn;e pynen of helle.<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">1_1 This last part is om. at the end, but extant in H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Auh hit on Englisch be dim and derk</L>
<L N="72">Ne nabbe no sauur bi-fore [a] clerk,</L>
<L>ffor lewed Men &thorn;at luitel connen</L>
<L>On Englisch hit is &thorn;us bi-gonnen.</L>
<L>Ac whose is witer and wys of wit</L>
<L N="76">And &yogh;erne bi-holde&thorn; &thorn;is ilke writ,</L>
<L>And con &thorn;at muchel of luitel<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. lintel. Cf. Fr. Latin Index: prudens lector qui norit sugere mel de petra oleumque de saxo durissimo, scriptum inveniet plenum dulcedine celesti.</NOTE> vnlouken</L>
<L>And Hony of &thorn;e harde ston souken,</L>
<L>Alle poyntes he fynde may</L>
<L>Of vre be-leeue and godes lay</L>
<L>&THORN;at bi-falle&thorn; to Godes Godhede</L>
<L>As wel as to his Monhede.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Offte &yogh;e habbe&thorn; I-herd ar &thorn;is</L>
<L N="84">Hou &thorn;e world I-maked is;</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i ne kep I nou&yogh;t to telle</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;at falle&thorn; to my spelle:</L>
<L>In Sixe dayes and seue niht</L>
<L N="88">God hedde al &thorn;e world I-diht;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o al was derwor&thorn;liche I-do,</L>
<L>&THORN;e seue&thorn;e day he tok reste and ro.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lustne&thorn; to me, lordynges.</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;o God atte begynnynges</L>
<L>Hedde I-maad heuene wi&thorn; ginne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Angeles so briht wi&thorn;-Inne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e eor&thorn;e &thorn;er-after &thorn;er-wi&thorn;,</L>
<L N="96">And al &thorn;at euere in hire bi-ly&thorn;:</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 94, 97-100 added to the French.</NOTE>Lucifer in heuene wox so proud</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. And, H. That</NOTE> he was a-non I-cast out,</L>
<L>And mo Angeles &thorn;en eni tonge mai telle</L>
<L N="100">ffullen a-doun wi&thorn; him to helle.</L>
<L>And &yogh;it was &thorn;e Sonne &thorn;o seuesy&thorn;e I-wis</L>
<L>Brihtore forso&thorn;e &thorn;en heo now is;</L>
<L>Also schon &thorn;e Mone a-niht</L>
<L N="104">So do&thorn; &thorn;e Sonne on day-liht.
<PB REF="00000366.tif" N="358"></L>
<L>Ne holde &yogh;e hit not for folye,</L>
<L>ffor so sei&thorn; &thorn;e prophete Ysaye.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e schaftes &thorn;at &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. shupte</NOTE> weren</L>
<L N="108">More mi&yogh;t and streng&thorn;e beren</L>
<L>Bi-fore &thorn;at Adam &thorn;e world for-les.</L>
<L>Allas, w&yogh;uch serwe and deol &thorn;er wes!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle heo beo&thorn; I-brouh[t] to grounde</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;at of his of-springe beo&thorn; I-founde;</L>
<L>Of heuene-blisse heo beo&thorn; I-flemed</L>
<L>And to deolful de&thorn; I-demed,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Reson is good and feir for whi,</L>
<L N="116">As I-chulle ow telle for-&thorn;i</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e schule loue God &thorn;e more</L>
<L>And him seruen and clepe to his ore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;O God hedde al &thorn;e world I-wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at &thorn;er ne faylede ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Beest ne ffisch, ne ffoul to fleon,</L>
<L>And vche &thorn;ing as hit ou&yogh;te to beon,</L>
<L>Blosme on Bou&yogh; and Breer on Rys,</L>
<L N="124">And alle &thorn;ing betere &thorn;en hit nou is;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o he hedde al wel I-don,</L>
<L>He com to &thorn;e valeye of Ebron;</L>
<L N="127">&THORN;er he made Adam and last<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. laft, H. at the last, Fr. auderrain.</NOTE> so Riche</L>
<L>Of eor&thorn;e, after hym-self I-liche,</L>
<L>And aftur his holy &thorn;rilli-hod</L>
<L>He schop his soule feir and good.</L>
<L>How mi&yogh;te he him more loue schowen</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;en his oune liknesse habben and owen?</L>
<L>To paradys he ladde him &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And caste sleep on him al-so</L>
<L>&THORN;at of his syde A Rib he nom,</L>
<L N="136">And &thorn;er-of Eue, his feere, com,</L>
<L>He &yogh;af Adam Eue to wyue,</L>
<L>To helpen; he &yogh;af him wittes fyue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. saveir. 139-144 added to the Fr.</NOTE></L>
<L>To delen &thorn;at vuel from &thorn;e good,</L>
<L N="140">&YOGH;if he wel him vnderstood;</L>
<L>He &yogh;af him &yogh;it more worschipe:<NOTE PLACE="marg">141, 143-4, 146, 150-1 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of al &thorn;e world &thorn;e lordschipe,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e schaftes of water and lond</L>
<L N="144">Scholden ben vnder his hond;
<PB REF="00000367.tif" N="359"></L>
<L>ffeirlek, and freodam, and muche miht,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e world to delen and diht,</L>
<L>And paradys, to wonen In</L>
<L N="148">Wi&thorn;-outen wo and serwe and pyn,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen de&thorn;, In goode lyue,</L>
<L>&THORN;er Ioye and Blisse is so ryue,</L>
<L>And euere to libben I-liche &yogh;ong,</L>
<L>O &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">o &thorn;at, until, cf. 472, 1404, 1412, Marina 210, Harr. 128. 148.</NOTE> of hem to weren and-sprong<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. at-sprong? Sim. at-sprong</NOTE></L>
<L N="153">&THORN;e noumbre<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. tale</NOTE> of &thorn;e soulen &thorn;at from heuene felle</L>
<L>&THORN;orw Lucifer a-doun to helle;</L>
<L>And whon hit for&thorn; com al &thorn;e stren,</L>
<L N="156">So bri&yogh;t heo scholden I-Blessed<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. glorifiez</NOTE> ben</L>
<L>So was &thorn;e Sonne, as I er tolde,</L>
<L>Brihtore &thorn;en heo now is seuen-folde,</L>
<L>And so heo scholden to heuene wende</L>
<L N="160">To &thorn;e Blisse wi&thorn;-outen ende</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen drede of de&thorn;es dome;</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e of-spring &thorn;at of hem come,</L>
<L>ffrom &thorn;at ilke day to &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="164">Scholde so stey&yogh;en to heuene-blis,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e heritage of wynne and wele,</L>
<L>A-Mong &thorn;e Mur&thorn;e of Aungeles fele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Two lawen Adam scholde I-wis</L>
<L N="168">Witen and holden In Paradis:</L>
<L>&THORN;at on him was &thorn;orw kynde i-let,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er was clept lawe I-set.</L>
<L>&THORN;at on him tau&yogh;te atte leste</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;orw kynde to holden godes heste;</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur lawe &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. was that</NOTE> him was set:</L>
<L>"Of &thorn;e Appel &thorn;ow neuer ne et</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e tre &thorn;at is for-bode."</L>
<L N="176">So him<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. he, H. hym</NOTE> seide and<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;at, H. and</NOTE> hi&yogh;te Gode</L>
<L>&THORN;at whon he of &thorn;e Appel ete,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw de&thorn; he scholde &thorn;e lyf forlete,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e kynde &thorn;at of him com</L>
<L N="180">Scholde &thorn;ole &thorn;ulke dom;<NOTE PLACE="marg">179-180 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;if he heolde his heste riht,</L>
<L>God &yogh;af him so muche miht</L>
<L>To welden al &thorn;is worldes winne,</L>
<L N="184">Wi&thorn;-outen wo and serwe and sinne.
<PB REF="00000368.tif" N="360"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Seisyn hedde Adam &thorn;o</L>
<L>To wonen in blisse euere and O.</L>
<L>In Muche Mur&thorn;e and Ioye he wes.</L>
<L N="188">A-wei, to sone he hit for-les,</L>
<L>His worschipe and his wel-fare,</L>
<L>Brou&yogh;te vs alle in muche care!</L>
<L>&THORN;o he of &thorn;e Appel eet,</L>
<L N="192">Godes heste he to-brek;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kuyndeliche and &thorn;e set ek,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e his lawen he to-brek,</L>
<L>And ra&thorn;ure he dude his wyues bode</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;en he heold &thorn;e heste of gode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us Adam &thorn;orw reu&thorn;ful rage</L>
<L>Was cast out of his heritage,</L>
<L>And out of Paradys I-driue,</L>
<L N="200">In swynk and swot in world to liue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Blisse of lyf he ha&thorn; forsaken,</L>
<L>And to deolful de&thorn; I-taken.</L>
<L>Carfuliche he ha&thorn; I-Coren!</L>
<L N="204">Now he &thorn;orw ri&yogh;t ha&thorn; I-loren</L>
<L>&THORN;e Mur&thorn;e &thorn;at he mi&yogh;te hauen,</L>
<L>Whom mai he to helpe crauen</L>
<L>Out of his heritage he is pult,</L>
<L N="208">ffor synne and for his owne gult.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 209-222 added to the Fr. (H. has same vv.)</NOTE>Lucifer gon wel lyke &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;o Adam was bi-swiken so&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor alle &thorn;e ffendes hedden onde</L>
<L N="212">&THORN;at he scholde come to &thorn;at blisful londe</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hedde &thorn;orw pruide for-lore;</L>
<L>Wel hit likede hem &thorn;er-fore.</L>
<L N="215">So muche wox heore miht &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e world moste after hem go;<NOTE PLACE="marg">same vv., 1313-4.</NOTE></L>
<L>And whon mon hedde I-liued in care,</L>
<L>Atte last he moste dyen &amp; for&thorn;-fare&mdash;</L>
<L>Ne mi&yogh;te him helpe no good dede</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at his soule moste<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. ne most</NOTE> to helle neede;</L>
<L>ffor so hit was to<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;o, H. to</NOTE> Adam bi-speke,</L>
<L>And god nolde no forward breke.</L>
<L>ffor<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. ffull, Fr. Trop</NOTE> eyle and hard and muche hit wes</L>
<L N="224">&THORN;e synne &thorn;at &thorn;us &thorn;e world for-les,
<PB REF="00000369.tif" N="361"></L>
<L>&THORN;at vche &thorn;ing vnder heuene-driht</L>
<L>So muche les of streng&thorn;e and miht!</L>
<L N="227">God ne wrouhte neuer &thorn;at &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;at out<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. mi(h)t? cf. 653.</NOTE> les &thorn;orw his wonyng<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. But hit peyred thowrgh his wonnyng. Cf. Fr.: <Q><L>Deu ne fist chose si haute</L><L>Nabessast pa[r] sa defaute.</L><L>Ke terriene chose feust,</L><L>Chescune chose son dreit eust,</L><L>Ne feust pechie que tant grieue.</L><L>Pechie, a parole brieue,</L><L>Cest defaute apertement&mdash;</L><L>Defaute e peche en un ses|tent.</L><L>Par defaute ot tant de perte,</L><L>Kar defaute fist aperte;</L><L>Defaute apres defaute fine</L><L>Fet par droit perdre seisine.</L></Q></NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor nis no wone on him I-long&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if synne nere so hard and strong;</L>
<L>ffor God &yogh;af vche &thorn;ing al his riht.</L>
<L>Ac sunne wonede heore alre miht&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor sunne and wone al is on.</L>
<L N="234">And wone dude Adam &thorn;o a-non</L>
<L>&THORN;o he godes heste at-seet,</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;o he &thorn;e Appel eet.</L>
<L>&THORN;orw wone he lees his seysyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw wone he brouhte him-self in pyne&mdash;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e kynges Court &yogh;it vche day</L>
<L N="240">Me vse&thorn; &thorn;ulke selue lay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOw is Adam wi&thorn; wo I-nome,</L>
<L>Sunnes &thorn;ral he is bi-come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at freore was er &thorn;en eny &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;at liuede vnder heuene-kyng.</L>
<L>He is &thorn;orw riht [his] &thorn;euwe and &thorn;ral</L>
<L N="246">To whos seruise he vnderstod wi&thorn;-al<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cf. Fr.:<Q><L>Nest il son serf apertement</L><L>Au ki seruice il entent?</L><L>Pus kil le seit, (est) en servage</L><L>E sanz franchise a estage.</L><L>H. vnderstondeth</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Whon<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. <Q><L>And when he him servid thorgh thewdome,</L><L>He dede withoute fre|dome.</L></Q></NOTE> he him serwede in &thorn;e-dome</L>
<L>And di&yogh;ede<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. dede?</NOTE> wi&thorn;-outen fredome.</L>
<L>And &thorn;euwe and &thorn;ral may not craue</L>
<L>&THORN;orw riht non heritage to haue:</L>
<L>As sone as he is &thorn;ral bi-come,</L>
<L N="252">His heritage is him bi-nome;</L>
<L>In Court ne in none londe</L>
<L>Me ne ou&yogh;te onswere him ne vndurstonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne he mot a-no&thorn;er seche</L>
<L N="256">ffor to schewe for him his speche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mowe his heritage craue;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. his? H. that</NOTE> kynde haue;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he beo I-boren fre,</L>
<L N="260">And &thorn;at he ne eete of &thorn;e tre;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he habbe I-wust wi&thorn;-Inne</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;reo lawen wi&thorn;-outen synne&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke two of Paradys,</L>
<L N="264">And &thorn;ulke of &thorn;e Mount Synays
<PB REF="00000370.tif" N="362"></L>
<L>&THORN;at to Moyses I-&yogh;iuen was,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer &yogh;ute I-holde nas</L>
<L>Of non &thorn;at euer dude sunne.</L>
<L N="268">Who mihte &thorn;enne such Mon munne</L>
<L>O&thorn;er &thorn;enchen or I-knowe</L>
<L>&THORN;at such wonder mihte schowe?</L>
<L>Siggen I may in &thorn;is stude</L>
<L>&THORN;erof, &thorn;at ich er dude,</L>
<L>ffor nou Ichul tellen of &thorn;e stryf</L>
<L>&THORN;at a-Mong &thorn;e foure sustren li&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>Ici reposera mun dit,</L><L>Si vus dirrai un respit</L><L>Ki bien toche ma matyre,</L><L>Por co le voil ci descrifre.</L></Q>H. <Q><L>Sey I may in &thorn;is stede</L><L>As I before dede,</L><L>ffor now is tyme that I hit telle,</L><L>ffor it behovyth to our spelle.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HIt was a kyng of muche miht,</L>
<L N="276">Of good wille and gret in-siht.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is kyng hedde a Sone,</L>
<L>Of such wit and of such wone,</L>
<L>Of such streng&thorn;e and of such chere</L>
<L N="280">As was his ffader in his manere;</L>
<L>Of on wille heo weoren bo,</L>
<L>And of on studefastschipe also,</L>
<L>Of on fulnesse<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. substance</NOTE> heo weoren out-riht</L>
<L N="284">And bo&thorn;e heo weoren of on miht.</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;e Sone &thorn;e ffader al be-gon<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. ordineit</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at bi-lay to his kynedom;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wit was his be-gynnynge,</L>
<L N="288">&THORN;e ffader wolde to ende bringe.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>Quankil voleit comenceir</L><L>Par son fiz le vout cheveir.</L></Q>H. <Q><L>Alle that was of his b.</L><L>The fadur hit wolde to ende b.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Foure douhtren hedde &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>And to vchone sunderlyng</L>
<L>He &yogh;af a dole of his fulnesse,</L>
<L N="292">Of his miht and of his wysnesse,</L>
<L>As wolde bi-fallen to vch on;</L>
<L>And &yogh;it was al &thorn;e folnesse on,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to him-self bi-lay;</L>
<L N="296">Wi&thorn;-oute whom he ne mai</L>
<L>His kindom wi&thorn; pees wysen,</L>
<L>Ne wi&thorn; rihte hit Iustisen.</L>
<L>Good is to nempnen hem for&thorn;i.</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;e furste dou&yogh;ter hette Merci&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kynges eldeste dou&yogh;ter heo is;</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er hette So&thorn;, I-wis;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde soster Is cleped Ri&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="304">Pees hette &thorn;e feor&thorn;e a-pli&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000371.tif" N="363"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;eos foure wi&thorn; worschipe</L>
<L>Mai no kyng lede gret lordschipe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is kyng, as &thorn;ou herdest ar &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="308">Hedde a &thorn;ral &thorn;at dude amis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for his gult strong and gret</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his lord was so I-vet,<NOTE PLACE="marg">= i-fed, odiosus? Fr.: Ke ver son seignur ot fet</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;orw be-siht of riht dom</L>
<L N="312">To strong prison was I-don</L>
<L>And bi-taken to alle his fon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sore him pyneden euerichon;</L>
<L>&THORN;at of no &thorn;ing heo nedden onde<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. envie (forced meaning)</NOTE></L>
<L N="316">Bote him to habben vnder honde;</L>
<L>Heo him duden in prisun of de&thorn;,</L>
<L>And pyneden him sore wi&thorn;-outen me&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>De misericordia.</HEAD>
<L>MErci &thorn;at a-non I-sei&yogh;;</L>
<L N="320">Hit eode hire herte swi&thorn;e neih,</L>
<L>Ne mai hire no &thorn;ing lengore holde,</L>
<L>By-foren &thorn;e kyng comen heo wolde</L>
<L>To schewen for&thorn; hire Resoun</L>
<L N="324">And to dilyuere &thorn;e prisoun.</L>
<L>"Vnderstond," qua&thorn; heo, "ffader myn!</L>
<L>&THORN;ow wost &thorn;at I am dou&yogh;ter &thorn;yn,</L>
<L>And am ful of Boxumnes,</L>
<L N="328">Of Milce and of Swetnes,</L>
<L>And al Ich habbe, ffader, of &thorn;e.</L>
<L>I beo-seche &thorn;at &thorn;ou here me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e [sorful]<NOTE PLACE="marg">so H.; Fr. dolent</NOTE> wrecche prisoun</L>
<L N="332">Mote come to sum Raunsum</L>
<L>&THORN;at a-Midden alle his fon</L>
<L>In strong prison [&thorn;ou] hast I-don.</L>
<L>Heo him made agulte, &thorn;ulke vnwreste,</L>
<L N="336">And bi-swikede him &thorn;orw heor feire beheste,</L>
<L>And seiden him &yogh;if he wolde &thorn;e Appel ete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at whon he hedde al I-ete,<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. And Goddis lawes forleten</NOTE></L>
<L N="339">He scholde habbe al &thorn;e miht of gode</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e treo &thorn;at him was forbode;<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 337-340 added to the Fr.</NOTE></L>
<L>And be-gylen<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sim. begilede; H. lyed</NOTE> him &thorn;erof, and heo<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in H.</NOTE> luytel rou&yogh;ten&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor falshede euer&yogh;ite heo souhten.
<PB REF="00000372.tif" N="364"></L>
<L>And falshede hem I-&yogh;olde be,</L>
<L N="344">And &thorn;e wrecche prisun I-sold to me!</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ow art kyng of Boxumnes,</L>
<L>Of Milce and of Swetnes,</L>
<L N="347">And I &thorn;i douhter alre eldest,</L>
<L>Ouer alle &thorn;e o&thorn;ere beldest;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.: Sur tuz tes oures nomee.</NOTE></L>
<L>Neuere I &thorn;i douhter neore</L>
<L>Bote Milce<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. my swetnesse. Fr. Si de celui pitie neusse.</NOTE> toward him were.</L>
<L>Milce and Merci he schal haue,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw Milce I-chulle &thorn;e prisun craue;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. Ta merci le doit salveir</NOTE></L>
<L N="353">ffor &thorn;in owne swete pite</L>
<L>I<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. I? Fr.:<Q><L>E ta tres doce pitie</L><L>Le doit mettre a sauvete.</L></Q></NOTE> schal him bringe to sauete.</L>
<L>&THORN;i Milce for him I crie euermore,</L>
<L N="356">And<NOTE PLACE="marg">And = until? or r. O &thorn;ou? H. Tylle he have i-funde thyne ore. Fr. Tant ke merci troverai.</NOTE> haue of him Milce and ore!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>De veritate.</HEAD>
<L>ANon whon So&thorn; &thorn;is I-sei&yogh;</L>
<L>Hou Merci, hire soster, hir herte bei&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. se plie</NOTE></L>
<L>And wolde &thorn;is &thorn;ral of prisun bringe</L>
<L N="360">&THORN;at Riht hedde him I-demet wi&thorn;-outen endinge:</L>
<L>Al heo chaunged hire mood,</L>
<L>And bi-foren &thorn;e kyng heo stood.</L>
<L>"ffader, I &thorn;e bi-seche, herkne to me!</L>
<L N="364">I ne may for-bere to telle hit &thorn;e</L>
<L>Hou hit<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in H.; cf. v. 645.</NOTE> me &thorn;inke&thorn; a wonder &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Of Merci, my suster,<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. Of my syster Mercyes</NOTE> wilnyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wolde wi&thorn; hire Milsful sarmon</L>
<L N="368">Diliuere &thorn;e &thorn;ral out of prison</L>
<L>&THORN;at swi&thorn;e agulte, &thorn;er ich hit seih</L>
<L>And tolde hit to Riht &thorn;at stood me neih.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> Fr.; Right is here introduced by the Engl. poet.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffader, ich sigge &thorn;e for-&thorn;i:</L>
<L N="372">&THORN;ou ouhtes nou&yogh;t to heere Merci,</L>
<L>Of no boone &thorn;at heo bi-seche&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Bote Riht<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in Fr.</NOTE> and Soo&thorn; &thorn;er-mide be.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ow louest so&thorn; and hatest lees,</L>
<L N="376">ffor of &thorn;i fulnesse I-comen Ich wes;</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;ow art kyng Rihtwys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 377-8 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Merci herte so reu&thorn;ful is</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &yogh;if heo mai saue wi&thorn; hire mylde speche</L>
<L N="380">Al &thorn;at heo wole fore bi-seche,
<PB REF="00000373.tif" N="365"></L>
<L>Neuer schal be mis-dede abouht,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou, kyng, schalt be douted ri&yogh;t nouht.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art also so trewe a kyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. And thou art all sothefaste k. Fr.:<Q><L>Mes tu es rois si veritables,</L><L>De corage si estables,</L><L>Ke rien ne quers fors verite.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>And stable of &thorn;ou&yogh;t in alle &thorn;yng.</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i me &thorn;inke&thorn; Merci wilne&thorn; wou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And speke&thorn; to-&yogh;eynes Ri&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. me</NOTE> I-nou&yogh;;</L>
<L>ffor Riht con hym in prison bynde</L>
<L N="388">He ou&yogh;te neuere Milce to fynde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 385-8 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>Milce and Merci he ha&thorn; for-loren&mdash;</L>
<L>He was warned &thorn;erof bi-foren;</L>
<L>Whi scholde me helpe &thorn;ulke mon</L>
<L N="392">&THORN;at nedde of him-self pite non?</L>
<L>His dom he mot habbe as So&thorn; con sugge,</L>
<L>And al his mis-dede a-bugge."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>De Iusticia.</HEAD>
<L>RIht I-herde &thorn;is talkyng:</L>
<L N="396">Anon heo stod bi-fore &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>"&THORN;i dou&yogh;tur," heo sei&thorn;, "I am, I wot bi &thorn;on,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou art, kyng, Riht domes-mon;</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;er. (W. takes mitte = mid &thorn;e.)</NOTE> be&thorn; rihte domes mitte,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ine werkes be&thorn; ful of witte.</L>
<L>&THORN;is &thorn;ral of whom my sustren dee&thorn; mene,<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. mevyn, Fr. dont parler oi</NOTE></L>
<L>Ha&thorn; deseruet as at ene;<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. Hath dome deserved as &yogh;e &yogh;evyn. Fr. Iugement ad deserui.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor in tyme, while &thorn;at he freo wes,</L>
<L N="404">He hedde wi&thorn; him bo&thorn;e Merci and pees,</L>
<L>And so&thorn; and riht he hedde bo,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his wille he wente hem fro</L>
<L>And tyed hym to wra&thorn;&thorn;e and wou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="408">To wreccheddam and serwe I-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at, &yogh;if Riht ge&thorn;,</L>
<L>He schal euere<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. for ever</NOTE> &thorn;olyen de&thorn;;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;o &thorn;ow him &thorn;e heste hi&yogh;test,</L>
<L N="412">&THORN;orw So&thorn; &thorn;ou him &thorn;e de&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. de&thorn; him</NOTE> di&yogh;test,<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. adds 2 vv.</NOTE></L>
<L>And I my-self him &yogh;af &thorn;e dom,</L>
<L>As sone as he hedde &thorn;e gult I-don;</L>
<L>ffor So&thorn; bere&thorn; witnesse &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>And elles nedde I no dom I-do.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he in Court bi-foren vs were,</L>
<L>&THORN;e dom &thorn;ou scholdest sone I-here.<NOTE PLACE="marg">v. 409 ff. cf. Fr.:<Q><L>Pur doit suffrir la mort,</L><L>Kar tu anceis li promis.</L><L>Ore soit en prison mis.</L><L>Kar iustice le destine,</L><L>Deske vienge le termine</L><L>Ke tu le voilles relever</L><L>E devant ta cort iuger</L></Q></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000374.tif" N="366"></L>
<L>ffor Riht ne spare&thorn; for to Iugge</L>
<L N="420">What-so-euere So&thorn; wol sugge;</L>
<L>&THORN;orw wisdam heo deme&thorn; alle,</L>
<L>As wole to his<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. heor</NOTE> gult bi-falle."&mdash;</L>
<L>SO&thorn; and Riht, lo &thorn;us heo sugge&thorn;,</L>
<L N="424">And &thorn;is &thorn;ral to de&thorn;e Iugge&thorn;;</L>
<L>Neuer nou&thorn;er ne speke&thorn; him good,</L>
<L>Ne<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. nes?</NOTE> non &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. of hem. Fr.: Puiske pitie nest oie.</NOTE> Merci vnderstood.</L>
<L>Ac as a Mon mis-I-rad<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. As a diswaryed mon mysrad</NOTE></L>
<L>On vche half he is mis-bilad.</L>
<L>Ne helpe&thorn; him no &thorn;ing wher-so he wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his fo fette&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. Ke l'ennemi nel assaut</NOTE> him In vche ende</L>
<L>And I-strupt him al start-naked,</L>
<L N="432">Of mi&yogh;t and streng&thorn;e al bare I-maked;</L>
<L>Him and al &thorn;at of him sprong</L>
<L>He dude a &thorn;euwedam vyl and strong</L>
<L>And made agult[en] swi&thorn;e I-lome,</L>
<L N="436">And Riht com after wi&thorn; hire dome;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen Merci and Pees heo con Iugge,</L>
<L>Euer aftur &thorn;at So&thorn; wol sugge.</L>
<L>Ne Pees mot not mid hem be,</L>
<L N="440">Out of londe heo mot fle,</L>
<L>ffor pees bi-leue&thorn; in no londe</L>
<L>Wher &thorn;er is werre, nuy and onde;</L>
<L>Ne Merci mot not a-Mong hem liue,</L>
<L N="444">Ac bo&thorn;e heo be&thorn; of londe I-driue.</L>
<L>Nis &thorn;er nout in world bi-leued</L>
<L>&THORN;at nis destrued and to-dreued,</L>
<L>And dreynt, for-loren and for-demed,</L>
<L N="448">But Ei&yogh;te soulen, &thorn;at weren I-&yogh;emed</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Schup, and &thorn;at weoren heo:</L>
<L>Noe, and his sones &thorn;reo,</L>
<L>And heore wyues &thorn;at heo hedden bi-fore&mdash;</L>
<L N="452">Of al &thorn;e world nas be-leued more.</L>
<L>Careful herte him ou&yogh;te come</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;enche&thorn; vppon &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;et? H. so</NOTE> dredful dome!</L>
<L>And al hit is &thorn;orw Riht and So&thorn;,</L>
<L N="456">&THORN;at wi&thorn;-outen Pees and Merci do&thorn;.
<PB REF="00000375.tif" N="367"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>De pace.</HEAD>
<L>SO &thorn;at Pees a last vp breek</L>
<L>And &thorn;us to hire ffader speek:</L>
<L>"I am &thorn;i dou&yogh;ter sau&yogh;t and some,</L>
<L N="460">And of &thorn;i fulnesse am I-come.</L>
<L>To-fore &thorn;e my playnt I make:</L>
<L>Mi two sustren me habbe&thorn; forsake,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen me heo do&thorn; heore dom,</L>
<L N="464">Ne Merci a-mong hem nou&yogh;t ne com.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.:<Q><L>Onkes apelee ne feu,</L><L>Pur co ne peut avoir refu</L><L>Nus home ke soit en vie:</L><L>Pur co sui diloec fuie.</L></Q>(The translator used a corrupted text.)</NOTE>ffor no &thorn;ing &thorn;at I<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. eny mon</NOTE> mi&yogh;te do</L>
<L>Ne moste Merci hem come to,</L>
<L>Ne for none kunnes fey</L>
<L>Ne moste ich hem come ney&yogh;,</L>
<L N="469">Ak &thorn;at dom is al heore owen.</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i Ich am of londe I-flowen,</L>
<L>And wole wi&thorn; &thorn;e lede my lyf,</L>
<L N="472">Euer o<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. on; cf. v. 152.</NOTE> &thorn;at Ilke stryf</L>
<L>&THORN;at a-mong my sustren Is a-wake,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw sauhtnesse mowe sum ende take.</L>
<L>Ac what is hit euer &thorn;e bet</L>
<L N="476">&THORN;at Riht and So&thorn; ben I-set,</L>
<L>Bote heo wite wel pees<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;eos</NOTE>?</L>
<L>Rihtes Mester hit is and wes</L>
<L>In vche dom pees to maken.</L>
<L N="480">Schal I &thorn;enne beo forsaken</L>
<L>Whon eueriche good for me<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. fourme</NOTE> is wrouht</L>
<L>And to habben me bi-&thorn;ouht<NOTE PLACE="marg">orig. bitouht. H. be in thowght, Fr. retreit</NOTE>?</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sim. Ac, H. But, Fr. Mes</NOTE> he me<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. ne</NOTE> louede neuere to fere</L>
<L N="484">&THORN;at Merci, my suster, nul not here.</L>
<L>Off vs foure, ffader, I-chul telle &thorn;e</L>
<L>Hou me &thorn;inke&thorn; hit ou&yogh;te to be.</L>
<L>Whon ffoure<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;e ff.</NOTE> be&thorn; to-gedere I-sent</L>
<L N="488">To don an euene Iuggement,</L>
<L>And schul &thorn;orw skil alle and some</L>
<L>&YOGH;iuen and demen euene dome,</L>
<L>&THORN;er ne ou&yogh;te no dom for&thorn; gon</L>
<L N="492">Er &thorn;en &thorn;e foure ben aton;</L>
<L>At on heo moten at-stonden alle</L>
<L>And loken se&thorn;&thorn;en hou dom wol falle.
<PB REF="00000376.tif" N="368"></L>
<L>Be vs ffoure &thorn;is I telle:</L>
<L N="496">We beo&thorn; not alle of on spelle;</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e Ich and Merci</L>
<L>We be-clepe&thorn; &thorn;e dom for&thorn;i;</L>
<L>Hit is al as Ri&yogh;t and So&thorn; wol deme,</L>
<L N="500">Merci ne me nis hit not qweme.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen vs &thorn;er is bale to breme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 500-1 om. in Sim. Fr.:<Q><L>Sanz nus est trop flaellez,</L><L>Pur co doit troveir pitiez.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i, ffader, &thorn;ow nime &yogh;eme!</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">In the Fr. vv. 503-512 precede v. 485, and vv. 509-10 precede v. 503.</NOTE>Of vche goodschipe Pees is ende,</L>
<L>Ne fayle&thorn; no weole &thorn;er heo wol lende,</L>
<L N="505">Ne wisdam nis not wor&thorn; an hawe</L>
<L>&THORN;er Pees fayle&thorn; to felawe;</L>
<L>And hose Pees loue&thorn;, wi&thorn;-outen gabbe,</L>
<L N="508">Pees wi&thorn;-outen ende he schal habbe.</L>
<L>Mi word ou&yogh;te ben of good reles,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. Mon dit doit porter grant fes.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou art kyng and prince of pes.</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i &thorn;ou ou&yogh;test to here me,</L>
<L N="512">And Merci my suster, &thorn;at clepe&thorn; to &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e &thorn;ral, &thorn;e prisoun,</L>
<L>Mote come to sum Raunsoun.</L>
<L>Vre wille, ffader, &thorn;ou do sone</L>
<L N="516">And here vre rihte bone!</L>
<L>ffor Merci euere clepe&thorn; to &thorn;e</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e prison dilyuered be,</L>
<L>And I-chul fleon and neuere come</L>
<L N="520">Bote my sustren ben sau&yogh;t and some."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E kynges sone al &thorn;is con heren</L>
<L>Hou his sustren hem to-beeren,</L>
<L>And sei&yogh; &thorn;is strif so strong awaken,</L>
<L N="524">And Pees and Merci al forsaken;</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn;-outen help of his wisdome</L>
<L>Ne mihten heo neuere to-gedere come.</L>
<L>"Leoue ffader," qua&thorn; he, "Ich am &thorn;i sone,</L>
<L N="528">Of &thorn;i wit and of &thorn;i wone,</L>
<L>And &thorn;i wisdam [me] clepe&thorn; me;</L>
<L>And so muche &thorn;ou louedest<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. louest</NOTE> me</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e world for<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;or&yogh;, Fr. par moi.</NOTE> me &thorn;ou wrou&yogh;test,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ou me in werke bou&yogh;test;<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. in thy werk browghtest. Fr. Dont tes fez tuz me ovres sunt. r. brou&yogh;test, from brou|ken = use (forced form)?</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor we beo&thorn; on in one fulnesse,</L>
<L N="534">In miht, in streng&thorn;e, and in hei&yogh;nesse;
<PB REF="00000377.tif" N="369"></L>
<L>I-chulle al don &thorn;at &thorn;i wille is,</L>
<L N="536">ffor &thorn;ou art kyng Rihtwis.</L>
<L>So muche, ffader, ich nyme &yogh;eme</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is strif &thorn;at is so breme,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for &thorn;e tale &thorn;at Merci tolde &thorn;e</L>
<L N="540">fful sore &thorn;e prisun rewe&thorn; me;</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i he rewe&thorn; me wel &thorn;e more</L>
<L>ffor Merci euere clepe&thorn; &thorn;in ore.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art, ffader, so milsful kyng:</L>
<L>Hire we schul heren of alle &thorn;ing.<NOTE PLACE="marg">541-4 cf. Fr.:<Q><L>Misericorde merci crie:</L><L>Premerement serad oie.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Al i-chul<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &yogh;e schulen, H. Alle here wyll I chull done. Fr. Trestut son uoler ferai.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sauhten So&thorn; and hire ful sone.</L>
<L>Nimen I-chulle &thorn;e &thorn;ralles weden,</L>
<L N="548">As So&thorn; &amp; Riht hit wolden and beoden,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. En verite e en dreiture</NOTE></L>
<L>And al one I-chul holde &thorn;e doom</L>
<L>As Iustise ouhte to don,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.:<Q><L>Sustendrai le iugement</L><L>E kank 'a iustice apent,</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>And maken I-chule Pees to londe come,<NOTE PLACE="marg">E peis en terre frai crier</NOTE></L>
<L N="552">And Pees &amp; Riht cussen &amp; be sau&yogh;t &amp; some,</L>
<L>And druyuen<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. dryuen</NOTE> out Werre, Nuy and Onde,</L>
<L>And sauen al &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. thi, Fr. ta</NOTE> folk in londe."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HOse &thorn;is forbysene con,</L>
<L N="556">He may openliche i-seo bi &thorn;on</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;is ilke tokenynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>K'iceste signefiance</L><L>Est en dieu une puissance.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Is Godes in-siht, Almihti kynge.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-[out]<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. But?</NOTE> God &thorn;e ffader nis maked nouht,</L>
<L N="560">&THORN;orw God &thorn;e Sone is al &thorn;ing wrouht,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.:<Q><L>De deu le pere est tute riens,</L><L>Par deu le fiz sunt fet tuz biens,</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>And alle &thorn;ing is folfuld out-riht</L>
<L>&THORN;orw God &thorn;e holigostes miht:</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;reo be&thorn; on, &thorn;ouh hit be so,</L>
<L N="564">In one fulnesse and in no mo.</L>
<L>He &yogh;iue<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &yogh;iue&thorn;, H. &yogh;eue</NOTE> his Blessynge wi&thorn; Mou&thorn; &amp; honde</L>
<L>To alle &thorn;at &thorn;is writ vnderstonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;E habbe&thorn; I-herd as ich ow tolde,</L>
<L N="568">ffor whi God &thorn;e world maken wolde,</L>
<L>And hou Adam forles &thorn;orw synne</L>
<L>World and Heuene, and al Mon-kynne:</L>
<L>&THORN;at for mi&yogh;t ne streng&thorn;e ne for no &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="572">No<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in H.</NOTE> mon nedde of him-self a Couryng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. recoverance</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne Angel mi&yogh;te Mon helpe on none wyse,</L>
<L>Ne Mon mi&yogh;te him-self fro de&thorn;e aryse.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.:<Q><L>Ne angle nel pout rechater</L><L>Ne home de mort relever.</L></Q></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000378.tif" N="370"></L>
<L>&THORN;enne moste nede beo &thorn;orw vche doom</L>
<L N="576">&THORN;at God of heuene Mon bi-com,</L>
<L>Mon &thorn;e de&thorn; &thorn;olen &thorn;orw serwen ryue,</L>
<L>And God vp rysen from de&thorn; to lyue&mdash;</L>
<L>Elles were alle for-lore to nouht</L>
<L>&THORN;at God hedde in &thorn;e world I-brouht.<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. i-wrowght Fr. <Q><L>Kar autrement peri feust</L><L>Tut quank'en siecle eust.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Herkene&thorn; [whuch]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. vchone</NOTE> Loue and Boxumnesse,</L>
<L N="582">Whuch Milce and eke Swetnesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God from heuene alihte[n] chees<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. and chees; H. to aly&yogh;t ches; cf. v. 1404.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor O [seli shep]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Mon, H. sele shepe, Fr. s'owaille.</NOTE> &thorn;at he lees!</L>
<L>[Ninti nine he leuede]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <Q><L>&thorn;ritti &yogh;eer he liuede,</L><L>H. His fadur blisse he leuede,</L></Q>Fr. <Q><L>Nonante noef i laissa;</L></Q> <I>see</I> Weymouth.</NOTE> and eode</L>
<L>To sechen on in vncou&thorn; &thorn;eode.</L>
<L N="587">&THORN;enne nis &thorn;er such herde-mon non,</L>
<L>Ne non<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in II.</NOTE> so milsful<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. mi&yogh;tful, Fr. merciable</NOTE> lord as he is on!</L>
<L>Whose wolde his herte on such lord holde</L>
<L>&THORN;at so muche loue him kui&thorn;e wolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lyk him-self wolde him make</L>
<L N="592">And si&thorn;en de&thorn; &thorn;olyen for his sake:</L>
<L>Er him ou&yogh;te &thorn;e herte to springe</L>
<L>&THORN;en he scholde him wra&thorn;&thorn;e for eny &thorn;inge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HErkene&thorn; now for&thorn;ure atte frome</L>
<L N="596">How vr Saueor wolde come.</L>
<L>To Abraham &thorn;e ti&thorn;inges comen;</L>
<L>&THORN;e prophetes hit vnder-nomen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is Moyses and Ionas,</L>
<L N="600">Abacuk and Helyas,</L>
<L>Daniel and Ieremye,</L>
<L>Dauid and Ysaye,</L>
<L>And Eliseu<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Elisen</NOTE> and Samuel</L>
<L N="604">Sigge&thorn; Godes comynge wel.</L>
<L>Wonder hit were hem alle to telle;</L>
<L>Ac herkene&thorn; hou Ysaye con spelle:</L>
<L><I>Puer natus est nobis, filius datus est nobis</I></L>
<L>"A child &thorn;er is I-boren to vs,</L>
<L N="608">And a sone I-&yogh;euen vs,</L>
<L>&THORN;at schal vp holden his kynedome;</L>
<L>And al &thorn;us schal ben his nome:</L>
<L>Wondurful, God, and of miht,</L>
<L N="612">And redeful, and fader ariht</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;e world &thorn;at her-aftur schal ben,
<PB REF="00000379.tif" N="371"></L>
<L>Prince of Pees me schal him sen"&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;eos be&thorn; &thorn;e nomen, as &yogh;e mowe leeuen,</L>
<L N="616">&THORN;at &thorn;e prophetes him<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. to him</NOTE> &yogh;eeuen.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;e wolen heren, tellen I-chulle</L>
<L>How &thorn;at child is wonderfolle.</L>
<L>Such wonder nas neuer I-herd in sawe,</L>
<L N="620">Ne neuere schal bi none dawe</L>
<L>ffor no tyme<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;inge? Fr. Pur riens ke peust avenir</NOTE> &thorn;at euer schal come,</L>
<L>As, God of heuene Mon bi-come.</L>
<L>ffor hose now I-se&yogh;e heere<NOTE PLACE="marg">Exemplum</NOTE></L>
<L N="624">A child &thorn;at riht I-limed nere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;reo ffeet and &thorn;reo honden beere;</L>
<L>And a-no&thorn;er &thorn;at o&thorn;erweis weere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hedde ffoot or Hond forlore;</L>
<L N="628">And heo weore bo&thorn;e so I-bore:</L>
<L>Weoren heo wonderfol, &thorn;eose two?</L>
<L>Nay, forso&thorn;e, neoren heo, no,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e on hedde kuynde ouer me&thorn;,</L>
<L N="632">And &thorn;at o&thorn;er to luyte, and so hit ge&thorn;,</L>
<L>Ac hit is as hit mot nede ben,</L>
<L>Of vn-mete kuynde a forschipte streon.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. mustre, monster</NOTE></L>
<L>Ak &thorn;at mihte Muche wonder ben<NOTE PLACE="marg">Exemplum</NOTE></L>
<L N="636">&YOGH;if me mi&yogh;te eny [mon]<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. seche a mon, Fr. un home</NOTE> I-seon</L>
<L>&THORN;at Monnes kuynde hedde al ariht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him neore to luite ne to muche wiht,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he were al so&thorn;fast mon</L>
<L N="640">&THORN;at no forschippyng weore him on,</L>
<L>And eke were good hors wi&thorn;-alle!</L>
<L>Such &thorn;ing may neuer bi-falle;</L>
<L>ffor<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. mes</NOTE> hose se&yogh;e a such gederyng,</L>
<L N="644">He mihte hit clepe a wonder &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>And &yogh;it is more wonder a &thorn;ousend-folde</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e child &thorn;at Ysay&yogh;e of tolde</L>
<L>And clepede him wonderful, for &thorn;on</L>
<L N="648">&THORN;at he is so&thorn; God and so&thorn; Mon.</L>
<L>ffor of Monhede ne wonte&thorn; him nouht;</L>
<L>And &thorn;orw him is al &thorn;ing I-wrouht;</L>
<L>And wi&thorn;-outen him is synne<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. withoute synne he is Fr.:<Q><L>D'umanite ne li faut rien,</L><L>E kil est plein deu, co veum bien:</L><L>Par lui tute rien est fet,</L><L>E sanz li nule rien n'est,</L><L>Kar en defaute n'est pas fet</L><L>Com auant vous ai retret.</L></Q></NOTE> euere,</L>
<L>ffor wone<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. wone therof</NOTE> dude he neuere,</L>
<L>Ne no schaft &thorn;orw him mi&yogh;te lees,
<PB REF="00000380.tif" N="372"></L>
<L>As bi-foren I-rad wes.<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. v. 228.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;ur God nis &thorn;en he &thorn;at heuene dihte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. drihte? cf. v. 915.</NOTE></L>
<L N="656">&THORN;at from heuene dude<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. to erthe</NOTE> alihte</L>
<L>And vnder vre wede vre kynde nom</L>
<L>And al so&thorn;fast Mon bi-com.</L>
<L>And whon he wolde alles bi-come Mon,</L>
<L N="660">He moste be boren of a wommon,</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke schaft to vnderfonge wi&thorn;-alle</L>
<L>&THORN;at ou&yogh;te to Monnes kynde bi-falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GOd nolde<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. my&yogh;ht, Fr. pout</NOTE> alihte in none Manere</L>
<L N="664">But in feir stude and in clere.</L>
<L>In feir stude and clene siker hit wes</L>
<L>&THORN;er god al-mihti his In ches:</L>
<L>In a Castel wel comeliche,</L>
<L N="668">Muche and ffeir<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. fer <I>or</I> siker? Fr. Bien fermez</NOTE> and loueliche;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e Castel of alle flour,</L>
<L>Of Solas and of Socour.<NOTE PLACE="marg">The same allegory of Mary as a Castle is treated in the Festial, 2nd sermon on Assumption-day.</NOTE></L>
<L N="671">In &thorn;e Merc<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Mere; merc = border. Fr. En la marche est assis.</NOTE> he stont bi-twene two,</L>
<L>Ne ha&thorn; he ferlak for no fo:</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e tour<NOTE PLACE="marg">= Castel</NOTE> is so wel wi&thorn;-outen,</L>
<L>So depe I-diched al-abouten,</L>
<L>&THORN;at none kunnes asaylyng</L>
<L N="676">Ne may him deruen for no &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>He stont on hei&yogh; Roche and sound,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. And</NOTE> is I-planed in to &thorn;e ground,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. E bien polie de ci quaval</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er ne mai wone non vuel &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Ne derue no gynnes castyng.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.:<Q><L>Ne engin ni peut geter</L><L>Ki de rien le peust grever.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L N="681">And &thorn;au&yogh; he be so loueliche,</L>
<L>He is so dredful and hateliche</L>
<L>To alle &thorn;ulke &thorn;at ben his fon,</L>
<L N="684">&THORN;at heo flen him euerichon.<NOTE PLACE="marg">681-4 om. in Fr.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffo[u]r smale toures &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;at</NOTE> be&thorn; abouten</L>
<L>To witen &thorn;e hei&yogh;e tour wi&thorn;-outen.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e beo&thorn; &thorn;re Bayles wi&thorn;-alle,</L>
<L N="688">So<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in H. &amp; Fr.</NOTE> feir I-diht wi&thorn; strong walle,</L>
<L>As heo beo&thorn; here-after I-write&mdash;</L>
<L>Ne may no mon &thorn;e feirschipe I-wite,</L>
<L>Ne no tonge ne may hit telle,</L>
<L N="692">Ne &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;enche, ne Mou&thorn; spelle.</L>
<L>On trusti Roche heo stonde&thorn; faste,
<PB REF="00000381.tif" N="373"></L>
<L>And wi&thorn; depe diches be&thorn; bi-caste;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e carnels so<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in H.</NOTE> stonde&thorn; vp-riht<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. E aurne de gran kerneaus</NOTE></L>
<L N="696">Wel I-planed and feir i-diht.</L>
<L>Seue Berbicans &thorn;er beo&thorn; I-wrouht,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret ginne al bi-&thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>And euerichon ha&thorn; &yogh;at and tour:</L>
<L N="700">&THORN;er neuer ne fayle&thorn; socour;</L>
<L>Neuer schal fo<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. Ne ja n'averat ennui Ki l&agrave; veut quere refui. (the translator read ennemi).</NOTE> him stonde wi&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ider wol flen to sechen gri&thorn;.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Castel is siker and feir abouten,</L>
<L N="704">And is al depeynted wi&thorn;-outen</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;reo heowes &thorn;at wel be&thorn; sene.</L>
<L>So is &thorn;e foundement al grene</L>
<L N="707">&THORN;at to &thorn;e Roche faste li&thorn;;</L>
<L>Wel is &thorn;at &thorn;er mur&thorn;e I-sih&thorn;!<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. De grant docour ni faut point.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e greneschipe laste&thorn; euere</L>
<L>And his heuh ne leose&thorn; neuere.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en a-bouten<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. aboue? om. in H.</NOTE> &thorn;at o&thorn;er heu&yogh;</L>
<L N="712">So is Inde and eke Bleu,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e Middel heu&yogh; we clepe&thorn; ariht,</L>
<L>And schyne&thorn; so feire and so bri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde heu&yogh; an-ouemast,</L>
<L>Ouer-wri&yogh;e&thorn; al and so is I-cast<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>La tierce colur par enson</L><L>Les karneaus covre environ;</L><L>Plus est vermeille que nest rose,</L><L>E piert une ardante chose;</L><L>Tant reflambeie environ</L><L>Ke tut covre le dongon.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn;-Innen and wi&thorn;-outen</L>
<L>&THORN;e castel lihte&thorn; al-abouten,</L>
<L>And is Raddore &thorn;en euere eny Rose schal,</L>
<L N="720">&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. Hit</NOTE> &thorn;unche&thorn; as hit barnde al.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-Inne, &thorn;e Castel is whit schinynge</L>
<L>So &thorn;e snow&yogh; &thorn;at is sneuwynge,</L>
<L N="723">And caste&thorn; &thorn;at li&yogh;t so wyde</L>
<L>After long<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. Andelong? H. Enlong on; Fr. De lung</NOTE> &thorn;e tour and be-syde;</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. Ther</NOTE> neuer come&thorn; &thorn;er wo ne wou&yogh;,</L>
<L>Ac swetnesse &thorn;er is euere I-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="727">A-Midde &thorn;e hei&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>En mi la tur plus hauteine</L><L>Est surdant une fonteigne</L></Q></NOTE> Tour Is springynge</L>
<L>A welle &thorn;at euere is eornynge,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; foure stremes, &thorn;at strike&thorn; wel</L>
<L>And erne&thorn; vppon &thorn;e grauel</L>
<L>And fulle&thorn; &thorn;e diches a-boute &thorn;e wal.</L>
<L N="732">Muche Blisse &thorn;er is ouer-al!</L>
<L>Ne dar he seche non o&thorn;er leche
<PB REF="00000382.tif" N="374"></L>
<L>&THORN;at mai riht of &thorn;is water cleche!</L>
<L>In &thorn;ulke derwor&thorn;e feire tour</L>
<L N="736">&THORN;er stont a Trone wi&thorn; muche honour,</L>
<L>Of whit Iuori, and feirore of liht</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;e someres-day whon hee<NOTE PLACE="marg">orig. heo</NOTE> is briht;</L>
<L N="739">Wi&thorn; Cumpas I-&thorn;rowen and wi&thorn; gin al I-do<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.: Par engin est compassez.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Seuene steppes &thorn;er beo&thorn; &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>&THORN;at oo<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. so, H. oo</NOTE> feire wi&thorn; Ordre I-ti&yogh;ed<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. i-joyned</NOTE> beo&thorn;.</L>
<L>ffeiror &thorn;ing In world no mon seo&thorn;:</L>
<L>ffor heuene-bouwe Is a-bouten I-bent,</L>
<L N="744">Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e hewes &thorn;at him be&thorn; I-sent.</L>
<L>Neuere so feir<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. so f. a</NOTE> Chay&yogh;ere</L>
<L>Nedde kyng ne Emperere.</L>
<L>Muche more feirschupe I-nou&yogh; &thorn;er wes</L>
<L N="748">&THORN;er God Almi&yogh;ten his In ches.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne nis &thorn;er such Castel non,</L>
<L>Ne neuer nas, but &thorn;ulke on,</L>
<L>Ne neuer-eft after be ne schal;</L>
<L N="752">ffor God of heuene hit dihte al</L>
<L>And wrou&yogh;te hit him-self, and al dude</L>
<L>To alihten in &thorn;ulke feyre stude</L>
<L>ffrom his kin[e]dam aboue<NOTE PLACE="marg">753 &amp; 755 added to the Fr.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L N="756">He cudde &thorn;e stude muche loue!</L>
<L>&THORN;is is &thorn;e Castel of loue and lisse,</L>
<L>Of Solace, of Socour, of Ioye and blisse,</L>
<L>Of Hope, Of Hele, Of Sikernesse,</L>
<L N="760">And ful of alle Swetnesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Is is &thorn;e Mayden[es bodi]<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. maydons body, Fr. Cest le cors de la pucele</NOTE> so freo;</L>
<L>&THORN;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;at</NOTE> neuer nas non bote heo</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; so fele &thorn;ewes I-warned<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. garnie</NOTE> wes<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. nes</NOTE></L>
<L N="764">So &thorn;at swete Mayden Marie wes.</L>
<L>Heo stont in &thorn;e Merc<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Mere</NOTE> bi-twene two:</L>
<L>Heo schilde<NOTE PLACE="marg">= schilt, 3 pr. ind.; Fr. Si nus est escu e targe Contre tuz nos enemis</NOTE> vs alle from vre fo</L>
<L>&THORN;at vs a-wayte&thorn; day and niht,</L>
<L N="768">Heo vs helpe&thorn; wi&thorn; al hire miht.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Roche &thorn;at is so trewe and trusti,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. si bien polie</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e Maydenes herte, for&thorn;i</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer synne &thorn;er-wi&thorn;-Inne com,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. Konques en mal ne mollist</NOTE></L>
<L N="772">Ac heo to seruen God al hire nom</L>
<L>And wuste hire<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. hire</NOTE> wi&thorn; muche boxumnesse,
<PB REF="00000383.tif" N="375"></L>
<L>Hire Maidenhod wi&thorn; swetnesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffoundement &thorn;at faste to &thorn;e Roche li&yogh;&thorn;,</L>
<L N="776">And &thorn;e feire greneschipe &thorn;er-wi&thorn;,</L>
<L>[Is] &thorn;e Maydenes bi-leeue so riht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; al hire bodi I-liht;</L>
<L>ffor hire bi-leeue &thorn;at is so trewe,</L>
<L N="780">&THORN;at euere is grene and euere newe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>La verdour que tant est bele</L><L>Sa foi tut tens renovele.</L></Q>H. <Q><L>For here beleve is so true</L><L>That ever hit is grene and newe.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>ffor hire<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in H. and Fr.</NOTE> bi-leeue is apertement</L>
<L>Of alle vertues foundement.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Middel heu&yogh; Is to wite<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>E puis est la meine colour,</L><L>De si tres bele doucour.</L><L>C'est la signefiance</L><L>Ke od tendrur<NOTE PLACE="marg">The translator read tendron. H. wes here lyvyng.</NOTE> en esperance</L><L>Servi tut tens son seignor</L><L>En humilite e en doucor</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e swetnesse and &thorn;e feirschipe;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e bi-tokenyng:</L>
<L>In goode hope, as so &yogh;ong &thorn;ing,<NOTE PLACE="marg">The translator read tendron. H. wes here lyvyng.</NOTE></L>
<L>[Heo] was oo<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. so</NOTE> bisy In swetnesse</L>
<L N="788">To seruen God In Boxumnesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde heu&yogh; and &thorn;e on-ouemast,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; ouer-al his liht I-cast</L>
<L>And as &thorn;au&yogh; hit barnde al hit is&mdash;</L>
<L N="792">Nis non of so muche pris:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e clere loue and briht</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo is al wi&thorn; I-liht,</L>
<L>And I-tent wi&thorn; &thorn;e fuir of loue,</L>
<L N="796">To serue god &thorn;at is hire aboue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E ffoure smale toures abouten</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi[te]&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. wi&thorn;, cf. v. 686.</NOTE> &thorn;e hei&yogh;e Tour wi&thorn;-outen,</L>
<L>ffoure hed-&thorn;ewes &thorn;at aboute hire [me] i-seo&thorn;,</L>
<L N="800">ffoure vertues cardinals &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;er, H. thei</NOTE> beo&thorn;:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is Streng&thorn;e and Sleihschupe,</L>
<L>Rihtfulnesse and Warschupe;<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. worschupe, H. warship, Fr. temperance</NOTE></L>
<L>Euerichon wi&thorn; a &yogh;at wi&thorn; ginne,</L>
<L N="804">&THORN;at may non vuel come &thorn;er-Inne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And whuche beo&thorn; [&thorn;e] &thorn;reo bayles &yogh;et</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; &thorn;e carnels be&thorn; so wel I-set,</L>
<L>And I-cast wi&thorn; cumpas and walled a-bouten,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>A beau compas environ</L><L>Si defendent le dongon</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wite&thorn; &thorn;e hei&yogh;e tour wi&thorn;-outen?</L>
<L>[B]ote &thorn;e Inemaste<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. Cele a la plus haut estage</NOTE> Bayle, I wot,</L>
<L>Bi-tokne&thorn; hire holy Maidenhod,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer for no-&thorn;ing I-worsed nas&mdash;</L>
<L N="812">So ful of Godes grace heo was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E Middel Bayle, &thorn;at wite &yogh;e,
<PB REF="00000384.tif" N="376"></L>
<L>Bi-tokne&thorn; hire holy chastite.</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;e ou[t]emaste<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. foreine</NOTE> Bayle</L>
<L N="816">Bi-tokne&thorn; hire holy sposayle.</L>
<L>Riht me clepe&thorn; hem Bayles, for-&thorn;i</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo habbe&thorn; &thorn;is ladi in here Bayli,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hire-self one, Makeles,<NOTE PLACE="marg">sanz per</NOTE></L>
<L N="820">Is Mayden chast and weddet wes.</L>
<L>&THORN;orw on of &thorn;eos bayles he mot teon</L>
<L>&THORN;at wol on ende I-borwed beon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E Seue [Berbicans]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Carnels</NOTE> abouten,</L>
<L N="824">&THORN;at wi&thorn; gret gin beon I-wrou&yogh;t wi&thorn;-outen</L>
<L>And wite&thorn; &thorn;is Castel so wel</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">= against, Fr. de</NOTE> Arwe and wi&thorn; Qwarel:</L>
<L>&THORN;at be&thorn; &thorn;e seuen vertues wi&thorn; winne</L>
<L N="828">To ouercome &thorn;e seuen dedly sinne.</L>
<L>&THORN;at is: pruide, &thorn;e biginnynge</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Roote of al vuel &thorn;inge,</L>
<L>Al maat and ouer-comen wes</L>
<L N="832">&THORN;orw Boxumnes &thorn;at heo ches;</L>
<L>And hire trewe loue ouer-com Envye;</L>
<L>And hire Abstinence Glotonye;</L>
<L>And Lecherye heo made fle</L>
<L N="836">&THORN;o[r]u&yogh; hire holy chastite;</L>
<L>And was<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. was was, H. all-so she</NOTE> distruyed Couetyse</L>
<L>&THORN;orw hire Largesse in vche wyse;</L>
<L>And euer<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. eueri, H. evermore</NOTE> wra&thorn;&thorn;e heo ouer-com</L>
<L N="840">&THORN;orw Mekenesse<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. &amp; H. pacience</NOTE> &thorn;at heo nom;</L>
<L>And hire gostliche gladynge</L>
<L>Destruyed Sleu&thorn;e &thorn;orw alle &thorn;inge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E welle springe&thorn; of alle<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. alle of</NOTE> grace</L>
<L N="844">&THORN;at fulle&thorn; &thorn;e diches in vche a place.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>La fontaigne isurt de grace,</L><L>Ki tut le chastel embrace;</L><L>Deu sa grace i ad done</L><L>E par mesure devise.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Godes grace to-dele&thorn; &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. so deled is</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;orw Meth wi&thorn;-al as his wille is.</L>
<L>Ac he louede so &thorn;is mayden apli&yogh;t</L>
<L N="848">&THORN;e folle of grace he hire &yogh;af out-riht;</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh whom &thorn;e grace &thorn;at ouer-fleot</L>
<L>Socoure&thorn; al &thorn;e world &yogh;ut.</L>
<L N="851">ffor-&thorn;i me may hire riht clepe and calle</L>
<L>O Blessed ladi<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. One i-blessed; ladi om. Fr. Sur tutes autres benuree.</NOTE> ouer o&thorn;ere alle.</L>
<L>And what mowe &thorn;e diches be
<PB REF="00000385.tif" N="377"></L>
<L N="854">But hire &thorn;olemode<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. volentrive</NOTE> pouerte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nones kunnes<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. ginnes? cf. vv. 680, 675. Fr.:<Q><L>Dont nul engin ne &THORN;eut geter</L><L>Ke le chasteu peust rien grever.</L></Q></NOTE> assaylyng</L>
<L>Ne may derue &thorn;e tour for no &thorn;ing&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;orw whom<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. whon?</NOTE> &thorn;e fend is ouer-comen,</L>
<L>And his miht al by-nomen.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. has 4 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FOr &thorn;is is &thorn;e ladi so gent &amp; fre</L>
<L N="860">&THORN;at God seide of to &thorn;e Neddre on &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er scholde comen a wommon bly&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. blyve</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at scholde al his pouste<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. chief, H. hed</NOTE> to-dryue.</L>
<L>I-blessed be &thorn;is Buyrde of prys,</L>
<L N="864">&THORN;at ouer al o&thorn;ure I-blessed is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at so feir was and good so sone</L>
<L>&THORN;at of hir bodi<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. alme, H. soule</NOTE> God made his trone</L>
<L>To his owne gistenynge,</L>
<L N="868">And nom flesch &amp; blod of hire, to bringe</L>
<L>His folk out of prisoun;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was vre Garysoun.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>Iceste dame est bele assez</L><L>Kant tant par ad de bontez,</L><L>Plus ke nule creature;</L><L>Meis quant li solaus de droiture,</L><L>Deuz, son seint cors enumbrat,</L><L>Mil itant embeli lad.</L></Q></NOTE> &THORN;is ladi is feir &amp; good &amp; fre</L>
<L>Whon heo ha&thorn; so muche bounte,</L>
<L>More &thorn;en eny schaft &thorn;at wes;</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. And tho</NOTE> &thorn;e Rihtwys sone<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. the sonne of ry&yogh;htwesnes,</NOTE> hire ches</L>
<L>And schadewede on hire in wolde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">= in virtue; <I>or</I> r. holde = flesh? H. And on heere when he shadowe wolde</NOTE></L>
<L N="876">And<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. He</NOTE> feirede hir more a &thorn;ousend-folde.</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;oru&yogh;</NOTE> &thorn;e faste &yogh;at he con in teo,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in H.</NOTE> at &thorn;e out-&yogh;ong he lette [hit] faste beo.</L>
<L>How so &thorn;at was beo we stille,</L>
<L N="880">ffor of alle &thorn;ing God may don his wille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>A</B>, derwor&thorn;e qween so gent &amp; fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at helpest<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. helpe&thorn;</NOTE> alle &thorn;at fleo&thorn; to &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Mi soule is comen to &thorn;e for nede;</L>
<L N="884">&THORN;at at &thorn;i &yogh;ate bat &amp; loude do&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. con</NOTE> grede,</L>
<L>Bat &amp; grede&thorn; and loude gon<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. con</NOTE> crye:</L>
<L>"Helpe me, Swete Mayden Marie!</L>
<L>Vndo, Ladi! I &thorn;e bi-seche.</L>
<L N="888">&THORN;ou lete me a luitel cleche</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ulke [grace] &thorn;at alle [con] frouere</L>
<L>&THORN;at gostliche beo&thorn; in herte pouere.</L>
<L>Lo hou I am bi-set heer-oute</L>
<L N="892">Wi&thorn; my &thorn;reo fon al-a-boute:</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend, &thorn;at wi&thorn; me fihte&thorn; euere,
<PB REF="00000386.tif" N="378"></L>
<L>&THORN;e world, my flesch&mdash;heo ne stunte&thorn; neuere,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen eny Me&thorn; on me heo fo&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. voth</NOTE></L>
<L N="896">Swi&thorn;e gret harm heo me do&thorn;.</L>
<L>Gret parlement heo habbe&thorn; I-nome.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend furst is<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. is formest</NOTE> for&thorn; I-come,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;reo hostes he de&thorn; me gret wo:</L>
<L N="900">Wi&thorn; pruide, &amp; wra&thorn;&thorn;e, &amp; sleu&thorn;e also.</L>
<L>&THORN;e world me ha&thorn; wi&thorn; two hostes bi-stonde:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is wi&thorn; couetyse and Onde.</L>
<L>And my fflesch me fonde&thorn; to spille</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Glotenye and wi&thorn; vuel<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. foule, Fr. fou delit</NOTE> wille.</L>
<L>Gret wra&thorn;&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. fy&yogh;ht; Fr. Grant damage (<I>al.</I> Bataile) m'ont esmu</NOTE> heo habbe&thorn; to me I-nome;</L>
<L>I am as campion ouer-come<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. Champium sui ja recru.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou me helpe, Mayde Marie,</L>
<L>Ichabbe I-lore &thorn;e Maystrie . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 vv. om., cf. H.:<Q><L>Thow that art to alle febulle leche,</L><L>Thow let me of thy dyches cleche,</L></Q>Fr. <Q><L>Tu que fiebles redrescez,</L><L>Fai me poser au fossez,</L><L>Ou li chastel est estable</L><L>E charite rest conestable.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;e Castel is faste &amp; stable,</L>
<L>And Charite is Constable."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;is castel ichabbe a luitel told,</L>
<L N="912">Ac more me mi&yogh;te a &thorn;ousend-fold:</L>
<L>ffor alle &thorn;e godschupus &thorn;at in &thorn;e world is</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is Castel I-comen is.</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;is laddre God, heuene d[r]ihte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. God Allmy&yogh;ht</NOTE></L>
<L N="916">ffrom heuene in to eor&thorn;e alihte</L>
<L>And nom of hire his Monhede,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw whom<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. whom?</NOTE> he wrey<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. covri</NOTE> his Godhede.</L>
<L>&THORN;is is &thorn;e &yogh;ard &thorn;at bere&thorn; &thorn;e flour,</L>
<L N="920">&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. The</NOTE> Maiden &thorn;at bar hire creatour.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;e "child is I-boren to vs,</L>
<L>And such a Sone I-&yogh;eue to vs."</L>
<L>And nis he "wonderful" &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L N="924">Whon he is &thorn;us for vs I-bore?</L>
<L>So muche wonder nis of no &thorn;inge</L>
<L>As two kuynden to-geder bringe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ei&thorn;er kuynde wi&thorn;-alle</L>
<L N="928">Habbe &thorn;at wole to heom bi-falle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer nou&thorn;er ne wonte no wiht,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;at ei&thorn;er habbe al his riht.</L>
<L>&THORN;at Is Ihesu, Godes sone,</L>
<L N="932">&THORN;at from heuene to eor&thorn;e wolde come</L>
<L>To sau&yogh;ten his sustren &thorn;at were to-boren,
<PB REF="00000387.tif" N="379"></L>
<L>And dilyueren &thorn;e prison &thorn;at was for-loren;</L>
<L N="935">Two kuynden he ha&thorn;, we witen bi &thorn;on,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. for</NOTE> he is so&thorn; God and so&thorn; Mon. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="marg">A passage of the Fr. text, vv. 845-912, is om. here and in H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>BI-hold now, Mon, to Godes miht</L>
<L>And his deden hou heo beo&thorn; diht<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>Regardez, homme, sa puis|sance</L><L>E sa grandor sanz flnance,</L><L>Ou circumscrip n'est mie,</L><L>E veez com il s'umilie.</L></Q></NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou a-boute nou&yogh;t fer se,<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. And this all-abowte thou well be-se</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. And</NOTE> bi-hold hou Boxum he wolde be</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wolde be boren of wommon</L>
<L>And for vre sake bi-comen mon.</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en be-hold hou he vs rede&thorn;</L>
<L N="944">And in to sauete vs lede&thorn;,</L>
<L>On ful swete manere &amp; on non o&thorn;ur,</L>
<L>And sei&thorn; &thorn;us to vs: "leue bro&thorn;ur,</L>
<L>I seo &thorn;e mis-lyken<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. myslyche i-gon</NOTE> &amp; al for-&yogh;emed<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. Io te voi ci esgarez</NOTE></L>
<L N="948">And out of &thorn;in owne lond I-flemed,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou seost wel &thorn;at for no &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;ow hast of &thorn;i-self no keueryng.</L>
<L>Ne beo &thorn;ou in wonhope non,</L>
<L N="952">Ac ful siker &thorn;ou beo &thorn;eron:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wole me louen<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. leuen, H. leve, Fr. crerre</NOTE> and vnderstonde,</L>
<L>I-chul &thorn;e bringe in to &thorn;in owne londe.</L>
<L>Ententyfliche<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. Oez moi tut sulement</NOTE> &thorn;ou herken to me</L>
<L N="956">And do &thorn;at ich comaunde &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Mi &yogh;ok is softe I-nowh to weren,</L>
<L>And my bur&thorn;ene li&yogh;t I-nouh to beren.</L>
<L>To Merci bi-houe<NOTE PLACE="marg">
H. To mercies bone; Fr. Pitie pur toi m'ad esmu.</NOTE> I am al I-nome,</L>
<L N="960">And &thorn;us I am for &thorn;e I-come.</L>
<L>And ich &thorn;e rede &thorn;ou suwe me,</L>
<L>I-chulle<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. And I-ch.</NOTE> &thorn;e batayle nyme for &thorn;e.</L>
<L>To ple I-chulle &thorn;is princes<NOTE PLACE="marg">i. e. Merci; Fr. Primes por toi voil pleider</NOTE> hauen,</L>
<L N="964">And &thorn;i rihte I-chulle crauen.</L>
<L>ffor Icham of &thorn;i lynage:</L>
<L>I may crauen &thorn;in heritage;</L>
<L>And Icham of freo nacion:</L>
<L N="968">Me oute I-here my reson;</L>
<L>And Ichabbe I-wust wi&thorn; wynne</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;reo lawen wi&thorn;-outen synne.<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 969-70 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e Ichulle to Batayle wende.</L>
<L N="972">siker<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. ffor siker</NOTE> beo &thorn;ou of ful good ende:</L>
<L>ffor Ichulle an ende ouurcome &thorn;at fiht
<PB REF="00000388.tif" N="380"></L>
<L>And to-dreynen<NOTE PLACE="marg">= dereynen, prove</NOTE> al &thorn;i riht.</L>
<L N="975">Ne darstou on er&thorn;e &thorn;enchen elles nouht</L>
<L>But God and &thorn;in euencristen to loue in trewe &thorn;ou&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lord, w&yogh;uch freschipe<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. frenschipe. Fr. franchise</NOTE>&mdash; hose nome &yogh;eme&mdash;</L>
<L>Whon he &thorn;at welde<NOTE PLACE="marg">3 sgl. ind.</NOTE> al &thorn;ing &amp; al mai deme,</L>
<L>Vs schewed such frenschip &amp; swetnes</L>
<L N="980">And a forbysne of Boxumnes!</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ulke forbisne me luitel telle&thorn; to,</L>
<L>And selden in &thorn;e world [is] I-se&yogh;en, ne &yogh;ore ha&thorn; do.<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. And selden in the world this vertu is do. Fr. Mes cele ensamp est poi tenue E trop reument el mund veue.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e worldlich mon euere I-liche</L>
<L>Loue&thorn; &thorn;ing &thorn;at is worldliche,</L>
<L N="985">Ac &thorn;e gost of charite &amp; of &thorn;olemodnesse</L>
<L>Loue&thorn; euer goodschipe &amp; Boxumnesse.</L>
<L>ffor whon to &thorn;e world him &yogh;eue&thorn; &thorn;e mon</L>
<L N="988">And &thorn;e worldes good him waxe&thorn; on,</L>
<L>He ne &thorn;enke&thorn; on God ne non o&thorn;er &thorn;ynge</L>
<L>Bote worldes catel to-geder bringe;</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;e catel ha&thorn; &thorn;e Maystrie a last,<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. om. a last</NOTE></L>
<L N="992">Hit<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;at hit</NOTE> is in his cofre bi-loke so fast,<NOTE PLACE="marg"> H. Hit maketh mon so rebell and hye Fr. Si ferm enz ses laz le lie (laz = lacs; the translator understood laie = coffer)</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at al he bicome&thorn; ouergart proud</L>
<L>And mis-do&thorn; his nei&yogh;ebors bo&thorn;e stille &amp; loud;</L>
<L>No-&thorn;ing ne wilne&thorn; he largesse,</L>
<L>But lordschupe and hei&yogh;nesse;</L>
<L>&THORN;e forbysne of Boxumnesse I-wys</L>
<L>Al &thorn;orw pruyde for&yogh;eten is.</L>
<L N="999">&THORN;eose ne mowen Ihesus suwen wi&thorn;,</L>
<L>ffor heore dede al to-lyth,<NOTE PLACE="marg"> cf. Fr.: <Q><L>Icous ihesum ne siwent mie,</L><L>Kar lur fet les contralie.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Ne his red ne leeue&thorn; heo nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;enne wolden heo wilnen ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1003">Of heritage in his kyn[e]dom&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; he in Batayle &thorn;e ple bi-won<NOTE PLACE="marg">v. 1004 om. in Fr. H. That he thorgh plee &amp; bataylle wane</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>Whon heo do&thorn; al &thorn;at he for-bat,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. forbet</NOTE></L>
<L>And no-&thorn;ing do&thorn; of &thorn;at he hat,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. het</NOTE></L>
<L N="1007">Ac euer seche&thorn; pride and hei&yogh;nesse,</L>
<L>Ne bidde&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sim. kepe&thorn;, H. loveth, Fr. voillent</NOTE> heo nou&yogh;t of boxumnesse?</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i Lucifer, as &yogh;e habbe&thorn; herd telle,</L>
<L>ffel from heuene a-doun to helle;</L>
<L>And also, I drede, heo scholden<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. schullen</NOTE> anende,</L>
<L N="1012">&THORN;ulke &thorn;at suche werkes do&thorn;, aftur him wende.<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. adds 2 vv.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac I ne sigge hit not for &thorn;on
<PB REF="00000389.tif" N="381"></L>
<L>&THORN;at mai ful wel eueriche goode mon</L>
<L>Habbe gret lordschupe &amp; hei&yogh;nesse,</L>
<L N="1016">Castels &amp; toures &amp; gret richesse,</L>
<L>And may wel don<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. welden</NOTE> &amp; godes wille holde</L>
<L>And libbe God to queme, wel, &yogh;if he wolde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he lyue&thorn; in loue<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. londe</NOTE> &amp; in Boxumnesse,</L>
<L N="1020">In So&thorn;schupe &amp; in Rihtwysnes;</L>
<L>ffor God wilne&thorn; no-&thorn;ing on eor&thorn;e her</L>
<L>But al monnes herte wi&thorn; trewe loue &amp; cler.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou mihte sum Mon asken &thorn;us:</L>
<L N="1024">Hou wolde God plede for vs,</L>
<L>Hou he eny batayle nom</L>
<L>And won vre ri&yogh;te &amp; [&thorn;e]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. a</NOTE> fend ouer-com.</L>
<L>Lustne&thorn; &thorn;enne to me nou,</L>
<L N="1028">And I-chulle ow tellen hou.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">Here is a change in the metre.</NOTE>&THORN;o Ihesu, Godes sone, in &thorn;e world was I-bore,</L>
<L>So stille &amp; derne he was &thorn;e fend fore</L>
<L>&THORN;at he of his come riht nou&yogh;t nuste,</L>
<L N="1032">Ac<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. As</NOTE> to beo lord and syre &yogh;it euere<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. eiwher? Fr. par tot</NOTE> he truste</L>
<L>As he hedde ben&mdash;ac his miht was bi-nome</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at Ihesu was I-bore &amp; in to &thorn;e world I-come.<NOTE PLACE="marg">v. 1034 om. in Fr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel &thorn;e fend him sei&yogh; In monnes weeden,</L>
<L>Ac he nust what he was, ne w&yogh;uch weren his deden.<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. ne of what dede. Fr.: E riens ne sout de quel affere</NOTE></L>
<L>He him sei&yogh; wel Mon &amp;<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in Sim.</NOTE> I-comen of Monkunne,</L>
<L>Ac euere in &thorn;e world he liuede wi&thorn;-oute sinne:</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend wondrede swi&thorn;e &amp; seide: "what artou?</L>
<L N="1040">Wher &thorn;ou be Godes sone &thorn;at art I-comen nou?</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is wyde world I-chul &yogh;euen &thorn;e,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ou bouwe &amp; honoure<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. adore; Fr. aorer, H. worship</NOTE> me."</L>
<L><STAGE><I>Respondit Iesus:</I></STAGE>&THORN;o seide Ihesu: "go a-wei, Sathan, go!</L>
<L N="1044">&THORN;i kuynde lord ne schalt &thorn;ow fonde so."</L>
<L><STAGE><I>Diabolus dicit:</I></STAGE>"What, wenestou I ne mowe vnderstonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at Icham prince &amp; lord of &thorn;is londe,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e Seisyne habbe longe I-be,</L>
<L N="1048">&THORN;orw &thorn;e hei&yogh;e kyng &thorn;at grant hit me?</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ing I seo, and alle &thorn;ing Ich wot,</L>
<L>But one &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t no-&thorn;ing I not.
<PB REF="00000390.tif" N="382"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou nymest ful muche an hond</L>
<L N="1052">To be-nymen me eny &thorn;ing in &thorn;is lond.</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; I nabbe miht ouer &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Wenestou my preie to be-nyme me?</L>
<L N="1055">Nay, for &thorn;at foreward &thorn;orw So&thorn; &amp; Riht</L>
<L>ffaste in godes court is congraffet<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. cyrografez</NOTE> apliht</L>
<L>&THORN;at hose passede godes heste,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. repeats Hose passede godes heste,</NOTE></L>
<L>He scholde be myn and in sunne leste,</L>
<L>An ende dyen &thorn;orw hard de&thorn; I-nouh;</L>
<L N="1060">And &thorn;e kyng of heuene nul do no wouh.</L>
<L>What, wenestou such foreward breke<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.: Mes bien tendra le covenant</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at was In Godes court I-speke?"</L>
<L N="1063"><STAGE><I>Respondit Ihesus:</I></STAGE>And &thorn;o swete Ihesu him onswerde and tolde:</L>
<L>"&THORN;at foreward on ende wel<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. god wel Fr.: Li covenanz fu bien tenu</NOTE> was I-holde;</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ou hit bi-gonne formast to breke,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;ou &thorn;orw treson to Monkuynde speke</L>
<L>And seidest &thorn;at treo him was forbode<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 1067-70 added.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1068">Lest he hedde &thorn;e miht of Gode,</L>
<L>Ac, wolde he of &thorn;e Appel ete,</L>
<L>&THORN;enne &thorn;ou seidest he hedde I-gete,<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. And wolde Goddys beheste lete</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in H.</NOTE> he scholde konnen al &thorn;at god con,</L>
<L N="1072">And he scholde neuer die for &thorn;on.</L>
<L>He agulte &thorn;orw &thorn;e, &amp; elles he wer skere.</L>
<L>Vnderstond my reson: &yogh;if hit skile were</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;au&yogh;</NOTE> &thorn;ou heddest alle forward of me,</L>
<L N="1076">And &thorn;ou noldest holden hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. hem?</NOTE> as anont &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. adds 2 vv.</NOTE>?"</L>
<L><STAGE><I>Diabolus dicit:</I></STAGE>"A, Ich am bi-tray&yogh;ed," quod<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. qua&thorn;; MS. qd</NOTE> &thorn;e fend &thorn;o,</L>
<L>"Nou Ich am &thorn;orw ple ouercomen so.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>O, dist le diables, trai sui</L><L>Kant en pleidant sui vencui.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Of whom &amp; hou come&thorn; hit,</L>
<L N="1080">Such reson &amp; such wit,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou so baldeliche darst nymen &thorn;e</L>
<L>fforte dispute a-&yogh;eynes me?</L>
<L>&THORN;orw ple Ichabbe I-loren al anon.</L>
<L N="1084">Ac<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. And, H. But, Fr. mes</NOTE> so ne may hit nou&yogh;t gon,</L>
<L>Algate he ha&thorn; mis-don,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw whon<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. whom</NOTE> he is in my prison;</L>
<L>And bote he beo for-bou&yogh;t of me,</L>
<L N="1088">He ne ou&yogh;te from wo disseysed be."<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.:<Q><L>Ne sanz redempcion por li</L><L>Ne serrai a tort deseisi.</L></Q></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000391.tif" N="383"></L>
<L><STAGE><I>Respondit Iesus:</I></STAGE>&THORN;o swete Ihesu to him con sugge:</L>
<L>"And Ichulle him &thorn;enne for-bugge."</L>
<L>[<I>Diab.</I>] "&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt him bugge to his feore,<NOTE PLACE="marg">= price</NOTE></L>
<L N="1092">He schal costen &thorn;e ful deore."</L>
<L>[<I>Jes.</I>] "Hou deore?" qua&thorn; Ihesu &thorn;o.</L>
<L>[<I>Diab.</I>] "As he is wor&thorn;; er &thorn;enne he go</L>
<L N="1095">Out of bonde of my prison."</L>
<L>[<I>Jes.</I>] "&THORN;at is skile," qua&thorn; Ihesu, "and good reson;</L>
<L>Ne kep I nou&yogh;t to-&yogh;eynes riht</L>
<L>&THORN;orw Maystrie bi-nyme &thorn;e no wiht."<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. 2 vv. more:<Q><L>"Fai me le donc volen|tiers!"</L><L>"Kest co donc ke tu quiers?"</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L><STAGE><I>Diabolus dicit:</I></STAGE>"No; ac er he dilyuered be,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou most also muche[wor&thorn;]delyuere me</L>
<L>As al &thorn;is world is nou [wor&thorn;] atte frome,</L>
<L N="1102">Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;ulke &thorn;at schulen heraftur come."<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.:<Q><L>Rendez moi donc que tant vaille</L><L>Com font ore tuz cil del mund</L><L>E quanka pres tuz iurs vendrunt.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L><STAGE><I>Ihesus dixit:</I></STAGE>"Ble&thorn;eliche," quod Ihesus, "al ichul don &thorn;is.</L>
<L N="1104">ffor my luttel fynger more wor&thorn; is</L>
<L>&THORN;en such an hondred worldes ben,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al &thorn;at folk &thorn;at me may herafter sen."</L>
<L N="1107"><STAGE><I>Diabolus dicit:</I></STAGE>&THORN;e fend &thorn;o to Ihesu onswere con:</L>
<L>"&THORN;at is al so&thorn;, I seo bi &thorn;on,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t al &thorn;e world demen &amp; dihte;</L>
<L>ffor<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. But</NOTE> nou ouer &thorn;e nabbe I no mihte.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.:<Q><L>Kar tut le mund pus iustiser,</L><L>Mes toi ne pus riens aprimer</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>And woldestou &thorn;i fynger &yogh;eue, &thorn;au&yogh; &thorn;ou so sugge,</L>
<L N="1112">So vnwor&thorn; &amp; so vyl chaffare to bugge?"</L>
<L><STAGE><I>Respondit Iesus:</I></STAGE>"&YOGH;e, and al my bodi, for his raunsoun,</L>
<L>But I-chul him habbe out of prisoun."<NOTE PLACE="marg">v. 1114 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>[<I>Diab.</I>] "&THORN;ou most &yogh;it more do ar &thorn;ou him habbe so:</L>
<L N="1116">&THORN;olen on eor&thorn;e wandre&thorn;e &amp; wo;</L>
<L>And, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wole a-menden his wou&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou most de&thorn; &thorn;olen &thorn;orw strong pyne I-nou&yogh;."<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. has 4 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>[<I>Jes.</I>] And &thorn;o swete Ihesu him onswerde to<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;o</NOTE>:</L>
<L N="1120">"Al &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast seid, al schal be do,&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor So&thorn; seide hit ou&yogh;te ben so,</L>
<L>And Riht com after [&amp; &yogh;ef] &thorn;e dom &thorn;o.<NOTE PLACE="marg">so H. Fr.: <Q><L>Kar verite le devise</L><L>E puis si ad iuge iustise.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>And more &thorn;en &thorn;ou hast i-seid I-chulle don,
<PB REF="00000392.tif" N="384"></L>
<L N="1124">To diliuere &thorn;e &thorn;ral out of prison."</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;e fend siker, &amp; wende wel e&thorn;e</L>
<L>fforte haue bi-&yogh;eten &thorn;orw his de&thorn;e;&mdash;</L>
<L>Ac he was cau&yogh;t and ouer-comen,</L>
<L N="1128">As fisch &thorn;at is wi&thorn; hok I-nomen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at whon &thorn;e worm he swolewe&thorn; a last</L>
<L>He is bi &thorn;e hok I-ti&yogh;ed fast.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>A</B>, Mon, nim &yogh;eme &amp; vnderstond &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1132">Hou fynliche in herte god loue&thorn; &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>Ore esgardez la doucor</L><L>E le conseil al sauveor:</L><L>Ke tant est leger a suffrir</L><L>Dont garisun peut venir.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wolde de&thorn; &thorn;olen &thorn;orw pyne wi&thorn;-outen me&thorn;</L>
<L>To saue &thorn;i soule from pyne of de&thorn;!</L>
<L>Al vre gult on him he wolde take,</L>
<L N="1136">And lodliche was bi-lad al for vre sake.</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;at neuer no sunne dude</L>
<L>Ne neuer nas wi&thorn; ful&thorn;e I-founden in no stude</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;e lymes &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e mon</L>
<L N="1140">Se&thorn;&thorn;en Adam formest sunne bi-gon,</L>
<L>Wolde &thorn;at his lymes alle I-pyned were,</L>
<L>To maken vs of sunne al quit &amp; skere.</L>
<L>ffor vre vnwrestschupe<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. iniquite</NOTE> here</L>
<L N="1144">&THORN;e coroune of &thorn;ornes on his hed he beere<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. ber</NOTE>;</L>
<L>And for vre folye<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. sy&yogh;ht myspende, Fr. pur le nos fous regarz. r. fol e&yogh;e</NOTE> also</L>
<L>His E&yogh;en weore blyntwharuet<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. blynwherued, Fr. bendez</NOTE> bo;</L>
<L>And al was his face bi-foulet wi&thorn; spot,</L>
<L N="1148">And eke grete boffetes among me him smot;</L>
<L>And for vre speche vnwreste &amp; vyl</L>
<L>Atter heo him dude to drinke I-meynt wi&thorn; Eisil;<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. adds 2 vv.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e otewyse werkes as &thorn;ere-anonden<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. anonde, H. ffor vnlawfull werk us avonde (!) Fr.<Q><L>Et pur nos mavois fez foreins</L><L>Se lessa percer piez e meins.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L N="1152">He lette bo&thorn;e &thorn;urlen his feet and honden<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. honde, plur.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>And for vre woke &thorn;ou&yogh;tes he &thorn;olede smerte</L>
<L>&THORN;at me his syde &thorn;urlede ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e herte.</L>
<L>What miht he &thorn;enne do for vs more?</L>
<L>No tonge may tellen of &thorn;at fore<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. of his soore</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne no monnes herte ne mihte &thorn;enche so</L>
<L>As he &thorn;olede for vs pyne and wo.</L>
<L>And ho is &thorn;at ne mi&yogh;te habbe pite</L>
<L N="1160">Of such frendschupe &amp; charite?</L>
<L>Suche beo &thorn;e duntes of Batayle</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;olede for vs wi&thorn;-outen fayle.</L>
<L>Ac [&thorn;o]<NOTE PLACE="marg">om., Fr. Mes quant, H. And he</NOTE> he &thorn;olede to de&thorn;e ben I-brou&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000393.tif" N="385"></L>
<L N="1164">Vre de&thorn; &thorn;orw his de&thorn; he ha&thorn; for-bou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>ffor more &thorn;olede he an hundret-folde</L>
<L>Serwe &amp; pyne, &thorn;o he dyen wolde,</L>
<L N="1167">&THORN;en &thorn;e fend mihte for eny synne</L>
<L>Leggen hond<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in H. Fr.:<Q><L>Ke diables neurent poeir</L><L>A humeine nature charger.</L></Q></NOTE> vppon monkunne.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e soule loue&thorn; &thorn;e bodi so</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuere heo nule him wende fro,</L>
<L>ffor no pyne ne for<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. ne for no</NOTE> sore,</L>
<L N="1172">&THORN;au&yogh; me hit to-hewe euermore,</L>
<L>Er &thorn;e fyf wittes ben<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. han? Fr.:<Q><L>Ainz ke le cors eit perdu</L><L>De tuz cinc sens la vertu</L></Q></NOTE> loren out-riht,</L>
<L>Al heore vertue and al heore mi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is, &thorn;e Siht and &thorn;e herynge,</L>
<L N="1176">&THORN;e speche and &thorn;e Smellynge,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e felynge, he schal leosen an<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sim. and</NOTE> ende</L>
<L>Ar he wole from &thorn;e bodi wende;</L>
<L>Kuynde ne may for no &thorn;inge</L>
<L N="1180">&THORN;olen her &thorn;e ti&thorn;elynge.<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. to-delinge? Fr.:<Q><L>Kar nature ne peut soffrir</L><L>L'alme einz del cors partir.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Ac he &thorn;at alle &thorn;ing mai welde,</L>
<L>Doublede his peyne an hondred-felde:</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;o he pynede<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. pendi, H. honged</NOTE> on &thorn;e Crois,</L>
<L N="1184">He &yogh;af his soule wi&thorn; loud vois.</L>
<L>&THORN;er he schewede &thorn;at he was God so,</L>
<L>Vre Raunsum he dude &thorn;o;</L>
<L>&THORN;e bodi &yogh;it liuede wi&thorn;-oute fayle,</L>
<L>And so he ouercom &thorn;e Batayle.</L>
<L>Kuynde ne mihte &thorn;ole such peyne non,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e fend ne mi&yogh;te hit neuer legen on.<NOTE PLACE="marg">1189-90 om. in H. Fr.:<Q><L>Tant ne peut diable charger</L><L>Ne nature endurer.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>A</B>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. And</NOTE> Marie, Mayden schene,</L>
<L N="1192">Mihtful Moder and Milde Qwene,</L>
<L>ffor deol mungen I ne may</L>
<L>&THORN;e pyne &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;oledest &thorn;ulke day.</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;e prophecye of Symeon</L>
<L N="1196">Was folfuld &thorn;o bi &thorn;on,</L>
<L>As wi&thorn; swerd in &thorn;ulke stounde</L>
<L>&THORN;ou heddest &thorn;o ful bitter wounde.</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;i Ioye doublede an hondrut-folde</L>
<L N="1200">&THORN;o he from de&thorn; vp rysen wolde&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; weore his passion,</L>
<L>Neore his Resurexion.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou se&yogh;e openliche in alle &thorn;inge
<PB REF="00000394.tif" N="386"></L>
<L N="1204">Of his Batayle &thorn;e endynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw whom<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. whom?</NOTE> &thorn;e fend was al mat</L>
<L>And &thorn;e world for-bou&yogh;t &amp; brou&yogh;t in stat.</L>
<L>&THORN;e trou&thorn;e of vs &amp; &thorn;e be-leeue also</L>
<L N="1208">Bi-leuede al in &thorn;e &thorn;o;<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. XXXVII. v. 83.</NOTE></L>
<L>In wonhope weore his disciples vchon,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ou weore studefast, euer In on&mdash;</L>
<L>Ne mi&yogh;te &thorn;e no &thorn;ing tornen out,</L>
<L N="1212">In trewe bileue euere &thorn;ou weore, stille &amp; loud.</L>
<L>Marie, Mooder of pite,</L>
<L>Mayden ful of alle bounte,</L>
<L>Vre bi-leeue was &thorn;o in &thorn;e, I-wis:</L>
<L N="1216">And nou al vre hope is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou bi-seche &thorn;i sone for vs,</L>
<L>&THORN;at so on Rode for-bou&yogh;t vs.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;E habbe&thorn; I-herd of swete Ihesu</L>
<L N="1220">Hou he &thorn;orw his muchel vertu</L>
<L>Vs rede&thorn; to goode euer-more,</L>
<L>And hou he wolde vs plede fore,</L>
<L>And hou he wolde to Batayle wende,</L>
<L N="1224">And hou he hit ouer-com an ende.</L>
<L>Nas &thorn;is a good redes-mon</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;as</NOTE> vs so deore for-buggen con,</L>
<L>And ha&thorn; I-rud<NOTE PLACE="marg">= prepare, so Hom. 2, 133.</NOTE> vs &thorn;e way</L>
<L N="1228">&THORN;er vchone of vs &thorn;at wole he may</L>
<L>To &thorn;e blisful Ioye come</L>
<L>&THORN;at so longe &thorn;orw adam<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. par Evain, through Eve.</NOTE> was bi-nome?&mdash;</L>
<L>Vnderstonde&thorn; nou for&thorn;ure no&thorn;eles</L>
<L N="1232">Hou he is God, and euere wes:</L>
<L>And &yogh;e mouwe openliche I-seon</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit ne may not elles ben.</L>
<L>O God al &thorn;e world wrou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="1236">And &thorn;ulke god vs alle forbou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>O&thorn;er God nis non &thorn;en he,</L>
<L>&THORN;e God of whom I seide er &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Persones &thorn;reo in &thorn;rille-hod</L>
<L N="1240">And o God cleped in on-hod.</L>
<L>Men<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> Me</NOTE> may also, Clerkes &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. &thorn;at. H. as clerkys con Fr.:<Q><L>E ses fez peut hom saveir</L><L>E la puissance deu veeir:</L></Q></NOTE> conne reden,</L>
<L>I-seon his godhede &thorn;orw his deden:</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e deden &thorn;at he dude here
<PB REF="00000395.tif" N="387"></L>
<L N="1244">[Were] wi&thorn; Godhede &amp; Monhede I-meynt<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. he dede. Fr.:<Q><L>Kar tuz ses fez furent mellez</L><L>De hommesce e de deitez</L></Q></NOTE> I-fere.</L>
<L>And nym nou &yogh;eme &amp; &thorn;ou miht sen<NOTE PLACE="marg">exemplum</NOTE></L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at ilke<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. this thyng</NOTE> mihte ben.</L>
<L>Hose hedde a swerd here</L>
<L N="1248">&THORN;at wel I-steled and kene were,</L>
<L>And he hit in to &thorn;e fuir dude,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit were brennynge in &thorn;e stude:</L>
<L>Ho is &thorn;at &thorn;enne mihte,</L>
<L N="1252">Whon hit barnde so brihte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fuyr to-delen &thorn;e stel fro</L>
<L>O&thorn;er &thorn;e Stel from &thorn;e fuir mo?</L>
<L>And hose wi&thorn; &thorn;e swerd smite,</L>
<L N="1256">Two kuynden he mi&yogh;te sen and wite:</L>
<L>&THORN;e Stel &thorn;orw kuynde kerue&thorn; apliht,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e fuir brande,<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. barneth, Sim. brenne&thorn;</NOTE> and &thorn;at is riht;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.: <Q><L>L'ascer trenchant per droiture</L><L>E le feu ardant par nature</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>And al of O swerd hit come.</L>
<L N="1260">Also is of Ihesu, Godes sone:</L>
<L>Two kuynden he ha&thorn;, we witen bi &thorn;on,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he is so&thorn; God and so&thorn; Mon.</L>
<L>ffor atte neces of &thorn;is princee (!)<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sim. ffor atte neoces of &thorn;is priuete; H. He shewed gret myraculle and privete; W. reads: ffor atte neces (r. no|ces) [he schewede] &thorn;is priuete. I think, &thorn;is p.&mdash;made is a later insertion.</NOTE></L>
<L>At &thorn;e Caane of Galylee</L>
<L>A Gistnynge he made, Architriclyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he torned water to wyn.<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Fr.: <Q><L>As noces seint archit[r]eclin</L><L>Kant leawe changat en vin,</L><L>Sis ydres i sunt pose</L><L>E implir les deawe ad comande;</L><L>Com homme emplir les roua,</L><L>Com dieu leawe en vin changa.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Sixe vessels &thorn;er weoren I-don:</L>
<L>Of water he bad hem fulle son;</L>
<L>As mon<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Anon, H. As by his monhede</NOTE> he bad don water &thorn;er-In,</L>
<L>And as God he turned hit to wyn;</L>
<L>And &thorn;is ilke dede was al on<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.: <Q><L>Et tut icest un oeur feu</L><L>E domme e de verrai den.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L N="1272">Of so&thorn;fast God and so&thorn;fast mon.</L>
<L>And elles-wher &thorn;er he eode,</L>
<L>Muche folk<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.: Ou tant de poeple siwi la</NOTE> him suwede of feole &thorn;eode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fyf &thorn;ousend men he ha&thorn; I-set</L>
<L N="1276">And wi&thorn; fyue louus &amp; twey fissches hem fed,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e Relef &thorn;at hem leuede bi-fore</L>
<L>Twelf cupe-ful weoren vp I-bore:</L>
<L>As Mon he hem &thorn;e bred to-breek,</L>
<L N="1280">And as God he ha&thorn; hem I-fulled ek.</L>
<L>Of La&yogh;ar also &thorn;ou miht i-seon e&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Hou<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. Kant</NOTE> he him arerede from &thorn;e de&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at foure dawes he lei&yogh; a-long
<PB REF="00000396.tif" N="388"></L>
<L N="1284">In &thorn;e Buriles,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sim. buriels</NOTE> &thorn;at he stonk;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; loud voys he clepede &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"La&yogh;ar, a-Rys and cum out to vs:"</L>
<L>Riht as mon he clepede to him,</L>
<L N="1288">And as God he arerede him.</L>
<L>In alle his deden me may wel I-sen</L>
<L>&THORN;at he is God and euer schal ben.</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke God alle &thorn;ing dihte,</L>
<L N="1292">&THORN;at in &thorn;e swete Mayden alihte.</L>
<L>Al vre be-leeue in him is,</L>
<L>Vre treu&thorn;e, and vre hope, I-wis,</L>
<L>Persones &thorn;reo in &thorn;rillihod,</L>
<L N="1296">And O God &thorn;au&yogh;, in on-hod.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou &yogh;e habbe&thorn; I-herd witterly</L>
<L>Hou he is god almihti.</L>
<L>Ac his streng&thorn;e ne may non telle,</L>
<L N="1300">Herte &thorn;enke, ne Mou&thorn; spelle.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e hei&yogh;e nome Ihesu</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; in him so muche vertu,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;at is in heuene hi&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="1304">A-bouen<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. in erthe, Fr. E en terre</NOTE> &amp; bi-neo&thorn;en, feor and nei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Bouwe&thorn; to &thorn;ilke nome vchon.</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i &thorn;er ne may hit telle non,</L>
<L N="1307">His miht &amp; his streng&thorn;e hou hit ge&thorn;,</L>
<L>But as a Mon &thorn;e Rynde fle&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.: Mes come en rongant lescorce</NOTE></L>
<L>Sumwhat touchen Ichulle fonde<NOTE PLACE="marg">Tochier la voil apertement Solunc le mieux ke jentenc.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;at Ich may vnderstonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Adam hedde I-loren &thorn;orw synne</L>
<L N="1312">Heuene &amp; eor&thorn;e &amp; paradyses winne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffend hedde such miht &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e world moste after him go;</L>
<L N="1315">ffor whom<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. whon. Fr.:<Q><L>Celui pur ki le mund fu fet</L><L>En son poeir out attreit</L></Q></NOTE> &thorn;e world was furst wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; him vnder I-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Such streng&thorn;e he him &thorn;o ches</L>
<L>&THORN;at prince of al &thorn;e world he wes.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>Tant de poeir dones avoit</L><L>Ke prince du mund se clamoit.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er nas non for his goodschupe,</L>
<L N="1320">ffor penaunce ne for holyschupe,</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; he pynede him-self in flesch and felle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e fend ne ladde him to helle.</L>
<L>Ac<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. And, H. But, Fr. Mes.</NOTE> &thorn;e streng&thorn;e of Ihesu, Godes sone,
<PB REF="00000397.tif" N="389"></L>
<L N="1324">Hym ha&thorn; al mated and ouer-come.</L>
<L>Ouercomen and I-mat he was ful sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he wende of him to done</L>
<L>As he hedde don of o&thorn;er alle</L>
<L N="1328">&THORN;at he lette in to helle falle&mdash;</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">1329-30 added to the Fr.</NOTE> Alle he ladde herbifore after his wille</L>
<L>And in to helle con<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. com</NOTE> hem spille.<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. In helle that he my&yogh;ht hem spylle.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e croys he con come</L>
<L N="1332">And wolde habben his soule I-nome.</L>
<L>Ac he faylede, &thorn;e Traytour!</L>
<L>He was a-bated of his tour!<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. anowre. Fr.: Il est de son torn abatuz</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor Godes Godhede him ha&thorn; doun cast</L>
<L N="1336">In to helle, and I-bounden fast.</L>
<L>ffor<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.: <Q><L>Ou il meimes est ale</L><L>Od salme sa deite. 1339-40 added to the Fr.</L></Q></NOTE> &thorn;orw his Godhede his soule eode</L>
<L>&THORN;idere, for hise &thorn;at hedden neode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;ore hedden him a-bide</L>
<L N="1340">And sore longeden to gon him mide.</L>
<L>Helle-&yogh;ates he al to-breek,</L>
<L>And to-daschte al &thorn;e fendes ek,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. Le poer du diable a toleit,</NOTE></L>
<L>A gret bite he bot, of helle nom<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>A enfern fist un grant mors,</L><L>Ke tuz les soens entreit hors.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L N="1344">And drouh alle hise out, vchon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at leeueden his come<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. nome; H. comyng; Fr. venue</NOTE> &amp; him knewe</L>
<L>And serueden him wi&thorn; herte trewe.</L>
<L>Such streng&thorn;e nas neuer I-herd ar &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="1348">Ne neuer schal, but of him, I-wis!</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e meste streng&thorn;e he al bi-reuede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e fend in &thorn;e world heuede.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>Ke tut le greingnor poeir</L><L>Ke feust el mund fist mater.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>He was en-Armed ful stronge,</L>
<L N="1352">&THORN;at his &yogh;at wuste ful longe:</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;o &thorn;e strengore him<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. him?Fr. <Q><L>Meis quant li plus fort sorveneit,</L><L>Ses espoilles lui ad toleit.</L></Q></NOTE> ouer com,</L>
<L>Gret preye he him bi-nom.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i him sei&thorn; wel Ysaye,</L>
<L N="1356">&THORN;at sei&thorn; in his prophecye</L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde "Myhtfol<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Myldefol</NOTE>" I-cleped ben.</L>
<L>His streng&thorn;e may no mon I-seon,</L>
<L>Ne no tonge ne mihte reden</L>
<L N="1360">Ne &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;enken his mihtful deden.</L>
<L>ffor his miht me ou&yogh;te him drede,</L>
<L>And for his swetnes him loue ful nede.</L>
<L>&THORN;is is vre [s]child<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. child, H. shild</NOTE> and vre help,
<PB REF="00000398.tif" N="390"></L>
<L N="1364">Vre streng&thorn;e and vre &yogh;elp,</L>
<L>Vre be-leue and vre socour,</L>
<L>Vre treu&thorn;e and vre honour;</L>
<L N="1367">&THORN;at so Boxum bi-com for vs,</L>
<L>He &yogh;af him-self to sauen vs.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>Ki tant se vout humilier</L><L>E soi doner pur nus sauver.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>And al o God dude &thorn;is,</L>
<L>ffader and sone and holigost, I-wis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sumdel &yogh;e habbe&thorn; i-herd nou riht</L>
<L N="1372">of his streng&thorn;e &amp; of his miht.</L>
<L>ac herkne&thorn; &yogh;it for&thorn;ure of Ysaye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at cleped him in his prophecie</L>
<L>'ffader of &thorn;e world &thorn;at scholde come<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>Pere au poeple ki vendroit,</L><L>Au siecle ke feut a venir.</L></Q></NOTE>.'&mdash;</L>
<L N="1376">ffor while he walkede her atte frome,</L>
<L>He folfulde in alle &thorn;inge</L>
<L>Alle holye prophetes biddynge.<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. bigynnynge, H. byddyng</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>Hou he Is ffader, &yogh;e schullen I-heren,</L>
<L N="1380">And hou we alle of him I-streoned weren.</L>
<L>&THORN;orw Adam we<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. trestuz pecherent</NOTE> sungeden furst vchon</L>
<L>And eeten &thorn;e Appel wi&thorn; him anon,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>Kanque de lui en|gendre furent</L><L>La maleicon kil out eurent.</L></Q></NOTE> alle we<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. that</NOTE> of him I-streoned weoren,</L>
<L>&THORN;e cors &thorn;at he beer alle we<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in H.</NOTE> beeren;</L>
<L>&THORN;orw kuynde we hedden &thorn;e curs alle&mdash;</L>
<L N="1386">&THORN;orw Riht ne mi&yogh;t hit elles bi-falle.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>Kar Adam nostre pere estoit</L><L>E charneument nus en|gendroit.</L></Q></NOTE> Adam vr fader, &thorn;e forme mon,</L>
<L>ffleschliche streoned vs euerichon:</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ulke flescliche streonynge</L>
<L>Beere vs Bale and Serwynge,</L>
<L>Neore &thorn;e grace of swete Ihesu,</L>
<L N="1392">&THORN;at vs strenede [&thorn;orw] gostliche vertu.</L>
<L>&THORN;orw Adam we weore to de&thorn;e I-demet:</L>
<L>&THORN;orw Ihesu vp rered and al I-quemed;</L>
<L>He is vre ffader ariht,</L>
<L N="1396">And<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. That</NOTE> so goodliche vs ha&thorn; I-diht</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; his blod he vs washed<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. waked. Fr. lava</NOTE> of sinne</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;t vs out of wo to winne&mdash;</L>
<L>Neuer ffader for no childe</L>
<L N="1400">Of fyn loue nas so freo ne mylde!</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;an? H. ffor Fr.: <Q><L>Kant il nus out tuz rechatez,</L><L>Par sa mort de mort delivrez,</L><L>En enfern puis s'en ala.</L></Q></NOTE> from &thorn;e Roode for vre neode</L>
<L>Riht in to helle he eode,</L>
<L>ffourti tymen &thorn;er he wes
<PB REF="00000399.tif" N="391"></L>
<L N="1404">O<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &THORN;o</NOTE> &thorn;at he vp risen ches&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was on &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day,</L>
<L>Erliche vppon a sonenday,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e ni&yogh;t fro<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. for?</NOTE> &thorn;e day to-brek&mdash;</L>
<L N="1408">So seide seynt Austin &thorn;o he spek;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him he drou&yogh; out alle hise</L>
<L>&THORN;at di&yogh;eden in his seruise,</L>
<L>ffrom &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he Adam wrou&yogh;te</L>
<L N="1412">[O]<NOTE PLACE="marg">om.</NOTE> &thorn;at he vp ros and vs for-bou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>To his disciples he him schewede I-lome</L>
<L>And Eet &amp; dronk, eode and come.</L>
<L>ffourti dawes he was heere fulliche,</L>
<L N="1416">And prechede hem godes kineriche.</L>
<L>Vppon<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. O &thorn;on = Till the Fr.: <Q><L>Deskes a l'ascen|cion</L><L>Ou il estoient &amp;c.</L></Q></NOTE> holy &thorn;oresday, &thorn;er on his nome</L>
<L>Heo weren I-gedered alle I-some</L>
<L>Vppon a stude, &thorn;er he among hem com</L>
<L N="1420">And of mis-bileue hem vndernom.</L>
<L>In whonhope and doute heo weoren vchon,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;et hed se&yogh;en</NOTE> heo se&yogh;en him alyue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. aryse? cf. Fr.: <Q><L>Kar tuz furent en dotance,</L><L>Ki resuscite veu l'eurent</L><L>E ne purkant nel creurent.</L></Q></NOTE> a lyues mon,</L>
<L>&THORN;o<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &THORN;e &yogh;it</NOTE> &yogh;it ne mihten heo for no wit</L>
<L>Riht to so&thorn;e I-leeuen hit.</L>
<L>Ac heore doute was vre bi-heue</L>
<L>And fastnede ful wel vre bi-leeue,</L>
<L>ffor muche vs dude sikernesse</L>
<L N="1428">Of Thomas misbileuenesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nolde for no mon &thorn;at was</L>
<L>Bi-leeuen &thorn;at he ded and<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. ded and</NOTE> arisen was</L>
<L N="1431">Ar he hedde hondlet &thorn;e wounde so wyde</L>
<L>&THORN;at longeus made in his syde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr.: <Q><L>Desk'en ses plaies sa mein mist</L><L>Ke Longis de lance fist.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>And seon &thorn;e woundes grene and weet<NOTE PLACE="marg">1433-6 added to the Fr.</NOTE></L>
<L>W&yogh;uche &thorn;at weoren on honden &amp; feet.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;O schewed Ihesus him his wondes wyde</L>
<L N="1436">In hondes &amp; feet, &amp; &thorn;ulke on his syde.</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou art, I-chot," qua&thorn; Thomas &thorn;o,</L>
<L>"Mi God and my lord also."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, Thomas," qua&thorn; Ihesu crist,</L>
<L N="1440">"&THORN;ou hit leuest for &thorn;ou hit sixt:</L>
<L>Alle heo moten I-blessed ben</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit leeuen &thorn;au&yogh; heo hit not sen."</L>
<L>Openliche he made &thorn;ulke day
<PB REF="00000400.tif" N="392"></L>
<L N="1444">ffaste and siker vre lay.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>A ceu iur vout apertement</L><L>La foi fermer de tute gent.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his disciples he set &thorn;o</L>
<L>As he was er I-wont to do,</L>
<L>And sette tweyne &amp; tweyne to gon</L>
<L N="1448">&YOGH;ond al &thorn;e world, to prechen vchon</L>
<L>To alle schaft and to alle wihte&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to mon &thorn;orw rihte<NOTE PLACE="marg">1449-50 om. in H.Fr. A universe creature, (cf. Marc. 16)Cest a homme par droiture</NOTE> &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo bi-leeuen in godes sone&mdash;&thorn;at is, in him<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. he</NOTE> &mdash;</L>
<L N="1452">And &thorn;at vche mon folwede him,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. fulwed be;Fr. <Q><L>Kil en le fiz deu creus|sent</L><L>E baptizez tuz feus|sent.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e ffader [nome] and in &thorn;e sone also</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e holy gost &thorn;at glit of hem bo;</L>
<L>ffor hose neore I-boren eft at &thorn;e frome,</L>
<L N="1456">In to heuene ne mi&yogh;te he neuer come;</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ulke &thorn;at be&thorn; I-fulwed in Riht bi-leeue</L>
<L>Schulen beo brou&yogh;t in Godes<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. gode Fr. Serrunt mis en sauvetez.</NOTE> bi-heue.</L>
<L>Wel openliche he schewe&thorn; vs &thorn;erfore</L>
<L N="1460">&THORN;at vche mon mot eft ben I-bore.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if we schulen eft I-boren ben,</L>
<L>We mote comen of sume<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. sunne; cf. Fr.: <Q><L>Mes puske rene serrum,</L><L>Eugendrure averum,</L><L>Cest del ewe e del esprit,</L><L>Ou nus engendra ihesu crist.</L></Q></NOTE> streon:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e water of vertu,</L>
<L N="1464">&THORN;er vs gostliche strene&thorn; swete Ihesu;</L>
<L>And whon he vs ha&thorn; so strened, I-wis,</L>
<L>fforso&thorn;e vre ffader he is,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne we alle his children be&thorn;.</L>
<L N="1468">Sikerliche, vnwrestliche he dee&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;at such ffader ne loue&thorn; wi&thorn; al his &thorn;ou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>He ne eet of &thorn;e Appel riht nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Baldeliche we mouwe &thorn;orw him craue</L>
<L N="1472">Vre Rihtes in heuene to haue;</L>
<L>ffor he ha&thorn; alle &thorn;e lawen I-wyst,<NOTE PLACE="marg">or. wust</NOTE> &mdash;</L>
<L>Of O poynt ne ha&thorn; he mist,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuere neore I-wust ne I-holde</L>
<L N="1476">Er<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. hent</NOTE> he him-self comen wolde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fforme Mon &thorn;at of eor&thorn;e com,</L>
<L>Brou&yogh;t vs werre, and pees bi-nom:</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur Mon from heuene com wi&thorn; meyn</L>
<L N="1480">And ha&thorn; I-&yogh;olden vre pees a&yogh;eyn.</L>
<L>ffleschliche was &thorn;e forme mon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at muche wo vs brou&yogh;te vppon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was out of paradys I-pult,
<PB REF="00000401.tif" N="393"></L>
<L N="1484">And al his ofspring for his gult:</L>
<L>Ac vre gostlych ffader, swete Ihesu,</L>
<L>Vs brynge&thorn; a&yogh;eyn &thorn;orw his vertu;</L>
<L N="1487">He &thorn;at from heuene com,</L>
<L>ffrom louh anhei&yogh; he vs vp nom.</L>
<L>&THORN;at from eor&thorn;e com, to eor&thorn;e he ge&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. <Q><L>Ki de terre est a terre ala,</L><L>Ki vint du ciel, a ciel munta.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at from heuene com to heuene he ste&thorn;.</L>
<L>On holy &thorn;oresday, &thorn;er al &thorn;e folk I-sei&yogh;</L>
<L N="1492">W&yogh;uche &thorn;at stoden a-bouten him neih,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wey he made, vs to lede,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;e skewes, &thorn;er he eode,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; so&thorn;nesse, and wey of li&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Fr.: <Q><L>La voie a ses seinz a fet</L><L>Par les nuwes ou il vet&mdash;</L><L>Vie, verite, et voie.</L></Q></NOTE>;</L>
<L N="1496">&THORN;e feire cumpanye<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. pray, Fr. proie</NOTE> him ladde wi&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he out of helle nom,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to muche blisse com.</L>
<L>To &thorn;ulke blisse he made hem wende</L>
<L N="1500">&THORN;at euer laste&thorn; wi&thorn;-outen ende;</L>
<L>&THORN;er he wone&thorn; as he dude er,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his ffader, O God &thorn;er,</L>
<L>Persones &thorn;reo in &thorn;rillihod,</L>
<L N="1504">And O God &thorn;au&yogh; in on-hod;</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;ing wrou&yogh;te, as &thorn;ou, mon, wost,</L>
<L>ffader &amp; sone &amp; holygost;</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. And thawgh</NOTE> vche nome of &thorn;ise &thorn;re</L>
<L N="1508">Sinderliche [be seid]<NOTE PLACE="marg">H. Byn syndry seyd; Fr.<Q><L>E s'il i a distinctiun</L><L>De trois persones par nun,</L><L>Ne purkant un sul deu dure</L></Q></NOTE> as he ou&yogh;te to be,</L>
<L>O God hit is wi&thorn;-outen care,</L>
<L>Of alle schaftes schuppare;</L>
<L>To whom Ioye &amp; honour bi-come</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen ende, &thorn;e holy gome.<NOTE PLACE="marg">In Halliwell's ed. here fol|lows a last part (see p. 403|6 below): on the 15 tokens, the day of doom, and the dowers in heven, in 308 vv.; and vv. 1513-24 are wanting.</NOTE> &mdash;</L>
<L>Now biseche we God for his Merci</L>
<L>Such lyf her leden and so trusti,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we his heste holden so long,</L>
<L N="1516">&THORN;ulke pes vs wonye among</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sende from heuene to monkinne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he wone wi&thorn; vs wi&thorn;-Inne,</L>
<L>And aftur &thorn;is lyf to Ioye wende.</L>
<L N="1520">&THORN;is writ in god nime&thorn; nou ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;er is ende and byginnynge,</L>
<L>So holy writ sey&thorn;, of alle &thorn;inge:
<PB REF="00000402.tif" N="394"></L>
<L>God leeue vs here so ende</L>
<L N="1524">&THORN;at we ben wor&thorn;i to heuene wende. Amen.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Then follows Ypotys, fol. CCXCVI, ed. before in <I>Altengl. Leg.</I>, N. F., p. 341-8, and from another MS., Cott. Calig. A II, with readings from Arund. 140, Ashm. 61, Cott. Tit. A XXVI, ib. p. 511&mdash;526; 2 other MSS., Ashm. 750 and Douce 323, were ed. in a dissertation, Berlin, 1887.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
