<ITEM>His feyre pray he hadde him wythe</ITEM>
<LABEL>1497</LABEL>
<ITEM>out of h. with him nome</ITEM>
<LABEL>1498</LABEL>
<ITEM>To meche ioy and blys he made hem come</ITEM>
<LABEL>1499</LABEL>
<ITEM>To that ioy and blysse . wynde</ITEM>
<LABEL>1500</LABEL>
<ITEM>Ther to lyvyn w. eynde</ITEM>
<LABEL>1501</LABEL>
<ITEM>dede</ITEM>
<LABEL>1502</LABEL>
<ITEM>is . and byth oon God ther</ITEM>
<LABEL>1503</LABEL>
<ITEM>Thre persons in Trinite</ITEM>
<LABEL>1504</LABEL>
<ITEM>And oon God in unite</ITEM>
<LABEL>1505</LABEL>
<ITEM>well inst. of mon</ITEM>
<LABEL>1507</LABEL>
<ITEM>And thawgh . these</ITEM>
<LABEL>1508</LABEL>
<ITEM>Byn syndry seyd as they shuld be</ITEM>
<LABEL>1509</LABEL>
<ITEM>On . w. dowte</ITEM>
<LABEL>1510</LABEL>
<ITEM>Maker of alle this world withinne and without</ITEM>
<LABEL>1511</LABEL>
<ITEM>Ioy, honoure, worship and lovyng</ITEM>
<LABEL>1512</LABEL>
<ITEM>Be to that God oure hevyn kyng. 
</ITEM>
</LIST>
<P><PB REF="00000411.tif" N="403">Instead of the last vv. in MS. Vernon, H. has the following further passage explaining how Jesus is prince of peace:<NOTE PLACE="foot">This passage is found in the French text, except the 15 tokens, which were added in the Engl. translation, the 2 last (vv. 1597-1612) being, however, adapted from a passage in the Fr., where vv. 1619-46 precede v. 1597.</NOTE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lusteneth &yogh;et forther of Ysayes spelle,</L>
<L>ffor now &yogh;e han herd me telle</L>
<L>How swete Ihesu oure fadur wes:</L>
<L N="1516">Herkenyth how he is now Prince of Pes.</L>
<L>Beforen I tolde &yogh;ow uchon</L>
<L>How he is into hevyn i-gon:</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;ht so, the sothe truly to syggen,</L>
<L>He shalle a&yogh;eyn come this world to iuggen,</L>
<L N="1521">In bodi and soule and Godhede,</L>
<L>To deme bothe queke and dede.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 1523-96 added to the Fr.</NOTE>But fyftene dayes before the dome</L>
<L N="1524">ffyftene tokyns ther shull come.</L>
<L>The furst day the see up ryse shall</L>
<L>And stonden on hye as a wall,</L>
<L>ffourti cupetys herre i-wys</L>
<L N="1528">Then eny hill in the world is.</L>
<L>That other day heo wole i-sonkyn byn,</L>
<L>That eny mon unnethe may here i-syn.</L>
<L>The thrid day heo woll be notheles</L>
<L N="1532">As full as heo furst wes,</L>
<L>And then woll whalles and grete fysshes with fynne</L>
<L>And all other smale fysshes that byn ther-inne</L>
<L>Gedryn hem on the watur uchone;</L>
<L>But that wot no mon but God allone</L>
<L N="1537">What is the betokenyng</L>
<L>Of the loude cry and &yogh;eiyng</L>
<L>Thet heo wolleth with loude stevyn</L>
<L N="1540">&yogh;evyn and crye up to hevyn.</L>
<L>And on the fourthe day heo shall</L>
<L>With red fyre brennen alle,</L>
<L>And alle other watrys in every stede</L>
<L>Shullen brenne as red as eny glede.</L>
<L>The fyfthe day the tren that don stonde</L>
<L>And floures and erbis in uche londe,</L>
<L N="1547">Blod thei shullen blede</L>
<L>In stede of here dewe, withoute drede.</L>
<L>The sixte day byth not bold</L>
<L>Palyse ne pylere ne no strong-hold,</L>
<L>Castell, toure, boure ne halle,</L>
<L N="1552">But thei shulle to-skatur and down|falle.</L>
<L>The sevynth day the stones uchon</L>
<L>Wolle lepe to-gedre and fy&yogh;ht anon,</L>
<L N="1555">That thorwgh the fy&yogh;ht that there woll byn</L>
<L>The stones woll breke and all to-flyn.</L>
<L>The ey&yogh;hte day betokynth gret wrache,</L>
<L N="1558">All &yogh;ende the world the erthe shall quake,</L>
<L>And men wolle flyn into uche hurne,</L>
<L>The erthequake shall be so loude and sturne;</L>
<L>And on thylke dredfull byttur day<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 1561-6 taken from the Fr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1562">The pepull woll crye weloway,</L>
<L>And sey to monteynes: 'falleth on us!</L>
<L>Erthe to-clyf and hyde us,</L>
<L N="1565">That we this fere and erthequake ne syn,</L>
<L>How wroth oure creature woll byn.'</L>
<L>ffor in alle hye hevyn-blys</L>
<L N="1568">Non so holi ne so good is,</L>
<L>Patryarch, apostelle, ne martire,</L>
<L>Confessor, ne virgine with so feyre attyre,</L>
<L>Prynce, potestate, ne angell,</L>
<L N="1572">Ne non so bry&yogh;ht archangelle,</L>
<L>That nold never synne done,</L>
<L>But he shall dredyn a&yogh;eyne that dome;</L>
<L>ffulle sore mowe heo then dreden</L>
<L>That byth alle full of synfull deden!</L>
<L N="1577">The nynthe day alle the valeis that byth,</L>
<L>And the hylles that we so hye syth,</L>
<L>Shull be made smethe and playn,</L>
<L N="1580">And into here kynde shull they not turne a&yogh;eyn.</L>
<L>The tenthe day shull all manere men</L>
<L>Gon out of here holes and of here den,</L>
<L>And renne abowte as they were wod,</L>
<L N="1584">As they cowthen nowther evyll ne good,</L>
<L>Ne thawgh here hert shulde to-breke,</L>
<L>On word my&yogh;ht not oon with other speke.</L>
<L>The elevynth day the mone and the sterres alle</L>
<L N="1588">Shulle adown to erthe falle.</L>
<L>The twelfthe day the bones of uche ded mon</L>
<L N="1590">Shull come togedre uchon,</L>
<L>Thawgh they be dryvyn nere so wyde,</L>
<L>At here byrynes<NOTE PLACE="marg">From A.-S. byrgen</NOTE> here soules they shull abyde.</L>
<L>The threttenyth day all maner men</L>
<L>Shull dyen anoon that lyven then,</L>
<L N="1595">That heo mowe togedre with other aryse</L>
<L>And takyn here dome of God ry&yogh;ht|wyse.</L>
<L>The fourteneth day, ther may no thyng werne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">In Fr., 1597-1618 follow after 1646.</NOTE></L>
<L>But alle the world on fyre shall berne,
<PB REF="00000412.tif" N="404"></L>
<L>Hevyn and erthe shull byn aleyde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. enflambirunt</NOTE></L>
<L N="1600">And the foure elementes shull be un|teyede;</L>
<L>ffor thike fyre shall clansyn the eyre</L>
<L>And makyn all thyng bry&yogh;ht and feyre,</L>
<L N="1603">And all the world shan (!) i-clansed byn;</L>
<L>But watur ther shall no mon eft i-syn,</L>
<L>Ne never fyre in the world me syth,</L>
<L>When that fyre shall ben aquenchith.</L>
<L>The fyftenethe day God wol taken</L>
<L N="1608">Hevyn and erthe, and all hit newe maken,</L>
<L>Not otherweys then hem beforen wrowght&mdash;</L>
<L>Loke thou thenke ne wylle hit nowght&mdash;</L>
<L N="1611">But he wole newen hem i-wys</L>
<L>In bettur state then heo weryn i-wys.</L>
<L>Ther-aftur Ihesu wole his dome demyn.</L>
<L>The angeles shulle come and blowe the bemyn.</L>
<L>ffurst shull in body and soule aryse</L>
<L>Alle that dyedyn in his servise,</L>
<L N="1617">And all that eke that shull to the blysse fonde</L>
<L>Shul furst aryse and on the ry&yogh;ht syde stonde.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">In Fr. 1619-46 follow after 1522.</NOTE>Then shall Ihesu come ry&yogh;ht this,</L>
<L>And his body tornen and showe to us</L>
<L N="1621">What peyne he suffred for ur sake</L>
<L>And how lodlyche he was for us i-take,</L>
<L>Wyth scorges i-betyn withoute gryth,</L>
<L>That the blode barst oute on icha lyth,</L>
<L>And how vylensli he wes ladde &yogh;et,</L>
<L>With crowne of thornes on his hed set,</L>
<L N="1627">And how he suffred that the nayles stode</L>
<L>Thorgh fete and honden into the rode,</L>
<L>And how the spere that him wonded smerte</L>
<L>Browght blod and watur from his hert;</L>
<L>And then Cryst woll clepe and calle</L>
<L N="1632">And sey: 'thus myche I suffre[d] for &yogh;ow alle.'</L>
<L>Then helpeth ther no pledyng there,</L>
<L>Ne forsakyng, ny answere;</L>
<L>Ne helpyth us ther castell ne toure,</L>
<L N="1636">Nowther palyse, halle, ne boure;</L>
<L>All thyng then shall torne to nowght</L>
<L>That is with monis hond i-wrowght.</L>
<L>Ther shull the synfull quake</L>
<L N="1640">And here tethe togedur hacke and shake.</L>
<L>Ther may segge thenne no mon</L>
<L>But that uchon shull seyn here mar|tyrdom,</L>
<L>And beforyn hym his iuggement sycorly</L>
<L N="1644">Shall byn i-wryten apertely,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> Fr.</NOTE></L>
<L>And allso his synnes ther shull be knowe</L>
<L>Tofore alle maner men bothe hie and lowe.<NOTE PLACE="marg">In Fr. here follow 1651-6, 1597-1618.</NOTE></L>
<L>Then woll swete Ihesu to hem be-syn</L>
<L N="1648">That shull that day i-saved byn,</L>
<L>And sey with mylde stevyn and swete:</L>
<L>"When I was hongry &yogh;e &yogh;eve me mete,</L>
<L>When I was afurst &yogh;e &yogh;eve me dryng,</L>
<L>When I was nake &yogh;e &yogh;eve me clothyng,</L>
<L N="1653">When I was herberlasse &yogh;e herberde me fayne,</L>
<L>Bothe in heete, in cold, in wynde and rayne,</L>
<L>And &yogh;e comforted me in prison eke,</L>
<L>And loked to me when I was seke:</L>
<L>Comyth, my blessed children uchon,</L>
<L>And receyvyth the blysfull ioy anon</L>
<L>That to &yogh;ow byth rewarded withoutyn endenge</L>
<L N="1660">ffro this worldis begynnyng."</L>
<L>Then shulle the blessed byn receyved<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. reysed, Fr. raui</NOTE> an hy&yogh;he</L>
<L>In hevyn to walke Ihesu ny&yogh;he.</L>
<L>And the cursede shull in erthe byn,</L>
<L N="1664">Of hevyn-blys they shull no-thyng i|syn,</L>
<L>But &yogh;et wyth the up-receyveng<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. reysyng, Fr. rauissement</NOTE> they shulle agryse</L>
<L>When the saved shull upryse,</L>
<L>So wery, so wrecched, so lodlyche,</L>
<L>I-charged with synne so hevyleche,</L>
<L N="1669">That all hevyli on the erthe they shull steke,</L>
<L>When<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. O &thorn;at? Fr. Deske</NOTE> thei heryn the domesmonis speke.</L>
<L>Wyth gret and grymfull wrathe full sone</L>
<L>Thei shull heryn a full hard dome:</L>
<L N="1673">"Goth with the develys and accurssed bestes,</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;e heded not my lawes and my hestes,</L>
<L>Into the fure that shall last for euere;</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;e han disserved here non other!"<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. 4 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>The blessed shull blysfull gon</L>
<L N="1678">In bodi and soule everichon,</L>
<L>As bry&yogh;ht as ys the sonne, withoute fayle;</L>
<L>Never hem nedeth to have travayle,</L>
<L>But ioy and blys that shall laste ever|more.</L>
<L N="1682">In good tyme the[i] were i-bore</L>
<L>That to that feste mowe takyn</L>
<L>That God wole with hem in hevyn makyn!</L>
<L>So myche ioy shall byn at theke feste,</L>
<L>That ever withouten ende shall leste:</L>
<L>&yogh;e, more ioy then hert may thenkyn,
<PB REF="00000413.tif" N="405"></L>
<L N="1688">Or eye i-syn, or &yogh;ere i-herkyn;</L>
<L>Seche ioy God hath i-grethed there</L>
<L>To hem that han loved him here.</L>
<L N="1691">And when they byth so endeles,</L>
<L>Thenne he is ary&yogh;ht Prince of Pes.</L>
<L>But theke that byth into helle i-nome,</L>
<L>Thei shull never out come,</L>
<L>And in theke stynkyng deth<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. dep</NOTE>-pytte</L>
<L N="1696">Thei shull byn i-pyned and to peyne i-knytte.</L>
<L>In gret sorewe and pyne thei byth full sore:</L>
<L>ffor thei lyvyn in wanhope evermore<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. La premiere peine si ert tristesce</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>Thei wolde dyen &yogh;ef thei my&yogh;hte,</L>
<L N="1700">But &yogh;et here soule may not thorgh ry&yogh;hte.<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 1699-1700 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>Uchon others peyne shall i-syn,</L>
<L>That here peyne shall dowble byn.</L>
<L>Another peyne they shull have of derknes,</L>
<L>With gret sore and gret hevynes.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. La tierce sera peuur</NOTE></L>
<L N="1705">And the four[th]e is fyre that may not be queynte,</L>
<L>And in stynkynge watur they shulle be dreynte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 1706-8 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>And pycche wallyng ever among.</L>
<L>Wayleway ever shall byn here song.</L>
<L>flor hidor or thidur wher-sere heo turne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. E puis hidur de ver le diable</NOTE></L>
<L N="1710">They syn the foule fynde in uche horne;</L>
<L>That he lothest were to syn,</L>
<L>He shall ever to-foryn hem byn.</L>
<L>And the stenche is over-alle there so strong,<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 1713 and 5 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>And byttur wormys there styketh among,</L>
<L>Neddris, snakys and taddis there strykyth,</L>
<L N="1716">No place shall he there i-syn that him lyketh.</L>
<L>Evermore withoutyn ende they shull be wepyng,</L>
<L>And wrynge here hondes with gret weyl|yng.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. Cruissant de denz reschinerunt</NOTE></L>
<L>Then shall the systere sey to the brother,</L>
<L N="1720">The fremed and the sybbe uchon to other:</L>
<L>"A, waryed wrecche, what<NOTE PLACE="marg">H whad</NOTE> doost thou here?</L>
<L>A-cursed be the tyme thou i-boryn were!</L>
<L>I may not for nothyng suffre the,</L>
<L>So foule thy synne stynketh on me.</L>
<L N="1725">ffor [mi]-nowne gret synne I styke in pyne,</L>
<L>But a thousonde-fold more I suffer for thyne!</L>
<L>&YOGH;e, but thou waryed wrecche forlore,</L>
<L N="1728">Accurssed be the tyme that thou were i-bore!</L>
<L>I am for-styfyd<NOTE PLACE="marg">= stifled</NOTE> among,</L>
<L>Thi synne stynketh on me so strong!"</L>
<L>Thus shall uchon to other menyn his sorewe</L>
<L N="1732">Ever withoutyn ende on evyn and morewe.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 1733-6 added.</NOTE>Thawgh the[r] sete<NOTE PLACE="marg">H the fete</NOTE> a mon for the nonys</L>
<L>And he my&yogh;ht lestyn<NOTE PLACE="marg">H leftyn</NOTE> in flesshe and bonys,</L>
<L>Half the sorewe he my&yogh;ht not telle</L>
<L N="1736">Ne the peynes that byth in helle.</L>
<L>Ther is nowther solace ne love i-wys,</L>
<L>Ther is wepyng, pyne, and sorewe withoute blys.</L>
<L N="1739">In theke foule stynkyng pytte</L>
<L>They shull in sorowe for ever be knytte.</L>
<L>Long is ever and long is oo,</L>
<L>But thei shull never come out of wo.<NOTE PLACE="marg">1741-2 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>The fynde shall here prince byn that they served er,</L>
<L N="1744">Sore withowten ende peyned they shull be ther.&mdash;</L>
<L>Ihesu in hevyn, as I seyde before,</L>
<L>Is<NOTE PLACE="marg">H As</NOTE> Pryns of Pes and shall byn ever|more;</L>
<L>His pes shall falle<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. faile</NOTE> never,</L>
<L>And his ioy and his blys that is ever.</L>
<L N="1749">Love, swetnesse, and pley</L>
<L>In hevyn hit neweth fro day to day.</L>
<L>The furst ioy that there shall byn,</L>
<L N="1752">The blessed shall hit i-syn</L>
<L>The swete face of his Lorde there,</L>
<L>His God and his shapere;</L>
<L>In his feyreship he may him showen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. s'esmirra</NOTE></L>
<L>And all thyng in him may knowen.</L>
<L>So full he shall byn of ioy and skyle</L>
<L>That he shall have all that he wyle;</L>
<L N="1759">What-sever he wylneth, withouten gabbe,</L>
<L>Be-se on him and he may it habbe.</L>
<L>Of hevyn he may i-se the wydnes,</L>
<L>The feyreshepe and the heynes;</L>
<L>And he may i-se the dereworth quene,</L>
<L>Goddis modur so bry&yogh;ht and shene,</L>
<L N="1765">The swete ma[i]de Seynt Marye,</L>
<L>And all the feyre company</L>
<L>Of angels so feyre and bry&yogh;ght,</L>
<L N="1768">They woll makyn him ioye with here my&yogh;ht;</L>
<L>The apostlys and the martiris,</L>
<L>The confessors and the virginis,</L>
<L>Alle wolle him ioy makyn&mdash;</L>
<L>Well is him that thidur may takyn!</L>
<L N="1773">And alle is fryndys he shall knowe there</L>
<L>That he hede in this world here,</L>
<L>ffadur and moder, syster and brother;
<PB REF="00000414.tif" N="406"></L>
<L>Miche ioy everichon shall make with other,</L>
<L N="1777">&YOGH;e, more then eny hert may under|stonde,</L>
<L>When thei hem syn in theke londe.</L>
<L>So my&yogh;hti thei shull byn everuchon</L>
<L>That whidur thei wolle thei may gon.<NOTE PLACE="marg">1780 and 1784 to be transp.</NOTE></L>
<L>And thei shull be so ly&yogh;ht and swyft</L>
<L>That whidur-sever they thenk they may be lyft.</L>
<L>And so slye and crafty<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. si sotils</NOTE> they shull byn alle</L>
<L N="1784">That thei shull do all thyng that in here hert doth falle.</L>
<L>And where-sere the toon the tother metyth,</L>
<L>With lovely chere thus he him gretyth:</L>
<L>'I-blessed be the Lord that the wrowght</L>
<L N="1788">And hidur to this blysse and ioy the browght!</L>
<L>I-blessed be the tyme that thou i-bore were,</L>
<L>So myche ioy I have that i se the here;</L>
<L>So myche blys I see on the</L>
<L N="1792">That all my blisse neweth me!'</L>
<L>Thet other answereth him anonry&yogh;ht:</L>
<L>'Ever i-blessed be God Allmy&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>That seche ioy hath i-&yogh;eve to the;</L>
<L N="1796">Therfore my ioy doubleth me.</L>
<L>On the I se mychelle ioy and blys,</L>
<L>That all my ioy newed is;</L>
<L>And ever here is myrthe and gret song,</L>
<L>And ever I se oure shapere among,</L>
<L N="1801">That i-like himselvyn us hath wrowght</L>
<L>And sethyn to this ioy us browght!</L>
<L>Mi ioy is doubled an hondred-fold,</L>
<L N="1804">ffor I have all that I wolde.'</L>
<L>Meche is the murthe that is at that feste,</L>
<L>That ever withoutyn ende shall leste.</L>
<L>He that is lest feyre there</L>
<L>Shall shyne as the sonne for ere<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. so clere</NOTE>;</L>
<L>No nyd is thenne that sonne<NOTE PLACE="marg">H sinne</NOTE> be there i-wys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">v. 1809-10 to be transp.</NOTE></L>
<L>They shull<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. That shall</NOTE> shyne seven-sythe bry&yogh;hter then heo now is.</L>
<L>When all thei shull be so bry&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="1812">Then by alle maner of ry&yogh;ht</L>
<L>He most be feyre and bry&yogh;ht and more clere</L>
<L>That more deserved that ioy here.</L>
<L>So mony wonynges me may ther i-syn,</L>
<L N="1816">And gret compani of angels that woll ther byn</L>
<L>In the ioy so mony and so ryche:</L>
<L>In diverse ioyes never oon other i-lyche.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The French text has 54 vv. more at the end.</NOTE></L>
<L>In which ioyes God, of his hi&yogh; grace,</L>
<L>In hevyn &yogh;eve &yogh;ow alle a place. Amen.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Here endyth the Castel of Love,<LB>Made i-wys for lewde mennis behove.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">

<PB REF="00000415.tif" N="407">
<HEAD>APPENDIX TO No. XXXVIII.</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="appendix">
<HEAD>The Myrour of lewed men.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Edited before, but very imperfectly, by M. Cooke, <I>R. Grosse|teste Carmina anglo-normannica</I>, Caxton Soc. 1852.</NOTE> A free version of Robert Grosseteste's <I>Chateau d'Amour</I>, by a Monk of Sawley, in Yorkshire. <I>MS. Egerton</I> 927 (<I>Yorkshire dialect</I>).</HEAD>
<P><NOTE PLACE="foot">This introduction is written in red. In the MS. final t, f, g have a thin tag (t, f), which I omit; ll is given by ll, h by h, d by d, k by k; don may be doun and done.&mdash;The MS., 8, vellum, written in the latter half of the 14th cent., only con|tains this poem, in 28 foll., each page &agrave; 24 lines; it is written in the large, clear northern type, is carefully executed, and is most likely a fair copy of the poet's own MS. It must, how|ever, be noted that the scribe frequently leaves out single words. "The Myrour of lewed men" is the title given at the end. The poem can hardly be called a translation: it condenses the narrative, adds from other sources, and introduces, not very happily, passages treating of points of Christian doctrine (10 Commandments, &amp;c.).</NOTE>IN the name of the fader and the son &amp; the haly gast. Here begynnes a romance of englische of the begynnyng of the world and of al that a lewed man has nede for to knawe for hele of soule. this romance turned [a]<NOTE PLACE="marg">name om.?</NOTE> Munk of sallay out of a frenche romance that sire Robert, Bisschope a<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. of</NOTE> ly|coln, made; and eked mekel therto, as him thoght spedeful to edificacion and swettenes of deuocion, and lering of lewed men. And here is no thing sayd bot as haly writ says and grete doctours: and therfor thou that redys this, and any comfort has ther-Inne, pray god be way of charite to haue mercy on him that turned it in this maner. And if thou couayt to loue god and to plese him, take [this] mirrour and loke oft ther-Inne.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHo-so wele thinkes, wele may say,</L>
<L>ffor of gode thoghtes comes gode dedes ay.</L>
<L>God send vs thoght to his plesyng,</L>
<L N="4">In whos fre wil hynges all thyng.
<PB REF="00000416.tif" N="408"></L>
<L>He is god and lord of my&yogh;tes mast,</L>
<L>The fader and sone and haligast;</L>
<L>In godhed are thise persones thre,</L>
<L N="8">And all are on god in trinite;</L>
<L>None is othir of thise persons thre,</L>
<L>Bot alle are on god and ay sal be.</L>
<L>Oure mede is to trowe this with stable thoght,</L>
<L N="12">Al-be-hit that mannes skil proues it noght;</L>
<L>Bot when we sal se god clerly,</L>
<L>Than sal we knawe this witerly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Of the begynnyng of the world.</HEAD>
<L>GOd in vj dayes made bothe erthe &amp; heuen,</L>
<L N="16">And, to make haliday, cessed at the seuen.</L>
<L>Heuen was occupid with angeles kynde,</L>
<L>Euermore on god for to haue thair mynde&mdash;</L>
<L>Bot many thorgh pride fel in to helle,</L>
<L N="20">Thar sal thei all with-outen ende dwelle.</L>
<L>Bothe sunne and mone [mor] bri&yogh;t thai ware</L>
<L>Then seuenfold then thay now are,</L>
<L>And all erthli thing more vertuous,</L>
<L N="24">Bi-for Adam thurgh synne was vicious;</L>
<L>And ilk a best sul[d] haue bowed to mannes will,</L>
<L>Had he neuer bi way of synne don none ill.</L>
<L>When god had the world so parfit made</L>
<L N="28">That no partie of hit defaut hade,</L>
<L>Then of erth he made Adam, of man age,</L>
<L>To his liknes in saule he was &amp; his ymage.</L>
<L>Of a rib of Adam syde, when he lay slepand,</L>
<L N="32">God made Eue, that sho to him suld ay be kepand.</L>
<L>Of on god made al man-kynde, for ilkon suld loue other</L>
<L>And non til other do wrong mor then til his brother.<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 33-4 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>What lyf my&yogh;t mor<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. mor ioyful?</NOTE> be schewed to man in charite</L>
<L N="36">Then in saule make him lik to the haly trinite,</L>
<L>Make him lord of al the world, ful of vertue&yogh;, &amp; wise,</L>
<L>Make him eir of heuen-blis &amp; sette him in paradis,</L>
<L>Thare he and all that come of him my&yogh;t leue with-outen deyng,</L>
<L>If thay vse the frut of lif &amp; kepe wel godes biddyng.
<PB REF="00000417.tif" N="409"></L>
<L N="41">Of all the trees of paradis bi goddis biddyng thei suld ete,</L>
<L>But the frut of the tre of wetyng of gode &amp; ille thei suld lete;</L>
<L>What tyme as thei ete of that, thai suld forfet thair heritage</L>
<L N="44">&amp; be oblischid to deth &amp; helle-payne, thai &amp; all thair lynage.</L>
<L>Bot, if thai had kepid wel all goddis biddyng,</L>
<L>Thai suld haue leued ioyfully, &amp; all thair ofspring,</L>
<L>Til thai had ben tan til heuen, to fille that fair place</L>
<L N="48">That thurgh pride of lucifer &amp; his feres voyde was;</L>
<L>Thare thai suld haue had mor ioye than hert may thenk or tunge telle,</L>
<L>&amp; neuer non of thair kynd suld haue suffride payn of helle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Of the losyng of the world thurgh synne.</HEAD>
<L>WHen adam &amp; eue sesyn hade in the blis of paradys,</L>
<L N="52">The fende, for he hade that ioye lost, enuy had to thair delice.</L>
<L>Then he come in neddir liknesse to eue with a wommans face,</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "whi bad god &yogh;e suld no&yogh;t ete of all trees that ther was?"</L>
<L>"Of all the trees," quad eue, "that thar is, we may ete at oure liking,</L>
<L>Out-tan on that is forbod, paraunter for dred of deyng."</L>
<L N="57">Than sayde the fend: "&yogh;e sall no&yogh;t deye therfore, god wot it wele,</L>
<L>Bot as god<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. godis, cf. v. 576.</NOTE> sall &yogh;e be, knawand bothe gode &amp; yuell."</L>
<L>Eue sagh that the frut was gode &amp; ful gretly lykand:</L>
<L>Sho tastid sone, &amp; gaf therof till her owen husband.</L>
<L N="61">Adam wolde no&yogh;t greue his wyf, bot sone he ete with hir.</L>
<L>Alas, that synne oblisched vs al til wikkid hell-fire!</L>
<L>Sone thai were put fro that place to sorow &amp; to care,</L>
<L N="64">That neuer my&yogh;t no creature recouer it mare.
<PB REF="00000418.tif" N="410"></L>
<L>Alle thing vnder heuen made was to mannes solace,</L>
<L>And therfor, syn he synned, all thai lesse vertue has.</L>
<L>All man-kynde for-thi was put to thraldom of the fende,</L>
<L N="68">And bounden all to his prison ay with-outen ende.</L>
<L>How may thrall with ri&yogh;t clayme a thing of fre heritage?</L>
<L>With his lord may he no&yogh;t mote, ne non of his lynage.</L>
<L>Thus was all this world lost; ther was no help in creature.</L>
<L N="72">Bot god wist what was his wil, that of all thing has cure.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Of the ten commaundements.<NOTE PLACE="marg">This passage is added to the Fr.</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>THen with the x commandements god forbed all synne</L>
<L>&amp; taght man how he my&yogh;t him gret mede wynne.</L>
<L>The first is, to worschipe on god and no mo.</L>
<L N="76">This biddyng sal be vnderstanden so</L>
<L>That it forbedes all mamettrie,</L>
<L>And also all maner of sorcerie.</L>
<L>Mammentrie is, to do creature that honour</L>
<L N="80">That thou suld do all-onely to thi creatour,</L>
<L>That is, worschipe him for him-self ouer all other thing.</L>
<L>A seint sal thou worschipe for he is his derlyng.</L>
<L>Ymages in the kirk that thou on lokes,</L>
<L N="84">Are to the as to the clerk are his gode bokes:</L>
<L>Thou sal not worschipe thaim bot for thair<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. that?</NOTE> sake</L>
<L>That thei bringe to thi mynd thi prayer to make.</L>
<L>The second is: tak not the name of thi god in vayn.</L>
<L>Ilk fals oth, vnleful &amp; idel<NOTE PLACE="marg">swering om.?</NOTE> is ther-agayn;</L>
<L N="89">He is ay in peril of synne dedly</L>
<L>That sweres bi goddis hert or any party.</L>
<L>This biddyng forbedes alle heresy,</L>
<L N="92">And also all feyned and fals ypocrisy.</L>
<L>The thrid is: thou sal kepe wel thi haliday.</L>
<L>That is thus mekel openly for to say:</L>
<L>Put fro the synne &amp; bodely werkyng,</L>
<L N="96">And gif the to god with hertly prayng.</L>
<L>Tak kepe here that on halyday marchandyse</L>
<L>Lettes man oft of goddes seruise.</L>
<L>The ferd is: worschipe thi fader &amp; thi moder.
<PB REF="00000419.tif" N="411"></L>
<L>Be way of kynde thes two may no&yogh;t be the to dere;</L>
<L N="101">To thaim ogh thou buxumnes &amp; honour,</L>
<L>And also in thair [nede] help and socour.</L>
<L>And haly kirk is thi moder gastly,</L>
<L N="104">And the keper of thi saule thi fadir, sot[h]ly;</L>
<L>And who so is thi warldly lord or thi kyng,</L>
<L>Is taken for thi fadir in this byddyng.</L>
<L>The fift is: thou salt no man sle vnlaghfully.</L>
<L N="108">That is to say, nother bodely ne gastly;</L>
<L>ffor ille ensaumple, hate, &amp; bakbityng</L>
<L>Are ille to thi neghbur gastly sleyng;</L>
<L>Hurtyng bothe gastly &amp; bodely is forbed,</L>
<L N="112">And wernyng of mete to the pour in peril of ded.</L>
<L>The sext is: thou sal don non auoutrie.</L>
<L>And this forbedes all maner of lecherie,</L>
<L>Bot it be betwix the &amp; thi wyf with gode entent,</L>
<L N="116">ffor to kepe the lagh of god in that sacrament.</L>
<L>The seuent biddes that thou sal no thing stele</L>
<L>Ne non othir mannes gode agayns his wille dele.</L>
<L>This forbedes fals cautels, deceit, and maystrie,</L>
<L N="120">That mas many to loise his gode vnri&yogh;twisly;</L>
<L>And who so harmes any man in this maner,</L>
<L>Sal no&yogh;t be saf, bot he make asseth at his power.</L>
<L>The aghtend is: bere agayn no man fals witnes,</L>
<L>And in tyme &amp; maner skilful layne thou sothfastnes</L>
<L N="125">When it is no&yogh;t lefful &amp; nedful to say,</L>
<L>And al lesyng eschue as wele as thou may.</L>
<L>The neyghend is: thi neghbur hous sal thou no&yogh;t coueit.</L>
<L N="128">In this is forboden assent to wrang &amp; deceit.</L>
<L>The tend is: thou sall no&yogh;t &yogh;erne another mannes wyf,</L>
<L>His seruant ne his other thing, that may helpe his lyue.</L>
<L>Here is forbeden alle maner of wikked couetyse</L>
<L N="132">That myght harme thi neghbur on any-maner wise.</L>
<L>If slik thoght come to thi hert, thou sal no&yogh;t assent,</L>
<L>Bot euer agayn-stande with gode auysement:</L>
<L>And then sal thou no&yogh;t falle in dedly synne,</L>
<L N="136">Bot ilk a tyme a croun of gret ioye wynne.</L>
<L>Thurgh this ten thou may wynne gret ioye, &amp; eschewe payn.
<PB REF="00000420.tif" N="412"></L>
<L>Bot more help mot open heuen-&yogh;ates the agayn.</L>
<L>Who-so suld agayn blis to man<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. mankynd?</NOTE> wynne,</L>
<L N="140">Him behoued be a man that my&yogh;t no&yogh;t synne,</L>
<L>And he most ay fulfille alle goddes wille</L>
<L>And neuer in thoght, word, ne dede don non ille;</L>
<L>Slik on my&yogh;t, if he wald, a gode raunson wage</L>
<L N="144">And bye agayn both man &amp;<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &amp; mannis?</NOTE> heritage.</L>
<L>Bot slik a man in erth my&yogh;t neuer be made,</L>
<L>If he of all creatours all vertues hade.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Of the restoring of the warld.</HEAD>
<L><B>A</B> Kyng ther was of souerayne worthines,</L>
<L N="148">fful of mercy &amp; wysdam &amp; all godenes.</L>
<L>A sone he hadde, knewe all his wille,</L>
<L>And my&yogh;t and wald al hit fulfille.</L>
<L>Thai were ay bothe al on substaunce,</L>
<L N="152">And betwix theim was no distaunce;</L>
<L>What as the fader wald haue amendyd,</L>
<L>By his sone godely hit suld be endid.</L>
<L>ffour doghters hade this grete kyng,</L>
<L N="156">That fulfillid all his likyng;</L>
<L>Thai were of his substance ilkon,</L>
<L>And all that substance was bot on.</L>
<L>Thai foure doghters thurgh comune assent</L>
<L N="160">Parformed al his iugement.</L>
<L>Bot if thise foure vse ay wele thair myght,</L>
<L>May neuer no rewme be rewled right.</L>
<L>The names of thaim with-outen les</L>
<L N="164">Are: Mercy, Sothfastnes, Right, &amp; Pes.</L>
<L>Mercy, when sho hade parceyued</L>
<L>How all man-kynde was deceyued</L>
<L>Thurgh the fende that be foul treson</L>
<L N="168">Has geten him to his prison</L>
<L>And euermore with enuy</L>
<L>Will torment him as enemy,</L>
<L>Sho was so stered to compassion</L>
<L N="172">That sho wald deliuere that prison.
<PB REF="00000421.tif" N="413"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Here spak Mercy.</HEAD>
<L>THus til her fader sho began</L>
<L>To pray him for synful man:</L>
<L>"Dere fader, kyng of my&yogh;tes mast,</L>
<L N="176">Thi doghter y am, wele thou wast,</L>
<L>fful of myknes, swetnes and pite;</L>
<L>Dere fader, all thes haue y of the.</L>
<L>Now here my praier for this prison,</L>
<L N="180">That he may be put til his raunson.</L>
<L>His enemys with thair falshede</L>
<L>Has put him to so gret nede</L>
<L>That he may neuer saued be,</L>
<L N="184">Bot thurgh mercy and gret pite.</L>
<L>Thair falshed may gretly letted be,</L>
<L>And that prison be &yogh;olden to me.</L>
<L>Dere fader, mercyful is thi name,</L>
<L N="188">And y thin eldest doghter ame;</L>
<L>That y were thi doghter, my&yogh;t y neuer say</L>
<L>Bot y wald euer for sinful man pray.</L>
<L>Thi mercy thurgh ri&yogh;t sall he haue,</L>
<L N="192">And thi gret mercy sal him saue.</L>
<L>I sal euer crie mercy to the</L>
<L>Til that wreched prison deliuerd be.</L>
<L>Dere fader, my praier may no&yogh;t be lette,</L>
<L N="196">ffor y am ouer all thi werkes to sette."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Here spak Sothfastnes.</HEAD>
<L>WHen the second sister, sothfastnes,</L>
<L>Hade herd, mercy thurgh here swetnes</L>
<L>Wold sone bye the synful prison agayn</L>
<L N="200">That sho hade iugged to ay-lastand payne,</L>
<L>Sho sayde: "dere fader, thi doghter am y,</L>
<L>As ner sib to the as is my sister mercy.</L>
<L>Mercy of no thing may wele gife the dome,</L>
<L N="204">Bot if y, sothfastnes, with her come;</L>
<L>Hir praier may no&yogh;t be herd of the</L>
<L>Bot if hit acordand be with me.</L>
<L>If all hir prayers suld ay be herd,</L>
<L N="208">Neuer no shrewe for the sul be ferd,
<PB REF="00000422.tif" N="414"></L>
<L>Ne neuer punist no wikkednes:</L>
<L>That is gretly agayns ri&yogh;twisnes;</L>
<L>ffor he suld haue no mercy</L>
<L N="212">That is dampned ri&yogh;twysly."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Here spak ri&yogh;twysnes.</HEAD>
<L>THen ri&yogh;twisnes, the third sister, sayde:</L>
<L>"Dere fader, in me is all dome laide;</L>
<L>I ne may no&yogh;t spare to say to the,</L>
<L N="216">All that sothfastnes telles to me</L>
<L>I mot dele to euer-ilk-one,</L>
<L>Gode or ill after thei haue done.</L>
<L>Thi wikkid seruant is in prison,</L>
<L N="220">As he was demed with gret reson.</L>
<L>I may no&yogh;t fro this sentence vary</L>
<L>Bot I to ri&yogh;t wald be contrary.</L>
<L>Mercy ne pite is non<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. man?</NOTE> worthi,</L>
<L N="224">ffor that he lost thaim wilfully."&mdash;</L>
<L>Alas catyf prison, now has thou no frende</L>
<L>Bot mercy, that praies for a gode ende!</L>
<L>Sothfastnes has accused the,</L>
<L N="228">And ri&yogh;twisnes has dampned the;</L>
<L>Thou &amp; all that of the come</L>
<L>To helle-fire has herd &yogh;our dome.</L>
<L>Thin enemy gret stired the to trespas,</L>
<L N="232">And ri&yogh;twisnes of the no mercy has,</L>
<L>And mercy may no&yogh;t be herd.</L>
<L>Ther-for pece may be ferd.</L>
<L>When no forgifnes may be,</L>
<L N="236">Thai may no&yogh;t dwelle in cuntre.</L>
<L>All mankynde dyes and is put to payn,</L>
<L>Bot Enok and Ely that sal come agayn.</L>
<L>Gret dole is to think on this,</L>
<L N="240">How al mankinde fordone is;</L>
<L>Sothfastnes &amp; ri&yogh;t has geuen thair iuggement,</L>
<L>Bot mercy &amp; pees were no&yogh;t of that assent.</L>
<L>If all go bi reddure of ri&yogh;t &amp; sothfastnes,</L>
<L N="244">How sall mercy and pes shewe the kinges godenes?</L>
<L>If al be thaim one deme sothfastnes &amp; ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Mercy, pete &amp; pece sal loise al thair my&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000423.tif" N="415"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Here spake Pece.</HEAD>
<L>NOw pece to the king begynnes to say:</L>
<L>"ffaire gode dere fader, thou has loued me ay,</L>
<L N="249">Thou art endles of pece prince &amp; also king,</L>
<L>And euer in pece salt thou be, for ther [is] thi dwellyng;</L>
<L>If y for debate suld away fle,</L>
<L N="252">Thou suld haue no place lykand to the.</L>
<L>Mi two dere susters now haue thai me forsaken,</L>
<L>And mercy with thaim two &yogh;it haue thai not taken;</L>
<L>With-outen vs thai be thaim-self han gyuen a iuggement,</L>
<L>That suld haue ben gyuen trewly with comen<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. c&omacr;e, r. commune?</NOTE> assent.</L>
<L>Ther-fore hit sal no&yogh;t ben of recorde</L>
<L>Til we four ben all of on acorde.</L>
<L>All erthly thing is made for gode pece,</L>
<L N="260">And with-outen<NOTE PLACE="marg">outen on the margin.</NOTE> hit may ben non ese.</L>
<L>Iustisry is neuermore nedeful</L>
<L>Bot when it is to pece spedeful.</L>
<L>How suld right &amp; sothfastnes auaile</L>
<L N="264">When thai wil no&yogh;t call me to thair counsaile,</L>
<L>Ne mercy my sister that ay so gode is,</L>
<L>That withouten hir no gilt amendid is<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. nis</NOTE>?</L>
<L>Ther-fore out of cuntre wil I fle</L>
<L N="268">Til my thre sisters acorded be.</L>
<L>If sothfastnes mete with mercy,</L>
<L>Then sall kis ri&yogh;twisnes &amp; y.</L>
<L>The prison calles euer vppon mercy,</L>
<L N="272">And mercy for him wil ay to the, king, cry</L>
<L>Til for him be paied al his raunson</L>
<L>And he be deliuered out of prison."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Here spak the Kinges sone.</HEAD>
<L>NOw the kinges sone has wele sene</L>
<L N="276">That debate is his sisters betwene</L>
<L>And hit may no&yogh;t wele be amesed</L>
<L>Bot in to his hande it be sesed.</L>
<L>He says to that my&yogh;ty kyng anon:</L>
<L N="280">"Dere fader, thou and I are all on,</L>
<L>On substance, on wysdam, &amp; on powere,</L>
<L>And god, while the holy gast is oure fere.
<PB REF="00000424.tif" N="416"></L>
<L>All on in substance if we be,</L>
<L N="284">Neuer-the-les in persons we are thre.</L>
<L>Thurgh me the warld thou made of no&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Thurgh me agayn let hit be boght!</L>
<L>Mercy has so mekel moued me</L>
<L N="288">That of that prison I haue pite.</L>
<L>Dere fader, I wil don al thi wille</L>
<L>And punysch al that is don ill:</L>
<L>I sal take the clething of that wretchid prison</L>
<L N="292">And priuily for him sal I paye raunson:</L>
<L>Of his kynde wil I become</L>
<L>And for him wil y take dome;</L>
<L>More payn then ri&yogh;t &amp; sothfastnes wold haue</L>
<L N="296">Wil y suffre, that prison for to saue.</L>
<L>On this maner sothfastnes and mercy</L>
<L>Sal sone be made gode frendes verraly;</L>
<L>Also pece and ri&yogh;twisnes</L>
<L N="300">Thai sal kis with gret swetnes."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Here spak the autour.</HEAD>
<L>WHo-so redes this romance,</L>
<L>Trowe in god with on substance.</L>
<L>Bot on is god &amp; persons thre,</L>
<L N="304">Non othir thing in god may be.</L>
<L>ffour sisters that we before rede,</L>
<L>Are foure vertues in the godhede:</L>
<L>To foure doghters thai haue lyknyng,</L>
<L N="308">ffor thai procure all gode doyng;</L>
<L>Bot all thai are on god of my&yogh;tes mast,</L>
<L>He is fader and sone and haly gast.</L>
<L>If thou trowe this wele &amp; stedfastly,</L>
<L N="312">Thou may haue mede ay-lastan[d]ly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Here spak the king.<NOTE PLACE="marg">This passage is added.</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>THe kyng has herd his awen sones speche,</L>
<L>That of all the warld is a god leche;</L>
<L>"Dere sone," he says, "thurgh the I made all thing,</L>
<L N="316">And all the warld hynges in thi keping;</L>
<L>Thou, &amp; the haly gast, with me</L>
<L>Dose all gode dede that done sal be;
<PB REF="00000425.tif" N="417"></L>
<L>Oure dede may neuer departid be,</L>
<L N="320">ffor all on god in kynde are we thre.</L>
<L>All only thou sal take manhede.</L>
<L>Bot all we thre sall do the dede,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as two virgyns clethes the third</L>
<L N="324">And &yogh;it none of thaim bot on is cled.</L>
<L>Dere sone, this was oure al thre<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. althre?</NOTE> purpos &amp; curage</L>
<L>When we made man to oure liknes &amp; ymage;</L>
<L>This hight y to Abraham and to dauid,</L>
<L N="328">And my prophetes acorded ther-with.</L>
<L>If mankynd sal out of his prison wynne,</L>
<L>A man mot for him dye that has no-maner synne,</L>
<L>That is of my&yogh;t to ryse fro dede to the lyue,</L>
<L N="332">And his with him out of prison ryue;</L>
<L>And siche my&yogh;t ther be neuer non</L>
<L>Bot he were bothe god &amp; man.</L>
<L>Dere sone, if thou wil dye &amp; suffre payne,</L>
<L N="336">Bothe aungel &amp; mankynde may be ful fayne.</L>
<L>That souerayne grace and meknes</L>
<L>Sall be so ful of swetnes,</L>
<L>That neuer may man wele haue in his mynnyng</L>
<L N="340">Bot he be sterid to loue the ouer al thing,</L>
<L>And titter be reson his hert suld brest</L>
<L>Then he for any thing suld breken thi hest."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Of ysaies prophecies.</HEAD>
<L>Off ihesu crist telles ysay</L>
<L N="344">To all mankynde verrayly:</L>
<L>How a child is born til vs,</L>
<L>And a sone is gyuen til vs,</L>
<L>His name sal be callid wonderful,</L>
<L N="348">Counsellour, &amp; god, &amp; strenghtful,</L>
<L>ffader of the warld that sal come,</L>
<L>And prince of pece sal be his nome.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Here spake the autour.</HEAD>
<L>Iff any best in shap passed cours of kynde,</L>
<L N="352">A wonder in that wald many man fynde;</L>
<L>Bot if a parfit man were a parfit as,</L>
<L>Mikel more meruayl wald man say it was;
<PB REF="00000426.tif" N="418"></L>
<L>Bot more maruayl may who so can</L>
<L N="356">How verraily is on bothe god &amp; man.</L>
<L>ffor he wald saue mankynde that fouly was lorn,</L>
<L>Child of a nerthly woman wald he be born.</L>
<L>Syn god in erth for loue of man wald mak his halle,</L>
<L N="360">Nede it was to make it best &amp; fairest of alle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; How ihesus entred in to a castil.</HEAD>
<L>THer-for a castel has the king made at his devys,</L>
<L>That thar<NOTE PLACE="marg">= dar</NOTE> neuer drede assaut of any enemys;</L>
<L>He sette hit on a whit roche thik &amp; hegh,</L>
<L N="364">With gode dykes al aboute, depe and dregh.</L>
<L>Men may neuer with no craft this castil doun myne,</L>
<L>Ne may neuer do harme to hit no-maner engyne.</L>
<L>This castil is euer ful of loue &amp; of grace,</L>
<L N="368">To al that any nede has, socour &amp; solace.</L>
<L>ffour toures ay hit has &amp; kernels fair,</L>
<L>Thre bailliees al-aboute that may no&yogh;t apair.</L>
<L>Nouther hert may wele thinke ne tung may wel telle</L>
<L N="372">Al the bounte &amp; the bewte of this ilk castell!</L>
<L>Seuen barbicans are sette so sekirly aboute</L>
<L>That no maner of shoting may greue fro with-oute.</L>
<L>This castel is paynted with-out with thre-maner colours:</L>
<L>Rede brennand colour is a-boue toward the fair tours,</L>
<L N="377">Meyne colour is ymyddes of ynde &amp; of blewe,</L>
<L>Grene colour be the ground, that neuer changes hewe.</L>
<L>Thes colours both<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. beth.</NOTE> [fer] &amp; nere castes so mekil li&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="380">That, when men behaldes thaim, comfort mekil thair si&yogh;t.</L>
<L>The castel al with-in, who-so may hit knawe,</L>
<L>Ay is blaunched als whit as any dryuen snawe.</L>
<L>ffour fair stremes in hit out of a welle springes</L>
<L N="384">ffro myddes the hegh tour, thai fille the dykinges;</L>
<L>So fair and so gode that liquour ther is</L>
<L>That he that drank oght therof my&yogh;t haue mekel blis.</L>
<L>A chaier of yuor ther was sette in this ilk tour,</L>
<L>With seuen grees vpward, with worschipe &amp; gret honour;</L>
<L N="389">Was neuer non half so fair in this warld sene,</L>
<L>Ne neuer non so semly hade prince ne quene;
<PB REF="00000427.tif" N="419"></L>
<L>Hit was made sotilly, &amp; al be compas cast,</L>
<L N="392">The raynbowe enuyround it al stedefast.</L>
<L>The kynges sone has made it for his awne se&mdash;</L>
<L>Was ther neuer non so fair ne neuer-more sal be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; What betokenes this castil.</HEAD>
<L>THis castil of solas &amp; of socour</L>
<L N="396">Is hir blissed body that bar oure saueour;</L>
<L>Hit was made for refuyt to all manes kynde&mdash;</L>
<L>Who-so fles ther-to, socour sal he fynde.</L>
<L N="399">The roche whit &amp; fair with his stablenes</L>
<L>Is the hert of hir in al halynes,</L>
<L>That sette hir to serue god with-outen any drede</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">The next leaves are misplaced.</NOTE>In souerayne clene meknes &amp; clene maydenhede.<MILESTONE N="14" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The grene colour bi the ground, that wil so wele last,</L>
<L N="404">Is the treuth of oure lady, that ay was stedefast.</L>
<L>The meyne colour in the myddest of this castil walle</L>
<L>Was stable hope to come to grace, that saue mankynd sall.</L>
<L>The rede colour abouen, brennand in the si&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="408">Was brennand loue of god &amp; man, that gyues mykil li&yogh;t.</L>
<L>No wonder if<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. of</NOTE> this castil ware ful whit with-Inne,</L>
<L>ffor the hert of that may was neuer foulyd with synne.</L>
<L>The four toures gret &amp; strong, that fair were to se,</L>
<L N="412">Ware gastly strenght &amp; sobernes, ri&yogh;t &amp; sutilte;</L>
<L>Thes four vertues stekes out al maner of wykkednes</L>
<L>And kepes fast with-ynne al that is godnes.</L>
<L>The baillies, on ay with-ynne a nother in thre stage,</L>
<L N="416">Are clene maydenhed, &amp; moderhed, &amp; in<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. in?</NOTE> trewe spousage;</L>
<L>Woman with thes thre bot seint mary was ther neuer non;</L>
<L>Bot who-so sal be sauf of synne, of thes he most haue on.</L>
<L>Seuen barbicans fair seuen vertues calle we,</L>
<L N="420">That in oure lady suffred no vice for to be:</L>
<L>ffor gret meknes in hir hert venquist ay al pride;</L>
<L>And hir gret charite enuy my&yogh;t not abyde;</L>
<L>Hir discrete abstinens fordid al glotonye;
<PB REF="00000428.tif" N="420"></L>
<L N="424">And hir clene maydenhed suffred no lecherie;</L>
<L>Wikkid couetyse in hir hert my&yogh;t neuer dwelle,</L>
<L>ffor wilful pouert in hir hert keped the castil;</L>
<L>Pacience in hir hert euer was so prest</L>
<L N="428">That synne of wrath ther-in my&yogh;t neuer haue rest;</L>
<L>Ther was so mekil in hir hert of comfort gastly</L>
<L>That ther my&yogh;t neuer synne of slewth dwelle ther-by.</L>
<L>The fair welle in the castil that filles ay the dykes,</L>
<L N="432">Is grace in goddes moder that synful man ay likes.</L>
<L>Thou that myster has of grace, go to this spring-welle;</L>
<L>Who so help has of hir, sal neuer go to helle.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 435-446 freely added.</NOTE>Make the dykes of meknes &amp; of gode wille</L>
<L N="436">And four stremes of that grace sal the sone fille:</L>
<L>On streme euermore sal the clene wasch of synne that is past,</L>
<L>Another agayn temptacion sal make the stedefast,</L>
<L>The thirde sal stere the to do werkes of charite,</L>
<L N="440">And the ferd sal bere the to blis that ay sal be.</L>
<L>This welle is euermore springand mercy &amp; pite;</L>
<L>If thou haue no part therof, it is al lange on the.</L>
<L>The trone of yuor is the saule of oure swete lady;</L>
<L N="444">Seuen grees that lys therto, are werkes of mercy;</L>
<L>The raynbowe that bendes ouer with his colours thre,</L>
<L>Is the my&yogh;t that couers hir of the haly trinite.</L>
<L>No wonder if this castel were ful fair in si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>When god, the sonne of ri&yogh;twisnes, wald ther-in li&yogh;t!</L>
<L N="449">He come thurgh the cloise &yogh;ate, &amp; when he went clois it was;</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as the bri&yogh;t sonne-beme comes &amp; goos thurgh the glas.<MILESTONE N="15" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al that man nede has of [is] in this ilk castell;</L>
<L N="452">He that help has of hit, has ynogh of wele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Here spak the autour.</HEAD>
<L>GEntil lady of this castell,</L>
<L>Let me my myscheue to the telle.</L>
<L>Moder of mercy &amp; qwene of pite,</L>
<L N="456">To synful man thou art ay avowe:</L>
<L>Ther-for at thi &yogh;ates now y lye,</L>
<L>Thi help and mercy for to crye;
<PB REF="00000429.tif" N="421"></L>
<L>Mercy sal y fast crie befor this louely tour,</L>
<L N="460">Euer til I fynde sum of thi socour.</L>
<L>Hope of help me made hider for to fle</L>
<L>When thre gret enemys fast pursued me:</L>
<L>On is the foule fende with al his companie,</L>
<L N="464">That puttes forth pride &amp; wrath &amp; gret enuye;</L>
<L>The secund is the fals warld with many schrewed gyse,</L>
<L>That shotes ay at me sharply with all couetise;</L>
<L>The third is myn awne flesch, to me a gret enemy,</L>
<L N="468">That prickes me with lecherie, sleuth, &amp; glotony.</L>
<L>Welle of mercy, I be ded &amp; sone al fordon</L>
<L>Bot a streme of thi grace come to me sone.</L>
<L>Lady, let me lye in thi castel dyke</L>
<L N="472">And wasch me wele ther to thi seruant like:</L>
<L>Then, if myn enemys wil me assaile,</L>
<L>In traist of thi gode help y tak that bataile.</L>
<L N="475">In this castil ihesu crist tok of the mankynd:</L>
<L>Ther-for hope y euer her<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. hir</NOTE> socour for to fynde;</L>
<L>Here hid god his gret power in mannes liknes</L>
<L>&amp; laide enbuschement for the fend &amp; al his wikkednes.<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. wilk|ednes</NOTE></L>
<L>Thou art the &yogh;ert of aaron that bar the faire flour,</L>
<L N="480">When thou in clene maydenhede bar thi creatour;</L>
<L>Thou art the stegh of iacob thurgh wham is gate to heuen&mdash;</L>
<L>He may hope wele of help that deuoutly wil the neuen.</L>
<L>The Kinges sone of al this world ligh the with-ynne</L>
<L N="484">ffor to saue &amp; socour wel al synful man of synne.&mdash;</L>
<L>Now he has acorded alle his sisters foure,</L>
<L>And pece is cryed for man heghe vp in the toure.</L>
<L>Now god &amp; man are to-geder both in O person;</L>
<L>Now has man ynogh wharwith to bye him fro prison;</L>
<L N="489">Now on man more parfit &amp; withouten lak</L>
<L>Than euer was Adam ar he goddis biddyng brak,</L>
<L>He is fre to plede for vs &amp; al oure ri&yogh;t dereigne,</L>
<L>And no creature may haue cause vp-on him to pleyn.</L>
<L>In token of the prince of pees, when he til vs come,</L>
<L>Pees was ouer-al in the world, &amp; reuling was in rome;</L>
<L N="495">Ioye is sungen now to god vpon hegh in heuen</L>
<L>And pes in erthe til al man that are of gode wil euen.
<PB REF="00000430.tif" N="422"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; How ihesus was gode counseillour.<MILESTONE N="13" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<L>NOw, man, behold thi saueour,</L>
<L>Howe he was gode counseillour,</L>
<L>To bringe the to thin heritage</L>
<L N="500">That was forfet thurgh outrage.</L>
<L>If thou wil ay folowe his rede,</L>
<L>Thou sal eschue ay-lastand dede</L>
<L>And so recouer the ioye of heuen,</L>
<L N="504">If thou wil folowe his counseill euen.</L>
<L>When he for the become man here,</L>
<L>He fand the a thrall, of no power</L>
<L>ffor to recouer that thou had lost,</L>
<L N="508">Bot he for thi ri&yogh;t wold pay the cost.</L>
<L>Then souerayn meknes and charite</L>
<L>Schewed ihesu <NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. xprist</NOTE>christ, thi lord, for the;</L>
<L>"Dere brothir," he said, "of the I haue pite grete,</L>
<L N="512">That al thi fair heritage fouly is forfait.</L>
<L>Neuer-the-lees fal no&yogh;t in despeir,</L>
<L>ffor of that heritage y am heir;</L>
<L>To double ri&yogh;t hit falles to me:<NOTE PLACE="marg">515-522 <I>al.</I> Fr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="516">The ton of thaim y may wele gyf the;</L>
<L>If thou wil kepe my comaundement,</L>
<L>Thou sal ay haue it verrament.</L>
<L>ffor I am god, blis is bounden to me so fast</L>
<L N="520">That y may neuer fro me hit cast;</L>
<L>ffor I am of adam kynde &amp; with-outen synne,</L>
<L>I may clayme his heritage &amp; bi skil hit wynne.</L>
<L>If thou wil<NOTE PLACE="marg">overlined.</NOTE> ouer al thing ri&yogh;t hertly loue me,</L>
<L N="524">And loue thin euen-cristen for the loue of me,</L>
<L>All thin enemys the agayn sal no-thing auaile,</L>
<L>And y sal sone for thi sake to me ta this bataile,</L>
<L>If thou wil hald [in] thi hert how y for the sal fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Mi &yogh;ok sal ay be swete to the, &amp; my birthin ful li&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Lerne at me, for I am mylde &amp; also meke of hert."</L>
<L N="530">Ther-to may mekel help ay wilful pouert:</L>
<L>Meknes is a verray token of him that is in grace,</L>
<L>And pride an euidence of him that charite non has;</L>
<L N="533">He that settes his hert to mekel on riches,</L>
<L>Thai drawe him sone te pride fro vertue of meknes.
<PB REF="00000431.tif" N="423"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Here spak the autour.</HEAD>
<L>NOw sues that man his lordes counsail</L>
<L N="536">That al to the contrary dos trauail?</L>
<L>How may he socour seke of ihesu meknes,</L>
<L>That settes him-self to mekel vpon heghnes?</L>
<L>Ther-for drede he may that so wil him bere</L>
<L N="540">Of a foul falling doun with lucifere.</L>
<L>Neuer-the-lees a riche man with his ri&yogh;twisnes,</L>
<L>And he loue ay god wele in hertly meknes,</L>
<L>He may wele saue his saule with fast fleyng of synne,<MILESTONE N="12" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And with werkes of mercy the Ioye of heuen wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; How ihesus mot with the fende.</HEAD>
<L>NOw here how thi lord mette [the fend] for thi ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="546">Atte last for thi loue put him to fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>When the godhede was hid in the mankynd</L>
<L N="548">And the fende in him no synne my&yogh;t fynde,</L>
<L>He tempted him with thre thinges that made adam dede.<NOTE PLACE="marg">548-563 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>"If thou be goddes sone," he said, "make of stones brede."</L>
<L N="551">"Noght only thurgh brede," quad ihesu crist, "leues man,</L>
<L>Bot thurgh ich word that comes of goddes wysdam."</L>
<L>The fend sette crist on the temple &amp; bad him lepe doun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. don</NOTE></L>
<L>Goddes aungeles to kepe him suld be redy &amp; boun,</L>
<L>If he were goddes sone, in handes thai suld him bere,</L>
<L>So at no ston suld he stumble ne nothing suld him dere.</L>
<L N="557">"Writen," quad ihesu crist, "in haly writ y rede:</L>
<L>Thou suld not tempte god thi lord, when thou has no nede."</L>
<L>The fend shewid him al the warld &amp; saide: "this gif y the,</L>
<L>If thou wil bowe doun to the ground &amp; so adour me."</L>
<L N="561">"Writen it is," quad ihesu crist, "thi god sal thou adoure,</L>
<L>And only sal thou serue him with so mekil honoure.</L>
<L>Go, satanas," quad ihesu crist, "for the am y no&yogh;t ferd."
<PB REF="00000432.tif" N="424"></L>
<L>"And I am prince," quad the fend, "of this midlerd;</L>
<L>I haue gode sesyn ther-ynne &amp; of ful lange tyme,</L>
<L N="566">And be confermyng of god al mankynd is myne.</L>
<L>ffor man brak goddes bydding &amp; of the appel ete,</L>
<L>He sal be in payn with me euermore, I the hete;</L>
<L>God wil not do so gret wrong to reue me my pray.</L>
<L>If he haue any ri&yogh;t, let se what he can say!</L>
<L>The couenant that god made, that sal I alway hold;</L>
<L N="572">No man for to breke it sal neuer be so bold."</L>
<L>"Man," quad ihesu, "hade keped al goddes biddyng,</L>
<L>Hade he no&yogh;t be lettid with [thi] betrayng,</L>
<L>When thou saide til eue 'for that mete sal no&yogh;t man dye,</L>
<L N="576">Bot &yogh;e sal be as goddes, bothe wyse &amp; sle.'</L>
<L>How may thou couenant reioys<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. de c. jouir</NOTE> be reson</L>
<L>That thou made man to breke be thi foul treson?"</L>
<L>"Alas," then quad the fend, "wher hade thou this connyng</L>
<L N="580">ffor to venquys me to-day thus with thi motyng?</L>
<L>Mote euermore how as thou mote will,</L>
<L>Man sal euermore be in my prison stille,</L>
<L>Bot if thou, be-fore he passe forth,</L>
<L N="584">Paye as mekil raunson for him as he is al worth."</L>
<L>"That is reson," quad ihesu crist, "&amp; that ful verrailye,</L>
<L>I wil no&yogh;t tak man fro the with vnskilful maistrie.</L>
<L>Loke what his raunson sal be skilfully,</L>
<L N="588">And I sal paye hit for him, &amp; that ful largely."</L>
<L>"Better," then quad the fend, "sal his raunson be</L>
<L>Then al this ilk warld is worth that thou now may se."<MILESTONE N="10" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"I graunt," quad ihesu crist, "to this couenant;</L>
<L N="592">ffor my lest fynger is mekil more vailiant</L>
<L>Then a thousand worldes, if that thai ware."</L>
<L>"Certes," quad the fend then, "that is al my care;</L>
<L>ffor of al this warld ay y haue sum skill,</L>
<L N="596">Bot in the is no thing sene at myn awen will.</L>
<L>And if thou wil gyue thi fynger him to bye,</L>
<L>Than sal thou make a febil marchandie.</L>
<L>And &yogh;it most thou suffre for him als mekil payn</L>
<L N="600">As he hade done &amp; he in helle euer hade layn."</L>
<L>Ihesu said: "I sal do more than thou has ast,<NOTE PLACE="marg">= asked</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000433.tif" N="425"></L>
<L>And this couenant betwix vs sal be made ful fast."</L>
<L>Then the fend him to the dede as for his prison toke,</L>
<L>And choked on the godhede as fisch dos on the hoke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Of cristes passion.</HEAD>
<L N="605">BEhald now the passion of cristes manhede,</L>
<L>How he gaf al him-self to socour the at nede,</L>
<L>Both body &amp; saul, &amp; his lymes alle</L>
<L N="608">Lete punysch for the, when that thou was thrall.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">609-624 added.</NOTE>Thre &amp; thirty &yogh;ere for the, to bye thi forfete,</L>
<L>He suffred cold, hungur &amp; thrist, &amp; trauail wonder grete.</L>
<L>Befor that he for synne of man til his passion &yogh;ode,</L>
<L>He prayed so hertly til his fader that he swette blode.</L>
<L N="613">He was tane as a thef, &amp; bounden wonder fast,</L>
<L>&amp; bette with hard knotty stringes whil thei wold last;</L>
<L>ffro the croun of the hed to the fote-sole</L>
<L N="616">No pece of his skyn my&yogh;t be founden hole.</L>
<L>ffete &amp; hande were drawen out &amp; nayled to the tre,</L>
<L>As straitly, for more penaunce, as euer thai my&yogh;t be;</L>
<L>He was lifted vpon hegh &amp; leten doun so fast</L>
<L>That all the vaynes &amp; the synnues in his body brast.</L>
<L N="621">All that blissed body stremed doun of blode,</L>
<L>ffor to wasch synne&mdash;ther was a noble flode!</L>
<L>His saule [was] ful drery agayn the deyng,</L>
<L N="624">To make asseth for thi saule wikked likyng.</L>
<L>The sharpe croun of thornes crouned him so fast</L>
<L>That the sharpnes of thaim in to the brayn brast,</L>
<L>And then he henged doun his heued with mekel meknes,</L>
<L N="628">ffor to make asseth for mannes proudnes.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> Fr.</NOTE></L>
<L>His eghen wex fade &amp; dym &amp; lost al thaire my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>ffor to make asseth alway for synne of mannes si&yogh;t.</L>
<L>His eres hard fals reproues with gret scornyng,</L>
<L N="632">ffor to make asseth fully for synne of oure hering.</L>
<L>His neys smelled of the Iewes snot &amp; foul spitting</L>
<L>That thei cast vpon his face to blode &amp; sweting:</L>
<L>This suffrance of ihesu crist that lord is of al thing</L>
<L N="636">May make asseth for all synne of oure smelling.</L>
<L>Bitter aisel and galle, when he was thristy,<MILESTONE N="11" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Drank he, to make fully asseth for mannes glotony.
<PB REF="00000434.tif" N="426"></L>
<L>When he was aght dayes old, with a culter of stone</L>
<L N="640">Thai karf his tendre membre away&mdash;that bi the lagh was don:</L>
<L>This penance of that child that was so worthi</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;t make asseth for synne of mannes lechery.<NOTE PLACE="marg">639-42 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al the body aboute with brising &amp; beting</L>
<L N="644">Was punysched ynogh for synne of touching.</L>
<L>His hende nayled to the crosse al for thi sake</L>
<L>May for synne of thin hend asseth ynogh make.</L>
<L>His fete nayled thurg<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. thurd</NOTE> with yrne nayles</L>
<L N="648">Made asseth for al thi wikkid trauayles.</L>
<L>He prayed for man til his fader hyngand an the croys</L>
<L>With bittir teres, &amp; &yogh;eld the gast with a gret voys.</L>
<L>He was both god &amp; man ful verraily,</L>
<L N="652">That so &yogh;elded the gast lyueand the body:</L>
<L>ffor saule goos neuer fro the body be the cours of kynde</L>
<L>Whyl thou may in the body fyue wittes fynde;</L>
<L>Bot god strenghed his body to suffre more reddure</L>
<L N="656">Than euer my&yogh;t haue suffred any other creature.</L>
<L>His hert that was clouen thurgh with a sharp spere,</L>
<L>That may make asseth for al synne that may dere;</L>
<L>His hert-blode &amp; clene water was ther-out bro&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="660">To wasch away al enuy &amp; al ille tho&yogh;t.</L>
<L>This of ful gret mercy is sette on comon broche,</L>
<L>And the welle of pite springes out of this roche.</L>
<L>If thou wil forsake synne &amp; cry mercy,</L>
<L N="664">Thou sal neuer faile ther-of, certaynly;</L>
<L>How that thou may synne with any lymme that is thine,</L>
<L>A lymme of crist is punysched to thi medicine.&mdash;</L>
<L N="667">When god thus suffred dede, as we rede in boke,</L>
<L>The sunne sone with-drogh his li&yogh;t, and the erthe whoke,<NOTE PLACE="marg">= quoke</NOTE></L>
<L>And the vail of the temple euen brast in two,</L>
<L>And the harde stones swiftly cleue also;</L>
<L>Many a man rose than that were before dede,</L>
<L N="672">And al bare thei wittenes of his godhede.<NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 667-672 added.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Of the sorowe of oure lady.</HEAD>
<L>WHat sorowe hopes thou then hade his modur mary,</L>
<L>When thing that has no reson for him was so sary!
<PB REF="00000435.tif" N="427"></L>
<L>Certes, lady, Symond swerd past thurgh-out thi hert,</L>
<L N="676">And the paynes of thi sone were in the ful smert,</L>
<L>That thi hert hade neuer lasted on non-kyn wyse</L>
<L>Hade thou no&yogh;t trewed stedfastly that he suld vprise.</L>
<L>Lady, what nede was the for to make sorowe,</L>
<L N="680">ffor thi sone dyed synful man to borowe?</L>
<L>Thou wote that he sal ryse agayn thurgh his awen my&yogh;t</L>
<L>&amp; with a body ful of ioye, apertely to thi si&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Thou wote the fend is venquist, &amp; wetes it no&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Til thi sone out of helle haue al his chosen bro&yogh;t.<MILESTONE N="16" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="685">ffro he dyed til he rose that [men] my&yogh;t him se,</L>
<L>Alle the trewth of halikerk was stedfast in the;</L>
<L>Alle his awen disciples of him thai were dredand,</L>
<L N="688">Bot the faith in thi hert ay it was lastand.</L>
<L>Dere lady, succour vs of dedly synnyng,</L>
<L>ffor the ioye that thou hade of his vprising!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; How ihesus is almy&yogh;ti.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fr. deus omnipotent</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>HE rose by his awne my&yogh;t, &amp; that verraily,</L>
<L N="692">And shewed so that he was ihesus almyghti.</L>
<L>He that al this warld made first of ri&yogh;t no&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Man dampned agayn with his blode he bo&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Thus has he gyuen vs a gode counsail,</L>
<L N="696">And thurgh ri&yogh;t venquist the fend in batail.</L>
<L>His lyf has shewed vs a ful redy gate</L>
<L>ffor to entre, if we will, in-with heuen-&yogh;ate.</L>
<L>ffor we sul traist on him in al oure nede,</L>
<L N="700">He shewed vs the my&yogh;t of god in his manhede.</L>
<L>Power of god and man was mellid in his dedis,</L>
<L>And that to stablenes of oure treuth gretly spedis.</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as a sharp swerd of the fire al glowand</L>
<L N="704">The egge kerues if he smyte, the hete is brennand,</L>
<L>So godhede &amp; manhede in o person</L>
<L>Shewed thair kyndnes<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. kyndes</NOTE> to mannes reson.</L>
<L>We rede: when he was called til a weddyng,</L>
<L N="708">Whan thaim failed wyne, sone at his bydding</L>
<L>Thai filled pottes of clene water in the stede of wyne:</L>
<L>And thai were turned in to wyne, &amp; that gode &amp; fyne.</L>
<L N="711">When he bad fette water, he shewed his manhed,</L>
<L>And when he turned hit to wyne, he shewed his godhed.
<PB REF="00000436.tif" N="428"></L>
<L>ffor he my&yogh;t haue made wyne with-outen water bro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as he made, when he wald, al the warld a<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. of</NOTE> no&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Also with fyue loues &amp; only fisches two</L>
<L N="716">He fedde, as we rede, fyue thousand &amp; mo;</L>
<L>When thai hade eten ynogh, all that ther were,</L>
<L>Twelf lepes of relef ful away thei bere.</L>
<L>His manhed to thaim all delt bret &amp; fische,</L>
<L N="720">Bot his godhed ther multiplied al this.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it we rede that lazar hade [lain] four dayes in his graue</L>
<L>When ihesu crist fro ded to lyue wald him vp haue;</L>
<L>ffirst he grette &amp; sithen he cryed to la&yogh;ar:</L>
<L N="724">That shewed that he was verray man thar;</L>
<L>When lazare rose fro the ded &amp; died<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. did</NOTE> mannes dede,</L>
<L>Then was shewed that in crist was verray godhede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Of the sacrament of the auter.<NOTE PLACE="marg">This passage is added.</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>GOd of all his meruailes made vs a gode mynd</L>
<L N="728">When he wold in forme of brede dwell with mankind.</L>
<L>Thurgh the vertue of cristes wordes of the sacrament</L>
<L>That the prest reherces at his messe with gode entent,</L>
<L>Brede in to cristes flesch, &amp; wyne in to his blode,<MILESTONE N="17" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="732">Sudanly is turned, for mannes gastly fode;</L>
<L>Nother brede ne wyne is after sacryng in the messe,</L>
<L>Bot verray goddes flesch &amp; blode, in thair liknes.</L>
<L>Ther is of brede &amp; wyne sauour, colour, &amp; figure,</L>
<L N="736">Lastand thurgh goddes wil agayn cours of nature;</L>
<L>But vnder this liknes is non other substance</L>
<L>Bot goddes body &amp; his blode with thair purtenance.</L>
<L>In crist god &amp; man, saul &amp; body, flesch &amp; blode</L>
<L N="740">Are so fast knyt to-geder with kynde &amp; loue gode</L>
<L>That whar that is any party of cristes awen body</L>
<L>Ther will god be &amp; thai all verraily.</L>
<L>Ther-for vndir liknes both of wyn &amp; brede</L>
<L N="744">Is verray both god &amp; man that for vs was dede.</L>
<L>This is goddes dede, &amp; passes mannes wit&mdash;</L>
<L>He has mekel mede that trewly trowes hit.</L>
<L>In this liknes gyues hit vs god, that is so gode,</L>
<L N="748">ffor we wald be escheu of rawe flesch &amp; of blode.</L>
<L>Brede &amp; wyne in the stomak taken to mete
<PB REF="00000437.tif" N="429"></L>
<L>Turnes in to flesch &amp; blode thurgh kyndly hete:</L>
<L>Whi may no&yogh;t god then, that al thing made of no&yogh;t</L>
<L N="752">And as haly writ sais many wonder wro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Turne sone in to flesch &amp; blode both brede &amp; wyne,</L>
<L>ffor to be to cristen man gastly medicine?</L>
<L>If thou receyue his flesch &amp; blode worthily,</L>
<L N="756">Thou sal be as [a] quik lym of his body;</L>
<L>And if thou kepe the so out of dedly synne,</L>
<L>As a cosyn of his thou sal heuen wynne.</L>
<L>The pask-lambe in the ald lawe that al men suld ete,</L>
<L>And man<NOTE PLACE="marg">i. manna, Hebr. man.</NOTE> that god send fro heuen til his folk [to] mete,</L>
<L N="761">&amp; blod that was euer offrid for clensyng of synne:</L>
<L>Was taken of his sacrament that oure help is ynne.</L>
<L>All the tokens of this sacrament that we ay can fynd</L>
<L N="764">In the old lawe, t[h]rugh trouth of this comes til oure mynd,</L>
<L>&amp; all the maruailes that god [wro&yogh;t] ar he man ware</L>
<L>&amp; [comen]<NOTE PLACE="marg">om., <I>or</I> r. boren?</NOTE> of that clene mayden &amp; modir that him bare.</L>
<L>If man wil with al his my&yogh;t loue this sacrament</L>
<L N="768">&amp; vse hit out of dedly synne ay with gode entent,</L>
<L>Nother tunge may wel telle ne hert may wel think</L>
<L>The noble and gastly profit of this mete &amp; drink.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; How ihesus is al strenghty.</HEAD>
<L>NOw hast thou herd wele how ihesus is almy&yogh;ty;</L>
<L N="772">Here now how he is ouer al other strenghty.</L>
<L>This name of ihesus has so gret in him<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. in him so gret</NOTE> vertu &amp; my&yogh;t</L>
<L>That all in heuen, erth &amp; helle suld til him loute with ri&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Oft in this name god mannes prayer spedes</L>
<L N="776">Agayn the fend that hit ful mekil dredes.</L>
<L>This name is mirthe in hering, &amp; comfort in si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Triacle in mouth &amp; in hert, that is of mekil my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Socour to all synful men, &amp; to seke solace,</L>
<L N="780">To him that is repentant ay ful of grace.</L>
<L>The fend was prince of this warld &amp; hade man in prison</L>
<L>Ay til our [lord] ihesu crist hade suffred passion;</L>
<L>Ther was non so hely<NOTE PLACE="marg">= haly</NOTE> that my&yogh;t in erth dwell</L>
<L N="784">Bot his saule, qwen he died, suld go to hell.</L>
<L>Hely men were in merknes ther thai no payn feld,</L>
<L>Bot the fend fro thair ioye agayn thair wil thaim held,
<PB REF="00000438.tif" N="430"></L>
<L>And the &yogh;ate of paradys was agayn thaim stoken,</L>
<L N="788">Til ihesus with his passion hade made it open.</L>
<L>When the fende sagh him wele on the crois hyngand,</L>
<L>He wend to haue made him forth ay in hell lengand;</L>
<L>Bot sone the saul with the godhede as a fere lyon</L>
<L N="792">And a kyng of al the warld, &amp; no&yogh;t as a prison,</L>
<L>Come to hell &amp; brast thair barres with his will fre,</L>
<L>And toke out all anon with him that dyed in charite.</L>
<L>Him calles men a lord strong and my&yogh;ty</L>
<L N="796">That has ay when he wil in batail the maistry.</L>
<L>Sone he venquist the fend &amp; cuttyd his power,</L>
<L>That he suld no&yogh;t tempt vs more then we mi&yogh;t bere.</L>
<L>Thus is ihesus our refut, strenght &amp; socour,</L>
<L N="800">Our help &amp; our hele, our ioye &amp; our honour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; How crist is oure fader gastly.</HEAD>
<L>HEre now how crist was oure formfader gastly,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as adam was to man formfader fleschly.</L>
<L>All that was of adam born, lost heuen for his synne,</L>
<L N="804">And all that cristes children will be bi him may hit wynne;</L>
<L>Baptisme has the vertu of cristes hert-blode,</L>
<L>To make thaim his childer that wil take hit with<NOTE PLACE="marg">wil om.?</NOTE> gode.</L>
<L>Thus ri&yogh;t as al men dyed thurgh adam,</L>
<L N="808">So may al be quikned agayn in cristes name.</L>
<L>Was neuer no fader that any son so dere hade bo&yogh;t</L>
<L>As crist, that man wesch of synne &amp; out of prison bro&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="812">In fourty houres after his ded herged he helle<NOTE PLACE="inter">[1 <I>verse wanting.</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>And apered to his disciples in many-maner wyse,</L>
<L>To proue soth that he said that he suld vprise.</L>
<L>He ete &amp; drank with thaim ichon, ri&yogh;t in thair si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And spak that was nedeful to thaim, mekel of gastli li&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="817">And elleuen of thaim he blamed sithen</L>
<L>ffor thei trowed no&yogh;t that he was vprisen.</L>
<L>Bot it was til our faith ful heply</L>
<L N="820">That Thomas of ynde trowed lattly,</L>
<L>Til he in to crist[<I>es</I>] hert-wond hade put his hand;</L>
<L>Than said he: "thou art my god &amp; my lord lyuand."
<PB REF="00000439.tif" N="431"></L>
<L>"ffor thou has sene me," quad crist, "now thou trowes ri&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Blissed be thai [that] trowes wele with-outen any si&yogh;t!"</L>
<L N="825">When our faith was thus confermed as thou has wele hard,</L>
<L>Then bad crist thei suld it preche thurgh-out al the warld,</L>
<L>And [baptize] all that wald be in trouth stedfast,</L>
<L N="828">In the name of the fader &amp; the son &amp; the haligast;</L>
<L>ffor ther [may] neuer non in heuen-blis wone</L>
<L>Bot he thurgh baptyme be made cristes awen sone.</L>
<L>In this fader was neuer no wemme of synne,</L>
<L N="832">The-for be him may [we] blis clayme &amp; wynne.</L>
<L>Adam come of erth &amp; band vs all to prison:</L>
<L>Crist then come fro heuen &amp; payed for vs raunson.</L>
<L>When he stegh vp agayn to heuen-riche blis,</L>
<L N="836">He tok al the ded with him that was his.</L>
<L>Ther he haldes sesyn in his heritage</L>
<L>To al that wil folow him of his lynage.</L>
<L>Thar fader &amp; sone &amp; haligast</L>
<L N="840">Are all on god of my&yogh;tes mast.</L>
<L>In si&yogh;t of this thre persons in on godhede</L>
<L>Sal be in heuen our gret ioye &amp; our mede;</L>
<L>Then sal we se in that ioyfulnes</L>
<L>How crist, our dere fader, is verray prince of pees.&mdash;</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">vv. 845-954 added.</NOTE>When ihesu crist of heuen had wonnen his gret ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Then was sent the haligast anon, as he hade hi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>His disciples hertes anon he wald enspire</L>
<L N="848">In the fader liknes with tunges of fire.</L>
<L>So the haligast was send &amp; sest thaim aboue,</L>
<L>That of the fader &amp; the sone is the gode loue,</L>
<L>And is al on god with thaim in verray vnite,</L>
<L N="852">Bot he is third person in the trinite.</L>
<L>When thei were thus fulfilled of the haligast,</L>
<L>Thai couth wele al langage &amp; speke hit sone in hast;</L>
<L N="855">Thai were so confermed in trouth &amp; al ful of grace</L>
<L>That for to preche goddes lawe thai dred no kinges face.
<PB REF="00000440.tif" N="432"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Of the articles of trouth.</HEAD>
<L>HEre now of the articles of our trouth that we al traist Inne,</L>
<L>&amp; the seuen sacrament&yogh; that soccours vs of synne.</L>
<L>We sal trowen in on god of my&yogh;tes alther-mast,</L>
<L N="860">That is the fader &amp; the sone &amp; the haligast;</L>
<L>None is other of this persones thre,</L>
<L>Bot all are on god in the<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. thre</NOTE> trinite:</L>
<L>Thes thre are on god &amp; on verray nature,</L>
<L N="864">That made first of ri&yogh;t no&yogh;t al-maner creature.</L>
<L>We trowe in haly kirk, &amp; haly mannes dedes,</L>
<L>That god ay with his grace thaim strenghtes wel &amp; spedes</L>
<L N="867">In trouth &amp; sacrament&yogh; &amp; dedes of charite,</L>
<L>Thurgh whilk to the repentant forgifnes of synne sal be.</L>
<L>He that trowes no&yogh;t as halikirk, is in dedly synne,</L>
<L>And mede in heuen in that state may he neuer wynne.</L>
<L>At day of dome sal al mankynd vprise,<NOTE PLACE="marg">This point is re|peated in v. 891.</NOTE></L>
<L N="872">ffor to take ay-lastand dome on many diuers wise;</L>
<L>The gode sal go to heuen to ay-lastand blis,</L>
<L>And the wikkid to helle-fire that ay-lastand is.</L>
<L>The aghtend article is of cristes manhede:</L>
<L N="876">How mary conceyued him in clen maydenhede;</L>
<L>When the aungel gabriel come &amp; gret hir with gode,</L>
<L>The haligast made a body of hir clennest blode,</L>
<L>&amp; put a saul in to hit that al wysdam can;</L>
<L N="880">Then god the sone toke that &amp; become man.</L>
<L>The neghend is that he of maiden mary was born</L>
<L>&amp; no-thing of hir maydenhede ther-for was lorn.</L>
<L>The tend is that he suffred paynes wilfully,</L>
<L N="884">Al to ded op-on the crois &amp; biryng of body.</L>
<L>The elleuend that crist in saule went doun to hell</L>
<L>&amp; toke out al his awen chosen that with him suld dwell.</L>
<L>The twelft is that he rose fro dede on the thrid day</L>
<L>And apperyd qwik in flesch with many tokens verray.</L>
<L>The thrittend is that he stegh vp hegh in to heuen,</L>
<L N="890">Ther he sittes in manhed with his fader euen.</L>
<L>The fourtend is that he sal come vpon domesday</L>
<L>And gyue ri&yogh;twis dome to qwik &amp; dede, that sal last ay.
<PB REF="00000441.tif" N="433"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Of the seuen sacraments.</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;Et the seuen sacrament&yogh; are nedful to kenne.</L>
<L>ffor baptyme of al synne may soccour all men;</L>
<L>For who as taas hit lawefully,</L>
<L N="896">Of synne is clensed al fully.</L>
<L>The secund sacrament is confermyng:</L>
<L>That agayn the fend is a gret strenghting.</L>
<L>The third is the sacrament of the auter,</L>
<L N="900">That is declared a litel befor here.</L>
<L>The ferth is penance ordaynd for mannes synne;</L>
<L>This lawefully has thre parties him with-Inne:</L>
<L>Sorow of hert, schrift of mouth, &amp; asseth making&mdash;</L>
<L N="904">This thre of mede &amp; grace bringes agayn taking.</L>
<L>The fift sacrament is for seke men anoynting:</L>
<L>This is soccour agayn al uenial synnyng.</L>
<L>The sext is ordour that clerkes has on diuerse wise,</L>
<L>And ther-thurgh has diuerse power in goddes seruise.</L>
<L N="909">That seuend betwix man &amp; womman is wedding,</L>
<L>ffor remedie of lecherie &amp; childer nurishing.</L>
<L>Thurgh gode &amp; laweful vsyng of any of this seuen</L>
<L>May men wele escheu payn &amp; li&yogh;tly come til heuen.</L>
<L N="913">Grace in this seuen heles man of al gastly sore;</L>
<L>And seuen vertues ables him that thou red be-fore.<NOTE PLACE="marg">v. 421 ff.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seuen giftes of the haligast helpes ay his dede,</L>
<L N="916">And seuen maner of blis parfourmes his mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Of the seuen giftes of the haligast.</HEAD>
<L>THe first gift, dred of god, puttes fro man pride mast</L>
<L>&amp; makes him wele-manerd, pouer in hert and tast;</L>
<L>&amp; that are thus meke in hert, &amp; pouer gastly,</L>
<L>Crist blesses thaim alway, &amp; heuen is thaires, treuly.</L>
<L N="921">The second gift is pite, that puttes out enuy</L>
<L>&amp; makes man to worschipe god, his fader gastly,</L>
<L>&amp; goddes lawe &amp; his neghbour for goddes awen sake,</L>
<L>&amp; thes gode dedes gode, benigne &amp; myld wil him make;</L>
<L N="925">Thai that has vertuously that ilk myldnes,</L>
<L>Ay sal haue lyuyng in mekil blissednes.</L>
<L>The third gift is cunnyng, that puttes away wrath</L>
<L>&amp; mas man to loue godenes, &amp; with wikkednes to wlath,
<PB REF="00000442.tif" N="434"></L>
<L N="929">And haue sorow for his synne &amp; taryyng of blis;</L>
<L>ffor this is man blissed, &amp; heuen sal be his;</L>
<L>This gift of cunnyng may no&yogh;t ful longe be</L>
<L N="932">With-outen gastly ioye &amp; gret charite.</L>
<L>The ferth gift is gastly strenght, that puttes away slouth</L>
<L>&amp; to eschape all perils mas man to haue trouth;</L>
<L>Hit mas man to suffre wel, &amp; long to bide ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; ri&yogh;t be done to god &amp; man &yogh;erne with al his my&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="937">&amp; who-so has this &yogh;ernyng &amp; hungres ri&yogh;twisnes,</L>
<L>Thai sal be ful-filled of hit &amp; haue gret blissednes.</L>
<L>That fift gift is counsail, that fordos couetise</L>
<L N="940">&amp; in hegh thing &amp; hard mas man of gode auyse;</L>
<L>Hit mas man ay gode &amp; benigne in alkyn thinge,</L>
<L>And rewles hym wele in warkes of mercy doyng;</L>
<L>&amp; all that warkes of mercy dos deuoutely,</L>
<L N="944">Are blissed of ihesu crist &amp; ay sal haue mercy.</L>
<L>The sext gift is vnderstanding, that glotery fordos</L>
<L>&amp; stires to certayn<NOTE PLACE="marg">= make certain</NOTE> trouth that him gastly behose,</L>
<L>&amp; makes him of all synne clene in hert to be;</L>
<L N="948">Suche men are blissid of crist, for thai sal god se.</L>
<L>The seuent gift is wysdam, that fordos lecherie</L>
<L>&amp; confortes man in Ioye of god &amp; pes swetly,</L>
<L>And mas man to kepe &amp; make pees with gret besines;</L>
<L>Siche are called goddes childer, &amp; sal haue blissednes.</L>
<L>In suffring oght for ri&yogh;t standes the aghtend blis,</L>
<L>&amp; who as euer suffres so, the rewme of heuen is his.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Of antecristes commyng.<NOTE PLACE="marg">This passage is added.</NOTE></HEAD>
<L N="955">THat tyme when god wil suffre, before the [day] of dome</L>
<L>To tempte &amp; pursue cristen men anticrist sal come;</L>
<L>He sal be born in babiloyn of the kynd of dan</L>
<L>That sum tyme here in erth of Iacob childer was an;</L>
<L N="959">He sal regne in Ierusalem &amp; him-self [crist] call.</L>
<L>Then many of ther wretched Iewes sal fast til him fall.</L>
<L>When he mas him god, his gode aungel sal him forsake,</L>
<L>Then the fend sal him enspire &amp; hede of wikkednes make;</L>
<L>He sal feyne thurgh fendes craft nere al cristes meruailes,
<PB REF="00000443.tif" N="435"></L>
<L N="964">Bot ay in him charite, mercy &amp; meknes failes.</L>
<L>Simple men sal he deceyue with miracles doyng,</L>
<L>Couetous with gret giftes, &amp; gode with punysching,</L>
<L N="967">He sal make men as god to adour his ymage</L>
<L>&amp; on thair [forehede]<NOTE PLACE="marg">a word om.: right hand <I>or</I> forehede, cf. Apoc. 13, 16.</NOTE> bere a mark of his seruage;</L>
<L>Who-so has no&yogh;t that mark, sal nouther bye ne sell,</L>
<L>Bot antecristes tyrant sal thaim to ded quell.</L>
<L>Be reson &amp; in haly writ it is goddes sawe:</L>
<L N="972">Thurgh payn sal god neuer stresse man to forsake his lawe,</L>
<L>Bot what as any man dos here with his fre will,</L>
<L>Sal turne him, after it is, to gode or to ill.</L>
<L>Betwix antecristes comyng &amp; his gret ill doyng</L>
<L N="976">Sal Ely &amp; Ennok com preche for mennes sauyng;</L>
<L>Then antecrist sal sle thaim in Ierusalem,</L>
<L>&amp; god sal raise thaim to lif &amp; tak thaim to his leme.</L>
<L>Bot thre &yogh;ere &amp; a half sal antecrist haue maistry&mdash;</L>
<L N="980">ffor to saue his chosen that ordayns goddes mercy.</L>
<L>Then thurgh goddes my&yogh;t sal that wikked be slayn,</L>
<L>&amp; all chosen that trespast then sal turne agayn.</L>
<L>The[n] ful many Iewes sal turne to cristes lawe,</L>
<L N="984">&amp; halikirk sal liue in pes out of tyrant&yogh; awe,</L>
<L>Shortir tyme or lenger, til that crist wil come,</L>
<L>To make the worldes ende &amp; gif his grete dome.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Of the day of dome.</HEAD>
<L>IN the same fourme in whilk crist suffrid payn,</L>
<L N="988">To deme both qwhik &amp; ded he sal come agayn.</L>
<L>Then sal he shewe his body stremand al on blode,</L>
<L>&amp; his hert clouen in two as he henge on rode,</L>
<L>&amp; say: "for &yogh;ow suffred I al this gret payn.</L>
<L N="992">Telles now what &yogh;e to me has done ther-agayn!"</L>
<L>Allas, what may then til him synful man say</L>
<L>That neuer wele with-outen synne spendes on day?</L>
<L>Man sal &yogh;elde acompt then of al that god him sende,</L>
<L N="996">Body &amp; saul, witte &amp; gode, how he has it spende,</L>
<L>&amp; of ilk a nydel word that euer he here spak;</L>
<L>In wikked word &amp; wikked dede then sal be gret lak.</L>
<L>After that degre of synne or of charite</L>
<L N="1000">That any man dyes Inne, sal he domed be.
<PB REF="00000444.tif" N="436"></L>
<L>Than sal clere conscience be mekil more of told</L>
<L>Than any gret lordship with a world ful of gold:</L>
<L>ffor al sal then perisch that we here now make,</L>
<L N="1004">&amp; synful man sal for drede sore tremble &amp; qwak.</L>
<L>All synne for whilk is no&yogh;t worthily asseth made here,</L>
<L>Bes shewed ther al openly, to shame &amp; gret lere.</L>
<L>Ilk a man then sal se his dome verraily</L>
<L N="1008">&amp; for gret drede of god thus sal thei all cry:</L>
<L>"Montayns, falles doun on vs, for to hid vs,</L>
<L>That we se no&yogh;t the wrath of god that is so hedous!</L>
<L>Allas that euer were we born any thing to craue,</L>
<L N="1012">ffor with-outen ende we are lorn, for nothing may vs saue.</L>
<L>Alas, alas, &amp; wele-away, wher-of may we &yogh;elp?</L>
<L>Whe are shent for euer &amp; ay, for no thing may vs help."</L>
<L>Haly writ sais that befor this dome</L>
<L N="1016">Ouer al this wide warld a huge fire sal come;</L>
<L>Seint Peter sais<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 Petr. 3, 10.</NOTE> that then al sal brenne</L>
<L>Erth &amp; water &amp; al the warld, &amp; al that is ther-Inne.</L>
<L>Heuens &amp; ayr &amp; all the elements</L>
<L N="1020">ffire thurgh brennyng then sal clens.</L>
<L>ffire sal no&yogh;t touche heuen in the whilk is blis,</L>
<L>Bot other heuens that vnder hit is.</L>
<L N="1023">The fire sal purge venial synne,</L>
<L>&amp; ful hard pyne thaim that dedly [syn] is lnne;<NOTE PLACE="marg">1021-4 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hit sal fordo thing that sal no&yogh;t endure,</L>
<L>And make al the remanant of fairer figure.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">1027-42 added.</NOTE>Then al the qwik bestes sal tak thair endyng,</L>
<L>That were made bot for a tyme of mannes leuyng.</L>
<L N="1029">The four elements sal be fairer seuen-fold</L>
<L>Then euer thai were any tyme, other newe or old.</L>
<L>Ther sal be no chaunging fro cold to the hete,</L>
<L N="1032">Ne non other tempest of wynd &amp; wedirs gret;</L>
<L>Al cold &amp; hete, foul venum, fylth &amp; stynk,</L>
<L>ffor to punish thaim in hell, sal doun then synk.<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. v. 1095.</NOTE></L>
<L>The heuens sal no&yogh;t turne aboute, bot stand ay in rest,</L>
<L N="1036">The sunne ay in the est, the mone in the west;</L>
<L>Ilkon sal be more clere seuen-fold than he was,</L>
<L>Bot[h] to goddes worschipe &amp; to mannes solas.
<PB REF="00000445.tif" N="437"></L>
<L>This sais god bi ysaie, that his wil wele knewe:</L>
<L N="1040">"Lo, I make both heuens &amp; erth all span-newe."</L>
<L>This fairnes of the warld sal dampned men no&yogh;t se,</L>
<L>ffor thai sal be in helle-payne or that fairnes sal be.</L>
<L>ffirst, when god wil, sall aungeles a gret noyse make,</L>
<L N="1044">&amp; crist thaim that are in blis sal with him take,</L>
<L>Then the remanant that sal be in that blis faire,</L>
<L>Sal be rauyst him agayn vp in to the aere.</L>
<L>All sall ryse fro ded to lyf of Adames lynage</L>
<L N="1048">Als in thair awen statur of thritty &yogh;er age;</L>
<L>All goddes chosen then sal ful parfit be,</L>
<L>With-outen any foulnes or superfluite.</L>
<L>Then sal crist say to thaim on his ri&yogh;t honde</L>
<L N="1052">A gode word, of all wordes comfortande:</L>
<L>"Come &yogh;e, my fader blissed, &amp; haues the reume of heuen,</L>
<L>That, befor the warld was made, [was] ordaynd &yogh;ow ful euen.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e gaf me mete whan I was hungry,</L>
<L N="1056">&YOGH;e gaf me drynk whan y was thristy;</L>
<L>When I hade nede &yogh;e harbard me;</L>
<L>When I was naked &yogh;e cleded me;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e visit me when I was seke,</L>
<L N="1060">And in prison &yogh;e wald me seke.</L>
<L>That &yogh;e did for my loue to the lest of myne,</L>
<L>That same &yogh;e did to myself, theron sal &yogh;e no&yogh;t tyne."</L>
<L>Then wikked men for heuenes of synne</L>
<L N="1064">Sall no&yogh;t agayn crist in to the aier wynne,</L>
<L>Bot thai on the erth [sal] cristes wordes here,</L>
<L>That sal be to thaim with-outen ende a lere,</L>
<L>When he sais: "go, waried, in to the fire of helle,</L>
<L N="1068">Thar &yogh;e in payne with-outen ende with the fend sal dwell.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e serued neuer ioye aylastandly,</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;e fulfilled no&yogh;t the warkes of mercy."&mdash;</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">1071-1090 added.</NOTE>Take now gode kepe here, wardly cristen man,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. men</NOTE></L>
<L N="1072">&amp; do thi saule profit als wele as thou can!</L>
<L>Thurgh warkes of mercy may men heuen wynne,</L>
<L>&amp; thai that dos thaim no&yogh;t, sal no&yogh;t come ther-Inne.&mdash;</L>
<L>Bot ther are seuen warkes of mercy bodely,
<PB REF="00000446.tif" N="438"></L>
<L N="1076">&amp; also other seuen warkes of mercy gastly;</L>
<L>Thurgh trewe kepyng of any of this seuen</L>
<L>May a trewe cristen man wel come to heuen.</L>
<L>Sex bodely warkes has thou befor redde,</L>
<L>The [seuent] taght Tobie when he beryd the dede.</L>
<L N="1081">Seuen gastly warkes, that are of more mede,</L>
<L>May thou hald in thi mynd to thin awen spede:</L>
<L>The first is for to teche the vncunnand.</L>
<L N="1084">The second is to counsail the doutand.</L>
<L>The third is to confort him that is sorowful.</L>
<L>The ferth is to chasty him that is in synne wilful.</L>
<L>The fift is to forgif him that has ill wratthed the.</L>
<L N="1088">The sext is to support him that irksum is to the.</L>
<L>The seuent is to pray to god for all thes hertely,</L>
<L>That he amend thaim of thair faute thurgh his gret mercy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Of the paynes of hell.<NOTE PLACE="marg">The next passages are treated freely: most of the particulars are added.</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>TVrne we now agayn, sum-what for to telle</L>
<L N="1092">Of the orrible paynes that ay are in helle.</L>
<L>Helle is a depe pit stynkand, with all myrknes:</L>
<L>Ther the dampned ay sal be halden in gret distres.</L>
<L>All that is in the warld of filth &amp; of stynk,</L>
<L N="1096">At day of dome sal doun thedir synk,</L>
<L>ffor to eke thair stynkand payne, al be hit gret.</L>
<L>ffor ther sal be of hell-fire wondir huge hete;</L>
<L>That brennand fire with-outen ende so gretly hit glowes</L>
<L N="1100">That al the watur in the warld may not sloken his lowes.</L>
<L>Ther is als gret cold on another side:</L>
<L>Ther sudanly for more payne in to hit sal thei glide.</L>
<L>Thai sal no&yogh;t haue no roume ther on be-side another,</L>
<L N="1104">Bot all be cast on a hepe as of turf a fother;</L>
<L>Ilkon sal stynk on other &amp; double his payne,</L>
<L>&amp; ilkon ay to greue other sall be ful fayne.</L>
<L>Ther sal be gnasting of teth for gretnes of payne,</L>
<L N="1108">And euer in the hert a sorowe souerayne</L>
<L>That thai haue lost for a litil lykyng of synne</L>
<L>The ioye of the si&yogh;t of god that al godenes is Inne;
<PB REF="00000447.tif" N="439"></L>
<L>&amp; this worme of conscience sal bit thaim euermore</L>
<L N="1112">&amp; ouer all paynes ay be to thaim a sore.</L>
<L>No likyng sal thai haue, shortly for to say,</L>
<L>Bot al thing agayn thair wil that thaim gref may.</L>
<L>&amp; thus sal thai be punist aylastandly,</L>
<L N="1116">With-outen hope of mercy or any remedy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Of the ioyes of heuen.</HEAD>
<L>THair ioye in heuen sal wele more be</L>
<L>Then any hert may think or any egh se,</L>
<L>Ne non ert[h]ly mannes ere may wele here</L>
<L N="1120">The Ioye that god has ordaynd til his awen dere.</L>
<L>This ioye sall haue then aylastand sekirnes,</L>
<L>ffor crist, kyng of ioye, sal then be prince of pes.</L>
<L>Ilk mannes body of thaim that god wil saue</L>
<L N="1124">ffour fair dowers of ioye in heuen sal haue:</L>
<L>&para; ffirst the body sal be [so] parfit there,</L>
<L>That no thing in al the warld my&yogh;t him there [dere],</L>
<L>All the fir of hell my&yogh;t him neuer brenne,</L>
<L N="1128">If he neuer so lange were laide ther-Inne.</L>
<L>&para; The second dower of the body sal be bri&yogh;tnes</L>
<L>That man sal haue that dede<NOTE PLACE="marg">= died</NOTE> in gastly clennes;</L>
<L>Ilk a body sal be there seuen-[fold]<NOTE PLACE="marg">om.</NOTE> more bri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1132">Then the sunne is here when it most li&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&amp; this gret bri&yogh;tnes of the body</L>
<L>Sal euermore cleth hit fair &amp; honestly.</L>
<L>&para; The third dower of the body sal be sutilnes,</L>
<L N="1136">ffor hit sal be so clensid of all rudnes</L>
<L>That non erthly body may lette hit to passe,</L>
<L>More then the sunne-beme is lettid be the glas.</L>
<L>&para; The ferth dower of the body sal be deliuernes,</L>
<L N="1140">ffor hit sal be clensid so wel of alkyn heuynes</L>
<L>That sudanly, whedir as the saul has &yogh;ernyng,</L>
<L>Thedir sal the body glide with-outen more letting.</L>
<L N="1143">In thes four dowers sal thi body be so parfit</L>
<L>That of all erthly ioye of hit sal be delit.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">1145-1172 added.</NOTE>Thre gastly parties of thi saul ioye sal fulfill:</L>
<L>Thes are vnderstanding, a mynd, &amp; a will.</L>
<L N="1147">Vndirstanding that here was in trewth stedfast</L>
<L>Of poyntes of oure faith that manes [reson past],<NOTE PLACE="marg">om.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000448.tif" N="440"></L>
<L>Sal in clere si&yogh;ht of god al that he trowed se,</L>
<L>&amp; in that souerayn fair si&yogh;t al ful of blis be.</L>
<L>All wysdam, al godenes, all fairnes, al my&yogh;t</L>
<L>Sal rauysh man to the loue of god in that fair si&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="1153">Man sal se in god as in a myrour</L>
<L>All that he wil or may be to his honour.</L>
<L>Ilk man as he deserued mor or lesse here,</L>
<L>Sal haue ther ay the si&yogh;t of god more or lesse clere;</L>
<L N="1157">Bot al sal be so fully payd in that si&yogh;t</L>
<L>That couayt clerer si&yogh;t non sal haue no my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And thus in the saul the vnderstanding</L>
<L N="1160">Sal ay be fulfilled of ioye &amp; likyng,</L>
<L>And this sal be in mannes saul the first dower,</L>
<L>After that he deserued when that he was here.</L>
<L>His will that here loued god ouer al thing</L>
<L N="1164">&amp; his euen-cristen for goddes bidding,</L>
<L>In the loue of god ther sal be so parfit</L>
<L>That al his &yogh;ernyng sal be ful of delit;</L>
<L>That loue sal be ay so gret, so gode, &amp; so faire</L>
<L>That nothing that may befall sal hit oght empaire.</L>
<L N="1169">His mynd that hoped to haue ioye thurgh grace &amp; mercy</L>
<L>&amp; dyed stedfast in trouth with-outen synne dedly,</L>
<L>Sal haue mekil more ioye then he euer wend,</L>
<L N="1172">&amp; sikirnes that hit last ay with-outen end.</L>
<L>So sal ilk blissed saul be fulfillid of blis</L>
<L>That hit may nothing &yogh;ern thare that hit may mys.</L>
<L>He has parfit blis that has al his will,</L>
<L N="1176">&amp; so be that he then<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. tben</NOTE> nothing will ill.</L>
<L>Ther sal nothing be that may greue, bot al liking,</L>
<L>That sal ay last sikirly with-outen endyng.</L>
<L>Sothly, [thes] thre dowers of the saul are the gret blis,</L>
<L N="1180">And mannes ioye is mesurd after he has of this.</L>
<L>This gret ioye is of gode loue &amp; likyng &amp; si&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Al other ioye toward this [is] of litil my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>As he that has the sunne-li&yogh;t vpon a fair day,</L>
<L N="1184">ffor many torches if he li&yogh;t no better se he may;</L>
<L>No&yogh;t more li&yogh;t, bot more maners of li&yogh;t he has,</L>
<L>&amp; that may be to him a maner of solace.</L>
<L>Clere si&yogh;t of god sal ther be mannes fode
<PB REF="00000449.tif" N="441"></L>
<L N="1188">And bri&yogh;tnes of body sal be clething gode.</L>
<L>Wark sal be thare, of god a mery louyng,</L>
<L>That neuer with-outen end sal haue irking.</L>
<L>If adam hade lyued to the warldes ende</L>
<L N="1192">And al the wittes of all men god had him send,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it my&yogh;t he no&yogh;t haue told fully</L>
<L>The lest poynt of that ioye, verraily.</L>
<L>Ther sal be nothing that may displese,</L>
<L N="1196">Bot al honeste &amp; gode that may ese.</L>
<L>[Thre]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. ffour</NOTE> maner of men sal haue a ioye special,</L>
<L>That is callid in haly writ of ioye a coronale;</L>
<L>Thes thre maners are: verray martires,</L>
<L N="1200">Alle-clene uirgines, &amp; haly techers.</L>
<L>Ilkon sal haue ther als [mekil] ioye of othir</L>
<L>Als he were a thousand sith his brothir;</L>
<L>Ilkon of other ioye sal haue a liking,</L>
<L N="1204">&amp; that sal be [to] thaim of ioye a doubling;</L>
<L>This doubling sal be in noumbre a gretnes,</L>
<L>No&yogh;t to the ioye before euen mykilnes.</L>
<L>After degre of loue of god that man hade here</L>
<L N="1208">Sal his ioye be mesurd, with-outen any were.</L>
<L>Man sal haue souerayne ioye in si&yogh;t of godhede,</L>
<L>And sithen a gret ioye of crist[es] manhede,</L>
<L>That he is both god &amp; man that bo&yogh;t him with his blode</L>
<L N="1212">&amp; deyned to shewe to man so hertly mekil gode;</L>
<L>That his brother sal euer be his lord &amp; his god,</L>
<L>That sal be a confort to him with-outen make od.</L>
<L>In him-self he has his ioye of al the dowers</L>
<L N="1216">Both of body &amp; of saul, as clerkes vs leres.</L>
<L>Of the qwene of heuen, our lady mary,</L>
<L>That is goddes moder &amp; well of mercy,</L>
<L>fflour of all uirgines &amp; avowe to mankynd,</L>
<L N="1220">May all that are in heuen gret confort fynd;</L>
<L>Amang all creatures sho has wele of all weles,</L>
<L>ffor sho is moder of the king that al ioye deles.</L>
<L>Sithen ix. ordres of aungeles comfortes man in blis,</L>
<L N="1224">With thair gret myrth &amp; ioyfulnes that thai may neuer mys;</L>
<L>Sithen al maner of men that to blis wendis,</L>
<L>And specialy all gode men frendes
<PB REF="00000450.tif" N="442"></L>
<L>Ekys<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Ek ys</NOTE> his ioye &amp; confort when thai are mette,</L>
<L N="1228">And that sall ay last with-outen any lette.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it heuen &amp; erth &amp; all creatures</L>
<L>Sal be to mannes ioye, whiles hit endures.</L>
<L>All the sorow &amp; paynes of hell ay-lastandly</L>
<L>Sall confort him that eschaped thaim thurgh mercy.</L>
<L N="1233">Thus sal man in heuen ay fynd ioye &amp; leth,</L>
<L>Aboue him, with-Inne him, aboute &amp; beneth.</L>
<L>Ay, sais seint austyn sothfastly,</L>
<L N="1236">Man suld forsake resonably</L>
<L>All the welthes of this warld euermore &amp; ay,</L>
<L>ffor to haue the ioye of heuen only a day.</L>
<L>How mekil more then suld man ay forsake synne</L>
<L>While he lyued in erth, that blis for to wynne?</L>
<L>The godenes of god, the fairnes, the wysdam, the my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>The ioye, the solace, the confort that ay is In his si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Passes all mannes mynd, vndirstanding &amp; wit,</L>
<L N="1244">Bot if he may come to blis fully &amp; clerly se hit.</L>
<L>Ther-for he that all creatures first made of no&yogh;t</L>
<L>And with his awne hert-blode al mankynd bo&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Thurgh his grace &amp; mercy graunt vs that ioye to se,</L>
<L N="1248">How thre persones are all on god in trinite.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Amen.</TRAILER>
<TRAILER><I>Here endes the myrour of lewed men.</I></TRAILER>
<TRAILER>A Munk made this myrour, only for lewed mennes sake.<LB> Thou that will se saule-hele, this thi myrour thou take!</TRAILER>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="39" TYPE="part">

<PB REF="00000451.tif" N="443">
<HEAD>[XXXIX. Of &thorn;re messagers of deeth.<NOTE PLACE="foot">So the title in Index. The poem was ed. before in Herrig's <I>Archiv</I> LXXIX, p. 432. It is an old imitation of the "Sayings of S. Bernhard," XLV.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<ARGUMENT>
<L>Her biginne&thorn; a tretis</L>
<L>Of &thorn;reo Messagers of de&thorn;, I-wis.</L>
</ARGUMENT>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E Mon &thorn;at is of wommon I-bore,</L>
<L>His lyf nis heere but a &thorn;rowe&mdash;</L>
<L>So sei&thorn; Iob vs heer-bi-fore</L>
<L N="4">Al in a Bok &thorn;at I wel knowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He hedde is Muynde al of his de&thorn;,</L>
<L>Wel sore he con grone and grunte,</L>
<L>And seide his lyf nas bote a Bre&thorn;,</L>
<L N="8">Heer mou we none stounde stunte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffrom de&thorn; may no mon be fre,</L>
<L>ffor his ri&yogh;te wol he not lete.</L>
<L>Now beo&thorn; &thorn;er Messagers &thorn;re</L>
<L N="12">A-Mong Monkuynde for to meete:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Auentures, Seeknesse, and Elde&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;eos beo&thorn; Messagers of de&thorn;;</L>
<L>To hem we moten vs alle &yogh;elde</L>
<L N="16">And louten &thorn;er vr Maystres ge&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon Deth come&thorn; &thorn;at is so derk,</L>
<L>&THORN;er May no Mon him wi&thorn;-stonde;</L>
<L>I take witnesse on a noble Clerk</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at wrot &thorn;eos vers wi&thorn; his honde:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Mors necat athletas,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. vetat ath letas</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Ego mortis nescio metas,</I></L>
<L><I>I[n]ter</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Iter</NOTE> <I>Res letas,</I></L>
<L N="24"><I>Caueat sibi quelibet etas&mdash;</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"De&thorn;, he sleth &thorn;is kempes kene,</L>
<L>And kynges in heore wor&thorn;ly won,</L>
<L>Riche &amp; pore alle bi-dene,</L>
<L N="28">&YOGH;ong ne Old spare&thorn; he non."
<PB REF="00000452.tif" N="444"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er is on of &thorn;is Messagers</L>
<L>&THORN;at of no mon wol take mede;</L>
<L>He is so hardi and so fers</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at alle Men of him haue drede:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &THORN;is</NOTE> Messager hette Auentours;</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes him may beo no strif;</L>
<L>Whon he come&thorn; to a Monnes hous,</L>
<L N="36">He take&thorn; bo&thorn;e hosebonde &amp; &thorn;e wyf.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He take&thorn; &thorn;e child In his Cradel,</L>
<L>&THORN;eih he beo bot o niht old;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kniht and horse in his sadel</L>
<L N="40">I-a[r]med, beo he neuer so bold.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of him beo vche Mon I-war</L>
<L>And mak him clene, ar he beo hent;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er nis no &yogh;eyn-char,</L>
<L N="44">Whon Auentures come&thorn; to turnement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mony mon lih&thorn; in dedly synne</L>
<L>And wene&thorn; &thorn;at he beo not vey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And Auentures come&thorn; wi&thorn; his ginne</L>
<L N="48">And hontu&thorn; til he haue his preye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In dedly sunne ho<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. he</NOTE> is I-founde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen schrift and repentaunce,</L>
<L>He ge&thorn; in to helle-grounde,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;er to suffre his penaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seint Poul bit we schulden awake&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is Clerkes witen as wel as I&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at we schulden vs clene make</L>
<L N="56">And of vr sinnes ben sori;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And bote we ben, we schulen abugge;</L>
<L>&THORN;er schal no pledur plede &thorn;at;</L>
<L>&THORN;er God vs fynt, he wol vs Iugge&mdash;</L>
<L N="60">Nou vche Mon be war bi &thorn;at.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor Auentures wol come as a &thorn;ef</L>
<L>Be nihte, whon men ben aslepe,</L>
<L>And taken awey &thorn;at him is leef&mdash;</L>
<L N="64">Nou awake&thorn;, &thorn;at &yogh;e mowe him kepe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANo&thorn;er Messager &thorn;er is</L>
<L>Of De&thorn;, whon crist wol him sende:</L>
<L>Seknesse, Ichaue I-herd ar &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;e Messager is swi&thorn;e hende.
<PB REF="00000453.tif" N="445"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon seeknesse come&thorn; to a mon,</L>
<L>He may be war &yogh;if he is sleih,</L>
<L>And grei&thorn;en his In, &yogh;if &thorn;at he con,</L>
<L N="72">And &thorn;enken &thorn;at de&thorn; is swi&thorn;e neih.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor seknesse come&thorn; apertely,</L>
<L>He ne dare&thorn; not in his den;</L>
<L>Hit is vre lordes Cortesy</L>
<L N="76">Wi&thorn; seknesse for to warne men.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mony Men, whon &thorn;at heo beo&thorn; seke,</L>
<L>To Ihesu Crist a clepen and cri&yogh;e</L>
<L>And to his Mylde Mooder eke</L>
<L N="80">And sigge: "now &thorn;ou help, Marie!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at we mowe be sound and saue</L>
<L>And keuere, &thorn;at we mowen habben vr hele,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e good &thorn;at we haue</L>
<L N="84">ffor Godes loue we wolen hit dele."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>We loue wel God in al vr &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>While we beo seeke &amp; sore smerte;</L>
<L>Whon we beo&thorn; hol, we louen him nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="88">He nis no lengor in vre herte&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Cum fero langorem,</I></L>
<L><I>ffero Religionis amorem;</I></L>
<L><I>Expers langoris</I></L>
<L N="92"><I>Non sum memor huius amoris.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of crist ne take&thorn; he non hede,</L>
<L>He na&thorn; no more wi&thorn; him to donne;</L>
<L>To &thorn;onken him for his goode dede,</L>
<L N="96">He &thorn;enke&thorn; no more &thorn;er-vpponne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Suche men ben ofte al-one I-let</L>
<L>To pleye as &thorn;e foul in &thorn;e lift,</L>
<L>Til Auentures haue wi&thorn; hem met,</L>
<L N="100">Be-Reue&thorn; hem bo&thorn;e hosel and schrift.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Men ou&yogh;ten holden vp bo&thorn;e heore honden</L>
<L>To God, while heo ben hol and feere,</L>
<L>To sende, whon he wol hem fonden,</L>
<L N="104">Seeknesse to ben heore Messagere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt poul sei&thorn;, vre lordes kniht,</L>
<L>In a pistel &thorn;at he wrot,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was strengest &amp; most of miht</L>
<L N="108">Whon god him wi&thorn; seknesse smot.
<PB REF="00000454.tif" N="446"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOw ichulle siggen ou of Elde,</L>
<L>Of Messagers he is &thorn;e &thorn;ridde.</L>
<L>Whon Monnes hed biginne&thorn; to elde,</L>
<L N="112">He may not do but beodes bidde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And he leone&thorn; vppon his Crucche,</L>
<L>Whon de&thorn; him bekne&thorn;, comen he mot;</L>
<L>Hit helpe&thorn; nou&yogh;t &thorn;auh he grucche,</L>
<L N="116">He schal wi&thorn;-stonde neuer a fot.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also fare&thorn; Elde as do&thorn; a sweyn</L>
<L>&THORN;at stonde&thorn; at his lordes &yogh;ate</L>
<L>And mot not wenden in a&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L N="120">ffor &thorn;e po[r]ter &thorn;at is &thorn;er-ate;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor no &yogh;iftes &thorn;at he may &yogh;iuen,</L>
<L>Ne feire wordes &thorn;at he mai speken;</L>
<L>He wor&thorn; out atte &yogh;ate I-driuen,</L>
<L N="124">Anon &thorn;e &yogh;ate for him is steken.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;if a Mon may libben heer</L>
<L>And ben of pouwer for to go</L>
<L>&THORN;e Elde of ffoure-score &yogh;er,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;at o&thorn;er del is serwe and wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor hose wole his lyf be-holde</L>
<L>ffrom biginnynge to &thorn;e ende,</L>
<L>Wel ofte may his herte colde</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;at not what wey he schal wende;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wel we witen we schule be ded,</L>
<L>Vr dwellyng her nis bote a while&mdash;</L>
<L>Ihesu crist vs wisse and rede,</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;at neuer &thorn;e ffend ne do vs gyle.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou is de&thorn; a wonder &thorn;ing</L>
<L>And grislich for to &thorn;enken on;</L>
<L>He ne spare&thorn; Emperour ne kyng,</L>
<L N="140">Ne Pope for al &thorn;e good &thorn;at he con.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wher ben heo &thorn;at biforen vs weoren,</L>
<L>&THORN;at weore so mihti in heore deden,</L>
<L>Houndes ladden and haukes beeren<NOTE PLACE="marg">Same v. in Sayings of St. Bernhard, v. 182,</NOTE></L>
<L N="144">An hontyng hei&yogh;e vppon heore steeden?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>De&thorn; hit ha&thorn; hem al by-raft,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hem &thorn;er nis no more pley.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at bere&thorn; monnes schaft,</L>
<L N="148">Schal go &thorn;at ilke selue wey.
<PB REF="00000455.tif" N="447"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vche Mon may be sore aferd</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; a soule for to saue,</L>
<L>Whon he ge&thorn; bi a Chirche-&yogh;erd</L>
<L N="152">And seo&thorn; wher dede men be&thorn; I-graue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Riche men habbe&thorn; riche stones,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle men mouwe biholde:</L>
<L>&THORN;er-vnder ligge&thorn; foule bones,</L>
<L N="156">I-beddet al in Clo&thorn; of colde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wel pore halle &thorn;er is I-maked,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen eny worldes winne;</L>
<L>Saue a Clout, men beo&thorn; al naked,</L>
<L N="160">Whon de&thorn; is comen I-cast &thorn;er-Inne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e halle-Roof is cast ful lowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;er beo&thorn; none Chaumbres wyde;</L>
<L>Me may reche &thorn;e helewowe</L>
<L N="164">And &thorn;e wal on vche a syde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heore bodies<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. bodie</NOTE> &thorn;at weoren so softe I-ba&thorn;en<NOTE PLACE="marg">strong form, analog. to laden</NOTE></L>
<L>And I-brou&yogh;t for&thorn; wi&thorn; Mete and drynk,</L>
<L>&THORN;er hit schal crepe ful of Ma&thorn;en&mdash;</L>
<L N="168">In al &thorn;is world nis foulore stynk.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Mon &thorn;at such a bodi se&yogh;e</L>
<L>Whon wormes hit ha&thorn; &thorn;orw-souht,</L>
<L>He ou&yogh;te wepe wi&thorn; his e&yogh;e</L>
<L N="172">And euere haue him in his &thorn;ouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er nis non so luyte ne so muche</L>
<L>&THORN;at is of fflesch, blod and bon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we ne schule ben alle suche,</L>
<L N="176">Whon we ben huled vnder a ston.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hou may eny mon be proud</L>
<L>ffor eny &thorn;ing &thorn;at he may gete,</L>
<L>Whon he is huled vnder a schroud,</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at is wormes mete?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at is vr moste fo,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore we don a gret folye</L>
<L>To loue &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at do&thorn; vs wo,</L>
<L N="184">And eke vr dedliche enemye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;if a Mon may libben heer</L>
<L>As longe as dude Matussale&mdash;</L>
<L>Ni&yogh;ene hundred &amp; nyne &amp; sixti &yogh;er</L>
<L N="188">So longe on eor&thorn;e liuede he&mdash;
<PB REF="00000456.tif" N="448"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at nis not also muche tyme</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at come&thorn; afterward</L>
<L>As fro &thorn;e sonne-rysing to prime&mdash;</L>
<L N="192">To sunfol men &thorn;at is ful hard.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at I schal seye nou take&thorn; kepe,</L>
<L>I drawe to witnesse seynt Austyn:</L>
<L>&THORN;at a Mon schal more wepe</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;at dampned is to helle-pyn,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;en is water vnder &thorn;e sonne,</L>
<L>And he wepe vche day a ter.</L>
<L>Auise&thorn; ow now, &yogh;if &thorn;at &yogh;e cunne,</L>
<L N="200">And do&thorn; &thorn;at &yogh;e ne come not &thorn;er!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Mon &thorn;at dampned is to helle,</L>
<L>His peyne may not ben for-bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ac endeles he schal &thorn;er dwelle;</L>
<L N="204">Almes-dede helpe&thorn; him nouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ei alle men &thorn;at libbe&thorn; nou&thorn;e</L>
<L>Weore prestes Masses to synge,</L>
<L>And duden al &thorn;at &thorn;ei euer cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="208">Ne scholden him of pyne bringe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at ilke soule &thorn;at is dryuen</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fendes in atte helle-&yogh;ate,</L>
<L>And his Iuggement be him &yogh;iuen,</L>
<L N="212">To bidde Merci hit is to late.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heuene hit is vre heritage,</L>
<L>To vre bihoue hit is diht,</L>
<L>[&YOGH;if]<NOTE PLACE="marg">om.</NOTE> we han do feute and homage</L>
<L N="216">To vre lord, as hit is riht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Synful mon, &yogh;if &thorn;at he falle&thorn;,</L>
<L>A-Rys vp and mak &thorn;i pees,</L>
<L>And cum to crist, whon &thorn;at he calle&thorn;</L>
<L N="220">To Ioye &thorn;at is endeles.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He &thorn;at is al-mihti kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hei&yogh;e sitte&thorn; In Trinite,</L>
<L>Graunt vs alle his blessyng,</L>
<L N="224">AMEN AMEN par charite.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="40" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000457.tif" N="449">
<HEAD>[XL. Two Songs of Love-longing.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">Title in Index: An orisoun to crist, Songes to vre lady, Orisones to vre lady rehersinge of crist what he dude and suffrede for mankynde. The two first poems (from v. 5) are extant in MS. Harl. 2253, fol. 75 and 77 (ed. in Wright, Specimens of Lyric Poets, Percy Soc. 1842, p. 57 and 68, and B&ouml;d|deker, Altengl. Dicht. 1878, p. 191 and 198); the 2nd, an imitation of St. Bernard's 'Jesu dulcis memoria' (Daniel Thes. hymn. I, p. 227), has, in MS. Vern., been divided into several parts, each headed by a stanza to St. Mary (MS. Harl. 2253 has a separate French song to St. Mary, f. 77: Marie mere al Salveour, ed. Wright), and expanded, by various additions (v. 17-44, 57|80, 141-191 &amp;c.) and ingredients (f. i. from Testam. Christi, v. 173 ff.) into a history of the Passion, forming at the same time a corollary to St. Mary. The original poems were composed in the South, the additions in the North (by Rich. Rolle?). Another love-song of this kind, in alliterative long-lines, is contained in the prose-part of MS. Vernon.</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>[I.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, now wol I synge<MILESTONE N="CCXCVII" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e a song of loue longinge:</L>
<L>Do in myn herte a welle springe</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e to louen ouer alle &thorn;inge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">v. 5-60 occurs as a separate poem in Harl. 2253 (ed. Wright).</NOTE>Swete Ihesu, kyng of blisse,</L>
<L>Min herte loue, Min herte lisse:</L>
<L>In loue, lord, &thorn;ou me wisse,</L>
<L N="8">And let me neuere &thorn;i loue misse.<NOTE PLACE="foot">7-8 H &THORN;ou art suete myd-y-wisse Wo is him &thorn;at &thorn;e shal misse.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, myn herte liht,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow art day wi&thorn;-oute niht:</L>
<L>&YOGH;iue me bo&thorn;e Grace and<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;ou &yogh;eve me strein&thorn;e &amp; eke m.</NOTE> miht</L>
<L N="12">ffor to loue<NOTE PLACE="foot">H louien</NOTE> &thorn;e ariht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, my soule<NOTE PLACE="foot">H huerte</NOTE> bote,</L>
<L>In myn herte &thorn;ou sette<NOTE PLACE="foot">H sete</NOTE> a Roote</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i loue &thorn;at is so swote,</L>
<L N="16">And weete hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ant lene</NOTE> &thorn;at hit springe mote!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, myn herte gleem,</L>
<L>Brihtore &thorn;en &thorn;e sonne Beem:</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou weore boren<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ybore &thorn;ou were</NOTE> In Bethleem,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;ou make in me &thorn;i loue-dreem.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;ou m. me here &thorn;i suete d.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, &thorn;i loue is swete&mdash;</L>
<L>Wo is him &thorn;at hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;e</NOTE> schal leete!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if me grace for to wepe</L>
<L N="24">ffor my synnes teres wete.<NOTE PLACE="foot">23-4 H &THORN;arefore me shulden ofte &thorn;e grete Wi&thorn; salte teres &amp; e&yogh;e wepe.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000458.tif" N="450"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, kyng of londe,</L>
<L>Mak &thorn;ou me to vnderstonde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;ou make me fer v.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at I may In myn herte fonde<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;at min herte mote f.</NOTE></L>
<L N="28">Hou swete is<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bue&thorn;</NOTE> &thorn;i loue-bonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, me rewe&thorn; sore</L>
<L>Of my misdedes I haue don &yogh;ore:</L>
<L>ffor-&yogh;if me, lord, I wol no more,</L>
<L N="32">But I &thorn;e aske Milce and ore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, Lord<NOTE PLACE="foot">H louerd</NOTE> myn,</L>
<L>Mi lyf, my soule is al<NOTE PLACE="foot">H myn huerte al is</NOTE> &thorn;in:</L>
<L>Vndo myn herte and li&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="foot">H liht</NOTE> &thorn;erin,</L>
<L N="36">And saue<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wite</NOTE> me from wikked<NOTE PLACE="foot">H fendes</NOTE> engyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">In H precede 45-8, then follows: Suete ihesu, me reowe&thorn; sore, Gultes &thorn;at y ha wro&thorn;t &yogh;ore, &THORN;arefore y bidde &thorn;in mylse &amp; ore, Merci, lord, ynul na more.</NOTE>Swete Ihesu, lord good,</L>
<L>ffor me &thorn;ou scheddest &thorn;i blessed blod<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;ou me bohtest wi&thorn; &thorn;i blod</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;in herte hit com<NOTE PLACE="foot">H orn; hit, om. in H.</NOTE> &thorn;e flod&mdash;</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;i Moder hit sau&yogh; wi&thorn; druyri mod<NOTE PLACE="foot">H seh &thorn;at &thorn;e by stod</NOTE>:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, Briht and Schene,</L>
<L>Heere me, lord, for I me mene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Y preye &thorn;e &thorn;ou here my bene</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;orw preyere of Marie, Milde qweene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ourh erndyng of &thorn;e heuene-q.</NOTE></L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at &thorn;i loue on me be sene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;at my bone be nou sene.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, Mi soule foode,</L>
<L>Alle werkes of &thorn;e ben goode;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;in werkes bue&thorn; bo suete &amp; gode</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou bou&yogh;test me vppon &thorn;e Rode</L>
<L N="48">And scheddest &thorn;eron &thorn;i swete blode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H For me &thorn;ou sheddest &thorn;i blode</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, Barn<NOTE PLACE="foot">H berne</NOTE> Best,</L>
<L>&THORN;i loue &thorn;ou in myn herte fest;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Wi&thorn; [&thorn;e] ich hope habbe rest</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon I go North, Sou&thorn;, Est or West,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Whe&thorn;er y be sou&thorn; o&thorn;er west</NOTE></L>
<L N="52">In &thorn;e al-one fynde I rest.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;e help of &thorn;e be me nest</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, wel may him be</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e schal<NOTE PLACE="foot">H may</NOTE> in &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot">om. in H</NOTE> blisse se!</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; loue-cordes drau&yogh; &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;at I may comen and wone wi&thorn; &thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">55-6 H: After mi soule let aungles te, For me ne gladie&thorn; gome ne gle.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000459.tif" N="451"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, heuene-kyng,</L>
<L>ffeir and best ouer<NOTE PLACE="foot">H of</NOTE> alle &thorn;ing:</L>
<L>Bring me in to &thorn;at loue-longyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;ou bring me of &thorn;is longing</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">To<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &amp;</NOTE> come to &thorn;e at myn endyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H adds: Suete ihesu, al folkes reed, Graunte ous er we buen ded, &THORN;e vnderfonge in fourme of bred, Ant se&thorn;&thorn;e to heouene &thorn;ou vs led.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>[II.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MArie Moder, Mylde Qween,</L>
<L>Send vs grace synne to flen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mowe &thorn;i sone i-sen</L>
<L N="4">And euere wi&thorn; hym in Blisse ben.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">This is a 2nd poem in Harl. 2253, fol. 77b, with the title: 'Dulcis ihesu memoria.'</NOTE>Ihesu, swete is &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Ne may no &thorn;ing so swete be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H No&thorn;ing so suete may be</NOTE></L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t &thorn;at mon may &thorn;enke or se,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Al &thorn;at [me] may wi&thorn; e&yogh;en se</NOTE></L>
<L N="8">Ne haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Haue&thorn; no</NOTE> swetnesse a&yogh;eynes &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, no song<NOTE PLACE="foot">H no&thorn;ing</NOTE> mai be swettore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H suettere</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne &thorn;ou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">H noht</NOTE> in herte<NOTE PLACE="foot">eor&thorn;e</NOTE> Blisfollere,</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t may be feeled lihtsomere<NOTE PLACE="foot">H lykerusere</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">&THORN;en &thorn;ou, so swete a louyere<NOTE PLACE="foot">H alumere</NOTE>!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i loue was vs<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wes ous</NOTE> so fre</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">H we</NOTE> from heuene brou&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="foot">H brohten</NOTE> &thorn;e,</L>
<L>ffor loue ful deore bou&yogh;test &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;ou deore bohtest</NOTE> me,</L>
<L N="16">ffor loue &thorn;ow henge<NOTE PLACE="foot">H hong</NOTE> on<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. or</NOTE> Roode-tre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">The next 7 stanzas om. in H.</NOTE>Ihesu, to &thorn;i disciples dere</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seydest wi&thorn; ful dreri chere</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei seeten alle I-feere</L>
<L N="20">A luytel ar &thorn;ou taken were&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;ou seydest &thorn;at &thorn;ou wore</L>
<L>fful of serwe and herte-sore,</L>
<L>And beed hem dwellen a while &thorn;ore</L>
<L N="24">While &thorn;ou beo-sou&yogh;test &thorn;i ffader ore;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;ou eodest on &thorn;i feete</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Mount of Olyuete,
<PB REF="00000460.tif" N="452"></L>
<L>And to &thorn;i ffader, er &thorn;ou leete,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;ow madest a boone wi&thorn; herte swete:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To him &thorn;ou seidest: "&yogh;if hit may be,</L>
<L>Deore ffader, I preye &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;is peyne passe a-wey from me;</L>
<L N="32">As &thorn;ow wolt so moot hit be!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;ou tornedest to hem &thorn;an:</L>
<L>And founde hem slepen vch a man;</L>
<L>&THORN;ow beede hem waken, &amp;, er &thorn;ou blan,</L>
<L N="36">A-non a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e wey &thorn;ou nam.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;us eft &thorn;e selue boone</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou beo-fore bi-gonne to done,</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;e &thorn;ridde tyme sone</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;ow madest, wi&thorn; a Milde mone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, wi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ou preye gon,</L>
<L>&THORN;e swot of blood from &thorn;e ron.</L>
<L>ffrom heuene an Angel lihte &thorn;on</L>
<L N="44">And &thorn;e cumfortede, God and Mon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">This st. is om. in H.</NOTE>MArie Mylde, freo and gent,</L>
<L>Preye for me&mdash;&thorn;ou art present&mdash;</L>
<L>Whon my soule is from me went,</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;at hit haue good Iuggement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, for loue &thorn;ou soffredest<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;oledest</NOTE> wrong,</L>
<L>Woundes sore and peynes<NOTE PLACE="foot">H pine</NOTE> strong;</L>
<L>&THORN;i peynes reu&thorn;ful weore and long,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;ine peynes rykene hit were long</NOTE></L>
<L N="52">Ne may me hit telle in spel<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ne may hem tellen spel</NOTE> ne song.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, for loue &thorn;ou suffredest so<NOTE PLACE="foot">H dre&yogh;edest; so, om. in H.</NOTE> wo</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">om. in H.</NOTE> bloodi stremes Ronne &thorn;e fro;</L>
<L>&THORN;i white bodi was bleyk<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;at &thorn;i bodi wes blak</NOTE> and blo&mdash;</L>
<L N="56">Vre sunnes hit made, weylawo<NOTE PLACE="foot">H For oure s. hit wes so</NOTE>!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">The next 6 stanzas om. in H.</NOTE>Ihesu, &thorn;i Coroune sat &thorn;e sore,</L>
<L>&THORN;e scourgyng whon &thorn;ow scourget wore;</L>
<L>Hit was for me&mdash;Ihesu, &thorn;in ore!&mdash;</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;e peynes &thorn;at &thorn;ow &thorn;oledest &thorn;ore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu swete, &thorn;ow heng on tre</L>
<L>Not for &thorn;i gult, but al for me,
<PB REF="00000461.tif" N="453"></L>
<L>ffor sunnes and gult a&yogh;eynes &thorn;e&mdash;</L>
<L N="64">Swete Ihesu, for-&yogh;if hem me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, whon &thorn;ow streyned wore,</L>
<L>&THORN;i peynes woxen more and more.</L>
<L>&THORN;i Mooder euer wi&thorn; &thorn;e was &thorn;ore,</L>
<L N="68">Wi&thorn; serweful sikynges and wi&thorn; sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, whi weore &thorn;ou pyned so</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer wrou&yogh;test wrong ne wo?</L>
<L>Hit was for me, and moni mo,</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at &thorn;ou so harde were bi-go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, what sauh &thorn;ow on me</L>
<L>Of ou&yogh;t &thorn;at neodful was to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou so harde on Roode-tre</L>
<L N="76">ffor me woldest pyned be?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, whi weore &thorn;ou so gelous,</L>
<L>So feruent and so disirrous</L>
<L>To buggen wi&thorn; pris so precious</L>
<L N="80">Wrecche Mon so vicious?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, for vs &thorn;ou henge<NOTE PLACE="foot">H for loue &thorn;ou stehe</NOTE> on Rode,</L>
<L>ffor loue &thorn;ou &yogh;eeue<NOTE PLACE="foot">H se&yogh;e</NOTE> &thorn;in herte-blode;</L>
<L>Loue &thorn;e made<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;ou madest</NOTE> vre soule foode,</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;i loue vs brouhte to alle goode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu my lemmon, &thorn;ou art so fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al<NOTE PLACE="foot">om. in H</NOTE> &thorn;ou dedest<NOTE PLACE="foot">H de&yogh;|edest</NOTE> for loue of me:</L>
<L>What<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Whet</NOTE> schal I for &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;arefore</NOTE> &yogh;eelde &thorn;e?</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;ow kepest not but &thorn;e loue of me.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;ar nys noht bote hit loue be,</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu my god, my lord,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ihesu</NOTE> my kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou askest<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ne askesd</NOTE> me non o&thorn;er &thorn;yng</L>
<L>But trewe loue and herte longyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &amp; eke seruyng</NOTE></L>
<L N="92">And loue-teres and stille<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wi&thorn; suete</NOTE> mournyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu my deore, my loue, my liht,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H I. my lyf, ihesu</NOTE></L>
<L>I wol &thorn;e louen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ich loue &thorn;e</NOTE> and &thorn;at is riht.</L>
<L>Do me &thorn;e louen<NOTE PLACE="foot">H loue &thorn;e</NOTE> wi&thorn; al my miht,</L>
<L N="96">And after<NOTE PLACE="foot">H for</NOTE> &thorn;e Mourne<NOTE PLACE="foot">H mournen</NOTE> dai &amp; niht!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, do me so loue<NOTE PLACE="foot">H seruen</NOTE> &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at my &thorn;ouht ay on<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;at euer mi &thorn;oht vpon</NOTE> &thorn;e be;
<PB REF="00000462.tif" N="454"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;in e&yogh;en lok on me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Wi&thorn; &thorn;ine suete e&yogh;en loke towart me</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">And Myldeliche my nede se!<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ant myldeliche myne, y preie, al &thorn;at &thorn;ou se</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">This stanza om. in H.</NOTE>MArie ladi, Mooder briht,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou darst, &thorn;ou wolt, &thorn;ou art of miht,&mdash;</L>
<L>Myn herte loue, my lyf, my liht,</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;ou prey for me bo&thorn;e day &amp; niht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i loue is<NOTE PLACE="foot">H be</NOTE> al my &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;er &thorn;ing ne recche I nouht,</L>
<L>But &thorn;at I haue a-&yogh;eyn &thorn;e wrouht<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Y &yogh;yrne to haue &thorn;i wille ywroht For &thorn;ou me hauest wel d. yb.</NOTE></L>
<L N="108">And &thorn;ou hast me so deore a-bouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, al-<NOTE PLACE="foot">om. in H.</NOTE>&thorn;au&yogh; I synful be,</L>
<L>fful longe hastou spared<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Wel longe &thorn;ou hauest y-sp.</NOTE> me;</L>
<L>&THORN;e more owe I to loue<NOTE PLACE="foot">H oh ich to louie</NOTE> &thorn;e</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;at &thorn;ou wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">om. in H.</NOTE> me hast<NOTE PLACE="foot">H hauest</NOTE> ben so fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">The next 6 lines om. in H.</NOTE>Ihesu, forso&thorn;e now nis no &thorn;ing</L>
<L>In al &thorn;is world of such lykyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at con so muche of loue-longyng,</L>
<L N="116">As &thorn;ou Ihesu, my deore swetyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, wel ou&yogh;t I loue &thorn;e,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou me schewest &thorn;i Rode-tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;i Coroune<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bac</NOTE> of &thorn;ornes, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;y</NOTE> nayles &thorn;re,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;e scharpe spere &thorn;at &thorn;orw-stong &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, of loue I seo tokenyng:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H of l. soth tocknynge</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;in Armes spradde to loue-cluppyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H sprede&thorn; to mankynde</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;in hed bouwede<NOTE PLACE="foot">H heued doun bowe&thorn;</NOTE> to swete cussyng,</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;i syde al opene to loue-schewyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H opene&thorn; to loue-longynge</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, whon I<NOTE PLACE="foot">H when ich</NOTE> &thorn;enke on &thorn;e</L>
<L>And loke vppon &thorn;e Roode-tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;i swete bodi bi-bled<NOTE PLACE="foot">H to-toren</NOTE> I se:</L>
<L N="128">Lord, do &thorn;at siht to wounde me!<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Hit make&thorn; heorte to smerte me.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i Moder<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;e quene</NOTE> &thorn;at bi &thorn;e stood,</L>
<L>Of loue-teres heo wepte<NOTE PLACE="foot">H weop</NOTE> a flood;</L>
<L>&THORN;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;in</NOTE> woundes and &thorn;yn holy blood</L>
<L N="132">Heo maden hire haue a<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Made hire huerte of</NOTE> dreri mood.
<PB REF="00000463.tif" N="455"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, loue &thorn;e dude to wepen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H I. suete l. &thorn;e d. gredyn</NOTE></L>
<L>Loue &thorn;e dude<NOTE PLACE="foot">H made</NOTE> &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot">om. in H.</NOTE> blod to sweten,</L>
<L>ffor loue &thorn;ou were sore beten,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H y-b.</NOTE></L>
<L N="136">Loue &thorn;e dude &thorn;i lyf to leten.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">The whole next section, lines 137-192, is left out in H.</NOTE>MArie, I prei &thorn;e, as &thorn;ou art fre,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i serwe parte wi&thorn; me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I mowe serwe here wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L N="140">And partiner of &thorn;i blisse be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i loue &thorn;ou tauhtest me</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swete wordes of herte fre</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou speek on Roode-tre&mdash;</L>
<L N="144">So ful of loue ne mihte non be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;e furste word was, as I rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;i deore ffader beede</L>
<L>&THORN;at he for&yogh;af hem heore misdede,</L>
<L N="148">Alle &thorn;at duden &thorn;e to dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;at o&thorn;er was I-wis</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou seidest, as writen is:</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e &thorn;eef schulde haue blis</L>
<L N="152">Wi&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;at day in paradis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde was of Mon:</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;i Mooder &thorn;e schulde forgon,</L>
<L>A Sone &thorn;ou hire be-tauhtest on,</L>
<L N="156">And seidest: "wommon, tak heer Ion!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, as &thorn;ou weore pyned more,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e word &thorn;ou seydest &thorn;ore:</L>
<L>"A," seydest &thorn;ow, "me &thorn;urste&thorn; sore"&mdash;</L>
<L N="160">Hit was for hem &thorn;at dampned wore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;e ffyf&thorn;e word Rewe&thorn; me</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow seidest on Roode-tre:</L>
<L>"Mi God, Mi God, hou may &thorn;is be</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast al forsake me?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;e Sixte word hit was</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou seidest "In manus tuas,"</L>
<L>Be-tauhtest &thorn;i ffader in &thorn;at plas</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;i soule, as his wille was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, In al &thorn;i peyne mest</L>
<L>Neuere was so meke best&mdash;
<PB REF="00000464.tif" N="456"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou seydest "Consummatum est,"</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;yn hed fel doun, &thorn;ou &yogh;elde &thorn;e gost.<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. gest</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;ou seidest; "alle &yogh;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at passen be &thorn;e wey bi me,</L>
<L N="175">A while a-byde&thorn;, come&thorn; and se</L>
<L>&YOGH;if eny serwe is lyk to me."<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Testamentum Christi, vv. 93-6.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;ou seidest: "tel &thorn;ow me,</L>
<L>Mi deore folk, what hit may be,</L>
<L>What haue I gult a&yogh;eynes &thorn;e</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at &thorn;ou so bitter art to me?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;ou seydest &thorn;enne more:</L>
<L>"Mi deore folk, &yogh;e tel me &yogh;ore,</L>
<L>Haue I wi&thorn; myn holi lore</L>
<L N="184">And gode dedes I-hurt so sore?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;ou seidest after &yogh;et:</L>
<L>"Mi deore wyn&yogh;ard, ne haue I &thorn;e set,</L>
<L>Mi ffader blisse &thorn;e bi-het,</L>
<L N="188">Wi&thorn; al my-self&mdash;what woldest &thorn;ou bet?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;ou seidest: "hou is &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Mi Swete, what haue I do mis</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou wi&thorn;-outen eny lis</L>
<L N="192">Me &yogh;eldest schome a&yogh;eyn Mi blis?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">This st. om. in H.</NOTE>MArie, &thorn;at slakest alle wo,</L>
<L>Helle-peynes schild me fro,</L>
<L>And &yogh;if me grace her do so</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;at I from henne to heuene go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, ffyue welles<NOTE PLACE="foot">H woundes</NOTE> I fynde in &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at loue spring to drawe me<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;y loue-sprenges tache&thorn; me</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Of Rede blod<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Of blod &amp; water</NOTE> &thorn;e stremes be,</L>
<L N="200">Mi soule of synnes wasschen heo.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Vs to whosshe from oure fon &thorn;re.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, my soule drau&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H saule drah</NOTE> &thorn;e to,</L>
<L>And mak myn herte<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Min heorte opene &amp;</NOTE> wyde vndo;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if hit &thorn;i loue<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;is hure of l.</NOTE> to drynke so,</L>
<L N="204">&THORN;at flessches lustes ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">H fleyssliche lust be al</NOTE> fordo!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">The next 2 stanzas om. in H.</NOTE>Ihesu, Muchel Ich owe &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Who schal hit al &yogh;elde &thorn;e?
<PB REF="00000465.tif" N="457"></L>
<L>Me bi-houe&thorn; &thorn;i-self hit be,</L>
<L N="208">As &thorn;ou pyne suffredest for me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i loue &yogh;ef me follyke,</L>
<L>In myn herte &thorn;at hit stike,</L>
<L>Mi soule hit &thorn;urle Inwardliche,</L>
<L N="212">&THORN;at hit be &thorn;yn enteerliche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ihesu crist</NOTE> do me loue &thorn;e so</L>
<L>&THORN;at, wher I beo or what<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &amp; what-so</NOTE> I do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I for weole ne for wo<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Lyf ne de&thorn;, weole ne wo</NOTE></L>
<L N="216">Ne let<NOTE PLACE="foot">H do</NOTE> myn herte torne &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;e turne</NOTE> fro.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">The next 3 stanzas om. in H. (Similar vv. occur in Rich. Rolle's 'Fourme of parfit liuing.')</NOTE>Ihesu lord, Mi swetyng,</L>
<L>Hold me euere in &thorn;y kepyng,</L>
<L>Mak of me &thorn;i derlyng,</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at I &thorn;e loue ouer alle &thorn;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, my weole and al my wynne,</L>
<L>Al my Ioye is &thorn;e wi&thorn;-Inne:</L>
<L>Now and euere kep me from synne,</L>
<L N="224">To do &thorn;i wille let me not blynne!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, mihtful Heuene-kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;i loue beo al my lykyng,</L>
<L>Mi mournyng and my longyng,</L>
<L N="228">Wi&thorn; swete teres wepyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &yogh;if me<NOTE PLACE="foot">H do me &thorn;at</NOTE> for &thorn;i name</L>
<L>Pacience In peyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Me like&thorn; to dre&yogh;e pyne</NOTE> and schame,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to my soule is<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;at is &thorn;y s.</NOTE> note and frame;</L>
<L N="232">And mak myn herte Mylde &amp; tame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, Al &thorn;at is feir to se,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;e, H se</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e fflessches lykyng may be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Al &thorn;at to fleyhs mai likyng be</NOTE></L>
<L>Al worldes blisse do me fle<NOTE PLACE="foot">H b. to leten, me</NOTE></L>
<L N="236">And al my tent &yogh;iue<NOTE PLACE="foot">Graunte, for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e.</NOTE> to &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">In H this stanza precedes the last 2 stanzas.</NOTE>MArie, Swete Mayden<NOTE PLACE="foot">H mayde</NOTE> fre,</L>
<L>ffor Ihesu [crist] be-seche I &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&THORN;i swete sone do loue<NOTE PLACE="foot">H louie</NOTE> me,</L>
<L N="240">And mak me wor&thorn;i &thorn;at hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">H y</NOTE> so be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, in &thorn;e beo al my &thorn;ou&yogh;t&mdash;
<PB REF="00000466.tif" N="458"></L>
<L>Of o&thorn;er &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">H blisse</NOTE> ne recche I<NOTE PLACE="foot">H recchy</NOTE> nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Whon I of &thorn;e may felen ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="244">&THORN;en is my soule wel of &thorn;ou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wel y-wroht</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &yogh;if &thorn;ou for-lete<NOTE PLACE="foot">H forletest</NOTE> me,</L>
<L>What may me lyken<NOTE PLACE="foot">H mi likyng</NOTE> of &thorn;at I se?</L>
<L>Blisse may non<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Mai no god blisse</NOTE> wi&thorn; me be,</L>
<L N="248">Til &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">H O &thorn;at</NOTE> &thorn;ou come a&yogh;eyn to me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;at me hast deore abouht,<NOTE PLACE="foot">249-252 H Ihesu, &yogh;ef &thorn;ou bist &yogh;eorne by|soht: When &thorn;ou comest, ant elles noht, No fleishlich lust ne wicked &thorn;oht In to myn heorte ne be y-broht.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al &thorn;at to synne drawe&thorn; ouht</L>
<L>Holliche puyt out of my &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="252">So &thorn;at I ne wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;e nou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, my soule is weddet<NOTE PLACE="foot">H spoused</NOTE> to &thorn;e&mdash;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; rihte hit ouhte &thorn;in owne to be<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ofte ych habbe misdon a&yogh;eynes &thorn;e;</NOTE>,</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; I haue synget a&yogh;eynes &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ihesu, &thorn;i merci is wel fre; Ihesu, merci y crie to &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L N="256">&THORN;i Merci is euere redi to me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu &thorn;i Merci, bi-leue<NOTE PLACE="foot">H I., wi&thorn; herte &thorn;i loue</NOTE> I craue&mdash;</L>
<L>Me bihoue&thorn; &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Hit bihoue&thorn; nede</NOTE> I hit haue;</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuh of grace vppon me laue,</L>
<L N="260">And wor&thorn;i me make &thorn;i loue to haue.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ant from alle harmes &thorn;ou me saue</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;ou be al my &yogh;ernyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H I., from me be al &thorn;at &thorn;yng &THORN;at me (r. &thorn;e) may be to mislik|yng; Al &thorn;at is nede &thorn;ou me bryng; To haue &thorn;i loue is my &yogh;yrnyng.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e be, lord, al my lykyng,</L>
<L>Mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t, my dede, and my Mournyng</L>
<L N="264">To haue &thorn;e Euere in loue-longyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, my leof,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H lif</NOTE> Mylde of mood,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H of milde</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi soule ha&thorn; neode<NOTE PLACE="foot">H gret n.</NOTE> of &thorn;i good:</L>
<L>Mak hit clene<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Tak hire treufole</NOTE> and &thorn;olemood,</L>
<L N="268">And ful hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">H hire</NOTE> of &thorn;i loue-flod.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H blod</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, my soule preye&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bidde y</NOTE> &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Let hit nou&yogh;t vnclo&thorn;ed be<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Eueremore wel vs be</NOTE>;</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Lines 271-284 om. in H.</NOTE>Clo&thorn;e hit wi&thorn; &thorn;i loue fre,</L>
<L N="272">Wi&thorn; goode werkes &thorn;at lyken &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, Beute ne aske I &thorn;e nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ne proude clo&thorn;es nobli wrou&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000467.tif" N="459"></L>
<L>Londes ne Rentes, deore bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="276">But hertly loue and clene &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, whonne so hit lyke&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Loue-sparkes send &thorn;ou me;</L>
<L>Mak myn herte al hot to be,</L>
<L N="280">Brennynde in &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MArie, &thorn;i sone preye hertely</L>
<L>ffor me, wrecche vnwor&thorn;y,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wole enterly</L>
<L N="284">Graunte me his Merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu almihti,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H al myhtful</NOTE> heuene-kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;i loue is a ful<NOTE PLACE="foot">H wel</NOTE> derne &thorn;ing;</L>
<L>May no mon hit witen &thorn;orw knowyng,</L>
<L N="288">But he hit feele &thorn;orw herte &thorn;enkyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">287-8 om. in H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">The next 2 st. om. in H.</NOTE>Ihesu, &yogh;if me &thorn;at I may see</L>
<L>&THORN;e Muchele good &thorn;ou hast do me.</L>
<L>And I vnkynde a&yogh;eyn haue be,</L>
<L N="292">ffor-&yogh;if me, lord, &thorn;at art so fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i loue and fleschly &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Wonen to-gedre ne mouwe &thorn;[e]i nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>As Hony &amp; galle to-gedre brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="296">Swete and Bitter a-corde&thorn; nou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ihesu, wel mai myn herte se &THORN;at milde &amp; meoke he mot be, Alle vn&thorn;ewes &amp; lustes fle, &THORN;at felen wole &thorn;e blisse of &thorn;e.</NOTE>Ihesu, wi&thorn; herte I &thorn;onke &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; I wrecche and sunfol be,</L>
<L>In trewe hope I preye &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;i Blisse &amp; Merci graunte &thorn;ou me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;auh I be vnwor&thorn;i</L>
<L>To loue &thorn;e, lord Almihti,</L>
<L>&THORN;i godnesse<NOTE PLACE="foot">H loue</NOTE> me make&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H m. to ben</NOTE> hardi</L>
<L N="304">Mi soule to don<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ant don me al</NOTE> in &thorn;i Merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i Merci cumforte&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;i mildenesse frore&thorn;</NOTE> me:</L>
<L>ffor no mon may so synful be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at synne wol leue<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &yogh;ef he let sunne</NOTE> and to &thorn;e fle,</L>
<L N="308">&THORN;at Merci ful redi fynde&thorn; he.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;at ne find socour at &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, for synful, as writen is,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H For sunful folk, suete ihesus</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou lihtest from &thorn;in hei&yogh;e blis<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;e h. hous</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000468.tif" N="460"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">H Pore &amp; lo&yogh;e &thorn;ou were for ous, &THORN;in heorte loue &thorn;ou sendest ous.</NOTE>In to Marie wombe, I-wis,</L>
<L N="312">To &yogh;iuen vs alle reste and lis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">The next st. om. in H.</NOTE>Ihesu, &thorn;au&yogh; I synful be,</L>
<L>I haue euere trust hope in &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, lord, I preye &thorn;e</L>
<L N="316">&THORN;at of my synnes amende &thorn;ou me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">In H this st. follows v. 384.</NOTE>Ihesu, &thorn;ou art so good a mon,</L>
<L>&THORN;i loue desyre I as<NOTE PLACE="foot">H y &yogh;yrne al-so</NOTE> I con;</L>
<L>Me to lette suffre &thorn;ing non,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;are-fore ne lette me nomon &THORN;ah ich for loue be blac ant won.</NOTE></L>
<L N="320">Swete Ihesu, my deore lemmon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, euere<NOTE PLACE="foot">H for&thorn;i</NOTE> beo-seche I &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;in Inward<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;i suete</NOTE> loue &thorn;ou graunte me;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; I &thorn;erto vnwor&thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at ich &thorn;are-to wor&thorn;i</NOTE> be,</L>
<L N="324">&THORN;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">om. in H.</NOTE> mak me wor&thorn;i, &thorn;at art so fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">This st. om. in H.</NOTE>MArie Milde, ful of pite,</L>
<L>Prey &thorn;i deore Sone for me</L>
<L>&THORN;at he graunte me to be</L>
<L N="328">Euere in blisse wi&thorn; him and &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu al swete, &thorn;at art<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ihesu</NOTE> al good,</L>
<L>Do &thorn;i loue drynke<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;i loue drynke&thorn;</NOTE> myn herte-blod.</L>
<L>&THORN;i loue me make&thorn; so swete<NOTE PLACE="foot">H swi&thorn;e</NOTE>-wod</L>
<L N="332">&THORN;at wonder blisful is my mood.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;at y ne drede for no flod.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ihesu, do me to seruen &thorn;e, Wher in londe so y be; When ich &thorn;e fynde, wel is me, &yogh;ef &thorn;ou ne woldest awey fle.</NOTE>Ihesu, do me do &thorn;i wille,</L>
<L>Nou and euere, loud and stille;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;i loue my soule fulfille</L>
<L N="336">And soffre neuere &thorn;at I do ille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">In H this st. precedes v. 393.</NOTE>Ihesu, &thorn;i loue is swete and strong,</L>
<L>Mi lyf is al &thorn;er-on<NOTE PLACE="foot">H on &thorn;e</NOTE> I-long:</L>
<L>Tech me, lord,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ihesu</NOTE> &thorn;i loue-song,</L>
<L N="340">Wi&thorn; swete teres euer a-mong.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &yogh;if &thorn;ou be from me go,</L>
<L>Min herte<NOTE PLACE="foot">H soule</NOTE> is ful of serwe &amp; wo;</L>
<L>What may I sey<NOTE PLACE="foot">H sugge</NOTE> but weylawo,</L>
<L N="344">Whon &thorn;ou, my swete, art went me fro<NOTE PLACE="foot">H When mi lif is me at-go.</NOTE>?
<PB REF="00000469.tif" N="461"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu &thorn;in ore, &thorn;ou rewe on<NOTE PLACE="foot">H of</NOTE> me!</L>
<L>Whon schal my soule<NOTE PLACE="foot">H For whenne shal ich</NOTE> come to &thorn;e?</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">347-8, 351-2 om. in H.</NOTE>Hou longe schal hit here be,</L>
<L N="348">&THORN;er I ne may &thorn;e, my lemmon, se?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i lore teche&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H bidde&thorn;</NOTE> me</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al myn herte to loue<NOTE PLACE="foot">H louie, to om.</NOTE> &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;i miht mak hit so be,</L>
<L N="352">&THORN;at &thorn;erto, lord, constreyne me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu my lef, my lord,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H lif, ihesu</NOTE> my kyng,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e my soule ha&thorn; gret longyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H My s. haue&thorn; to &thorn;e &yogh;yrnyng.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast hit weddet wi&thorn; &thorn;i Ryng:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H When &thorn;i wille is, to &thorn;e hire bryng, &THORN;ou art suetest of alle &thorn;yng.</NOTE></L>
<L N="356">Whon &thorn;i wille is, to &thorn;e hit bring.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;at deore bou&yogh;test me,</L>
<L>Mak me wor&thorn;i to<NOTE PLACE="foot">om. in H.</NOTE> come to &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Alle my sunnes for&yogh;if &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L N="360">&THORN;at I may comen &amp; wone wi&thorn; &thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;at ich wi&thorn; blisse &thorn;e mowe se.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu al<NOTE PLACE="foot">H so</NOTE> feir, my lemmon<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ihesu so</NOTE> briht,</L>
<L>I &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &THORN;at i</NOTE> be-seche wi&thorn; al my miht:</L>
<L>Bring my soule in to &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot">H &thorn;e</NOTE> liht,</L>
<L N="364">&THORN;er is day and neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">H day wi&thorn;-oute</NOTE> niht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;in help at myn endyng,</L>
<L>Tac my soule at my di&yogh;yng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ant ine &thorn;at dredful out wendyng.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seende hit socour &amp; cumfortyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Send my soule god weryyng</NOTE></L>
<L N="368">&THORN;at hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">H y</NOTE> ne drede no wikked<NOTE PLACE="foot">non eouel</NOTE> &thorn;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, ffor &thorn;i Merci fre<NOTE PLACE="foot">H I., &thorn;i grace, &thorn;at is so fre!</NOTE></L>
<L>In siker hope do &thorn;ou me</L>
<L>To<NOTE PLACE="foot">H At</NOTE> scapen peyne &amp; come to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="372">And euere in blisse wi&thorn; &thorn;e be.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H To &thorn;e blisse &thorn;at ay shal be.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, Ihesu, Blessed<NOTE PLACE="foot">H ful wel</NOTE> ben heo<NOTE PLACE="foot">H he</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;i blisse mowe &thorn;e se<NOTE PLACE="foot">H mowen be</NOTE></L>
<L>And haue folliche<NOTE PLACE="foot">H fulliche habbe</NOTE> &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e:</L>
<L N="376">Swete Ihesu, &thorn;ou graunte hit me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i Blisse<NOTE PLACE="foot">H loue</NOTE> ha&thorn; non endynge;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H endyng</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er nis no serwe ne no wepynge,
<PB REF="00000470.tif" N="462"></L>
<L>But pees &amp; Ioye wi&thorn; gret lykynge:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Bote ioie &amp; blisse ant lykyng</NOTE></L>
<L N="380">Swete Ihesu, &thorn;erto vs bringe. Amen. &mdash; &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Last stanza om. in H.</NOTE>Hose ofte sei&thorn; &thorn;is wi&thorn; good wille,</L>
<L>Schal fynde grace his loue to fille;</L>
<L>Holygost his herte schal tille,</L>
<L N="384">ffrom synne him bringe &amp; ffendes ille.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="41" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>XLI. A luytel tretys of Love. Of godes passyon.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Title in Index om.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu Crist, &thorn;at is so fre,</L>
<L>To Monnes soule speke&thorn; he:</L>
<L>"Ichaue," he sei&thorn;, "I-weddet &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="4">And in myn honden I-writen &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Al &thorn;at in &thorn;is world is ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;i loue I-chaue hit wrou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en after so deore &thorn;e bou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at of my lyf ne rou&yogh;te I nou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"What miht I more don &thorn;en &thorn;is:</L>
<L>&THORN;en comen out of my ffader blis</L>
<L>And suffren<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. suffred</NOTE> mony a schome, I-wis,</L>
<L N="12">ffor to bringe &thorn;e to blis?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;ritti wynter on eor&thorn;e I &yogh;ode,</L>
<L>In pyne &amp; penaunce, for &thorn;i gode;</L>
<L>Atte laste I dy&yogh;ede on Roode</L>
<L N="16">And &yogh;af for &thorn;e myn herte-blode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Al my bodi was riuen and rent,</L>
<L>Mi face was al bi-spit and schent,</L>
<L>To saue &thorn;e, Mon, &thorn;er &thorn;ou were dempt&mdash;</L>
<L N="20">ffor al &thorn;at was myn entent.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"ffrom myn herte &thorn;orw my syde</L>
<L>Blod and water gon &thorn;orw glyde</L>
<L>And clanse &thorn;e of ful&thorn;e and pride&mdash;</L>
<L N="24">So wolde non don In world so wyde!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"In al &thorn;is world nis no mon</L>
<L>So muche loue&thorn; his lemmon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wolde suffre pyne on</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;at I for &thorn;e &thorn;olede mony on!
<PB REF="00000471.tif" N="463"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Myn herte forso&thorn;e clef in-two</L>
<L>ffor muche pyne and muche wo&mdash;</L>
<L>Al for &thorn;e I &thorn;olede so,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne scholdest to helle go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Mi soule, &thorn;at was wi&thorn;-outen synne,</L>
<L>Ede for &thorn;e to helle-pynne</L>
<L>And leesede &thorn;e out, &thorn;at was &thorn;er-inne</L>
<L N="36">In serwe &amp; care &thorn;at neuer schulde blinne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Whon I was sprad on &thorn;e Rode-tre,</L>
<L>Muche was &thorn;e loue Ich hedde to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Elles hed ich I-leten al be;</L>
<L N="40">Bote loue wolde not suffre me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"ffor loue me brou&yogh;te out of my rest,</L>
<L>ffor loue I restede In Marie brest;</L>
<L>ffor loue I &thorn;olede pynes werst,</L>
<L N="44">ffor loue made myn herte berst.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Whon Ich heyng vppon &thorn;e Roode,</L>
<L>ffor loue I schedde al my blode&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;enk &thorn;eron, synful, In &thorn;i mode,</L>
<L N="48">Lef &thorn;i sunne and do sum goode!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Loue made<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. make&thorn;</NOTE> me al for&yogh;ete</L>
<L>Harde pynes and duntes grete,</L>
<L>Whon I was for &thorn;i loue I-bete</L>
<L N="52">And as a &thorn;ef bounden lad in &thorn;e strete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Loue made me bere &thorn;e Rode-tre</L>
<L>On my bare scholde[r] for &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;e blod doun stremede bi bac &amp; &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="56">Whon I dude hongen vppon &thorn;e Rode-tre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Mon, Mon, for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e</L>
<L>Mi peynes dude queme me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for delyt hit &thorn;ou&yogh;te me.</L>
<L N="60">Do nou kuyndeliche &amp; quit hit me!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"More for &thorn;e I-chaue don &yogh;ete:</L>
<L>I-chaue I-mad me &thorn;i mete</L>
<L>And &yogh;iue &thorn;e my-self at ete,</L>
<L N="64">ffrom helle-pyne &thorn;e to gete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Loke what wolt &thorn;ou &yogh;elde me</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;at Ichaue don for &thorn;e!</L>
<L>Non o&thorn;er &thorn;ing kep I of &thorn;e</L>
<L N="68">But onliche &thorn;at &thorn;ou loue me.
<PB REF="00000472.tif" N="464"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Cum to me and haue my blis,</L>
<L>And I &thorn;e wole cluppe and cus.</L>
<L>Ich &yogh;iue &thorn;e al my-self, I-wis,</L>
<L N="72">To do wi&thorn; what &thorn;i wille is.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&YOGH;if &thorn;ou hast ben fouled wi&thorn; synne,</L>
<L>Torn a&yogh;eyn to me and blynne:</L>
<L>And I &thorn;e &yogh;iue heuene-wynne&mdash;</L>
<L N="76">So lo&thorn; me is &thorn;at we a-twynne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now and nomeliche at myn endyng,</L>
<L>Swete Ihesu, heuene-kyng,</L>
<L>In &thorn;i wille &yogh;if me lykyng,</L>
<L N="80">Wi&thorn; studefast hope &amp; hol louyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;at art of gode for&yogh;elde,</L>
<L>ffor&yogh;ite me nou&yogh;t in myn elde;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if me studefast hope and belde</L>
<L N="84">To haue &thorn;e, lord, euer in my welde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, Lyon strong,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow &thorn;at neuere louedest wrong,</L>
<L>Chastise me wi&thorn; myn owne wande</L>
<L N="88">And let me neuere to helle gande.<NOTE PLACE="marg">for gange</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, lo&thorn;les lombe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swettor is &thorn;en hony-Combe,</L>
<L>And was boren of Marie wombe:</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;ou bring vs to heuene on &thorn;i ri&yogh;t honde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete Ihesu, &thorn;e feireste wiht,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou art Rihtwysnesse and riht,</L>
<L>&YOGH;iue vs for &thorn;in holy miht</L>
<L N="96">Alle comen to heuene briht. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="42" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[XLII. Of Clene Maydenhod.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">Title in Index: &THORN;at crist is called lemman to a clene soule. This poem was edited before by Furnivall, <I>The Sta|cions of Rome</I>, E. E. T. S. 1867.</NOTE> Of clene Maydenhod, To be weddet clanly to god.</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Off a trewe loue clene &amp; derne</L>
<L>I-chaue I-write &thorn;e a Ron,
<PB REF="00000473.tif" N="465"></L>
<L>How &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t, &yogh;if &thorn;ow wolt, lerne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[line repeated in MS.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">ffor to loue &thorn;i lemmon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at trewest is of alle berne</L>
<L>And most of loue chacche con.</L>
<L>Beo war, for he is sumdel steorne,</L>
<L N="8">His e&yogh;e is euere &thorn;e vppon.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ou art wrouht of such a kynde:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen loue mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou not be;</L>
<L>And neuermore schalt &thorn;ou fynde</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at is so swete and feir as he.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou miht hym to &thorn;e bynde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; trewe loue-bondes &thorn;re,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al &thorn;in herte, wille, &amp; mynde,</L>
<L N="16">ffrom &thorn;e wol he neuer fle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Heddest &thorn;ou founden such a feere<NOTE PLACE="marg">on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at weore so feir as Absolon,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-to so strong to tere</L>
<L N="20">As in his tyme was Sampson,</L>
<L>So Riche &thorn;er-to &thorn;at he were</L>
<L>And so wys as Salomon;</L>
<L>I-wis, to him riht nou&yogh;t hit were<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. nere</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast chosen to &thorn;i lemmon.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>ffor monnes loue, &yogh;if &thorn;ou beo-holde,</L>
<L>Hit laste&thorn; but a luytel res,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; gyle is al bi-folde,</L>
<L N="28">Hit is ffikel, ffals and les;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou wenest hit best to holde,</L>
<L>Hit wende&thorn; a-wey as wyndes bles,</L>
<L>And bi-come&thorn; wrest and colde&mdash;</L>
<L N="32">ffor trewe loue hit neuer nes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>Loue &thorn;at wol not wi&thorn; &thorn;e a-byde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou hit desyre, &thorn;ou hast wouh;</L>
<L>Ar &thorn;ou beo war, hit wol to-glyde,</L>
<L N="36">Hit is fikel, ffals and ffrou&yogh;;
<PB REF="00000474.tif" N="466"></L>
<L>Hit is a-weyward In vche<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. In vche in vch</NOTE> a syde,</L>
<L>Whiles hit laste&thorn;, vnwrest &amp; wouh&mdash;</L>
<L>Beo war and seo what wol be-tyde:</L>
<L N="40">Hit wol to-dryue as lef on bouh.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e loue &thorn;at wole to serwe wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou do hit al out of &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>And his loue in &thorn;in herte bynde</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at ha&thorn; &thorn;i loue so deore a-bou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;if &thorn;ou heddest al to &thorn;e ende</L>
<L>Heuene &amp; eor&thorn;e &thorn;orw&yogh;-out souht,</L>
<L>To fynde a feere &thorn;at weore so hende</L>
<L N="48">As he, I-wys hit weore for nou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>He is of Mood wel Meke and Mylde,</L>
<L>ffreo of herte, strong of miht,</L>
<L>Of glade chere, of wordes vn-wylde,</L>
<L N="52">Of louesum leore and Ei&yogh;en briht.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt do &thorn;e in his mylde</L>
<L>And him al-one loue ariht,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-Inne &thorn;in herte wol he bylde</L>
<L N="56">And wone wi&thorn; &thorn;e, bo&thorn;e day and niht.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>Wel more mur&thorn;e is in his steuen</L>
<L>&THORN;en herte may &thorn;enke or tonge neme;</L>
<L>As be &thorn;e swan &thorn;e blake Rauen,</L>
<L N="60">Also be him &thorn;e sonne-gleme;</L>
<L>No more is no &thorn;ing to him I-lyche</L>
<L>&THORN;en Galle is to &thorn;e hony-streme.</L>
<L>Of him is al &thorn;e Ioye of heuene-riche,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at wi&thorn; his grace alle &thorn;ing wol leme.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;if Mon be ded and he him Ryne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">= hrine, touch</NOTE></L>
<L>He reise&thorn; him to lyue anone&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor wele &amp; wynne, serwe and pyne</L>
<L N="68">Al is Buxom to him one.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow him wole in herte wel tyne</L>
<L>And kepe, &thorn;at he not from &thorn;e gon,
<PB REF="00000475.tif" N="467"></L>
<L>Holde him wi&thorn; loue-lyne&mdash;</L>
<L N="72">ffor o&thorn;er bond holde&thorn; him non.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>Is non founden here in londe</L>
<L>&THORN;at is so Riche Mon of ffee,</L>
<L>ffor more good he ha&thorn; in honde</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;en herte may &thorn;enke or ei&yogh;e mai se;</L>
<L>Nis kyng, kniht, sweyn ne bonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo to him mote Boxum be.</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; I-send a derne sonde</L>
<L N="80">And desyre&thorn; to haue &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>He aske&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e nou&thorn;er lond ne leode,</L>
<L>Gold ne seluer ne precious stone&mdash;</L>
<L>To such &thorn;inges ha&thorn; he no neode,</L>
<L N="84">Al &thorn;at is good is wi&thorn; hym one.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wi&thorn; him &thorn;i lyf wolt lede</L>
<L>And graunte to ben his owne lemmon,</L>
<L>I wot ful wel what wor&thorn; &thorn;i meede:</L>
<L N="88">fforso&thorn;e, &thorn;e heuene-riche won.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e weyes ben alle &thorn;ere I-bete</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Riche gold &thorn;at schyne&thorn; briht;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ioyful song in vche a strete&mdash;</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;er is day and neuer-more niht;</L>
<L>To synge wol &thorn;ei neuer lete,</L>
<L>To worschupe god wi&thorn; al heore miht.</L>
<L>&THORN;at Blisse forso&thorn;e schal be &thorn;e mete,</L>
<L N="96">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou Ihesu crist loue ariht.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;i lemmon qweme</L>
<L>And to his brihte boure be brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In Chastite kep &thorn;ou &thorn;e clene,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne be I-wemmed nouht.</L>
<L>Non hony-Com &thorn;at renne&thorn; on streme</L>
<L>Was neuer &yogh;ut so swete wrouht,</L>
<L>Ne neuere so briht sonne-gleme</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;en Mayden &thorn;at is clene of &thorn;ou&yogh;t!
<PB REF="00000476.tif" N="468"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>While &thorn;ou art clene vnder gore,</L>
<L>Bi-fore God &thorn;ou art ful hei&yogh;e&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;er is no &thorn;ing he loue&thorn; more</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;en Maidenhod to wonen him nei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Ne lerne &thorn;ou neuere &thorn;at ilke lore</L>
<L>Wher-&thorn;orw &thorn;ou leose Mayden Bei&yogh;e&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ing &thorn;at mon may fynde no more,</L>
<L N="112">Bot he hit kepe, he is vn-sle&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; al &thorn;e gold of Arabye,</L>
<L>Riche Rynges and &yogh;ymmes-stone,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e tresour of Asye,</L>
<L N="116">Of o&thorn;er londes euerichone,</L>
<L>Weore bi-taken in &thorn;i Baylye,</L>
<L>To welden and hauen in &thorn;i wone:</L>
<L>Hit neore nou&yogh;t to &thorn;e druwerie</L>
<L N="120">Of clene Maidenhod al-one!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>Hose &thorn;is &yogh;eem-ston miht</L>
<L>Louken in a swete loue-ryng,</L>
<L>He schulde schyne also briht</L>
<L N="124">As sonne do&thorn;, wi&thorn;-outen endyng,</L>
<L>And beo holden a ful swete wiht</L>
<L>Bi-fore god, [for] al Monkynde</L>
<L>&THORN;at wolde in a Mayden liht&mdash;</L>
<L N="128">fful swete hit is of hire &thorn;e Muynde!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>Lord, &yogh;if us miht and grace</L>
<L>Chaste lyf [to lede] &thorn;at we ne spille,</L>
<L>Verrey compungcion and space,</L>
<L N="132">Repentaunce of dedes ille;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if vs miht to folwe &thorn;i trace</L>
<L>Euer-more, bo&thorn;e loude &amp; stille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e siht of &thorn;i swete face</L>
<L N="136">On domes-day we may come tille.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="43" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000477.tif" N="469">
<HEAD>XLIII. A Mournyng Song of the loue of God.<MILESTONE N="CCXCIX" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">Title in Index: &THORN;at god is ouer alle &thorn;yng to be loued.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>TO loue I-chulle beginne</L>
<L>Ihesu bo&thorn;e day and niht;</L>
<L>Of ffleschlich loue to blynne</L>
<L N="4">I-chul don al my miht.</L>
<L>Ihesu wi&thorn;-outen synne</L>
<L>In a Mayden he liht;</L>
<L>Mi loue al for to wynne,</L>
<L N="8">Ihesu bi-com my kniht.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>He fau&yogh;t a-&yogh;eyn my fo,</L>
<L>A-wey he ha&thorn; me led</L>
<L>&THORN;at me wrou&yogh;te ful wo</L>
<L N="12">In care &thorn;er I was sted;</L>
<L>&THORN;orw ferly fiht and &thorn;ro</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffeloun is from me fled,</L>
<L>Mi lemmon let him slo,</L>
<L N="16">In loue to make my bed.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Mi lemmon is ful trewe</L>
<L>Of loue, and ful studefast,</L>
<L>Alle dayes I-liche newe</L>
<L N="20">He loue&thorn; al on a &thorn;rast.</L>
<L>I wolde &thorn;at alle him knewe</L>
<L>And on him loue cast&mdash;</L>
<L>Scholde non of hem alle rewe,</L>
<L N="24">Nou&thorn;er furst no last.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>Mi lemmon is so meke,</L>
<L>So hende, so swete, so stille;</L>
<L>fful Mylde he is in speche,</L>
<L N="28">Wi&thorn;-outen wordes grille;</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode he wole al eche,</L>
<L>ffor&yogh;eten he wole al ille.
<PB REF="00000478.tif" N="470"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if I fleo, he wol me seche,</L>
<L N="32">And wi&thorn; loue he wole me tille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;eroute al-&thorn;auh he stonde</L>
<L>Callynge at my &yogh;ate</L>
<L>Til him frese fot and honde,</L>
<L N="36">ffaste vn-to a stake,</L>
<L>He ne take&thorn; staf ne wonde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wra&thorn;&thorn;e me for to wake;</L>
<L>Mi loue him bynde&thorn; as bonde,</L>
<L N="40">&YOGH;if I him mur&thorn;es make.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>He wol me loueliche a-byde</L>
<L>Al-&thorn;auh I dwelle ful longe,</L>
<L>He wol me no-&thorn;ing be-chide</L>
<L N="44">Al-&thorn;au&yogh; I-chaue &thorn;e wronge;</L>
<L>He sei&thorn;: "bi-hold my syde,</L>
<L>And whi on Rode Ich honge.</L>
<L>ffor my loue lef &thorn;i pride,</L>
<L N="48">And I &thorn;e wole vnderfonge."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;at art so hende,</L>
<L>So swete and so &thorn;olemood</L>
<L>ffrom &thorn;e whon so we weende:</L>
<L N="52">Allas, &thorn;at we hit vnder- stod,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e cou&thorn;e leende</L>
<L>And loue wi&thorn; miht and mood,</L>
<L>To haue wi&thorn;-outen ende</L>
<L N="56">Heuene, &thorn;at is so good!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>Ihesu for me is herte</L>
<L>Let &thorn;urle &thorn;orw-out his syde,</L>
<L>And duntes &thorn;olede smerte</L>
<L N="60">And woundes deope and wyde;</L>
<L>Wo and al vnquerte</L>
<L>He &thorn;olede, to fordo pride,</L>
<L>&THORN;e foule synne &thorn;at me gerte</L>
<L N="64">In helle from him me hyde.
<PB REF="00000479.tif" N="471"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>Ihesu, my lemmon swete:</L>
<L>Of loue &thorn;at &thorn;ou art trewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is seene in hondes and fete,</L>
<L N="68">In heued, in huyde and hewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;i bodi of blod al wete,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou gon on me rewe</L>
<L>And me brou&yogh;test from grete</L>
<L N="72">And from my foule loue vntrewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>So deore hastou me bouht</L>
<L>To bringe me out of pyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;er I was Inne I-brouht,</L>
<L N="76">I and mo of myne.</L>
<L>Ihesu, so fer &thorn;ou me sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Me and mo of &thorn;yne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;i lyf was &thorn;e nouht&mdash;</L>
<L N="80">So lo&thorn; &thorn;e was vs tyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>Mi lemmon let him take,</L>
<L>Putte &amp; Bete and Bynde,</L>
<L>So sore as him mihte ake,</L>
<L N="84">His hondes him behynde:</L>
<L>And al was for my sake,</L>
<L>Mi loue so he heold In mynde.</L>
<L>Ich ou&yogh;te euere serwe make,</L>
<L N="88">Vn-trewe &yogh;if he me fynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>Wi&thorn; pyne vppon &thorn;e Rode</L>
<L>Me bou&yogh;te my deore lemmon,</L>
<L>Swete Ihesu &thorn;e goode,</L>
<L N="92">So muchel of loue he con!</L>
<L>&THORN;e teres he lette of blode</L>
<L>ffor me whon he bi-gon.</L>
<L>Madde &thorn;ei aren and woode</L>
<L N="96">To leuen him for Sathan!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>On Roode he wolde abyde,&mdash;</L>
<L>He wolde nou&yogh;wher fer fle,
<PB REF="00000480.tif" N="472"></L>
<L>Nou&thorn;er go ne Ryde,</L>
<L N="100">ffor nayled he is to &thorn;e tre.</L>
<L>He sprede&thorn; his Armes wyde,</L>
<L>ffor loue as we mowe se;</L>
<L>His herte &thorn;oru&yogh;-out his syde</L>
<L N="104">He &yogh;iue&thorn; vs, he is so fre!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>Mi lemmon ha&thorn; so sprad</L>
<L>His Armes &thorn;at be&thorn; so longe:</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i am I nou&yogh;t dred,</L>
<L N="108">He wol me vnderfonge.</L>
<L>Whon I was from hym fled,</L>
<L>On hym he tok &thorn;e wronge,</L>
<L>To de&thorn;e til he was bled,</L>
<L N="112">ffor my loue wolde he honge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>He bekene&thorn; vs to blisse</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; louynde chere so swete,</L>
<L>His Mou&thorn; he beode&thorn; to cusse;</L>
<L N="116">ffor vs his lyf he leete</L>
<L>To lere vs and to wisse,</L>
<L>And nayled &thorn;orw-out his feete,</L>
<L>Of Mede &thorn;at we ne misse</L>
<L N="120">His hondes beo&thorn; &thorn;orw weete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>Swete Ihesu, &thorn;i ore!</L>
<L>&THORN;at al hast in &thorn;i miht,</L>
<L>What mihtest &thorn;ow do more</L>
<L N="124">ffor me, &thorn;i wrecched wiht?</L>
<L>Of loue &thorn;ou art my lore,</L>
<L>To come to heuene briht.</L>
<L>&THORN;at herte may be ful sore</L>
<L N="128">To loue &thorn;e &thorn;at is not diht!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>Now wol I crie and grete&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor serwe hit is nei&yogh; &thorn;at I berste,</L>
<L>Min herte-blod to blede</L>
<L N="132">ffor my lef &thorn;at is &thorn;us feste.
<PB REF="00000481.tif" N="473"></L>
<L>Ihesu, &yogh;if &thorn;at I schal spede,</L>
<L>&THORN;i-self &thorn;enne is bote beste.</L>
<L>ffor grymly grete I drede,</L>
<L N="136">Wi&thorn; &thorn;i bodi &yogh;if I reste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>How mihti but I grete</L>
<L>Til I eode out of my wit?</L>
<L>I seo my lemmon blede</L>
<L N="140">To de&thorn;e, to liggen in put;</L>
<L>His syde is schoren as schrede,</L>
<L>His herte a spere ha&thorn; hut&mdash;</L>
<L>And al for my misde[de]</L>
<L N="144">Was he so felli smit!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>Now wot I me no won,</L>
<L>Lemmon, what I do miht.</L>
<L>I seo Marie and Ion,</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;i Mooder and &thorn;y kniht,</L>
<L>fful druri is hire mon</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e &thorn;at weore so briht&mdash;</L>
<L>Nou is &thorn;er deolfolore non</L>
<L N="152">Ne vnlikkore in siht.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;yn e&yogh;en briht as Sonne,</L>
<L>Mone and Sterres alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei woxe deske and dimme,</L>
<L N="156">&THORN;i feire Rode dude falle;</L>
<L>&THORN;i blod was al out Runne.</L>
<L>To drinke whon &thorn;ou gonne calle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wikked men beoden &thorn;e Eysel &amp; atter,</L>
<L N="160">Bitterore &thorn;en &thorn;e galle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>Wi&thorn; spittyng and wi&thorn; fen</L>
<L>And blod out-beten sore</L>
<L>&THORN;ow weore al out of ken,</L>
<L N="164">A La&yogh;er as &thorn;ow wore.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei beote &thorn;e, &thorn;i foo-men,</L>
<L>Of loue to lere vs lore&mdash;
<PB REF="00000482.tif" N="474"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou be blessed, amen,</L>
<L N="168">Now and euer-more!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L>Sore I seo &thorn;e buye</L>
<L>Al my loue-plawe&mdash;</L>
<L>Al is for my folye</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;at &thorn;ou dri&yogh;est heer a &thorn;rawe.</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;en may I crie,</L>
<L>And her and huyde to-drawe,</L>
<L>I seo my lemmon dy&yogh;e</L>
<L N="176">On Roode wi&thorn;-outen lawe!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L>Allas, Allas, out ay,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer was I boren!</L>
<L>His de&thorn; is Iewes play,</L>
<L N="180">His Coroune is of &thorn;orn.</L>
<L>Mi lemmon, weylaway!</L>
<L>ffor me is lyf ha&thorn; lorn,</L>
<L>His bodi is al blodi</L>
<L N="184">Be-hynden and bi-foren.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L>I seo in eor&thorn;e synke,</L>
<L>Lemmon, &thorn;in herte-blode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow wi&thorn; pyne and swynke</L>
<L N="188">ffor me scheddest on &thorn;e Roode.</L>
<L>&THORN;erof whi ne moste I drynke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is so swete and goode,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e &thorn;at I mihte &thorn;inke</L>
<L N="192">ffor loue ay til I eode wode?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L>Allas, &thorn;at I ne cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Lemmon, don al &thorn;i wille</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; werk, and word of mou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="196">Bo&thorn;e loude and stille!</L>
<L>Almihti god hit ou&thorn;e</L>
<L>I mihte &thorn;e to me tille,</L>
<L>So briht so sonne in Sou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="200">Of &thorn;e &thorn;at I mihte haue my wille.
<PB REF="00000483.tif" N="475"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L>Marie Mooder Milde,</L>
<L>Mi lemmon is &thorn;i sone&mdash;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him &thorn;ou eodest wi&thorn; childe,</L>
<L N="204">ffor me wi&thorn; him to wone.</L>
<L>I haue ben wood and wylde:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou preye him &thorn;at I cone</L>
<L>Loue him, &amp; &thorn;at he me schilde,</L>
<L N="208">Or eny o&thorn;er to mone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L>Alle o&thorn;ere I-chulle forsake</L>
<L>And don out of my &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, Ihesu, I me take&mdash;</L>
<L N="212">So deore &thorn;ou hast me bouht!</L>
<L>Al o&thorn;er loue wol make</L>
<L>Endynge and waxe to nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;i loue nul I forsake,</L>
<L N="216">ffor &thorn;at bringe&thorn; vs alle o-loft.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L>To wone wi&thorn; &thorn;e, bi-leue</L>
<L>Lemon, vnder &thorn;i tre&mdash;</L>
<L>May no pyne me greue</L>
<L N="220">Ne do me fro &thorn;e fle.</L>
<L>I wol in at &thorn;i sleue,</L>
<L>Al in &thorn;in herte to be,</L>
<L>Myn herte schal berste and cleue,</L>
<L N="224">Vn-trewe ar &thorn;ou me se.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L>fful hard hit is, &thorn;i bed:</L>
<L>A treo &thorn;at stonde&thorn; stille,</L>
<L>In wo and weder sted;</L>
<L N="228">&THORN;eroute he honge&thorn; on hille,</L>
<L>ffor-beten and for-bled</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Men &thorn;at wolden hem spille.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;us ha&thorn; loue &thorn;e led,</L>
<L N="232">&THORN;i lemmon for to tille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;i-self &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t not schelde,</L>
<L>Ne torne, so art &thorn;ou fest;
<PB REF="00000484.tif" N="476"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast nout on to helde</L>
<L N="236">&THORN;in hed, on for to rest,</L>
<L>Almihti kyng to welde</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at is worst and best.</L>
<L>Hou miht<NOTE PLACE="marg">orig. mihti</NOTE> I euer &thorn;e &yogh;elde</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;e loue &thorn;at &thorn;us wol lest?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L>Clo&thorn;ing hast &thorn;ou non&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor scorn men make&thorn; &thorn;e bare;</L>
<L>&THORN;i ffrendes aren from &thorn;e gon,</L>
<L N="244">And flowen &thorn;at wi&thorn; &thorn;e ware,</L>
<L>Alle bote Marie and Ion,</L>
<L>fful of serwe and care&mdash;</L>
<L>fful dreri is here mon,</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;i pyne is al &thorn;e mare!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L>Ihesu Crist, my lemmon swete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at dy&yogh;edest on &thorn;e Rode-tre,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al my miht I &thorn;e bi-seche</L>
<L N="252">ffor &thorn;yne woundes two and &thorn;re,</L>
<L>&THORN;at as depe in to myn herte</L>
<L>Mot &thorn;i loue I-stiked be</L>
<L>As was &thorn;e spere in to &thorn;yn herte,</L>
<L N="256">Whon &thorn;ou suffredest de&thorn; for me.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="44" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>XLIV. Her is a luytel Sarmoun, &thorn;at is of good edificacioun.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Title in Index: A luytul sermoun of good edificacioun.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>[Ten 8-line stanzas; after the first, <I>ab, cb, db, eb.</I>]</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At a Sarmoun &thorn;er I seet</L>
<L>A comely clerk<NOTE PLACE="marg">k over line.</NOTE> Ich herde crauen,</L>
<L>Wyse wordes he &thorn;er speek</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e Mon &thorn;at wolde in herte hauen;</L>
<L>Ich herde ffrere Henri spellen:</L>
<L>"Lete no sunnes in ow dwellen;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Mon &thorn;at is taken in dedly synne,</L>
<L N="8">He may wel witen In wo to wellen.
<PB REF="00000485.tif" N="477"></L>
<L>"A &thorn;ing hit is &thorn;at we schul do,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Mon &thorn;at &thorn;enke&thorn; to liuen in le:</L>
<L>Schrift to taken, and &thorn;at be tyme&mdash;</L>
<L N="12">We haue no Borwes heer to be;</L>
<L>Whon we hauen, to holde faste,</L>
<L>We ne mowe raples &thorn;orw &thorn;o &thorn;re</L>
<L>To Bere &thorn;e croune to-fore &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at for vs &thorn;olede de&thorn; on tre.</L>
<L>"He<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. He</NOTE> &thorn;at for vs &thorn;olede de&thorn; on tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou Rihtwys lord, &thorn;ou deme so:</L>
<L>Wis vs to &thorn;at ilke stude</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;er</NOTE> euere is wele and neuer wo.</L>
<L>God, lete neuere vr wille vr wit be-swiken,</L>
<L>ffor whi, vr soule for to slo.</L>
<L>Ihesu crist, &thorn;ou mihtful kyng,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;ou haue merci on me and mo.</L>
<L>"Mon on Molde, &thorn;ou mak &thorn;e &yogh;are</L>
<L>A-&yogh;eyn &thorn;i de&thorn; on domes-day;</L>
<L>&THORN;enk vppon &thorn;i muchele neode,</L>
<L N="28">Wher &thorn;i soule resten may&mdash;</L>
<L>Heuene or helle wher hit be-tyde&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mai&yogh;t wel witen &thorn;ou liuest &thorn;er ay.</L>
<L>Crist schild vs from &thorn;at ilke stude,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;er no mon o&thorn;er ne mene ne may.</L>
<L>"Mai no mon o&thorn;er hem bi-menen,</L>
<L>ffor sek and sori heo &thorn;er se;</L>
<L>&THORN;er is hot and cold and hunger wi&thorn;</L>
<L N="36">And &thorn;retes&mdash;&thorn;o beo&thorn; vuele &thorn;re,</L>
<L>ffurst and hunger and &thorn;esternesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euere schal lyue wi&thorn;-outen lee.<NOTE PLACE="marg">orig. leo, corr. to lee.</NOTE></L>
<L>Crist schild vs from &thorn;at ilke stude,</L>
<L N="40">ffrom Bale &thorn;er neuere no bote ne be.</L>
<L>"Ne miht &thorn;ou seo, synful Mon,</L>
<L>So do&thorn; &thorn;e ffisschere wi&thorn; his hok:</L>
<L>Hou he tese&thorn; on &thorn;e Banke</L>
<L N="44">A brodly breyd I &thorn;e Brok;</L>
<L>Come&thorn; &thorn;e ffisch and fonge&thorn; hit,</L>
<L>So wro&thorn;ly wrie&thorn; on &thorn;e Crok,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffisch is be-wyled &thorn;orw &thorn;e worm&mdash;</L>
<L N="48">So wo is &thorn;e ffisch &thorn;at he hit tok.
<PB REF="00000486.tif" N="478"></L>
<L>"Hok bi-tokene&thorn; helle-pyne&mdash;</L>
<L>What helpe&thorn; hit to hele wi&thorn; &thorn;e?</L>
<L>Wommon is worm, &thorn;er heo is wikke&mdash;</L>
<L N="52">May no mon &thorn;orw his sunnes se.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Mon is ffisch and fonge&thorn; hire&mdash;</L>
<L>Him weore wel betere to leten hire be,</L>
<L>To huyden his hed and hi&yogh;en a-wey,</L>
<L N="56">ffrom dedly synne &thorn;er-with fle.</L>
<L>"&THORN;is prechours &thorn;at bi-foren vs speken,</L>
<L>Wel liht a Beren heore tonge in wold</L>
<L>To wissen vs to &thorn;at ilke stude,</L>
<L N="60">So holy writ hit ha&thorn; hem told.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we wol lusten to heore lore,</L>
<L>We ou&yogh;ten be fayn, and ful bold</L>
<L>To wonen in &thorn;at ilke stude</L>
<L>&THORN;er Ihesu crist &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. &thorn;at? Cf. <I>Lay Folks' Mass-Book</I>, v. 407:<Q><L>And so &thorn;e leuacioun &thorn;ou be|halde,</L><L>for &thorn;at is he &thorn;at iudas salde,</L><L>And sithen was scourged &amp; don on rode, &amp;c.</L></Q></NOTE> Iudas solde.</L>
<L>"&THORN;er Ihesu crist &thorn;e Iudas solde</L>
<L>He lene vs lust in lawe to lyuen,</L>
<L>Wit and wisdam to vnderstonden,</L>
<L N="68">Wi&thorn; schrift al for to schruden vs here.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we haue wille to wikkedlek,</L>
<L>God lete vs &thorn;ere stunte and stere;</L>
<L>He deme so lord at domes-day</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at we mote, lord, in &thorn;i wey fere.</L>
<L>"In &thorn;i wey fere, lord, I wolde ben,</L>
<L>To wonen in &thorn;at wor&thorn;li won.</L>
<L>Heo &thorn;at on &thorn;i lift hond leuen,</L>
<L N="76">Wel grislych hit is whon &thorn;ou art gon:</L>
<L>A ben I-haried in to helle-pyne,</L>
<L>To Bale &thorn;er neuer ne bote nis non.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at al &thorn;is world schal demen,</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;ou Rihtwys lord, &thorn;ou rewe on Mon. Amen."<NOTE PLACE="foot">Then follows Roberd of Cicyle, fol. 299 (ed. in <I>Sammlung altenglischer Legenden</I> 1878, p. 209, from 5 MSS.).</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="45" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000487.tif" N="479">
<HEAD>XLV. Her is a disputison bi-twene chi[l]d Jhesu &amp; Maistres of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lawe of Jewus.</HEAD>
<P>Ed. before by Horstmann in <I>Altengl. Leg.</I>, 1875, p. 211-14. Miss A. F. Parker collates the text with the MS. henceforward.</P><P>[Twenty-five 8-line stanzas, one 12: <I>ab, ab, ab, ab.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><MILESTONE N="300" UNIT="folio">Lustne&thorn; lordes, leoue in londe:</L>
<L>So&thorn;eli sawes I wol &yogh;ou telle</L>
<L>Of gentyl Ihesu, I vnderstonde,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e ffalse ffei fonded to felle.</L>
<L>ffor wo ne wrake ne wolde he wonde</L>
<L>Of Trinite trewe to Iewes telle,</L>
<L>He sat in see, he nolde not stonde,</L>
<L N="8">As best of barnes &thorn;at bar &thorn;e Belle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e gospel sei&thorn; In &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>Whon Ihesu was of twelf &yogh;er age,</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e Temple he com to lere</L>
<L N="12">Wrangful wrecches &thorn;at wrou&yogh;t outrage.</L>
<L>Maystres wondrede, &thorn;at &thorn;er were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lawes lerede in heore langage,</L>
<L>And seide: "child, what destou &thorn;ere?</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;ou sittest stalled in vre stage."</L>
<L>A Mayster seide to Ihesu:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou scholdest lerne, and nou&yogh;t teche;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou spillest speche; what seystou?</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;i wrangful wordes worche&thorn; wreche,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou repungnest in pres a-&yogh;eyn vr prou;</L>
<L>As preised prophete, &thorn;e peple preche.</L>
<L>Stunt a stounde &thorn;i sawe of Gru!</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;i wit to teche may not reche.</L>
<L>"&THORN;ow schuldest lerne A. b. c,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e fayle&thorn; a foundement;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou tellest tales of Trinite!</L>
<L N="28">In wonderwyse &thorn;i wit is went.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt leorne, &thorn;ou miht &thorn;he,</L>
<L>ffor wonder wit on &thorn;e is sent;</L>
<L>Of Bales Boote &thorn;ou miht be,</L>
<L N="32">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou neore In errour hent."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu seide: "I may wel se</L>
<L>&THORN;i Bok is blynt, and &thorn;ou art blent;
<PB REF="00000488.tif" N="480"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou farest foule, so &thorn;ynke&thorn; me,</L>
<L N="36">ffor lewed lore on &thorn;e is lent.</L>
<L>Whi is A Bi-fore b?</L>
<L>Tel me, &thorn;at spekest in present,</L>
<L>Or I schal tymeli teche &thorn;e</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;i Reson ra&thorn;e &thorn;e schal Repent."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maister wi&thorn; wel wikked wille</L>
<L>Spak in pres of people a-pliht;</L>
<L>"Ihesu, &thorn;ou art a grameful gille,</L>
<L N="44">I Rede Ra&thorn;e &thorn;ou lerne a-Riht;</L>
<L>And bote &thorn;ou stonde a stounde stille,</L>
<L>To Betyng Bare &thorn;ou schalt be diht."</L>
<L>Qwa&thorn; Ihesu: "&thorn;at is no skille,</L>
<L N="48">I com not hider for to fiht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&YOGH;it," qua&thorn; Ihesu, "of myn askyng</L>
<L>&THORN;ou ne &yogh;iuest non onswere.</L>
<L>I am ful Old, &thorn;eih I be &yogh;ing.</L>
<L N="52">A louely lore I wol &thorn;e lere&mdash;</L>
<L>Tak &thorn;is tale of my teching:</L>
<L>A Is prys, wi&thorn;-oute pere,</L>
<L>lettre of &thorn;reo and is o &thorn;ing;</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;reo partyes A ha&thorn; knet I-fere.</L>
<L>"Bi A Biginne&thorn; &thorn;e lettrure,</L>
<L>ffo[r] A is lyk &thorn;e Trinite.</L>
<L>&THORN;reo partyes A ha&thorn; of Mesure,</L>
<L N="60">Knet in knotte on A wol be.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt lerne, &thorn;ou miht hure</L>
<L>Hou A is lyk &thorn;e deite.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Deite is, &thorn;is is sure,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;reo and on, In Maieste,</L>
<L>And euer her after heo schul dure</L>
<L>In-departable alle &thorn;re.</L>
<L>Nou hastou lerned, tac &thorn;ou cure,</L>
<L N="68">Hou A is most of dignite."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maister seide in &thorn;at stounde:</L>
<L>"What artou, lettrure to lere?</L>
<L>Bi Moyses lawe, nis not founde</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;e lawes &thorn;at &thorn;ou tellest heere.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seist in &thorn;is ilke grounde</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou art old and &yogh;ong I feere';
<PB REF="00000489.tif" N="481"></L>
<L>&THORN;i sawe so&thorn;li nis not founde;</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;erfore &thorn;ou art me no-&thorn;ing dere.</L>
<L>"Stond &thorn;ou stille swi&thorn;e, I seye,</L>
<L>And louely lustne to my lore,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou miht bi alle weye</L>
<L N="80">Beo ful wys for euer-more.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast wit In memorie</L>
<L>And wel &yogh;ong &thorn;i wit is core;</L>
<L>Hit is medlet wi&thorn; ffolye,</L>
<L N="84">And &thorn;at greue&thorn; me grimly sore.</L>
<L>"Of Moyses vr lawe we had</L>
<L>And nou newe &thorn;ow wolt teche.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i sawe swi&thorn;e am I sad,</L>
<L N="88">Of &thorn;e Trinite to spille speche.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou greuest me, I am not glad,</L>
<L>With lu&thorn;er lawes &thorn;ou lu&thorn;er leche;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou spekest of godhed as child al mad,</L>
<L N="92">ffor&thorn;er &thorn;en &thorn;i wit wol reche."</L>
<L>A-no&thorn;er Mayster seide in hi&yogh;e:</L>
<L>"Child, her is a wonder &thorn;ing!</L>
<L>&THORN;ow kennest comeli Clergye,</L>
<L N="96">And &yogh;it to teche &thorn;ou art to &yogh;yng;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast not lerned, as men seye:</L>
<L>Hou hastou &thorn;enne &thorn;i connyng?</L>
<L>Deueles deme&thorn; Mon to dy&yogh;e:</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;i tonge ha&thorn; tast of heore teching.</L>
<L>"&THORN;i wrongful wordes worche&thorn; wrake.</L>
<L>&THORN;ow seist &thorn;at god is on and &thorn;re.</L>
<L>I Bede &thorn;in errour &thorn;ou forsake,</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;ou spekest of &thorn;ing &thorn;at mai not be.</L>
<L>As ouer-come &thorn;ou worth of-take,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;is peple hit schal se.</L>
<L>&THORN;is qwestion to &thorn;e I make:</L>
<L N="108">Tel me what is &thorn;e Trinite?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, as best &thorn;at bar &thorn;e belle,</L>
<L>Wolde wite riht a-non,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he cou&thorn;e o &thorn;ing telle</L>
<L N="112">Of prechynge prophetes wonder won,</L>
<L>"&THORN;at seide crist scholde dwelle</L>
<L>Her on eor&thorn;e a-mong his fon,
<PB REF="00000490.tif" N="482"></L>
<L>Alle &yogh;or lawes to fulfelle;</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;is wol &yogh;or lawes euerichon.</L>
<L>"Crist is liht of god Almiht</L>
<L>And of Godes liht I-core.</L>
<L>Ysaye spac her-of a-pliht:</L>
<L N="120">Of a Mayden he scholde be bore.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mi&yogh;t wel wite hit is riht,</L>
<L>He schal bugge &thorn;at is for-lore.</L>
<L>God is &thorn;e ffader, Crist sone &amp; liht;</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;e sone is geten wi&thorn;-outen hore.</L>
<L>"ffor as &thorn;e sonne &yogh;iue&thorn; his leem</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he wi&thorn; cloudes is not let,</L>
<L>So com crist as sonne-Beem</L>
<L N="128">In to &thorn;at Buirde &thorn;at Bales bet.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou take wel good &yogh;eem</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;e sonne-Beem euere is set</L>
<L>Vndeparted, so is &thorn;e strem</L>
<L N="132">Of crist with God mid knottes knet.</L>
<L>"Now tak herto good entent:</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffader liht in &thorn;e sone schal be,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffader liht &yogh;it nis nou&yogh;t blent,</L>
<L N="136">Al is o liht In Deite.</L>
<L>&THORN;en is hit proued bi Argument,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ffader and sone, o liht beo&thorn; he;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy spirit wi&thorn; hem present,</L>
<L N="140">Heo &thorn;reo Beo&thorn; God In Trinite.</L>
<L>"ffor &thorn;e Trinite, I &thorn;e seye,</L>
<L>A is lettre of alle cheef;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore he is in alle weye</L>
<L N="144">Put bi-fore: her is good preef!</L>
<L>&THORN;e Trinite &thorn;ei schal seo wi&thorn; e&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Alle Men &thorn;at ben him leof;</L>
<L>&THORN;en is mon A preised prei&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;at to &thorn;e Trinite do&thorn; no greef!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maistres seide of &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at deueles tauhte him clergye;</L>
<L>"A Mayde," &thorn;ei seide, "bi prophetes sawe,</L>
<L N="152">Schal bere crist, kyng of glorie.</L>
<L>Wel we witen, and wel is knawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Olde Ioseph weddet Marie;
<PB REF="00000491.tif" N="483"></L>
<L>O&thorn;er record cunne we non drawe,</L>
<L N="156">He nis not crist bi prophecie."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu spac with Mylde chere</L>
<L>To Iewes &thorn;at gonne grede &amp; crie:</L>
<L>"ffare&thorn; feire, ffrendes deore,</L>
<L N="160">&yogh;e ffare&thorn; foule wi&thorn; folye.</L>
<L>And o &thorn;ing a-non &yogh;e schul heere:</L>
<L>What sei&thorn; &thorn;e prophete Ysaye?</L>
<L>Heo schal be weddet wi&thorn;oute pere,</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;e Mylde Mooder of Messye.</L>
<L>"Ysaye sei&thorn; a-no&thorn;er &thorn;ing:</L>
<L>Crist in &thorn;e lawe schal be bore&mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at mot ben In weddyng,</L>
<L N="168">And elles cristes lawe is lore.</L>
<L>Prophetes speeke of his comyng</L>
<L>At Iesse bi-gon &thorn;e more.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it ha&thorn; crist no bi-gynnyng,</L>
<L N="172">Al-&thorn;au&yogh; &thorn;at crist be mon I-core.</L>
<L><I>Ioseph uirga floruit fatu Ysaye;</I></L>
<L><I>Coniunx, lex ut monuit, mater fit Messye.</I>"</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maystres And Iewes mo,</L>
<L N="176">Of &yogh;onge Ihesu hedde meruayle,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at he was comen hem to,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wit and clergye to assayle.</L>
<L>Of hem hedde Ihesu mony a fo,</L>
<L N="180">ffor heore wit gon sone fayle;</L>
<L>Monye with-drawe and gonne go,</L>
<L>Whon heore clergye hem nolde vayle.</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e Temple com Marie:</L>
<L N="184">Heo say&yogh; hire sone In see was set,</L>
<L>And tau&yogh;te &thorn;e peple bi clergye</L>
<L>Of loueli lawe wi&thorn;-oute let.</L>
<L>To him heo seide Riht in hei&yogh;e:</L>
<L N="188">"Now is my Bale myd boote I-bet!</L>
<L>&THORN;i ffader and I wel sorie</L>
<L>&THORN;e haue&thorn; sou&yogh;t, &amp; nou&yogh;wher met.</L>
<L><I>Ego &amp; pater tuus dolentes querebamus te.</I>"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="192">Ihesu seide in &thorn;at stounde:</L>
<L>"Mi ffader wille is &thorn;at I do;</L>
<L>I wol vn-bynde &thorn;at was bounde:
<PB REF="00000492.tif" N="484"></L>
<L>Mi ffader wole &thorn;at hit beo so.</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;e peple I preche wi&thorn; facounde</L>
<L>And I teche ffrend and fo;</L>
<L>Mi sarmoun is bo&thorn;e so&thorn; &amp; sounde;</L>
<L>On me is ffader and sone also.</L>
<L N="200">"Mi ffader lawe I wol fulfelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore I am hider I-sent;</L>
<L>Dou&yogh;ter and Moder, to &thorn;e I telle,</L>
<L>Elles weore &thorn;e world I-schent.</L>
<L N="204">Mi ffader wol with-oute dwelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I teche ow In present;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffendes fare doun to felle</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; with wrong &thorn;e world went."</L>
<L N="208">Romayns &thorn;er were wonder won</L>
<L>&THORN;at cunnynge were of Clergye;</L>
<L>Bi prophecie heo wusten vchon</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was crist with-outen lye;</L>
<L N="212">Honourede him for crist anon,</L>
<L>ffor his miht &amp; his maistrie.</L>
<L>Preye we crist &thorn;at we so don,</L>
<L N="215">To geten &thorn;e gle in his glorie. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="46" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>XLV. A disputison by=twene a cristenemon and a Jew.</HEAD>
<P>Ed. before in Horstmann's <I>Sammlung altengl. Leg.</I>, Heil|bronn 1878, p. 204 ff.; three stanzas, vv. 145-192, are printed in <I>Warton's Hist. of Engl. Poetry</I>, ed. Hazlitt, III, 181-3.</P><P>[Twenty 16-line stanzas: <I>aaab, cccb, dddb, eeeb.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Alle Bli&thorn;e mote &thorn;ei be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at folyes ble&thorn;eliche wole fle.</L>
<L>How hit bitidde bi-&yogh;onde s&eacute;&eacute;,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e so&thorn;e I wol &yogh;ow say.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Toun of Parys&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is A Cit&eacute;&eacute; of Prys&mdash;</L>
<L>Twey men mette &thorn;at weore wys,</L>
<L N="8">And wente bi &thorn;e way.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei weore Clerkes of Diuinite,
<PB REF="00000493.tif" N="485"></L>
<L>Crafti Men in heore degre.</L>
<L>Ei&thorn;er, Maister wolde be,</L>
<L N="12">ffoonde&thorn; &yogh;if &thorn;ei may.</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;ei desputed so faste,</L>
<L>While &thorn;e day mihte<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. mihti</NOTE> laste,</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;er o&thorn;er cou&thorn;e caste,</L>
<L N="16">Beo Rihtwys lay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e ton was of Engelonde,</L>
<L>A Cristene Mon, Ich vnderstonde;</L>
<L>He hedde I-souht ouer &thorn;e sonde,</L>
<L N="20">Wondres to se;</L>
<L>He hedde I-lernd of Clergys,</L>
<L>As Men do&thorn; &thorn;at beo&thorn; wys:</L>
<L>&THORN;e mon &thorn;at most is of prys,</L>
<L N="24">Maister moste be.</L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;er was A Ieu&yogh; riht,</L>
<L>A Mon muchel of his miht;</L>
<L>To his trou&thorn;e hedde he tiht,</L>
<L N="28">Trewe as &thorn;e tre:&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at wol I apertly preue:</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke lay &thorn;at he on leeue,</L>
<L>ffor no gold &thorn;at [me] mihte him &yogh;eue,</L>
<L N="32">Chaunge wolde not he.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e Cristene Mon seide as he &thorn;ou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>"Lo, &yogh;onde vr god &thorn;at vs bou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>O&thorn;er trouwe &thorn;ou hit nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="36">Bi daye nor bi niht?</L>
<L>Certeynliche, &yogh;onde is he</L>
<L>&THORN;at for vs di&yogh;ede on &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>And also bouwed him to be</L>
<L N="40">In A Buyrde Briht,</L>
<L>As heo wemles was,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e cler as &thorn;e glas;</L>
<L>Bi-twene Oxe and an As</L>
<L N="44">I-bore was &thorn;at kniht,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e &yogh;ol ful &yogh;are,</L>
<L>Al for vr wel-fare.
<PB REF="00000494.tif" N="486"></L>
<L>Woldest &thorn;ou leeue on my lare,</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;i lykyng were liht!"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e Ieu&yogh; sone seide &thorn;are:</L>
<L>"Ar we ffor&thorn;ere fare&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;er is O god, and no mare,</L>
<L N="52">Hei&yogh;ly in holde,</L>
<L>And, as I trowe, in &thorn;e trone,</L>
<L>He schop &thorn;e sonne and &thorn;e Moone;</L>
<L>But he hedde neuer no sone</L>
<L N="56">ffor synful was solde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e grete god calle we&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is semely to se:</L>
<L>O&thorn;er may &thorn;er non be,</L>
<L N="60">&YOGH;onger ne Olde.</L>
<L>Wharto makestou &thorn;i mone?</L>
<L>I trouwe, &thorn;i wit beo &thorn;e wone;</L>
<L>Al mis artou gone</L>
<L N="64">Heer on &thorn;is wolde."<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. molde</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e cristen Mon stonde&thorn; stille,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en he talke&thorn; him tille</L>
<L>And sei&thorn;: "&thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. &thorn;at?</NOTE> &thorn;i wikked wille</L>
<L N="68">Schal worche &thorn;e ful wo.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou leuest not in &thorn;e Mes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer God &thorn;er in Is<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. es</NOTE>:</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i lyking is &thorn;e les,</L>
<L N="72">And loren artou so,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;i careful kynde</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer bi-com of his strende.</L>
<L>Men schal in Baret &thorn;e bynde,</L>
<L N="76">And bete &thorn;e ful blo.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou schalt of &thorn;is world wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt be tau&yogh;t to &thorn;e fende,</L>
<L>And euermore wi&thorn;-outen ende</L>
<L N="80">In-to &thorn;e pyne go."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e Ieu&yogh; bi-gon him to greue:</L>
<L>"&THORN;at wol I apertly preue,
<PB REF="00000495.tif" N="487"></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of Adam and of Eue</L>
<L N="84">Of hem we weore alle I-wrouht.</L>
<L>And I dar wage wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>Tonnes of wyn &thorn;re</L>
<L>&THORN;at I schal lete &thorn;e him se,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;ou seist &thorn;at &thorn;e bouht,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e vuel and &thorn;e gode:</L>
<L>Hou he was don on &thorn;e Roode;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at bi him stoode</L>
<L N="92">Whon he to de&thorn;e was brouht.</L>
<L>So const &thorn;ou not do</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;i clergye; &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>As haue I reste o&thorn;er Ro,</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;i Reson is nou&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e cristen mon Mildely gon malt:</L>
<L>"I telle &thorn;e, truwaunt for-talt:</L>
<L>Men schal in prison &thorn;e palt,</L>
<L N="100">And putte &thorn;e to pyne;</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;ou lete me him se</L>
<L>&THORN;at for vs dyede on &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;e Maystrie &yogh;eue I &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="104">To &thorn;e and alle &thorn;yne.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ow holde &thorn;at we say!</L>
<L>To morwe, set we &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>We schal wende on vr way</L>
<L N="108">To winne vs &thorn;e wyne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Mon &thorn;at fayles of his fare,</L>
<L>Al loren is his lare;</L>
<L>He may droupe and dare</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;at schal his trou&thorn;e tyne."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;ei woke al &thorn;e niht,</L>
<L>Til on &thorn;e Morwen at day-liht</L>
<L>&THORN;e cristene mon Ros Riht,</L>
<L N="116">And radly gon say</L>
<L>His Matyns in &thorn;e Mornyng;</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e his Masse gon he syng;</L>
<L>He &thorn;onked vr lord in alle &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="120">As he &thorn;at most may.
<PB REF="00000496.tif" N="488"></L>
<L>Soone &thorn;ei metten, as &thorn;ei miht.</L>
<L>"Haue I-don," he seide, "artou diht</L>
<L>ffor to holde &thorn;at &thorn;ou hiht?</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;is is vr day.</L>
<L>O&thorn;er a nay, or A &yogh;a?</L>
<L>Soone tel &thorn;ou me swa!"</L>
<L>Him grauntes for-to ga,</L>
<L N="128">And went on heore way.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e Cristen mon seide son,</L>
<L>Whon his Masse was don:</L>
<L>"I wol take god me vppon,</L>
<L N="132">And bere him wi&thorn; me:</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in lond and in leode,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e lasse is my drede:</L>
<L>&THORN;e mon &thorn;at to him take&thorn; hede,</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;e better he may be.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis non enemy in helle,</L>
<L>Non so fers ne so felle,</L>
<L>And he here of vre lord telle,</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;at on Is in &thorn;re:</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e gold in &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>He wolde not byde him a stounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at he nolde freschly founde,</L>
<L N="144">And a-wey fle."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>ffor&thorn; heo wenten on &thorn;e ffeld</L>
<L>To an Hul &thorn;ei bi-heold.</L>
<L>&THORN;e eor&thorn;e cleuet as a scheld</L>
<L N="148">On &thorn;e grounde grene.</L>
<L>Sone fond &thorn;ei a stih:</L>
<L>&THORN;ei went &thorn;er-on radly;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Cristene mon hedde ferly</L>
<L N="152">What hit mihte mene.</L>
<L>After &thorn;at sti&yogh; lay a strete,</L>
<L>Clene I-pauet wi&thorn; grete.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei fond a maner &thorn;at was meete</L>
<L N="156">Wi&thorn; Mur&thorn;es ful schene,</L>
<L>Wel coruen and wrouht,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; halles hei&yogh;e vppon loft.
<PB REF="00000497.tif" N="489"></L>
<L>To a place weore &thorn;ei brouht,</L>
<L N="160">As paradys &thorn;e clene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;er was foulene song,</L>
<L>Muche Mur&thorn;es a-mong&mdash;</L>
<L>Hose lenge wolde long,</L>
<L N="164">fful luitel him &thorn;ouht.</L>
<L>On vche a syde of &thorn;e halle,</L>
<L>Pourpul, pelure and palle;</L>
<L>Wyndouwes I &thorn;e walle,</L>
<L N="168">Was wonderli I-wrouht.</L>
<L>&THORN;er was dosers on &thorn;e dees,</L>
<L>Hose &thorn;e cheef wolde ches,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuere Ricchere wes</L>
<L N="172">In no sale souht.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e Mot and &thorn;e molde</L>
<L>Schon al on red golde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cristen mon hedde ferli on &thorn;at folde</L>
<L N="176">&THORN;at &thorn;ider was brou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;er was Erbes growen grene,</L>
<L>Spices springynge bi-twene;</L>
<L>"Such hedde I non sene,</L>
<L N="180">ffor-so&thorn;e, as I say."</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;restel song ful schille,</L>
<L>He newed notes at his wille;</L>
<L>ffeire ffloures to fille,</L>
<L N="184">ffeire in &thorn;at ffey.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e Rounde table good,</L>
<L>Hou Arthur in eor&thorn;e &yogh;od,</L>
<L>Sum sat and sum stod</L>
<L N="188">O &thorn;e grounde grey&mdash;</L>
<L>Hit was a wonderful siht:</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei weore quik men diht,</L>
<L N="192">To seo hou &thorn;ey play.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e Iew&yogh; sone in &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>He spak &thorn;er a word of pryde:
<PB REF="00000498.tif" N="490"></L>
<L>Hose wol lenge and abyde</L>
<L N="196">May lusten and lere.</L>
<L>Til a Nonnerie &thorn;ei came;</L>
<L>But I knowe not &thorn;e name:</L>
<L>&THORN;er was mony a derwor&thorn;e dame</L>
<L N="200">In Dyapre dere.</L>
<L>Squi&yogh;ers in vch a syde</L>
<L>In &thorn;e wones so wyde.</L>
<L>"Heer schul we lenge and abyde,</L>
<L N="204">Auntres to heere."</L>
<L>&THORN;enne swi&thorn;e speke&thorn; he</L>
<L>Til a ladi so fre</L>
<L>And bidde&thorn;: &thorn;at he welcome be,</L>
<L N="208">"Sire Water, my feere."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;er was Bordes I-clo&thorn;ed clene</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; schire clo&thorn;es and schene.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e a wasschen, I weene,</L>
<L N="212">And wente to &thorn;e sete.</L>
<L>Riche metes was for&thorn; brouht,</L>
<L>To alle men &thorn;at good &thorn;ouht;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Cristen mon wolde nouht</L>
<L N="216">Drynke nor ete.</L>
<L>&THORN;er was wyn ful clere</L>
<L>In mony a feir Maseere,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er drynkes &thorn;at weore dere</L>
<L N="220">In Coupes ful gret.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;&thorn;e was schewed hem bi,</L>
<L>Mur&thorn;e and Munstralsy,</L>
<L>And preyed hem do gladly</L>
<L N="224">Wi&thorn; Rial Rehet.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>By &thorn;e Bordes vp &thorn;ei stode.</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ei for&thorn;ere &yogh;ode,</L>
<L>So weore &thorn;ei war of a Rode</L>
<L N="228">fful Ra&thorn;e, as I Rede,</L>
<L>And a bodi &thorn;er-vppon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at woundes hedde mony on;</L>
<L>Bi him stod Marie and Ion,</L>
<L N="232">Wepynde good spede,
<PB REF="00000499.tif" N="491"></L>
<L>O&thorn;ur Apostles of prys,</L>
<L>Poul and Peter &thorn;e wys,</L>
<L>And seint Ion &thorn;e Baptys,</L>
<L N="236">Was douhti of dede.</L>
<L>Whon he was schewed to &thorn;e siht,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of leom and of liht</L>
<L>&THORN;e Mon &thorn;at most was of miht,</L>
<L N="240">His woundes gon blede.<MILESTONE N="302:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e Ieu&yogh;, sone seide he:</L>
<L>"Holden is &thorn;at I hihte &thorn;e."</L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;er seide: "&thorn;at schal I se,</L>
<L N="244">Certeynly, ful sone."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Cristen Mon hedde a derwor&thorn; &thorn;inge,</L>
<L>On his Bodi, he gon hit brynge:</L>
<L>&THORN;at a prest schulde wi&thorn; synge</L>
<L N="248">Whon Masse schulde be don.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be god so fre</L>
<L>&THORN;at for me di&yogh;ed on &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>Here &thorn;i sone mai &thorn;ou se,"</L>
<L N="252">And heold him a-bouen.</L>
<L>Whon he was schewed to &thorn;e siht,</L>
<L>He barst &thorn;e Buyldynge so briht.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e was derk as &thorn;e niht,</L>
<L N="256">Heore sonne and heore mone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>Al &thorn;e gere &thorn;at was gay</L>
<L>Was &thorn;enne I-wasted a-way.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Cristene Mon gon say:</L>
<L N="260">"Beon &thorn;eos &thorn;i godes here?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ieuh onswerde him wi&thorn; 'nay'</L>
<L>And ofte Merci gon him pray:</L>
<L>"I wol leue my lay,</L>
<L N="264">And on &thorn;i lore lere.</L>
<L>Sore I doute me of dred.</L>
<L>I haue i-lost my wed:</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at are for&thorn; fled</L>
<L N="268">Was fendes in feere,</L>
<L>Non good, but al ille."</L>
<L>No more he tented hem tille.
<PB REF="00000500.tif" N="492"></L>
<L>Heo &thorn;o stoden o &thorn;e hulle</L>
<L N="272">&THORN;er &thorn;ey furst were.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;us he &yogh;eldes him &yogh;are,</L>
<L>Al for his wel-fare.</L>
<L>He seide: "of Blisse I haue be bare</L>
<L N="276">Se&thorn;&thorn;en I was furst born.</L>
<L>Now knowe I wel &thorn;at hit mai be</L>
<L>&THORN;at O-fold god Is in &thorn;re:</L>
<L>Whuch &thorn;at &thorn;ou brou&yogh;t wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;is day at Morn.</L>
<L>He is vre heuene kyng,</L>
<L>Makere of alle &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>And schop &thorn;e fruit for to spryng,</L>
<L N="284">Bo&thorn;e Curnel and Corn."</L>
<L>&THORN;us he Rapes of his res,</L>
<L>To vre God he him ches,</L>
<L>Let al his lu&thorn;ernes,</L>
<L N="288">Was poynt to be lorn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ei wente to &thorn;e Cite,</L>
<L>A-cordet, as &thorn;ei scholde be.</L>
<L>Who was payed bote he,</L>
<L N="292">And ei&thorn;er of o&thorn;er!</L>
<L>He &thorn;onked god his swete sonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hedde brou&yogh;t out of bonde,</L>
<L>Wel I-wonne to his honde,</L>
<L N="296">Bli&thorn;ely his Bro&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Mete and drynke &thorn;ei hedde at wille,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen grucchyng or grille</L>
<L>In trou&thorn;e tente &thorn;ei &thorn;er tille,</L>
<L N="300">And lafte al &thorn;at o&thorn;er.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Mon &thorn;at ha&thorn; synne I-wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en repentes him ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>God is a-payed, &thorn;at vs bou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="304">Leeue we non o&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>What was &thorn;e Monnes nome I-lyk</L>
<L>But Sir Water of Berewyk?
<PB REF="00000501.tif" N="493"></L>
<L>He was wonynge I &thorn;e Ryk,</L>
<L N="308">At Roome was called.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope &yogh;af him pouste&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at mony mon mihte se&mdash;</L>
<L>Penitauncer for to be</L>
<L N="312">Of &yogh;onge and of olde,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e to soyle and to schriue</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e to Mon and to<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. two</NOTE> wyue,</L>
<L>Eke to mende heore lyue</L>
<L N="316">And to &thorn;e trou&thorn;e holde.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne tok &thorn;ei &thorn;e Ieu&yogh;,</L>
<L>Anon cristend hym neu&yogh;;</L>
<L>&THORN;us to vre God he hym kneu&yogh;</L>
<L N="320">And &yogh;eply him &yogh;olde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="47" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[XLVII. How to hear Mass.<NOTE PLACE="foot">So the title in Index. The poem was ed. before by Canon Simmons in "The Lay Folks' Mass Book," 1879, E. E. T. S., p. 128 ff. (His sidenotes are reprinted here.) It is a free Mid|land version of Dan Jeremy's Massbook for Laymen, a northern translation of which was ed., from 4 MSS., by Simmons, l. c. The liturgical prayers are mostly omitted in MS. Vernon, either because prayers of that kind were given before in MS. Vernon, or because the uses were different in different churches.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<ARGUMENT>
<L>Her teche&thorn; &thorn;ys tretys &thorn;enne<MILESTONE N="302b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hou mon scholde here hys masse;</L>
<L>Hit is ful nedful to alle menne,</L>
<L>To more and eke to lasse.</L>
</ARGUMENT>

<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;ong &amp; olde, More and lasse,</L>
<L>fful god hit is to here a Masse,</L>
<L N="3">&THORN;at Cristendam ha&thorn; tan.</L>
<L>Hit was mad for soule-hele,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Pater noster wi&thorn; bedes<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. dedes</NOTE> fele,</L>
<L N="6">And de profundis Is on.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Pater noster Is pris preyere,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; o&thorn;er orisons mony and sere.</L>
<L N="9">Holde&thorn; ow stille as ston:</L>
<L>And &yogh;e schul here &thorn;e beste &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer &yogh;e herde of Olde or &yogh;yng</L>
<L N="12">As wyde as mon ha&thorn; gon.
<PB REF="00000502.tif" N="494"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lustne&thorn; here, &amp; &yogh;e wol ly&thorn;e:</L>
<L>Of a talkyng I wol &yogh;ou ki&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="15">Cumfort to al Mon-kynde:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e Meedes of &thorn;e Masse.</L>
<L>Eueri mon bo&thorn;e more and lasse</L>
<L N="18">Schulde haue hit in his mynde,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at &yogh;e scholde &yogh;or seruise seye</L>
<L>And priueliche &yogh;or preyers preye</L>
<L N="21">To him &thorn;at may vn-bynde,</L>
<L>In saluyng of &yogh;or synnes seuene,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e mihtful kyng of heuene,</L>
<L N="24">Vr ffader &thorn;at we schal fynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And hou vr ffader schal be founde</L>
<L>To vche a mon &thorn;at is I-bounde</L>
<L N="27">In sunne, as I ow say.</L>
<L>His suffrance we may se,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at he suffre&thorn; &thorn;e and me</L>
<L N="30">Wi&thorn; miht al &thorn;at he may,</L>
<L>And euere is redi vr bales to bete,</L>
<L>To loke what tyme &thorn;at we wol leete,</L>
<L N="33">In-to vr laste day;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we ben in wille to leue vr synne,</L>
<L>He teche&thorn; vs wel hou we schal wynne</L>
<L N="36">To heuene &thorn;e hei&yogh;e way.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What mon wolde now suffre so</L>
<L>His sone I-slayen, and hedde no mo,</L>
<L N="39">But &yogh;if he mi&yogh;te lyue a-&yogh;eyn;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he for traytrie weore take,</L>
<L>Sone he schulde be forsake</L>
<L N="42">Or elles so&thorn;li slayn.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou dost a dedly synne,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e while &thorn;at &thorn;ou dwellest &thorn;er-Inne</L>
<L N="45">&THORN;ou puttest to his payn;</L>
<L>&THORN;e same he suffred for vr sake,</L>
<L>&THORN;en most merci a-mendes make</L>
<L N="48">Bo&thorn;e wi&thorn; miht and mayn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;orw his Merci and his miht</L>
<L>He rewe&thorn; of vs, a-&yogh;eynes &thorn;e riht,</L>
<L N="51">As Rihtwysnes wol rede.
<PB REF="00000503.tif" N="495"></L>
<L>Rihtwysnes wolde, assone</L>
<L>As we dedly synne haue done,</L>
<L N="54">To dampne vs to &thorn;e dede:</L>
<L>&THORN;en most Merci be Mayster most</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;e miht of &thorn;e holy gost,</L>
<L N="57">And stonde wi&thorn; vs in stede;</L>
<L>And lenge wi&thorn; vs in leo and lede,</L>
<L>Til we beo don out of &thorn;at dede</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;orw bone of holy bede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wi&thorn; &yogh;or leue, I wol be-gynne</L>
<L>Of a Mater for to mynne,</L>
<L N="63">A good &thorn;ing for to make,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e hexte &thorn;ing hit is</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer was mad: &thorn;at is &thorn;e Mes,</L>
<L N="66">Monnes sunnes to slake.</L>
<L>Eueri day &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t se</L>
<L>&THORN;e same bodi &thorn;at di&yogh;ed for &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="69">Tent &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt take,</L>
<L>In figure and in fourme of Bred,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Ihesu dalte, er he weore ded,</L>
<L N="72">ffor his disciples sake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On &thorn;e hexte &thorn;ing to here,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e lihtest for to lere,</L>
<L N="75">ffor lewed men In lare,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at &yogh;e schul &yogh;or seruise say,</L>
<L>And priueliche &yogh;or preyers pray,<MILESTONE N="302b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="78">In churche whon &thorn;at &yogh;e are.</L>
<L>I do ow wel to witen wi&thorn;-outen drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Masse was mad for monnes nede,</L>
<L N="81">ffor al folk lasse and mare.</L>
<L>As &thorn;e prest sei&thorn; his preyere,</L>
<L>So schulde vche mon &thorn;at him gon here,</L>
<L N="84">And &thorn;ei wuste what hit ware.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;if I seide &thorn;is word wi&thorn; my wit,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen witnesse of holi writ</L>
<L N="87">Wisdam weore hit non;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore I wole &thorn;at &yogh;e hit witen,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at we fynde hit writen</L>
<L N="90">Wi&thorn; Auctours mony on.
<PB REF="00000504.tif" N="496"></L>
<L>Of Austin, Ambrose, Bernard, and Bede,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it heore Resons wol I rede</L>
<L N="93">A-Mong &yogh;ow euerichon.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei make muynde of mony a mede</L>
<L>&THORN;at we schul haue for vre good dede,</L>
<L N="96">To churche whon &thorn;at we gon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ow biginnest to go</L>
<L>Ou&thorn;er to &thorn;e churche or fro,</L>
<L N="99">To here a Masse &yogh;if &thorn;ou may,</L>
<L>Eueri fote &thorn;at &thorn;ou gas,</L>
<L>&THORN;yn Angel poynte&thorn; hit vch a pas,</L>
<L N="102">&THORN;e Prince of heuene to pay.</L>
<L>&THORN;at day schalt &thorn;ou elde nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou beo studefast in &thorn;i &thorn;ouht</L>
<L N="105">On God &thorn;at is verray;</L>
<L>Not Blynt &thorn;at day schalt &thorn;ou not be</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;i sauiour hast se,</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;orw him &thorn;at mihtes may.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A ffair grace God ha&thorn; &thorn;e &yogh;iuen,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i sunnes and &thorn;ou be schriuen</L>
<L N="111">&THORN;at day &thorn;ou hast god se:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be ded &thorn;e same day,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt be founden I &thorn;e fay,</L>
<L N="114">Hoseled as &thorn;ou hed be.</L>
<L>Baldely mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou swete and swynke</L>
<L>ffor to wynne &thorn;e Mete and drinke</L>
<L N="117">Wi&thorn;-outen tray or tene;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou be in eny drede,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e better schalt &thorn;ou spede</L>
<L N="120">To keuere of cares kene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou haue eny wey to wende,</L>
<L>I rede &thorn;ou here a masse to ende</L>
<L N="123">In &thorn;e Morennynge &yogh;if &thorn;ow may;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou may not do so,</L>
<L>I rede, beo vnderne ar &thorn;ou go,</L>
<L N="126">Or elles be hei&yogh; midday.</L>
<L>Serteynliche wi&thorn;-outen fayle</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt not leose of &thorn;i trauayle</L>
<L N="129">Not half a foote of way;
<PB REF="00000505.tif" N="497"></L>
<L>O &thorn;i bodi &thorn;ou schalt be lihtore,</L>
<L>And &thorn;i weyes wende &thorn;e Rihtore,</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;orwh him &thorn;at mihtes may.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Ouh he be nou&yogh;t at &thorn;i lykynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest &thorn;at schal &thorn;y masse synge,</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;erfore lette &thorn;ou nouht:</L>
<L>His Masse schal be as<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>altered from</I> a <I>to</I> as <I>by another hand.</I></NOTE> good to heere</L>
<L>As Monk, Chanoun, Hermyte or ffrere,&mdash;</L>
<L N="138">&THORN;us &thorn;enk hit in &thorn;y &thorn;ouht,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; his preyere and his bone</L>
<L>Bi-fore God come not so sone</L>
<L N="141">As he &thorn;at neuer synne wrou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Ihesu crist, souereyn of al,</L>
<L>He may deeme bo&thorn;e gret and smal,</L>
<L N="144">&THORN;us Doctours han I-souht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Ambrose sei&thorn;, hose rede&thorn; riht:</L>
<L>&THORN;e Masse Is of so muche miht,</L>
<L N="147">&THORN;er nys no mon &thorn;at May,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;at he be old or &yogh;onge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ten&thorn;e part telle wi&thorn; tonge,</L>
<L N="150">&THORN;ei&yogh; he schulde liue for ay.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Exposission is so expres,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al &thorn;e priuete of &thorn;e Mes,</L>
<L N="153">Serteyn wi&thorn;-oute delay,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, cou&thorn;e a mon neuere so muche of art,</L>
<L>He mihte not telle &thorn;e ten&thorn;e part,</L>
<L N="156">&THORN;au&yogh; he hedde &thorn;ou&yogh;t to say.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Ierom sei&thorn;: for soules sere,<MILESTONE N="302b:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;auh a Mon wolde a &thorn;ousent &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="159">Do a Masse for to synge,</L>
<L>Hit<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. His</NOTE> is nou&thorn;er more ne las</L>
<L>But vch a soule schal haue a mas&mdash;</L>
<L N="162">Hit is so hei&yogh; a &thorn;inge.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it I Rede ow go to chirche,</L>
<L>Godes werkes for to worche,</L>
<L N="165">In-to vr laste endynge:</L>
<L>Haue we no doute of vr dole,</L>
<L>Vch soule schal haue a masse al hole,</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;orw help of heuene-kynge.
<PB REF="00000506.tif" N="498"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>fful hard hit were to vre bi-houe</L>
<L>Vch a prouerbe for to proue</L>
<L N="171">Of &thorn;eos Auctours alle;</L>
<L>Serteynliche wi&thorn;-outen lees</L>
<L>Of sum of hem &thorn;en wol I sees</L>
<L N="174">ffor &thorn;ing &thorn;at may be-falle;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if I drou&yogh; hem on leng&thorn;e,</L>
<L>I trou no mon schulde haue &thorn;e streng&thorn;e</L>
<L N="177">To stonde and heere hem alle.</L>
<L>Lewed men, and &yogh;e wol list,</L>
<L>fful fayn I wolde &thorn;at &yogh;e hit wist</L>
<L N="180">On Crist whon &yogh;e schulde calle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To calle on Crist wi&thorn; mylde chere,</L>
<L>Lewed Men, I schal &yogh;ou lere.</L>
<L N="183">Whon &thorn;at &thorn;e prest bi-ginnes,</L>
<L>Whon he sei&thorn; his Confiteore,</L>
<L>ffeire he loute&thorn; &thorn;e Auter bi-fore,</L>
<L N="186">To schriue him of his synnes.</L>
<L>Serteynly, wi&thorn;-oute delay</L>
<L>And &yogh;e for &thorn;e prest pray,</L>
<L N="189">And he atte Masse &yogh;ou mynne,</L>
<L>Sikerli I dar wel say,</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis no tonge &thorn;at telle may</L>
<L N="192">What Mede &thorn;at &yogh;e may wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But &yogh;it I telle &yogh;ou, sikerly:</L>
<L>And &yogh;e preye but only</L>
<L N="195">ffor &yogh;or owne hele,</L>
<L>I do &yogh;ow to witen wi&thorn;-outen drede</L>
<L>&YOGH;e beo not wor&thorn; so muche meede,</L>
<L N="198">Not be &thorn;e haluendele,</L>
<L>As &thorn;i kuynde puttes &thorn;e to</L>
<L>To don vuele he biddes &thorn;e do.</L>
<L N="201">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wol wone in weole,</L>
<L>Prey for &thorn;e prest, and he for &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&THORN;at Is a preyere of charite,</L>
<L N="204">&THORN;en mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou synge of loue lele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Loue is trewe in vche a leede;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou do ille, vuel schalt &thorn;ou spede</L>
<L N="207">ffor al &thorn;e craftes &thorn;at &thorn;ou con.
<PB REF="00000507.tif" N="499"></L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at &thorn;ou comest &thorn;e chirche with-Inne</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou sest &thorn;e prest bi-gynne,</L>
<L N="210">Take his vestimens on:</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou do as I sey &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Knele a-doun vppon &thorn;i kne,</L>
<L N="213">Noyse &thorn;at &thorn;ow make non;</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e stond vp at &thorn;i seruise,</L>
<L>And serue god on &thorn;is wyse,</L>
<L N="216">Al folk euerichon:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou schalt say: "&thorn;i drihten</L>
<L>And deore god almihten,</L>
<L N="219">And In Marie I me a-seure,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo saue vs alle,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e grete and smalle,</L>
<L N="222">Of sunnes we be&thorn; vn-pure;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at I may me schriue</L>
<L>Of al my wikked lyue</L>
<L N="225">To Prest &thorn;at bere&thorn; &thorn;e cure,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I haue I-wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And in herte I-&thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="228">As vnkuynde creature.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"I was vn-kuynde,</L>
<L>And was &thorn;enne blynde,</L>
<L N="231">To worche a-&yogh;eynes his wille</L>
<L>&THORN;at fust me wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;e me bou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="234">ffro peynes he was put to ille.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore we pray</L>
<L>To &thorn;e to-day,</L>
<L N="237">&THORN;at knowes bo&thorn;e good and ille:<MILESTONE N="303:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Graunt vs lyue,</L>
<L>We may vs schriue,</L>
<L N="240">Vr penaunce to folfille."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>We schal prey&yogh;e Ihesus</L>
<L>&THORN;at he for&yogh;iue vs</L>
<L N="243">Vr sunnes, &thorn;at we may synge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we may pray</L>
<L>&THORN;e Prince to-day,</L>
<L N="246">Schop eor&thorn;e and alle &thorn;inge,
<PB REF="00000508.tif" N="500"></L>
<L>&THORN;at in Clannesse</L>
<L>We may &thorn;e Messe</L>
<L N="249">&THORN;orw miht of heuene-kynge,</L>
<L>So deorliche to do,</L>
<L>To torne &thorn;e to</L>
<L N="252">Vs alle to good endynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Certes, sires, ful good hit is</L>
<L>To stonde stille at &thorn;e Mes,</L>
<L N="255">Sum good word for to say;</L>
<L>Whuche &thorn;at &yogh;e wole preye fore,</L>
<L>&THORN;auh &yogh;e do for mony a score,</L>
<L N="258">At a Masse &yogh;e may;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;o &thorn;at &yogh;e nempne nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>But only &thorn;enke in &yogh;or &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="261">&THORN;at &yogh;e wolde fore pray,</L>
<L>I do ow to wite wi&thorn;-outen doute,</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis no soule a Masse wi&thorn;-oute,</L>
<L N="264">But he haue helle for ay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wust I my ffader in flesch and felle</L>
<L>Weore holliche I-holden in helle,</L>
<L N="267">&THORN;er weore non hope of hele,</L>
<L>To preye for him I cou&thorn;e no Red,</L>
<L>No more &thorn;en for a Dogge were ded,</L>
<L N="270">But let hem wi&thorn; him dele.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it I rede we go to chirche,</L>
<L>Godes werkes for to worche,</L>
<L N="273">&YOGH;if we wole wone in wele;</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e hit is vnknowe to vs,</L>
<L>We schul preye for alle ffidelibus</L>
<L N="276">To Rewe soules &thorn;at be&thorn; lele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;it I bidde &yogh;ou take&thorn; good tent</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e holde no parlyment</L>
<L N="279">Wi&thorn; no cristen mon,</L>
<L>Whon &yogh;e come &thorn;e Churche with-Inne,</L>
<L>And &yogh;e seo &thorn;e prest bi-ginne</L>
<L N="282">Take &thorn;e vestimens on:</L>
<L>&THORN;e foule fend so fel is,</L>
<L>He writ &yogh;or wordes I-wis</L>
<L N="285">On a Rolle euerichon.
<PB REF="00000509.tif" N="501"></L>
<L>Also witnesse&thorn; seynt Austine,</L>
<L>&THORN;at furst wit in Engelond gan lene,</L>
<L N="288">And preche<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. preched</NOTE> &thorn;e treu&thorn;e bi-gon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">The Mass-Book does not contain this anecdote. It is in R. Brunne's <I>Handlyng Synne</I>, p. 287-8.</NOTE>Ar seynt Austin In Engelond come,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; pope<NOTE PLACE="marg">pope <I>erased.</I></NOTE> Gregori of Rome</L>
<L>fful long tyme gon he dwelle.</L>
<L>Vppon a day for worschupefulnesse</L>
<L>&THORN;e Pope<NOTE PLACE="marg">pope <I>erased.</I></NOTE> wolde synge a Messe</L>
<L N="294">As him ful fayre bi-felle:</L>
<L>He made a signe to seynt Austyne,</L>
<L>ffor he schulde ben his dekne digne</L>
<L N="297">To Rede &thorn;e gospelle.</L>
<L>And as he radde, &thorn;en sauh he &thorn;en</L>
<L>Two wyues, as &yogh;e may witen,</L>
<L N="300">Tales &thorn;en gonne &thorn;ei telle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Austin herde &thorn;is wordes alle;</L>
<L>In A wyndow on &thorn;e walle</L>
<L N="303">&THORN;er bi-fore his face</L>
<L>A foul fend he sau&yogh; &thorn;er-In,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; penne &amp; enke &amp; parchemin,</L>
<L N="306">As God &yogh;af him &thorn;e grace;</L>
<L>He wrot so faste til &thorn;at he want,</L>
<L>ffor his parchemyn-skin was so scant,</L>
<L N="309">To speken &thorn;ei hedde such space;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his tee&thorn; he gon hit togge,</L>
<L>And so radli he gon hit Rogge</L>
<L N="312">&THORN;at al &thorn;e Rolle gon race.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So harde raced he &thorn;at Rolle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he chopped his Cholle</L>
<L N="315">A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e Marbel-ston.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e folk I &thorn;e chirche About</L>
<L>Was a-stoneid of &thorn;at clout<MILESTONE N="303:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="318">And herden hit euerichone.</L>
<L>Seynt Austin sei&yogh; hou faste he drouh:</L>
<L>He barst on lauhtre, and loude louh.</L>
<L N="321">&THORN;e Pope<NOTE PLACE="marg">Pope <I>erased.</I></NOTE> ful sore gon grone,</L>
<L>ffor serwe nei&yogh; &thorn;e Pope<NOTE PLACE="marg">Pope <I>erased.</I></NOTE> wept.</L>
<L>After masse, Austyn he met,</L>
<L N="324">And Mekely made his mone.
<PB REF="00000510.tif" N="502"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He made his mone wi&thorn; mylde mod:</L>
<L>"Whi weore &thorn;ou so wikked and wod</L>
<L N="327">ffor to do &thorn;at dede?</L>
<L>A worse dede miht &thorn;ou neuer done."</L>
<L>Austin onswerde him ful sone&mdash;</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;erof he hedde gret drede:</L>
<L>"Lord, greue &yogh;e nou&yogh;t til &thorn;at &yogh;e wite.</L>
<L>A foul fend I say site&mdash;</L>
<L N="333">Serwe mot ben his mede!&mdash;</L>
<L>Two wyues sat &yogh;onder langare,</L>
<L>Alle heore wordes wrot he &thorn;are</L>
<L N="336">Vppon a Rolle to rede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;ei tok no tent til heore Mas:</L>
<L>Al heore wordes more and las,</L>
<L N="339">He wrot hem euerichon;</L>
<L>ffor to speke &thorn;ei hedde such space,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend wrot wi&thorn; a foul face</L>
<L N="342">Til his Parchemyn was al gon.</L>
<L>Whon his parchemyn was al spende,</L>
<L>He rauhte &thorn;e Rolle bi &thorn;e ende,</L>
<L N="345">Wi&thorn; his teth a-non</L>
<L>He logged, &thorn;at al in-synder gon lasch,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his hed he &yogh;af a dasch</L>
<L N="348">A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e Marbel-ston.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Lord, greue &yogh;e not for &thorn;at dunt!</L>
<L>He stoneyd me, and made me stunt</L>
<L N="351">Stille out of my steuene.</L>
<L>I wol sigge as I se&yogh;e,</L>
<L>ffor a word wol I not ly&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="354">Be Mihtful kyng of heuene."</L>
<L>He ladde him for&thorn;, as I trowe,</L>
<L>Til he com to &thorn;e wynt-douwe</L>
<L N="357">&THORN;at I be-fore gon nemene:</L>
<L>ffoul &thorn;ei fond &thorn;er I-sched,</L>
<L>As blac as pich was I-spred</L>
<L N="360">Vppon &thorn;e Aschelers euene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is is wonder &thorn;ing wi&thorn;-outen drede;</L>
<L>&THORN;er was neuer fend blod mihte blede,</L>
<L N="363">He ha&thorn; nou&thorn;er flesch ne bon;
<PB REF="00000511.tif" N="503"></L>
<L>But god wolde &thorn;at hit were so,</L>
<L>To chastise hem and o&thorn;er mo</L>
<L N="366">&THORN;at to churche gun gon.</L>
<L>Til a Masse was seid to ende,</L>
<L>A Mon schulde talke with fo nor frende,</L>
<L N="369">But holde him stille as ston;</L>
<L>&THORN;at hous was mad for preyere</L>
<L>To Ihesu and to his Moder dere,</L>
<L N="372">To &thorn;onke hem al heore lon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At &thorn;e wyues gon &thorn;ei witen</L>
<L>What &thorn;ei seiden whon &thorn;ei siten</L>
<L N="375">Seynt Austyn hem bi-syde,</L>
<L>Bi heore onswere &thorn;ei wuste ful wel</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei hedde spoken muchel vncel,</L>
<L N="378">And in heore hertes gun hyde.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, sires, I rede &yogh;e loke,</L>
<L>God tent I wolde &yogh;e toke,</L>
<L N="381">ffor &thorn;ing &thorn;at may bi-tyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e mesure &yogh;ou &thorn;e mare,</L>
<L>Of speche &thorn;at &yogh;e ow spare,</L>
<L N="384">At Masse whon &thorn;at &yogh;e byde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e Pope<NOTE PLACE="marg">Pope <I>erased.</I></NOTE> greued him wel &thorn;e lasse;</L>
<L>He let comaunden at &thorn;e Masse</L>
<L N="387">Of &thorn;at Miracle to mynne,</L>
<L>And also bad wi&thorn; ful good wille</L>
<L>&THORN;at eueri Mon schulde stonde stille</L>
<L N="390">Whon he come&thorn; &thorn;e churche with-Inne;</L>
<L>And &thorn;enke<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;enne</NOTE> hou wel &thorn;at god may wreke</L>
<L>Euerich a word &thorn;at we speke;</L>
<L N="393">We do ful muche synne:</L>
<L>A Prest mi&yogh;t be let of his mes,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is world mi&yogh;t fare &thorn;e wers,</L>
<L N="396">Vs alle to wo to wynne.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Vr ffader vre al-weldyng is,<MILESTONE N="303:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>God let vs neuere his mur&thorn;es mis.</L>
<L N="399">Lord, halwed be &thorn;i name.</L>
<L>In heuene and eor&thorn;e &thorn;i wille</L>
<L>Be don, and &thorn;at is skille,</L>
<L N="402">Or elles we ben to blame.
<PB REF="00000512.tif" N="504"></L>
<L>Vr vche-dayes bred &yogh;if vs to-day.</L>
<L>&THORN;at we may trustily whon we schul away</L>
<L N="405">To come to &thorn;i kyndame.</L>
<L>God kepe vs to vre laste endynge,</L>
<L>Let neuer &thorn;e fend wi&thorn; fals fondynge</L>
<L N="408">Cumbre vs in no schame."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is pater noster schulde ben vsed</L>
<L>And for non orison beo refused,</L>
<L N="411">I schal &yogh;ow telle for whi:</L>
<L>Of his Mou&thorn; hit was maad,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;is world long and braad</L>
<L N="414">Out of Bale gan buy&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Leeue hit wel, and not wene hit,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pater noster contened</L>
<L N="417">Alle &thorn;ing hollye</L>
<L>&THORN;at vs neode&thorn;, and non o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e for &thorn;is world and &thorn;at o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="420">Quik whon we schal dye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At &thorn;e gospel, were ful good</L>
<L>Studefastliche &thorn;at &yogh;e stod,</L>
<L N="423">ffor no &thorn;ing &thorn;at &yogh;e stured hit;</L>
<L>Al &yogh;or lykyng &thorn;er-on lei&thorn;</L>
<L>To wite what &thorn;e prest sei&thorn;,</L>
<L N="426">Holliche &thorn;at &yogh;e here hit.</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; &yogh;e vnderstonde hit nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e may wel wite &thorn;at god hit wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="429">And &thorn;erfore wisdam were hit</L>
<L>ffor to worschupe al godes werkes,</L>
<L>To lewed men &thorn;at ben none clerkes.</L>
<L N="432">&THORN;is lesson, now go lere it.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And whi &yogh;e schulde &thorn;is lessun lere,</L>
<L>Herkne&thorn; alle and &yogh;e may here.</L>
<L N="435">&THORN;er a Neddre hauntes,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e may wel fynde, and &yogh;e wol seche,</L>
<L>He vnderstond no&thorn;ing &thorn;i speche</L>
<L N="438">Whon &thorn;ou hire enchauntes,</L>
<L>Neuer&thorn;eles heo wot ful wel</L>
<L>What is &thorn;i menynge eueri-del</L>
<L N="441">Whon &thorn;at &thorn;ou hire endauntes.
<PB REF="00000513.tif" N="505"></L>
<L>So fare&thorn; &thorn;er vnderstondyng fayles,</L>
<L>&THORN;e verrey vertu &yogh;ow alle a-vayles</L>
<L N="444">&THORN;orw grace &thorn;at god &yogh;ow grauntes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon &thorn;e gospel is I-don,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it wolde I, gode men euerichon,</L>
<L N="447">&THORN;at &yogh;e cou&thorn;e &yogh;or crede;</L>
<L>What tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e prest say</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e mi&yogh;te &yogh;or-self pray,</L>
<L N="450">fforso&thorn;e hit were gret nede;</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;e trewely trouwe &thorn;er-Inne,</L>
<L>And fulliche out of &yogh;or mou&thorn; hit mynne,</L>
<L N="453">&THORN;er-to liht muche mede.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &yogh;e trowe and wol not telle,</L>
<L>So dude &thorn;e fend &thorn;at from heuene felle,</L>
<L N="456">And do&thorn; hit nouht in dede,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou neuere so trewely trowe,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-oute dede ful luytel hit douwe,</L>
<L N="459">So do&thorn; &thorn;e deuel &thorn;at dredes.</L>
<L>But seynt Iacob, Iosepes bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Sei&thorn; &thorn;at we schal don non o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="462">In his pistel whose redes.</L>
<L>Such &thorn;ing as &thorn;ou seyst and doos,</L>
<L>&THORN;i Nei&yogh;ebor wol &thorn;erof make Roos</L>
<L N="465">What lyf &thorn;at &thorn;ow lede.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-In a storie in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>He sei&thorn; &thorn;at trou&thorn;e is but dede</L>
<L N="468">But hit be don in dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;it beo &thorn;er mo men lyuing in lede</L>
<L>&THORN;at I wolde cou&thorn;e heore crede,</L>
<L N="471">And whon &thorn;ei cou&thorn;e ken hit.</L>
<L>I haue I-seid as I con:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;er beo euer eny mon</L>
<L N="474">&THORN;at sei&thorn; he con a-mende hit,</L>
<L>ffaute &thorn;er-Inne &yogh;if &thorn;at he fynde,</L>
<L>Mak no scornynge me be-hynde</L>
<L N="477">But a&yogh;eyn to me he sende hit,<MILESTONE N="303b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Or elles help &thorn;at I may here hit.</L>
<L>&THORN;us an Englisch as I lernde hit</L>
<L N="480">I haue I-&thorn;ouht to ende hit.<NOTE PLACE="marg">The Engl. text is, however, omitted.</NOTE> . . . . .
<PB REF="00000514.tif" N="506"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Resun I schal reden ow riht</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;e day bi-fore &thorn;e niht</L>
<L N="483">Was ordeynt for to be.</L>
<L>ffor Adam of &thorn;e Appel eete,</L>
<L>Ihesu Crist vr bales con beete,</L>
<L N="486">&THORN;at dyed vppon &thorn;e Tre;</L>
<L>Out of liht &thorn;at he was Inne,</L>
<L>In-to helle for his sinne,</L>
<L N="489">Holliche &thorn;er was he;</L>
<L>He was banischt out of blis</L>
<L>In-to helle, bo&thorn;e he and his,</L>
<L N="492">Bi-foren &thorn;at was so fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;it a Resun I schal &yogh;ou say:</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;e niht bi-fore &thorn;e day</L>
<L N="495">Was ordeynt, I schal &yogh;ou telle:</L>
<L>ffor Ihesus suffred woundes fyue,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;&thorn;e a-Ros fro de&thorn; to lyue,</L>
<L N="498">And after herwede helle;</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;esternes &thorn;orw his miht</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn he put him to &thorn;e liht</L>
<L N="501">Whuch &thorn;at he fro felle,</L>
<L>And dude him a&yogh;eyn in paradis</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hedde lost bo&thorn;e he &amp; his,</L>
<L N="504">Wi&thorn; speche as I ow spelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Aluytel bi-fore &thorn;e prest wasch</L>
<L>Let him not his offryng asch</L>
<L N="507">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou &thorn;enke for to offre;</L>
<L>Whon he torne&thorn; a-non &thorn;e tille,</L>
<L>Go vp to him with ful good wille</L>
<L N="510">And &thorn;i peny him profre.</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; &thorn;ou be not &thorn;er-to in dette,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt &thorn;inke hit ful wel bi-set,</L>
<L N="513">I swere bi seynt Cristofre;</L>
<L>Of sinnes hit wol make &thorn;e to sese,</L>
<L>And &thorn;i catel also encrese</L>
<L N="516">Of seluer in &thorn;i Cofre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But fayn I wolde &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;us seide</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou in his hond hit leide,</L>
<L N="519">Or &thorn;enk hit in &thorn;i &thorn;ouht:
<PB REF="00000515.tif" N="507"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">Similar prayer in Mass|Book, v. 247.</NOTE> "God, &thorn;at was In Bethleem bore,</L>
<L>&THORN;reo kynges kneled &thorn;e beo-fore,</L>
<L N="522">And heore offryng brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou tok heore offryng of alle &thorn;re:</L>
<L>So receyue &thorn;is of me,</L>
<L N="525">And for&yogh;ete me nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I may euere wi&thorn; &thorn;e wone,</L>
<L>And kuyndelich clepe &thorn;e godes sone,</L>
<L N="528">On &thorn;e Roode as &thorn;ou me bou&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon he ha&thorn; waschen, &thorn;en he walkes,</L>
<L>Priueliche and stille he stalkes</L>
<L N="531">To his Auter a&yogh;eyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste &thorn;ing he do&thorn;, wi&thorn;-oute doute,</L>
<L>To his weuede &thorn;en wol he loute,</L>
<L N="534">&THORN;e so&thorn;e is nou&yogh;t to leyn;</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e he stonde&thorn; vp-riht,</L>
<L>His hondes heue&thorn; vppon hiht</L>
<L N="537">Him-self for to sayn,</L>
<L>&THORN;enne he torne&thorn; him to &yogh;ow.</L>
<L>Cristene men, herkene&thorn; now</L>
<L N="540">And preye&thorn; wi&thorn; al &yogh;or mayn . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="marg">(Prayer omitted.)</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;en he biginnes his secre;</L>
<L>Adoun &thorn;enne knele &yogh;e</L>
<L N="543">A luyte while way,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at he se&thorn; <I>per omnia,</I></L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;e <I>Sursum corda.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Mass-Book, v. 306-7.</NOTE></L>
<L N="546">What is &thorn;at to say?</L>
<L>Hit is a nedful note to nemen:</L>
<L>"Hef vp &yogh;or hertes in to heuen</L>
<L N="549">To him &thorn;at al mihtes may."</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e schul &yogh;e &thorn;onke him &thorn;us</L>
<L>Of bodi and soule has &yogh;iuen vs,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us-maner schul &yogh;e pray . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="marg">(Prayer omitted.) cf. Mass-Book, v. 314-326.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lustne&thorn; alle to &thorn;is &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Bi-twene &thorn;e <I>sanctus</I> and &thorn;e sakeryng</L>
<L N="555">&YOGH;e schal preye stondynge&mdash;</L>
<L>Hit semes wel in &thorn;at whyle</L>
<L>&THORN;at god in his Exyle</L>
<L N="558">In &thorn;is world was wonynge.
<PB REF="00000516.tif" N="508"></L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e schul &yogh;e knele a-doun</L>
<L>And &thorn;enke vppon his passioun</L>
<L N="561">&THORN;at he hedde heer suffrande,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at he suffrede woundes fyue,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;e he ros from de&thorn;e to lyue</L>
<L N="564">And nou has heuene in hande.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;it schul &yogh;e preye for eny &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Bi-twene &thorn;e <I>sanctus</I> and &thorn;e sakeryng</L>
<L N="567">Til &thorn;at &thorn;e belle knelle.<NOTE PLACE="marg">The Mass-Book, v. 336-397, contains the prayer.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if eny mon ha&thorn; scorn to here hit,</L>
<L>Be my trou&thorn;e, wisdam weore hit</L>
<L N="570">&THORN;at he heolde him stille;</L>
<L>&THORN;e same mon &yogh;e lau&yogh;whe to scorn</L>
<L>Was of a Mayden in Bethleem born,</L>
<L N="573">Me &thorn;inke &yogh;e don ful ille.</L>
<L>Whose has hoker gas hame;</L>
<L>To telle hit &yogh;ou me &thorn;inkes no schame,</L>
<L N="576">I preue hit bi a Bille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Godes fflesch he reiseth o lofte</L>
<L>And his blod feir and softe</L>
<L N="579">In &thorn;e chalis wi&thorn;-Inne:</L>
<L>&THORN;en schul &yogh;e knele a-doun</L>
<L>And sey a luyte orisoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Mass-Book, v. 428-436.</NOTE></L>
<L N="582">ffor no &thorn;ing &thorn;at &yogh;e blynne.</L>
<L>God &thorn;at on &thorn;e Rode was slon,</L>
<L>&THORN;o two and he beo&thorn; bo&thorn;e on,</L>
<L N="585">&THORN;at dyed for al monnes synne.</L>
<L>After &thorn;e prest his Armes sprede&thorn; he,</L>
<L>In toknynge he dyed vppon &thorn;e tre</L>
<L N="588">ffor me and al mon-kunne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon &thorn;e pater noster is don,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Agnus dei he go&thorn; ful son&mdash;</L>
<L N="591">Herkne&thorn; hende in halle&mdash;</L>
<L>"Godes lomb" hit is to sei,</L>
<L>"&THORN;is worldes sinne to don a-wey<NOTE PLACE="marg">cf. Mass-Book, v. 516 ff.</NOTE></L>
<L N="594">And haue merci on vs alle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e same lomb hit is to minne,</L>
<L>To don a-wei &thorn;is worldes synne,</L>
<L N="597">To &thorn;e we crie and calle,
<PB REF="00000517.tif" N="509"></L>
<L>Ihesu, for &thorn;i miht and grace</L>
<L>A-bate vr synnes In vch a place,</L>
<L N="600">&THORN;i pes mot on vs falle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whon he ha&thorn; vsed, he walke&thorn; riht</L>
<L>To Lauatorie &thorn;er hit is diht,</L>
<L N="603">ffor to wassche his hende.</L>
<L>So gostly he comes a-geyn,</L>
<L>Vn-to god for to preyen</L>
<L N="606">Sum special grace hym sende,</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e folk &thorn;at &thorn;er wore</L>
<L>Whuch &thorn;at he ha&thorn; preyed fore</L>
<L N="609">&THORN;at a Masse may mende.</L>
<L>&THORN;en to knele hit is best,</L>
<L>Til hit cum to <I>Ite Missa est</I></L>
<L N="612">Be seid in to &thorn;e ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;enne schul &yogh;e knele a-doun</L>
<L>And sei a luytel Orisoun</L>
<L N="615">Riht on &thorn;is Maneere&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Orisoun is of seynt Ambrose,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he properly in prose</L>
<L N="618">Made in his preyere;</L>
<L>&THORN;en to preye is ful good tyme.</L>
<L>I con not wonder wel ryme</L>
<L N="621">On latin &yogh;ou to lere,</L>
<L>But no&thorn;eles I wol assay</L>
<L>As nei&yogh; &thorn;e text as euer I may&mdash;</L>
<L N="624">Herkne and &yogh;e may heere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"God &thorn;at di&yogh;ed vppon &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e prest receyuede bodile</L>
<L N="627">Vppon &thorn;e Auter-ston,</L>
<L>Graunt vs grace, whon we hennes go,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we may wor&thorn;ily don al so,</L>
<L N="630">In vre concience al-on.</L>
<L>After vr dedes &amp; we be demed,</L>
<L>ffrom his blisse we schal be flemed,</L>
<L N="633">Out of &thorn;at wor&thorn;li won.</L>
<L>God graunt vs grace In wille &amp; word</L>
<L>We may be wor&thorn;i to his bord,</L>
<L N="636">Vr lord leue vs &thorn;at lon."
<PB REF="00000518.tif" N="510"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;it prei vr ladi, as I ow telle,<MILESTONE N="303b:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e for&yogh;ete not &thorn;e god-spelle,</L>
<L N="639">ffor no &thorn;ing &thorn;at may bi-falle;</L>
<L>Tac a good entent &thorn;er-to:</L>
<L>Hit is &thorn;e <I>In principio</I></L>
<L N="642">On latin &thorn;at men calle.</L>
<L>A &yogh;er and fourti dayes atte lest</L>
<L>ffor <I>verbum caro factum est</I></L>
<L N="645">To pardoun haue &yogh;e schalle;</L>
<L>Mon or wommon schul haue &thorn;is</L>
<L>&THORN;at kneles doun &thorn;e eor&thorn;e to kis&mdash;</L>
<L N="648">ffor-&thorn;i &thorn;enk on hit alle!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now haue I endet so as is</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maner and &thorn;e Mede of &thorn;e Mes,</L>
<L N="651">&THORN;erof I am ful bli&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ne more &thorn;erof to mele wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>I haue seid as I cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="654">I &thorn;onke god fele si&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Of my trauayle is me nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Wolde &yogh;e &thorn;enke hit in &yogh;or &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="657">And in &thorn;e chirche hit ki&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;en were hit lykynge of &yogh;or mynde,</L>
<L>And gret cumfort to al Monkynde,</L>
<L N="660">Hose wol lusten and ly&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;it is &thorn;er &thorn;reo &thorn;inges on &thorn;e Bok,</L>
<L>Sikerly &thorn;at I out tok</L>
<L N="663">And neuer dar make in Mynde;</L>
<L>Hit was wel &thorn;ou&yogh;t at my likynge</L>
<L>I ches hit out bi heuene-kynge,</L>
<L N="666">&THORN;e to&thorn;er is &yogh;it bi-hynde.</L>
<L>But better &thorn;ing &thorn;en I haue told,</L>
<L>Herde &yogh;e neuere of &yogh;ong ne old,</L>
<L N="669">On ground &thorn;at men may fynde;</L>
<L>Saue fyue wordes, wi&thorn;-outen drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no mon but a prest schulde rede</L>
<L N="672">Is comen of cristen kynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God &thorn;at dy&yogh;ed vppon &thorn;e Roode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bou&yogh;t vs wi&thorn; his blessed blode</L>
<L N="675">Vp-on &thorn;e harde tre,
<PB REF="00000519.tif" N="511"></L>
<L>&YOGH;iue vs grace, bo&thorn;e more and lasse,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;e Masse</L>
<L N="678">Vr soules mai saued be.</L>
<L>ffader &amp; Sone and Holigost,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou art lord of mihtes most</L>
<L N="681">And sittes In Trinite,</L>
<L>Whon we schal dye, no lengor dwelle,</L>
<L>Kep vs from &thorn;e pyne of helle,</L>
<L N="684">AMEN ffor charite.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Then follows, fol. 303, &THORN;e guldene trental&mdash;Pope Gregory's, p. 260-7 above&mdash;repeated, with quite the same text.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="48" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[XLVIII. Savings of St. Bernard: Man's three foes.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">Title in Index: &THORN;at a man had &thorn;re enemys. The same poem is extant in MS. Laud 108 (together with the Vision of St. Paul), ed. by me in Herrig's Archiv 1874, and MS. Harl. 2253, fol. 106, ed. in Wright, Spec. of lyric poetry, p. 101.</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Her telle&yogh; seynt Bernard Mon ha&thorn; &thorn;reo enemys hard.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seint Bernard sei&thorn; in his Bok</L>
<L>&THORN;at Mon is worm &amp; wormes Cok,</L>
<L N="3">And wormes he schal feden;</L>
<L>Whon his lyf is him bi-reued,</L>
<L>In his Rug and in his heued</L>
<L N="6">Wol foule wormes breden.
<PB REF="00000520.tif" N="512"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fflesch schal melten from &thorn;e bon,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Senewes sundren euerichon,</L>
<L N="9">&THORN;e Bodi schal de-fyen;</L>
<L>And &yogh;e &thorn;at wolen &thorn;e so&thorn;e sen,</L>
<L>Vnder &thorn;e graues &thorn;er &thorn;ey ben,</L>
<L N="12">And loke&thorn; hou &thorn;ei ly&yogh;en.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;I fflesch fi&yogh;te&thorn; a&yogh;eyn &thorn;i gost.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou schalt dyen &thorn;ou hit nost,</L>
<L N="15">Whe&thorn;er day or niht;</L>
<L>Woltou niltou, &thorn;ou schalt dy&yogh;en,</L>
<L>Ne may no Raunsoun &thorn;e for-buy&yogh;en&mdash;</L>
<L N="18">&THORN;ou grei&thorn; &thorn;e whil &thorn;ou miht!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mon, &thorn;ou art of feble fom,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow ne hast her no siker hom,</L>
<L N="21">&YOGH;if &thorn;ow bi-seo &thorn;e ariht;</L>
<L>Vre riht wonynge were elles-where.</L>
<L>Lord let vs comen &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="24">ffor his muchele miht.
<PB REF="00000521.tif" N="513"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of feble fro&thorn;, Mon, is &thorn;i lyf,</L>
<L>Whon de&thorn; drawe&thorn; his kene knyf,</L>
<L N="27">I rede &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;e schryue;</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;if &thorn;ou be-seo &thorn;i-self a-riht,</L>
<L>ffinstou not her but flit &amp; fiht,</L>
<L N="30">Whiles &thorn;ou art in &thorn;is lyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vnstable is &thorn;i lyf I-diht,</L>
<L>Nou art &thorn;ou heuy, nou artou liht,</L>
<L N="33">Sturtynde as a Ro;</L>
<L>Nou &thorn;ou richest, &amp; now &thorn;ou porest,</L>
<L>Nou art &thorn;ou sek, now &thorn;ou rekeuerest,</L>
<L N="36">In wandre&thorn; and In wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;i fflesch sei&thorn; Niht and day</L>
<L>"I wole haue ese while I may,"</L>
<L N="39">&THORN;i soule sei&thorn; "nay,</L>
<L>Ac &yogh;if &thorn;ou bere hit to muchel me&thorn;,</L>
<L>Hit wol &thorn;e worchen soule de&thorn;</L>
<L N="42">And wo &thorn;at la[s]te&thorn; ay."
<PB REF="00000522.tif" N="514"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us striue&thorn; euer more &thorn;ei two,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on egge&thorn; to, &thorn;at o&thorn;ur fro,</L>
<L N="45">Ne conne &thorn;ei neuer blynne;</L>
<L>Ac, wel we mowen vs-seluen i-sen,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule ou&yogh;te Maister ben</L>
<L N="48">Al &thorn;e pris for to wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mon, I rede &thorn;at &thorn;ou be wys,</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou falle, sone arys,</L>
<L N="51">Ne ligge &thorn;ou none stounde.</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;if &thorn;ou worche wel wi&thorn; &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;e godspel sei&thorn;, and so&thorn; hit is,</L>
<L N="54">&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast blisse I-founde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mon, beo nou&yogh;t &thorn;i-self vn-cou&thorn;,</L>
<L>Ac loke what come&thorn; out at &thorn;i Mou&thorn;</L>
<L N="57">And elles-wher a-bouten;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou nyme rihtliche keep,</L>
<L>ffyndest &thorn;ou non so vyl donge-hep,</L>
<L N="60">Wi&thorn;-Innen no wi&thorn;-owten.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac &thorn;ou hast in &thorn;at vyle hous</L>
<L>A &thorn;ing &thorn;at is ful precious,</L>
<L N="63">And dere it was I-bouht;
<PB REF="00000523.tif" N="515"></L>
<L>Ac I &thorn;e holde for wylde and wood,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou &yogh;iue so muchel good</L>
<L N="66">To &thorn;e ffeond for nouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mon, &thorn;ou hast &thorn;reo lu&thorn;er fon,</L>
<L>Heore nomes con I wel vchon</L>
<L N="69">&YOGH;if I schal touchen alle:</L>
<L>&THORN;yn oune flesch, &thorn;e world, &thorn;e fend.</L>
<L>Ac he &thorn;at schulde best be &thorn;i frend</L>
<L N="72">Do&thorn; &thorn;e ra&thorn;est to falle,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;at is &thorn;i flesch, &thorn;i furste fo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou pamprest and seruest so,</L>
<L N="75">&YOGH;if ich hit dorste seyen.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou dost &thorn;i soule muche wrong,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou makest his fo so strong</L>
<L N="78">To fihten him a&yogh;eyn.
<PB REF="00000524.tif" N="516"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">From here MS. Vernon differs from the other MSS.</NOTE>Of &thorn;e furste fo so fel</L>
<L>Muche wonder hit is to tel,</L>
<L N="81">Hose schulde riht be-gynne:</L>
<L>&THORN;at such a foul stinkynde sek</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; such a bur&thorn;en in his nek</L>
<L N="84">Of serwe and of synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is Careyn &thorn;at &thorn;ou berest a-bouten,</L>
<L>So vyl wi&thorn;-Innen and wi&thorn;-outen,</L>
<L N="87">A luytel wormes mete;</L>
<L>Euer &thorn;e bet &thorn;at &thorn;ou him do,</L>
<L>Siker be &thorn;ou, euer-mo</L>
<L N="90">&THORN;e worse he wol &thorn;e gete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou &thorn;enke her-vppon</L>
<L>Hou vyl a vessel hit is on,</L>
<L N="93">ffor al &thorn;e metes and drynkes,</L>
<L>Hou hit schal foulore smelle &amp; smake</L>
<L>&THORN;en eny careyne &thorn;at is forsake</L>
<L N="96">Of best &thorn;at bre&thorn;e stinkes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor hose bi-heolde &thorn;i bodi ariht</L>
<L>After &thorn;i de&thorn; a fourtene niht,</L>
<L N="99">Neore he &thorn;i frend neuer so good,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he nolde hi&yogh;en him away</L>
<L>And &thorn;ynken seuen &yogh;er of a day</L>
<L N="102">&THORN;at he bi &thorn;e stod.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;yn o&thorn;er fo Is a wonder &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&THORN;is world, wi&thorn; diuerse fondyng</L>
<L N="105">Tempte&thorn; &thorn;e more &amp; more;
<PB REF="00000525.tif" N="517"></L>
<L>ffals hit is and feir hit seme&thorn;,</L>
<L>And whon hit aller best &thorn;e qweme&thorn;,</L>
<L N="108">Hit greue&thorn; &thorn;e ful sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is ffo ha&thorn; so ablendet &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t nou&yogh;t bi-fore &thorn;e se</L>
<L N="111">How vyl &thorn;ou art and pore,</L>
<L>Hou bare in to &thorn;is world &thorn;ou come,</L>
<L>Ne hou bare &thorn;ou wendest home</L>
<L N="114">In to &thorn;i puttes ore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He schewe&thorn; &thorn;e wele &amp; worldes wynne</L>
<L>And dilyces so mony kinne,</L>
<L N="117">And egge&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;er-to;</L>
<L>He reue&thorn; &thorn;e mony a nihtes rest.</L>
<L>fforsake schuldestou such a gest</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at &thorn;e con seruen so.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor whon &thorn;ou hast gedred al &thorn;i pride,</L>
<L>Come&thorn; de&thorn; on &thorn;at o&thorn;er syde</L>
<L N="123">And reue&thorn; &thorn;e al I-feere.</L>
<L>And whon he ha&thorn; &thorn;e doun I-cast,</L>
<L>He wol deceyuen &thorn;e atte last,</L>
<L N="126">As hit &thorn;in neuer nere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac to &thorn;i put he wol &thorn;e leden,</L>
<L>And leue &thorn;e &thorn;ere wormes to feden&mdash;</L>
<L N="129">Loke whuch a seruise!</L>
<L>He serue&thorn; &thorn;e of &amp; of no more;</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;i lyue lustnest his lore,</L>
<L N="132">He quyte&thorn; &thorn;e on &thorn;is wyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ri&yogh;t so schaltou go &thorn;i wey</L>
<L>Naked and bare&mdash;weylawey!</L>
<L N="135">Wrecche, hou hastou sped!
<PB REF="00000526.tif" N="518"></L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou haue eny good wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>In word, in werk or in &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="138">&THORN;at berest &thorn;ou to &thorn;i bed.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E &thorn;ridde fo, I may &thorn;e telle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e foule fend of helle,</L>
<L N="141">&THORN;e worste fo of alle.</L>
<L>Vnderstonde, he loue&thorn; &thorn;e nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He wol chaungen al &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="144">And maken &thorn;e foule to falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vnderstonde, he nolde &thorn;e no good,</L>
<L>He wolde marren al &thorn;i mood&mdash;</L>
<L N="147">&THORN;ow war &thorn;e from his hok!</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou do as I &thorn;e seye,</L>
<L>Al his wrenches miht &thorn;ou leye</L>
<L N="150">Al mid his oune crok.<SUP>*</SUP>
<PB REF="00000528.tif" N="520"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;e fend &thorn;orw his fondyng</L>
<L>Or for defaute of wi&thorn;-stondyng</L>
<L N="153">In eny synne ha&thorn; &thorn;e cast,</L>
<L>A-Rys vp as a Champioun,</L>
<L>Stond stif and fal no more a-doun</L>
<L N="156">ffor such a wyndes blast.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ow go In to &thorn;e feire feld</L>
<L>And tak vr lord to &thorn;i scheld,</L>
<L N="159">&THORN;in hond &thorn;ou strecche and fonde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enk vppon him wi&thorn; mylde mod</L>
<L>&THORN;at for &thorn;e &yogh;af his herte-blod</L>
<L N="162">And get &thorn;at lyflich londe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ow take &thorn;e crois to &thorn;i staf</L>
<L>And &thorn;enk on him &thorn;at &thorn;eron &yogh;af</L>
<L N="165">His lyf &thorn;at was so lef;</L>
<L>Wite wel &thorn;i fot wi&thorn; staues ord</L>
<L>And mak &thorn;e traytur speke &thorn;e word</L>
<L N="168">And wrek &thorn;e on &thorn;at &thorn;ef.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffiht faste for &thorn;yn owne riht</L>
<L>And get &thorn;e heuene-blisse briht,</L>
<L N="171">While &thorn;ou hast tyme &thorn;er-to;</L>
<L>&THORN;in owne heritage hit is,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erof schaltou neuer mis</L>
<L N="174">But &yogh;if &thorn;ou hit fordo.
<PB REF="00000529.tif" N="521"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac &yogh;if &thorn;ow haue wel in muynde</L>
<L>Hou feble &thorn;at &thorn;ou art of kuynde,</L>
<L N="177">And hou &thorn;ou gost to nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Hit mihte wel &thorn;in herte whetten</L>
<L>And of fflesches lustes letten,</L>
<L N="180">Weore &thorn;ou wel bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Where ben heo &thorn;at bi-foren vs weren,</L>
<L>&THORN;at houndes ladden &amp; haukes beeren</L>
<L N="183">And hedden feld and wode;</L>
<L>&THORN;is Riche ladys in heore bour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wereden gold in heore tressour,</L>
<L N="186">Wi&thorn; heore brihte rode?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ei eeten and dronken &amp; maden hem glad,</L>
<L>In Ioye was al heore lyf I-lad,</L>
<L N="189">Men knelede hem bi-foren:</L>
<L>&THORN;ei beren hem here so stout and hi&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Ac in twynklyng of an ei&yogh;e</L>
<L N="192">Heore soules were for-loren.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wher is &thorn;at gomen and &thorn;at song,</L>
<L>&THORN;at traylyng &amp; &thorn;at comelich &yogh;ong,</L>
<L N="195">&THORN;o haukes and &thorn;e houndes?</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at Ioye is went a-wey,</L>
<L>Heore weole is comen to weilawei,</L>
<L N="198">To monye harde stoundes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heore paradys &thorn;ei hedden hyr,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. her</NOTE></L>
<L>And now &thorn;ei liggen in helle-fyr,<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. fer</NOTE></L>
<L N="201">&THORN;er pit and peyne is euere;</L>
<L>Strong is &thorn;ere in peyne and wo,</L>
<L>Ac hopen &thorn;ar hem neuer-mo,</L>
<L N="204">ffor out ne comen &thorn;ei neuere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas, &thorn;at &thorn;ei euere were boren or bred</L>
<L>&THORN;at heer on eor&thorn;e such lyf han led</L>
<L N="207">And deserued such meedes,</L>
<L>To brennen in &thorn;e fuir of helle,</L>
<L>Euer-more &thorn;er-Inne to dwelle</L>
<L N="210">And glowen in &thorn;o gledes!
<PB REF="00000530.tif" N="522"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac Moder &amp; Mayden, heuene-Qween,</L>
<L>As we hopen &thorn;at &thorn;ou wol ben</L>
<L N="213">Vr warant from &thorn;e fende:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou help vs dedly synne to fleen,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at we mote &thorn;i sone seen</L>
<L N="216">World wi&thorn;-outen ende. AMEN.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Then follows 'Kyng of Thars,' ed., with MS. Auchinl., in <I>Engl. Stud.</I></NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>MS. Laud 108, fol. 198 a.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HErkniez me a luytel &thorn;rowe,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at wollez ou-self i-knowe,</L>
<L N="3">Wise &thorn;ei &yogh;e beo:</L>
<L>Ichulle ou telle, ase ich can,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat holie writ spekz of Man,</L>
<L N="6">&YOGH;if &yogh;e wullez i-heore me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seint bernard seith in his bok</L>
<L>&THORN;at man is worm and wormes cok,</L>
<L N="9">For he schal wormes fede;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wan his lijf him is bi-reued,</L>
<L>In his rug and in his heued</L>
<L>Schullen grisliche wormes brede.
<PB REF="00000520.tif" N="512"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;i fleschs schal melte fram &thorn;e bon,</L>
<L>&THORN;i senues sundriez euerech-on,</L>
<L N="15">&THORN;i bodi schal al to-sie.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at wollez &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-seo,</L>
<L>Vndoz &thorn;e burieles &thorn;are hi beoz,</L>
<L N="18">And lokiez &yogh;wat &thorn;are lie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Man, &thorn;u art a feble fom;</L>
<L>Here nast &thorn;ou no siker hom,</L>
<L N="21">I segge it &thorn;e wel stille.</L>
<L>&THORN;i ri&yogh;hte hom is elles-&yogh;wer&mdash;</L>
<L>Ihesus us graunti to come &thorn;er,</L>
<L N="24">&YOGH;wan it is his wille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;i flesch stant a-&yogh;ein &thorn;i gost;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wanne &thorn;u schalt dei&yogh;e, &thorn;u it nost,</L>
<L N="27">No&thorn;ur day ne ny&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>Nedescostes &thorn;ou most dei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Ne may no raunchoun &thorn;e fur-buye&mdash;</L>
<L N="30">Striue &thorn;e &yogh;wile &thorn;ou mi&yogh;ht!
<PB REF="00000521.tif" N="513"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of feble wynd, man, is &thorn;i lijf,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wanne dez drawez is scharpe knyf,</L>
<L N="33">&THORN;ou do &thorn;e sone to schriue;</L>
<L>For, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou canst loken ari&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Ne hast &thorn;ou here bote fi&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;e &yogh;wile &thorn;ou ar aliue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nov &thorn;u art wrong, nov &thorn;u art ry&yogh;ht,<MILESTONE N="198b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Nou &thorn;ou art heuy, nou &thorn;u art ly&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="39">&THORN;ou lepest also a ro;</L>
<L>Nov &thorn;u art sik, nou &thorn;ou art coueret,</L>
<L>Nov &thorn;ou art riche, nou &thorn;u art pouere&mdash;</L>
<L N="42">Ne is &thorn;is muche wo?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;i flesch &thorn;e seith bo&thorn;e ni&yogh;ht and day:</L>
<L>"Ichulle habbe ayse &thorn;e &yogh;wile i may."</L>
<L N="45">&THORN;i soule seith a-&yogh;ein him "nay!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich am a&yogh;ein &thorn;e of muche meth,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou bringust me to helle to &thorn;e deth,</L>
<L N="48">And to wo &thorn;at lastez ay."
<PB REF="00000522.tif" N="514"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us it farez bi-twene heom to,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on seith "let," &thorn;at o&thorn;ur seith "do,"</L>
<L N="51">Ne connen huy neuere blinne.</L>
<L>Ake wel &yogh;e mouwen ov-self i-seo:</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule ou&yogh;hte maister to beo,</L>
<L N="54">&THORN;e maistrie for to winne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A, man, ne beo nou&yogh;ht &thorn;i-sulf vnkouth,</L>
<L>Loke &yogh;wat comez out of &thorn;i mouth,</L>
<L N="57">And elles-&yogh;ware with-oute.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt nime wel guod kepe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou ne findest bote a foul doung hepe,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;ei &thorn;ou loke &thorn;e al a-boute.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Man, &thorn;u hast in &thorn;i foule hous</L>
<L>A deorewor&thorn;e &thorn;ing and precious,</L>
<L N="63">And ful deore it was a-bou&yogh;ht.
<PB REF="00000523.tif" N="515"></L>
<L>Ich holde &thorn;e more &thorn;ane wod,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if [&thorn;ou] letest so muche guod</L>
<L N="66">&THORN;e feond habbe al for nou&yogh;ht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Man, beo &thorn;ou i-war and eke wys:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou doun fallest, sone aris,</L>
<L N="69">Ne lie &thorn;ou none stounde.</L>
<L>With al &thorn;i mi&yogh;ht &yogh;if &thorn;ou dost &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;i soule &thorn;e seyth, and soth it is,</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at blisse &thorn;ou hast i-founde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Man, &thorn;ou hauest &thorn;reo wicke fon.</L>
<L>Heore names i can nemme echon,</L>
<L N="75">&YOGH;if ich schal tellen hem alle:</L>
<L>&THORN;in owene flechs, &thorn;e world, &thorn;e feond.</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at best scholde beo &thorn;i freond,</L>
<L N="78">Maketh &thorn;e ra&thorn;est doun falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou clo&thorn;est him with fair[e] schroud,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou makest &thorn;i fo fat and proud,</L>
<L N="81">To fy&yogh;hte &thorn;e a-&yogh;ein;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou dost &thorn;i-sulf wel muche wronk:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou makest &thorn;i fo fat and strong,</L>
<L N="84">&YOGH;if ich it dorste seyen.
<PB REF="00000524.tif" N="516"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Man, do &thorn;u bi conseil and bi red</L>
<L>And with-drau&yogh; &thorn;ou him of is bred,</L>
<L N="87">And watur &yogh;if him to drinke;</L>
<L>Ne lat him no-&thorn;ing Idel gon,</L>
<L>Ake do him pines mani on,</L>
<L N="90">And ofte forto swynke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To coueitise of mani &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;e world &thorn;e drawez a misliking;</L>
<L N="93">A-&yogh;eynes &thorn;e more and more.
<PB REF="00000525.tif" N="517"></L>
<L>Fals he is and fayr he semez;</L>
<L>Alre best &yogh;wane he &thorn;e quemez,</L>
<L N="96">He &thorn;e bindez sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou wost &thorn;is world schal gon to nou&yogh;ht;</L>
<L>Ne hast &thorn;ou no &thorn;ing hidere i-brou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Ne nou&yogh;ht ne schalt bere with &thorn;e.</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;ou schalt al one gon &thorn;i wey,</L>
<L>With-outen stede and palefrey,</L>
<L N="102">With-oute gold and feo.
<PB REF="00000526.tif" N="518"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;i &thorn;ridde fo is &thorn;e foule wi&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fondeth bo&thorn;e day and ny&yogh;ht</L>
<L N="105">With his guyles alle.</L>
<L>Wel &thorn;ou wost he ne louez &thorn;e nou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>He fondez ay to chaungen &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="108">And makez &thorn;e forto falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou wost wel he nele &thorn;e no guod,</L>
<L>He wolde hauen &thorn;in herte-blod&mdash;</L>
<L N="111">Beo iwar of his hok!</L>
<L>Ake do ase ich &thorn;e habbe i-seid,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ine &thorn;reo fon wor&thorn;ez a-leyd</L>
<L N="114">With heore owene Crok.<SUP>*</SUP></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;u seist "&thorn;is spel is hard,</L>
<L>I ne may nou&yogh;ht holde &thorn;is foreward,</L>
<L N="117">Holde ne wel it dri&yogh;e,"</L>
<L>A luytel &thorn;ing ich axi &thorn;e&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seie it me par charite&mdash;</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at &thorn;ou me nou&yogh;ht ne lye!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;ware beoth nou &thorn;ei &thorn;at bi-fore us weren,</L>
<L>&THORN;at houndes ladden and hauekes beren</L>
<L N="123">And hadden field and wode?</L>
<L>&THORN;is riche leuedies in heore bour,</L>
<L>&THORN;et wereden gold on heore tressour,</L>
<L N="126">With heore bri&yogh;hte rode?
<PB REF="00000527.tif" N="519"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Huy eten and dronken and maden hem glad,</L>
<L>Here lyf was al in Ioye a-lad,</L>
<L N="129">Men knevleden hem bi-fore;</L>
<L>Huy beren heom here so swi&thorn;e hey&yogh;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;oru&yogh; twinklingues of heore ey&yogh;en</L>
<L N="132">Heore soules beon alle for-lore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;ware beoz &thorn;ulke &thorn;at cou&thorn;en so wel</L>
<L>With vnri&yogh;hte and wrongliche echdel</L>
<L N="135">Winne rentes and londes,</L>
<L>And nolden nou&yogh;ht here beon aknowe</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was unri&yogh;htfulliche heore owe,</L>
<L N="138">For &thorn;e worldes schonde?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ulke &thorn;at deiden on vr&thorn;e here</L>
<L>And wonnen ou&yogh;ht in swuch manere,</L>
<L N="141">Londes o&thorn;ur rente,</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e i segge it eou to-wisse,</L>
<L>Huy ne comiez neuere in heuene|b[l]isse,</L>
<L>Ake in helle huy schullen stunte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ei huy ligge sike longue</L>
<L>And in heore dez-bedde &thorn;ienchez "mid wronge</L>
<L N="147">To &thorn;ulke &thorn;ing we come,"</L>
<L>Fain huy wolden, hadden huy space,</L>
<L>Ake manie nabbez &thorn;er-to no grace,</L>
<L N="150">To &yogh;elden a-&yogh;ein eft-sone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;are seith &thorn;e bok a-pli&yogh;ht</L>
<L>&THORN;at eorl ne baroun cler[c] ne kny&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="153">Bacheler ne sweyn,</L>
<L>No&thorn;ing ne mouwe huy with onri&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is manere habbe no wi&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="156">Bote huy it &yogh;elden a&yogh;ein.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;ware is &thorn;is hoppingue and &thorn;is song,</L>
<L>&THORN;is ridingue and &thorn;is proute &yogh;ong,</L>
<L N="159">&THORN;is hauekes and &thorn;is houndes?</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at weole is went awey;</L>
<L>&THORN;at Joy&yogh;e is come to weilawey,</L>
<L N="162">And to mani harde stoundes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ole &thorn;ou, man, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>A luyte pine &thorn;at man &thorn;e bit;</L>
<L N="165">With-drau&yogh;h &thorn;ine ayses ofte.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &thorn;ine pines &thorn;e &thorn;inchen on-lede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;ench opon &thorn;e muchele mede:</L>
<L N="168">Hit schal &thorn;e liken softe.
<PB REF="00000528.tif" N="520"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;e feond, &thorn;at foule &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>With wicke roun o&thorn;ur vuel egging</L>
<L N="171">Hauez &thorn;e ene a-kast,</L>
<L>Op stond and beo guod Chaumpiun,</L>
<L>And ne fal &thorn;ou non more a-doun</L>
<L N="174">For a luytel blast.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou tak &thorn;e rode to &thorn;i staf,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enk on him &thorn;at &thorn;aron &yogh;af</L>
<L N="177">His lif &thorn;at was so leof;</L>
<L>He &yogh;af it for &thorn;e, &thorn;ou &yogh;eld it him;</L>
<L>A-&yogh;ein is fo a staf &thorn;u nim</L>
<L N="180">And awrek him on &thorn;at &thorn;eof!
<PB REF="00000530.tif" N="522"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Marie, moder, houene-quen,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou canst, and mi&yogh;ht, and owest to ben</L>
<L N="183">Ore help a&yogh;ein &thorn;e feonde:</L>
<L>Help us sunnes forto fleon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we moten &thorn;i sone i-seon</L>
<L N="186">In Joye with-outen ende. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>MS. Harl. 2253, fol. 106 a.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lustne&thorn; alle a lutel &thorn;rowe,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at wolle&thorn; ou-selue y-knowe,</L>
<L N="3">Vnwys &thorn;ah y be:</L>
<L>Ichulle telle ou ase y con</L>
<L>Hou holy wryt speke&thorn; of mon&mdash;</L>
<L N="6">Herkne&thorn; nou to me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e holy mon say&thorn; in is bok</L>
<L>&THORN;at mon is worm &amp; wormes kok,</L>
<L N="9">Ant wormes he shal vede;</L>
<L>When is lif is hym by-reued,</L>
<L>In is rug &amp; in ys heued</L>
<L N="12">He shal foule wormes brede.
<PB REF="00000520.tif" N="512"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fleyhs shal rotie from &thorn;e bon,</L>
<L>&THORN;e senewes vntuen eueruchon,</L>
<L N="15">&THORN;e body shal to-fye.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at wolle&thorn; &thorn;at so&thorn;e y-suen,</L>
<L>Vnder grases, &thorn;er hue buen,</L>
<L N="18">By-holde&thorn; whet &thorn;er lye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mon is mad of feble fom,</L>
<L>Ne ha&thorn; he no syker hom</L>
<L N="21">To stunte alle-wey stille;</L>
<L>Ys ryhte stude is elles-wher&mdash;</L>
<L>Ihesu, bring vs alle &thorn;er,</L>
<L N="24">&YOGH;ef hit be &thorn;y wille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fleysh stont a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e gost</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou shalt de&yogh;e, ner &thorn;ou nost,</L>
<L N="27">Nou&thorn;er day ne nyht;</L>
<L>On stede ne sitte &thorn;ou ner so he&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et a-last &thorn;ou shalt de&yogh;e&mdash;</L>
<L N="30">Grey&thorn; &thorn;e whil &thorn;ou myht.
<PB REF="00000521.tif" N="513"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In false wonyng is monnes lyf,</L>
<L>When de&thorn; drawe&thorn; is sharpe knyf,</L>
<L N="33">Do &thorn;e sone to shryue;</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;ef &thorn;ou const loke a-riht,</L>
<L>Nast &thorn;ou no&thorn;yng bote fyght</L>
<L N="36">Whil &thorn;ou art a-lyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou &thorn;ou hast wrong, &amp; nou ryht,</L>
<L>Nou &thorn;ou art heuy &amp; nou lyht,</L>
<L N="39">&THORN;ou lepest ase a roo;</L>
<L>Nou &thorn;ou art sekest &amp; nou holest,</L>
<L>Nou &thorn;ou art rychest &amp; nou porest&mdash;</L>
<L N="42">Nis &thorn;is muche woo?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;y fleysh ne swy[n]ke&thorn; nyht ne day,</L>
<L>Hit wol han eyse whil hit may,</L>
<L N="45">Ant &thorn;e soule say&thorn;: 'nay,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef ich &thorn;e buere to muche me&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wolt me bringe to helle-de&thorn;,</L>
<L N="48">Ant wo &thorn;at laste&thorn; ay."
<PB REF="00000522.tif" N="514"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us hit ge&thorn; bi-tuene hem tuo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on sai&thorn; "let," &thorn;at o&thorn;er sey&thorn; "do."</L>
<L N="51">Ne wune hue nout lynne;"</L>
<L>Wel we mowe alle y-se</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule shulde maister be,</L>
<L N="54">&THORN;e pris forte wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne be &thorn;e nout &thorn;i fleysh vncou&thorn;,</L>
<L>Loke whet come&thorn; out of &thorn;y mou&thorn;,</L>
<L N="57">And elles-wher wy&thorn;-oute;</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;ou nymest wel god keep,</L>
<L>Ne fyndest &thorn;ou non so fyl dung-heep,</L>
<L N="60">Ant &thorn;ou loke a-boute.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou &thorn;ou hast in &thorn;at foul hous</L>
<L>A &thorn;yng &thorn;at is ful precious,</L>
<L N="63">fful duere hit ys a-boht;
<PB REF="00000523.tif" N="515"></L>
<L>Icholde &thorn;e ful wilde &amp; wod,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;ou lesest so muche god,</L>
<L N="66">And &yogh;euest hit for noht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mon, be war &amp; eke wis</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;ou fallest, sone a-rys,</L>
<L N="69">Ne by &thorn;ou none stounde;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al &thorn;i myhte &thorn;ou do &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;y soule sih&thorn;, &amp; so&thorn; hit ys</L>
<L N="72">Blysse ichaue y-founde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mon, &thorn;ou hauest wicked fon,</L>
<L>&THORN;e alre-worst is &thorn;at on (!),</L>
<L N="75">Here nomes y shal telle;</L>
<L>&THORN;yn oune fleysh &thorn;y worst is fend (!);</L>
<L>&THORN;at best shulde be &thorn;y frend,</L>
<L N="78">&THORN;at most do&thorn; &thorn;e to quelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou clo&thorn;est him in feir[e] shroud,</L>
<L>Ant makest &thorn;y fomon fat &amp; proud,</L>
<L N="81">&YOGH;ef y durste seyn;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou dest &thorn;y-selue muche wrong,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou makest him bo fat &amp; strong,</L>
<L N="84">To fyhte &thorn;e a&yogh;eyn.
<PB REF="00000524.tif" N="516"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Do my counsail &amp; my reed:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-drah hym ofte of is breed,</L>
<L N="87">Ant &yogh;ef him water drynke;</L>
<L>Ne let hym no&thorn;ing ydel go,</L>
<L>Bote pyne do hym &amp; wo,</L>
<L N="90">Ant ofte let hym swynke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Coueytise of mony &thorn;yng</L>
<L>&THORN;e world &thorn;e bringe&thorn; in fleish lykyng,</L>
<L N="93">Ant &yogh;eue&thorn; &thorn;e more &amp; more;
<PB REF="00000525.tif" N="517"></L>
<L>ffals he is &amp; feyr he seme&thorn;,</L>
<L>Alre-best when he &thorn;e queme&thorn;</L>
<L N="96">He bynde&thorn; &thorn;e fol sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;enne shal he go to noht:</L>
<L>Nast &thorn;ou no&thorn;ing hyder y-broht,</L>
<L N="99">Ne nout shalt buere wy&thorn; &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt al one go &thorn;y wey,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-oute stede &amp; palefrey,</L>
<L N="102">Wi&thorn;-oute gold &amp; fee.
<PB REF="00000526.tif" N="518"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lucifer, &thorn;at foule wyht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wes him-selue so feyr &amp; bryht,</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;urh prude fel to helle;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; foule wille &amp; foul &thorn;oht</L>
<L>He fonde&thorn; bringe &thorn;e to noht,</L>
<L N="108">Ant &thorn;e forte quelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ench &thorn;at he &thorn;e nes nout god,</L>
<L>He wolde haue &thorn;yn huerte-blod&mdash;</L>
<L N="111">War &thorn;e for his hokes!</L>
<L>Do nou ase ichaue &thorn;e seyd,</L>
<L>Ant alle &thorn;re shule ben a-leyd</L>
<L N="114">Wi&thorn; huere foule crokes.<SUP>*</SUP></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;ou seist "my spel ys hard,"</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne miht &thorn;is foreward</L>
<L N="117">Holde ne dre&yogh;e,</L>
<L>A lutel &thorn;yng y aske &thorn;e&mdash;</L>
<L>Sey me so&thorn;, par charite,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;er-of &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne le&yogh;e!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wher be&thorn; hue &thorn;at by-foren vs were,</L>
<L>Lordes, ledyes, &thorn;at hauekes bere,</L>
<L N="123">Haden feld &amp; wode?</L>
<L>&THORN;e ryche ledies is huere bour</L>
<L>&THORN;at wereden gold on huere tressour,</L>
<L N="126">Wi&thorn; huere bryhte rode?
<PB REF="00000527.tif" N="519"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hue eten &amp; dronken &amp; maden huem glad,</L>
<L>Huere lyf al wi&thorn; ioie y-lad,</L>
<L N="129">Me knelede huem by-fore;</L>
<L>Hue beren huem so swy&thorn;e he&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And in a twynglyng of an e&yogh;e</L>
<L N="132">So hue weren for-lore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wher bue&thorn; hue, &thorn;y wedes longe?</L>
<L>&THORN;is muchele mur&thorn;e, ioie, &amp; songe?</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;is hauekes &amp; &thorn;is houndes?</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at weole is wend a-way,</L>
<L>Ant al is turnd to weylaway,</L>
<L N="138">To monye harde stoundes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Huere parais hue maden here</L>
<L>Ant nou hue ligge&thorn; in helle yfere,</L>
<L N="141">&THORN;at fur huem berne&thorn; euer;</L>
<L>Stronge y-pyne &amp; stronge in wo,</L>
<L>Longe is ay &amp; longe ys o,</L>
<L N="144">Out ne come&thorn; hue neuer.
<PB REF="00000528.tif" N="520"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;e feond, &thorn;e foule &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>&THORN;ourh wycked werk o&thorn;er eggyng</L>
<L N="147">A-doun ha&thorn; &thorn;e y-cast,</L>
<L>Vp, &amp; be god champioun,</L>
<L>Stond &amp; fal no more a-doun</L>
<L N="150">For a lutel blast,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tac &thorn;e rode to &thorn;y staf,</L>
<L>Ant &thorn;enke on him &thorn;at for &thorn;e &yogh;af</L>
<L N="153">His lyf &thorn;at was so luef;</L>
<L>He hit &yogh;ef, &thorn;ou &thorn;onke hym;</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;y fo such staf &thorn;ou nym,</L>
<L N="156">Ant wrek &thorn;e on &thorn;at &thorn;uef.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="49" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000530.tif" N="522">
<HEAD>[XLIX. Prouerbes of diuerse profetes and of poetes and of o&thorn;ur seyntes.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">So the title in Index. Similar collections of sayings of fam|ous men, in prose, are frequent in northern MSS. (f. i. Rawl. A, Bodl. 938). A collection, comprising all the sayings of 'Philo|sophers' under each name, is Caxton's 'Dictes and Sayings of the Philosophers,' fol. (1st ed. Westm., 1477, 2nd ed. Westm., 1480?, 3rd ed. Westm., 1490?&mdash;the 1st ed. being the 1st book printed in England; it was reproduced from Christie Miller's perfect copy by W. Blades, London 1877). These were originally compiled in Latin ab. 1350, and in 1410 translated into French by Guilleaume de Tignonville, from which version Earl Rivers made the English transl. ed. by Caxton: (it contains Sayings of Sedechias, Hermes, Tac, Zalquinus, Omer, Solon, Sabyon, Ypo|cras, Pitagoras, Dyogenes, Socrates, Platon, Aristotle, Alexander Tholome, Assaron, Legmon, Anese, Sacdarge, Thesille, S. Gre|gorie, Galyen). Lord Tollemache has a varying MS of the <I>Dictes.</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Cher amys, receuez de moy</I><MILESTONE N="cccvi" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L><I>Vn ben present ke vous enuoy,</I></L>
<L><I>Nunpas de or ne de Argent,</I></L>
<L><I>Mes de bon enseignement;</I></L>
<L N="5"><I>Ki en escripture ai troue</I></L>
<L><I>E de latin translate</I></L>
<L><I>En comun langage pur amis</I></L>
<L><I>Ke de clergie ne ount a-pris.</I></L>
<L><I>Trestut est sen e verite</I></L>
<L N="10"><I>Ke issi trouere&yogh; en Romaunce.</I>
<PB REF="00000531.tif" N="523"></L>
<L N="11"><I>Ki ben len entent e souent list,</I><MILESTONE N="307:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L><I>Prou en auera e delist;</I></L>
<L><I>Dount cely seit de dieu benet</I></L>
<L><I>Ki sa entente bien i mest.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>DAUID.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Inicium sapiencie timor domini.</HEAD>
<L N="15"><I>Li sages dit en soun lyuere</I></L>
<L><I>Ke comencement de bien viuere</I></L>
<L><I>Sour tote rien est de doter</I></L>
<L><I>Dampne dieu e honourer.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="15">&THORN;e wyse mon in his bok ha&thorn; &thorn;is seying</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e biginnyng of good liuyng</L>
<L>Ouer alle &thorn;ing is God to drede</L>
<L N="18">And him to worschupe wi&thorn; al vr spede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>In bonis sit cor tuum in diebus iuuentutis tue.</HEAD>
<L N="19"><I>Le Auctor dit ke vostre entente</I></L>
<L><I>Deue&yogh; mettre en ta iuuente</I></L>
<L><I>De tou&yogh;t pecches vous retrere,</I></L>
<L><I>E bones heueres</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">= oevres</NOTE> <I>vser e fere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="19">&THORN;is Auctor sei&thorn; verreyment</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;i &yogh;ou&thorn;e &thorn;ou schalt do &thorn;in entent</L>
<L>To wi&thorn;-drawe &thorn;e fro sinnes euer-mo,</L>
<L N="22">And goode werkes vse and do.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Audendo crescit virtus, tardando timor.</HEAD>
<L N="23">Cum <I>plus targe&thorn; de bien ouerer</I></L>
<L><I>Plus serre&yogh; pourous de comencer;</I></L>
<L><I>Par comencement vertu acrest,</I></L>
<L><I>E par targer retret est.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="23">&THORN;e lattor &thorn;ou art of good worching</L>
<L>&THORN;e more feruol &thorn;ou schalt be of bi-ginnyng;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;orw bi-ginnyng vertu encresce&thorn;,</L>
<L N="26">And &thorn;orw latschipe hit is wi&thorn;-drawe &amp; cese&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>ISAYAS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sola vexacio dabit intellectum.</HEAD>
<L N="27"><I>En trauaile mette&yogh; cors e quer</I></L>
<L><I>Pur la parole dieu oyer;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar par parole len quert sen,</I></L>
<L N="30"><I>E par sen se garde len.</I>
<PB REF="00000532.tif" N="524"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="27">In trauayle set bodi and herte i-fere</L>
<L>Godes word ay wel to here;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;orw word lernen wit men,</L>
<L N="30">And be wit Men kepen hem &thorn;en.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALAMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Qui odit correpcionem insipiens erit; melius est enim a sapiente corripi quam a stulto adulari.</HEAD>
<L N="31"><I>Si vous haye&yogh; de estre reprys,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne serre&yogh; iammes ben a-pris;</I></L>
<L><I>Meu&yogh; vaut tenson de veir disour</I></L>
<L><I>Ke deceyte de lonsengour.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="31">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou hate to be repreyuet auht,</L>
<L>Schalt &thorn;ou neuer be wel I-tauht;</L>
<L>Bettre is chidyng of a so&thorn; seyere</L>
<L N="34">&THORN;en deceyuyng of a losyngere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IEREMIAS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Confessori monstra delictum.</HEAD>
<L N="35"><I>Si vous aue&yogh; de ren mesfet</I></L>
<L><I>E puis defende&yogh; vostre fest,</I></L>
<L><I>Pluis est dieu de ceo greue</I></L>
<L><I>Ke eyn&yogh; ne fust del pecche.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="35">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou hast don a&yogh;eyn god auis</L>
<L>And after defendest hit I-wis,</L>
<L>God is more greuet of &thorn;at defendyng</L>
<L N="38">&THORN;en of &thorn;e furste sungyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IACOB.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Non est hic aliud nisi domus dei &amp; porta celi.</HEAD>
<L N="39"><I>Souent haunte&yogh; les mosters</I></L>
<L><I>E la dieu prie&yogh; volunters;</I></L>
<L><I>la porte de ciel oy nomer,</I></L>
<L><I>par ou vus couent le cel entrer.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="39">Ofte to churche loke &thorn;ow sterte</L>
<L>And prei &thorn;er to god wi&thorn; al &thorn;in herte;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;ate of heuene I haue herd hit cald,</L>
<L N="42">Be &thorn;e w&yogh;uche in to heuene entre &thorn;ou schalt</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALAMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vis habere imperium, impera tibi.</HEAD>
<L N="43"><I>Si vous desire&yogh; graunt honour,</I></L>
<L><I>Ieo vous fray Emperour:</I>
<PB REF="00000533.tif" N="525"></L>
<L><I>Emperour le dey nomer</I></L>
<L><I>Ki sei meymes set Iusticer.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="43">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou desyre gretliche honour,</L>
<L>I schal &thorn;e make an Emperour;</L>
<L>An Emperour I schal him calle</L>
<L N="46">&THORN;at con him-self Iustifie (!) ouer alle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Noli<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Volo</NOTE> auertere faciem tuam ab vllo paupere.</HEAD>
<L N="47"><I>Si vus desire&yogh; de dieu la grace,</I></L>
<L><I>De nuly poure turne&thorn; la face,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke dieu ne turne sa face de vous&mdash;</I></L>
<L><I>Si dit le sage a nous tous.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="47">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou desyre of god to haue grace,</L>
<L>ffrom no pore mon turne &thorn;i face,</L>
<L>Leste god turne his face from &thorn;e&mdash;</L>
<L N="50">&THORN;e wise mon teche&thorn; alle &thorn;us, parde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>TOBIAS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Si multum tibi fuerit, habundanter tribue.</HEAD>
<L N="51"><I>Si poy as, poy durras,</I></L>
<L><I>E durras mout si mout as;</I></L>
<L><I>Si rien ne as mout durras</I></L>
<L><I>Quaunt de doner la volunte as.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="51">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou haue luytel, luitel &yogh;iue and do;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou haue muchel, muche &yogh;iue also;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou haue nou&yogh;t, muche &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;iue</L>
<L N="54">And &thorn;i wille be to &yogh;iue &yogh;if &thorn;ou were I-&thorn;riue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>RAPHAEL.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Elemosina purgat peccata &amp; facit inueniri vitam eternam.</HEAD>
<L N="55"><I>Bon est estre augmoners;</I></L>
<L><I>Deu&yogh; bens est pur ce apparaylers</I>:</L>
<L><I>De ces pecches remissioun,</I></L>
<L><I>E vye perdurable en guerdoun.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="55">Hit is good to don almes-dede,</L>
<L>ffor twei godes ben ordeynt to &thorn;i mede:</L>
<L>On is of &thorn;i sunnes remission,</L>
<L N="58">&THORN;at to&thorn;ur euer-lastinge lyf to &thorn;i gerdon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Auarus nullis est bonus, in se pessimus.</HEAD>
<L N="59"><I>Mal est estre trop auers</I>,
<PB REF="00000534.tif" N="526"></L>
<L><I>Deu&yogh; mauls est pur ce aparrayles:</I></L>
<L><I>De sa malice longe record,</I></L>
<L><I>E peyne horible a-pres la mort.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="59">Hit is euel to ben auerous,</L>
<L>Tweyn euel &thorn;ingus &thorn;erfore ben ordeynt to vs:</L>
<L>Long record of &thorn;at malice,</L>
<L N="62">And horible peyne for suche vice.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Conscienciam pocius quam famam time; nullum magis time quam te ipsum: alium effugere potes, te ipsum numquam.</HEAD>
<L N="(63)"><I>Plus dote&yogh; ta conscience</I></L>
<L><I>Ke de nul autre la presence;</I></L>
<L><I>Ta conscience ne eschapere&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Autri presence bien porre&yogh;.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="63">Loke &thorn;ou doute more &thorn;i concience</L>
<L>&THORN;en o&thorn;er mennes presence;</L>
<L>&THORN;in oune concience mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou not skap,</L>
<L N="66">O&thorn;ur mennes presence &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t in hap.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Non viuas aliter in solitudine quam in foro.</HEAD>
<L N="(67)"><I>Vse&yogh; de fere priuement</I></L>
<L>Cum <I>fere vole&yogh; de-vaunt la gent,</I></L>
<L><I>Ou par cas vous eschapera</I></L>
<L><I>ffet ou dit ke mes auendra.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="67">Vse &thorn;e to do priueliche</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou wolt do to-fore men openliche,</L>
<L>Or elles paraunter &thorn;e may askap</L>
<L N="70">Word or dede or sum mis hap.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quid communicabit cacabus ad ollam.</HEAD>
<L N="(71)"><I>Ne vous bote&yogh; trop auaunt</I></L>
<L><I>De quere greuaunce al puissaunt;</I></L>
<L><I>Rien ne vaut au pot de tere</I></L>
<L><I>Countre le Caudron tener guere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="71">Put &thorn;e not to ferfor&thorn;, I rede now,</L>
<L>To greue him &thorn;at is mihtyore &thorn;en &thorn;ow;</L>
<L>Hit nis not wor&thorn; an old Botoun</L>
<L N="74">An eor&thorn;ene pot to fihte wi&thorn; a Caudroun.
<PB REF="00000535.tif" N="527"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SERAFYN.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pondus super se tollit qui diciori se socius fuerit.</HEAD>
<L N="(75)"><I>Ne trop ne quere&yogh; especiaute</I></L>
<L><I>De homme ki est en dignete;</I></L>
<L><I>Vos beaus presens receiuera,</I></L>
<L><I>Si rien ne ly done&yogh; il vous greuera,</I></L>
<L><I>Si poure deuene&yogh; il vous mokera</I>&mdash;</L>
<L N="(80)"><I>De autre bounte ne espere&yogh; ia.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="75">Drau&yogh; vppon &thorn;e no specialte</L>
<L>Of Mon &thorn;at is of gret dignite;</L>
<L>&THORN;i feire presentes he wole receue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou &yogh;iue nou&yogh;t he wole &thorn;e greue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou waxe pore he wol skorne &thorn;e&mdash;</L>
<L N="80">Wayte of him neuere o&thorn;er bounte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Melius est vicinus iuxta quam f[r]ater procul.</HEAD>
<L N="(81)"><I>De vostre veisyn pres de vous</I></L>
<L><I>Seye&yogh; tendre e gelous;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar meu&yogh; vaut bon veisyn</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ne fet frere loyn&yogh; tayn.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="81">Of &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebor &thorn;at nei&yogh; is to &thorn;e</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou tendre and haue him in cherte;</L>
<L>ffor bettre is a nei&yogh;ebore nei&yogh;e</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;en a bro&thorn;ur fer fro &thorn;in ei&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Acceptum beneficium eterne memorie est inserendum.</HEAD>
<L N="(85)"><I>Ne mete&yogh; iammes en obly</I></L>
<L><I>Vn bien-fet de vostre amy;</I></L>
<L><I>En quer vus soit tut-Iours tenu</I></L>
<L><I>Le bien ke aue&yogh; vne fe&yogh; receu.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">ffor-&yogh;ete &thorn;ou neuere out of &thorn;i mynde</L>
<L>A benfet don of &thorn;i frende;</L>
<L>In herte loke &thorn;ou holde stedefast</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;e benfet &thorn;at &thorn;ou ones hast.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SERAFYN.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stude meditari, si bene velis fari.</HEAD>
<L N="(89)"><I>Si vne pense vous saut enquer,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne seye&yogh; pas primesauter</I>
<PB REF="00000536.tif" N="528"></L>
<L><I>De fere ou dyre ceke pense&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>De-vaunt ceke vus seie&yogh; bien auyse&yogh;</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="89">&YOGH;if in &thorn;in herte falle a &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To hasti loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou be nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>To do o&thorn;er speke &thorn;in entent,</L>
<L N="92">Til &thorn;ou haue take good auysement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ne petas quod negaturus es, Nec neges quod petiturus es.</HEAD>
<L N="(93)"><I>Ne prie&yogh;</I> iammes <I>a vostre amy</I></L>
<L><I>Chose ke vous ne fre&yogh; a ly;</I></L>
<L><I>Ne vous ne deue&yogh; pas nyer</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. vyer</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Ce ke est a demaunder.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="93">Prei not &thorn;i frend to bisilye</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou woldes him denye;</L>
<L>Ne denye &thorn;ou not &thorn;at is asked &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="96">&YOGH;if hit be couenable asked to be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Qui beneficium dare nescit in-iuste petit.</HEAD>
<L N="(97)"><I>Ki mout ad e rien ne doyne,</I></L>
<L><I>Pur demaunder mot ne soyne;</I></L>
<L><I>En demaundaunt quert hountage</I></L>
<L><I>Ki ne fet a autres nuil auauntage.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="97">Hose ha&thorn; muche and nul not &yogh;iue,</L>
<L>Ou&yogh;t to aske he nis not &thorn;riue;</L>
<L>In his askyng he gete&thorn; hountage</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;at to non o&thorn;ur wole do auauntage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Beneficium accipere est libertatem vendere.</HEAD>
<L N="(101)"><I>Cil est franc pur fere dreyt</I></L>
<L><I>Ki doun ne present ne receyt;</I></L>
<L><I>Ky doun receit san&yogh; soun desert,</I></L>
<L><I>Sa fraunchise vent e pert.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="101">ffreo he is to do men riht</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;ift ne present take&thorn; of no wiht;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at &yogh;iftes [take&thorn;] wi&thorn;-outen decert,</L>
<L N="104">His freodam he sulle&thorn; &amp; leose&thorn; apert.
<PB REF="00000537.tif" N="529"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Multi quasi inuencionem estimant fenus et prestiterunt molestiam hijs qui se adiuuerunt; dum accipiunt manus osculantur, &amp; in tempore redicionis loquntur verba tedij.</HEAD>
<L N="105"><I>Perne&yogh; garde en vostre a-prest</I></L>
<L><I>A ky vous preste&yogh; queus il est;</I></L>
<L><I>Tels se fet auant amy</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Thus far the poem is in the Simeon MS.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Ki par toun prest tei ert enemy.</I></L>
<L><I>Quant il receyt yl beise ta meyn,</I></L>
<L><I>Quant rendre deit tei apele vileyn,</I></L>
<L><I>E vo&yogh; rent pur vos ben-fe&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Vile represes alautre me&yogh;.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="105">Whon &thorn;ou lenest &thorn;i &thorn;ing, tak hede of &thorn;is</L>
<L>To whom &thorn;ou lenest and what he is;</L>
<L>Such mon to-fore schewe&thorn; him &thorn;i frende,</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at schal be &thorn;in enemy at &thorn;e ende;</L>
<L>Whon he receyue&thorn; he wol cusse &thorn;in honde,</L>
<L>Whon he schulde paie he wol cal &thorn;e cherl bonde;</L>
<L>He wol &thorn;e &yogh;elde for &thorn;i gode dede</L>
<L N="112">ffoul repreyuynge to &thorn;i mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Amici quidem graues sunt, inimici leues.</HEAD>
<L N="113"><I>Vous poye&yogh; auer tel amy</I></L>
<L><I>Ke plus vou&yogh; vaudreit vn enemy;</I></L>
<L><I>De vo&yogh; deuers lun nad cure,</I></L>
<L><I>Lautre ne seit poynt de mesure</I></L>
<L><I>De a-prompter ne de venir,</I></L>
<L><I>De soiourner a soun pleiser;</I></L>
<L><I>Dount plus vous greuera tel ameste</I></L>
<L N="120"><I>Ke de lautre le enemiste.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="113">Such a frend &thorn;ou miht haue sikerli</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou were bettre haue an enemy;</L>
<L>&THORN;at on of &thorn;i moneye ha&thorn; hede ne cure,</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;at o&thorn;ur na&thorn; wi&thorn; hym no mesure</L>
<L>To Borwe of &thorn;e ne of ofte comyng</L>
<L>Ne to soiourne at his likyng.</L>
<L>Such frendschupe &thorn;e greue schal more parde</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;en &thorn;at o&thorn;eres enemi&yogh;te.
<PB REF="00000538.tif" N="530"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SAULUS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Admone illos non litigiosos esse, set mansuetos ad omnes.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si vous aue&yogh; vos seruauns</I></L>
<L><I>Ki vous sount contrariauns,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne les tense&yogh; pas souent&mdash;</I></L>
<L><I>Seint Eglise le defent;&mdash;</I></L>
<L><I>Mes ki ne cert a soun auenaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>Prenge conge e vous auaunt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SAMUEL.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Loquere domine quia audit seruus tuus.</HEAD>
<L N="121"><I>Mout est li seruaunt de mal escole</I></L>
<L><I>Ki soffri ne peut la parole</I></L>
<L><I>Soun seignour a ky il sert,</I></L>
<L>Quant <I>par sa parole rien ne pert.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="121">He is vuel wor&thorn;i Clo&thorn; or bord</L>
<L>&THORN;at may not suffre a luytel word</L>
<L>Of his lord &thorn;at he serue&thorn; to,</L>
<L N="124">Whon for such a word leose&thorn; neuur &thorn;e mo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SERAFYN.</HEAD>
<HEAD>A &yogh;elantibus te absconde consilium.</HEAD>
<L N="125"><I>Ne moustre&yogh; pas tut vostre quer</I></L>
<L><I>A vostre seruaunt; kar de leger</I></L>
<L><I>Ky ore est prest, ert loyns de vous;</I></L>
<L><I>Ke auaunt set vn, donke sauerunt tous.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="125">Schewe not &thorn;in herte outerliche</L>
<L>To &thorn;i seruaunt. for-whi lihtliche</L>
<L>To-day he is wi&thorn; &thorn;e, to-morwe he flit;</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;at tofore wuste but on, &thorn;en moni schul wit.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quod uis esse tacitum nemini dixeris.</HEAD>
<L N="129"><I>Si vus blame&yogh; petit ou graunt</I></L>
<L><I>Ki vostre conseil est mys auaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>Ki ne blame&yogh; vous vostre quer,</I></L>
<L><I>Ki vostre counseil ne set celer.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="129">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou blame luitel or muche</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;i counseil is outet openliche,</L>
<L>Blame &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t &thorn;in oune herte wel,</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;at cou&thorn;e not hele &thorn;in oune counseil.
<PB REF="00000539.tif" N="531"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sicut sagitta in femore canis, sic verbum in corde stulti.</HEAD>
<L N="133"><I>Sete e counseil a-cordent bien</I></L>
<L><I>En quer de fol e en quise de chen;</I></L>
<L><I>Leun e lautre fount courte soiour,</I></L>
<L><I>Par bouche pasent saun&yogh; restour.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="133">An arwe in an houndes buttoke</L>
<L>And counseil in a foles herte istoke</L>
<L>A-corde&thorn; wel, for nou&thorn;ur make&thorn; soiourning;</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;orw mou&thorn; &thorn;ei passen wi&thorn;-outen restreyning.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IOB.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Noli de seruis querelam facientibus credere priusquam facti veritas aperte discernatur.</HEAD>
<L N="137"><I>Si vous oye&yogh; encusement</I></L>
<L><I>De akun de vostre gent,</I></L>
<L><I>En quere&yogh; prymes la verite,</I></L>
<L><I>De-vaunt ke en seye&yogh; trop greue.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="137">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou here eni accusacioun</L>
<L>Of eni of &thorn;y peple in feld or toun,</L>
<L>Enquere furst &thorn;erof &thorn;e verite</L>
<L N="140">Or &thorn;ou &thorn;erfore in herte greue &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>AUGUSTINU[S].</HEAD>
<HEAD>Qui enim credit verba loquencium, cum ceteri per risus gaudent decorem, per doloris cruciabitur merorem.</HEAD>
<L N="141"><I>Souent auent de meynte bon fet</I></L>
<L><I>Par medisaun&yogh; bestorne est;</I></L>
<L><I>Kyke tut creyt quant-ke homme li dist,</I></L>
<L><I>Il ert mourne&yogh; quant autre rist.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="141">Ofte hit falle&thorn; &thorn;at mony good ded</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; euel-siggers is ouer-torned;</L>
<L>Hose leeue&thorn; vche monnes seying,</L>
<L N="144">Whon o&thorn;ur lau&yogh;when, he schal make murning.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IEREMIAS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Erubescere nescierunt, propterea cadent inter ruentes.</HEAD>
<L N="145"><I>Si vous perde&yogh; curtesye [&amp;] bounte,</I></L>
<L><I>Vous cheyere&yogh; tut en vyle hounte;</I></L>
<L><I>Hounte, curteisye e seyntete</I></L>
<L><I>Par a-cord sount freres iure.</I>
<PB REF="00000540.tif" N="532"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou lese curtesye and bounte</L>
<L>To falle in foul schame hit bi-houe&thorn; &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Good schame, holynesse, &amp; curtesye</L>
<L N="148">As Bre&thorn;uren ben sworen, witterlye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Enormiter petit qui se beneficium dedisse dicit.</HEAD>
<L N="149"><I>Vileynement quert il louer</I></L>
<L><I>Ky sei auaunte de soun doner;</I></L>
<L><I>Ky a prodomme doyne doun,</I></L>
<L><I>Asse&yogh; receyt saun&yogh; autre guerdoun.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="149">In foul maner he aske&thorn; a louwaunce</L>
<L>&THORN;at of his &yogh;ifte make&thorn; bobaunce;</L>
<L>Hose &yogh;iue&thorn; a &yogh;ift to a good man,</L>
<L N="152">I-nouh he take&thorn; wi&thorn;-oute reward &thorn;an.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IPOCRAS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cui non videtur bona sua esse amplissima, miser est, quamuis sit dominus tocius mundi.</HEAD>
<L N="153"><I>Yl est bien cheytif apele&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Ky se pleynt e ad a-se&yogh;:</I></L>
<L><I>Mes ky tut le mond fust le suen,</I></L>
<L><I>Yl vus dirroyt ki il nust ren.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="153">A wrecche forso&thorn;e me may hym cal</L>
<L>&THORN;at pleyne&thorn; him and ha&thorn; i-nou&yogh; at al;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh; al &thorn;e world were only his,</L>
<L N="156">He wolde seie he hedde nou&yogh;t, i-wis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SERAFYN.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Non credas inimico tuo in eternum, &amp; si inimicus tuus uadat tibi obuiam, firma animum tuum &amp; custodi te ab illo.</HEAD>
<L N="157"><I>Vostre enymi ne creie&yogh; ia</I></L>
<L><I>De nuyl ren ke il vous dirra;</I></L>
<L><I>Cum plus vus mostre bien sembla[n]t,</I></L>
<L><I>Plus dote&yogh; le fet suaunt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="157">Leef neuer &thorn;in enemi, ho-so hit be,</L>
<L>Of no &thorn;ing &thorn;at he speke&thorn; to &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Whon he &thorn;e make&thorn; fe[i]rest spekyng</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;en drede &thorn;ou most his dedes suwyng.
<PB REF="00000541.tif" N="533"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>ffrequencia peragit deesse locum remedio dum vicia mores sunt.</HEAD>
<L N="161"><I>Si vous bye&yogh; de estre prodomme,</I></L>
<L><I>Retree&yogh; vus de mal custume;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar par custume de mes-fere</I></L>
<L><I>Maueyse tecche comense plere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="161">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou caste &thorn;e good mon to be,</L>
<L>ffrom euel custom euer drawe &thorn;e;</L>
<L>ffor bi wone of vuel doyng</L>
<L>Vuel tecches turne&thorn; in to plesyng;</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;ing plese&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou scholdest hat,</L>
<L N="166">Better &thorn;e hedde ben to-fore forsaken &thorn;at.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Honor est homini cum separat se a contencionibus, stulti autem miscentur contumelijs.</HEAD>
<L N="167"><I>Mout est honeste vileynye</I></L>
<L><I>Estre vencu en tenserye,</I></L>
<L><I>E mout est vileyne curteysye</I></L>
<L><I>Empromter de ylek la Mestrye.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="167">Hit is a wel honeste vileynye</L>
<L>In chydyng to be ouercomen, sikerlye,</L>
<L>But hit is a vileyn curtesye</L>
<L N="170">&THORN;erof to bere a-wey &thorn;e maystrie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cum inferiori contendere sordidum est, cum superiori furiosum.</HEAD>
<L N="171"><I>Si vous tense&yogh; vostre soget,</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo est graunt vileynye e led;</I></L>
<L><I>Si vous tense&yogh; ton cumpaynon,</I></L>
<L><I>Par tant fre&yogh; discencion;</I></L>
<L><I>Si vous tense&yogh; ton souereyn,</I></L>
<L><I>Se est deuerye tut pleyn.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="171">&YOGH;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou chyde &thorn;i soget,</L>
<L>Hit is to &thorn;e vileynye gret;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;i felawe &yogh;if &thorn;ou chyde,</L>
<L>Discencion &thorn;ou schalt make &thorn;at tyde;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou chyde &thorn;i souereyn,</L>
<L N="176">Men mow seye &thorn;ou art wod, certeyn.
<PB REF="00000542.tif" N="534"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SERAFYN.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Risus dencium &amp; incessus hominis enunciant de illo.</HEAD>
<L N="177"><I>Seye&yogh; tu&yogh; iours de beau semblaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>Me&yogh; ne mye trop haut ryaunt;</I></L>
<L><I>Ly fous est conu par sa rise,</I></L>
<L><I>E ly sages par sa meurte.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="177">Loke &thorn;ou euere be of feir chere,</L>
<L>Lauhwe not to muche as nyce of geere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fol is knowen bi his lauhwhing,</L>
<L N="180">And &thorn;e wyse bi his sad beryng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Remedium iniurie est obliuio, ingenuitas non recipit contumeliam.</HEAD>
<L N="181"><I>Si nully fous vous sourdye,</I></L>
<L><I>Vous ne aue&yogh; meyllour remedye</I></L>
<L><I>Ke de mettre en oblyaunce</I></L>
<L><I>Les soties de sa parlaunce;</I></L>
<L N="185"><I>Kar si vous vole&yogh; mettere a uoyr</I></L>
<L><I>Au Matin ceoke yl dist al seir,</I></L>
<L><I>Vous procure&yogh; par tel espreue</I></L>
<L><I>A vous meymes hounte neue.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="181">&YOGH;if a fol speke to &thorn;e vilenye,</L>
<L>&THORN;en is &thorn;e beste remedye</L>
<L>ffor to for&yogh;ete alle-maner wreche</L>
<L N="184">Of &thorn;e folyes of his speche;</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;if &thorn;ou woldest hit putte to so&thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;at he seyde ouur ni&yogh;t vppon &thorn;e morwening,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mi&yogh;test procure wi&thorn; such prouyng</L>
<L N="188">To &thorn;i-self newe schamyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>ECCLESIASTES.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Melior est canis viuus leone mortuo.</HEAD>
<L N="189"><I>Meu&yogh; vaut vn chyen seyn e fort</I></L>
<L><I>Ke vn leon tut freyt mort,</I></L>
<L><I>E meu&yogh; vaut pouerte od bounte</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ne fet richesse od maueysete.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="189">Better is a quik and an hol hounde</L>
<L>&THORN;en a ded lyon liggyng on grounde,</L>
<L>And better is pouert wi&thorn; godnes</L>
<L N="192">&THORN;en richesse wi&thorn; wikkednes.
<PB REF="00000543.tif" N="535"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Melius est vocari ad olera cum caritate quam ad vitulum saginatum cum odio.</HEAD>
<L N="193"><I>Meu&yogh; vaut potage saun&yogh; autre mes</I></L>
<L><I>Od charite e od bone pes,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke graunt delyces od tensoun&mdash;</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo dist ly sages en sa resoun.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="193">Bettre is potage wi&thorn;-outen o&thorn;ur mes</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; charite and good[e] pes,</L>
<L>&THORN;en mony delyces wi&thorn; chydyng&mdash;</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;is is &thorn;e wyse monnes seying.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>ECCLESIASTES.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Melius est ire ad domum luctus quam ad domum conuiuij.</HEAD>
<L N="197"><I>Meu&yogh; vaudreit ver homme mort</I></L>
<L><I>Ke noble feste de Iolyf port;</I></L>
<L><I>Le vn vus presente vostre fyn,</I></L>
<L><I>Le autre vous fest a folye enclyn.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="197">Bettre hit were a ded mon to se</L>
<L>&THORN;en a feste of gret noblete;</L>
<L>&THORN;at on presente&thorn; &thorn;i laste dawe,</L>
<L N="200">&THORN;at o&thorn;er &thorn;e make&thorn; to folye drawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Optimum est obliuisci quod non potest recuperari, &amp; sine murmure pati quod non potest emendari.</HEAD>
<L N="201"><I>Graunt sen est de oblyer</I></L>
<L><I>Chose perdu saun&yogh; recouerer,</I></L>
<L><I>E de soffrer saun&yogh; groundiler</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo ke vous ne poyes amender.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="201">Hit is wisdam to putte in for&yogh;etyng</L>
<L>&THORN;ing &thorn;at is lost wi&thorn;-outen rekeueryng,</L>
<L>And to suffre not grucchinde</L>
<L N="204">&THORN;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t not amende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>RUBEN.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Puer non comparet &amp; ego quo ibo? puer, id est inno|cencia, non comparet.</HEAD>
<L N="205"><I>Les fous se pleynent de lour estat,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke il par tut sount greue&yogh; e mat;</I>
<PB REF="00000544.tif" N="536"></L>
<L><I>Quident bien fere de chaunger luy</I></L>
<L><I>E par tut treuen[t] ennuy.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="205">ffoles playnen hem of here astat,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei ben greuet and al mat;</L>
<L>Hit to chaunge &thorn;ei wene be wel,</L>
<L N="208">After is a-nuy eueridel.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>ECCLESIASTES.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Omnis animus deponendus est, non ante placebit tibi vllus locus.</HEAD>
<L N="209"><I>Ky male tecche en ly a,</I></L>
<L><I>Chaunger lu ne ly vaudra ia;</I></L>
<L><I>Sa vye amende e ly vaudra</I></L>
<L><I>En checun lu la ou il demora.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="209">&THORN;at in him-self ha&thorn; eny chalaunge,</L>
<L>Hit nul not profyte ofte to chaunge;</L>
<L>Amende &thorn;i lyf &amp; profyte hit wole wel,</L>
<L N="212">ffor in eueri place &thorn;en &thorn;ou may&yogh;t dwel.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SERAFYN.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Non des filio nec fratri tuo potestatem super te in vita tua; nec des alijs possessionem tuam, ne forte peniteat te.</HEAD>
<L N="213"><I>Taunt cum poye&yogh; aleyne trere,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne vus demette&yogh; de vostre tere,</I></L>
<L><I>Pur vous mettre en autri garde;</I></L>
<L><I>Meu&yogh; vaut ke toun fi&yogh; seit garde</I></L>
<L><I>Ke vus seye&yogh; en soun daunger,</I></L>
<L><I>A ky vous solye&yogh; comaunder.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="213">As longe as &thorn;ou may&yogh;t holde in honde,</L>
<L>Dismette &thorn;e nou&yogh;t of &thorn;i londe</L>
<L>To ben o&thorn;ur mennes vnderlyng;</L>
<L>Hit is better hit be in &thorn;in owne kepyng</L>
<L>&THORN;en to ben in his daunger</L>
<L N="218">Whom &thorn;ou were wont bidde go fer or ner.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Non propter amorem fac tibi executorem heredem essendum nec medicum viuendum.</HEAD>
<L N="219"><I>Ne fete&yogh; ia pur nuyl amour</I></L>
<L><I>De vostre heyr executour,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne vostre heyr ficiscien,</I></L>
<L><I>En esperaunce de viuere seyn.</I>
<PB REF="00000545.tif" N="537"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="219">ffor loue ne nou&thorn;er for honour</L>
<L>Mak not &thorn;in heir &thorn;in executour,</L>
<L>Ne mak &thorn;in heir no ficiscian,<NOTE PLACE="marg">orig. ficiscien, as on p. 538.</NOTE></L>
<L N="222">In hope to liue euer hol man.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SAMPSON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Abij in terram philistini, videns-que mulierem hanc assumpsi michi, quia placuit oculis meis.</HEAD>
<L N="223"><I>Sy vous byes femme prendre,</I></L>
<L><I>Nest pas bon loyns enprendre,</I></L>
<L><I>De prendre femme desconue</I></L>
<L><I>Ne tou&yogh;t a-fermer a la premere vue.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="223">&YOGH;if &thorn;ow &thorn;enke a wyf to take,</L>
<L>Of ferre cuntre wommon forsake;</L>
<L>An vnknowen to take anon-riht</L>
<L N="226">Is nou&yogh;t to Aferme at &thorn;e furste siht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Non sis &yogh;elotes, hoc est dictu: non &yogh;eles mulierem sinus tui.</HEAD>
<L N="227"><I>Si vous aue&yogh; femme bele</I></L>
<L><I>E la desire&yogh;</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">orig. disire&yogh;</NOTE> <I>auer lele,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne la reproue&yogh; de cumpaygnye</I></L>
<L><I>De nul autre par gelosye;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar vous la fre&yogh; partaunt amer</I></L>
<L><I>Cely ke auaunt ne voit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. vout</NOTE> <I>regarder.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="227">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou haue a feir wyf</L>
<L>And wolt &thorn;at heo be trewe of lyf,</L>
<L>Repreue hire for no Cumpaygnye</L>
<L>Of no mon for gelesye;</L>
<L>Him to loue so &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t make hire bolde</L>
<L N="232">On whom to-fore heo nolde be-holde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SYRAC.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Qui parcit virge, odit filium; si non percusserit eum virga, morietur.</HEAD>
<L N="233"><I>Si vus ame&yogh; vostre enfaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>A-se&yogh; ly done&yogh; de verge silaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>E ly fre&yogh; conquere los</I></L>
<L><I>Saun&yogh; de bruser en ly nul os.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="233">&YOGH;if &thorn;i child be not a-fert,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if him i-nouh of &thorn;e &yogh;erd;
<PB REF="00000546.tif" N="538"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt him so make a good mon</L>
<L N="236">Wi&thorn;-outen brekynge of eny bon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SYRAK.</HEAD>
<HEAD>ffilie tibi sunt : serua corpus earum &amp; ne ostendas hila|rem faciem ad illas.</HEAD>
<L N="237"><I>Ne mustre&yogh; pas especiaute</I></L>
<L><I>A vostre file desmarie;</I></L>
<L><I>Plus serreyt baut de mes-fere,</I></L>
<L><I>Si ele</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. eole</NOTE> <I>quidast ta grace conquere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="237">Schewh &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t to muchel specialte</L>
<L>To &thorn;i dou&yogh;ter, &yogh;if heo vn-maried be,</L>
<L>Leste heo waxe to bold of face</L>
<L N="240">Vuel to do in hope of grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Trade filiam tuam &amp; grande opus feceris.</HEAD>
<L N="241"><I>Si ta file mesface, vous tene&yogh; perdu</I></L>
<L><I>Quant-ke aue&yogh; en ly despendu;</I></L>
<L><I>Dount bone bosoygne fre&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Si par tens la marie&yogh;.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="241">&YOGH;if &thorn;i douhter falle in mis-doyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;en holdest &thorn;ou lost al &thorn;i spendyng;</L>
<L>A good dede &thorn;erfore hit were</L>
<L N="244">Be tyme for to marie hire.<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. here = hire</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Crudelem medicum facit intemperans.</HEAD>
<L N="245"><I>Si vous haunte&yogh; beueries,</I></L>
<L><I>Vous en prendres maladyes;</I></L>
<L><I>Rette&yogh; donke a vostre meyn</I></L>
<L><I>La duresce del ficiscien.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="245">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be wont drynke muche wi&thorn;-alle,</L>
<L>In to gret seknesse &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t falle;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mai&yogh;t wyte &thorn;in oune hond &thorn;en</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;e hardnesse of &thorn;i ficiscien.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SYRAC.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Noli pro amico inimicus fieri proximo.</HEAD>
<L N="249"><I>Si veysyn autre me&yogh;-dit de bouche,</I></L>
<L><I>E la chose ne vous touche,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne vous face&yogh; ia partye. . . . .</I>
<PB REF="00000547.tif" N="539"></L>
<L><I>Od le vn od lautre saun&yogh; mester,</I></L>
<L><I>Ky par cas vus puet greuer.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="249">&YOGH;if &thorn;at neih&yogh;ebors to-gedere chyde</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ing touche not &thorn;e &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou make &thorn;e no partye</L>
<L N="252">Wi&thorn; on ne o&thorn;ur for heore folye;</L>
<L>ffor cuntek come&thorn; to acord,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne scholdestou be at discord</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; on or o&thorn;ur and haue repreue</L>
<L N="256">Of him par cas &thorn;at mihte &thorn;e greue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SYRAC.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Odia multorum sub osculo latent.</HEAD>
<L N="257"><I>Ne eye&yogh; ia trop affiaunce</I></L>
<L><I>En bele&yogh; paroles ne en contynaunce;</I></L>
<L><I>Tel se profre de vous beyser</I></L>
<L><I>Ke vous het formen[t] de quer.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="257">Loke &thorn;ou haue nou&yogh;t to gret affyaunce</L>
<L>In feire wordes and in cuntinaunce;</L>
<L>Such mon parauntre profre&thorn; &thorn;e to kis</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;at in herte ha[te]&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. hate&thorn;</NOTE> &thorn;e, I-wis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Odia que latuerunt panduntur si titubaueris.</HEAD>
<L N="261"><I>Ceo troueres bien: si vous cheye&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>En angusse de aduersite&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>De qy vous quyde&yogh; auer amy,</I></L>
<L><I>Lors vous serra fort enemy.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="261">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou falle in aduersite,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schal fynde and wite, parde,</L>
<L>Of whom &thorn;ou wendest a frend haue had,</L>
<L N="264">&THORN;en wole to &thorn;e be enemy sad.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Non omnem<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. omni</NOTE> hominem inducas in domum tuam ad secretum cordis tui.</HEAD>
<L N="265"><I>ffort serreyt a homne sey garder</I></L>
<L><I>De tou&yogh; ke ly sount contre quer;</I></L>
<L><I>Pur ce ne seye&yogh; trop apert</I></L>
<L><I>De mustrer counseil a descouert.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">Hard hit were to mon him kepe or asterte</L>
<L>ffrom al &thorn;ing &thorn;at is a&yogh;eynes his herte;
<PB REF="00000548.tif" N="540"></L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t &thorn;erfore to redy</L>
<L N="268">&THORN;i counseyl to schewe openly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SYRAC.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Multi interierunt per linguas suas.</HEAD>
<L N="269"><I>Meynt homme chet en graunt damage</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ia ne vendreit a tel ryuage</I></L>
<L><I>Ne fust sa lange demeyne</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ly chace a tele peyne.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="269">Mony mon falle&thorn; in gret damage</L>
<L>ffor of his speche he is outrage,</L>
<L>His owne tonge he may hit wyte</L>
<L N="272">&THORN;at driue&thorn; him to such dispyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IACOBUS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nullus hominum linguas domare potest.</HEAD>
<L N="273"><I>Lange est norice de hounte e blame,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke met plusours en male fame;</I></L>
<L><I>De tou&yogh; mals est Reyngne e dame,</I></L>
<L><I>Kar souent honist cors e alme.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="273">&THORN;e tonge is noryce of alle blame</L>
<L>And mony mon putte&thorn; in vuel fame;</L>
<L>Of al eueles hit is queene &amp; ladi</L>
<L N="276">And fordo&thorn; bo&thorn;e soule and bodi.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quietissime viuerent homines si tollerent ista duo verba : meum et tuum.</HEAD>
<L N="277"><I>Si deu&yogh; mos nee&yogh; ne fusent,</I></L>
<L><I>Bone pes trestous vssent;</I></L>
<L><I>Meen e vostre, ces deu&yogh; mos</I></L>
<L><I>ffount entre plusours graunt descors.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="277">&YOGH;if twey wordes neuer hedde be mad,</L>
<L>Eueri mon good pes mi&yogh;t ha had;</L>
<L>Myn and &thorn;yn, heore ei&thorn;er word</L>
<L N="280">Bi-twene mony men make&thorn; discord.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>AZARYAS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Non est officij tui, sed illorum qui constituti sunt ad huiuscemodi misterium.<NOTE PLACE="marg">? ministerium</NOTE></HEAD>
<L N="281"><I>Si vous estes en cumpaygnye</I></L>
<L><I>Ou checun ad sa Baylye,</I>
<PB REF="00000549.tif" N="541"></L>
<L><I>Ne seye&yogh; ia entremettour</I></L>
<L><I>De lour offys maugre lour.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="281">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be in cumpaignye</L>
<L>Wher vche mon ha&thorn; his baylye,</L>
<L>Maugre of hem be not so nyce</L>
<L N="284">To entremete &thorn;e of heore offyce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IERONIMUS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>ffrustra niti &amp; nichil aliud querere nisi odium, extreme demencie est.</HEAD>
<L N="285"><I>De quere maugre san&yogh; nul pru</I></L>
<L><I>haute deuerie est tenu;</I></L>
<L><I>Si vous ne poye&yogh; ambedeu&yogh; fere,</I></L>
<L><I>Le sages dist qe vous deue&yogh; tere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="285">To gete &thorn;e maugre wi&thorn;-outen prou,</L>
<L>A wood mon I-holde be schaltou;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t not geten bo&thorn;e at on res,</L>
<L N="288">&THORN;e wyse mon bidde&thorn; &thorn;e holde &thorn;i pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IHESUS CRISTUS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eadem mensura qua mensi fueritis alijs, remecietur vobis; dimitt[it]e &amp; dimittetur vobis.</HEAD>
<L N="289"><I>Si nuli mesfe&yogh; vous eit,</I></L>
<L><I>E puis par autre greue seit;</I></L>
<L><I>Si tele greuaunce bien vous plest,</I></L>
<L><I>Pur vous abesser dieu est prest.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="289">&YOGH;if eny mon ha&thorn; &thorn;e misdo,</L>
<L>And a-no&thorn;ur haue greued him also:</L>
<L>&THORN;erof &yogh;if &thorn;ou be proud and fayn,</L>
<L N="292">God wol &thorn;e meke, in certayn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SAULUS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Omnem<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. omnium</NOTE> filium quem recipit deus corripit &amp; castigat.</HEAD>
<L N="293"><I>Pense&yogh; tou&yogh;iours ke dieu vus cleyme</I></L>
<L><I>Pur le sen, e vous eyme,</I></L>
<L><I>Si vous ave&yogh; vn</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. in</NOTE> <I>greuaunce,</I></L>
<L><I>Pur auer aylours alleggaunce.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="293">&THORN;enk euere, god cleyme&thorn; &thorn;e his to be,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at for loue he visyte&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Whon he &thorn;e seende&thorn; eny greuaunce,</L>
<L N="296">Elleswher hit is to haue alleggaunce.
<PB REF="00000550.tif" N="542"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IHESUS CRISTUS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>ffili, recordare quia recepisti bona in vita tua.<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. sua</NOTE></HEAD>
<L N="297"><I>Tou&yogh; Iours eye&yogh; pour en quer</I></L>
<L><I>Ke dieu vous voylle en fyn dampner</I></L>
<L><I>Si vous aue&yogh; saun&yogh; contredist</I></L>
<L><I>En ceste secle tut vostre delist.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="297">Eueriday ha &thorn;ou in herte dredyng</L>
<L>Leste god &thorn;e dampne at &thorn;e endyng</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow haue al &thorn;e world at wille</L>
<L N="300">Wi&thorn;-oute wi&thorn;-stondyng loud or stille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IUDYTH.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Omnes qui placuerunt deo, per multas tribulaciones transierunt.</HEAD>
<L N="301"><I>E tou&yogh; les sein&yogh; passe&yogh; sount</I></L>
<L><I>Par dure greuaunce de ceste mound:</I></L>
<L><I>E vous, ky estes peccheur,</I></L>
<L><I>Quide&yogh; passer saun&yogh; nul estur?</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="301">Si&thorn;en &thorn;eos seyntes ben passed euerichon</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world wi&thorn; tribulacion,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou, &thorn;at art a sinful man,</L>
<L N="304">Wenest &thorn;ow wi&thorn;-outen to passen &thorn;an?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>NABUGODONOSOR.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Contra omnes precipue qui contempserunt me egredere, nec parcet oculus tuus.</HEAD>
<L N="305"><I>Cum plus vous a-force&yogh; de bien fere,</I></L>
<L><I>De le maufe auere&yogh; plus forte guere;</I></L>
<L><I>Mes len ne scet en a-saut</I></L>
<L><I>Ki chet bas ne ky mounte haut.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="305">&THORN;e more &thorn;ou peynest &thorn;e wel to do,</L>
<L>&THORN;e strengor werre &thorn;e fend meue&thorn; &thorn;e to;</L>
<L>But in a-saut men wite not wel-neih</L>
<L N="308">Ho falle&thorn; doun, ho clymbe&thorn; an heih.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>LABAN.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quare abiecisti me, &amp; me ignorante fugere voluisti?</HEAD>
<L N="309"><I>Ky se retret de vanite</I></L>
<L><I>E ce doyne a bounte,</I></L>
<L><I>De male gent serra mesdit,</I></L>
<L><I>Mes a deu ert le plus parfit.</I>
<PB REF="00000551.tif" N="543"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="309">Whose<NOTE PLACE="marg">whoso: see 'Hose,' l. 437.</NOTE> him wi&thorn;-drawe&thorn; from vanite</L>
<L>And &yogh;iue&thorn; him-self to bounte,</L>
<L>Euel men him wole edwyt,</L>
<L N="312">But to god he schal be &thorn;e more parfyt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>O quam magnum est non laudari &amp; esse laudabilem!</HEAD>
<L N="313"><I>A bone houre fut il ne</I></L>
<L><I>Ky est preysable e poy preyse;</I></L>
<L><I>Cum meyns receit ici de honour,</I></L>
<L><I>Plus ly vaudra a chef detour.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="313">In good tyme he was boren, I-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at preisable is and not preised is;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lasse he take&thorn; her of honour,</L>
<L N="316">&THORN;e more parfyt is at &thorn;e chef doctour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IHESUS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Maledicam benediccionibus vestris.</HEAD>
<L N="317"><I>Icil est dist</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. dit</NOTE> <I>malure</I></L>
<L><I>Ky est maueys e mout preyse;</I></L>
<L><I>De tel honour vent hountage,</I></L>
<L><I>Ou paraler en graunt damage.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="317">He is called corsed verreyliche</L>
<L>&THORN;at euel is and preised is muche;</L>
<L>Of such worschupe come&thorn; hountage,</L>
<L N="320">And also spekyng of gret damage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>OLYUA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nunquid possum deserere dulcedinem meam quam diu homines vtuntur.</HEAD>
<L N="321"><I>Homme ke ad a-se&yogh; dount viuere</I></L>
<L><I>E de charge est delyuere,</I></L>
<L><I>Merueyle est ke yl veut guerper</I></L>
<L><I>Soun repos pur homme seruer.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="321">&THORN;e mon &thorn;at ha&thorn; i-nouh to his liuyng</L>
<L>And delyuered is of gret chargyng,</L>
<L>Wonder hit is he wole forsake</L>
<L N="324">His rest, &amp; to monnes seruyse him take.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>FICUS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nunquid possum deserere dulcedinem meam, ut nec lingua promouear?
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000552.tif" N="544">
<L N="325"><I>Plus est merueyle del encloysterer,</I></L>
<L><I>Ky taunt de douceour put enbracer,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke desyre forayne prelacie</I></L>
<L><I>Ke peut toler sa</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. sy</NOTE> <I>douce vye.</I></L>
<L><I>Cil ke meyns vaut plus desyre</I></L>
<L><I>Prelacye, de estre vn syre;</I></L>
<L><I>Rien ne pense de ceo ke apent</I></L>
<L><I>ffors soul de quere honour de gent.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="325">Hit is merueyle of &thorn;e cloysterer,</L>
<L>&THORN;at so gret swetnesse may fynde &thorn;er,</L>
<L>&THORN;at desyre&thorn; outward prelacye</L>
<L N="328">&THORN;e whuche his swete lyf mai distruye.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at is lest wor&thorn; most wole desyre</L>
<L>Of prelacye, to ben a syre;</L>
<L>No &thorn;ing he &thorn;enke&thorn; to good profyt,</L>
<L N="332">But honour of &thorn;e world is his delyt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>AMALEK.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Conduxit sibi viros inopes et vagos ad interficiendum.</HEAD>
<L N="333"><I>Par la Meynee put len conustre</I></L>
<L><I>De quele tecches est lour dustre;</I></L>
<L><I>Le sage tret a ly les sages,</I></L>
<L><I>E ly volage</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. vologe</NOTE> <I>les volages.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="333">Be &thorn;e ledyng a mon may knowe, i-wis,</L>
<L>Of what tecches his leder is;</L>
<L>&THORN;e wyse mon drawe&thorn; to him &thorn;e wyse,</L>
<L N="336">And &thorn;e wilful mon to<NOTE PLACE="marg">om. to</NOTE> mon<NOTE PLACE="marg">r. men</NOTE> of his gyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quantum aleator est doctior in arte, tantum est nequior.</HEAD>
<L N="337"><I>Cil ke meu&yogh; scet iuer a des,</I></L>
<L><I>ffet a preiser le meyns de ase&yogh;;</I></L>
<L><I>Cum plus est sotil en cel art,</I></L>
<L><I>Plus est tenu de mal part.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="337">He &thorn;at pleye&thorn; best at &thorn;e des,</L>
<L>Preyse&thorn; faste &thorn;e hondes of hasarderes;</L>
<L>&THORN;e more sotil he is of &thorn;at art,</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;e more he stont on euel part.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nocet bonis qui parcit malis.
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000553.tif" N="545">
<L N="341"><I>Cil ke maueys sauue de hounte,</I></L>
<L><I>Les bone gens de bonte afrounte;</I></L>
<L><I>Quant ly leres passe quyte,</I></L>
<L><I>Ly leaus ad hounte, quant homme len dyte.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="341">He &thorn;at saue&thorn; a schrewe from schame,</L>
<L>To gode men he schewe&thorn; blame;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e &thorn;ef passe&thorn; quyt a-way,</L>
<L N="344">&THORN;e trewe mon ha&thorn; schome, what-euer men sai.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Parcit pecunie qui non parcit mense.</HEAD>
<L N="345"><I>Ki sauuer veut soun doner,</I></L>
<L><I>Corteis seit de soun manger;</I></L>
<L><I>Ou il li [c]ustra a-se&yogh; plus,</I></L>
<L><I>Si de sa table seit gelous.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="345">He may saue moneye and gete</L>
<L>&THORN;at wol be curteys of his mete;</L>
<L>After gret spendyng he may wayt</L>
<L N="348">&THORN;at of mete &amp; drink is to strayt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IONAS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Qui custodit vanitates, frustra misericordiam dei querit.</HEAD>
<L N="349"><I>Ky en pecche sa vye meyne</I></L>
<L><I>E de ben fere a ceo se peyne,</I></L>
<L><I>La merci deu demaund en veyn,</I></L>
<L><I>Si yl de pecche ne eit de-deyn.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="349">Hose lede&thorn; his lyf in sinne</L>
<L>And of euel dedes wol not blinne,</L>
<L>Godes merci he aske&thorn; in veyn,</L>
<L N="352">But he forsake his synne, certeyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SYRAK.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Non te pigeat visitare infirmos, quia proinde dileccione dei amaberis.</HEAD>
<L N="353"><I>Ne lesse&yogh; pas de visiter</I></L>
<L><I>Le malades de bon quer;</I></L>
<L><I>Par taunt serre&yogh; le plus parfit</I></L>
<L><I>En lamour douce Ihesu crist.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="353">Loke to visyte &thorn;at &thorn;ou be smert</L>
<L>&THORN;e seke folk wi&thorn; gode hert;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t be &thorn;e more parfyt</L>
<L N="356">In &thorn;e loue of Ihesu crist.
<PB REF="00000554.tif" N="546"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sine consilio nichil facito graue, et post factum non penitebis.</HEAD>
<L N="357"><I>Saun&yogh; counseil ne face&yogh; ren:</I></L>
<L><I>E a-pres le fet vous sauere&yogh; ben</I></L>
<L><I>Ky bon counseil vous valut,</I></L>
<L><I>Meske il auaunt vous desplut.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="357">Wi&thorn;-outen counseil do no gret &thorn;ing;</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at dede &thorn;ou schal haue good knowing</L>
<L>&THORN;at gode counseyl dude &thorn;e profyte,</L>
<L N="360">Wi&thorn;-outen whuche &thorn;ou scholdest had<NOTE PLACE="marg">[= ha had]</NOTE> lyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>ECCLESIASTES.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Per tristiciam vultus corrigitur animus delinquentis.</HEAD>
<L N="361"><I>Si parler oye&yogh; le destretour,</I></L>
<L><I>Mustre&yogh; semblaunt de tristour;</I></L>
<L><I>Quaunt lautre verra ke il vous desplet,</I></L>
<L><I>Il se retrera de parler si led.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="361">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou herest speke a bacbitour,</L>
<L>Contenaunce to him mak of irrour;</L>
<L>Whon he seo&thorn; hit like&thorn; not &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="364">Cece of his speche anon wol he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Amicis prestabis fidem, subditis pietatem, omnibus equi|tatem.</HEAD>
<L N="365"><I>A vos amys done&yogh; fey,</I></L>
<L><I>A tote gent dreyture en sey,</I></L>
<L><I>plyaunce a vos souereyns,</I></L>
<L><I>E mesure a vos vileyns.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="365">To &thorn;i frendes tak &thorn;ou credence,</L>
<L>Do vche mon riht be concience,</L>
<L>Be meke to hym &thorn;at aboue &thorn;e is set,</L>
<L N="368">And haue mesure to &thorn;i soget.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Priusquam promittas delibera, ut quod promiseris facias.</HEAD>
<L N="369"><I>De-vaunt ke vus promette&yogh; ren,</I></L>
<L><I>Si fere le vole&yogh; auise&yogh; vous bien;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar mout promettere e ren doner</I></L>
<L><I>ffet meynt homme a chalanger.</I>
<PB REF="00000555.tif" N="547"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="369">Or &thorn;ou bi-hote enydel,</L>
<L>Wher &thorn;ou wolt do so, bi-&thorn;enk &thorn;e wel;</L>
<L>ffor muche to bi-hote &amp; &yogh;iue but softe,</L>
<L N="372">Make&thorn; mon to be chalanged ofte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Qui cito dat, mutuum recipit.</HEAD>
<L N="373"><I>Meynt homme tent de greinour fes</I></L>
<L><I>Vn petit doun saun&yogh; promes,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke grant chose, quaunt il le prent</I></L>
<L><I>A-pres promes de long atent.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="373">Mon holde&thorn; a luite &yogh;ift more dere</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen be-heste wi&thorn; gode chere,</L>
<L>&THORN;en he wolde of a gret &thorn;inge</L>
<L N="376">Of bi-heste wi&thorn; long tariinge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>In multiloquio non deest peccatum; qui custodit linguam suam custodit animam suam.</HEAD>
<L N="377"><I>En mout desparoles sourt folye;</I></L>
<L><I>Ky gard sa lange gard sa vye;</I></L>
<L><I>Ky sa lange ne scet tener,</I></L>
<L><I>En cumpaygnye se fet hayer.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="377">Muche speche nis not wi&thorn;-outen strif;</L>
<L>Hose kepe&thorn; his tonge kepe&thorn; his lyf;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at his tonge con not holde,</L>
<L N="380">In cumpaygnye a schrewe is tolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>GREGORIUS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cum venter reficitur, lingua relaxabitur.</HEAD>
<L N="381"><I>Large table e plentiuouse</I></L>
<L><I>Norist Iangle sourfetouse;</I></L>
<L><I>Quaunt la cors ben refest est,</I></L>
<L><I>De mesparler la lange est prest.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="381">Large table and plentyuouse</L>
<L>Make&thorn; men of Ianglyng surfetouse;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e bodi I-fuld is,</L>
<L N="384">&THORN;e tonge is redi to speke amis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stultus si tacuerit, sapiens erit.</HEAD>
<L N="385"><I>Si vn fol ne parlat ren,</I></L>
<L><I>Len quideroyt ke il scet graunt ben;</I>
<PB REF="00000556.tif" N="548"></L>
<L><I>Mes quant il comence a Iangler,</I></L>
<L><I>Arere tourne il cel quider.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">A fol &yogh;if he speke no &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Men wene he beo wys in doyng;</L>
<L>Whon he bi-gynne&thorn; to Iangle fast,</L>
<L N="388">&THORN;en men knowen wel his cast.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Anus cum nubit, morti delicias facit.</HEAD>
<L N="389"><I>Quant femme se marie en graunt age,</I></L>
<L><I>A soun estat fet hountage,</I></L>
<L><I>E soun cors ad oblyge</I></L>
<L><I>ffere vn present a pecche.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="389">An old wommon &thorn;at take&thorn; hosebonde,</L>
<L>Heo worche&thorn; hir-self schome and schonde</L>
<L>To hire a-stat, &amp; hire bodi bounde is wi&thorn;-Inne</L>
<L N="392">A present for to bere to synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SYRAK.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quanto maior es humilia te in omnibus, et coram deo inuenies graciam.</HEAD>
<L N="393"><I>Cum plus vous sente&yogh; meu&yogh; valer</I></L>
<L><I>Plus vous deue&yogh; humilier;</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. humilie&yogh;</NOTE></L>
<L><I>E cum plus vous humilie&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Vostre bounte plus enhauce&yogh;.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="393">&THORN;e herre of stat &thorn;at &thorn;ou be</L>
<L>&THORN;e more meke haue &thorn;ou &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;e more &thorn;ou hast of mekenesse</L>
<L N="396">&THORN;e fastore &thorn;ou encresest of goodnesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Miserum te iudico qui nunquam fuisti miser.</HEAD>
<L N="397"><I>Cyl est cheitifs a droyt nome</I></L>
<L><I>Ke vnke ne soffri cheytiuete;</I></L>
<L><I>Ia ne vendre&yogh; a bon los</I></L>
<L><I>Si vous ne perde&yogh; souent repos.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="397">A Caytif forso&thorn;e he i-called may be</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer soffred caytyfte;</L>
<L>Good los neuer &thorn;ou gest</L>
<L N="400">But &yogh;if &thorn;ou leose oftesy&thorn;e &thorn;i rest.
<PB REF="00000557.tif" N="549"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SAULUS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ad magna premia non poteris venire nisi per magnos labores.</HEAD>
<L N="401"><I>Repos e los, cum il me semble,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne a-cordent pas bien en-semble;</I></L>
<L><I>Ou yl vous couent perdre los</I></L>
<L><I>Ou souent lesser vostre repos.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="401">Gret los &amp; reste, me &thorn;inke&thorn; wel,</L>
<L>A-corden to-gedere neuer a del;</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur &thorn;ou most &thorn;i loos lese</L>
<L N="404">Or ofte-tymen for-go &thorn;yn ese.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IOSEPH.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cum dixit mulier: dormi mecum; qui non adquiescens relicto pallio fugit.</HEAD>
<L N="405"><I>Ne entre&yogh; iammes san&yogh; cumpaygnye</I></L>
<L><I>Ou femme est soule de male vye;</I></L>
<L><I>Si vous ne a-corde&yogh; a sa luxure,</I></L>
<L><I>Ele vous mettra la rage sure.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="405">Entre &thorn;ou neuere wi&thorn;-outen conpaygnie</L>
<L>&THORN;er wommon al-one is of vilenye;</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;if &thorn;ow parfourne not lecherye,</L>
<L N="408">On &thorn;e heo wol &thorn;enne sette a crie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laus &amp; lasciuia non habent concordiam.</HEAD>
<L N="409"><I>Envye destruit bone vye,</I></L>
<L><I>E los est perdu par lecherie;</I></L>
<L><I>Lecherie &amp; bon los</I></L>
<L><I>Ne serrount Iammes ensemble clos.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="409">Envye good lyf wol distruye,</L>
<L>And loos is lost &thorn;orw lecherye;</L>
<L>Lecherye and good loos</L>
<L N="412">Ne mowe not euere to-geder be clos.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Miserrima est fortuna que caret inimico.</HEAD>
<L N="413"><I>Dure cheaunce vent a cely</I></L>
<L><I>Ky est de tut san&yogh; enemy;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar si eust grace de byen vyuere,</I></L>
<L><I>De enemiste ne serroyt delyuere.</I>
<PB REF="00000558.tif" N="550"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="413">Harde chaunce is hym be-fal</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; non enemy at al;</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;if grace of good lyf hedde he,</L>
<L N="416">He nere not dilyuered of enemyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>P[r]incipium discordie est ex com[m]u[n]i suum facere.</HEAD>
<L N="(417)"><I>Enchesun est de bon acord</I></L>
<L><I>Quant checun se paye de soun sort;</I></L>
<L><I>Induccion est a discord</I></L>
<L><I>A-proprier comoune atort.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="417">&THORN;e cause of acord is, god hit wot,</L>
<L>Whon vche mon is payed of his lot;</L>
<L>But of discord &thorn;e cause nou is</L>
<L N="420">Whon mon wol make comun &thorn;ing his.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Melior est vir paciens viro forti, et qui dominatur animo suo expugnatore vrbium.</HEAD>
<L N="(421)"><I>Meu&yogh; vaut celi ky fet destresse</I></L>
<L><I>A ly meymes en hastiuesse,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke cely ky peut conquere</I></L>
<L><I>Tut vn pays par force de guere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="421">He is more wor&thorn; &thorn;at con distresse</L>
<L>Him-self, and refreyne in hastinesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;en he &thorn;at may fulli conquerre</L>
<L N="424">Al a cuntre bi streng&thorn;e of werre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>CONSTANTINUS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vicisse naciones est virtus populorum, vincere autem vicia est virtus<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. est v. est</NOTE> morum.</HEAD>
<L N="(425)"><I>Ky tere ou cite en guere prent,</I></L>
<L><I>Par force le fest de sa gent;</I></L>
<L><I>Mes cyl qui amestrie soun quer demeyne,</I></L>
<L><I>Soul deit auer los souereyne.</I></L>
<L><I>Sages est tenu ky scet fere mal,</I></L>
<L><I>Sen ne symplesse ne ount poynt degal:</I></L>
<L><I>La meyn senestre est mys a destre,</I></L>
<L><I>E tort en dreyt pur gayn a crestre.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="425">He &thorn;at bi werre take&thorn; lond or cite,</L>
<L>Be streng&thorn;e of his peple &thorn;at do&thorn; he;
<PB REF="00000559.tif" N="551"></L>
<L>But he &thorn;at ha&thorn; maystred his owne herte clos,</L>
<L N="428">He ha&thorn; onliche a souereyn los.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at con euel is holde wys and wor&thorn;,</L>
<L>Symplesse &amp; wit ne mowe not for&thorn;;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lufthalf is put vppon &thorn;e riht,</L>
<L N="432">And wrong for wynnyng ouur ri&yogh;t ha&thorn; miht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SYRAC.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Melior est vir simplex in simplicitate sua ambulans, quam diues in vijs prauis.</HEAD>
<L N="(433)"><I>Meu&yogh; vaut folye de symplesse,</I></L>
<L><I>Ou nule cautele le alme blesse,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke les grauns sen&yogh; de cest mound,</I></L>
<L><I>Ky la lei deu souent defount.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="433">Better is folye &thorn;at falle&thorn; of symplesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;er as cautel in soule nis more ne lesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;en of &thorn;is world al &thorn;e wit,</L>
<L N="436">ffor ofte-tyme &thorn;e lawe of god distruie&thorn; hit.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMON.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Qui calumpniatur pauperem ut arguatur<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. arguatur</NOTE> diuicias, dabit ipse diciori se &amp; egebit.</HEAD>
<L N="(437)"><I>Ky fet a pours duresce ou peyne,</I></L>
<L><I>pur encrestre ces biens demeyne,</I></L>
<L><I>Il durra a-ce&yogh; plus a souereyns</I></L>
<L><I>E de tou&yogh; biens il auera le meyns.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="437">Hose do&thorn; to pore duresse or peyne,</L>
<L>To encrese his richesse, certeyne,</L>
<L>An herre mon schal parte wi&thorn; his riches,</L>
<L N="440">And of alle godes he schal haue &thorn;e les.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SALOMON.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Follows after the 2nd Fr. v.</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEAD>Omnia mea mecum sunt, Iusticia et prudencia &amp;c.</HEAD>
<L N="(441)"><I>Ne quide&yogh; ia ke chose seit uostre</I></L>
<L><I>Dont autres dyent cest la</I> nost[re];</L>
<L><I>Vostre est ou mal ou ben</I></L>
<L><I>Ke fet aue&yogh;, saun&yogh; autre rien.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="441">Trouwe &thorn;ou neuere &thorn;at &thorn;ing be &thorn;in</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur mon sei&thorn; '&thorn;is is myn;'</L>
<L>&THORN;yn is &thorn;yn euel o&thorn;ur good doyng</L>
<L N="444">&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast wrou&yogh;t, wi&thorn;-outen o&thorn;ur monnus &thorn;ing.
<PB REF="00000560.tif" N="552"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SENECA.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bona mea intacta fero.</HEAD>
<L N="(445)"><I>Si vus aue&yogh; tere e meson,</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo ne dure fors ke vne seson;</I></L>
<L><I>Od vous irrount vo&yogh; ben-fes,</I></L>
<L><I>Mes la meson demert en pes.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="445">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou haue lond, hous or yle,</L>
<L>&THORN;elke nul dure but a while;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e schal go &thorn;i gode dede,</L>
<L N="448">&THORN;in hous abit, wi&thorn;-oute drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>ECCLESIASTES.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Breuis oracio penetrat celum.</HEAD>
<L N="(449)"><I>Mout escrire e nent lyre</I></L>
<L><I>Poy uaut, pour veyr dyre;</I></L>
<L><I>De tou&yogh; orisons le alme est puwe</I></L>
<L><I>Ke par delyt sount conseuwe.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="449">Muche to write &amp; no &thorn;ing rede,</L>
<L>Luitel is worth, wi&thorn;-outen drede;</L>
<L>Orisouns helpen soules of men</L>
<L N="452">&THORN;at wi&thorn; delyt conseyued hem.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>CATO.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Legere &amp; non intelligere est necligere.</HEAD>
<L N="(453)"><I>En teu manere la lettre lyse&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Ke la sentence entendre sache&yogh;;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar nent entendre e mout lyre,</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo dit Caton, fet a despyre.</I></L>
<L><I>Purce voyl ieo ici lesser</I></L>
<L><I>De plus prouerbes translater,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ceus ky lysent cest escrit</I></L>
<L><I>En countre</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[? courte]</NOTE> <I>parole eyent delyst.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="453">Lettres &thorn;ou schalt rede on such manere</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou vnderstonde &thorn;e sentence clere;</L>
<L>Muche to rede wi&thorn;-outen vnderstonding,</L>
<L N="456">Caton sei&thorn; hit is a dispysyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore I wole after &thorn;is resoun</L>
<L>Of &thorn;es prouerbes cesse of &thorn;e translacioun;</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;at wol rede &thorn;is wrytyng,</L>
<L N="460">In schorte wordes may haue lykyng.
<PB REF="00000561.tif" N="553"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>AUGUSTINUS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Qui pro alijs orat, pro se ipso laborat.</HEAD>
<L N="(461)"><I>Ore prie&yogh; tous pur le houm</I></L>
<L><I>Ke</I> vus presente <I>ceste lessoun,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke il par vostre oreisoun</I></L>
<L><I>Vygne a bone sauuacioun.</I></L>
<L><I>Ore deu, ky est pleyn de cen,</I></L>
<L><I>Nous doyne bone fyn, Amen.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="461">Nou preye&thorn; alle wi&thorn; deuocion</L>
<L>ffor hym &thorn;at made &thorn;is lesson,</L>
<L N="463">&THORN;at he &thorn;orw &yogh;oure orisoun</L>
<L>Mouwe come to sauacion.</L>
<L>And god, &thorn;at made alle &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="466">&YOGH;if vs alle good endyng.</L>
<TRAILER>A. M. E. N. Amen.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="50" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Cato]</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>[Parvus Cato]</HEAD>
<HEAD>L. Her bi-ginne&thorn; luytel Caton.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The Engl. text was ed. by Goldberg, <I>Anglia</I> 1884, VII, p. 165 ff. It is a translation of Monk Everard's French transl., extant in MS. Arund. 292, f. 88-105, ca. 1250 (ed. by Stengel, <I>Ausg. und Abh. d. Roman. Phil.</I> XLVII, Marburg 1886); MS. Paris Bibl. Nat. 477 (ed. by Le Roux de Lincy, <I>Livre des Prov. Franc.</I>, 2nd ed. 1859, II, p. 439 ff.; readings given by Stengel l. c.), and MSS. Vernon and Simeon. [Other, perhaps earlier, Fr. translations are that by Elie de Wincestre in MSS. St. John's Coll. Oxford 178, 13th cent., Corp. C. C. Cbr. 405, Harl. 4388, ed. by Stengel l. c., and that of an anonymous in MS. Harl. 4657, ed. by Stengel l. c.; cf. P. Meyer, <I>Romania</I> VI, 20.] Everard le moine is most likely the one mentioned by Tanner: "Everardus, Scotus, in canonicatu Kirkham (Yorkshire) socius primusque abbas Monasterii de Holme Cultram in Cumbria: scripsit Vitam S. Adam|nani lib. 1, Vit. S. Cumenei Albi lib. 1, Vit. S. Waltheni lib. I; claruit A. MCXLV; Dempster" (see, however, Wright, <I>Biogr. Brit.</I> II, 123 ff., who rejects this identity).&mdash;Other Engl. translations are that in MS. Arund. 168, in royal stanzas, and that ed. by Caxton: <I>Parvus Cato, Magnus Cato</I> (a transl. by Benedict Burgh, undertaken on behalf of Will. Bourchier, son of the Earl of Essex), 1st ed. Westminster? ante 1479? (unique in Cambr. Univ. Libr.), 2nd ed. Westm.? ante 1479? (unique at Chatsworth), 3rd ed. fol. Westm.? 1481? (The same Caxton ed. an elaborate commentary on Cato's Distichs, translated by him from the Fr. in 1483, Westm. 1484?).</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Almihti god in Trinite</L>
<L>leeue vs wel to spede,</L>
<L>Send vs of his holy grace</L>
<L N="4">And help vs at vr nede.</L>
<L>Now hose wole, he may here</L>
<L>In Englisch langage
<PB REF="00000562.tif" N="554"></L>
<L>How &thorn;e wyse mon tauhte his sone,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at was of tendere age.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>1.</HEAD>
<L><I>CAtun estoyt payen</I></L>
<L><I>E ne sauoyt rien</I></L>
<L><I>De cristiene ley,</I></L>
<L><I>E ne-pur-quaunt ne dist</I></L>
<L><I>Riens</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Biens</NOTE> <I>en soun escrist</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. estrist</NOTE></L>
<L><I>En-countre nostre fey.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="9">Catun was an he&thorn;ene mon,</L>
<L>Cristned was he nouht:</L>
<L>In word ne in werk a&yogh;eynes vr fey</L>
<L N="12">No techyng he non tauht.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>2.</HEAD>
<L><I>Kar tut se encord</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> concorde</NOTE></L>
<L><I>E ren ne se descord,</I></L>
<L><I>Al</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">S A, P A la</NOTE> <I>seynt escripture;</I></L>
<L><I>Amender len porrat</I></L>
<L><I>Cely qui vodrat</I></L>
<L><I>Mettre</I> [<I>i</I>] <I>sa cure.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="13">To holy writ al in his bok</L>
<L>A-cordyng was he euere;</L>
<L>Of god of heuene com his wit,</L>
<L N="16">Of o&thorn;er com hit neuere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>3.</HEAD>
<L><I>Issi cum ieo quit,</I></L>
<L><I>Del seynt espirit</I></L>
<L><I>La grace en ly estoyt;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar ne sen ne sauer</I></L>
<L><I>Nul nest pur veir</I></L>
<L><I>Ky de deu ne seyt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>4.</HEAD>
<L><I>Kar</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> Par</NOTE> <I>len-seignement</I></L>
<L><I>Ke dan&yogh; Catun despent</I></L>
<L><I>En soun fi&yogh; aprendre,</I></L>
<L><I>Me semble ke il aprent</I></L>
<L><I>Moy e tote gent,</I></L>
<L><I>Si le volum entendre.</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>2 st. om.</P><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Si oir le volez,</L>
<L>Ver mei escutez</L>
<L>Amiablement.</L>
<L>Priez sanz essoine</L>
<L>Pur auerard le moine</L>
<L>Ki cest ouvraige enprent.</L>
<L>Priez pur le moine</L>
<L>Ke deu sun quer aluine</L>
<L>De mal e de peche,</L>
<L>E ke li doint sa grace</L>
<L>Ke ceste chose face</L>
<L>Selung la uerite.</L>
</LG></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000563.tif" N="555"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="17">&THORN;e lore &thorn;at he tau&yogh;te his sone,</L>
<L>Is neodful to vs alle;</L>
<L>Vnderstond<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Vnderstonstond</NOTE> hose wole,</L>
<L N="20">ffor caas &thorn;at may be-falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">21-8 = Fr. 5 &amp; 6.</NOTE>Whon &thorn;at he sau&yogh; eny mon</L>
<L>Out of rihtful weye,</L>
<L>Hem to teche as hit was best</L>
<L N="24">He letted for non ei&yogh;e,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei mihte lerne and here</L>
<L>Siker heore lyf to lede</L>
<L>And gedre wit in heore &yogh;ou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="28">And God to loue and drede.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Cum animaduerterem quam-plurimos homines graui|ter errare in via morum, succurrendum opinioni eorum &amp; consulendum forte existimaui,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">existinaui</NOTE> <I>maxime ut gloriose uiuerent et honorem contingerent.</I></P>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>5 (7).</HEAD>
<L><I>Cum ie moy a-parceuoye</I></L>
<L><I>plusours de la voye</I></L>
<L><I>de mours forueyer,</I></L>
<L><I>Auis pur voyr mestoyt</I></L>
<L><I>ke graunt ben serroyt</I></L>
<L><I>de eus conseyler,</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>6.</HEAD>
<L><I>Pur ce nomement</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> memement</NOTE></L>
<L><I>ke gloriousement</I></L>
<L><I>en le</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> el</NOTE> <I>mound vesquisent</I></L>
<L><I>E par tel affere</I></L>
<L><I>dignete&yogh; en tere</I></L>
<L><I>E honour conquisent.</I></L>
</LG>
<P>Nunc <I>te, fili carissime, docebo</I> quo <I>pacto animi tui morem</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> mores</NOTE> <I>componas.</I></P>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>7.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ore, beu fi&yogh; trescher,</I></L>
<L><I>Te voyl enseigner,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke vous</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> tu en</NOTE> <I>seyes sage,</I></L>
<L><I>Par quel couenaunt</I></L>
<L><I>Tu purras eneuaunt</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> en auant</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Aorner toun corage.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="29">Deore sone, I schal &thorn;e teche</L>
<L>&THORN;e maners of my wille,
<PB REF="00000564.tif" N="556"></L>
<L>Hou &thorn;ou schat hem ordeyne</L>
<L N="32">And godes lawe to folfille.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Igitur mea precepta [ita] legito, vt intelligas: legere &amp; non intelligere est negligere.</I></P>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>8.</HEAD>
<L><I>Pur ces enchesons,</I></L>
<L><I>Beu&yogh; fi&yogh;, tey somons</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tu me preceps lyce&yogh;;</I></L>
<L><I>Mes nent entendre e lyre</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo fet a despire,</I></L>
<L><I>Si voyl ke tei en chastie&yogh;.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="33">Mi biddyng and my teching</L>
<L>In herte hem vnderstonde;</L>
<L>Ofte to here &amp; nou&yogh;t lerne</L>
<L N="36">Hit is bo&thorn;e schame &amp; schonde.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Ideoque deo supplica. parentes ama. cognatos cole.</I></P>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>9 (11).</HEAD>
<L><I>Deu aore&yogh;,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">A. ameras, P. amez</NOTE></L>
<L><I>A ly requere&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Dount as mester.</I></L>
<L><I>Pere e Mere ame&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Vos parens honoures,</I></L>
<L><I>E mout les ei&yogh;es cher.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="37">Worschupe god, &amp; him biseche</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ing &thorn;ou hast mestere.</L>
<L>ffader &amp; Moder loue &thorn;ou wel</L>
<L N="40">And hold hem leoue and dere.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Datum serua. foro te para.</I></P>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>10.</HEAD>
<L><I>Mout seit ben garde</I></L>
<L><I>Chose ke tey est done</I></L>
<L><I>Par deu ou par gent.</I></L>
<L><I>Al marche quant ale&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Ben</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> Bel</NOTE> <I>vous atorne&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>E enseygnement.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">A. acemement, P. ascemeement</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="41">Keep &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;e is &yogh;iuen</L>
<L>&THORN;orw God or &thorn;orw mon.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou schalt to market,</L>
<L N="44">A-tyre &thorn;e as &thorn;ou con.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Mutuum da. cum bonis ambula.</I></P>
<P><I>Cui des videto. ad consilium ne accesseris antequam voceris.</I>
<PB REF="00000565.tif" N="557"></P>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>11.</HEAD>
<L><I>A leaus preste&yogh;.</I></L>
<L><I>Od les bons ale&yogh;.</I></L>
<L><I>Sy veye&yogh; a ky face&yogh; douns.</I></L>
<L><I>A counseyl ne aproche&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Avaunt-ke vous seye&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Apele&yogh; ou somouns.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="45">Lene &thorn;i good to trewe men,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er-of falle no wrake.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou go wi&thorn; &thorn;e goode,</L>
<L N="48">And wikked men forsake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To hem also &thorn;ou &yogh;iue &thorn;i &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;erof &thorn;e wole bi-seke.</L>
<L>Neuer to counseyl &thorn;at &thorn;ou come,</L>
<L N="52">But &yogh;if &thorn;ou cleped be eke.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Conuiua raro. mundus esto. Quod satis est dormi. saluta libenter.</I></P>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>12 (14).</HEAD>
<L><I>Relement</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>r.</I> Rerement</NOTE> <I>geste&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>E chaste</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> Net e ch.</NOTE> <I>seie&yogh;.</I></L>
<L><I>Dorme&yogh; ase&yogh; saun&yogh; plus.</I></L>
<L><I>Volunters les</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>om.</I> les</NOTE> <I>salue&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Ces ke vous veyes</I></L>
<L><I>Vener a-countre vous.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="53">Mak &thorn;i gestnyng seldene,</L>
<L>And be chast and clene.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if i-nouh with-outen more.</L>
<L N="56">Grete men feire by-dene.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Coniugem ama. cede maiori.</I></P>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>13.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ta femme par amour</I></L>
<L><I>Ame&yogh;. a greynour</I></L>
<L><I>Tut tens done&yogh; lu;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar quant nas le pouer</I></L>
<L><I>Ke puisse&yogh; encountrer</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">A. Quel pusses cuntre ester</NOTE></L>
<L>Cum <I>il vous seyt tenu.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Nest pas bel le giu.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="57">Loue &thorn;i wyf, and &yogh;if stude to &thorn;e grete</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;i pouwer is lesse;</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;ou metest hem in &thorn;e wey,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;ou drede of heore distresse.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Magistrum metue. vino te tempora. verecundiam serua.</I>
<PB REF="00000566.tif" N="558"></P>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>14.</HEAD>
<L><I>Toun mestre chescun vre</I></L>
<L><I>Dote&yogh; sy eie&yogh; mesure</I></L>
<L><I>Quant beyure vyn deuras.</I></L>
<L><I>Garde&yogh; ke tu seye&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Hountous a la fee&yogh;,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> tute veies</NOTE></L>
<L><I>E donke ben le fras.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="61">A-Mesure &thorn;e in drynkynge;</L>
<L>To fleo folye be snelle.</L>
<L>Gedere wit of wyse men,</L>
<L N="64">And let hit wi&thorn; &thorn;e dwelle.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Libros lege; quod legeris memento. rem tuam custodi.</I></P>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>15.</HEAD>
<L><I>Lyueres enlise&yogh;</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">A. Tes livres lirras, P. Livres lisez</NOTE>;</L>
<L><I>E ceo ke lu auere&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne mette&yogh; en obly.</I></L>
<L><I>Garde&yogh; ben ta chose:</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo est fest</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> Ceo faut</NOTE> <I>en poy de pose</I></L>
<L><I>Ke long tens est quili.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> cuilli</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">Bokes lere; &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast herd,</L>
<L>And hold hem in &thorn;i &thorn;ouht.</L>
<L>Keep &thorn;i &thorn;ing, &amp; sone hit not spende</L>
<L N="68">In long tyme deore was bouht.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Lib[e]ros erudi. diligenciam adhibe. Blandus esto. iusiurandum serua.</I></P>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>16 (18).</HEAD>
<L><I>Tes enfaun&yogh; apren</I></L>
<L><I>Ben sauer e sen.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. seen</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Si seie&yogh; diligent.</I></L>
<L><I>Seies douce e suef,</I></L>
<L><I>E ne mye gref.</I></L>
<L><I>Garde&yogh; toun serment.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="69">Wit &amp; wisdam, ble&thorn;eliche</L>
<L>&THORN;i children &thorn;at &thorn;ou teche!</L>
<L>Swere &thorn;ou not but hit be so&thorn;,</L>
<L N="72">ffor drede of godes wreche.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>ffamiliam cura. irasci ab re noli. Neminem irriseris.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. irasceris.</NOTE> <I>meretricem fuge.</I></P>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>17.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ta meyne chastie,</I></L>
<L><I>E ne seye&yogh; mye</I></L>
<L><I>Pur petist irre&yogh;.</I></L>
<L><I>Ne-scharnye&yogh; nulli&mdash;</I>
<PB REF="00000567.tif" N="559"></L>
<L><I>Ceo vous comaunt e pri.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. epri</NOTE></L>
<L><I>La puteyne fue&yogh;.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="73">C[h]astise<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Castise</NOTE> feire &thorn;i seruauns.</L>
<L>ffor luitel beo not wro&thorn;.</L>
<L>Hordam &thorn;ou forsake,</L>
<L N="76">And scornyng be &thorn;e lo&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>In iudicium adesto; ad pretorium stato.</I></P>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>18.</HEAD>
<L><I>Volunters eyde&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>A tuens, quant</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> A ceus ke vus p.</NOTE> <I>poyes,</I></L>
<L><I>Quant es</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">A. uent, P. estes</NOTE> <I>al Iugement;</I></L>
<L><I>A la prouosterie</I></L>
<L><I>Esteyes, e ne flecche&yogh; mye</I></L>
<L><I>Pur Or ne pur Argent.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="77">Ble&thorn;eliche &thorn;ou hem helpe</L>
<L>&THORN;at stonden in Iugement;</L>
<L>fflecche not for no bi-heste,</L>
<L N="80">ffor &yogh;ifte ne for rent.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Literas disce. consultus esto.</I></P>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>19 (21).</HEAD>
<L><I>Par escripture</I></L>
<L><I>Tut tens a-seure</I></L>
<L><I>Tes di&yogh; e tes fe&yogh;.</I></L>
<L><I>E counsayl perne&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Nent sages enseigne&yogh;</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A. A sages e a senez, P. Des s. e des s.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Quant il tent ple&yogh;.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">A P. Quant deis tenir les (P tes) plez.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="81">Let holy writ beo &thorn;i mirour</L>
<L>In word and eke in dede.</L>
<L>Of wyse men tak &thorn;i counseyl,</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at con &thorn;e wisse and rede.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Bonis benefacito. virtute vtere. Tutis</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. tute</NOTE> <I>consule. maledicus ne esto.</I></P>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>20.</HEAD>
<L><I>ffetes bens</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> ben</NOTE> <I>a bons,</I></L>
<L><I>E nomement a tuens.</I></L>
<L><I>E vse&yogh; tes vertu&yogh;.</I></L>
<L><I>Seur counsayl done&yogh;.</I></L>
<L><I>Maudyt ne seye&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne maudie&yogh; nuls.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">Bere &thorn;e wel to alle gode men;</L>
<L>And schrewes, forsake hem alle.
<PB REF="00000568.tif" N="560"></L>
<L>Haunte gode werkes &amp; warie not,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at hit not on &thorn;e falle.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Troco lude; aleas fuge.</I></P>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>21.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si Iuer vole&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Al tupet iue&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>E nent ala</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">A. al, P. a</NOTE> <I>hasard;</I></L>
<L><I>Le tables fue&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tenu ne seye&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Ne fol ne</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">A. Na fous na, P. A fol ne a</NOTE> <I>musard.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="89">Tak a Toppe, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt pleye,</L>
<L>And not at &thorn;e hasardrye.</L>
<L>ffleo &thorn;ou foles in alle wyse,</L>
<L N="92">And vse no vileynye.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Existimacionem retine.</I></P>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>22.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si vous quide&yogh; ren</I></L>
<L><I>De mal ou de ben</I></L>
<L><I>Dount tu nes mye cert,</I></L>
<L><I>Donkes fetes come sage,</I></L>
<L><I>Le retene&yogh; en toun corage,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ne seit descouert.</I><NOTE PLACE="inter">[The Engl. transl. wanting.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">In the MS. v. 81-4 follow here, but belong to the next proverb.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<P><I>Patere legem quam ipse tuleris.</I></P>
<P><I>Equ[u]m iudica. nil mentire.</I></P>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>23 (25).</HEAD>
<L><I>Soffre&yogh; en dreit de tei</I></L>
<L><I>Meymes cele ley</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tu as done.</I></L>
<L><I>Dreyt tut tens iugge&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>E rien ne mente&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Kar ceo ert equite.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">A. est hunte, P. est vice</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="93">Such lawe as &thorn;ou hast brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And haunted hast bi-fore,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou most hit mekely suffre,</L>
<L N="96">ffor winnyng or for lore.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Beneficij accepti memor esto. Pauca in conuiuio</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. comunio</NOTE> <I>loquere. minime iudica.</I></P>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>24.</HEAD>
<L><I>Benefice ke as resceu</I></L>
<L><I>En remembrer eie&yogh; deu,</I></L>
<L><I>Pur fere en guerdon.</I></L>
<L><I>E[n] comune</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">A. conuiuie, P. feste</NOTE> <I>poy parle&yogh;.</I>
<PB REF="00000569.tif" N="561"></L>
<L><I>Homme pur nent</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">A. Hume nul ne</NOTE> <I>iuge&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Kar ce[o] est trayson.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> detrasciun</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="97">&THORN;e godnesse &thorn;at men do &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou haue hit ofte in mynde;</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t skile hit wole eke,</L>
<L N="100">Or elles &thorn;ou art vn-kynde.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Illud stude agere quod iustum est. pugna pro patria.</I></P>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>25.</HEAD>
<L><I>Taunt cum es en vye,</I></L>
<L><I>De fere estudye</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo ke a dreyt apent.</I></L>
<L><I>E si tu veyes la guere,</I></L>
<L><I>Cumbate&yogh; pur la</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">r. ta</NOTE> <I>tere</I></L>
<L><I>E toun pays defent.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="101">&THORN;enk &thorn;ou euere in &thorn;i lyue</L>
<L>&THORN;ing &thorn;at falle&thorn; to riht.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at Batayle come in to londe,</L>
<L N="104">Defende hit faste wi&thorn; fiht.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Aliena noli concupiscere. parem pacienter vince.</I></P>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>26.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ne voyles</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">or. voylles</NOTE> <I>en toun quer</I></L>
<L><I>Autri ben coueyter</I></L>
<L><I>Pur nul auenture.</I></L>
<L><I>Veindre e sormounter</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. e esorm.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Voyle&yogh; uostre per</I></L>
<L><I>Par soffraunce e mesure.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="105">O&thorn;er mennes &thorn;ing with wronge</L>
<L>Coueyte hit nou&yogh;t in herte.</L>
<L>Haue mesure al of &thorn;i-self,</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at wrong &thorn;e not smerte.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Minorem ne contemseris. Noli confidere in tua fortitudine.</I></P>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>27 (29).</HEAD>
<L><I>Ky est meyndre de tey,</I></L>
<L><I>Tut</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> Me(s) ke</NOTE> <I>seye&yogh; vous rey,</I></L>
<L><I>Vnkes ne despise&yogh;.</I></L>
<L><I>E si tu force ne</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> <I>as,</I></L>
<L><I>En tey ne affye&yogh; pas,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne trop ne [te] preyse&yogh;.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="109">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou beo a strong mon</L>
<L>And riche of worldes good,
<PB REF="00000570.tif" N="562"></L>
<L>Dispyse &thorn;ou no luytel mon,</L>
<L N="112">Ne hate hym in &thorn;y mod.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Nichil arbitrio uirium feceris, [Libenter amorem ferto.</I>]<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Noli confidere in tua fortitudine.</NOTE></P>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>28.</HEAD>
<L><I>Par propre volunte</I></L>
<L><I>Ren ne seit ouere</I></L>
<L><I>De quant ke tu fras.</I></L>
<L><I>Volunters e de gre</I></L>
<L><I>Suffrez amiste</I></L>
<L><I>Quaunt purchase le as.</I><NOTE PLACE="end">. . . . .[English wanting].</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER><B>Here endet petyt caton.</B></TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>[Magnus Cato]</HEAD>
<HEAD>Incipit liber catonis.</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Si deus est animus, nobis ut carmina dicunt, Hic tibi precipue sit pura mente colendus.</I></P>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>29.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si deu a cultifier</I></L>
<L><I>Est od pure pencer,</I></L>
<L><I>Cum dient les dyte&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>E seit toun corage</I></L>
<L><I>fferm en son estage,</I></L>
<L><I>Saunz estre remue&yogh;.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="113">ffor god is lord of alle &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>As prophetes tellen i-mene,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt him in werk honoure,</L>
<L N="116">And wi&thorn; &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;tes clene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Plus uigila semper: ne sompno deditus esto: Nam diuturna quies uicijs alimenta ministrat.</I></P>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>30.</HEAD>
<L><I>Tut tens gardez vous</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tu veylez plus</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ne prengez sompne;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar par trop dormer</I></L>
<L><I>Veum souent cheir</I></L>
<L><I>En vices meynt</I> homme.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="117">Loke &thorn;ou wake more &thorn;en sleple,<NOTE PLACE="marg">? slepe</NOTE></L>
<L>And god in alle &thorn;ing drede;</L>
<L>Long rest and luitel swynk</L>
<L N="120">To vices hit wol &thorn;e lede.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000571.tif" N="563">
<P><I>Virtutem primam esse puta compescere linguam: Proximus ille deo est qui scit racione tacere.</I></P>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>31.</HEAD>
<L><I>La vertu premere</I></L>
<L><I>Ke a tey seit chere,</I></L>
<L><I>Est lange refreyner;</I></L>
<L><I>A deu est procheyn</I></L>
<L><I>Ke par reson certeyn</I></L>
<L><I>Sceet tere e parler.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="121">Kep &thorn;i tonge skilfulliche:</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste vertu forso&thorn;e hit is;</L>
<L>He is next vnto god</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;at kepe&thorn; hit wel i-wis.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Sperne repungnando tibi tu contrarius esse: Conueniet nulli qui secum desidet ipse.</I></P>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>32.</HEAD>
<L><I>A sey meymes nul ne seyt</I></L>
<L><I>Contrarius en soun dreyt</I></L>
<L><I>Ne endist ne enfance;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar ky ke descorde a sey,</I></L>
<L><I>Od nul autre, cum ieo crey,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne auera concordaunce.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="125">Be not frouward to &thorn;i-self</L>
<L>In word ne in werk:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; such a mon may non acord&mdash;</L>
<L N="128">So telle&thorn; &thorn;e wyse clerk.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Si uitam inspicias hominum, si denique mores, Cum culpas alios nemo sine crimine viuit.</I></P>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>33.</HEAD>
<L><I>Quaunt autre blameras,</I></L>
<L><I>Tey meymes Iugeras</I></L>
<L><I>Tut premerement;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar nul nest ke vit,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne graunt ne petit,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke mout ne mesprent.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="129">Whon &thorn;ou blamest o&thorn;er men,</L>
<L>&THORN;yn oune Iuge &thorn;ou ne be!</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis no mon with-outen lak,</L>
<L N="132">As men may wel ofte i-se.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Que nocturna tenes, quamuis sint cara, relinque: Vtilitas opibus preponi tempore debet.</I>
<PB REF="00000572.tif" N="564"></P>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>34.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ceo qe vous auez cher,</I></L>
<L><I>Dount quidez enpeirer,</I></L>
<L><I>De tey osteras;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar il est</I> profyt</L>
<L><I>Richesse en despyt</I></L>
<L><I>Luer deueras.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="133">&THORN;ing &thorn;at wole apeire &thorn;i stat,</L>
<L>Beo hit &thorn;e neuer so lef,</L>
<L>Hastiliche do hit &thorn;e fro,</L>
<L N="136">Or &thorn;ou &thorn;ole &thorn;e gref.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Constans &amp; lenis ut res expostulat esto: Temporibus mores sapiens sine crimine mutat.</I></P>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>35.</HEAD>
<L><I>Red e suef seyez</I></L>
<L><I>Solum ce ke tu veyez</I></L>
<L><I>Cum les choses ount;</I></L>
<L><I>Ly sages saunz blamer</I></L>
<L><I>Ces mours fet atemprer</I></L>
<L><I>Solum ke les choses sount.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="137">Studefast &amp; stille &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>As &thorn;i catel wol aske:</L>
<L>&THORN;e wyse mon liue&thorn; withouten blame,</L>
<L N="140">ffor he con wel hym taske.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Nil temere uxori de seruis crede querenti: Sepe etenim mulier quem coniux diligit odit.</I></P>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>36.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ne errez folement</I></L>
<L><I>Ta femme, quaunt souent</I></L>
<L><I>De tes seruauns se cleyme:</I></L>
<L><I>Kar souent eschet</I></L>
<L><I>Ke la dame het</I></L>
<L><I>Ceus ky ly syre eyme.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="141">Leeue not &thorn;i wyf fulliche</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i seruans pleynande:</L>
<L>Ofte falle&thorn;, &thorn;e wyf hit hate&thorn;</L>
<L N="144">&THORN;at loue&thorn; &thorn;e goode hosebande.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Cumque mones aliquem nec se uelit ipse moneri, Si tibi sit carus, noli desistere ceptis.</I></P>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>37.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si de ces folies</I></L>
<L><I>A kuns chasties</I>
<PB REF="00000573.tif" N="565"></L>
<L><I>E il ne voyl entendre,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne deyez pur ceo cescer,</I></L>
<L><I>Pur quey le eyez cher,</I></L>
<L><I>Mes plus eplus reprendre.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt chastise eny mon,</L>
<L>&THORN;ouh he loue not &thorn;i lore;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he be dere, leue him nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="148">But vndertake hym more.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Contra verbosos noli contendere verbis: Sermo datur multis, animi sapiencia paucis.</I></P>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>38.</HEAD>
<L><I>En-countre ianglour,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ne eyez deshonour,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne voylles estriuer:</I></L>
<L><I>Kar meynt homme ad iangle</I></L>
<L><I>En vertu de sa lange,</I></L>
<L><I>Est poy de sauer.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="149">A&yogh;eynes men ful of wordes</L>
<L>Stryue &thorn;ow riht nouht:</L>
<L>Wordes is &yogh;iuen to alle men,</L>
<L N="152">And wisdam selden brouht.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Dilige sic alios ut sis tibi carus amicus; Sit bonus esto bonis ne te mala dampna sequantur.</I></P>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>39.</HEAD>
<L><I>Les autres issi amez</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tu a tey meymes seyez</I></L>
<L><I>Cheir a-mys;</I></L>
<L><I>Si seyes bon a bons</I></L>
<L><I>E taunt donez a tuens,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tey ne seyt le pys.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="153">Loue so wel o&thorn;ure men,</L>
<L>&THORN;in oune frend &thorn;at &thorn;ou be;</L>
<L>Beo so good to alle men,</L>
<L N="156">&THORN;at harm from &thorn;e fle.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Rumores fuge, ne incipias nouus auctor haberi: Nam nulli tacuisse nocet, nocet esse locutum.</I></P>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>40.</HEAD>
<L><I>Noueles fuez,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke troue ne seyes</I></L>
<L><I>Blaundour ne tenu;</I></L>
<L><I>Tere ne nuist pas</I>,
<PB REF="00000574.tif" N="566"></L>
<L><I>De parler haut ou bas</I></L>
<L><I>Mal vener ay veu.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="157">Of newe tales &thorn;ou ne be</L>
<L>ffurst makere I-founde:</L>
<L>Wikked tales a-mong men</L>
<L N="160">Bringe&thorn; loue to grounde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Rem tibi promissam certam promittere noli: Rara fides ideo quia multi multa locuntur.</I></P>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>41.</HEAD>
<L><I>Chose a tey promise,</I></L>
<L><I>A autre en nule guise</I></L>
<L><I>Ne le promettez auaunt:</I></L>
<L><I>En le mound y ad poy de fey,</I></L>
<L><I>Meynt homme est dreyt en sey</I></L>
<L><I>ffauours e blaundiaunt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="161">&THORN;ing &thorn;at &thorn;e by-hoten is,</L>
<L>Loke on none wyse</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou bi-hote hit to non o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="164">ffor &thorn;er mihte strif aryse.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Cum te aliquis laudat iudex tuus esse memento: Plus alijs de te quam tu tibi credere noli.</I></P>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>42.</HEAD>
<L><I>Quaunt tu tey orras loyer,</I></L>
<L><I>Iuggez en toun quer</I></L>
<L><I>Ly quel est veir ou noun,</I></L>
<L><I>Eia autre ne creyez</I></L>
<L><I>De vertu ke tu eyez.</I></L>
<L><I>Plus ke ta resoun.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="165">&YOGH;if men preise &thorn;e for godnesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;in oune herte &thorn;ou tast;</L>
<L>Leeue non bettre &thorn;en &thorn;i self,</L>
<L N="168">Whe&thorn;er &thorn;ou &thorn;at vertu hast.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Officium alterius multis narrare memento, Atque alijs cum tu benefeceris ipse sileto:</I></P>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>43.</HEAD>
<L><I>A autri seruisez</I></L>
<L><I>Voyl ke tu preysez</I></L>
<L><I>De-uaunt tote gent;</I></L>
<L><I>Mes quant tu bien fras,</I></L>
<L><I>Ia nent enparleras</I></L>
<L><I>Par moun loement.</I>
<PB REF="00000575.tif" N="567"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="169">&THORN;ou mai&yogh;t o&thorn;ur mennes goodnesse</L>
<L>Preisen wi&thorn;-outen blame,</L>
<L>But not &thorn;in owne be-fore men,</L>
<L N="172">ffor hit were but a schame.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Multorum cum facta senex &amp; dicta recenses, ffac tibi succurrant iuuenisque feceris ipse.</I></P>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>44.</HEAD>
<L><I>Seiez en ta iuuente</I></L>
<L><I>E metez vostre entente</I></L>
<L><I>De ben dyre e fere;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar quaunt veyllard regeies</I></L>
<L><I>En ces fez e diz,</I></L>
<L><I>Le tuen puissez retrere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="173">Sun, do her in &thorn;i &yogh;ou&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;ing &thorn;at &thorn;e mouwe helpe;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou art an old mon aftur,</L>
<L N="176">&THORN;erof &thorn;enne mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou &yogh;elpe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Ne cures siquis tacito sermone loquatur: Conscius ipse sibi de se putat omnia dici.</I></P>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>45.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si homme nuil ren</I></L>
<L><I>A vous parout ben,</I></L>
<L><I>Ia ne eizes enui;</I></L>
<L><I>Ky ke mauueis se sent,</I></L>
<L><I>Il quide ke tote gent</I></L>
<L><I>Parlent de ly.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="177">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou seo men speke stille,</L>
<L>A-Meoued beo &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;e wikked mon wene&thorn; &thorn;at alle men</L>
<L N="180">Haue him in heore &thorn;ouht.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Cum fueris felixque sunt aduersa caueto: Non eodem cursu respondent (vltima) primis.</I></P>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>46.</HEAD>
<L><I>Taunt cum es benure,</I></L>
<L><I>En-countre aduersyte</I></L>
<L><I>Deuez vous eschure;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar le comencement</I></L>
<L><I>E le defynement</I></L>
<L><I>Ne sount pas de vne mesure.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="181">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou, mon, be meke and mylde,</L>
<L>ffleo al frouward &thorn;ing;
<PB REF="00000576.tif" N="568"></L>
<L>&THORN;e laste tale to &thorn;e furste</L>
<L N="184">&YOGH;if non onsweryng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Cum dubia &amp; fragilis sit nobis uita tributa, In mortem alterius spem tu tibi ponere noli.</I></P>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>47.</HEAD>
<L><I>Kant si est dotouse</I></L>
<L><I>E freille e perilouse</I></L>
<L><I>Vostre vye ici,</I></L>
<L><I>Mout est graunt enfance</I></L>
<L><I>Pur mettre sei en esperance</I></L>
<L><I>En la mort de autri.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="185">&para; Si&thorn;en &thorn;at vre lyf is frele</L>
<L>&THORN;at to vs alle is &yogh;iuen,</L>
<L>In non o&thorn;ur monnes de&thorn;</L>
<L N="188">Hope &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t to liuen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Exiguum munus cum det tibi pauper amicus, Accipito placide, plene laudare memento.</I></P>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>48</HEAD>
<L><I>Kant vn petit doun</I></L>
<L><I>Tei ad en baundoun</I></L>
<L><I>De toun poure amy,</I></L>
<L><I>Reseue&yogh; le bonement,</I></L>
<L><I>E plenerement</I></L>
<L><I>Tene&yogh; par tut dely.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="189">&YOGH;if eny of &thorn;i pore frendes</L>
<L>&YOGH;iue &thorn;e a &yogh;ift smal,</L>
<L>Receyue &thorn;ou hit ble&thorn;eliche,</L>
<L N="192">And &thorn;onk him feire &thorn;ou schal.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Infantem nudum cum te natura creauit, Paupertatis onus pacienter ferre memento.</I></P>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>49.</HEAD>
<L><I>Kant en le mound venistis vif,</I></L>
<L><I>Poure e cheytif,</I></L>
<L><I>E nu e dolent,</I></L>
<L><I>Le charge de pouerte,</I></L>
<L><I>De meseyse e de pite</I></L>
<L><I>Suffre&yogh; le bonement.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="193">&para; Si&thorn;en &thorn;at kynde ha&thorn; &thorn;e formed</L>
<L>A luytel naked chylde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e charge of pouert loke &thorn;ou bere,</L>
<L N="196">And beo bo&thorn;e meke &amp; mylde.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000577.tif" N="569">
<P>&para; <I>Ne timeas illam que uite est ultima finis: Qui mortem metuit amittit gaudia uite.</I></P>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>50.</HEAD>
<L><I>Kant tei estut morir</I></L>
<L><I>E a ta fyn vener,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne deye&yogh; la mort doter;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar ky doute la mort,</I></L>
<L><I>Ia ioye ne desport</I></L>
<L><I>Ne put en le mound auer.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="197">&para; Whon &thorn;ou schalt nedelich ones dye</L>
<L>And he&thorn;ene awey to wende,</L>
<L>Doute hit not, for &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;er-of</L>
<L N="200">Mihte &thorn;e fulliche schende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Si tibi pro meritis nemo respondet amicus, Incusare deum noli, set te ipse coerce.</I></P>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>51.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si nul amy en fei</I></L>
<L><I>Ne respoygne a tey</I></L>
<L><I>De bens ke fet li as,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne uoylle&yogh; deu blamer;</I></L>
<L><I>Tei deue&yogh; refrener,</I></L>
<L><I>E ly ne blameras.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="201">&para; &YOGH;if no mon onswere to &thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;i goddede bi nome,</L>
<L>Wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;e not &thorn;erfore wi&thorn; god,</L>
<L N="204">Bote &thorn;i-seluen blame.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Ne tibi quid desit quesitis, vtere parce; Vt-que quod est serues, semper tibi deesse putato.</I></P>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>52.</HEAD>
<L><I>Le tuen purchas despent</I></L>
<L><I>Esparniablement</I></L>
<L><I>Solum ceo qe vous veye&yogh; mester;</I></L>
<L><I>E quyde&yogh; tote veys,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tu ren ne eye&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Pur ben le meu&yogh; garder.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="205">&para; Spene &thorn;i good mesurabliche,</L>
<L>Purchased &thorn;au&yogh; &thorn;ei be;</L>
<L>And hope alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast</L>
<L N="208">Awey mihte falle from &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quod prestare potes, ne bis promiseris vlli, Ne sis uentosus dum vis bonus esse videri.</I>
<PB REF="00000578.tif" N="570"></P>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>53.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ne promette&yogh; pas souent,</I></L>
<L><I>Done&yogh; mout doucement</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo ke vole&yogh; doner,</I></L>
<L><I>Kar ne seye&yogh; auauntour</I></L>
<L><I>Dount vous voylle&yogh; honour</I></L>
<L><I>E los epris auer.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="209">&para; &THORN;ing also &thorn;at &thorn;ou may &yogh;iue,</L>
<L>Twyes bi-hote hit nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Beo not ful of wikked wynt</L>
<L N="212">And leose not &thorn;i fore &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Qui simulat verbis, nec corde est fidus amicus; Tu quoque fac simile: sic ars deluditur arte.</I></P>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>54.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si acuns par parler,</I></L>
<L><I>E ne mye de quer,</I></L>
<L><I>Se feyne toun amy,</I></L>
<L><I>Deceyue&yogh; art par art,</I></L>
<L><I>E de la tue part</I></L>
<L><I>fface&yogh; a-taunt dely.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="213">&para; Hose feyne&thorn; him frend with word</L>
<L>And not wi&thorn; herte stable,</L>
<L>With such a seruyse serue &thorn;ou him,</L>
<L N="216">And telle him tale of fable.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Noli homines blando nimium sermone probare: ffistula dulce canit volucrem dum decipit auceps.</I></P>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>55.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ne voylles losenger</I></L>
<L><I>Ne homme trop loer,</I></L>
<L><I>ffors ke solum le dreit;</I></L>
<L><I>Doucement chaunte le frestel,</I></L>
<L><I>Quant le oysellour le oysel</I></L>
<L><I>Trait a deceit.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="217">&para; Preyse no mon but in his riht</L>
<L>With no losengerye;</L>
<L>&THORN;e foulere chacche&thorn; briddes feole</L>
<L N="220">Wi&thorn; swete melodye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum tibi sint nati nec opes, tunc artibus illos Instrue, quo possint inopem defendere vitam.</I></P>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>56.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si vous ne eyes manans</I></L>
<L><I>E aue&yogh; mout enfauns</I>,
<PB REF="00000579.tif" N="571"></L>
<L><I>ffetes les aprendre</I></L>
<L><I>Acune menestraucie,</I></L>
<L><I>Par vnt ke il pussent la vye</I></L>
<L><I>de pouerte defendere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="221">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou haue children monye</L>
<L>And goodes none bute smale,</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;ou hem to craft sette,</L>
<L N="224">&THORN;er-wi&thorn; to beeten heore bale.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quod vile est, carum; quod carum, vile putato: Sic tibi nec cupidus, nec auarus nosceris vlli.</I></P>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>57.</HEAD>
<L><I>Dount autres vnt cherte</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo eye&yogh; en vilte,</I></L>
<L><I>E le vil eye&yogh; cher:</I></L>
<L><I>E ia nyers blame</I></L>
<L><I>Pur escharcete</I></L>
<L><I>Ne pur coueyter.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="225">&para; &THORN;at is good chep may beo dere,</L>
<L>And deore good chep also;</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou beo not coueytous</L>
<L N="228">Ne gredi ek &thorn;er-to.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Que culpare soles, ea tu ne feceris ipse: Turpe est doctori, cum culpa redarguit ipsum.</I></P>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>58.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ceo ke tu veus blamer,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne voylle&yogh; pas amer</I></L>
<L><I>Ne fere pur nul plet:</I></L>
<L><I>Il ne auent a nuly</I></L>
<L><I>De blamer autry</I></L>
<L><I>De ceo ke il meymes fet.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="229">&para; &THORN;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou art wont to blame,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou do hit nouht!</L>
<L>Schome hit is a mon to blame</L>
<L N="232">&THORN;ing &thorn;at he ha&thorn; wrouht.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quod iustum est, petito, vel quod videatur honestum: Nam stultum est petere, quod possit iure negari.</I></P>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>59.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si fere veus requeste,</I></L>
<L><I>Pense&yogh; come honeste</I></L>
<L><I>Tu le pusse&yogh; fere;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar ceo ke len pardreyt</I>
<PB REF="00000580.tif" N="572"></L>
<L><I>En-countre dyre deit,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne fet pas a requere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="233">&para; Aske &thorn;ing &thorn;at rihtful is</L>
<L>Or honest in &thorn;i siht:</L>
<L>ffolye hit is to aske &thorn;e good</L>
<L N="236">&THORN;at is to werne wi&thorn; riht.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Ignotum tibi tu noli preponere notis: Cognita iudicio constant[i], incognita casu.</I></P>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>60.</HEAD>
<L><I>Tut tens eye&yogh; tu</I></L>
<L><I>Plus priue le conou</I></L>
<L><I>Ke le trespassaunt;</I></L>
<L><I>Ta chose ne quere&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Quant auer le deue&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Purueye&yogh; tei ben auaunt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="237">&para; Loue bettre a knowen frend</L>
<L>&THORN;en mon of fer cuntre:</L>
<L>&THORN;orw de-faute of knoweleching</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;ou mai&yogh;t i-greued be.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[<I>Lines</I> 245-8, 'Sum tyme . . . . .in riht' <I>follow wrongly here in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum dubia in certis uersetur vita periculis,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[periclis, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>Pro lucro tibi pone diem,</I> <NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. qui . . . . .]</NOTE> <I>quocumque laboras.</I></P>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>61.</HEAD>
<L><I>Quant vie est en peril</I></L>
<L><I>En I-cest exil</I></L>
<L><I>Ce est dolour a pert,</I></L>
<L><I>Ki ke vnkes es en labour</I></L>
<L><I>ffacet ke checun iour</I></L>
<L><I>de gayner seies cert.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="241">&para; Si&thorn;en dredful is de&thorn;, diliueret</L>
<L>In eor&thorn;e to al monkunne,</L>
<L>Do &thorn;i labour eueri day</L>
<L N="244">Sum good forte winne.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Vincere cum possis, interdum vince ferendo;</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[cede sodali, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>Obsequio quoniam dulces retinentur amici.</I></P>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>62.</HEAD>
<L>&para; <I>Quant veindre en puras,</I></L>
<L><I>Souent len durras</I></L>
<L><I>A toun cher cumpaynoun;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar nyert la mort parfyt</I></L>
<L><I>Si renes est fet ou dyt</I></L>
<L><I>Ki de-plese a hom.</I>
<PB REF="00000581.tif" N="573"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="245">&para; Sum tyme spare &thorn;i felawe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[The MS. has l. 245-8 after l. 240.]</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou ouercome him miht;</L>
<L>Parfyt loue is &thorn;er non</L>
<L N="248">Whon &yogh;e striue in riht.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[<I>Lines</I> 249-252, 'To &yogh;eue luitel . . . . .lete,' <I>wrongly follow here in the MS., and are also repeated in their proper place.</I>]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Ne dubites, cum magna petas, impendere parua: Hiis etenim rebus coniungit gracia caros.</I></P>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>63.</HEAD>
<L>&para; <I>Ne dote&yogh; pas ou tu oses,</I></L>
<L><I>Ou tu requers graunt choses</I></L>
<L><I>Le petis doner;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar veises amis</I></L>
<L><I>Solum ce ke mest auis</I></L>
<L><I>Par taunt entre amer.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="249">To &yogh;eue luitel, dred &thorn;e nou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[See note above.]</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ou askest grete</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i frendes and neihebors&mdash;</L>
<L N="252">&THORN;at costum wol not lete.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Litem inferre caue, cum quo tibi gracia iuncta est: Ira odium generat, concordia nutrit amorem.</I></P>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>64.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ne moue&yogh; ia toun corn</I></L>
<L><I>En-vers toun compaynon</I></L>
<L><I>Ne en-vers toun bien veilaunt;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar Ire engendre haiour,</I></L>
<L><I>E concorde amour&mdash;</I></L>
<L><I>Garde&yogh; vous partaunt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="253">&para; To &thorn;i felawe wel willynge</L>
<L>Sture &thorn;ou no chidynge;</L>
<L>Wra&thorn;&thorn;e gedere&thorn; gret hate,</L>
<L N="256">Loue norissche&thorn; sau&yogh;tynge.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Seruorum ob culpam</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Servorum culpa, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>cum te dolor vrget in Iram, Ipse tibi moderare, tuis ut parcere possis.</I></P>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>65.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si tu pur mesfet,</I></L>
<L><I>Ki toun seruaunt ad fet,</I></L>
<L><I>As del Ire al quer,</I></L>
<L><I>Tei meymes a-mesure,</I></L>
<L><I>Ki puisset a cel houre</I></L>
<L><I>A tuens esparnier.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="257">&para; &YOGH;if serwe of gult of seruauns</L>
<L>Wol &thorn;e bringe in care,
<PB REF="00000582.tif" N="574"></L>
<L>I rede &thorn;ou tempre &thorn;e so wel</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;at tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ou hem spare.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para;  <I>Quem superarepotes, interdum uince ferendo; Maxima etenim morum est</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Maxima enim morum, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>semper paciencia virtus.</I></P>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>66.</HEAD>
<L><I>Quaunt tu aueras pouer</I></L>
<L><I>De autre sourmounter,</I></L>
<L><I>Donke vendras par suffraunce;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar estre pacient</I></L>
<L><I>Est graunt a-faitement,</I></L>
<L><I>E meynt homme auaunce.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="261">&THORN;e mon &thorn;at &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t ouergo,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; suffrance him ouercome;</L>
<L>Meknes is vertu gret</L>
<L N="264">Wi&thorn; pure riht of dome.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Conserua pocius, que sunt iam parta labore: Cum labor in dampno est, crescit mortalis egestas.</I></P>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>67.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ce garde&yogh; sagement</I></L>
<L><I>Ki tu nomement</I></L>
<L><I>As conquis par labour;</I></L>
<L><I>Quant est en perte,</I></L>
<L><I>Donke crest mortele pouerte</I></L>
<L><I>E anguisse e dolour.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">&para; &THORN;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast gederet</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret bisynesse,</L>
<L>Wysliche &thorn;ou hem spene,</L>
<L N="268">ffor pereles more and lesse.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Dapsilis interdum notis &amp; carus amicis; Cum fueris felix, semper tibi proximus esto.</I></P>
<LG N="68" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>68.</HEAD>
<L><I>A tei conu&yogh; die&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Seie&yogh; a tote fee&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Large a Mesure;</I></L>
<L><I>Mes plus seie&yogh; amy</I></L>
<L><I>A tei ke a autri,</I></L>
<L><I>Tant cum ben tei dure.</I><NOTE PLACE="inter">[four English lines omitted: also out of Addit. 22,283.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>[<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harl. MS. 4657]</NOTE><I>Telluris si forte u]elis cognoscere cultus,</I> [<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harl. MS. 4657]</NOTE><I>Virgilium le]gito; quod si mage nosse laboras</I></P>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>69.</HEAD>
<L>[<I>Si tu</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Addit. 22,283,<MILESTONE N="120:3" UNIT="folio">]</NOTE>] <I>voles sauer,</I></L>
<L>[<I>Dois ta t</I>]<I>eres cultifier</I>
<PB REF="00000583.tif" N="575"></L>
<L>[<I>Ke</I>] <I>ble ne fayle mye,</I></L>
<L><I>Virgile liset&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>En sauer enpurre&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>A-se&yogh; de gramarie.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="269">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt knowe &thorn;e til&thorn;e of eor&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e fayle corn none,</L>
<L>Go and red virgiles bok&mdash;</L>
<L N="272">&THORN;e craft he tau&yogh;te vchone.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <NOTE PLACE="foot">Harl. MS. 4657, leaf 40 back, at foot, prefixes this spurious line: 'Humanos si forte uelis depellere morbos;' but MS. Harl. 116, leaf 106 back, of B. Burgh's <I>Cato</I>, has, rightly, only the one line of the text above.</NOTE> <I>Herbarum vires, Macer tibi carmine dicet.</I></P>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>70.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si vous vole&yogh; ffisicien</I></L>
<L><I>Estre e sauer bien</I></L>
<L><I>Doner les medicines,</I></L>
<L><I>Macer, ke ne ment,</I></L>
<L><I>Les grauns vertues aprent</I></L>
<L><I>De herbes ede Racynes.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="273">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt ben a ffisicien,</L>
<L>ffor vueles to &yogh;iuen bote,</L>
<L>Macer &thorn;e streng&thorn;e of grases telles,</L>
<L N="276">Bo&thorn;e of crop and Rote.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Si roma[na] cupis &amp; punica noscere bella, Lucanum queras, qui martis prelia dicet.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[dixit, V. R.]</NOTE></P>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>71.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si voil ke tu ne fayles,</I></L>
<L><I>De sauer les batayles</I></L>
<L><I>De Aufrike e de Rome,</I></L>
<L><I>Lucan aperne&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Kar i-leok troueres</I></L>
<L><I>De Batayle la somme.</I></L>
<L N="277">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt knowe &thorn;e Batayle</L>
<L>Of Aufrik or of Rome,</L>
<L>Red a Bok &thorn;at hette Lucan,</L>
<L N="280">He wol &thorn;e telle vchone.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Si quid amare libet, uel discere amare legendo, Nasonem petito: [sin autem tibi cura</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[cura tibi, V. R., and Addit. MS. 22,283.]</NOTE> <I>hec est</I>, (Harl. MS. 116, lf. 107)]</P>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>72.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si vole&yogh; sauer amours,</I></L>
<L><I>Come ly plusours</I>,
<PB REF="00000584.tif" N="576"></L>
<L><I>Lise&yogh; les Ouides,</I></L>
<L><I>E tost saueras amer,</I></L>
<L><I>E plus des ami&yogh; aueres</I></L>
<L><I>Ki tu ne quides.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="281">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt witen of derne loue</L>
<L>And haue &thorn;i fflessches wille,</L>
<L>Sech Ouide: he con &thorn;e telle</L>
<L N="284">&THORN;e Maners loude and stille.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <SUP>1</SUP><I>Sin autem cura tibi hec est,</I><SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="N1">[1_1 This belongs metrically to the last couplet, as in Addit. 22, 283: see p. 575.]</NOTE> <I>ut sapiens uiuas, audi, que discere possis.</I></P>
<P><I>Per que semotum uiciis deducitur eu[u]m.</I></P>
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>73.</HEAD>
<L><I>E si de cest nas cure,</I></L>
<L><I>Mes sen e mesure,</I></L>
<L><I>Voyle&yogh; aprendre</I></L>
<L><I>Par ount come sage</I></L>
<L><I>Puisset toun corage</I></L>
<L><I>De uices defendre.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="285">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt liue wisliche,</L>
<L>In &yogh;ou&thorn;e &thorn;i lyf amende;</L>
<L>In &thorn;in elde &thorn;ow mai&yogh;t betere</L>
<L N="288">ffrom vices &thorn;e defende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Ergo ades; &amp; que sit sapiencia, disce legendo.</I></P>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>74.</HEAD>
<L><I>Verie&yogh;</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[? Venez]</NOTE> <I>donke auaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>Si orras en lisaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>Si voile&yogh; entendre,</I></L>
<L><I>Syre, coynteyse,</I></L>
<L><I>Ben e bone a-prise</I></L>
<L><I>Voyl en tei despendre.</I></L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, as in Addit. 22,283.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Si potes, ignotis eciam prodesse memento: Vtilius regno est, meritis adquirere amicos.</I></P>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>75.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si vous poye&yogh;, a tou&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>A cuns e meylours</I></L>
<L><I>Pense&yogh; de profiter;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar ben e honour fre&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>E les amis conquere&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke uaut meu&yogh; qe regner.</I></L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, as in Addit. 22,283.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<PB REF="00000585.tif" N="577">
<P><I>Mitte archana dei, celum</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[coelumque, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>inquirere quit sit; Cum sis mortalis, que sunt mortalia, cura.</I></P>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>76.</HEAD>
<L><I>Quant tu es mortel,</I></L>
<L><I>Les estres de ciel</I></L>
<L><I>Ne deue&yogh; vous enquere;</I></L>
<L><I>A dampne deu lesses</I></L>
<L><I>Auer les priuites</I></L>
<L><I>De ciel e de tere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="289">&para; Enquere not of priuites</L>
<L>Of God ne eke of heuene;</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en &thorn;at &thorn;ou art dedliche,</L>
<L N="292">Keep &thorn;e in &thorn;i weies euene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Linque metum leti; nam, stultum est tempore in omni; Dum mortem metuis, amittis</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[amittere, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>gaudia vite.</I></P>
<LG N="77" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>77.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ne dotes pas la mort,</I></L>
<L><I>Quant ceo est nostre sort;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar mout serreit folye</I></L>
<L><I>Pur pour de la mort</I></L>
<L><I>De perdre le desport</I></L>
<L><I>Ki est en ceste vye.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="293">&para; fforsak &thorn;ow &thorn;e drede of de&thorn;,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en hit &thorn;in Auntur is;</L>
<L>He leose&thorn; &thorn;e Ioye of his lyf</L>
<L N="296">&THORN;at doute&thorn; hit, I-wis.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Iratus de re incerta contendere noli: Impedit ira animum, ne possit cernere uerum.</I></P>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>78.</HEAD>
<L><I>Quant tu es irre&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>De chose ne estriue&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Dount nestes certifie;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar Ire le corage</I></L>
<L><I>Desturbe, ke il ne seit sage</I></L>
<L><I>De entendre verite.</I></L>
<L N="297">&para; Striue no &thorn;ing in &thorn;i wra&thorn;&thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ing vn-certeyne;</L>
<L>Wra&thorn;&thorn;e destruye&thorn; monnes wit,</L>
<L N="300">Whon so&thorn; may not beo sei&yogh;ene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>ffac sumptum propere, cum res desiderat ipsa; Dapsilis interdum,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Dandum etenim est aliquid, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>cum tempus postulat aut res.</I>
<PB REF="00000586.tif" N="578"></P>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>79.</HEAD>
<L><I>Tes despenses despent</I></L>
<L><I>Mout corteisement</I></L>
<L><I>En beyuere e en viaunde,</I></L>
<L><I>Kar tei estot despendre</I></L>
<L><I>Solum ke poye&yogh; entendre</I></L>
<L><I>Ke le tens demaunde.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="301">Sum-while spend Mete and drink</L>
<L>Hastiliche, I rede;</L>
<L>Hit falle&thorn; mon to spende his good</L>
<L N="304">Whon tyme hit wole in stede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quod nimium est, fugito, paruo gaudere memento; Tuta magis</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[mage est, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>puppis, modico que flumine fertur.</I></P>
<LG N="80" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>80.</HEAD>
<L><I>De Mesure hayes,</I></L>
<L><I>De petit seie&yogh; lees,</I></L>
<L><I>Kar ceo est mesure;</I></L>
<L><I>La nef ke veut sor le vnde</I></L>
<L><I>Ke guerres nest parfounde,</I></L>
<L><I>Plus est enseure.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="305">&para; To make mur&thorn;e of luitel &thorn;ing;</L>
<L>To muche, &thorn;ou hit fleo;</L>
<L>Schip is more siker in luitel water</L>
<L N="308">&THORN;en in &thorn;e deope s&eacute;&eacute;.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quod pudeat, socios prudens celare</I> memento: <I>Ne plures culpent id, quod tibi displicet uni.</I></P>
<LG N="81" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>81.</HEAD>
<L><I>Coyntement cele&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ne seit vergonde&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Les fe&yogh; ton compaynoun;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar plusours partey</I></L>
<L><I>Blamerunt en dreit de sei</I></L>
<L><I>Ces mesfe&yogh; en comun.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="309">&para; Hele &thorn;ing &thorn;at schame&thorn; men,</L>
<L>Qweynte mon &yogh;if &thorn;ou beo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er men blame not</L>
<L N="312">&THORN;ing &thorn;at greue&thorn; &thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harl. MS. 4657,<MILESTONE N="91b" UNIT="folio">]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Nolo putes, prauos homines peccata lucrari: Temporibus peccata latent, &amp;</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[sed, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>tempore parent.</I></P>
<LG N="82" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>82.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ne voyl qe vous guide&yogh;</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[quidez. Addit. 22,283.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Ne dais quider ke male gent</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Ke homme par pecches</I>
<PB REF="00000587.tif" N="579"></L>
<L>[<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. torn away. Supplied from Addit. MS. 22,283.]</NOTE> <I>Puisse ren</I>] <I>gayner</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><Q><L>ke pecche aiment, e le funt suuent,</L><L>ke pru emporterunt;</L><L>Ne pot ester ke tus pecches</L><L>ke or sunt cuuers, e cel&eacute;&eacute;s;</L><L>En aucun tens se mustrunt.]</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>[<I>Kar pecche</I>]<I>s escapisent</I></L>
<L>[<I>E en tens</I>] <I>arere issent</I></L>
<L>[<I>E renden</I>]<I>t mal louer.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="313">[I nul n]ot &thorn;at &thorn;ou hope</L>
<L>Wicked men sunnes winne;</L>
<L>Sunnes askapen ofte in tounes,</L>
<L N="316">And schewen In tyme and blinne.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Corporis</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. corpus]</NOTE> <I>exigui vires contempnere noli: Consilio pollet, cui uim natura negauit.</I></P>
<LG N="83" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>83.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ne eie&yogh; en despit</I></L>
<L><I>La force del petit,</I></L>
<L><I>Kar se ne uaut guere;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar la ou force faut,</I></L>
<L><I>Bon counseil vaut,</I></L>
<L><I>Quant homme ad a fere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="317">&para; Ne haue &thorn;ou not in dispit</L>
<L>&THORN;e bodi of luitel mon:</L>
<L>In pes and werre &thorn;er streng&thorn;e is wone,</L>
<L N="320">Good wisdam ofte he con.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quem</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Cui, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>scieris non esse parem [te</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>tibi</I>, Addit. 22,283.]</NOTE> <I>tempore cede: Victorem a uicto superari sepe videmus.</I></P>
<LG N="84" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>84.</HEAD>
<L><I>Souent desporteras</I></L>
<L><I>Cely ke pluis bas</I></L>
<L><I>De tei est, e mynour:</I></L>
<L><I>Kar nous aoums veu</I></L>
<L><I>Souent le vencu</I></L>
<L><I>Reueyndre le vencour.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="321">&para; &THORN;ouh a mon be not &thorn;i peere,</L>
<L>ffor-bere &thorn;ou him in cas:</L>
<L>Ofte we seon &thorn;e strengor falle</L>
<L N="324">&THORN;orw him &thorn;at feblore was.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Aduersus</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. Aduersum]</NOTE> <I>notum noli contendere verbis: Lis minimis verbis interdum maxima cressit.</I></P>
<LG N="85" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>85.</HEAD>
<L><I>A conu ne od pier</I></L>
<L><I>Ne voiles estriuer,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne en Ieu ne adecertes;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar graunt cuntek souent</I>
<PB REF="00000588.tif" N="580"></L>
<L><I>De poy sourt entre gent,</I></L>
<L><I>Dount venent graunt pertes.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="325">&para; A&yogh;eines knowen mon ne frend,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne striue;</L>
<L>Gret contek of smale wordes</L>
<L N="328">Waxe&thorn; ofte ful ryue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Quod</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Quid, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>deus intendat, noli perquirere sorte; Quod</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Quid, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>statuit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[statuat, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>de te, sine te deliberat ipse.</I></P>
<LG N="86" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>86.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ne voile&yogh; pas enquere</I></L>
<L><I>Par sort ke deu voyl fere</I></L>
<L><I>De tei ne de autri;</I></L>
<L><I>Mes serf tei face&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Souent les salue&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>E tut tei mettes en ly.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="329">&para; Aske not what god wol do</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e world bi cas;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;e and o&thorn;ur alle</L>
<L N="332">He mai worche wi&thorn; his gras.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Inuidiam nimio cultu uitare memento; Que si non ledat</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ledit, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>tamen hanc sufferre molestum est.</I></P>
<LG N="87" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>87.</HEAD>
<L><I>Pur eschure envye,</I></L>
<L><I>Garde&yogh; ke ne seyes mye</I></L>
<L><I>Trop noble de vesture;</I></L>
<L><I>Si homme ne nust grauntment,</I></L>
<L><I>ffolye fust ne quident</I></L>
<L><I>E envye sa porture.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="333">&para; Envye, wi&thorn; gret bisinesse</L>
<L>Beo-&thorn;enk &thorn;e forte fleo;</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;er mennes euel fare,</L>
<L N="336">Envye make&thorn; him gleo.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Esto forti animo,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[animo forti, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>cum sis dampnatus inique: Nemo diu gaudet, qui iudice uincit iniquo.</I></P>
<LG N="88" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>88.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si dampne es a tort,</I></L>
<L><I>Garde&yogh; ke seie&yogh; fort</I></L>
<L><I>E ferm en toun corage;</I></L>
<L><I>Nuil homme sen Ioyet longement</I></L>
<L><I>Ky par mal Iugement</I></L>
<L><I>Vit e par outrage.</I>
<PB REF="00000589.tif" N="581"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="337">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou be dampned falsliche,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou beo of wille strong;</L>
<L>No mon Ioye&thorn; long aftur,</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;at ouer-come&thorn; wi&thorn; wrong.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Litis preterite, noli maledicta referre; Post inimicicias iram meminisse, malorum est.</I></P>
<LG N="89" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>89.</HEAD>
<L><I>De tensoun trespasse&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Puis ke il est pardone&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne dei&yogh; le dite&yogh; retrere;</I></L>
<L><I>A pre amistes</I></L>
<L><I>Nest Ire acordes</I></L>
<L><I>Par homme debonere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="341">&para; Of Contek ones for&yogh;iuen,</L>
<L>Reherce no wikkednesse;</L>
<L>&THORN;e wikked mon &thorn;e wikked dedes</L>
<L N="344">Recordet, bo&thorn;e more and lasse.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Nec te collaudes, nec te culpaueris ipse: Hoc faciunt stulti, quos gloria vexat inanis.</I></P>
<LG N="90" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>90.</HEAD>
<L><I>Tei ne deue&yogh; loyer</I></L>
<L><I>Ne tei meymes blamer,</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo eye&yogh; en memorie;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar se fount i ceus</I></L>
<L><I>Ke sount bricons e fous</I></L>
<L><I>E pleyn de veyne glorie.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="345">&para; Preise no mon him-seluen,</L>
<L>Ne blame him-self also;</L>
<L>So don foles, &thorn;at veyn glorie</L>
<L N="348">Trauayle&thorn; euer-mo.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Vtere quesitis modice: cum sumptus abundat, Labitur exiguo, quod partum est tempore longo.</I></P>
<LG N="91" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>91.</HEAD>
<L><I>Done&yogh; e dispent</I></L>
<L><I>Mesurablement,</I></L>
<L><I>Si cum la chose est;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar il est fest en poy detens,</I></L>
<L><I>Quant nest garde par sens,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke long tens quili est.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="349">&para; &YOGH;if and spend a-tempreliche</L>
<L>&THORN;e good &thorn;at &thorn;ou may winne;
<PB REF="00000590.tif" N="582"></L>
<L>Catel is long in gederyng,</L>
<L N="352">And sone a-wei wol renne.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Insipiens esto, cum tempus postulat, aut res: Stulticiam simulare loco prudencia summa est.</I></P>
<LG N="92" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>92.</HEAD>
<L><I>ffol voil qe tu seie&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Solum ceo ke tu veie&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Coment la chose vet;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar cointise est graunt</I></L>
<L><I>Defendre sei noun-sauaunt</I></L>
<L><I>Pur soun esplet.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="353">&para; ffeyne &thorn;e fol, &thorn;ei &thorn;ou be wys,</L>
<L>&THORN;er fooles aren beo-deene;</L>
<L>A Mon to feynen him on &thorn;at wyse</L>
<L N="356">Is wismon, als I wene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Luxuriam fugito, simul &amp; vitare memento Crimen Auaricie; nam sunt contraria fame.</I></P>
<LG N="93" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>93.</HEAD>
<L><I>ffue&yogh; lecherie</I></L>
<L><I>E ne ame&yogh; mye</I></L>
<L><I>Nuil de ces delyces;</I></L>
<L><I>E Auarice ausy;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar ce sache&yogh; de fy,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ceus doynent graunt vices.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="357">&para; Lecherie and Glotenie,</L>
<L>ffleo hem bo&thorn;e bi name;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei ben two wikked vices,</L>
<L N="360">And bringe men ofte in fame.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Noli tu quedam referenti credere semper: Exigua est tribuenda fides, quia multa locuntur.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[loquuntur]</NOTE></P>
<LG N="94" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>94.</HEAD>
<L><I>A ces counteous</I></L>
<L><I>Ne creye&yogh; mye a tous</I></L>
<L><I>Ke countent meynt a fere;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar mout I ad paroles</I></L>
<L><I>ffauces e foles,</I></L>
<L><I>E poi de fei entere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="361">&para; Leeue &thorn;ou not alle mennes tales,</L>
<L>Deceyuet &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne beo;</L>
<L>Mon &thorn;at telle&thorn; mony &thorn;inges,</L>
<L N="364">ffals most nede sum beo.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000591.tif" N="583">
<P>&para; <I>Quod potu</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Quae potus, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>peccas, ignoscere tu tibi noli; Nam nullum crimen uini est, set culpa bibentis.</I></P>
<LG N="95" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>95.</HEAD>
<L><I>A tey ne seit il pardone</I></L>
<L><I>Quant tu es en-yuere</I></L>
<L><I>De beiuere ke mout vaut;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar en le vyn nei&yogh;t il pas</I></L>
<L><I>Ne en la coupe le trespas,</I></L>
<L><I>Mes en le trop beuaunt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="365">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou sunge in drinkyng,</L>
<L>Bi-&thorn;enk &thorn;e of &thorn;at cas;</L>
<L>&THORN;e gult is not in &thorn;e ale ne wyn,</L>
<L N="368">But is &thorn;yn oune trespas.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Concilium archanum tacito committe</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. committere.]</NOTE> <I>sodali: Corporis auxilium medico committe fideli.</I></P>
<LG N="96" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>96.</HEAD>
<L><I>De ta priuite</I></L>
<L><I>A cumpaynoun cele</I></L>
<L><I>Dye&yogh;, e ueye&yogh; ke il ne seit volage;</I></L>
<L><I>Toun cors a mediciner</I></L>
<L><I>A Mire deue&yogh; bayler</I></L>
<L><I>Ke seit lel e sage.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="369">&para; Counseil &thorn;er no foly is,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i felawe &thorn;ou hele;</L>
<L>Put &thorn;i body, whon &thorn;ou art seek,</L>
<L N="372">To leche &thorn;at is lele.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Successus dignos noli tu</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Noli successus indignos, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>ferre moleste: Indulget fortuna malis, ut ledere possit.</I></P>
<LG N="97" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>97.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si par ta deserte</I></L>
<L><I>Tei auygne mal ou</I> perte,</L>
<L><I>Nel preygne&yogh; trop ases;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar fortune esleue</I></L>
<L><I>Les maueis, qe ele les greue</I></L>
<L><I>Plus apren lent apres.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[No English given.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>Lines</I> 373-6, p. 584, 'To suffre . . . . .drede,' <I>wrongly follow here in the Vernon MS., and in the Simeon, Addit. MS.</I> 22,283, <I>leaf</I> 121, <I>col.</I> 2.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Prospice, qui ueniunt, hos casus esse ferendo[s]: Nam leuius ledit, quicquid preuidimus ante.</I></P>
<LG N="98" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>98.</HEAD>
<L><I>Les mals pur meu&yogh; suffrer</I></L>
<L><I>Ke poyent auener,</I></L>
<L><I>Coyntement puruei;</I>
<PB REF="00000592.tif" N="584"></L>
<L><I>De taunt purrount le meyne</I></L>
<L><I>Quant il sount priue dens</I></L>
<L><I>Greuer a tei.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="373">&para; To suffre wo &thorn;at is to comen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Lines 373-6 are a repetition of those on page 583, after no. 97 of the French.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Porueye &thorn;e for nede;</L>
<L>Hap &thorn;at we han sei&yogh;en ar &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="376">Do&thorn; us more to drede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Rebus in aduersis animum submittere noli; Spem retine: spes una hominem nec morte relinquid.</I></P>
<LG N="99" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>99.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ne seie&yogh; sourmounte</I></L>
<L><I>Par nul aduersite,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke vous neie&yogh; tort,</I></L>
<L><I>Mes de bone cheuaunce,</I></L>
<L><I>E eies en esperaunce</I></L>
<L><I>Quant es al poynt de mort.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="377">&para; Dred no tribulacion,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ou hast &thorn;e riht;</L>
<L>Of good hope euer &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L N="380">And stonde with al &thorn;i miht.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Rem, tibi quam noscis aptam, dimittere noli; ffronte capillata, post est occasio calua.</I></P>
<LG N="100" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>100.</HEAD>
<L><I>Chose profitable&mdash;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar fortune est changable&mdash;</I></L>
<L><I>Ne seit de tei lesse;</I></L>
<L><I>Le frount od peil est bel</I></L>
<L><I>Quant le hatirel</I></L>
<L><I>Chauf y ert epele.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Par la frount pelu</I></L>
<L><I>De vous seit entendu</I></L>
<L><I>De riche comensail;</I></L>
<L><I>E par la chef de riers</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tot est auf eres</I></L>
<L><I>Le poure defynail.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="381">&para; Profitable &thorn;ing to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Leeue hit not to &yogh;are;</L>
<L>&THORN;at forehed is lodly</L>
<L N="384">&THORN;at is calouh and bare.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quod sequitur specta: que quod</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[specta: quodque, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>imminet ante, videto; Illum imitare deum, partem qui spectat vtramque.</I>
<PB REF="00000593.tif" N="585"></P>
<LG N="101" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>101.</HEAD>
<L><I>I ceo qe pert deuaunt</I></L>
<L><I>Seie&yogh; entendaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>E ceo ke suyt apres;</I></L>
<L><I>E li deu tot dreit,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke le vn e lautre veyt,</I></L>
<L><I>en sue&yogh; a des.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">&para; Ende and beginnynge of &thorn;i werk</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;ou hem bi-holde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke god folewe bisiliche</L>
<L N="388">&THORN;at alle &thorn;ing ha&thorn; in wolde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>fforcius</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Fortior, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>ut ualeas, interdum parcior esto: Pauca uoluptati debentur, plura saluti.</I></P>
<LG N="102" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>102.</HEAD>
<L><I>Mesurable deyes</I></L>
<L><I>Estre a cune feye&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Tut seie&yogh; Mout pussaunt;</I></L>
<L><I>Mout deyt homme a sante,</I></L>
<L><I>E poy a Iolifte,</I></L>
<L><I>Estre entendaunt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="389">&para; &THORN;e hardiore &thorn;ou holde &thorn;i good,</L>
<L>&THORN;e strengore &thorn;at &thorn;ou be;</L>
<L>Mony &thorn;ing to hele<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. helle.</NOTE> falle,</L>
<L N="392">And fewe to Iolyte.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Iudicium populi numquam contempseris vnus: Ne nulli placeas, dum uis contempnere multos.</I></P>
<LG N="103" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>103.</HEAD>
<L><I>Iammes Iugement</I></L>
<L><I>Ou le peple se consent,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne despise&yogh; soul;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar ky mout despit</I></L>
<L><I>Par fet ou par dit,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne ert ame de nuil.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="393">&para; To Iugement of &thorn;e peple</L>
<L>Dispise &thorn;ou neuere al-one;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at dispise&thorn; mony men,</L>
<L N="396">He is loued of none.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Sit tibi precipue, quod primum est, cura salutis; Tempora ne culpes, cum sit</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[sis, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>tibi causa do[lo]ris.</I></P>
<LG N="104" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>104.</HEAD>
<L><I>Tut premerement</I></L>
<L><I>A ta sancte entent,</I>
<PB REF="00000594.tif" N="586"></L>
<L><I>Quant fei&yogh;tes toun labour;</I></L>
<L><I>Le houre ne blame&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Kar deu par uos pecche&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Le chaunge tot en iour.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="397">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;e bi-fallen serwe on honde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tyme ne blame &thorn;ou nouht;</L>
<L>God, for vre sunnes alle,</L>
<L N="400">Chaunged werk and &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Sompnia ne cures; nam mens humana quod optat</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[optans, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>Dum vigilat, sperat, per sompnum cernit id Ipsum.</I></P>
<LG N="105" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>105.</HEAD>
<L><I>De songe ke vous songe&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Counte ne counte&yogh;;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar quant homme est veilaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>Ce ke il coueit e espeir,</I></L>
<L><I>E puis le veut auer</I></L>
<L><I>Cel meimes en dormaunt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="401">&para; &THORN;ing &thorn;at &thorn;e mette in sweuene,</L>
<L>Telle hit not wakand;</L>
<L>Hit is &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou coueyted</L>
<L N="404">Er longe bi-fore-hand.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Hoc quicumque uelis carmen cognoscere lector, Hec precepta feras</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Quum p. ferat, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>que sunt gratissima uite,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>Commoda multa feres: sin autem spreveris illud, Non me scriptorem, sed te neg|lexeris ipse.</I>]</NOTE></P>
<LG N="106" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>106.</HEAD>
<L><I>Kar ki ke vnkes serras</I></L>
<L><I>Ki cest dit vodras</I></L>
<L><I>En lysaunt entendre,</I></L>
<L><I>Veie&yogh; toun corage</I></L>
<L><I>A tei ke seie&yogh; sage</I></L>
<L><I>E coueite&yogh; a prendre.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="405">REdere, who-so &thorn;at hit be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is dite wol knowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Comaundement with him bere</L>
<L N="408">And nou&yogh;t to hy&yogh;e ne lowe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Instrue preceptis animum, ne</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[nec, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>discere cesses; Nam sine doctrina uita est quasi mortis ymago.</I></P>
<LG N="107" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>107.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ne cesses en toun corage</I></L>
<L><I>De aprendre ke seie&yogh; sage</I></L>
<L><I>Mout amyablement;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar si cum morte ymage</I>
<PB REF="00000595.tif" N="587"></L>
<L><I>Est homme en checun age</I></L>
<L><I>Ky nul ben a prent.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="409">&para; ffor&thorn;ure &thorn;i wille wi&thorn; wisdam</L>
<L>And sese not for to lere;</L>
<L>Monnes lyf is lyk a ded ymage,</L>
<L N="412">Witles &yogh;if hit were.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Commoda multa feres; sin autem spreueris illud, Non me scriptorem, sed te neglexeris ipsum.</I></P>
<LG N="108" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>108.</HEAD>
<L><I>Mout aueras</I> profit,</L>
<L><I>Si tu a cet escrit</I></L>
<L><I>A prendre met ta peyne;</I></L>
<L><I>E si tu ne les lyse&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Pas ne dispise&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>E ffras toun prou demeyne.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="413">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt don aftur me,</L>
<L>Proffyt &thorn;ou schalt haue;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow wolt dispise me not,</L>
<L N="416">&THORN;in oune worschupe &thorn;ou saue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum recte uiuas, ne cures verba malorum; Arbitrii nostri non est quod quisque loquatur.</I></P>
<LG N="109" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>109.</HEAD>
<L><I>Cum vous uiue&yogh; dreit e ben,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne tei seit de ren</I></L>
<L><I>Ky ly maueis dient;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar nad nul de pouwer</I></L>
<L><I>Les bouches estoper</I></L>
<L><I>A ceu&yogh; ke mal vous leyent.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="417">&para; Mekeliche &thorn;ou suffre chidyng</L>
<L>Of fool o&thorn;er of moppe;</L>
<L>Hit is not in vre pouwer</L>
<L N="420">Vche monnes mou&thorn; to stoppe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Productus testis, saluo tamen ante pudore, Quantumcumque potes, celato crimen amici.</I></P>
<LG N="110" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>110.</HEAD>
<L><I>Quant es auaunt mene</I></L>
<L><I>Testemonier verite,</I></L>
<L><I>Sauue&yogh; le tuen honour</I></L>
<L><I>Toun amy sauueras,</I></L>
<L>Quant <I>qi tu purras</I>,
<PB REF="00000596.tif" N="588"></L>
<L><I>De blame de soun seygnour.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Sermones blandos blesosque cauere memento: Simplicitas veri fama est, fraus ficta loquendi.</I></P>
<LG N="111" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>111.</HEAD>
<L><I>Paroles bleysauntes</I></L>
<L><I>E les blandiauntes</I></L>
<L><I>Deue&yogh; vous despire;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar nuil homme ne deit</I></L>
<L><I>A nuly par dreit</I></L>
<L><I>ffeyntement verite dire.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Dyre verite</I></L>
<L><I>En simplicite,</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo est bone fame;</I></L>
<L><I>ffeyntement parler</I></L>
<L><I>E verite celer</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo est boydie e blame.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="421">&para; Swete wordes of losengri,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei beo likande,</L>
<L>Eueriche mon ou&yogh;te hem to fle,</L>
<L N="424">And fals hem vnderstande.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Segniciem fugito, que uite ignauia fertur; Nam cum animus languet, consumit inercia corpus.</I></P>
<LG N="112" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>112.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si tu ne fue&yogh; peresse</I></L>
<L><I>Par dreite destresse,</I></L>
<L><I>Maueis ert ta vye;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar ly quer languirat</I></L>
<L><I>Par taunt cum peresce ad</I></L>
<L><I>Le cors en sa bailye</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="425">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou ne wolt sleu&thorn;e forsake</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ful gret bisynesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;i lyf is badde, &thorn;i bodi sone</L>
<L N="428">Schal falle in seknesse.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Interpone tuis interdum gaudia curis, Vt possis animo quemuis sufferre laborem.</I></P>
<LG N="113" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>113.</HEAD>
<L><I>Entermettre deue&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>De Ioyous estre a la fe&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>E heiter ta nature,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke puisses saun&yogh; damage</I>
<PB REF="00000597.tif" N="589"></L>
<L><I>Suffrir en toun corage</I></L>
<L><I>Le trauayl ke vous vent sure.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="429">&para; Sum tyme to &thorn;i studiing</L>
<L>&THORN;ou puit Ioye euere among;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt betere afturward</L>
<L N="432">Suffre trauayle strong.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Alterius dictum aut factum ne carpseris unquam, Exemplo simuli ne te derideat alter.</I></P>
<LG N="114" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>114.</HEAD>
<L><I>Autri dyt ne fet</I></L>
<L><I>Ne voylles</I> par <I>nuil plet</I></L>
<L><I>Reprendre ne blamer;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar si autre de tey</I></L>
<L><I>Le face en dreyt de cey,</I></L>
<L><I>Il te veut peiser.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="433">&para; O&thorn;ur monnes word ne werk</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne blame,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne mouwe in such a caas</L>
<L N="436">Scorne &thorn;e bi &thorn;e same.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quod tibi sors dederit tabulis supprema notato, Augendo serua, ne sis, quem fama loquatur.</I></P>
<LG N="115" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>115.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ce ke tei chet en sort</I></L>
<L><I>Quant toun Ancestre est mort,</I></L>
<L><I>Entenk le pur ben garder;</I></L>
<L><I>E pur sauuer ta fame,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tu ne eye&yogh; blame,</I></L>
<L><I>Pense&yogh; de ceo anoyter.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="437">&para; &THORN;ing &thorn;at Aunter ha&thorn; &thorn;e &yogh;iuen</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;i frend is ded,</L>
<L>Kep, and saue &thorn;i gode los,</L>
<L N="440">And beo I-holden no qued.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum tibi diuicie superant in fine senecte, Munificus facito uiuas, nec parcus amicis.</I></P>
<LG N="116" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>116.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si a la fyn de ta veilesse</I></L>
<L><I>Tei abounde ta richesse,</I></L>
<L><I>Escars ne seies pas,</I></L>
<L><I>Mes en tens despent</I></L>
<L><I>E dones largement,</I></L>
<L><I>Taunt cum tu purras.</I>
<PB REF="00000598.tif" N="590"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="441">&para; &YOGH;if in &thorn;in ende of &thorn;in elde</L>
<L>&THORN;e falle richesse strong,</L>
<L>Beo not to scars, freliche dispende</L>
<L N="444">&THORN;er neod is euer among.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Vtile consilium dominus ne despice serui; Nullius sensum, si prodest, tempseris vnquam.</I></P>
<LG N="117" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>117.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ne seie&yogh; despisaunt</I></L>
<L><I>Le counseil toun seruaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>Si il est profitable;</I></L>
<L><I>Ne lesse&yogh; le sen de nuly</I></L>
<L><I>Quant tu veie&yogh; desi</I></L>
<L><I>Ke il seit couenable.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="445">&para; Dispise no counseil of &thorn;i mon,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he beo profitable;</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e wit of o&thorn;ur men,</L>
<L N="448">&YOGH;if hit beo resonable.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Rebus &amp; in censu si non est, quod fuit ante, ffac viuas contentus eo, quod postulat vsus.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[q. tempora praebent, V.R.]</NOTE></P>
<LG N="118" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>118.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si tu ne seie&yogh; manaunt</I></L>
<L><I>Cum as este deuaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>Cum ly plusours sount,</I></L>
<L><I>A tei seit suffisaunt</I></L>
<L><I>Le petit e le graunt,</I></L>
<L><I>Solum ke le tens respount.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="449">&para; &YOGH;if hit beo not in &thorn;i catel</L>
<L>As sum-tyme was bi-fore,</L>
<L>Hold &thorn;e payed of &thorn;in hap</L>
<L N="452">And haue non herte sore</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Vxorem fuge ne ducas sub nomine dotis, Nec retinere velis, si ceperit esse molesta.</I></P>
<LG N="119" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>119.</HEAD>
<L><I>ffemme prendre ne deie&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Pur bien ke seit, mes veies</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ele te seit honeste;</I></L>
<L><I>Ne pur nuil desyr</I></L>
<L><I>Ke vole&yogh; reteyner</I></L>
<L><I>Si ele te seit moleste</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<PB REF="00000599.tif" N="591">
<P>&para; <I>Multorum disce exemplo, que facta sequaris, Que fugias; uita est nobis aliena magistra.</I></P>
<LG N="120" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>120.</HEAD>
<L><I>Le ensaumple receyue&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>De mou&yogh;, ke vous sache&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>qey fere e quey lesser;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar quel ke il seit,</I></L>
<L><I>Autri sauer vous deit</I></L>
<L><I>A prendre ou chastier.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="453">&para; Ensaumple tak of mony men</L>
<L>What werkes &thorn;e folewe schal;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lyf of o&thorn;ure goode men</L>
<L N="456">Is Maistres to us alle.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quod potes, id temptes,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>tenta</I>, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>operis ne pondere pressus Succumbat labor, &amp; frustra temptata relinquis.</I></P>
<LG N="121" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>121.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ce ke tu poyes fere,</I></L>
<L><I>Dount quides a chef trere</I></L>
<L><I>Asaie&yogh; en meynte guise,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tey ne tut a pres</I></L>
<L><I>Pur le anuy del fes</I></L>
<L><I>Guerper la tue aprise.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="457">&para; &THORN;at &thorn;ou may assaye wel,</L>
<L>I rede, no more, &thorn;ou bere;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou dost, &thorn;ou lest &thorn;i swik,</L>
<L N="460">And ouer cark wol &thorn;e dere.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quod nosti factum non recte, noli silere,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[haud recte factum, nolito tacere, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>Ne videare malos imitari uelle tacendo.</I></P>
<LG N="122" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>122.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ce ke toun cen veit</I></L>
<L><I>Ouerer en-countre dreit,</I></L>
<L><I>Tere pas ne deies;</I></L>
<L><I>Ke homme ne seit quidaunt</I></L>
<L><I>Ke voyles enteysaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>En suere le maueis.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="461">&para; &THORN;at &thorn;ou wost is euel wra&thorn;&thorn;e,</L>
<L>ffor-hele &thorn;ou hit nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou suwe no wikked mon</L>
<L N="464">In wille nou&thorn;er in &thorn;ouht.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Iudicis auxilium sub iniqua lege rogato; Ipse etiam</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. eniam</NOTE> <I>leges cupiunt, ut iure regantur.</I>
<PB REF="00000600.tif" N="592"></P>
<LG N="123" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>123.</HEAD>
<L><I>Elise&yogh; Iuge a tei,</I></L>
<L><I>Quant tu veye&yogh; ke la ley</I></L>
<L><I>Passe outre gre;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar les dreite leis</I></L>
<L><I>Voylent tote feis</I></L>
<L><I>A dreit estre gouerne.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="465">&para; Aske to &thorn;e help of Iuge,</L>
<L>Vnder wikked lawes;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei wol be gouernet al with riht,</L>
<L N="468">Beo nihtes and bi dawes.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quod merito pateris, pacienter ferre memento, Cumque reus tibi</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[tibi reus, MS.]</NOTE> <I>sis, ipsum te iudice dampna.</I></P>
<LG N="124" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>124.</HEAD>
<L><I>Seie&yogh; pacient,</I></L>
<L><I>Suffres bonement</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo ke as deserui;</I></L>
<L><I>Si tu tei veies coupable,</I></L>
<L><I>Iuges tei a dampnable,</I></L>
<L><I>Nel le mete&yogh; a autri.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="469">&para; &THORN;in harme suffre mildeliche</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou serued wi&thorn; riht,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou gulti deme &thorn;i-self</L>
<L N="472">And non o&thorn;er wiht.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Multa legas</I> fac[i]to: perlectis, perlege<NOTE PLACE="marg">[neglige, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>multa;</I> Nam <I>miranda</I> canunt, <I>sed non</I> credenda, <I>poete.</I></P>
<LG N="125" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>125.</HEAD>
<L><I>Lyse&yogh; mout de dytes</I></L>
<L><I>E plus relise&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Autres mout auere;</I></L>
<L><I>Merueiles dyent grauns</I></L>
<L><I>Ly poyetes en lour chauns,</I></L>
<L><I>Si len les peut crere.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="473">&para; Gedere &thorn;inges in &thorn;in herte</L>
<L>&THORN;at beon to &thorn;in biheue;</L>
<L>&THORN;is poete telle&thorn; of merueyles</L>
<L N="476">&THORN;at aren not alle to leue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Inter conuiuas fac sis sermone modesta,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[modestus, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>Ne dicare loquax dum vis vrbanus haberi.</I></P>
<LG N="126" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>126.</HEAD>
<L><I>Gard tei tote fee&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tu a get ne seye&yogh;</I>
<PB REF="00000601.tif" N="593"></L>
<L><I>fforfetous in parole,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke pur Iangleour</I></L>
<L><I>Ne tey tignent ly plusour,</I></L>
<L><I>Enent pur enseigne.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="477">&para; Among &thorn;i gistes alle</L>
<L>A-tempre be of word,</L>
<L>Beo corteis and Iangle not</L>
<L N="480">&THORN;er &thorn;ou art set at bord.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Coniugis irate noli tu uerba timere; Nam lacrimis struit insidias, dum</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Nam str. ins. lacr., quum, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>femina plorat.</I></P>
<LG N="127" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>127.</HEAD>
<L><I>Quant ta</I> [<I>femme</I>] <I>est yree</I></L>
<L><I>E dit sa rampone,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne tene&yogh; vers ly plet;</I></L>
<L><I>Mes quant ele ploure,</I></L>
<L><I>Gard tei a cel houre,</I></L>
<L><I>Kar donke est en get.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="481">&para; Drede not &thorn;i wyf whon heo is wro&thorn;,</L>
<L>Mak heo hit neuer so stoute;</L>
<L>Whon heo weope&thorn; and make&thorn; deol,</L>
<L N="484">Of hire &thorn;enne is more doute.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Vtere quesitis, sed ne videaris abuti; Qui sua consumunt, cum deest, aliena secuntur.</I></P>
<LG N="128" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>128.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ta chose despent</I></L>
<L><I>Mesurablement,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ele ne tei fayle;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar kike liseon gaste,</I></L>
<L><I>De autri en haste</I></L>
<L><I>Conquera sa vitayle.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>ffac tibi proponas, mortem non esse timendam: Que bona si non est, finis tamen illa malorum est.</I></P>
<LG N="129" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>129.</HEAD>
<L><I>ffete&yogh; taunt en ta vye</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ne estut mye</I></L>
<L><I>Doter mort ne peyne;</I></L>
<L><I>ffyn est de tu&yogh; mals</I></L>
<L><I>Mort, e taunt ly vals</I></L>
<L><I>A ben de soun demeyne.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<PB REF="00000602.tif" N="594">
<P><I>Vxoris linguam, si linguam si frugi est, ferre memento; Namque malum [est] nil uelle pati, nil</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[non v. p., nec, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>posse tacere.</I></P>
<LG N="130" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>130.</HEAD>
<L><I>Soffre&yogh; ta mulier</I></L>
<L><I>Quant la oye&yogh; ben parler,</I></L>
<L><I>En tote repose;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar nent voyler soffrir</I></L>
<L><I>E a voyl poy teyser,</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo est male chose.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Dilige non ega</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Aequa diligito, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>caros pietate parentes, Nec matrem offendas dum uis bonus esse parenti.</I></P>
<LG N="131" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>131.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ame&yogh; te chere parens</I></L>
<L><I>De quer parfit de-dens,</I></L>
<L><I>E nent malement;</I></L>
<L><I>Ne offende&yogh; ta mere,</I></L>
<L><I>Si voylles pleiser toun pere</I></L>
<L><I>E seruer a talent.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="485">&para; ffader and moder loke &thorn;ou loue</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; parfyt herte wi&thorn;-inne;</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne wra&thorn;&thorn;e hem nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="488">Heore benison to winne.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Securam quicumque cupis deducere vitam, Nec uiciis aderre animum, que</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[haerere animos, qui, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>moribus obsunt.</I></P>
<LG N="132" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>132.</HEAD>
<L><I>kike vnkes vie pure</I></L>
<L><I>Honeste e a mesure</I></L>
<L><I>Desire&yogh; amener,</I></L>
<L><I>En toun corage</I></L>
<L><I>Trestut toun age</I></L>
<L><I>De vices deue&yogh; garder.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="489">Siker lyf hose wole</L>
<L>In &thorn;is world abyde,</L>
<L>put his wylle in gode &thorn;ewes,</L>
<L N="492">And alle wikked let slyde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Hec precepta tibi semper relegenda memento: Invenies aliquid, quod te vitare magistro.</I></P>
<LG N="133" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>133.</HEAD>
<L><I>Eie&yogh; en memorie</I></L>
<L><I>Le vers de cest estorie</I></L>
<L><I>Souernelement;</I>
<PB REF="00000603.tif" N="595"></L>
<L><I>Kar chose y troueras</I></L>
<L><I>Ke eschure deueras</I></L>
<L><I>pur toun amendement.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Despice diuicias, si uis animo esse beatus; Quas qui suscipiunt, mendicant semper auari.</I></P>
<LG N="134" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>134.</HEAD>
<L><I>Richesce despise&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Si benure estre vole&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>En toun corage;</I></L>
<L><I>Les coueitous ount</I></L>
<L><I>Petit, e poures sount</I></L>
<L><I>En trestut lour age.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Comoda nature nullo</I> tibi tempore deerunt, <I>Si</I> contentus <I>eo fueris</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Si fueris c. eo, V. R.]</NOTE> quod <I>postulat vsus.</I></P>
<LG N="135" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>135.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ia ne serra le houre</I></L>
<L><I>Kaunt a ta nature</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ne es a plente,</I></L>
<L><I>Pur quei ke sen te dure</I></L>
<L><I>Euoyle&yogh; de mesure</I></L>
<L><I>Estre apaye.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="493">&para; &THORN;e propertes of nature</L>
<L>Redi to &thorn;e &thorn;ei be,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou beo payed of &thorn;at &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="496">&THORN;at god ha&thorn; sent &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum sis in-cautus, nec racione gubernas, Noli fortunam, que non est, dicere cecam.</I></P>
<LG N="136" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>136.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si fous es e bricoun</I></L>
<L><I>E ceo qe as par reson</I></L>
<L><I>Ne gouerne&yogh; mye,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne deies blamer nul houre</I></L>
<L><I>Pur ta mesauenture,</I></L>
<L><I>Mes meymes ta folye.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="497">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou beo no queynte mon</L>
<L>To gouerne &thorn;i bailye,</L>
<L>Blame not Aunter afterward,</L>
<L N="500">But wite hit &thorn;i folye.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000604.tif" N="596">
<P>&para; <I>Dilige denarium,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[denari, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>set parce dilige, formam, Quem nemo sanctus nec honestus captat habere.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[ab aere, V. R.]</NOTE></P>
<LG N="137" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>137.</HEAD>
<L><I>Nent pur sa beute,</I></L>
<L><I>Mes pur la necessite,</I></L>
<L><I>Ame&yogh; le dener;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar ceo est la somme,</I></L>
<L><I>Nuil seint ne honest homme</I></L>
<L><I>Nele coueit a auer.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="501">&para; Loue &thorn;e peny for &thorn;e nede,</L>
<L>ffor o&thorn;er beute non;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy mon coueite&thorn; hit not</L>
<L N="504">No more &thorn;en a ston.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum fueris locuples, corpus curare memento; Eger diues habet nummos, set non habet ipsum.</I></P>
<LG N="138" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>138.</HEAD>
<L><I>Pur garer toun cors,</I></L>
<L><I>Despent tes treshors,</I></L>
<L><I>Graunt ben a tei fra</I></L>
<L><I>Prenk ke poies auer,</I></L>
<L><I>Le riche nad nuil dener</I></L>
<L><I>Quant sey meimes na.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="505">&para; Spene &thorn;i tresour, feyne &thorn;e not,</L>
<L>&THORN;i bodi for to hele;</L>
<L>What prou may &thorn;i catel do,</L>
<L N="508">But hele wol with &thorn;e dele?</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Verbera cum tuleris discens aliquando magistri, ffer patris imper[i]um,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[ingenium, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>cum verbis exit in iram.</I></P>
<LG N="139" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>139.</HEAD>
<L><I>Quant acun houre</I></L>
<L><I>Suffres la batoure</I></L>
<L><I>Del mei&yogh;tre pur aprendre,</I></L>
<L><I>Ben deis toun pere en Ire</I></L>
<L><I>Soffrir de tei mesdire,</I></L>
<L><I>E ne mye tei defendre.</I></L>
<L N="509">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou haue soffred betyng</L>
<L>Of Maister for &thorn;i lore,</L>
<L>Do &thorn;i fader comaundement</L>
<L N="512">Bo&thorn;e lasse and more.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Res age, que prosunt: rursus uitare memento, In quibus</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[quis, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>error inest, nec spes est certa laboris.</I>
<PB REF="00000605.tif" N="597"></P>
<LG N="140" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>140.</HEAD>
<L><I>ffetes ceo ky profyte;</I></L>
<L><I>Mes iceo ke delyte</I></L>
<L><I>Ou il y ad trespas,</I></L>
<L><I>I ceo dount nestes seur,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke sauf seit toun labour;</I></L>
<L><I>Si tu me creies, lerras.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="513">&para; Do &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;e profite may,</L>
<L>Or helpe &thorn;e atte last;</L>
<L>O&thorn;ere wikkede errours</L>
<L N="516">A-wei from &thorn;e &thorn;ou cast.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quod donare potes, gratis concede roganti; Nam gratis fecisse bonis, in parte</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[recte f. b., in parte. V. R.]</NOTE> <I>lucrosum est.</I></P>
<LG N="141" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>141.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ceo qi poies doner,</I></L>
<L><I>Done&yogh; de bon quer</I></L>
<L><I>A ly ke quert aye;</I></L>
<L><I>kar fere debonerement</I></L>
<L><I>Ben a bone gent,</I></L>
<L><I>Gayn est enpartye.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="517">&para; &THORN;at &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t with rihte &yogh;ef,</L>
<L>To pore &thorn;ou graunte at nede;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou not &thorn;e riche mon,</L>
<L N="520">&THORN;er is no soule mede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quod tibi suspectum est, confestim discute, quid sit; Namque solent, primo que sunt neglecta, nocere.</I></P>
<LG N="142" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>142.</HEAD>
<L><I>Enquere chose entende&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Souent la recordes,</I></L>
<L><I>Pur ben sauer la cure;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar pas nest petit</I></L>
<L><I>Pur auer en despit</I></L>
<L><I>Les choses ke pount nure.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; Cum <I>te detineat</I> veneris dampnosa <I>uoluptas, Indulgere gule noli</I>, que ventris <I>amica est.</I></P>
<LG N="143" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>143.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si a countre toun profit</I></L>
<L><I>Le maueis delyt</I></L>
<L><I>Tei tent de lecherie,</I></L>
<L><I>Donke voyl sor tote ren</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tu tei gardes bien</I></L>
<L><I>De Glotonerie.</I>
<PB REF="00000606.tif" N="598"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="521">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt fihte with flessches lust,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes lecherie,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou most with-drawe of diuers metes,</L>
<L N="524">And vse no glotenie.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum tibi preualide fuerint in corpore vires, ffac sapias; quo</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[sic, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>tu poteris vir fortis haberi.</I></P>
<LG N="144" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>144.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si fort es euaylaunt</I></L>
<L><I>De cors e ben puissaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>Od tut ceo seye&yogh; sage,</I></L>
<L><I>Si purras estre pru&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>E a fort tenu&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>En tut vostre age:</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="525">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou be mon of bodi strong,</L>
<L>Auyse &thorn;e wel in &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Puyt &thorn;i streng&thorn;e in-to prou,</L>
<L N="528">And elles hit helpe&thorn; &thorn;e nou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum tibi preponas animalia cuncta timere, Vnum precipio tibi plus hominem</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. hom. plus.]</NOTE> <I>esse timendum.</I></P>
<LG N="145" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>145.</HEAD>
<L><I>Quant taunt frele estes</I></L>
<L><I>Ke vous dotes les bestes</I></L>
<L><I>E le serpens,</I></L>
<L><I>Mout deue&yogh; doter</I></L>
<L><I>Homme de feloun quer,</I></L>
<L><I>E fuer le tut tens.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="529">&para; Si&thorn;en &thorn;ou art so frele of kuynde</L>
<L>Wilde bestes to doute,</L>
<L>Doute wel more wikked men,</L>
<L N="532">And come not in heore route.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Auxilium a notis petito, si forte laboras; Nec quisquam melior medicus, quam fidus amicus.</I></P>
<LG N="146" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>146.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si tei sourt mester</I></L>
<L><I>De tes amys requer</I></L>
<L><I>Socours e aye,</I></L>
<L><I>Meillor nul ne say</I></L>
<L><I>Myre qe amy veray</I></L>
<L><I>En tote ceste vye.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="533">&para; Aske in trauayle help of frende,</L>
<L>To wisse &thorn;e and to rede,
<PB REF="00000607.tif" N="599"></L>
<L>Beter leche knowe I non</L>
<L N="536">&THORN;en trewe frend is at neode.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum sis ipse nocens, moritur cur uictima pro te? Stulticia in</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[est, V. R.]</NOTE><I> mortem alterius sperare salutem.</I></P>
<LG N="147" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>147.</HEAD>
<L><I>Salu en autri mort</I></L>
<L><I>Espeirer, ceo est tort</I></L>
<L><I>E folye e vice.</I></L>
<L><I>Par quele resoun prouable</I></L>
<L><I>Quant tu es coupable</I></L>
<L><I>De toun sacrifice.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Cum tibi uel socium, uel fidum queris amicum, Non fortuna tibi</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[tibi fortuna, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>est hominis, sed vita petenda.</I></P>
<LG N="148" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>148.</HEAD>
<L><I>Su tu as desyr</I></L>
<L><I>De lel amy choiser</I></L>
<L><I>Ou bele cumpaignye,</I></L>
<L><I>De enquere lauenture</I></L>
<L><I>De homme neye&yogh; cure,</I></L>
<L><I>Mes de la bone vye.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Vtere quesitis opibus; fuge nomen auari. Quid tibi diuicie prosunt, si</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Quo tibi divitias, si semper, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>pauper abundas?</I></P>
<LG N="149" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>149.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ceo ke tu as purchase,</I></L>
<L><I>Vse&yogh; en honestete,</I></L>
<L><I>ffue&yogh; le noun de escars.</I></L>
<L><I>Dount sert ta richesce,</I></L>
<L><I>Quant tu viues en destresce,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke nuil ben ne as?</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Si famam seruare cupis, dum uiuis, honestam, ffac fugias animo, que sunt mala gaudia uite.</I></P>
<LG N="150" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>150.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si uole&yogh; garder ta fame</I></L>
<L><I>De vilenye ede blame,</I></L>
<L><I>Taunt cum es uiuaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>En Ioyes de ceste mound</I></L>
<L><I>Ke mout maueis sount</I></L>
<L><I>Ne seie&yogh; consentaunt.</I>
<PB REF="00000608.tif" N="600"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="537">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt kepe &thorn;i gode loos</L>
<L>ffrom wiked sunne and blame,</L>
<L>To veyne ioyes of &thorn;is world</L>
<L N="540">ffor-sak hem alle bi name.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum sapias animo, noli irridere senectam; Nam quocumque sene,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[quicumque senet, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>puerilis sensus in illo est.</I></P>
<LG N="151" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>151.</HEAD>
<L><I>Pur quei ke seie&yogh; sage,</I></L>
<L><I>Ia homme de veilage</I></L>
<L><I>Ne serras gabaunt;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar kaunt homme enueillist,</I></L>
<L><I>Le sen ly enfeblist</I></L>
<L><I>E si deuent enfaunt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="541">&para; In old mon is childes wit,</L>
<L>So&thorn; &thorn;ou schalt hit fynde;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be wys, scorn him not,</L>
<L N="544">Hit falle&thorn; to his kuynde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Disce aliquid; nam, cum subito fortuna recedit,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[recessit, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>Ars remanet uitamque hominis non deserit vnquam.</I></P>
<LG N="152" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>152.</HEAD>
<L><I>Aperne&yogh; a-kun art,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke, si fortune senpart</I></L>
<L><I>de tei sodeynement,</I></L>
<L><I>le art od tei remeyndra,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke trop ne tei lerra</I></L>
<L><I>Esguare entre gent.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="545">&para; Leorn sum good, whil &thorn;ou miht;</L>
<L>Auenture ha&thorn; no make;</L>
<L>Mester wol not fayle &thorn;i lyf,</L>
<L N="548">Hit nul &thorn;e neuere forsake.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Prospicito cuncta</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Perspicito tecum, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>tacitus, quod quisque loquatur: Sermo hominum mores celat, set &amp; indicat idem.</I></P>
<LG N="153" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>153.</HEAD>
<L><I>A chekun parlement seye&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>E entendaunt tote fe&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Mes teisaunt tei couere;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar la parole a plusours hommes</I></L>
<L><I>Lour mours e lour custumes</I></L>
<L><I>Clerement descouere.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<PB REF="00000609.tif" N="601">
<P><I>Exerce studium, quam-uis perceperis artem: Vt cura ingenium, quoque sic</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[sic et, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>manus adiuat usum.</I></P>
<LG N="154" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>154.</HEAD>
<L><I>Le estudie haunteras,</I></L>
<L><I>Ia seit I ceo ke tu as</I></L>
<L><I>Le art aperceu;</I></L>
<L><I>Estudie engein encuse,</I></L>
<L><I>E la meyn homme vse</I></L>
<L><I>Meynte tel aum veu.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="549">Haunte studie, &thorn;au&yogh; &thorn;ou haue</L>
<L>Wel conceyued &thorn;i craft,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wille and wit and &thorn;in hond</L>
<L N="552">To-gedere ben i-laft.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Multum uenturi ne cures tempora fati: Non metuit mortem qui s[c]it contempnere uitam.</I></P>
<LG N="155" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>155.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ne eies pas graunt cure</I></L>
<L><I>De penser a quel hure</I></L>
<L><I>Tu as a morer;</I></L>
<L><I>La mort ne dote&yogh; mye</I></L>
<L><I>Cyl ke veut sa vye</I></L>
<L><I>En despit auer.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>Disce, set a doctis: indoctos ipse doceto; propaganda est etenim</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[etenim est, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>rerum doctrina bonarum.</I></P>
<LG N="156" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>156.</HEAD>
<L><I>De aseygnement apren,</I></L>
<L><I>E tu de toun sen</I></L>
<L><I>Autres deis aprendre;</I></L>
<L><I>Soun sen e soun sauer</I></L>
<L><I>Pur ben multiplier</I></L>
<L><I>Deit chescun despendre.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="553">&para; Heeren &thorn;ou schalt of wyse men;</L>
<L>And loke wel in &thorn;i mood</L>
<L>&THORN;i wit to spene wysliche,</L>
<L N="556">And eke &thorn;in o&thorn;er good.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Hoc bibe quod possis, si tu uis viuere sanus: Morbi namque mali causa</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[M. causa mali nimia, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>est quecumque voluptas.</I></P>
<LG N="157" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>157.</HEAD>
<L><I>Si tu veus viuere seyn,</I></L>
<L><I>Beue&yogh; ke tu seyes pleyn</I></L>
<L><I>E ke bien puisaunt;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar chescun delyt est vein,</I>
<PB REF="00000610.tif" N="602"></L>
<L><I>E encheson certeyn</I></L>
<L><I>De maladye graunt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="557">&para; Drink &thorn;at &thorn;ou beo me&thorn;ful,</L>
<L>And lyue in hele good;</L>
<L>ffoul delyt in drunkennesse</L>
<L N="560">Make&thorn; men ofte ful wood.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Laudaris quodcumque palam, quecumque probaris, Prospice</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Hoc vide, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>ne rursus leuitatis crimine dampnes.</I></P>
<LG N="158" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>158.</HEAD>
<L><I>Ceo ke tu as lowe</I></L>
<L><I>En comunite</I></L>
<L><I>Par tei derechef,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne seit a redampner</I></L>
<L><I>Pur nul regreter,</I></L>
<L><I>Taunt seie&yogh; sage e gref.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="561">&para; &THORN;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast ones preised</L>
<L>Be-fore &thorn;e folk ouer al,</L>
<L>Blame hit not &thorn;er-afturward,</L>
<L N="564">Beo hit gret or smal.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Tranquillis rebus, que su[n]t aduersa caueto:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[timeto, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>Rursus in aduersis, melius sperare memento</I></P>
<LG N="159" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>159.</HEAD>
<L><I>Quant es ben a eise,</I></L>
<L><I>Pense&yogh; donke de meseise,</I></L>
<L><I>Pur tei humilier;</I></L>
<L><I>Quant es en aduersite&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Mout graunt bens esperes,</I></L>
<L><I>pur tei cumforter.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="565">&para; In &thorn;i weol&thorn;e &thorn;ou &thorn;enk of wo,</L>
<L>So mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou &thorn;e meke;</L>
<L>In wo also haue hope of helpe,</L>
<L N="568">So maist &thorn;ou cumforte &thorn;e seke.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><I>[Discere ne cesses: cura sapientia crescit: Rara datur longo prudentia temporis usu.]</I></P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Parce laudato; nam, quem tu sepe probaris, Vna dies, qualis fuerit, demonstrat,</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[ostendet, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>amicus.</I></P>
<LG N="160" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>160.</HEAD>
<L>Mesurablement</L>
<L><I>Loye&yogh; tote gent</I></L>
<L><I>De kes al esprouer;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar vn Iour ver tei fra</I>
<PB REF="00000611.tif" N="603"></L>
<L><I>Ky amy tei serra,</I></L>
<L><I>Quant aueras graunt mester.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="569">&para; Preise a mon so scarsliche,</L>
<L>Whom &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt him proue;</L>
<L>He schal sum tyme schewe openliche</L>
<L N="572">Wher he &thorn;e hate or loue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Ne pudiat, que nescieris, te uelle doceri: Scire aliquid laus est; turpe</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[culpa, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>est, nil discere uelle.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Hounte ne eie&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo ky uous ne saue&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>En-quere e a prendre;</I></L>
<L><I>Los est de sauer ben,</I></L>
<L><I>E mal, de nuile ren</I></L>
<L><I>Voler entendre.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="573">&para; &THORN;at &thorn;ou ne const, schome &thorn;e not</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;ere to ben I-tauht;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at nout con, ne nout wol lerne,</L>
<L N="576">May neuer ben I-sau&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum uenere &amp; bacho lis est, coniuncta</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[sed iuncta, V. R.]</NOTE> <I>voluptas. Quod lautum est, animo complectere, set fuge lites.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>De-sour beuerie</I></L>
<L><I>Sourt tensoun e folye,</I></L>
<L><I>Sens nul ou petit,</I></L>
<L><I>E de lecherie</I></L>
<L><I>Estryf e briconye,</I></L>
<L><I>Mes mout vnt graunt folye.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Le maueis delyt</I></L>
<L><I>Eye&yogh; en despit,</I></L>
<L><I>E fue&yogh; le tensoun;</I></L>
<L><I>Vnkes despise&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Les bens ke tu preise&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>En ta discrecioun.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Dimissos animo tacitos que cauere</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[ac tacitos vitare, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>memento: Quo</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Qua, V.R.</NOTE> <I>flumen placidum est, forsan latet alciori</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[altius, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>vnda.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>En checun tens elu</I></L>
<L><I>Tel homme eschu</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tut Iour est tensaunt;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar il auent ke lounde</I>,
<PB REF="00000612.tif" N="604"></L>
<L><I>Ke est plus parfounde</I></L>
<L><I>Ou eole est meyns mouaunt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="577">&para; In vche stude, in vche tyme,</L>
<L>&THORN;e stille mon &thorn;ou drede and fle;</L>
<L>&THORN;er water is most deope,</L>
<L N="580">&THORN;e lasse &thorn;er &thorn;en steres he.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum tibi displiciat rerum fortuna tuarum, Alter[i]us specta, quo sis discrimine peior.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Si en nule ren</I></L>
<L><I>Tei ne achese ben</I></L>
<L><I>Cum fet a autre gent,</I></L>
<L><I>Veie&yogh; si tu eie&yogh; tecche</I></L>
<L><I>Ou vice en quey ceo pecche,</I></L>
<L><I>E taunt tost tei ament.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="581">&para; &YOGH;if auenture nul not &thorn;e serue</L>
<L>As he do&thorn; o&thorn;er men,</L>
<L>Bi-hold &thorn;i tecches or &thorn;i sunne,</L>
<L N="584">Wher &thorn;ou beo gulti &thorn;en.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quod potes, id tempta: litus nam</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[nam litus, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>carpere remis Tucius est multo, quam uelum tendere in altum.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>A-saye&yogh; en a-prise ben</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tu ne prengne&yogh; ren</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ne pusse&yogh; acheuer;</I></L>
<L><I>Plus est seur a fere</I></L>
<L><I>De nager pres de tere</I></L>
<L><I>Ky en haute mer sigler.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="585">A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e strem ne striue &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ne nui&yogh;e &thorn;e not wi&thorn; wrong;</L>
<L>ffor eueri werk wronglich wrouht</L>
<L N="588">God wol venge a-mong.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Contra hominem iustum praue contendere noli: Sepe</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Semper, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>enim deus iniustas vlciscitur iras.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>A countre homme dreiturer</I></L>
<L><I>Ne voyle&yogh; estriuer</I></L>
<L><I>A tort, ne ly mesdire:</I></L>
<L><I>Kar totes houres prent</I></L>
<L><I>Deus gref vengement</I></L>
<L><I>De torcenouse yre.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<PB REF="00000613.tif" N="605">
<P>&para; <I>Ereptis opibus, noli tu flere</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[maerere, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>dolendo: Set gaude pocius, si te contingat</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[tibi si contingit, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>habere.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Si tu perdes auer,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne uoyles pas doler</I></L>
<L><I>Pur doubler toun damage;</I></L>
<L><I>Mes si deule te reueyt,</I></L>
<L><I>Recef le gayn od heit&mdash;</I></L>
<L><I>Si fre&yogh; ke mout sage.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="589">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou leosest &thorn;i worldes good,</L>
<L>To gret deol mak &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;er, &yogh;if &thorn;e fayle &thorn;e chaunce,</L>
<L N="592">Haue Ioye in &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Est iactura grauis, que sunt, amittere dampnis: Sunt quedam, que ferre decet pacienter amicum.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Damage gref e fyer</I></L>
<L><I>Dount homme deit doler,</I></L>
<L><I>Ceo est perdre soun amy;</I></L>
<L><I>Mes meynt est damage</I></L>
<L><I>Pur quei ia ly sage</I></L>
<L><I>Ne ert dolent ne mari.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Tempora longa tibi noli promittere vite: Quocumque ingrederis, sequitur mors, corporis vmbram.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Ne vous promette&yogh; mye</I></L>
<L><I>Tens de longe vye,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke bricoun tenu ne seie&yogh;:</I></L>
<L><I>Ou ke vnkes uas eyns ou hors,</I></L>
<L><I>Le vmbre de toun cors</I></L>
<L><I>Ensuit mort tote fe&yogh;.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="593">&para; Haue non hope to liuen longe,</L>
<L>But diht &thorn;e euere on hi&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Wher-so &thorn;ou gost, niht or day,</L>
<L N="596">&THORN;i de&thorn; folewe&thorn; &thorn;e neihe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Ture deum placa: vitulum sine crescat aratro; Ne credas placare deum, cum cede litatur.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>En tens a deu celestre</I></L>
<L><I>Offre&yogh;, e soffres crestre</I></L>
<L><I>Le vel a la charue;</I></L>
<L><I>Crere ne voyle&yogh;</I>
<PB REF="00000614.tif" N="606"></L>
<L><I>Ke dieu de ceo seit le&yogh;</I></L>
<L><I>Ke homme les bestes tue.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cede locum lesis fortune</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[laesus Fortunae, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>cede potenti; Ledere qui poterit, prodesse aliquando valebit.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Done&yogh; lu a graunt,</I></L>
<L><I>E suffre&yogh; le pussaunt</I></L>
<L><I>Quant il fet mal a tey;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar cil ke peut blesser,</I></L>
<L><I>Purra profyter</I></L>
<L><I>Acune fe&yogh;, ceo crey.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="597">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou stude to grete men,</L>
<L>&THORN;auh ofte &thorn;ei greue&thorn; &thorn;e;</L>
<L>O&thorn;er-tyme &thorn;ei may &thorn;e profyte&mdash;</L>
<L N="600">And her-of loke &thorn;ou leeue me.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum tu</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Quum quid, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>peccaris, castiga te ipse subinde: Vulnera dum sanas, dolor est medicina doloris.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Si vous pecches par folye,</I></L>
<L><I>Tey meymes enchastye,</I></L>
<L><I>E ceo ben aprement;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar dolour est medecyne</I></L>
<L><I>De dolour ke ne fyne</I></L>
<L><I>De tous dolours lentent.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="601">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou sum tyme dost a sunne,</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;ou hit amende;</L>
<L>Serwe is medicine of &thorn;i gult,</L>
<L N="604">And God is wonder hende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Dampnaris nunquam post longum tempus amicum; Mutauit mores: sed pignora prima memento.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Si toun amy change</I></L>
<L><I>Soun corage pur vyl hange,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne le voilles dampner;</I></L>
<L><I>Mes ke il ad samour</I></L>
<L><I>Chaunge&yogh; en Amour</I></L>
<L><I>Vers tey deis remembrer.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Gracior officijs, quo sis mage carior, esto: Ne nomen subeas, quod dicitur, officij perdi.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[officiperdi, V.R.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000615.tif" N="607"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Cum vous cher tey eies</I></L>
<L><I>De taunt pener tey deyes</I></L>
<L><I>Pur seruer plus a gre,</I></L>
<L><I>Ke vous ne seyes nome</I></L>
<L><I>Maueis, ne a-pele</I></L>
<L><I>A uostre eyn degre.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="605">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou beo holden deore with frend,</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ou serue &thorn;e more to gre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wikked reson bi good enchesun</L>
<L N="608">Beo not put on &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Suspectus caueas, ne sis miser omnibus horis: Nam timidis &amp; suspectis aptissima mors est.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Les suspecious</I></L>
<L><I>Sount tut tens pourous,</I></L>
<L><I>Lour vye est en meseyse;</I></L>
<L><I>A teus vaut meu&yogh; morir</I></L>
<L><I>Ke tel mal suffrer</I></L>
<L><I>Od tote lur ese.</I></L>
<L>. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inter">[English wanting, space left.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum seruos fueris proprios mercatus in vsus Et famulos dicas, homines tamen esse memento.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Si a ta volunte</I></L>
<L><I>Serfs as achate,</I></L>
<L><I>Pur auer a toun vsus,</I></L>
<L><I>E quaunt ke vus seruerunt,</I></L>
<L><I>Pense&yogh; ke hommes sount</I></L>
<L><I>Ansy ben cum vous.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="609">&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou haue seruauns mony on,</L>
<L>To werk and don vsage,</L>
<L>Beo-&thorn;enk &thorn;e wel &thorn;at &thorn;ei beo men</L>
<L N="612">And lyk to &thorn;in ymage.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Quam primum rapienda tibi est occacio prima: Ne rursus queras, que iam neglexeris ante.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Les bens ke poyes erraunt</I></L>
<L><I>prendre en auaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>Ne les mettes en respyt;</I></L>
<L><I>Oum tu y fauderas</I></L>
<L><I>Quant auer les voderas</I></L>
<L><I>Issi cum ieo quit.</I>
<PB REF="00000616.tif" N="608"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="613">&para; Tak what &thorn;ing &thorn;e profred is</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t redi haue;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at nul not whon he may,</L>
<L N="616">Ofte ha&thorn; not whon he wol craue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Morte repentina noli gaudere malorum: ffelices obeunt, quorum sine crimine uita est.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>En-ioyer ne te deis</I></L>
<L><I>Quant tu veies le maueis</I></L>
<L><I>Morer sodeynement;</I></L>
<L><I>Kar les benures</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ne&yogh; sount enpecches</I></L>
<L><I>Vount a defynement.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="617">&para; Of sodeyn de&thorn; of wikked men</L>
<L>Ioye ne make &thorn;ou none;</L>
<L>Holy men and of lyue clene</L>
<L N="620">Diden so als mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou done.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum coniux tibi sit, nec</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Quum tibi fit conjux, ne, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>res &amp; fama laborat, Vita ne</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Vitandum, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>ducas inimicum nomen amici.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Si femme as ou amye</I></L>
<L><I>E homme la sordye</I></L>
<L><I>De acun toun amy,</I></L>
<L><I>Ia pur ceo ne enuye&yogh;,</I></L>
<L><I>De-uaunt ke cert seyes,</I></L>
<L><I>Mal quer vers ly.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="621">&para; &YOGH;if men tellen harm bi &thorn;i wyf</L>
<L>Or o&thorn;er ffrend beo name,</L>
<L>Til hit beo proued, leeue hit nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="624">Empeyre &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t hire fame.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Cum tibi contigerit studio cognoscere multa, ffac discas multa; culpa est nil velle</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[et vita nescire, D.]</NOTE> <I>doceri.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Mout seie&yogh; ententyfs</I></L>
<L><I>Tut eie&yogh; vus mout apris</I></L>
<L><I>En estudiaunt,</I></L>
<L><I>E plus e plus a-pren</I></L>
<L><I>Sauer e sen,</I></L>
<L><I>Taunt cum es uiuaunt.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="625">&para; &THORN;ouh &thorn;at &thorn;ou knowe fele &thorn;inges</L>
<L>Be studie and bi lore,
<PB REF="00000617.tif" N="609"></L>
<L>Let not o Bok, bisiliche</L>
<L N="628">Beo lernynge euer-more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Coueyte not to muche good,</L>
<L>And do aftur my red;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ouerdon gredi mon</L>
<L N="632">Begge&thorn; ofte his bred.<NOTE PLACE="foot">G. E. Weber says, in <I>Corpus Poet. Latin.</I>, 1833, p. 1198: 'Additur denique distichon satis ineptum: <I>Miraris verbis nudis</I>,' &amp;c. The Various Readings above are from his text.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P>&para; <I>Mireris verbis nudis me scribere versus? Hos breuitas sensus fecit congungere</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[coniungere, V.R.]</NOTE> <I>binos.</I></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><I>Tu as merueyle se quit</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ieo ay ces vers escrit</I></L>
<L><I>Issy nuement;</I></L>
<L><I>Mes ceo est lenchesoun</I></L>
<L><I>Ke ieo deisse ma Resoun</I></L>
<L><I>En deus vers breuement.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="633">&para; &THORN;e merueyles of &thorn;ise nakede vers</L>
<L>Beo&thorn; maked bi two and two:</L>
<L>&THORN;e schortnesse of my luitel wit</L>
<L N="636">Dude me en-Ioynen hem so.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wise men may a-mende &thorn;is ieste,</L>
<L>And resouns puten and eche:</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at reden on &thorn;is bok,</L>
<L N="640">&THORN;erof I hem biseche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Alle &thorn;at reden and wolle recorden</L>
<L>&THORN;is smale techinges bi-dene,</L>
<L>God hem graunte, &thorn;orw his grace,</L>
<L N="644">Of heore sunnes be clene. Amen!</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="51" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>LI. The Stacions of Rome. [The Prolog only.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOrd Ihesu crist In Trinite,<MILESTONE N="314" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;reo persones In vnite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on God is in makynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is and was of alle &thorn;inge,</L>
<L>Seende us grace now so biginne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mowe so heuene winne,
<PB REF="00000618.tif" N="610"></L>
<L>&THORN;at mowe we not don here,</L>
<L N="8">Bot ur soules ben of sunne clere.</L>
<L>Hose wot his soule In synne bounde,</L>
<L>I wol him techen In a stounde,</L>
<L>Where he may medicyn fynde</L>
<L N="12">His soule of sunne to vnbynde,</L>
<L>And from pyne him saue sikerly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e fuir of helle is redy;</L>
<L>And also from &thorn;e fuir of helle,</L>
<L N="16">Wher-of &thorn;e peynes no mon con telle.</L>
<L>&para; To grete Rome gon he mote,</L>
<L>&THORN;er is &thorn;e Medicyn, crop and Rote,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men clepe&thorn; pardoun.</L>
<L N="20">&YOGH;onge and Olde in eueri toun,</L>
<L>&THORN;er is forso&thorn;e welle of grace</L>
<L>To alle &thorn;at visyte&thorn; &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>And ben in loue and charite</L>
<L N="24">Touward vche mon what so he be,</L>
<L>And kepe&thorn; him clene to his ende,</L>
<L>Nedes to heuene moste he wende</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen peyne lasse or more,</L>
<L N="28">His soule to dwellen euere &thorn;ore.</L>
<L>&THORN;at may vche mon at Rome fynde,</L>
<L>And clene his soule of synne vnbynde,</L>
<L>As I her-after ow schal telle.</L>
<L N="32">In diuerse churches, and &yogh;e wol dwelle,</L>
<L>An holy lyf is in &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>Men may hit leeue, hose ha&thorn; grace.</L>
<L>Seouen hundret and fifti &yogh;er be-foren</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;at vr lord Ihesu was boren,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Two knihtes come from troye</L>
<L>In-to Itayle with muchel Ioye,</L>
<L>Is cleped Remous and Romilus,</L>
<L N="40">As olde Cronycles telle&thorn; &thorn;us.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei weoren bre&thorn;eren of muchel miht,</L>
<L>And muchel douted in fiht,</L>
<L>And foundeours of Rome, &thorn;at grete cit&eacute;&eacute;,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at is ful of grace and dignite,</L>
<L>And cleped is Rome after hem,</L>
<L>As cronicles telle&thorn; alle men.
<PB REF="00000619.tif" N="611"></L>
<L>Al was he&thorn;ene &thorn;at was &thorn;er-Inne,</L>
<L N="48">fful of wikkednes and of sinne,</L>
<L>Til peter and poul, and seynt Ion,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er holye mony on,</L>
<L>&THORN;ider come wi&thorn; godes miht</L>
<L N="52">To cristene &thorn;e peple day and niht,</L>
<L>To teche hem cristes lore,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e lasse and eke &thorn;e more.</L>
<L>&THORN;er weore &thorn;ei mony a gret stounde,</L>
<L N="56">So harde in meschef and sunne I-bounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at cristendam ne wolden take,</L>
<L>Ne heore Maumetrie forsake;</L>
<L>And slowen Peter and poul also,</L>
<L N="60">And o&thorn;er seintes mony mo:</L>
<L>Mony Miracle of hem gon falle</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Cite of &thorn;e hei&yogh;e halle,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Martires &thorn;at &thorn;ei hedde made,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at coude no better rade,</L>
<L>And cristned bi-comen mony one</L>
<L>Of he&thorn;ene men &thorn;at weren in Rome.</L>
<L>&THORN;e moredel &thorn;at weore &thorn;er-inne,</L>
<L N="68">And also al &thorn;at &thorn;ei mihte winne.</L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;o &thorn;at wolde not cristned be,</L>
<L>Weore he bonde, weore he fre,</L>
<L>To de&thorn;e anon was he don,</L>
<L N="72">Moste &thorn;er no gold for him gon;</L>
<L>In-to Rome &thorn;us com cristendom,</L>
<L>And for vr alre sauacion.</L>
<L>&para; Now &thorn;is schal beo &thorn;e parclose,</L>
<L N="76">No more to speken of &thorn;is prose,</L>
<L>But of holynesse and dignite,</L>
<L N="78">Graunted in chirches of &thorn;at cite.</L>
<L>HOse wole his soule leche . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="end">[The rest of the poem, after 1. 78, is printed in No. 25 of the E. E. Text Society's Original Series, 1867, pages 1-24, and is therefore not repeated here. Had I recollected that the next poem&mdash;the 'Disputation'&mdash;had been printed by our late lamented friend, Dr. Richard Morris, in his <I>Legends of the Holy Rood</I>, E. E. T. Soc., 1871, p. 131-149, and (from the Royal MS. 18, A 10) p. 197-209, it would not have found place here; but I'd forgotten all about it till the revise came, and therefore do not cancel it.&mdash; F., 14 June, 1894.]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="52" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000620.tif" N="612">
<HEAD>LII. Disputation between Mary and the Cross.</HEAD>
<P>[40 Alliterative Stanzas: nos. 1 and 40, either nine lines with 2 central rymes, <I>aaaa, bcccb;</I> or 17 lines, <I>aab, aab, aab, aab, cdddc;</I> nos. 2-39, thirteen lines <I>abab, abab, cdddc.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Oure ladi freo, on Rode treo, made hire mon:<MILESTONE N="315b:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Heo seid, "on &thorn;e, &thorn;e fruit of me, is wo bigon;</L>
<L>Mi fruit I seo, in blodi bleo, among his fon;</L>
<L>Serwe I seo, &thorn;e veines fleo, from blodi bon.<NOTE PLACE="foot">These 4 lines might each be set in 4 threes, <I>aab</I>, as those in stanza 40 (p. 626) are in the MS, the printed below as single lines.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">Cros, &thorn;ou dost no trou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>On a pillori my fruit to pinne.</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; no spot of Adam sinne:</L>
<L>fflesch and veines nou fleo a-twinne;</L>
<L N="9">Wherfore I rede of routhe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="10">Cros, &thorn;i bondes schul ben blamed,</L>
<L>Mi fayre fruit &thorn;ou hast bi-gyled,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fruites Mooder was neuere a-famed,</L>
<L N="13">Mi wombe is feir, founden vn-fuyled.</L>
<L>Chyld, whi artou not a-schamed</L>
<L>On a pillori to ben I-piled?</L>
<L>Grete Iewes &thorn;us weore gramed,</L>
<L N="17">And dyede for heore werkes wyled.</L>
<L N="18">In mournyng I may melte;</L>
<L>Mi fruit &thorn;at is so holi halwed,</L>
<L>In a feeld is fouled and falwed;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; grete Iewes he is galwed,</L>
<L N="22">And dye&thorn; for Monnes gelte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="23">FOr grete Iewes, galwes weire grei&thorn;ed,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer to Robbyng Ronne ryf.</L>
<L>Whi schal my sone on &thorn;e beo leid,</L>
<L N="26">&THORN;at neuer nuy&yogh;ed mon nor wyf?</L>
<L>A drinke of de&thorn;, so&thorn;liche seid,</L>
<L>Cros, &thorn;ou &yogh;euest &thorn;e lord of lyf,
<PB REF="00000621.tif" N="613"></L>
<L>His veynes to-bursten wi&thorn; &thorn;i breid.</L>
<L N="30">Mi fruit stont nou in a strong stryf;</L>
<L N="31">Blod from hed is hayled;</L>
<L>ffouled is my fayre fruit,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer dude tripet ne truit.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;eues &thorn;at loueden ryot and ruit,</L>
<L N="35">Whi schal my sone be nayled?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="36">&THORN;oru&yogh; Iugement &thorn;ou art en-Ioynet</L>
<L>To bere fooles ful of sinne.</L>
<L>Mi sone from &thorn;e schulde beon ensoynet,</L>
<L>And neuere his blod vppon &thorn;e rinne;</L>
<L N="40">But nou is tru&thorn;e wi&thorn; tresun teynet,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;eoues to honge fer in fenne;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; feole nayles his limes ben feynet;</L>
<L>A careful Moder men mai me kenne;</L>
<L N="44">In Bales I am bounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;at fruit was of a Mayden born,</L>
<L>On a &thorn;eoues tre is al to-torn.</L>
<L>A Broche &thorn;orw-out his brest [is] born,</L>
<L N="48">His holi herte ha&thorn; wounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="49">Tre! &thorn;ou art loked bi &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;eoues, traitours, on &thorn;e to dye;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? deye]</NOTE></L>
<L>But now is trou&thorn;e wi&thorn; tresun drawe,</L>
<L>And vertu falle&thorn; in vices weye;</L>
<L N="53">But loue and treu&thorn;e in so&thorn;fast sawe</L>
<L>On a treo traytours hem teye;</L>
<L>Vertu is wi&thorn; vices slawe.</L>
<L>Of alle vertues my sone is keye,</L>
<L N="57">Vertu swettore &thorn;en spices;</L>
<L>In fot and hond bere&thorn; blodi prikke,</L>
<L>His hed is ful of &thorn;ornes &thorn;ikke;</L>
<L>&THORN;e goode honge&thorn; a-mong &thorn;e wikke;</L>
<L N="61">Vertu dye&thorn; wi&thorn; vices.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="62">Tre vnkynde, &thorn;ou schalt be kud;</L>
<L>Mi sone step-Moder, I &thorn;e calle.
<PB REF="00000622.tif" N="614"></L>
<L>Mi fruit was born wi&thorn; beestes on bed,</L>
<L>And be my flesch my flour gan falle.</L>
<L N="66">Wi&thorn; my brestes, my brid I fed;</L>
<L>Cros! &thorn;ou &yogh;euest him Eysel and Galle.</L>
<L>Mi white Rose Red is spred,<MILESTONE N="316:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at fostred was in a fodderes stalle.</L>
<L N="70">ffeet and fayre hondes</L>
<L>&THORN;at nou ben croised, I custe hem ofte;</L>
<L>I lulled hem, I leid hem softe.</L>
<L>Cros! &thorn;ou holdest hem hi&yogh;e on lofte,</L>
<L N="74">Bounden in bledyng bondes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="75">Mi loue i-lolled vp in &thorn;e eyr,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; cradel bond I gan him bynde.</L>
<L>Cros! he stike&thorn; nou on &thorn;i steir,</L>
<L>Naked a-&yogh;eyn &thorn;e wylde wynde.</L>
<L N="79">ffoules fourmen heor nestes in &thorn;e eyr;</L>
<L>Wolues, in den, reste &thorn;ei fynde;</L>
<L>Bot Godes sone, in heuene heir,</L>
<L>His hed nou leone&thorn; on &thorn;ornes tynde.</L>
<L N="83">Of mournyng I may mynne:</L>
<L>Godes hed ha&thorn; reste non,</L>
<L>But leone&thorn; on his scholder bon;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ornes &thorn;orwh his flesch[e] gon;</L>
<L N="87">His wo I wytte hit sinne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="88">Cros! to slen, hit is &thorn;i sleiht;</L>
<L>Mi fayre fruit &thorn;ou berest fro blis.</L>
<L>Cros! &thorn;ou holdest him so heih on hei&yogh;&thorn;,</L>
<L>Mi fruites feet I mai not kis.</L>
<L N="92">Mi mou&thorn; I pulte, my sweore I strei&yogh;t</L>
<L>To cusse his feet, so&thorn; &thorn;ing hit is.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes from &thorn;e cros me kei&yogh;t;</L>
<L>On me &thorn;ei made heore mouwes amis,</L>
<L N="96">Heore games and heore gaudes;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes wrou&yogh;ten me ful wo.</L>
<L>Cros! I fynde &thorn;ou art my fo.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou berest my brid beten blo,</L>
<L N="100">Among &thorn;eose fooles fraudes."
<PB REF="00000623.tif" N="615"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="101">Cristes cros &yogh;af onswere:</L>
<L>"Ladi, to &thorn;e I owe honour;</L>
<L>&THORN;i brihte palmes nou I bere;</L>
<L>Mi schyning schewe&thorn; &thorn;orw &thorn;i flour;</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;i feire fruit on me ginne&thorn; tere;</L>
<L>&THORN;i fruit me florische&thorn; in blod colour.</L>
<L>To winne &thorn;e world &thorn;at lay in lere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. lure]</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at Blosme Blomed vp in &thorn;i bour,</L>
<L N="109">Ac not for &thorn;e al-one,</L>
<L>But for to winne al &thorn;is werld</L>
<L>&THORN;at swelte vndur &thorn;e deueles swerd;</L>
<L>&THORN;orw feet and hond God let him gerd,</L>
<L N="113">To a-mende monnes mone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L N="114">Adam dude ful huge harmes</L>
<L>Whon he bot a bite vndur a bouh;</L>
<L>Wherfore &thorn;i sone ha&thorn; sprad his Armes</L>
<L>On a treo tyed wi&thorn; teone I-nouh.</L>
<L N="118">His flesch is smite wi&thorn; de&thorn;es &thorn;armes,</L>
<L>And swelte&thorn; heer in a swemly swouh.</L>
<L>His Breste is bored wi&thorn; de&thorn;es swarmes;</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his de&thorn;, fro de&thorn; he drouh</L>
<L N="122">Alle his leoue freondes,</L>
<L>As O&yogh;ie spac in prophecie;</L>
<L>And seide, '&thorn;i sone, seinte Marie,</L>
<L>His de&thorn; slou&yogh; de&thorn; on Caluarie,</L>
<L N="126">&YOGH;af lyf wi&thorn;-outen endes.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L N="127">&THORN;e stipre<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? MS. scipre]</NOTE> &thorn;at is vnder &thorn;e vyne set,</L>
<L>May not bringe for&thorn; &thorn;e grape;</L>
<L>&THORN;eih &thorn;e fruit on me&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? <I>for</I> me]</NOTE> beo knet,</L>
<L>His scharpe schour haue I not schape.</L>
<L N="131">Til grapes to &thorn;e presse beo set,</L>
<L>&THORN;er renne&thorn; no red wyn in rape;</L>
<L>Neuere presse pressed bet.</L>
<L>I presse wyn for kniht and knape,</L>
<L N="135">Vp-on a Blodi brinke.</L>
<L>I presse a grape with strok and stryf;
<PB REF="00000624.tif" N="616"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Rede wyn renne&thorn; ryf;</L>
<L>In Samaritane, God &yogh;af a wyf</L>
<L N="139">&THORN;at leof licour to drinke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L N="140">LAdi! loue do&thorn; &thorn;e to alegge!</L>
<L>&THORN;i fruit is prikked wi&thorn; speres ord;</L>
<L>On Cros, wi&thorn;-outen knyues egge,</L>
<L>I kerue fruit of godes hord:</L>
<L N="144">Al is al red, Rib and Rugge;</L>
<L>His bodi blede&thorn; a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e bord;</L>
<L>I was piler and bar a brugge;</L>
<L>God is weie, witnesse of word,</L>
<L N="148">God sei&thorn; he is so&thorn;fast weye.</L>
<L>Mony folk slod to helle slider;</L>
<L>To heuene, mihte no mon &thorn;ider,</L>
<L>Til god dyed, and tau&yogh;te whider</L>
<L N="152">Men drawen whon &thorn;ei dye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L N="153">Moyses ha&thorn; fourmed in his figour,</L>
<L>A whit lomb, and non o&thorn;er beste,</L>
<L>Schulde be sacred vr saueour,</L>
<L>And be mete of mihtes meste.</L>
<L N="157">I was &thorn;at cheef chargeour;</L>
<L>I bar flesch for folkes feste,</L>
<L>Ihesu crist vre saueour,</L>
<L>He fede&thorn; bo&thorn;e lest and meste;</L>
<L N="161">Rosted a-&yogh;eyn &thorn;e sonne,</L>
<L>On me lay &thorn;e lomb of loue;</L>
<L>I was plater, his bodi a-boue;</L>
<L>Til feet and hondes al to-cloue,</L>
<L N="165">Wi&thorn; blood I was bi-ronne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L N="166">&YOGH;it Moyses in Rule ha&thorn; rad,</L>
<L>We schulde ete vr lomb in sour vergeous;</L>
<L>Sour vergeous mai make vr soules glad,</L>
<L N="169">To serwe sore for sunnes ours.</L>
<L>Sour vergeous schal make &thorn;e deuel adrad,<MILESTONE N="316:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor he flecche&thorn; fro godes spous.
<PB REF="00000625.tif" N="617"></L>
<L>Beo a staf stonde&thorn; sad,</L>
<L>Whon &yogh;e fongen flesch in godes hous.</L>
<L N="174">&THORN;at staf is Cristes Crouche;</L>
<L>Stonde&thorn; stifli bi &thorn;at stake,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at &yogh;e fongen flesch in Cake;</L>
<L>&THORN;en schal no feond maystri make,</L>
<L N="178">&YOGH;oure soules for to touche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L N="179">For pardoun schewe&thorn; be a shrine:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; nayl and brede, on bord is smite</L>
<L>Rede lettres write be lyne,</L>
<L>Bluwe, Blake, among men pite.</L>
<L N="183">Vr lord I likne to &thorn;is signe:</L>
<L>His bodi vppon a bord was bite;</L>
<L>In Briht[e] blod, his bodi gan schyne:</L>
<L>Hou wo him was, may no mon wite,</L>
<L N="187">Red vp on &thorn;e Roode.</L>
<L>Vr pardoun, brede from top too to,</L>
<L>Writen hit was wi&thorn; wonder wo;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Rede woundes and strokes blo,</L>
<L N="191">Vre Book was bounden in bloode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L N="192">Adam stod vp in stede;</L>
<L>In Bitter galle, his gost he dreint:</L>
<L>A-&yogh;eyn &thorn;at galle, God &yogh;af vs mede;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swete Merci, Bitter is queynt.</L>
<L N="196">His Bodi was Book, &thorn;e Cros was brede,</L>
<L>Whon Crist for vs &thorn;eron was cleynt.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> weynt]</NOTE></L>
<L>No mon gat pardoun wi&thorn; no bede,</L>
<L>Weor he neuere so sely a seynt,</L>
<L N="200">Til book on bord was sprad,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sharpe nayles dunted and driue,</L>
<L>Til feet and hondes al to-riue;</L>
<L>His herte blod, vre book ha&thorn; &yogh;iue,</L>
<L N="204">To make vr gostes glad."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L N="205">Cristes Cros &yogh;it spac &thorn;is speche:</L>
<L>"ffurst was I presse, wyn to wringe;
<PB REF="00000626.tif" N="618"></L>
<L>I bere a Brugge, wei to teche,</L>
<L>&THORN;er semely Aungeles sitte and synge.</L>
<L N="209">Lord of loue and lyues leche,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e was set sely sacrynge;</L>
<L>To winne &thorn;e world &thorn;at was in wreche,</L>
<L>&THORN;e cros was brede, pardoun to bringe.</L>
<L N="213">Pardoun In book is billed:</L>
<L>What is pardoun, vppon to minne?</L>
<L>Hit is for&yogh;iuenes of dedly sinne:</L>
<L>Whon blod was writen on cristes kinne,</L>
<L N="217">Pardoun was fulfilled."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L N="218">Oure ladi seide, "Cros! of &thorn;i werk,</L>
<L>Wonder &thorn;e not, &thorn;ei&yogh; I be wro&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;us seide Poule, Cristes clerk:</L>
<L>&THORN;e feolle Iewes, wi&thorn; false o&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="222">Iewes ston-hard in sinnes merk,</L>
<L>Beoten a lomb wi&thorn;-outen lo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Softer &thorn;en watur vndur serk,</L>
<L>Meode or Milk [i-]medled bo&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="226">&THORN;e Iewes weoren harde stones:</L>
<L>Softur &thorn;en watur or eny licour,</L>
<L>Or dew&yogh; &thorn;at li&thorn; on &thorn;e lilie flour,</L>
<L>Was cristes bodi, in blod colour:</L>
<L N="230">&THORN;e Iewes wolden ha broken his bones.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L N="231">And mony a prophete gan make mon,</L>
<L>And seide: lord! send us &thorn;i lomb</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e wildernesses ston,</L>
<L>To fende vs from &thorn;e lyon cromp</L>
<L N="235">Of mylde mount of Syon;</L>
<L>Be-com mon In a Maydens womb,</L>
<L>Made a bodi wi&thorn; blessed bon,</L>
<L>In a Maidens blod &thorn;i bodi flomb;</L>
<L N="239">At Barreres weore debate:<MILESTONE N="316:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;orw&yogh; stones In &thorn;e wildernes,</L>
<L>Men mi&yogh;te better ha crepet I-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;en bored in-to heuene blis,</L>
<L N="243">Til blod brac vp &thorn;e &yogh;ate.
<PB REF="00000627.tif" N="619"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L N="244">Sin monnes sone was so nedi</L>
<L>To beo lad wi&thorn; lomb[e] mylde,</L>
<L>Whi weore gylours so gredi</L>
<L>ffor to defoule my faire childe?</L>
<L N="248">Cros! whi weore &thorn;ou so redi</L>
<L>To rende my fruit feor in fylde?"</L>
<L>"Ladi, to make &thorn;e deuel dredi,</L>
<L>God schop me a scheld, schame to schilde,</L>
<L N="252">Til lomb of loue dyede,</L>
<L>And on me &yogh;eld &thorn;e gost wi&thorn; vois.</L>
<L>I was chose a Relik chois;</L>
<L>&THORN;e signe of Ihesu cristes crois,</L>
<L N="256">&THORN;er dar no deuel abyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L N="257">Moni folk I fende from heore fos,&mdash;</L>
<L>Cristes Cros &thorn;is sawes seide:&mdash;</L>
<L>Heuene &yogh;ates weore closed clos,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e lomb of loue dyede;</L>
<L N="261">&THORN;is is write in tixt and glos;</L>
<L>After Cristes de&thorn;, prophetes preide</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e lomb of loue dyed and ros,</L>
<L>In helle pyne, monkynde was teyde.</L>
<L N="265">At houre of his none,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lomb of loue seyde his &thorn;ou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Nou is folfuld, &thorn;at wel is wrou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>A mon is out of bondes brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="269">And heuene dores vndone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L N="270">Wi&thorn; &thorn;e ffader &thorn;at al schal folfille,</L>
<L>His sone to heuene is an help;</L>
<L>I was piler, and stod ful stille;</L>
<L>After o&thorn;ur &yogh;iftes now gostes &yogh;elp.</L>
<L N="274">&THORN;e fend &thorn;at al &thorn;is world wolde kille,</L>
<L>His swerd he pulte vp in his kelp;</L>
<L>To helle he horlede from &thorn;at hille,</L>
<L>Beerynge as a Beore whelp.</L>
<L N="278">A beore is bounden and beted,</L>
<L>Cristes Cros ha&thorn; craked his croun;
<PB REF="00000628.tif" N="620"></L>
<L>&THORN;e lomb ha&thorn; leid &thorn;e Lyoun a-doun;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lomb is lord in eueri toun,</L>
<L N="282">So cristes blod ha&thorn; pleted.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L N="283">In holy writ &thorn;is tale is herde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at goode &yogh;iftes god vs &yogh;af.</L>
<L>God sei&thorn; himself he is schepherde;</L>
<L>And vche an heerde bi-houe&thorn; a staf:</L>
<L N="287">&THORN;e Cros I calle &thorn;e heerdes &yogh;erde;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-wi&thorn;, &thorn;e deuel, a dunt he &yogh;af,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e &yogh;erde, &thorn;e wolf he werde;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; duntes drof him al to draf.</L>
<L N="291">&THORN;e Cros &thorn;is tale tolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was staf in &thorn;e heerdes hond;</L>
<L>Whon schep breken out of heore bond,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wolf he wered out of lond,</L>
<L N="295">&THORN;at deuoured cristes folde."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L N="296">&YOGH;it seide &thorn;e Meke Marie:</L>
<L>"Roode! &thorn;ou reendest my Rose al red,</L>
<L>&THORN;reo Iewes coomen from Caluari</L>
<L>&THORN;at day &thorn;at Ihesu &thorn;oled ded;</L>
<L N="300">Alle &thorn;ei seiden &thorn;ei weore sori;</L>
<L>ffor-dolled in a dronknyng dred,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei tolden hem alle wherfore and whi</L>
<L>Heore hertes were colde as lumpyng led;</L>
<L N="304">&THORN;e furste heore tale tolde:</L>
<L>'Whon crist was knit with corde on a stok,</L>
<L>His bodi bledde a&yogh;ein &thorn;at blok;</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="316b:1" UNIT="folio">&THORN;orw feet and hondes nayles gan knok,</L>
<L N="308">&THORN;en gan myn herte to colde.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L N="309">&THORN;e Secounde seide: 'nay, not &thorn;at!</L>
<L>&THORN;at dude serwe in-to myn herte schete,</L>
<L>But whon &thorn;e Roode ros, &amp; doun was squat,</L>
<L>&THORN;e nayles renten him hondes and feete;</L>
<L N="313">&THORN;orw-out his helm, &thorn;e harde hat,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ornes, in-to his flesch gan crepe;
<PB REF="00000629.tif" N="621"></L>
<L>His Ioyntes vn-Ioynet, I tok good gat;</L>
<L>&THORN;o weop I water, and teeres leete,</L>
<L N="317">To care I was enclyned;</L>
<L>In cloddres of blod, his her was clunge;</L>
<L>&THORN;e flesch was from &thorn;e bones swonge;</L>
<L>Drui&yogh;e drinkeles was his tonge;</L>
<L N="321">His lippes to-clouen and chyned.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L N="322">&THORN;e &thorn;ridde seide: '&thorn;is &thorn;ouhte me lest<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? MS. left]</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;eose peynes and o&thorn;er mo,</L>
<L>&THORN;is peyne &thorn;ouhte me peyne mest,</L>
<L>Al his flesch he let of flo.</L>
<L N="326">His Mylde Moder stod him nest,</L>
<L>Loked vpward, And hire was wo.</L>
<L>A swerd swapped hire &thorn;orw &thorn;e brest;</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e cros &thorn;e knyf com &thorn;o;</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;is siht sauh I my-selue;</L>
<L>&THORN;e swerd of loue &thorn;orw hire gan launce;</L>
<L>Heo swapte on swownyng &thorn;orw &thorn;at chaunce:</L>
<L>To scornen hire &thorn;ei gan daunce,</L>
<L N="334">Iewes bi ten and twelue.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L N="335">Sin Iewes made so muchel mon</L>
<L>To seon my brid bounden in brere;</L>
<L>In sad serwyng moste I gon,</L>
<L>To seon blodi my chyldes chere.</L>
<L N="339">ffadres &amp; Modres &thorn;at walken in won,</L>
<L>Schul loue heore children beo skiles clere;</L>
<L>&THORN;eose two loues weore in me al on,</L>
<L>ffor fader and moder I was here;</L>
<L N="343">&THORN;eose two loues in me weore dalt;</L>
<L>I was fader of his flesch;</L>
<L>His Moder hedde an herte nesch;</L>
<L>Mi serwe flowed as water fresch;</L>
<L N="347">Weopyng and wo I walt.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L N="348">IN me weore tacched sorwes two:</L>
<L>[I]n &thorn;e fader mihte non abyde,
<PB REF="00000630.tif" N="622"></L>
<L>ffor he was euere in reste and Ro,</L>
<L>Ioyned in his Ioyes wyde.</L>
<L N="352">I serwed sore for to sei so;</L>
<L>I say whon &thorn;at my derlyng dide;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; duntes he was to de&thorn;e i-do;</L>
<L>Vp-on a tre his bodi was soyled.</L>
<L N="356">Whon trou&thorn;e is told and darted,</L>
<L>Of alle Ioyes God is welle,</L>
<L>&THORN;er mihte no serwe in him dwelle,</L>
<L>I serwed sore, as Clerkes telle;</L>
<L N="360">Mi pyne was not departed.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L N="361">&THORN;E hattore loue, &thorn;e caldore care,</L>
<L>Whon frendes fynde heore fruit defoyled;</L>
<L>&THORN;e dispitous Iewes nolde not spare</L>
<L>Til trie fruit weore tore and toyled.</L>
<L N="365">Neuer Mayden Mournede mare;</L>
<L>I sauh my child ben surded and soyled,</L>
<L>Myn herte to-clef wi&thorn; swerd of care;</L>
<L>I sau&yogh; my brid with blod bem<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. ben]</NOTE>-oyled.</L>
<L N="369">As Symeon seide beo-forn,</L>
<L>&THORN;e swerde of serwe, scharp I-grounde,</L>
<L>Schulde &yogh;iue myn herte a wounde:</L>
<L>In more wo &thorn;en I was bounde,</L>
<L N="373">Neuere buirde ha&thorn; born.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L N="374">&THORN;e dede wor&thorn;ily gan wake;</L>
<L>&THORN;e dai turned to nihtes donne;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Merke Mone gan Mournyng make;<MILESTONE N="316b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e lyht out leop of &thorn;e sonne;</L>
<L N="378">&THORN;e temple walles gan chiuere &amp; schake;</L>
<L>Veiles in &thorn;e temple, a-two &thorn;ei sponne.</L>
<L>Cros! whi noldestou not crake,</L>
<L>Whon rihtful blod on &thorn;e was ronne,</L>
<L N="382">And kuyndes losten heore kende?</L>
<L>Whon my fruit on &thorn;e was fast,</L>
<L>Cros! whi weore &thorn;ou not agast?</L>
<L>&THORN;ow stod stif as eny mast,</L>
<L N="386">Whon lyf left vp his ende.
<PB REF="00000631.tif" N="623"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L N="387">Whon &thorn;at Prince of Paradys</L>
<L>Bledde bo&thorn;e brest and bak,</L>
<L>An he&thorn;ene clerk was seint Denys:</L>
<L>He seide, &thorn;is world wente al to wrak;</L>
<L N="391">He sau&yogh; &thorn;e planetes passen out of here pris;</L>
<L>&THORN;e brihte sonne gan waxen blak:</L>
<L>&THORN;e clerk &thorn;at was so wonderly wys,</L>
<L>Wonder wordes &thorn;er he spak.</L>
<L N="395">Denys, &thorn;is grete Clerke, seide,</L>
<L>'&THORN;e day of doom drawe&thorn; to an ende;</L>
<L>Al vr kuyndes ha&thorn; lost vr kende,</L>
<L>Til God &thorn;at dyed for vch a kuynde,</L>
<L N="399">ffor Monnes kuynde deyde.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L N="400">Foules fellen out of heore fliht;</L>
<L>Beestes gan Belwe in eueri binne.</L>
<L>Cros! whon Crist on &thorn;e was cliht,</L>
<L>Whi noldestou not of mournyng minne?"</L>
<L N="404">&THORN;e Cros seide, "ladi briht!</L>
<L>I bar ones &thorn;i fruit for monnes sinne,</L>
<L>More to amende monnes riht,</L>
<L>&THORN;en for eny weol&thorn;e &thorn;at I gan winne;</L>
<L N="408">Wi&thorn; blod, God bou&yogh;te his bro&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Whon Adam, Godes biddyng brak,</L>
<L>He bot a bite &thorn;at made vs blak,</L>
<L>Til fruit weore tied on treo wi&thorn; tak;</L>
<L N="412">O fruit for ano&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L N="413">Sin Cristes Cros &thorn;at kepe&thorn; &yogh;ifte,</L>
<L>Graunted of &thorn;e fadres graunt,</L>
<L>I was loked I schulde vp lifte</L>
<L>Godes sone and maydenes faunt,</L>
<L N="417">No Mon hedde scheld of schrifte;</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel stod lyk a lyon raumpaunt,</L>
<L>Mony folk In-to helle he clihte,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e crosses dunt &yogh;af him a daunt.</L>
<L N="421">Mi dedes are bounden and booked;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e werkes &thorn;at I haue wrouht,
<PB REF="00000632.tif" N="624"></L>
<L>Weore founden in &thorn;e ffaderes fore-&thorn;ouht;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, ladi, lakke&thorn; me nouht,</L>
<L N="425">I dude as me was looked.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L N="426">&THORN;orw Blod &amp; watur, cristendam was wrouht,</L>
<L>Holy writ witnesse&thorn; hit wel,</L>
<L>And in wille of so&thorn;fast &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>A Mon mai be cristened skil;</L>
<L N="430">&THORN;at blod &thorn;at us alle bouht,</L>
<L>Digne cristenyng gan vs del.</L>
<L>At cristenyng, crist for-&yogh;at vs nouht,</L>
<L>His blessede blod whon we gan fel.</L>
<L N="434">Maiden, Moder, and Wyue,</L>
<L>&THORN;i fruit ha&thorn; &yogh;iuen vs baptem:</L>
<L>Cristened we weore In Red[de] rem,</L>
<L>Whon his bodi bledde on &thorn;e Beem</L>
<L N="438">Of Cipresse and Olyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L N="439">As Ihesu seide to Nichodemus,</L>
<L>'But a Barn be twy&yogh;es born,</L>
<L>Whon domus-day schal blowen his bemus,</L>
<L>He may elles liggen loddere for-lorn.</L>
<L N="443">ffurst of a wombe &thorn;er reu&thorn;e remus;</L>
<L>Si&thorn;&thorn;e in a font &thorn;er synne awey is schorn.'</L>
<L>I was cros to monnes quemus,</L>
<L>I bar &thorn;e fruit &thorn;ow bar bi-forn</L>
<L N="447">ffor &thorn;i beryng Al one.</L>
<L>But &yogh;if I hedde I-boren him eft,</L>
<L>ffrom riche reste mon hedde beo-reft.</L>
<L>In a loren logge I-left,</L>
<L N="451">Ay to grunte and grone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L N="452">&THORN;ou art I-Crouned heuene quene,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;e bur&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou beere;</L>
<L>&THORN;i garlond is al of graces grene,</L>
<L>Helle, Emperesse, in heuene Empere;</L>
<L N="456">I am a Relyk &thorn;at shine&thorn; shene,</L>
<L>Men wold wite wher &thorn;at I were.
<PB REF="00000633.tif" N="625"></L>
<L>At &thorn;e parlement wol I bene,</L>
<L>On domes-day prestly a-pere,</L>
<L N="460">Whon Ihesu schal seye riht &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>'Trewely, vppon &thorn;e Roode tre,</L>
<L>Mon, I dyede for &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Mon, what hastou don for me</L>
<L N="464">To beon my frendly feere?'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L N="465">At &thorn;e parlement, shul putten vp pleynyng,</L>
<L>Hou Maydenes fruit on me gan sterue,</L>
<L>Spere &amp; spounge and sharp nayling</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;e harde hat &thorn;e heued shal kerue,</L>
<L N="469">Shul preie to &thorn;at rihtful kyng;</L>
<L>Vche mon schal haue as &thorn;ei a-serue;</L>
<L>Rihtful schul ryse to riche restyng,</L>
<L>Truyt and tripet to helle shal sterue.</L>
<L N="473">Mayden, Meoke and Mylde,</L>
<L>God ha&thorn; taken in &thorn;e his fleschly trene;</L>
<L>I bar &thorn;i fruit leo&thorn;i and lene;</L>
<L>Hit is riht &thorn;e Roode helpe to a-rene</L>
<L N="477">Wrecches &thorn;at wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;i chylde."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<L N="478">&THORN;E queen a-cordet wi&thorn; &thorn;e cros,<MILESTONE N="316b:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And a&yogh;eyn him spak no more speche.</L>
<L>&THORN;e queen &yogh;af &thorn;e Cros a cos;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ladi of loue, loue gan seche,</L>
<L N="482">&THORN;ei&yogh; hire fruit on him were di&yogh;t to dros,</L>
<L>Whon rendyng ropus gan him reche.</L>
<L>Cristes cros ha&thorn; kept vs from los,</L>
<L>Maries preyers, And God, vr leche,</L>
<L N="486">&THORN;e qween and &thorn;e Cros acorde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e qween bar furst, &thorn;e cros afturward,</L>
<L>To fecche folk from helleward,</L>
<L>On holy stayers to steyen vpward,</L>
<L N="490">And regne wi&thorn; God vr lorde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<L N="491">&THORN;E Clerk &thorn;at fourmed &thorn;is figour,</L>
<L>Of Maries wo to wite som,
<PB REF="00000634.tif" N="626"></L>
<L>He saih him-self &thorn;at harde stour,</L>
<L>Whon godes armus weore rent aroun.</L>
<L N="495">&THORN;e Cros is a cold Creatour,</L>
<L>And euere &yogh;it ha&thorn; ben def and dom.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei&yogh; &thorn;is tale beo florisshed with faire flour,</L>
<L>I preue hit on Apocrafum,</L>
<L N="499">ffor witnesse was neuer foundet</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuere cristes cros spak;</L>
<L>Oure ladi leide on him no lak;</L>
<L>Bot to pulte &thorn;e deuel abak,</L>
<L N="503">We speke hou crist was woundet.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<L>IN ffleschly wede, God gan<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. gam</NOTE> him hede, Of Mylde May,</L>
<L>Was bore to blede, As Cristes Crede So&thorn;ly wol say;</L>
<L>On a stokly stede He Rod, we Rede, In Red Array;</L>
<L>ffrom deueles drede, &THORN;at Duyk vs lede, At domes-day,<NOTE PLACE="foot">These 4 lines are written as 4 stanzas, <I>aab</I>, in the MS. See st. 1.</NOTE></L>
<L N="508">Whon peple schal parte and pace</L>
<L>To heuene halle, or to helle woode,</L>
<L>Cristes cros and cristes blode,</L>
<L>And Marie preiers &thorn;at ben ful goode,</L>
<L N="512">Grant vs &thorn;e lyf of grace! Amen!</L>
<TRAILER>Explicit disputacio inter Mariam<LB>Et Crucem, secundum Apocrafum.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="53" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>LIII. Susannah, or Seemly Susan.</HEAD>
<P>[28 alliterative Stanzas of thirteen: <I>abab abab, cdddc</I>, the last adding a couplet <I>aa.</I>]</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;er was in Babiloine a bern, in &thorn;at borw riche,<MILESTONE N="317:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at was a Ieu&yogh; ientil, &amp; Ioachin he hiht;</L>
<L>He was so lele in his lawe, &thorn;er liued non him liche;</L>
<L N="4">Of alle riche arayes, &thorn;at renke<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;at renke arayes (Gollancz)</NOTE> he was riht;</L>
<L>His Innes &amp; his orchardus were with a dep dich,</L>
<L>Halles &amp; herbergages, hei&yogh; vppon heiht.</L>
<L>To seche &thorn;oru &thorn;at cite, &thorn;er nas non sich,</L>
<L N="8">Of erbus, and of erberi, so auenauntliche I-diht
<PB REF="00000635.tif" N="627"></L>
<L N="9">&THORN;at day,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-Inne &thorn;e sercle of sees</L>
<L>Of Erberi, and Alees,</L>
<L>Of alle Maner of trees</L>
<L N="13">So&thorn;ely to say.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="14">&para; He hed a wif hi&yogh;t Susan, was sotil and sage;</L>
<L>Heo was Elches dou&yogh;tur, eldest and eyre,</L>
<L>Louelich &amp; liliewhit, on of &thorn;at lynage,</L>
<L N="17">Of alle fason of foode, frelich and feire;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei lerned hire lettrure of &thorn;at langage,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maundement of Moises &thorn;ei marked to &thorn;at may,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Mount of Synai &thorn;at went in Message</L>
<L N="21">&THORN;at &thorn;e Trinite bi-tok of tables a peire</L>
<L N="22">To Rede.</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;ei lerne hire &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>Cleer Clergye to knawe;</L>
<L>To God stod hire gret awe,</L>
<L N="26">&THORN;at wlonkest in weede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="27">&para; He hedde an orchard newe, &thorn;at nei&yogh;ed wel nere,</L>
<L>&THORN;er Iewus with Ioachim priueliche gon playe,</L>
<L>For he real &amp; riche, of rentes euer &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="30">Honest and auenaunt, and honorablest aye,</L>
<L>I-wis &thorn;er haunted til her hous, hende, &yogh;e mai here,</L>
<L>Two demers<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. do|mus]</NOTE> of &thorn;at lawe, &thorn;at dredde were &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>Preostes and presidens, preised als peere,</L>
<L N="34">Of whom vr souerein lord sawes gan say,</L>
<L N="35">And tolde</L>
<L>How heor wikkednes comes,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e wrongwys domes</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei haue gyue to gomes,</L>
<L N="39">&THORN;is Iuges of olde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="40">&para; &THORN;us &thorn;is dredful demers on daies &thorn;ider drewe,</L>
<L>Al for gentrise and Ioye of &thorn;at Iuwesse,</L>
<L>To go in his gardeyn, &thorn;at gayliche grewe:</L>
<L N="43">To fonge flourus and fruit, &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;ei no fresse;
<PB REF="00000636.tif" N="628"></L>
<L>And whon &thorn;ei sei&yogh; Susan, semelich of hewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei weor so set vppon hire, mi&yogh;t &thorn;ei not sese,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei wolde enchaunte &thorn;at child, hou schold heo eschewe;</L>
<L N="48">And &thorn;us &thorn;is cherlus vnchaste, in chaumbre hir chese Wi&thorn; chere.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; two Maidenes al on,</L>
<L>Semelyche Suson,</L>
<L>On dayes in &thorn;e merion,</L>
<L N="52">Of Mur&thorn;es wol here.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="53">&para; Whon &thorn;eos perlous prestes perceyued hire play,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;e wrecches to bewile &thorn;at worly in wone;</L>
<L>Heore wittes wel wai-wordus &thorn;ei wrethen awai,</L>
<L N="56">And turned fro his teching, &thorn;at teeld is in trone.</L>
<L>ffor siht of here souerayn, so&thorn;li to say,</L>
<L>Heore hor heuedus fro heuene &thorn;ei hid apon one;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei cau&yogh;t, for heor couetyse, &thorn;e cursyng of kai;</L>
<L N="60">ffor ri&yogh;twys Iugement recordet &thorn;ei none,</L>
<L N="61">&THORN;ey two.</L>
<L>Euery day bi day,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Pomeri &thorn;ei play,</L>
<L>Whiles &thorn;ei mihte Susan assay,</L>
<L N="65">To worchen hire wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="66">&para; In &thorn;e seson of somere, with Sibelle and Ione,</L>
<L>Heo grei&thorn;ed hire til hire gardin, &thorn;at growed so grene;</L>
<L>&THORN;er lyndes and lorers were lent vpon lone,</L>
<L N="69">&THORN;e sauyne and sypres, selcou&thorn; to sene,</L>
<L>&THORN;e palme and &thorn;e poplere, &thorn;e pirie, &thorn;e plone,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iunipere ientel, Ionyng bi-twene,</L>
<L>&THORN;e rose ragged on rys, richest on Rone,</L>
<L N="73">I-&thorn;euwed with &thorn;e &thorn;orn, trinaunt to sene,</L>
<L N="74">So tiht.</L>
<L>&THORN;er weore Pope-iayes prest,</L>
<L>Nightyngales vppon nest,</L>
<L>Bli&thorn;est Briddes o &thorn;e best,</L>
<L N="78">In Blossoms so briht.
<PB REF="00000637.tif" N="629"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="79">&para; &THORN;e Briddes, in Blossoms, &thorn;ei beeren wel loude,</L>
<L>On olyues and amylliers, and al kynde of trees:</L>
<L>&THORN;e popeiayes perken, and pruynen for proude;<MILESTONE N="317:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="82">On peren and pynappel, &thorn;ei ioyken in pees,</L>
<L>On croppus of canel, keneliche &thorn;ei croude;</L>
<L>On grapes &thorn;e goldfinch &thorn;ei gladen and glees.</L>
<L>&THORN;us schene briddus in schawe schewen heore schroude;</L>
<L N="86">On ffirres and fygers, &thorn;ei fongen heore seetes</L>
<L N="87">In ffay.</L>
<L>&THORN;er weore growyng so grene,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Date wi&thorn; &thorn;e Damesene;</L>
<L>Turtils troned on trene,</L>
<L N="91">By sixti, I say&yogh;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="92">&para; &THORN;e fyge and &thorn;e filbert were fodemed so fayre,</L>
<L>&THORN;e chirie and &thorn;e chestein, &thorn;at chosen is of hewe,</L>
<L>Apples and Almaundus, &thorn;at honest are of ayre,</L>
<L N="95">Grapus and garnettes, gayliche &thorn;ei grewe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e costardes comeliche in cu&thorn;&thorn;es &thorn;ei cayre,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Britouns, &thorn;e Blaunderers, Braunches &thorn;e bewe,</L>
<L>ffele flourus and fruit, frelich of flayre,</L>
<L N="99">With wardons winlich, and walshenotes newe,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;ey waled.</L>
<L>Ouer heor hedes gon hyng</L>
<L>&THORN;e wince and &thorn;e wederlyng;</L>
<L>Spyces speden to spryng,</L>
<L N="104">In Erbers enhaled.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="105">&para; &THORN;e chyue and &thorn;e chollet, &thorn;e chibolle, &thorn;e cheue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e chouwet, &thorn;e cheuerol, &thorn;at schaggen on niht;</L>
<L>&THORN;e persel, &thorn;e passenep, poretes to preue,</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;e pyon, &thorn;e peere, wel proudliche I-piht;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lilye, &thorn;e louache, launsyng wi&thorn; leue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sauge, &thorn;e sorsecle, so semeliche to siht;</L>
<L>Columbyne and Charuwe, clottes &thorn;ei creue,</L>
<L N="112">With Ruwe and Rubarbe, Ragget ariht,</L>
<L N="113">No lees;</L>
<L>Daysye and Ditoyne,
<PB REF="00000638.tif" N="630"></L>
<L>Ysope and Aueroyne,</L>
<L>Peletre and Plauntoyne,</L>
<L N="117">Proudest In pres.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L N="118">&para; Als &thorn;is schaply &thorn;ing, &yogh;ede in hire &yogh;arde</L>
<L>&THORN;at was hir hosbondus, and hire &thorn;at holden with hende,</L>
<L>"Nou folk be faren from us, &thorn;ar us not be ferde;</L>
<L N="121">Aftur myn oynement warliche &yogh;e weende;</L>
<L>Aspie&thorn; nou specialy &thorn;e &yogh;ates ben sperde,</L>
<L>ffor we wol wassche us I-wis bi &thorn;is welle strende."</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i &thorn;e wif werp of hir wedes vn-werde;</L>
<L N="125">Vndur a lorere ful lowe &thorn;at ladi gan leende</L>
<L N="126">So sone.</L>
<L>By a wynliche welle,</L>
<L>Susan caste of hir kelle;</L>
<L>Bote feole ferlys hire bi-felle</L>
<L N="130">Bi Midday or none.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L N="131">&para; Nou were &thorn;is domus men derf drawen in derne,</L>
<L>Whiles &thorn;ei seo &thorn;at ladi was laft al hire one;</L>
<L>fforte heilse &thorn;at hende, &thorn;ei hi&yogh;ed ful &yogh;erne;</L>
<L>With wordus &thorn;ei worshipe &thorn;at worliche in wone:</L>
<L N="135">"Wolt &thorn;ou, ladi, for loue, on vre lay lerne,</L>
<L>And vndur &thorn;is lorere ben vr lemmone?</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ne &thorn;arf wonde for no wi&yogh;t vr willes to werne;</L>
<L>ffor alle gomus &thorn;at scholde greue, of gardin ar gone</L>
<L N="139">In ffeere.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou &thorn;is neodes deny,</L>
<L>We schal telle trewely,</L>
<L>We toke &thorn;e wi&thorn; a-voutri</L>
<L N="143">Vnder &thorn;is Lorere."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L N="144">&para; &THORN;en Susan was serwful, and seide in hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>"I am with serwe bi-set on eueriche syde:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if I assent to &thorn;is sin, &thorn;at &thorn;is segges haue sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="147">I be bretenet and brent in baret to byde;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if I nikke hem with nai, hit helpe&thorn; me nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Such toret and teone take&thorn; me &thorn;is tyde.
<PB REF="00000639.tif" N="631"></L>
<L>Are I &thorn;at worthliche wrethe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. wreche]</NOTE> &thorn;at al &thorn;is world wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="151">Betere is wemles weende of &thorn;is world wyde."</L>
<L N="152">Wi&thorn; &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;o Cast heo a Careful cri,</L>
<L>&THORN;is loueliche Ladi:</L>
<L>Hir seruauns hedde selli,</L>
<L N="156">No wonder I-wis.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L N="157">&para; Whon kene men of hir court comen til hir cri,</L>
<L>Heo hedde cast of hir calle, and hire keuercheue;</L>
<L>In at a priue posterne &thorn;ei passen in hi,</L>
<L>And findes &thorn;is prestes wel prest, her poyntus to preue:</L>
<L N="161">&THORN;o seide &thorn;e loselle a-loude to &thorn;e ladi,<MILESTONE N="317:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"&THORN;ou hast gon wi&thorn; a gome, &thorn;i god to greue,</L>
<L>And ligge with &thorn;i lemon In a-voutri:</L>
<L N="164">Bi &thorn;e lord and &thorn;e lawe &thorn;at we onne leeue,"</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;ey swere.</L>
<L>Alle hire seruauns &thorn;ei shont,</L>
<L>And stelen a-wey in a stont;</L>
<L>Of hire weore &thorn;ei neuer wont</L>
<L N="169">Such wordes to here.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L N="170">&para; Hir kinrede, hir cosyns, and al &thorn;at hire knewe,</L>
<L>Wrong handes I-wis, and wepten wel sore,</L>
<L>Sykeden for susan, so semeliche of hewe;</L>
<L N="173">Al onwyse of &thorn;at wyf, wondred &thorn;ei wore.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei dede hire in a dungon, &thorn;er neuer day dewe,</L>
<L>While domus men were dempt, &thorn;is dede to clare,</L>
<L>Marred in Manicles &thorn;at made wer newe,</L>
<L N="177">Meteles, whiles &thorn;e Morwen to Middai &amp; mare,</L>
<L N="178">In drede.</L>
<L>&THORN;er com hir fader so fre,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al his affinite;</L>
<L>&THORN;e prestes sauns pite,</L>
<L N="182">And ful of ffalshede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L N="183">&para; &THORN;o seide &thorn;e Iustises on bench to Ioachim &thorn;e Iewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was of Iacobus kynde, gentil of dedes;
<PB REF="00000640.tif" N="632"></L>
<L>"Let senden aftur Susan, so semelych of hewe,</L>
<L N="186">&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast weddet to wif, wlankest in wedes.</L>
<L>Heo was in trou&thorn;e, as we trowe, tristi and trewe;</L>
<L>Hir herte holliche on him &thorn;at &thorn;e heuene hedes."</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;ei brou&yogh;t hire to &thorn;e barre, hir bales to brewe.</L>
<L N="190">Nou&thorn;ur dom ne de&thorn;, &thorn;at day heo ne dredes</L>
<L N="191">Als &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Hir hed was &yogh;olow as wyre,</L>
<L>Of gold fyned wi&thorn; fyre;</L>
<L>Hire scholdres schaply and schire,</L>
<L N="195">&THORN;at bureliche was bare.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L N="196">&para; Nou is Susan in sale, sengeliche arayed</L>
<L>In a selken schert, with scholdres wel schene.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Ros vp with rancour &thorn;e Renkes reneyed;</L>
<L N="199">&THORN;is comelich accused with wordes wel kene:</L>
<L>Homliche on hir heued, heor hondus &thorn;ei leyed,&mdash;</L>
<L>And heo wepte for wo, no wonder I wene,&mdash;</L>
<L>"We schul presenten &thorn;is pleint, hou &thorn;ou euer be paied,</L>
<L N="203">And sei sadliche &thorn;e so&thorn;, ri&yogh;t as we haue sene,</L>
<L N="204">O Sake."</L>
<L>&THORN;us wi&thorn; cauteles waynt,</L>
<L>Preostes presented &thorn;is playnt;</L>
<L>&YOGH;it schal trou&thorn;e hem a-taynt,</L>
<L N="208">I dar vnder-take.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L N="209">&para; "&THORN;orw-out &thorn;e pomeri, we passed us to play,&mdash;</L>
<L>Of preiere and of penaunce was vre purpose;&mdash;</L>
<L>Heo com with two Maidens, al richeli &thorn;at day,</L>
<L N="212">In riche robus arayed, red as &thorn;e rose.</L>
<L>Wylyliche heo wyled hir wenches a-way,</L>
<L>And comaunded hem kenely &thorn;e &yogh;ates to close.</L>
<L>Heo eode to a &yogh;ong mon in a valay,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>alterd from</I> valey]</NOTE></L>
<L N="216">&THORN;e semblaunt of Susan wolde non suppose,</L>
<L N="217">ffor so&thorn;.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;is cause &thorn;at we say,</L>
<L>Heo wyled hir wenches a-way;</L>
<L>&THORN;is word we witnesse for ay,</L>
<L N="221">Wi&thorn; tonge and wi&thorn; to&thorn;.
<PB REF="00000641.tif" N="633"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whon we &thorn;at semblaunt sei&yogh;, we siked wel sare,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>alterd from</I> sore]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor sert of hir souureyn, and for hir owne sake;</L>
<L>Vr copus weore cumberous, and cundelet vs care,</L>
<L N="225">But &yogh;it we trinet a trot, &thorn;at traytur [to] take.</L>
<L>He was borlich and bigge, bold as a bare,</L>
<L>More mi&yogh;ti mon &thorn;en we, his Maistris to Make.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e &yogh;ate &yogh;aply &thorn;ei &yogh;eoden wel &yogh;are,</L>
<L N="229">And he lift vp &thorn;e lach, and leop ouer &thorn;e lake,</L>
<L N="230">&THORN;at &yogh;outhe.</L>
<L>Heo ne schunte for no schame,</L>
<L>But bouwed aftur for blame.</L>
<L>Heo nolde cuy&thorn;e vs his name,</L>
<L N="234">ffor craft &thorn;at we cou&thorn;e."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Nou heo is dampned on deis, with deol &thorn;au&yogh; hir deu[e],</L>
<L>And hir domus men vnduwe do hir be with-drawen:</L>
<L N="237">Loueliche heo louted, and lacched hir leue,</L>
<L>At kynred and cosyn &thorn;at heo hed euere i-knawen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>alterd from</I> knowen]</NOTE></L>
<L>Heo asked Merci with mou&thorn; in &thorn;is mischeue:</L>
<L>"I am sakeles of syn," heo seide in hir sawen;</L>
<L>"Grete god of his grace, &yogh;or gultus for-&yogh;iue,<MILESTONE N="317b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at do&thorn; me derfliche be ded and don out of dawen</L>
<L N="243">Wi&thorn; dere.</L>
<L>Wolde god &thorn;at I miht</L>
<L>Speke wi&thorn; Ioachim a niht,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en to de&thorn; me be diht,</L>
<L N="247">I charge hit not a pere."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Heo fel doun flat in &thorn;e flore, hir feere whon heo fond,</L>
<L N="249">Carped to him kyndeli, as heo ful wel cou&thorn;e:</L>
<L>"I-wis I wra&thorn;&thorn;ed &thorn;e neuere, at my witand,</L>
<L>Nei&thorn;er in word ne in werk, in elde ne in &yogh;ou&thorn;e,"</L>
<L>Heo keuered vp-on hir kneos, and cussed his hand,</L>
<L>"ffor I am dampned, I ne dar disparage &thorn;i mou&thorn;."</L>
<L N="254">Was neuer more serwful segge, bi se nor bi sande,</L>
<L>Ne neuer a soriore siht, bi nor&thorn; ne bi sou&thorn;,</L>
<L N="256">&THORN;o &thorn;are.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei toke &thorn;e ffeteres of hire feete,
<PB REF="00000642.tif" N="634"></L>
<L>And euere he cussed &thorn;at swete:</L>
<L>"In o&thorn;er world schul we mete:"</L>
<L N="260">Seide he no mare.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L N="261">&para; &THORN;en Susan &thorn;e serwfol seide uppon hi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Heef hir hondus on hi&yogh;, bi-held heo to heuene:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou maker of Middelert &thorn;at most art of miht,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e sonne and &thorn;e see, &thorn;ou sette vppon seuene;</L>
<L N="265">Alle my werkes &thorn;ou wost, &thorn;e wrong and &thorn;e riht,</L>
<L>Hit is nedful nou &thorn;i names to nempne</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e I am deolfolich dampned, and to de&thorn; diht.</L>
<L>Lord, herteliche tak hede, and herkne my steuene</L>
<L N="269">So ffre!</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t not be sene</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; no fleschliche eyene,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wost wel &thorn;at I am clene;</L>
<L N="273">Haue Merci nou on me!"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Nou &thorn;ei dresse hire to de&thorn; with-outen eny drede,</L>
<L>And lede for&thorn; &thorn;at ladi, louesum of lere.</L>
<L>Grete god, of his grace, of gultes<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? gyftes, G.]</NOTE> vngnede,</L>
<L N="277">Help with &thorn;e holi gost, and herde hir preyere.</L>
<L>He directed &thorn;is dom, and &thorn;is delful dede,</L>
<L>To Danyel &thorn;e prophete, of dedes so dere,</L>
<L>Such &yogh;iftes god him &yogh;af in his &yogh;ou&thorn;ehede:</L>
<L N="281">&YOGH;it failed hit a fourteniht ful of &thorn;e &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="282">Nouht layne.</L>
<L>&THORN;o criede &thorn;at freoly foode,</L>
<L>"Whi spille &yogh;e Innocens blode?"</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e[i] stoteyd and stode,</L>
<L N="286">&THORN;is ferlys to frayne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "What signefyes, gode sone, &thorn;ese sawus &thorn;at &thorn;ou seis?"</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;ese Maisterful men [with] mou&thorn;es can mele.</L>
<L>"&THORN;ei be fendus, al &thorn;e frape, I sei hit in fei&thorn;;</L>
<L N="290">And in folk of I[s]rael be foles wel fele.</L>
<L>Vmbiloke &yogh;ou, lordes; such lawes ben lei&thorn;;</L>
<L>Me &thorn;inke&thorn; &yogh;or dedes vnduwe, such domus to dele.</L>
<L>A&yogh;ein to &thorn;e &yogh;ild-halle &yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. &thorn;e]</NOTE> gomes vn-grei&thorn;;</L>
<L N="294">I schal, be proces apert, disproue &thorn;is a-pele
<PB REF="00000643.tif" N="635"></L>
<L N="295">ffor nede.</L>
<L>Lat twinne hem in two,</L>
<L>For now wakne&thorn; heor wo;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei schal graunte, ar &thorn;ei go,</L>
<L N="299">Al heore falshede."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L N="300">&para; &THORN;ei diseuered hem sone, and sette hem sere;</L>
<L>And sodeynly askede, &thorn;ei brou&yogh;t in-to &thorn;e sale;</L>
<L>Bi-fore &thorn;is &yogh;onge prophete &thorn;is preost gon apere,</L>
<L N="303">And he him apeched sone with chekes wel pale,</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou hast I-be presedent, &thorn;e peple to steere;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou dotest nou on &thorn;in olde tos in &thorn;e dismale.</L>
<L>Now schal &thorn;i conscience be knowen, &thorn;at euer was vnclere;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast in babiloygne on benche brewed muche bale,</L>
<L N="308">Wel bolde.</L>
<L>Nou schal &yogh;or synnes be seene,</L>
<L>Of ffals domes bi-deene,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;eose In Babiloyne han bene</L>
<L N="312">Iugget of Olde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L N="313">&para; &THORN;ou seidest &thorn;ou se&yogh;e Susanne sinned in &thorn;i siht.</L>
<L>Tel nou me trewly, vnder what tre?"</L>
<L>"Mon, bi &thorn;e muche god, &thorn;at most is of miht,</L>
<L N="316">Vndur a Cyne, so&thorn;li my-seluen I hir se."</L>
<L>"Nou &thorn;ou lyest in &thorn;in hed, bi heuen vppon hiht!</L>
<L>An Angel with a naked swerd &thorn;e nei&yogh;es wel nere;</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; brandist his brond brennynde so bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To Marke &thorn;i middel at a Mase in more &thorn;en in &thorn;re,</L>
<L N="321">No lese.<MILESTONE N="317b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou Brak godes Comaundement,</L>
<L>To sle such an Innocent</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; eny fals Iuggement</L>
<L N="325">Vn-duweliche on dese."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Nou is &thorn;is domus-mon with-drawen with-outen eni drede,</L>
<L>And put in-to prison a&yogh;eyn in-to place.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei brou&yogh;ten &thorn;e to&thorn;ur for&thorn;, whom &thorn;e barn bede,</L>
<L N="329">To-fore &thorn;e folk and &thorn;e faunt freli of face:
<PB REF="00000644.tif" N="636"></L>
<L>"Cum for&thorn;, &thorn;ou corsed caytif, &thorn;ou Canaan!" he sede;</L>
<L>"Bi-cause of &thorn;i couetise &thorn;ou art in &thorn;is case.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast disceyuet &thorn;i-self with &thorn;in oune dede;</L>
<L N="333">Of &thorn;i wit for a wyf, bi-wiled &thorn;ou wase</L>
<L N="334">In wede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sey nou, so mote &thorn;ou &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Vnder what kynde of tre,</L>
<L>Semeli Susan &thorn;ou se</L>
<L N="338">Do &thorn;at derne dede?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L N="339">&para; &THORN;ou gome of gret elde, &thorn;in hed is grei hored;</L>
<L>Tel hit me treweli, ar &thorn;ou &thorn;i lyf tyne."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at ro&thorn;li cherl ruydely rored,</L>
<L>And seide bi-fore &thorn;e prophet, "&thorn;ei pleied bi a prine."</L>
<L>"Nou &thorn;ou liest loude, so helpe me vr lord!</L>
<L>ffor ful&thorn;e of &thorn;i falshed &thorn;ou schalt ha euel pine;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou and &thorn;i cursed cumpere, &yogh;e mou not a-corde.</L>
<L N="346">&YOGH;e schul be drawen to &thorn;e de&thorn; &thorn;is dai ar we dine</L>
<L N="347">So Ra&thorn;e.</L>
<L>An Angel is neih honde,</L>
<L>Takes &thorn;e domes of &yogh;or honde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a Brennynge bronde</L>
<L N="351">To byte &yogh;ou ba&thorn;e."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L N="352">&para; &THORN;en &thorn;e folk of Israel felle vppon knes,</L>
<L>And lowed &thorn;at loueli lord &thorn;at hire &thorn;e lyf lent.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e gomus &thorn;at hire god wolde gladen and glees,</L>
<L N="355">&THORN;is prophete so pertli proues his entent.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei trompe bifore &thorn;is traiturs, and traylen hem on tres</L>
<L>&THORN;orow-out &thorn;e Cite, bi comuyn assent.</L>
<L>Hose leeue&thorn; on &thorn;at lord, &thorn;ar him not lees,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;us his seruaunt saued &thorn;at schold ha be schent</L>
<L N="360">In Sete.</L>
<L>&THORN;is ferlys bi-fel</L>
<L>In &thorn;e days of Danyel:</L>
<L>&THORN;e pistel witnesse&thorn; wel</L>
<L N="364">Of &thorn;at profete.</L>
<L>Ihesu crist, wi&thorn; mylde steuene,</L>
<L>Graunt us alle &thorn;e blisse of heuene! Amen!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="54" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000645.tif" N="637">
<HEAD>LIV. Testamentum Christi.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>MS. Vernon, Fol. 317 b.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Jhesu, kyng of heuene and helle,</L>
<L>Mon and wommon, I wol &thorn;e telle</L>
<L>What loue I haue I-don to &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Loke what &thorn;ou hast don to me!
<PB REF="00000646.tif" N="638"></L>
<L>Of alle Joye &thorn;ou weore out pult</L>
<L>With resoun and wi&thorn; &thorn;in oune gult;</L>
<L>Pore &thorn;ou weore I-dryuen a-way,</L>
<L N="8">As a best &thorn;at go&thorn; on-stray.</L>
<L>ffrom my kindome I com doun,</L>
<L>Te seche &thorn;e from toun to toun;</L>
<L>Min heritage, &thorn;at is so fre,</L>
<L N="12">In &thorn;i mischef to &yogh;iue hit &thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000647.tif" N="639"></L>
<L>And whon &thorn;at &yogh;ifte I &yogh;iuen &thorn;e scholde,</L>
<L>I dude as &thorn;e lawe wolde:</L>
<L>To a Mayden I meked me,</L>
<L N="16">ffor no chalange schulde be;</L>
<L>wel dernely I kepte &thorn;e and me</L>
<L>Til I my tyme wolde se,</L>
<L>ffourti wokes and fourti dawes,</L>
<L N="20">To folfulle &thorn;e olde lawes.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Mayden was trewe, mylde &amp; fre,</L>
<L>Heo receyued me for &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;orw my monhede and my grace,</L>
<L N="24">&thorn;us com sesyng furst on place.</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;e sesyng was do so,</L>
<L>fful gret envye hedde &thorn;enne &thorn;i fo;</L>
<L>&thorn;enne Belsebub and Sathanas</L>
<L N="28">Hedde gret wonder whi hit was;
<PB REF="00000648.tif" N="640"></L>
<L>&thorn;ei fondede me wi&thorn; felony,</L>
<L>wi&thorn; pride, couetyse and gloteny,</L>
<L>And wel &thorn;ei wuste I was a mon;</L>
<L N="32">But synne in me founde &thorn;ei non.</L>
<L>Harde &thorn;ei &thorn;reted me in her &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ilke sesyng schulde be deore abou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&thorn;ei sende heore sergeauns with maystrie,</L>
<L N="36">with wo and serwe me to distruye,</L>
<L>And wel &thorn;ei founde hem geyned nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;ur help was in my &thorn;ou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>More siker &thorn;e to make</L>
<L N="40">A&yogh;eyn &thorn;i foos, ful of wrake,</L>
<L>Heuene and eor&thorn;e in present</L>
<L>To make a chartre of feffement;</L>
<L>In such a maner &thorn;en moste hit be</L>
<L N="44">&thorn;at I moste &yogh;iue my lyf for &thorn;e:
<PB REF="00000649.tif" N="641"></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou art ded, and I am lyf,</L>
<L>And I moste dye to &yogh;iue &thorn;e lyf.</L>
<L>Mony a wei haue I go</L>
<L N="48">In hongur and &thorn;urst, colde and wo,</L>
<L>&thorn;ritti winter and more &thorn;en two,</L>
<L>Or my dede weore al I-do</L>
<L>Ne mihte I fynde no parchemyn</L>
<L N="52">ffor to laste wi&thorn;-outen fyn;</L>
<L>Bote, as good loue bad me do,</L>
<L>Min oune skin I tok &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>To gete me frendes, I &yogh;af good mede;</L>
<L N="56">So do&thorn; &thorn;e pore &thorn;at ha&thorn; gret nede:
<PB REF="00000650.tif" N="642"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On a &thorn;oresday a soper I made,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e frend and fo to maken glade,</L>
<L>wi&thorn; mete and drynk to soulus fode,</L>
<L N="60">with holi word my flesch and blode:</L>
<L>And &thorn;is I made for Monkynde,</L>
<L>Mi loue-dedes to haue in mynde:</L>
<L><I>Hoc facite in meam commemoracionem.</I></L>
<L>Or I fro &thorn;e bord a-ras,</L>
<L N="64">Of my frend bi-trayed I was;</L>
<L>He fond me goande in &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e Leoun go&thorn; to his pray:
<PB REF="00000651.tif" N="643"></L>
<L><I>Susceperunt me sicut leo paratus ad predam.</I></L>
<L>A curtul I hedde and clo&thorn;us mo,</L>
<L N="68">And sone I hedde hem alle for-go:</L>
<L>So hedde I &thorn;is chartre writen,</L>
<L>&thorn;o was I naked, wel may &yogh;e witen;</L>
<L>&thorn;ei casten lot as wolde bi-falle,</L>
<L N="72">whe&thorn;er on schulde haue hem or parten alle.</L>
<L>ffrend and fo &thorn;at with me metten,</L>
<L>In my neode alle me for-letten;</L>
<L>And to a piler I was I-piht,</L>
<L N="76">Togget and tauwed al &thorn;e niht,</L>
<L>And wasschen in myn owne blode,</L>
<L>And strayte I-streynet on &thorn;e Rode,</L>
<L>Streyned to druye on Rode-tre,</L>
<L N="80">As parchemyn owe&thorn; for to be.
<PB REF="00000652.tif" N="644"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here now, and &yogh;e schul witen</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;is chartre was I-writen.</L>
<L>Vppon myn neb was mad &thorn;e ynke</L>
<L N="84">wi&thorn; &thorn;e Jewes spittyng on me to stynke.</L>
<L>&thorn;e penne &thorn;at &thorn;e lettre was wi&thorn; writen,</L>
<L>weore scourges &thorn;at I was wi&thorn; smiten.</L>
<L>How mony lettres &thorn;eron beon,</L>
<L N="88">Red, and &thorn;ou miht wite and seon:</L>
<L>ffif &thorn;ousend foure hundred fyfti and ten</L>
<L>woundus on me, bo&thorn;e blak and wen.</L>
<L>To schewen on alle my loue-dede,</L>
<L N="92">Mi-self I wole &thorn;is chartre rede.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e Men &thorn;at gon bi &thorn;is weye,</L>
<L>A-byde&thorn; a luytel, I ow preye,</L>
<L>And rede&thorn; alle on &thorn;is parchemyn,</L>
<L N="96">&yogh;if eny serwe beo lyk to myn:</L>
<L><I>O nos omnes qui transitis per uiam,</I></L>
<L>Stonde&thorn; and here&thorn; &thorn;is chartre red,</L>
<L>whi I am woundet and al for-bled.
<PB REF="00000653.tif" N="645"></L>
<L>'<I>Sciant presentes &amp; futuri,</I></L>
<L>wite &yogh;e &thorn;at are and schal be-tyde,</L>
<L N="100">&thorn;at Jhesu crist wi&thorn; blodi syde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was boren in Bedleem</L>
<L>And offred in to Jerusalem,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynges sone of heuene aboue,</L>
<L N="104">with mi ffadres wille and loue</L>
<L>Made a sesyng whon I was born,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, Monkynde, &thorn;at was forlorn.</L>
<L>wi&thorn; my cha[r]tre here present</L>
<L N="108">I make nou a confirmament:</L>
<L>&thorn;at I haue graunted and &yogh;iuen</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, Monkynde, with me to liuen</L>
<L>In my Rewme of heuene-blis,</L>
<L N="112">To haue and to holden wi&thorn;-outen mis,</L>
<L>In a condicion, &yogh;if &thorn;ou be kynde</L>
<L>And my loue-dedes haue in Mynde;</L>
<L>ffre to haue, and fre to holde,</L>
<L N="116">wi&thorn; al &thorn;e purtynaunce to wolde,
<PB REF="00000654.tif" N="646"></L>
<L>Myn heritage &thorn;at is so fre.</L>
<L>ffor homage ne for feute</L>
<L>No more wol I aske of &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="120">But a foure-leued gras &yogh;eld &thorn;ou me:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Olef is so&thorn;fast schrifte,</L>
<L>&thorn;e to&thorn;ur is for synne herte-smerte,</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;ridde is "I wol no more do so,"</L>
<L N="124">&thorn;e feor&thorn;e is "drede god euermo";</L>
<L>whon &thorn;eose four leues to-geder ben set,</L>
<L>A "trewe loue" men clepen hit.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is Rente boo nou&yogh;t be-hynde,</L>
<L N="128">ffor &thorn;orw &thorn;e &yogh;er &thorn;ou may hit fynde;</L>
<L>Elles mai &thorn;ou not fynde hit in my wounde,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er mai "trewe loue" wel be founde.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou falle and gretly mis-take,</L>
<L N="132">Mi dede I wole neuer forsake;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou amende &thorn;e, and Merci craue,</L>
<L>&thorn;in heritage &yogh;ut schalt &thorn;ou haue.'
<PB REF="00000655.tif" N="647"></L>
<L>&THORN;e seles &thorn;at hit was seled wi&thorn;,</L>
<L N="136">&thorn;ei were grauen vp-on a sti&thorn;;</L>
<L>Of gold nor seluer weore &thorn;ei nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of stel and Iren were &thorn;ei wrou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>with &thorn;e spere of stel myn herte &thorn;ei stongen</L>
<L N="140">&thorn;orw myn herte and &thorn;orw my longen;</L>
<L>Iren nayles &thorn;urleden me</L>
<L>&thorn;orw feet and hondes to &thorn;e tre.</L>
<L>&THORN;e selyng-wax was deore abou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="144">At myn herte rote hit was sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And tempred al wi&thorn; vermiloun</L>
<L>Of my rede blod &thorn;at ran doun:
<PB REF="00000656.tif" N="648"></L>
<L><I>Factum est cor meum tanquam cera liquescens in medio ventris mei.</I></L>
<L>ffyue seles weore I-set &thorn;eron:</L>
<L N="148">ffader and sone, god and mon;</L>
<L>&thorn;e fyf&thorn;e is for to leeue most,</L>
<L>&thorn;at icomen of &thorn;e holygost.</L>
<L>In pleyn pouwer &thorn;i stat to make,</L>
<L N="152">A croune on myn hed [I gon] to take</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ornus, in toknyng &thorn;at I am kyng</L>
<L>And freoly may &yogh;iue &thorn;e &thorn;i &thorn;ing:</L>
<L>&thorn;is witnesse&thorn; &thorn;is Jewes alle;</L>
<L N="156">On kneos &thorn;ei gonne to me falle,</L>
<L>And seiden loude on heore scornyng,</L>
<L>"Heil be &thorn;ou, lord, and Jewes kyng!"
<PB REF="00000657.tif" N="649"></L>
<L>Bi-twene two men &thorn;is [chartre] was seeled;</L>
<L N="160">&thorn;ei bo&thorn;e weore seke; &thorn;at on I heled,</L>
<L>Bi-twene two &thorn;eues on hih I-piht,</L>
<L>In toknyng &thorn;at I am mon of miht,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Nor&thorn; and West on hei&yogh; hille</L>
<L N="164">&thorn;at I may deme bo&thorn;e gode and ille,</L>
<L><I>Quia neque ab oriente neque ab occidente.</I> </L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>A</B>-&thorn;hurst I was ful sore I-swonken,</L>
<L>&thorn;e beuerege moste nede be dronken:</L>
<L>A loue-drynke I asked of &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="168">Eysel and galle &thorn;ou &yogh;af to me:</L>
<L>&thorn;is witnesse&thorn; Matheu and Jon,</L>
<L>Luk and Mark and monyon,
<PB REF="00000658.tif" N="650"></L>
<L>And nomeliche my moder swete;</L>
<L N="172">ffor heo lafte neuere teres to lete:</L>
<L>Ar &thorn;is chartre writen was,</L>
<L>fful ofte heo seide allas allas!</L>
<L>So bare I was of worldes gode,</L>
<L N="176">whon I schulde dye on &thorn;e Rode,</L>
<L>&thorn;at I hedde nou&yogh;t wher-of to take,</L>
<L>Mi testament wher-of to make,</L>
<L>But of my leoue moder dere:</L>
<L N="180">heo stod bi me with serwful chere;
<PB REF="00000659.tif" N="651"></L>
<L>And whon I my cosyn hire bi-toke,</L>
<L>heo caste me mony a serwful loke.</L>
<L>In knowleching I made a cri,</L>
<L N="184">"<I>Pater, pater, lama&yogh;abatani.</I>"</L>
<L>Bi-hold &thorn;ou, mon, with herte and e&yogh;e,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;i loue hou I schal dye:
<PB REF="00000660.tif" N="652"></L>
<L><I>Consummatum est</I>, &thorn;is chartre is doon.</L>
<L N="188">Mon, &thorn;ou hast ouercome &thorn;i foon!
<PB REF="00000661.tif" N="653"></L>
<L>To helle I wente, &thorn;is chartre to schewe</L>
<L>Bi-fore &thorn;i fo, Sathanas &thorn;e schrewe;
<PB REF="00000662.tif" N="654"></L>
<L>&thorn;o he was schent and brouht to grounde,</L>
<L N="192">wi&thorn; nayles bored and speres wounde,</L>
<L>A strayt couenaunt I-mad &thorn;er was</L>
<L>Bi-twene me and Sathanas:</L>
<L>Al my catel to haue away,</L>
<L N="196">&thorn;at he me refte with false pray.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>A</B> &yogh;ein I com, and made a feste</L>
<L>AMong &thorn;e leste and &thorn;e meste:</L>
<L>A parti &thorn;o gunne knowe me,</L>
<L N="200">&thorn;at I was mon of gret pouste.</L>
<L>&thorn;e feeste laste fourti dawes,</L>
<L>To do men knowe my newe lawes;</L>
<L>&thorn;at feeste was al of ioye and blis,</L>
<L N="204">&thorn;at Esterday &yogh;it cleped is.
<PB REF="00000663.tif" N="655"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On endenture I lafte wi&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;at euer &thorn;ou schuldest siker be:</L>
<L>In preostes hondes my flesch and blode,</L>
<L N="208">&thorn;at for &thorn;e dyede on &thorn;e Rode.</L>
<L>A by-keye I tok &thorn;e also:</L>
<L>&thorn;e token &thorn;at I was on I-do,</L>
<L>To bere with &thorn;e wher &thorn;at &thorn;ou go;</L>
<L N="212">&thorn;enne &thorn;ar &thorn;e not drede of &thorn;i fo.
<PB REF="00000664.tif" N="656"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To my fader I moste gon,</L>
<L>ffor al his wille haue I don.</L>
<L>A cote-armour I bar with me,</L>
<L N="216">ffor &thorn;at I tok of &thorn;y liuere;</L>
<L>&thorn;e clo&thorn; was riche and ful fyn,</L>
<L>&thorn;e chaumpe hit was of red camelyn.</L>
<L>A ful feir mayden to me hit wrou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="220">Oute of hire boure I hit brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Poudret with fyue roses rede,</L>
<L>ffyf woundes &thorn;at I &thorn;oled dede.</L>
<L>whon I come eft a&yogh;eyn to &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="224">&thorn;er-bi &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t knowe me.</L>
<L>&THORN;eose &thorn;at beo&thorn; of rente be-hynde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;eose dedes haue not in mynde,</L>
<L>fful sore may &thorn;ei ben a-dred</L>
<L N="228">whon &thorn;is cha[r]tre schal be red:</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;eose schul go to helle-pyne;</L>
<L>And with me to blisse schul go alle myne.
<PB REF="00000665.tif" N="657"></L>
<L>Pay &thorn;i rente, keep &thorn;e from gylt,</L>
<L N="232">Cum and cleyme whon &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilt,</L>
<L>&thorn;e blisse &thorn;at loste oure frende."</L>
<L>to &thorn;e whuche blisce, crist vs bringe withouten ende!</L>
<TRAILER>A. M. E. N. Amen.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>MS. Harl. 2382 (leaf 111, back).</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wo-so wil ouer-rede this boke,</L>
<L>and with gostly eyen ther-on loke,</L>
<L>to other scole dare he not wende,</L>
<L N="4">to saue his soule fro &thorn;e fende,</L>
<L>.;. Then for to do as this boke tellith;</L>
<L>for holi wryt for-sothe it spellith.</L>
<L>ther-for y pray yow for charite</L>
<L N="8">that this boke shal rede or se,</L>
<L>that your herte &amp; al your mynde</L>
<L>kep derworthly that ye here fynde;</L>
<L>and ful-filleth it in dede</L>
<L N="12">that ye shal in this boke rede!&mdash;</L>
<L>.;. Now ye shal here anon-righte,</L>
<L>your sauyour speke to yow as-tyte</L>
<L N="15">wordes of a chartour &thorn;at he hath wroght,</L>
<L>that ye may knowe in al your thoght.</L>
<L>and who this boke can vnderstonde,</L>
<L>teche it forth thurgh al the londe.</L>
<L N="19">Vntil other &thorn;at this hath not sene,</L>
<L>to saue here soules right as here owne;</L>
<L>els ye shal not with-outen Strif</L>
<L>fro this world passe to &thorn;e lond of lyf.</L>
<L>&para; Now y wil be-gynne to rede &thorn;eron;</L>
<L N="24">his pes he yeue vs euery-chon!</L>
<L>"Ihesu, lord of heuene and hell,</L>
<L>man &amp; womman, y wol yow tell,</L>
<L>loke what loue y do to the,</L>
<L N="28">and loke what thu has do to me!
<PB REF="00000646.tif" N="638"></L>
<L>.;. ffro paradise thu were out pilt,</L>
<L>with care &amp; sorwe &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> were out spilt,</L>
<L>forth thu were drawe a-way,<MILESTONE N="112" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="32">as a beste that goth astray.</L>
<L>ffro my right y cam a-doun,</L>
<L>to seke the fro toune to toun,</L>
<L>to helpe the in thy myschef&mdash;</L>
<L N="36">Derworth soule, &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> art me lef!&mdash;</L>
<L>myn heritage, that is so fre,</L>
<L>in thi myschef to yef it the.
<PB REF="00000647.tif" N="639"></L>
<L>And when this sesyng y yeue shulde,</L>
<L N="40">y dud as the Jewys wolde:</L>
<L>.;. Til a mayde y be-toke me,</L>
<L>when &thorn;at y conceuyd shuld be.</L>
<L>the mayde was trewe, mylde &amp; fre,</L>
<L N="44">she me receuyd for &thorn;e loue of the.</L>
<L>nyne mo[n]thes with here y was,</L>
<L>to make a-mendys for thi trespas,</L>
<L>or y in to this world was born</L>
<L>to saue man-kynde &thorn;at was forlorn.</L>
<L N="49">thurgh my vertu &amp; my grace</L>
<L>thus cam the sesyng first in place.</L>
<L>.;. Virgyn Marie, mayden mylde,</L>
<L>with me went thus gret with childe.</L>
<L N="53">and when this sesyng was al y-do,</L>
<L>fful grete envy had thy foo,</L>
<L>that cursed fende Sathanas,</L>
<L N="56">had gret wonder whi it was,</L>
<L>whi y loued so moche the,</L>
<L>that so vnkynde has ben to me;
<PB REF="00000648.tif" N="640"></L>
<L>wroth he was, (it helped hym noght,)</L>
<L N="60">the to helpe was al my thoght.</L>
<L>he tempted me in so gret foly,<MILESTONE N="112b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>pride, couetise and glotony,</L>
<L>and well he wist y was a man;</L>
<L N="64">but synne in me found he nan.</L>
<L>for-sothe, right hard he thretid me</L>
<L>that y shold dere abye for the,</L>
<L>to destroye me thurgh his myght</L>
<L>and put the for euer out of my sight.</L>
<L>.;. Now, derworth soule, herken to me<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Carta feoffamenti, <I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>and a new ioye shal y telle the:</L>
<L>to make a charter of feffement,</L>
<L N="72">heuene &amp; erthe shal be present;</L>
<L>but in soche a maner it most be</L>
<L>&thorn;at y shal yelde my lyf for the;</L>
<L>and when y am ded, man, be &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> kynde,</L>
<L N="76">and haue this charter in &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> mynde.
<PB REF="00000649.tif" N="641"></L>
<L>for an enmy that hath the soght;</L>
<L>but yet shal y the lese noght,</L>
<L>for y wol dye for thy<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. for thy for thi</NOTE> foly,</L>
<L N="80">and bryng &thorn;e in to my company.</L>
<L>I am a-lyue and thu art ded,</L>
<L>y wol yeue my lyf ayenst &thorn;e qued;</L>
<L>for to helpe the y am redy,</L>
<L N="84">to saue the euer fro thyn enmy.</L>
<L>for many a way, [man,] haue y go,</L>
<L>in hunger, thurste, colde &amp; wo,</L>
<L>xxx<SUP>ti</SUP> wynter and thre &thorn;erto,</L>
<L N="88">or my disese were<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. well</NOTE> al y-do.</L>
<L>parchement to fynde wyst y none,</L>
<L>to make a charter ayenst &thorn;i fone</L>
<L>that wil leste with-oute ende:</L>
<L N="92">.;. herken now to my word hende!</L>
<L>But, as trewe loue bade me do,<MILESTONE N="113" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>my owne skynne y toke &thorn;erto.</L>
<L>and when y had so y-do,</L>
<L N="96">wel fewe frendis had y tho;</L>
<L>to gete me frendis y yeaf gret mede,</L>
<L>as doth &thorn;e pore &thorn;at hath gret nede.</L>
<L>.;. but to yeue the y had no more,</L>
<L N="100">for &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> soule that was for-lore,</L>
<L>then my soule to yeue for the,</L>
<L>that for the dyed apon a tre.
<PB REF="00000650.tif" N="642"></L>
<L>Apon a thursday a soper y made</L>
<L>to frend &amp; foo, to make hem glade,</L>
<L N="105">of bred &amp; wyne the sacrament,</L>
<L>for euer to be my Testament,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[Nota bene de sacramento <I>in margin.</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>which is my flesh &amp; my blode,</L>
<L N="108">to tho that lyuen in mylde mode,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;o that dyen out of charite</L>
<L N="110">their dampnacion euer to be.</L>
<L>.;. Here wol y foure wordes yow teche;</L>
<L>and to &thorn;e peple loke ye hem preche:</L>
<L><I>Hoc facite in meam commemoracionem;</I></L>
<L>that they haue hem euer in mynde,</L>
<L>here mede in heuene shal they fynde.</L>
<L>thes wordes twocheth &thorn;e sacrament</L>
<L N="116">that men receueth, verrament.</L>
<L>it semeth many, &amp; is but one;</L>
<L>it semeth bred, &amp; it is none;<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota bene</NOTE></L>
<L>it is quyk, &amp; semeth ded:</L>
<L N="120">it is my body in fourme of bred.</L>
<L>.;. This made y only for mankynde,</L>
<L>my wonderful dedis to haue in mynde:</L>
<L>who-so receueth it in clennes,<MILESTONE N="113b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="124">Saued shal be, &amp; com to blys;</L>
<L>and to haue in mynde my passion,</L>
<L>that shal be thi saluacion.</L>
<L>.;. Or y fro the borde aros,</L>
<L>of my disciple be-trayed y was.</L>
<L>when y had soped, he ros anone;</L>
<L N="130">to grete maistris he gan gone,</L>
<L>and brought them with hym in &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>as a lyon &thorn;at goth a-boute his pray:
<PB REF="00000651.tif" N="643"></L>
<L><I>Susceperuut [me] sicut leo paratus ad predam.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">textus</NOTE></L>
<L>.;. Anone they be-gunne to spoile me,</L>
<L N="134">and seid y shuld dye on a tre;</L>
<L>my mantylle and other clothes mo,</L>
<L>alle y had them sone for-go;</L>
<L N="137">they cast lot emonges them alle</L>
<L>whe&thorn;er one shuld haue them, or parte hem alle.</L>
<L>but<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> So <I>or</I> Sone</NOTE> alle my clothes fro me thei token;</L>
<L>and alle my frendis sone me for-soken;</L>
<L>naked y Stod emong my fone;</L>
<L N="142">for other socoure had y none;</L>
<L>redy they were me to despise,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>r.</I> dysese</NOTE></L>
<L>but none &thorn;er were me for to plese.</L>
<L>.;. They made scourges hard &amp; grete,</L>
<L>ther-with my body shuld be bete;</L>
<L>and thogh y wold haue pleyned me,</L>
<L>ther shuld to me no socour haue be.</L>
<L N="149">ful sore a-ferd, for-sothe y was,</L>
<L>when they led me so gret a pas!</L>
<L>To a piler y was bound al &thorn;e nyght,</L>
<L>togged &amp; betyn til day-light,</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="114" UNIT="folio">and wasshen with myn owne blode,</L>
<L>that al the erthe aboute cold stode.</L>
<L>and so y stod bounden al the nyght,</L>
<L>til on the morwe &thorn;at it was bright</L>
<L>they Strayned me hard apon a tre,</L>
<L N="158">as parchement auxhte to be.
<PB REF="00000652.tif" N="644"></L>
<L>.;. hereth now, &amp; ye shal wetyn</L>
<L N="160">how this charter was y-writen:</L>
<L>ouer al my face felle the enke,</L>
<L>thornes in my hed gan to synke.</L>
<L N="163">the pennys that &thorn;e lettris writen.</L>
<L>were scourges &thorn;at y was with smyten.</L>
<L>How many lettris that ther-on bene,</L>
<L N="167">rede, and thu may wete &amp; sene:</L>
<L>V thousant thousant V.Cl &amp; x then<NOTE PLACE="foot">nota de vulneribus Christi (<I>in margin</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L>wondes in my body, bo&thorn;e red &amp; wan.</L>
<L>ffor to shewe the of my loue-dede,</L>
<L>my-self y wol here &thorn;e charter rede.</L>
<L><I>O vos omnes qui transitis per viam,</I></L>
<L><I>attendite &amp; videte si est dolor sicut meus:</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">textus (<I>in margin</I>)</NOTE></L>
<L>.;. Ye men that goth forth bi &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>be-holde &amp; se bothe nyght &amp; day.</L>
<L>and redith apon this parchemyn,</L>
<L>yf any sorowe be as gret as myn.</L>
<L>Stondeth &amp; herkeneth &thorn;e charter red,</L>
<L N="175">why y am wonded &amp; al for-bled.
<PB REF="00000653.tif" N="645"></L>
<L><I>Sciant presentes &amp; futuri.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Carta Christi.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>.;. 'Wetyn &thorn;o here &amp; tho &thorn;at be to come</L>
<L>that Ihesus of na&yogh;areth, god-is sone,</L>
<L>Vnderstondeth wel &amp; &thorn;o &thorn;at wol abide</L>
<L>that Iesus hath a blody Syde,<MILESTONE N="114b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="181">that born was in Beth[l]ehem</L>
<L>and ouer-more offred in to Ierusalem,</L>
<L>the kyngis sone of heuene a-boue,</L>
<L N="184">a mercyful fader that wel y loue.</L>
<L>I made a Seisyng when y was born,</L>
<L>to saue man-kynde that was forlorn.</L>
<L>But with my charter here in present</L>
<L>y make to mannys soule a feffement:</L>
<L N="189">that y haue y-graunted &amp; yeue</L>
<L>to mankynde, with me to lyue</L>
<L>In my kyngdom of heuene-blys,</L>
<L N="192">to haue &amp; holde with-outen mys,</L>
<L>with this condicion, &thorn;at thu be kynde</L>
<L>and my workes to haue in mynde,</L>
<L>frely to haue, and frely holde,</L>
<L>with al the purtenaunce to be holde,
<PB REF="00000654.tif" N="646"></L>
<L N="197">and in my blisse euer to dwelle</L>
<L>for the rente &thorn;at y shal the telle.</L>
<L>.;. Myn heritage that is so fre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nota hie de libero redditu Christi (<I>in margin</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">for homage or els for fewte,</L>
<L>no more wol y aske of the,</L>
<L>but a iiij-levid gras yeld &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> me:</L>
<L N="203">that one lef is verry shrifte;</L>
<L>&thorn;at other is, for &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> synne &thorn;e smerte;</L>
<L>the thirde is, wille no more do so,</L>
<L>the fourthe, &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> penance mekely do;</L>
<L>When thes levis to-geder ben set,</L>
<L N="208">a "trew-loue" men callen hit.</L>
<L>Of this rent be not be-hynde:</L>
<L>the way to heuene then may &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> fynde;</L>
<L>yf &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> this rente truly pay me,<MILESTONE N="115" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>my gret mercy I shal shewe to the.</L>
<L N="213">for if thu falle in gret mystake,</L>
<L>my charter wol I &thorn;e not forsake;</L>
<L>yf thu amende, and mercy craue,</L>
<L>thyn heritage then shalt &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> haue.'
<PB REF="00000655.tif" N="647"></L>
<L>.;. Thes selys that it is selyd with,</L>
<L N="218">they were made alle at a Smyth;</L>
<L>of golde ne Siluer were thei noght;</L>
<L>of Stile and yren were they wroght:</L>
<L N="221">with a spere of Stile myn hert was stonge</L>
<L>thurf my syde &amp; thurf my lunge;</L>
<L>apon my side they made a wonde,</L>
<L>myn herte-blode ran doune to grounde;</L>
<L>with yren nayles they smyten me</L>
<L>thurghe fete &amp; handes on &thorn;e rode-tre.</L>
<L>.;. The selyng-wax was dere y-boght,</L>
<L N="228">at myn herte rote it was sought,</L>
<L>al tempred with fyne vermylon</L>
<L>of my red blode that ran adoun.
<PB REF="00000656.tif" N="648"></L>
<L><I>Factum est cor meum tanquam cera liquessens</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">euangelium</NOTE></L>
<L><I>in medio ventris mei.</I></L>
<L>.;. My sealis bene y-set ther-on:</L>
<L N="232">fader &amp; sone, god and man,</L>
<L>the firste, that is be-leve most,</L>
<L>that y cam of the holy gost.</L>
<L>ther-for here may thu now se</L>
<L N="236">&thorn;at y am a kyng of gret poste;</L>
<L>in playn power thi state to make,</L>
<L>a crowne of thornes on my hed y take:</L>
<L N="239">.;. This croune be-tokeneth y am a kyng</L>
<L>and frely may yeue thyn owne thyng:</L>
<L>this wittenesseth wel &thorn;e Iewys alle,</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="115b" UNIT="folio">on kneys they gonne be-fore me falle</L>
<L>and lowde seyd in here Scornyng</L>
<L>"al haylle thu lord, of Iewys kyng."
<PB REF="00000657.tif" N="649"></L>
<L N="245">.;. Be-twene ij thevis &thorn;e charter was selyd,</L>
<L>bothe were syke, &thorn;at one was helyd,</L>
<L>be-twene ij thevis high y-plight,</L>
<L>in token that I was lord of myght;</L>
<L>this be-tokeneth bothe good &amp; ill,</L>
<L>atte day of dome to saue or spill.</L>
<L>.;. fful dry y was &amp; thursted sore;</L>
<L>but of soche drynke y myght no more:</L>
<L>for aysel &amp; galle they yeaf to me.</L>
<L>but one drynke aske y of the:</L>
<L>that &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> be louyng toward &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> foone&mdash;</L>
<L N="256">other drynke of &thorn;e aske y none;</L>
<L>yf thu me loue, haue this in mynde:</L>
<L>to &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> enmyes thu be right kynde.</L>
<L>ensample &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> mayst take here of me:</L>
<L N="260">for loue of the y hong on a tre,</L>
<L>But [seid] "my fader, y pray now the,</L>
<L>apon myn enmyes thu haue pite;"</L>
<L>And as y do, do thu to thyne,</L>
<L>and saued shalt &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> be fro helle-pyne.</L>
<L>.;. Here [of] be wittenesse mo then on:</L>
<L N="266">Mark, Mathew, Luke and Iohn,
<PB REF="00000658.tif" N="650"></L>
<L>and namely my moder swete,</L>
<L N="268">that for me blody terys gan lete.</L>
<L>for, there she stode vnder the rode,</L>
<L>she sawe my body al on blode</L>
<L>that fro my fete vnto my hede</L>
<L N="272">y was not els but al blode-rede;</L>
<L>No word to me &thorn;er myght she speke,</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="116" UNIT="folio">it semed ny here herte wold breke;</L>
<L>no wonder was thogh she were woo</L>
<L>when she sawe me on &thorn;e crosse y-do.</L>
<L>.;. ffor sorwe of here y made a cry</L>
<L>and seid ful lowde "<I>heli lama&yogh;aba|thany.</I>"</L>
<L>anone she fell doune in sownyng,</L>
<L N="280">right be-fore me at myn endyng.</L>
<L>the peynes that y suffred were ful sore,</L>
<L>but for my moder they were the more.</L>
<L>when y layd my hed here &amp; there,</L>
<L>my moder chaunged al here chere;</L>
<L N="285">ful fayn she wold haue holpe me,</L>
<L>but for the Iewys it myght not be.</L>
<L>my peynes were tho fulle smerte,</L>
<L>the swerd of sorwe perced here herte;
<PB REF="00000659.tif" N="651"></L>
<L>when to seynt Iohn y here be-toke,</L>
<L N="290">She cast on me a drewry loke,</L>
<L>as y had here all forsake</L>
<L>and to a-nother sone y had here take;</L>
<L>And or this charter writen was,</L>
<L>ful ofte she sayd alas alas.</L>
<L>.;. Apon my shulder y leyd my hed</L>
<L N="296">when y drow fast to my ded;</L>
<L>for so bare was y of worly good,</L>
<L>when y shold [dye] apon the rood,</L>
<L>that y ne had where-of to take,</L>
<L N="300">rest of my hed where-of to make.</L>
<L>pore &amp; riche, haue euer in mynde,</L>
<L>when ye in this world no rest may fynde,</L>
<L>what rest y han only for the,</L>
<L N="304">when y hong nayled apon a tre!</L>
<L>wel may &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> knowe &thorn;at y had non,</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="116b" UNIT="folio">for &thorn;er y stode amonge my foon.</L>
<L>when thu amonge thi foen art broght,</L>
<L>be redy to suffre with alle thi thoght.</L>
<L>to stande at barre it is wel harde,</L>
<L>as ye be worthy to haue rewarde:</L>
<L N="311">thu [&thorn;at] for me suffrest wrong,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> shal be sothely on my right hond;</L>
<L>thu &thorn;at vengest the apon thi brother,</L>
<L>thou standest not &thorn;er, but on &thorn;at other;</L>
<L>and yf thu wilt the sothe knowe:</L>
<L>right as &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> sowest, so shalt &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> mowe.</L>
<L N="317">.;. I fele me now so ful of woo,</L>
<L>that out of this world y most go;</L>
<L>with peynes of deth, hard am y bounde;</L>
<L N="320">my soule shal passe here in &thorn;is stounde.</L>
<L>be-hold now, man, with herte &amp; eye,</L>
<L>for thi loue how y shal dye.
<PB REF="00000660.tif" N="652"></L>
<L>y hong on crosse for loue of the:</L>
<L N="324">forsake thi synne for loue of me,</L>
<L>mercy aske, and amende &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sone</L>
<L>and y foryeue &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> that is mysdone;</L>
<L>for ful of mercy y am, truly,</L>
<L N="328">to alle tho that cryen mercy.</L>
<L>What shal it greue to repente the</L>
<L>and in endeles ioye to dwelle with me?</L>
<L>.;. ffor tho that wil no mercy crye,</L>
<L>they shal to helle when they dye.</L>
<L>now when y haue one word spoke,</L>
<L>myn eyen to-geder most y loke:</L>
<L>thu Synful man, haue pite on me,</L>
<L N="336">for thyn owne sowle for charite!</L>
<L>Thes wordes y most nedis speke,</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="117" UNIT="folio">and then my herte shal to-breke:</L>
<L>.;. <I>Consum</I>[<I>m</I>]<I>atum est;</I> &thorn;is charter is don.</L>
<L>man, &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> hast now ouer-come al &thorn;<SUP>&iacute;</SUP> foon.
<PB REF="00000661.tif" N="653"></L>
<L N="341">Anone y went to helle, &thorn;at charter to shewe</L>
<L>be-fore Sathanas, &thorn;at olde shrewe:
<PB REF="00000662.tif" N="654"></L>
<L>there y hym shent &amp; broght to grounde</L>
<L>thurgh my nayles pitous wounde.</L>
<L>and after a cownant made &thorn;er was</L>
<L N="346">be-twene me and Sathanas:</L>
<L>alle my catelle to haue away,</L>
<L>that he be-rafte me with his pray.</L>
<L>.;. The thirde day y made a fest</L>
<L N="350">to the moste and to the lest:</L>
<L>the fest was of ioye &amp; blys,</L>
<L>that Ester-day called ys.
<PB REF="00000663.tif" N="655"></L>
<L>one indenture y left to the,</L>
<L N="354">where-of &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> shalt euer syker be:</L>
<L>In prestys handes my fleshe &amp; blode,</L>
<L>that for the was hanged on &thorn;e rode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">nota bene <I>in margin.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>who-so-euer be-leveth ther-on,</L>
<L>endeles payn shal he fynde non;</L>
<L>al-thogh y dyed, yet dyeth not he,</L>
<L N="360">for he shal rise &amp; lyue with me.</L>
<L>.;. A wel faire thyng y tok &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> also:</L>
<L>a token of the crosse y was on do,</L>
<L>to bere with the so where thu go,</L>
<L N="364">to kepe the euer fro thy foo.
<PB REF="00000664.tif" N="656"></L>
<L>to my fader y most gone,</L>
<L>for al his wille haue y done:</L>
<L>I take my lef, ye haue me seyne;</L>
<L N="368">atte day of dome y come ageyne,</L>
<L>man to deme after his wirke&mdash;<MILESTONE N="117b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>this is the wille of al-holi kyrke&mdash;</L>
<L>and euer after in ioye to dwelle,</L>
<L N="372">Saue to be fro the peyn of helle.</L>
<L>.;. A cote-armuur I bere here with me,</L>
<L>the which y toke of thy lyuere;</L>
<L N="375">this cote is riche &amp; wel fyne,</L>
<L>the champe is now of red satyne;</L>
<L>a wel faire mayde me it be-tought</L>
<L>and out of here boure I it broght;</L>
<L N="379">poudred it is with v. roses red,</L>
<L>wondes y suffred with peynes of ded.</L>
<L>.;. And when y come ageyn to the,</L>
<L>bi this clothyng thu may know me.</L>
<L>tho &thorn;at ben of this rent be-hynde,</L>
<L>and my wondes wilnot haue in mynde,</L>
<L>wel sore shal they bene a-dred</L>
<L N="386">when this charter shal be red;</L>
<L>of the hy Justice be they ful ware,</L>
<L>for-sothe thene shal he none spare,
<PB REF="00000665.tif" N="657"></L>
<L>for alle &thorn;e synnes &thorn;at thu has wroght</L>
<L N="390">fram &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> youthe, shalle be soght.</L>
<L>for power of my fader y haue</L>
<L>to saue alle thoo &thorn;at mercy craue.</L>
<L>.;. Now pay thi rent, while &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> has space,</L>
<L N="394">yf thu wilt of me haue grace;</L>
<L>and yf thu dye ful sodenly,</L>
<L>apon &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> soule y shal haue mercy.</L>
<L>A cownant is made betwene vs two:</L>
<L>as I haue done, so most thu do.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">nota <I>in margin</I>: line 400 begins leaf 118.</NOTE>Loke what &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> pater noster seith to the:</L>
<L N="400">"right as y foryeue, foryef &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> me;"</L>
<L>and do ther-after, yf thu wilt,</L>
<L>so that thi soule be not spilt.</L>
<L>.;. Apon al holi writ y may put me,</L>
<L>where y be curteyse or no to the;</L>
<L N="405">be thu lerid or be thu lewde,</L>
<L>the way to heuene y haue &thorn;e shewde</L>
<L>by the texte of holy writ,</L>
<L N="408">in what place &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> wilt seke it.</L>
<L>ther-for y byd the pay thy rent,</L>
<L>that with the fend &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> be not shent;</L>
<L>with me to blisse then shalt &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> come,</L>
<L N="412">and in my blisse &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> shalt wone.</L>
<L>To that blisse y may the bryng,</L>
<L>that of myght made al thyng."</L>
<TRAILER><I>Explicit Testamentum Christi.</I></TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>MS. much faded in parts, and hardly legible. When y stands for &thorn;, it is printed &thorn;.</I>]</NOTE> Reg. 17, C xvii (leaf 112, back).</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He &thorn;at wyll rede ouer &thorn;is boke</L>
<L>&amp; with hys gostly high &thorn;er-in loke,</L>
<L>To &thorn;er scole thare hym no&yogh;t wende</L>
<L N="4">To sawe hys saule fro &thorn;e fende</L>
<L>&thorn;an for to do as &thorn;is boke spelles,</L>
<L>ffor holy wryte for sothe it telles.</L>
<L>Ware-fore I pray &yogh;ow for charyte,</L>
<L N="8">&YOGH;e &thorn;at &thorn;is bok sall rede or se,</L>
<L>Wyt all &yogh;oure hart &amp; al &yogh;oure mynd</L>
<L>kepe dernely &thorn;at &yogh;e &thorn;er-in fynd,</L>
<L N="11">And ful-fylles it in dede<MILESTONE N=":2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e sall in &thorn;is boke fynd &amp; rede!</L>
<L>Now sal &yogh;e here with-outyn delyte</L>
<L>&yogh;oure sawyour spek to &yogh;ou als-tyte</L>
<L>A charter how mans saule as boght,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;ow most kepe with al &yogh;oure toght.</L>
<L>to mak a charter be-heves mek thynge:</L>
<L>parchemyn forsothe, pen, &amp; ynke,</L>
<L>Wax &amp; cele, wytnes also,</L>
<L N="20">&thorn;e rent &thorn;at &thorn;u sal to &thorn;i lord do.</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="113" UNIT="folio">Wen &yogh;e &thorn;is charge knaw vndyrstand,</L>
<L>Telles it forthe in all &thorn;is land</L>
<L N="23">to o&thorn;er &thorn;at as it no&yogh;t sene,</L>
<L>to sawe &thorn;er saules &amp; &yogh;oures be dene!</L>
<L>fo[r] &yogh;e &thorn;at can &amp; wyll no&yogh;t teche</L>
<L>O&thorn;er men &thorn;er sawles to leche,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e sal no&yogh;t pase wi&thorn;-outyn stryfe</L>
<L N="28">fro &thorn;is warlde to &thorn;e land of lyfe.</L>
<L>Now wyl I begyn to rede &thorn;er-on&mdash;</L>
<L>Ald youre pese now euer-ilkon!&mdash;</L>
<L>"Ihesu, lord of heuen &amp; helle,</L>
<L N="32">Man &amp; woman I wyll &thorn;e tell,</L>
<L>loke wat luf I af done for &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; lok wat &thorn;u as done for me!
<PB REF="00000646.tif" N="638"></L>
<L N="35">After my-self &thorn;u was &thorn;e best,</L>
<L>Of all creatures &thorn;ou was &thorn;e fayrest;</L>
<L>A fayrere creature myght neuer non be:</L>
<L>Aftyre my-selfe made I &thorn;e.</L>
<L>A place I toke &thorn;e &thorn;at was of charge,</L>
<L N="40">Paradyse, to play in at &thorn;i large.</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;ou was vnbuxum to me,</L>
<L>And toke a napull of &thorn;e tre</L>
<L N="43">&thorn;at I forbed &thorn;ou suld no&yogh;t take,</L>
<L>&thorn;u was drywyn oute, &amp; eue, &thorn;i make;</L>
<L>Oute of paradys was &thorn;ou qwytte;</L>
<L>wi&thorn; soro &amp; care &thorn;an was &thorn;ou knytte,</L>
<L>And forthe &thorn;ou was drywyn away,</L>
<L N="48">Als wauand best &thorn;at gos on stray.</L>
<L>My holy aungell cherubyn,</L>
<L>wi&thorn; a burnyng swerde, &thorn;eder I sent hym;</L>
<L>he ex[p]ellyd &thorn;e fro &thorn;en &thorn;edyre,</L>
<L N="52">And drawe &thorn;e out, &thorn;u wyst neuer wyder,</L>
<L>bot trawylt aboute fro place to place,</L>
<L>chargyd with sore, wyt-outyn solauce.</L>
<L>Helpe &thorn;am-self sum-wat can ilk beste;</L>
<L N="56">bot of al o&thorn;er &thorn;u cowthe &thorn;e leste.</L>
<L>And wen &thorn;ou was so law kest,<MILESTONE N="113:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at of any helpe &thorn;ou hadyst &thorn;e lest,</L>
<L>No to whan &thorn;ou suld plene &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="60">In so mykyl thoght sette I &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;at for &thorn;e ful fast my ded by-soght,</L>
<L>for al &thorn;at I had to &thorn;e wroght:</L>
<L>fro heuen to herthe I come don,</L>
<L N="64">to seke &thorn;e fro towne to town,</L>
<L>to helpe &thorn;e in &thorn;i myschef,</L>
<L>dere-worthy saule, &thorn;at was me lef;</L>
<L>My blysful body &thorn;at [es] so fre,</L>
<L N="68">In &thorn;i myschef to gyf it &thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000647.tif" N="639"></L>
<L>Bot ar I &thorn;at grace gyf &thorn;e suld,</L>
<L>fyrst for &thorn;i luf dy I wold.</L>
<L>vntyl a madyn I be-tak me</L>
<L N="72">fyrst wen I wold consawed be;&mdash;</L>
<L>to knaw hyre name with-outyn mys,</L>
<L>Mary, godes moder, called scho is.&mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;e maydyn was myld, trew &amp; fre,</L>
<L N="76">Scho consaywed me for luf of &thorn;e.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">The next lines are damaged by wet.</NOTE>[Nyne monthes with hyr I was],</L>
<L>to make amendys [for &thorn;i trespas],</L>
<L N="79">ar [I in to &thorn;is world was born]</L>
<L>to sawe &thorn;e [man &thorn;at was forlorn].</L>
<L>throght my [vertu &amp; my grace]</L>
<L>&thorn;us come &thorn;e [sesyng fyrst in place].</L>
<L N="83">vergyn mary, maydyn myld,</L>
<L>wi&thorn; me &thorn;us went scho gret with chyld.</L>
<L>wen gabryell gret hyre [so] gentilly,</L>
<L>Scho answerd with 'ecceancilla domini.'</L>
<L>Anon scho was with chyld &thorn;ore,</L>
<L N="88">a maydyn as scho was before.</L>
<L>Bot wen &thorn;is was broght to hende,</L>
<L>gret enwy &thorn;er-at had &thorn;e fende;</L>
<L>&thorn;at cursyd fende, wyckyd satanas,</L>
<L N="92">Had gret wonder why it was</L>
<L>&thorn;at hy suld do so mykyll for &thorn;e<MILESTONE N="113b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at so vnkynd has bene to me.
<PB REF="00000648.tif" N="640"></L>
<L>wrothe was&mdash;it helpys hym noght:&mdash;</L>
<L N="96">to dystroy &thorn;e was hys thoght.</L>
<L>ad he ouer-come &thorn;ee, &thorn;ou may wele knawe</L>
<L>he wolde af halden &thorn;e full law!</L>
<L>He temp[t]yd me to gret foly,</L>
<L N="100">Pryd, cowetys, &amp; glotony,</L>
<L>for [he] wyst I<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. I wyst I was I]</NOTE> was a man;</L>
<L>Bot syn in me [ne] fonde he nan.</L>
<L>for sothe, ful hard thert he me,</L>
<L N="104">&thorn;at bargan dere boght suld be;</L>
<L>To put &thorn;e for euer out of my syght,</L>
<L>He purpose hym bothe day &amp; nyght.</L>
<L>Bot, <SUP>2</SUP>dere saule, her-kyn<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[2_2 MS. dere worthy saule hye kyn]</NOTE> to me,</L>
<L N="108">And gode techyng I sal telle &thorn;e.</L>
<L>I wyll mak a charter of feoffefment,</L>
<L>Hewen &amp; erthe sall be present.</L>
<L>Bot in &thorn;at maner most it made be</L>
<L N="112">&thorn;at me most gyf my lyfe for &thorn;e;</L>
<L>for leuer me has to dy, I-wysse,</L>
<L>&amp; bryng &thorn;e to my endles blysse,</L>
<L>&thorn;an &thorn;u be lost euermore me fro,</L>
<L N="116">&amp; to endles payne &thorn;e fende &thorn;e to.</L>
<L>Bot wen I em ded, saule, be &thorn;ou kynd,</L>
<L>&amp; af &thorn;is charter in &thorn;i mynd!
<PB REF="00000649.tif" N="641"></L>
<L>for I wyll dy for &thorn;i foly,</L>
<L N="120">to bryng &thorn;e to my company.</L>
<L>to helpe &thorn;e I em ay redy,</L>
<L N="122">&amp; fayne to sawe &thorn;e fro &thorn;i enmy.</L>
<L>Bot many a way, saule, af I gone,</L>
<L>In hungyre &amp; thyrst, &amp; cald as stone,</L>
<L>thyrty wynter &amp;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. fully &amp;]</NOTE> iij fully,</L>
<L>wen my dysese was done trewly.</L>
<L N="127">to mak &thorn;i charter of &thorn;i wele-fare,</L>
<L>parchemen to fynde wyst I neuer ware</L>
<L>&thorn;at wyld last to &thorn;e warldes end;&mdash;</L>
<L>harkyns now to my wordes hend!&mdash;</L>
<L>Bot as trew loue<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. lyue</NOTE> bad me do,</L>
<L N="132">loke ware I af not done so.</L>
<L>&thorn;is wordys are &thorn;us to vnderfong</L>
<L>to lewed men in ynglys tong:</L>
<L N="135">My flesche trewly es mans fode,</L>
<L>&thorn;at for mans saule dyed on &thorn;e rode;</L>
<L>My blode for sothe &thorn;i drynk sal be,</L>
<L>&thorn;at for &thorn;e was sched on &thorn;e rod[e] tre.</L>
<L>wo-so it resaywes wyt-outyn mys,</L>
<L N="140">Sawyd sal he be, &amp; cum to blys;</L>
<L>he &thorn;at takys it vnworthy, &amp; not for|thy[n]k,</L>
<L>hys awne Iuggement he etys &amp; drynk.</L>
<L N="143">for &thorn;ou vnworthe resawes me,</L>
<L>&thorn;u belewys no&yogh;t &thorn;at I suld be he.
<PB REF="00000650.tif" N="642"></L>
<L>Belewe &thorn;is wordes as ye say,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;u ert damned for euer &amp; ay;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;u belewe &thorn;is &thorn;at I &thorn;e telle,</L>
<L N="148">Body &amp; saule &thorn;u gose to helle.</L>
<L>My wordys ere &thorn;is &thorn;at I em he;</L>
<L>wo be-lewys, blyssyd he be;</L>
<L>wyt me sall dwel for euer I-wysse,</L>
<L N="152">&thorn;at sese me no&yogh;t, &amp; lewys in &thorn;isse.</L>
<L>thynk on &thorn;is wordys, I charge &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Als euer &thorn;u wyll sawed be;</L>
<L>And put in &thorn;i mynd my passyon,</L>
<L N="156">wylk sall be &thorn;i saluacyon.</L>
<L>At ilk a tyme thynk &thorn;u so,</L>
<L>And so sall &thorn;u ouer-come &thorn;i fo;</L>
<L>It es &thorn;e best leson &thorn;at &thorn;ou may lere&mdash;</L>
<L N="160">&thorn;i gostly enmy aw to fere;&mdash;</L>
<L>for &thorn;e grettest temptacyon,</L>
<L>wyt &thorn;is &thorn;ou may lay all don.</L>
<L>af it in mynde stedfastly,</L>
<L N="164">And &thorn;u sall af &thorn;i purpos, trewly.</L>
<L>&thorn;us dyd my dyscipulles &thorn;at supped wi&thorn; me;</L>
<L>And als I bad &thorn;am do, so do &yogh;e!</L>
<L N="167">Bot or &thorn;at I fra &thorn;e borde rase,</L>
<L>Of my dyscypulle<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. dyscypulles</NOTE> betrayd I was:</L>
<L>Wen he had supyd, he rase o-none;</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="114" UNIT="folio">To &thorn;e maysteres of law gun he gone,</L>
<L>And broght &thorn;am wi&thorn; hym in &thorn;at way,</L>
<L>Als a lyon &thorn;at gase about hys pray.
<PB REF="00000651.tif" N="643"></L>
<L N="173">And wen &thorn;ai were &thorn;edyre comen,</L>
<L>&thorn;ai layd hande on me, &amp; me nomen.</L>
<L>Onone &thorn;ai be-gan to spoyle me,</L>
<L N="176">And sayde I suld dye on tre;</L>
<L>My mantyl &amp; o&thorn;er clothes mo,</L>
<L>&thorn;ai had &thorn;am sone tane me fro;</L>
<L N="179">&thorn;ai cast lotys how it suld falle,</L>
<L>wylk on suld af, or parte &thorn;am halle.</L>
<L>Sone al my clothes &thorn;[a]i fro me toke,</L>
<L>&amp; all my frendes me for-soke;</L>
<L>Nakyd I stode emong my fone,</L>
<L N="184">for o&thorn;er socur had I none;</L>
<L>Redy &thorn;ai were [me] for to dysese,</L>
<L>bot no &thorn;er was me for to plese.</L>
<L>&thorn;ai made schourge scharp &amp; grete,</L>
<L N="188">ware-wi&thorn; &thorn;ai suld my body bete.</L>
<L>be-syde I stod, &amp; saw all &thorn;is;</L>
<L>ful sore I gan me drede I wys;</L>
<L>Gyf &thorn;at I wold af plened me,</L>
<L N="192">to me suld no socure af be.</L>
<L>Sone me to slo, acordyd &thorn;ai ware.</L>
<L>to my fader I made my prayere:</L>
<L>'fader of mercy! comforte af I none;</L>
<L>Al my dyscypules fro me ere gone;</L>
<L N="197">&thorn;e iewes cry fast I sall be dede:</L>
<L>do &thorn;i wyll, fader, I can no no&thorn;er rede!</L>
<L>to &thorn;e I mak my mone, I em welle spylte;
<PB REF="00000652.tif" N="644"></L>
<L>to-morne sall I dye for mans gylte.'</L>
<L N="201">&thorn;an myght I no&thorn;er spek nor gon;</L>
<L>I was so sore bette, I fell don onon.</L>
<L>&thorn;ai sayd: 'spede vs fast in &thorn;is stond,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he to a pelere fast were bound!'</L>
<L>Al ful of mys-comfort for sothe I was,</L>
<L>wen &thorn;ai led me forthe so gret pase.</L>
<L N="207">To a pelar &thorn;ai band me sore,</L>
<L>On me &thorn;ai had no pyte &thorn;ore;<MILESTONE N=":2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>'be mery,' &thorn;ai sayd, '&amp; mak gode chere!</L>
<L>we are &thorn;i frendes all &thorn;at stande here;</L>
<L>we ere &thorn;ai &thorn;at sall &thorn;e no&yogh;t forsak</L>
<L N="212">tyll on a cros &thorn;i dede &thorn;u tak;</L>
<L>we sall neuer forsak &thorn;e,</L>
<L>to &thorn;u to a tre nayled be.'</L>
<L>&thorn;e soro I had, myght no tong tell:</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at I dyd, was to sawe fro hell.</L>
<L N="217">So stode I bondyn all &thorn;at nyght,</L>
<L>to of &thorn;e morne &thorn;at it was day-lyght:</L>
<L>to me &thorn;ai come &amp; sayd: 'gode morne!</L>
<L N="220">Mak mery, for ded es sworne.'</L>
<L>Onone &thorn;ai bet me full rewfully,
<PB REF="00000653.tif" N="645"></L>
<L>And als a ded man &thorn;ai lefe me, trewly.</L>
<L>A, saule, for &thorn;e tholyd I &thorn;is lasche!</L>
<L>My [blod] ran oute at ilka dasche,</L>
<L N="225">&thorn;at fro my fot vnto my hede</L>
<L>was not els bot all blode rede;</L>
<L>for bathe by-hynd &amp; als be-fore,</L>
<L N="228">all for-betyn was I &thorn;ore.</L>
<L>wo loked on my wysage,</L>
<L>&thorn;ai myght se a refull ymage;</L>
<L>I telle here in gode trewthe,</L>
<L N="232">&thorn;ai myght of me a had rewthe!</L>
<L>wen I was lesyd fro &thorn;at pylere,</L>
<L>for sothe I had a rewful chere,</L>
<L N="235">for alle aboute me, &thorn;er I stode,</L>
<L>&thorn;er was no thyng bot lyuered blode.</L>
<L>to me &thorn;ai spak with boste chere:</L>
<L>'&thorn;is cros to &thorn;e mounte &thorn;ou sal bere!'</L>
<L>were-opon &thorn;ai strened me</L>
<L N="240">Als gode parchemen aw to be.</L>
<L>here now, &amp; &yogh;e sall wyttyn</L>
<L>how &thorn;is charter was &thorn;us wrytyn.</L>
<L N="243">On al my face fell blak ynk,</L>
<L>wen &thorn;e thornes in my hed gan synk.
<PB REF="00000654.tif" N="646"></L>
<L>&thorn;is pennys &thorn;at &thorn;is lettyrs wrytyn,</L>
<L>was &thorn;e scorcheges &thorn;at I was wi&thorn; smytyn.</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="114b:1" UNIT="folio">How many letters on &thorn;e charter be,</L>
<L N="248">Byde &amp; &thorn;u may wyte &amp; see:</L>
<L>v Ml iiij c lx, als I telle can,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[5,460]</NOTE></L>
<L>were wondys blody rede &amp; wan.</L>
<L>And for to schaw &thorn;e my luf-dede,</L>
<L N="252">My self wylle &thorn;e charter rede."</L>
<L>goddis son of heuen, &thorn;e sothe to say,</L>
<L>&thorn;is wordy[s] spake on gode fryday,</L>
<L>pyned on &thorn;e mounte of calwery,</L>
<L N="256">to &thorn;e pepull &thorn;at passyd hym by:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e all &thorn;at passe here by me,</L>
<L>takys hete, &amp; lok vp with &yogh;oure hee,</L>
<L>And rede opon &thorn;is parchemyne,</L>
<L N="260">If any soro be lyke to myne.</L>
<L>tak hete, &amp; here &thorn;is charter be redde,</L>
<L>how I am wondyd &amp; fo[r]bledde.</L>
<L>'knaw &yogh;e &thorn;at here ere, &amp; forto come,</L>
<L>&thorn;at I, ihesus of na&yogh;aret, godys sone,</L>
<L N="265">as gyn for euer, &amp; grauntyd,</L>
<L>and be &thorn;is charter confermed,</L>
<L>how mans sawle in my ioy to belde,</L>
<L>wyt all &thorn;e purtenance &thorn;er-with to welde,
<PB REF="00000655.tif" N="647"></L>
<L>to af &amp; to hald with-outy[n] mysse</L>
<L>&thorn;at for-sayd place, heuen-blysse,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at blyssed place for euer to dwell,</L>
<L N="272">for &thorn;e rent &thorn;at I sall &thorn;e tell,</L>
<L>&thorn;at blysfull place &thorn;at is so fre,</L>
<L>with-outyn omage or fewte.</L>
<L>for, sone, I aske of &thorn;e no more,</L>
<L N="276">bot a foure-lewed gyrsse pay me &thorn;er|fore:</L>
<L>&thorn;e fyrst lewe es schryft so smert;</L>
<L>&thorn;e secund, for &thorn;i syn, soro of hart;</L>
<L>&thorn;e thyrd es 'I wyll no more do so';</L>
<L>&thorn;e ferthe es penance ewened &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L N="281">wen &thorn;is lewes ere to-geder knytte,</L>
<L>a 'trew-luf' men may calle itte.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is rent be &thorn;u no&yogh;t be-hynd,</L>
<L>&thorn;e way to heuen if &thorn;u wyll wynd!</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ou &thorn;is rent treuly pays me,</L>
<L>My gret mercy sall I gyf &thorn;e.</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou fall, &amp; gretely mystake,</L>
<L N="288">&yogh;it &thorn;is charter will not I forsake;</L>
<L>for wo so mendes, &amp; mercy wyll crafe,</L>
<L>My blystful ioy trewly sall he hafe.</L>
<L>Bot many ere now lywyng here</L>
<L N="292">&thorn;at pays not &thorn;er rent be &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>Bot labures ful fere in dyuerse warke;&mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;is knawes bothe lewde &amp; clarke;&mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore in wat a-state god has &thorn;e sent,</L>
<L N="296">Do trewly &thorn;i labure, &thorn;an pays &thorn;ou &thorn;i rent.</L>
<L>&thorn;i gostly warkes &thorn;at &thorn;ou sal werke,</L>
<L>Are &thorn;e sacrementes of haly kyrke:
<PB REF="00000656.tif" N="648"></L>
<L>&thorn;e fyrst, &thorn;at &thorn;ou af &thorn;e baptysacyon;</L>
<L N="300">&thorn;e secund es &thorn;i confirmacyon;</L>
<L>&thorn;e thyrd: wat ordyr or degre &thorn;ou hawe,</L>
<L>kepe it reght, &amp; &thorn;an ert &thorn;ou sawe;</L>
<L>&thorn;e fowrth es wedlak, for soth I-wys,</L>
<L N="304">So &thorn;at &thorn;ou sal not do a mys;</L>
<L>&thorn;e fyfte es penance, if &thorn;ou it work</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e prest of haly kyrk;</L>
<L>&thorn;e sexte es &thorn;at &thorn;ou be-leue on my flesche &amp; blod,</L>
<L N="308">&thorn;e sacriment on &thorn;e auter &thorn;at dyed on rode;</L>
<L>&thorn;e sewent es &thorn;i laste endyng,</L>
<L>to sawe &thorn;e fro &thorn;i enme at &thorn;i passyng.</L>
<L>do &thorn;u &thorn;us &thorn;is warke &yogh;ere be &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>And dred &thorn;e neuer of fyndes fere;</L>
<L>And wo so dose here &thorn;e warkis of mercy,</L>
<L>he squenches &thorn;e fyre in purgatory.</L>
<L N="315">Opon &thorn;e cros me thyrstyd sore,</L>
<L>bot of swylk drynk myght I nomore:</L>
<L>Aysyl &amp; gall gaf &thorn;ai me.</L>
<L>Bot a no&thorn;er drynk ask I of &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&thorn;u luf &thorn;i foo in worde &amp; thoght:</L>
<L N="320">o&thorn;er drynk af &thorn;e ask I noght.</L>
<L>Als &thorn;u me lufes, af &thorn;is in mynde:</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="115:1" UNIT="folio">Be &thorn;u no&yogh;t to &thorn;i enmy vnkynde;</L>
<L>Ensawmpull &thorn;u sall take of me:</L>
<L N="324">ffor luf of my fo I hang on a tre,
<PB REF="00000657.tif" N="649"></L>
<L>And prayd my fader of mercy,</L>
<L>Of my enmys to af pety;</L>
<L N="327">&amp; als I dyd, do &thorn;u to &thorn;ame,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou wyll be sawed fra hell-payne!</L>
<L>wo so dose as I now telle,</L>
<L>In heuen for euer with me sall dwelle.</L>
<L>here-of ere wyttnens many one:</L>
<L N="332">Marke, Mathu, Luke, &amp; Ione,</L>
<L>And namely my moder swete,</L>
<L>&thorn;at for my blode teres gan grete.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er scho stode vnder &thorn;e rode;</L>
<L N="336">Scho saw my body al on blode,</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e partyce of my body</L>
<L>were brokyn at &thorn;e pelere, treuly.</L>
<L>ffor me sho was &thorn;erfore ful wo.</L>
<L N="340">And so were wemen many mo:</L>
<L>&thorn;er stode for-sothe be syde me,</L>
<L>My moder, Magdalan, &amp; Cleophe;</L>
<L>&thorn;er stode be syde &thorn;e crose al-so,</L>
<L N="344">Ion euangelyst, ful fulle of wo.</L>
<L>&amp; I sayd to my moder mary:</L>
<L>'Be-halde &thorn;i sone &thorn;at standes &thorn;e by!'</L>
<L N="347">To Ion I spak wordes of pyte:</L>
<L>'Be-hald &thorn;i moder! hy tak hyre to &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>Wen I spak &thorn;is wordes &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Vntyll hyre hart &thorn;ai went ful nere;</L>
<L>wen I to Ion my cosyn h[i]re toke,</L>
<L N="352">Scho cast on me a rewfull loke,</L>
<L>Als I had hyre all for-sakyn</L>
<L>And tyll a nothere hyre sone takyn;
<PB REF="00000658.tif" N="650"></L>
<L>Onone scho fell downe in swounynge</L>
<L N="356">Be-for &thorn;e cros at my dyynge.</L>
<L>&thorn;e paynes &thorn;at I hade were full sore,</L>
<L>Bot for my moder &thorn;ai were wel more!</L>
<L>ffor soro of my passion I made a cry,</L>
<L N="360">And cryed 'hely lama &yogh;abatany.'</L>
<L>it semed my moder hart wald brek;</L>
<L>No worde to me &thorn;er myght scho speke;</L>
<L>No wonder was if hyre were wo,<MILESTONE N=":2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="364">wen sho saw me dyght so!</L>
<L>wen I layde my hede now here &amp; &thorn;are,</L>
<L>My moder chaunged all hyre chere;</L>
<L N="367">Scho wold fayne af hulpon me,</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;e Iewe[s] it myght not be.</L>
<L>&thorn;e paynes of hyre were full smerte;</L>
<L>&thorn;e swerd of soro perchyd hyre harte;</L>
<L>Bot or &thorn;is charter &thorn;us wrytyn was,</L>
<L N="372">Many tymes scho sayd alas!</L>
<L>ffull wo hyre was, as &thorn;u may se:</L>
<L>af it in mynde for luf of me!</L>
<L>wen hyre payns were sumwat ouer-gon,</L>
<L N="376">vp to my face scho lokyd onon,</L>
<L>&amp; saw I dro fast to myne endyng:</L>
<L>Ouer scho felle ofte in swonyng,</L>
<L>&amp; sayd: 'alas! weder sall I gone?</L>
<L>Sumtyme had I a sone, now af I none.'</L>
<L>My moder payns gan me sore rew;</L>
<L>ffor strong es luf of frendes trew;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er luffes none so tendyrly</L>
<L N="384">As dos &thorn;e modyre namely.</L>
<L>wen hyre payn[e]s were paste,</L>
<L>To mary magdalan scho spak in haste:</L>
<L>'Mary magdalan, helpe &thorn;ou me!</L>
<L N="388">hy se my sone dye on &yogh;on tre.'
<PB REF="00000659.tif" N="651"></L>
<L>Magdalan sayd: 'I can no no&thorn;er rede,</L>
<L>I knele &amp; se my lorde nere dede;</L>
<L>ffull grete soro has smytyn my harte,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it me rewes &thorn;i payn[e]s smarte;</L>
<L N="393">ffor me were lewer to dy onone</L>
<L>&thorn;an for to se &thorn;e mak &thorn;is mone.</L>
<L>Cumme with me! I sall &thorn;e bryng</L>
<L N="396">ffro &thorn;is wo &amp; &thorn;is mornyng</L>
<L>In-tylle a tempull here be-fore;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;u has wepyd here full sore.'</L>
<L>My moder answerd to magdalayn:</L>
<L N="400">'Walde &thorn;ou af me a-way so fayn?</L>
<L>I had gret ioy wen I hym bare:</L>
<L>Suld I now lewe hym hanga[n]d &thorn;are,</L>
<L>And sofur hym so for to be,</L>
<L N="404">&thorn;at was my myrthe &amp; al my gle?</L>
<L>Magdalan, for sothe vnkynde I were</L>
<L>to go away &amp; lefe hym &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="407">&thorn;erfore be crose here lyf I wyll,</L>
<L>ffor hys syght had I neuer my fyll;</L>
<L>Sum-tyme wen he lokyd me on,<MILESTONE N="115b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>It was my most ioy of ilkon.</L>
<L>he was &thorn;e fayrest &thorn;at euer was borne,</L>
<L N="412">&amp; now es crowned with a garland of thorne!'</L>
<L>I prayd hyre go were hyre wylles was,</L>
<L>for I wold byde &amp; syng alas!</L>
<L N="415">I prayd &thorn;am go weder &thorn;ai wolde,</L>
<L>ffor a song of murnyng syng I sulde.</L>
<L>Scho sette hyre down be syde &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L>&amp; lokyd o-pon hyre blody fode:</L>
<L>&amp; als scho stode &amp; lokyd me on,</L>
<L N="420">Scho saw my lyfe was nere gon.</L>
<L>Alas, alas! gan sho syng;</L>
<L>ffull fast hyre handis gan scho wryng;</L>
<L>wyt grete soro &thorn;us all &thorn;e day,</L>
<L N="424">hyre song was euer 'walaway!'</L>
<L>'A, my dere-worthy chyld, now cal I &thorn;e</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;i fadyre in trinyte;
<PB REF="00000660.tif" N="652"></L>
<L>ffader of mercy, now dyes my son,</L>
<L N="428">wyt me may he no lenger won.</L>
<L>ffader, I pray &thorn;e, lat me dye onon,</L>
<L>&thorn;at we may bothe ly vnder a ston!</L>
<L>Now pas he, fadyre, as it es &thorn;i wyll,</L>
<L>I wate he es dede, he hyngis soo styll.</L>
<L N="433">Alas, wat sal I do? forsothe, I wate neuer,</L>
<L>Bot for to gret my fyll, wyls he es &thorn;us nere.'</L>
<L>A wyle scho sat &amp; spak rete noghte,</L>
<L N="436">It semed as scho had gret toghte.</L>
<L>O-none scho gan tremul huglely,</L>
<L>And forto gryse gretly with hyre body;</L>
<L>&thorn;er scho swoned &amp; wex nere dede,</L>
<L>hyre face wex wane &amp; nothyng rede,</L>
<L N="441">hyre hene were blody, h[y]re lyppys were blo,</L>
<L>hyre brest gan ryse, hyre hart was wo,</L>
<L>hyre fayre wysage was all blody,</L>
<L>hyre tethe were lokyn, scho was rewly.</L>
<L>Magdalan sayd scho was dede &thorn;are;</L>
<L>Ion euaungelyst had mekyll kare,</L>
<L N="447">&amp; to magdalan sayd in haste:</L>
<L>'lat hyre not loke on hym so faste!</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="115:2" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e syght of hym, it es so rew,</L>
<L>Makys hyre euer-more soro new.'</L>
<L>Ione &amp; magdalan full lang &thorn;er satte</L>
<L N="452">Or &thorn;ai of hyre any worde gatte.</L>
<L>Pure I was, as &thorn;u may knaw;</L>
<L>My hede I bowed &thorn;er ful laaw:</L>
<L>So bare I was of warldely gode,</L>
<L N="456">Wen I sul dye opon &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L>&thorn;at I had no&yogh;t were-of to take,</L>
<L>Reste vnto my hede to make.</L>
<L N="459">Pure man, af &thorn;is mynde</L>
<L>Wen &thorn;u no rest in warlde may fynde,</L>
<L>Wat reste I had onely for &thorn;e</L>
<L>Wen I hange nayled opon a tre.</L>
<L>Wele may &thorn;u knaw &thorn;at none I had,</L>
<L>Emang my enmys &thorn;er I was stad!</L>
<L>Wen &thorn;u emang &thorn;i enmys ert broght,</L>
<L>Be redy to sofure wyt all &thorn;i thoght.
<PB REF="00000661.tif" N="653"></L>
<L>To frande at bare it [es] full hard,</L>
<L N="468">As &thorn;u as wroght to be reward.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at sofures dyses for luf of me,</L>
<L>On my reght hand wend sall he;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at wengys hym on hys bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="472">Sal not do so, bot go on &thorn;e to&thorn;er.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at wyll &thorn;e sothe knaw,</L>
<L>Swylk as he owes, swylk sall he maw;</L>
<L>Swylke as &thorn;i warkis here in &thorn;i lywyng,</L>
<L>Swylk sal be &thorn;i reward at &thorn;i endyng.</L>
<L N="477">I fele me now so ful of wo,</L>
<L>&thorn;at oute of &thorn;is warld me most go;</L>
<L>Wyt paynes of dede I am bonde;</L>
<L>My saule sal passe now in &thorn;is stonde.</L>
<L>Be-hald now, man, with &thorn;i gostely hee,</L>
<L>Now for &thorn;i luf [how] I sall<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. sall sall]</NOTE> dye.</L>
<L>I hyng on crosse for luf on &thorn;e:</L>
<L N="484">for-sake &thorn;i syn for luf of me;</L>
<L>Mercy aske, Amende &thorn;e sone,</L>
<L>And I for-gyf &thorn;at &thorn;u as mys done;</L>
<L>fful of mercy I am, trewly,<MILESTONE N="116" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="488">To all &thorn;ase &thorn;at askys mercy.</L>
<L>Wat sal it grefe &thorn;e to repent &thorn;e,</L>
<L>In hendeles Ioy to dwelle with me?</L>
<L>for &thorn;ai &thorn;at wyll no mercy crye,</L>
<L N="492">&thorn;ai sall to helle wen &thorn;ai dye.</L>
<L>&thorn;u &thorn;at wyll my blys wyn,</L>
<L>Nedes &thorn;e must forsak &thorn;i syn.</L>
<L>Now wen I af a worde spokyn,</L>
<L N="496">My nehen sall to-geder be lokyn:</L>
<L>&thorn;u synfull man, af pyte on me,</L>
<L>ffor here I dye for luf of &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;is wordes must me nedys speke,</L>
<L N="500">And &thorn;er-wyt my hart wyll breke:</L>
<L>Consummatum est: Now es all done!</L>
<L>&thorn;e lyght was lost of sone &amp; mone;</L>
<L>Gret wonder &thorn;er men myght hawe:</L>
<L N="504">dede men ryse oute of &thorn;er grawe;</L>
<L>&thorn;e stones brast, &thorn;e erth gan quake,</L>
<L>ffendys &thorn;er ware &thorn;at ware ful blake,</L>
<L>&thorn;e wayle of &thorn;e tempull in two it felle:</L>
<L N="508">All &thorn;is was done, I &thorn;e telle.
<PB REF="00000662.tif" N="654"></L>
<L>Bot, dere saule, be &thorn;ou reght glade!</L>
<L>Be-twyx &thorn;e &amp; me pese es made.</L>
<L>Hy went to helle &thorn;is charter to schew,</L>
<L>To satanas &thorn;at es so mekyll a schrew;</L>
<L>&thorn;er I hym schent &amp; broght to grounde</L>
<L>Thrught my nayles, spere &amp; wounde,</L>
<L>And after a conant made &thorn;er was</L>
<L N="516">Be-twene me &amp; satanas:</L>
<L>Alle my catell to af a-way,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he refte me with hys fals pray.</L>
<L>&thorn;e thyrd day I rase, &amp; made a fest</L>
<L N="520">Vnto &thorn;e most &amp; vnto &thorn;e lest:</L>
<L>&thorn;e fest was of ioy &amp; blyse;</L>
<L>Pasche-day called it ese.</L>
<L>&thorn;e seles &thorn;at &thorn;e charter es seled with,<MILESTONE N="116:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="524">&thorn;ai ware made at a smythe;</L>
<L>Of golde nor syluur were &thorn;ai noght:</L>
<L>Wyt a spere to my hart &thorn;ai soght;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Iryn nayles &thorn;ai nayled me</L>
<L N="528">Thrugh fote &amp; hand vntyl a tre;</L>
<L>On &thorn;is maner was I stong</L>
<L>Thrugh my scynne &amp; my long;</L>
<L>In my reght syde &thorn;ai mad a wonde;</L>
<L>&thorn;e blode ran downe to &thorn;e grownde.</L>
<L N="533">&thorn;e selyng-wax was dere boght;</L>
<L>At my hart-rote &thorn;ai it soght,</L>
<L>Als it were tempurde wi&thorn; vermy[ly]on</L>
<L>Of my hart blode &thorn;at ran &thorn;er don.
<PB REF="00000663.tif" N="655"></L>
<L N="537">ffywe selys here set &thorn;er opane:</L>
<L>ffader &amp; son, god &amp; mane,</L>
<L>&thorn;e fyrst es to belewe most,</L>
<L N="540">&thorn;at I come of &thorn;e holy gost.</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore here now may &thorn;ou se</L>
<L>&thorn;att I am kyng of gret pouste.</L>
<L>In playne powere &thorn;i state to make,</L>
<L>A crowne of throrne to me gon I take:</L>
<L>&thorn;is crowne betakyns &thorn;at I am kyng,</L>
<L>And frely may gyf my nawne thyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;is wyttyns wele of &thorn;e iewes all:</L>
<L N="548">On kne be-for me gan &thorn;ai fall,</L>
<L>&amp; lowde &thorn;a cryed on &thorn;er cryyng,</L>
<L>'Hayle be &thorn;ou, &thorn;e iewes kyng!'</L>
<L>Be-twene two thefes &thorn;is charter was celyd&mdash;</L>
<L N="552">&thorn;ai bothe were seke, &thorn;e tone was helyd;&mdash;</L>
<L>Be-twene &thorn;e thefes vppe was I dyght,</L>
<L>In tokynnyng &thorn;at I was kyng of myght.</L>
<L>&thorn;is betokyns bothe gode &amp; ylle,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e day of dome to sawe &amp; spylle.</L>
<L>&thorn;is charter &thorn;us celyd, lewe I wyll &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="558">ware-by &thorn;u sall ay sekyr be:</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="116:1" UNIT="folio">My precyus body, of &thorn;e preste hande</L>
<L>for to resaywe, &thorn;u sall vnderstand.</L>
<L>My precyus body es &thorn;e sacrament,</L>
<L>&thorn;at [at] many a autyre verament</L>
<L>&thorn;e prestes sakyre at &thorn;er messe,</L>
<L N="564">Wedyre &thorn;ai can more or lesse.</L>
<L>he &thorn;at faythefully lewes &thorn;er-opon,</L>
<L>endeles pyne sall he fele non;</L>
<L>All if he dye, &yogh;it dyes not he;</L>
<L>Vppe sal he ryse, &amp; lyfe wyt me.
<PB REF="00000664.tif" N="656"></L>
<L N="569">To my fader wyll I now sone,</L>
<L>ffor all hys wylle now af [I] done;</L>
<L>I take my lewe at alle &amp; summe:</L>
<L>On &thorn;e day of dome, agayn I comme,</L>
<L N="573">Men to deme after &thorn;er warkys,</L>
<L>&thorn;is es &thorn;e belewe of haly kyrkys,&mdash;</L>
<L>And euer more after in ioy to dwelle,</L>
<L>Sawyd to be fro &thorn;e payns of helle.</L>
<L>Bot a cote-armur I bere with me,</L>
<L>&thorn;at I toke of &thorn;i lyuer so fre;</L>
<L N="579">&thorn;e cote es ryche &amp; wnder fyne,</L>
<L>&thorn;e chaumpe es now of rede satyne.</L>
<L>A ful fayre maydyn me it worgh;</L>
<L>Out of hyre bure to me it brogh.</L>
<L>&thorn;is cote es poudered with fywe ros rede,</L>
<L>wondis &thorn;at I sofurd wen I suld be dede;</L>
<L N="585">ffywe: wen I comme agayn to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Be thys clethyng &thorn;ou may ken me.</L>
<L>&thorn;ai &thorn;at ere of &thorn;er rent be-hynde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;is wordes wyl not af in mynde,</L>
<L N="589">fful sore may &thorn;ai be adrede</L>
<L>Wen &thorn;is charter sall be rede;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e hee iustys be &thorn;ai wele ware,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;an forsothe I sall no&yogh;t spare;
<PB REF="00000665.tif" N="657"></L>
<L>ffor alle &thorn;i syns &thorn;at &thorn;u as worght<MILESTONE N=":2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffro &thorn;i &yogh;ongthe &thorn;ai sall be soght.</L>
<L N="595">And of my gret mercy I forgyf &thorn;e</L>
<L>Syns &thorn;at &thorn;u schrywen of wyld be.</L>
<L>Pay &thorn;is rent, wo so has space,</L>
<L>Als he of me wyll gete grace;</L>
<L>Repent hym, wo so dyes sodanly,</L>
<L N="600">for of hys saule I may af mercy.</L>
<L>A cownant es made be-twyx vs two:</L>
<L>Als I af sayd, loke &thorn;at &thorn;u do so!</L>
<L>Loke wat &thorn;i pater noster spekes to &thorn;e:</L>
<L N="604">'Als I forgyf, lorde, for-gyf me!'</L>
<L>Do &thorn;er-after reght as &thorn;u wyllt,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;i saule be not spylt.</L>
<L>On holy wryte I may put me,</L>
<L N="608">Wedyre I be curtas or no&yogh;t to &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Be &thorn;e texte of holy wrytte,</L>
<L>In wat place &thorn;u wyll seke itte,&mdash;</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou lered, be &thorn;u lewed,&mdash;</L>
<L N="612">&thorn;e way to heuen I af &thorn;e schewed.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore I byd &thorn;e pay &thorn;i rent,</L>
<L>&thorn;at with &thorn;e fende &thorn;u be not schent!</L>
<L>Wyt me to blys &thorn;an sall &thorn;u comme,</L>
<L>And in my blys &thorn;an sall &thorn;u wonne."</L>
<L N="617">Vnto &thorn;at blys he vs bryng,</L>
<L>&thorn;at of noght made alle thyng!
</L>
</LG>

