<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>1. Mercy passes all Things.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Printed by Furnivall from the Simeon MS., with collations from the Vernon, in <I>Early English Poems and Lives of Saints</I>, p. 118, <I>Philolog. Soc. Trans.</I> 1872.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>(16 <I>stanzas of</I> 12, <I>abab abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>BI west, vnder a wylde wode-syde,</L>
<L>In a launde, &thorn;er I was lente,</L>
<L>Wlanke deor on grounde gunne glyde,</L>
<L N="4">And lyouns Raumping vppon bente,</L>
<L>Beores, wolues wi&thorn; Mou&thorn;es wyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e smale Beestes &thorn;ei al to-rente;</L>
<L>&THORN;er haukes vn-to heore pray &thorn;ei hyde,</L>
<L N="8">Of whuche, to on .I. tok good tente:</L>
<L>A Merlyon, a Brid had hente,</L>
<L>And in hire foot heo gan hit bringe;</L>
<L>Hit cou&thorn;e not speke, but &thorn;us hit mente:</L>
<L N="12">How Merci passe&thorn; alle &thorn;inge.
<PB REF="00000667.tif" N="659"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Merci was in &thorn;at Briddes muynde,</L>
<L>But &thorn;erof kneu&yogh; &thorn;e Hau[e]k non,</L>
<L>ffor in hir foot heo gan hit bynde,</L>
<L N="16">And heold hit stille as eny ston;</L>
<L>Heo dude after &thorn;e cours of kynde,</L>
<L>And flei&yogh; in-to a treo anon.</L>
<L>&THORN;orw kuynde &thorn;e Brid gan Merci fynde:</L>
<L N="20">ffor on &thorn;e morwe heo let hit gon.</L>
<L>fful stille .I. stod my-self al-on,</L>
<L>To herken hou &thorn;at Brid gan synge:</L>
<L>A-wey wol wende bo&thorn;e Mur&thorn;e and moon,</L>
<L N="24">And Merci passe&thorn; alle &thorn;inge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; How Merci passe&thorn; streng&thorn;e &amp; ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Mony a wyse seo we may.</L>
<L>God ordeyned Merci, most of miht,</L>
<L N="28">To beo aboue his werkes ay.</L>
<L>Whon deore Ihesu schal be diht</L>
<L>To demen vs at doomes-day,</L>
<L>Vr sunne wol beo so muche in siht,</L>
<L N="32">We schul not wite what we schul say;</L>
<L>fful fersliche Ri&yogh;t wol vs affray,</L>
<L>And blame vs for vr mis-lyuing:</L>
<L>&THORN;en dar non prese for vs to pray,</L>
<L N="36">But Merci &thorn;at passe&thorn; alle &thorn;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Riht wolde sle vs for vr synne,</L>
<L>Miht wolde don execucion;</L>
<L>And Riht-wyse god &thorn;en wol be-gynne</L>
<L N="40">fforte reherce vs &thorn;is resoun:</L>
<L>"I made &thorn;e, Mon, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou minne,</L>
<L>Of feture lich myn owne fasoun,</L>
<L>And after crepte In-to &thorn;i kinne,</L>
<L N="44">And for &thorn;e suffred passioun;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ornes kene &thorn;en was &thorn;e croun</L>
<L>fful scharpe vppon myn hed standyng;</L>
<L>Min herte-blood ran from me doun;</L>
<L N="48">And I for-&yogh;af &thorn;e alle &thorn;ing.
<PB REF="00000668.tif" N="660"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Myn herte-blood for &thorn;e gan blede,</L>
<L>To buye &thorn;e from &thorn;e fendes blake,</L>
<L>And I for-&yogh;af &thorn;e &thorn;i misdede.</L>
<L N="52">What hast &thorn;ou suffred for my sake?</L>
<L>Me hungred, &thorn;ou woldest not me fede,</L>
<L>Ne neuer my furst ne woldestou slake;</L>
<L>Whon I of herborwe hedde gret nede,</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;ou woldest not to &thorn;in hous me take;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou se&yogh;e me a-mong todes blake,</L>
<L>fful longe in harde prison lyng.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lying]</NOTE></L>
<L>Let seo what onswere constou make,</L>
<L N="60">Wher weore &thorn;ou kynde in eny &thorn;ing?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "And hou .I. quenched al &thorn;i care,</L>
<L>Lift vp &thorn;in ei&yogh;e and &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t se</L>
<L>Mi woundes wete, blodi al bare,</L>
<L N="64">As .I. was rau&yogh;t on Roode-tre.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou se&yogh;e me for defaute forfare,</L>
<L>In seknes and in pouerte:</L>
<L>&YOGH;it of &thorn;i good woldestou not spare,</L>
<L N="68">Ne ones come to visyte me.</L>
<L>Al eor&thorn;li &thorn;ing .I. &yogh;af to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e Beest and fisch &amp; foul fleoyng,</L>
<L>And tolde &thorn;e hou &thorn;at charite</L>
<L N="72">And Merci passe&thorn; alle &thorn;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Hou mihtou eny merci haue</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer desyredest non to do?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou se&yogh;e me naked and clo&thorn;es craue;</L>
<L N="76">Barehed and Barefot gan I go:</L>
<L>On me &thorn;ou vochedest no &thorn;ing saue,</L>
<L>But beede me wende &thorn;i wones fro.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou se&yogh;e me ded aboue to graue</L>
<L N="80">On Bere seuen dayes and mo:</L>
<L>ffor luitel dette I ou&yogh;te &thorn;e &thorn;o,<MILESTONE N="407:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou forbed my buri&yogh;ing.</L>
<L>&THORN;i pater noster seyde not so,</L>
<L N="84">ffor Merci passe&thorn; alle &thorn;ing."
<PB REF="00000669.tif" N="661"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;eos are &thorn;e werkes of Merci seuene,</L>
<L>Of w&yogh;uche crist wol vs areyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle schul stoney wi&thorn; &thorn;at steuene</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at euer tresoun mi&yogh;te a-teyne.</L>
<L>ffor heer but &yogh;if we make vs euene,</L>
<L>&THORN;er may no miht ne &yogh;iftes &yogh;eyne.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne to &thorn;e kyng of heuene,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;e Bok sei&thorn; &thorn;at we schul seyne:</L>
<L>"Wher hastou, lord, in prisoun leyne?</L>
<L>Whonne weore &thorn;ou in eor&thorn;e dwellyng?</L>
<L>Whon se&yogh;e we &thorn;e in such peyne?</L>
<L N="96">Whon askedest &thorn;ou vs eny &thorn;ing?"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Whon &yogh;e se&yogh;e ou&thorn;er Blynd or lame</L>
<L>&THORN;at for my loue asked &yogh;ou ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at &yogh;e duden in myn name,</L>
<L N="100">Hit was to me, bo&thorn;e deede &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>But &yogh;e &thorn;at hated cristendame,</L>
<L>And of my wra&thorn;&thorn;e neuer ne rou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;our seruise schal ben endeles schame</L>
<L N="104">Helle-fuir &thorn;at slakes nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And &yogh;e &thorn;at wi&thorn; my blood .I. bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at loued me in &yogh;oure lyuynge,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schul haue &thorn;at &yogh;e haue sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="108">Merci &thorn;at passe&thorn; alle &thorn;inge."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;is tyme schal tyde, hit is no nay,</L>
<L>And wel is him &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;at grace</L>
<L>ffor to plese his god to pay,</L>
<L N="112">And Merci seche while he ha&thorn; space!</L>
<L>ffor beo vr mou&thorn; crommed with clay</L>
<L>Wormes blake wol vs enbrase:</L>
<L>&THORN;en is to late, Mon, in good fay,</L>
<L N="116">To seche to A-Mende of &thorn;i trespace.</L>
<L>With mekenes &thorn;ou may heuene purchase:</L>
<L>O&thorn;er Meede &thorn;ar &thorn;e non bring,</L>
<L>But knowe &thorn;i god in vche a case,</L>
<L N="120">And loue him best of any &thorn;ing.
<PB REF="00000670.tif" N="662"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To god and non weore holden meste</L>
<L>To loue, and his wra&thorn;&thorn;e eschuwe.</L>
<L>Now is non so vnkuynde a beeste</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;at lasse do&thorn; &thorn;at weore him duwe;</L>
<L>ffor Beestes and foules, more &amp; leeste,</L>
<L>&THORN;e cours of kynde alle &thorn;ei suwe.</L>
<L>And whonne we breken Godes heste,</L>
<L N="128">A&yogh;eynes kuynde we ben vn-trewe:</L>
<L>ffor kuynde wolde &thorn;at we him knewe</L>
<L>And dradde him most in vre doing.</L>
<L>Hit is no riht &thorn;at he vs rewe,</L>
<L N="132">But Merci passe&thorn; alle &thorn;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Now harlotrye for mur&thorn;e is holde,</L>
<L>And vertues tornen in-to vice,</L>
<L>And Symonye ha&thorn; chirches solde,</L>
<L N="136">And lawe is waxen Couetyse;</L>
<L>Vr fei&thorn; is frele to flecche &amp; folde,</L>
<L>ffor treu&thorn;e is put to luytel prise;</L>
<L>Vre God is glotenye and golde,</L>
<L N="140">Dronkenes, Lecherye and dyse:</L>
<L>Lo heer vr lyf and vre delyce,</L>
<L>Vr loue, vr lust and vre lykyng.</L>
<L>&YOGH;et, &yogh;if we wole repente and ryse,</L>
<L N="144">Merci passe&thorn; alle &thorn;inge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Vn-lustily vr lyf we lede,</L>
<L>Monhod and we twynne in two;</L>
<L>To heuen ne helle take we non hede,</L>
<L N="148">But on day come, a no&thorn;er go.</L>
<L>Who is a mayster now but meede,</L>
<L>And pruide, &thorn;at wakened al vr wo?</L>
<L>We stunte, nei&thorn;er for schame ne drede,</L>
<L N="152">To teren vr god from top to to,</L>
<L>ffor-swere his soule, his herte also,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e Menbres &thorn;at we cun Mynge:</L>
<L>fful harde vengeaunce wol falle on &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="156">But merci passe&thorn; alle &thorn;inge.
<PB REF="00000671.tif" N="663"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And corteis knihthod and clergye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wont were vices to forsake,</L>
<L>Are nou so Rooted in Ribaudye</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at o&thorn;ur mer&thorn;es lust hem not make.</L>
<L>A-wei is gentyl cortesye,<MILESTONE N="407:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And lustines his leue ha&thorn; take;</L>
<L>We loue so slou&thorn;e and harlotrie,</L>
<L N="164">We slepe as swolle swyn in lake.</L>
<L>&THORN;er wol no worschupe wi&thorn; vs wake</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at Charite beo mad a kyng:</L>
<L>And &thorn;en schal al vr synne slake,</L>
<L N="168">And Merci passe&thorn; alle &thorn;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; .I. munge no more of &thorn;is to &yogh;ou,</L>
<L>Al-&thorn;au&yogh; .I. cou&thorn;e &yogh;if &thorn;at .I. wolde,</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;e han herd wel whi &amp; hou</L>
<L N="172">Bi-gon &thorn;is tale &thorn;at I haue tolde.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is men knowen wel .I.-nouh,</L>
<L>ffor Merlyons feet ben colde;</L>
<L>hit is heor kynde on Bank and bouh</L>
<L N="176">A quik Brid to hauen and holde,</L>
<L>ffrom foot to foot to flutte and folde,</L>
<L>To kepe hire from clomesyng;</L>
<L>As .I. an hau&thorn;orn gan bi holde,</L>
<L N="180">.I. sau&yogh; my self &thorn;e same &thorn;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whon heo hedde holden so al niht,</L>
<L>On Morwe heo let hit gon a-way:</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er gentrie tau&yogh;t hire so or nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="184">I con not telle &yogh;ou, in good fay!</L>
<L>But, God, as &thorn;ou art ful of mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; we plese &thorn;e not to pay,</L>
<L>Graunt vs repentaunce and respi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="188">And schrift and hosel, or we day;</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou art God and mon verray,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou beo vr help at vre endyng,</L>
<L>Bi-fore &thorn;i face &thorn;at we mai sai:</L>
<L N="192">'Now Merci passe&thorn; alle &thorn;inge.'
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000672.tif" N="664">
<HEAD>2. Deo Gracias I.</HEAD>
<P>(11 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>IN a Chirche, &thorn;er .I. con knel</L>
<L>&THORN;is ender day in on Morwenynge,</L>
<L>Me lyked &thorn;e seruise wonder wel;</L>
<L N="4">ffor-&thorn;i &thorn;e lengore con .I. lynge.</L>
<L>.I. sei&yogh; a Clerk a book for&thorn; bringe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at prikked was in mony a plas;</L>
<L>ffaste he sou&yogh;te what he scholde synge:</L>
<L N="8">And al was Deo Gracias.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Alle &thorn;e queristres in &thorn;at qwer,</L>
<L>On &thorn;at word fast gon &thorn;ei cri.</L>
<L>&THORN;e noyse was good, &amp; .I. drou&yogh; neer</L>
<L N="12">And called a prest ful priueli,</L>
<L>And seide: "sire, for &yogh;or curtesi</L>
<L>Tel me, &yogh;if &yogh;e habbe&thorn; spas,</L>
<L>What hit mene&thorn;, and for whi</L>
<L N="16">&YOGH;e singe Deo Gracias?"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In selk &thorn;at comeli clerk was clad,</L>
<L>And ouer a lettorne leoned he;</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his word he maade me glad,</L>
<L N="20">And seide: "sone, I schal telle &thorn;e:</L>
<L>ffader and Sone In Trinite,</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy gost, ground of vr graas,</L>
<L>Also oftesi&thorn;e &thorn;onke we</L>
<L N="24">As we sei Deo Gracias.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "To &thorn;onke &amp; blesse him we ben bounde</L>
<L>With al &thorn;e mur&thorn;es &thorn;at mon mai Minne:</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e world in wo was wounde</L>
<L N="28">Til &thorn;at he crepte in to vr kinne:</L>
<L>A louesum buirde he li&yogh;te with-Inne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wor&thorn;iest &thorn;at euer was,</L>
<L>And schedde his blod for vre sinne:</L>
<L N="32">And &thorn;erfore Deo Gracias."
<PB REF="00000673.tif" N="665"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;en seide &thorn;e preost: "sone, be &thorn;i leue</L>
<L>.I. moste seie for&thorn; my seruise,</L>
<L>.I. preye &thorn;e tak hit nou&yogh;t in greue;</L>
<L N="36">ffor &thorn;ou hast herd al my deuise,</L>
<L>Bi-cause whi hit is clerkes wyse,</L>
<L>And holychirche muynde of hit maas,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e prince so muchel of prise,</L>
<L N="40">fforte synge Deo Gracias."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Out of &thorn;at chirche .I. wente my way,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;at word was al my &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And twenti tymes .I. con say,</L>
<L N="44">"God graunte &thorn;at .I. for-&yogh;ete hit nou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; I weore out of bonchef brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>what help weore to me to seye allas?</L>
<L>In &thorn;e nome of god, what-euer be wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="48">I schal seie Deo gracias.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "In Mischef and in bonchef bo&thorn;e,<MILESTONE N="407b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">The leaf-numbers here are modern, and on the general wrong plan of making each leaf a folio, instead of the double open page, the back of the left leaf and the front of the right one, which the old numbering always rightly adopts.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at word is good to seye and synge,</L>
<L>And not to wayle ne to bi wro&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;au&yogh; al be nou&yogh;t at vre lykynge.</L>
<L>ffor langour schal not euer lynge,</L>
<L>And sum tyme plesaunse wol ouer-pas,</L>
<L>But ay in hope of a-mendynge,</L>
<L N="56">.I. schal seye Deo Gracias."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A-Mende &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast don amis,</L>
<L>And do wel &thorn;enne, and haue no drede,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er so &thorn;ou beo In bale or blis!</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;i goode suffraunce schal gete &thorn;e mede,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou &thorn;i lyf in lykyng lede.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou beo kuynde in vch a cas,</L>
<L>&THORN;onk &thorn;i god, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wel spede,</L>
<L N="64">Wi&thorn; &thorn;is word, Deo Gracias.
<PB REF="00000674.tif" N="666"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if god ha&thorn; &yogh;iue &thorn;e vertues mo</L>
<L>&THORN;en he ha&thorn; o&thorn;ure two or &thorn;re,</L>
<L>&THORN;enne I rede &thorn;ou rule &thorn;e so</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;at men may speke worschupe bi &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Be fert of pruide, &amp; bost &thorn;ou fle,</L>
<L>&THORN;i vertues let no ful&thorn;e de-faas,</L>
<L>But kep &thorn;e clene, corteis &amp; fre,</L>
<L N="72">And &thorn;enk on Deo Gracias.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou beo mad an Offycer,</L>
<L>And art a Mon of muche miht,</L>
<L>What cause &thorn;ou demest, loke hit be cler,</L>
<L N="76">And reue no mon from him his riht,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou beo strong and fers to fiht.</L>
<L>ffor envye neuer mon &thorn;ou chas,</L>
<L>But drede &thorn;i god bo&thorn;e dai &amp; ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="80">And &thorn;enk on deo gracias.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if we &thorn;is word in herte wol haue,</L>
<L>And ay in loue and leute leende,</L>
<L>Of crist bi couenaunt we mow craue</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at Ioye &thorn;at schal neuer haue ende,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world whon we schul wende,</L>
<L>In-to his paleys for to paas,</L>
<L>And sitte a-mong his seintes hende,</L>
<L N="88">And &thorn;er synge Deo Gracias.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>3. Against my Will, I take my Leave.</HEAD>
<P>(8 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Nou Bernes, Buirdus bolde and bly&thorn;e,</L>
<L>To blessen ow her nou am .I. bounde;</L>
<L>.I. &thorn;onke &yogh;ou alle a &thorn;ousend si&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="4">And prei god saue &yogh;ou hol and sounde;</L>
<L>Wher-euer &yogh;e go, on gras or grounde,</L>
<L>He ow gouerne with-outen greue</L>
<L>ffor frendschipe &thorn;at .I. here haue founde;</L>
<L N="8">A-&yogh;eyn mi wille .I. take mi leue.
<PB REF="00000675.tif" N="667"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffor frendschipe &amp; for &yogh;iftes goode,</L>
<L>ffor Mete &amp; Drinke so gret plente</L>
<L>&THORN;at lord &thorn;at rau&yogh;t was on &thorn;e Roode,</L>
<L N="12">He kepe &thorn;i comeli cumpayne;</L>
<L>On see or lond, wher &thorn;at &yogh;e be,</L>
<L>He gouerne ow wi&thorn;-outen greue;</L>
<L>So good dispest &yogh;e han mad me,</L>
<L N="16">A&yogh;ein my wille .I. take my leue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A&yogh;ein mi wille al-&thorn;ou&yogh; .I. wende,</L>
<L>.I. may not al-wey dwellen here,</L>
<L>ffor eueri &thorn;ing schal haue an ende,</L>
<L N="20">And frendes are not ay .I.-fere;</L>
<L>Be we neuer so lef and dere,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world al schul we meue;</L>
<L>And whon we buske vn-to vr bere,</L>
<L N="24">A&yogh;eyn vr wille we take vr leue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And wende we schulle, .I. wot neuer whenne,</L>
<L>Ne whoderward &thorn;at we schul fare;</L>
<L>But endeles blisse, or ay to brenne,</L>
<L N="28">To eueri mon is &yogh;arked &yogh;are.</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i .I. rede vch mon be ware,</L>
<L>And lete vr werk vr wordes preue,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at no sunne vr soule forfare</L>
<L N="32">Whon &thorn;at vr lyf ha&thorn; taken his leue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whon &thorn;at vr lyf his leue ha&thorn; lauht,</L>
<L>Vr bodi lith bounden bi &thorn;e wowe,</L>
<L>Vr richesses alle from vs ben raft,</L>
<L N="36">In clottes colde vr cors is &thorn;rowe.</L>
<L>Wher are &thorn;i frendes ho wol &thorn;e knowe?</L>
<L>Let seo ho wol &thorn;i soule releue?</L>
<L>.I. rede &thorn;e, mon, ar &thorn;ou ly lowe,</L>
<L N="40">Beo redi ay to take &thorn;i leue.
<PB REF="00000676.tif" N="668"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Be redi ay, what euer bi-falle,<MILESTONE N="407b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al sodeynli lest &thorn;ou be kiht;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wost neuer whonne &thorn;i lord wol calle,</L>
<L N="44">Loke &thorn;at &thorn;i laumpe beo brennynge briht;</L>
<L>ffor leue me wel, but &thorn;ou haue liht,</L>
<L>Riht foule &thorn;i lord wol &thorn;e repreue,</L>
<L>And fleme &thorn;e fer out of his siht,</L>
<L N="48">ffor al to late &thorn;ou toke &thorn;i leue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Nou god, &thorn;at was in Bethleem bore,</L>
<L>He &yogh;iue vs grace to serue him so</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mai come his face to-fore,</L>
<L N="52">Out of &thorn;is world whon we schul go;</L>
<L>And for to a-mende &thorn;at we mis-do,</L>
<L>In Clei or &thorn;at we clynge and cleue,</L>
<L>And mak vs euene wi&thorn; frend and fo,</L>
<L N="56">And in good tyme to take vr leve.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Nou haue&thorn; good dai, gode men alle,</L>
<L>Haue&thorn; good dai, &yogh;onge and olde,</L>
<L>Haue&thorn; good day, bo&thorn;e grete and smalle,</L>
<L N="60">And graunt-Merci a &thorn;ousend folde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if euere .I. mi&yogh;te, ful fayn .I. wolde</L>
<L>Don ou&yogh;t &thorn;at weore vn-to &yogh;ow leue.</L>
<L>Crist kepe ow out of cares colde,</L>
<L N="64">ffor nou is tyme to take my leue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>4. God is Love.</HEAD>
<P>(7 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab abab.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Deus caritas est:</L>
<L>A, deore god, omnipotent,</L>
<L>Lord &thorn;ou madest bo&thorn;e foul &amp; best,</L>
<L N="4">On eor&thorn;e to mon &thorn;ou here hit sent.</L>
<L>.I. warne &yogh;ow alle, bo&thorn;e more &amp; lest,</L>
<L>Charite .I. rede &thorn;at &yogh;e hent;</L>
<L>ffor hit is cristes hest,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at schal come to &thorn;e Iugement.
<PB REF="00000677.tif" N="669"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffor whon he come&thorn; a domes-day</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;is world hit schal wel se,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wikked he bidde&thorn; to gon heor way,</L>
<L N="12">In bitter penaunce for euere to be;</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e goode wol &thorn;at lord say:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e schul alle wende wi&thorn; me</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e blisse for euere and ay;</L>
<L N="16">Et qui manet in caritate."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God &thorn;at made bo&thorn;e heuene &amp; helle,</L>
<L>Vre swete lord of Na&yogh;are&thorn;:</L>
<L>Adam &thorn;at was so feir of felle</L>
<L N="20">ffor his folyes he suffred de&thorn;.</L>
<L>In God forso&thorn;e he schal dwelle,</L>
<L>In charite ho so ge&thorn;,</L>
<L>Hit is so&thorn; &thorn;at I ou telle,</L>
<L N="24">Bi-hold and seo:&mdash;In deo manet.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Crist was toren vch a lim,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e Roode he was .I.-do.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend &thorn;at was so derk and dym,</L>
<L N="28">To &thorn;e crois he com &thorn;o,&mdash;</L>
<L>Crist, al charite is in him&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere he ouer-com vs to.</L>
<L>Charite .I. rede &thorn;at &thorn;ou nym,</L>
<L N="32">And &thorn;enne Deus est in eo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Let Charite nou awake,</L>
<L>And do hit &thorn;er neod is;</L>
<L>Heuene forso&thorn;e &thorn;en mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou take</L>
<L N="36">And come to &thorn;at riche blis:</L>
<L>Nou crist, for his Moder sake,</L>
<L>Let vs neuere &thorn;is place mis,</L>
<L>And schild vs from &thorn;e fendes blake,</L>
<L N="40">And Sit deus in nobis.
<PB REF="00000678.tif" N="670"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And charite .I. rede &thorn;at we be-ginne</L>
<L>As bi-fore alle o&thorn;er games,</L>
<L>And schriue vs clene of vre synne,</L>
<L N="44">ffor so dude Peter, Ion and Iames,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore god hem dwelled wi&thorn;-Inne,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei weoren alle wi&thorn;-outen o&thorn;er blames.</L>
<L>Crist, let vs heuene wynne,</L>
<L N="48">E(t) nos ipso maneamus.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God &thorn;at dwelle&thorn; in gret solas</L>
<L>In heuene, &thorn;at riche regnyng,</L>
<L>And for vs &thorn;olede gret trespas</L>
<L N="52">Wonder muche at vre muntyng,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e Roode don he was,</L>
<L>In gret dispyt .I.-cleped a kyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;enke&thorn; nou&thorn;e On Deus caritas,</L>
<L N="56">And bring vs alle to good endyng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>5. Deo Gracias II.</HEAD>
<P>(6 <I>stanzas of</I> 8; <I>one abab baba; five abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L><B>M</B> .I. word is Deo gracias,</L>
<L>In world wher me be wel or wo;</L>
<L>Hou scholde I lau&yogh;whe or sigge Allas<MILESTONE N="407b:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4">ffor, leeue me wel, hit [ne] laste&thorn; o,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh; hit greue, hit wol ouer go,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou&yogh;t chaunge&thorn;, for such is graas.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, wher me beo wel or wo,</L>
<L N="8">I sey not But deo gracias.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou&yogh; I beo riche of gold so red,</L>
<L>And liht to renne as is a Ro,</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;ur is boun to begge his bred</L>
<L N="12">Wi&thorn; brestes blak and bleynes blo.</L>
<L>Whon .I. seo good de-parted so:</L>
<L>To sum Mon God sent gret solas,</L>
<L>And sum Mon ay to liuen in wo,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;en sei .I. Deo Gracias.
<PB REF="00000679.tif" N="671"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou he beo pore and lyue in peyn,</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er mon proude&thorn; as do&thorn; a poo,</L>
<L>Whon mur&thorn;e is his &amp; Mourning myn,</L>
<L N="20">As may be-falle to me and mo,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if fortune wolde be so my fo</L>
<L>ffrom me to turne hir freoly faas;</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e god may sende bo&thorn;e weole &amp; wo,</L>
<L N="24">I sei not but Deo Gracias.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A lord of worschup &yogh;if .I. ware,</L>
<L>And weore falle doun in a wro,</L>
<L>Siknesse sitte&thorn; me so sare,</L>
<L N="28">And serwe wol nei&yogh; myn herte slo,</L>
<L>&THORN;us am I bounde from top til to,</L>
<L>And I turmente so for my trespas:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if God may loose me of &thorn;at wo,</L>
<L N="32">And &thorn;enne I sey Deo Gracias.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whon I hedde spendyng her-be-forn,</L>
<L>&THORN;er wolde no felauschip fonde me fro,</L>
<L>But herkne &amp; hi&yogh;e to myn horn,</L>
<L N="36">ffor in myn hond &thorn;er stod non ho.</L>
<L>Nou a-peere&thorn; non of &thorn;o;</L>
<L>So pouert a-peired ha&thorn; my plas.</L>
<L>Ho may haue wele wi&thorn;-oute wo?</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;erfore I sey Deo gracias.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Almihti, corteis, Crouned kyng,</L>
<L>God, graunt vs grace to rule vs so</L>
<L>&THORN;at we may come to &thorn;i wonyng,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;er is wele wi&thorn;-outen wo.</L>
<L>Milde Mayde, prey &thorn;i sone also,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he for-&yogh;iue vs vre trespas,</L>
<L>And afterward in-to heuene go,</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;er to synge Deo gracias. Amen.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="6" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000680.tif" N="672">
<HEAD>6. Each Man ought himself to know.</HEAD>
<P>(9 <I>stanzas of</I> 12, <I>abab abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>IN a Pistel &thorn;at poul wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>.I. fond hit writen, &amp; seide riht &thorn;is:</L>
<L>Vche cristne creature knowen himself ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="4">His oune vessel. and so&thorn; hit is.</L>
<L>Nere help of him &thorn;at vs deore bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>We weoren bore to luytel blis;</L>
<L>Whon al &thorn;i gode dedes be&thorn; &thorn;orw-sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="8">Seche, and &thorn;ou schalt fynden A-mis.</L>
<L>Eueri mon scholde .I.-knowen his,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is luitel, as .I. trowe;</L>
<L>To teche vs self, crist vs wis;</L>
<L N="12">flor vche mon ou&yogh;te him-self to knowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Knowe &thorn;i-self what &thorn;ou ware,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou were of &thorn;i moder born,</L>
<L>Ho was &thorn;i moder &thorn;at &thorn;e bare,</L>
<L N="16">And ho was &thorn;i fader &thorn;er-bi-foren;</L>
<L>Knowe hou &thorn;ei be&thorn; for&thorn; fare;</L>
<L>So schaltou &thorn;ei&yogh; &thorn;ou hed sworen.</L>
<L>Knowe &thorn;ou come hider wi&thorn; care;</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;ou nost neuer &yogh;if &thorn;ou byde til morn;</L>
<L>Hou lihtly &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t be forlorn,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou &thorn;i sinne schriue &amp; schowe;</L>
<L>ffor lond or ki&thorn;, Catel or corn,</L>
<L N="24">Vche mon oute him-self to knowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Knowe &thorn;i lyf; hit may not last,</L>
<L>But as a blast blouh out &thorn;i breth;</L>
<L>Tote, and bi a no&thorn;er mon tast;</L>
<L N="28">Riht as a glentand glem hit geth.</L>
<L>What is al &thorn;at for&thorn; is past?</L>
<L>hit fare&thorn; as a fuir of heth.</L>
<L>&THORN;is worldes good awey wol wast,</L>
<L N="32">ffor synnes seeknesse &thorn;i soule sle&thorn;.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is a ful delful de&thorn;,<MILESTONE N="408" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To saue &thorn;i soule and &thorn;ou be slowe,
<PB REF="00000681.tif" N="673"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;i Maystrie medel &thorn;i me&thorn;,</L>
<L N="36">ffor vche mon ou&yogh;te him-self to knowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou &thorn;i-self knowe con,</L>
<L>&para; Sit doun, and tac Countures rounde,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e furst &thorn;ou monnes wit bi-gon</L>
<L N="40">Hou ofte sunne &thorn;e ha&thorn; .I.-bounde.</L>
<L>And for vch a synne lei &thorn;ou doun on,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ou &thorn;i synnes haue .I.-sou&yogh;t vp sounde;</L>
<L>Counte &thorn;i goode dedes euerichon,</L>
<L N="44">Abyd &thorn;er a while and stunte a stounde;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou fele &thorn;e siker and sounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;onk &thorn;ou &thorn;i god, as &thorn;ou wel owe;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou art In sunne .I.-bounde</L>
<L N="48">Amende &thorn;e, and &thorn;i-self knowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Knowe what god ha&thorn; for &thorn;e do:</L>
<L>Made &thorn;e after his oune liknes;</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e, he com from heuene also,</L>
<L N="52">And di&yogh;ede for &thorn;e wi&thorn; gret distres.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e he soffrede bo&thorn;e pyne and wo;</L>
<L>Knowe &thorn;ou him and alle his:</L>
<L>Who-so greue&thorn; him Is wor&thorn;i to go</L>
<L N="56">To helle-fuir, but he hit red[r]es,</L>
<L>And he be demed bi rihtfulnes;</L>
<L>But his grace is so wyde .I.-sowe,</L>
<L>ffrom his wra&thorn;&thorn;e .I. rede vs bles,</L>
<L N="60">ffor vche mon ou&yogh;te him-self to knowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Knowe &thorn;i-self &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt dye,</L>
<L>But what tyme, &thorn;ou nost neuer whenne;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a twynklyng of an ei&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="64">Eueri day &thorn;ou hi&yogh;est &thorn;e henne;</L>
<L>&THORN;i fleschly foode &thorn;e wermes wol fye:</L>
<L>Vche cristen mon ou&yogh;te &thorn;is to kenne.</L>
<L>Loke aboute and wel a-spye,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;is world do&thorn; bote bi-traye menne;</L>
<L>And beo war of &thorn;e fuir &thorn;at euer schal brenne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enk &thorn;ou regnest her but a &thorn;rowe;
<PB REF="00000682.tif" N="674"></L>
<L>Heuene-blisse &thorn;ou schal haue &thorn;enne,</L>
<L N="72">ffor vche mon ou&yogh;te him self to knowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Knowe &thorn;i flesch, &thorn;at wol rote;</L>
<L>ffor certes, &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t not longe endure;</L>
<L>And nedes dye, hennes &thorn;ou mote,</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;ei &thorn;ou haue kyngdam<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. kyngdan</NOTE> and Empyre.</L>
<L>And sone &thorn;ou schalt beo forgote;</L>
<L>So schal souereyn, so schal syre.</L>
<L>Hose leeue&thorn; not &thorn;is, I. trouwe he dote,</L>
<L N="80">ffor eueri mok most in-to myre.</L>
<L>Preye we to god vr soules enspire,</L>
<L>Or we ben logged in er&thorn;e lowe,</L>
<L>Heuene to haue to vr huire;</L>
<L N="84">ffor vche mon ou&yogh;te him-self to knowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Knowe &thorn;i kuynde Creatoure,</L>
<L>Knowe what he for &thorn;e dide;</L>
<L>Knowe &thorn;is worldly honoure,</L>
<L N="88">Hou sone &thorn;at hit is for&thorn; .I.-slyde.</L>
<L>Ende of Ioye Is her doloure;</L>
<L>Streng&thorn;e stont vs in no stide,</L>
<L>But longyng &amp; beoing in laboure;</L>
<L N="92">Vr Bost, vr Brag is sone ouerbide.</L>
<L>Arthur and Ector &thorn;at we dredde,</L>
<L>Deth ha&thorn; leid hem wonderly lowe.</L>
<L>Amende &thorn;e, Mon, euene for&thorn; mide,</L>
<L N="96">ffor vche mon ou&yogh;te him-self to knowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;i Concience schal &thorn;e saue and deme</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;at &thorn;ou beo ille or good;</L>
<L>Grope aboute, and tak good &yogh;eme,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;er mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou wite, but &thorn;ou beo wood,</L>
<L>&THORN;er schalt &thorn;ou &thorn;e same seone.</L>
<L>Aske Merci wi&thorn; Mylde mood,</L>
<L>AMende &thorn;e, &thorn;ou wot what .I. mene.</L>
<L N="104">Vche creatur &thorn;at beres bon and blood,</L>
<L>Preye we to god &thorn;at dyed on Rode,</L>
<L>Ar vre bre&thorn; beo out .I.-blowe,
<PB REF="00000683.tif" N="675"></L>
<L>&THORN;at cristes face mai ben vr foode,</L>
<L N="108">ffor vche mon ou&yogh;te him self to knowe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="7" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>7. Think on Yesterday.</HEAD>
<P>(15 <I>stanzas of</I> 12, <I>abab abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Whon Men beo&thorn; muriest at heor Mele,</L>
<L>i&thorn; mete &amp; drink to maken hem glade,</L>
<L>[i&thorn;] worschip &amp; wi&thorn; worldlich wele</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;ei ben so set, &thorn;ey conne not sade;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei haue no deynte for to dele<MILESTONE N="408:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben deuoutli made,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei weene heor honour &amp; heore hele</L>
<L N="8">Schal euer laste &amp; neuer diffade.</L>
<L>But in heor hertes .I. wolde &thorn;ei hade,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei gon ricchest men on array,</L>
<L>Hou sone &thorn;at god hem may de-grade,</L>
<L N="12">And sum tyme &thorn;enk on &yogh;usterday.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;is day, as leef we may be liht</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al &thorn;e mur&thorn;es &thorn;at men may vise,</L>
<L>To Reuele wi&thorn; &thorn;is buirdes briht,</L>
<L N="16">Vche mon gayest on his gyse;</L>
<L>At &thorn;e last, hit drawe&thorn; to niht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at slep most make his Maystrise.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at he ha&thorn; .I.-kud his miht,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;e morwe he boske&thorn; vp to rise,</L>
<L>&THORN;en al drawe&thorn; hem to fantasy[s]e;</L>
<L>Wher he is bi-comen, con no mon say,&mdash;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if heo wuste &thorn;ei weore ful wise,&mdash;</L>
<L N="24">ffor al is tornd to &yogh;esterday.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whose wolde &thorn;enke vppon &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Mihte fynde a good enchesun whi</L>
<L>To preue &thorn;is world al-wei .I.-wis</L>
<L N="28">Hit nis but fantum and feiri,</L>
<L>&THORN;is er&thorn;ly Ioye, &thorn;is worldly blis</L>
<L>Is but a fikel fantasy;
<PB REF="00000684.tif" N="676"></L>
<L>ffor nou hit is, and nou hit nis,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;er may no mon &thorn;er-inne affy.</L>
<L>Hit chaunge&thorn; so ofte &amp; so sodeynly,</L>
<L>To-day is her, to-morwe a-way.</L>
<L>A siker ground ho wol him gy,</L>
<L N="36">I rede he &thorn;enke on &yogh;uster-day.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffor &thorn;er nis non so strong in stour,</L>
<L>ffro tyme &thorn;at he ful waxen be,</L>
<L>ffrom &thorn;at day for&thorn;, euer-vch an hour,</L>
<L N="40">Of his streng&thorn;e he leost a quantite;</L>
<L>Ne no buryde so briht in bour,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ritti wynter, .I. enseure &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo ne schal fade as a flour,</L>
<L N="44">Luite and luite leosen hire beute.</L>
<L>&THORN;e so&thorn;e &yogh;e may &yogh;or-self I-se,</L>
<L>Beo &yogh;or eldres in good fay;</L>
<L>Whon &yogh;e ben grettest in &yogh;our degre,</L>
<L N="48">I rede &yogh;e &thorn;enke on &yogh;esterday.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Nis non so fresch on fote to fare,</L>
<L>Ne non so fayr on fold to fynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei ne schul a bere be brou&yogh;t ful bare:</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;is wrecched world nis but a wynde;</L>
<L>Ne non so stif to stunte ne stare,</L>
<L>Ne non so bold, Beores to bynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he na&thorn; warmynges to beo ware,</L>
<L N="56">ffor god is so cortys and so kynde.</L>
<L>Bi-hold &thorn;e lame, &thorn;e bedrede, &thorn;e blynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bit &yogh;ou be war whil &thorn;at &yogh;e may;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei make a Mirour to &yogh;or mynde,</L>
<L N="60">To us &thorn;e schap of &yogh;esterday.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;e lyf &thorn;at ony mon schal lede,</L>
<L>Be&thorn; certeyn dayes atte last,</L>
<L>&THORN;en moste vr terme schorte nede;</L>
<L N="64">Be o day comen, ano&thorn;er is past.</L>
<L>Herof and we wolde take good hede</L>
<L>And in vr hertes a-countes cast,
<PB REF="00000685.tif" N="677"></L>
<L>Day bi day, wi&thorn;outen drede,</L>
<L N="68">Toward vr ende we drawe&thorn; ful fast.</L>
<L>&THORN;en schal vr bodies in er&thorn;e be &thorn;rast,</L>
<L>Vr Careyns chouched vnder clay;</L>
<L>Her-of we ou&yogh;te beo sore agast,</L>
<L N="72">And we wolde &thorn;enke on &yogh;esterday.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Salamon seide in his poysi,</L>
<L>He holde&thorn; wel betere wi&thorn; an hounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at is lykyng and Ioly,</L>
<L N="76">And of seknesse hol and sounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;en be a Leon, &thorn;ou&yogh; he ly</L>
<L>Cold and ded vppon &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L>Wherof serue&thorn; his victori,</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at was so stif in vche a stounde?</L>
<L>&THORN;e moste fool, I herde respounde,</L>
<L>Is wysore whil he lyue may,</L>
<L>&THORN;en he &thorn;at hedde a &thorn;ousend pounde</L>
<L N="84">And was buried &yogh;uster-day.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Socrates sei&thorn; a word ful wys:<MILESTONE N="408:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hit were wel betere for to se</L>
<L>A Mon &thorn;at nou parte&thorn; and dys,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;en a feste of Realte;</L>
<L>&THORN;e feste wol make his flesch to ris,</L>
<L>And drawe his herte to vanite;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Bodi &thorn;at on &thorn;e Bere lys,</L>
<L N="92">Schewe&thorn; &thorn;e same &thorn;at we schal be.</L>
<L>&THORN;at ferful fit may no mon fle,</L>
<L>Ne wi&thorn; no wiles win hit a-way;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore a-mong al Iolyte,</L>
<L N="96">Sum tyme &thorn;enk on &yogh;usterday.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; But &yogh;it me merueyles ouer al</L>
<L>&THORN;at god let mony mon croke and elde,</L>
<L>Whon miht &amp; streng&thorn;e is from hem fal,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;at &thorn;ei may not hem-self a-welde;</L>
<L>And now &thorn;is beggers most principal,</L>
<L>&THORN;at good ne profyt may non &yogh;elde.
<PB REF="00000686.tif" N="678"></L>
<L>To &thorn;is purpos onswere .I. schal,</L>
<L N="104">Whi god sent such men boote &amp; belde;</L>
<L>Crist, &thorn;at Made bo&thorn;e flour &amp; felde,</L>
<L>Let suche men lyue, forso&thorn;e to say,</L>
<L>Whon a &yogh;ong mon on hem bi-helde,</L>
<L N="108">Scholde seo &thorn;e schap of &yogh;esterday.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A no&thorn;ur skile &thorn;er is, for whi</L>
<L>&THORN;at God let such men liue so longe:</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei be&thorn; treacle and remedi</L>
<L N="112">ffor synful men &thorn;at han do wronge.</L>
<L>In hem &thorn;e seuen dedes of Merci</L>
<L>A Mon may fulfille a-monge;</L>
<L>And also &thorn;is proude men may &thorn;er-bi</L>
<L N="116">A feir Mirour vnderfonge.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er nis non so stif ne stronge,</L>
<L>Ne no ladi [so] stout ne gay,</L>
<L>Bi-hold what ouer hor hed con honge,</L>
<L N="120">And sum tyme &thorn;enk on &yogh;usterday.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I. haue wist, sin I. cu&thorn;e meen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at children ha&thorn; bi candel liht</L>
<L>Heor schadewe on &thorn;e wal i-sen,</L>
<L N="124">And Ronne &thorn;er-after al &thorn;e niht;</L>
<L>Bisy a-boute &thorn;ei han ben</L>
<L>To cacchen hit wi&thorn; al heore miht,</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;ei cacchen hit, best wolde wene,</L>
<L N="128">Sannest hit schet out of heor siht;</L>
<L>&THORN;e schadewe cacchen &thorn;ei ne miht,</L>
<L>ffor no lynes &thorn;at &thorn;ei cou&thorn;e lay.</L>
<L>&THORN;is schadewe .I. may likne a-riht</L>
<L N="132">To &thorn;is world and &yogh;usterday.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In-to &thorn;is world whon we be&thorn; brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>We schul be tempt to couetyse,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;i wit schal be &thorn;orw-sou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="136">To more good &thorn;en &thorn;ou may suffyse.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou &thorn;enkest best in &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>On Richesse, fo[r]te regne and ryse,
<PB REF="00000687.tif" N="679"></L>
<L>Al &thorn;i trauayle turne&thorn; to nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="140">ffor sodeynly on de&thorn; &thorn;ou dyese;</L>
<L>&THORN;i lyf &thorn;ou hast .I.-lad wi&thorn; ly&yogh;es,</L>
<L>So &thorn;is world gon &thorn;e be-tray.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore .I. rede &thorn;ou &thorn;is dispys,</L>
<L N="144">And sum tyme &thorn;enk on &yogh;uster-day.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Mon, &yogh;if &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebor &thorn;e Manas</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur to culle or to bete,</L>
<L>.I. knowe me siker in &thorn;e cas</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;at &thorn;ou wolt drede &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebores &thorn;rete,</L>
<L>And neuer a day &thorn;i dore to pas</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-oute siker defense and grete,</L>
<L>And ben purueyed in vche a plas</L>
<L N="152">Of sekernes and help to gete;</L>
<L>&THORN;in enymy woltou not for-&yogh;ete,</L>
<L>But ay beo afert of his affray:</L>
<L>Ensaumple herof .I. wol &yogh;ou trete,</L>
<L N="156">To make &yogh;ou &thorn;enke of &yogh;uster-day.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Wel &thorn;ou wost wi&thorn;-outen fayle</L>
<L>&THORN;at de&thorn; ha&thorn; manast &thorn;e to dye;</L>
<L>But whon &thorn;at he wol &thorn;e a-sayle,</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at wost &thorn;ou not, ne neuer may spye.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt don be my counsayle,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; siker defence beo ay redye!</L>
<L>ffor siker defence in &thorn;is batayle,</L>
<L N="164">Is clene lyf, parfyt and trye.</L>
<L>Put &thorn;i trust in godes Mercye,<MILESTONE N="408b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hit is &thorn;e beste at al assay,</L>
<L>And euer among &thorn;ou &thorn;e en-nuye</L>
<L N="168">In-to &thorn;is world and &yogh;uster-day.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Sum men sei&thorn; &thorn;at de&thorn; is a &thorn;ef,</L>
<L>And al vnwarned wol on him stele;</L>
<L>And .I. sey nay, and make a pref,</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;at de&thorn; is studefast, trewe and lele,</L>
<L>And warne&thorn; vche mon of his greef,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wol o day wi&thorn; him dele:
<PB REF="00000688.tif" N="680"></L>
<L>&THORN;e lyf &thorn;at is to ow so leof,</L>
<L N="176">He wol &yogh;ou reue, and eke or hele;</L>
<L>&THORN;is poyntes may no mon him repele.</L>
<L>He come&thorn; so baldely to pyke his pray,</L>
<L>Whon men beo&thorn; muryest at heor Mele:</L>
<L N="180">I rede &yogh;e &thorn;enke on &yogh;usterday.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="8" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>8. Keep well Christ's Commandments.</HEAD>
<P>(13 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L><B>I</B> warne vche leod &thorn;at liue&thorn; in londe,</L>
<L>And do hem dredles out of were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei most studie and vnderstonde,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e lawe of crist to loue and lere.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis no mon fer ne nere</L>
<L>&THORN;at may him-seluen saue vn-schent,</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at caste&thorn; wi&thorn; concience clere</L>
<L N="8">To kepe wel Cristes Comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ow most haue o God, and no mo,</L>
<L>And serue him bo&thorn;e with mayn and miht;</L>
<L>And ouer alle &thorn;inges loue him also,</L>
<L N="12">ffor he ha&thorn; lant &thorn;e lyf and liht.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou beo nuy&yogh;ed day or niht</L>
<L>In peyne be meke and pacient,</L>
<L>And rule &thorn;e ay be reson riht,</L>
<L N="16">And kep wel Cristes Comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And let &thorn;i nei&yogh;hebor, frend and fo,</L>
<L>Riht frely of &thorn;i frendschupe fele,</L>
<L>In herte &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilne hem so</L>
<L N="20">Riht as &thorn;ou woldest &thorn;i-self weore wele;</L>
<L>And help to sauen hem from vncele,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heore soules beo not schent,</L>
<L>And also heore care &thorn;ou helpe to kele,</L>
<L N="24">And kepe wel Cristes comaundement.
<PB REF="00000689.tif" N="681"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In Idel, Godes nome tak &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>But cese, and saue &thorn;e from &thorn;at synne;</L>
<L>Swere bi no &thorn;ing &thorn;at God ha&thorn; wrouht;</L>
<L N="28">Be war his wra&thorn;&thorn;e, lest &thorn;ou hit wynne;</L>
<L>But bisy &thorn;e her bale to blynne</L>
<L>&THORN;at blaberyng are wi&thorn; o&thorn;es blent,</L>
<L>Vncou&thorn;e &amp; knowen &amp; of &thorn;i kynne,</L>
<L N="32">And kep wel cristes comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In clannes and in cristes werk</L>
<L>Haue mynde to holden &thorn;in haly day,</L>
<L>And drauh &thorn;e &thorn;enne from dedes derk,</L>
<L N="36">Wi&thorn; al &thorn;i meyne, Mon and may;</L>
<L>And men vnsau&yogh;te, loke &thorn;ou assay</L>
<L>To sau&yogh;ten hem &thorn;enne at on assent,</L>
<L>And pore and seke &thorn;ou plese &amp; pay,</L>
<L N="40">And kepe wel cristes Comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;i ffader, &thorn;i Moder, &thorn;ou worschupe bo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt boteles bale escheuwe;</L>
<L>With counseil cumforte him, with mete &amp; clo&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="44">As &thorn;ou sest hem neode&thorn; newe;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ei talke of tales vntrewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou torn hem out of &thorn;at entent,</L>
<L>And cristes lawe help &thorn;at &thorn;ei knewe,</L>
<L N="48">And kep wel cristes Comaundement!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Sle no mon wi&thorn; wikked wille,</L>
<L>Be war, and vengeaunce tak &thorn;ou non;</L>
<L>In word ne dede, loude ne stille,</L>
<L N="52">Bakbyte &thorn;ou no mon, blod ny bon,</L>
<L>But ay let gabbynges glyde and gon</L>
<L>A-wey wher &thorn;ei wol glace or glent,</L>
<L>And help &thorn;at alle men ben at on,</L>
<L N="56">And kep wel cristes comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Stele &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebors &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;ur with stillnes ne wi&thorn; strif,
<PB REF="00000690.tif" N="682"></L>
<L>Nor with no-maner wrong getyng,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;i self, &thorn;i seruaunt, child ne wyf;</L>
<L>To sulle &amp; buye &yogh;if &thorn;ou be ryf,</L>
<L>Wayte al-way &thorn;at wrong be went;</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou wolt lyue &thorn;e lastyng lyf,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;ou kepe wel cristes comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffals witnesse loke &thorn;ow non bere,<MILESTONE N="408b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow wolt in blisse a-byde,</L>
<L>&THORN;i nei&yogh;ebore wityngly to dere,</L>
<L N="68">Ne no mon nou&thorn;er in no syde;</L>
<L>But loke &thorn;at no mon be anuy&yogh;ed,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou may him from harmes hent,</L>
<L>And help &thorn;at falshede beo distruiet,</L>
<L N="72">And kep wel cristes comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Sunge &thorn;ou not in lecherie;</L>
<L>Such lust vn-leueful, let hit pas;</L>
<L>Consente &thorn;ou not to such folye,</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at founden is so foul trespas,</L>
<L>And loke &thorn;at nou&thorn;er more ne las</L>
<L>&THORN;i lykyng on &thorn;at lust be lent,</L>
<L>Leste &thorn;ou synge &thorn;is songe 'allas,</L>
<L N="80">ffor brekyng of cristes comaundement.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;i nei&yogh;hebors wyf coueyte &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Vnleuefully a&yogh;eynes &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hire to sunge in word ne &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="84">And from &thorn;at deede euer &thorn;ou &thorn;e drawe,</L>
<L>And neuer sey to hire no sawe</L>
<L>To make hire to synne assent,</L>
<L>Ne plese hire not with no mis-plawe,</L>
<L N="88">But kep wel cristes comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;i nei&yogh;hebors hous, wenche ne knaue,</L>
<L>Vnskilfully coueyte &thorn;ou nouht,</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;it his good with wrong to haue;</L>
<L N="92">ffor hit lest &thorn;ou to bale be brouht.</L>
<L>ffor whon &thorn;e so&thorn;e schal vp be souht,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou in-to &thorn;is sunnes assent,
<PB REF="00000691.tif" N="683"></L>
<L>fful bitterly hit mot be bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="96">ffor brekyng of cristes Comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Vche mon &thorn;at wol &thorn;is lessun lere</L>
<L>And loue&thorn; a laweful lyf to lede,</L>
<L>He may not misse on none manere</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;e mer&thorn;e of heuene to his mede;</L>
<L>ffor crist him here wol helpe &amp; hede,</L>
<L>And he&thorn;ene in-to heuene hent.</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i .I. preye &thorn;at crist vs spede</L>
<L N="104">Kuyndely to kepe his comaundement.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="9" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>9. Who says the Sooth, he shall be shent.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See the after poem, "But thou say sooth, thou shalt be shent," no. 29, p. 740.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>(8 <I>stanzas of</I> 12, <I>abab abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;E Mon &thorn;at luste to liuen in ese</L>
<L>Or eny worschupe her to ateyne,</L>
<L>His purpos I counte not wor&thorn; a pese,</L>
<L N="4">Witterli, but he ordeyne</L>
<L>&THORN;is wikkid world hou he schal plese</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al his pouwer and his peyne;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he schal kepe him from disese,</L>
<L N="8">He mot lerne to flatere and feyne;</L>
<L>Herte &amp; mou&thorn; loke &thorn;ei ben tweyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei mowe not ben of on assent;</L>
<L>And &yogh;it his tonge he mot restreyne,</L>
<L N="12">ffor hos sei&thorn; &thorn;e so&thorn;e, he schal be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;us is &thorn;e so&thorn;e .I.-kept in close,</L>
<L>And vche mon make&thorn; touh and queynte</L>
<L>To leue &thorn;e tixt and take &thorn;e glose;</L>
<L N="16">Eueri word &thorn;ei coloure and peynte.</L>
<L>Summe &thorn;er aren &thorn;at wolden suppose</L>
<L>ffor no tresour forte ben teynte:</L>
<L>Let a mon haue not to lose,</L>
<L N="20">He schal fynde frenschipe feynte.
<PB REF="00000692.tif" N="684"></L>
<L>Summe &thorn;at semen an Innocent,</L>
<L>Wonder trewe in heore entent,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei beo&thorn; agast of eueri pleynt,</L>
<L N="24">ffor hos sei&thorn; &thorn;e so&thorn;e, he schal be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;e wikked wone we may warie,</L>
<L>&THORN;at eueri man &thorn;us Inward bledes.</L>
<L>Let a lord haue his Corlarie,</L>
<L N="28">he schal wel knowe of al his dedes;</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; he be next his sacratarie,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; flaterynge his lord he fedes,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; sum speche he most him tarie,</L>
<L N="32">And &thorn;us wi&thorn; lesynges him he ledes;</L>
<L>To gabben his lord most him nedes,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; sum blaundise make him blent:</L>
<L>To leosen his offys euere he dredes,</L>
<L N="36">ffor &yogh;if he &thorn;e so&thorn;e sei&thorn;, he schal be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And al is wrong; &thorn;at dar .I. preue;</L>
<L>ffor let a mon be sore .I.-wounde,</L>
<L>Hou schulde a leche &thorn;is mon releeue,</L>
<L N="40">But &yogh;if he mi&yogh;te ronsake &thorn;e wounde?</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;au&yogh; hit smerte &amp; sumdel greue,<MILESTONE N="408b:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;it most he suffre a luitel stounde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he kneuh of his mischeue,</L>
<L N="44">Wi&thorn; salues he mi&yogh;te make him sounde.</L>
<L>Were grace at large, &thorn;at lippe i-bounde,</L>
<L>Hap and hele mihte we hent;</L>
<L>Lac of leche wol vs confounde,</L>
<L N="48">ffor hos sei&thorn; &thorn;e so&thorn;e, he schal be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffor let a frere in Godes seruise</L>
<L>&THORN;e pereles to &thorn;e peple preche,</L>
<L>Of vre misdede &amp; vre quyntise,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;e trewe tixt to telle and teche;</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; he beo riht witti and wyse,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it luytel &thorn;onk he schal him reche,</L>
<L>And summe &thorn;er ben &thorn;at wol him spise,</L>
<L N="56">And ble&thorn;ely wayte him wi&thorn; sum wreche.
<PB REF="00000693.tif" N="685"></L>
<L>&THORN;is pore prechour &thorn;ei wolen apeche</L>
<L>At counseyl and at parliment;</L>
<L>But &yogh;if he kepe him out of heore cleche,</L>
<L N="60">ffor his so&thorn; sawe he schal be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at god was boren,</L>
<L>&THORN;is world was neuer so vntrewe;</L>
<L>Men recchen neuer to ben for-sworen,</L>
<L N="64">To reuen &thorn;at is hem ful duwe;</L>
<L>&THORN;e peynted word &thorn;at fel bi-foren,</L>
<L>Be-hynde, hit is ano&thorn;er hewe.</L>
<L>Whon Gabriel schal blowe his horn,</L>
<L N="68">His feble fables schul hym rewe:</L>
<L>&THORN;e tonges &thorn;at such bargeyn gon brewe,</L>
<L>Hit weore non harm &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei were brent.</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;is gyle is founde vp of newe,</L>
<L N="72">ffor hos sei&thorn; so&thorn;, he schal be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Si&thorn;en &thorn;e so&thorn;e dar no mon say,</L>
<L>ffor drede to gete him a fo,</L>
<L>Best .I. holde hit, in good fay,</L>
<L N="76">Let o day come, ano&thorn;er go</L>
<L>And mak as murie as we may,</L>
<L>Til eueri frend parte o&thorn;ur fro.</L>
<L>.I. drede hit drawe&thorn; to domes-day,</L>
<L N="80">Such saumples we han, &amp; o&thorn;er two:</L>
<L>Now knowes a child bo&thorn;e weole &amp; wo</L>
<L>&THORN;at scholde ben an Innocent,</L>
<L>Whil hit is &yogh;ong, is norissched so;</L>
<L N="84">But hos sei&thorn; so&thorn;, he schal be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;is world wol han his wikked wone,</L>
<L>ffor so&thorn;e, hit wol non o&thorn;er be;</L>
<L>His cursede cours &thorn;at is bi-gonne,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;er may no mon from hit fle</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; longe a-mong vs ronne,</L>
<L>His oune defaute mai he not se.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fader trust not to &thorn;e sone,</L>
<L N="92">Ne non to o&thorn;er in no degre;
<PB REF="00000694.tif" N="686"></L>
<L>ffalshede is called a sotilte</L>
<L>And such a nome hit ha&thorn; hent.</L>
<L>&THORN;is lesson lerne&thorn; alle at me:</L>
<L N="96">Ho sei&thorn; &thorn;e so&thorn;e, he schal be schent.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="10" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>10. Fy on a faint Friend!</HEAD>
<P>(9 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Frenschipe faile&thorn; &amp; fullich fade&thorn;;</L>
<L>ffei&thorn;ful frendes fewe we fynde,</L>
<L>But glosers &thorn;at vche mon glade&thorn;</L>
<L N="4">Wi&thorn; feire bi-heste&thorn; and wordes as wylde.</L>
<L>But let a mon ones be cast be-hynde,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;is world turmented &amp; tenet,</L>
<L>He schal ful sone ben out of mynde.</L>
<L N="8">And &thorn;ere, fy on a feynt frend!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;e while &thorn;at &thorn;ou ledest &thorn;i lyf in ese</L>
<L>And goodlich gouernest &thorn;yn astate,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyndest Inouwe &thorn;at wol &thorn;e plese</L>
<L N="12">And folwe &thorn;i wil bo&thorn;e erliche &amp; late.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;i los bi-gynne to abate,</L>
<L>And &thorn;y good from &thorn;e gon wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei schul be &thorn;e furste &thorn;at &thorn;e wol hate:</L>
<L N="16">And &thorn;er, fy on a feynt frende!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;us &thorn;ou schalt, ar &thorn;ou haue nede,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;i frendes folly I-knowen</L>
<L>And seyen heo dor not helpen &thorn;e</L>
<L N="20">ffor drede, for fere &thorn;ei lost her owen.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &thorn;at sum tyme wente ful lowe,</L>
<L>hem luste no lengore wi&thorn; &thorn;e to lende,</L>
<L>Beo-hynde &thorn;i bak heo make&thorn; a Mouwe.</L>
<L N="24">And &thorn;er, fy on a feynt frende!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To &thorn;i-self trust al-wei best,<MILESTONE N="409" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor as &thorn;ou dost, so schaltou haue.</L>
<L>Brek &thorn;e leste bou&yogh; of &thorn;i nest,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;e fyndest .I.-nouwe wol hit &thorn;e bi-raue,
<PB REF="00000695.tif" N="687"></L>
<L>And wole dispise &thorn;e and repraue,</L>
<L>And sakeles wayte &thorn;e schame and schende:</L>
<L>In such a cas, so god me saue,</L>
<L N="32">And euere, fy on a feynt frende!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt not ben frendles,</L>
<L>Lern to kepe &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast;</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou be not penyles,</L>
<L N="36">Ne spend &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t &thorn;i good in wast.</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ou haue nede, &thorn;i frendes<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. frendest</NOTE> a-tast,</L>
<L>W&yogh;uche be stif &amp; w&yogh;uche wol bende;</L>
<L>And &thorn;er &thorn;ou fynde bouwynde or bast,</L>
<L N="40">And euer, fy on a feynt frende!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In fei&thorn;, &thorn;at ffrendschip hold .I. nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>To profer &thorn;e, whon &thorn;ou hast no nede;</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;ou weore in daunger brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="44">Hose helpe&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;enne is wor&thorn;i meede.</L>
<L>Hose wolde &thorn;e nou&thorn;er profre ne beode,</L>
<L>He serue&thorn; &thorn;onk wi&thorn;-outen ende;</L>
<L>Such frendes are fewe I-laft in leode.</L>
<L N="48">And &thorn;erfore, fy on a feynt frende!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Ho scholde eny frendschupe ben .I.-founde?</L>
<L>Good fei&thorn; is flemed out of &thorn;is londe;</L>
<L>&THORN;er is more treu&thorn;e in an hounde</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;en in sum mon, .I. vnderstonde.</L>
<L>Knackes &amp; mowes &thorn;ei han In honde</L>
<L>Witterli to plese &thorn;e fende.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at furst &thorn;at frendschip fonde,</L>
<L N="56">Euer fy on him, for a feynt frende!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Eueri mon .I. counseile</L>
<L>To gouerne him in such a wyse,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if hit so beo &thorn;at frendschup fayle,</L>
<L N="60">His owne deden wol maken him ryse;</L>
<L>Hold him In a mene asyse</L>
<L>Euer to beo corteys and hende;
<PB REF="00000696.tif" N="688"></L>
<L>&THORN;en baldely may he dispise,</L>
<L N="64">Euere fy on a feynt frende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;i[s] lessun loke &thorn;at &yogh;e leore,</L>
<L>Whon &yogh;e ha&thorn;e so&thorn;e sou&yogh;t and seid;</L>
<L>Trust on non such frendschup here;</L>
<L N="68">Ho sannest do, is tytes bi-trayed.</L>
<L>Loke al &yogh;or loue on him beo leyd,</L>
<L>ffor vs on Rode was prikket &amp; prenet;</L>
<L>Do we so &thorn;at crist beo payet</L>
<L N="72">And &thorn;enne we hauen a syker frend.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="11" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>11. Thank God of all.</HEAD>
<P>(17 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>BI a wey wandryng as .I. went</L>
<L>Sore .I. syked for serwyng sad;</L>
<L>ffor harde happes &thorn;at .I. haue hent,</L>
<L N="4">Mournyng mad me al-most mad.</L>
<L>Vn-til a lettre al-one me lad</L>
<L>&THORN;at wel was writen on a wal;</L>
<L>A blisful word &thorn;er .I. rad</L>
<L N="8">Euere to &thorn;onke god of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;au&yogh; &thorn;ou waxe blynd or lome,</L>
<L>Or eny seknesse on &thorn;e be set,</L>
<L>&THORN;enk riht wel hit is no schome,</L>
<L N="12">Wi&thorn; such grace god ha&thorn; &thorn;e gret.</L>
<L>In serwe &amp; tene &thorn;ou art .I.-knit,</L>
<L>And &thorn;i catel bi-ginne&thorn; to fal;</L>
<L>.I. not neuere hou &thorn;ou myst do bot,</L>
<L N="16">But euere to &thorn;onke god of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou welde worldes goode,</L>
<L>Ryally rayed in &thorn;i rest,</L>
<L>ffeir of face, freoly of foode,</L>
<L N="20">Nis non &thorn;e lyk, bi Est ne West,
<PB REF="00000697.tif" N="689"></L>
<L>&YOGH;it god may senden as him lust,</L>
<L>Riches to torne as a Bal.</L>
<L>In vche a maner .I. holde hit best,</L>
<L N="24">Euere to &thorn;onke god of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;i catel be-ginne to pase,</L>
<L>And after waxest a pore mon,</L>
<L>Tak good cumfort &amp; bere good face,</L>
<L N="28">And trust on hym &thorn;at al good won.</L>
<L>In God furst al goodnes bi-gon;</L>
<L>He may vs reue bo&thorn;e bour and hal.</L>
<L>Better cumfort .I. non con,</L>
<L N="32">But euer to &thorn;onke god of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;enk on Iob &thorn;at was so riche,<MILESTONE N="409:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hou he wox pore from day to day;</L>
<L>His beestes doun dy&yogh;eden in eueri diche</L>
<L N="36">His catel vanischt al a-way;</L>
<L>.I.-put he was in pore array</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;er in purpul ne in pal,</L>
<L>But in symple wede, as clerkes say,</L>
<L N="40">And euer he &thorn;onked god of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffor faute of Catel, Iobpus floures</L>
<L>ffaded and fel clene him fro;</L>
<L>In seknesse he soffred scharpe schoures</L>
<L N="44">Wi&thorn; honger, chele, repreof &amp; wo.</L>
<L>God sende him hele and catel bo,</L>
<L>Toun and tour, and steede in stal,</L>
<L>ffor he neuer grucched in wele ne wo,</L>
<L N="48">But euer &thorn;onked God of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Hose serue&thorn; crist wi&thorn; trewe entent,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffend &thorn;erto wol han Envye,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw mis-beeleeue to make him schent,</L>
<L N="52">And he him cacche in his baylye.</L>
<L>&THORN;auh he &thorn;in hele and catel struye,</L>
<L>Let studefast herte stonde in stal,
<PB REF="00000698.tif" N="690"></L>
<L>And trustne to God &thorn;at sit so hei&yogh;e</L>
<L N="56">And euer to &thorn;onken him of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Ac mony mon come&thorn; vp of nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And gete&thorn; godes gret plente;</L>
<L>&THORN;orw pruide &amp; bost he make&thorn; tou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="60">And clene for-&yogh;it his pouerte.</L>
<L>&THORN;en grete wronges worche&thorn; he</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at he may ouer cal,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at &thorn;ei mowe no for&thorn;er fle,</L>
<L N="64">But euer to &thorn;onke god of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Me prike&thorn; &thorn;e Oxe in &thorn;e plouh,</L>
<L>Whon he is &yogh;ong, vntoun and wylde,</L>
<L>He wol Rore and make hit touh,</L>
<L N="68">And of his drau&yogh;t ben vn-bylde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e more he torne&thorn; out of his tylde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e driuere wole him boxe and Bral:</L>
<L>So god wol &thorn;e, but &thorn;ou be mylde,</L>
<L N="72">And euere to &thorn;onken him of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; A&yogh;eyn God to grucche is gret trespas,</L>
<L>&THORN;at such sondes may sende bi est &amp; west;</L>
<L>&THORN;i worldlich wo may turne to solas</L>
<L N="76">Whon &thorn;ou lyst clongen &amp; closed in chest,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou schalt wenden to trauayl or rest,</L>
<L>&THORN;i worldlich weole hit is but smal.</L>
<L>In vche a maner, hit is &thorn;e best,</L>
<L N="80">Euer to &thorn;onke God of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffor goddes loue, so do we,</L>
<L>ffor he may bo&thorn;e &yogh;iue and take;</L>
<L>In what meschef &thorn;at euer we be,</L>
<L N="84">he is mihti I-nou&yogh; vr serwe to slake.</L>
<L>Good amendes he wol vs make,</L>
<L>And we to him wol crie &amp; cal,</L>
<L>What weole or wo &thorn;at we in wake,</L>
<L N="88">And euer to &thorn;onken god of al.
<PB REF="00000699.tif" N="691"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ei&yogh; &thorn;ou be in prisun cast</L>
<L>Or eny distresse men do&thorn; &thorn;e beode,</L>
<L>ffor godes loue &thorn;ou beo studefast</L>
<L N="92">And haue good mynde vppon &thorn;i crede.</L>
<L>&THORN;enk God feyle&thorn; &thorn;e neuer at neode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at derwor&thorn;e duyk vs deme schal.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou art wo, &thorn;erto tak hede,</L>
<L N="96">And euer to &thorn;onken him of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &thorn;ei &thorn;i frendes from &thorn;e fayle</L>
<L>And de&thorn; ha raft hem of heore lyue,</L>
<L>Wharto schuldestou wepe or waile?</L>
<L N="100">Hit is no boote wi&thorn; god to striue.</L>
<L>God maade bo&thorn;e Mon and wyue;</L>
<L>hit is skil he tak vs; we ben his &thorn;ral.</L>
<L>What-so &thorn;ou &thorn;ole or elles to &thorn;ryue,</L>
<L N="104">Euer to &thorn;onke god of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Diuerse sondes crist ha&thorn; .I.-sent</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e here and eke in o&thorn;er place:</L>
<L>Tac we hit wi&thorn; trewe entent,</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;e sannore he wole sende vs grace.</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; &thorn;at vr bodies ben brou&yogh;t in bace,</L>
<L>Let not &yogh;or hertes ben vn-tal,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enk &thorn;at god is &thorn;er he was,</L>
<L N="112">And euer to &thorn;onken him of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffor Godes loue be not to wylde,<MILESTONE N="409:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Reule &yogh;ow in Reson alle to Route,</L>
<L>And tak wi&thorn; trewe tent &amp; mylde,</L>
<L N="116">Diuerse sondes crist sent a-boute:</L>
<L>&THORN;en dar .I. seyen wi&thorn;-outen doute,</L>
<L>In heuene-blisse is maad vr stal,</L>
<L>To Riche &amp; pore &thorn;at lowe wol loute,</L>
<L N="120">Euer to &thorn;onke God of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;is world is good &amp; nou&yogh;t in gesse</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at wolen kuynde be,
<PB REF="00000700.tif" N="692"></L>
<L>And parte aboute of heore richesse</L>
<L N="124">To hem &thorn;at ben In pouerte.</L>
<L>A wonder &thorn;ing hit is to se</L>
<L>&THORN;at kuynde loue adoun schal fal.</L>
<L>Better cumfort non con .I. me,</L>
<L N="128">But euer to &thorn;onke god of al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;it .I. radde for&thorn;er-more&mdash;</L>
<L>Trewe entent I tok &thorn;ertil,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at crist may riht wel vr stat restore,</L>
<L N="132">Hit nis nou&yogh;t to striuen a&yogh;eines his wil.</L>
<L>He may vs saue, he may vs spil;</L>
<L>&THORN;enk riht wel we ben his &thorn;ral.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; we haue not al vr wil,</L>
<L N="136">Euermore &thorn;onke we god of al.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="12" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>12. This World fares as a Fantasy.</HEAD>
<P>(11 <I>stanzas of</I> 12, <I>abab abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L><B>I</B> wolde witen of sum wys wiht</L>
<L>Witterly what &thorn;is world were.</L>
<L>Hit fare&thorn; as a foules fliht,</L>
<L N="4">Now is hit henne, now is hit here;</L>
<L>Ne be we neuer so muche of miht,</L>
<L>Now be we on benche, nou be we on bere,</L>
<L>And be we neuer so war and wiht,</L>
<L N="8">Now be we sek, now beo we fere;</L>
<L>Now is on proud wi&thorn;-outen peere,</L>
<L>Now is &thorn;e selue .I.-set not by;</L>
<L>And whos wol alle &thorn;ing her[t]ly here,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;is world fare&thorn; as a ffantasy.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;e sonnes cours we may wel kenne,</L>
<L>Aryse&thorn; Est and ge&thorn; doun West.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ryuers in-to &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute; &thorn;ei renne,</L>
<L N="16">And hit is neuer &thorn;e more al-mest.</L>
<L>Wyndes Rossche&thorn; her and henne,</L>
<L>In snou&yogh; and reyn is non arest.
<PB REF="00000701.tif" N="693"></L>
<L>&para; Whon &thorn;is wol stunte, ho wot, or whenne,</L>
<L N="20">But only god on grounde grest?</L>
<L>&THORN;e eor&thorn;e in on is euer prest,</L>
<L>Now bi-dropped, now al druy&yogh;e.</L>
<L>But vche gome glit for&thorn; as a gest;</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;is world fare&thorn; as a ffantasye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Kunredes come, &amp; kunredes gon,</L>
<L>As Ioyne&thorn; generacions;</L>
<L>But alle heo passe&thorn;, euerichon,</L>
<L N="28">ffor al heor preparacions,</L>
<L>Sum are for-&yogh;ete clene as bon</L>
<L>A-mong alle-maner nacions.</L>
<L>So schul men &thorn;enken vs no-&thorn;ing on,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at nou han &thorn;e ocupacions,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;eos disputacions</L>
<L>Idelyche all vs ocupye,</L>
<L>ffor crist make&thorn; &thorn;e creacions,</L>
<L N="36">And &thorn;is world fare&thorn; as a fantasye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whuch is Mon, ho wot, and what,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;at he be ou&yogh;t or nouht?</L>
<L>Of Er&thorn;e &amp; Eyr growe&thorn; vp a gnat,</L>
<L N="40">And so do&thorn; Mon whon al his souht.</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; mon be waxen gret and fat,</L>
<L>Mon melte&thorn; a-wey so de&thorn; a mouht;</L>
<L>Monnes miht nis wor&thorn; a Mat,</L>
<L N="44">But nuy&yogh;e&thorn; him-self and turne&thorn; to nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Ho wot, saue he &thorn;at al ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Wher mon bi-come&thorn; whon he schal dye?</L>
<L>Ho knowe&thorn; bi dede, ou&yogh;t bote bi &thorn;ou&yogh;t?</L>
<L N="48">ffor &thorn;is world fare&thorn; as a fantasye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Dye&thorn; mon, and beestes dye,</L>
<L>And al is on Ocasion:</L>
<L>And alle o de&thorn;, hos bo&thorn;e drye,</L>
<L N="52">And han on Incarnacion;</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;at men beo&thorn; more sley&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Al is o comparison.
<PB REF="00000702.tif" N="694"></L>
<L>ho wot &yogh;if monnes soule sty&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="56">And bestes soules synke&thorn; doun?</L>
<L>Who knowe&thorn; Beestes entencioun,<MILESTONE N="409b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>On heor creatour how &thorn;ei crie,</L>
<L>Saue only god &thorn;at knowe&thorn; heore soun?</L>
<L N="60">ffor &thorn;is world fare&thorn; as a fantasye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Vche secte hope&thorn; to be saue,</L>
<L>Baldely bi heore bi-leeue,</L>
<L>&para; And vchon vppon God heo craue:</L>
<L N="64">Whi schulde God wi&thorn; hem him greue?</L>
<L>Vchon trouwe&thorn; &thorn;at o&thorn;ur Raue,</L>
<L>But alle heo cheose&thorn; God for cheue,</L>
<L>And hope in God vchone &thorn;ei haue,</L>
<L N="68">And bi heore wit heore worching preue.</L>
<L>&THORN;us mony maters men dou meue,</L>
<L>Sechen heor wittes hou and why,</L>
<L>But Godes Merci vs alle bi-heue,</L>
<L N="72">ffor &thorn;is world fare&thorn; as a fantasy.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffor &thorn;us men stumble &amp; sere heore wittes,</L>
<L>And meue&thorn; maters mony and fele;</L>
<L>Summe leeue&thorn; on him, sum leue&thorn; on hit,</L>
<L N="76">As children leorne&thorn; for to spele.</L>
<L>But non seo&thorn; non &thorn;at a-bit,</L>
<L>Whon stilly de&thorn; wol on hym stele.</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;at hext in heuene sit,</L>
<L N="80">He is &thorn;e help and hope of hele;</L>
<L>ffor wo is ende of worldes wele:</L>
<L>Vche lyf loke wher &thorn;at .I. lye.</L>
<L>&THORN;is world is fals, fikel and frele,</L>
<L N="84">And fare&thorn; but as a fantasye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Wharto wilne we forte knowe</L>
<L>&THORN;e poyntes of Godes priuete?</L>
<L>More &thorn;en him lustnes forte schowe,</L>
<L N="88">We schulde not knowe in no degre,</L>
<L>And Idel bost is forte blowe</L>
<L>A Mayster of diuinite;
<PB REF="00000703.tif" N="695"></L>
<L>&THORN;enk we lyue in eor&thorn;e her lowe,</L>
<L N="92">And God an hei&yogh; in Mageste.</L>
<L>Of Material Mortualite</L>
<L>Medle we &amp; of no more Maistrie.</L>
<L>&THORN;e more we trace &thorn;e Trinite,</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;e more we falle in fantasye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; But leue we vre disputisoun,</L>
<L>And leeue on him &thorn;at al ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>We mowe no[t] preue bi no resoun</L>
<L N="100">Hou he was born &thorn;at al vs bou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>But hol in vre entencioun</L>
<L>Worschipe we him in herte &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>ffor he may turne kuyndes vpsedoun</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;at alle kuyndes made of nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Whon al vr bokes ben for&thorn; brouht,</L>
<L>And al vr craft of clergye,</L>
<L>And al vr wittes ben &thorn;orw-out sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="108">&YOGH;it we fare&thorn; as a fantasye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Of fantasye is al vr fare,</L>
<L>Olde &amp; &yogh;onge and alle I-fere.</L>
<L>But make we murie &amp; sle care</L>
<L N="112">And worschipe we god, whil we ben here,</L>
<L>Spende vr good and luytel spare;</L>
<L>And vche mon cheries o&thorn;eres cheere,</L>
<L>&THORN;enk hou we comen hider al bare,</L>
<L N="116">Vr wey wendyng is in a were.</L>
<L>Prey we &thorn;e prince &thorn;at ha&thorn; no pere,</L>
<L>Tac vs hol to his Merci</L>
<L>And kepe vr Concience clere,</L>
<L N="120">ffor &thorn;is world is but fantasy.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Bi ensaumple men may se:</L>
<L>A gret treo growe&thorn; out of &thorn;e grounde;</L>
<L>No &thorn;ing a-bated &thorn;e eor&thorn;e wol be</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;au&yogh; hit be huge, gret and rounde.</L>
<L>Riht &thorn;er wol Rooten &thorn;e selue tre,</L>
<L>Whon elde ha&thorn; maad his kuynde aswounde;
<PB REF="00000704.tif" N="696"></L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; &thorn;er weore rote suche &thorn;re,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;e eor&thorn;e wol not encrece a pounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;us waxe&thorn; &amp; wante&thorn; Mon, hors &amp; hounde;</L>
<L>ffrom nou&yogh;t to nou&yogh;t &thorn;us henne we hi&yogh;e</L>
<L>And her we stunte&thorn; but a stounde,</L>
<L N="132">ffor &thorn;is world is but fantasye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="13" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>13. Ay, Mercy, God!</HEAD>
<P>(12 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>As I wandrede her bi weste</L>
<L>ffaste vnder a forest syde,</L>
<L>I sei&yogh; a wiht went him to reste,</L>
<L N="4">Vnder a bou&yogh;h he gon a-byde;</L>
<L>&THORN;us to crist ful &yogh;eor[n]e he cri&yogh;ede,</L>
<L>And bo&thorn;e his hondes he held on hei&yogh;:</L>
<L>"Of pouert, plesaunce &amp; eke of pruide.</L>
<L N="8">Ay, Merci, God, And graunt-Merci.<NOTE PLACE="foot">I take <I>Merci</I> to be used in this poem in the twofold sense of Mercy and Thanks.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; God, &thorn;at I haue I-greuet &thorn;e</L>
<L>In wille &amp; werk, in word and dede,</L>
<L>Almihti lord, haue Merci of me</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at for my sunnes &thorn;i blod gon schede!</L>
<L>Of wit &amp; worschupe, weole &amp; wede</L>
<L>I &thorn;onke &thorn;e, lord, ful Inwardly;</L>
<L>Al in &thorn;is world, hou euere I spede,</L>
<L N="16">Ay Merci, god, And graunt Merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Graunt Merci, god, of al &thorn;i &yogh;ifte,</L>
<L>Of wit &amp; worschupe, weole &amp; wo;</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e, lord, myn herte I lifte,</L>
<L N="20">Let neuer my dedes twynne. vs a-two.</L>
<L>Merci &thorn;at I haue mis do,</L>
<L>And sle me nou&yogh;t sodeynly!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; ffortune wolde be frend or fo,</L>
<L N="24">Ay Merci, God, And graunt Merci.
<PB REF="00000705.tif" N="697"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I am vnkuynde, and &thorn;at I knowe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou hast kud me gret kuyndenes;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore wi&thorn; humbel herte and lowe,</L>
<L N="28">Merci and for-&yogh;iuenes</L>
<L>Of Pruyde and of vnboxumnes!</L>
<L>What eueri sonde be, &thorn;us sey I,</L>
<L>In hap and hele, and in seknes,</L>
<L N="32">Ay Merci, god, And graunt Merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Graunt Merci, God, of al &thorn;i grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fourmed me wi&thorn; wittes fyue,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ffeet and hond, &amp; eke of face</L>
<L N="36">And lyflode, whil I am alyue.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en &thorn;ou hast &yogh;iue me grace to &thorn;ryue,</L>
<L>And I haue Ruled me Rechelesly,</L>
<L>I weore to blame, and I wolde striue,</L>
<L N="40">But Merci, God, And Graunt Merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Merci &thorn;at I haue mis-spent</L>
<L>Mi wittes fyue! &thorn;erfore I wepe;</L>
<L>To dedly synnes ofte haue I asent,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;i Comaundemens cou&thorn;e I neuer kepe;</L>
<L>To sle my soule In sunne I slepe,</L>
<L>And lede my lyf in Lecheri,</L>
<L>ffrom Couetyse cou&thorn;e I neuere crepe;</L>
<L N="48">Ay Merci, God, And Graunt Merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Of o&thorn;es grete and Gloteny,</L>
<L>Of wanhope and of wikked wille:</L>
<L>Bacbyte my nei&yogh;hebors for enuy,</L>
<L N="52">And for his good I wolde him culle;</L>
<L>Trewe men to Robbe and spille,</L>
<L>Of Symony and with surquidri;</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;at euere I haue don ille,</L>
<L N="56">Ay Merci, God, And graunt Merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Bi lawe I scholde no lengor liue</L>
<L>&THORN;en I hedde don a dedly synne;
<PB REF="00000706.tif" N="698"></L>
<L>Graunt Merci &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde forgiue,</L>
<L N="60">And &yogh;eue me space to mende me Inne!</L>
<L>ffrom wikked dedes &amp; I wolde twynne,</L>
<L>To Receyue me &yogh;e beo redi</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;i blisse &thorn;at neuer schal blynne.</L>
<L N="64">Nou Merci, God, And graunt Merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Graunt Merci, for &thorn;ou madest me,</L>
<L>Merci, for I haue don a-Mis;</L>
<L>Min hope, Min help is hol in &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="68">And &thorn;ou hast &yogh;ore bi-heiht me &thorn;is:</L>
<L>Whos euere is Bapti&yogh;ed schal haue Blis,</L>
<L>And he Rule him Rihtwysli.</L>
<L>To worche &thorn;i wille, lord, &thorn;ou me wis!</L>
<L N="72">Nou Merci, God, And graunt Merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; So&thorn;fast god, what schal I say,</L>
<L>how schulde I amendes make,</L>
<L>&THORN;at plesed &thorn;e neuere in-to &thorn;is day</L>
<L N="76">Ne schop me nou&yogh;t mi sunnes forsake?</L>
<L>But schrift of mou&thorn;e mi sunnus schal slake,</L>
<L>And I schal sece and beo sori,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;i Merci I me take.</L>
<L N="80">Nou Merci, God, [And] Graunt Merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffader &amp; sone and holigost,</L>
<L>Graunt Merci, God, wi&thorn; herte liht,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou woldest not &thorn;at I weore lost.</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;e ffader ha&thorn; &yogh;iuen me a miht,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sone a science and a siht</L>
<L>And wit to welde me worschupely,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Holigost vr grace ha&thorn; diht.</L>
<L N="88">Nou Merci, God, And graunt Merci.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;is is &thorn;e Trone &thorn;at twynned neuere,</L>
<L>And preued is persones &thorn;re,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is and was and schal ben euere,</L>
<L N="92">Only God in Trinite;
<PB REF="00000707.tif" N="699"></L>
<L>help vs, Prince of alle pite,</L>
<L>Atte day &thorn;at we schal dy,</L>
<L>&THORN;i swete face &thorn;at we may se.</L>
<L N="96">Nou Merci, God, And Graunt Merci.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="14" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>14. Truth ever is best.</HEAD>
<P>(9 <I>stanxas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>HOse wolde him wei a-vyse</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is wrecched world, I weene,</L>
<L>I hope ful wel he schulde dispise</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e foule falshede &thorn;at &thorn;er-in bene.</L>
<L>Certes, sum day schal be sene,</L>
<L>Much eor&thorn;ly labour schal be lest;</L>
<L>Whon good and vuel vr dedes schal deme,</L>
<L N="8">We schal wel fynde &thorn;at treu&thorn;e is best.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>Treu&thorn;e is best for kyng and kniht,</L>
<L>Certes, hose ri&yogh;t wol rede;</L>
<L>Among &thorn;is ladyes feir and briht</L>
<L N="12">Hit schulde be loued in vch a leode;</L>
<L>&THORN;is Marchauns wor&thorn;li vnder wede,</L>
<L>To buy&yogh;e &amp; selle &thorn;ei ben ful prest,</L>
<L>Among hem alle schuld no falshede,</L>
<L N="16">But vsen trou&thorn;e, &thorn;at euere i[s] best.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Sikerli, I dar wel say,</L>
<L>In al &thorn;is world nis heo ne he,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei wolde fayn, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ei may,</L>
<L N="20">Leden heore lyf in prosperite,</L>
<L>And als swi&thorn;e as &thorn;ei schulde dy&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Til heuene &thorn;at &thorn;ei mote come ful prest.</L>
<L>&THORN;at noble plase &thorn;ei nei&yogh;e ner neih</L>
<L N="24">But &yogh;if &thorn;ei meyntene trou&thorn;e for best.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>Trou&thorn;e schal deme vs alle be-dene,</L>
<L>He wol do trewely and no wrong;
<PB REF="00000708.tif" N="700"></L>
<L>I hope we schal bo&thorn;e seye and sene</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;at we han contraried him al to long.</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore, lordes bo&thorn;e stout and strong</L>
<L>&THORN;at may deeme her riht as &thorn;&eacute; lest,</L>
<L>ffor Godes loue wis &thorn;ou so among,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at trou&thorn;e be meyntened for &thorn;e best.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>And &thorn;erfore haue &thorn;is in &yogh;our muynde,</L>
<L>Hose medle&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e lawe:</L>
<L>Let neuer falshed a&yogh;eynes vnkuynde</L>
<L N="36">ffordon trou&thorn;e ne so&thorn; sawe.</L>
<L>ffor falshed euermore schal stonde awe</L>
<L>On trou&thorn;e &thorn;au&yogh; he be neuer so prest.</L>
<L>ffor godes loue let neuer gold &thorn;e drawe</L>
<L N="40">A&yogh;eynes trou&thorn;e &thorn;at euer is best.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>Wolde we rule us al wi&thorn; trou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And mak him hollych vr gouernour,</L>
<L>We schulde keuere out of synne &amp; slou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="44">And of Chiualrye bere &thorn;e flour:</L>
<L>ffor trou&thorn;e in were may most endour,</L>
<L>And euer is biggest at &thorn;e lest.</L>
<L>ffor godes loue, graunt we him socour,</L>
<L N="48">And mayntene trou&thorn;e &thorn;at euer is best.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>Trou&thorn;e was sum tyme here a lord;</L>
<L>wi&thorn; him alle vertues, as I wene;</L>
<L>&YOGH;it Spayne, Brutayne wol bere record,</L>
<L N="52">And o&thorn;er diuerse londes be-dene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we endouwed hem as &thorn;ei schulde bene,</L>
<L>And made hem lordes to lyue in rest:</L>
<L>&THORN;er dorste no falshede with hem be sene,</L>
<L N="56">So loued &thorn;ei trou&thorn;e, &thorn;at euer is best.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>Wolde we &yogh;it lete trou&thorn;e a&yogh;eyn</L>
<L>Be lord, and bere his heritage,</L>
<L>Al o&thorn;er londes schuld be ful fayn</L>
<L N="60">To don vs feute and homage:
<PB REF="00000709.tif" N="701"></L>
<L>Baldelych &thorn;is dar I wage,</L>
<L>And falshede &amp; his lore weore lest,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei schulde not dure vn-to a page</L>
<L N="64">To werre with trou&thorn;e &thorn;at euer is best.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>ffalshed may wel regne a while</L>
<L>&THORN;orw Meyntenaunce of couetise;</L>
<L>Atte last his grount wol him be-gyle,</L>
<L N="68">A while &thorn;ou&yogh; he be neuer so wyse.</L>
<L>ffalshed ha&thorn; ben most in pris</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e bi North and eke bi West:</L>
<L>We schul him hunte as Cat do&thorn; mys,</L>
<L N="72">Whon trou&thorn;e him cheues &thorn;at euer is best.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="15" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>15. Charity is no longer dear.</HEAD>
<P>(14 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>HOse wolde be-&thorn;enke him weel</L>
<L>Ou &thorn;is world is went, I-wis,</L>
<L>And cou&thorn;e enterly grope &amp; feel</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e foule falshede &thorn;at &thorn;er-in is,</L>
<L>I durste be bold, so haue I blis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mony good mon schuld haue mateere</L>
<L>Te meue &amp; mourne and fare a-Mis,</L>
<L N="8">ffor charite is no lengor cheere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>Mony a Mon, riht as him seeme&thorn;,</L>
<L>A &thorn;ing &thorn;at he neuer kneuh ne wist,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e lordes &amp; Mene Men he deme&thorn;,</L>
<L N="12">And speke&thorn; of hem ri&yogh;t as him list.</L>
<L>Allas! for &yogh;if a mon nou trist</L>
<L>His bro&thorn;er or his cosyn neere,</L>
<L>He schal be deceyued in his fist,</L>
<L N="16">ffor charite is no lengore cheere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at speke&thorn; most, as I leeue,</L>
<L>And demen men so al aboute,
<PB REF="00000710.tif" N="702"></L>
<L>Wher no faute vppon hem cleue,</L>
<L N="20">&YOGH;us, be my trou&thorn;e, hit is no doute,</L>
<L>Such Men may not ben wi&thorn;-oute,</L>
<L>No more &thorn;en hecgh wi&thorn;-outen Brere;</L>
<L>Envye is wi&thorn; hem so stoute,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at charite is no lengore chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>ffor &thorn;reo lettynges &thorn;at &thorn;er bene,</L>
<L>A Mon mai not deeme rihtwislye:</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste lettyng, as I wene,</L>
<L N="28">A &thorn;ing &thorn;at is to fer from ei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Or elles a &thorn;ing may beo to nei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Schal lette his siht, &thorn;au&yogh; hit be clere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde is, &thorn;at he deme&thorn; bi,</L>
<L N="32">Whon charite is no lengore chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;e mai in feelde sum tyme i-se</L>
<L>A bosck &thorn;at stonde&thorn; ful fer &thorn;e fro,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e schal deme hit schal be</L>
<L N="36">Mon or Beest, hors, on of &thorn;o:</L>
<L>And al is wrong to deeme hit so,</L>
<L>Certes, as &yogh;e schal after lere.</L>
<L>So demes a Mon ofte be his ffo,</L>
<L N="40">Whon charite is no lengore chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou hast an huge envy,</L>
<L>And hatest a mon wi&thorn; al &thorn;i miht,</L>
<L>Liue &thorn;at mon neuer so rihtwisly,</L>
<L N="44">&YOGH;it schaltou deme he liue&thorn; not riht;</L>
<L>Envye stoppe&thorn; &thorn;er &thorn;i siht,</L>
<L>And make&thorn; fer, &thorn;at schulde be neere,</L>
<L>And lac of loue lette&thorn; &thorn;i liht,</L>
<L N="48">Whon charite is no lengore chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>Vppon &thorn;in E&yogh;e-lide &thorn;er mai ley</L>
<L>A spot or elles a mote, I-wis,</L>
<L>And for bicause hit is so nei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;ou mai&yogh;t not seo hit, so haue I blis,
<PB REF="00000711.tif" N="703"></L>
<L>To deme treuly what hit is;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;i doom falle&thorn; in a weere.</L>
<L>So deme&thorn; a mon ofte sy&thorn;es a-mis,</L>
<L N="56">Whon &thorn;at his herte is set from cheere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou louest &thorn;i bro&thorn;er so</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i loue passe&thorn; al a-syse,</L>
<L>What &thorn;at euer &thorn;i bro&thorn;er do,</L>
<L N="60">Euel or wrong in eny wyse,</L>
<L>Al is wel to &thorn;in avise,</L>
<L>Bi cause &thorn;ou louest him so entere;</L>
<L>His defaute constou not spise,</L>
<L N="64">ffor &thorn;er &thorn;in herte is set to chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>Let a lechour heere a-spye</L>
<L>A &yogh;ong mon with a wommon rage,</L>
<L>And nou&thorn;er of heom ne &thorn;enke folye,</L>
<L N="68">But wel may falle of o linage,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it wol &thorn;at lechour &thorn;inke outrage,</L>
<L>And deeme &thorn;ei wolde do mis I-fere:</L>
<L>Such deemyng aske&thorn; sliper wage,</L>
<L N="72">ffor charite &thorn;er is no-&thorn;ing cheere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>And ri&yogh;t so fare&thorn; hit, be my trou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a proud Mon &amp; a Couetous,</L>
<L>A wrecche &thorn;at liue&thorn; al in Slou&yogh;&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="76">And eke a mon &thorn;at is vicyous;</L>
<L>He wenes vch mon &thorn;at is vertuous</L>
<L>Vse&thorn; his wyse and his maneere;</L>
<L>So fare&thorn; Men &thorn;at be&thorn; Envyous,</L>
<L N="80">Whon Charite is no lengor chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>Let a trewe mon bi &thorn;e Rood,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is good, honest and sad,</L>
<L>He weene&thorn; &thorn;at vche mon be good,</L>
<L N="84">He nolde not demen a mon weore bad.</L>
<L>But wrecched fooles &thorn;at beo&thorn; mad,</L>
<L>&THORN;at con not wel heore tonge steere,
<PB REF="00000712.tif" N="704"></L>
<L>To deme &thorn;e worste &thorn;ei ben ful glad,</L>
<L N="88">Whon Charite is no lengor cheere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>I leeue &thorn;er beo no mon alyue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he his warison scholde winne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at cou&thorn;e enterliche knowe &amp; skreue</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;e lyf &thorn;at is sum mon wi&thorn;-Inne;</L>
<L>ffor summe &thorn;at seme&thorn; most wi&thorn; synne,</L>
<L>In hap of synne may beo most clere.</L>
<L>Of such demyng I rede &yogh;e blynne,</L>
<L N="96">ffor Charite &thorn;er is no-&thorn;ing chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at leouest is to lak,</L>
<L>And deme&thorn; men so al bideene,</L>
<L>Vn-bynt &thorn;e bur&thorn;en on &yogh;or bak,</L>
<L N="100">And loke furst &thorn;at &yogh;or-self be clene.</L>
<L>Al such demyng, as I wene,</L>
<L>Schulde beo reseruet to godes poueere;</L>
<L>So me &thorn;inke&thorn; hit best to beone,</L>
<L N="104">ffor &thorn;en schal charite ben most cheere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>Certes, and &yogh;e loke ariht,</L>
<L>A good word no more wol weye</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit li&thorn; on &yogh;or tonge as liht,</L>
<L N="108">As &thorn;e worste &thorn;at &yogh;e con seye.</L>
<L>Such Idel wordes, I ou preye,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e louke hem faste in &yogh;oure forcere,</L>
<L>And let concience bere &thorn;e keye;</L>
<L N="112">ffor &thorn;en schal charite be most chere.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="16" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>16. Of Women cometh this Worldes Weal.</HEAD>
<P>(10 <I>stanzas of</I> 12, <I>abab abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>In worschupe of &thorn;at Mayden swete,</L>
<L>Mylde Marie, Moder and May,</L>
<L>Alle gode wimmen wol I grete,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;at god fende hem from vch afray;
<PB REF="00000713.tif" N="705"></L>
<L>With muche menske mote &thorn;ei mete,</L>
<L>And wel wor&thorn;e alle wymmen ay!</L>
<L>Al vr Bale &thorn;ei may beete,</L>
<L N="8">Serteynliche, I dar wel say;</L>
<L>And hose blame&thorn; hem niht or day,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Bale mot heore tonge belle.</L>
<L>I preue hit wel, ho-euer sei&thorn; nay:</L>
<L N="12">Of wimmen come&thorn; &thorn;is worldes welle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>But moni vn-witti wiht is woode,</L>
<L>Vn-wysliche wimmen wol dispyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ben I-boren of wimmen blode:</L>
<L N="16">I-wis, such wihtes ben vn-wyse,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ei defoule heor oune foode.</L>
<L>Such grimly goostes may agryse,</L>
<L>wi&thorn; &thorn;ulke &thorn;at dude god on &thorn;e Rode:</L>
<L N="20">At dredful dom such schal aryse,</L>
<L>Be Iugged wi&thorn; &thorn;e hei&yogh;e Iustise</L>
<L>To folewe &thorn;e false feendes fele,</L>
<L>And rikene wi&thorn; &thorn;e vnrihtwyse,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at of wymmen come&thorn; worldes welle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Sum sei&thorn; wimmen ha&thorn; be-gilt</L>
<L>Adam, Sampson and Salamon,</L>
<L>And sei&thorn; &thorn;at wimmen ha&thorn; I-spilt</L>
<L N="28">Mony a wys wor&thorn;i mon:</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;ei greggen wymmens gilt;</L>
<L>Of Monnes riken &thorn;ei neuer on.</L>
<L>And monnes falshed weore fulfild,</L>
<L N="32">I trowe &thorn;er weore twenti a&yogh;eynes on,</L>
<L>Of Macabeus, Iudas and Ion,</L>
<L>Alisaundre and o&thorn;er feole,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with monnes gult was fordon;</L>
<L N="36">But of wimmen come&thorn; &thorn;is worldes wele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>And Iudas gentil Ihesu solde</L>
<L>&THORN;at saued alle &thorn;at was forlore!</L>
<L>And monnes falsed weore I-tolde,</L>
<L N="40">Men miht rikene moni a score.
<PB REF="00000714.tif" N="706"></L>
<L>Wommon wrou&yogh;te riht as god wolde:</L>
<L>&THORN;at gult made god to ben I-bore:</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore beo &yogh;e neuer so bolde</L>
<L N="44">To blame wymmen neuer-more</L>
<L>ffor nou&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue don bifore,</L>
<L>ffor monnes schome I rede &yogh;e hele!</L>
<L>Wimmen for Men ofte suffre&thorn; sore,</L>
<L N="48">But of wymmen come&thorn; &thorn;is worldes wele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>Wimmen wrou&yogh;te neuer no wrong</L>
<L>But &thorn;orw Monnes entysement.</L>
<L>Men seche&thorn; wimmen so strong,</L>
<L N="52">And sei in Bale &thorn;ei mote be brent,</L>
<L>And ligge aboute hem so long,</L>
<L>To bringen hem til heore a-sent;</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;orw monnes false song,</L>
<L N="56">Ofte wymmen ha&thorn; be schent.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if eny such be in present,</L>
<L>Stille holde him, I rede he stell,</L>
<L>And preise wimmen in good entent,</L>
<L N="60">ffor of wymmen come&thorn; &thorn;is worldes wele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>God worschuped wimmen in his lyue,</L>
<L>And kept hem in his cumpaygnye,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e widewe, wenche and wyue</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at was wi&thorn;-outen vilenye.</L>
<L>Hose luste with wymmen striue,</L>
<L>I rede he drede him for to dye,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;at synne sone him schriue,</L>
<L N="68">And to vr ladi Merci crye;</L>
<L>And in worschip of Marie</L>
<L>Such vn-Redines &thorn;at &yogh;e repele!</L>
<L>Defende&thorn; &yogh;ou alle from such folye,</L>
<L N="72">ffor of wymmen come&thorn; al &thorn;is worldes wele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>I holde &thorn;at Brid muche to blame</L>
<L>&THORN;at defoule&thorn; his oune nest;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wost wel a wommon was &thorn;i dame,</L>
<L N="76">I-Boren and fed of hire Brest.
<PB REF="00000715.tif" N="707"></L>
<L>But moni gabben on heore dame;</L>
<L>To blame wymmen &thorn;ei &thorn;inke hit best.</L>
<L>Stunte&thorn; for &yogh;or owne schame;</L>
<L N="80">Of such resouns I rede &yogh;e rest;</L>
<L>To preyse wymmen &thorn;at &yogh;e be prest!</L>
<L>Wymmen ben hende in hete and chele,</L>
<L>Wimmen glade&thorn; vch a godly gest,</L>
<L N="84">ffor of wymmen come&thorn; &thorn;is worldes wele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>Wymmen wrappen vs in wede</L>
<L>Whon we beo naked boren and bare,</L>
<L>And of hire flesch fostre&thorn; and feede,</L>
<L N="88">And &yogh;arken vs whon we ben &yogh;are.</L>
<L>Whon we ben old, &thorn;ei moste vs hede,</L>
<L>And keuere vs out of mony a care;</L>
<L>Whon we be nasti, nou&yogh;t at neode,</L>
<L N="92">Neore wimmen help, hou schulde we fare?</L>
<L>At dredful dom whon we schal dare</L>
<L>ffor fere of false fendes feole,</L>
<L>Whon vche mon schal his speche spare,</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;en wommon help is al vr weole.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>ffor God and Mon was fer atwinne</L>
<L>Whon he made Monkuynde of S&eacute;&eacute;-flod:</L>
<L>I wolde wite, whon &thorn;at Eue gon spinne,</L>
<L N="100">Bi whom &thorn;at &yogh;oure gentrie stod?</L>
<L>Hou be-come &yogh;e godes kinne,</L>
<L>But barelych &thorn;orw &thorn;e wommones blod?</L>
<L>Allas, hou may men for synne</L>
<L N="104">Speke bi wymmen ou&yogh;t bote good!</L>
<L>Wimmen beo&thorn; so mylde of mood,</L>
<L>Louesum, loueli, lyf and lele.</L>
<L>Witnes on him &thorn;at died on Rood,</L>
<L N="108">Of wymmen come&thorn; &thorn;is worldes wele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>God, &thorn;at made bo&thorn;e Sonne and Mone,</L>
<L>To alle wymmen Socour he sende,</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;e dedes &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue done,</L>
<L N="112">Kepe hem from &thorn;e false fende.
<PB REF="00000716.tif" N="708"></L>
<L>And to Marie I bidde a bone:</L>
<L>Warde wymmen, wher-so-euer &thorn;ei wende,</L>
<L>ffrom synne and serwe schylde hem sone,</L>
<L N="116">Wher in londe &thorn;at euer &thorn;ei lende!</L>
<L>I warne alle &thorn;at be wimmenes frende,</L>
<L>I con not preise hem &thorn;e haluendele,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; I &thorn;us schortliche make an ende:</L>
<L N="120">Of wymmen come&thorn; &thorn;is worldes wele.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="17" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>17. The Praise of Mary, Mother of Christ.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Note the effective repetitions in lines 57 and 101.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>(13 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Off alle floures feirest fall on,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is Marie, Moder fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bar &thorn;e child of flesch and bon,</L>
<L N="4">Ihesu, Godes sone in Maieste.</L>
<L>A loue-likyng is come to me</L>
<L>To serue &thorn;at ladi, qwen of blis,</L>
<L>Ay better and better in my degre,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;e lengor &thorn;at I liue, I-wis.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>So hertly I haue I-set my &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>vppon &thorn;at buyrde of buyrdes best;</L>
<L>ffor al-&thorn;auh I seo hire nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="12">Min herte schal fully wi&thorn; hire be fest.</L>
<L>Ihesu &thorn;at sek milk of hire brest,</L>
<L>To &yogh;ou bo&thorn;e I be-heete:</L>
<L>Mi loue schal holly wi&thorn; &yogh;ou rest,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;au&yogh; I be not wor&thorn;i ne meete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Sertes, swete, on &yogh;ou is al</L>
<L>Min helpyng at myn endyng-day;</L>
<L>&THORN;at I be not &thorn;e fendes &thorn;ral,</L>
<L N="20">Marie, to &yogh;or sone &yogh;e pray.</L>
<L>Hou schal I do, my swete may,</L>
<L>But &yogh;if I loue &yogh;ou souereynly?
<PB REF="00000717.tif" N="709"></L>
<L>Elles miht men boldly bi me say</L>
<L N="24">Daunger mad vnskilfuly.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>Hose be&thorn;enke&thorn; him, I-wis,</L>
<L>Of &yogh;or gret goodnesse and &yogh;or grace,</L>
<L>He scholde neuer wilne to don amis,</L>
<L N="28">Ne luste to loue in o&thorn;er place.</L>
<L>In hope to seo &yogh;or blessed face,</L>
<L>And dwelle wi&thorn; &yogh;ou at myn endynge,</L>
<L>And haue relese of alle trespace,</L>
<L N="32">Ladi, &thorn;au&yogh; I mourne I synge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>Lentun-dayes, &thorn;ei ben longe,</L>
<L>And nou weor good tyme to amende</L>
<L>&THORN;at we be-foren han do wronge;</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;is world nis no&thorn;ing, as I wende.</L>
<L>In sori tyme my lyf Isspend;</L>
<L>&THORN;is world is fals, and &thorn;at I feel;</L>
<L>But Marie Moder me amende,</L>
<L N="40">A-Mis I fare, and no&thorn;ing wel.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>But &thorn;at swete wor&thorn;li wyf,</L>
<L>Hire goodly loue &thorn;at I may gete,</L>
<L>Al my Ioye wol turne to strif,</L>
<L N="44">And I may syke with wonges wete:</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at I &thorn;enke on &thorn;at swete,</L>
<L>Me &thorn;inke&thorn; hit is so good a &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>I sey to eueri mon &thorn;at I meete</L>
<L N="48">"Gode, go wey, and let me nou&yogh;t!"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>Loue me ha&thorn; in Bales brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>ffor on such &thorn;at I suppose,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is so studefast in hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at cou&thorn;e neuere gabbe ne glose.</L>
<L>Hose hire loue&thorn;, he schal not lose,</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;it be-giled heo neuer no wiht.</L>
<L>I likne &thorn;at ladi to &thorn;e Rose:</L>
<L N="56">I-blessed beo &thorn;at buirde briht!
<PB REF="00000718.tif" N="710"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>Me longede neuere so sore, so sore,</L>
<L>To seo my loueli ladi deere.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if heo neore, we neore but lore,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at ladi lofsum most of lere.</L>
<L>And wite hit wel wi&thorn;-outen weere:</L>
<L>Whon I &thorn;enk on hire semblaunt sad,</L>
<L>&THORN;er wol no wys mon blame me here,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;au&yogh; &thorn;at I go murie and glad.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>A louely lyf to loken vp-on,</L>
<L>So is my ladi, &thorn;at Emperys;</L>
<L>Mi lyf I dar leye &thorn;er-vppon,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;at princesse is peerles of prys,</L>
<L>So feir, so clene, so good, so wys,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto trewe as eny steel,</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis no such to my deuys:</L>
<L N="72">Lor God, &thorn;at I loue hire wel!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>To &thorn;is newe &yogh;er, my ladi sweete,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al myn herte in good entent,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fyue Aues I ow grete,</L>
<L N="76">And preye ou take &thorn;is feire present;</L>
<L>And schape so &thorn;at I beo not schent,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en of &yogh;ou Merci gon springe.</L>
<L>ffor al my loue is on &yogh;ou lent,</L>
<L N="80">Sweete, swettest of alle-skunnes &thorn;inge!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;is is &thorn;e remenaunt of my lust,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I not whe&thorn;er my ladi mylde</L>
<L>To my loue haue inly trust,</L>
<L N="84">Bicause Monkuynde is frele and wylde.</L>
<L>But, ladi, for &yogh;oure blisful childe,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en al my loue is leyd on &thorn;e,</L>
<L>In heuene help me a boure to bylde,</L>
<L N="88">Ladi, &yogh;if &thorn;i wille be.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e loue &thorn;at I haue &yogh;eorned &yogh;ore,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng of loue graunt hit me!
<PB REF="00000719.tif" N="711"></L>
<L>In eor&thorn;ly loue is luytel store,</L>
<L N="92">ffor al &thorn;at nis but vanyte.</L>
<L>Wher I schal euer &thorn;at day I-se,</L>
<L>To plese my ladi ones to pay?</L>
<L>Heo is of colour and beute</L>
<L N="96">As fresch as is &thorn;e Rose In May.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>Hose lust not loue, let hym be-leue,</L>
<L>ffor I wol holde &thorn;at I haue hiht;</L>
<L>&THORN;at lust schal no mon from me reue</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;at I nul loue my ladi briht.</L>
<L>Loue, loue, do me riht,</L>
<L>Marie Mooder, Mayden clene,</L>
<L>In heuene of &thorn;e to haue a siht,</L>
<L N="104">Ladi, to &thorn;e my mone I mene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="18" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>18. Maiden Mary and her Fleur de Lys.</HEAD>
<P>(17 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>MArie Mayden, Moder Mylde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at blisful Bern in bosum beere,</L>
<L>Cheef &amp; chast &thorn;ou ches of chylde</L>
<L N="4">Of alle wymmen In world &thorn;at were:</L>
<L>Saue vs sound, and socur vs here,</L>
<L>As princes is preised &amp; proued for prys.</L>
<L>What leode &thorn;is lesson lykes to lere,</L>
<L N="8">Be token hit is &thorn;e fflourdelys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;at freoli flour weore fair to fynde,</L>
<L>what gome wolde go &thorn;er as hit greu&yogh;.</L>
<L>As Maacer herof made in his Mynde;</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;us kenned him Catoun, his craftes he kneu&yogh;,</L>
<L>What segge on soil &thorn;at &thorn;at seed seu&yogh;,</L>
<L>Hit is holy at myn avys;</L>
<L>Aboue &thorn;e Braunches be&thorn; Blosmes neu,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;e lele cheses faire &thorn;e fflourdelys.
<PB REF="00000720.tif" N="712"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ou lele ladi, I likne to &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;e flour, to &thorn;i semeli sone also</L>
<L>&THORN;e blisful Blosme &thorn;at euer mihte be,</L>
<L N="20">Treuly &thorn;at was be-twix &yogh;ou to.</L>
<L>Whon we weore wrapped al in wo</L>
<L>&THORN;orw werkes &thorn;at we had wrou&yogh;t wrongwys,</L>
<L>&THORN;i godnes gert vs grai&thorn;ly go</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;orw vertu of &thorn;i fflourdelys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>fful grei&thorn;li was &thorn;e graunted grace</L>
<L>Whon Gabriel from god &thorn;e gret,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fel to &thorn;i feet bi-fore &thorn;i face,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;e Murieste meetyng &thorn;at euer was met.</L>
<L>So sittyngli hire sawes heo set,</L>
<L>As a wommon bo&thorn;e war and wys:</L>
<L>"To seo &thorn;i seruaunt and &thorn;i soget;"</L>
<L N="32">And &thorn;er bi-gon furst &thorn;i fflourdelys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>In hond &thorn;ou haddest &amp; heold vr hele;</L>
<L>&THORN;orw him &thorn;at hadde hei&yogh; heuene in holde</L>
<L>What Mur&thorn;e was mad no Mou&thorn; mi&yogh;t mele,</L>
<L N="36">Whon &thorn;ou &thorn;at wor&thorn;ly hed wonnen in wolde.</L>
<L>He com to keuere vs of cares colde,</L>
<L>His pepul he put in paradys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at tyde and tyme &thorn;e Angel tolde,</L>
<L N="40">Of &thorn;e schulde springe &thorn;e fflourdelys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;at Blisful Barn of &thorn;e was born</L>
<L>&THORN;at suffred trauayle, bo&thorn;e trey and tene,</L>
<L>Throly &thorn;hrusten, &amp; throng wi&thorn; &thorn;orn,</L>
<L N="44">Of his cunreden vnkuynde and kene,</L>
<L>ffrom top to-torn al bi-deene,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes &thorn;ei Iugged his Iuwys,</L>
<L>And dy&yogh;ed for Adam deedes bi-deene,</L>
<L N="48">And &thorn;enne was sprongen &thorn;e fflourdelys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>A studi steer &thorn;er stod ful steere</L>
<L>ffor steeres-men &thorn;at bi stremes gun stray,
<PB REF="00000721.tif" N="713"></L>
<L>And neore his wor&thorn;ly wille weore,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;ei wolde haue went a wilful way;</L>
<L>No feyntysenes &thorn;ei founden in fay,</L>
<L>&THORN;at burth was buried In Marbel bys,</L>
<L>And whon god wolde he went his way,</L>
<L N="56">And &thorn;enne was sprad &thorn;e fflourdelys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>Where his wor&thorn;li wilnyng was,</L>
<L>Hit weore to wite whoder he went;</L>
<L>&THORN;e geynest gate grei&thorn;li he tas,</L>
<L N="60">Til derknes dipt doun he decent;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;ates he russchede, and al to-Rent,</L>
<L>&THORN;er Lucifer, &thorn;at lu&thorn;ere, lys;</L>
<L>Adam and Eue bi hond he hent,</L>
<L N="64">And tau&yogh;te hem faire &thorn;e fflourdelys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;us ha&thorn; &thorn;is heende herewed helle,</L>
<L>Al Adames of-spring out ha&thorn; tan;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend, &thorn;at was bo&thorn;e fers and felle,</L>
<L N="68">He ti&yogh;ed til a stok, stille as stan.</L>
<L>Vp of his graue &thorn;en is he gon,</L>
<L>As God and Mon to-gedere gon Rys,</L>
<L>Bodily bo&thorn;e in blod and bon</L>
<L N="72">To &thorn;e Maudeleyn he schewed &thorn;e fflourdelys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;us purchased he &thorn;e pepul heor pees</L>
<L>And goodly for-&yogh;af hem al heore gilt,</L>
<L>And seide, "Adam, eft nou I &thorn;e sese</L>
<L N="76">In blisse, &thorn;at for blod was buld;</L>
<L>No wey wonde, but wurch what &thorn;ou wilt."</L>
<L>&THORN;us ha&thorn; he now bitau&yogh;t &thorn;at wyse,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us feole prophecies ben folfild</L>
<L N="80">Of Marie wi&thorn; &thorn;i fflourdelyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>Of bounte berestou &thorn;e &thorn;e best;</L>
<L>Was neuer no buirde such beute bare;</L>
<L>Crist of &thorn;e com, vre cumfort to kest,</L>
<L N="84">To &yogh;elde &thorn;e &thorn;at we &yogh;erned &yogh;are.
<PB REF="00000722.tif" N="714"></L>
<L>At his stei&yogh;ynge, &thorn;ei stod to stare</L>
<L>How cleer in Clouden he cloumben is;</L>
<L>What wy in &thorn;at wor&thorn;ily wonyng ware,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;er miht he fynden &thorn;e fflourdelys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;us was al &thorn;is world in weere;</L>
<L>&THORN;en seide two wy&yogh;es in weedes whyt:</L>
<L>"To hei&yogh; heuene what be-holde &yogh;e here?</L>
<L N="92">Is Ihesu take from &yogh;ow &thorn;us tyd?</L>
<L>A-peere he schal in propre plyt</L>
<L>As he in werk[e] con vanys;</L>
<L>Her afturward hit weore to wite,</L>
<L N="96">Of hire &thorn;at bar &thorn;e fflourdelys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>So lelly his loue on &thorn;e was lent,</L>
<L>&THORN;i longyng, ladi, for to lete;</L>
<L>So semely sondes after &thorn;e he sent,</L>
<L N="100">Be-sydes him self to sitte in sete;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei song al samen with soun ful swete,</L>
<L>As schewen and stand in &thorn;istoris;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; more mur&thorn;es mi&yogh;t neuer mon meete,</L>
<L N="104">But &thorn;er to fynde &thorn;e fflourdelys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>Si&thorn;en &thorn;ou &thorn;i wor&thorn;ly wones hast wonnen,</L>
<L>And wones In worschipe at &thorn;i wille,</L>
<L>Vre grith was graunted, vr grace bigunnen,</L>
<L N="108">ffor vs &thorn;at was ordeyned &thorn;ertille.</L>
<L>Puire dette proue&thorn; bi proper skille</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt vs socour in &thorn;i seruys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at grei&thorn;es was for greuaunce to grille,</L>
<L N="112">And for to bere &thorn;e flourdelys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>Of al &thorn;e floures bi ffrith and ffelde,</L>
<L>Hit is &thorn;e freolokest for to fynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at weole &amp; wit and wisdam welde,</L>
<L N="116">And al &thorn;is word ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t In wynde.</L>
<L>Nou, comely kyng, Corteis and kynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at halp vs heere from vre enemys,
<PB REF="00000723.tif" N="715"></L>
<L>&THORN;e mon &thorn;at &thorn;is matere made in mynde</L>
<L N="120">Seide: non is lich to &thorn;e fflourdelys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>Hedde not Adam don &thorn;at dede,</L>
<L>Vr bitter bales hed neuer ben bou&yogh;t</L>
<L>On no maner, for no-kenes nede,</L>
<L N="124">Ne for no werkes we schuld haue wrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;us I &thorn;enk hit in my &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Monkynde for vs bi-com so chys;</L>
<L>his blisful Blod &thorn;orw him &thorn;ei sou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="128">Vs ou&yogh;te to prey to &thorn;e fflourdelys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>Nou Marie Mayden, Moder clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;i semeli Sone &thorn;at beres &thorn;e fflour,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if vs grace ow to qweme</L>
<L N="132">And plese Ihesu, vr saueour.</L>
<L>Bryng vs out of dette &amp; dedly synne,</L>
<L>To liue and dye in &thorn;i seruys,</L>
<L>Heuene blisse &thorn;at we may wynne</L>
<L N="136">And wone &thorn;er wi&thorn; &thorn;i fflourdelys.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="19" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>19. Seldom seen is soon forgot. (On Edward III, his Sons, and Richard II.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Printed from the Simeon MS., Brit. Mus., Addit. 22,283, leaf 132, in T. Wright's <I>Political Poems and Songs</I>, Rolls Series 14, vol. i, p. 215-218.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>(14 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Adere God, what mai &thorn;is be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;ing weres &amp; waste&thorn; awai?</L>
<L>ffrendschip is but a vanyte,</L>
<L N="4">vnne&thorn;e hit dures al a day;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei beo so sliper<NOTE PLACE="foot">cliper, Wright, and in l. 79, p. 721.</NOTE> at assai,</L>
<L>So leof to han, and lo&thorn; to lete,</L>
<L>And so fikel in heore fai,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at selden I-sei&yogh;e Is sone for&yogh;ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>I sei hit not wi&thorn;-outen a Cause,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore takes riht good hede,
<PB REF="00000724.tif" N="716"></L>
<L>ffor &yogh;if &yogh;e construwe wel &thorn;is Clause,</L>
<L N="12">I puit &yogh;ou holly out of drede</L>
<L>&THORN;at for puire schame &yogh;or hertis wol blede,</L>
<L>And &yogh;e &thorn;is Matere wysli trete:</L>
<L>He &thorn;at was vr moste spede,</L>
<L N="16">Is selden I-seye and sone for&yogh;ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Sum tyme an Englisch Schip we had,</L>
<L>Nobel hit was and heih of tour;</L>
<L>&THORN;orw al cristendam hit was drad,</L>
<L N="20">And stif wolde stande In vch a stour,</L>
<L>And best dorst byde a scharp schour</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er stormes, smale and grete:</L>
<L>Now is &thorn;at schip &thorn;at bar &thorn;e flour</L>
<L N="24">Selden se&yogh;e and sone for&yogh;ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>In-to &thorn;at schip &thorn;er longed a Roo&thorn;ur,</L>
<L>&THORN;at steered &thorn;e schip &amp; gouerned hit;</L>
<L>In al &thorn;is world nis such a no&thorn;ur,</L>
<L N="28">As me &thorn;inke&thorn; In my wit;</L>
<L>Whyl Schip and Ro&thorn;ur to-geder was knit,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei dredde nou&thorn;er tempest, druy&yogh;e nor wete:</L>
<L>Nou be &thorn;ei bo&thorn;e In-synder flit:</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at selden sey&yogh;e is sone for&yogh;ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>Scharpe wawes &thorn;at Schip has sayled,</L>
<L>And sayed alle sees at auentur;</L>
<L>ffor wynt ne wederes neuer hit fayled,</L>
<L N="36">Whil &thorn;e Ro&thorn;ur mihte enduir;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute; were rouh or elles dimuir,</L>
<L>Gode hauenes &thorn;at Schip wolde gete:</L>
<L>Nou is &thorn;at Schip, I am wel suir,</L>
<L N="40">Selde I-seye and sone for-&yogh;ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;is goode Schip, I may remene</L>
<L>To &thorn;e chilualrye of &thorn;is londe:</L>
<L>Sum tyme &thorn;ei counted nou&yogh;t a Bene</L>
<L N="44">Beo al ffraunce, Ich vnderstonde,
<PB REF="00000725.tif" N="717"></L>
<L>&THORN;ei tok &amp; slou&yogh; hem with heore honde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e power of ffraunce, bo&thorn; smal &amp; grete,</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;t &thorn;e king hider to byde her bonde:</L>
<L N="48">And nou riht sone hit is for&yogh;ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;at Schip hadde a ful siker mast,</L>
<L>And a sayl strong and large,</L>
<L>&THORN;at made &thorn;e gode schip neuer agast</L>
<L N="52">To vndertake a &thorn;ing of charge;</L>
<L>And to &thorn;at Schip &thorn;er longed a Barge,</L>
<L>Of al ffraunce &yogh;af nou&yogh;t a clete,</L>
<L>To vs hit was a siker targe:</L>
<L N="56">And now riht clene hit is for&yogh;ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e Ro&thorn;ur was nou&thorn;er Ok ne Elm,</L>
<L>Hit was Edward &thorn;e &thorn;ridde, &thorn;e noble kniht;</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince his sone bar vp his helm,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at neuer scoumfited was in fiht.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng him rod and Rouwed ariht,</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince dredde nou&thorn;ur stok nor strete.</L>
<L>Nou of him we lete ful liht:</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at selde is se&yogh;e is sone for&yogh;ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e swifte Barge was Duk henri,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noble kniht &amp; wel assayed,</L>
<L>And in his leggaunce wor&thorn;ili</L>
<L N="68">He a-bod mony a bitter brayd;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at his enemys ou&yogh;t outrayed,</L>
<L>To chartis hem wolde he not lete.</L>
<L>Nou is &thorn;at lord ful lowe I-leyd:</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at selde is se&yogh;e is sone for&yogh;ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;is gode comunes, bi &thorn;e Rode,</L>
<L>I likne hem to &thorn;e Schipes mast,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with heore catel &amp; heore goode</L>
<L N="76">Meyntened &thorn;e werre bo&thorn; furst &amp; last.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wynd &thorn;at bleu&yogh; &thorn;e schip wi&thorn; Blast,</L>
<L>hit was gode pre&yogh;ers, I sei hit a trete.
<PB REF="00000726.tif" N="718"></L>
<L>Nou is deuoutnes out I-cast,</L>
<L N="80">And mony gode dedes ben clen for&yogh;ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;us ben &thorn;is lordes I-leid ful lowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e stok is of &thorn;e same Rote,</L>
<L>An Ympe bi-ginnes for to growe</L>
<L N="84">And &yogh;it I hope schal ben vr bote,</L>
<L>To holde his fomen vnder fote</L>
<L>And as a lord be set in sete.</L>
<L>Crist leue &thorn;at he so mote,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at selden I se&yogh;e be not for&yogh;ete!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>Weor &thorn;at Impe ffully growe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he had sarri sap and pi&thorn;,</L>
<L>I hope he schulde be kud and knowe</L>
<L N="92">ffor Conquerour of moni a ki&thorn;;</L>
<L>He is ful lyflich in lyme and li&thorn;,</L>
<L>In armes to trauayle and to swete.</L>
<L>Crist leeue we so fare him wi&thorn;,</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;at selden se&yogh;e be neuer for&yogh;ete!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>And &thorn;erfore holliche I ou Rede;</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;is Ympe beo fully growe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vch a Mon vp wi&thorn; &thorn;e hede,</L>
<L N="100">And Mayntene him bo&thorn;e hei&yogh;e and lowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffrensche men cunne bo&thorn;e boste &amp; blowe,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; heore scornes vs to-&thorn;rete,</L>
<L>And we beo&thorn; bo&thorn;e vnkuynde &amp; slowe:</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;at selden se&yogh;e is sone for&yogh;ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>And &thorn;erfore, gode sires, take&thorn; reward</L>
<L>Of &yogh;or douhti kyng &thorn;at dy&yogh;ede in age,</L>
<L>And to his sone Prince Edward,</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at welle was of alle Corage:</L>
<L>Suche two lordes of hei&yogh; parage</L>
<L>In not in eor&thorn;e whon we schal gete,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>I know not</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>And nou heore los biginne&thorn; to swage:</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;at selde I-se&yogh;e is sone for&yogh;ete.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="20" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000727.tif" N="719">
<HEAD>20. A Warning to be ware. (On the Earthquake of 1382.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Printed from the Simeon MS. by T. Wright in <I>Polit. Poems and Songs</I>, Rolls Series, i. 250-2.</NOTE>)</HEAD>
<P>(11 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Yit is God a Curteis lord</L>
<L>And Mekeliche con schewe his miht;</L>
<L>ffayn he wolde bringe til a-cord</L>
<L N="4">Monkuynde, to liue in treu&thorn;e ariht.</L>
<L>Allas! whi set we &thorn;at lord so liht,</L>
<L>And al to foule wi&thorn; him we fare?</L>
<L>In world is non so wys, no wiht,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at &thorn;ei ne haue warnyng to be ware.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>We may not seye, but &yogh;if we ly&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god wol vengaunce on vs stele,</L>
<L>ffor openly we seo wi&thorn; ei&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;is warnynges beo&thorn; wonder &amp; fele.</L>
<L>But nou &thorn;is wrecched worldes wele</L>
<L>Make&thorn; vs liue in Sunne and care.</L>
<L>Of Mony Merueyles I may of Mele,</L>
<L N="16">And al is warnyng to be ware.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Whon &thorn;e Comuynes bigan to ryse,</L>
<L>Was non so gret lord, as I gesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei in herte bi-gon to gryse,</L>
<L N="20">And leide heore Iolyte in presse.</L>
<L>Wher was &thorn;enne heore wor&thorn;inesse,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei made lordes droupe &amp; dare?</L>
<L>Of alle wyse men I take witnesse,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;is was a warnyng to be ware.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>Bi-fore, &yogh;if men hedde haad a graas,</L>
<L>Lordes mihte wondur weel</L>
<L>Han let the rysing &thorn;at &thorn;er was,</L>
<L N="28">But &thorn;at god &thorn;ou&yogh;te &yogh;it sumdel</L>
<L>&THORN;at lordes schulde his lordschup feel,</L>
<L>And of heore lordschipe make hem bare.
<PB REF="00000728.tif" N="720"></L>
<L>Trust &thorn;er-to as trewe as steel,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;is was a warnyng to be ware.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>And also, whon &thorn;is eor&thorn;e qwok,</L>
<L>Was mon<NOTE PLACE="foot">non.&mdash;Wright.</NOTE> so proud, he nas a-gast,</L>
<L>And al his Iolite for-sok,</L>
<L N="36">And &thorn;ou&yogh;t on god whil &thorn;at hit last;</L>
<L>And alsone as hit was ouer past,</L>
<L>Men wox as vuel as &thorn;ei dude are!</L>
<L>Vche mon in his herte may cast,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;is was a warnyng to be ware.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>ffor so&thorn;e, &thorn;is was a lord to drede,</L>
<L>So sodeynly mad Mon agast!</L>
<L>Of gold &amp; seluer &thorn;ei tok non hede,</L>
<L N="44">But out of her houses ful sone &thorn;ei past.</L>
<L>Chaumbres, Chimeneys al to-barst,</L>
<L>Chirches &amp; Castels foule gon fare,</L>
<L>Pinacles, Steples to grounde hit cast;</L>
<L N="48">And al was warnyng to be ware.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e Meuyng of &thorn;is eor&thorn;e I-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at schulde bi cuynde be ferm &amp; stabele,</L>
<L>A pure verrey toknyng hit is,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at Mennes hertes ben chaungable,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at to falsed &thorn;ei ben most Abul;</L>
<L>ffor wi&thorn; good fei&thorn; wol we not fare:</L>
<L>Leef hit wel wi&thorn;-outen fabel;</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;is was a warnyng to be ware.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e Rysing of &thorn;e comuynes in londe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pestilens,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Possibly the 5th plague,&mdash;the Black Death of 1348-9 being the First, the plague of 1361 the Second, that of 1368-9 the Third, and that of 1375 the Fourth, while that of 1390-1 was the Fifth.&mdash;Creighton, i. 206-219. But a less Plague was in 1382.</NOTE> and &thorn;e eor&thorn;e-quake,</L>
<L>&THORN;eose &thorn;reo &thorn;inges, I vnderstonde,</L>
<L N="60">Beo-tokenes<NOTE PLACE="foot">Beoth tokenes.&mdash;Wright.</NOTE> &thorn;e grete vengaunce &amp; wrake
<PB REF="00000729.tif" N="721"></L>
<L>&THORN;at schulde falle for synnes sake,</L>
<L>As &thorn;is Clerkes conne de-clare.</L>
<L>Nou may we chese to leue or take,</L>
<L N="64">ffor warnyng haue we to ben ware.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>Euere I drede, be my trou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;er may no warnyng stande in sted;</L>
<L>We ben so ful of synne and slou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;e schame is passed &thorn;e sched of hed,</L>
<L>And we liggen riht heuy as led,</L>
<L>Cumbred in &thorn;e ffendes Snare.</L>
<L>I leeue &thorn;is beo vr beste Red</L>
<L N="72">To &thorn;enke on &thorn;is warnyng &amp; be ware.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>Sikerliche, I dar wel saye,</L>
<L>In such a plyt &thorn;is world is in:</L>
<L>Mony for wynnyng wolde bi-traye</L>
<L N="76">ffader and Moder and al his kin.</L>
<L>Nou were heih tyme to be-gin</L>
<L>To A-Mende vr mis &amp; wel to fare;</L>
<L>Vr bagge honge&thorn; on a sliper<NOTE PLACE="marg">cliper, Wright.</NOTE> pyn,</L>
<L N="80">Bote we of &thorn;is warnyng be ware.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>Be war, for I con sey no more,</L>
<L>Be war for vengauns of trespas,</L>
<L>Be war and &thorn;enk vppon &thorn;is lore,</L>
<L N="84">Be war of &thorn;is sodeyn cas,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it Be war while we haue spas,</L>
<L>And &thorn;onke &thorn;at child &thorn;at Marie bare</L>
<L>Of his gret godnesse and his gras</L>
<L N="88">Sende vs such warnyng to be ware.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="21" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>21. Love Holy Church and its Priests.</HEAD>
<P>(8 <I>stanzas of</I> 8; <I>nos.</I> 1 <I>and</I> 2 <I>abab cdcd; nos.</I> 3-8 <I>abab abab.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Crist &yogh;iue vs grace to loue wel holichirch,</L>
<L>Or elles, certes, we don riht nouht,
<PB REF="00000730.tif" N="722"></L>
<L>And let vs neuere a&yogh;eynes hit worche:</L>
<L N="4">ffrom &thorn;enne vre cristendom is brouht.</L>
<L>Preostes weore at vre biginnynge;</L>
<L>W&yogh;uche God ha&thorn; graunted hem pouete</L>
<L>ffor vs to rede I-wis and synge,</L>
<L N="8">Is non so gret a dignyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ei &yogh;af vs vre Cristenynge,</L>
<L>And at vr buriinge &thorn;ei moste be.</L>
<L>To worschipe hem in alle &thorn;inge,</L>
<L N="12">Muchel &thorn;erto holden beo we.</L>
<L>Godus bodi may no mon make</L>
<L>But preostes al-one, as we rede:</L>
<L>Kyng ne Emperour, I non out-take,</L>
<L N="16">ffor alle heore richesses of lond or leode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Of alle Ordres he beres &thorn;e prys,</L>
<L>Kyng, Duyk, o&thorn;er Emperour,</L>
<L>&THORN;ouh heo weren &thorn;e fflourdelys,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at is richest of alle colour.</L>
<L>In Matynes and vses &thorn;ei ben wys,</L>
<L>To bringe vs to vr longe bour,</L>
<L>And vche day synge&thorn; a Masse to &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="24">And schewe&thorn; vs Ihesus, vre sauiour.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>In Matyns and Masse &thorn;ei beren &thorn;e prys,</L>
<L>And in heore orisons for vs &thorn;ei pray:</L>
<L>&THORN;er is no mon &thorn;at is wys</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;at o&thorn;ur record bi heom may say.</L>
<L>Hose loue&thorn; &thorn;is ordre, I holde him wys,</L>
<L>ffor certeyn so&thorn; and in good fay,</L>
<L>In holy chirche &thorn;ei don seruys</L>
<L N="32">Bo&thorn;e bi nihtes and bi day.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>But hose euer wole &thorn;is ordre bere,</L>
<L>Wys and witti moste he be,</L>
<L>Grete o&thorn;es may he non swere,</L>
<L N="36">Ne falshede nou&thorn;er don ne se;
<PB REF="00000731.tif" N="723"></L>
<L>By-fore &thorn;e Bisschop receyue&thorn; he &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And take&thorn; &thorn;e &yogh;ok of chastite.</L>
<L>A-vyse hem wel hou he hit were,</L>
<L N="40">O&thorn;er elles him schal rewe o&thorn;er me.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>Whon we ben falle in eny mischef,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; serwe In dedly synne I-bounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;en is &thorn;e prest vs ful leef,</L>
<L N="44">ffor he may helen vs of &thorn;at wounde.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er is non so strong a &thorn;eef</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer tok cristendom on godes grounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he most haue a preest bi-foren his de&thorn;,</L>
<L N="48">Or elles he schal warie &thorn;e stounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>On domes-day whon we schul meete</L>
<L>&THORN;at dredful Iuge forte se,</L>
<L>&THORN;en is schrift to vs ful seete:</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;e prest &thorn;erof record beres he.</L>
<L>Of alle bales he may beete</L>
<L>Vnder god In Trinite;</L>
<L>&THORN;enne Schrift &amp; hosul is ful swete,</L>
<L N="56">And hit trewely holden be.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;is ordre I rede &thorn;at we honoure,</L>
<L>And so I counseyle &thorn;at we do,</L>
<L>And take penaunce for sunnes oure</L>
<L N="60">Whuche &thorn;e prest ha&thorn; Iuned vs to;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> Inned]</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;en schal we come to &thorn;at boure</L>
<L>&THORN;er euere is Ioye wi&thorn;-outen wo.</L>
<L>Ihesu bring vs and socoure.</L>
<L N="64">Out of &thorn;is world whon we schal go.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="22" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>22. Try to say the best. Control your Tongue.</HEAD>
<P>(7 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Qween of heuene, Moder and may,</L>
<L>Saue hem alle nou &thorn;at ben here.
<PB REF="00000732.tif" N="724"></L>
<L>A noble word haue I herd say,</L>
<L N="4">fful profytable &thorn;at is to lere,</L>
<L>Bi-twene God and Mon In fere</L>
<L>To wynne worschupe hose euer lust:</L>
<L>Now &thorn;enk vpon &thorn;is word so dere</L>
<L N="8">And fond euermore to seye &thorn;e best.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>Spek non euel in no place,</L>
<L>But kepe &thorn;i tonge and get &thorn;e a frend;</L>
<L>&THORN;at wikked word from &thorn;e nou pace,</L>
<L N="12">Hit is but tysyng of &thorn;e fend.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou beo in eny euel tent</L>
<L>And k[n]owe hit for an euel geste,</L>
<L>Keep &thorn;i tonge curteys and gent,</L>
<L N="16">And fond euermore to sey &thorn;e beste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Now, for his loue &thorn;at bou&yogh;te &thorn;e dere,</L>
<L>Let not &thorn;i tonge haue al &thorn;e wil!</L>
<L>What artou &thorn;e bettre or &thorn;e more nere,</L>
<L N="20">Wi&thorn; a wikked word &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebor to spil?</L>
<L>ffor Mari loue, tak tente &thorn;er-tille,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;ou gost bi Est o&thorn;ur Weste,</L>
<L>Euur to kepe &thorn;i tonge stille</L>
<L N="24">O&thorn;ur elles to fonde to sey &thorn;e beste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou sey &thorn;e beste wi&thorn; al &thorn;i miht,</L>
<L>Men wol esschewe by-fore &thorn;e</L>
<L>To speke evel bi eny wiht,</L>
<L N="28">ffor &thorn;ou wolt not heore felawe be;</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ou spekest, &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t se</L>
<L>Wordes &thorn;at ben wikked and preste.</L>
<L>Nou, for his loue &thorn;at dyed on tre,</L>
<L N="32">ffonde euermore to sey &thorn;e beste!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>In halle o&thorn;ur in chaumbre wher &thorn;ow gos,</L>
<L>What &thorn;ou here and what &thorn;ou se,</L>
<L>Euure &thorn;ou kepe &thorn;i tonge clos,</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;at men frayne nou&yogh;t at &thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000733.tif" N="725"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou heere faute o&thorn;er eny fole,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou may here bi mony a geste,</L>
<L>Nou, for his loue &thorn;at dyed on tre,</L>
<L N="40">ffonde euer more to sey &thorn;e beste!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>Wi&thorn; eny mon &yogh;if &thorn;ou haue ben eke</L>
<L>In his seruyse bi niht o&thorn;er day,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e good &thorn;at &thorn;ou may, speke,</L>
<L N="44">Whon &thorn;at &thorn;ou art went a-way:</L>
<L>&THORN;enne wol men bi &thorn;e say,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou art curteys and wel I-bleste.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou knowe ou&yogh;t &thorn;at disese may,</L>
<L N="48">ffonde euur more to sey &thorn;e beste!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou beo riche mon of mony a beeste,</L>
<L>And stifli &thorn;ou may stonde in stede,</L>
<L>Pore men disese nou&yogh;t bi doing ne cheste;</L>
<L N="52">Nou&thorn;er for word ne for dede,</L>
<L>But help hem wel in alle heore nede,</L>
<L>So crist &thorn;i soule bringe to reste.</L>
<L>Nou to &thorn;is word &yogh;e take good hede:</L>
<L N="56">ffor Marie loue to seye &thorn;e beste.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="23" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>23. Tarry not till to-morrow.</HEAD>
<P>(9 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Ilke a wys wiht scholde wake</L>
<L>And waite, with werk heuen to wynne,</L>
<L>Sadliche, for goddes sake,</L>
<L N="4">And set &yogh;oure soule sauely fro synne.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou haue kynges of &thorn;i kynne,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;i clos, catel and corn,</L>
<L>Amende &thorn;i misses more and minne,</L>
<L N="8">And mak no tarijng til to-Morn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ou leod &thorn;at liues as lord in londe,</L>
<L>&THORN;enk hou lowe &thorn;ou schalt aliht,
<PB REF="00000734.tif" N="726"></L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; &thorn;ou haue hundredus at &thorn;in honde</L>
<L N="12">To holde &thorn;in heste in herte has hiht.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou bragge for &thorn;i Be&yogh;anus briht,</L>
<L>Bi-holde hou bare &thorn;at &thorn;ou was born;</L>
<L>&THORN;is dai &thorn;ou dresse &thorn;i dole and diht,</L>
<L N="16">Leste &thorn;at &thorn;ou dye longe er to-Morn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ou freike &thorn;at art in frendschupe fast</L>
<L>And &thorn;inkest no foot mon is &thorn;i fere;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;i pompe and pride is past,</L>
<L N="20">A pore renaunt schal beo &thorn;i pere.</L>
<L>Loke in londe, and &thorn;ou mai lere</L>
<L>Hou li&yogh;tly &thorn;at &thorn;i lyf is lorn;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;i bodi is brouht on bere,</L>
<L N="24">As &thorn;ou hast browen, &thorn;ou broukest to-Morn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>Gome, er &thorn;ou giue vp &thorn;i gost,</L>
<L>Bi-grei&thorn; ho schal gripe &thorn;i goode:</L>
<L>He schal hit haue &thorn;ou hatest most:</L>
<L N="28">So fares hit ofte, be myn hode!</L>
<L>&THORN;en al &thorn;i fee fonges but foode.</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i ordeyne &thorn;i fare be-forn,</L>
<L>And with a-boue mende &thorn;i mis in mode:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> a bone]</NOTE></L>
<L N="32">Hit wol &thorn;e menske a&yogh;eyn to-Morn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>Parte with &yogh;or godes in priuete</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e pore with-outen pride:</L>
<L>Hit wol &thorn;e brynge in blisse to be,</L>
<L N="36">Wi&thorn;-outen bale to buylde &amp; byde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sette &thorn;i seketur fro &thorn;i syde,</L>
<L>He wol &thorn;e swyke &thorn;ou&yogh; he be sworn,</L>
<L>&THORN;in hord, whon he may, hent o&thorn;ur hyde,</L>
<L N="40">Trust him not after to-Morn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e Sikernes of &thorn;i Seketoure,</L>
<L>&THORN;is is &thorn;e so&thorn;e to seo and say;</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; he for &thorn;i loue lurke and loure,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at he has lauht he wol nou&yogh;t lay,
<PB REF="00000735.tif" N="727"></L>
<L>But skelpe and scrope al &thorn;at he may;</L>
<L>He lettes nou&thorn;er for ska&thorn;e ne skorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;i goodes whon he has geten a-way,</L>
<L N="48">Trust nou&yogh;t on hem after to-Morn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>Mony a wiht wenes ful wel</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world &thorn;ei schal neuur wende;</L>
<L>ffor feole lykinges &thorn;at &thorn;ei feel,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;ei make no fors of fo nor frende.</L>
<L>Now trust riht wel &thorn;ei schal be tenede,</L>
<L>Ar bodi and soule a-two be torn.</L>
<L>Of er&thorn;ly ese &thorn;is is &thorn;e ende,</L>
<L N="56">Here to-day, a-wey to-morn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>Ihesus &thorn;at on &thorn;e Rode was don,</L>
<L>ffrom wo and wondre&thorn; &thorn;ou vs wisse!</L>
<L>Gladly graunte us vre bone</L>
<L N="60">And bryng us blessedly to &thorn;i blisse!</L>
<L>ffor vre loue, So&thorn; hit is,</L>
<L>&THORN;i syde wi&thorn; scharpe spere was schorn:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou saue us &thorn;at we ben not his</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at wolde &thorn;at we weore tynt to-Morn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>Marie Moder, Mayden Mylde,</L>
<L>On al mon-kuynde &yogh;e haue Merci!</L>
<L>In feole ful&thorn;es we ben fuylede;</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;is world vse&thorn; &thorn;e flessches foly;</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;i sone &thorn;ou calle and cry,</L>
<L>Crist crounet wi&thorn; kene &thorn;orn,</L>
<L>He &yogh;iue vs grace to wone him by!</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;en schal vs tyde no teone to-Morn.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="24" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>24. Make Amends for thy Sins.</HEAD>
<P>(12 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Bi a wode as I gon ryde.</L>
<L>walkynge al mi-self alone,
<PB REF="00000736.tif" N="728"></L>
<L>A boske of briddes bad me abyde</L>
<L N="4">Bi-cause &thorn;er songe mo &thorn;en one.</L>
<L>Among &thorn;o foules euerichone,</L>
<L>To on, gret hede I gan take,</L>
<L>ffor he seyde wi&thorn; reu&thorn;ful mone,</L>
<L N="8">"ffor &thorn;i sunnes a-Mendes make!"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>"Make amendes, mon, trewely,"</L>
<L>Seide &thorn;at foul wi&thorn; fe&thorn;eres blake.</L>
<L>In myn herte i-went, wo was I,</L>
<L N="12">ffor he me bad amendes make.</L>
<L>I stod and studied al &thorn;at day;</L>
<L>&THORN;at resun made me a niht to wake:</L>
<L>&THORN;en fond I &thorn;reo skiles in good fay</L>
<L N="16">Whi he me bad a-mendes make.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e furste skile &thorn;at I gan fynde,</L>
<L>As hit bi-semes in my witte,</L>
<L>Is a &thorn;ing &thorn;at comes of kynde:</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at eueri mon schal haue a pitte.</L>
<L>Whon top and to to-gedre is knitte,</L>
<L>&THORN;en schal &thorn;i proude wordes aslake.</L>
<L>ffor-&thorn;i in eor&thorn;e er &thorn;ou be ditte,</L>
<L N="24">Mon, of &thorn;i synnes a-mendes make!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er skile is: &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt dye,</L>
<L>Whuche tyme &thorn;ou wost nere.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou wustest witerly,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;ow woldest fle &thorn;i de&thorn; for fere.</L>
<L>&THORN;i laste bour schal ben a Bere,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;i frendes &thorn;e may take.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore do wel while &thorn;ou art here,</L>
<L N="32">And for &thorn;i sunnes a-Mendes make!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde skile wol do &thorn;e wo</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou &thorn;enkest &thorn;er on I-wis:</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;i lyf is clene I-go,</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;ou wost nere whoder to bale or blis.
<PB REF="00000737.tif" N="729"></L>
<L>I fynde no clerk con telle me &thorn;is;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore my serwe bi-ginnes to wake.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou &thorn;enkest to don a-mis,</L>
<L N="40">Haue mynde of &thorn;is &amp; amendes make!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>Ensaumple we may sen al day</L>
<L>As crist schewes among vs alle:</L>
<L>To-day &yogh;if &thorn;ou be stout and gay,</L>
<L N="44">To-morn &thorn;ou lyst ded bi &thorn;e walle.</L>
<L>Merci &thorn;enne to crie and calle,</L>
<L>Hit is to late &thorn;i leue to take.</L>
<L>Be war of folye er &thorn;ou falle,</L>
<L N="48">And for &thorn;i sunnes amendes make!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou haue don a dedly synne</L>
<L>wher-&thorn;orw &thorn;i soule scholde be schent,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e &yogh;er &thorn;ou wolt lye &thorn;er-Inne</L>
<L N="52">In derknes til hit beo lent;</L>
<L>&THORN;en a ffrere &thorn;ou wolt hent,</L>
<L>&THORN;i parisch prest for schame forsake.</L>
<L>Of alle suche dedes, verament,</L>
<L N="56">I rede &thorn;e beo wys, &amp; amendes make!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be kyng and croune bere,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is world be at &thorn;i wil,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it schaltou be pore as &thorn;ou was ere,</L>
<L N="60">And &thorn;at &thorn;ou knowest bi puire skil:</L>
<L>A schete schal &thorn;i body hule</L>
<L>And huyde &thorn;i cors for sinnes sake.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore repente &thorn;ou hast do ille,</L>
<L N="64">And for &thorn;i synnes amendes make!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou beo a fryk mon in &thorn;i floures,</L>
<L>And haue vn-bou&yogh;t bo&thorn;e purpel &amp; pal,</L>
<L>At Masse ne Matyns ne at houres</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;ou kepes not come with-in &thorn;e chirche wal,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-in &thorn;i Sauor is ful smal,</L>
<L>Of sleu&thorn;e may &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t awake:
<PB REF="00000738.tif" N="730"></L>
<L>On day &thorn;ou schalt leue hit al;</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;erfore I rede, Amendes make!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; &thorn;ou haue riches gret plente,</L>
<L>In world while &thorn;ou liuest here,</L>
<L>God made &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebur as wel as &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="76">And bou&yogh;t &yogh;ou bo&thorn;e I-liche dere;</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; he be nou&yogh;t &thorn;i worldes pere,</L>
<L>Do him no wrong, for synnes sake!</L>
<L>To nou&yogh;t shal turne &thorn;i proude chere:</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;erfore I rede, &thorn;ou amendes make.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou bere &thorn;e feir and euen,</L>
<L>&THORN;au&yogh; &thorn;ou be lord, Bayli o&thorn;ur Meire,</L>
<L>ffor ofte men meten at vn-set steuen;</L>
<L N="84">Coueyte not &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebor to peyre.</L>
<L>&THORN;is world nis but a chirie feire,</L>
<L>Nou is hit in sesun, nou wol hit slake,</L>
<L>To-day artou lord, to-morn is &thorn;in heire:</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;erfore I rede, &thorn;ou amendes make.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>Nou god, &thorn;at was in bethleem boren,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en died vppon &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>Let vs neuer ben for-loren,</L>
<L N="92">Lord, &yogh;if &thorn;i wille be.</L>
<L>Marie Moder, Mayden briht,</L>
<L>Preye for vr synnes sake,</L>
<L>In heuene of &thorn;i sone to haue a siht,</L>
<L N="96">And heer in eor&thorn;e, Amendes make.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="25" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>25. Suffer in Time, and that is best.</HEAD>
<P>(6 <I>stanzas of</I> 12, <I>abab abab bcbc, and one of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Whon alle so&thorn;es ben souht and seene,</L>
<L>Euerichone at heore deuys,</L>
<L>Euer among, in tray and tene,</L>
<L N="4">Mur&thorn;e is meyt wi&thorn; malys;
<PB REF="00000739.tif" N="731"></L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes cumfort come&thorn; cares kene,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes vche a uertu is a vys.</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e vertues &thorn;at &thorn;er beone,</L>
<L N="8">To suffre, hit is a &thorn;ing of prys.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore he &thorn;at wol be wys,</L>
<L>And loue to rule him siker in rest,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at he beo not to nys,</L>
<L N="12">But suffre in tyme, and &thorn;at is best.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou beo mon of mene a-syse</L>
<L>Or gret lord in duresse,</L>
<L>And &thorn;i stat may not suffise</L>
<L N="16">Of &thorn;i wronge to gete red[r]esse,</L>
<L>&THORN;en mostou worchen on &thorn;is wyse,</L>
<L>And schewe to him such boxumnesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at rou&thorn;e in his herte may ryse</L>
<L N="20">And wi&thorn;-drawe his grete distresse;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he be Mesured wi&thorn; Mekenesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;en pite in him hit wol be preste.</L>
<L>Among alle &thorn;ing, as I gesse,</L>
<L N="24">To suffre in tyme and &thorn;at is beste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be mon of gret degre,</L>
<L>And a pore mon in his place</L>
<L>fful wrongfully has greued &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="28">And don &thorn;e gref wi&thorn; his trespace,</L>
<L>&THORN;e cuntrey con wel knowe and se</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mai be venget in &thorn;at case;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be perset wi&thorn; pite,</L>
<L N="32">&YOGH;it woltou spare him for a space.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou so goodly schewe &thorn;i grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;e holigost is in &thorn;e feste:</L>
<L>&THORN;en godes blessyng schaltou in-brace,</L>
<L N="36">And suffre [in] tyme and &thorn;at is beste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>Hit is luytel wor&thorn;, sei&thorn; Socrates,</L>
<L>A glasen pot, is wayk and liht,</L>
<L>To puiten him self to fer in pres</L>
<L N="40">A-&yogh;eynes a caudrun for to fiht.
<PB REF="00000740.tif" N="732"></L>
<L>&THORN;e so&thorn;e al day is seene in siht:</L>
<L>&THORN;e weikest ay bi-neo&thorn;e is cast.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore sei I, bi god almiht,</L>
<L N="44">To suffre [in] tyme and &thorn;at is best.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>Mon, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;e state meyntene.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; lordes In counseil forte sette,</L>
<L>&THORN;er euer mon moste in certeyne</L>
<L N="48">Schewe his wisdom and his witte:</L>
<L>&THORN;en, what-so-euer hapnes &thorn;e to seyne,</L>
<L>Let al &thorn;i wordes to wisdam knitte,</L>
<L>Or summe of &thorn;e feeres wol taken in deyne,</L>
<L N="52">And for pruyde reson hitte.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou here hem so chyde or flitte,</L>
<L>&THORN;er wol no reson in hem reste,</L>
<L>Holt &thorn;i tonge and &thorn;i mou&thorn; ditte,</L>
<L N="56">And suffre [in] tyme and &thorn;at is beste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>And aftur, whon &thorn;ou woldest not wene,</L>
<L>Whon alle so&thorn;es ben sou&yogh;t and sayd,</L>
<L>&THORN;i wordes &thorn;ei wole take by-deene,</L>
<L N="60">And of &thorn;i speche &thorn;ei wol holde hem payd:</L>
<L>&THORN;en schul &thorn;ei abassched beone,</L>
<L>And of heer errours ben dismayed,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;i wisdam schal be set and sene</L>
<L N="64">And alle heore folys ben displayed.</L>
<L>Hasti men ben ofte outrayede</L>
<L>Whon heore tonges ben to preste.</L>
<L>Hose ha&thorn; ben ofte of sore hokes braide,</L>
<L N="68">Soffre [in] tyme and &thorn;at is beste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;if hit bi-tide&thorn; be niht o&thorn;er day</L>
<L>To falle in-til a cumpaignye</L>
<L>&THORN;er nyse folk wi&thorn; folyes play,</L>
<L N="72">And out of reson &thorn;ei &yogh;elle and crie,</L>
<L>&THORN;en mostou worchen wi&thorn; &thorn;is assay,</L>
<L>And holde vp oyl by and by,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ou mowe priuely go &thorn;i way;</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;en kui&thorn;est &thorn;ou wel &thorn;at &thorn;ou art slih;
<PB REF="00000741.tif" N="733"></L>
<L>I holde hit riht a gret foly</L>
<L>To schewe reson &thorn;er non wol reste.</L>
<L>&THORN;er bi God and vre ladi,</L>
<L N="80">Suffre in hym and &thorn;at is beste.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="26" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>26. Mane nobiscum, Domine!</HEAD>
<P>(10 <I>stanzas of</I> 8; 9 <I>abab bcbc; the</I> 10<I>th abab baba.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>IN Somer bi-fore &thorn;e Ascenciun</L>
<L>At Euensong on a Sonundai</L>
<L>Dwellyng in my deuociun</L>
<L N="4">ffor &thorn;e pees fast gon I prai:</L>
<L>I herde a Reson to my pai,</L>
<L>&THORN;at writen was with wordes &thorn;re,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us hit is, schortly to say:</L>
<L N="8">Mane nobiscum domine!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>What &thorn;is word is forte mene</L>
<L>On Englisch tonge, I schal &yogh;ou telle:</L>
<L>In Concience and we be clene,</L>
<L N="12">Digne &thorn;i, lord, with vs to dwelle,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e feondes pouste for to felle,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at for vs. di&yogh;ede vppon &thorn;e tre;</L>
<L>In wit and worschipe, wei and welle,</L>
<L N="16">Mane nobiscum, domine!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou from deth was risen and gon,</L>
<L>&THORN;en as a Palmere for&thorn; gon pas,</L>
<L>&THORN;o met &thorn;ou pilgrimes makyng moon,</L>
<L N="20">But &yogh;it &thorn;ei wust neuer who &thorn;ou was.</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;en Carpes Cleophas:</L>
<L>&THORN;e Niht is neih as we may se,</L>
<L>&THORN;e liht of &thorn;e dai is waxen las:</L>
<L N="24">Mane nobiscum, domine!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>Dwelle with vs, vr fader dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;i bidyng is in heuene-blis,
<PB REF="00000742.tif" N="734"></L>
<L>And euure &thorn;i name be halewed here.</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;i kyngdom let vs neuere mis.</L>
<L>In heuene &thorn;i wille folfuld is,</L>
<L>And heere in eor&thorn;e &thorn;at hit so be!</L>
<L>&THORN;e Rihtwys weyes &yogh;e wolde vs wis,</L>
<L N="32">Mane nobiscum, domine!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>Vr bred, vr vche dayes foode,</L>
<L>Drihten deore, &thorn;ou vs diht.</L>
<L>Vr dette, God &thorn;at is so goode,</L>
<L N="36">ffor-&yogh;iue vs for &thorn;i muchele miht,</L>
<L>As we schul heom wi&thorn; herte liht</L>
<L>&THORN;at in vr dette or daunger be.</L>
<L>Leste we Rule vs not a-riht,</L>
<L N="40">Mane nobiscum, domine!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>Dwelle wi&thorn; vs, lord, leste we haue teene,</L>
<L>Lede us to no temptacion.</L>
<L>In eny synne &yogh;if we beo seene,</L>
<L N="44">We prey &thorn;e of Merci and pardoun;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al &thorn;e Mekenes &thorn;at we moun,</L>
<L>We schal crye, knelyng on kne:</L>
<L>Vppon bere whon we beo boun,</L>
<L N="48">Mane nobiscum, domine!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>Lord, dwelle with vs in al ur neode;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;e we haue no miht,</L>
<L>Vr hondes vp til vr hed to beode,</L>
<L N="52">Wit nor weole sauere&thorn; no siht.</L>
<L>In eny caas &yogh;if we ben cliht,</L>
<L>We con not but we crie to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>In al vr neode bo&thorn;e day and niht,</L>
<L N="56">Mane nobiscum, domine!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>Ho dwelle&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e, &thorn;ar haue no doute</L>
<L>ffor no synne ne sodeyn chaunce.</L>
<L>But ay &thorn;e fend is fast aboute</L>
<L N="60">To putte vs, lord, fro &thorn;i plesaunce;
<PB REF="00000743.tif" N="735"></L>
<L>Whon we beo&thorn; out of gouernaunce,</L>
<L>Vr flesch is frele, we can not fle:</L>
<L>Keep us out of al cumbraunce,</L>
<L N="64">Mane nobiscum, domine!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>Dwelle wi&thorn; us, lord of loue and pes,</L>
<L>And make &thorn;i wonynge vs wi&thorn;-inne,</L>
<L>In Charite &thorn;at we encres,</L>
<L N="68">And kep vs out of dedly synne;</L>
<L>Torn neuer &thorn;i face from us to twynne;</L>
<L>ffor Marie loue, &thorn;at Mayden fre,</L>
<L>Whon we schal eny werk beo-gynne</L>
<L N="72">Mane nobiscum, domine!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>Mane nobiscum, domine!</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;e we ben riht nouht.</L>
<L>What Ioye or Blis weore &thorn;at to &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="76">To &thorn;eose &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast deore abouht?</L>
<L>In word, In wille, In herte and &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>We schul preye to &thorn;e Trinite:</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world whon we be brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="80">Mane nobiscum, domine!</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="27" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>27. A Prayer to the Virgin Mary.</HEAD>
<P>(14 <I>stanzas of</I> 12, <I>abab abab cdcd.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L><I>AVe Maris stella, dei Mater Alma,</I></L>
<L><I>Atque semper virgo, felix celi porta.</I></L>
<L>Heil, sterre of &thorn;e S&eacute;&eacute; so briht!</L>
<L>&THORN;ow graunt vs to ben vr gyde;</L>
<L>Godes holi Moder riht,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;i worschipe walke&thorn; wyde;</L>
<L>Al-wey Mayden &thorn;orw his miht,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow sittest bi his syde;</L>
<L>Blesset &yogh;ate of heuene liht,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;ow rede vs riht to ryde!</L>
<L>Ladi, we ben maked al glad:</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou weore meoke I-founde,
<PB REF="00000744.tif" N="736"></L>
<L>Godes Moder weore &thorn;ou mad,</L>
<L N="12">I-Blesset beo &thorn;at stounde!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>Liknet artou to sterre of s&eacute;&eacute;,</L>
<L>To lihten vs, grete and smale;</L>
<L>Godes Moder ay to be,</L>
<L N="16">ffor vs &thorn;ou telle vr tale;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;i Maydenhod so fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou bring vs out of bale;</L>
<L>Help us in-to heuene fle</L>
<L N="20">Out of &thorn;is wopes dale.</L>
<L>Ladi, bring vs out of wo!</L>
<L>ffrom Bales &thorn;ou vs borwe!</L>
<L>Godes Moder and Mayden also,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;ou saue vs out of sorwe!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L><I>Sumens illud Aue Gabrielis ore,</I></L>
<L><I>ffunda nos in pace, mutans nomen eue.</I></L>
<L>Takyng &thorn;at word Aue&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at sonde sat &thorn;e seete&mdash;</L>
<L>Of Gabriels mou&thorn; so fre,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;orw God he gon &thorn;e grete.</L>
<L>Prei for us in pes to be,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mur&thorn;es mo to meete;</L>
<L>Eues name i-tornd for &thorn;e</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at sit us softe and swete.</L>
<L>Ladi blisful, Meoke and Mylde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at word in Ioye us pultus;</L>
<L>Godes Moder, prei &thorn;i childe</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;at he for-&yogh;iue vr gultus.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>Aue wor&thorn;ily &thorn;e fel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e &yogh;arked &yogh;ore</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at Angel Gabriel,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;orw &yogh;ift of Godes lore.</L>
<L>Prey us pes, &thorn;er to be snel,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou salue us of vr sore;</L>
<L>Si&thorn; &thorn;at Eue is tornd so wel,</L>
<L N="44">vr blisse is wel &thorn;e more.
<PB REF="00000745.tif" N="737"></L>
<L>Ladi, qween of paradys,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e we schullen calle,</L>
<L>Godes Moder, wommon wys,</L>
<L N="48">And Mekest most of alle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L><I>SOlue vincla reis, profer lumen cecis,</I></L>
<L><I>mala nostra pelle, bona cuncta posce.</I></L>
<L>Gulti bondes here vnbynd,</L>
<L>Vr gultes ben to fele;</L>
<L>Seend hem siht &thorn;at here aren blynd,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;ou bring vs to &thorn;i wele;</L>
<L>Put a-wey vr wikked wynt,</L>
<L>Vr synful lyf &thorn;ou heele;</L>
<L>Alle goodes aske and grynt,</L>
<L N="56">And sent vs of &thorn;at Meole.</L>
<L>Ladi, nou &thorn;at hit is &thorn;us,</L>
<L>Help we weore vnbounde;</L>
<L>Godes Moder, prei for vs</L>
<L N="60">To him wi&thorn; blodi wounde!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>WE han agult, vnbynd us here,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Merci fond vs fede;</L>
<L>Send &thorn;e blynde, lokyng clere,</L>
<L N="64">To hele us here tak hede;</L>
<L>Put a-wei vr wik in weere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at do&thorn; us dri&yogh;e and drede;</L>
<L>Aske us God wi&thorn;-outen peere,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;at holliche heuene meede.</L>
<L>Laydi, nou &thorn;in help a-non,</L>
<L>&THORN;er of &thorn;at we ne fayle;</L>
<L>Godes Moder, a-&yogh;ein vr fon</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;ou most be Countur tayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L><I>MOnstra te esse matrem, sumat par te precem</I></L>
<L><I>qui pro nobis natus tulit esse tuus.</I></L>
<L>Scheuh &thorn;at Moder art, enclyn</L>
<L>To him &thorn;at dy&yogh;ed on Roode;</L>
<L>He, &thorn;orw&yogh; &thorn;e, tak preyer myn,</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at bou&yogh;t us wi&thorn; his bloode;
<PB REF="00000746.tif" N="738"></L>
<L>Boren for us was he so fyn,</L>
<L>Hit com al vs to goode;</L>
<L>He bi-com heere sone &thorn;yn,</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;i Milk &thorn;en was his foode.</L>
<L>Godus Modur, &thorn;ou him beere,</L>
<L>&THORN;i Milk nas non Ilyche,</L>
<L>Ladi, him to fostren heere;</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at Bur&thorn;e was ful riche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>MOdur, scheuh &thorn;at &thorn;ou art fre;</L>
<L>&THORN;e may no mur&thorn;e misse;</L>
<L>Do &thorn;at we ben herd &thorn;orw &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;ou bring us to &thorn;i blisse.</L>
<L>I-boren for us forso&thorn;e was he,</L>
<L>&THORN;e synful men to wisse,</L>
<L>He &thorn;at tok &thorn;i child to be,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;i Mou&thorn; wi&thorn; his to kisse.</L>
<L>Ladi briht, wi&thorn; ei&yogh;en gray,</L>
<L>Such cos &thorn;ou geete with winne;</L>
<L>Godus Modur, Niht and day</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;ou help vs out of sinne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L><I>Virgo singularis, inter omnes mitis,</I></L>
<L><I>nos culpis solutos mites fac &amp; castos.</I></L>
<L>One, peereles Maide now,</L>
<L>&THORN;in help adoun &thorn;ou seende;</L>
<L>A-mong vchone, Meoke artou,</L>
<L N="100">A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e we ben vn-heende;</L>
<L>Sinne bond vs, &thorn;ow wost hou,</L>
<L>&THORN;is world vs wol a-bleende;</L>
<L>Make vs meoke, cast in a vou</L>
<L N="104">In-to vr lyues ende.</L>
<L>Ladi, bring vs out of strif,</L>
<L>Vs geyne&thorn; nouht to &yogh;elpe;</L>
<L>Godus Modur, al vr lyf</L>
<L N="108">We spillen, bote &thorn;ou helpe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>Mayden al-one, buyrde briht,</L>
<L>Wel brihtor &thorn;en &thorn;e Sonne;
<PB REF="00000747.tif" N="739"></L>
<L>Mekest Mayden, most of miht,</L>
<L N="112">Vr gatus &thorn;ou bi-gonne;</L>
<L>Sinne bond vs day and niht,</L>
<L>We spillen &thorn;at we sponne:</L>
<L>Mak vs meke and clene in siht,</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;en is vr game I-wonne.</L>
<L>Ladi, lene vs of &thorn;i liht,</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;it we ben to blynde;</L>
<L>Godes modur, send vs miht,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;e rihte wei to wende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L><I>VItam presta puram, iter para tutum,</I></L>
<L><I>Vt videntes Ihesum semper colletemur.</I></L>
<L>And leen vs clene lyf also,</L>
<L>&THORN;is lyf is serwe and sake;</L>
<L>Diht vs siker wei to go,</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;is sunful lyf &thorn;ou slake;</L>
<L>Get vs Ihesus to seo &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw siht of him to a-wake,</L>
<L>vs to gladschupe euer-mo,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;in help vs &thorn;ou by-take.</L>
<L>Ladi louelich, feir and fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou lilye whyt of face,</L>
<L>Godus Moder briht of ble,</L>
<L N="132">We tristen to &thorn;i grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>Clene lyf &yogh;if vs to-day</L>
<L>And for&thorn;ward euer-more,</L>
<L>Grei&thorn; vs here a syker way;</L>
<L N="136">We stomble ofte and sore;</L>
<L>Siht of Ihesu, wel &thorn;ou may,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if hit &thorn;i wille wore,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;at siht to glade vs ay,</L>
<L N="140">So lyking is &thorn;i lore.</L>
<L>Ladi al in liht I-schrud,</L>
<L>&THORN;eos wordes ben ful so&thorn;e;</L>
<L>Godus Modur, Qween I-kud,</L>
<L N="144">Tak &thorn;i seruauns to &thorn;e.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="28" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000748.tif" N="740">
<HEAD>28. A Prayer to the Trinity.</HEAD>
<P>(2 <I>stanzas of</I> 12, <I>abab abab cdcd.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L><I>Sit laus deo patri, summo christo decus,</I></L>
<L><I>spiritui sancto, tribus, honor vnus. Amen.</I></L>
<L>In God ffader heryng sit,</L>
<L>&THORN;er aftur schul we calle;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Sone al ful of wit</L>
<L N="4">On kneo we schullen falle;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Holigost, to vs &thorn;ou flit</L>
<L>In graces for to walle;</L>
<L>Wit and Grace and streng&thorn;e hit,</L>
<L N="8">We schul hem herie alle.</L>
<L>On is God of mihtes most</L>
<L>ffei&thorn; fully for to fonde,</L>
<L>ffader and Sone and Holigost</L>
<L N="12">Al on is vnderstonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;E ffader was, and ay schal be,</L>
<L>And is wi&thorn;-outen ende;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Sone dyede vppon &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L N="16">Vr falce foon to schende;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holygost, &thorn;at make&thorn; &thorn;re,</L>
<L>&THORN;at may vs grace seende:</L>
<L>Al is on In Trinite,</L>
<L N="20">What wey &thorn;ou turne or weende.</L>
<L>I may sei wi&thorn;-outen bost</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy Book leyh neuere.</L>
<L>ffader and Sone and holygost</L>
<L N="24">Beo wi&thorn; us nou and euere! amen.<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>The Vernon MS. ends here. Nos.</I> 29-30 <I>are from the Simeon MS., Addit.</I> 22,283, <I>Brit. Mus., leaf</I> 134.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="29" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>29. But thou say Sooth, thou shalt be shent.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See the former "Who says the Sooth, he shall be shent," p. 683.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>(9 <I>stanzas of</I> 12, <I>abab abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Who so loueth endeles rest,</L>
<L>&THORN;is false world &thorn;en mot he fle,
<PB REF="00000749.tif" N="741"></L>
<L>And dele &thorn;er-wi&thorn; bot as a gest,</L>
<L N="4">And leue hit not in no degre.</L>
<L>Hit is but trouble &amp; tempest,</L>
<L>ffals fantasye &amp; vanite;</L>
<L>In &thorn;at &thorn;raldom who so is I-&thorn;rest</L>
<L N="8">Him mot eschewe al charite.</L>
<L>&THORN;at day &thorn;at eueri mon schal se</L>
<L>His dedes schewed &amp; his entent,</L>
<L>What maner mon so &thorn;at he be,</L>
<L N="12">But he sey soth, he schal be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>Seyth now dauid in his sawe</L>
<L>In &thorn;e sauter book openly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at whoso to &thorn;e worldus lust drawe,</L>
<L N="16">In his lyf is leef to lye</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne leue&thorn; not on godus lawe,</L>
<L>But forsake&thorn; hit wylfully.</L>
<L>And, for him stont of god no awe,</L>
<L N="20">In bremful bale he schal hit by,</L>
<L>When concience his werk schal wrye;</L>
<L>And as he do&thorn;, he dom schal hente:</L>
<L>Whit-outen restores or remedye,</L>
<L N="24">But he sey soth, he schal be schente.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>A lesyng is with-outen doute</L>
<L>Wel worse &thorn;en sommen taken hede,</L>
<L>ffor, haue &thorn;e tonge onus told hit oute,</L>
<L N="28">Abrod &thorn;en schal hit sprynge &amp; sprede,</L>
<L>And renne ful ryf in eueri route;</L>
<L>And be hit onus so blowen on brede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey men wolden aftur knele &amp; loute;</L>
<L N="32">Men may not stoppe hit with no mede.</L>
<L>Such lesyngus &thorn;en I rede &yogh;e drede,</L>
<L>Lest &yogh;e in bittur bales ben brent.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er nis non so styf on stede,</L>
<L N="36">But he sey soth, he schal be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ou miht als chep robbe a mon</L>
<L>As with a lesyng lese his name.
<PB REF="00000750.tif" N="742"></L>
<L>What so &thorn;ou spekest, where or whanne,</L>
<L N="40">Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou no mon diffame.</L>
<L>Sey &thorn;e sothe, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou kan,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou suppose to here a blame,</L>
<L>fful sore &thorn;e stonde elles schal &thorn;ou ban</L>
<L N="44">When truthe &thorn;i tales schal a-tame.</L>
<L>To greue god, hit is no game,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lust &amp; lykyng ha&thorn; &thorn;e lent;</L>
<L>ffor outh &thorn;at &thorn;ou const forge or frame,</L>
<L N="48">But &thorn;ou sey soth, &thorn;ou schalt be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be &thorn;rat to take &thorn;e deth</L>
<L>ffor seyng soth, be not agast;</L>
<L>Let not &thorn;e sothe be set be-neth,</L>
<L N="52">But truthe to mayntene, be ay studefast.</L>
<L>&THORN;enke &thorn;i lyf is but a breth,</L>
<L>&THORN;enke &thorn;ou schalt passen, as mo han past.</L>
<L>Clottes of clay &thorn;i cors schal cleth,<MILESTONE N=":2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="56">&THORN;i careyne vn-to wormes cast,</L>
<L>When Gabriel schal blowe his blast,</L>
<L>ffor soth sawe schaltou neuer repent.</L>
<L>&THORN;en leue hit lely, at &thorn;e last</L>
<L N="60">But &thorn;ou sey soth, &thorn;ou schalt be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>Alas! what corsed lyf is &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men dreden more &thorn;e world now here</L>
<L>&THORN;en him &thorn;at wrou&yogh;te &thorn;e world I-wys,</L>
<L N="64">And al &thorn;ing ha&thorn; in his pouwere.</L>
<L>As men in questus seyn ofte a-mys,</L>
<L>And stoppen quereles otrewe &amp; clere;</L>
<L>Such men &thorn;enke&thorn; not on heuen blys,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;at &yogh;euen verdites in such manere.</L>
<L>Truthe &amp; kuyndenesse knyt in fere,</L>
<L>God aske&thorn; of vs non o&thorn;er rent;</L>
<L>&THORN;enne wyte hit wel withoute were,</L>
<L N="72">But &thorn;ou sey soth, &thorn;ou schalt be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ey &thorn;ou kacche blame a &thorn;rowe</L>
<L>ffor seyng soo&thorn; more or lasse,
<PB REF="00000751.tif" N="743"></L>
<L>&THORN;enne aftur w&thorn;en &thorn;e treu&thorn;e is I-knowe</L>
<L N="76">Among goode men, as I gesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt be leef vch mon to trowe</L>
<L>And worschyp for &thorn;i sothfastnesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore I rede bo&thorn;e hye and lowe,</L>
<L N="80">Sey soth and lette for no dystresse.</L>
<L>&THORN;yn owne wordus schul bere witnesse</L>
<L>A-&yogh;eyn &thorn;e at &thorn;i Iuggement;</L>
<L>When grete god &thorn;at doom schal dresse,</L>
<L N="84">But &thorn;ou sey soth, &thorn;ou schalt be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>Hold vp no monnus oyl, I rede,</L>
<L>When he wendu&thorn; out of &thorn;e wey,</L>
<L>ffor such glosyngus make&thorn; mony quede,</L>
<L N="88">When non &thorn;e so&thorn;e dar to him say.</L>
<L>Such flaterynge schal luyte stond in stude</L>
<L>When god &thorn;e grete doom schal aray;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at best now here con plede,</L>
<L N="92">I leue he schal be lewede &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>Whan crist schal his woundes dysplay,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for vs was on rode I-rent,</L>
<L>And vche mon schal take his pay,</L>
<L N="96">But &thorn;ou sey soth, &thorn;ou schalt [be] schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>ffor seyng so&thorn;, &thorn;ou miht not synne,</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;ou sclaundre eny wy&yogh;th;</L>
<L>Sclaundre no mon more ne nynne,</L>
<L N="100">ffor sclaundre stynke&thorn; in godus sy&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Elles what quarel &thorn;ou art ynne,</L>
<L>Sey &thorn;e so&thorn;e, ay meynteyne &thorn;e ry&yogh;th;</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is wyse &thorn;ou miht wynne</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;e blysse a-boue &thorn;at blesse&thorn; bry&yogh;th,</L>
<L>And endeles lyf &thorn;at laste&thorn; ly&yogh;th.</L>
<L>&THORN;us I am sure &thorn;at &thorn;ou miht hent,</L>
<L>And elles, when de&thorn; &thorn;i doom schal dy&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="108">But &thorn;ou sey so&thorn;, &thorn;ou schalt be schent.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="30" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000752.tif" N="744">
<HEAD>30. A Morning Thanksgiving and Prayer to God.</HEAD>
<P>(11 <I>stanzas of</I> 8, <I>abab bcbc.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>I&thorn;onke &thorn;e, lord god, ful of miht,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al &thorn;at euer I con &amp; may,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hast me sauet &thorn;is ilke niht</L>
<L N="4">And suffret me forto abyde &thorn;is day.</L>
<L>I-blesset be &thorn;ou euer &amp; ay,</L>
<L>And halewed be &thorn;in hy&yogh;e name;</L>
<L>And worschypet be &thorn;ou, lord, al-way,</L>
<L N="8">Wi&thorn; hy&yogh;e &amp; lowe, wylde &amp; tame.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>In &thorn;e name of god &thorn;at al &thorn;ing wrou&yogh;th,</L>
<L>Heuen &amp; er&thorn;e and vche creature;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e name of ihesu &thorn;at me dere bou&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at is god, godus sone so pure;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holygost, god in o figure,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, o god in persones &thorn;re,</L>
<L>I be-take &thorn;is day of me cure,</L>
<L N="16">And wi&thorn; &thorn;i tokene I marke me:</L>
<L>In nomine patris &amp; filij &amp; spiritus sancti, Amen.</L>
<L>Pater noster. Aue maria. Et Credo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="17">Lord god, &thorn;at &thorn;is day woldust make,</L>
<L>And schope me to lyue &thorn;er-ynne,</L>
<L>My body &amp; soule I &thorn;e be-take.</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;is day, lord, kep me out of synne,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; trou&thorn;e &thorn;is day my lyflode to wynne,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at I do &thorn;e non offens,</L>
<L>ffrom &thorn;i lawe &thorn;at I ne twynne,</L>
<L N="24">Ne breke &thorn;i ten commaundementes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>Lord god Ihesu, as &thorn;ou were boren in a dawynge,</L>
<L>Of a virgyne pure &amp; clene,</L>
<L>Kepe me, lord, &thorn;is morewenynge,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;is day in dedly synne &thorn;at I not byn lene,</L>
<L>ffor wyninge of er&thorn;elyche godus:<MILESTONE N="134:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffrom flessch[ly] lustus &amp; lykynge,
<PB REF="00000753.tif" N="745"></L>
<L>Kepe me, lord, wi&thorn; &thorn;i pressyos blod,</L>
<L N="32">ffrom temptacions of &thorn;e fende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>And as &thorn;ou were turmentud sore</L>
<L>In &thorn;at selue tyde of niht,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bobbyng, scorny[n]ge &amp; wel more,</L>
<L N="36">ffort hit were dayes light</L>
<L>[. . . . . ight]</L>
<L>Sende me &thorn;is day do sum good dede</L>
<L>In lettyng wrong &amp; doyng riht,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at &thorn;ou, lord, mouwe quyte me my mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>As &thorn;ou were lord, when hit was day,</L>
<L>Ofte examnet wi&thorn; wordus grete,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bysschopes of ful gret aray,</L>
<L N="44">Wi&thorn; proude prynces &thorn;at &thorn;e con &thorn;rete,</L>
<L>Sende me &thorn;is day drynk &amp; mete,</L>
<L>And susteyne me in &thorn;i seruise;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if I be mys-hap, lord, &thorn;e fo[r]&yogh;ete,</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;orw &thorn;e, lord, let me aryse!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>Lord I be-take &thorn;e my fiue wyttes;</L>
<L>Myn y&yogh;en, &thorn;at I synge not in sy&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Lord, my mouth open hit in &thorn;i werkes,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;er-wi&thorn; &thorn;at I may speke tru&thorn;e &amp; ri&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Myn heryng, lord god, dele &amp; dy&yogh;h</L>
<L>To here no&thorn;ing a&yogh;eyn &thorn;i wille;</L>
<L>My nese, lord ihesu ful of my&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="56">Kepe hit &thorn;at I non vuel smel.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>Lord, kep &amp; lede my feet also</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo don &thorn;i seruyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with hem I not mys go.</L>
<L N="60">Myn honden, lord, kep on alle wyse,</L>
<L>And set hem, lord, in such asyse</L>
<L>&THORN;at I, [o] lord, with hem not synne.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if I do, lord, let me aryse,</L>
<L N="64">And let me not longe lygge &thorn;erynne.
<PB REF="00000754.tif" N="746"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ey&yogh; I haue syngut her-be-fore,</L>
<L>Let me not for-garte &thorn;i grace.</L>
<L>I crye &thorn;e mercy, lord, euer more;</L>
<L N="68">Of amendement, lord, sende sum space,</L>
<L>And sende my soule for my trespace.</L>
<L>&THORN;enke, lord, I am &thorn;i creature,</L>
<L>And sende me, lord, help now in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;i mercy out ouer al mesure.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>Lord, wharto woldust vengaunce take</L>
<L>On me &thorn;at &yogh;elde me &thorn;us gulty?</L>
<L>I may not amendus make,</L>
<L N="76">But put me holly in &thorn;i mercy,</L>
<L>And for my synne I am sorye:</L>
<L>&THORN;enk, of my self no my&yogh;th I haue;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou me help, in synne I dye:</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;i grace, mercy,<NOTE PLACE="foot">? for 'grete mercy'</NOTE> lord, may me saue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>My soule, my body, lord god ihesu,</L>
<L>I now by-take in &thorn;i kepynge;</L>
<L>Kepe me, lord, in &thorn;i vertu,</L>
<L N="84">In al my werk &amp; al my worchynge.</L>
<L>In &thorn;i nome be al my doynge!</L>
<L>In &thorn;e nome of Ihesu I be-gynne:</L>
<L>Lord god ihesu al weldynge,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;is day kepe me out of synne! Amen!<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>The rest of the leaf is blank.</I>]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

