<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>1. Christ on the Cross.</HEAD>
<P>(6 <I>stanzas of</I> 10 <I>lines each, abab ccb ccb. &thorn; is for MS. y.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Hi sike al wan hi singe,</L>
<L>for sorue &thorn;at hi se:</L>
<L>Wan hic wit wepinge</L>
<L N="4">bi-holde a-pon &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>Hi se ihesu mi suete</L>
<L>his herte blode for-lete</L>
<L N="7">for &thorn;e luue of me.</L>
<L>His wondis wexin wete:</L>
<L>Marie milde and sute,</L>
<L N="10">&thorn;u haf merci of me!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="11">Hey a-pon a dune,</L>
<L>as al folke hit se may,</L>
<L>a mile wytt-hute &thorn;e tune,</L>
<L N="14">a-bute &thorn;e mid day,</L>
<L>&thorn;e rode was op a-reride:</L>
<L>his frendis werin al of-ferde,
<PB REF="00000762.tif" N="754"></L>
<L N="17">&thorn;ei clungin so &thorn;e cley.</L>
<L>&thorn;e rod stonit in ston,</L>
<L>Mari hir selfe al-hon,</L>
<L N="20">hir songe was way-la-way.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="21">Wan hic him bi-holde</L>
<L>wyt hey and herte bo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Hi se his bodi colde,</L>
<L N="24">his ble waxit alle bloe;</L>
<L>He honge al of blode,</L>
<L>se hey a-pon &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L N="27">bi-twixin &thorn;efis two.</L>
<L>Hu soldi singe mor?</L>
<L>Mari, &thorn;w wepe sor;</L>
<L N="30">&thorn;u wist of al his woe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="31">Wel ofte wan hi siche,</L>
<L>hi make mi mone;</L>
<L>Hiuel hic<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? hit]</NOTE> may me like,</L>
<L N="34">and wondir nis hit non,</L>
<L>Wan hi se honge hey,</L>
<L>Ande bitter peynis drei,</L>
<L N="37">Ihesu my lemmon.</L>
<L>His wondis sor[e] smerte,</L>
<L>&thorn;e sper his at his herte,</L>
<L N="40">Ande &thorn;orit his side gon.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. rubd</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="41">&THORN;e naylis beit al to longe,</L>
<L>&thorn;e smyt his al to sleye,</L>
<L>&thorn;ue bledis al to longe,</L>
<L N="44">&thorn;e tre his al to heye,</L>
<L>&thorn;e stonis waxin wete:</L>
<L>Allas, ihesu, mi suete,</L>
<L N="47">feu frendis hafdis &thorn;ue;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. rubd</NOTE></L>
<L>But sin Ion murnid,</L>
<L>And Mari wepnid,</L>
<L N="50">&thorn;at al &thorn;i sorug seys.
<PB REF="00000763.tif" N="755"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="51">Wel ofte wan hi slepe,</L>
<L>wit soru hic ham &thorn;oit soit;</L>
<L>Wan hi wake and wende,</L>
<L N="54">hi &thorn;enke in mi &thorn;oit,</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at man beit wode!</L>
<L>bi-holdit an &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L N="57">and silit hic [han broit]<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. rubd.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hir souelis in to sin,</L>
<L>for any worlde hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">? worldis.</NOTE> win,</L>
<L N="60">&thorn;at was so der hi-boyt.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>2. Hail, Mary! Digby MS. 2, leaf 6, back.</HEAD>
<P>(<I>A ryme-beginning poem.</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">See <I>Early English Poems and Lives of Saints</I>, in Philol. Soc. Trans. 1872, and note the frequent central rymes here.</NOTE> 5 <I>stanzas of</I> 8 <I>lines, aaaa abab.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">Hayl, mari! hic am sori:</L>
<L>haf pite of me, and merci!</L>
<L>mi leuedi, to &thorn;e i cri:</L>
<L N="4">for mi sinnis, dred ham hi,</L>
<L>wen hi &thorn;enke hat hi sal bi,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hi haf mis hi-don</L>
<L>in worde, in worke, in &thorn;oith, foli:</L>
<L N="8">leuedi, her mi bon!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="9">Mi bon &thorn;u her, leuedi der,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hic aske wit reuful cher!</L>
<L>&thorn;u len me her,<NOTE PLACE="foot">'lefdi der' follows, dotted under as a mistake.</NOTE> wil hic am fer,</L>
<L N="12">do penanx in mi praier;</L>
<L>ne let me noth ler, &thorn;at &thorn;u ber,</L>
<L>at mi nendin day;</L>
<L>&thorn;e worlais, &thorn;ai wil be her,</L>
<L N="16">fort[to] take &thorn;air pray.
<PB REF="00000764.tif" N="756"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="17">To take &thorn;ar pray, alse hi her say</L>
<L>&thorn;ai er redi, boyt nite<NOTE PLACE="foot">Note the absence of the guttural <I>gh.</I> Compare Capgrave's Chronicle, and his St. Katharine, E. E. T. Soc.</NOTE> and day;</L>
<L>so strange er &thorn;ai, &thorn;at we ne may</L>
<L N="20">A-gaynis &thorn;aim stond, so way la way,</L>
<L>but &thorn;u gif helpus, mitteful<NOTE PLACE="foot">Note the absence of the guttural <I>gh.</I> Compare Capgrave's Chronicle, and his St. Katharine, E. E. T. Soc.</NOTE> may,</L>
<L>Wit &thorn;i sunes grace;</L>
<L>Wan &thorn;u comes, &thorn;ai flet a-wai;</L>
<L N="24">dar &thorn;ai not se &thorn;i face.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="25">&THORN;i face to se, &thorn;u grant hit me,</L>
<L>lefdi ful-fillid of pite,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hi may be in Ioy wit &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="28">to se &thorn;i sone in trinite,</L>
<L>&thorn;at sufferid pine, and ded for me</L>
<L>and for al man-kyn:</L>
<L>his flesse was sprade on rode tre,</L>
<L N="32">to leysus al of sine.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="33">Of sine and kar, he maked vs bar,</L>
<L>Wan he &thorn;ollid pines sar;</L>
<L>to drupe and dar, we athe wel mare,</L>
<L N="36">alse for &thorn;e hondis doyt &thorn;e har,</L>
<L>wan we &thorn;enke hu we sal far</L>
<L>wan he sal dem vs alle,</L>
<L>we sal haf ned[e &thorn;an &amp;] &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="40">a-pon mari to calle, &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>3. A Resolve to Reform.</HEAD>
<P>(<I>A ryme-beginning poem.</I> 3 <I>stanzas of</I> 6, <I>aaab ab. &thorn; is for MS. y.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">No more willi wiked be;<MILESTONE N="15" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Forsake ich wille &thorn;is world-is fe,</L>
<L>&thorn;is wildis wodis, &thorn;is folen gle;</L>
<L N="4">ich wul be mild of chere:</L>
<L>of cnottis scal mi girdil be,</L>
<L N="6">becomme[n] ich wil frere.
<PB REF="00000765.tif" N="757"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="7">Frer menur i wil me make,</L>
<L>and lecherie i wille asake;</L>
<L>to ihesu crist ich wil me take,</L>
<L N="10">and serue in holi churche,</L>
<L>all in mi ouris for to wake,</L>
<L N="12">goddis wille to wurche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="13">Wurche i wille &thorn;is workes gode,</L>
<L>for him &thorn;at boyht us in &thorn;e rode;</L>
<L>from his side ran &thorn;e blode;</L>
<L N="16">so dere he gan vs bie:</L>
<L>for sothe i tel him mor &thorn;an wode,</L>
<L N="18">&thorn;at haytit<NOTE PLACE="foot">? for 'hantith,' practises.</NOTE> licherie<NOTE PLACE="end"><I>MS. Digby</I> 86, <I>c.</I> 1275 A.D., <I>leaf</I> 125, <I>back. Bodleian Library.</I></NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>4. Les di&yogh; de seint bernard comenceent .I. ci tres beaus.<NOTE PLACE="head">(Printed before in Anglia, III. 59, etc., by Varnhagen.)</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>(9 <I>stanzas of</I> 6, <I>aab, ccb.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e blessing of heuene king,</L>
<L>And of his moder, &thorn;at swete &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="3">Mote we all hauen!</L>
<L>He ous &yogh;eue good beginning,</L>
<L>And clene lif at oure ending;</L>
<L N="6">&THORN;at auhte we alle craven.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>Lestne&thorn; me a luitel &thorn;rowe,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at wilen ou selven cnowe!</L>
<L N="9">Ounwis &thorn;au ich be,</L>
<L>.I. shal hou tellen, alse ich can,</L>
<L>Wat holy writ speke&thorn; of man;</L>
<L N="12">Lestne&thorn; nou to me!
<PB REF="00000766.tif" N="758"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Seint bernard sei&thorn; in his bok,</L>
<L>&THORN;a[t] man is werm, and wermes hok,</L>
<L N="15">And wermes he shal feden;</L>
<L>Wen his lif him is bireued,</L>
<L>In his rug and in his heued</L>
<L N="18">Shulen grisliche wermes breden.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e fles sal melten from &thorn;e bon,</L>
<L>&THORN;e senewes sundren euerichon,</L>
<L N="21">&THORN;e body hit sal defien.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at wilen &thorn;at so&thorn;e .I.-seen,</L>
<L>Oundo&thorn; &thorn;e graues &thorn;ere &thorn;ey been,</L>
<L N="24">And loke&thorn; wat &thorn;ere lien.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>Mon, &thorn;ou art a feble fom,</L>
<L>Ne hauest &thorn;ou here non siker hom;</L>
<L N="27">Ne seye ich &thorn;e bote skil;</L>
<L>&THORN;i ri&yogh;te stude is helles wer;</L>
<L>Ihesus lete ous comen &thorn;er,</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;orou his swete wil!<MILESTONE N="126" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;i fles stont a&yogh;ein &thorn;i gost:</L>
<L>Wen &thorn;ou shalt deyen, &thorn;ou ne wost,</L>
<L N="33">Nou&thorn;er day ne ni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Nedes costes &thorn;ou most deyen,</L>
<L>Ne may no rauncoun &thorn;e forbeyen;</L>
<L N="36">Grey&thorn;e &thorn;e wiles &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>A fikel wind, mon, is &thorn;i lif,</L>
<L>And de&thorn; drawe&thorn; his sarpe knif;</L>
<L N="39">&THORN;ou do &thorn;e sone sriue!</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou counne loke ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ne hauest &thorn;ou here bote fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="42">&THORN;e wiles &thorn;ou art aliue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>For nou &thorn;ou art wrong, nou &thorn;ou art ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Nou &thorn;ou art heui, nou &thorn;ou art li&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="45">&THORN;ou skippest alse a ro;
<PB REF="00000767.tif" N="759"></L>
<L>Nou &thorn;ou art sek, and nou &thorn;ou coverest;</L>
<L>Nou &thorn;ou art riche, and nou &thorn;ou pouerest;</L>
<L N="48">Ne is &thorn;is muchel wo?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;i fles &thorn;e sey&thorn; ni&yogh;t and day,</L>
<L>.I. wile hauen eise wil .I. may;</L>
<L N="51">&THORN;i soule &thorn;e sei&thorn; nay:</L>
<L>If ich &thorn;e bere to muchel me&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wilt me bringen helle de&thorn;,</L>
<L N="54">And wo &thorn;at laste&thorn; ay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;us hit go&thorn; bitwenen hem two;</L>
<L>&THORN;at on sei&thorn; 'let,' &thorn;at o&thorn;er 'do,'</L>
<L N="57">Ne cunne&thorn; hey ne nere bilinnen;</L>
<L>Wel we mowen alle .I.-seen,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule auhte maister to been,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;e pris hoe hautte to winnen.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>Mon, be &thorn;ou nout &thorn;i self ouncou&thorn;;</L>
<L>Loke wat come&thorn; out at &thorn;i mou&thorn;,</L>
<L N="63">Ne findest &thorn;ou non so fouvel dinghep,<NOTE PLACE="foot">altered from 'dinhhep': l. 64 is written after l. 66.</NOTE><MILESTONE N=":2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ey &thorn;ou loke al abouten,</L>
<L>And elles wer wi&thorn;-houten,</L>
<L N="66">Wel hinderliche &thorn;ou nim &thorn;e kep.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ou hauest, man, in &thorn;at foule hous,</L>
<L>A &thorn;ing &thorn;at is wel precious;</L>
<L N="69">Wel dere hit wes .I.-bouht:</L>
<L>Ich helde &thorn;e for wilde and wod,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou letest so muchel god,</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;e deuel hauen for nouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>Mon, be waker and be wis;</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou doun fallest, sone aris,</L>
<L N="75">Ne li &thorn;ou none stounde:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle &thorn;i mi&yogh;te, if &thorn;ou dost &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;i soule seyt, and so&thorn; hit is,</L>
<L N="78">Ioye &thorn;ou hauest .I.-founde.
<PB REF="00000768.tif" N="760"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14: Man's Three Foes. The First, his Flesh.)</HEAD>
<L>Mon, &thorn;ou hauest &thorn;re wikke fon;</L>
<L>Here nomes con ich euerich on;</L>
<L N="81">Nou ich shal tellen alle:</L>
<L>&THORN;in owene fles, &thorn;e world, &thorn;e fend;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at scholde ben &thorn;i frend,</L>
<L N="84">He do&thorn; &thorn;e ra&thorn;est falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ou clo&thorn;est him wi&thorn; faire sroud,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou makest &thorn;i fomen fat and proud.</L>
<L N="87">If ich hit dourste seyen;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou dost &thorn;i self wel muchel wrong,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou makest &thorn;i foman fat and strong</L>
<L N="90">To fi&yogh;ten &thorn;e a&yogh;ein.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ou do bi counsail and bi red;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;drau him hofte of his bred,</L>
<L N="93">And luitel &yogh;ef him to drinken;</L>
<L>Ne let him no&thorn;ing Idel gon;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou do him pines mani on,</L>
<L N="96">And ofte do him to swinken.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17: Man's Second Foe, the World.)</HEAD>
<L>To coveitise of mani &thorn;ing,<MILESTONE N="126b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e werld &thorn;e drawe&thorn;; and misliking</L>
<L N="99">Hit giue&thorn; &thorn;e more and more.</L>
<L>Fals he his, and feir he seme&thorn;,</L>
<L>And alrebest, wen he &thorn;e queme&thorn;,</L>
<L N="102">He binde&thorn; &thorn;e wel sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ou wost &thorn;e world shal gon to nout,</L>
<L>Ne hauest &thorn;ou no&thorn;ing hider ibrout,</L>
<L N="105">Ne nout shalt bere wi&thorn; &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt alone gon &thorn;i way,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-oute stede and palefray,</L>
<L N="108">Wi&thorn;-oute gold and fe.
<PB REF="00000769.tif" N="761"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19: Man's Third Foe, the Fiend.)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;i &thorn;ridde fo, &thorn;at foule wi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fonde&thorn; bo&thorn;e day and ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="111">&THORN;eron hise gilles alle:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wost wel he ne loue&thorn; &thorn;e nout,</L>
<L>He fonde&thorn; to chaunge &thorn;i &thorn;out,</L>
<L N="114">And do &thorn;e for to falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ou wost he ne wille &thorn;e no god;</L>
<L>He wolde hauen &thorn;in herte blod;</L>
<L N="117">&THORN;ou be war of his hok!</L>
<L>Do nou also ich haue &thorn;e seid,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;re sulen ben aleid</L>
<L N="120">Wi&thorn; here owene crok.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>If &thorn;ou seyst &thorn;is spelis hard,</L>
<L>Ne may .I. nout swech foreward</L>
<L N="123">Holden, ne wel drie;</L>
<L>A litel &thorn;ing ich axe &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sei me so&thorn;, par charite,</L>
<L N="126">&THORN;er-of &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne lie.<NOTE PLACE="end"><I>c.</I> 1275. <I>MS. Digby</I> 86, <I>leaf</I> 126, <I>back, col.</I> 1.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>5. Ubi sonnt qui ante nos fuerount?</HEAD>
<P>(10 <I>stanzas of</I> 6, <I>aab, ccb.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Uuere be&thorn; &thorn;ey biforen vs weren,</L>
<L>Houndes ladden and hauekes beren,</L>
<L N="3">And hadden feld and wode?</L>
<L>&THORN;e riche leuedies in hoere bour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wereden gold in hoere tressour,</L>
<L N="6">Wi&thorn; hoere bri&yogh;tte rode,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>Eten and drounken, and maden hem glad;</L>
<L>Hoere lif was al wi&thorn; gamen .I.-lad,</L>
<L N="9">Men keneleden hem biforen;
<PB REF="00000770.tif" N="762"></L>
<L>&THORN;ey beren hem wel swi&thorn;e heye;</L>
<L>And in a twincling of an eye</L>
<L N="12">Hoere soules weren forloren.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Were is &thorn;at lawing and that song,</L>
<L>&THORN;at trayling and that proude &yogh;ong,</L>
<L N="15">&THORN;o hauekes and &thorn;o houndes?</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at ioye is went away,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wele is comen to weylaway,</L>
<L N="18">To manie harde stoundes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>Hoere paradis by nomen here,</L>
<L>And nou &thorn;ey lien in helle .I.-fere;</L>
<L N="21">&THORN;e fuir hit brennes heuere:</L>
<L>Long is ay, and long is ho,</L>
<L>Long is wy, and long is wo;</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;ennes ne come&thorn; &thorn;ey neuere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>Dre&yogh;y here man, &thorn;enne, if &thorn;ou wilt,</L>
<L>A luitel pine &thorn;at me &thorn;e bit;</L>
<L N="27">Wi&thorn;drau &thorn;ine eyses ofte;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey &thorn;i pine be oun-rede,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou &thorn;enke on &thorn;i mede,</L>
<L N="30">Hit sal &thorn;e &thorn;inken softe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>If &thorn;at fend, &thorn;at foule &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&THORN;orou wikke roun, &thorn;orou fals egging,</L>
<L N="33">&THORN;ere ne &thorn;ere &thorn;e haue&thorn; .I.-cast,</L>
<L>Oup, and be god chaunpioun!</L>
<L>Stond, ne fal namore adoun</L>
<L N="36">For a luytel blast!<MILESTONE N="127" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ou take &thorn;e rode to &thorn;i staf,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enk on him &thorn;at &thorn;ereoune &yogh;af</L>
<L N="39">His lif &thorn;at wes so lef:</L>
<L>He hit &yogh;af for &thorn;e; &thorn;ou &yogh;elde hit him;</L>
<L>A&yogh;ein his fo, &thorn;at staf &thorn;ou nim,</L>
<L N="42">And wrek him of &thorn;at &thorn;ef!
<PB REF="00000771.tif" N="763"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>Of ri&yogh;tte bileue &thorn;ou nim &thorn;at sheld,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wiles &thorn;at &thorn;ou best in &thorn;at feld,</L>
<L N="45">&THORN;in hond to strenk&thorn;en fonde,</L>
<L>And kep &thorn;y fo wi&thorn; staues ord,</L>
<L>And do &thorn;at traytre scien &thorn;at word;</L>
<L N="48">Biget &thorn;at mvrie<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? MS.]</NOTE> londe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ere-inne is day wi&thorn;-houten ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen ende, strenk&thorn;e and mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="51">And wreche of euerich fo;</L>
<L>Mid god him-selwen eche lif,</L>
<L>And pes and rest wi&thorn;oute strif,</L>
<L N="54">Wele wi&thorn;-outen wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>Mayden moder, heuene quene,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mi&yogh;t and const, and owest to bene</L>
<L N="57">Oure sheld a&yogh;ein &thorn;e fende:</L>
<L>Help ous sunne for to flen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we moten &thorn;i sone .I.-seen,</L>
<L N="60">In ioye wi&thorn;-outen hende. Amen!</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="6" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>6. Channcoun de noustre Dame. (A Dialog between Christ on the Cross and his Mother.)<NOTE>Printed before in Anglia, II. 253 seq.</NOTE></HEAD> 
<P>(9 <I>stanzas of</I> 6, <I>aab, ccb.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>"Stond wel, moder, ounder rode,</L>
<L>Bihold &thorn;i child with glade mode;</L>
<L N="3">Moder, bli&thorn;e mi&yogh;t &thorn;ou be,"</L>
<L>"Sone, how may ich bli&thorn;e stonde?</L>
<L>Ich se &thorn;ine fet, and &thorn;ine honde,</L>
<L N="6">.I.-nayled to &thorn;e harde tre."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>"Moder, do wey &thorn;i wepinge!</L>
<L>Ich &thorn;olie de&thorn; for monnes kuinde;</L>
<L N="9">Wor mine gultes ne &thorn;olie .I. non."<MILESTONE N="127:2" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000772.tif" N="764"></L>
<L>"Sone, ich fele &thorn;e de&thorn;es stounde;</L>
<L>&THORN;at swerd is at min hertes grounde,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at me byheyte simeon."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>"Moder, do wei &thorn;ine teres:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wip awey &thorn;e blodi teres;</L>
<L N="15">Hy do&thorn; me worse &thorn;ene mi de&thorn;."</L>
<L>"Sone, hou mi&yogh;tte ich teres werne?</L>
<L>I se &thorn;ine blodi woundes herne</L>
<L N="18">From &thorn;in herte to &thorn;i fot."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>"Moder, nou .I. may &thorn;e seye,</L>
<L>Betere is, &thorn;at ich one deye,</L>
<L N="21">&THORN;en alle mankyn to helle go."</L>
<L>"Sone, .I. se &thorn;i body .I.-swonge,</L>
<L>&THORN;in honde, &thorn;in fet, &thorn;i bodi .I.-stounge:</L>
<L N="24">Hit nis no wonder &thorn;ey me be wo."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>"Moder, if ich &thorn;e dourste telle,</L>
<L>If ich ne deye, &thorn;ou gost to helle:</L>
<L N="27">.I. &thorn;olie de&thorn; for monnes sake."</L>
<L>"Sone, &thorn;ou me bi-hest so milde;</L>
<L>.I.-comen hit is of monnes kuinde,</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;at ich sike, and serewe make."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>"Moder, merci, let me deye,</L>
<L>And Adam out of helle beye,</L>
<L N="33">And monkin &thorn;at is forlore."</L>
<L>"Sone, wat sal me &thorn;e stounde?</L>
<L>&THORN;ine pinen me bringe&thorn; to &thorn;e grounde;</L>
<L N="36">Let me dey[e] &thorn;e bifore!"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>"Swete moder, nou &thorn;ou fondest</L>
<L>Of mi pine &thorn;er &thorn;ou stondest;</L>
<L N="39">Wi&thorn;-houte mi pine nere no mon."</L>
<L>"Sone, .I. wot .I. may &thorn;e telle,<MILESTONE N="127b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hote hit be, &thorn;e pine of helle;</L>
<L N="42">Of more pine, ne wot .I. non."
<PB REF="00000773.tif" N="765"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>"Moder of moder, &thorn;us .I. fare;</L>
<L>Nou &thorn;ou wost wimmanes kare;</L>
<L N="45">&THORN;ou art clene mayden on."</L>
<L>"Sone, &thorn;ou helpest alle nede,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;o &thorn;at to &thorn;e wille grede,</L>
<L N="48">May and wif, and fowel wimmon."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>"Moder, .I. ne may no lengore dwelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e time is comen, .I. go to helle:</L>
<L N="51">I &thorn;olie &thorn;is for &thorn;ine sake."</L>
<L>"Sone, .I.-wis .I. wille founde?</L>
<L>.I. deye almest; .I. falle to grounde:</L>
<L N="54">So serwful de&thorn; nes never non!"</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="7" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>7. Here biginne&thorn; &thorn;e same of Seint bede, prest.</HEAD>
<P>(7 <I>stanzas of</I> 6, <I>aab, aab, or aab, ccb.</I>)</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1; Of Heaven and Hell.)</HEAD>
<L>Holi gost, &thorn;i mi&yogh;tte</L>
<L>Ous wisse and rede and di&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="3">And help ous and teche</L>
<L>To witen ous wi&thorn; &thorn;e onwi&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bi day and by ni&yogh;tte</L>
<L N="6">&THORN;enche&thorn; ous bipeche,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>Make&thorn; ous to don sunne,</L>
<L>And abben to monkunne</L>
<L N="9">Swi&thorn;e muchel honde.</L>
<L>He &thorn;enche&thorn; ous biwinne,</L>
<L>And wonien ous wi&thorn;inne,</L>
<L N="12">And ouer ous habben honde:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Ac bidde we crist &yogh;erne</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at he hem werne</L>
<L N="15">For his mildenesse,</L>
<L>For hy &thorn;at to hem sulen turne,</L>
<L>In helle hy shulen forberne,</L>
<L N="18">In hewche &thorn;esternesse.<MILESTONE N="127b:2" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000774.tif" N="766"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>We houten oure suppinde</L>
<L>Herien of alle &thorn;inge,</L>
<L N="21">And louien hine wel swi&thorn;e,</L>
<L>For he ous wille werien,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fendes ous ne derien,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at folle be&thorn; of ni&thorn;e;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>Ne be we nout here</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e fele &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="27">Bote we her, we henne wende:</L>
<L>Makein ous clene and skere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we in heuene, englene fere,</L>
<L N="30">Ben ho wi&thorn;-outen ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>In heuene, in &thorn;e blisse</L>
<L>&THORN;at muchel is midiwisse,</L>
<L N="33">And leste&thorn; euere more;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-inne is reste and lisse;</L>
<L>Ne may &thorn;er no mon misse,</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;at louie&thorn; godes ore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>Ac hit sai&thorn; in &thorn;e gospelle,</L>
<L>Ne may non tounge al telle,</L>
<L N="39">&THORN;e blisse &thorn;at &thorn;er is euere,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e pine of helle,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-to we be&thorn; wel swelle,</L>
<L N="42">Awey hit ne hende&thorn; nevere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;er-inne is chele and hete,</L>
<L>And hounger ounimete,</L>
<L N="45">And &thorn;urst alles to kene;</L>
<L>Pikede be&thorn; &thorn;e shete,</L>
<L>And wormes &thorn;er be&thorn; kete,</L>
<L N="48">To don &thorn;e soule tene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;erinne is wop and woninge,</L>
<L>And muchel bimeninge</L>
<L N="51">&THORN;at hoe .I.-boren were;<MILESTONE N="128" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000775.tif" N="767"></L>
<L>Ac &thorn;er nis non hendinge,</L>
<L>Ne non a&yogh;ein-cher-hinge,</L>
<L N="54">&THORN;at enes come&thorn; &thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>Wel we owen nimen gome</L>
<L>He &thorn;at elles &thorn;ider come,</L>
<L N="57">And seruen heuene kinge,</L>
<L>And bidden him .I.-lome,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ous at &thorn;e dome,</L>
<L N="60">Of here pine bringe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>Oute we owre sunnen leten,</L>
<L>And munien crist, and beten,</L>
<L N="63">Of alle oure misdede;</L>
<L>To doinde hoe be&thorn; swete,</L>
<L>For-&thorn;y ous is helle &yogh;ete,</L>
<L N="66">Helle &thorn;at is ounlede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12: aab, aab. The Seven Chief Sius.)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e seuene heued sunne</L>
<L>&THORN;at we be&thorn; ofte wi&thorn;inne,</L>
<L N="69">&THORN;e soule wolle&thorn; amerre;</L>
<L>Hoe be&thorn; of swikele kunne,</L>
<L>&THORN;ermide &thorn;e wi&thorn;erwinne</L>
<L N="72">Ous alle &thorn;enche&thorn; to bicherre.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13: aaa, bba)</HEAD>
<L>Modinesse, and ouerfastnesse,</L>
<L>Onde, wrathes, swikelnesse,</L>
<L N="75">Hordom, and &yogh;euernesse;</L>
<L>&THORN;is we houten alle ounderstonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at moni men in londe</L>
<L N="78">Bringe&thorn; to sorinesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14: aab, aab)</HEAD>
<L>For &thorn;is be&thorn; &thorn;e seuene</L>
<L>&THORN;at bringe&thorn; out of heuene,</L>
<L N="81">Swi&thorn;e fele monne;</L>
<L>&THORN;e weyes be&thorn; in hoere wene</L>
<L>Mid wepinde steuene;</L>
<L N="84">In-to helle hoe shulen &thorn;enne.<MILESTONE N="128:2" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000776.tif" N="768"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15: aab, ccb. The Pride of Rich Folk.)</HEAD>
<L>Hoe wene&thorn; monie of &thorn;ise riche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he henglen ben .I.-liche</L>
<L N="87">For hoere proude clo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore hoe sulen scriken,</L>
<L>And in helle siken,</L>
<L N="90">And crien hit foul wrothe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16: aab, aab)</HEAD>
<L>So wene&thorn; &thorn;is wreche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hoe ne weren riche</L>
<L N="93">For-&thorn;i &thorn;at hoe haytte nabbe&thorn;;</L>
<L>Ac<NOTE PLACE="foot">? MS. 'et': also in other lines.</NOTE> satanas &thorn;e wreche</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule wille drecche</L>
<L N="96">Wen hoe ani got habbe&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;er iche midiwisse</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;tte comen to blisse,</L>
<L N="99">If he hit wolde her nye,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e wreche may wel misse,</L>
<L>Bote he his pouernesse</L>
<L N="102">In mildenesse &thorn;olie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18: The Sins of Monks and Priests.)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;is monekes wene&thorn; soumme,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gedere&thorn; garisoumme,</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;at hoe hit shulen brouke;</L>
<L>Ac wene<NOTE PLACE="foot">? MS. At-wene.</NOTE> &thorn;e de&thorn; shal comen,</L>
<L>Hit shal hem ben binomen,</L>
<L N="108">Bitaut hoe be&thorn; &thorn;e pouke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e prest &thorn;at singe&thorn; masse</L>
<L>&THORN;oru godes herienesse,</L>
<L N="111">And wot of techinge,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-of nul don almesse,</L>
<L>In euche sorinesse</L>
<L N="114">His soule he may bringe.
<PB REF="00000777.tif" N="769"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20: The Sins of Knights.)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;es kni&yogh;ttes be&thorn; wel bolde,</L>
<L>For hy abbe&thorn; aquolde</L>
<L N="117">Here ani cristine were;<MILESTONE N="128b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For-&thorn;i sa[t]anas &thorn;e holde</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule wil atholde,</L>
<L N="120">And makien hire oun i-fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21: The Sins of Lawyers.)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;es plaidours be&thorn; wel kene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at werie&thorn; red and grene.</L>
<L N="123">And al &thorn;is ounri&yogh;t deme&thorn;:</L>
<L>Hy shulen, wi&thorn;-houten wene,</L>
<L>To helle &thorn;at is so kene,</L>
<L N="126">&THORN;er &thorn;e fendes reme&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22: The Sins of Chapmen.)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;is chapmen monie bi strete,</L>
<L>Hy be&thorn; swikele ounimete,</L>
<L N="129">Hy ne recche&thorn; &thorn;an hy swerien</L>
<L>For to abben here bi&yogh;ete;</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i satanas &thorn;e kete,</L>
<L N="132">Here soule wille derien.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23: The Working Bondman.)</HEAD>
<L>Of alle men on londe,</L>
<L>Mest swinke&thorn; &thorn;e bonde,</L>
<L N="135">And mest bi&yogh;et mit ri&yogh;te;</L>
<L>If he cou&thorn;e ounderstonde</L>
<L>And te&thorn;ege ri&yogh;t ounder his honde,</L>
<L N="138">To crist he comen mi&yogh;tte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L>Ac for alle his biswinke,</L>
<L>If he may comen to sottes drinke,</L>
<L N="141">And stelen cristes teu&thorn;inge,</L>
<L>Sstrong de&thorn; hit wile him &thorn;enke,</L>
<L>Depe in helle winke</L>
<L N="144">His soule he may bringe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25: The Sins of Proud Ladies.)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;es proude leuedies</L>
<L>&THORN;at louen driweries,</L>
<L N="147">And breken here spousinge,
<PB REF="00000778.tif" N="770"></L>
<L>And do&thorn; to-gabbie,</L>
<L>&THORN;at loveden simonie</L>
<L N="150">Of eni gode &thorn;inge;<MILESTONE N="128b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L>Hy drawe&thorn; here wede,</L>
<L>Mid selkene &thorn;rede</L>
<L N="153">.I.-frendet and .I.-bounde:</L>
<L>Swart and swi&thorn;e ounlede</L>
<L>Bemen hy shulen, and grede</L>
<L N="156">Depe in helle grounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27: Lecherous Monks and Nuns.)</HEAD>
<L>Monekes and eremites and nonnen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hem witen ne cunnen</L>
<L N="159">Wi&thorn; swecche lecherie,</L>
<L>Hy shulen to &thorn;ere oun-winne:</L>
<L>Alle here clo&thorn;es dounne</L>
<L N="162">Ne shulen hem warauntie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L>So&thorn;liche al betere him were</L>
<L>&THORN;at hy .I.-boren nere,</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;at &thorn;ider shule wende:</L>
<L>Warin ich ou here;</L>
<L>For &yogh;e &thorn;at enes come&thorn; &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;er &yogh;e be&thorn; ha-bouten hende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L>Aat<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. Aat <I>for</I> Ac</NOTE> hy wene&thorn; libbie</L>
<L>And longe sunegie,</L>
<L N="171">And &thorn;ene at &thorn;en ende</L>
<L>Here sunnen al anendie,</L>
<L>And birewsie,</L>
<L N="174">And se&thorn;&thorn;en to heuene wende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L>Ne ben &yogh;e nout so ownriste</L>
<L>Nou to ihesu criste,</L>
<L N="177">&THORN;er-to ich ou lere;</L>
<L>For &thorn;er nes non &thorn;at weste,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-houten ihesu criste,</L>
<L N="180">Wen his hon day were.
<PB REF="00000779.tif" N="771"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L>For ous ne be&thorn; nout so e&thorn;e</L>
<L>To-&yogh;eines houre de&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="183">&THORN;awe ous moowen so wel hede,<MILESTONE N="129" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne speken bote oun&thorn;ewe,</L>
<L>For ous be&thorn; stronge and wre&thorn;e</L>
<L N="186">To beten oure misdede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L>Nout wi&thorn; criste scolde</L>
<L>Beten ous &thorn;enne on londe</L>
<L N="189">To habben houre ri&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>Wen we him seruen nolde,</L>
<L>Ne laufoul ben, ne holde,</L>
<L N="192">Her we non for&thorn;er ne mi&yogh;tte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L>So&thorn;liche, wen we be&thorn; dede,</L>
<L>Euerich sal fongen mede</L>
<L N="195">After his herihinge,</L>
<L>Bote we ous &thorn;e bet bihede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule hit shal .I.-frede,</L>
<L N="198">&THORN;at fare&thorn; to pininge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e hali me binde&thorn;,</L>
<L>In here me him &thorn;ringe&thorn;,</L>
<L N="201">And bringe&thorn; him hounder er&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Wor meshim .I.-finde&thorn;,</L>
<L>To axnen hoe him grinde&thorn;,</L>
<L N="204">&THORN;arto hy shulen wor&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L>He li&thorn; and rote&thorn; lowe,</L>
<L>He ne haue&thorn; &thorn;at be his owe</L>
<L N="207">Of aytte ne of londe,</L>
<L>Ne now&thorn;er mey ne mowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er doren a &thorn;rowe</L>
<L N="210">Bi hem sitten ne stonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L>Ac<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. At</NOTE> wer be&thorn; &thorn;anne his haytte,</L>
<L>&THORN;a he here raytte,</L>
<L N="213">And in &thorn;is lif wonne?
<PB REF="00000780.tif" N="772"></L>
<L>So&thorn;liche hy be&thorn; bi-pay&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>Swecche o&thorn;ere hoe be&thorn; bitai&yogh;tte,</L>
<L N="216">Lat him no &thorn;onk ne cunne.<MILESTONE N="129:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L>Ac wer be&thorn; &thorn;enne his ringes,</L>
<L>And his proude &thorn;inges,</L>
<L N="219">And his golt-peinte gloue?</L>
<L>Wor al his proude &thorn;inges,</L>
<L>Ne vaille&thorn; him no &thorn;inges</L>
<L N="222">&THORN;enne to his bihoue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<L>Sothliche, naked and bare,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wop and wi&thorn; kare,</L>
<L N="225">&THORN;ou come to &thorn;isse liue;</L>
<L>And so &yogh;e sulen eft-senes fare;</L>
<L>.I. saye &thorn;e soth wi&thorn;-oute sware;</L>
<L N="228">Grey&thorn;e&thorn; ou biliue!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39: nine lines)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e salt &thorn;e world forleten and lewe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? rvmes]</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er-of &yogh;e shulden &thorn;enken ene,</L>
<L N="231">And oure sunne aquenche</L>
<L>Mid beden and mid almesse,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen idelnesse,</L>
<L N="234">If &yogh;e mi&yogh;tten at-blenche</L>
<L>From &thorn;e sori satanasse,</L>
<L>And from his swikelnesse</L>
<L N="237">And from his heuele wrenche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<L>If &thorn;ou fallest in sunne,</L>
<L>Ne li &thorn;ou nout &thorn;er-inne;</L>
<L N="240">Hie&thorn;e &thorn;e oup to arisen,</L>
<L>And shend &thorn;e wi&thorn;erwine</L>
<L>Satanas mid his pine,</L>
<L N="243">And do&thorn;e also &thorn;e wise.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41)</HEAD>
<L>For mon nohute nout to abbe soule,</L>
<L>Wen his wrecche licome</L>
<L N="246">In sunnen be .I.-falle,
<PB REF="00000781.tif" N="773"></L>
<L>Ac abbeyes houte dome,</L>
<L>And ounwren his sunnen .I.-lome,</L>
<L N="249">And crist in fuir pine&thorn; alle.<MILESTONE N="129b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42: The Good of Shrift.)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e mon him let wel sriven,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ene fend out driven,</L>
<L N="252">Ne &thorn;arf him nout shomie,</L>
<L>For ne be&thorn; in &thorn;isse live,</L>
<L>Wepmen ne wimmen fiue</L>
<L N="255">&THORN;at ofte ne svnegie&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43)</HEAD>
<L>At<NOTE PLACE="marg">? for <I>Ac</I></NOTE> &thorn;es modie gome</L>
<L>And leuedies and &thorn;e ounrome</L>
<L N="258">Loute&thorn; hem also &thorn;e ounwise,</L>
<L>And &thorn;es &yogh;ounlinges somme,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey &thorn;at hoe to srifte come,</L>
<L N="261">Hoe be&thorn; sottes and shomefaste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44)</HEAD>
<L>Hy nulle&thorn; so&thorn; tellen,</L>
<L>&THORN;an me shulde hem quellen,</L>
<L N="264">Hy ounsweren here misdede:</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i hoe shulen in helle</L>
<L>Euere gronen and swelle,</L>
<L N="267">And euere-mo ben &thorn;er-inne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(45)</HEAD>
<L>Wenne eni grome&thorn; sore,</L>
<L>&THORN;e grome &thorn;unche&thorn; more</L>
<L N="270">&THORN;en al hore o&thorn;er pine.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bi prestes lore</L>
<L>Nolden herien godes hore,</L>
<L N="273">&THORN;enne hoe hit shullen biwine.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46: The Last Judgment.)</HEAD>
<L>At &thorn;e mounte of olifete,</L>
<L>&THORN;er we ous shulen alle .I.-mete;</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode and &thorn;e ounwreste,</L>
<L N="277">&THORN;e day wor&thorn; milde and sete;</L>
<L>And bitter unimete</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at forlete</L>
<L N="279">To don godes heste.
<PB REF="00000782.tif" N="774"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;er cume&thorn; god on his rode,<MILESTONE N="129b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And his side his a blode,</L>
<L N="282">And sewe&thorn; on he ous boute.</L>
<L>Afered be&thorn; &thorn;enne &thorn;e gode,</L>
<L>And wo is &thorn;enne &thorn;e ouermode</L>
<L N="285">&THORN;at &thorn;er-of ne route.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48)</HEAD>
<L>"Loke&thorn;," sey&thorn; god nou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>"Wat ich for ou ou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="288">Wat ich for ou gon &thorn;olie;</L>
<L>Luitel &thorn;onk &yogh;e me cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ne mid werke ne mid mou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="291">Nolden &yogh;e me &thorn;onkie."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(49)</HEAD>
<L>At<NOTE PLACE="marg">For <I>Ac</I></NOTE> he sey&thorn; &thorn;enne to &thorn;e gode,</L>
<L>And to his milde moder,</L>
<L N="294">"&YOGH;e duden gode dede;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e me fedden and srudden,</L>
<L>And wel me bihedden</L>
<L N="297">&THORN;o ich among ou hede,</L>
<L>And leide me a softe bedde;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore ich ou wole aredde,</L>
<L N="300">For nou &yogh;e habbe&thorn; nede."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(50)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e gode sege&thorn; &thorn;enne,</L>
<L>"Louerd, were and wenne</L>
<L N="303">Duden we &thorn;e gode deden?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;use," he sei&thorn;, "&thorn;e poure monne,</L>
<L>&THORN;o hoe help neden nen,</L>
<L N="306">Bote as hoe for me beden;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51)</HEAD>
<L>"At<NOTE PLACE="marg">For <I>Ac</I></NOTE> &yogh;e, mine gode midiwisse,</L>
<L>To heueriche blisse</L>
<L N="309">To-day &yogh;e shulen wende;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e at our sede, to sorinesse</L>
<L>And to suche &thorn;esternesse,</L>
<L N="312">And &thorn;er ben euere, bouten ende."
<PB REF="00000783.tif" N="775"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52)</HEAD>
<L>He sei&thorn; &thorn;enne to &thorn;e wreche,</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e nolden nout hof me recche;<MILESTONE N="130" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="315">For hounger ich aswal &thorn;route:</L>
<L>&YOGH;e nolden me in fecche,</L>
<L>Ou self &yogh;e weren so frecche,</L>
<L N="318">So modi and so proude."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(53)</HEAD>
<L>Hoe grede&thorn; &thorn;enne on heye,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wrecches and &thorn;e ounweye</L>
<L N="321">&THORN;at loueden &thorn;e ounredes,</L>
<L>And sigge&thorn;, "louerd, wi&thorn; oure eye</L>
<L>We &thorn;e neuere ne seye</L>
<L N="324">&THORN;er &thorn;ou nede heuedest."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(54)</HEAD>
<L>God sey&thorn;, "&yogh;u se mine</L>
<L>Povere ounhole hine</L>
<L N="327">&THORN;at to oure dore come:</L>
<L>For chele hoe heueden pine,</L>
<L>For hounger hoe gonnen chine;</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;er-of ne nome &yogh;e gome;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(55)</HEAD>
<L>"&THORN;er-of &yogh;e nolden hede,</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;euen hem of oure brede,</L>
<L N="333">Ne of drinke ne of clo&thorn;e:</L>
<L>To-day &yogh;e sulen frede,</L>
<L>And ounder-fongen mede,</L>
<L N="336">For, me &yogh;e be wel lo&thorn;e."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(56)</HEAD>
<L>Hoe &yogh;erre&thorn; &thorn;enne and grede&thorn;;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fendes hem for&thorn; lede&thorn;,</L>
<L N="339">Bo&thorn;e licome and soule,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;e&thorn; hem, and grede&thorn;,</L>
<L>Stike&thorn; hem and brede&thorn;</L>
<L N="342">Wi&thorn; pikes and wi&thorn; howeles.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(57)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e soule sey&thorn; to onsuare,</L>
<L>"Licom, al &thorn;ou forfare</L>
<L N="345">So wrechede and so ounlede,
<PB REF="00000784.tif" N="776"></L>
<L>Wor &thorn;ou ous hauest .I.-wrout &thorn;is fare,</L>
<L>And .I.-brout ous ewche kare</L>
<L N="348">&THORN;at euere we shulen &thorn;olie.<MILESTONE N="130:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(58)</HEAD>
<L>"At<NOTE PLACE="marg">For <I>Ac</I></NOTE> &thorn;e gode and &thorn;e clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;an hoe .I.-seien ous &thorn;enne,</L>
<L N="351">Al &thorn;at cun &thorn;at we of come,</L>
<L>Nulle hoe neuer ene</L>
<L>Birewen ne bimene,</L>
<L N="354">Ne &thorn;ar-to nimen gome.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(59)</HEAD>
<L>"Hem self, hoe be&thorn; so bli&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at hoe of wone si&thorn;e</L>
<L N="357">Moten ane day wonie,</L>
<L>And &thorn;onke&thorn; god swi&thorn;e</L>
<L>Ofte and monie si&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="360">&THORN;at hy hit mosten herie."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(60)</HEAD>
<L>At<NOTE PLACE="marg">For <I>Ac</I></NOTE> &yogh;if we ous wolden vel di&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>And leden ous mid ri&yogh;tte</L>
<L N="363">&THORN;e wiles &thorn;at we her were,</L>
<L>Ich ou sugge and pli&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e domes &yogh;e mi&yogh;tte</L>
<L N="366">Ben englene fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(61)</HEAD>
<L>At<NOTE PLACE="marg">For <I>Ac</I></NOTE> bidde we oure dri&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at dayes sop and ni&yogh;tte</L>
<L N="369">&THORN;at do hour soule bote,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at we mi&yogh;tte</L>
<L>.I.-seiene ben at si&yogh;tte</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e hengles bri&yogh;tte:</L>
<L N="373">Amen, so hit be mote! Amen!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="8" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000785.tif" N="777">
<HEAD>8. Coment le santex noustre dame fu primes cuntxoue.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Printed by Horstmann, <I>Altenglische Legenden</I>, 1881, p. 220 <I>seq.</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Leuedi swete and milde,</L>
<L>For loue of &thorn;ine childe</L>
<L N="3">&THORN;at is foul of mi&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>Me &thorn;at am to wilde,</L>
<L>From shome &thorn;ou me shilde</L>
<L N="6">Bi day and eke bi ni&yogh;tte!<MILESTONE N="130b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>Ich wille biginnen here,</L>
<L>And tellen &thorn;e manere,</L>
<L N="9">Nou at &thorn;isse stounde,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i sauter here,</L>
<L>Mid wel gode chere,</L>
<L N="12">Ou hit wes .I.-founde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Send me &thorn;ine grace,</L>
<L>Nou in &thorn;isse place</L>
<L N="15">So wel for to done;</L>
<L>Ich nou bidde &thorn;i grace,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-to lif and space;</L>
<L N="18">Here nou mine bone!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>Ariche man was wile,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nolde none gile;</L>
<L N="21">He louede holi chirche;</L>
<L>Bi sides him a mile,</L>
<L>On abbey of seint gile,</L>
<L N="24">His helderne gonne werche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>God lif &thorn;is man ladde;</L>
<L>One sone he hadde,</L>
<L N="27">&THORN;at gode dedes dede;
<PB REF="00000786.tif" N="778"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; clo&thorn; and wi&thorn; bedde,</L>
<L>His sone faire he sredde</L>
<L N="30">In &thorn;at ilke stede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>Monk he &thorn;ere bicom,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; abit he &thorn;er nom</L>
<L N="33">Bi his fader wille.</L>
<L>Him louede god and mon,</L>
<L>So faire he bigon,</L>
<L N="36">Wor euere he wes stille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>His fader him bimenede</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;er-inne wende,</L>
<L N="39">So &yogh;ong sholde .I.-wis.<MILESTONE N=":2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He dede after him sende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is nou &thorn;at ende,</L>
<L N="42">And made him muchel blis.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>A maister hadde his sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; him wes .I.-come,</L>
<L N="45">Cointe .I.-nou and sley;</L>
<L>Hit wes his .I.-wone,</L>
<L>To techen alle and some</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;e ordre fer and ney.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>He hede ofte aboute,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-innen and wi&thorn;-oute,</L>
<L N="51">Wi&thorn; &thorn;e louerd on day;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sone he lek &thorn;er oute,</L>
<L>He hede for to aloute;</L>
<L N="54">Tellen ich ou may.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e leuedi ful of mi&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bar oure dri&yogh;tte,</L>
<L N="57">In a chapele &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Bi day and eke bi ni&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>Out when he comen mi&yogh;tte,</L>
<L N="60">Were ware he were.
<PB REF="00000787.tif" N="779"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>Ou alle ich telle may,</L>
<L>On houndred, ewche day,</L>
<L N="63">He gretingges seyde;</L>
<L>Wel he held his lay,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e ordre, bi mi fay,</L>
<L N="66">For loue of &thorn;at meyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>Wel he hedde bi-wrout,</L>
<L>Wor god wes his &thorn;out,</L>
<L N="69">&THORN;at wes wel .I.-sene;</L>
<L>He ne les hit nohut,</L>
<L>Wor he hit hadde about;</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;eron his gode bene.<MILESTONE N="131" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>Ne let he none stounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne fel to grounde,</L>
<L N="75">And on kne was bat,</L>
<L>And &thorn;oute of &thorn;e wonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at god for al &thorn;e mounde</L>
<L N="78">On rode heuede .I.-sprad.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>On houndret, to &thorn;e meyde,</L>
<L>Aue maries he seyde,</L>
<L N="81">Bi tale heche daye,</L>
<L>Ne hit nout ne aleyde;</L>
<L>Ac so wel he pleyde,</L>
<L N="84">Ri&yogh;t so&thorn; for to saye,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;at he sau wel bri&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>Oure leuedi foul of mi&yogh;tte,</L>
<L N="87">A settres-day .I.-wis,</L>
<L>Were hoe sat wel ri&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>.I.-clo&thorn;ed half bi si&yogh;tte,</L>
<L N="90">And seyde to him &thorn;is:
<PB REF="00000788.tif" N="780"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>"Mi monk, ne dred &thorn;e nout,</L>
<L>For .I. &thorn;e haue .I.-bout,</L>
<L N="93">And &thorn;e ich wille take;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hauest so goed-ful wraut,</L>
<L>Ne worst &thorn;ou nout bikaut;</L>
<L N="96">Goed ne shal &thorn;e lake.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>"Ich &thorn;onke &thorn;e her nou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou, wi&thorn; &thorn;ine mou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="99">Me hauest .I.-paied wel;</L>
<L>Bi nor&thorn;e and eke bi [sou&thorn;e]<NOTE PLACE="foot">The right lower corner of the MS. has come unpasted, and has fallen off. The words are supplied from the Auchinleck MS. in <I>A Penniworth of Witte</I>, Abbotsford Club, ed. D. Laing, and <I>Altenglische Legenden</I>, 1881, p. 221-3.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hit shal ben w[el (i)cou&thorn;e]</L>
<L N="102">&THORN;ine dedes [euerich del].</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>"Ac &thorn;ou m[ost more say]</L>
<L>Wor[me now euche day]</L>
<L N="105">Fifti al bi score<MILESTONE N="131:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of aue maries,</L>
<L>Fifti on day &thorn;ries,</L>
<L N="108">Wite nou were-fore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>"&THORN;at is ri&yogh;t mi sauter,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou shalt witen her,</L>
<L N="109">Hou hit shal ben do:</L>
<L>Fifty sege bi-fore,</L>
<L>Tene euere bi score,</L>
<L N="112">And on anteme &thorn;erto,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>"In tokning of &thorn;e blisse</L>
<L>&THORN;at fel me mid i-wisse</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;o &thorn;e aungele to me com,</L>
<L>And seyde me tidinge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of me sholde springe</L>
<L N="118">He &thorn;at is god and mon.
<PB REF="00000789.tif" N="781"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>"After, say wel sone,</L>
<L>Fifti mid idone,</L>
<L N="121">Al for &thorn;at ilke blisse</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wi&thorn;-outen [sore]<NOTE PLACE="foot">Corner of the MS. gone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wolde of me ben [bore]</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;er [of ne misse]</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L>"&THORN;er-aft[er &thorn;ou shalt say]</L>
<L>Eft [fifti euche day]</L>
<L N="127">Bi [&thorn;ine fingres ten]</L>
<L>O[f aue maries]</L>
<L>[Euche day &thorn;ries]</L>
<L N="130">[Telle hit fele men!]</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L>["Fifti at &thorn;en ende,]</L>
<L>[For I shude wende]</L>
<L N="133">[To mi sone &thorn;o,]</L>
<L>[For blis and for to amende,]</L>
<L>[&THORN;at he to me gan sende]</L>
<L N="136">To me comen and go.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L>"He broute me to blisse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer ne shal misse,</L>
<L N="139">In &thorn;at ilke stounde.</L>
<L>Blesced be &thorn;at time,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle brovte of pine,</L>
<L N="142">&THORN;at weren &thorn;erinne .I.-bounde!"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L>"<B>A</B>, leuedi, .I. &thorn;e grete,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou art fair and swete,</L>
<L N="145">And goed to serui wel;</L>
<L>Graunte me &thorn;in ore,</L>
<L>Wor .I. shal euere more</L>
<L N="148">Don &thorn;is euerich del.
<PB REF="00000790.tif" N="782"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L>"If ich dourste and cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ich wolde .I.-witen nou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="151">Leuedi, here of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Wi &thorn;e faille&thorn; gore,</L>
<L>Sleue, and nammore</L>
<L N="154">Of clo&thorn; &thorn;at ich .I.-se."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L>"&THORN;is clo&thorn; &thorn;ou me &yogh;eue</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Corner of the MS. gone.</NOTE>[On Se]ttresday a&yogh;ein eue,</L>
<L N="157">[&THORN;orou] Aue maries.</L>
<L>[&THORN;o &thorn;ou] me gvnne greten,</L>
<L>[And nolde] to sugen leten</L>
<L N="160">[Twies e]wche dayes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L>["For &thorn;ou most say more]</L>
<L>[&THORN;ries fifti bi score,]</L>
<L N="163">[Al-so .I. teld &thorn;e,]</L>
<L>[To-day a seveni&yogh;tte]</L>
<L>[.I.-clothed al ari&yogh;tte]</L>
<L N="166">[&THORN;ou shalt me fair .I.-se]</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L>["Be here of al scille,]</L>
<L>[And say wi&thorn; gode wille]</L>
<L N="169">Alle &thorn;e gretinges;<MILESTONE N="131b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And I shal &thorn;e bringe</L>
<L>From mi sone, &thorn;e kinge,</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;anne gode tidinges."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L>Marie wente away,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e monke euche day</L>
<L N="175">Seyde, ri&yogh;t &thorn;re si&thorn;es,</L>
<L>Mid wel gode wille,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e loude and stille</L>
<L N="178">&THORN;ese Aue maries.
<PB REF="00000791.tif" N="783"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;at day a seveni&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>Oure leuedi foul of mi&yogh;tte</L>
<L N="181">To &thorn;at moneke com,</L>
<L>.I.-clo&thorn;ed swi&thorn;e bri&yogh;tte</L>
<L>In &thorn;at wede al ri&yogh;tte,</L>
<L N="184">And &thorn;onkede &thorn;at mon:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L>"Fair is, lo, mi wede,</L>
<L>For bedes &thorn;at &thorn;ou bede,</L>
<L N="187">And &thorn;ou hauest quemet me:</L>
<L>Mi sone &thorn;e wille rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no&thorn;ing &thorn;e nadrede,</L>
<L N="190">Here ich hit telle &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L>"Vuene &thorn;ou art home .I.-come,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt Abbot bicome,</L>
<L N="193">For &thorn;in Abbot shal deye.</L>
<L>Haue euere in &thorn;i wone</L>
<L>To suggen mi coustome,</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;ine Aues euche daye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L>"Wend ouer al aboute</L>
<L>[A]nd preche inne and oute</L>
<L N="199">[&THORN;at] &thorn;is is mi sauter;</L>
<L>[For al] &thorn;at euche day</L>
<L>[Wille &thorn;is] for me saye,</L>
<L N="202">I shal hem ben wel ner.<MILESTONE N="132" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L>"Monek, ich telle hit &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou most, al for me,</L>
<L N="205">Wenden wide wore,</L>
<L>And telle &thorn;is tidinge,</L>
<L>And mine sone bringe</L>
<L N="208">Wel fele him bifore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L>"Wor &thorn;oru Aue maries</L>
<L>&THORN;at mon shal sayen &thorn;ries</L>
<L N="211">In &thorn;e worshipe of me,
<PB REF="00000792.tif" N="784"></L>
<L>I shal hem helpen alle</L>
<L>&THORN;at to me wilen kalle,</L>
<L N="214">For so&thorn; ich telle hit &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L>"Nis non &thorn;at shal deien,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wille &thorn;ries seien</L>
<L N="217">&THORN;ese Aue maries,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-outen hosel and srifte,</L>
<L>Bi daye ne bi ni&yogh;tte,</L>
<L N="220">Wor none folies;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<L>"He shal in euche place</L>
<L>Wel finden mi grace</L>
<L N="223">At his liues ende;</L>
<L>And he shal hauen space,</L>
<L>And finden godes grace,</L>
<L N="226">Him al to amende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<L>"Gon ich wille henne:</L>
<L>Sey hit to mani menne</L>
<L N="229">&THORN;is, and make hit cou&thorn;,</L>
<L>Wor seue &yogh;er after &thorn;is</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt deye .I.-wis,</L>
<L N="232">Ich telle hit &thorn;e wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<L>"So longe is &thorn;i time</L>
<L>To holden &thorn;e and &thorn;ine,</L>
<L N="235">And hem for to teche;<MILESTONE N="132:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>After &thorn;at, of pine</L>
<L>&THORN;ou worst .I.-brout wi&thorn; mine,</L>
<L N="238">Wor .I. shal ben &thorn;i leche.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41)</HEAD>
<L>Marie wente away;</L>
<L>&THORN;e monek rod ni&yogh;t and day,</L>
<L N="243">Folk to gode bringe;</L>
<L>&THORN;oru &thorn;is ilke &thorn;inge</L>
<L>And &thorn;oru his prechinge,</L>
<L N="244">Goed wes &thorn;e tidinge.
<PB REF="00000793.tif" N="785"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42)</HEAD>
<L>Nou ich bidde here</L>
<L>Ou alle wi&thorn; godes chere</L>
<L N="247">&THORN;at &yogh;e suggen &thorn;ries,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wel gode wille,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e loude and stille</L>
<L N="250">&THORN;ese Aue maries.<NOTE PLACE="end">(<I>Les ounsse peines de enfer</I> follow, which Stengel printed in his Catalog of this MS.)</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="9" TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>A Confession of Sins, and a Prayer to Christ.<NOTE PLACE="foot">From a cut-down leaf of a late 14th-century MS., sent by the Rev. J. R. Burton, Headmaster of Kidderminster Grammar School, to the Deputy-Keeper of MSS. at the British Museum, Mr. G. F. Warner, who kindly showd it to me, and got Mr. Burton's leave for me to copy and print it.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete ihesu crist, to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Copable wrecche ich &yogh;elde me,</L>
<L>Of sennes &thorn;at ich habbe ydo</L>
<L N="4">Yn al my lyue hider-to,</L>
<L>In pride, yn wra&thorn;&thorn;e, in vyl enuye,</L>
<L>Yn glotonye, yn lecherye,</L>
<L>Yn sleu&thorn;e, lord, yn &thorn;y seruyse,</L>
<L N="8">And of &thorn;is wordles coueytise:</L>
<L>To ofte ich habbe, yn myne lyue,</L>
<L>Ysen&yogh;ed wit my wittes fyue,</L>
<L>Wit eren yhered, wit e&yogh;en sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="12">Wit senfol speche dey &amp; ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Wit cleppinges, wit kessenge also,</L>
<L>Wit hondes yhandled, wit fet ygwo,</L>
<L>Wit herte senfolliche y&thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="16">Wit al my body euele y wro&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And of al my [grete] folye,</L>
<L>Mercy, lord, mercy, ich crye!</L>
<L>Al-&thorn;a&yogh; ich sen&yogh;ede euere,</L>
<L N="20">Lord, ich for-soc &thorn;e neuere.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;ou me none med[e]</L>
<L>Efter my senful dede, [. . . . .]
<PB REF="00000794.tif" N="786"></L>
<L>Ak efter, lord, &thorn;y grete [pite],<NOTE PLACE="marg">[back]</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">Lord ihesu, asoyle &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L>And send me ofte, er [y deye],</L>
<L>Sor&yogh;e of herte and teres o[f e&yogh;e]</L>
<L>For sennes &thorn;at ich habbe [ido]</L>
<L N="28">Yn al my lyue hider[to];</L>
<L>And let me neuere b[e so nice]</L>
<L>To do no maner dede [of vice],</L>
<L>So &thorn;at ich, at myn end[yng day]</L>
<L N="32">Clene of senne deye [may],</L>
<L>Srifte and housele at [myn ende],</L>
<L>&THORN;at my saule mote [wende]</L>
<L>Yn-to &thorn;at blisse of [hevenriche]</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;er &thorn;ou regnest, lo[rd, ].<NOTE PLACE="end">[Two lines are no doubt left out after l. 22: the sense wants, 'If thou rewardest me according to my sinful deeds, <I>I must go to hell</I>,' or some equivalent words to make a couplet.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
